window.WIKI_DATA = [{"slug":"argollean-brotherhood","title":"The Argollean Brotherhood","category":"factions","status":"active","tags":["faction","criminal","eladran","first-empire","artifacts","intelligence","fort-meade","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood\">The Argollean Brotherhood</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Argollean Brotherhood</strong> is a criminal network connected to old <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> noble houses that survived the fall of the First Empire. They exist marginally and resentfully within <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> imperial society, executing plans and deeds on behalf of these houses: intelligence work, artifact acquisition, and the occasional removal of obstacles.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"overview\">Overview</h2>\n<p>The Brotherhood are not common criminals. They are criminals with a lineage, which makes them more dangerous and harder to prosecute. Their operations are disciplined, their motivations are ideological as much as financial, and their networks extend through the remnants of the old Eladran aristocracy.</p>\n<p>They execute plans and deeds on behalf of the old <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> noble houses: intelligence work, artifact acquisition, and occasional removal of obstacles. Their members are trained, discreet, and motivated by a sense of cultural grievance that gives their work a conviction ordinary criminal enterprise lacks.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"primary-interest-first-empire-artifacts\">Primary Interest: First Empire Artifacts</h2>\n<p>The Brotherhood&#39;s primary commercial interest is relics and artifacts of the First Empire -- items that the old Eladran houses regard as cultural inheritance, and which the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> regards as state property.</p>\n<p>They move these items through networks that bypass official channels, returning them to the Eladran houses they consider their rightful owners. This trade is lucrative, but it is not purely mercenary -- the Brotherhood genuinely believes these artifacts belong to the descendants of those who created them, not to the empire that conquered their makers.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"presence-in-fort-meade\">Presence in Fort Meade</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade&#39;s</a> position on the trade route between <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> makes it a natural waypoint for Brotherhood operations. Members are embedded in the settlement, though they remain unidentified.</p>\n<p>They are not aggressive toward the general population. Their interest is focused on the flow of artifacts from the <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> ruins and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- sites that have begun producing relics of genuine First Empire provenance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-malachor-and-the-imperial-academy\">Relationship with Malachor and the Imperial Academy</h2>\n<p>The Brotherhood and <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> share a mutual distaste maintained at professional distance. Both want the same things -- the artifacts flowing out of the <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> ruins and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>.</p>\n<p>The Brotherhood regards the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> as a body that believes ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> heritage belongs to the Empire rather than to its descendants. Malachor considers their perspective provincial and ungrateful.</p>\n<p>They will not cooperate. Neither will move openly against the other -- for now. The equilibrium is maintained by the fact that neither faction has enough leverage or manpower at Fort Meade to risk open confrontation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"hook-for-the-reclaimers\">Hook for the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>The Brotherhood will become aware of what the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> recover from the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. Whether they approach as buyers, competitors, or hostile actors depends entirely on what comes up and how the Reclaimers handle it.</p>\n<p>If the Reclaimers recover artifacts the Brotherhood considers Eladran cultural property and attempt to sell them through official channels (or to <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a>), the relationship will turn adversarial. If the Reclaimers are willing to deal, the Brotherhood can offer coin, information, and access to networks the party cannot reach on their own.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"local-leadership-arannis-venn\">Local Leadership: Arannis Venn</h2>\n<p>The Brotherhood&#39;s local operations at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> are led by <strong>Arannis Venn</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Arannis Venn</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Eladran</span> script, marks him to those who know what to look for.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison settlement where the Brotherhood operates covertly</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Imperial Academy historian and rival artifact hunter</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The scholarly institution the Brotherhood opposes ideologically</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> -- The ancient civilization whose heritage the Brotherhood claims to protect</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- Ruins producing First Empire artifacts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- Underground site producing artifacts of significant value</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The party whose discoveries may draw Brotherhood attention</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire the Brotherhood exists within, resentfully</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- Southern terminus of the trade route the Brotherhood uses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- Northern terminus of the trade route</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">arannis-venn</a> -- Local Brotherhood leader at Fort Meade</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"burnished-scale","title":"The Burnished Scale","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["religion","militant-order","heresy-of-the-flame"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-burnished-scale\">The Burnished Scale</h1>\n<p>The Burnished Scale is a militant religious order within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, defined by its role in one of the most dangerous internal crises the Empire has ever faced -- the <strong>Heresy of the Flame</strong> in 304 IY.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-heresy-of-the-flame-304-iy\">The Heresy of the Flame (304 IY)</h2>\n<p>Under the leadership of <strong>Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas</strong>, the Burnished Scale launched an <strong>unauthorized purge</strong> targeting those they deemed heretics, apostates, and enemies of the true faith. The purge was conducted without the sanction of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> or the authority of the Emperor, representing a direct challenge to both religious and secular governance.</p>\n<p>Vargas and his followers believed they were acting in defense of doctrinal purity, but the violence and scope of the purge rapidly destabilized entire provinces. What began as a campaign of religious enforcement threatened to ignite full-scale civil war within the Empire.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-assassination-and-its-aftermath\">The Assassination and Its Aftermath</h2>\n<p>The crisis reached its breaking point when the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a>, acting on the Emperor&#39;s orders, <strong>assassinated Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas</strong>. The killing of the Burnished Scale&#39;s leader decapitated the movement but did not immediately quell the unrest. Vargas&#39;s followers viewed his death as martyrdom, and the Empire teetered dangerously close to open conflict.</p>\n<p>It fell to the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> to intervene, brokering a resolution that pulled the Empire back from the brink. The Heresy of the Flame left deep scars on imperial politics and religious life, and the events of 304 IY remain a cautionary tale about the dangers of unchecked zealotry.</p>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>The Burnished Scale&#39;s purge and its aftermath reshaped the relationship between the Empire&#39;s religious and secular authorities. The crisis demonstrated both the fragility of imperial unity and the necessity of institutional checks on militant faith. The memory of Lord-Pentient Vargas remains a divisive subject -- reviled by some as a fanatic, venerated by others as a martyr who died for the purity of the Flame.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Talons</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"congregation-of-the-hollow-sun","title":"Congregation of the Hollow Sun","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["faction","religious","secretive","cult","bone-creek","backlands","long-term-threat","hollow-sun","heresy","shaw","seros","thousand-temples","refugees","avari","scalpers","scarification","suffering","purification"],"html":"<h1 id=\"congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\">Congregation of the Hollow Sun</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The temples speak of fire, brothers. They speak of flame as if it warms. But I have seen the flame that burns in silence. I have heard it speak in the dark, where no sun can reach.&quot; -- <a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a>, Sermon of the Hollow Light</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;What they worship in their temples is not the Sun, but its shadow! They weigh you with false scales, built by cowards in golden robes.&quot; -- <a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The <strong>Congregation of the Hollow Sun</strong> is a secretive religious movement operating across the Province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, led by the charismatic cleric <strong><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a></strong>, who calls himself the <strong>Prophet of the True Dawn</strong>. The Congregation represents a <strong>long-term threat</strong> -- a slowly building movement whose full theology, membership, and ultimate trajectory remain contested even by those who study it. While the other power players in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> and beyond struggle over gold, territory, and influence, Shaw is building something far more dangerous: a community of true believers who feel -- perhaps for the first time in their lives -- that someone has told them the truth about their suffering.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"shaws-theology\">Shaw&#39;s Theology</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-stolen-sun\">The Stolen Sun</h3>\n<p>Shaw&#39;s theology begins with a claim that the official church has suppressed: that <strong><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></strong> -- or whatever the Unconquered Sun truly is -- has been <strong>stolen</strong>. The faith of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> is a shadow of the original truth -- a flattering lie designed to keep the wealthy comfortable and the poor compliant. The scales have been weighted from the beginning. The justice that the Thousand Temples preach is justice for those who can afford it. The light they worship is not the Sun but its reflection, distorted by centuries of institutional corruption, political accommodation, and deliberate suppression of truths that would threaten the comfort of those who benefit from the lie.</p>\n<p>This is not merely theological criticism. Shaw does not argue that the Thousand Temples are imperfect or in need of reform. He argues that they are <strong>fundamentally false</strong> -- that the entire institutional structure of Empyrean worship as practiced in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> is built on a foundation of deliberate deception.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-hollow-sun\">The Hollow Sun</h3>\n<p>In place of the warm, distant, benevolent light of orthodox <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> worship, Shaw proposes the <strong>Hollow Sun</strong> -- not the comfortable divine radiance that the Thousand Temples preach, but something <strong>colder, more total, and radically egalitarian</strong>.</p>\n<p>The Hollow Sun <strong>sees through you</strong>. It does not care about birth, coin, silk on your tongue, or the endorsement of senators. It wants your <strong>weight</strong> -- your pain, your purity, the thing that remains when everything false has been scraped away. It demands not wealth or status but authenticity -- the raw, unadorned truth of what you are when pretension, comfort, and self-deception have been stripped away.</p>\n<h3 id=\"salvation-through-suffering\">Salvation Through Suffering</h3>\n<p>Shaw&#39;s theology of salvation is built on suffering. Salvation is not granted to the comfortable or the powerful. It is available to those who have been <strong>reduced to what cannot be taken away</strong> -- who have been stripped of everything except the irreducible core of their being by the grinding weight of frontier life, poverty, violence, and despair.</p>\n<p>This salvation is <strong>available to the refugee and the slave as fully as to the magistrate</strong>. In fact, it is more available to them -- because they have already been stripped, already been reduced, already been scraped clean of the pretensions and comforts that insulate the wealthy from the Hollow Sun&#39;s gaze. The poor, the desperate, the broken -- they are closer to the truth than any senator in his marble hall.</p>\n<p>This is an enormously appealing message in a province full of people the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire</a> has failed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"recruitment-and-following\">Recruitment and Following</h2>\n<h3 id=\"who-follows-shaw\">Who Follows Shaw</h3>\n<p>The Congregation draws from the populations that the Empire has most thoroughly abandoned:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Refugee quarters</strong> -- the displaced, the dispossessed, the people who have lost everything to beastman raids, imperial neglect, and frontier violence. Shaw tells them their suffering has meaning. No one else has.</li>\n<li><strong>The Scalper population</strong> -- bounty hunters, mercenaries, and frontier desperadoes who kill <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> for gold and carry trauma that no temple has addressed. Shaw offers them a framework for understanding what they have done and what has been done to them.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> communities</strong> -- the marginalized survivors of the Avari Confederation, whose culture was systematically destroyed after <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> burned the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a>. Shaw&#39;s critique of imperial institutions resonates with people who have experienced the Empire&#39;s power at its most destructive.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"shaws-charisma\">Shaw&#39;s Charisma</h3>\n<p>Shaw is <strong>eloquent, genuinely charismatic, and capable of a self-effacement that makes his followers feel they are discovering truth for themselves</strong>. He does not preach at people. He does not demand conversion. He speaks, and what he says lands with the weight of something his listeners have always suspected but never heard articulated. His followers do not feel recruited. They feel recognized.</p>\n<p>This is what makes Shaw dangerous. A demagogue can be exposed. A fraud can be revealed. But Shaw may not be either. He may be exactly what he appears to be -- a man who has seen something true and cannot stop telling people about it. Whether that truth is divine, demonic, or merely the natural product of a brilliant mind operating in a broken world is the question that no one has answered.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"shaws-methods\">Shaw&#39;s Methods</h2>\n<p>Shaw <strong>moves</strong>. He appears, preaches, converts, and moves on before the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> can engage. He does not establish permanent facilities or visible infrastructure. He does not challenge the Temples directly. He arrives in a community, speaks to the people the Temples have failed, says something that sounds unbearably true, and leaves behind a community of poor people who feel that something real has been said about their lives.</p>\n<p>By the time the Temples learn he was there, he is gone. By the time they send a representative to assess the situation, the converts are already meeting, already praying, already organizing around the theology Shaw planted. The Congregation grows not through institutional machinery but through the propagation of an idea -- and ideas, once planted, are difficult to uproot.</p>\n<p>Shaw calls himself the <strong>Prophet of the True Dawn</strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-unease-of-the-thousand-temples\">The Unease of the Thousand Temples</h2>\n<p>What makes the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> uneasy about the Congregation is not merely its heterodox theology. Heterodoxy is common enough on the frontier, and the Temples have dealt with heretics before. What disturbs the institutional church is the <strong>undercurrent of suffering and purification language</strong> in Shaw&#39;s preaching.</p>\n<p>Shaw speaks of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pain</strong> -- not as affliction to be endured but as instrument of transformation. Pain purifies. Pain reveals. Pain strips away everything false and leaves only what is real.</li>\n<li><strong>Blood</strong> -- not as sacrifice in the Cthonic sense but as proof of commitment. To bleed for the Hollow Sun is to demonstrate the sincerity of your devotion in a way that words and wealth cannot match.</li>\n<li><strong>Being scraped clean</strong> -- the process of purification through which the believer is reduced to their essential self. The language is violent. The imagery is not comfortable.</li>\n<li><strong>Burning</strong> -- the fire that burns in silence, the flame that illuminates by consuming. Shaw&#39;s fire does not warm. It transforms, and transformation is not painless.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Congregation performs <strong>rites of physical endurance and ritual scarification</strong>. Whether these represent genuine asceticism -- the disciplined mortification of the flesh in pursuit of spiritual purity, a practice with precedent in legitimate Empyrean traditions -- or the beginning of something darker is an unanswered question.</p>\n<p>The line between asceticism and blood-cult is thin, and Shaw walks it with the confidence of someone who either does not see it or does not care.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"leadership\">Leadership</h2>\n<h3 id=\"ezekiel-shaw-cleric-6\">Ezekiel Shaw -- Cleric 6</h3>\n<p>The Congregation is led by <strong><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a></strong>, a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> Cleric 6 who serves as its founder, preacher, and spiritual authority.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Cleric 6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>2</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>30</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+3-(mace,-1d6+1)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>wis</strong></td>-<td>16</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>shaw-possesses-proficiencies-in-<strong>leadership</strong>,-<strong>prophecy</strong>,-and----most-troublingly----<strong>black-lore</strong>,-the-knowledge-of-dark-and-forbidden-traditions.-his-spells-include-<strong>bless</strong>,-<strong>hold-person</strong>,-and-<strong>cure-disease</strong>.</p>-<p>his-ability-to-heal-disease-alone-makes-him-one-of-the-most-valuable-individuals-in-the-[[the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, where disease is rampant and qualified healers are almost nonexistent. This gives him enormous leverage -- the grateful sick become the faithful, and the faithful become the Congregation.</p>\n<p>For Shaw&#39;s full statistics, spells, and detailed profile, see <strong><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a></strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-name-hollow-sun\">The Name: &quot;Hollow Sun&quot;</h2>\n<p>The name carries layered significance within Shaw&#39;s theology:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hollow</strong> -- The Sun as preached by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> is hollow because it has been emptied of its true content. The real Sun -- the Hollow Sun -- is the void that remains when the false light is stripped away. It is not empty. It is cleared. The hollowness is not absence but preparation.</li>\n<li><strong>Sun</strong> -- Shaw does not reject the solar imagery of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> worship. He claims it. The Hollow Sun is the true Sun, and what the Temples worship is its shadow. This appropriation of orthodox imagery makes the Congregation&#39;s theology difficult to combat -- Shaw speaks in the same language as the faith he opposes.</li>\n<li><strong>Congregation</strong> -- Not cult, not brotherhood, not cabal. A congregation: an assembly of ordinary faithful gathered around shared belief. The framing is deliberate and effective.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"threat-assessment\">Threat Assessment</h2>\n<p>The Congregation is classified as a <strong>long-term threat</strong> based on:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Growing membership</strong> from populations the Empire has failed -- refugee quarters, Scalper communities, marginalized Avari</li>\n<li><strong>Secretive operations</strong> that obscure the movement&#39;s true size and capabilities</li>\n<li><strong>Shaw&#39;s significant personal power</strong> -- Cleric 6 with combat capability and healing magic</li>\n<li><strong>Black Lore proficiency</strong> suggesting engagement with forbidden knowledge</li>\n<li><strong>Prophetic claims</strong> that may foretell an event the Congregation is working to bring about</li>\n<li><strong>The suffering/purification theology</strong> whose endpoint remains unclear -- asceticism or blood-cult</li>\n<li><strong>Shaw&#39;s mobility</strong> -- his ability to appear, convert, and vanish before institutions can respond</li>\n<li><strong>The genuine appeal of the message</strong> -- Shaw says things that sound true to people whose lives confirm them</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-other-faiths\">Relationship to Other Faiths</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> / <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></strong> -- Direct opposition. Shaw accuses the Thousand Temples of suppressing the truth about the Unconquered Sun. The Temples regard Shaw as a heretic at best, a Cthonic agent at worst.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a></strong> at the House of Silence in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> -- A priest of genuine faith who represents the orthodox tradition Shaw attacks. A potential flashpoint.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcos Varanes</a></strong> and the <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-bleak-sons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bleak Sons</a> -- Militant followers of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> whose fanatical devotion could drive direct confrontation with Shaw if they become aware of his activities.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></strong> -- The state religion. Shaw&#39;s theology exists in opposition to the institutional Empyrean, though his relationship to the underlying Empyrean tradition is more ambiguous.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Tradition</a></strong> -- Shaw&#39;s Black Lore proficiency and the suffering-oriented theology raise questions about Cthonic influence. Whether the Hollow Sun is an Empyrean heresy or a Cthonic deception disguised in solar language is unanswered.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The True Dawn</strong> -- Shaw calls himself Prophet of the True Dawn. What is the dawn he prophesies? A literal event? A spiritual transformation? Something worse?</li>\n<li><strong>The Scarification Rites</strong> -- What is the full extent of the Congregation&#39;s ritual practices? Where does asceticism end and something darker begin?</li>\n<li><strong>Infiltration</strong> -- Joining the Congregation risks falling under Shaw&#39;s magnetic influence, but it may be the only way to learn its true scope and goals.</li>\n<li><strong>Competing Faiths</strong> -- The Congregation, the House of Silence, and the Bleak Sons represent three radically different expressions of faith in the same region. Their intersection could produce theological debate, political maneuvering, or open violence.</li>\n<li><strong>The Hidden Light</strong> -- Shaw speaks of hidden light and silent flame. Is this metaphor, prophecy, or reference to a specific supernatural force?</li>\n<li><strong>Shaw&#39;s Madness</strong> -- Is Shaw truly mad, genuinely prophetic, or something more dangerous than either?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> -- The Prophet of the True Dawn</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The settlement where the Congregation operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier province where Shaw recruits</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- The Empyrean god whose worship Shaw challenges</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">thousand-temples</a> -- The institution Shaw accuses of suppressing truth</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> -- The orthodox priest; potential rival</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">marcos-varanes</a> -- The militant of Seros; potential confrontation</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The state religion Shaw opposes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The dark tradition that may influence Shaw&#39;s theology</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological crisis underlying Shaw&#39;s claims</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel-earth-hunger</a> -- Another heterodox religious tradition in Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a> -- Another practitioner operating outside orthodox frameworks</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The sacred tradition Shaw&#39;s Avari followers may still revere</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/wekko\" class=\"wiki-link\">wekko</a> -- Another prophetic figure; parallels with the Congregation</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"drussine-guard","title":"The Drussine Guard","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["faction","military","private-army","drussine-guard","sanctuary","citadel","governor-drussus","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-drussine-guard\">The Drussine Guard</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Drussine Guard</strong> is <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus&#39;s</a> personal army -- approximately <strong>2,000 soldiers</strong> stationed in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. It is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, and its loyalty is to the <strong>Governor personally</strong>, not to the city, the province, or the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Private military force / personal army</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Strength</strong></td>\n<td>~2,000 soldiers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Commander</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Skiothan</span> crisis). It is not the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a>. It is <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus&#39;s</a> <strong>private army</strong> -- a legal distinction that matters enormously in imperial politics and not at all in practice.</p>\n<p>In practice, the Drussine Guard is the dominant military force in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. With ~2,000 soldiers -- compared to <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> ~100 at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch&#39;s</a> ~600 -- the Guard outnumbers every other armed force in the province combined. It is better trained, better equipped, and better paid than any of them.</p>\n<p>The Guard serves multiple functions simultaneously:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Police force</strong> -- maintaining order in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, supplementing and often superseding the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a></li>\n<li><strong>Security apparatus</strong> -- protecting the Governor, the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Citadel</a>, and critical infrastructure</li>\n<li><strong>Garrison</strong> -- defending the city against external threats</li>\n<li><strong>Political insurance</strong> -- ensuring that no faction in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> can challenge the Governor&#39;s authority through force</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"recruitment-training\">Recruitment &amp; Training</h2>\n<p>Recruitment into the Drussine Guard is <strong>selective</strong>. Candidates are drawn from the professional military class -- veterans, career soldiers, and men with proven martial ability. But martial skill alone is not sufficient. Every recruit is <strong>screened for loyalty</strong> to the Governor.</p>\n<p>This screening is thorough. Family connections, personal history, political associations, and character are all evaluated. Men with divided loyalties -- to the Emperor, to other patrons, to ideological causes -- are quietly rejected. The Guard recruits soldiers who will follow the Governor&#39;s orders without hesitation, without question, and without regret.</p>\n<p>Training is rigorous and ongoing. The Guard drills regularly, maintains high standards of physical fitness, and practices formation fighting, urban combat, and counter-insurgency techniques. They are professional soldiers in every sense.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"pay-equipment\">Pay &amp; Equipment</h2>\n<p>Pay in the Drussine Guard is <strong>excellent</strong> -- significantly above the imperial standard for equivalent rank. This serves multiple purposes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It attracts the best available soldiers</li>\n<li>It creates economic dependence on the Governor (soldiers who leave the Guard take a significant pay cut)</li>\n<li>It reinforces loyalty (well-paid soldiers are less susceptible to bribery or recruitment by rivals)</li>\n<li>It generates gratitude and personal attachment to Drussus</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Equipment is the best available in the Backlands. The Guard is outfitted with quality arms, armor, and supplies. They look professional because they are professional, and the visual impression reinforces their authority.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"command-structure\">Command Structure</h2>\n<h3 id=\"colonel-marcian-vex-commander\">Colonel Marcian Vex -- Commander</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/colonel-vex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Colonel Marcian Vex</a></strong> commands the Drussine Guard. Fighter 9, he is <strong>loyal to <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussus</a> personally</strong> -- not merely professionally obedient but genuinely devoted to the Governor&#39;s cause. Vex is grim and efficient, a man who does not waste words, does not tolerate incompetence, and does not second-guess his orders.</p>\n<p>Vex was handpicked by Drussus for the command. His loyalty has been tested and proven over years of service. He is the mechanism through which the Governor&#39;s will becomes military action.</p>\n<p>Below Vex, the Guard operates through a standard military hierarchy:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Senior Officers</strong> -- Company and battalion commanders, responsible for specific sectors or functions</li>\n<li><strong>Junior Officers</strong> -- Platoon leaders and specialists</li>\n<li><strong>Non-Commissioned Officers</strong> -- Sergeants and corporals who manage day-to-day operations</li>\n<li><strong>Rank and file</strong> -- The soldiers themselves</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"deployment\">Deployment</h2>\n<p>The Drussine Guard maintains presence throughout <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Citadel</a></strong> -- Primary barracks and headquarters. The largest concentration of Guard forces. In an emergency, the Citadel can be sealed and held indefinitely.</li>\n<li><strong>Garrison posts throughout the city</strong> -- Guard stations in every district except the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a>, providing visible presence and rapid response capability</li>\n<li><strong>Gate posts</strong> -- Guard detachments at the city&#39;s major entrances</li>\n<li><strong>Escort details</strong> -- Protection for the Governor, senior officials, and important shipments</li>\n<li><strong>Patrol routes</strong> -- Regular patrols through all major districts</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Guard does <strong>not</strong> patrol the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a> refugee quarter. This is policy, not oversight -- the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> community polices itself, and Guard presence would provoke rather than stabilize.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-other-forces\">Relationship with Other Forces</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-city-watch\">The City Watch</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> (~600 strong) is the nominal municipal police force. In theory, the Watch handles civil law enforcement while the Guard handles military security. In practice, the Guard supersedes the Watch whenever it chooses. Watch officers know this and generally defer to Guard authority without resistance.</p>\n<p>The Watch is ostensibly independent but in practice answers to the Governor through the chain of command. It is a secondary force -- useful for routine policing but politically subordinate to the Guard in every way that matters.</p>\n<h3 id=\"legate-marcellus\">Legate Marcellus</h3>\n<p>The Drussine Guard&#39;s existence is one of the reasons <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> is so politically isolated. With ~100 soldiers under his command compared to the Guard&#39;s ~2,000, Marcellus cannot challenge the Governor&#39;s military supremacy. The Guard ensures that the only significant military power in the Backlands belongs to Drussus.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-laced-hand\">The Laced Hand</h3>\n<p>The Drussine Guard is the implicit threat that keeps the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> in line. <a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Castellan Thibaud</a> understands that if the Governor ever decides the criminal syndicate is more trouble than it is worth, the Guard will dismantle it. This knowledge shapes the Laced Hand&#39;s behavior -- they remain useful, profitable, and never provocative enough to warrant destruction.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"political-significance\">Political Significance</h2>\n<p>The Drussine Guard is the physical expression of <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus&#39;s</a> power. Its existence transforms him from a political appointee into a military strongman. Key implications:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Provincial autonomy</strong> -- With the imperial legions recalled to fight <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> incursions, the Guard is the only significant military force in the Backlands. This makes the Governor effectively autonomous.</li>\n<li><strong>Factional balance</strong> -- No other faction in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> can challenge the Governor through force. The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Consortium</a> must compete through politics, economics, and influence -- domains where the Governor also excels.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperial tension</strong> -- A provincial governor maintaining a 2,000-strong personal army is, at minimum, unusual. Whether the Emperor is aware, concerned, or simply too occupied with the Skiothan wars to act is unknown.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gm-notes\">GM Notes</h2>\n<p>The Drussine Guard should be played as a <strong>professional, efficient, and intimidating</strong> military force. Key principles:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>They are not bullies.</strong> They do not harass civilians for sport. They enforce the Governor&#39;s will with the minimum force necessary -- but they will use maximum force if required, without hesitation.</li>\n<li><strong>They are everywhere.</strong> PCs operating in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> will encounter Guard patrols, guard posts, and Guard checkpoints regularly. The Guard&#39;s presence is a constant reminder of who holds power.</li>\n<li><strong>They are loyal.</strong> Attempts to bribe, subvert, or recruit individual Guard members will almost always fail. The screening process and the excellent pay ensure that most soldiers are genuinely committed.</li>\n<li><strong>They are the ceiling.</strong> The Guard represents the upper limit of what force can accomplish in Sanctuary without the Governor&#39;s approval. Any plan that involves fighting the Guard is a plan that involves fighting 2,000 professional soldiers and the full weight of the Governor&#39;s apparatus.</li>\n<li><strong>Colonel Vex is the face of the Guard.</strong> Interactions with Guard leadership go through Vex, and Vex is not interested in negotiations, excuses, or appeals. He follows orders.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- patron and commander-in-chief</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/colonel-vex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Colonel Marcian Vex</a> -- Guard commander</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city they garrison</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Citadel</a> -- headquarters</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> -- subordinate civil police force</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> -- military rival at Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a> -- criminal syndicate kept in line by Guard presence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- the province</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"house-aurel","title":"House Aurel","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["great-house","conservative","thousand-temples","empyrean-faith","religious-orthodoxy","politics"],"html":"<h1 id=\"house-aurel\">House Aurel</h1>\n<p><strong>House Aurel</strong> is the most doctrinally conservative of the Great Houses. The Aurels maintain deep and longstanding ties to the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>, promoting cultural purity, religious orthodoxy, and the divine authority of the Emperor. They view the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> not merely as law but as sacred revelation, and they regard any deviation from tradition as heresy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Empyrean Faith</span>. Where other houses treat religion as one element of political life among many, the Aurels view it as the foundation of all legitimate authority. Their core convictions include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> as sacred revelation</strong> -- Not merely a legal code or moral framework, but the direct word of the divine, to be followed without compromise or reinterpretation</li>\n<li><strong>Divine authority of the Emperor</strong> -- The Emperor rules by divine mandate. His authority is not merely political but spiritual, granted by the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a> through the institutions of the faith</li>\n<li><strong>Cultural purity</strong> -- The traditions, customs, and practices of the Mithrian people are sacred and must be preserved against foreign contamination, cosmopolitan dilution, and heretical innovation</li>\n<li><strong>Religious orthodoxy</strong> -- The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> are the guardians of spiritual truth, and their authority in matters of faith is absolute</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"influence\">Influence</h2>\n<p>The house&#39;s influence is strongest among three constituencies:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The priesthood</strong> -- House Aurel&#39;s deep ties to the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> give them unparalleled access to the Empire&#39;s religious hierarchy. Aurel-aligned priests serve in temples across the Empire, and the house&#39;s patronage supports seminaries, shrines, and religious institutions.</li>\n<li><strong>The rural aristocracy</strong> -- Provincial nobles who view the capital&#39;s cosmopolitanism with suspicion find in House Aurel a champion of traditional values and hierarchies.</li>\n<li><strong>Traditional military families</strong> -- Officers and soldiers who see the Empire as a divinely ordained institution, not merely a political entity, are naturally drawn to the Aurel worldview.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"rivalries\">Rivalries</h2>\n<p>House Aurel is frequently at odds with the more cosmopolitan houses:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-malventi\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Malventi</a></strong> -- The Aurels view the Malventi as morally compromised and dangerously cosmopolitan. The Malventi&#39;s foreign trade connections, rumored involvement in the slave trade, and indifference to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> are anathema to everything the Aurels stand for.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a></strong> -- The Kalomenes&#39; procedural gamesmanship and institutional manipulation strike the Aurels as a perversion of the sacred order. The Aurels believe in hierarchy, duty, and obedience -- not loopholes and legal technicalities.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Conversely, House Aurel generally supports <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a>&#39;s hold on the throne, provided the Emperor continues to uphold the faith and its institutions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a> -- religious institution deeply tied to House Aurel</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean Faith</a> -- the faith House Aurel champions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a> -- the sacred texts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Great Houses</a> -- overview of all noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-malventi\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Malventi</a> -- ideological opponents</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a> -- political rivals</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Burnished Scale</a> -- militant arm of the Temples</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"house-decimus","title":"House Decimus","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["great-house","ruling-house","imperial-throne","politics","mithra-city","imperial-talons"],"html":"<h1 id=\"house-decimus\">House Decimus</h1>\n<p><strong>House Decimus</strong> is the ruling house of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, the most powerful of the Great Houses by virtue of holding the Imperial throne itself. The house secured its dominance during the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> in 270 IY, when <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> emerged victorious from the brutal civil war that followed the assassination of the mad Emperor <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a>. Since that time, the Decimus line has held the Imperial seat without interruption.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td>Emperor <span class=\"dead-link\">Aurex</span> of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>. Aurex&#39;s madness and cruelty had brought the Empire to the brink of collapse, and when his own sister killed him -- leaving no heir -- the resulting power vacuum plunged the Empire into civil war.</p>\n<p>The scholar-emperor <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Numerius</a> was briefly installed on the throne but was murdered after only 87 days. Generals and governors vied for supremacy. From this crucible, <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> emerged triumphant, founding the dynasty that rules to this day.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-succession-crisis\">The Succession Crisis</h3>\n<p>The succession of House Decimus has not always been smooth. <strong>Julian Decimus</strong>, a previous Emperor, named his son <strong>Diometian</strong> as heir -- a decision that triggered civil war when rival claimants and discontented houses refused to accept the appointment. The resulting conflict reshaped the political order of the Empire and demonstrated that even the ruling house is not immune to the factional violence that defines Mithrian politics.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"power-and-influence\">Power and Influence</h2>\n<p>House Decimus enforces its will through the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a>, an elite cadre of spies, informants, and assassins who serve the Emperor directly. The Talons operate outside normal Imperial law and are feared throughout the Empire as instruments of the throne&#39;s displeasure. Their existence is an open secret among the imperial elite -- their reputation alone serves as a deterrent against those who would move against the ruling house.</p>\n<p>Beyond the Talons, House Decimus commands the full apparatus of imperial governance: the legions, the bureaucracy, the treasury, and the legal authority of the throne. The Emperor&#39;s word is law, and while the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> retains deliberative power, it has been stripped of binding legislative authority since <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> founded the Empire in 1 IY.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-status\">Current Status</h2>\n<p>Emperor <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> firmly holds the Empire in his grasp. In 378 IY, he recalled armies from the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> to face the Skiothan threat on the western frontier -- a strategic decision that left the frontier provinces undermanned and contributed to the current lawlessness of the Backlands. Following the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> in 377 IY, the Emperor issued an Imperial Bounty on beastmen, unleashing a wave of mercenaries and killers into the frontier provinces.</p>\n<p>The Decimus dynasty faces threats on multiple fronts: <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> in the Backlands, Skiothan raiders to the west, lingering unrest in Morn, and the ever-present political maneuvering of rival Great Houses. The question that haunts the Empire is whether the Decimus line can hold what <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> won -- or whether the patterns of decline that destroyed the Valerian dynasty will repeat themselves.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a></strong> -- The house whose throne the Decimus line took. Relations are defined by the Valerians&#39; smoldering resentment and persistent rumors of restoration schemes.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a></strong> -- Wields tremendous institutional power and has never truly accepted subordination to any ruling house.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-severian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Severian</a></strong> -- Enigmatic and difficult to read. The Talons cannot fully penetrate their networks, which makes them a persistent concern.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Aurel</a></strong> -- Aligned with the throne on matters of tradition and divine authority, but their deep ties to the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> give them an independent power base.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a></strong> -- Newest Great House. Close ties to the legions make them a potential ally or a potential threat.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-malventi\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Malventi</a></strong> -- Foreign connections make them invaluable but invite suspicion of disloyalty.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> -- current Emperor and patriarch</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> -- founder of the dynasty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Talons</a> -- elite spies and assassins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> -- the civil war that brought House Decimus to power</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a> -- the mad Emperor whose assassination created the power vacuum</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Great Houses</a> -- overview of all noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"house-drussus","title":"House Drussus","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["great-house","military","newest-house","backlands","sanctuary","drussine-guard","politics"],"html":"<h1 id=\"house-drussus\">House Drussus</h1>\n<p><strong>House Drussus</strong> is the youngest of the Great Houses, having risen to prominence through the battlefield accomplishments of its founder and current patriarch, <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Valerios Drussus</a>. The house was built on military excellence rather than inherited from a lineage of power. House Drussus maintains close ties to the Imperial legions and is widely seen as the house of soldiers. Their rise is resented by older houses who view them as upstarts, but the Drussus name commands genuine respect among the officer corps and the common soldiery.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Valerios Drussus</span> made his name as a competent and aggressive general, earning glory and wealth in the Empire&#39;s many frontier campaigns. He was not born to the purple -- he built his house from nothing, parlaying military success into political capital with a precision that made older houses nervous.</p>\n<p>The house has since leveraged military wealth and reputation into broader political power. Strategic marriages, acquisition of merchant houses and estates, and the systematic placement of loyalists throughout the provincial bureaucracy have given House Drussus a power base that extends far beyond the battlefield.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-backlands\">The Backlands</h2>\n<p>Governor Drussus was appointed to the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> in 365 IY -- a posting initially seen as semi-exile. Whether he accepted it willingly or was maneuvered into it is unknown. What is certain is that he has made the most of it. Over fifteen years, he has executed a systematic consolidation of power in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> that includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Personal command of the <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a>, approximately 2,000 soldiers loyal to him personally</li>\n<li>Control over the City Watch (~600 strong)</li>\n<li>Strategic marriages binding merchant families and minor nobility to House Drussus</li>\n<li>Steady acquisition of economic assets throughout the province</li>\n<li>Gradual placement of loyalists throughout the bureaucracy</li>\n<li>A tacit arrangement with the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> criminal syndicate</li>\n</ul>\n<p>His personal wealth now competes with the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>. His control over the bureaucracy is absolute. The Drussine Guard is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the Backlands.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"reputation-among-the-great-houses\">Reputation Among the Great Houses</h2>\n<p>The older houses -- <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Valerian</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kalomenes</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurel</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-severian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severian</a> -- view House Drussus with varying degrees of contempt, wariness, and grudging respect. The Drussus name carries no ancient lineage, no storied ancestors, no centuries of accumulated prestige. What it carries is the loyalty of soldiers, the wealth of a province, and the ruthless competence of its patriarch.</p>\n<p>Whether House Drussus will endure beyond its founder -- whether it can establish the institutional depth and dynastic continuity that defines a true Great House -- remains to be seen.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- patriarch and founder</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/colonel-vex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Colonel Marcian Vex</a> -- Drussine Guard commander</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Drussine Guard</a> -- the Governor&#39;s personal army</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- provincial capital and seat of power</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Citadel</a> -- Governor&#39;s fortress-seat</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- the province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Great Houses</a> -- overview of all noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a> -- criminal syndicate with tacit arrangement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> -- commercial rival/ally</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"house-kalomenes","title":"House Kalomenes","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["great-house","politics","mithrian-league","imperial-senate","patronage","institutional-power"],"html":"<h1 id=\"house-kalomenes\">House Kalomenes</h1>\n<p><strong>House Kalomenes</strong> was once the most powerful house in the old <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a>, wielding unrivaled influence in the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> before the rise of the Empire. When <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> declared himself Emperor in 1 IY, the Kalomenes were among those defeated and forced to bend the knee. The house has never forgotten this humiliation, nor has it ever truly accepted subordination.</p>\n<p>Today, House Kalomenes commands tremendous power in the courts and political institutions of the Empire. Where other houses wield swords, the Kalomenes wield patronage, precedent, and procedural manipulation with lethal precision.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrian League</span> -- the confederation of free city-states that preceded the Empire -- House Kalomenes was the dominant political force. They controlled the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Senate</a>, shaped legislation, and wielded the kind of institutional power that made them effectively the rulers of the League in all but name.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-humiliation\">The Humiliation</h3>\n<p>When <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> seized power and declared himself the first Emperor, the Kalomenes were among the houses that resisted. They raised armies, marshaled their allies, and fought to preserve the old order. They lost. Defeated on the battlefield, House Kalomenes was forced to bend the knee to the new Emperor -- a humiliation that has defined the house&#39;s character and ambitions for centuries.</p>\n<p>The Kalomenes have never forgotten. Every subsequent generation has been raised with the memory of what was lost and the conviction that the current order is illegitimate -- or, at the very least, that the Kalomenes&#39; rightful place is far higher than any Emperor has been willing to grant.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"power-and-methods\">Power and Methods</h2>\n<p>House Kalomenes does not rely on military force or direct confrontation. Their power lies in the Empire&#39;s institutions themselves:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Patronage networks</strong> -- The house sponsors dozens of tributary houses, creating a web of obligation and loyalty that extends across the Empire</li>\n<li><strong>Legal and procedural expertise</strong> -- Kalomenes lawyers, advocates, and political operatives are the most skilled in the Empire. They can delay, obstruct, or redirect imperial policy through the courts and the Senate with devastating effectiveness</li>\n<li><strong>Institutional memory</strong> -- The house maintains archives and precedent records that give them an encyclopedic knowledge of imperial law, senatorial procedure, and bureaucratic process. They know every loophole, every exception, every obscure ruling that can be weaponized</li>\n<li><strong>Client networks</strong> -- An extensive network of clients, operatives, and informants embedded throughout the imperial bureaucracy</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Kalomenes do not need to overthrow the Emperor. They can accomplish their goals by making governance impossible without their cooperation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a></strong> -- The ruling house. The Kalomenes accept the throne&#39;s authority publicly while undermining it institutionally whenever their interests require.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a></strong> -- Both houses share the experience of having been displaced by imperial power, though the Kalomenes lost their position to the Valerians&#39; ancestor in the first place. The dynamic is complex.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-malventi\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Malventi</a></strong> -- The Kalomenes&#39; institutional conservatism sometimes clashes with Malventi cosmopolitanism, though both houses are pragmatic enough to cooperate when interests align.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Aurel</a></strong> -- Frequently at odds. The Aurels view the Kalomenes&#39; procedural games as undermining the sacred order of the Empire.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Great Houses</a> -- overview of all noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> -- the Emperor who defeated them</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Senate</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> -- the ruling house</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"house-malventi","title":"House Malventi","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["great-house","commerce","trade","massaran-kingdoms","urgathoa","foreign-connections","politics"],"html":"<h1 id=\"house-malventi\">House Malventi</h1>\n<p><strong>House Malventi</strong> derives its power from commerce, particularly trade connections that extend far beyond the borders of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. The house maintains deep ties to the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Kingdoms</a> and <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoa</a>, trafficking in exotic goods, rare materials, and -- by persistent and credible rumor -- slaves. The Malventi are cosmopolitan, pragmatic, and largely indifferent to the ideological concerns that animate other houses.</p>\n<p>Their foreign connections make them invaluable as intermediaries and intelligence sources, but also invite suspicion of disloyalty. Many in the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> view the Malventi as dangerously unpatriotic, more loyal to profit than to the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Massaran Kingdoms</span></strong> -- The remnants of the old Massaran Empire that was overthrown in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a>. Most Mithrians view the Massaran successor states with deep distrust. The Malventi view them as customers.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoa</a></strong> -- A distant and poorly understood power. Malventi traders are among the few Mithrians who maintain regular contact with Urgathoan merchants and officials.</li>\n<li><strong>Exotic goods and rare materials</strong> -- The Malventi traffic in substances, artifacts, and commodities that cannot be obtained within the Empire&#39;s borders. This trade is enormously profitable and gives the house access to resources that other houses cannot match.</li>\n<li><strong>Slaves</strong> -- The most damaging accusation leveled against House Malventi is their alleged involvement in the slave trade. The house neither confirms nor denies these rumors, which persist because the Malventi&#39;s trading partners in the Massaran Kingdoms and Urgathoa are known to practice slavery openly.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character-and-philosophy\">Character and Philosophy</h2>\n<p>The Malventi are defined by pragmatism. They do not care about bloodlines, traditions, or theological disputes except insofar as these things affect commerce. They are cosmopolitan in outlook, comfortable dealing with foreigners, and deeply skeptical of the ideological rigidity that characterizes houses like <a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Aurel</a>.</p>\n<p>This pragmatism makes them effective negotiators, reliable trading partners, and valuable intelligence sources. It also makes them deeply suspect in the eyes of those who believe that loyalty to the Empire and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> should take precedence over profit.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Aurel</a></strong> -- Frequent antagonists. The Aurels view the Malventi as morally compromised and dangerously cosmopolitan. The Malventi view the Aurels as provincial zealots.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a></strong> -- Both houses are pragmatic enough to cooperate when interests align, despite their very different approaches to power.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a></strong> -- The ruling house values Malventi intelligence and commercial connections while distrusting their foreign loyalties.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-severian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Severian</a></strong> -- Both houses operate in shadows and trade in information. The relationship is opaque.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Great Houses</a> -- overview of all noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean War</a> -- the war that overthrew the Massaran Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Aurel</a> -- ideological opponents</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"house-severian","title":"House Severian","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["great-house","ancient","enigmatic","eladra","shadow-politics","secrets","politics"],"html":"<h1 id=\"house-severian\">House Severian</h1>\n<p><strong>House Severian</strong> is among the oldest houses in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, yet also the most enigmatic. The Severians operate through hidden channels, preferring shadow influence to open political contest. Their true wealth and the full extent of their networks are unknown even to the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a>. Persistent rumors hold that the Severian bloodline carries <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> ancestry -- a claim that, if true, would link the house to the ancient <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> and its arcane legacy. The Severians neither confirm nor deny these rumors, and their occasional displays of uncanny insight and influence do nothing to dispel them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">house-severian</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Distinction</strong></td>\n<td>Ancient, secretive, rumored [[Eladra</span> blood</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Power Base</strong></td>\n<td>Hidden networks, shadow influence, unknown wealth</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Approach</strong></td>\n<td>Operates through hidden channels; avoids open political contest</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"mystery-and-reputation\">Mystery and Reputation</h2>\n<p>House Severian is defined by what is not known about them. Other Great Houses -- even those that operate through intrigue and maneuvering -- maintain visible power structures: estates, armies, patronage networks, tributary houses. The Severians maintain all of these, but their true assets are hidden. Their wealth cannot be accurately assessed. Their agents cannot be reliably identified. Their goals cannot be confidently predicted.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a> -- the Emperor&#39;s own spies and assassins -- have been unable to fully penetrate Severian networks. This fact alone speaks volumes. The Talons are the most feared intelligence apparatus in the Empire, and their inability to map the Severian organization suggests either extraordinary operational security or resources that exceed what any noble house should possess.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-eladra-question\">The Eladra Question</h2>\n<p>The most persistent and troubling rumor about House Severian concerns their bloodline. Whispers have circulated for centuries that the Severians carry <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> ancestry -- that somewhere in their family tree, the blood of the ancient <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>&#39;s foremost scholars and sorcerers was introduced.</p>\n<p>If true, this would be a matter of enormous significance. The Eladra were the architects of Argollean civilization, the discoverers of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, and the builders of wonders that have never been equaled. Their transformation into the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> -- corrupted by <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> power into something no longer human -- was one of the defining tragedies of Mithrapos&#39;s history. Eladra blood in a Great House would raise questions about arcane ability, longevity, and loyalties that no amount of political maneuvering could answer.</p>\n<p>The Severians neither confirm nor deny these rumors. Their occasional displays of uncanny insight -- knowing things they should not know, predicting events before they unfold, moving with a precision that suggests foreknowledge -- do nothing to put the whispers to rest.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"political-position\">Political Position</h2>\n<p>House Severian does not compete openly for political power. They do not sponsor legislation, they do not make public alliances, and they do not engage in the theatrical rivalries that define relationships between other Great Houses. Instead, they influence events from the shadows -- a word here, a favor there, a piece of information delivered at precisely the right moment to precisely the right person.</p>\n<p>This makes them difficult to oppose, difficult to ally with, and difficult to trust. Other houses deal with the Severians cautiously, aware that any interaction may be only the visible surface of a much deeper game.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a></strong> -- The ruling house views the Severians with wariness. The Talons&#39; inability to penetrate their networks is a source of ongoing concern.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a></strong> -- Both ancient houses, both diminished from former heights, but in very different ways. The Valerians lost their throne openly; the Severians&#39; losses -- if any -- are invisible.</li>\n<li><strong>All other houses</strong> -- Treat the Severians with caution. No house can confidently claim to understand Severian motivations or to predict their actions.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Great Houses</a> -- overview of all noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Talons</a> -- unable to fully penetrate Severian networks</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> -- the ancient race whose blood the Severians may carry</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Races and Cultures of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"house-valerian","title":"House Valerian","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["great-house","ancient-lineage","bellasarius","politics","prestigious-bloodline"],"html":"<h1 id=\"house-valerian\">House Valerian</h1>\n<p><strong>House Valerian</strong> possesses the most prestigious bloodline in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, claiming direct descent from <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> -- the legendary general who, alongside the prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a>, overthrew the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> (663 BE). For centuries, the Valerians held the Imperial throne as a near-birthright. Today, the house retains immense prestige and wealth but lacks the political muscle to reclaim the throne -- though many believe the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</span> was the war-chief who fought alongside the <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> to overthrow the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its sorcerer-kings in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a>. His descendant <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> seized power in 1 IY, declaring himself the first Emperor of <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra</a> and founding the imperial dynasty. For centuries thereafter, the Valerian name was synonymous with the throne.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-decline\">The Decline</h3>\n<p>The house&#39;s fortunes declined after a succession of poor Emperors who squandered the legacy of their ancestors. This trajectory of decay culminated in the reign of <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a>, whose madness and cruelty brought the Empire to the very brink of destruction. Aurex was assassinated by his own sister, an act of desperate necessity that left no heir and ended the Valerian dynasty&#39;s hold on power forever.</p>\n<p>The ensuing chaos -- the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> (270 IY) -- saw <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> triumph in the civil war and establish <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> as the new ruling dynasty. The Valerian claim to the throne was permanently broken.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-standing\">Current Standing</h2>\n<p>House Valerian retains enormous wealth and the prestige of its ancient name. The Valerian bloodline is still regarded with reverence by traditionalists, historians, and those who remember that the Empire was built by Valerian hands. However, the house lacks the political muscle, military power, and institutional leverage to challenge <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> directly.</p>\n<p>Many believe -- and many fear -- that the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration. Whether this is true or merely the paranoia of rival houses is impossible to say with certainty. The Valerians maintain their dignity, their wealth, and their silence on the subject.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"notable-members\">Notable Members</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Basilios Valerian</a></strong> -- Current patriarch of the house</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</a></strong> -- Military commander of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> and commanding officer of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>. A career soldier of the Valerian line, now isolated at the frontier by <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a>&#39;s political containment.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a></strong> -- Legendary founder and ancestor (deceased)</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a></strong> -- First Emperor (deceased)</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a></strong> -- The mad Emperor whose assassination ended the dynasty (deceased)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a></strong> -- The house that took the throne from them. The relationship is defined by Valerian resentment and Decimus wariness.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a></strong> -- Both houses share a history of having been displaced. The Kalomenes lost power when Marcus Valerian declared himself Emperor; the dynamic between these two ancient houses is complex.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Aurel</a></strong> -- Traditionalists who respect the Valerian bloodline but support the divine authority of whoever holds the throne.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian / Bellasarius Valerian</a> -- founder and first Emperor</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a> -- the mad Emperor who ended the dynasty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</a> -- prominent living member</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> -- the civil war that ended Valerian rule</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean War</a> -- the war that made the Valerian name</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> -- the ruling house that replaced them</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Great Houses</a> -- overview of all noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"imperial-academy","title":"The Imperial Academy","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["imperial-academy","sorcery","gnostic-geometry","mithrian-empire","archmages","seekers","primarch","mithra-city"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-imperial-academy\">The Imperial Academy</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;The Emperor rules the world of men, but the Academy governs what is possible within it.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Archmage Thoss</strong>, <em>On the Bounds of Sovereignty</em>, banned in three provinces</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Imperial Academy is the official state-sanctioned seat of sorcerous learning within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. It is both a prestigious university of learning and a political power in its own right, operating outside the traditional structure of Imperial ministries. The Academy answers nominally to the Emperor, but in practice it exercises a degree of autonomy that few other institutions within the Empire can match. Its influence extends into military strategy, state policy, provincial governance, and the regulation of all sorcerous activity across the Empire&#39;s vast territories.</p>\n<p>The Academy is a pillar of imperial stability and ambition, but also a hotbed of secrecy, rivalry, and experimentation. Behind its alabaster walls, Archmages pursue research both sanctioned and clandestine, political factions maneuver for influence, and the boundaries of what is possible are tested -- sometimes in defiance of the Academy&#39;s own stated prohibitions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"location-and-architecture\">Location and Architecture</h2>\n<p>The Imperial Academy is located in <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, the capital of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Its towering spires are the highest structures within the city, able to be seen from leagues away -- a deliberate architectural statement of the Academy&#39;s power, prestige, and ambition. The spires serve both practical and symbolic purposes: their height aids in certain sorcerous observations and experiments, while their visibility from such great distance ensures that every citizen of Mithra City lives within sight of the Academy&#39;s dominion.</p>\n<p>The Academy&#39;s grounds are extensive, encompassing lecture halls, libraries, laboratories, dormitories, administrative chambers, and the private quarters of the Archmages. The walls are of alabaster, and the overall impression is one of austere, forbidding magnificence.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"governance-and-leadership\">Governance and Leadership</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-conclave-of-archmages\">The Conclave of Archmages</h3>\n<p>A conclave of <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Archmages</a> forms the ruling council of the Academy. Appointment to the conclave is a lifelong position, decided by the Emperor himself. This makes each seat on the council a matter of intense political significance -- not only within the Academy but within the broader Imperial power structure. The Emperor&#39;s ability to appoint Archmages gives the throne a measure of control over the Academy, while the lifelong nature of the appointment ensures that individual Archmages can accumulate considerable independent power over the course of their tenure.</p>\n<p>The conclave deliberates on matters of curriculum, research policy, institutional governance, and the Academy&#39;s relationship with the Imperial state. Decisions are reached through a combination of formal voting, factional negotiation, and -- according to persistent rumor -- sorcerous coercion.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-primarch\">The Primarch</h3>\n<p>Every seven years, the conclave will vote on one of their members to become the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Primarch</a>. The Primarch serves as a figurehead of some executive power within the Academy and holds the position of direct advisor to the Emperor. The Primarch is the public face of the Academy, representing it in state ceremonies, Imperial councils, and diplomatic negotiations. While the Primarch&#39;s executive authority within the Academy is formally limited -- they are first among equals, not an absolute ruler -- the combination of institutional prestige and direct access to the Emperor gives the Primarch considerable informal power.</p>\n<p>The seven-year election cycle ensures a degree of turnover in the Academy&#39;s leadership while the lifelong nature of the Archmages&#39; appointments provides institutional continuity. The tension between these two principles -- change and stability -- is a defining feature of the Academy&#39;s internal politics.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-seekers\">The Seekers</h2>\n<p>Citizens of the Empire hold the Academy in fear and contempt, and much of this animosity is directed at the Academy&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seekers</a>. The Seekers are agents of the Academy who prowl the provinces, searching for those who possess the power of sorcery. They travel the length and breadth of the Empire, testing children and young adults for sorcerous aptitude. When talent is discovered, enrollment is not optional -- the individual is taken to the Academy whether they or their family consent or not.</p>\n<p>If a family cannot afford the pricey tuition required for formal enrollment, the Seekers will enslave the future student, designating them as a <strong><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">servus</a></strong> -- a bonded servant of the Academy. The servus serves in this capacity until such a time that they can pay their tuition through service. This practice, while entirely legal under Imperial law, is deeply resented by the common people. Parents dread the arrival of Seekers in their communities, and stories of families hiding talented children or fleeing their homes to avoid the Seekers are common throughout the provinces.</p>\n<p>Despite the cruelty of the system, the Academy is fond of pointing out that some of its most powerful and distinguished graduates rose from the ranks of the servus. These individuals, born into poverty and enslaved by the institution that would educate them, ascended through sheer talent, determination, and ruthlessness to become some of the most powerful High Mages to ever live. The Academy cites these examples as proof that the system is meritocratic at its core -- a claim that its critics regard with considerable skepticism.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"sorcerous-tradition\">Sorcerous Tradition</h2>\n<p>The Academy teaches and practices a form of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">geometric gnostic sorcery</a>, rooted in the ancient formulae of the <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a> -- the Argollean grimoire recovered by the <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> along with the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>. This tradition holds that sorcery is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout reality -- a structured, lawful cosmos established by the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>.</p>\n<p>The formulae and incantations of gnostic geometry are difficult to master, requiring years of rigorous study, intense mental discipline, and precise execution. However, the power they confer is much greater than that available to a hedge-mage or warlock working outside the Academy&#39;s traditions. Academy-trained sorcerers can achieve feats of destruction, construction, divination, and transmutation that are simply beyond the reach of self-taught practitioners.</p>\n<h3 id=\"prohibited-disciplines\">Prohibited Disciplines</h3>\n<p>Other forms of sorcery are strictly prohibited by the Academy. The following disciplines are expressly forbidden, and their practice is punishable by death:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Necromancy</strong> -- the animation, summoning, or manipulation of the dead</li>\n<li><strong>Transmogrification</strong> -- the fundamental alteration of living flesh, including self-modification</li>\n<li><strong>Demon-binding</strong> -- the summoning, communication with, or enslavement of entities from the <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a></li>\n</ul>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;The Scale may weigh the soul, but it is the Academy that defines what a soul can be.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Magistrate Verna Astell</strong>, executed for practicing forbidden transmogrification rituals</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The fate of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magistrate Verna Astell</a> serves as a stark reminder of the consequences of violating the Academy&#39;s prohibitions. Astell, a magistrate of some standing, was discovered to have been conducting transmogrification experiments -- altering living flesh in ways the Academy deemed an abomination. She was arrested, tried before the conclave, and executed. Her final words, quoted above, are frequently cited by critics of the Academy as evidence that the institution&#39;s true concern is not the protection of the public but the preservation of its own monopoly on power.</p>\n<h3 id=\"clandestine-research\">Clandestine Research</h3>\n<p>Despite the severity of these prohibitions, rumors persist of clandestine research conducted within the Academy&#39;s deepest laboratories -- experiments that push against or outright violate the Academy&#39;s own stated rules. The nature of this research is unknown to outsiders, but whispered speculation includes forbidden transmogrification, communication with entities from the Beyond, and experiments with necromantic energy. Whether these rumors reflect reality or are merely the product of public suspicion and the Academy&#39;s culture of secrecy is impossible to determine from the outside.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-academy-and-warfare\">The Academy and Warfare</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> once held a near-monopoly on sorcery, and the Imperial Academy was the instrument of that monopoly. For centuries, the Academy&#39;s trained battle-mages ensured Mithrian battlefield dominance, their geometric sorcery capable of devastating enemy formations, shattering fortifications, and deciding the outcome of entire wars. No rival power could field sorcerers of comparable skill or power, and this advantage was a cornerstone of Imperial military strategy.</p>\n<p>Over time, however, the destructive powers of mages have proliferated beyond the Academy&#39;s control. Hedge-mages, warlocks, and sorcerers trained in rival traditions have appeared in increasing numbers among the Empire&#39;s enemies. The Academy&#39;s monopoly has eroded, and with it the Empire&#39;s guaranteed battlefield superiority.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-battle-of-blue-mound-360-368-iy\">The Battle of Blue Mound (360--368 IY)</h3>\n<p>The consequences of uncontrolled sorcerous warfare were demonstrated with devastating finality at the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> (360--368 IY). The conflict pitted Imperial forces led by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a>, one of the Academy&#39;s most powerful battle-mages, against the army of <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a>, a sorcerer of formidable power operating outside any institutional framework.</p>\n<p>The war dragged on for eight years before culminating in a direct sorcerous duel between Cynar and Jarn Murky-Eye. The duel escalated beyond all control, unleashing cataclysmic energies that annihilated both armies entirely and left the battlefield a blasted wasteland. Neither combatant survived.</p>\n<p>The Battle of Blue Mound prompted significant reforms in how the Empire deploys its mages in combat. The model of the singular, all-powerful battle-mage was abandoned in favor of <strong>combined arms tactics</strong> -- integrating squad mages into conventional military formations, where their sorcery supplements rather than replaces conventional weapons and tactics.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-death-of-usil-348-iy\">The Death of Usil (348 IY)</h3>\n<p>The Academy&#39;s role as the Empire&#39;s foremost authority on metaphysical matters was tested by the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Death of Usil</a> in 348 IY, when violent earthquakes and storms of unprecedented ferocity struck across <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. The Academy attributed the catastrophe to &quot;fluctuations in the gnostic patterns that govern the metaphysical reality of Mithrapos&quot; -- a scientific explanation consistent with their understanding of the axioms that underpin reality.</p>\n<p>The priests of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faiths offered a competing explanation: an Empyrean god -- <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Usil</a> -- had died, and the cosmic upheaval was the consequence of that divine death. The Academy rejected this interpretation but could not disprove it, and the event became a defining moment in the ongoing rivalry between sorcerous and religious authority within the Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"kolani-munitions\">Kolani Munitions</h3>\n<p>The peace treaty that ended the <a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a> included a provision that further diminished the Academy&#39;s exclusive military importance: the Empire gained access to <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, providing Imperial commanders with destructive capabilities that do not depend on the Academy&#39;s sorcerers. This development has been a source of quiet resentment within the Academy, which views the adoption of non-sorcerous weapons technology as a diminishment of its institutional importance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"public-perception\">Public Perception</h2>\n<p>The Academy occupies an ambivalent position in the public imagination of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. It is respected for its power and feared for its authority, but it is also resented for its arrogance, its secrecy, and the predatory practices of its <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seekers</a>. Common citizens regard the Academy as a necessary evil at best -- an institution that provides the Empire with essential sorcerous capability while extracting a heavy toll in freedom, dignity, and trust.</p>\n<p>The Academy&#39;s critics -- and they are numerous, though few dare to speak openly -- accuse it of hoarding knowledge, suppressing rival traditions, enslaving the talented, and conducting forbidden research in defiance of its own rules. Its defenders counter that without the Academy&#39;s discipline and control, sorcery would be an unregulated catastrophe, as dangerous to its practitioners and bystanders as to any enemy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Archmages</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Primarch</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seekers</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Death of Usil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magistrate Verna Astell</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"imperial-senate","title":"The Imperial Senate","category":"factions","status":"active","tags":["faction","political","mithrian-league","senate","governance","performative","hereditary","patronage","imperial"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-imperial-senate\">The Imperial Senate</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The Senate is where speeches are given, petitions are heard, and nothing is decided. It is a theater of governance -- the costumes are magnificent, the performances are impassioned, and the audience left long ago.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Imperial Senate</strong> is a remnant of the old <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a> governing body. Once a powerful institution with genuine legislative and executive authority, the Senate has declined into a largely performative body -- a forum for speeches, petitions, and political theater that retains the trappings of power without its substance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Legislative/advisory body (nominal)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Active, but largely performative</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Origin</strong></td>\n<td>Remnant of the old <span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrian Empire&#39;s</span> political structure -- it is an institution that everyone acknowledges, many attend, and no one obeys. Its origins in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a> gave it genuine authority in an earlier age, when the League was a confederation of equals and the Senate was the forum where those equals negotiated, legislated, and governed.</p>\n<p>The transformation of the League into the Empire changed the Senate&#39;s function without abolishing its form. As imperial power concentrated in the Emperor and the bureaucratic apparatus of the state, the Senate&#39;s authority was progressively hollowed out. What remains is a body that retains the architecture, the ceremony, and the rhetoric of governance without the binding authority that once gave those things meaning.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"membership\">Membership</h2>\n<p>Seats in the Imperial Senate are <strong>hereditary or appointed</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hereditary seats</strong> pass through the <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a> and old families that held them during the League era. These seats carry the prestige of lineage and the weight of tradition, though the authority they represent has long since migrated to other institutions.</li>\n<li><strong>Appointed seats</strong> are granted by the Emperor or through the mechanisms of imperial patronage. These appointments are tools of political management -- rewards for loyalty, incentives for cooperation, or consolation prizes for those who might otherwise cause trouble.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Senators hold <strong>prestige</strong>. They are addressed with deference, consulted with the appearance of seriousness, and treated as persons of consequence. This prestige is genuine within the social hierarchy of the Empire, even if the legislative authority it once accompanied has evaporated.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"function\">Function</h2>\n<p>The Senate&#39;s practical function in the current imperial order is threefold:</p>\n<h3 id=\"political-theater\">Political Theater</h3>\n<p>The Senate floor is a stage. Senators deliver speeches on matters of policy, morality, and imperial direction. These speeches are often eloquent, sometimes brilliant, and rarely consequential. The audience is not the Senate itself but the broader political class -- the speeches signal positions, establish alliances, and advance or undermine reputations.</p>\n<h3 id=\"petitions-and-patronage\">Petitions and Patronage</h3>\n<p>The Senate receives petitions from citizens, provinces, and institutions seeking imperial favor, redress, or attention. The Senate&#39;s ability to act on these petitions is limited, but the act of petitioning -- and the Senate&#39;s response to petitions -- creates a mechanism of patronage that Senators use to build and maintain political networks.</p>\n<h3 id=\"influence-through-rhetoric\">Influence Through Rhetoric</h3>\n<p>Senators can influence policy through rhetoric and patronage, even without binding authority. A sufficiently persuasive speech, a well-timed petition, or a strategic alliance of Senatorial voices can create political pressure that the Emperor and the imperial bureaucracy must acknowledge, if not obey. The Senate&#39;s power is the power of opinion, reputation, and social pressure -- real in its effects, even if informal in its mechanisms.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-imperial-power\">Relationship to Imperial Power</h2>\n<p>The Senate lacks <strong>binding authority</strong>. It cannot legislate, cannot tax, cannot command armies, and cannot compel the Emperor or the imperial administration to act. Its resolutions are advisory at best, ignored at worst.</p>\n<p>This arrangement suits the imperial order. The Senate provides a venue for political expression that might otherwise find less manageable outlets. Ambitious nobles, frustrated provinces, and aggrieved parties can bring their grievances to the Senate floor, where they are heard, debated, and -- crucially -- contained. The Senate functions as a pressure valve, allowing the political class to feel heard without granting them the power to act.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a> -- The original governing body from which the Senate descends</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire the Senate nominally advises</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">great-houses</a> -- The noble families that hold hereditary Senate seats</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor</a> -- The actual locus of imperial authority</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"imperial-talons","title":"The Imperial Talons","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["espionage","imperial-institution","house-decimus"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-imperial-talons\">The Imperial Talons</h1>\n<p>The Imperial Talons are an elite order of spies and assassins operating within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. They answer to no ministry, no senate committee, and no military chain of command -- their loyalty belongs solely and absolutely to the Emperor. The Talons serve as the hidden hand of <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a>, enforcing the ruling dynasty&#39;s power through intelligence gathering, covert operations, and targeted killings.</p>\n<h2 id=\"role-and-purpose\">Role and Purpose</h2>\n<p>Where the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a> projects imperial power openly and the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> controls the arcane, the Talons operate in shadow. They are the Emperor&#39;s instrument for dealing with threats that cannot be addressed through conventional means -- internal conspiracies, disloyal nobles, heretical movements, and foreign agents operating within imperial borders.</p>\n<p>The Talons&#39; existence is an open secret among the imperial elite. Their reputation alone serves as a deterrent: those who move against House Decimus know that the Emperor&#39;s reach extends far beyond the legions and the law.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-heresy-of-the-flame\">The Heresy of the Flame</h2>\n<p>The Talons&#39; most historically significant operation was the assassination of <strong>Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas</strong> during the <strong>Heresy of the Flame</strong> in 304 IY. Vargas, the leader of the <a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Burnished Scale</a>, had launched an unauthorized religious purge that threatened to tear the Empire apart. When the crisis reached a point where diplomatic resolution seemed impossible, the Talons were dispatched.</p>\n<p>The assassination of Vargas eliminated the figurehead of the heretical movement, but it did not immediately resolve the crisis. The Empire teetered on the brink of civil war until the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> intervened to broker a fragile peace.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Burnished Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Military</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"laced-hand","title":"The Laced Hand","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["faction","criminal","syndicate","thieves-guild","sanctuary","harbor","smuggling","black-market","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-laced-hand\">The Laced Hand</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Laced Hand</strong> is <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary&#39;s</a> criminal syndicate -- an organized, hierarchical underworld operation that controls the docks, smuggling, the black market, protection rackets, gambling dens, and information brokerage throughout the city. Operating with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus&#39;s</a> <strong>tacit approval</strong>, the Laced Hand occupies a unique position: simultaneously criminal and quasi-institutional, feared and relied upon, illegal and essential.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Criminal syndicate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Base of Operations</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Sanctuary</span> for generations, surviving changes in governors, shifts in imperial policy, and periodic crackdowns by adapting, compromising, and -- when necessary -- eliminating threats with surgical precision.</p>\n<p>The organization is <strong>not universally hated</strong>. It provides services the city needs:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Docking assistance</strong> -- Ships entering Sanctuary&#39;s harbor navigate the Laced Hand&#39;s system. Dock assignments, loading/unloading crews, and cargo security all flow through Laced Hand-controlled unions.</li>\n<li><strong>Dispute resolution</strong> -- In the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> and parts of the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Commons</a>, the Laced Hand settles disputes faster and more reliably than the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a>. Their judgments are enforced.</li>\n<li><strong>Moving goods quietly</strong> -- Not all smuggling is contraband. Merchants who need to avoid customs duties, move sensitive cargo, or bypass bureaucratic delays turn to the Laced Hand.</li>\n<li><strong>Criminal safety valve</strong> -- By keeping the underworld organized, the Laced Hand prevents the chaos of competing gangs, random violence, and uncontrolled crime. The Governor understands this.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"leadership\">Leadership</h2>\n<h3 id=\"castellan-thibaud-boss\">Castellan Thibaud -- Boss</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Castellan Thibaud</a></strong> is the current boss of the Laced Hand. Master Thief 7, age 52.</p>\n<p>Thibaud rose through the organization&#39;s ranks over <strong>thirty years</strong>, beginning as a dockside pickpocket and advancing through every level of the hierarchy. He is <strong>intelligent, cautious, and remarkably well-read</strong> -- more like a crime CEO than a typical underworld boss. He does not swagger, threaten, or posture. He manages.</p>\n<p><strong>Key traits:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Operates from <strong>multiple hideouts</strong> throughout the city, rarely using the same location twice in succession</li>\n<li><strong>Rarely seen in public</strong> -- most of Sanctuary&#39;s population would not recognize him on the street</li>\n<li>Runs the Laced Hand as a <strong>hierarchical, quasi-legal operation</strong> with clear chains of command, standardized procedures, and something approaching corporate discipline</li>\n<li>Focused on <strong>profit and stability</strong>, not flash or violence. Violence is a tool, not a policy. When it is used, it is precise and purposeful.</li>\n<li>Understands that his organization exists at the <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor&#39;s</a> pleasure and could be destroyed if Drussus ever decided the arrangement was no longer useful</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Thibaud&#39;s greatest asset is his <strong>patience</strong>. He does not react to provocations. He does not make emotional decisions. He calculates, waits, and acts when the moment is right.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"operations\">Operations</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-dockworkers-union\">The Dockworkers&#39; Union</h3>\n<p>The Laced Hand&#39;s most visible operation. Control of the dockworkers&#39; union gives them effective control over the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> district. Nothing enters or leaves <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> by sea without the Laced Hand&#39;s knowledge and, implicitly, their permission.</p>\n<h3 id=\"warehousing-smuggling\">Warehousing &amp; Smuggling</h3>\n<p>The Laced Hand controls a network of warehouses throughout the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> and parts of the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Commons</a>. These serve dual purposes: legitimate storage for merchants and concealed storage for contraband, stolen goods, and items that need to disappear for a while.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-black-market\">The Black Market</h3>\n<p>Goods that cannot be sold through legitimate channels -- stolen property, restricted items, contraband -- flow through the Laced Hand&#39;s black market. This is not a single location but a network of dealers, brokers, and contacts operating throughout the city.</p>\n<h3 id=\"protection-rackets\">Protection Rackets</h3>\n<p>Merchants and business owners in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> and parts of the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Commons</a> pay regular fees to the Laced Hand. In exchange, they receive genuine protection -- from theft, from competitors, from random violence, and from the Laced Hand itself.</p>\n<h3 id=\"gambling-dens\">Gambling Dens</h3>\n<p>The Laced Hand operates gambling establishments throughout <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, ranging from upscale houses catering to wealthy merchants to dockside dice games for sailors. All pay a cut to the organization.</p>\n<h3 id=\"discretion-houses\">Discretion Houses</h3>\n<p>The Laced Hand maintains <strong>&quot;discretion houses&quot;</strong> in most districts. These serve triple duty:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Information brokers</strong> -- where intelligence is bought and sold</li>\n<li><strong>Meeting places</strong> -- neutral ground for negotiations between parties who cannot be seen meeting publicly</li>\n<li><strong>Safe houses</strong> -- temporary shelter for those who need to disappear</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The discretion houses are the backbone of the Laced Hand&#39;s intelligence network and one of their most valuable services.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-crimson-anchor-tavern\">The Crimson Anchor Tavern</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crimson Anchor Tavern</a> in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> is the Laced Hand&#39;s <strong>primary operations hub</strong>. On the surface, it is a busy dockside tavern -- loud, crowded, smelling of salt and beer. Beneath that surface, it is the nerve center of the organization&#39;s daily operations.</p>\n<p><strong>Proprietor: Mara</strong> -- Has worked at the Crimson Anchor for <strong>20 years</strong>. Knows everyone worth knowing in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary&#39;s</a> underworld. Functions as an informal intelligence clearinghouse, message drop, and first point of contact for those seeking to do business with the Laced Hand. Mara is not Laced Hand leadership -- she is infrastructure. Without her, the organization&#39;s communication network would be significantly degraded.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-arrangement-with-the-governor\">The Arrangement with the Governor</h2>\n<p>The Laced Hand operates with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus&#39;s</a> <strong>tacit approval</strong>. This arrangement is unspoken but understood by both parties:</p>\n<p><strong>What the Laced Hand provides:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Intelligence from the docks -- who is arriving, what they carry, who they meet</li>\n<li>Subtle removal of individuals who are inconvenient to the Governor but cannot be openly dealt with</li>\n<li>A criminal safety valve -- organized crime is predictable and manageable; disorganized crime is not</li>\n<li>Economic lubrication -- the black market moves goods and services that the legitimate economy cannot</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>What the Governor provides:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Non-interference -- the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> does not aggressively pursue Laced Hand operations</li>\n<li>Stability -- the Governor does not allow rival criminal organizations to challenge the Laced Hand&#39;s dominance</li>\n<li>Implicit protection -- the Laced Hand&#39;s position is secure so long as it remains useful</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thibaud</a></strong> understands the fragility of this arrangement. It exists because Drussus finds it useful. The moment it becomes more trouble than it is worth, the <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> will crush the Laced Hand without hesitation. Thibaud manages accordingly -- keeping his operations profitable but not provocative, useful but not indispensable enough to demand concessions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"structure\">Structure</h2>\n<p>The Laced Hand is organized hierarchically:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Boss</strong> (<a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Castellan Thibaud</a>) -- overall leadership and strategic direction</li>\n<li><strong>Lieutenants</strong> -- each controls a specific district or operation (docks, smuggling, gambling, protection, etc.)</li>\n<li><strong>Captains</strong> -- manage day-to-day operations within their lieutenant&#39;s territory</li>\n<li><strong>Operatives</strong> -- skilled thieves, enforcers, smugglers, and information brokers</li>\n<li><strong>Associates</strong> -- dockworkers, lookouts, messengers, and others who work with the Laced Hand but are not full members</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Advancement is based on reliability, profit generation, and discretion. Violence is not rewarded unless it was necessary and executed cleanly.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-other-factions\">Relationship with Other Factions</h2>\n<h3 id=\"prelate-voth-the-temple\">Prelate Voth &amp; the Temple</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Voth</a> regards the Laced Hand as a moral rot. The Temple monitors Laced Hand activities through its own intelligence network and occasionally interferes when criminal operations become too brazen or impact Temple interests. The Laced Hand, in turn, avoids operating in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sunward</a> and treats Temple property and personnel as off-limits.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-academy\">The Imperial Academy</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> is largely indifferent to the Laced Hand, and the Laced Hand treats Academy matters as outside its scope. Occasional transactions occur -- an antiquarian who needs an artifact moved quietly, a scholar who needs information from the docks -- but there is no formal relationship.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-avari-community\">The Avari Community</h3>\n<p>The Laced Hand has limited presence in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a>. The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> community polices itself, and the Laced Hand has calculated that the profit potential of the refugee quarter does not justify the difficulty of operating there.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gm-notes\">GM Notes</h2>\n<p>The Laced Hand should be played as a professional organization, not a street gang. Key principles:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>They are businesspeople first.</strong> Profit, stability, and institutional survival drive their decisions, not ego or territoriality.</li>\n<li><strong>Violence is a tool, not a culture.</strong> When the Laced Hand uses violence, it is precise, purposeful, and designed to send a specific message. Random violence is bad for business.</li>\n<li><strong>They are a useful resource for PCs.</strong> Need information? Need something moved? Need someone found? The Laced Hand can provide -- for a price. They are not enemies by default.</li>\n<li><strong>They are dangerous when crossed.</strong> The same professionalism that makes them reasonable also makes them methodical in retribution. Crossing the Laced Hand means dealing with an organization that has been eliminating problems for generations.</li>\n<li><strong>Thibaud is the key.</strong> If PCs interact with Laced Hand leadership, they interact with Thibaud -- and he is smarter, more patient, and better informed than they expect.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Harbor</a> -- primary territory</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Crimson Anchor Tavern</a> -- operations hub</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Castellan Thibaud</a> -- boss</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- tacit patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Severan Voth</a> -- moral opponent</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Drussine Guard</a> -- the threat that enforces good behavior</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Commons</a> -- secondary territory</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> -- nominal law enforcement</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mithrian-marines","title":"The Mithrian Marines","category":"factions","status":"active","tags":["faction","military","marines","mithrian","elite","shroud","empyrean","8th-undying","second-war-of-morn","lycandite","ferocity"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-mithrian-marines\">The Mithrian Marines</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Send the Regulars if you want to win the battle. Send the Marines if you want the enemy stacked like firewood.&quot; -- Captain Pollimer Motts, 8th Company Marines, 14th Army</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Mithrian Marines</strong> are an elite branch of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> military, famous for their ferocity in combat and their distinctive religious practice -- the worship of <a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> god of crossing and passage.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Elite military branch</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Allegiance</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Shroud</span></strong> -- the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> god of crossing and passage. Where most imperial soldiers observe the broader Empyrean pantheon with varying degrees of sincerity, the Marines have adopted Shroud as their patron with particular devotion.</p>\n<p>Shroud presides over transitions -- the crossing of thresholds, the passage from one state to another, the boundary between the living and the dead. For the Marines, this domain has specific and practical meaning: they are the ones who carry enemies across that boundary, and they worship the god who stands at the gate.</p>\n<p>This devotion gives Marine units a spiritual cohesion that supplements their military discipline. They do not merely fight together -- they share a religious identity that frames their violence as sacred function, their casualties as offerings, and their survival as evidence of divine favor.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-8th-undying\">The 8th Undying</h2>\n<p>The most famous Marine unit is the <strong>8th Undying</strong> -- the 8th Company Marines of the 14th Army, who earned their epithet during the <strong>Second War of Morn</strong> in 371 IY.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-second-war-of-morn-371-iy\">The Second War of Morn (371 IY)</h3>\n<p>During the Second War of Morn, the 14th Army was shattered by <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lycandite</a> fanatics -- an enemy whose religious fervor and physical transformation made them exceptionally dangerous opponents. The 14th Army broke. Its regular formations collapsed under the pressure of an enemy that did not retreat, did not negotiate, and did not die easily.</p>\n<p>The 8th Company Marines did not break.</p>\n<p>What the 8th Company did in the aftermath of the 14th Army&#39;s destruction earned them the name &quot;Undying&quot; -- a title that speaks to both their refusal to die and their capacity to inflict death on an enemy that had already destroyed a conventional army. The 8th Undying became legendary, a unit whose name carried weight sufficient to alter the calculations of enemies who heard it.</p>\n<p>Captain <strong>Pollimer Motts</strong> of the 8th Company Marines summarized the distinction between regular forces and Marines with characteristic bluntness: the Regulars win battles; the Marines leave nothing standing.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-imperial-military-doctrine\">Role in Imperial Military Doctrine</h2>\n<p>The Marines serve a specific function within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire&#39;s</a> combined arms doctrine. They are not a general-purpose formation -- they are a specialist instrument deployed when conventional forces are insufficient or when the political and military situation demands a particular kind of result.</p>\n<p>Their deployment signals escalation. When the Marines are committed, the Empire has decided that the situation requires not merely military resolution but the kind of resolution that discourages future resistance. This makes them both invaluable and politically sensitive -- their use carries implications that extend beyond the immediate tactical situation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire the Marines serve</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">shroud</a> -- The Empyrean god of crossing/passage worshipped by the Marines</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The broader religious tradition to which Shroud belongs</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lycandite</a> -- The fanatics who shattered the 14th Army</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> -- The broader military structure</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">kolani-munitions</a> -- Another specialist element of Mithrian combined arms doctrine</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mithrian-military","title":"The Mithrian Military","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["military","mithrian-empire","imperial-institution"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-mithrian-military\">The Mithrian Military</h1>\n<p>The Mithrian Military is the vast, structured, and brutally efficient professional army of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Born from the citizen-soldier ideals enshrined in the Measure and the Scale, the military has served as both the instrument of imperial expansion and the shield against the Empire&#39;s many enemies.</p>\n<h2 id=\"origins-and-the-legionary-tradition\">Origins and the Legionary Tradition</h2>\n<p>The military was originally built around vast legions of heavy infantry -- disciplined formations of citizen soldiers who carved the Empire out of a hostile world. As Mithra conquered new peoples, the defeated were enlisted as <strong>auxiliaries</strong>, fighting alongside the legions in exchange for the promise of full citizenship upon completion of their service. Military service has long been the surest path to land ownership, the core aspiration of every Mithrian citizen.</p>\n<h2 id=\"transformation-by-sorcery\">Transformation by Sorcery</h2>\n<p>The proliferation of destructive sorcery on the battlefield fundamentally transformed the Mithrian way of war. Where once Mithra held a near-monopoly on organized sorcerous power through the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, rival nations and elder civilizations have since developed their own devastating magical capabilities. <strong>Elder sorcery</strong> in particular is devastatingly destructive, capable of shattering formations and reducing fortifications to rubble.</p>\n<p>In response, the military has evolved from a force built around massed heavy infantry into a <strong>combined arms, highly mobile, and adaptable</strong> fighting force. The rigid legion structure has given way to more flexible doctrines suited to surviving and prevailing on a battlefield shaped by magic.</p>\n<h2 id=\"modern-composition\">Modern Composition</h2>\n<p>The contemporary Mithrian Military integrates a wide array of specialized units:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Line infantry</strong> -- still the backbone, though deployed in looser, more adaptive formations</li>\n<li><strong>Squad mages</strong> -- Academy-trained sorcerers embedded at the tactical level</li>\n<li><strong>Scouts and assassins</strong> -- operating ahead of and behind enemy lines</li>\n<li><strong>Sappers</strong> -- combat engineers specializing in fortification and demolition</li>\n<li><strong>Kolani munitions teams</strong> -- employing advanced explosive and incendiary weapons acquired from the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> as part of the peace settlement following the Dog Soldier War</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"the-mithrian-marines\">The Mithrian Marines</h2>\n<p>Among the most feared elements of the military are the <strong>Mithrian Marines</strong>, a seaborne fighting force with a fearsome reputation. The Marines are notable for their worship of <strong>Shroud</strong>, an Empyrean god associated with death, the sea, and the passage between worlds -- an unusual devotion that sets them apart from the broader imperial religious culture centered on the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-8th-undying\">The 8th Undying</h2>\n<p>The <strong>8th Undying</strong> are legendary heroes whose fame dates to the Second War of Morn in 371 IY. Their exploits during that conflict have passed into military legend, and their name is invoked as a standard of valor and sacrifice within the ranks.</p>\n<h2 id=\"strategic-challenges\">Strategic Challenges</h2>\n<p>Despite its formidable capabilities, the Mithrian Military is stretched dangerously thin. On the Empire&#39;s borders, <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> and <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan</a> barbarian forces continually test the legions&#39; ability to hold the line. The combination of vast frontier commitments, the rising threat of elder sorcery, and the logistical demands of maintaining a professional army across a continent-spanning empire has placed the military under mounting strain.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Talons</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon","title":"Order of the Scarlet Ribbon","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["faction","religious-order","empyrean","bladedancer","iman","militant-order","priestesses","noble-patrons"],"html":"<h1 id=\"order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\">Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</strong> is a militant religious order connected to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith. The Order trains bladedancers -- warrior-devotees who combine martial discipline with religious devotion in service to the Empyrean temples and their patrons. It is the order from which <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> was driven for speaking too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Militant religious order</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Faith</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Empyrean</span> faith, producing warriors who fight as an act of worship and worship through the act of fighting.</p>\n<p>The Order is led by its priestesses, who serve as both spiritual authorities and institutional administrators. They govern the training of initiates, maintain the Order&#39;s relationship with the Empyrean temples, and manage the political connections that sustain the institution&#39;s funding and social standing.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-corruption\">The Corruption</h2>\n<p>Beneath the Order&#39;s public face of religious devotion and martial discipline lies a more complicated reality. The priestesses of the Order maintain relationships with noble patrons -- relationships that blur the boundary between spiritual authority and secular power, between religious service and political transaction.</p>\n<p>These arrangements are the open secret of the Order. Everyone within the institution understands them. The noble patrons provide funding, political protection, and social standing. In return, the priestesses provide services that extend beyond the merely spiritual -- access, influence, the prestige of association with a respected religious order, and other accommodations that are understood but not named.</p>\n<p>This exchange is tolerated because it is necessary. The Order cannot sustain itself on faith alone. It requires resources, and resources come from patrons, and patrons expect returns on their investment. The priestesses who serve their patrons&#39; interests rather than their faith&#39;s teachings do so because the alternative -- institutional poverty and political irrelevance -- is worse. Or so the reasoning goes.</p>\n<p>The corruption is not dramatic or violent. It is the ordinary, grinding corruption of an institution that has learned to survive by compromising its stated principles. It is the kind of corruption that everyone sees and no one names, because naming it would require confronting the gap between what the Order claims to be and what it actually is.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"imans-expulsion\">Iman&#39;s Expulsion</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> was a bladedancer of the Order -- trained in its martial and devotional traditions, shaped by its discipline, loyal to its stated ideals. She was also honest in a way that the Order could not tolerate.</p>\n<p>Iman spoke too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons. She named the corruption -- the exchange of spiritual authority for secular patronage, the priestesses who served their benefactors rather than their faith. She said it aloud, in terms that could not be misunderstood or politely ignored.</p>\n<p>For this, she was driven from the Order. Not for being wrong -- the corruption she identified was real and widely known -- but for being honest about it. The Order could tolerate the corruption itself. What it could not tolerate was someone saying so. Iman&#39;s expulsion was not a punishment for falsehood but for truth -- the one unforgivable sin in an institution built on comfortable lies.</p>\n<p>Iman subsequently came to <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> and joined <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>, where her bladedancer training and her directness found a more welcoming context.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-the-empyrean-faith\">Relationship with the Empyrean Faith</h2>\n<p>The Order of the Scarlet Ribbon is connected to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith -- one of the major religious traditions of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. The precise nature of this connection -- whether the Order is an official arm of the Empyrean temples, an independent order operating under Empyrean auspices, or a semi-autonomous institution with its own governance -- is not fully clarified in available sources.</p>\n<p>What is clear is that the Order draws its spiritual authority from the Empyrean tradition and its martial practice from the bladedancer discipline associated with that tradition. The priestesses who lead the Order derive their legitimacy from their religious role, even as their actual function has become increasingly entangled with secular patronage.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- Former member, expelled for honesty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party Iman joined after her expulsion</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> -- The faith to which the Order is connected</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- Iman&#39;s current close relationship, who values the directness the Order punished</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- Where Iman went after her expulsion</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history of the campaign</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"red-river-consortium","title":"Red River Consortium","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["faction","trading-company","consortium","bone-creek","backlands","commerce","scalpers"],"html":"<h1 id=\"red-river-consortium\">Red River Consortium</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Red River Consortium</strong> is a trading company operating in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, most notably through its <strong>Red River Exchange</strong> in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>. The Consortium has positioned itself as the economic backbone of the Scalper trade, profiting from the Imperial Bounty by serving as the intermediary between Scalpers and the imperial treasury.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-red-river-exchange\">The Red River Exchange</h2>\n<p>The Red River Exchange is the <strong>largest building in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a></strong> — a physical testament to the Consortium&#39;s wealth and power in the settlement. It serves two primary functions:</p>\n<h3 id=\"loot-and-treasure-sales\">Loot and Treasure Sales</h3>\n<p>Scalpers sell their plundered loot and treasure to the Exchange. The Consortium&#39;s merchants are <strong>shrewd negotiators</strong>, ensuring that the Exchange profits handsomely from every transaction. Scalpers fresh from the field, desperate for coin, are often at a disadvantage when haggling with the Exchange&#39;s experienced traders.</p>\n<h3 id=\"beastman-scalp-redemption\">Beastman Scalp Redemption</h3>\n<p>The Exchange is where <strong><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> scalps are sold</strong> in exchange for the Imperial Bounty of one imperial gold mark per scalp. The Consortium takes a <strong>transaction fee</strong> on every scalp redeemed — a cut of the Emperor&#39;s own bounty that flows directly into Consortium coffers. Given the volume of scalps passing through Bone Creek, this fee represents an enormous and steady revenue stream.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"security\">Security</h2>\n<p>The Consortium employs an <strong>army of hardened guardsmen and bodyguards</strong> to protect the Exchange, its merchants, its inventory, and its gold. In a settlement as lawless as Bone Creek, this private security force makes the Red River Exchange one of the few places where violence is reliably punished. It also makes the Consortium a military power in its own right within the settlement.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"leadership\">Leadership</h2>\n<h3 id=\"cassian-varro-lord-merchant\">Cassian Varro — Lord Merchant</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a></strong> serves as the <strong>Lord Merchant</strong> of the Red River Exchange — the Consortium&#39;s chief representative in Bone Creek. He is described as a polished and shrewd businessman who is deeply involved in the local economy and political dealings of the settlement.</p>\n<p>Varro is not merely an administrator; he is an active political player shaping Bone Creek&#39;s future through his alliance with <a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"alliances\">Alliances</h2>\n<p>The Consortium, through Varro, is a <strong>close ally</strong> of <strong><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a></strong>, proprietor of Double Sevens. Together, they represent the strongest power bloc in Bone Creek — one oriented toward commerce, order, and the gradual civilization of the frontier. This alliance stands in opposition to the rougher, more lawless influence of <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a> and his network.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-the-scalper-economy\">Role in the Scalper Economy</h2>\n<p>The Red River Consortium sits at the center of the entire Scalper economy in Bone Creek:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Scalpers</strong> risk their lives hunting <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> for scalps</li>\n<li><strong>The Exchange</strong> buys the scalps and redeems the Imperial Bounty (taking a transaction fee)</li>\n<li><strong>The Exchange</strong> also buys any loot or treasure Scalpers recover (at negotiated — often unfavorable — prices)</li>\n<li><strong>The Consortium</strong> profits from both the transaction fees and the markup on resold goods</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This position gives the Consortium enormous economic leverage. Every mark that flows through Bone Creek passes through the Exchange at some point, and the Consortium takes its cut each time.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> — Lord Merchant and local leader of the Consortium</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The settlement where the Exchange operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">tolliver-watts</a> — Close ally of the Consortium</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> — Rival power in Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures whose scalps fuel the Consortium&#39;s business</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> — The empire whose bounty the Consortium profits from</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"scalper-gangs","title":"Scalper Gangs","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["faction","scalpers","gangs","bounty","beastmen","bone-creek","backlands","violence","frontier"],"html":"<h1 id=\"scalper-gangs\">Scalper Gangs</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Scalper gangs</strong> are organized groups of bounty hunters operating in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, drawn to the frontier by Emperor <strong>Justinian Claudius Decimus&#39;s</strong> decree offering <strong>one imperial gold mark</strong> for every <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> scalp delivered to an authorized exchange point. These gangs represent the organized edge of the Scalper trade — bands of fighters who have banded together under charismatic or powerful leaders to hunt beastmen more effectively, claim territory, and survive in one of the most dangerous regions of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>.</p>\n<p>Those who seek the Imperial Bounty are called <strong>Scalpers</strong>. Hard men and women who come from every walk of life, drawn by the allure of imperial gold, a Scalper&#39;s life is one of <strong>chaos, violence, and peril</strong>. For whatever reason, each Scalper has left their former life behind and journeyed to the edge of civilization.</p>\n<p>The veteran Scalpers are unlike any men one might encounter elsewhere — their <strong>eyes dulled from the horrors they have seen and endured, or tinged with a glint of madness</strong>. Some even <strong>bear the marks of corruption</strong> openly. They say, those who hunt the beastmen are changed. They say:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;The Bounty takes its toll.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-gangs\">The Gangs</h2>\n<h3 id=\"skin-eaters\">Skin Eaters</h3>\n<p><strong>Leader:</strong> <a href=\"#/page/skinner\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skinner</a> — Assassin 5 (<a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a>)</p>\n<p>The <strong>most notoriously brutal</strong> of the Scalper gangs. The Skin Eaters are defined by their leader&#39;s savage reputation and their willingness to engage in methods that go far beyond what is necessary to collect the Imperial Bounty. <a href=\"#/page/skinner\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skinner</a> wears <strong>beastman-hide armor</strong> crafted from the skins of his kills — a walking trophy and a statement of absolute dominance over his prey.</p>\n<p>Skinner is cold, intense, and feared throughout the Backlands. Covered in scars and never seen without a blade, rumors say he is not entirely sane. His proficiencies in <strong>Tracking</strong>, <strong>Ambushing</strong>, and <strong>Torture</strong> paint a picture of a methodical predator who hunts with lethal efficiency and dispatches his prey with deliberate cruelty.</p>\n<p>The Skin Eaters embody the <strong>darkest extreme</strong> of the Scalper trade — the point where hunting becomes butchery and survival becomes savagery.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Stats:</strong> AC 4, HP 28, ATK +4 (Hooked Axe 1d8+2), Dex 15</p>\n<p>For Skinner&#39;s full profile, see <strong><a href=\"#/page/skinner\" class=\"wiki-link\">skinner</a></strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"the-dregs\">The Dregs</h3>\n<p><strong>Leader:</strong> <a href=\"#/page/bottlecap-juno\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bottlecap Juno</a> — Barbarian 4</p>\n<p>The <strong>wild card faction</strong> of the Scalper gangs. The Dregs are as unpredictable as their leader — a grinning, possibly mad barbarian who leads through raw charisma and physical intimidation rather than any coherent strategy or ideology. <a href=\"#/page/bottlecap-juno\" class=\"wiki-link\">Juno</a> wears a <strong>necklace of bent coins</strong> and fights with a great axe and berserker fury.</p>\n<p>The Dregs cannot be easily bought, threatened, or reasoned with. Their unpredictability makes them unreliable allies and terrifying enemies. Where other gangs can be anticipated, the Dregs operate on instinct and impulse, making them a chaotic element in any conflict they enter.</p>\n<p>Juno&#39;s proficiencies in <strong>Berserkergang</strong>, <strong>Intimidation</strong>, and <strong>Survival</strong> reflect a leader who fights in a frenzy, terrifies his enemies, and keeps his people alive in the wilderness through sheer stubborn resilience.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Stats:</strong> AC 3, HP 34, ATK +4 (Great Axe 1d10+1), Str 15</p>\n<p>For Juno&#39;s full profile, see <strong><a href=\"#/page/bottlecap-juno\" class=\"wiki-link\">bottlecap-juno</a></strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"the-baldric-brothers\">The Baldric Brothers</h3>\n<p><strong>Leader:</strong> <a href=\"#/page/kael-baldric\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kael Baldric</a> — Fighter 4 (<a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a>) — <strong>CURRENTLY MISSING</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Five <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> brothers</strong> with a <strong>fearsome reputation</strong> in the Backlands. The Baldric Brothers are <strong>rarely seen apart</strong> — they operate as a single, cohesive fighting unit, and their coordination and mutual loyalty make them far more dangerous than their individual capabilities would suggest. They are known for getting <strong>jobs done quickly and violently</strong>.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/kael-baldric\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kael</a>, the eldest, is the leader — stern, protective, and fiercely family-loyal. He is <strong>completely bald</strong> with <strong>black-chain tattoos</strong> and fights with a bastard sword. His proficiencies in <strong>Leadership</strong> and <strong>Survival</strong> reflect his role as the group&#39;s commander and guide.</p>\n<p>Kael is <strong>currently missing</strong>. His unexplained disappearance is deeply troubling — the brothers are never apart, and Kael&#39;s absence suggests something has gone catastrophically wrong. This creates an immediate <strong>investigation or rescue hook</strong> for anyone who encounters the remaining four brothers.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Stats:</strong> AC 3, HP 30, ATK +4 (Bastard Sword 1d10+1), Str 15</p>\n<p>For Kael&#39;s full profile, see <strong><a href=\"#/page/kael-baldric\" class=\"wiki-link\">kael-baldric</a></strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"the-hollow-men\">The Hollow Men</h3>\n<p><strong>Leader:</strong> <a href=\"#/page/wekko\" class=\"wiki-link\">Wekko</a> — Witch-Doctor 6 (<a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a>)</p>\n<p>The most <strong>ominous and alien</strong> of the Scalper gangs. The Hollow Men are defined by their <strong>ritualistic nature</strong> and the unsettling, cultic authority of their masked, silent leader. <a href=\"#/page/wekko\" class=\"wiki-link\">Wekko</a> is <strong>always masked</strong> and <strong>perpetually silent</strong> — a figure who exists in the space between the human and the supernatural, commanding his followers through force of presence and spiritual power rather than words.</p>\n<p>The Hollow Men are not merely bounty hunters — they are practitioners of something older and darker than the Imperial Bounty. Wekko&#39;s spells include <strong>Cause Fear</strong>, <strong>Curse</strong>, and <strong>Speak with Dead</strong>, and his proficiencies in <strong>Terror</strong>, <strong>Prophecy</strong>, and <strong>Healing</strong> suggest a witch-doctor who wields the full spectrum of spiritual power — from healing the living to commanding the dead.</p>\n<p>The Hollow Men represent a <strong>cultic presence</strong> in the Scalper trade, and Wekko&#39;s prophetic abilities give them the potential to shape events through foretelling as well as violence.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Stats:</strong> AC 5, HP 24, ATK +3 (Bone Spear 1d6+1), Wis 16</p>\n<p>For Wekko&#39;s full profile, see <strong><a href=\"#/page/wekko\" class=\"wiki-link\">wekko</a></strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"the-bleak-sons\">The Bleak Sons</h3>\n<p><strong>Leader:</strong> <a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcos Varanes &quot;The Measure&quot;</a> — Paladin 5 (<a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a>)</p>\n<p>The most <strong>disciplined and ideologically driven</strong> of the Scalper gangs. The Bleak Sons are <strong>zealous militant followers of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></strong>, the god of justice and the balanced scale. Under <a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varanes&#39;s</a> leadership, they treat the beastman hunts not as a mercenary enterprise but as a <strong>holy crusade</strong> — a sacred duty imposed by divine will.</p>\n<p>Varanes — &quot;The Measure&quot; — is the most formidable physical combatant among the gang leaders. Clad in full armor (AC 1) with 38 hit points and a +5 attack bonus, he is a devastating warrior. His <strong>bronze scale fetish</strong> amulet marks him as a devoted servant of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, and his proficiencies in <strong>Intimidation</strong>, <strong>Theology</strong>, and <strong>Divine Blessing</strong> make him both a military and spiritual commander.</p>\n<p>The Bleak Sons are a <strong>possible ally or fanatic adversary</strong>. Their discipline and combat effectiveness make them the most valuable potential partners in the Backlands, but their rigid moral code and Varanes&#39;s absolute certainty in his own righteousness make them inflexible and judgmental. Those who do not meet their standards are viewed not as neutral parties but as sinners.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Stats:</strong> AC 1, HP 38, ATK +5 (Morning Star 1d8+2), Str 17</p>\n<p>For Varanes&#39;s full profile, see <strong><a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">marcos-varanes</a></strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"the-withered-craw\">The Withered Craw</h3>\n<p><strong>Secret Controller:</strong> <a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn the Misshapen</a> — Mage 7 (<a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a>)</p>\n<p>The <strong>most secretive</strong> of the Scalper gangs — and for good reason. The Withered Craw operates under the guise of a standard bounty-hunting operation, but is in reality <strong>secretly controlled by <a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn the Misshapen</a></strong>, an exiled, crippled mage who uses the gang to <strong>enslave beastmen rather than kill them</strong>. While other Scalper gangs bring back scalps, the Withered Craw brings back living captives — delivering them to Malyn for purposes that are unknown and almost certainly forbidden.</p>\n<p>Malyn himself never appears publicly. His apprentice <strong>Lynara</strong> — an <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> Nightblade 3 with golden skin and pale Eladran eyes — serves as the gateway to Malyn&#39;s operations. She is curious, intelligent, and <strong>morally torn</strong> by the nature of her master&#39;s work, making her a potential point of leverage for anyone investigating the Withered Craw&#39;s true activities.</p>\n<p>The Withered Craw&#39;s existence is a closely guarded secret. If it were discovered that they enslave beastmen rather than kill them, the reaction from other Scalper gangs, the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>, and imperial authorities would be swift and violent.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Stats (Malyn):</strong> AC 8, HP 18, ATK +2 (Staff 1d6), Int 17\n<strong>Key Stats (Lynara):</strong> AC 4, HP 13, Dex 16</p>\n<p>For Malyn&#39;s full profile, see <strong><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</a></strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"comparative-overview\">Comparative Overview</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Gang</th>\n<th>Leader</th>\n<th>Class</th>\n<th>HP</th>\n<th>Best Stat</th>\n<th>Defining Trait</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Skin Eaters</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">skinner</td>\n<td>Skinner</span></td>\n<td>Assassin 5</td>\n<td>28</td>\n<td>Dex 15</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>The Dregs</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">bottlecap-juno</td>\n<td>Bottlecap Juno</span></td>\n<td>Barbarian 4</td>\n<td>34</td>\n<td>Str 15</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Baldric Brothers</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">kael-baldric</td>\n<td>Kael Baldric</span></td>\n<td>Fighter 4</td>\n<td>30</td>\n<td>Str 15</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Hollow Men</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">wekko</td>\n<td>Wekko</span></td>\n<td>Witch-Doctor 6</td>\n<td>24</td>\n<td>Wis 16</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Bleak Sons</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">marcos-varanes</td>\n<td>Marcos Varanes</span></td>\n<td>Paladin 5</td>\n<td>38</td>\n<td>Str 17</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Withered Craw</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</td>\n<td>Malyn the Misshapen</span></td>\n<td>Mage 7</td>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>Int 17</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-scalper-economy\">The Scalper Economy</h2>\n<p>The Scalper gangs exist within an economic ecosystem centered on <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>The Hunt</strong> — Gangs venture north into beastman territory, risking their lives to kill (or, in the Withered Craw&#39;s case, capture) beastmen</li>\n<li><strong>The Scalps</strong> — Beastman scalps are brought back to Bone Creek as proof of kills</li>\n<li><strong>The Exchange</strong> — Scalps are sold at the <strong>Red River Exchange</strong>, operated by the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>, in exchange for imperial gold marks (minus a transaction fee)</li>\n<li><strong>The Spend</strong> — Gold flows into Bone Creek&#39;s taverns, shops, and services — the Pretty Peach (<a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a>), Double Sevens (<a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a>), Tackle and Harness, and other establishments</li>\n<li><strong>The Cycle</strong> — Scalpers resupply, recover, and head back out to hunt again</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This cycle keeps Bone Creek alive and profitable, but it also ensures a constant flow of violence, trauma, and corruption through the settlement. The veteran Scalpers&#39; &quot;dulled eyes&quot; and &quot;marks of corruption&quot; are the human cost of this economy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"inter-gang-dynamics\">Inter-Gang Dynamics</h2>\n<p>The six Scalper gangs exist in a state of <strong>competitive coexistence</strong> — they are not allies, but outright gang warfare would be counterproductive when there are beastmen to hunt and bounties to collect. Tensions exist along several axes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Brutality vs. Discipline</strong> — The Skin Eaters and the Bleak Sons represent opposite approaches to the Scalper trade. Skinner&#39;s savage methods and Varanes&#39;s righteous zeal could easily spark a confrontation.</li>\n<li><strong>Chaos vs. Order</strong> — The Dregs&#39; unpredictability is anathema to the Bleak Sons&#39; rigid discipline and the Baldric Brothers&#39; family cohesion.</li>\n<li><strong>Secrecy vs. Transparency</strong> — The Withered Craw&#39;s hidden agenda, the Hollow Men&#39;s ritualistic secrecy, and the Congregation of the Hollow Sun&#39;s covert recruitment all create layers of hidden activity beneath the surface of the Scalper trade.</li>\n<li><strong>Leadership Vacuum</strong> — Kael Baldric&#39;s disappearance creates instability among the Baldric Brothers, potentially shifting the balance of power among the gangs.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement and economic hub</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province where the gangs operate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures the gangs hunt for the Imperial Bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — The ruined city whose fall created the Scalper trade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> — The trading company that profits from the scalp bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> — The empire that issued the bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/skinner\" class=\"wiki-link\">skinner</a> — Leader of the Skin Eaters</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bottlecap-juno\" class=\"wiki-link\">bottlecap-juno</a> — Leader of the Dregs</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kael-baldric\" class=\"wiki-link\">kael-baldric</a> — Leader of the Baldric Brothers (missing)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/wekko\" class=\"wiki-link\">wekko</a> — Leader of the Hollow Men</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">marcos-varanes</a> — Leader of the Bleak Sons</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</a> — Secret controller of the Withered Craw</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> — Leader of the Congregation of the Hollow Sun (not a Scalper gang, but operates within the same ecosystem)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a> — Secretive religious group connected to the Scalper community</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-gallus\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-gallus</a> — The nominal law enforcer who does nothing about gang activities</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> — Power broker who interacts with all the gangs</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> — Lord Merchant who controls the bounty exchange</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"thousand-temples","title":"The Thousand Temples","category":"factions","status":"unknown","tags":["religion","imperial-institution","the-flame"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-thousand-temples\">The Thousand Temples</h1>\n<p>The Thousand Temples is the official religious institution of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, serving as the organized body through which the faith of the Flame is administered, interpreted, and protected. Headquartered in <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, the Thousand Temples holds authority over religious doctrine, priestly ordination, and the sacred process of canonization.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-flame-and-its-priests\">The Flame and Its Priests</h2>\n<p>The priests of the Thousand Temples are able to <strong>channel the Flame</strong>, drawing upon its divine power to perform miracles, heal, and ward against darkness. However, the nature of this gift is mysterious even to those who wield it -- priests can channel the Flame, but they <strong>cannot truly teach it</strong>. The ability appears to be granted rather than learned, setting it apart from the formulaic sorcery of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>. This distinction places the Flame outside the Academy&#39;s regulatory authority and has been a source of tension between the two institutions.</p>\n<h2 id=\"sainthood\">Sainthood</h2>\n<p>One of the Thousand Temples&#39; most significant functions is the <strong>anointing of Saints</strong>. Sainthood is typically granted posthumously to individuals who exhibited the <strong>seven virtues of the Scale</strong> during their lifetime -- a rigorous standard that ensures the sanctity of the honor.</p>\n<p>However, the process is not entirely insulated from politics. Some Emperors have pressured the Thousand Temples to grant Sainthood to <strong>living individuals</strong>, a practice that blurs the line between spiritual recognition and political propaganda. The Temples have historically resisted such pressure, though not always successfully.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-heresy-of-the-flame\">The Heresy of the Flame</h2>\n<p>The Thousand Temples played a critical role during the <strong>Heresy of the Flame</strong> in 304 IY. When the <a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Burnished Scale</a> launched an unauthorized religious purge under Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas, and the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a> assassinated Vargas in response, the Empire was driven to the edge of civil war. It was the Thousand Temples that <strong>intervened to prevent open conflict</strong>, brokering a resolution that preserved imperial unity -- though the scars of the crisis persisted for generations.</p>\n<h2 id=\"notable-figures\">Notable Figures</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>High Priest Anton</strong> -- a prominent figure within the current leadership of the Thousand Temples, whose influence extends across both religious and political spheres.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Burnished Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Talons</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"andraste","title":"Andraste, the Holy Dancer","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["andraste","empyrean","deity","saint","holy-dancer","compassion","strength","joy","heron","twin-swords","nasga"],"html":"<h1 id=\"andraste-the-holy-dancer\">Andraste, the Holy Dancer</h1>\n<p>Andraste is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title of the Holy Dancer. Her spheres of divine influence encompass compassion, strength, and joy — a trinity of virtues that reflects the Empyrean understanding that true strength is not cold or joyless but is expressed through the fullness of lived experience. She is the goddess who teaches that the body is not merely a vessel for the soul but an instrument through which divine virtue is enacted in the world. To dance is to move with purpose, to feel deeply, and to endure — and so the Holy Dancer embodies all three.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"twin-swords\">Twin Swords</h3>\n<p>Andraste&#39;s holy symbol is a pair of twin swords, crossed at the blade. The twin swords represent the duality at the heart of her nature — compassion and strength, gentleness and ferocity, the capacity to comfort and the capacity to defend. A single sword is a weapon; twin swords are a dance. The symbol reminds the faithful that compassion without the strength to act upon it is mere sentiment, and strength without compassion to guide it is mere violence. The Holy Dancer carries both, and her followers are called to do the same.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-heron\">The Heron</h3>\n<p>The heron is Andraste&#39;s sacred animal. Herons are creatures of extraordinary grace and patience — they stand motionless in still water for hours before striking with sudden, decisive precision. This mirrors Andraste&#39;s teaching that joy and compassion are not passive states but require discipline, awareness, and the willingness to act decisively when the moment demands it. The heron is also a creature of liminality, dwelling at the boundary between water and land, sky and earth — a fitting companion for a goddess whose domain spans the full range of bodily experience.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"compassion\">Compassion</h3>\n<p>Andraste&#39;s compassion is not a soft or sentimental thing. It is the fierce, active compassion of one who sees suffering and moves to address it — not through prayer alone but through direct action. The Holy Dancer teaches that to witness pain and do nothing is a failure of virtue, that compassion demands the courage to intervene, to protect, to heal. Her followers are called to be present in moments of suffering, to offer not merely words of comfort but the strength of their hands and the resolve of their hearts.</p>\n<h3 id=\"strength\">Strength</h3>\n<p>Strength, in Andraste&#39;s teaching, is inseparable from compassion. It is the physical and spiritual capacity to act upon one&#39;s convictions, to stand firm when others falter, to carry burdens that would crush lesser wills. The Holy Dancer does not teach passive endurance but active, joyful engagement with the challenges of existence. Her strength is the strength of the dancer — not the brute force of the battering ram but the controlled, purposeful power of a body trained to move with intention and grace.</p>\n<h3 id=\"joy\">Joy</h3>\n<p>Joy is the third and perhaps most distinctive of Andraste&#39;s spheres. In the theology of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>, joy is not mere happiness or pleasure but a profound spiritual state — the recognition that life, with all its suffering and struggle, is fundamentally beautiful and worthy of celebration. The Holy Dancer teaches that joy is an act of defiance against the entropy and despair that the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> powers seek to spread, that to dance in the face of darkness is itself a form of worship and resistance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> himself, Andraste is no longer worshipped as a goddess in her own right within the orthodox practice of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>. Following the theological consolidation that elevated <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> to the position of supreme and singular deity, the lesser Empyrean gods were reinterpreted as Saints — mortal exemplars of divine virtue who achieved transcendence through their embodiment of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>. Andraste is now venerated as Saint Andraste, the patron saint of compassion, dancers, healers, and those who serve others through physical labor and bodily sacrifice.</p>\n<p>Despite this formal demotion, devotion to Andraste remains deeply embedded in the popular religion of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Shrines to the Holy Dancer can be found in healing houses, dance halls, and the quarters of midwives and surgeons. Soldiers pray to her before battle — not for victory, which belongs to <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and <a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hector</a>, but for the strength to show mercy to the defeated and compassion to the wounded. Her feast day is celebrated with communal dances, charitable acts, and the ritual crossing of twin swords above the heads of the faithful.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cthonic-mirror-nasga\">Cthonic Mirror: Nasga</h2>\n<p>Andraste&#39;s Cthonic counterpart is <a href=\"#/page/nasga\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nasga</a>, the Mistress of Pain and Pleasure. Both deities operate within the domain of the body&#39;s experience — sensation, physicality, the raw immediacy of flesh and nerve. Where Andraste teaches that bodily experience is sanctified through compassion, strength, and joy, Nasga teaches that the body is an instrument of desire and domination, that pain and pleasure are the only truths that matter, and that the strongest are those who can both inflict and endure the most extreme sensations.</p>\n<p>The mirror between Andraste and Nasga is one of the most theologically significant pairings in the Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology. It illustrates the fundamental Empyrean teaching that every virtue has a shadow, every divine truth a dark reflection. The same raw material of bodily experience that Andraste sanctifies through compassion, Nasga corrupts through obsession. The faithful are warned that the line between Andraste&#39;s joy and Nasga&#39;s pleasure is thinner than most would like to admit.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/nasga\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nasga</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hector</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"bel","title":"Bel, the Slaughterprince","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["bel","cthonic","deity","slaughterprince","lord-of-war","war","conquest","blood","manticore","black-gauntlet","bel-tharach","earth-hunger","argolle","dunwick","seros"],"html":"<h1 id=\"bel-the-slaughterprince\">Bel, the Slaughterprince</h1>\n<p>Bel is one of the seven <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, known by the titles of the Slaughterprince and the Lord of War. His spheres of divine influence encompass war, conquest, and blood — the raw, unrestrained violence that the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a> celebrates as the purest expression of will and the ultimate arbiter of truth. Where the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> war-gods <a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a> and <a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hector</a> teach that warfare must be governed by discipline, honor, and moral purpose, Bel teaches that war is its own purpose — that the strong have the right to take what they can hold, that conquest is the natural state of existence, and that blood spilled in battle is the most sacred offering any being can make.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-black-gauntlet\">The Black Gauntlet</h3>\n<p>Bel&#39;s unholy symbol is a black gauntlet — a mailed fist of dark iron, clenched and ready to strike. The black gauntlet is a deliberate inversion of <a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a>&#39;s burning gauntlet: where Damocles&#39;s fist burns with the divine flame of righteous purpose, Bel&#39;s fist is dark, cold, and purposeless save for the act of striking itself. The black gauntlet represents war stripped of all moral justification — violence as an end in itself, power exercised for no reason other than the capacity to exercise it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-manticore\">The Manticore</h3>\n<p>The manticore is Bel&#39;s sacred animal — a monstrous predator combining the body of a great cat, the wings of a bat, and a tail bearing venomous spines. The manticore is not a natural creature but a thing of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic origin</a>, a being designed for nothing but killing. It hunts not for food or territory but for the pleasure of the hunt itself. In Cthonic theology, the manticore represents the ideal warrior in Bel&#39;s image: a perfect engine of destruction, unburdened by mercy, honor, or any purpose beyond the next kill.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"war\">War</h3>\n<p>War, in Bel&#39;s teaching, is the fundamental state of the cosmos — the natural condition from which peace is merely a temporary and unnatural deviation. The Slaughterprince teaches that <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice did not create a cosmos of order and harmony but a cosmos of contest, where the strong destroy the weak and the survivors inherit a world shaped by their victory. War is not a failure of civilization but the truth that civilization was built to conceal. Every law, every treaty, every declaration of peace is merely a pause in the eternal war — a moment of exhaustion before the next round of bloodshed.</p>\n<h3 id=\"conquest\">Conquest</h3>\n<p>Conquest is war directed toward a specific end: the subjugation of the defeated by the victorious. Bel teaches that conquest is the natural right of the strong — that those who can take territory, enslave populations, and impose their will upon others have earned the right to do so by virtue of their strength alone. This teaching places Bel in direct theological opposition to <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, who holds that authority derives from divine mandate and moral fitness rather than mere power. Both gods claim sovereignty over the will to impose order, but where Seros builds, Bel subjugates.</p>\n<h3 id=\"blood\">Blood</h3>\n<p>Blood is the sacred substance of Bel&#39;s worship — the physical medium through which the Slaughterprince&#39;s power flows and the offering most pleasing to him. Blood spilled in battle is the highest form of sacrifice in Bel&#39;s theology, but blood shed in any context of dominance and submission — ritual sacrifice, blood sport, even the blood of the harvest — carries spiritual significance. The centrality of blood to Bel&#39;s worship connects him to some of the most ancient and persistent religious practices in the known world, including the agricultural blood rites that predate the formal theology of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cthonic-mirror-of-seros\">Cthonic Mirror of Seros</h2>\n<p>Bel is the Cthonic mirror of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> — both gods claim sovereignty over the will to impose order upon the cosmos, but they represent diametrically opposed understandings of what order means and how it should be achieved. Seros imposes order through law, justice, and the cultivation of virtue — he builds, he judges, he illuminates. Bel imposes order through force, conquest, and the elimination of all who resist — he conquers, he subjugates, he dominates.</p>\n<p>The mirror between Bel and Seros is the deepest and most consequential in the entire Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology. It reflects the fundamental question at the heart of all theology and all politics: is order best achieved through justice or through power? Through the consent of the governed or the force of the conqueror? Seros and Bel give opposite answers, and the conflict between those answers has shaped the history of the world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-bel-tharach-agricultural-blood-rites\">The Bel-Tharach: Agricultural Blood Rites</h2>\n<p>In the rural villages of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, particularly in the agricultural communities of the backlands, a form of Bel worship persists that differs dramatically from the martial cult of the Slaughterprince. Known as the <a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel-tharach</a> — the earth-hunger — these rites involve the offering of blood to the soil itself, in the belief that the earth is hungry, that the land demands blood to remain fertile, and that the refusal to feed the earth with blood will result in crop failure, blight, and famine.</p>\n<p>The bel-tharach is ancient — far older than the formal theology of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a>, older perhaps than the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> itself. It is a primal, visceral form of religious practice rooted in the intimate relationship between farming communities and the land they work. The blood offerings are typically animal — a chicken, a goat, a pig slaughtered at planting or harvest time and its blood poured directly onto the fields — but darker traditions persist in isolated communities, and rumors of human sacrifice in service of the earth-hunger have circulated for as long as anyone can remember.</p>\n<p>The fundamental question — whether the agricultural Bel of the bel-tharach and the Slaughterprince of the Cthonic war-cult are the same entity — remains unanswered. Some theologians argue that the earth-hunger is a debased survival of an even older deity whose identity has been absorbed by Bel over the centuries. Others hold that Bel is Bel, that war and harvest are both forms of the same cosmic transaction — the exchange of blood for power — and that the farmer who feeds the earth and the warrior who feeds the battlefield are both, in the end, serving the same hungry god.</p>\n<h3 id=\"bel-worship-in-dunwick\">Bel Worship in Dunwick</h3>\n<p>Bel worship has been documented in <a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a>, where his cult operates with varying degrees of secrecy depending on local conditions and the vigilance of <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple</a> authorities. The presence of Bel worship in settled communities represents a persistent challenge to the Empyrean order — a reminder that the Slaughterprince&#39;s theology of strength and blood resonates with those who feel abandoned by the promises of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and unprotected by the justice of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hector</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel-Earth Hunger</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Awakening</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"bellasarius","title":"Bellasarius, the Father","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["bellasarius","empyrean","deity","saint","the-father","courage","service","fatherhood","horse","eagle","valerian","vestari","empyrean-war","mithrian-empire"],"html":"<h1 id=\"bellasarius-the-father\">Bellasarius, the Father</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;In the name of the Father, the spear finds its mark, and the faithless are made to kneel.&quot;\n— Vestari oath of service</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Bellasarius is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title of the Father. His spheres of divine influence encompass courage, service, and fatherhood — the protective, sacrificial virtues of the patriarch who places himself between his family and the dangers of the world. Bellasarius is the god of those who lead not from behind but from the front, who demand nothing of their followers that they would not first demand of themselves, and who understand that true authority is not a privilege to be enjoyed but a burden to be borne.</p>\n<p>Bellasarius holds a unique position in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> because the historical figure who bears his name — Bellasarius Valerian — is one of the most important mortals in the history of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. The relationship between the god Bellasarius and the mortal Bellasarius Valerian is a subject of theological debate, but the prevailing orthodoxy of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> holds that the mortal was an avatar or vessel of the divine Bellasarius, chosen to enact the god&#39;s will in the material world at the most critical moment in human history.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"eagle-clutching-a-spear\">Eagle Clutching a Spear</h3>\n<p>Bellasarius&#39;s holy symbol is an eagle clutching a spear in its talons — a martial and regal emblem that combines the imagery of divine vision (the eagle, which sees all from above) with the imagery of martial action (the spear, the weapon of the infantry commander who leads from the front). The eagle represents the Father&#39;s watchfulness, his capacity to see threats before they arrive and to act decisively to protect those in his care. The spear represents his willingness to fight, to place himself in harm&#39;s way, to be the first point of contact between his charges and the forces that threaten them.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-horse\">The Horse</h3>\n<p>The horse is Bellasarius&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its strength, loyalty, and the intimate partnership it forms with its rider. The war horse carries its rider into battle, bears the weight of armor and rider without complaint, and charges into danger at the command of its master. In Empyrean theology, the horse represents the ideal of partnership in service — the understanding that the greatest deeds are accomplished not by individuals acting alone but by partners who trust each other absolutely and work together toward a common purpose. The horse also represents the virtue of noble bearing — the capacity to carry oneself with dignity and purpose even in the most desperate circumstances.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"courage\">Courage</h3>\n<p>Courage is the foundational virtue of Bellasarius&#39;s teaching — not the reckless bravery that charges blindly into danger but the considered, purposeful courage of the leader who assesses the threat, weighs the cost, and then acts decisively despite his fear. The Father teaches that true courage is not the absence of fear but the refusal to allow fear to override duty. A father who does not fear for his children is a fool; a father who allows his fear to prevent him from protecting them is a coward. Bellasarius demands that his followers feel their fear fully and then act anyway.</p>\n<h3 id=\"service\">Service</h3>\n<p>Service, in Bellasarius&#39;s teaching, is the essence of leadership. The Father does not reign — he serves. His authority exists not for his own benefit but for the protection and welfare of those in his care. Bellasarius teaches that the leader who uses his position for personal gain has betrayed the most sacred trust that can be placed upon a mortal soul, and that the truest measure of a father&#39;s worth is not what he accumulates for himself but what he provides for his family. This teaching has profound political implications within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, where Bellasarius&#39;s theology serves as the moral foundation for the obligation of the nobility to serve the common good.</p>\n<h3 id=\"fatherhood\">Fatherhood</h3>\n<p>Fatherhood is both literal and metaphorical in Bellasarius&#39;s teaching. Literally, the Father is the patron of fathers, husbands, and all who bear the responsibility of providing for and protecting a family. Metaphorically, fatherhood encompasses any relationship in which one person assumes responsibility for the welfare of others — the commander and his soldiers, the lord and his vassals, the teacher and his students. Bellasarius teaches that fatherhood is the highest calling available to a mortal soul, and that the father who faithfully discharges his duties participates in the same divine act of protection and provision that <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> performs for all of creation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-historical-bellasarius-valerian\">The Historical Bellasarius Valerian</h2>\n<p>The historical Bellasarius Valerian was the great general who, alongside the Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a>, led the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> that overthrew the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> in 663 BE (Before Empire). While <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> provided the spiritual vision and prophetic authority that united the Empyrean faithful, it was Bellasarius who provided the military genius and personal courage that translated that vision into victory on the battlefield. Together, they broke the power of the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a> and liberated the peoples who had lived under Massaran tyranny for generations.</p>\n<p>Following the victory in the Empyrean War, Bellasarius Valerian founded the Mithrian state — the political entity that would eventually grow into the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. He established the principles of governance, military organization, and civic duty that continue to define Mithrian civilization centuries later. His legacy is not merely military but institutional: the Mithrian state is, in a very real sense, his creation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"house-valerian\">House Valerian</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>, one of the <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a> of the Mithrian Empire, claims direct descent from Bellasarius Valerian himself. This claim gives House Valerian an unparalleled legitimacy among the nobility — they are the bloodline of the Father, the living legacy of the man who founded the Empire and whose divine patron is one of the nine Empyrean gods. The political implications of this lineage are immense, and House Valerian has leveraged its ancestral connection to Bellasarius throughout the Empire&#39;s history.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-vestari\">The Vestari</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a> — the elite warrior-aristocrats of the Mithrian Empire — trace their nobility to Bellasarius Valerian. The Vestari tradition holds that Bellasarius established the first Vestari order from among his most trusted companions during the Empyrean War, creating a martial aristocracy bound by oaths of service, courage, and paternal responsibility. To be Vestari is to be a spiritual descendant of Bellasarius, to carry forward the traditions he established, and to embody the virtues of the Father in every aspect of one&#39;s life.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Bellasarius is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Bellasarius is the patron saint of fathers, commanders, founders, and all who bear the weight of leadership. His feast day is one of the most important holidays in the Mithrian calendar — a day of family gatherings, military parades, and the renewal of oaths of service.</p>\n<p>Devotion to Saint Bellasarius is perhaps the most politically significant of all the Empyrean saint cults. His eagle-and-spear emblem adorns the banners of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>, the shields of the <a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a>, and the gates of every military fortress in the Empire. Invocation of Saint Bellasarius is a standard element of coronation ceremonies, military commissions, and the swearing of feudal oaths. He is the patron saint of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> itself — the spiritual father of the nation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"cthonic-faith","title":"The Cthonic Faith","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["cthonic","religion","theology","dark-gods","aurelion","cults","massaran","undeath","awakening","human-sacrifice","thune","veil"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-cthonic-faith\">The Cthonic Faith</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;You are limited by your senses, which pin you to this place, to this time. Your sorrows, your angers, your love — it divides you from what your heart of hearts knows. You are a stranger to yourself. Inside you resides a mote of the Aurellion, implanted within you at the moment of atomic creation. In the end you will find yourself at the beginning. When the Awakening occurs and we stand before Him, at last you will finally know yourself — know him. And the warmth that encompasses you will be the warm blood of the afterbirth of a True Resurrection.&quot;\n— A Cthonic cultist, burned at the stake</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Cthonic faith is not a religion in any sense that a citizen of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> would recognize. It has no central authority, no unified scripture, no ordained priesthood bound by shared doctrine. It is, instead, a tangled web of dark cults, secret traditions, ancient heresies, and forbidden practices — a sprawling, hydra-headed constellation of beliefs united only by their devotion to forgotten and hungering gods and other malevolent primal beings older than memory. Where the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> builds temples of stone and gold, the Cthonic faithful worship in caves, crypts, and ruins. Where the Empyrean faith preaches order, light, and the sanctity of life, the Cthonic traditions embrace darkness, power, consumption, and the annihilation of the weak.</p>\n<p>The Cthonic faith is strictly illegal under <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> law. Its practitioners, when discovered, face execution — typically by burning, a grim irony given the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> theology of cremation. And yet, despite centuries of persecution, the Cthonic traditions endure. They persist in the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar Kingdoms</a>, where they remain the dominant spiritual practice. They survive among the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoans</a>, who carry their dark rites across borders and boundaries. They fester in the forgotten places of the Empire itself — in the deep cellars beneath old cities, in the crypts of ancient families, in the ruins of civilizations that predate the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> by millennia. The documented worship of <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a> in <a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a> is only the most recent and most visible reminder that the Cthonic faith is not a relic of the past but a living, hungry presence within the Empire&#39;s own borders.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-aurelion-a-shared-origin-a-divided-interpretation\">The Aurelion: A Shared Origin, A Divided Interpretation</h2>\n<p>Both Empyrean and Cthonic traditions agree on the fundamental nature of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>. He was the supreme designer of the cosmos, who sacrificed himself in the act of creation. His essence permeates the cosmos and all living things. It is his sacrifice that gives beings their souls and makes the practice of <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">sorcery</a> possible.</p>\n<p>But where the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed himself out of love — to purge the universe of entropy and evil, to separate light from darkness — the Cthonic faith holds a radically different interpretation. In Cthonic theology, the Aurelion sacrificed himself to eliminate weakness. The act of cosmic creation was not an expression of compassion but of dominance — a violent pruning of all that was soft, fragile, and unworthy. The universe that resulted is not a garden tended by benevolent gods but a battleground, a crucible of competition where only the powerful survive and only the strongest are worthy of the Aurelion&#39;s legacy.</p>\n<p>This fundamental theological divergence — sacrifice as love versus sacrifice as dominion — is the fault line upon which the entire spiritual history of the known world has fractured.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-soul-in-cthonic-theology\">The Soul in Cthonic Theology</h2>\n<p>The Cthonic understanding of the soul is perhaps the most profoundly disturbing aspect of the faith to Empyrean sensibilities, and the one that most clearly illustrates the irreconcilable gulf between the two traditions.</p>\n<p>In Cthonic theology, the soul is not a sacred spark destined for peaceful reunion with the divine. It is fuel. It is raw material. It is meat for the grinding.</p>\n<h3 id=\"death-and-consumption\">Death and Consumption</h3>\n<p>Upon death, the Cthonic faith teaches that the soul is consumed — devoured as fuel for new life. There is no gentle weighing, no merciful judgment, no peaceful halls of rest. The soul is seized, broken apart, and fed into the churning engine of creation. Each new life that enters the world contains within it not a single, pristine soul but the remnants of thousands, perhaps millions, of other souls — fragments of the dead, shards of the consumed, sent screaming into the world to feed something more powerful than itself.</p>\n<p>This is not viewed as tragedy by the Cthonic faithful. It is viewed as truth — as the fundamental operating principle of a cosmos designed by a god who valued strength above all else. The strong consume the weak. The powerful grow more powerful by devouring the essence of the less powerful. This is not cruelty; it is the natural order. It is the Aurelion&#39;s design.</p>\n<h3 id=\"no-paradise-no-reincarnation\">No Paradise, No Reincarnation</h3>\n<p>The Cthonic faith offers no paradise, no peaceful afterlife, no comforting promise of reunion with the divine. For the vast majority of souls, death brings only one of two fates: consumption — the dissolution of identity as the soul is broken apart and fed into the cycle of predatory creation — or oblivion, the utter annihilation of self. The only alternative is undeath — the forcible retention of the soul within the material world through necromantic arts, a practice that the Cthonic traditions regard not as abomination but as a legitimate exercise of power. To cheat death through undeath is to demonstrate the kind of strength and will that the Aurelion himself embodied in the act of creation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"soul-consolidation-and-apotheosis\">Soul Consolidation and Apotheosis</h3>\n<p>The ultimate aspiration of the most devoted and powerful Cthonic practitioners is singular apotheosis — the consolidation of enough consumed souls into a single being that it achieves a form of godhood, a restoration of the Aurelion&#39;s original, undivided power. This is the theological justification for centuries of human sacrifice, soul harvesting, and necromantic experimentation: every soul consumed brings the practitioner one step closer to becoming, in essence, a new Aurelion. The cosmos, in this view, is not a place of harmony and balance but an arena of cosmic competition, and the ultimate prize is the throne of creation itself.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-rites-of-the-dead-preservation-and-the-awakening\">The Rites of the Dead: Preservation and the Awakening</h2>\n<p>In direct and deliberate opposition to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> practice of cremation, the Cthonic faith mandates the preservation of the body after death. Bodies are kept intact — buried, interred in crypts, sealed in tombs — so that the physical identity of the deceased is maintained. The corpse is not a discarded husk to be burned; it is a vessel, a repository, a container that must be kept whole for the day of reckoning.</p>\n<p>This practice is rooted in the Cthonic doctrine of <strong>the Awakening</strong> — the prophesied future event in which the Cthonic gods will return to the material world, the barriers between life and death will shatter, and the faithful will enjoy a true, bodily resurrection. Not a spiritual ascension, not a metaphorical reunion with the divine, but a literal, physical resurrection of the flesh. The dead will rise from their crypts. The bones will re-clothe themselves in flesh. The faithful who preserved their bodies will stand again in the light of their hungering gods and be rewarded for their devotion with eternal, embodied life.</p>\n<p>The Awakening is the central eschatological promise of the Cthonic faith — the event toward which all Cthonic practice and sacrifice is ultimately directed. It is the reason bodies are preserved. It is the reason crypts are tended. It is the reason the Cthonic faithful endure persecution, torture, and death at the hands of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> without renouncing their beliefs. To be burned — to have one&#39;s body destroyed in the Empyrean fashion — is, in Cthonic theology, to be annihilated utterly, denied the possibility of resurrection, cast out from the Awakening forever. This is why the Empyrean practice of burning captured Cthonic cultists is regarded not merely as execution but as a form of spiritual genocide.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"human-sacrifice\">Human Sacrifice</h2>\n<p>Human sacrifice is a common practice among the Cthonic faithful. It is not an aberration, not a corruption of the faith by extremists, but a central and theologically justified component of Cthonic worship. The logic is brutally consistent with Cthonic theology: if the strong are meant to consume the weak, if souls are fuel for the powerful, then the deliberate sacrifice of living beings to the hungering gods is simply the most direct and honest expression of the cosmic order.</p>\n<p>Sacrificial rites vary enormously among the different Cthonic cults and traditions, reflecting the faith&#39;s fractured and decentralized nature. Some cults practice elaborate ritual murders with complex symbolic frameworks. Others engage in mass sacrifices. Some reserve the practice for captured enemies; others sacrifice willing devotees who believe their deaths will accelerate their own gods&#39; return. The common thread is the offering of life — of soul, of essence, of the mote of the Aurelion that resides within every living being — to powers that are hungry, ancient, and patient.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cthonic-gods\">The Cthonic Gods</h2>\n<p>The gods of the Cthonic faith are not the orderly, comprehensible deities of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> pantheon. They are forgotten and hungering gods — primal beings older than memory, entities that predate the ordered cosmos and perhaps predate the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice itself. They are worshipped not out of love or gratitude but out of fear, ambition, and the desperate hope that service to these powers will grant the faithful a share of their terrible strength.</p>\n<p>Among the Cthonic gods whose worship has been documented within or near the borders of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a></strong> — The Slaughterprince, whose worship has been documented in <a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a> and whose cult represents one of the most persistent Cthonic presences within Imperial territory.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The full extent of the Cthonic pantheon is unknown and perhaps unknowable, given the faith&#39;s secretive and fragmented nature. New gods — or very old ones — seem to surface with disturbing regularity, emerging from ancient ruins, forgotten texts, and the fevered visions of those who peer too deeply beyond the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cthonic-faith-and-the-veil\">The Cthonic Faith and the Veil</h2>\n<p>The relationship between the Cthonic faith and the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a> — the metaphysical barrier between the material world and the realm Beyond — is intimate, dangerous, and theologically central. <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> sorcery, the most powerful and feared form of <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic</a> in the known world, draws its power from Beyond the Veil, from the chaotic and alien energies that exist outside the ordered cosmos. For Cthonic practitioners, this is not merely a magical technique but a spiritual practice: communion with the Cthonic gods and demons that dwell beyond the Veil is understood as the path to apotheosis, the means by which a mortal soul can transcend its limitations and achieve the kind of singular, consuming power that the Cthonic faith venerates above all else.</p>\n<p>This theological connection between Cthonic worship and Veil-sorcery is one of the reasons the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> regards all unregulated sorcery with deep suspicion. To draw power from Beyond is, in the Empyrean understanding, to traffic with the very forces of darkness and entropy that the Aurelion sacrificed himself to contain. The line between a scholar studying the Veil and a Cthonic cultist seeking communion with hungering gods is, in the eyes of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, vanishingly thin.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-thune-and-the-cthonic-way\">The Thune and the Cthonic Way</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> are perhaps the purest living embodiment of Cthonic theology in practice. Thune society is organized around the principle that the strongest consume and rule the weakest — a social order that mirrors the Cthonic understanding of the cosmos itself. Among the Thune, might is not merely right; it is the only right. Power is its own justification. The weak exist to serve the strong, and the strong exist to consume the weak and grow stronger still. This is not cruelty in the Thune understanding; it is fidelity to the Aurelion&#39;s design, the honest and unflinching acceptance of a universe built on predation and dominance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cthonic-worship-in-the-modern-era\">Cthonic Worship in the Modern Era</h2>\n<p>Despite the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>&#39;s centuries-long campaign of suppression, the Cthonic faith remains a living force in the world. It is still openly worshipped in the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar Kingdoms</a>, where the fall of the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> did not extinguish the old traditions but merely scattered them into a patchwork of competing kingdoms, each with its own Cthonic practices and patron deities. The <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoans</a> carry Cthonic rites and beliefs across the known world, their nomadic existence making them nearly impossible to suppress. And within the Empire itself, Cthonic cults persist in the shadows — patient, hidden, and waiting for the Awakening that their faith promises will come.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Awakening</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar Kingdoms</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoan</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"cthonic-pantheon","title":"Cthonic Pantheon","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["cthonic","pantheon","dark-gods","dirgion","iskara","bel"],"html":"<h1 id=\"cthonic-pantheon\">Cthonic Pantheon</h1>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic faith</a> worships a collection of forgotten, hungering gods and malevolent primal beings older than memory. Unlike the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean pantheon</a>, which has been consolidated under the singular worship of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, the Cthonic gods remain distinct and competitive -- each commanding their own cults, rites, and sacrificial traditions. There is no unified church, no central authority, and no orthodoxy. The Cthonic pantheon is as fractured and predatory as the worldview it represents.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-cthonic-gods\">The Cthonic Gods</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Name</th>\n<th>Titles</th>\n<th>Spheres</th>\n<th>Holy Symbol</th>\n<th>Sacred Animal</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>Dirgion</td>\n<td>Doombringer, Lord of Death</td>\n<td>Death, undeath</td>\n<td>Fiery eye skull</td>\n<td>Vulture</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Iskara</td>\n<td>Mother of Monsters, Demon Queen</td>\n<td>Chaos, darkness</td>\n<td>Ouroboros</td>\n<td>Hydra</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Kaleth</td>\n<td>Dark Watcher, Elder Eye</td>\n<td>Madness, knowledge, entropy</td>\n<td>An eye</td>\n<td>Fungus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bel</td>\n<td>The Slaughterprince, Lord of War</td>\n<td>War, conquest, blood</td>\n<td>Black gauntlet</td>\n<td>Manticore</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Galmorm</td>\n<td>The Poisoner, The Trickster</td>\n<td>Treachery, poison, thievery</td>\n<td>Horned rat</td>\n<td>Rat</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nasga</td>\n<td>Mistress of Pain and Pleasure</td>\n<td>Beauty, pain, lust</td>\n<td>A rose</td>\n<td>Snake</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ravanor</td>\n<td>The Bitter Prince, Horned One</td>\n<td>Rulership, power, tyranny</td>\n<td>Antlered crown</td>\n<td>Stag</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h2 id=\"dirgion-the-doombringer\">Dirgion, the Doombringer</h2>\n<p>Dirgion is the Lord of Death and the patron of undeath. His followers seek to defy the annihilation that awaits all souls by binding themselves to the mortal world through necromantic rites. Of all the Cthonic gods, Dirgion&#39;s influence is perhaps the most feared -- his cults operate in crypts and ossuaries, raising the dead and preserving the bodies of the faithful for the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a>. His symbol, the fiery eye skull, is a mark of dread wherever it is found.</p>\n<h2 id=\"iskara-the-demon-queen\">Iskara, the Demon Queen</h2>\n<p>Iskara is the Mother of Monsters, a primordial force of chaos and darkness. She is credited with the creation of many of the world&#39;s most terrible creatures, and her cults are devoted to the unleashing of entropy upon the ordered world. The ouroboros -- the serpent consuming its own tail -- serves as her holy symbol, representing the endless cycle of destruction and creation that she embodies.</p>\n<h2 id=\"kaleth-the-dark-watcher\">Kaleth, the Dark Watcher</h2>\n<p>Kaleth is the Elder Eye, the god of madness, forbidden knowledge, and entropy. His worshippers seek truths that mortal minds were not meant to contain, and many are driven insane by what they discover. Kaleth&#39;s cults are among the most secretive and intellectually dangerous of the Cthonic traditions. His sacred &quot;animal&quot; is not an animal at all but fungus -- a reflection of his association with decay, parasitism, and the slow dissolution of order.</p>\n<h2 id=\"bel-the-slaughterprince\">Bel, the Slaughterprince</h2>\n<p>Bel is the Lord of War in his most brutal and unrestrained form. Where <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a> of the Empyrean represents war as strategy and cunning, Bel represents war as slaughter, conquest, and the spilling of blood for its own sake. His black gauntlet is raised by warlords and berserkers, and his manticore symbolizes the fusion of predatory cunning with raw destructive force.</p>\n<h2 id=\"galmorm-the-poisoner\">Galmorm, the Poisoner</h2>\n<p>Galmorm is the Trickster, the god of treachery, poison, and thievery. His worshippers operate in the shadows -- assassins, poisoners, thieves, and those who prefer to win through deception rather than strength. The horned rat is his symbol, a creature of cunning survival thriving in the margins of civilization.</p>\n<h2 id=\"nasga-mistress-of-pain-and-pleasure\">Nasga, Mistress of Pain and Pleasure</h2>\n<p>Nasga governs beauty, pain, and lust -- the intoxicating overlap of pleasure and suffering. Her cults are seductive and cruel, drawing followers with promises of ecstasy and binding them with agony. The rose is her symbol, beautiful and thorned, and the snake her sacred animal, hypnotic and venomous.</p>\n<h2 id=\"ravanor-the-bitter-prince\">Ravanor, the Bitter Prince</h2>\n<p>Ravanor is the Horned One, the god of rulership, power, and tyranny. He represents dominion not earned through virtue but seized through force and held through fear. His antlered crown symbolizes the raw, primal claim to sovereignty, and the stag -- proud, territorial, and violent in its contests for dominance -- is his sacred animal. Ravanor&#39;s worship appeals to those who desire power above all else.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon and Saints</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Massar Kingdoms</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"damocles","title":"Damocles, Victor of One Hundred Stratagems","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["damocles","empyrean","deity","saint","victor","war","cunning","victory","fox","burning-gauntlet"],"html":"<h1 id=\"damocles-victor-of-one-hundred-stratagems\">Damocles, Victor of One Hundred Stratagems</h1>\n<p>Damocles is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title Victor of One Hundred Stratagems. His spheres of divine influence encompass war, cunning, and victory — not the brutal, indiscriminate slaughter glorified by the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> war-god <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a>, but the disciplined, intelligent application of force in pursuit of righteous ends. Damocles is the god of the general who wins through superior planning, the strategist who turns an enemy&#39;s strength against him, the commander who achieves victory without unnecessary bloodshed. His hundred stratagems are not merely military tactics but metaphors for the hundred ways that wisdom, applied with courage and cunning, can overcome seemingly insurmountable obstacles.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-burning-gauntlet\">The Burning Gauntlet</h3>\n<p>Damocles&#39;s holy symbol is a burning gauntlet — an armored fist wreathed in flame. The gauntlet represents martial power, the closed fist of disciplined force, while the flame signifies the divine fire of righteous purpose that transforms mere violence into sanctified action. A fist without flame is brutality; flame without a fist is impotent rage. The burning gauntlet is both — controlled, directed, purposeful force illuminated by the light of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and guided by the virtues of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-fox\">The Fox</h3>\n<p>The fox is Damocles&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its legendary cunning, adaptability, and resourcefulness. The fox does not charge its prey head-on as a lion might; it observes, waits, adapts, and strikes when the moment is most favorable. In Empyrean theology, the fox represents the virtue of strategic thinking — the understanding that the greatest victories are won not by the strongest army but by the wisest commander. Fox imagery is common in <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a> heraldry, particularly among scout companies and intelligence officers.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"war\">War</h3>\n<p>Damocles&#39;s domain over war is distinct from the domains of other war-associated deities in the Empyrean and Cthonic pantheons. Where <a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hector</a> embodies the disciplined valor of the individual warrior and <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a> glorifies war as conquest and slaughter, Damocles presides over the art of warfare itself — the grand strategy, the operational planning, the logistical mastery that determines the outcome of campaigns. He is the patron of generals, tacticians, and military theorists, the god invoked not in the chaos of the melee but in the quiet of the command tent where battles are won before the first sword is drawn.</p>\n<h3 id=\"cunning\">Cunning</h3>\n<p>Cunning, in Damocles&#39;s teaching, is not deception but intelligence applied with moral purpose. The Victor of One Hundred Stratagems does not advocate lying, treachery, or dishonorable conduct — these are the domain of <a href=\"#/page/galmorm\" class=\"wiki-link\">Galmorm</a>, the Cthonic Trickster. Rather, Damocles teaches that wisdom demands flexibility, that rigid thinking is the enemy of victory, and that the truly virtuous commander uses every resource at his disposal — including misdirection, feints, and unconventional tactics — to achieve righteous ends with minimum loss of life.</p>\n<h3 id=\"victory\">Victory</h3>\n<p>Victory is the ultimate purpose of Damocles&#39;s teachings — not victory for its own sake, which is the corruption preached by <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a>, but victory in service of justice, order, and the protection of the innocent. Damocles teaches that true victory is achieved when the enemy is defeated, the innocent are protected, and the cost in blood and suffering is minimized. A victory that destroys what it sought to protect is no victory at all.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Damocles is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Damocles is the patron saint of military commanders, strategists, diplomats, and all who seek to resolve conflicts through intelligence and skill rather than brute force. His feast day is marked by war games, strategic competitions, and the recitation of famous stratagems from <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> military history.</p>\n<p>Within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a>, devotion to Saint Damocles remains exceptionally strong. Officers are expected to study the &quot;Hundred Stratagems&quot; — a collection of tactical and strategic principles attributed to the god — as part of their formal training. Temples dedicated to Saint Damocles often double as military academies, and his burning gauntlet is displayed alongside the Winged Sun of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> in war rooms and command posts throughout the Empire.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hector</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/galmorm\" class=\"wiki-link\">Galmorm</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"dirgion","title":"Dirgion, the Doombringer","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["dirgion","cthonic","deity","doombringer","death","undeath","necromancy","vulture","fiery-eye-skull"],"html":"<h1 id=\"dirgion-the-doombringer\">Dirgion, the Doombringer</h1>\n<p>Dirgion is one of the seven <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, known by the titles of the Doombringer and the Lord of Death. His spheres of divine influence encompass death and undeath — the twin aspects of mortality that the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a> reinterprets not as natural transitions to be accepted but as enemies to be conquered through will, power, and forbidden knowledge. Dirgion teaches that death is not the passage to divine judgment that the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> proclaims but an annihilation to be resisted by any means necessary — and that undeath, far from being an abomination, is the ultimate expression of the will to survive.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-fiery-eye-skull\">The Fiery Eye Skull</h3>\n<p>Dirgion&#39;s unholy symbol is a skull with a single fiery eye blazing in its socket — the death&#39;s head that refuses to die, the consciousness that persists beyond the dissolution of the flesh. The fiery eye represents awareness, will, and power maintained even after the body has decayed and crumbled. It is the central image of Dirgion&#39;s theology: that death is not an ending but a transformation, and that those with sufficient will and knowledge can pass through death and emerge on the other side with their consciousness intact and their power magnified. The skull is the reality of mortality; the fiery eye is the refusal to accept that reality.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-vulture\">The Vulture</h3>\n<p>The vulture is Dirgion&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its intimate association with death and its capacity to derive sustenance from what others abandon as dead and worthless. The vulture does not kill; it waits for death to occur and then transforms the dead into fuel for the living. In Cthonic theology, the vulture represents the principle that death is not waste but raw material — that the corpse, properly handled, is not refuse to be buried but a resource to be utilized. This theology provides the spiritual foundation for the necromantic practices that are Dirgion&#39;s most notorious legacy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"death\">Death</h3>\n<p>Death, in Dirgion&#39;s teaching, is the supreme enemy — the final annihilation that all living beings instinctively resist and that the strongest and wisest among them can learn to overcome. The Doombringer rejects the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> teaching that death is a natural and divinely ordained passage to judgment and reward. Instead, Dirgion teaches that death is the ultimate expression of cosmic entropy — the force of dissolution that seeks to unmake everything <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> created — and that resisting death is not a sin but the highest possible act of will and self-assertion.</p>\n<p>This teaching places Dirgion in direct theological opposition to <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, who holds the role of judge of the dead, and to <a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a>, who serves as psychopomp and guide of souls across the threshold. For Dirgion&#39;s followers, the soul that submits to Seros&#39;s judgment and allows Shroud to carry it across the threshold has surrendered — has accepted annihilation and called it salvation. The true warrior against death refuses the crossing entirely.</p>\n<h3 id=\"undeath\">Undeath</h3>\n<p>Undeath is the practical application of Dirgion&#39;s resistance to death — the state achieved by those who have passed through death and emerged on the other side with their consciousness, power, and will intact. Dirgion&#39;s followers seek undeath through a variety of necromantic rites, the specific practices of which vary among different cults and traditions but which share a common theological foundation: the belief that the soul can be anchored to the material world beyond the natural span of mortal life through the application of forbidden knowledge and sufficient will.</p>\n<p>Undeath, in Dirgion&#39;s theology, is not a curse but a triumph — the ultimate victory over the entropy that <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice was meant (in the Cthonic interpretation) to impose upon the universe. The lich, the vampire, the revenant — these are not abominations but exemplars, beings who have achieved what Dirgion demands of all his followers: the refusal to die.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cult-activities\">Cult Activities</h2>\n<p>Dirgion&#39;s cults are among the most feared and reviled religious organizations in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and beyond. They operate in secret, gathering in crypts, ossuaries, catacombs, and any other spaces associated with death and the dead. Their activities center on necromantic rites — the raising and binding of the dead, the creation of undead servants, the research into lichdom and other forms of self-directed undeath, and the study of death&#39;s mechanisms in pursuit of methods to circumvent them.</p>\n<p>The discovery of a Dirgion cult is considered a mark of dread wherever it occurs. The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> treat Dirgion worship as one of the most serious spiritual offenses, and the secular authorities of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> deal with confirmed Dirgion cultists with extreme severity. Despite this, the cults persist — because Dirgion&#39;s central promise, the conquest of death, is perhaps the most seductive promise any deity has ever made.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Awakening</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"empyrean-faith","title":"The Empyrean Faith","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["empyrean","religion","theology","seros","aurelion","flame","thousand-temples","reincarnation","cremation","enador"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-empyrean-faith\">The Empyrean Faith</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;As the flame gives light, so too does it burn. Thus is the soul weighed beneath the eyes of Seros, the Winged Sun, who watches all with measure unerring.&quot;\n— Anton, High Priest of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Empyrean faith is the dominant religious tradition of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, a monotheistic-pantheistic theology centered on the worship of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> — the supreme designer of the cosmos — and the veneration of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, the Winged Sun, as the principal deity of the Empyrean pantheon. It teaches that all existence flows from a single act of divine sacrifice, that the cosmos is a battleground between light and darkness, and that the soul of every living being carries within it a sacred spark destined for eventual reunification with the divine. The Empyrean faith is the state religion of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, enshrined in law, enforced by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, and woven into every facet of Mithrian civic, military, and cultural life.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-aurelion-and-the-cosmic-sacrifice\">The Aurelion and the Cosmic Sacrifice</h2>\n<p>At the heart of Empyrean theology lies the doctrine of the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice. The <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> is understood not as a god among gods, but as the supreme and singular architect of all reality — a being of such incomprehensible totality that the cosmos itself is merely the residue of his self-destruction. Both Empyrean and <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> traditions agree on the fundamental nature of the Aurelion: he was the supreme designer of the cosmos, who sacrificed himself in the act of creation. His essence permeates the cosmos and all living things. It is the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice that gives beings their souls and makes the practice of <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">sorcery</a> possible.</p>\n<p>Where the two faiths diverge — violently and irreconcilably — is in their interpretation of the purpose and meaning of that sacrifice.</p>\n<p>The Empyrean faith teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed himself to purge the universe of entropy and evil, separating light from darkness in the first and most fundamental act of cosmic ordering. Before the sacrifice, all things existed in a state of undifferentiated chaos — a roiling, formless void in which creation and destruction, good and evil, order and entropy were indistinguishable. The Aurelion, in his infinite wisdom and compassion, chose to unmake himself so that light could be divided from shadow, so that life could be distinguished from death, and so that the forces of order and civilization could have a foundation upon which to build. This act of supreme selflessness is the theological model for all Empyrean virtue — the belief that sacrifice in service of something greater than oneself is the highest possible expression of the divine spark within.</p>\n<p>The Empyrean gods — <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> chief among them — are understood as emanations or aspects of the Aurelion&#39;s will, fragments of his divine intention given form and purpose in the aftermath of the sacrifice. They are the architects of order, the advocates of life and civilization, the shepherds who guide living souls toward spiritual purity and eventual reunification with the Aurelion through the great cycles of existence.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-soul-and-its-journey\">The Soul and Its Journey</h2>\n<p>Empyrean theology posits a detailed and carefully ordered cosmology of the soul. Every living being possesses a soul — a mote of the Aurelion&#39;s essence, implanted at the moment of creation. This soul is not merely a metaphysical abstraction; it is the literal substance of divine light, the fragment of the Aurelion that connects each mortal creature to the cosmic whole. It is the soul that allows sentient beings to reason, to love, to create, and — for those with the gift — to channel the <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">Flame</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"death-and-the-weighing\">Death and the Weighing</h3>\n<p>When a living being dies, the Empyrean faith teaches that its soul is ushered to the afterlife, a process overseen by <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> himself. In the afterlife, the soul&#39;s valor and deeds are weighed — literally measured against the virtues of <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a>. This is not a metaphorical process in Empyrean theology but a literal cosmic event: the soul stands before the divine judgment, and its worth is assessed against the totality of its earthly life.</p>\n<p>Noble and heroic souls — those who embodied the seven virtues of the Scale, who lived with honor, courage, compassion, and purpose — pass through this judgment and enter the <strong>Halls of Seros</strong>, a place of peace, radiance, and communion with the divine. In the Halls, these worthy souls rest in serene contemplation, awaiting the ultimate reunification with the Aurelion that the faith teaches will come at the end of all cycles. These souls are not idle; they are venerated as heroes and legends, and many are found to be widely worshipped as <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Saints</a> in their own right, their names invoked in prayer, their deeds recounted in liturgy, their intercession sought by the living.</p>\n<h3 id=\"reincarnation\">Reincarnation</h3>\n<p>Souls that are found wanting — not wicked, but incomplete, unfinished in their journey toward spiritual perfection — are returned to the cycle of mortal life through reincarnation. The Empyrean faith does not view reincarnation as punishment but as opportunity: each new life is a chance to grow closer to the divine ideal, to better embody the virtues of the Scale, to refine the soul&#39;s inner light until it shines brightly enough to pass the weighing and enter the Halls. The number of cycles a soul might endure is unspecified in Empyrean doctrine; some theologians of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> have debated whether the process is infinite or bounded, but no consensus has ever been reached.</p>\n<p>This cyclical understanding of the soul creates a profound Empyrean reverence for life in all its forms. Every living creature, no matter how humble, may carry within it a soul on its journey toward the divine. This is one of the theological foundations for the Empyrean emphasis on compassion, mercy, and the protection of the innocent — any being might be a soul on the cusp of its final incarnation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cremation-and-the-rites-of-the-dead\">Cremation and the Rites of the Dead</h2>\n<p>The practice of cremation is one of the most visible and non-negotiable tenets of the Empyrean faith. The Empyrean faith instructs that bodies be burned upon death, so that the soul can more quickly enter the afterlife where it will be judged. The theological reasoning is precise: the soul, upon departing the body, must journey to the afterlife for its weighing, and the destruction of the physical vessel by fire accelerates this process, freeing the soul from its material anchor and allowing it to ascend unimpeded toward the judgment of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>.</p>\n<p>To allow a body to decay naturally — to leave it unburned, to permit the slow dissolution of flesh — is considered a minor sacrilege, a sign of negligence or ignorance. But to actively prevent the body&#39;s destruction through mummification, embalming, or other methods of preservation is a far graver sin. The Empyrean faith teaches that such practices trap the soul, binding it to the material world and preventing it from completing its journey. This theological position places the Empyrean faith in direct and irreconcilable opposition to the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a>, which mandates the preservation of the body in anticipation of the prophesied <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a>.</p>\n<p>The cremation rites are performed by priests of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, who recite passages from <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a> as the body is consumed by flame. In military contexts, particularly among the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a>, the rites may be performed by a commanding officer if no priest is available, and mass cremations on the battlefield are a grim but common occurrence in the Empire&#39;s many wars. The ashes of the dead are typically scattered or interred in family urns, though the ashes of particularly revered individuals may be preserved in reliquaries within temples.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"centuries-of-secret-worship\">Centuries of Secret Worship</h2>\n<p>The Empyrean faith as it exists today is the product of millennia of persecution, secrecy, and eventual triumphant revolution. For thousands of years, the followers of the Empyrean gods congregated in secret for fear of subjugation from their <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> masters. The worship of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and the other Empyrean gods was forbidden under the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>, driven underground, and punished with death. Empyrean believers met in hidden cellars, in remote caves, in the shadows of the very crypts and ruins that the Cthonic cults claimed as their own sacred spaces.</p>\n<p>During this long period of oppression, the Empyrean faith survived through oral tradition, whispered prayers, and the fierce devotion of a scattered and persecuted community. The gods of the Empyrean pantheon were invoked in hushed tones, their names passed from parent to child in secret, their rites performed in darkness for fear of the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a> and their Cthonic priesthoods. The faith&#39;s survival through these centuries of subjugation is regarded by modern Empyrean theologians as proof of its divine truth — that the light of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> could not be extinguished even by the deepest darkness of Cthonic tyranny.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-prophet-enador-and-the-revolution\">The Prophet Enador and the Revolution</h2>\n<p>The turning point in the history of the Empyrean faith — and indeed in the history of the known world — came with the emergence of the Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a>. Enador is the single most important figure in Empyrean religious history. It was Enador who retrieved the sacred text known as <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a>, a document of immense theological and legal significance that outlined the core beliefs, virtues, and laws of the Empyrean faith. Alongside the Measure and the Scale, Enador also recovered the <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a> grimoire, though the precise relationship between these two texts and the circumstances of their discovery are subjects of intense scholarly debate at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end.&quot;\n— The Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> to the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer King</a> Sebek</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Armed with the divine mandate of the Measure and the Scale, Enador launched a holy war against the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its Cthonic rulers. This was not merely a military campaign but a religious revolution — a cosmic struggle between the forces of light and darkness, order and entropy, civilization and barbarism. Enador&#39;s war was long, brutal, and transformative. Its eventual success — the overthrow of the Massaran Empire and the destruction or scattering of its Cthonic priesthoods — led directly to the founding of <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> and, in time, the establishment of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> itself.</p>\n<p>Enador&#39;s revolution established the Empyrean faith not merely as one religion among many but as the foundational ideology of an entire civilization. The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> is, in a very real sense, the political and military expression of Empyrean theology — a civilization built on the principles of the Measure and the Scale, governed by the light of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, and dedicated to the eternal war against the forces of darkness and entropy that the Cthonic faiths represent.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-empyrean-pantheon-and-the-rise-of-saints\">The Empyrean Pantheon and the Rise of Saints</h2>\n<p>Throughout the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, the worship of Empyrean gods besides <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> is extremely rare. In the centuries since the founding of the Empire, the Mithrians have effectively supplanted most of the Empyrean mythological tradition with the singular worship of Seros, the Winged Sun, the Unconquered Sun, the Silent One. The other gods of the Empyrean pantheon — once vibrant figures of worship and devotion — have been largely forgotten, relegated to ancient texts and the debate halls of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>, where they are discussed as subjects of historical and philosophical interest rather than objects of living faith.</p>\n<p>In their place, a pantheon of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Saints</a> has arisen. Saints are mortal individuals, posthumously anointed by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, who in life exhibited the seven virtues of <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a> to an extraordinary degree. These Saints have become, in practice, minor gods to the Serosian faithful — their names invoked in prayer, their intercession sought in times of need, their lives held up as models of virtue and devotion. Several militant orders have been founded in the names of particular Saints, and the cult of the Saints is one of the most vibrant and dynamic aspects of contemporary Empyrean worship.</p>\n<p>The one significant exception to the dominance of Seros worship is the veneration of the Empyrean god <a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a> among the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a>, particularly the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a>. Shroud&#39;s worship persists in military culture as a patron of soldiers, of those who walk in the shadow of death, and of those who must do grim and necessary work in the service of the light.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-flame\">The Flame</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">Flame</a> is the priestly magic of the Empyrean faith — a manifestation of divine power channeled through the virtue and spiritual purity of the practitioner. Unlike the arcane sorcery drawn from the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a>, the Flame is not a learned skill in any conventional sense. It cannot be studied from textbooks, memorized from formulae, or acquired through intellectual effort alone. The Flame is channeled through virtue — through the living embodiment of the principles outlined in <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a>.</p>\n<p>This creates a profound tension within the institutional structure of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>. The Flame is the most visible and dramatic proof of the Empyrean faith&#39;s divine truth — when a priest of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> calls upon the Flame and light answers, it is taken as direct evidence of the god&#39;s favor and the practitioner&#39;s worthiness. And yet the Thousand Temples barely teach the Flame in any formal sense, because the consensus among Empyrean theologians is that it cannot be taught — it must be lived. A priest who walks the path of the Measure and the Scale, who genuinely embodies the seven virtues, who burns with sincere devotion and righteous purpose, may find the Flame answering their call. A priest who merely memorizes the words and performs the rituals without inner transformation will find only silence.</p>\n<p>This doctrine means that the ability to channel the Flame is, in practice, vanishingly rare even among the ordained clergy of the Thousand Temples. Many priests serve their entire lives without ever manifesting it. Those who do are regarded with tremendous reverence and are often fast-tracked to positions of authority within the Temple hierarchy, or held up as candidates for eventual Sainthood.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Saints</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"empyrean-pantheon","title":"Empyrean Pantheon and Saints","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["empyrean","pantheon","gods","saints","seros"],"html":"<h1 id=\"empyrean-pantheon-and-saints\">Empyrean Pantheon and Saints</h1>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a> originally encompassed a full pantheon of gods, each governing distinct aspects of mortal life and the cosmic order. In the modern <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> has risen to overwhelming dominance, and most of the other Empyrean gods are now venerated as Saints rather than actively worshipped as deities. Their divine origins have been reframed by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> as legendary mortal lives of extraordinary virtue.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-empyrean-gods\">The Empyrean Gods</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Name</th>\n<th>Titles</th>\n<th>Spheres</th>\n<th>Holy Symbol</th>\n<th>Sacred Animal</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">seros</td>\n<td>Seros</span></td>\n<td>The Silent One, The Unconquered Sun</td>\n<td>Light, law, civilization</td>\n<td>Winged sun</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Andraste</td>\n<td>The Holy Dancer</td>\n<td>Compassion, strength, joy</td>\n<td>Twin swords</td>\n<td>Heron</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Damocles</td>\n<td>Victor of One Hundred Stratagems</td>\n<td>War, cunning, victory</td>\n<td>Burning gauntlet</td>\n<td>Fox</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Eramus</td>\n<td>The Shepherd</td>\n<td>Wisdom, duty, steadfastness</td>\n<td>Shepherd&#39;s crook</td>\n<td>Dog</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Euphrosyne</td>\n<td>The Candle</td>\n<td>Hope, willpower, resolve</td>\n<td>A candle</td>\n<td>Gazelle</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hector</td>\n<td>The Bronze Lord</td>\n<td>Discipline, martial prowess, justice</td>\n<td>Crossed swords</td>\n<td>Lion</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mina</td>\n<td>The Hand</td>\n<td>Grace, art, beauty</td>\n<td>A chisel</td>\n<td>Swan</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sagramore</td>\n<td>The Martyr</td>\n<td>Loyalty, endurance, sacrifice</td>\n<td>Broken manacles</td>\n<td>Ox</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bellasarius</td>\n<td>The Father</td>\n<td>Courage, service, fatherhood</td>\n<td>Eagle clutching spear</td>\n<td>Horse</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">enador</td>\n<td>Enador</span></td>\n<td>The Light in the Dark</td>\n<td>Vision, journey, time</td>\n<td>Open scroll</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h2 id=\"from-gods-to-saints\">From Gods to Saints</h2>\n<p>The transition from active godhood to saintly veneration was not sudden or violent. As Mithrian culture centralized its religious identity around <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, the other Empyrean gods were gradually absorbed into a framework of sainthood administered by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>. Their myths were reinterpreted as hagiographies -- tales of mortal individuals whose lives so perfectly embodied the virtues of <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Scale</a> that they earned a place of honor in the afterlife and the devotion of the faithful.</p>\n<p>Saints are posthumously anointed by the Thousand Temples. To qualify, an individual must have exhibited the seven virtues of the Scale to an extraordinary and well-documented degree. The process of canonization involves extensive theological review, testimony from witnesses, and approval by the senior clergy.</p>\n<h2 id=\"notable-saints\">Notable Saints</h2>\n<p>Many of the figures listed above now hold the title of Saint within the Thousand Temples. Andraste is invoked by those seeking courage tempered with compassion. Damocles is the patron of military strategists. Eramus is beloved by scholars, magistrates, and teachers. Sagramore is honored by prisoners, laborers, and all who endure suffering with dignity.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a>, the Light in the Dark, holds a unique position as both a saint and a historical prophet. It was Enador who rediscovered <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Measure and the Scale</a> along with the <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a> grimoire, fundamentally shaping the religious and legal foundations of the Mithrian Empire.</p>\n<p>Bellasarius, the Father, is widely venerated as a model of paternal duty -- courage wielded in service to family, community, and the state. His eagle-and-spear symbol is common in households and military barracks alike.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-living-tradition\">The Living Tradition</h2>\n<p>While the old gods may no longer command the fervent worship they once did, their influence persists. Their symbols adorn temples and armor. Their stories are told to children. Their virtues shape the moral framework of Mithrian society through <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Scale</a>. In this sense, the Empyrean pantheon has not died -- it has been transformed, its divine fire redistributed across a constellation of saintly exemplars orbiting the singular radiance of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros, the Winged Sun</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"enador","title":"Enador, the Light in the Dark","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["enador","empyrean","deity","saint","prophet","light-in-the-dark","vision","journey","time","owl","scroll","empyrean-war","measure-and-the-scale","anthyllium","massaran-empire","sorcerer-kings"],"html":"<h1 id=\"enador-the-light-in-the-dark\">Enador, the Light in the Dark</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end.&quot;\n— The Prophet Enador to <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer King</a> Sebek</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Enador is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title the Light in the Dark. His spheres of divine influence encompass vision, journey, and time — the prophetic virtues of those who see what others cannot, who venture into darkness to retrieve what the world has lost, and who understand the long arc of time as a force that shapes the destiny of nations and souls alike. Enador is the god of prophets, pilgrims, scholars, and seekers — those who leave the safety of the known world to pursue truth in places where truth has been buried, forgotten, or deliberately hidden.</p>\n<p>Enador occupies a singular position in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> because the historical Enador was not merely a mortal vessel of the divine but the Prophet of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> himself — the individual chosen by the Unconquered Sun to retrieve the most sacred artifacts of the faith and to lead the holy war that would reshape the world. No other figure in Empyrean history, save perhaps <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius</a> Valerian, has had so direct and measurable an impact on the course of civilization.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-open-scroll\">The Open Scroll</h3>\n<p>Enador&#39;s holy symbol is an open scroll — a document unrolled and ready to be read. The scroll represents knowledge recovered, wisdom revealed, truth brought from darkness into light. It is deliberately distinguished from a closed or sealed scroll, which would represent hidden or forbidden knowledge. Enador&#39;s scroll is open — his truth is meant to be shared, studied, and applied. The symbol also references Enador&#39;s most famous act: the recovery of <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a>, the ancient grimoire that contained the formulae of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, alongside <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a>, the sacred text of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-owl\">The Owl</h3>\n<p>The owl is Enador&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its association with wisdom, night-vision, and the ability to see clearly in darkness. The owl hunts when others sleep, perceives what others cannot, and moves through the night with silent, purposeful precision. In Empyrean theology, the owl represents the prophet&#39;s gift — the capacity to perceive truths hidden from ordinary sight, to navigate the darkness of ignorance and deception, and to bring back knowledge that illuminates the path forward for those who cannot see it themselves.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"vision\">Vision</h3>\n<p>Vision, in Enador&#39;s teaching, is the capacity to perceive truth beyond the surface of things — to see the hidden patterns, the buried connections, the long-term consequences that escape ordinary perception. Enador&#39;s vision is not merely physical sight but spiritual and intellectual penetration: the ability to discern <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s design in the apparent chaos of the world, to read the signs of the times, and to understand what must be done when others are paralyzed by confusion or fear. The Prophet teaches that vision is both a gift and a discipline — some are born with keener sight than others, but all can sharpen their perception through study, contemplation, and the cultivation of inner silence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"journey\">Journey</h3>\n<p>The journey is central to Enador&#39;s mythology and theology. His greatest act — the recovery of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> and <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a> — was accomplished through a physical and spiritual journey of immense difficulty and danger. Enador teaches that truth is not found in comfort and safety but in the willingness to leave the known behind, to venture into hostile territory, and to endure the hardships of the road in pursuit of something greater than personal security. Every pilgrimage undertaken by the Empyrean faithful is, in some sense, a recapitulation of Enador&#39;s original journey.</p>\n<h3 id=\"time\">Time</h3>\n<p>Time is the most esoteric of Enador&#39;s spheres — the understanding that the cosmos unfolds according to patterns and rhythms that operate on scales far beyond the span of a single human life. The Prophet teaches that patience is not passivity but the recognition that some truths can only be revealed through the passage of time, that some victories can only be won by those willing to plan and labor across generations, and that the ultimate triumph of light over darkness is not a single decisive battle but a long, patient process of recovery, restoration, and renewal.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-prophets-great-work\">The Prophet&#39;s Great Work</h2>\n<h3 id=\"recovery-of-the-sacred-texts\">Recovery of the Sacred Texts</h3>\n<p>Enador&#39;s defining act was the recovery of two texts of immeasurable importance: <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a> — the sacred scripture of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> that codifies the moral and theological foundations of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> — and <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a> — the ancient grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality, the foundational text of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>. These texts had been lost, hidden, or suppressed during the long centuries of the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>&#39;s dominion, and their recovery was essential to the spiritual and intellectual renewal that made the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> possible.</p>\n<p>The circumstances of the recovery — where the texts were found, what Enador endured to retrieve them, what forces opposed him — are the subject of extensive hagiographic literature within the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, though the precise historical details are debated by scholars.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-empyrean-war\">The Empyrean War</h3>\n<p>Armed with the recovered texts and the prophetic authority of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> himself, Enador led the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> alongside the general <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius</a> Valerian. This was the great holy war that overthrew the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a> in 663 BE (Before Empire). Enador provided the spiritual vision, the prophetic legitimacy, and the theological framework that united the diverse peoples suffering under Massaran tyranny into a single, unified force. <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius</a> provided the military genius to translate that vision into battlefield victory.</p>\n<p>The Empyrean War was not merely a political revolution but a cosmic event — the moment when the forces of Empyrean light decisively broke the power of the sorcerer-tyrants who had ruled through <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> bargains and arcane oppression. Enador&#39;s famous warning to Sorcerer King Sebek — that mercy has its end — is one of the most quoted passages in Empyrean scripture.</p>\n<h3 id=\"founding-of-mithra-city\">Founding of Mithra City</h3>\n<p>The victory in the Empyrean War led directly to the founding of <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> and, eventually, the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Enador&#39;s holy war created the conditions for Bellasarius Valerian to establish the Mithrian state, and the theological and legal principles articulated by Enador in the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> became the moral and legal foundation of the new civilization. In this sense, Enador is not merely a prophet but the co-founder of Mithrian civilization itself.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Enador is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Enador is the patron saint of prophets, scholars, pilgrims, and seekers of lost knowledge. His feast day is marked by scholarly gatherings, the reading of sacred texts, and the departure of pilgrimages to holy sites associated with his journey.</p>\n<p>Devotion to Saint Enador is particularly strong among the clergy of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, among scholars and mages of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, and among those who undertake pilgrimages. His open scroll is displayed in libraries, scriptoriums, and lecture halls, and students of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> traditionally offer a prayer to the Prophet before beginning their studies — for it was Enador who recovered the knowledge they seek to master.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"eramus","title":"Eramus, the Shepherd","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["eramus","empyrean","deity","saint","shepherd","wisdom","duty","steadfastness","dog","shepherds-crook"],"html":"<h1 id=\"eramus-the-shepherd\">Eramus, the Shepherd</h1>\n<p>Eramus is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title of the Shepherd. His spheres of divine influence encompass wisdom, duty, and steadfastness — the quiet, unglamorous virtues that hold civilizations together long after the heroes and conquerors have passed into legend. Eramus is not the god of great deeds or dramatic revelations but the god of the long watch, the patient hand, the steady voice that guides the faithful through the ordinary trials of daily life. He is the god of magistrates and teachers, of farmers and parents, of all who bear the weight of responsibility without complaint and carry it faithfully to the end.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-shepherds-crook\">The Shepherd&#39;s Crook</h3>\n<p>Eramus&#39;s holy symbol is a shepherd&#39;s crook — the simple, curved staff used by herders to guide and protect their flocks. The crook is simultaneously a tool of gentle guidance and firm correction: it can draw a wandering sheep back to the flock, and it can fend off a wolf at the gate. This duality is central to Eramus&#39;s teaching — that wisdom without the willingness to enforce it is mere philosophizing, and that authority without wisdom is tyranny. The shepherd&#39;s crook is one of the humblest symbols in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a>, deliberately eschewing the martial imagery of swords and gauntlets for a tool associated with common labor.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-dog\">The Dog</h3>\n<p>The dog is Eramus&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its loyalty, vigilance, and devotion to duty. The sheepdog does not seek glory or recognition; it works tirelessly, endures hardship without complaint, and places the safety of the flock above its own comfort. In Empyrean theology, the dog represents the ideal of selfless service — the willingness to serve not because service brings reward but because service is its own justification. Dogs are welcomed in temples dedicated to Saint Eramus, and it is considered deeply auspicious for a stray dog to appear at a threshold during times of uncertainty.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"wisdom\">Wisdom</h3>\n<p>Eramus&#39;s wisdom is practical rather than esoteric. It is not the arcane knowledge of <a href=\"#/page/kaleth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kaleth</a> or the visionary insight of <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> but the accumulated, hard-won understanding that comes from years of patient observation, careful thought, and honest engagement with the world as it is. The Shepherd teaches that true wisdom begins with the acknowledgment of one&#39;s own ignorance and grows through the disciplined practice of listening, questioning, and reflecting. His followers are counselors, teachers, and judges — those whose wisdom serves others rather than aggrandizing themselves.</p>\n<h3 id=\"duty\">Duty</h3>\n<p>Duty is the cornerstone of Eramus&#39;s teaching. The Shepherd holds that every living being has obligations — to family, to community, to the divine order established by <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> and maintained by <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. These obligations are not burdens to be resented but callings to be embraced, for it is through the faithful performance of duty that the individual soul aligns itself with the cosmic order and earns its place in the divine plan. Eramus teaches that the smallest duty faithfully performed is more pleasing to the gods than the grandest gesture undertaken for selfish reasons.</p>\n<h3 id=\"steadfastness\">Steadfastness</h3>\n<p>Steadfastness is the virtue that binds wisdom and duty together. It is the refusal to abandon one&#39;s post, to betray one&#39;s principles, to surrender to despair when the task grows difficult and the end seems far away. The Shepherd endures. He does not flee when the wolves come; he does not falter when the storm breaks. He stands, crook in hand, and does what must be done. In a cosmos threatened by the entropy and chaos of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> powers, steadfastness is perhaps the most necessary of all virtues.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Eramus is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Eramus is the patron saint of teachers, magistrates, shepherds, farmers, and all who serve in positions of quiet authority. His feast day is celebrated with community gatherings, the settling of disputes, and the recognition of those who have served their communities with distinction.</p>\n<p>Devotion to Saint Eramus is particularly strong in rural areas of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, where his practical, duty-centered theology resonates with the rhythms of agricultural life. Village priests often model their ministry on Eramus&#39;s example, serving as counselors, mediators, and educators as much as spiritual leaders. The Shepherd&#39;s crook is a common sight above the doors of schoolhouses, courtrooms, and village halls throughout the Empire&#39;s provinces.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"euphrosyne","title":"Euphrosyne, the Candle","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["euphrosyne","empyrean","deity","saint","candle","hope","willpower","resolve","gazelle","flame"],"html":"<h1 id=\"euphrosyne-the-candle\">Euphrosyne, the Candle</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Each living being carries a spark of the Aurelion within its soul. To embody the Measure and the Scale you can reshape the world with your soul&#39;s fire.&quot;\n— Euphrosyne</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Euphrosyne is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title of the Candle. Her spheres of divine influence encompass hope, willpower, and resolve — the inner virtues that sustain the faithful when external circumstances offer no comfort, when the darkness is total and the path forward invisible. Euphrosyne is the goddess of the single flame that refuses to be extinguished, the last light burning in the deepest night. She teaches that the spark of the divine — the fragment of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> that resides within every living soul — is sufficient to overcome any darkness, provided the will to carry it forward does not falter.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-candle\">The Candle</h3>\n<p>Euphrosyne&#39;s holy symbol is a single lit candle — the simplest, most fragile source of light imaginable. A candle can be extinguished by a gust of wind, drowned by a splash of water, smothered by a careless hand. And yet a single candle, carefully tended, can illuminate a room, guide a traveler through darkness, or kindle a bonfire that warms a hundred souls. The candle represents the Empyrean teaching that the smallest spark of divine virtue, nurtured through willpower and resolve, can overcome seemingly infinite darkness. The symbol is deliberately humble — not a blazing sun or a roaring fire but a single, quiet flame that burns because someone chose to light it and refuses to let it die.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-gazelle\">The Gazelle</h3>\n<p>The gazelle is Euphrosyne&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its grace, speed, and remarkable endurance. Gazelles are creatures of the open plain — exposed, vulnerable, with no armor or weapons save their speed and their unbreakable will to survive. They do not fight their predators; they outrun them, outlast them, refuse to surrender to exhaustion or despair. In Empyrean theology, the gazelle represents the virtue of hope in action — not passive wishing but the active, tireless pursuit of survival and freedom against overwhelming odds.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"hope\">Hope</h3>\n<p>Hope, in Euphrosyne&#39;s teaching, is not optimism — it is not the belief that things will improve or that circumstances will change. Hope is the decision to act as though the light matters even when the darkness seems total. It is a choice, not a feeling, and it requires the same discipline and courage as any martial virtue. The Candle teaches that despair is the ultimate victory of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> powers — that to surrender hope is to extinguish the spark of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> within one&#39;s own soul and to hand that territory to the forces of entropy and darkness without a fight.</p>\n<h3 id=\"willpower\">Willpower</h3>\n<p>Willpower is the fuel that keeps the candle burning. Euphrosyne teaches that the divine spark within every soul is not self-sustaining — it must be actively maintained through an act of will, through the conscious decision to align oneself with the virtues of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> and to resist the temptations of despair, apathy, and surrender. Willpower is not stubbornness or obstinacy; it is the directed, purposeful application of inner strength toward righteous ends. It is what separates the saint from the merely pious, the hero from the merely brave.</p>\n<h3 id=\"resolve\">Resolve</h3>\n<p>Resolve is willpower sustained over time — the commitment to continue when hope is thin and the will is exhausted. Euphrosyne&#39;s resolve is not the dramatic courage of the battlefield but the quiet, grinding determination of the long siege, the endless march, the years of patient labor toward a goal that may never be reached. She teaches that the greatest acts of virtue are not the spectacular ones but the sustained ones — the faithful who keep the candle lit not for a moment but for a lifetime.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-flame\">The Flame</h2>\n<p>Euphrosyne&#39;s teachings are intimately connected to the priestly magic known as <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a> — the divine power channeled through virtue, sacrifice, and righteous purpose. Her famous declaration that every living being carries a spark of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> within its soul is one of the foundational texts of Flame theology. It is Euphrosyne who articulated the principle that divine magic is not drawn from external sources — not from the geometric patterns of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> or the alien energies beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a> — but from the fire that burns within the soul itself. To embody the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> is to fan that spark into a conflagration capable of reshaping reality.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> barely teach <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a> in the current era, but Euphrosyne&#39;s words remain the theological cornerstone for those rare priests and paladins who still wield it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Euphrosyne is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a goddess in her own right. Saint Euphrosyne is the patron saint of the desperate, the imprisoned, the besieged, and all who endure suffering with unbroken will. Her feast day is celebrated by the lighting of candles in windows — one for each member of the household — and by prayers for those who suffer in darkness.</p>\n<p>Devotion to Saint Euphrosyne is especially common among prisoners, refugees, and those facing terminal illness. Her candle appears in the cells of those condemned to execution, in the windows of plague-houses, and in the hands of soldiers marching into battles they do not expect to survive. She is the last saint invoked, the final prayer offered, the light carried into the darkness when all other lights have failed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"galmorm","title":"Galmorm, the Poisoner","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["galmorm","cthonic","deity","poisoner","trickster","treachery","poison","thievery","rat","horned-rat"],"html":"<h1 id=\"galmorm-the-poisoner\">Galmorm, the Poisoner</h1>\n<p>Galmorm is one of the seven <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, known by the titles of the Poisoner and the Trickster. His spheres of divine influence encompass treachery, poison, and thievery — the arts of the weak who survive and prosper through cunning, deception, and the willingness to strike from the shadows when a direct confrontation would mean certain defeat. Galmorm is the god of those who cannot win fairly and so refuse to play fairly — the liar, the assassin, the thief, the poisoner who slips death into a cup of wine and watches with quiet satisfaction as the strong choke on it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-horned-rat\">The Horned Rat</h3>\n<p>Galmorm&#39;s unholy symbol is a horned rat — a rat bearing small, curving horns, an image that combines the association of rats with disease, filth, and secret infestation with the supernatural menace of horns, traditionally a marker of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> power. The horned rat represents Galmorm&#39;s central teaching: that the weak, the despised, and the overlooked are the true inheritors of power. The rat thrives where other creatures perish — in the walls, in the sewers, in the refuse heaps of civilization. It is everywhere, it is indestructible, and it operates entirely outside the notice and control of those who consider themselves its masters.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-rat\">The Rat</h3>\n<p>The rat is also Galmorm&#39;s sacred animal in its natural form — the common rat that infests every city, every ship, every granary and warehouse in the known world. Rats are survivors. They adapt to any environment, exploit any resource, and reproduce with a speed that renders extermination campaigns futile. In Cthonic theology, the rat represents the principle that survival and proliferation, not honor and virtue, are the true measures of success. The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods may claim the lion and the eagle, but it is the rat that has conquered the world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"treachery\">Treachery</h3>\n<p>Treachery is Galmorm&#39;s primary virtue — the willingness to betray trust, break oaths, and exploit the loyalty of others for personal advantage. The Trickster teaches that trust is a vulnerability, that oaths are chains worn by the foolish, and that the only truly free being is the one who refuses to be bound by any commitment that does not serve their own interests. This teaching is anathema to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>, which holds loyalty, honor, and the keeping of oaths as fundamental virtues — and Galmorm&#39;s followers take particular pleasure in exploiting those virtues against the faithful.</p>\n<h3 id=\"poison\">Poison</h3>\n<p>Poison is Galmorm&#39;s preferred instrument — the weapon of the weak against the strong, the tool that renders martial prowess, armor, and fortification irrelevant. A single drop in a cup, a smear on a doorknob, a dusting of powder on a letter&#39;s seal — poison strikes where swords cannot reach, bypasses every defense, and kills with a efficiency that no battlefield can match. Galmorm&#39;s followers are students of toxicology, herbalism, and alchemy, experts in the identification, preparation, and deployment of substances that kill, incapacitate, or manipulate.</p>\n<h3 id=\"thievery\">Thievery</h3>\n<p>Thievery is the redistribution of resources from those who have them to those with the skill and daring to take them — and in Galmorm&#39;s theology, this is not a crime but a correction. The Trickster teaches that property, like power, belongs to whoever is clever enough to acquire it, and that the wealthy and powerful who believe their possessions are secure are simply waiting to be educated. Galmorm&#39;s followers are thieves, burglars, pickpockets, and confidence artists — practitioners of an art that the Empyrean order condemns but that the Cthonic faith celebrates as a demonstration of the principle that cunning is superior to strength.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cult-activities\">Cult Activities</h2>\n<p>Galmorm&#39;s cults are among the most difficult to detect and eradicate, precisely because deception and concealment are the fundamental skills that define his worship. Where the cults of <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a> or <a href=\"#/page/dirgion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dirgion</a> can be identified by their blood-soaked altars and necromantic horrors, Galmorm&#39;s followers leave no trace — or, more accurately, they leave traces designed to mislead. A Galmorm cult might operate for years within a city&#39;s thieves&#39; guild, a merchant house, or even a <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple</a> chapter without detection, its members indistinguishable from their legitimate neighbors.</p>\n<p>The Trickster&#39;s cults are organized in cells, with no member knowing the identities of more than a handful of others. Information is compartmentalized, loyalty is maintained through mutual blackmail rather than genuine devotion, and betrayal — the supreme Galmorm virtue — is simultaneously the cult&#39;s greatest tool and its greatest vulnerability. Galmorm cults frequently self-destruct as members betray each other, only to reform elsewhere with new members and new configurations.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"hector","title":"Hector, the Bronze Lord","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["hector","empyrean","deity","saint","bronze-lord","discipline","martial-prowess","justice","lion","crossed-swords"],"html":"<h1 id=\"hector-the-bronze-lord\">Hector, the Bronze Lord</h1>\n<p>Hector is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title of the Bronze Lord. His spheres of divine influence encompass discipline, martial prowess, and justice — the warrior virtues that the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> holds as essential to the maintenance of cosmic order. Where <a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a> presides over the art of war at the strategic level, Hector embodies the personal virtues of the warrior: the discipline to train relentlessly, the skill to fight with lethal precision, and the justice to wield deadly force only in righteous cause. He is the god of the soldier in the line, the knight on the field, the individual who stands between the innocent and those who would harm them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"crossed-swords\">Crossed Swords</h3>\n<p>Hector&#39;s holy symbol is a pair of crossed swords — an ancient martial emblem representing the readiness to fight and the discipline to fight with honor. Unlike the twin swords of <a href=\"#/page/andraste\" class=\"wiki-link\">Andraste</a>, which signify the duality of compassion and strength, Hector&#39;s crossed swords represent the intersection of martial skill and moral purpose. The crossing point is the moment of decision — where the blade meets the cause, where violence becomes justice or justice becomes violence. The symbol reminds the faithful that the sword is morally neutral; it is the hand that holds it and the cause that guides it that determine whether its use is righteous.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-lion\">The Lion</h3>\n<p>The lion is Hector&#39;s sacred animal, chosen as the supreme symbol of martial courage, strength, and nobility. The lion does not hunt through cunning or ambush — it confronts its prey directly, openly, with raw power and unyielding aggression. In Empyrean theology, the lion represents the ideal warrior: brave without recklessness, powerful without cruelty, dominant without tyranny. Lion imagery is ubiquitous in <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a> heraldry, and the lion&#39;s roar is invoked in battle cries across the Empire&#39;s legions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"discipline\">Discipline</h3>\n<p>Discipline is the foundation upon which all of Hector&#39;s other virtues are built. The Bronze Lord teaches that martial prowess without discipline is mere savagery, and justice without discipline is mere vengeance. Discipline is the daily practice of training the body and mind to respond correctly under the most extreme pressure — to hold formation when every instinct screams retreat, to show mercy when rage demands blood, to maintain honor when dishonor would be easier and more expedient. Hector&#39;s discipline is not the cold, mechanical obedience of a mindless automaton but the hard-won self-mastery of a warrior who has chosen to subordinate personal desire to the demands of duty and justice.</p>\n<h3 id=\"martial-prowess\">Martial Prowess</h3>\n<p>Martial prowess is the practical application of discipline — the ability to fight effectively, to defend the innocent, and to defeat the enemies of order and light. Hector does not glorify violence for its own sake; he teaches that martial skill is a sacred trust, a talent cultivated through years of training and sacrifice that must be employed only in service of righteous cause. The Bronze Lord demands excellence from his followers — not merely adequate competence but relentless pursuit of mastery. A warrior who stops training has betrayed the trust placed in him.</p>\n<h3 id=\"justice\">Justice</h3>\n<p>Justice is the moral compass that directs Hector&#39;s martial virtues toward righteous ends. Without justice, discipline becomes oppression and martial prowess becomes tyranny. The Bronze Lord teaches that the warrior&#39;s ultimate purpose is not victory but justice — that the sword exists to protect the innocent, punish the wicked, and maintain the order established by <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and codified in the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>. Hector&#39;s justice is direct and uncompromising: guilt is punished, innocence is defended, and the strong are held to a higher standard than the weak.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Hector is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Hector is the patron saint of soldiers, knights, guards, and all who bear arms in defense of the innocent. His feast day is marked by martial tournaments, weapons inspections, and the swearing of oaths of service.</p>\n<p>Devotion to Saint Hector is the most widespread of all the Empyrean saints within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a>. Every barracks has a shrine to the Bronze Lord, every regiment carries his crossed swords alongside the Winged Sun of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, and every recruit is taught that martial prowess without honor is an abomination. The military courts of the Empire invoke Saint Hector&#39;s name when passing judgment on soldiers accused of dishonorable conduct, and his crossed swords are displayed prominently in every court-martial chamber.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/andraste\" class=\"wiki-link\">Andraste</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"iskara","title":"Iskara, the Mother of Monsters","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["iskara","cthonic","deity","mother-of-monsters","demon-queen","chaos","darkness","ouroboros","hydra"],"html":"<h1 id=\"iskara-the-mother-of-monsters\">Iskara, the Mother of Monsters</h1>\n<p>Iskara is one of the seven <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, known by the titles of the Mother of Monsters and the Demon Queen. Her spheres of divine influence encompass chaos and darkness — the primordial forces that existed before <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice imposed order upon the cosmos and that continue to press against the boundaries of reality, seeking to reclaim what was taken from them. Iskara is the goddess of things that should not be — creatures born from the corruption of natural forms, monstrosities that defy the categories and laws established by the Empyrean order, beings that exist in defiance of the cosmic design and draw their power from that very defiance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-ouroboros\">The Ouroboros</h3>\n<p>Iskara&#39;s unholy symbol is the ouroboros — the serpent that devours its own tail, the ancient symbol of cyclical destruction and renewal, of entropy feeding upon itself to generate new forms of chaos. The ouroboros represents Iskara&#39;s fundamental teaching: that creation and destruction are not opposites but aspects of the same process, that the ordered cosmos is not a stable structure but a temporary arrangement constantly being consumed and reconstituted by the forces of chaos that underlie it. The serpent eating itself is simultaneously self-destruction and self-creation — the perfect emblem of Iskara&#39;s domain.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-hydra\">The Hydra</h3>\n<p>The hydra is Iskara&#39;s sacred animal — the many-headed serpent that cannot be killed through conventional means, whose severed heads regenerate and multiply. The hydra represents Iskara&#39;s central principle: that chaos is unkillable, that the forces of disorder cannot be permanently defeated because they are woven into the fabric of reality itself. Cut off one head and two grow in its place. Destroy one monstrous incursion and three more emerge from the darkness. The hydra is a theological statement about the futility of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> project — the impossible dream of permanently ordering a cosmos that is, at its foundation, chaotic.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"chaos\">Chaos</h3>\n<p>Chaos is Iskara&#39;s primary domain — not the colloquial chaos of mere disorder or confusion but the metaphysical chaos that predates creation itself. In Cthonic theology, the cosmos was originally a formless void of infinite potential, and <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice imposed structure, law, and limitation upon that void. Iskara represents the void&#39;s refusal to be fully tamed — the persistent pressure of infinite possibility against the finite structures of ordered reality. Her followers believe that the order imposed by the Aurelion is a cage, that the laws of nature are chains, and that true liberation lies in the dissolution of all structure and the return to the primordial chaos from which all things arose.</p>\n<h3 id=\"darkness\">Darkness</h3>\n<p>Darkness, in Iskara&#39;s teaching, is not merely the absence of light but a positive, active force — the original state of the cosmos before <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> separated light from dark, the womb from which all things were born and to which all things will eventually return. Iskara&#39;s darkness is creative, fertile, and dangerous — it is the space where new forms gestate, where mutations and monstrosities take shape, where the rigid categories of the Empyrean order break down and recombine into something unprecedented. The Mother of Monsters does not merely dwell in darkness; she uses it as her workshop, her laboratory, her birthing chamber.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-mother-of-monsters\">The Mother of Monsters</h2>\n<p>Iskara&#39;s most feared aspect is her role as the creator and patron of monsters — beings that violate the natural order established by <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> and maintained by <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. In Cthonic theology, monsters are not errors or corruptions but deliberate creations — living arguments against the Empyrean claim that the cosmos is ordered, lawful, and good. Every chimera, every aberration, every creature that defies natural classification is a child of Iskara, a proof that chaos cannot be fully contained and that the boundaries between species, between forms, between the possible and the impossible, are more permeable than the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> would like to admit.</p>\n<p>Iskara&#39;s cult is feared throughout the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and beyond for its involvement in the creation of monstrous beings through <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic rituals</a>, the breeding of unnatural creatures, and the summoning of entities from beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a>. The Demon Queen&#39;s followers view these acts not as abominations but as sacred works — contributions to Iskara&#39;s ongoing project of demonstrating that order is an illusion and that the true nature of reality is chaos.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Awakening</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"kaleth","title":"Kaleth, the Dark Watcher","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["kaleth","cthonic","deity","dark-watcher","elder-eye","madness","knowledge","entropy","eye","fungus"],"html":"<h1 id=\"kaleth-the-dark-watcher\">Kaleth, the Dark Watcher</h1>\n<p>Kaleth is one of the seven <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, known by the titles of the Dark Watcher and the Elder Eye. His spheres of divine influence encompass madness, knowledge, and entropy — a triad that reflects the Cthonic teaching that ultimate knowledge is inseparable from the dissolution of the mind that contains it. Kaleth is the god of the truth that destroys the knower, the revelation that shatters sanity, the understanding so complete and so terrible that the mind cannot contain it and breaks apart under its weight.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-eye\">The Eye</h3>\n<p>Kaleth&#39;s unholy symbol is a single eye — open, unblinking, staring without context or expression. The eye has no face around it, no lid to close, no tears to shed. It simply watches. It sees everything. And in the act of seeing, it unmakes what it observes. The eye represents Kaleth&#39;s central teaching: that observation is not passive but active, that to truly see something is to change it, and that the ultimate act of seeing — the comprehension of the totality of reality — would destroy reality itself. The eye is both a warning and a promise: a warning to those who seek knowledge without understanding the price, and a promise to those who are willing to pay it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"fungus\">Fungus</h3>\n<p>Kaleth&#39;s sacred organism is not an animal but a fungus — the vast, patient, decentralized networks of mycelium that grow through darkness, decompose the dead, and break down the structures of the living world into their constituent elements. Fungus represents Kaleth&#39;s domain of entropy in its most literal form: the slow, inexorable dissolution of organized matter into formless substrate. But fungus is also a network of information — mycorrhizal webs that connect trees across forests, transmitting chemical signals and nutrients through underground channels invisible to the naked eye. In Cthonic theology, the fungal network is a metaphor for Kaleth&#39;s own consciousness: vast, decentralized, patient, and present everywhere that decay occurs.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"madness\">Madness</h3>\n<p>Madness, in Kaleth&#39;s teaching, is not a disease but a state of perception — the condition that results when a finite mind encounters infinite truth. The Dark Watcher teaches that sanity is a defense mechanism, a set of cognitive walls that the mind erects to protect itself from the unbearable totality of reality. These walls are necessary for survival, but they are also limitations — they prevent the mind from perceiving the true nature of the cosmos, which is vastly more complex, more terrifying, and more beautiful than any sane mind can comprehend. Kaleth&#39;s madness is the demolition of those walls, the flooding of consciousness with raw, unfiltered reality. It is simultaneously destruction and enlightenment.</p>\n<h3 id=\"knowledge\">Knowledge</h3>\n<p>Knowledge is the substance that drives the mind to madness — the actual content of the revelations that Kaleth offers to those who seek him out. Kaleth&#39;s knowledge is not the practical wisdom of <a href=\"#/page/eramus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eramus</a> or the prophetic vision of <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> but something far more fundamental: knowledge of the underlying structure of reality, of the hidden mathematics that govern the cosmos, of the true nature of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice and what it actually created. This knowledge is related to, but distinct from, the formulae of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> — where gnostic geometers work with carefully controlled portions of metaphysical truth, Kaleth offers the whole, unmediated, and uncontrolled.</p>\n<h3 id=\"entropy\">Entropy</h3>\n<p>Entropy is the physical manifestation of Kaleth&#39;s domain — the universal tendency toward disorder, dissolution, and the breakdown of organized structures. In Cthonic theology, entropy is not a flaw in the cosmos but its fundamental nature — the truth that the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> refuses to acknowledge, the reality that all order is temporary, all structures are provisional, and all things will eventually return to the formless potential from which they arose. Kaleth does not cause entropy; he embodies the awareness of it. He is the god who watches everything fall apart and who understands, with perfect clarity, why it must.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cult-activities\">Cult Activities</h2>\n<p>Kaleth&#39;s cults are among the most intellectually dangerous religious organizations in the known world. Unlike the blood-soaked rites of <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a> or the necromantic horrors of <a href=\"#/page/dirgion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dirgion</a>, Kaleth&#39;s worship often begins with genuine scholarly inquiry — the desire to understand the nature of reality more deeply than the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> or the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> permit. Seekers who push too far into forbidden knowledge, who question the comfortable certainties of Empyrean theology, who look too deeply into <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a> and the entities beyond it — these are the souls most vulnerable to Kaleth&#39;s call.</p>\n<p>The result is a cult composed not of thugs and madmen but of scholars, mages, and seekers who have been broken by what they learned. Kaleth&#39;s followers often retain extraordinary intellectual capabilities even as their sanity erodes — they can perceive patterns invisible to others, solve problems that baffle conventional minds, and access knowledge that no living being should possess. But this capability comes at a terrible price: the progressive dissolution of identity, empathy, and connection to the human world. The most advanced of Kaleth&#39;s followers become something barely recognizable as human — vessels of knowledge without the emotional or moral framework to use it responsibly.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eramus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eramus</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mina","title":"Mina, the Hand","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["mina","empyrean","deity","saint","the-hand","grace","art","beauty","swan","chisel"],"html":"<h1 id=\"mina-the-hand\">Mina, the Hand</h1>\n<p>Mina is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title of the Hand. Her spheres of divine influence encompass grace, art, and beauty — the creative virtues through which the divine order is made manifest in the material world. Mina teaches that beauty is not frivolity but a fundamental expression of cosmic truth, that the impulse to create is a reflection of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s original act of creation, and that the artist who shapes stone, paint, music, or word into something beautiful participates in the ongoing work of bringing order and meaning to an imperfect world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-chisel\">The Chisel</h3>\n<p>Mina&#39;s holy symbol is a chisel — the sculptor&#39;s fundamental tool, the instrument by which raw stone is transformed into art. The chisel represents the principle that beauty does not emerge from nothing but is carved from the rough material of the world through skill, patience, and vision. Every block of stone contains a statue; it requires the Hand to reveal it. The chisel also carries a subtle theological message: creation requires destruction. To sculpt is to remove, to cut away, to sacrifice the superfluous in service of the essential. Mina&#39;s art is not additive but reductive — the pursuit of the truth that lies hidden within.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-swan\">The Swan</h3>\n<p>The swan is Mina&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its extraordinary grace and beauty. The swan moves through water with effortless elegance, its visible serenity concealing the ceaseless, powerful motion beneath the surface. In Empyrean theology, the swan represents the ideal of art — the appearance of effortless beauty that in reality demands enormous discipline, training, and labor. The swan also symbolizes transformation: the ugly duckling that becomes the most beautiful of birds, mirroring the artist&#39;s capacity to transform base materials into transcendent works.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"grace\">Grace</h3>\n<p>Grace, in Mina&#39;s teaching, is the quality of moving through the world with awareness, intention, and beauty. It is not mere physical elegance but a spiritual discipline — the practice of bringing conscious attention and aesthetic sensibility to every action, every word, every gesture. The Hand teaches that grace is available to all, not merely to the talented or the privileged, and that the farmer who plows a straight furrow, the mason who lays a true wall, and the mother who braids her daughter&#39;s hair all participate in the same divine impulse toward beauty and order.</p>\n<h3 id=\"art\">Art</h3>\n<p>Art is the highest expression of Mina&#39;s teaching — the creation of works that embody divine truth in material form. The Hand does not distinguish between high art and craft, between the sculptor&#39;s marble masterpiece and the potter&#39;s functional bowl. All creation undertaken with skill, care, and devotion to beauty is sacred. Mina teaches that the cosmos itself is the ultimate work of art — <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s masterpiece, the original creative act from which all subsequent creation flows — and that every artist, in however small a way, continues the work that the Aurelion began.</p>\n<h3 id=\"beauty\">Beauty</h3>\n<p>Beauty, for Mina, is not subjective preference but objective reality — a fundamental property of the cosmos as real and measurable as mass or distance. The Empyrean cosmology holds that beauty is the visible manifestation of divine order, the sensory evidence that the cosmos is structured, meaningful, and purposeful. Ugliness, decay, and entropy are the marks of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> influence — the corruption of form and meaning that the forces of darkness spread wherever they gain purchase. To create beauty is therefore an act of spiritual warfare, a direct challenge to the entropic forces that seek to unmake the world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Mina is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a goddess in her own right. Saint Mina is the patron saint of artists, sculptors, architects, musicians, poets, and all who create beauty through skilled labor. Her feast day is celebrated with exhibitions of art, musical performances, and the dedication of new public works.</p>\n<p>Devotion to Saint Mina is particularly strong among the artisan guilds of <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> and other major urban centers of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Guild halls are decorated with her chisel emblem, and apprentices traditionally offer prayers to the Hand before beginning their first major work. Architects invoke her blessing before laying foundation stones, and it is considered deeply inauspicious to begin construction on a significant building without first dedicating the work to Saint Mina&#39;s grace.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"nasga","title":"Nasga, Mistress of Pain and Pleasure","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["nasga","cthonic","deity","mistress-of-pain","pleasure","beauty","pain","lust","snake","rose","andraste"],"html":"<h1 id=\"nasga-mistress-of-pain-and-pleasure\">Nasga, Mistress of Pain and Pleasure</h1>\n<p>Nasga is one of the seven <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, known as the Mistress of Pain and Pleasure. Her spheres of divine influence encompass beauty, pain, and lust — the domains of sensation, desire, and the body&#39;s capacity for both ecstasy and agony. Nasga teaches that the body is the only truth, that sensation is the only knowledge worth possessing, and that the ultimate expression of power is the ability to control what others feel — to be the source of their pleasure and the author of their pain.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-rose\">The Rose</h3>\n<p>Nasga&#39;s unholy symbol is a single rose — beautiful, fragrant, and armed with thorns that draw blood from the hand that reaches for it. The rose represents the inseparability of beauty and pain in Nasga&#39;s theology: the flower cannot be possessed without the wound, the pleasure cannot be enjoyed without the price. The rose is a trap — it lures with beauty and punishes with pain, and Nasga&#39;s followers believe this is the fundamental mechanism of the cosmos itself. Every pleasure carries a hidden thorn; every beauty conceals a blade. Those who understand this truth control the transaction. Those who do not are its victims.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-snake\">The Snake</h3>\n<p>The snake is Nasga&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its sinuous beauty, its venomous bite, and its ancient association with temptation, sensuality, and forbidden knowledge. The snake moves with a grace that is both mesmerizing and threatening, its beauty and its danger coexisting in a single, fluid form. In Cthonic theology, the snake represents the principle that attraction and danger are the same force — that the most beautiful things are the most dangerous, and that the impulse to reach for beauty despite knowing the danger is the most powerful drive in mortal nature.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"beauty\">Beauty</h3>\n<p>Beauty, in Nasga&#39;s teaching, is not the wholesome, virtue-aligned beauty celebrated by <a href=\"#/page/mina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mina</a> in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> but a weaponized force — the capacity to compel desire, to override rational judgment, and to draw the observer into a transaction they do not fully understand. Nasga&#39;s beauty is the beauty of the lure, the bait, the trap that is irresistible precisely because it is beautiful. Her followers cultivate physical beauty with obsessive dedication, not as an expression of divine order but as an instrument of power and control.</p>\n<h3 id=\"pain\">Pain</h3>\n<p>Pain is the other face of Nasga&#39;s domain — the counterweight to beauty and pleasure, the thorn on the rose. The Mistress teaches that pain is not merely suffering but information — the most honest, most immediate, most undeniable form of communication between one being and another. Pain cannot be ignored, cannot be misinterpreted, cannot be denied. It cuts through all pretense, all social convention, all the elaborate fictions that civilized beings construct to protect themselves from reality. Nasga&#39;s followers study pain with the same devotion that scholars bring to books — learning to inflict it with precision, to modulate it with artistry, and to use it as a tool of domination and transformation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"lust\">Lust</h3>\n<p>Lust is desire stripped of sentiment — the raw, consuming hunger for another person&#39;s body, attention, or submission. Nasga teaches that lust is the most fundamental drive in mortal nature, more powerful than fear, more persistent than ambition, more honest than love. Her followers do not merely indulge lust but weaponize it, using desire as a mechanism of control — both their own desire, which they learn to master and direct with ruthless discipline, and the desire of others, which they learn to provoke, manipulate, and exploit.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cthonic-mirror-of-andraste\">Cthonic Mirror of Andraste</h2>\n<p>Nasga is the Cthonic mirror of <a href=\"#/page/andraste\" class=\"wiki-link\">Andraste</a>, the Holy Dancer. Both deities operate within the domain of the body&#39;s experience — sensation, physicality, the raw immediacy of flesh and nerve. Where Andraste teaches that bodily experience is sanctified through compassion, strength, and joy, Nasga teaches that the body is an instrument of desire and domination, that pain and pleasure are the only truths that matter, and that the strongest are those who can both inflict and endure the most extreme sensations.</p>\n<p>The mirror between Andraste and Nasga illuminates the Empyrean-Cthonic theology&#39;s understanding of physicality. The body is the same — the nerve endings, the muscles, the capacity for sensation — but the meaning assigned to bodily experience is diametrically opposed. Andraste sanctifies the body through compassion; Nasga weaponizes it through desire. The same dance that Andraste performs as worship, Nasga performs as seduction. The same strength that Andraste directs toward protection, Nasga directs toward domination.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/andraste\" class=\"wiki-link\">Andraste</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mina</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Awakening</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"ravanor","title":"Ravanor, the Bitter Prince","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["ravanor","cthonic","deity","bitter-prince","horned-one","rulership","power","tyranny","stag","antlered-crown","sagramore"],"html":"<h1 id=\"ravanor-the-bitter-prince\">Ravanor, the Bitter Prince</h1>\n<p>Ravanor is one of the seven <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, known by the titles of the Bitter Prince and the Horned One. His spheres of divine influence encompass rulership, power, and tyranny — the domains of political authority exercised without moral constraint, of dominion pursued as an end in itself, of the will to rule elevated to the status of a divine imperative. Ravanor is the god of kings who answer to no one, of lords who rule through fear rather than consent, of every form of authority that exists to serve the ruler rather than the ruled.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-antlered-crown\">The Antlered Crown</h3>\n<p>Ravanor&#39;s unholy symbol is an antlered crown — a circlet of royal authority surmounted not by jewels or crosses but by the branching antlers of a great stag. The antlered crown combines the imagery of civilized authority (the crown) with the imagery of primal, natural dominance (the antlers of the stag in rut, which fights other males for supremacy through raw physical contest). The symbol represents Ravanor&#39;s teaching that all political authority, no matter how elaborately dressed in law and custom, ultimately rests on the same foundation as the stag&#39;s dominance over its herd: the willingness and ability to destroy rivals through superior force.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-stag\">The Stag</h3>\n<p>The stag is Ravanor&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for the yearly contest of rut in which males fight for dominance, the right to mate, and supremacy over the herd. The stag&#39;s antlers — which grow, are used in combat, and are shed only to regrow larger the following year — represent the cyclical nature of power: the constant contest, the inevitable challenge, the perpetual need to defend one&#39;s position against rivals. In Cthonic theology, the stag represents the principle that power must be constantly fought for and defended, that authority unchallenged becomes weak, and that the true ruler is the one who can defeat all challengers and maintain supremacy through force of will.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"rulership\">Rulership</h3>\n<p>Rulership, in Ravanor&#39;s teaching, is the natural right of the strong — not a sacred trust conferred by the gods (as the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> teaches) but a prize seized by those with the power and will to take it. The Bitter Prince rejects the Empyrean concept of legitimate authority — the idea that rulers govern by divine mandate, that their authority is conditional upon the faithful discharge of duty, and that the ruled have a right to just governance. In Ravanor&#39;s theology, the only legitimate authority is the authority of the strongest, and the only check on a ruler&#39;s power is the emergence of someone stronger.</p>\n<h3 id=\"power\">Power</h3>\n<p>Power is the substance of Ravanor&#39;s domain — the raw capacity to impose one&#39;s will upon others, to shape the world according to one&#39;s desires, to stand above the mass of ordinary beings and direct their lives according to one&#39;s own vision. The Horned One teaches that power is not a means to an end but the end itself — that the accumulation and exercise of power is the highest possible achievement of the mortal soul, and that those who possess power are under no obligation to use it for any purpose other than the maintenance and expansion of their own dominion.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tyranny\">Tyranny</h3>\n<p>Tyranny is power freed from moral constraint — rulership without accountability, authority without obligation, dominion without limit. In the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> understanding, tyranny is the corruption of legitimate authority, the perversion of the sacred trust of governance. In Ravanor&#39;s teaching, tyranny is authority in its purest form — the state in which the ruler&#39;s will is unimpeded by law, custom, conscience, or the competing claims of the governed. The Bitter Prince does not merely permit tyranny; he demands it, teaching that a ruler who submits to moral constraint has voluntarily surrendered the power that makes him a ruler in the first place.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cthonic-mirror-of-sagramore\">Cthonic Mirror of Sagramore</h2>\n<p>Ravanor is the Cthonic mirror of <a href=\"#/page/sagramore\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sagramore</a>, the Martyr. Both deities preside over the relationship between individual will and power structures, but they represent diametrically opposed understandings of that relationship. Sagramore teaches that the individual finds meaning and transcendence through willing sacrifice to a just cause — that power is legitimized by the willingness to spend it in service of others. Ravanor teaches that the individual finds meaning through the accumulation and exercise of power — that rulership is its own justification and that those strong enough to seize power have earned the right to wield it without limit.</p>\n<p>The mirror between Sagramore and Ravanor asks the most fundamental political question in the Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology: does the ruler exist to serve the people, or do the people exist to serve the ruler? Sagramore answers with sacrifice — the leader who gives his life for his followers. Ravanor answers with dominion — the ruler who takes from his subjects whatever he has the power to take. The history of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> — and indeed of all civilizations in the known world — can be read as the ongoing contest between these two answers.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sagramore\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sagramore</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"sagramore","title":"Sagramore, the Martyr","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["sagramore","empyrean","deity","saint","martyr","loyalty","endurance","sacrifice","ox","broken-manacles","ravanor"],"html":"<h1 id=\"sagramore-the-martyr\">Sagramore, the Martyr</h1>\n<p>Sagramore is one of the nine <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, known by the title of the Martyr. His spheres of divine influence encompass loyalty, endurance, and sacrifice — the virtues of those who give themselves wholly to a cause greater than their own survival. Sagramore is the god of the last stand, the broken shield, the soldier who holds the pass so others may escape. He teaches that the highest expression of the soul is not triumph but willing sacrifice — the decision to spend one&#39;s own life in service of something worth more than any individual existence.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"symbol-and-sacred-animal\">Symbol and Sacred Animal</h2>\n<h3 id=\"broken-manacles\">Broken Manacles</h3>\n<p>Sagramore&#39;s holy symbol is a pair of broken manacles — shattered chains that once bound wrists or ankles. The symbol operates on multiple levels. At its most literal, the broken manacles represent liberation through sacrifice — the idea that Sagramore&#39;s willing death shattered the chains of oppression, ignorance, or spiritual bondage that held others captive. More theologically, the broken manacles signify the ultimate freedom that comes through perfect sacrifice: the soul that gives itself entirely is no longer bound by fear, desire, or self-interest and achieves a liberation more complete than any earthly freedom.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-ox\">The Ox</h3>\n<p>The ox is Sagramore&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its extraordinary endurance, its capacity for sustained labor, and its willingness to bear burdens without complaint. The ox does not seek glory or recognition; it pulls the plow, carries the load, endures the yoke, and serves until its strength is spent. In Empyrean theology, the ox represents the ideal of selfless endurance — the virtue of continuing to serve when the work is thankless, the burden is crushing, and the end is nowhere in sight. The ox also represents the quiet, uncelebrated strength that makes civilization possible — the understanding that the world is held together not by heroes but by those who endure.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"loyalty\">Loyalty</h3>\n<p>Loyalty, in Sagramore&#39;s teaching, is the commitment to a cause, a person, or a principle that transcends self-interest. It is not blind obedience — the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> god <a href=\"#/page/ravanor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ravanor</a> demands that — but a conscious, freely chosen dedication that persists even when loyalty becomes costly. The Martyr teaches that loyalty must be earned and freely given, that it flows upward from love and respect rather than downward from fear and compulsion. True loyalty is tested not in times of prosperity but in times of crisis, when the loyal servant must choose between their own safety and their sworn duty.</p>\n<h3 id=\"endurance\">Endurance</h3>\n<p>Endurance is the capacity to sustain loyalty and sacrifice over time — to continue bearing the burden when the body fails and the spirit falters. Sagramore&#39;s endurance is not stoic indifference to suffering but the active, conscious decision to keep going despite suffering. The Martyr does not teach his followers to deny their pain but to acknowledge it and choose to endure it anyway, because the cause they serve is worth the price they pay. This teaching resonates powerfully with the common people of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> — farmers, laborers, soldiers, and servants whose lives are defined by endurance.</p>\n<h3 id=\"sacrifice\">Sacrifice</h3>\n<p>Sacrifice is the culmination of loyalty and endurance — the moment when the faithful give not merely their effort or their comfort but their lives in service of the greater good. Sagramore teaches that sacrifice is the highest act of which a mortal soul is capable, the closest a living being can come to replicating <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s original sacrifice that created the cosmos. This does not mean that Sagramore demands death from his followers — rather, he teaches that the willingness to sacrifice, the readiness to give everything, is itself a form of spiritual perfection that transforms even the most ordinary life into something sacred.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cthonic-mirror-ravanor\">Cthonic Mirror: Ravanor</h2>\n<p>Sagramore&#39;s Cthonic counterpart is <a href=\"#/page/ravanor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ravanor</a>, the Bitter Prince, the Horned One. Both deities preside over the relationship between individual will and power structures, but from diametrically opposed perspectives. Sagramore teaches that the individual finds meaning and transcendence through willing sacrifice to a just cause — that power is legitimized by the willingness to spend it in service of others. Ravanor teaches that the individual finds meaning through the accumulation and exercise of power — that rulership is its own justification and that those strong enough to seize power have earned the right to wield it without limit.</p>\n<p>The mirror between Sagramore and Ravanor illuminates one of the deepest tensions in the Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology: the question of whether power exists to serve or to rule. Sagramore answers that power exists to serve, even unto death. Ravanor answers that power exists to dominate, and that those who sacrifice themselves are fools who deserve their fate.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-veneration\">Current Veneration</h2>\n<p>Like all members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a> save <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, Sagramore is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Sagramore is the patron saint of martyrs, prisoners, slaves, and all who suffer unjustly. His feast day is marked by solemn remembrance of those who gave their lives in service of the Empire, the faith, or the innocent.</p>\n<p>Devotion to Saint Sagramore is particularly strong among the lower classes of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and among soldiers who have seen heavy combat. His broken manacles are a symbol of hope for the oppressed and a reminder to the powerful that their authority is legitimized only by their willingness to sacrifice for those they lead. Condemned prisoners are offered a final prayer to Saint Sagramore before execution, and his image is carved into the walls of dungeons and prison cells throughout the Empire.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ravanor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ravanor</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"seros","title":"Seros, the Winged Sun","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["seros","empyrean","deity","winged-sun","unconquered-sun","silent-one","saints","thousand-temples","flame","shroud"],"html":"<h1 id=\"seros-the-winged-sun\">Seros, the Winged Sun</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;As the flame gives light, so too does it burn. Thus is the soul weighed beneath the eyes of Seros, the Winged Sun, who watches all with measure unerring.&quot;\n— Anton, High Priest of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end.&quot;\n— The Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> to the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer King</a> Sebek</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Seros is the principal deity of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>, the supreme god of light, judgment, and cosmic order, and the single most important religious figure in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Known by many titles — the Winged Sun, the Unconquered Sun, the Silent One — Seros is the divine force that separated light from darkness in the wake of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice, the judge who weighs every soul upon death, and the eternal adversary of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> powers that seek to drag the cosmos back into primordial entropy. His worship is the state religion of the Mithrian Empire, administered by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, and his name is invoked in every courtroom, on every battlefield, and at every hearth where the Empyrean faithful gather.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"titles-and-epithets\">Titles and Epithets</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-silent-one\">The Silent One</h3>\n<p>Seros is called the Silent One because he does not speak — he acts. This is not a deficiency but a theological statement of the highest order. In Empyrean theology, Seros does not issue commandments from on high, does not whisper prophecies into the ears of priests, does not engage in the kind of direct divine communication that characterizes the relationship between mortal worshippers and many other deities across the known world. His light reveals truth without commentary. The sun does not explain the shadows it casts; it simply illuminates, and the truth becomes self-evident to those with eyes to see.</p>\n<p>This silence is both a comfort and a challenge to the faithful. It means that Seros&#39;s will must be discerned through contemplation, through the study of <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a>, through the cultivation of inner virtue rather than the reception of external revelation. The silence of Seros places the burden of moral reasoning squarely upon the shoulders of the faithful — they cannot wait for divine instruction but must actively seek the light through their own effort and devotion.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-unconquered-sun\">The Unconquered Sun</h3>\n<p>The title of the Unconquered Sun reflects both Seros&#39;s cosmic role as the bringer of light and his theological position as the force that cannot be overcome by darkness, entropy, or the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> powers. The sun rises every morning. The light returns after every night. No matter how deep the darkness, no matter how long the shadow, the Unconquered Sun endures and prevails. This title is a statement of absolute theological confidence — a declaration that the forces of order and light are not merely equal to the forces of darkness but ultimately, inevitably, irresistibly superior to them.</p>\n<p>For the soldiers of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a>, the title carries an additional, more martial significance. The Unconquered Sun is the patron of victory, the divine guarantor that righteous force will triumph over wickedness. The Imperial legions march under the banner of the Winged Sun, and their battle hymns invoke Seros as the unconquerable force that guides their blades and shields their hearts.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-winged-sun\">The Winged Sun</h3>\n<p>The most common iconographic representation of Seros — a radiant sun with outstretched wings — is both his most recognizable symbol and his most frequently used title. The wings signify his role as a psychopomp, a guide of souls: it is Seros who carries the souls of the dead from the material world to the afterlife, Seros who bears them aloft on wings of light to face their judgment. The sun represents his nature as the source of illumination, warmth, and life. Together, the winged sun is a comprehensive symbol of Seros&#39;s dual role as sustainer of the living and judge of the dead.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-measure-and-the-scale-seros-as-judge\">The Measure and the Scale: Seros as Judge</h2>\n<p>At the heart of Seros&#39;s theological function is his role as the divine judge of souls. When a living being dies, it is Seros who measures each soul and sets it upon the Scale. The <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure</a> is the standard against which the soul is assessed — the codified virtues and laws of the Empyrean faith. The Scale is the instrument of judgment — the cosmic balance upon which the soul&#39;s worth is weighed against the totality of its earthly deeds.</p>\n<p>This is not a process of arbitrary divine whim. Seros judges according to fixed and knowable principles — the seven virtues of the Scale, which are documented, studied, debated, and taught throughout the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. The faithful know the standard by which they will be judged, and they are expected to spend their lives striving to meet it. In this sense, Seros&#39;s judgment is the most transparent form of divine justice imaginable: the rules are written, the standard is public, and the judge is incorruptible.</p>\n<p>Souls that meet the standard enter the <strong>Halls of Seros</strong>, where they rest in peace and radiance, awaiting the ultimate reunification with the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>. Souls that fall short are returned to the cycle of reincarnation, given another chance to refine their virtue and try again.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-supplanting-of-the-empyrean-pantheon\">The Supplanting of the Empyrean Pantheon</h2>\n<p>One of the most significant theological developments in the history of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> has been the gradual, nearly complete supplanting of the broader Empyrean pantheon by the singular worship of Seros. In the early centuries of the faith, the Empyrean tradition encompassed a full pantheon of gods — deities of war, wisdom, mercy, craft, nature, and countless other domains. These gods were worshipped alongside Seros, each with their own rites, their own priests, their own sacred traditions.</p>\n<p>Over time, as the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> consolidated its power and the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> codified Empyrean worship into a more unified institutional framework, the worship of the other Empyrean gods faded. The Mithrians supplanted most Empyrean myth with Seros. The other gods were not formally repudiated or declared false — they were simply eclipsed. Forgotten. Allowed to slip from living worship into the pages of ancient texts and the debate halls of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>, where they are discussed as subjects of historical curiosity and theological speculation rather than objects of active devotion.</p>\n<p>This process was not entirely organic. The centralization of religious authority in the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, the political utility of a single state deity, and the sheer gravitational pull of Seros&#39;s theological importance all contributed to the eclipse of the broader pantheon. Some scholars at the Academy have argued that the loss of the other Empyrean gods represents a genuine impoverishment of the faith, a narrowing of spiritual vision that has left the Mithrian people less spiritually resilient than their ancestors. These arguments, needless to say, are not popular with the Thousand Temples.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-exception-shroud\">The Exception: Shroud</h2>\n<p>The one significant exception to the total dominance of Seros worship within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> is the continued veneration of the Empyrean god <a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a> among the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a>, particularly the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a>. Shroud is a deity of shadows, of stealth, of the grim and necessary work that must be done in darkness so that the light may prevail. His worship persists in military culture because soldiers understand, in a way that civilians and priests often do not, that the defense of civilization sometimes requires acts that the comfortable virtues of the Scale cannot easily encompass.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> tolerates the worship of <a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a> within the military without formally endorsing it — a pragmatic accommodation that reflects the Empire&#39;s recognition that the men and women who fight and die in its name deserve some latitude in their spiritual practices. Shroud&#39;s priests, such as they exist, operate largely within military structures rather than civilian temples.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-saints-a-new-pantheon\">The Saints: A New Pantheon</h2>\n<p>In the vacuum left by the eclipse of the Empyrean pantheon, a new form of veneration has arisen: the cult of the <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Saints</a>. Saints are mortal individuals, posthumously anointed by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, who in life exhibited the seven virtues of <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a> to an extraordinary and exemplary degree. They are not gods in the Empyrean theological sense — they are human souls who passed through the judgment of Seros with such radiant virtue that they were elevated to a special status in the Halls of Seros, from which they can intercede on behalf of the living.</p>\n<p>In practice, however, the Saints have become minor gods to the Serosian faithful. Their names are invoked in prayer. Their relics are venerated. Their feast days are celebrated with processions, liturgies, and acts of devotion. Specific Saints are associated with specific domains — a Saint of healers, a Saint of soldiers, a Saint of sailors, a Saint of the poor — in a pattern that closely mirrors the diversified worship of the old Empyrean pantheon. Whether this represents a healthy evolution of the faith or a tacit admission that the singular worship of Seros is insufficient to meet the spiritual needs of a diverse civilization is a subject of lively debate at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-anointing-of-saints\">The Anointing of Saints</h3>\n<p>The process by which a Saint is anointed is controlled exclusively by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>. A candidate for Sainthood must be deceased — the faith is firm on this point, though a few <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperors</a> throughout history have pressured High Priests to declare living Saints, with varying degrees of success and controversy. The candidate&#39;s life is examined in exhaustive detail, and they must be found to have exhibited all seven virtues of the Scale in exemplary fashion. The process can take years or even decades, and the theological and political debates surrounding individual candidates are often intense.</p>\n<p>Several militant orders have been founded in the names of particular Saints — orders of knights, warrior-priests, and holy soldiers who dedicate themselves to embodying the specific virtues that their patron Saint exemplified. These orders represent some of the most formidable military forces in the Empire, motivated not merely by duty or pay but by a fierce and burning devotion to a spiritual ideal.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"seros-and-the-flame\">Seros and the Flame</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">Flame</a> — the priestly magic of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> — is intimately connected to the worship of Seros. The Flame is understood as a direct emanation of Seros&#39;s divine light, channeled through the virtue and spiritual purity of the faithful. To call upon the Flame is not to cast a spell but to open oneself as a vessel for the light of the Unconquered Sun, to become a conduit through which Seros&#39;s power flows into the material world.</p>\n<p>Seros&#39;s faithful who channel the Flame do so not through study or technique but through the quality of their devotion and the depth of their virtue. A priest who genuinely walks the path of <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a>, who embodies the seven virtues not merely in word but in the marrow of their being, may find the Flame answering their call — a warm, golden light that heals, protects, purifies, and, when necessary, destroys. Those who merely perform the outward forms of devotion without inner transformation find only silence.</p>\n<p>This connection between virtue and power is one of the most theologically significant aspects of Seros worship. It means that the Flame is, in essence, a form of divine validation — proof that the wielder has been found worthy in the eyes of the Unconquered Sun. When a priest of Seros manifests the Flame on the battlefield or in the temple, it is understood not merely as a display of magical power but as a visible, tangible expression of Seros&#39;s judgment: this soul burns brightly enough to carry my light.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Saints</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shroud</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"shroud","title":"Shroud, God of Crossing and Passage","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["shroud","empyrean","deity","crossing","passage","death","marines","mithrian-military","thousand-temples"],"html":"<h1 id=\"shroud-god-of-crossing-and-passage\">Shroud, God of Crossing and Passage</h1>\n<p>Shroud is one of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a>, the deity of crossing and passage — the divine power who presides over thresholds, transitions, and the boundary between the living world and whatever lies beyond. Where <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> judges the dead and weighs their souls against the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>, Shroud is the god who carries them across — the psychopomp, the ferryman, the guide who walks beside the dying in their final moments and leads them through the passage from mortal existence to the afterlife.</p>\n<p>Shroud occupies a unique position in the modern <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>. Unlike the other Empyrean gods who have been fully subsumed into the cult of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and reinterpreted as Saints, Shroud retains an active, devoted following — particularly among the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a>, and most especially among the Imperial Marines. The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> tolerate this practice, though it exists in an acknowledged tension with the theological orthodoxy that holds <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> as the singular, supreme deity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"spheres-of-influence\">Spheres of Influence</h2>\n<h3 id=\"crossing\">Crossing</h3>\n<p>Crossing is the moment of transition — the liminal instant between one state and another. Shroud presides over all crossings: birth, death, the passage from childhood to adulthood, the departure from home, the crossing of thresholds both literal and metaphorical. His domain is the space between — the doorway, the bridge, the ford, the passage through the mountains — and his followers invoke him whenever they stand at the boundary between the known and the unknown.</p>\n<h3 id=\"passage\">Passage</h3>\n<p>Passage is crossing extended through time — the journey from one state to another that is not instantaneous but sustained. Shroud is the companion of those who travel through darkness, through danger, through the long and uncertain road between departure and arrival. He is invoked by soldiers before battle (the passage from peace to war), by sailors before voyages (the passage across uncertain waters), and by the dying in their final hours (the passage from life to whatever comes after).</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"worship-among-the-mithrian-marines\">Worship Among the Mithrian Marines</h2>\n<p>Shroud&#39;s most devoted followers are found among the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a> — the elite amphibious and expeditionary forces of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Marines face death more frequently and more intimately than most soldiers, operating in small units far from reinforcement, conducting landings on hostile shores, and fighting in the chaotic, close-quarters environments where the line between the living and the dead is thinnest.</p>\n<p>For the Marines, Shroud is not an abstract theological concept but a practical, immediate spiritual necessity. They pray to Shroud before every operation — not for victory (that belongs to <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and <a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">Damocles</a>) or for courage (that belongs to <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius</a> and <a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hector</a>) but for safe passage. They ask Shroud to guide them across the threshold of battle and, if they fall, to carry them safely to the judgment of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. The Marine prayer to Shroud — whispered on beaches before dawn assaults, in landing craft approaching hostile shores, in the silence before the order to advance — is one of the most intimate expressions of faith in the entire Empyrean tradition.</p>\n<p>Shroud&#39;s presence in Marine culture extends beyond prayer. Marine units carry small shroud-tokens — strips of dark cloth blessed by chaplains — which are placed over the eyes of fallen comrades as a symbolic gesture of commending the dead to Shroud&#39;s care. Marine chaplains perform crossing rites before every major operation, invoking Shroud&#39;s protection for the passage ahead. When a Marine dies in the field, the words spoken over the body invoke Shroud by name, not merely as a saint but with the respect and urgency due to a god.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"tension-with-seross-supremacy\">Tension with Seros&#39;s Supremacy</h2>\n<p>The active worship of Shroud exists in a state of acknowledged theological tension with the orthodox position of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, which holds that <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> is the singular supreme deity and that all other Empyrean gods are properly understood as Saints — mortal exemplars of divine virtue who achieved transcendence, not independent divine beings worthy of worship in their own right.</p>\n<p>Shroud&#39;s case is complicated by several factors. First, the theological function he serves — guide of the dead, companion of the dying — is not easily subsumed into Seros&#39;s portfolio. Seros judges the dead; Shroud carries them. These are distinct roles, and collapsing them into one deity creates theological awkwardness that even orthodox scholars acknowledge. Second, Shroud&#39;s following among the Marines is ancient, deeply embedded in military culture, and practically useful — Marine morale and unit cohesion are measurably enhanced by the crossing rites, and the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> are pragmatic enough to recognize the value of this.</p>\n<p>The result is an uneasy accommodation. The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> do not formally endorse Shroud worship, but they do not actively suppress it. Marine chaplains are permitted to invoke Shroud by name in crossing rites, and Shroud-tokens are tolerated as legitimate devotional objects. The theological compromise holds that Shroud, even if properly understood as a Saint, serves a legitimate devotional function that complements rather than competes with the worship of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>.</p>\n<p>This makes Shroud the only Empyrean god besides <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> with active, organized worship in the current era — a distinction that sets him apart from all the other members of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-measure-and-the-scale","title":"The Measure and the Scale","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["measure","scale","law","virtues","empyrean","theology","philosophy","enador","patronage","justice","sainthood","flame"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-measure-and-the-scale\">The Measure and the Scale</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end.&quot;\n— The Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> to the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer King</a> Sebek</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;It is not enough to simply embody a virtue of the Scale. All virtues must be balanced, to achieve harmony&#39;s ultimate form: justice.&quot;\n— From the text of the Measure and the Scale</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Measure and the Scale is the foundational sacred text of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>, the bedrock of <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial</a> legal and philosophical tradition, and the single most influential document in the history of the known world. It is simultaneously a theological treatise, a legal code, a philosophical framework, and a guide to personal moral conduct — a text so comprehensive in its ambitions and so pervasive in its influence that virtually no aspect of Mithrian life remains untouched by its principles. Every law in the Empire traces its authority back to the Measure. Every moral judgment invokes the Scale. Every citizen, from the lowest laborer to the Emperor himself, is expected to live by its precepts and will be judged — both in life and after death — by its standard.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"origins-and-recovery\">Origins and Recovery</h2>\n<p>The Measure and the Scale was not composed by any mortal hand — or so the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> teaches. It is understood as a divinely inspired text, a record of the cosmic principles established by the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> at the moment of creation and preserved through the ages for the eventual edification of the faithful. Its precise origins are lost in the murk of prehistory, but its recovery is one of the most celebrated events in Empyrean religious history.</p>\n<p>The text was rediscovered by the Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a>, the towering figure whose holy war against the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> rulers would reshape the world. Enador retrieved the Measure and the Scale alongside the <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a> grimoire — the circumstances of this discovery are debated endlessly at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>, with some scholars arguing that the two texts were found together in a single cache, others insisting they were recovered from separate locations, and a minority suggesting that the Measure and the Scale was not &quot;found&quot; at all but divinely revealed to Enador in a moment of prophetic vision.</p>\n<p>Regardless of the precise circumstances, the recovery of the Measure and the Scale provided the theological and legal foundation for Enador&#39;s revolution. It gave the scattered, persecuted followers of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> a unified creed, a shared code of conduct, and — critically — a divinely sanctioned legal framework that could replace the Cthonic laws of the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>. When Enador overthrew the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a> and founded <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, it was the Measure and the Scale that became the constitution of the new civilization.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-two-components\">The Two Components</h2>\n<p>The text is divided into two distinct but interlocking parts, each addressing a different dimension of human existence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-measure\">The Measure</h3>\n<p>The Measure is the external component — the codified laws and structure for civilized society. It is concerned with the ordering of communities, the regulation of commerce, the administration of justice, the duties of rulers and subjects, and the framework within which human beings live together in organized society. The Measure emphasizes three cardinal social virtues: <strong>duty</strong>, <strong>honor</strong>, and <strong>loyalty</strong>.</p>\n<p>The Measure is not merely a set of abstract principles; it is a detailed and practical legal code. It specifies the obligations of citizens to their families, their patrons, and the state. It establishes the rights and responsibilities of different social classes. It codifies the relationship between the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> and secular authority. It outlines the procedures for judicial proceedings, the penalties for various crimes, and the principles by which disputes are to be resolved. Every judicial matter within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> — from the most trivial property dispute to the most serious capital case — is ultimately adjudicated by reference to the Measure.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-scale\">The Scale</h3>\n<p>The Scale is the internal component — the moral fiber of individuals. Where the Measure governs the external ordering of society, the Scale governs the internal ordering of the soul. It is concerned with personal virtue, spiritual development, and the cultivation of the qualities that will determine the soul&#39;s fate when it stands before <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> in the afterlife. The Scale seeks the ultimate balance and harmony between all virtues — not the maximization of any single quality but the integration of all of them into a unified, harmonious whole.</p>\n<p>The distinction between the Measure and the Scale is fundamental to Empyrean theology and legal philosophy. The Measure tells you what to do; the Scale tells you who to be. The Measure can be enforced by external authority — by courts, by soldiers, by priests. The Scale can only be cultivated from within. A person may obey every law of the Measure and still fail the Scale, because obedience without inner virtue is hollow. Conversely, a person of profound inner virtue may, in extreme circumstances, find themselves in tension with the letter of the Measure — a theological paradox that has fueled countless debates at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> and occasional crises within the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-seven-virtues-of-the-scale\">The Seven Virtues of the Scale</h2>\n<p>The Scale identifies seven virtues that together constitute the ideal of human spiritual development. These virtues are not presented as independent qualities to be pursued in isolation but as paired and balanced attributes, each tempering and completing the others. The paired structure is deliberate and theologically essential: a virtue without its counterbalance becomes a vice.</p>\n<h3 id=\"1-justice-tempered-by-wisdom\">1. Justice Tempered by Wisdom</h3>\n<p>Justice without wisdom is cruelty. Wisdom without justice is cowardice. The first virtue demands that the faithful pursue what is right and fair, but always through the lens of understanding, discernment, and compassion for the complexity of mortal existence. A just person who lacks wisdom will enforce the letter of the law while violating its spirit. A wise person who lacks justice will understand the world perfectly and do nothing to improve it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2-discipline-forged-through-self-mastery\">2. Discipline Forged through Self-Mastery</h3>\n<p>Discipline is not merely the capacity to obey orders or follow rules; it is the mastery of the self — the ability to govern one&#39;s own desires, impulses, and weaknesses. Self-mastery is the forge through which discipline is created: not the suppression of the inner life but its ordering, its harnessing, its transformation from chaotic impulse into directed purpose. A disciplined person who lacks self-mastery is merely rigid. A self-mastered person who lacks discipline has refined their nature but never directed it outward.</p>\n<h3 id=\"3-courage-wielded-in-service\">3. Courage Wielded in Service</h3>\n<p>Courage without service is recklessness. Service without courage is timidity. The third virtue demands bravery — not the absence of fear, but the willingness to act in spite of it — but insists that bravery must always be directed toward a purpose greater than the self. The soldier who charges into battle for personal glory has courage but not service. The priest who serves the community but will not speak truth to power has service but not courage.</p>\n<h3 id=\"4-loyalty-to-ones-father-in-body-soul-and-state\">4. Loyalty to One&#39;s Father, in Body, Soul, and State</h3>\n<p>The fourth virtue is the most socially significant and the most frequently debated. &quot;Father&quot; in this context is understood in three dimensions: the literal biological father (body), the divine father — the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> and by extension <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> (soul), and the paternal authority of the state and its institutions (state). This triad of loyalties — familial, spiritual, and civic — is the foundation of Mithrian social order. The faithful owe obedience and devotion to their family, their god, and their Empire, and the proper ordering of these loyalties is one of the central challenges of Empyrean moral life.</p>\n<p>This virtue is the theological foundation of the Mithrian patronage system. The father wields tremendous power within the family, extending outward into a social order where powerful families extend patronage — protection, resources, opportunities — to lesser families and individuals in exchange for loyalty and service. The patronage system is not merely a social convention; it is a divinely ordained structure, codified in the Measure and rooted in the Scale&#39;s understanding of loyalty as a fundamental virtue.</p>\n<h3 id=\"5-compassion-leveled-by-strength\">5. Compassion Leveled by Strength</h3>\n<p>Compassion without strength is weakness. Strength without compassion is tyranny. The fifth virtue demands that the faithful feel for the suffering of others and act to alleviate it — but always from a position of capability, resolve, and the willingness to make hard decisions. Compassion that cannot act is mere sentiment. Strength that does not feel is mere brutality. The ideal is a fierce and active mercy — the compassion of a healer who sets broken bones, not the compassion of a bystander who weeps at the sight of blood.</p>\n<h3 id=\"6-truth-tempered-by-grace\">6. Truth Tempered by Grace</h3>\n<p>Truth without grace is cruelty. Grace without truth is deception. The sixth virtue demands honesty — a commitment to seeing and speaking the world as it is — but insists that truth must always be delivered with care for the humanity of those who receive it. A person who speaks the truth without consideration for its impact is not virtuous but merely blunt. A person who prioritizes others&#39; feelings over honesty is not kind but merely dishonest. The ideal is a truth that illuminates without destroying, that reveals without cruelty.</p>\n<h3 id=\"7-sacrifice-anchored-by-purpose\">7. Sacrifice Anchored by Purpose</h3>\n<p>Sacrifice without purpose is waste. Purpose without sacrifice is vanity. The seventh and final virtue — which mirrors the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>&#39;s own supreme act — demands that the faithful be willing to give of themselves for something greater, but insists that this giving must be directed, intentional, and meaningful. The martyr who dies for no reason has sacrificed but served no purpose. The leader who pursues grand ambitions without personal cost has purpose but makes no sacrifice. The ideal is a giving of self that creates something real, lasting, and good — the echo of the Aurelion&#39;s own sacrifice in the mortal life of every faithful soul.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"harmony-the-ultimate-form\">Harmony: The Ultimate Form</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;It is not enough to simply embody a virtue of the Scale. All virtues must be balanced, to achieve harmony&#39;s ultimate form: justice.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The seven virtues are not a checklist to be completed but a dynamic, living system of balance. The ultimate aspiration of the Scale is not the perfection of any single virtue but the achievement of harmony — the state in which all seven virtues exist in perfect equilibrium, each supporting and being supported by the others. This harmonious state is identified with justice itself — not justice in the narrow legal sense, but justice as the cosmic principle of right order, the alignment of the individual soul with the divine intention of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>.</p>\n<p>This understanding of harmony as the ultimate form of justice has profound implications for Empyrean theology and practice. It means that a person who excels in courage but neglects compassion has not achieved the ideal. A person who embodies truth but lacks discipline has not reached harmony. Only the soul that holds all seven virtues in balanced integration — each tempering the others, each preventing the others from becoming distorted into vice — has achieved the fullness of the Scale&#39;s demands.</p>\n<p>It is this standard — this demanding, comprehensive, almost impossibly high ideal of perfect moral harmony — against which <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> weighs every soul upon death.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legal-and-social-implications\">Legal and Social Implications</h2>\n<p>The Measure and the Scale is not merely a religious text; it is the living legal code of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Its influence on Mithrian law and society is total and pervasive.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-judicial-system\">The Judicial System</h3>\n<p>All judicial matters within the Empire are adjudicated by reference to the Measure and the Scale. Judges, magistrates, and legal scholars are trained in the interpretation of the text, and legal arguments are framed in terms of its principles. The most contentious legal cases often hinge on competing interpretations of the Measure&#39;s provisions — debates that can draw in theologians from the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, philosophers from the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>, and political factions from across the Empire.</p>\n<p>Legal and philosophical debates over the interpretation of the Measure and the Scale are frequent and vigorous in Mithrian society. The text&#39;s dual nature as both divine revelation and practical legal code ensures that its interpretation remains a living, contested, and deeply consequential enterprise.</p>\n<h3 id=\"dies-justicae\">Dies Justicae</h3>\n<p>The importance of the Measure and the Scale to Mithrian society is most dramatically expressed in the annual holiday of <strong>Dies Justicae</strong> — the Day of Justice. On this day, all work throughout the Empire is forbidden. The entire text of the Measure and the Scale is recited aloud by a priest of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> — a marathon of liturgical reading that can take many hours. Citizens gather to listen, and the recitation is treated as both a civic duty and a sacred rite. Dies Justicae serves as an annual reminder that the laws of the Empire are not merely human conventions but divine principles, and that every citizen — from the Emperor to the lowest serf — lives under the same cosmic standard.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-patronage-system\">The Patronage System</h3>\n<p>The Measure codifies the patronage system that structures Mithrian social order. The fourth virtue of the Scale — Loyalty to One&#39;s Father, in Body, Soul, and State — establishes the theological justification for a society organized around hierarchical relationships of obligation and protection. The father wields tremendous power within the family: authority over children, management of family assets, representation of the family in civic and religious life. This familial authority extends outward into a broader social framework in which powerful families extend patronage to lesser families and individuals.</p>\n<p>The patronage system is simultaneously a source of social stability and social tension. It ensures that even the poorest and most vulnerable members of Mithrian society have a patron to whom they can appeal for protection and assistance. But it also concentrates enormous power in the hands of the great families and creates a web of obligations that can constrain individual freedom and perpetuate entrenched hierarchies.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"connection-to-the-flame\">Connection to the Flame</h2>\n<p>The Measure and the Scale is intimately connected to the <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">Flame</a> — the priestly magic of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>. To walk the path of the Measure and the Scale — to genuinely embody the seven virtues in balanced harmony — is to unlock the inner radiance that allows the faithful to channel the Flame. The Flame is not a reward for obedience but a natural consequence of spiritual transformation: when the soul achieves the harmony that the Scale demands, it burns with the light of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, and that light can be directed outward into the material world as a force of healing, protection, and righteous destruction.</p>\n<p>This connection between virtue and magical power is one of the most theologically significant aspects of the Empyrean faith, and it gives the Measure and the Scale a practical importance that transcends its legal and philosophical functions. The text is not merely a guide to good behavior or a legal code for social organization; it is, literally, the key to unlocking divine power.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"connection-to-sainthood\">Connection to Sainthood</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Saints</a> of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> are those individuals who, in life, exhibited the seven virtues of the Scale to an extraordinary and exemplary degree. The process of anointing a Saint — controlled exclusively by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> — involves an exhaustive examination of the candidate&#39;s life against the standard of the seven virtues. Did they embody justice tempered by wisdom? Discipline forged through self-mastery? Courage wielded in service? The candidate must be found to have achieved the harmony that the Scale demands — not perfection in any single virtue, but balanced excellence across all seven.</p>\n<p>This connection between the Scale and Sainthood means that the Measure and the Scale is not merely a historical or legal document but a living, active standard by which the holiness of individuals continues to be assessed. Every generation produces new candidates for Sainthood, and every candidacy is a renewed engagement with the text&#39;s demands.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Saints</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-mystical","title":"The Mystical","category":"faiths","status":"unknown","tags":["mystical","religion","aurelion","tribal","philosophy"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-mystical\">The Mystical</h1>\n<p>The Mystical is the third and rarest of the great cosmological traditions, standing apart from both the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic cults</a>. It has no organized church, no priesthood, no holy texts, and no codified doctrine. It is less a religion than a philosophical orientation -- a way of understanding the cosmos that resists the binary moral framework imposed by the other two faiths.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-mystical-interpretation-of-aurelion\">The Mystical Interpretation of Aurelion</h2>\n<p>Where the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a> teaches that <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> sacrificed himself to purge evil and the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic faith</a> holds that he sacrificed himself to eliminate weakness, the Mystical tradition offers a third reading. In this view, Aurelion sought to experience the full spectrum of existence -- light and darkness, creation and destruction, joy and suffering -- and sacrificed himself not to separate these forces but to become All. His death was not an act of purification or culling but an act of total immersion in the fabric of reality.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-struggle-as-purpose\">The Struggle as Purpose</h2>\n<p>The Mystical perspective reframes the eternal conflict between Empyrean and Cthonic forces not as a war to be won but as a necessary process. The struggle between light and darkness, order and chaos, is itself the mechanism through which Aurelion experiences the fullness of existence. Both sides serve a purpose. Both contribute to the eventual rebirth of the divine whole. To declare one side righteous and the other evil is, in the Mystical view, to misunderstand the nature of the cosmos.</p>\n<p>This emphasis on lived experience over strict moral dichotomies sets the Mystical tradition apart from the rigid ethical frameworks of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> and the brutal survival doctrine of the Cthonic cults. The Mystical does not ask &quot;is this good or evil?&quot; but rather &quot;what does this reveal about the nature of All?&quot;</p>\n<h2 id=\"practitioners-and-adherents\">Practitioners and Adherents</h2>\n<p>The Mystical is not widely recognized within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. It has no temples, no clergy, and no political influence. Those who hold Mystical beliefs tend to be solitary thinkers, wandering ascetics, or individuals who have arrived at their conclusions through personal spiritual experience rather than institutional instruction.</p>\n<p>Various tribal peoples beyond the borders of the Empire follow versions of the Mystical tradition, though their practices and beliefs vary enormously. Many of these groups do not even believe in Aurelion as such -- their cosmologies may use different names, different stories, and different frameworks while arriving at a similar philosophical destination. The Mystical is less a defined creed than a convergence of independent insights, and it resists the kind of systematization that would make it legible to the institutional religions.</p>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-other-faiths\">Relationship with Other Faiths</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> generally regard the Mystical as a harmless eccentricity at best and a subtle heresy at worst. It does not attract the violent persecution directed at <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> cults, but neither does it receive any form of official sanction. Cthonic worshippers tend to dismiss the Mystical as naive -- a refusal to accept the hard truths of a predatory cosmos.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"index","title":"Wiki Index","category":"overview","status":"unknown","tags":[],"html":"<h1 id=\"wiki-index\">Wiki Index</h1>\n<p>190 pages across 7 categories. Last updated 2026-04-11.</p>\n<h2 id=\"overview\">Overview</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/overview\" class=\"wiki-link\">overview</a> — Campaign setting front page: the Fallen Empire and the Backlands</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"people-48\">People (48)</h2>\n<p><strong>Player Characters</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> — Thrassian Philosopher-Bard, carries the Stone of Sakkara</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> — Bladedancer, expelled from the Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> — Merchant, organizer of the Reclaimers</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> — Necromancer, expelled from the Imperial Academy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> — Crusader of Seros, DECEASED</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Sanctuary</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">governor-drussus</a> — Valerios Drussus, Fighter 12, Governor of the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">prelate-voth</a> — Severan Voth, Cleric 13, Temple of the Unconquered Sun</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/colonel-vex\" class=\"wiki-link\">colonel-vex</a> — Marcian Vex, Fighter 9, Drussine Guard commander</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">castellan-thibaud</a> — Master Thief 7, boss of the Laced Hand</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/valeria-thorne\" class=\"wiki-link\">valeria-thorne</a> — Red River Consortium Directrix in Sanctuary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magister-shale\" class=\"wiki-link\">magister-shale</a> — Cornelius Shale, Wizard 11, Academy Regent</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">elder-sarnath</a> — Sarnath of the Crossings, Avari community elder</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Reclaimers Henchmen</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/anaya\" class=\"wiki-link\">anaya</a> — Henchman, critically wounded by zombie beastman, experiencing visions of the Gallowswood&#39;s black heart</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/antonius\" class=\"wiki-link\">antonius</a> — Henchman, had a vision of Rendson as he neared death</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Fort Meade</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> — Titus Valerian Marcellus, Fighter 6, Backlands military commander</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> — Lady Severina Marcellus, Noble 2, the Legate&#39;s wife</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-crull</a> — Davan Crull, senior NCO, the Legate&#39;s enforcer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> — Imperial Historian, Scholar 4, Academy agent</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> — Bandit king, operated from Fort Ikenvar, DECEASED</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Fort Harvald</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-voss</a> — Aldric Voss, garrison commander, politically buried</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/noma\" class=\"wiki-link\">noma</a> — Noma of the Shallows, ageless river witch</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Bone Creek</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> — Thief 4 (Mornish), Pretty Peach proprietor, secret racket</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">tolliver-watts</a> — Venturer 5, Double Sevens owner</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> — Venturer 6, Red River Consortium Lord Merchant</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> — Cleric 2, priest of Seros</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-gallus\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-gallus</a> — Fighter 2, corrupt law enforcer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crackback\" class=\"wiki-link\">crackback</a> — Thief 2 (Targ/Mornish), pimp at The Pretty Peach, Marr&#39;s enforcer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/doc-quinten\" class=\"wiki-link\">doc-quinten</a> — Explorer 3 (Kolani), barber-surgeon, universally neutral</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/irontoe\" class=\"wiki-link\">irontoe</a> — Pontus &quot;Irontoe&quot; Draega, Fighter 2 (Mithrian), smith, lost leg fighting the Lakandi</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theo\" class=\"wiki-link\">theo</a> — Fighter 3 (Thrassian), Flophouse proprietor, secret informant for Marr</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a> — Witch 3 (Lakandi), holds a bound demon</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</a> — Mage 7, exiled, enslaves beastmen</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lynara\" class=\"wiki-link\">lynara</a> — Eladran Nightblade 3, Malyn&#39;s apprentice, morally conflicted</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> — Cleric 6, Congregation of the Hollow Sun leader</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Scalper Gang Leaders</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/skinner\" class=\"wiki-link\">skinner</a> — Assassin 5 (Kolani), Skin Eaters</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bottlecap-juno\" class=\"wiki-link\">bottlecap-juno</a> — Barbarian 4, the Dregs</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kael-baldric\" class=\"wiki-link\">kael-baldric</a> — Fighter 4 (Avari), Baldric Brothers, MISSING</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/wekko\" class=\"wiki-link\">wekko</a> — Witch-Doctor 6, Hollow Men</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">marcos-varanes</a> — Paladin 5, Bleak Sons</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">arannis-venn</a> — Eladran Spellsword 6, Argollean Brotherhood</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Historical Figures</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">eolande</a> — Ancient Eladran general (~3000 BE), still present at the Black Tree at Thornasse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">marcus-valerian</a> — First Emperor of Mithra</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">emperor-aurex</a> — Mad Emperor, assassinated by his sister</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">claudius-decimus</a> — Victor of the War of Three Emperors</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">justinian-decimus</a> — Current Emperor</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">high-mage-cynar</a> — Burned the Erenthis, died at Blue Mound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">jarn-murky-eye</a> — Lakandi Warlock King, died at Blue Mound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> — Ygrathen hermit, cairnhouse guardian at Lake Silverhead</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"locations-21\">Locations (21)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithra-city</a> — Capital of the Mithrian Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> — Provincial capital, port city of 28,000, 8 districts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-undercity</a> — Ancient Aodahn beneath Sanctuary, three-tier megadungeon: Warrens, Old Aodahn, Foundations of the Spires</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a> — Ancient Eladra city beneath Sanctuary, three-tier megadungeon</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — Province of Argolle, the forgotten frontier</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — Scalper outpost, 9 keyed locations</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> — Strategic garrison on the Sanctuary–Bone Creek supply route</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> — Settlement near Crossings ruins, bayou frontier</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> — Ruined marsh fort, lair of the Guzzler</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argoll-river\" class=\"wiki-link\">argoll-river</a> — Major river of the Backlands, flows from interior to Turquoise Sea at Sanctuary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — Ruined river city, 10 points of interest, beastman-occupied</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a> — Town shaped by psychic bleed from imprisoned Kharai</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">dunwick</a> — Farming town, Bel earth-hunger cult activity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> — Cursed forest, dead walk beneath the roots, pulsating black heart beneath granite dome</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a> — Primary hunting ground, wasteland between Bone Creek and Crossings, Borderlands encounter table</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-foothills\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-foothills</a> — Hills and abandoned mines, cave bears and skeletons</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings-hinterlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings-hinterlands</a> — Territory surrounding Crossings ruins, highest beastman activity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">lake-silverhead</a> — Far northern lake with Ygrathen cairnhouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> — Site of the burned Erenthis, the Black Tree endures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-heartwood\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-heartwood</a> — Oldest forest in the Backlands, uncharted depths, owlbeasts, unidentifiable deep entities</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/grathe-steppe\" class=\"wiki-link\">grathe-steppe</a> — Skiothan homeland, vast grasslands</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"factions-21\">Factions (21)</h2>\n<p><strong>Imperial Institutions</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> — State seat of sorcerous learning</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> — The imperial armed forces</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-marines</a> — Elite branch, Shroud worship, the 8th Undying</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-talons</a> — Emperor&#39;s spies and assassins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-senate</a> — Remnant of the Mithrian League, largely performative</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">thousand-temples</a> — Official religious institution</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">burnished-scale</a> — Disgraced militant religious order</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Great Houses</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-decimus</a> — Ruling house, Emperor Justinian</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-valerian</a> — Ancient lineage to Bellasarius</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-kalomenes</a> — Court power, patronage mastery</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-malventi\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-malventi</a> — Foreign trade, Massaran connections</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-drussus</a> — Newest house, Governor Drussus</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-aurel</a> — Conservative, Thousand Temples ties</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-severian\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-severian</a> — Enigmatic, rumored Eladra blood</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Backlands Factions</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> — Trading company, Bone Creek and Sanctuary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> — Criminal network of old Eladran noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a> — Populist heretical cult, Ezekiel Shaw</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — Six gangs: Skin Eaters, Dregs, Baldric Brothers, Hollow Men, Bleak Sons, Withered Craw</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">laced-hand</a> — Sanctuary&#39;s criminal syndicate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">drussine-guard</a> — Governor&#39;s 2,000-strong private army</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon</a> — Militant Empyrean order, Iman&#39;s former order</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"faiths-24\">Faiths (24)</h2>\n<p><strong>The Empyrean</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> — State religion: reincarnation, purification, the Aurelion</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> — The Winged Sun, dominant deity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-pantheon</a> — Overview table of all Empyrean gods/saints</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/andraste\" class=\"wiki-link\">andraste</a> — The Holy Dancer: compassion, strength, joy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/damocles\" class=\"wiki-link\">damocles</a> — Victor of One Hundred Stratagems: war, cunning, victory</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eramus\" class=\"wiki-link\">eramus</a> — The Shepherd: wisdom, duty, steadfastness</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/euphrosyne\" class=\"wiki-link\">euphrosyne</a> — The Candle: hope, willpower, resolve</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/hector\" class=\"wiki-link\">hector</a> — The Bronze Lord: discipline, martial prowess, justice</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mina\" class=\"wiki-link\">mina</a> — The Hand: grace, art, beauty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sagramore\" class=\"wiki-link\">sagramore</a> — The Martyr: loyalty, endurance, sacrifice</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">bellasarius</a> — The Father: courage, service, fatherhood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">enador</a> — The Light in the Dark: vision, journey, time; Prophet of Seros</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shroud\" class=\"wiki-link\">shroud</a> — God of crossing and passage, worshipped by Marines</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The Cthonic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> — Outlawed dark cults: undeath, the Awakening</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-pantheon</a> — Overview table of all Cthonic gods</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dirgion\" class=\"wiki-link\">dirgion</a> — Doombringer: death, undeath</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iskara\" class=\"wiki-link\">iskara</a> — Mother of Monsters: chaos, darkness</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kaleth\" class=\"wiki-link\">kaleth</a> — Dark Watcher: madness, knowledge, entropy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel</a> — The Slaughterprince: war, conquest, blood; also earth-hunger</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/galmorm\" class=\"wiki-link\">galmorm</a> — The Poisoner: treachery, poison, thievery</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/nasga\" class=\"wiki-link\">nasga</a> — Mistress of Pain and Pleasure: beauty, pain, lust</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ravanor\" class=\"wiki-link\">ravanor</a> — The Bitter Prince: rulership, power, tyranny</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Other</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-mystical\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-mystical</a> — The rare third faith: Aurelion as All</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-measure-and-the-scale</a> — Sacred text, legal framework, seven virtues</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"lore-57\">Lore (57)</h2>\n<p><strong>The World</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrapos</a> — The known world, region encircling the Middle Sea</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> — Political structure, governance, social order</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">great-houses</a> — The seven Great Houses overview</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">massaran-empire</a> — Ancient sorcerer-king empire, overthrown in the Empyrean War</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>History &amp; Events</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> — Complete timeline from 4100 BE to 380 IY</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-war</a> — 663 BE: Enador and Bellasarius vs the Massaran Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">war-of-three-emperors</a> — 270 IY: Aurex&#39;s death, Numerius&#39;s 87 days, Decimus rises</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">dog-soldier-war</a> — 272-291 IY: don&#39;Kolani guerrilla war, Jute&#39;s peace</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakan-campaigns</a> — 360-368 IY: Eight-year war against Lakandi</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">battle-of-blue-mound</a> — Cynar vs Jarn Murky-Eye, mutual annihilation</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">sacking-of-crossings</a> — 377 IY: Beastman horde destroys Crossings</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Magic &amp; Metaphysics</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic-and-sorcery</a> — Overview of the three traditions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">gnostic-geometry</a> — Nine-fold geometric patterns, Academy sorcery</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> — Living membrane between mortal realm and the Beyond</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-flame</a> — Empyrean priestly magic, divine spark</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-anthyllium</a> — Ancient grimoire of gnostic formulae</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-aurelion</a> — Supreme cosmic being, three interpretations of the sacrifice</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-beyond</a> — The multiversal reality beyond the Veil</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-awakening</a> — Cthonic prophecy, event in progress in Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> — Are Empyrean and Cthonic gods the same divided powers?</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> — Effects of Cthonic influence on living creatures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> — Living Eladran monuments, hostile to Cthonic corruption</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-black-tree\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-black-tree</a> — Scorched Erenthis stump at Thornasse, roots endure, Eolande encountered here, dryad, dreams</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-womb-curse\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-womb-curse</a> — Mystery mentioned by Eolande, connected to Eladra/Elvora, urgently sought by Malachor</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> — Eladran necropolis beneath Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> — Ancient imprisoned beings, Ygrathen cairnhouses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel-earth-hunger</a> — Agricultural blood cult in Argolle farming villages</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-stone-of-sakkara</a> — Artifact carried by Theodotus, amplifies demonic hunger toward innocence, draws the Guzzler</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> — Demonic entity at Fort Ikenvar, drawn south by the Stone of Sakkara, escalating trail of violence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> — Demon-binding sorcery</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">kolani-munitions</a> — Deadly Kolani weapons, gained via Dog Soldier War</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/backlands-field-guide\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-field-guide</a> — Comprehensive survival reference: flora, fauna, hazards for all Backlands regions</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Races &amp; Cultures</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> — Overview of all peoples</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-culture\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-culture</a> — Dominant imperial culture, three-part naming</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">thrassian</a> — Mountain tribal warriors</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/corcanoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">corcanoan</a> — Volcanic island seafarers</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">mornish</a> — Peninsula of Morn, rebellious</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">kolani</a> — Plains/forest tribes, Kolani Irregulars</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> — Conquered seafarers, Erenthis tradition, Crossings refugees</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lysean\" class=\"wiki-link\">lysean</a> — Loyal breadbasket, drought-devastated</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">targ</a> — Magically created race, former slaves</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">shenti</a> — Former Massaran subjects</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tet\" class=\"wiki-link\">tet</a> — Tezerat Plateau, Enador found the Measure here</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> — Wasteland warriors, demon-binders</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">skiothan</a> — Nomadic horse warriors, True Names</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">grathar</a> — Tall reclusive people, Ygrathen blood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">massar</a> — Former sorcerer-king culture</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">vestari</a> — Cosmopolitan allies, Bellasarius lineage</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rinoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">rinoan</a> — Northern tribal confederation, blue/yellow eyes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> — Ancient Argollean race, built Erenthis and Aodahn</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> — Immortal, corrupted by the Veil</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> — Reptilian slave soldiers, await the Awakening</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — Massaran-created monstrous humans</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> — Oldest race, cairnhouse builders</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Reference</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-calendar\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-calendar</a> — Valerian Calendar: 13 months, holidays</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/languages-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">languages-of-mithrapos</a> — Dead and living languages</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> — The player character party</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"sessions-1\">Sessions (1)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> — Campaign session history and PC roster</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"sources-14\">Sources (14)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-fallen-empire-primer\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-fallen-empire-primer</a> — Foundational setting document</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-the-backlands</a> — Backlands province and Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-fort-meade</a> — Fort Meade garrison and political dynamics</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-dramatis-personae\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-dramatis-personae</a> — Full NPC roster with stat blocks</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-crossings-poi\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-crossings-poi</a> — Crossings ruins points of interest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-faiths-of-argolle\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-faiths-of-argolle</a> — Religious traditions, Erenthis, Kharai, Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-sanctuary-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-sanctuary-city</a> — Sanctuary city supplement, 8 districts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-crossings-supplement\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-crossings-supplement</a> — Crossings Adventure Supplement, 32 keyed locations, 7 districts, 5 beastman factions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-gilded-vigil</a> — The Gilded Vigil tomb crawl, Cairnhill Breaks, Kharai innocence question</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-backlands-regional-overview\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-backlands-regional-overview</a> — Backlands Regional Overview, 4 wilderness regions, Varro&#39;s criminal enterprise</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-random-notes\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-random-notes</a> — Shaw&#39;s Sermon, Codex of Ninefold Stillness, eulogies, session prep</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-backlands-timeline\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-backlands-timeline</a> — Backlands provincial timeline 283-380 IY</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-first-empire-history\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-first-empire-history</a> — History of the First Empire, Eladra, Argollean Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-next-session-reference\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-next-session-reference</a> — Session prep: Eolande at the Black Tree, Stone of Sakkara crisis, Legate&#39;s charter proposal</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/src-woodsmans-field-notes\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-woodsmans-field-notes</a> — Woodsman&#39;s Field Notes: flora, fauna, survival across four Backlands regions</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"aodahn","title":"Aodahn","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","ruins","ancient","eladra","empyrean","megadungeon","undercity","sanctuary","aodahn","mystery","spires","argollean"],"html":"<h1 id=\"aodahn\">Aodahn</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;As though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned.&quot; -- Chronicler Varro Silk</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Aodahn</strong> is the ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> harbor-city upon whose ruins <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> was built. The name is an <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> word meaning &quot;sanctuary&quot; or &quot;refuge&quot; -- a name the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrians</a> unconsciously preserved when they founded their own city atop the ruins. Aodahn was built by the true, uncorrupted <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> -- possibly the last community of their kind in the world -- and its remnants represent one of the greatest archaeological mysteries and most dangerous adventuring environments in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Name</strong></td>\n<td>Aodahn (Argollean: &quot;sanctuary&quot; or &quot;refuge&quot;)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Built By</strong></td>\n<td>The <span class=\"dead-link\">Elvora</span> -- the corrupted elven peoples known elsewhere in the world. The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> were something <strong>older and purer</strong>, a people who maintained their connection to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> when others fell away. They were true children of the Empyrean gods, and their works reflected a level of craft and understanding that the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> has never approached.</p>\n<p>Aodahn may have been the <strong>last Eladra community in the world</strong>. If so, its loss -- or transformation, or ascension, or whatever occurred -- represents the final chapter of a civilization that existed before human history began.</p>\n<p>At least one <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> agent is believed to be present in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> at any given time, watching and guarding secrets about what lies below. These agents are subtle, patient, and nearly impossible to identify. Their purpose is unknown -- whether they guard the Threshold, monitor human activity, or pursue some deeper agenda is a matter of speculation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-five-ivory-spires\">The Five Ivory Spires</h2>\n<p>The most visible remnants of Aodahn are the <strong>five ivory spires</strong> that punctuate <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary&#39;s</a> skyline. Each spire is carved from a <strong>single stone</strong> so white it seems to emit light. Each rises <strong>three hundred feet or more</strong> above the harbor. Their proportions are calculated in ratios that <strong>trouble human perception</strong> -- they appear simultaneously too tall and too slender, too massive and too delicate, as though human geometry and Eladra geometry do not quite overlap.</p>\n<h3 id=\"theories-of-purpose\">Theories of Purpose</h3>\n<p>Modern <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> scholars suspect that the spires are <strong>engineered conduits of <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> vitality</strong>, analogous to <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis trees</a> but constructed rather than grown. If this theory is correct, the implications are enormous: Aodahn was not simply a city. It was a <strong>project</strong> -- an engineered environment designed to channel, concentrate, or amplify Empyrean energy for a specific purpose.</p>\n<p>The nature of that purpose remains unknown. Theories include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ascension preparation</strong> -- the spires were infrastructure for a planned transcendence</li>\n<li><strong>Defensive array</strong> -- the spires protected the city from metaphysical threats</li>\n<li><strong>Communication network</strong> -- the spires connected Aodahn to other Eladra sites or to the Empyrean itself</li>\n<li><strong>Energy harvest</strong> -- the spires gathered Empyrean vitality for unknown applications</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"documented-phenomena\">Documented Phenomena</h3>\n<p>The spires cause <strong>documented sensory phenomena</strong> in their vicinity:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sounds in unknown languages</strong> -- whispered conversations in tongues no living scholar can identify, heard most clearly at dawn and dusk</li>\n<li><strong>Sensation of being observed</strong> -- a persistent, unmistakable feeling of attention from an unseen source</li>\n<li><strong>Fleeting images</strong> -- momentary visions of non-existent people and places, glimpsed at the edge of perception and gone when looked at directly</li>\n<li><strong>Emotional resonance</strong> -- feelings of profound peace, terrible grief, or desperate urgency that arise without cause and pass without trace</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Several <strong>cults</strong> have formed around the spires over the centuries, each interpreting the phenomena differently. The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple of the Unconquered Sun</a> monitors these cults and suppresses those that become destabilizing.</p>\n<h3 id=\"individual-spires\">Individual Spires</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Academy Spire</strong> -- One spire was incorporated into the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy Tower</a>, which was constructed <strong>around</strong> it rather than breaking it down. The spire rises through the Tower&#39;s interior, serving as both architectural centerpiece and object of continuous study. <a href=\"#/page/magister-shale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magister Cornelius Shale</a> and his scholars have spent decades attempting to understand its properties.</li>\n<li><strong>The Garden Spire</strong> -- Another spire stands in the <strong>Eladra Spire Garden</strong>, a public space in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ivory Quarter</a>. The Garden produces particularly vivid visions at sunset, drawing curious scholars, devoted cultists, and occasional madmen in equal measure.</li>\n<li><strong>Three additional spires</strong> -- distributed across <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, each surrounded by varying degrees of development, superstition, and restricted access.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-abandonment\">The Abandonment</h2>\n<p>When the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrians</a> first arrived at the site, they found Aodahn <strong>completely abandoned</strong>. This was not the aftermath of war, plague, siege, or flight. There was <strong>no evidence of catastrophe</strong> of any kind.</p>\n<p>The city was simply <strong>empty</strong>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Belongings remained in homes</li>\n<li>Workshops stood open, tools laid out as if in mid-use</li>\n<li>Food rotted on tables</li>\n<li>Personal effects -- clothing, jewelry, documents -- were undisturbed</li>\n<li>No bodies, no blood, no signs of struggle</li>\n<li>No defensive preparations, no evidence of evacuation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The chronicler <strong>Varro Silk</strong>, among the first Mithrian scholars to examine the site, wrote that Aodahn felt &quot;as though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned.&quot;</p>\n<h3 id=\"academic-theories\">Academic Theories</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> has proposed several theories to explain the Abandonment:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Threshold Hypothesis</strong> -- The Eladra used the spires to open a door to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> or to another plane of existence and stepped through, leaving the physical world behind</li>\n<li><strong>The Ascension Model</strong> -- The Eladra transcended physical form, shedding their bodies (which dissolved) and becoming something non-corporeal</li>\n<li><strong>The Catastrophic Severance Theory</strong> -- An accident or external force severed the Eladra&#39;s connection to the Empyrean, destroying them instantly and completely</li>\n<li><strong>The Recall</strong> -- The Eladra were summoned by their gods and departed willingly, leaving everything behind because nothing material would be needed</li>\n</ul>\n<p>None of these theories are proven. The truth, if it can be determined at all, likely lies in the <strong>Foundations of the Spires</strong> -- the deepest level of the <a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Undercity</a>, where the Threshold is said to exist.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-undercity-three-tier-megadungeon\">The Undercity -- Three-Tier Megadungeon</h2>\n<p>Below the surface streets of <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, the ruins of Aodahn extend downward in three distinct tiers, forming one of the most extensive and dangerous dungeon environments in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tier-1-the-warrens-levels-1-3\">Tier 1: The Warrens (Levels 1--3)</h3>\n<p>The uppermost levels, accessible through numerous known entrances throughout the city. The Warrens are a transition zone between the surface world and the true ruins -- partially settled by smugglers, outcasts, and those with reason to avoid the light, but increasingly dangerous as one descends.</p>\n<p><strong>Inhabitants:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Giant vermin (rats, spiders, centipedes) -- thriving in the darkness and refuse</li>\n<li>Oozes -- drawn to the moisture and organic waste</li>\n<li>Smuggler gangs -- using the tunnels as hidden routes between <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary&#39;s</a> districts</li>\n<li>Outcast settlements -- small communities of those who cannot or will not live on the surface</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Collapsed tunnels and flooded passages</li>\n<li>Hidden caches left by smugglers and previous explorers</li>\n<li>Smuggler routes connecting the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a>, <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Commons</a>, and other districts</li>\n<li>Occasional Eladra architecture visible through natural collapse</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Danger Level:</strong> Low to moderate. Manageable by experienced adventurers.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tier-2-old-aodahn-levels-3-7\">Tier 2: Old Aodahn (Levels 3--7)</h3>\n<p>Below the Warrens, the character of the ruins changes dramatically. Here, the preserved heart of the ancient Eladra city lies largely intact. The architecture becomes <strong>alien</strong> -- proportions shift, materials defy identification, spaces exist that should not be possible given the geometry above. The area is saturated with <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> energy, producing persistent strange phenomena.</p>\n<p><strong>Inhabitants:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Construct guardians -- <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>-built automatons still operational after centuries, maintaining patrol routes and responding to intrusion with mechanical precision</li>\n<li>Doppelgangers -- entities of unknown origin that have taken up residence in the abandoned city</li>\n<li>Minotaurs -- drawn to the labyrinthine passages</li>\n<li>Minor elementals -- manifesting spontaneously from the concentrated Empyrean energy</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Preserved Eladra workshops, libraries, and living spaces -- still containing artifacts, documents, and equipment</li>\n<li>Empyrean energy saturation causes minor reality distortions: lights without source, sounds without origin, time moving at inconsistent rates</li>\n<li>Strange phenomena: flickering illumination in sealed chambers, conversations in unknown languages echoing through empty halls, fleeting images of Eladra going about lives that ended centuries ago</li>\n<li>Architecture that does not obey human geometric conventions</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Danger Level:</strong> Significant. Requires well-equipped and experienced parties. The constructs alone are dangerous, and the environmental effects of Empyrean saturation add unpredictability.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tier-3-foundations-of-the-spires-levels-7\">Tier 3: Foundations of the Spires (Levels 7+)</h3>\n<p>The deepest known level of the Undercity. Here, at the roots of the great spires, the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> built something extraordinary -- the infrastructure of whatever process they ultimately used to depart the physical world. The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> energy is overwhelming. Reality itself becomes unreliable.</p>\n<p><strong>Inhabitants:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Masterwork constructs -- far more powerful than those found in Old Aodahn, designed to protect the most critical installations</li>\n<li>Major elementals -- powerful beings manifesting from the extreme concentration of Empyrean energy</li>\n<li>Entities of unknown origin -- things that exist in the space between the physical world and whatever lies beyond the Threshold</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Features:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Threshold</strong> -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened. The door has <strong>not fully closed</strong>. Whatever process the Eladra used to depart left a permanent weakness in the boundary between the physical world and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a>. This is the source of the phenomena that pervade all of Aodahn -- the sounds, the visions, the sensation of being watched. It is a wound in reality, and it has not healed.</li>\n<li>Empyrean energy so concentrated that mortal flesh reacts unpredictably -- healing, harming, transforming, or simply refusing to behave as expected</li>\n<li>Magical effects are amplified, distorted, or inverted in the Threshold&#39;s vicinity</li>\n<li>The roots of the spires themselves, visible as massive pillars of white stone descending into the bedrock, still humming with energy after centuries</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Danger Level:</strong> Extreme. Few have reached this level and returned. Those who have describe experiences that they struggle to articulate -- as though the language for what they witnessed does not yet exist.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"significance\">Significance</h2>\n<p>Aodahn is not merely an archaeological curiosity or an adventuring site. It is a <strong>living mystery</strong> -- a place where the past has not fully become the past, where the Eladra&#39;s departure left a mark that the world has not yet absorbed.</p>\n<p>For the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a>, it represents the greatest unsolved puzzle in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> -- perhaps in the world. For the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple</a>, it is a potential theological crisis: if the Eladra achieved a form of ascension outside the framework of the Unconquered Sun&#39;s theology, what does that imply about the faith? For the <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor</a>, it is a resource -- artifacts from the Undercity are valuable, and knowledge of the spires could be leveraged politically. For the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> agents who still watch from the shadows, it is something else entirely -- a trust, a burden, a promise kept across centuries.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gm-notes\">GM Notes</h2>\n<p>Aodahn should be treated as the <strong>deep background mystery</strong> of <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. Key principles:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>It does not need to be the focus.</strong> The mystery of the Eladra and the Threshold can exist as atmosphere and background for dozens of sessions before becoming directly relevant.</li>\n<li><strong>It should always be felt.</strong> The spires are visible from anywhere in the city. The phenomena are documented. The Undercity is always below. Even in political adventures that never go underground, Aodahn is present.</li>\n<li><strong>The Threshold is real.</strong> Whatever the Eladra did, it left a permanent mark. The door has not fully closed. This is the source of the phenomena -- and potentially a source of much greater threats or opportunities.</li>\n<li><strong>The megadungeon scales with the campaign.</strong> The Warrens are appropriate for low-level parties. Old Aodahn challenges experienced adventurers. The Foundations of the Spires are endgame content.</li>\n<li><strong>The Eladra agents are watching.</strong> At least one is likely in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> at any time. They are subtle, nearly impossible to identify, and their agenda is unknown. They are a wild card that the GM can deploy when the time is right.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city built upon Aodahn&#39;s ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Eladra</a> -- the builders</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean</a> -- the divine source of the spires&#39; power</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis Trees</a> -- natural analogues to the spires&#39; function</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Ivory Quarter</a> -- district built atop the ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> -- institution studying the ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magister-shale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magister Cornelius Shale</a> -- Academy Regent</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Undercity</a> -- the megadungeon</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- the province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Elvora</a> -- the corrupted elven peoples (distinct from the Eladra)</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"argoll-river","title":"Argoll River","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","river","backlands","crossings","sanctuary","fort-harvald","argent-bay","trade-route","neglect","beastmen"],"html":"<h1 id=\"argoll-river\">Argoll River</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Argoll River</strong> is the major waterway of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, flowing from the interior highlands to the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Turquoise Sea</a> at <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. It is the primary geographic artery of the province -- the feature around which settlement, trade, and military strategy have organized for millennia.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Major river</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Region</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the-backlands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Source</strong></td>\n<td>Interior highlands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Mouth</strong></td>\n<td>[[sanctuary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Delta</strong></td>\n<td>[[crossings</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Key Crossings</strong></td>\n<td>The Stone Yoke Bridge (at [[crossings</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Key Settlements</strong></td>\n<td>[[sanctuary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Current Condition</strong></td>\n<td>Clogged, neglected, slow, brown, stinking</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography\">Geography</h2>\n<p>The Argoll River flows from the interior of the Backlands toward the coast, passing through or near several key locations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>[[Sanctuary</span></strong> -- The provincial capital sits at the river&#39;s mouth where it empties into the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Turquoise Sea</a>. The ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> city of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> was built at this same location, suggesting the river has been a center of civilization for millennia.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a></strong> -- Located on the river delta, this settlement serves as a forward base near the ruins of Crossings.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a></strong> -- The ruined river city sits at the delta where the Argoll empties into <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argent Bay</a>. The city&#39;s name reflects its historical role as a crossing point -- the convergence of seven imperial roads at the river.</li>\n<li><strong>The Stone Yoke Bridge</strong> -- Spans the river&#39;s widest channel at Crossings, serving as the primary entry point into the ruined city.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-condition\">Current Condition</h2>\n<p>The Argoll River is <strong>clogged with six years of neglect and beastman filth</strong>. Since the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> in 377 IY (or 374 IY per the alternate timeline), the river has deteriorated from a navigable trade artery into a sluggish, foul waterway:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Slow</strong> -- choked by debris, silt, and years without maintenance</li>\n<li><strong>Brown</strong> -- muddied by uncontrolled erosion and contamination</li>\n<li><strong>Stinking</strong> -- polluted by beastman habitation, rotting vegetation, and the general decay of an untended watershed</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Before the fall of Crossings, the Argoll was a vital trade route connecting the interior settlements to the coast and, through Sanctuary&#39;s harbor, to the broader <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Its degradation is a physical manifestation of the Backlands&#39; collapse -- a river that once carried commerce now carries filth.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"historical-significance\">Historical Significance</h2>\n<p>The Argoll River has been the spine of civilization in the Backlands across three distinct eras:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> Era</strong> -- The Eladra built <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> at the river&#39;s mouth, recognizing its strategic value as the gateway between sea and interior.</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> / <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> Era</strong> -- The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a> centered their civilization along the river, with <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings/Thornasse</a> as their cultural heart and the great <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> planted at the river delta.</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> Era</strong> -- The Empire built its Backlands infrastructure along the river corridor, with Sanctuary as the capital and Crossings as the major interior trade hub, connected by seven imperial roads.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The river&#39;s name likely derives from <strong>Argolle</strong>, the imperial province in which it flows.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"strategic-importance\">Strategic Importance</h2>\n<p>Control of the Argoll River means control of the Backlands. Whoever holds <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> at the mouth and can project power upriver to <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> controls the province&#39;s economic and military lifeline. The current situation -- where Sanctuary is held by <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> but Crossings is occupied by 800 <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- represents a fractured strategic picture. The river connects two worlds: imperial civilization at the coast and beastman-occupied ruins in the interior.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- Provincial capital at the river&#39;s mouth</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- Ruined city at the river delta</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> -- Settlement on the river delta</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argent Bay</a> -- Bay where the Argoll meets the sea at Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province the river defines</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">sacking-of-crossings</a> -- The event that led to the river&#39;s neglect</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a> -- Ancient Eladran city at the river&#39;s mouth</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"bone-creek","title":"Bone Creek","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["settlement","outpost","bone-creek","backlands","scalpers","frontier","bounty"],"html":"<h1 id=\"bone-creek\">Bone Creek</h1>\n<p>Deep in the Northern <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, as far as any man is willing to go, sits the outpost of <strong>Bone Creek</strong>. A ramshackle frontier settlement that has reinvented itself as the epicenter of the Scalper trade, Bone Creek is a place of desperate ambition, casual violence, and hard-won survival.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>It&#39;s far too cold, you&#39;re always hungry, and you&#39;re just as likely to get shanked in the streets as you are to meet your doom on the Slog. With a little luck you might be able to kill a few of the fucking beastmen and make enough coin to put some food in your belly.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>But here, in Bone Creek, luck can only get you so far. The veteran Scalpers are unlike any men you have ever encountered, their eyes dulled from the horrors they have seen and endured, or tinged with a glint of madness. Some even bear the marks of corruption openly.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>They say, those who hunt the beastmen are changed.</em>\n<em>They say, &quot;The Bounty takes its toll.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-silver-rush\">The Silver Rush</h3>\n<p>Years ago, a silver rush in the nearby foothills led to an influx of prospectors, speculators, and miners. Those days are long gone. The mines are barren and forgotten, and until recently the outpost was in decline, nearly abandoned — a ghost of its former self slowly dying on the frontier.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-scalper-rush\">The Scalper Rush</h3>\n<p>Two years ago, a great horde of <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> attacked and sacked the city of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. The few refugees who managed to escape with their lives tell stories of the horrors the beastmen inflicted upon the citizens of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire</a> that day. Now, those same beastmen have settled in the ruin of the city and begun to push farther south, kidnapping farmers, raiding, and worse.</p>\n<p>By the decree of the Emperor <strong>Justinian Claudius Decimus</strong>, the beastmen are to be culled. Vile subhumanoid creatures, the beastmen have an unnatural propensity for violence and are responsible for committing unspeakable atrocities. The price of a beastman scalp is <strong>one imperial gold mark</strong>, creating an entirely new rush for Bone Creek — not for silver, but for blood.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"scalpers\">Scalpers</h2>\n<p>Those who seek the Imperial Bounty are called <strong>Scalpers</strong>. Hard men and women who come from every walk of life, drawn by the allure of the Imperial Bounty, a Scalper&#39;s life is one of chaos, violence, and peril.</p>\n<p>For whatever reason, each Scalper has left their former life behind and journeyed to the edge of civilization. The veteran Scalpers are unlike any men one might encounter elsewhere — their eyes dulled from the horrors they have seen and endured, or tinged with a glint of madness. Some even bear the marks of corruption openly.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"locations-in-bone-creek\">Locations in Bone Creek</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-flophouse\">The Flophouse</h3>\n<p>A former barn converted into a single large room filled with straw mattresses, blankets, and a community pot of stew. The food is not very good, the floor is hard, and it can be bitterly cold in winter. It is the cheapest accommodation in town and the first stop for most newly arrived Scalpers.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr#theo\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theo</a></strong>, the proprietor, does not suffer delinquent payments. He carries a brutal cudgel, and no one dares cross him. Beneath his gruff exterior, however, Theo is secretly in <strong><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr&#39;s</a></strong> pocket — feeding him information on Scalper gangs, rumors, and activities within town. The Flophouse serves as Marr&#39;s eyes and ears on the newest and most vulnerable arrivals.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Theo</strong> — Proprietor. Carries a brutal cudgel. Secret informant for <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"the-pretty-peach\">The Pretty Peach</h3>\n<p>A tavern and inn serving watered-down ale, cheap wine, and decent food. Hard beds are available for a few marks, though decent rooms are in high demand. The Pretty Peach is the domain of <strong><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a></strong>, its proprietor — a hardened frontiersman with a storied reputation.</p>\n<p>Thaddeus has a deal with the local pimp <strong>Crackback</strong>, a brutish <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">targ</a> who employs several working girls. A simmering rivalry with <a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Double Sevens</a> directly across the street has resulted in large-scale brawls on more than one occasion.</p>\n<p>Thaddeus secretly operates a <strong>racket</strong> within town, using the Pretty Peach as his base of operations and Theo at the Flophouse as his informant network.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a></strong> — Proprietor. Hardened frontiersman. Secret racketeer.</li>\n<li><strong>Crackback</strong> — A brutish <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">targ</a>. Local pimp and Marr&#39;s right-hand man. Employs several working girls.</li>\n<li><strong>Trixie</strong> — A young and beautiful slave girl.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"double-sevens\">Double Sevens</h3>\n<p>Located directly across the street from the Pretty Peach, <strong>Double Sevens</strong> is a relatively new establishment operated by the wealthy merchant <strong><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a></strong>. It caters to the more successful Scalpers and the burgeoning burgher class of Bone Creek, offering a notable step up in quality from the Peach.</p>\n<p>Double Sevens serves imported spirits, wines, and ales. It hosts gambling tables and employs its own prostitutes, who are &quot;held to a higher standard than Peach girls.&quot; <strong>Madame Selka</strong>, a young and beautiful <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shenti</a> woman, oversees the working girls and has frequent, public arguments with Watts.</p>\n<p>Watts is a close ally of <strong><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a></strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>, and ultimately seeks to bring civilization to Bone Creek — transforming it from a lawless outpost into something resembling a proper town.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a></strong> — Proprietor. Wealthy merchant. Ally of <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a>. Seeks to civilize Bone Creek.</li>\n<li><strong>Madame Selka</strong> — Young, beautiful <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shenti</a> woman. Oversees the working girls. Has frequent public arguments with Watts.</li>\n<li><strong>Frog</strong> — Watts&#39; assistant and advisor. A lifelong slave. Expert with administration and numbers.</li>\n<li><strong>Three-Finger Kanos</strong> — Bodyguard and head of security for Double Sevens.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"tackle-and-harness\">Tackle and Harness</h3>\n<p>An all-purpose general shop and small stable run by <strong>Royce and Rhoda Harbecke</strong> and their children. The shop caters specifically to Scalper needs, carrying a wide inventory of goods useful for hunting <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ranka</a> or exploring the wilderness. A small, newly built stable is attached.</p>\n<p>The Harbeckes are honest and hard-working <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> citizens — a rare breed in Bone Creek. One of their children could potentially be hired as a henchman.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Royce Harbecke</strong> — Co-owner. Honest Mithrian citizen.</li>\n<li><strong>Rhoda Harbecke</strong> — Co-owner. Wife of Royce.</li>\n<li><strong>Harbecke children</strong> — Help run the shop. Potential henchman hires.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"gretas-tinctures\">Greta&#39;s Tinctures</h3>\n<p>An old recluse named <strong>Greta</strong> sells minor alchemical items and herbs from this small shop. Greta has lived in Bone Creek longer than almost anyone else in the settlement. She is strange and eccentric, with no known family.</p>\n<p>Rumors persist that Greta is a <strong>witch</strong> who serves a demonic being. Whether these rumors hold any truth is unknown, but few are willing to test them.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Greta</strong> — Old recluse. Alchemist and herbalist. Rumored witch who may serve a demonic being. One of the longest residents of Bone Creek.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"bone-creek-surgery\">Bone Creek Surgery</h3>\n<p>The local barber surgeon, known simply as <strong>Doc</strong> (real name <strong>Quinten</strong>), operates out of this establishment. Services include bloodletting, amputations, and minor dentistry. Doc also offers baths, hair cutting, shaving, and enemas.</p>\n<p>He is hardly the most talented barber surgeon in the land, but he is the only one in Bone Creek, and that counts for something on the frontier.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Doc (Quinten)</strong> — Barber surgeon. Mediocre talent, but the only medical professional in town.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"irontoe-smithing\">Irontoe Smithing</h3>\n<p><strong>Pontus &quot;Irontoe&quot;</strong> lost his leg fighting the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> and now walks on an iron foot attached to a wooden leg — hence his name. He is a skilled smith capable of both weapon and armor smithing, though he is often too busy for serious commissions.</p>\n<p>Irontoe has recently taken on several apprentices. His loud voice can frequently be heard chastising his students from across town.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pontus &quot;Irontoe&quot;</strong> — Smith. Lost his leg fighting the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a>. Iron foot on wooden leg. Skilled but perpetually busy. Loud and demanding taskmaster.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"the-house-of-silence\">The House of Silence</h3>\n<p>The church of <strong><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></strong> in Bone Creek. It was recently taken over by a young priest named <strong><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a></strong> after the previous priest, <strong>Father Draven</strong>, succumbed to disease.</p>\n<p>Brother Marco made the long trek to Bone Creek alone after claiming to have received a vision from <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. He arrived malnourished and wounded, but undeterred. His weekly service now draws enough attendees that many must stand, spending hours in silent prayer. In a place as godless as Bone Creek, Marco&#39;s devotion has struck a chord.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a></strong> — Young priest of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. Arrived alone after a vision. Malnourished and wounded on arrival. Services are standing-room-only.</li>\n<li><strong>Father Draven</strong> (deceased) — Previous priest. Succumbed to disease. Known as a drunkard.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"red-river-exchange\">Red River Exchange</h3>\n<p>The <strong>largest building in town</strong>, owned and operated by the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>. This is where Scalpers sell their plundered loot and treasure, and critically, where <strong>beastman scalps are sold</strong> in exchange for the Imperial Bounty (minus a transaction fee).</p>\n<p>The merchants of the Exchange are shrewd negotiators who employ an army of hardened guardsmen and bodyguards. The Exchange is both the economic heart of Bone Creek and the Consortium&#39;s seat of power in the settlement.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a></strong> serves as <strong>Lord Merchant</strong> — a polished, shrewd businessman deeply involved in the local economy and political dealings of Bone Creek. He is a close ally of <a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Key NPCs:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a></strong> — Lord Merchant. <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> representative. Polished and shrewd. Deeply involved in local politics and economy.</li>\n<li>Numerous hardened guardsmen and bodyguards (unnamed).</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"power-dynamics\">Power Dynamics</h2>\n<p>Bone Creek&#39;s politics revolve around three interconnected power blocs:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a></strong> — Controls the Pretty Peach and the Flophouse (through Theo). Operates a secret racket. Backed by Crackback and street-level muscle. Represents the old, rough frontier way of doing things.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a></strong> — Controls Double Sevens. Backed by wealth, Madame Selka&#39;s operation, and Three-Finger Kanos&#39;s security. Allied with Cassian Varro. Represents the push toward civilization and order.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a> / <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a></strong> — Controls the Red River Exchange and the flow of money. The economic backbone of Bone Creek. Allied with Watts.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The simmering rivalry between <strong>the Pretty Peach</strong> and <strong>Double Sevens</strong> has already resulted in large-scale brawls and shows no signs of cooling. This conflict mirrors a deeper tension in Bone Creek: whether the settlement will remain a lawless frontier outpost or evolve into something more civilized.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"complete-npc-registry\">Complete NPC Registry</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Name</th>\n<th>Location</th>\n<th>Role</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Theo</strong></td>\n<td>The Flophouse</td>\n<td>Proprietor; secret informant for Marr</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**<span class=\"dead-link\">thaddeus-marr</td>\n<td>Thaddeus Marr</span>**</td>\n<td>The Pretty Peach</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Crackback</strong></td>\n<td>The Pretty Peach</td>\n<td>Targ pimp; Marr&#39;s right-hand man</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Trixie</strong></td>\n<td>The Pretty Peach</td>\n<td>Young slave girl</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**<span class=\"dead-link\">tolliver-watts</td>\n<td>Tolliver Watts</span>**</td>\n<td>Double Sevens</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Madame Selka</strong></td>\n<td>Double Sevens</td>\n<td>Shenti madam; oversees working girls</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Frog</strong></td>\n<td>Double Sevens</td>\n<td>Slave; assistant/advisor; expert administrator</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Three-Finger Kanos</strong></td>\n<td>Double Sevens</td>\n<td>Bodyguard; head of security</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Royce Harbecke</strong></td>\n<td>Tackle and Harness</td>\n<td>Shop co-owner</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rhoda Harbecke</strong></td>\n<td>Tackle and Harness</td>\n<td>Shop co-owner</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Greta</strong></td>\n<td>Greta&#39;s Tinctures</td>\n<td>Alchemist; rumored witch</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Doc (Quinten)</strong></td>\n<td>Bone Creek Surgery</td>\n<td>Barber surgeon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pontus &quot;Irontoe&quot;</strong></td>\n<td>Irontoe Smithing</td>\n<td>Smith; lost leg fighting Lakandi</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**<span class=\"dead-link\">brother-marco</td>\n<td>Brother Marco</span>**</td>\n<td>House of Silence</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Father Draven</strong> (deceased)</td>\n<td>House of Silence</td>\n<td>Former priest; drunkard</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**<span class=\"dead-link\">cassian-varro</td>\n<td>Cassian Varro</span>**</td>\n<td>Red River Exchange</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The province in which Bone Creek is located</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — The sacked city whose fall created the Scalper trade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures hunted for the Imperial Bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> — The trading consortium that runs the Exchange</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> — Proprietor of the Pretty Peach and local power broker</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">tolliver-watts</a> — Proprietor of Double Sevens and would-be civilizer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> — Lord Merchant of the Red River Exchange</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> — Priest of Seros at the House of Silence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> — The god worshipped at the House of Silence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> — The barbarians Irontoe fought before losing his leg</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> — The empire whose bounty drives the Scalper economy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> — The nearest major port city in the Backlands</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"cairnhill","title":"Cairnhill","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","town","cairnhouse","kharai","psychic-bleed","dreams","ygrathen","argollean-brotherhood","scrubland","argolle","backlands","cairnhill-breaks","mount-argolle","thune","harpies","gilded-oath","elvora"],"html":"<h1 id=\"cairnhill\">Cairnhill</h1>\n<p><strong>Cairnhill</strong> is a town on the scrubland edge of the Province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, built around -- or rather, near -- a <strong>cairnhouse</strong> containing one or more of the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a>, the Imprisoned Ones. The town and its people have been shaped by six to seven generations of exposure to the <strong>psychic bleed</strong> emanating from the cairnhouse: a slow, persistent pressure that has molded human consciousness into something subtly but distinctly different from the norm.</p>\n<p>Cairnhill is not a cursed place. Its people are not corrupted, damaged, or diminished. They are <strong>changed</strong> -- adapted, over generations, to a presence that most people cannot perceive and would not survive unchanged. The residents of Cairnhill are what happens when human beings live in close proximity to something vast and patient and fundamentally other for long enough that the otherness becomes part of who they are.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cairnhouse\">The Cairnhouse</h2>\n<p>The cairnhouse stands on the hill from which the town takes its name. It is a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> construction -- built using binding traditions that predate the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> by an unknown span of time, designed to imprison one or more of the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> using techniques no contemporary practitioner can replicate.</p>\n<p>The town does not allow anyone near the hill.</p>\n<p>This prohibition is not law in the Mithrian sense. It is not enforced by guards or fortifications. It is simply understood -- by the residents of Cairnhill, by the few outsiders who have reason to visit, by everyone who has learned what the hill is and what happens to those who approach it without the understanding that comes from having lived with it for generations. The people of Cairnhill protect the cairnhouse not because they worship what is inside, but because they know what it is and what would happen if the binding were disturbed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-psychic-bleed\">The Psychic Bleed</h2>\n<p>The cairnhouse does not perfectly contain what is inside. The beings imprisoned within press against the walls of their binding constantly, with the patience of something that has more time than the dam. The pressure leaks. Over six to seven generations, this leakage -- the psychic bleed -- has shaped the people of Cairnhill.</p>\n<h3 id=\"effects-on-residents\">Effects on Residents</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Too-complete attention.</strong> Cairnhill residents attend to their surroundings with a focus and thoroughness that unsettles outsiders. Their gaze does not wander. Their awareness does not drift. They are present with an intensity that exceeds ordinary human attentiveness -- not hostile, not aggressive, simply fully, completely aware.</li>\n<li><strong>Tolerance for enclosed spaces and darkness.</strong> Conditions that produce claustrophobia or discomfort in others are comfortable -- genuinely comfortable -- for Cairnhill residents. Tight spaces, deep darkness, the absence of sky and light -- these are not threatening environments. They are natural. This tolerance is not learned or cultivated. It is inherited, bred into the population by generations of proximity to something that exists in enclosed darkness.</li>\n<li><strong>A different relationship to time.</strong> Cairnhill residents are patient in a way that exceeds discipline or temperament. They experience the passage of time at a different weight. Hours and days and seasons move through their awareness with a cadence that outsiders find difficult to match. They are not slow -- they are calibrated to a timescale that is not human.</li>\n<li><strong>Perceptiveness below normal awareness.</strong> Cairnhill residents perceive things that others do not -- not visions or supernatural insight, but a baseline environmental awareness that operates below conscious attention. They notice what others miss. They feel shifts in atmosphere, mood, and presence that register nowhere in ordinary human perception. This is not a skill. It is a condition of their existence, shaped by generations of living beside something that communicates in pressures too subtle for normal senses.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-dreams\">The Dreams</h2>\n<p>Every resident of Cairnhill dreams of <strong>vast enclosed spaces</strong>.</p>\n<p>The dreams feature halls, corridors, and chambers of impossible scale -- structures too large to exist beneath any hill, lit by no visible source, built in geometries that are not quite wrong but not quite right. The spaces are immense, deeply other, and entirely real. They are not nightmares. They do not frighten. They simply are -- as present and persistent as the waking world, as familiar as the streets of the town itself.</p>\n<p>Residents of Cairnhill discuss the geography of their shared dreams with the <strong>casual familiarity of people discussing shared weather</strong>. They know the corridors. They recognize the chambers. They have navigated the impossible halls in sleep since childhood, and their parents before them, and their parents&#39; parents before them. The dream geography is as real to them as the physical geography of the town.</p>\n<p><strong>It has never occurred to them that outsiders do not share the same dreams.</strong></p>\n<p>This is perhaps the most telling indicator of how thoroughly the psychic bleed has shaped the community. The dreams are not aberrant. They are not discussed as unusual or remarkable. They are simply part of life -- as natural and unremarkable as the hill, as the darkness they do not fear, as the patience that runs deeper in them than it does in anyone else.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood\">The Argollean Brotherhood</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> seeks access to the cairnhouse for the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> binding structures it contains. The Brotherhood is not interested in the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> themselves -- they want the knowledge of how to bind them. The binding tradition that produced the cairnhouses represents an achievement of containment magic that no contemporary institution can replicate, and the Brotherhood considers this knowledge invaluable.</p>\n<p>The town of Cairnhill does not allow anyone near the hill.</p>\n<p>This tension has been building for years. The Brotherhood sends scholars, petitioners, negotiators. Cairnhill refuses them -- not with violence, not with argument, but with the implacable patience of people who have been shaped by something that has more time than anything built to contain it. The Brotherhood wants what it wants. Cairnhill will not give it. Neither side has yielded.</p>\n<p>The Brotherhood&#39;s frustration is compounded by the fact that the other known cairnhouse in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- the one at <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a> -- is watched over by <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a>, a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> hermit who has guarded his charge for centuries and is even less likely to permit access.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cairnhill-breaks\">The Cairnhill Breaks</h2>\n<p>Three miles east of Cairnhill, the scrubland gives way to broken grey limestone ridges known as the <strong>Cairnhill Breaks</strong>. The terrain rises toward the eastern horizon where <strong>Mount Argolle</strong> stands, its white volcanic plume visible for miles across the province. The Breaks are a landscape of layered history:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Lower gullies</strong> choked with <strong>maquis scrub</strong> -- dense, thorny Mediterranean-type vegetation that makes ground-level navigation slow and difficult</li>\n<li><strong>Upper cliffs</strong> of bare limestone, carved by the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire#first-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> into <strong>terraces, archways, and inscription panels</strong> -- monumental stonework that has survived centuries of weathering and neglect</li>\n<li><strong>Highest crags</strong> occupied by <strong>harpy nests</strong> -- the winged predators have claimed the most inaccessible peaks, making aerial approach dangerous and establishing the Breaks as territory that sensible travelers avoid</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"mount-argolle\">Mount Argolle</h3>\n<p><strong>Mount Argolle</strong> dominates the eastern horizon beyond the Cairnhill Breaks -- a volcanic peak whose <strong>white plume</strong> is a constant presence in the sky above the province. The mountain gives its name to the broader region of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> and serves as a geographic landmark visible from most of the surrounding territory. The volcanic activity is ongoing but not immediately threatening; the plume is a steady exhalation rather than an eruption.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-thune-remnant\">The Thune Remnant</h3>\n<p>Among the lower ruins of the Cairnhill Breaks dwell the <strong>Thune remnant</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">lizard-folk</a> descendants of <strong>Argollean slave-soldiers</strong> who served the First Empire and never left after its collapse. They have inhabited the ruins of the Breaks for centuries, maintaining their own culture, their own relationship with the landscape, and their own understanding of what lies buried beneath the hills.</p>\n<p>The Thune remnant are not hostile by default, but they are territorial and wary. They regard the Cairnhill Breaks as ancestral ground -- not because their ancestors built the ruins (they did not) but because their ancestors were brought here as soldiers and never given anywhere else to go. The Breaks are the only home they have known for generations.</p>\n<p>Their relationship with the sealed <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> is distinct from that of the Cairnhill townsfolk. While the human residents of Cairnhill have been shaped by the psychic bleed into something subtly other, the Thune remnant have developed a <strong>religious relationship</strong> with the imprisoned entity. Some among them regard the Kharai as a <strong>sleeping god</strong> -- a divine being imprisoned by the enemies of their people. This belief has produced factions like the <strong>Covenant of the Open Hand</strong>, a Thune group that seeks to weaken the seals and free what they consider a deity unjustly imprisoned.</p>\n<p>The weakening of the seals at <a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Gilded Vigil</a> has emboldened the Thune remnant. They have grown bolder in recent months, pushing further from their usual territory and taking a more active interest in the guardian tomb network that threads through the Breaks.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-guardian-tomb-network\">The Guardian Tomb Network</h3>\n<p>The Cairnhill Breaks contain a network of <strong><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> guardian tombs</strong> -- stations on a <strong>seal-circuit</strong> that reinforces the imprisonment of the Kharai beneath the hill. Each tomb houses a member of the <strong>Gilded Oath</strong>, warrior-priests who underwent the <strong>Sevenfold Wounding</strong> and entered a state of partial undeath to maintain the seals in perpetuity. The guardian tomb known as <a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Gilded Vigil</a> -- the Second Seal station -- is the site where the guardian Veranthas has broken his covenant, weakening the seal network and drawing multiple factions to the Breaks.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- The Imprisoned Ones contained within the cairnhouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- The Ygrathen hermit guarding the other known cairnhouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">lake-silverhead</a> -- The location of the other cairnhouse in Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The faction seeking cairnhouse access</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> -- The builders of the cairnhouses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province where Cairnhill is located</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The tradition from which the Kharai are notably distinct</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-gilded-vigil</a> -- The guardian tomb in the Cairnhill Breaks where the Second Seal has been compromised</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> -- The civilization that created the Gilded Oath and the seal-circuit</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> -- The lizard-folk remnant inhabiting the Breaks</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"crossings-hinterlands","title":"The Crossings Hinterlands","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["wilderness","hinterlands","crossings","backlands","encounters"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-crossings-hinterlands\">The Crossings Hinterlands</h1>\n<p><strong>The Crossings Hinterlands</strong> are the territory immediately surrounding the ruined city of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>. This region is significantly more dangerous than <a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Slog</a> -- <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> activity is dramatically higher here, and the encounter table reflects the proximity to a major beastman population center. The undead presence is also more severe, with wraiths and wights stalking alongside the living threats.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography\">Geography</h2>\n<p>The Hinterlands form a ring of increasingly dangerous territory around the <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> ruins. As travelers approach the ruined city, the frequency and lethality of encounters escalates sharply. The landscape transitions from the open scrub of <a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Slog</a> into terrain marked by the ruins of outlying settlements, overgrown roads, and the detritus of the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">377 IY sacking</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"access\">Access</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a></strong> is the staging point for entering the Crossings Hinterlands. Parties venturing into this territory typically provision and gather intelligence at Fort Harvald before pushing into the Hinterlands and ultimately into <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> itself.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"encounter-table\">Encounter Table</h2>\n<p>Roll <strong>1d8</strong> for each encounter:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Roll</th>\n<th>Encounter</th>\n<th>Number</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">beastmen</td>\n<td>Beastman Orcs</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">beastmen</td>\n<td>Beastman Gnolls</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">beastmen</td>\n<td>Beastman Ogre</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Grave Ghouls</td>\n<td>1d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Stirges</td>\n<td>1d10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Wight</td>\n<td>1d2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Wraith</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Troll</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>The Hinterlands encounter table is notably more dangerous than <a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Slog&#39;s</a>. Key differences:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Beastman gnolls</strong> replace goblins -- gnolls are a more formidable threat than the goblin warbands of the Slog.</li>\n<li><strong>Beastman ogres</strong> appear as a standalone encounter -- a single ogre is a serious threat to an unprepared party.</li>\n<li><strong>Wraiths</strong> are present -- incorporeal undead that do not appear in the Slog&#39;s table. Their presence near <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> may be connected to the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> or the <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Trolls</strong> cap the table, same as the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>No brigands or human hostiles</strong> -- this territory is too deep into beastman country for human bandits to operate.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city at the center of the Hinterlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> -- The staging point for entering the Hinterlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a> -- The less dangerous wasteland south of the Hinterlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province containing the Hinterlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The dominant threat in the Hinterlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">sacking-of-crossings</a> -- The 377 IY event that created this wasteland</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- The Eladran necropolis beneath Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-awakening</a> -- The Cthonic prophecy connected to the region</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"crossings","title":"Crossings","category":"locations","status":"destroyed","tags":["ruins","beastmen","crossings","nethercity","erenthis","krysea","thornasse"],"html":"<h1 id=\"crossings\">Crossings</h1>\n<p><strong>Crossings</strong> is a ruined <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> river city in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, located west of <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> at the delta of the <a href=\"#/page/argoll-river\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argoll River</a> where it empties into <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argent Bay</a>. Once a major trade hub sitting at the convergence of seven imperial roads, the city was <strong>sacked by a vast, organized horde of <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a></strong> in <strong>377 IY</strong> (per the <a href=\"#/page/src-fallen-empire-primer\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fallen Empire Primer</a>; the <a href=\"#/page/src-the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands timeline</a> places this event at <strong>374 IY</strong> -- note this discrepancy). The sacking prompted Emperor <strong>Justinian Claudius Decimus</strong> to issue the imperial scalp bounty of one gold mark per beastman scalp, creating the entire Scalper trade and transforming <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> from a dying silver-rush outpost into the epicenter of the bounty economy.</p>\n<p>Today, approximately <strong>800 beastmen</strong> occupy the ruins, divided among <strong>five mutually hostile factions</strong>. The city is classified as <strong>Outlands (Ruins)</strong> -- a shattered monument to imperial failure, a haunted labyrinth crawling with beastmen, undead, and beasts, and a treasure trove of lost wealth from three distinct civilizations layered one atop another.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Former Names</strong></td>\n<td>Thornasse (Avari) / Krysea (First Empire / Eladran)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>West of <span class=\"dead-link\">Eladra</span> when <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> was still a fishing village. High towers rose above the river delta. Krysea fell when its people were destroyed by the <strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a></strong> slave soldiers they had created. The ruins were buried and forgotten -- but they are still down there, beneath the Avari foundations, beneath the Mithrian pavement. The <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> entrance at Location 32 leads down into what remains.</p>\n<h3 id=\"thornasse-avari\">Thornasse (Avari)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> built <strong>Thornasse</strong> around the great <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a></strong> trees left behind by the Eladra. The fruit of a single Erenthis could feed a dozen men. The roots ran down into something old and warm beneath the earth. The trees were sacred -- the largest, at the city center, served as the <strong>spiritual axis of the Avari Confederation</strong> for generations.</p>\n<h3 id=\"crossings-mithrian-349-iy-onward\">Crossings (Mithrian, 349 IY onward)</h3>\n<p>In <strong>349 IY</strong>, the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> High Mage <strong><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a></strong> burned the great Erenthis at the city center. Avari resistance collapsed. The Mithrians renamed the settlement <strong>Crossings</strong>, paved over the Avari foundations, and built baths, forums, and temples in the imperial style. The city thrived for <strong>28 years</strong> before the sacking.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-sacking-377-iy\">The Sacking (377 IY)</h2>\n<p>The sacking of Crossings was unlike anything the Backlands had seen. This was not the usual goblin warband or orc raider -- it was an <strong>organized, coordinated, vast</strong> assault. Three gates were breached simultaneously. The harbor was sealed before a single ship could flee. The killing lasted <strong>three days</strong>.</p>\n<p>Senator <strong><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassius</a></strong> named the <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor</a> directly: the relief force was delayed, recalled, or never existed. The Governor&#39;s only response was the scalp bounty.</p>\n<p><strong>Who organized the horde?</strong> No one has answered this question. The beastmen in the ruins now are fractured, territorial, and mutually hostile -- nothing like the disciplined force that broke the gates. Something drove them together. Whatever it was, <strong>it does not appear to be doing so anymore.</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-city-today\">The City Today</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-approaches\">The Approaches</h3>\n<p>For <strong>two miles in every direction</strong> from the walls, the landscape has been stripped bare. Beastmen scavenged all timber for fuel and crude palisades. The former dense river-forest is now a grey waste of stumps and bracken. Nothing grows above knee height. The sky sits large and cold.</p>\n<p>The river is clogged with filth -- six years of neglect. Fallen timber, detritus, and the occasional bloated body turning in the current. The smell reaches travelers a full mile out.</p>\n<h3 id=\"first-sight\">First Sight</h3>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>The road ends at open wasteland. Where forest stood, stumps run to the horizon in every direction. The ruins of Crossings rise ahead across the river -- towers broken and scorched black. The great bridge still stands. Below it, the river runs slow and brown, carrying things you do not want to look at directly. The city behind the bridge is dark even in morning light. You can hear the aqueduct running somewhere inside. You can also hear drums.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"the-aqueduct\">The Aqueduct</h3>\n<p>The Mithrian aqueduct <strong>still functions</strong>. Water flows through channels beneath the streets -- a running, eerie constant throughout the ruins. The aqueduct serves as both a <strong>navigation tool</strong> and a <strong>hazard</strong>: the channels have destabilized several districts, and the [[#the-drowned-market|Drowned Market]] floods deeper every year.</p>\n<p>Underground or in enclosed spaces, the sound of running water imposes <strong>-1 to all Hear Noise throws</strong>.</p>\n<p>The main channels serve as <strong>reliable navigation landmarks</strong> throughout the city.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-lights\">The Lights</h3>\n<p>At night, <strong>lights move in the Temple District</strong>. No one who investigated has returned with an explanation. The light comes from the eyes of the [[#the-hollow-father|Hollow Father]].</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-drum-lullaby\">The Drum-Lullaby</h2>\n<p>Sung by mothers in the Backlands:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>Don&#39;t look out, child, don&#39;t look at the window.</em>\n<em>Lay your head down; let me hum the drum.</em>\n<em>Count the night-fires -- one and two and three now.</em>\n<em>Head down, eyes closed, till the morning comes.</em></p>\n<p><em>What they take by night, they leave by morning.</em>\n<em>What is lost is lost, and gone is gone.</em>\n<em>But you are here, and I am here beside you.</em>\n<em>Head down, eyes closed, to the drum.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"five-beastman-factions\">Five Beastman Factions</h2>\n<p>Approximately <strong>800 beastmen</strong> inhabit the ruins, divided among five factions that are <strong>mutually hostile</strong> but share a wariness of armed unknowns. The organized force that broke the gates no longer exists -- what remains is a fractured, territorial patchwork.</p>\n<h3 id=\"goblins-of-the-scale\">Goblins of the Scale</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Territory</strong>: Temple District</li>\n<li><strong>Leader</strong>: The [[#the-hollow-father|Hollow Father]]</li>\n<li><strong>Details</strong>: The goblins worship and obey an <strong>undead <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> mummy</strong> wrapped in cloth that speaks in a language no beastman should know. The lights that move at night in the Temple District come from the Hollow Father&#39;s eyes. The goblins carry maps and are more organized than typical goblin bands.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"gnolls-of-the-governor\">Gnolls of the Governor</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Territory</strong>: The [[#the-governors-palace|Governor&#39;s Palace]]</li>\n<li><strong>Leader</strong>: A gnoll war-chief</li>\n<li><strong>Details</strong>: The gnoll war-chief holds a <strong>Mithrian noblewoman prisoner</strong>, captured six months ago. She may still be alive.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"orcs-of-the-scar\">Orcs of the Scar</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Territory</strong>: Old Quarter and Forum</li>\n<li><strong>Details</strong>: The orcs roam the Old Quarter and the area around the Forum. Orc scavengers encountered in the deeper ruins are often lost and frightened -- separated from their warband and desperate.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"hobgoblins-of-the-iron-ring\">Hobgoblins of the Iron Ring</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Territory</strong>: The [[#the-iron-ring|Arena]]</li>\n<li><strong>Details</strong>: The hobgoblins occupy the arena and demand tolls from anyone passing through their territory. The <strong>&quot;bridge tax&quot;</strong> is <strong>1d6 gold marks per person</strong>. They keep the arena crypts locked and will not say why -- they have lost four of their own down there.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"ghouls-of-the-bridge\">Ghouls of the Bridge</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Territory</strong>: Beneath the [[#the-stone-yoke-bridge|Stone Yoke Bridge]]</li>\n<li><strong>Details</strong>: Not truly a faction. They simply eat whoever falls. Ghouls beneath the Stone Yoke Bridge will <strong>not attack a person carrying Avari grave-goods</strong> -- the reason has been forgotten, but grandmothers in the Backlands still remember.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"neutral-ground-the-forum-of-seven-roads\">Neutral Ground: The Forum of Seven Roads</h3>\n<p>In the [[#the-forum-of-seven-roads|Forum of Seven Roads]], <strong>all beastmen observe the Neutral Ground rule</strong> -- no violence. Three factions trade there every <strong>tenday</strong>. This is the best place to talk to a beastman without being attacked on sight.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"special-rules\">Special Rules</h2>\n<h3 id=\"structural-collapse\">Structural Collapse</h3>\n<p>When charging, ramming, or casting area spells in roofed structures, roll <strong>1d6</strong>. On a <strong>1</strong>, a roof or wall section becomes unstable and <strong>collapses the next round</strong>, dealing <strong>2d8 damage</strong> (save vs. Petrification for half).</p>\n<h3 id=\"aqueduct-noise\">Aqueduct Noise</h3>\n<p>Running water imposes <strong>-1 to all Hear Noise throws</strong> when underground or in enclosed spaces. Main channels serve as reliable navigation landmarks.</p>\n<h3 id=\"beastman-reactions\">Beastman Reactions</h3>\n<p>Five factions are mutually hostile but share wariness of armed unknowns. The <strong>Neutral Ground rule</strong> at the Forum of Seven Roads is universally observed.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-warm-ground\">The Warm Ground</h3>\n<p>In the Old Quarter near the [[#the-blackened-stump|Blackened Stump]], the ground is <strong>noticeably warm</strong>. Characters who sleep here experience <strong>vivid dreams of crystalline towers and a vast dark sky of wrong stars</strong> -- visions of ancient Krysea. Mages and Clerics who sleep on the warm ground <strong>recover spells normally</strong> but wake with <strong>one additional non-memorized cantrip</strong> lodged in their mind.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"seven-districts-and-thirty-two-keyed-locations\">Seven Districts and Thirty-Two Keyed Locations</h2>\n<p>The Adventure Supplement maps the city into districts with level-appropriate content.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-approaches-and-old-quarter-locations-1-11\">The Approaches and Old Quarter (Locations 1-11)</h3>\n<p><strong>Level Range</strong>: 1st-3rd level</p>\n<p>This district covers the Stone Yoke Bridge, the Blackened Stump, and the ruined outskirts. It is the entry point for parties approaching from the south.</p>\n<h4 id=\"location-1-the-stone-yoke-bridge\">Location 1: The Stone Yoke Bridge</h4>\n<p>A <strong>massive Mithrian stone bridge of three arches</strong>, still intact, spanning the widest channel of the river delta. Built to endure centuries, it has survived the sacking where lesser structures crumbled. Its stones are stained dark with old smoke and river silt.</p>\n<p><strong>Chains</strong> that once supported harbor gates now clatter in the wind like bones -- a haunting sound that echoes across the delta.</p>\n<p>A <strong>tribe of ghouls</strong> lives underneath the bridge, feeding on corpses dumped by the beastmen above. The ghouls are not interested in fighting -- they have a reliable food source and see no reason to risk conflict with the living. They will <strong>not attack anyone carrying Avari grave-goods</strong>.</p>\n<p>The bridge is the primary entry point into the ruins and could serve as a defensible position.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-blackened-stump\">The Blackened Stump</h4>\n<p>A <strong>raised mound of overgrown vegetation</strong> choked with thick thorns, weeds, and thistle, from which the <strong>scorched stump of the great Erenthis</strong> juts into the air. A squat, ruined Mithrian barracks sits nearby, half-consumed by encroaching vegetation.</p>\n<p>The surrounding area radiates <strong>unnatural warmth</strong> -- the [[#the-warm-ground|Warm Ground]] effect described in Special Rules.</p>\n<p>A <strong>deranged and twisted <a href=\"#/page/the-black-tree\" class=\"wiki-link\">dryad</a></strong> resides here, desperately trying to lure a fitting man to rebirth the dead tree. Her madness is driven by the death of her Erenthis -- the core of her being, the anchor of her existence. She is not evil in the traditional sense; she is broken, desperate, and willing to do terrible things to restore what she has lost.</p>\n<p><strong>The Black Tree is not dead.</strong> Its roots still move. Whatever <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a> burned in 349 IY, he did not kill -- only changed it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"temple-district-and-civic-heart-locations-12-22\">Temple District and Civic Heart (Locations 12-22)</h3>\n<p><strong>Level Range</strong>: 3rd-5th level</p>\n<p>This district encompasses the territory of the <strong>Goblins of the Scale</strong>, the Forum of Seven Roads, and the Governor&#39;s Palace. It is the political and spiritual center of both the old city and the new beastman occupation.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-temple-of-the-balanced-scale\">The Temple of the Balanced Scale</h4>\n<p>A temple within the ruins, now occupied by the <strong>Goblins of the Scale</strong> and their master, the <strong>Hollow Father</strong>. The temple may be connected to the faith of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, the Balanced Scale.</p>\n<h5 id=\"the-hollow-father\">The Hollow Father</h5>\n<p>The Hollow Father is an <strong>undead <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> mummy</strong> -- wrapped in cloth, speaking in a language no beastman should know. The lights that move through the Temple District at night come from its eyes. It commands the goblins absolutely. The combination of beastman muscle and ancient undead intelligence makes this one of the most dangerous locations in the ruins.</p>\n<p>The Hollow Father&#39;s presence raises critical questions: What is an Elvoran mummy doing in a Mithrian city built on Avari foundations built on Eladran ruins? How old is it? What does it want?</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-forum-of-seven-roads\">The Forum of Seven Roads</h4>\n<p>A <strong>wide stone plaza</strong> where seven paved imperial roads converged -- the physical and symbolic heart of Crossings. Broken columns ring the space, inscribed with distances, tolls, and imperial decrees. Statues of Mithrian magistrates lie toppled, faces shattered.</p>\n<p>The beastmen use the Forum as <strong>neutral ground</strong>. Three factions trade here every <strong>tenday</strong>. No violence is permitted -- a rule observed since the Sacking itself. This is the <strong>best place to talk to a beastman</strong> without immediate combat.</p>\n<p>The Forum floor is cracked. The ground beneath is <strong>hollow</strong> -- ancient tunnels, some say Eladran, some say older.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-governors-palace\">The Governor&#39;s Palace</h4>\n<p>Occupied by the <strong>Gnolls of the Governor</strong>. The gnoll war-chief holds a <strong>Mithrian noblewoman prisoner</strong>, captured six months ago. She may still be alive.</p>\n<p>The rumor of a governor&#39;s safe room in the palace basement, stocked for siege, is <strong>false</strong>.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-governors-walk\">The Governor&#39;s Walk</h4>\n<p>A <strong>raised colonnade</strong> overlooking the river delta, once used for processions and civic announcements. Statues of lawgivers line the colonnade -- heads smashed, torsos scarred by beastman desecration.</p>\n<p>The wind whistles through the columns like low voices -- a haunting acoustic effect created by the architecture interacting with river breezes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"harbor-drowned-market-and-iron-ring-district-locations-23-32\">Harbor, Drowned Market, and Iron Ring District (Locations 23-32)</h3>\n<p><strong>Level Range</strong>: 4th-6th level</p>\n<p>This district covers the hobgoblin-controlled arena, the flooded commercial district, and the harbor ruins.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-drowned-market\">The Drowned Market</h4>\n<p>Once the commercial heart of Crossings, now <strong>knee- to waist-deep in water</strong> fed by the still-functioning aqueduct. Stone stalls and counting houses stand half-submerged. The district floods deeper every year.</p>\n<p>A <strong>corrupted giant crocodile</strong> has moved into the flooded district -- size of a boat, twisted by evil energies. It has eaten three scalpers in the last season alone.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-broken-harbor\">The Broken Harbor</h4>\n<p>Rotting piers, capsized ships, and shattered cranes define the Broken Harbor. The harbor <strong>silted up after the sacking</strong>, trapping ship hulls in the mud. Tar and pitch still cling to the harbor stones.</p>\n<p>A <strong>colony of giant crabs</strong> has moved into the harbor, nesting among the wrecked ships.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-iron-ring\">The Iron Ring</h4>\n<p>A <strong>half-collapsed stone arena</strong> with tiered seating. The sands are dark with old blood. Rusted portcullises beneath the arena floor still grind open when disturbed -- the mechanical systems are partially functional.</p>\n<p>Bones litter the edges of the arena floor, <strong>carefully stacked in places</strong> -- someone or something has been organizing the dead.</p>\n<p>The <strong>Hobgoblins of the Iron Ring</strong> occupy the arena and control access. They keep the <strong>arena crypts locked</strong> and will not say why. They have lost four of their own down there.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-salt-baths\">The Salt Baths</h4>\n<p>Once a vast public bath complex fed by the aqueduct. The <strong>roof has collapsed</strong>, exposing steaming basins crusted with white salt and lime. Broken mosaics on remaining walls depict scenes of civic life -- citizens bathing, merchants trading, officials deliberating. These are among the best-preserved artistic remnants of the pre-sacking city.</p>\n<h4 id=\"the-counting-halls\">The Counting Halls</h4>\n<p>A row of long stone buildings once used by guilds and trade houses. Vault doors hang open -- contents long looted. Shelves of ledgers rot in the damp air. Counting tables remain, covered in meaningless tally marks scratched by beastmen.</p>\n<p>A <strong>sealed vault</strong> exists beneath the Counting Halls. The combination is cut into the <strong>underside of the Registrar&#39;s desk</strong>.</p>\n<h4 id=\"location-32-the-nethercity-entrance\">Location 32: The Nethercity Entrance</h4>\n<p>The deepest point in the mapped ruins. This entrance connects to a <strong>deeper dungeon</strong> -- the remains of ancient <strong>Krysea</strong> and whatever lies beneath it. Appropriate for any level willing to face what waits below.</p>\n<p>The Forum floor cracks hint at what is down there: ancient tunnels, some Eladran, some older. The aqueduct taps the same water table. That is why the water tastes of iron.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"rumors-d12\">Rumors (d12)</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Roll</th>\n<th>Rumor</th>\n<th>Truth</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Goblins worship something old wrapped in cloth that speaks in an unknown language. Light at night comes from its eyes.</td>\n<td><strong>True</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>The Black Tree is not dead. Roots move. Whatever Cynar burned, he did not kill -- only changed it.</td>\n<td><strong>True</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>Gnoll war-chief in Governor&#39;s Palace has a Mithrian noblewoman prisoner, captured 6 months ago, may still be alive.</td>\n<td><strong>True</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Sealed vault under the Counting Halls. Combination cut into underside of Registrar&#39;s desk.</td>\n<td><strong>Partly true</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Forum floor is cracked -- ground hollow beneath. Ancient tunnels, some say Eladran, some say older.</td>\n<td><strong>Partly true</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Crocodile in the flooded market is the size of a boat. Ate three scalpers last season.</td>\n<td><strong>Partly true</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Hobgoblins keep the arena crypts locked. Won&#39;t say why. Lost four of their own down there.</td>\n<td><strong>Partly true</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Whole district on east side beastmen never go near. Streets perfectly clean. Like nothing happened.</td>\n<td><strong>False</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>Ghouls under Stone Yoke Bridge will not attack a person carrying Avari grave-goods. Grandmother knew why.</td>\n<td><strong>True</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>Governor&#39;s safe room still intact in palace basement, stocked for siege.</td>\n<td><strong>False</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>Beastmen don&#39;t fight in the Forum -- neutral ground since the Sacking. Three factions trade every tenday.</td>\n<td><strong>True</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>Crossings sits on Krysea. Krysea sits on something with no name. Aqueduct taps same water table. That&#39;s why water tastes of iron.</td>\n<td><strong>Partly true</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"encounter-tables\">Encounter Tables</h2>\n<h3 id=\"table-a-open-ruins-d20\">Table A: Open Ruins (d20)</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Roll</th>\n<th>Encounter</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>1-2</td>\n<td><strong>Goblin Patrols</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3-4</td>\n<td><strong>Orc Raiders</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5-6</td>\n<td><strong>Hobgoblin Toll Parties</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7-8</td>\n<td><strong>Gnoll Hunters</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td><strong>Warg Packs</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td><strong>Grave Ghouls</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td><strong>Zombies</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td><strong>Skeleton Patrols</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td><strong>Strix</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td><strong>Giant Crab Spiders</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15-16</td>\n<td><strong>Rival Scalpers</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td><strong>Beastman Duels</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18</td>\n<td><strong>Structural Collapse</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>19</td>\n<td><strong>Aqueduct Burst</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>20</td>\n<td><strong>Wights</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"table-b-old-quarter-and-temple-district-d20\">Table B: Old Quarter and Temple District (d20)</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Roll</th>\n<th>Encounter</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>1-2</td>\n<td><strong>Goblin Gangs</strong> (carry maps)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3-4</td>\n<td><strong>Skeleton Sentinels</strong> (immune to fire, wearing Thune-era armor)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5-6</td>\n<td><strong>Orc Scavengers</strong> (lost and frightened)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7-8</td>\n<td><strong>Goblin Champions</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9-10</td>\n<td><strong>Zombie Congregations</strong> (shuffle toward Temple District in procession)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11-12</td>\n<td><strong>Wights</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13-14</td>\n<td><strong>Hollow Father&#39;s Eye</strong> (goblin shaman observer)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td><strong>Dryad&#39;s Lure</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16-17</td>\n<td><strong>Corrupted Ground</strong> (revealing Krysean stairs)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18-19</td>\n<td><strong>Skeleton Throngs</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>20</td>\n<td><strong>The Hollow Father itself</strong> (with honor guard)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"strategic-significance\">Strategic Significance</h2>\n<p>Crossings remains strategically vital despite its destruction:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Forward Base</strong>: The beastmen use the ruins as a forward base for pushing south into imperial territory. As long as they hold Crossings, they have a fortified position from which to launch raids.</li>\n<li><strong>Seven Roads</strong>: The seven paved imperial roads that once brought trade now provide beastmen with routes of advance into the Backlands.</li>\n<li><strong>River Crossing</strong>: The Stone Yoke Bridge controls movement across the delta. Whoever holds the bridge controls the river.</li>\n<li><strong>Lost Wealth</strong>: The ruins contain Mithrian wealth -- the sealed vault beneath the Counting Halls, the treasures of the Temple, the cargo of the Broken Harbor -- along with Eladran artifacts in the Nethercity below.</li>\n<li><strong>Recapture</strong>: Taking Crossings back would deal a devastating blow to beastman power in the Backlands and restore imperial control over a critical trade route.</li>\n<li><strong>The Nethercity</strong>: Whatever lies beneath the ruins -- Krysea, and whatever Krysea sits on -- represents a deeper mystery and a deeper danger than the surface occupation.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier province where Crossings is located</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> -- The nearest imperial fortification, east of the ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argoll-river\" class=\"wiki-link\">argoll-river</a> -- The river at whose delta Crossings stands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The Scalper settlement that exists because of Crossings&#39; fall</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The creatures who sacked and now occupy the city</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that built and lost Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a> -- The High Mage who burned the great Erenthis in 349 IY</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> -- The sacred Avari trees, one of which still lives beneath the Blackened Stump</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The ancient Eladran ruins beneath the city</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The gangs that hunt beastmen in response to the fall of Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> -- The trading company that profits from the scalp bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> -- The Lord Merchant who oversees bounty redemption</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- The Eladran, Avari, and Mithrian peoples connected to Crossings&#39; history</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- The faith of the Balanced Scale; the Temple may be connected to this tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> -- The slave soldiers who destroyed Krysea</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"dunwick","title":"Dunwick","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","town","backlands","coastal-plain","seros","bel","earth-hunger","farming","argolle","brother-cavin","cthonic"],"html":"<h1 id=\"dunwick\">Dunwick</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;A fine town. Good fields. Good people. The temple is well-attended and the harvest is generous. One might almost call it blessed -- if one did not look too carefully at who is absent on which days, and why.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Dunwick</strong> is a farming town on the coastal plain of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>, in the province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>. It is one of the wealthier agricultural communities in the region -- prosperous, hospitable, and unremarkable to the casual visitor. Its fields produce harvests that exceed what soil and climate alone can explain.</p>\n<p>Beneath the surface, Dunwick is entangled in the ancient agricultural blood rites of <a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel-tharach -- the earth-hunger</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>Coastal plain of <span class=\"dead-link\">Backlands</span> can be civilized.</p>\n<p>The prosperity is real. It is also sustained by something that predates the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, and the faith of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> by centuries. The farming villages of the coastal plain -- Dunwick among them -- practice agricultural blood rites tied to the cycle of planting, petition, and sacrifice. These rites share a name and possibly an identity with <a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel the Slaughterprince</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> war-god of blood, conquest, and slaughter.</p>\n<p>The community does not discuss these rites with outsiders. Questions about them are met not with evasion but with silence -- the silence of people who have decided, collectively and without discussion, that outsiders do not need to know.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-temple-of-seros\">The Temple of Seros</h2>\n<p>Dunwick maintains a Temple of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> in the town square. It is well-built, well-attended, and entirely orthodox in its public presentation. The people come to services. They observe the holy days. They tithe. Everything appears in order.</p>\n<p>It is the absences that accumulate. Certain families do not attend temple on certain days. Certain holy days, planting days, and harvest days see particular members of the congregation simply vanish from the pews. No explanation is offered. None is expected.</p>\n<p>The temple stands as a genuine institution of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a> -- but it exists alongside something older, and the two have reached an accommodation that the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> would condemn if it understood its nature.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"brother-cavin\">Brother Cavin</h2>\n<p><strong>Brother Cavin</strong> is a young priest of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> assigned to Dunwick&#39;s temple. He is a man of genuine piety -- sincere, earnest, and committed to his calling. He has been at his posting for two years.</p>\n<p>He is deeply uncomfortable.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Role</strong></td>\n<td>Priest of <span class=\"dead-link\">Bel-tharach</span> -- the earth-hunger. These rites follow the agricultural year:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Blood offering at planting</strong> -- Blood is given to the earth at the beginning of the growing season. The specifics vary by community.</li>\n<li><strong>Petition at harvest</strong> -- Gratitude for what the earth has given, acknowledgment of what the earth has taken, a request for continued favor. This is not prayer -- it is transaction.</li>\n<li><strong>Sacrifice at the year&#39;s close</strong> -- The most significant of the three rites, and the one about which outsiders know the least. The sacrifice closes the cycle, settles the account, and prepares the ground for the next year&#39;s exchange.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The demands have grown over generations. What begins as modest exchange becomes, over time, something that cannot be unmade without cost. Each generation inherits a more prosperous arrangement and a more demanding patron.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel-earth-hunger</a> -- The agricultural blood rites practiced in Dunwick&#39;s surrounding villages</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- The Empyrean god whose temple stands in Dunwick</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province in which Dunwick is located</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- The province containing Dunwick&#39;s coastal plain</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The tradition to which the earth-hunger may belong</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">thousand-temples</a> -- The institution that would condemn Dunwick&#39;s rites</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The official faith Dunwick publicly observes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological crisis of Empyrean/Cthonic mirroring relevant to Dunwick</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"fort-harvald","title":"Fort Harvald","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","settlement","fort","backlands","border-forts","frontier","crossings","avari","refugees","bayou","beastmen","nethercity","argolle"],"html":"<h1 id=\"fort-harvald\">Fort Harvald</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;On a foggy morning the towers of Crossings rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man. The old ones say you can hear it breathing.&quot;</em>\n-- local saying</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Fort Harvald</strong> is a small, battered frontier settlement in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>, built around the remains of an imperial border fort. It sits mere miles from the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- close enough that the broken skyline of the destroyed city is visible on the horizon. Fort Harvald is not a garrison in any meaningful strategic sense. It is a place where people come to be forgotten -- <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> refugees who lost everything in the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a>, loggers, trappers, river folk, and <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalpers</a> drawn by the beastman bounty. The tone of the settlement is one of suspended grief: a bayou frontier outpost living in the permanent shadow of catastrophe.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Population</strong></td>\n<td>Low hundreds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Inhabitants</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> refugees, loggers, trappers, river folk, <span class=\"dead-link\">scalper-gangs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Garrison</strong></td>\n<td>10 soldiers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Commanding Officer</strong></td>\n<td>[[sergeant-voss</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dominant Powers</strong></td>\n<td>Voss (military), [[fort-harvald</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Proximity to Crossings</strong></td>\n<td>Miles -- ruins visible on horizon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Beastman Threat</strong></td>\n<td><strong>High</strong> -- enormous herds near [[Crossings</span>, far more dangerous than northern Backlands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Tone</strong></td>\n<td>Suspended grief. Bayou frontier. A place for the forgotten.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-fort\">The Fort</h2>\n<p>Fort Harvald is built on solid <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a>-era stone foundations -- ancient masonry that has endured for millennia -- with later <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> additions in varying states of disrepair. The walls hold. The interior buildings do not. Leaking roofs, rotted barracks, and a collapsed storehouse define the garrison&#39;s physical condition. The garrison flag has faded to near-white -- a detail that says everything about the Empire&#39;s investment in this posting.</p>\n<p>The fort was never meant to be a settlement. It was a military installation, part of the chain of border forts constructed after the failed <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a>. But after the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a>, refugees, drifters, and opportunists gathered around it, and a community of sorts coalesced in the shadow of its walls. The fort is now the administrative and military center of a settlement that has no formal charter, no imperial recognition, and no future that anyone here cares to discuss.</p>\n<p>Salvage from <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> has been built into Fort Harvald&#39;s walls and structures. Crossings is literally underfoot -- its stones, its timbers, its memory woven into the fabric of the place that replaced it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"garrison\">Garrison</h2>\n<p>The garrison of Fort Harvald consists of ten soldiers under the command of <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Aldric Voss</a>. This is not a prestigious posting. It is a punishment, a dead end, or a first assignment for those who drew the shortest straw. Despite this, the garrison functions -- largely due to Voss&#39;s stubborn competence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"sergeant-aldric-voss\">Sergeant Aldric Voss</h3>\n<p><em>Main article: <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Aldric Voss</a></em></p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aldric Voss</a></strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> male in his late 40s. He was once a capable and promising soldier -- the kind of career officer who should have risen to command a company or a fort of actual strategic significance. One political mistake buried him here permanently: he supported the wrong Senator in a dispute with the <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate-Governor</a>, and his career was over. He was passed over for promotion and assigned to Fort Harvald, where he has remained ever since.</p>\n<p>Voss runs a tight ship. He is <strong>not corrupt</strong> -- a rarity in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. He knows that <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Silvan Orro</a> reports to the Governor, but he has said nothing about it yet. Whether this silence represents calculation, resignation, or simply the exhaustion of a man who has spent years fighting battles he cannot win is unclear.</p>\n<h3 id=\"garrison-personnel\">Garrison Personnel</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Corin bar-Aldric</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> local. His family lives in the Refugee Quarter. His loyalty to the garrison is conditional on the garrison&#39;s treatment of his people. He serves because it puts food on the table and gives his family a measure of protection, not because he believes in the Empire.</li>\n<li><strong>Essa von-Halvard</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> local, Corin&#39;s sister. Quieter and more watchful than her brother. She knows the delta paths -- the waterways, the mud tracks, the routes through the marshland that no map records. An invaluable asset for anyone venturing into the wilderness.</li>\n<li><strong>Tomas Fides</strong> -- Young. This is his first posting. He is visibly terrified -- of the beastmen, of the ruins, of the sounds that carry across the delta at night, of everything. He will attach himself to any courageous figure who shows him kindness or leadership. He has written four unsent letters home.</li>\n<li><strong>Old Brek</strong> -- Veteran. Was in <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> when it fell. He never speaks of it. He knows the ruins of Crossings intimately -- their layout, their dangers, their secrets. Getting him to share that knowledge would require extraordinary trust or extraordinary need.</li>\n<li><strong>The Other Six</strong> -- Reliable, professional, unremarkable. They are loyal to Voss personally more than to the Empire -- a distinction that matters in a place where the Empire has effectively abandoned its own.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-locations\">Key Locations</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-fur-shed\">The Fur Shed</h3>\n<p>The social heart of Fort Harvald. Not a tavern in any formal sense -- more of a trading post, gathering place, and community center rolled into one. The Fur Shed is where news is exchanged, deals are struck, disputes are mediated, and the settlement&#39;s fragile social fabric is maintained.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Maren Ashfoot</a></strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> female, 50s -- runs the Fur Shed. She was born in <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, lost everything in the sacking, and rebuilt herself here through sheer force of will. Maren knows everyone in Fort Harvald and most of what happens within it. She is the settlement&#39;s unofficial leader in all matters not involving the garrison.</p>\n<p>Maren maintains a <strong>hidden stash of Crossings salvage</strong> -- artifacts, valuables, and personal effects recovered from the ruins. The nature and significance of this stash are known to very few. Whether she keeps it as a memorial, as insurance, or for some other purpose, only Maren knows.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-refugee-quarter\">The Refugee Quarter</h3>\n<p>The largest concentration of <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> in Fort Harvald. The Quarter was built almost entirely from salvage scavenged from <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- timber, stone, ironwork, and domestic objects carried across the delta by refugees who had nothing else. The architecture is improvised and ramshackle, but there is a fierce dignity to it -- the refusal of a displaced people to simply disappear.</p>\n<p><strong>Elder <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Havar bar-Kessian</a></strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> male, 70s -- is the unofficial leader of the Refugee Quarter. He remembers <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> in its prime, before the sacking, when it was a thriving settlement with markets, temples, and a future. Havar maintains a <strong>ledger of every Crossings dead, recorded by name</strong> -- a labor of grief and memory that he has pursued with obsessive dedication since the sacking. The ledger is the most complete record of the dead that exists.</p>\n<p>Havar suspects <strong>imperial complicity</strong> in the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a>. He believes -- though he cannot prove -- that the destruction was enabled not merely by negligence but by deliberate betrayal: that someone in the Imperial hierarchy profited from the fall of Crossings or allowed it to happen to serve a political end. He has no proof. The suspicion eats at him.</p>\n<h3 id=\"river-trade-post\">River Trade Post</h3>\n<p>The commercial hub of Fort Harvald, located on the waterfront where river traffic connects the settlement to the broader trade networks of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Silvan Orro</a></strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> male, 40s -- operates the River Trade Post. He is too polished for this posting. His manners, his dress, his connections, and his resources all suggest a man who belongs in a provincial capital, not a bayou frontier settlement. Orro is connected to <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>, and he almost certainly functions as an <strong>intelligence asset for the Governor</strong> -- reporting on conditions, personalities, and activities in Fort Harvald and the surrounding region.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Voss</a> knows what Orro is. He has said nothing about it yet.</p>\n<h3 id=\"skinning-grounds\">Skinning Grounds</h3>\n<p>The processing area where <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalpers</a> bring their kills and where beastman hides, teeth, claws, and scalps are weighed, graded, and prepared for transport. The smell is indescribable.</p>\n<p><strong>Pek</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">Targ</a> male, heavily scarred, missing his right ear -- runs the weighing station at the Skinning Grounds. Pek keeps <strong>private shorthand records</strong> of the transactions that pass through his station -- records written in a notation that no one else in Fort Harvald can read. Someone pays for this information. Who, and what they do with it, is unknown.</p>\n<h3 id=\"shrine-of-the-unnamed\">Shrine of the Unnamed</h3>\n<p>A small, rough-built shrine at the edge of the settlement where the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> of Fort Harvald gather for worship, remembrance, and grief.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Ossian</a></strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> male, 30s -- tends the shrine. He has no formal religious training. His rites are <strong>syncretic</strong> -- a blend of <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> worship, older Avari traditions, and a folk cult of remembrance for the dead of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. The shrine serves a community that has lost its temples, its priests, and its certainties, and Ossian has improvised a spiritual practice from the wreckage.</p>\n<p>Small <strong>supernatural events</strong> have been occurring at the shrine. Candles light themselves. Names appear on the memorial wall that Ossian did not write. These events are subtle, infrequent, and deeply unsettling. Ossian has noticed. He has <strong>told no one</strong>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"noma-of-the-shallows\">Noma of the Shallows</h3>\n<p><em>Main article: <a href=\"#/page/noma\" class=\"wiki-link\">Noma of the Shallows</a></em></p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/noma\" class=\"wiki-link\">Noma</a></strong> lives apart from the settlement, on a platform structure built over a backwater channel in the marshes. Her race and age are unknown. She speaks with what might be a <a href=\"#/page/corcanoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Corcanoan</a> accent. She worships something old -- something that has <strong>no name</strong> and predates the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> and <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> theological frameworks.</p>\n<p>Noma has lived here <strong>longer than anyone can remember</strong> -- which is a problem, because the settlement of Fort Harvald is only a few years old. She was here before the settlement existed, before the refugees came, before the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a>. How long she has been here, and what sustained her in the marshes alone, is unknown.</p>\n<p>Noma <strong>knows what lies in the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a></strong>. She may not say freely. Those who seek her out may find that her knowledge comes at a price, or with conditions, or wrapped in riddles that only make sense when it is too late.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-shadow-of-crossings\">The Shadow of Crossings</h2>\n<p>Fort Harvald exists in the permanent shadow of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- physically, psychologically, and spiritually. The ruins of the destroyed city are close enough to shape every aspect of life in the settlement.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>On clear days</strong>, the broken skyline of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> is visible on the horizon. The people of Fort Harvald have learned not to look too long.</li>\n<li><strong>On foggy mornings</strong>, the tower silhouettes rise from the mist -- somehow worse than seeing them clearly. The local saying captures it precisely: the towers rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man.</li>\n<li><strong>At night</strong>, lights move in the ruins. No one investigates. No one has investigated for a long time. Whatever moves in <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> after dark, the people of Fort Harvald have made their peace with not knowing.</li>\n<li><strong>Sounds carry</strong> across the delta at night. They are not always identifiable. They are always wrong.</li>\n<li>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters</a></strong> recently killed 300 <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> in the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and report that terrifying <strong>monsters</strong> lurk deeper within -- things worse than beastmen, things that suggest the ruins connect to something far older and more dangerous than a razed frontier town.</li>\n<li>Salvage from <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> is built into the walls, structures, and foundations of Fort Harvald. Crossings is literally underfoot. The dead city&#39;s bones are the living settlement&#39;s skeleton.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"hooks-and-tensions\">Hooks and Tensions</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Voss and Orro</strong>: The sergeant knows the trader is a spy. The spy does not know he has been identified. This standoff cannot last.</li>\n<li><strong>Havar&#39;s Suspicion</strong>: The elder believes the Empire let Crossings fall on purpose. If he finds proof, the consequences for Fort Harvald -- and for the Governor -- could be severe.</li>\n<li><strong>The Shrine</strong>: Something supernatural is happening at the Shrine of the Unnamed. Brother Ossian is keeping it secret, but the events are escalating.</li>\n<li><strong>Noma</strong>: A woman of unknown race and age who predates the settlement she lives beside and who knows the secrets of the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. Her presence raises questions that no one in Fort Harvald is equipped to answer.</li>\n<li><strong>The Ruins</strong>: Crossings is not empty. It is not safe. The monsters within are worse than beastmen. And the ruins may connect to the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- to the ancient Argollean underworld that predates the Empire by millennia.</li>\n<li><strong>Pek&#39;s Records</strong>: Someone is paying the Targ at the Skinning Grounds for intelligence. Who, and why?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- The destroyed city whose shadow defines Fort Harvald</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> -- The catastrophe that created the settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Aldric Voss</a> -- Commanding officer of the garrison</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/noma\" class=\"wiki-link\">Noma of the Shallows</a> -- The mysterious hermit of the marshes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Maren Ashfoot</a> -- Unofficial leader of the civilian community</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Silvan Orro</a> -- River trader and probable intelligence asset</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Havar bar-Kessian</a> -- Elder of the Refugee Quarter</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Ossian</a> -- Keeper of the Shrine of the Unnamed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a> -- Lord Merchant of the Red River Consortium</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> -- Trade organization connected to Orro</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters</a> -- Scalper company active in the Crossings ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The ancient Argollean underworld beneath Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> -- The displaced people of Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a> -- The failed campaigns that prompted the border forts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a> -- The bounty economy that draws killers to the frontier</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"fort-ikenvar","title":"Fort Ikenvar","category":"locations","status":"destroyed","tags":["location","military","fort","ruin","marsh","backlands","border-forts","rook","the-guzzler","demonic","stone-of-sakkara","frontier"],"html":"<h1 id=\"fort-ikenvar\">Fort Ikenvar</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;There is nothing left of Fort Ikenvar that resembles a fort. The walls have slumped into the bog. The gates are gone. The barracks are flooded to the eaves. What remains is a ruin in the process of being swallowed by the earth -- and something in that ruin that swallows everything else.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Fort Ikenvar</strong> is a ruined imperial marsh fort east of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>. Once a functional outpost in the chain of border forts constructed after the failed <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a>, it has collapsed into the wetland and is now little more than a half-sunken ruin in a bog.</p>\n<p>It is occupied by <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a></strong> -- a demonic entity of unknown origin that hungers without intelligence, purpose, or agenda.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>East of <span class=\"dead-link\">Backlands</span> frontier. It formed part of the chain of border forts alongside <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> and <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a>, constructed after the failed <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a> to secure the Empire&#39;s frontier. At some point, the fort&#39;s foundations gave way to the marsh beneath them, and the structure began its slow collapse into the wetland. The garrison was withdrawn and the fort was abandoned.</p>\n<p>What remains is a ruin in the process of being consumed by the earth -- walls slumped into bog, gates gone, barracks flooded. The marsh has reclaimed most of the structure, and what stands above the waterline is unstable, rotting, and treacherous.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"rooks-base-of-operations\">Rook&#39;s Base of Operations</h2>\n<p>The bandit leader <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> used Fort Ikenvar as his base of operations during his campaign of terror against the settlements and trade routes of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. The ruin&#39;s remote location in the marsh made it difficult for the garrison at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> to locate and assault -- the approach was treacherous, the terrain favored the defender, and the fort&#39;s very ruination made it an unlikely place for anyone to look.</p>\n<p>Rook&#39;s banditry grew increasingly violent over time -- targeted attacks on residents, disappeared travelers, deliberate intimidation campaigns. The garrison at Fort Meade could not resolve the threat.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> ultimately tracked Rook to Fort Ikenvar and destroyed him there, ending the bandit crisis that had terrorized the region for months. This victory was experienced by <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> as both a professional humiliation and a political opportunity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-guzzler\">The Guzzler</h2>\n<p>Following Rook&#39;s destruction, <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a> -- a demonic entity of unknown origin -- took up residence in the ruins of Fort Ikenvar.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Nature</strong></td>\n<td>Demonic entity</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Intelligence</strong></td>\n<td>None in any meaningful sense</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Motivation</strong></td>\n<td>Hunger. It eats what it finds. It does not discriminate.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Containment</strong></td>\n<td>Generally contained to the marsh, but this containment is not absolute</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Current Threat</strong></td>\n<td>Drawn toward <span class=\"dead-link\">Fort Meade</span> by the presence of the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>, which <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> carries. The entity cannot precisely locate the Stone, but it can sense its pull. This attraction has compromised the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature.</p>\n<p>The ~100 soldiers garrisoned at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> are not equipped for a demonic incursion. If the Guzzler is drawn out of the marsh in force, the garrison will face a threat it was never designed to counter.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"strategic-significance\">Strategic Significance</h2>\n<p>Fort Ikenvar&#39;s destruction removed the eastern anchor from the chain of border forts. Where three forts once provided overlapping coverage -- <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harvald</a> on the west, <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Meade</a> in the center, Ikenvar on the east -- only two remain functional. The eastern approach to the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> is now undefended by permanent fortification, covered only by patrols and the natural barrier of the marsh itself.</p>\n<p>The marsh that consumed the fort now serves as the primary barrier on the eastern approach -- an unreliable substitute for stone walls and a garrison.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The central garrison west of Fort Ikenvar</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> -- The western border fort, still functional</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- The demonic entity occupying the ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- The bandit who used Fort Ikenvar as his base</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The party that destroyed Rook at Fort Ikenvar</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> -- The artifact drawing the Guzzler toward Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- The Reclaimer who carries the Stone of Sakkara</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Commander of the Backlands garrison</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province in which Fort Ikenvar stands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakan-campaigns</a> -- The failed campaigns that prompted construction of the border forts</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"fort-meade","title":"Fort Meade (Fort Caldras)","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","military","garrison","fort","backlands","trade-route","frontier","border-forts"],"html":"<h1 id=\"fort-meade-fort-caldras\">Fort Meade (Fort Caldras)</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><strong>Naming Note:</strong> The <a href=\"#/page/src-backlands-regional-overview\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands Regional Overview</a> uses &quot;Fort Caldras&quot; consistently for this location. All other sources use &quot;Fort Meade.&quot; These are the same installation. The wiki uses &quot;Fort Meade&quot; as the primary name with &quot;Fort Caldras&quot; as an alias.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The road to Bone Creek runs through Fort Meade. Every coin, every crust of bread, every soldier who ever held that frontier passed through these gates. Marcellus knows it. The Governor knows it. The difference is only one of them acts on it.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Fort Meade</strong> is the most strategically significant military installation in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. It controls the flow of food, goods, soldiers, information, and coin between the imperial interior and the frontier. The settlement around the fort exists to support it, not the other way around.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>South of <span class=\"dead-link\">Backlands</span>. It controls the flow of food, goods, soldiers, information, and coin between the imperial interior and the frontier. <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> cannot survive long without supply caravans passing through Fort Meade. The settlement around the fort exists to support the garrison, not the other way around.</p>\n<p>There is no entertainment district, no gambling hall, no brothel quarter. Vice is informal and tolerated so long as it does not interfere with garrison function. The garrison&#39;s mean streak -- a reflection of <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> himself -- sets the tone. People here are practical, cautious, and not inclined to involve themselves in affairs that are not their own.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-trade-route\">The Trade Route</h2>\n<p>Fort Meade sits astride the central trade route between <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, making it the primary chokepoint for all commerce and supply flowing to and from the frontier.</p>\n<h3 id=\"northbound-to-bone-creek\">Northbound to Bone Creek</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Food staples</li>\n<li>Salt</li>\n<li>Tools</li>\n<li>Rope</li>\n<li>Lamp oil</li>\n<li>Manufactured goods</li>\n<li>Replacement soldiers (rarely)</li>\n<li>Correspondence</li>\n<li>Coin</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"southbound-to-sanctuary\">Southbound to Sanctuary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Beastman scalps</li>\n<li>Relics and salvage</li>\n<li>Furs and pelts</li>\n<li>Raw timber</li>\n<li>Occasional prisoners</li>\n<li>Reports to <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Governor</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"revenue-and-political-leverage\">Revenue and Political Leverage</h3>\n<p>Fort Meade levies taxes and fees on all goods passing in both directions -- this generates considerable revenue. <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> uses this revenue to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Maintain his soldiers&#39; loyalty</li>\n<li>Fund intelligence operations against <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Governor</a></li>\n<li>Support household expenses</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The food dependency of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> is Fort Meade&#39;s most significant political weapon. If the Legate embargoed caravans, Bone Creek would feel it within weeks. The political war between <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Legate</a> and <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Governor</a> has remained cold precisely because of this mutual awareness -- the Legate applies enough pressure to remind the Governor of dependence, but not enough to justify formal reprisal.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"rooks-banditry-the-wounds-that-remain\">Rook&#39;s Banditry -- The Wounds That Remain</h2>\n<p>Months of <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook&#39;s</a> banditry left deep wounds on Fort Meade and its surroundings. The bandits grew increasingly violent over time -- targeted attacks on residents, disappeared travelers, deliberate intimidation campaigns. The anxiety of that period has not fully lifted.</p>\n<p>People are relieved that <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> is dead, but they remember how close things came to breaking. The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> ultimately delivered what the garrison could not -- the destruction of Rook at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>. This fact is not lost on the Legate, who experienced it as both a professional humiliation and a political opportunity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"fort-ikenvar-nearby-threat\">Fort Ikenvar -- Nearby Threat</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> sits east of Fort Meade in a sunken marsh. It was once a functional imperial outpost but is now a ruin sinking into a bog. <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> used it as his base of operations before the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> destroyed him there.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-guzzler\">The Guzzler</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Guzzler</a> -- a demonic entity of unknown origin -- now occupies Fort Ikenvar. It is not intelligent in any meaningful sense. It simply hungers and eats what it finds. It does not discriminate and has no agenda beyond feeding.</p>\n<p>Residents of Fort Meade fear the Guzzler with particular dread. The entity is generally contained to the marsh, but this containment is not absolute. The Guzzler has been drawn toward Fort Meade by the presence of the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>, which <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> carries. It cannot precisely locate the Stone, but it can sense its pull.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-figures\">Key Figures</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</a></strong> -- Commanding officer. Cold, calculating, quietly cruel. Commands ~100 soldiers. House Valerian.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a></strong> -- The Legate&#39;s wife. More politically sophisticated than her husband. The real political engine of the household.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a></strong> -- Imperial Academy historian. Scholarly, manipulative, in love with Severina. Cataloguing artifacts from the frontier.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Davan Crull</a></strong> -- The Legate&#39;s enforcer at ground level. Eleven years of service have compressed him into something hard and efficient.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Arannis Venn</a></strong> -- Local leader of the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> (covert).</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"power-factions\">Power Factions</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-legates-household\">The Legate&#39;s Household</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcellus</a> and <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severina</a> operate as a political unit, though their methods differ sharply. The Legate commands through cold authority; Severina moves people through warmth, curiosity, and social intelligence. Between them, they control the garrison, the trade route revenue, and the flow of information.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood-covert\">The Argollean Brotherhood (Covert)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> has members embedded in the settlement, though they remain unidentified. Their primary interest is the flow of artifacts from the <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> ruins and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. They are not aggressive toward the general population. Fort Meade&#39;s position on the trade route makes it a natural waypoint for their operations.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-academy-malachor\">The Imperial Academy (Malachor)</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> represents the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy&#39;s</a> interests -- documenting the province&#39;s history and cataloguing recovered artifacts. His presence creates friction with the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brotherhood</a>, as both factions want the same relics for very different reasons.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The frontier settlement dependent on Fort Meade&#39;s supply route</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- Southern terminus of the trade route</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Commanding officer of Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- The Legate&#39;s wife and political partner</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Imperial Academy historian stationed at Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-crull</a> -- Senior NCO and the Legate&#39;s enforcer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- Ruined marsh fort east of Fort Meade, lair of the Guzzler</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- Demonic entity occupying Fort Ikenvar</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- The bandit whose campaign terrorized the region</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- Covert criminal network with presence in Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The scholarly institution Malachor represents</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province in which Fort Meade stands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">governor-drussus</a> -- The Legate&#39;s political rival</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> -- Artifact drawing the Guzzler toward Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The party who destroyed Rook and resolved the bandit crisis</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"gallowswood","title":"Gallowswood","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["wilderness","forest","cursed","backlands","encounters","outlands","abominations"],"html":"<h1 id=\"gallowswood\">Gallowswood</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Men who enter the Gallowswood armed come back afraid. Men who enter unarmed do not come back.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Gallowswood</strong> is a vast, cursed deciduous forest west of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>. Dense with ancient oaks whose boughs choke the moonlight, the Gallowswood is a place where the dead walk beneath the roots. It is classified as <strong>Outlands</strong> territory -- a step beyond the Borderlands, deeper into the wild, and significantly more dangerous than <a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Slog</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography\">Geography</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;There is a quality of silence in the Gallowswood. A specific silence, like the forest holding its breath. When that silence comes, something is watching. Something is waiting.&quot; -- Unnamed woodsman</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Gallowswood is a vast deciduous forest of ancient oaks, grey ash, and black-barked hawthorn. The canopy is thick enough to turn noon into dusk -- a green, uncertain light filters to the forest floor even at midday, and by evening the interior is pitch black. The undergrowth is thick with tangled roots, moss-covered deadfall, and thickets of bramble that make movement slow and navigation difficult.</p>\n<p>This is not merely an old forest in tree terms. It is old in the way places remember things. The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> knew it as sacred and dangerous before the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolleans</a> arrived. Avari warnings are still carved on stones at its borders -- and the Avari do not waste effort on warnings they do not mean.</p>\n<p>The forest represents the untamed character of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> frontier -- territory that the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> claims on maps but does not control in practice. The chain of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">border forts</a> defends against incursions from the wilderness beyond, but regions like the Gallowswood exist within the nominal borders of the province, reminders that imperial authority thins rapidly beyond the trade routes and garrison towns.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"terrain-and-travel\">Terrain and Travel</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Territory Type</strong></td>\n<td>Outlands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Encounter Frequency</strong></td>\n<td>Once per 6-mile hex traveled; once per 12 hours resting/stationary (day or night)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Night Travel</strong></td>\n<td>Shift one column right on encounter table (more dangerous encounters)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Travel through the Gallowswood is not undertaken lightly. Those who enter without preparation, arms, and numbers may not return. The dense canopy and tangled undergrowth make it easy to become disoriented, and the things that live beneath the trees are actively hostile.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"encounter-table\">Encounter Table</h2>\n<p>Roll <strong>1d8</strong> for each encounter:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Roll</th>\n<th>Encounter</th>\n<th>Number</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Common Wolves</td>\n<td>2d4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">beastmen</td>\n<td>Beastman Goblins</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>Bandits</td>\n<td>1d6+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Grave Ghouls</td>\n<td>1d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Dire Wolves</td>\n<td>1d4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Wight</td>\n<td>1d2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Lycanthrope / Werewolf</td>\n<td>1d4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Troll</td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p><strong>Night travel shifts one column right</strong>, meaning encounters skew toward the more dangerous end of the table. A party traveling through the Gallowswood at night is more likely to encounter dire wolves, wights, werewolves, and trolls than wolves and goblins.</p>\n<p>The encounter table reflects the forest&#39;s cursed nature. The undead presence (ghouls and wights) is not incidental -- the dead walk here. Wolves and dire wolves hunt in packs beneath the canopy. <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastman</a> goblins use the forest as cover for their movements. Bandits shelter in the deep woods where the law cannot reach. The werewolves and the troll represent the deeper, older threats -- things that have always been in the Gallowswood, things that predate the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire&#39;s</a> claim on this land.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"flora\">Flora</h2>\n<p>The Gallowswood supports several plants of significant practical and medicinal value. See <a href=\"#/page/backlands-field-guide\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-field-guide</a> for the full regional flora reference.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Black Hawthorn</strong></td>\n<td>Dark bark, pale spring flowers, red fall berries</td>\n<td>Berries edible but bitter. One of the Gallowswood&#39;s defining trees.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Belladonna</strong></td>\n<td>Found near old Argollean burial mounds; purple berries</td>\n<td><strong>Poison.</strong> Do not consume. Serves as a marker -- where belladonna clusters, an <span class=\"dead-link\">the Backlands</span> has foxes. The Gallowswood does not. The absence is information -- what killed the foxes, or what keeps them out, is unknown.</p>\n<h3 id=\"deer\">Deer</h3>\n<p>Deer are present but extremely skittish. If deer are running, do <strong>not</strong> pause to assess what they are fleeing from. Run with them. Whatever flushed the deer is worse than the deer think you are.</p>\n<h3 id=\"crab-spiders\">Crab Spiders</h3>\n<p>Dog-sized ambush predators that match the texture of bark. They position themselves at chest-height on tree trunks and wait motionless for prey to pass within striking distance.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Venom</strong>: Paralytic. A bitten victim is immobilized while the spider feeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Surprise</strong>: Check at <strong>-2 for surprise</strong> when entering areas of dense tree cover. The <strong>Alertness</strong> proficiency negates this penalty.</li>\n<li>Crab spiders are solitary hunters. They do not swarm. But a single crab spider is enough to kill an armored man if it achieves surprise.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"argollean-burial-mounds\">Argollean Burial Mounds</h2>\n<p>Old <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> burial mounds are scattered through the Gallowswood. They are identifiable by the clustering of <strong>belladonna</strong> around their bases. The mounds predate the forest&#39;s current cursed state -- the dead were buried here during the Argollean period, and whatever happened to the Gallowswood afterward was not kind to them.</p>\n<p>The relationship between the burial mounds and the Gallowswood&#39;s undead population (ghouls and wights on the encounter table) is likely not coincidental.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"avari-warning-stones\">Avari Warning Stones</h2>\n<p>Carved stones at the Gallowswood&#39;s borders bear <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> warnings. These predate the Argollean arrival in the region. The Avari did not carve warnings lightly -- their tradition is oral, and committing a warning to stone indicates something they considered important enough to outlast their own memory. The warnings have not been fully translated, but their intent is unmistakable: do not enter.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"navigation\">Navigation</h2>\n<p>Navigation in the Gallowswood is exceptionally treacherous:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Moss grows on ALL sides of trees.</strong> The thick canopy diffuses light so completely that the standard &quot;moss grows on the north side&quot; rule is useless here.</li>\n<li><strong>Compass unreliable.</strong> Something in the forest interferes with magnetic navigation. Whether this is a natural mineral deposit or something else is unknown.</li>\n<li><strong>Follow water downhill.</strong> The most reliable method of finding your way out. Streams flow downhill and eventually leave the forest.</li>\n<li><strong>Old Avari path markers</strong> exist -- carved stones and wooden poles placed centuries ago. Some sequences of markers are intact and navigable. However, <strong>some marker sequences were not intended for outsiders</strong> and may lead to places the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> considered sacred, dangerous, or both.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-dome-and-the-abominations\">The Dome and the Abominations</h2>\n<p>A massive clearing approximately <strong>half a day&#39;s travel</strong> into the deep wood. Before the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> horde was broken at the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a>, beastman tribes congregated here around an artifact of unknown origin and nature. The beastmen are gone now.</p>\n<p><strong>Something remains.</strong></p>\n<p>Creatures wander out of the Dome&#39;s vicinity -- things the woodsmen call <strong>abominations</strong>. They are described as loose bags of shifting flesh, their surfaces constantly growing and absorbing mouths, eyes, and tentacles in a nauseating cycle of formation and dissolution. They are not natural creatures. They are not undead. They are something else.</p>\n<h3 id=\"abomination-combat-profile\">Abomination Combat Profile</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Detail</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Speed</strong></td>\n<td>Fast -- faster than they appear, which is already unsettling</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Attacks</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Three attacks per round</strong> (shifting flesh generates multiple appendages simultaneously)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Venom</strong></td>\n<td>Paralytic toxin. Failed save = paralysis for <strong>1d3 turns</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Immunities</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Immune to sleep, charm, and hold</strong> effects. Whatever intelligence drives them is not a mind that can be influenced by such magic.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>The Dome&#39;s connection to the pulsating black heart beneath the granite dome (see below) is unclear but almost certainly significant. The beastman artifact, the abominations, and the black heart may be three manifestations of the same phenomenon -- or three separate horrors that happen to share the same cursed ground.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-black-heart\">The Black Heart</h2>\n<p>From session accounts: there is a <strong>pulsating black heart</strong> beneath a <strong>granite dome</strong> somewhere deep in the Gallowswood. Twisted crimson veins grow from it, spreading through the earth like roots.</p>\n<p>Characters have experienced dreams about this heart -- sensing <strong>malevolent evil</strong> radiating from the cancerous ball of flesh, but also an <strong>awakened lust for power</strong>. The heart calls to those who have been touched by darkness.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/anaya\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anaya</a></strong> (henchman) speaks of this heart calling to her after being wounded by a zombie beastman. She describes the pull as something beyond mere temptation -- a voice beneath thought, an ache in the blood. <strong><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">Greta</a></strong> is visibly disturbed by Anaya&#39;s visions but does not share why. Greta&#39;s silence on this matter is conspicuous given her knowledge of <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">binding traditions</a> and <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> phenomena.</p>\n<p>The nature of the black heart is unknown. It may be connected to the <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a>, to the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, or to something older still. Its presence beneath the Gallowswood may explain why the dead walk here -- why this forest, of all the forests in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>, is cursed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier province containing the Gallowswood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The frontier settlement east of the Gallowswood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a> -- The wasteland bordering the Gallowswood to the east</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-heartwood\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-heartwood</a> -- The older, deeper forest beyond the Gallowswood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The nearest major garrison</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a> -- Witch who is disturbed by visions of the black heart</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-awakening</a> -- The Cthonic prophecy that may be connected to the black heart</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- The Eladran necropolis that may share a connection with the heart</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- Goblins who use the forest for cover</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> -- Ancient people whose warning stones mark the Gallowswood borders</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The Argollean civilization whose burial mounds dot the forest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/backlands-field-guide\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-field-guide</a> -- Comprehensive survival reference including Gallowswood flora</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that claims but does not control this territory</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"grathe-steppe","title":"Grathe Steppe","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","steppe","skiotha","grathar","nomadic","horse-warriors","raids","slavery","frontier","wilderness"],"html":"<h1 id=\"grathe-steppe\">Grathe Steppe</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The steppe does not end. It simply becomes something else -- farther east, farther north, beyond the reach of maps and the patience of empires. The Skiotha do not conquer it. They move through it, as natural to the grass sea as the wind.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Grathe Steppe</strong> is a vast grassland expanse that serves as the homeland of the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> nomadic horse warriors. It also hosts small communities of <a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Grathar</a> people. The steppe lies beyond the effective reach of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiotha</a> who ride it are a persistent threat to the Empire&#39;s western provinces.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>East and north of the <span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrian Empire</span>, inhospitable to the settled agriculture and permanent fortification that define imperial civilization. The steppe does not support cities, garrisons, or the administrative apparatus of empire. It supports movement -- and the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiotha</a> have mastered movement across it as no other people have.</p>\n<p>The steppe resists conquest not through military strength but through geography. It is too vast to garrison, too open to fortify, and too sparse to sustain the supply lines that imperial armies require. Campaigns into the steppe have historically exhausted themselves -- armies march in, find no fixed positions to assault, and are harassed by mounted raiders who refuse set-piece battle until the invaders are weakened by distance and deprivation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-skiotha\">The Skiotha</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> nomadic horse warriors are the dominant people of the Grathe Steppe. They are raiders, herders, and warriors who live by the rhythm of the grasslands -- moving with their herds, fighting from horseback, and striking the settled provinces of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> when opportunity presents.</p>\n<p>The Skiotha raid the Empire&#39;s western provinces, taking slaves and treasure. These raids are not the sporadic violence of disorganized bandits -- they are the systematic economic activity of a warrior culture that views the settled lands as a resource to be harvested. Slaves taken in raids serve the Skiothan economy; treasure funds the acquisition of goods the steppe cannot produce.</p>\n<p>The Empire has never fully pacified the Skiothan threat. The chain of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">border forts</a> and frontier garrisons exists in part to contain and deter these incursions, but the steppe is too vast and the Skiotha too mobile for permanent military solutions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-grathar\">The Grathar</h2>\n<p>Small <a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Grathar</a> communities also inhabit the Grathe Steppe, coexisting with the dominant <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> population. The relationship between the Grathar and the Skiotha on the steppe -- whether cooperative, subordinate, or merely tolerated -- reflects the broader dynamics of peoples who share territory without sharing culture.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiotha</a> -- The nomadic horse warriors who dominate the steppe</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">grathar</a> -- The secondary inhabitants of the Grathe Steppe</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire whose western provinces suffer Skiothan raids</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- The peoples of Mithrapos</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"lake-silverhead","title":"Lake Silverhead","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","lake","argolle","ygrathen","kharai","cairnhouse","varek-ashstone","imprisoned","far-north","vigil"],"html":"<h1 id=\"lake-silverhead\">Lake Silverhead</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The lake is still. The island is silent. The cairnhouse has stood for centuries, and the thing inside it has not moved. Varek watches from the northern shore. He has watched for longer than any human life should allow. He does not speak of what happens if the vigil ends.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Lake Silverhead</strong> is a lake in the far north of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> province. At its center lies an island holding a cairnhouse of <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> construction. Within the cairnhouse, a <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> is imprisoned. On the northern shore, the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> hermit <strong><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a></strong> maintains a centuries-long vigil over the site.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>Far north of <span class=\"dead-link\">Argolle</span>, remote from the garrison towns and trade routes that define life in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>. It is not a site of commerce, settlement, or strategic interest. It is a site of containment.</p>\n<p>The island at the center of the lake holds a cairnhouse -- a structure of <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> construction, built with the characteristic methods and materials of that ancient and enduring people. Within the cairnhouse, a <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> is imprisoned. The nature of the imprisonment -- whether physical, magical, spiritual, or some combination -- reflects <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> methods of containment that predate the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> by centuries.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cairnhouse\">The Cairnhouse</h2>\n<p>The cairnhouse on the island is of <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> construction -- built to contain, to endure, and to hold what is placed within it for as long as the structure stands. The <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> built to last, and their containment structures are among the most durable works of any civilization in <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> imprisoned within represents a threat sufficient to justify centuries of continuous vigil by a single <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> guardian. The specific nature of the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> -- its identity, its power, the circumstances of its imprisonment -- are known to <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a> and perhaps to no one else living.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"varek-ashstone\">Varek Ashstone</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a></strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> hermit who lives on the northern shore of Lake Silverhead. He maintains a centuries-long vigil over the cairnhouse and its prisoner -- a duration that speaks to either the extraordinary longevity of the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> people or to methods of life-extension that are not widely understood.</p>\n<p>Varek&#39;s vigil is solitary, deliberate, and unbroken. He does not seek company, does not welcome visitors, and does not explain his purpose to those who stumble upon him. He watches the island. He has watched for a very long time. The implication is clear: if the vigil ends, something happens -- and whatever that something is, Varek has judged it worth spending centuries to prevent.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- The Ygrathen hermit maintaining vigil on the northern shore</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> -- The imprisoned entity within the cairnhouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> -- The ancient people who built the cairnhouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- The province in which Lake Silverhead is located</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The broader frontier region</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrapos</a> -- The known world in which Lake Silverhead exists</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mithra-city","title":"Mithra City","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["capital","mithrian-empire"],"html":"<h1 id=\"mithra-city\">Mithra City</h1>\n<p>Mithra City is the capital of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and the seat of imperial power. Encircled by <strong>alabaster white walls</strong>, the city stands as the political, religious, and sorcerous heart of the known world. From within its boundaries, the Emperor rules over the vast territories of the Empire, supported by a dense concentration of institutions that together form the machinery of imperial governance.</p>\n<h2 id=\"landmarks-and-institutions\">Landmarks and Institutions</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-palace\">The Imperial Palace</h3>\n<p>The Emperor governs from the imperial palace at the city&#39;s center, the symbolic and literal seat of <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> authority. The palace complex houses the imperial court, the Emperor&#39;s personal guard, and the chambers from which edicts are issued to every corner of the Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-academy\">The Imperial Academy</h3>\n<p>The towering spires of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> are the <strong>highest structures in the city</strong>, visible from miles beyond the walls. The Academy serves as the state-sanctioned center of sorcerous learning and a political power in its own right, its Archmages wielding influence that rivals that of the imperial ministries.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-senate\">The Imperial Senate</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> convenes in Mithra City, serving as the deliberative body through which the noble houses, provincial governors, and civic leaders participate in imperial governance. While the Emperor holds ultimate authority, the Senate remains a significant forum for political negotiation and factional maneuvering.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-thousand-temples\">The Thousand Temples</h3>\n<p>The headquarters of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> are located within the city, making Mithra City the spiritual capital of the Empire as well as its political one. The Temples&#39; presence ensures that religious authority remains physically proximate to the throne -- a deliberate arrangement that reflects the intertwining of faith and governance in Mithrian society.</p>\n<h2 id=\"significance\">Significance</h2>\n<p>Mithra City is more than a capital -- it is the embodiment of the Empire itself. The concentration of the Academy, the Senate, the Thousand Temples, and the imperial throne within its walls means that every major current of imperial life -- political, military, religious, and arcane -- flows through and from this single city. Control of Mithra City is, in practical terms, control of the Empire.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Military</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Talons</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Burnished Scale</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mount-argolle","title":"Mount Argolle","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["mount-argolle","argolle","volcano","first-empire","eladra","thune","harpies","gilded-oath","cairnhill-breaks","cairnhill"],"html":"<h1 id=\"mount-argolle\">Mount Argolle</h1>\n<p><strong>Mount Argolle</strong> is an active volcanic mountain east of <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a>, the geographical and historical heart of the region that bears its name. Its white volcanic plume is visible from the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]] and serves as a perpetual landmark for travelers, settlers, and the creatures that inhabit its slopes. The mountain is simultaneously a natural wonder, a ruin of the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a>, and a living ecosystem of predators and remnant peoples.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography\">Geography</h2>\n<p>Mount Argolle rises from the eastern edge of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, beyond the fractured limestone foothills known as the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]]. The mountain is volcanic -- not dormant but active, venting a persistent white plume from its summit that can be seen for dozens of miles in clear weather. The plume serves as a navigational reference point throughout the eastern Backlands, a column of pale smoke marking the boundary between settled territory and the deep interior.</p>\n<p>The mountain&#39;s lower slopes are traversable, though difficult. The upper reaches are sheer cliffs, carved and shaped by the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> of the First Empire into architectural forms that blur the line between natural formation and deliberate construction. Above the carved levels, the highest crags are bare volcanic rock -- wind-scoured, sulfur-stained, and inhabited by creatures that tolerate the heat and fumes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cairnhill-breaks\">The Cairnhill Breaks</h2>\n<p>The <strong>Cairnhill Breaks</strong> are a region of fractured limestone foothills lying between <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> and Mount Argolle. The terrain is broken, irregular, and difficult to navigate -- a landscape of shattered ridgelines, collapsed sinkholes, narrow defiles, and exposed rock faces where the limestone has cracked and tilted under geological stress.</p>\n<p>The Breaks are not empty. The fractured terrain provides shelter and concealment for a variety of inhabitants:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>[[#gilded-oath-guardian-tombs|Gilded Oath guardian tombs]]</strong> are scattered throughout the Breaks, built into the rock faces and ridge crests by the First Empire to watch over the approaches to Mount Argolle.</li>\n<li>Predators and territorial creatures use the defiles and sinkholes as hunting grounds.</li>\n<li>The terrain itself is hazardous -- unstable footing, hidden drops, and narrow passages that can trap the unwary.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Travel through the Cairnhill Breaks requires either local knowledge or considerable caution. The route from <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> to Mount Argolle passes through the Breaks by necessity, and every mile of the journey is contested terrain.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"first-empire-ruins\">First Empire Ruins</h2>\n<p>The upper cliffs of Mount Argolle were carved by the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> into monumental architectural forms:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Terraces</strong> -- broad, level platforms cut into the cliff face, connected by carved stairways. These terraces served purposes that combined the residential, the ceremonial, and the military. Their scale suggests they were built to accommodate large numbers of people -- or beings -- and their positioning provides commanding views of the surrounding landscape.</li>\n<li><strong>Archways</strong> -- massive carved openings in the rock, framing passages that lead deeper into the mountain&#39;s interior. Some archways are purely decorative, marking boundaries between zones of the carved complex. Others are functional, providing access to chambers and corridors within the mountain itself.</li>\n<li><strong>Inscription panels</strong> -- carved surfaces bearing text and imagery in the Eladran script. The panels are weathered but legible in places, recording histories, dedications, and ritual formulae from the height of the First Empire. The content of these inscriptions has not been systematically studied by modern scholars -- the mountain&#39;s current inhabitants discourage academic visitation.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The ruins are extensive. The First Empire did not merely build on Mount Argolle -- it reshaped the mountain&#39;s upper third into a complex that integrated natural volcanic rock with carved architecture on a scale that rivals the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> in ambition, if not in subterranean depth.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-inhabitants\">Current Inhabitants</h2>\n<h3 id=\"harpies\">Harpies</h3>\n<p>The highest crags of Mount Argolle are home to nesting <strong>harpies</strong> -- predatory creatures that exploit the mountain&#39;s thermal updrafts and inaccessible perches. The harpies are territorial and aggressive, defending their nesting sites against any intrusion. Their presence makes the upper reaches of the mountain extremely dangerous for any creature that cannot fly, and their hunting range extends into the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]] below.</p>\n<h3 id=\"thune-remnant\">Thune Remnant</h3>\n<p>The lower ruins of Mount Argolle are inhabited by a <strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> remnant</strong> -- descendants of the Argollean slave-soldiers who were created through <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire#transmogrification\" class=\"wiki-link\">Transmogrification</a> to serve the First Empire. When the Thune rebelled and destroyed the Empire that made them (c. 1700 BE), not all Thune joined the successor civilization that became the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a>. Some remained in the ruins of their creation, in the carved mountain where they had served.</p>\n<p>These remnant Thune have lived among the lower ruins of Mount Argolle for millennia. They are not the Thune of the historical empires -- they are a people shaped by long isolation, by the volcanic mountain&#39;s harsh environment, and by proximity to the First Empire&#39;s abandoned architecture and whatever lingers within it. Their relationship with the ruins is complex -- they inhabit structures built by the civilization that created and enslaved their ancestors, and they guard them with a possessiveness that combines territorial instinct with something deeper.</p>\n<p>The Thune remnant&#39;s attitude toward outsiders ranges from suspicious to hostile. They do not welcome visitors, they do not trade, and they do not explain themselves.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gilded-oath-guardian-tombs\">Gilded Oath Guardian Tombs</h2>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gilded Oath</a></strong> guardian tombs are scattered throughout the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]] between <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> and Mount Argolle. These are not conventional burial sites. They are <strong>guardian installations</strong> -- tombs built to house warriors interred with the expectation that they would continue to serve in death as they served in life.</p>\n<p>The tombs were constructed by the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> to protect the approaches to Mount Argolle. Each tomb is a fortified structure built into the limestone terrain of the Breaks, positioned to watch over passes, defiles, and routes of approach. The interred guardians were placed according to a defensive scheme that treated the entire Cairnhill Breaks as a layered security perimeter around the mountain.</p>\n<p>Whether the guardians within these tombs remain active -- whether the Cthonic preservation that sustained them has endured across millennia -- is a question that travelers through the Breaks sometimes answer involuntarily.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"significance\">Significance</h2>\n<p>Mount Argolle is the physical anchor of the region&#39;s deep history. The mountain predates every civilization that has claimed this territory. The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> carved it. The <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> inherited it. The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> has never controlled it. The mountain stands at the intersection of geological time and historical time -- a volcano that was sacred before recorded history and remains inhabited by the descendants of the civilization that carved its cliffs.</p>\n<p>For adventurers and scholars, Mount Argolle represents one of the most significant -- and most dangerous -- First Empire sites accessible from the settled <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. The <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> may be larger, but Mount Argolle&#39;s ruins are exposed, visible, and guarded by inhabitants who have had millennia to learn every carved passage and hidden chamber.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a> -- The nearest settlement, gateway to the Cairnhill Breaks</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-empire</a> -- The First Empire that carved the mountain&#39;s upper cliffs</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The civilization that built the original mountain complex</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> -- The slave-soldiers whose descendants inhabit the lower ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- The subterranean complex beneath Crossings, built by the same civilization</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- Other products of First Empire Transmogrification in the region</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province in which Mount Argolle stands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/backlands-provincial-history\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-provincial-history</a> -- The modern history of the region</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gilded Oath</a> -- The guardian tradition that produced the tombs in the Cairnhill Breaks</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"sanctuary","title":"Sanctuary","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","city","capital","provincial-capital","backlands","port","harbor","sanctuary","aodahn","eladra","megadungeon","market"],"html":"<h1 id=\"sanctuary\">Sanctuary</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The bones of what came before are visible everywhere. Impossible geometry of Eladra spires, strange angles of ruined streets, names lingering in Imperial bureaucracy like ghosts of a language no one speaks anymore. Sanctuary is not built on ruins. Sanctuary is ruins, with a city draped over them like a shroud.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Sanctuary</strong> is the provincial capital of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> and the last true city in the province. A metropolitan port built upon the ruins of <strong><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a></strong>, the great <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> harbor-city, Sanctuary is the economic, political, religious, and scholarly center of the Backlands. It is a city built on tension -- between factions, between past and present, between the Empire&#39;s fading reach and the ambitions of those who would fill the vacuum.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>Mouth of the <span class=\"dead-link\">Backlands</span>. Everything else -- <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a>, <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Crossings</a> (now destroyed) -- is a town, settlement, or outpost by comparison. Sanctuary is metropolitan. It has districts, institutions, guilds, temples, academies, a functioning port, and a population measured in tens of thousands.</p>\n<p>The city is ethnically diverse. <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> bureaucrats and soldiers form the ruling class. Merchants from <a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">Morn</a> haggle in the markets. Sailors from <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassia</a> fill the harbor taverns. <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> refugees from the sacking of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Crossings</a> crowd the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a>. <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> traders pass through with goods from the wastes. Scholars from across the known world come to study at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>.</p>\n<p>The bones of what came before are visible everywhere. The impossible geometry of <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> spires, the strange angles of ruined streets, names lingering in Imperial bureaucracy like ghosts of a language no one speaks. Five ivory spires -- each carved from a single stone so white it seems to emit light, each three hundred feet or more above the harbor -- dominate the skyline. They are not Mithrian. They predate the Empire by centuries, perhaps millennia. They are remnants of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a>, and they are a reminder that Sanctuary is not built on ruins. Sanctuary <em>is</em> ruins, with a city draped over them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"aodahn-the-city-before\">Aodahn -- The City Before</h3>\n<p>The ruins upon which Sanctuary stands are called <strong><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a></strong> -- an <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> word meaning &quot;sanctuary&quot; or &quot;refuge.&quot; The name predates the Mithrian city by centuries, and the Mithrians kept it, perhaps unconsciously recognizing its aptness.</p>\n<p>Aodahn was built by the true children of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods -- the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>, who were <strong>not</strong> corrupted <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>. The Eladra were something older and purer, a people who maintained their connection to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> when others fell away. Their city reflected this. The five ivory spires, each carved from a single stone and proportioned in ratios that trouble human perception, rose over three hundred feet above the harbor. Modern <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> scholars suspect the spires are <strong>engineered conduits of Empyrean vitality</strong>, analogous to <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis trees</a> but constructed rather than grown. If true, Aodahn was not simply a city -- it was a <strong>project</strong>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-abandonment\">The Abandonment</h3>\n<p>When the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrians</a> arrived, they found Aodahn <strong>abandoned</strong>. No records of war or catastrophe. No evidence of plague, siege, or flight. The city was simply empty. The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> had vanished. Belongings remained. Workshops stood open. Food rotted on tables. The people were gone.</p>\n<p>The chronicler <strong>Varro Silk</strong> wrote that the city felt &quot;as though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned.&quot;</p>\n<p>No satisfactory explanation has ever been offered. The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> has theories -- the Threshold hypothesis, the Ascension model, the Catastrophic Severance theory -- but none are proven. What is known is that the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> are not entirely gone. At least one Eladra agent is believed to be present in Sanctuary at any given time, watching, guarding secrets about what lies below.</p>\n<h3 id=\"imperial-foundation\">Imperial Foundation</h3>\n<p>Sanctuary was formally established as an imperial trading post in <strong>283 IY</strong>, taking advantage of the natural harbor and the Argoll River&#39;s navigability inland. The existing ruins provided building material and shelter. The spires, too massive and too strange to demolish, were incorporated into the growing city.</p>\n<p>By <strong>350 IY</strong>, Sanctuary had grown large enough and become strategically important enough to be designated the <strong>provincial capital</strong> of the Backlands. The governor&#39;s seat was established in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Citadel</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> was chartered, and the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple of the Unconquered Sun</a> raised its Grand Temple in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sunward</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography\">Geography</h2>\n<p>Sanctuary sits at the mouth of the <a href=\"#/page/argoll-river\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argoll River</a> where it empties into the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Turquoise Sea</a>. The city rises from the waterfront in tiers, with the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> at the lowest elevation and the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Citadel</a> at the highest. The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> spires punctuate the skyline at irregular intervals, their white stone catching the light at all hours.</p>\n<p>Below the surface streets, the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> extend downward in three tiers, forming a vast <a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Undercity</a> that has never been fully explored.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-situation-380-iy\">Current Situation (380 IY)</h2>\n<p>The Emperor&#39;s attention has turned westward, fighting <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> incursions that threaten the imperial heartland. Legions have been recalled from the provinces. The Backlands garrison has been stripped to skeletal levels. The province is effectively autonomous, and everyone knows it.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> has used this vacuum ruthlessly. He has consolidated personal power with frightening efficiency over the fifteen years of his tenure. The <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> -- his <strong>private army</strong>, not technically the provincial military -- now numbers <strong>2,000 strong</strong>. His control over the bureaucracy is absolute. His personal wealth competes with the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>.</p>\n<p>Every faction fears him. Every faction courts him. No one knows what he intends.</p>\n<p>The balance of power in Sanctuary is a web of mutual suspicion and careful accommodation:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a></strong> holds military and bureaucratic supremacy but must maintain appearances of imperial loyalty</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Voth</a></strong> and the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple</a> hold moral authority and extensive intelligence networks</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a></strong> controls the underworld with the Governor&#39;s tacit approval</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a></strong> guards ancient knowledge and maintains independence through scholarly prestige</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Red River Consortium</a></strong> holds economic leverage through trade monopolies</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> community</strong> survives in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a>, led by <a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elder Sarnath of the Crossings</a></li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-eight-districts\">The Eight Districts</h2>\n<h3 id=\"1-the-citadel\">1. The Citadel</h3>\n<p>The fortress-seat of the Governor. Occupies the highest ground in the city, behind walls-within-walls. The architecture is a mix of austere military-functional construction and grand palatial display -- the Governor lives here, and his power radiates outward from this point.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Locations (9 keyed):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Governor&#39;s Palace</strong> -- Seat of <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Valerios Drussus</a>. Administrative heart of the province.</li>\n<li><strong>Drussine Guard Barracks</strong> -- Housing and training facilities for the ~2,000 soldiers of the <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a></li>\n<li><strong>Provincial Archive</strong> -- Imperial records, census data, tax rolls, legal precedent</li>\n<li><strong>Military Mint</strong> -- Where the province&#39;s coinage is struck</li>\n<li><strong>Prisoner&#39;s Vault</strong> -- The Governor&#39;s personal prison, separate from civil gaols</li>\n<li><strong>Citadel Gate</strong> -- Primary entrance, heavily fortified</li>\n<li><strong>War Room</strong> -- Strategic planning center</li>\n<li><strong>Officer&#39;s Quarters</strong> -- Housing for senior <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> officers, including <a href=\"#/page/colonel-vex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Colonel Marcian Vex</a></li>\n<li><strong>Armory</strong> -- Arsenal for the garrison</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Citadel is effectively a self-contained military installation within the city. In the event of civil unrest, the Governor could hold the Citadel indefinitely with the forces at his disposal.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"2-the-ivory-quarter\">2. The Ivory Quarter</h3>\n<p>Built atop the ruins of ancient <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a>, the Ivory Quarter takes its name from the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> spires that rise here. The atmosphere is scholarly and watchful -- students, researchers, and antiquarians fill the streets, but there is always the sense of being observed, whether by Academy security or by something older.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Locations (9 keyed):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Academy Tower</strong> -- The central structure of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, constructed <strong>around</strong> one of the Eladra spires rather than demolishing it. The spire rises through the Tower&#39;s interior, over 300 feet tall, and serves as both architectural centerpiece and object of study. Regent: <a href=\"#/page/magister-shale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magister Cornelius Shale</a>, Wizard 11.</li>\n<li><strong>Artifact Vault</strong> -- Secured repository for recovered relics and Eladra artifacts</li>\n<li><strong>Academy Library</strong> -- One of the largest collections of texts in the Backlands</li>\n<li><strong>Antiquarians Guild</strong> -- Organization of relic-hunters, scholars, and collectors</li>\n<li><strong>Eladra Spire Garden</strong> -- Public gardens surrounding another Eladra spire. Documented phenomena at sunset: visions, sounds in unknown languages, sensation of being watched. Several cults have formed around the spires.</li>\n<li><strong>Scholar&#39;s Row</strong> -- Boarding houses, bookshops, and scriptoria catering to students</li>\n<li><strong>Academy Security Post</strong> -- The Academy maintains its own security force, independent of the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a></li>\n<li><strong>Alchemist&#39;s Corner</strong> -- Cluster of alchemical shops and workshops</li>\n<li><strong>The Cartographer</strong> -- Map shop specializing in Backlands geography and Undercity surveys</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"3-the-sunward\">3. The Sunward</h3>\n<p>The religious heart of Sanctuary. Dominated by the Temple of the Unconquered Sun and its associated structures. <a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Severan Voth&#39;s</a> influence is absolute here -- the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple</a> functions as a state within a state in this district.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Locations (8 keyed):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Grand Temple of the Unconquered Sun</strong> -- The largest religious structure in the Backlands. Seats <strong>3,000</strong> worshippers. Center of <a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Voth&#39;s</a> authority.</li>\n<li><strong>Monastic Complex</strong> -- Housing and training for the Temple&#39;s monastic orders</li>\n<li><strong>Pilgrim&#39;s House</strong> -- Shelter and services for pilgrims traveling to Sanctuary</li>\n<li><strong>Temple of Mitra</strong> -- Secondary temple dedicated to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mitra</a></li>\n<li><strong>Shrine of Seros</strong> -- Smaller shrine to <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><strong>Healing House</strong> -- Temple-run hospital and healing center. Free healing for the faithful, subsidized for others.</li>\n<li><strong>Scriptorum</strong> -- Where Temple scribes copy, preserve, and produce religious texts</li>\n<li><strong>Temple Guard Post</strong> -- The Temple maintains its own guards within the Sunward</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"4-the-harbor\">4. The Harbor</h3>\n<p>The economic engine of Sanctuary. The wharves, warehouses, and shipyards of the Harbor generate the wealth that keeps the city functioning. The district smells of salt, tar, and exotic goods. It is loud, boisterous, and dangerous.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> controls the Harbor through the dockworkers&#39; union. Nothing moves through the port without their knowledge and often their approval.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Locations (9 keyed):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Crimson Anchor Tavern</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> operations hub. Proprietor <strong>Mara</strong> has worked here 20 years and knows everyone worth knowing. Public house on the surface, nerve center of criminal operations beneath.</li>\n<li><strong>Customs House</strong> -- Imperial customs authority (now largely controlled by the Governor&#39;s apparatus)</li>\n<li><strong>Shipyard</strong> -- Construction and repair of sailing vessels</li>\n<li><strong>Maritime Guild</strong> -- Association of captains, navigators, and ship owners</li>\n<li><strong>Merchant&#39;s Exchange</strong> -- Where large-scale commercial deals are brokered</li>\n<li><strong>Salt Warehouses</strong> -- Storage for one of the Backlands&#39; most valuable commodities</li>\n<li><strong>Dockworkers&#39; Union Hall</strong> -- Nominally a labor organization, effectively a <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> front</li>\n<li><strong>Harbor Watch Post</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> station, often compromised by Laced Hand influence</li>\n<li><strong>Fishmarket</strong> -- Daily market for the harbor&#39;s catch, active before dawn</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"5-the-commons\">5. The Commons</h3>\n<p>Where most of Sanctuary&#39;s population lives. Dense, crowded, teeming with humanity. Tenements rise five and six stories. The Grand Market sprawls through the center. Every craft, trade, and profession is represented. The district is ethnically and economically diverse -- Mithrian tradespeople live alongside <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> merchants, foreign sailors, and everyone in between.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> presence is regular but authority is distributed among local strongmen and neighborhood bosses. The <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> maintains order in their own fashion -- protection rackets double as informal policing.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Locations (12+ keyed):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Grand Market</strong> -- The largest open market in the Backlands. Daily trading in goods from across the known world.</li>\n<li><strong>Crafters&#39; Quarter</strong> -- Smiths, tanners, weavers, potters, carpenters clustered by trade</li>\n<li><strong>The Tenements</strong> -- Dense residential blocks, 5-6 stories, housing thousands</li>\n<li><strong>Commons Watch Station</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> headquarters for the district</li>\n<li><strong>The Brass Lamp</strong> -- Popular tavern and gathering place</li>\n<li><strong>Moneylenders&#39; Row</strong> -- Financiers, moneylenders, and pawnbrokers</li>\n<li><strong>Bathhouse</strong> -- Public bathing and social gathering</li>\n<li><strong>Courier&#39;s Hall</strong> -- Where messages, packages, and small goods are dispatched throughout the city and beyond</li>\n<li><strong>Butcher&#39;s Lane</strong> -- Food market and slaughterhouse district</li>\n<li><strong>Weavers&#39; Hall</strong> -- Guild hall for the textile trades</li>\n<li><strong>Apothecary Row</strong> -- Herbalists, healers, and medicine sellers</li>\n<li><strong>The Rag Market</strong> -- Secondhand goods, salvage, and bargain traders</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"6-the-ashward\">6. The Ashward</h3>\n<p>The refugee quarter. When <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Crossings</a> was sacked, thousands of <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> fled south to Sanctuary. They were given marginal land on the city&#39;s edge -- the Ashward -- and left largely to their own devices. The district is desperate, impoverished, and dangerous, but it is also dignified. The Avari have maintained their own community leadership, their own traditions, and their own identity.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Details:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Population: 8,000--10,000 (mostly Avari refugees)</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elder Sarnath of the Crossings</a></strong> -- Age 71, community leader. Respected, stubborn, determined to preserve Avari identity and culture</li>\n<li>Avari have <strong>not assimilated</strong> into Sanctuary&#39;s Mithrian culture. They remain distinct -- their own language, customs, governance</li>\n<li>Shanty settlements on marginal land -- flooding, poor sanitation, inadequate infrastructure</li>\n<li>Camp markets selling Avari goods, food, and crafts</li>\n<li>Makeshift temples to Avari gods</li>\n<li>The Ashward is policed primarily by Avari themselves -- <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a> rarely enters, <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> never</li>\n<li>Dangerous for outsiders unfamiliar with Avari customs and community structures</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"7-the-undercity-ruins-of-aodahn\">7. The Undercity -- Ruins of Aodahn</h3>\n<p>Beneath Sanctuary lies the true <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> -- the ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> city, only partially explored, extending downward in three tiers. This is a <strong>three-tier megadungeon</strong> that represents one of the most significant adventuring environments in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>.</p>\n<h4 id=\"tier-1-the-warrens-levels-1-3\">Tier 1: The Warrens (Levels 1--3)</h4>\n<p>The uppermost levels of the Undercity, accessible through numerous known entrances throughout the city. The Warrens are partially settled -- smugglers, outcasts, and those with reason to avoid the surface maintain hidden communities here. Beyond the settled areas, the Warrens become increasingly dangerous.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inhabitants:</strong> Giant vermin (rats, spiders, centipedes), oozes, smuggler gangs, outcast settlements</li>\n<li><strong>Features:</strong> Collapsed tunnels, flooded passages, hidden caches, smuggler routes connecting districts</li>\n<li><strong>Danger Level:</strong> Low to moderate. Manageable by experienced adventurers.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4 id=\"tier-2-old-aodahn-levels-3-7\">Tier 2: Old Aodahn (Levels 3--7)</h4>\n<p>Below the Warrens lies the preserved heart of the ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> city. Here, the architecture becomes alien -- proportions shift, materials defy identification, spaces exist that should not be possible given the geometry above. The area is saturated with <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> energy, producing strange phenomena: lights without source, sounds without origin, time moving at inconsistent rates.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inhabitants:</strong> Construct guardians (still operational after centuries), doppelgangers, minotaurs, minor elementals</li>\n<li><strong>Features:</strong> Preserved Eladra workshops, libraries, and living spaces. Empyrean energy saturation causes minor reality distortions. Strange phenomena -- flickering lights, sounds in unknown languages, fleeting images of people and places that do not exist.</li>\n<li><strong>Danger Level:</strong> Significant. Requires well-equipped and experienced parties.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4 id=\"tier-3-foundations-of-the-spires-levels-7\">Tier 3: Foundations of the Spires (Levels 7+)</h4>\n<p>The deepest known level of the Undercity. Here, at the roots of the great spires, the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> built something extraordinary. This is where scholars believe the <strong>Ascension</strong> -- whatever it was -- actually occurred. The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> energy is overwhelming. Reality itself becomes unreliable.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inhabitants:</strong> Masterwork constructs (far more powerful than those above), major elementals, entities of unknown origin</li>\n<li><strong>Features:</strong> <strong>The Threshold</strong> -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened. The door has not fully closed. Empyrean energy is so concentrated that mortal flesh reacts unpredictably. Magical effects are amplified, distorted, or inverted.</li>\n<li><strong>Danger Level:</strong> Extreme. Few have reached this level and returned.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"8-outer-districts-outskirts\">8. (Outer Districts / Outskirts)</h3>\n<p>Beyond the walls, the outskirts of Sanctuary include farms, small settlements, and the sprawl of the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a> refugee camps. These areas are nominally under the Governor&#39;s authority but in practice are loosely governed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-organizations\">Key Organizations</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-governors-apparatus\">The Governor&#39;s Apparatus</h3>\n<p>The machinery of <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus&#39;s</a> power. This includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Drussine Guard</a></strong> (~2,000 soldiers) -- the Governor&#39;s personal army, loyal to him personally</li>\n<li><strong>The Provincial Bureaucracy</strong> -- Tax collectors, magistrates, record-keepers, functionaries, all screened for loyalty to the Governor</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The City Watch</a></strong> (~600) -- Ostensibly independent municipal police, in practice answerable to the Governor through the chain of command</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Together, these institutions give Drussus near-total control over the city&#39;s administrative, military, and law enforcement functions.</p>\n<h3 id=\"temple-of-the-unconquered-sun\">Temple of the Unconquered Sun</h3>\n<p>Led by <strong><a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Severan Voth</a></strong>, Cleric 13. The Temple is the most significant religious institution in the Backlands and functions as a check on secular power. It operates from the Grand Temple in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sunward</a> and maintains monastic orders, a healing house, and an extensive intelligence network.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-laced-hand\">The Laced Hand</h3>\n<p>Sanctuary&#39;s <strong>criminal syndicate</strong>, operating with the Governor&#39;s tacit approval. Led by <strong><a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Castellan Thibaud</a></strong> (Master Thief 7). Controls the docks, smuggling, black market, protection rackets, and gambling dens. Operations hub: <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Crimson Anchor Tavern</a> in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a>. See <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a> for full details.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-academy-of-sanctuary\">The Imperial Academy of Sanctuary</h3>\n<p>The Backlands&#39; premier institution of learning and magical research. Regent: <strong><a href=\"#/page/magister-shale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magister Cornelius Shale</a></strong>, Wizard 11. Housed partially around one of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> spires. Maintains its own security force and artifact vault. See <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> for full details.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-red-river-consortium-sanctuary-branch\">The Red River Consortium (Sanctuary Branch)</h3>\n<p>The great trading company&#39;s Sanctuary operations. Directrix: <strong><a href=\"#/page/valeria-thorne\" class=\"wiki-link\">Valeria Thorne</a></strong>, age 58. Politically aligned with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a>. The Consortium&#39;s wealth in Sanctuary competes with the Governor&#39;s own. See <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> for full details.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-avari-community\">The Avari Community</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> refugee population of the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a>, led by <strong><a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elder Sarnath of the Crossings</a></strong> (age 71). A distinct community within Sanctuary that has not assimilated into Mithrian culture. Maintains its own leadership, customs, language, and traditions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"economy-trade\">Economy &amp; Trade</h2>\n<p>Sanctuary is the largest market in the Backlands (Market Class III). Its port connects the province to maritime trade routes across the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Turquoise Sea</a>, while the <a href=\"#/page/argoll-river\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argoll River</a> provides access to the interior.</p>\n<p><strong>Major exports:</strong> Salt, relics and artifacts from the <a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Undercity</a>, processed goods, administrative services\n<strong>Major imports:</strong> Food staples, manufactured goods, luxury items, soldiers (formerly), scholars</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> between them control most of the city&#39;s commerce -- the former through legitimate trade monopolies, the latter through the docks, smuggling, and the black market.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"power-dynamics\">Power Dynamics</h2>\n<p>The political landscape of Sanctuary is defined by the relationships between its major factions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussus</a> vs. <a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Voth</a>:</strong> Cold and formal. They do not trust each other but maintain equilibrium. Drussus does not interfere with Temple internal affairs; Voth does not publicly oppose the Governor&#39;s authority. Both recognize that either could seriously damage the other.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussus</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a>:</strong> Tacit arrangement. The Laced Hand provides intelligence, removes inconvenient people, and keeps the underworld organized. In exchange, the Governor does not interfere with their operations.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussus</a> vs. <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a>:</strong> A silent political war fought at a distance. Marcellus at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> represents the only other significant military authority in the province.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> independence:</strong> The Academy maintains neutrality through scholarly prestige and the value of its services. It cooperates with all factions and is beholden to none.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> marginalization:</strong> The Ashward community is largely ignored by Sanctuary&#39;s power brokers, which is both a source of suffering and a form of protection.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"adventure-hooks\">Adventure Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Undercity</a> megadungeon offers exploration from the relatively safe Warrens down to the reality-warping Foundations of the Spires</li>\n<li>Factional intrigue between the Governor, Temple, Laced Hand, and Academy provides endless political adventure</li>\n<li>The mystery of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> disappearance and the Threshold remains unsolved</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> refugee politics and the community&#39;s desperate situation offer moral complexity</li>\n<li>The Governor&#39;s true intentions remain unknown -- is he building a personal empire, preparing for imperial collapse, or something else?</li>\n<li>Trade disputes, smuggling operations, and Harbor politics provide economic adventure</li>\n<li>The spires&#39; documented phenomena -- visions, sounds, sensations -- offer supernatural mystery</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gm-notes\">GM Notes</h2>\n<p>Sanctuary is the Backlands&#39; urban hub. It should feel like a real city -- complex, layered, contradictory. Key principles:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Every faction has legitimate grievances and legitimate strengths.</strong> There are no simple villains here.</li>\n<li><strong>The Undercity is always present.</strong> Even in political adventures, the ancient ruins beneath the streets are a constant reminder that Sanctuary is built on something older and stranger than the Empire.</li>\n<li><strong>The Governor is the linchpin.</strong> Every major plot in Sanctuary passes through <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussus</a> at some point. His intentions are deliberately ambiguous.</li>\n<li><strong>The Eladra mystery is the deep background.</strong> It does not need to be the focus of any given session, but it should always be felt -- in the spires, in the phenomena, in the occasional Eladra agent glimpsed and then gone.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> -- the ancient Eladra city beneath Sanctuary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- provincial governor</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Severan Voth</a> -- head of the Temple of the Unconquered Sun</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a> -- criminal syndicate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Drussine Guard</a> -- the Governor&#39;s personal army</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> -- scholarly institution</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> -- trading company</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- the province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> -- military installation to the north</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> -- frontier settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Crossings</a> -- destroyed Avari settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> -- military commander at Fort Meade</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-backlands","title":"The Backlands (Province of Argolle)","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["province","backlands","argolle","frontier","mithrian-empire","avari","setting"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-backlands-province-of-argolle\">The Backlands (Province of Argolle)</h1>\n<p>The province of <strong>Argolle</strong>, commonly known as <strong>the Backlands</strong>, is the forgotten frontier of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Once the ancestral homelands of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> people, this war-scarred region exists at the very edge of imperial civilization, a place where the Empire&#39;s grip has grown so weak that law, order, and hope have all but evaporated.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;There is no soil out here, only the ash of Empires. The trees breathe rot and the water tastes of the dead. I seen it, I seen what waits beneath the ground. This land is not cursed — no, no, no — it remembers. Every war, every broken oath, every forgotten god — it sings them back into the marrow of the earth. That&#39;s why we can&#39;t leave. We&#39;re not stuck. We&#39;ve been claimed.&quot;</em>\n— <strong>Father Draven</strong>, drunken priest</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"overview\">Overview</h2>\n<p>The Backlands carries a legacy of violence and war stretching back centuries, having been the site of numerous conflicts since the days of the ancient <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire#argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>. It is a land defined by its suffering — every generation brings new wars, new atrocities, and new reasons for the earth to remember.</p>\n<p>Today, the Backlands is a sparsely populated, poorly defended frontier territory. Its settlements cling to existence against a tide of threats both external and internal. The land itself seems hostile to civilization, as if the accumulated trauma of ages has seeped into the very soil.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-political-situation\">Current Political Situation</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-withdrawal-378-iy\">The Withdrawal (378 IY)</h3>\n<p>Two years ago, as the great <strong>Skiotha</strong> host threatened the very yoke of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire</a>, the Emperor <strong>Justinian Claudius Decimus</strong> recalled the local armies and garrisons from the Backlands, leaving the province undermanned and poorly defended. This single act effectively abandoned the Backlands to its fate, stripping it of the military strength needed to maintain order and defend its borders.</p>\n<h3 id=\"military-command\">Military Command</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</a></strong> commands what remains — a small force of men tasked with guarding several border forts. These fortifications were originally constructed after the failed <strong>Lakan Campaigns</strong> years past, built to hold back the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> threat from the wastes. Now they serve as the thin, crumbling line between the Empire&#39;s frontier and whatever lies beyond.</p>\n<h3 id=\"civil-governance\">Civil Governance</h3>\n<p><strong>Governor Valerios Drussus</strong> of <a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a> is the imperial governor of the Backlands. He seems content to rest on his laurels in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, the only major port city left in the province. His inaction and distance from the frontier&#39;s problems have left settlements like <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> and the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> to fend for themselves.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-sacking-of-crossings\">The Sacking of Crossings</h2>\n<p>Six years ago (approximately 374 IY), a horde of <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a>, wild and savage monsters long thought defeated, sacked the city of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. The beastmen committed untold atrocity and violence upon the citizens there. The few refugees who managed to escape with their lives tell stories of the horrors inflicted that day.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><strong>Note:</strong> There is a discrepancy in the sources regarding the date of the Sacking of Crossings. The Backlands source document places it six years ago (374 IY), while the campaign primer dates it to 377 IY. The exact date remains uncertain.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In response to the sacking, the Emperor declared an <strong>Imperial Bounty</strong> upon all beastmen, offering imperial gold marks for their scalps. This decree created an entirely new economy — the <strong>Scalper</strong> trade — and drew hard men and women from every walk of life to the Backlands, seeking fortune in violence. The outpost of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> became the epicenter of this grim new industry.</p>\n<p>The beastmen, for their part, have settled in the ruin of Crossings and begun to push farther south, kidnapping farmers, raiding settlements, and worse.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-lakandi-threat\">The Lakandi Threat</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> of the wastes stir once more. These savage barbarians have long been enemies of both the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a>. They were brutally subjugated in several wars against the Empire — the <strong>Lakan Campaigns</strong> — and the border forts now commanded by <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> were built in their aftermath.</p>\n<p>But subjugation has not broken them. The Lakandi silently stew beneath the surface, and whispers of rebellion are not uncommon. With the imperial garrison reduced to a skeleton force, the threat of a Lakandi uprising is more dangerous than ever.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-features\">Key Features</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ancestral homeland</strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> people</li>\n<li><strong>Province of Argolle</strong> — a formal province of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li>Located on the <strong>forgotten frontier</strong>, as far from the imperial heartland as one can get</li>\n<li>Left <strong>undermanned and poorly defended</strong> since 378 IY when armies were recalled</li>\n<li><strong>Legacy of violence</strong> stretching back to the Argollean Empire</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> threat emanating from the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a></li>\n<li>The <strong>Imperial Bounty</strong> on beastmen scalps, fueling the Scalper economy</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> stirring in the wastes, with whispers of rebellion</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> as the only major port city remaining</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> as the primary Scalper outpost on the northern frontier</li>\n<li>Border forts from the <strong>Lakan Campaigns</strong> era, now undermanned</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"notable-figures\">Notable Figures</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Name</th>\n<th>Role</th>\n<th>Location</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>**<span class=\"dead-link\">legate-marcellus</td>\n<td>Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</span>**</td>\n<td>Military commander of the Backlands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Governor Valerios Drussus</strong></td>\n<td>Imperial Governor (of <span class=\"dead-link\">house-drussus</td>\n<td>House Drussus</span>)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</strong></td>\n<td>Emperor of the <span class=\"dead-link\">mithrian-empire</td>\n<td>Mithrian Empire</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Father Draven</strong></td>\n<td>Drunken priest (deceased — succumbed to disease)</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">bone-creek</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>[[mithrian-empire</span> — The empire that claims dominion over the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> — The people whose ancestral homeland is Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper outpost on the northern frontier</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — The sacked city, now occupied by beastmen</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> — The only major port city in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-drussus</a> — The noble house of the provincial governor</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> — The imperial military, now largely withdrawn</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The subhumanoid creatures terrorizing the frontier</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> — The barbarians of the wastes, stirring toward rebellion</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> — The trading consortium operating in the Backlands</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-foothills","title":"The Foothills","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["wilderness","foothills","mines","backlands","encounters"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-foothills\">The Foothills</h1>\n<p><strong>The Foothills</strong> are a rugged region of hills and abandoned mines in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>. The terrain is rough, broken by old mine shafts, cave systems, and rocky ridgelines that provide shelter to a variety of dangerous inhabitants -- from <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> goblins and brigands to the undead that stir in the deep places.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography\">Geography</h2>\n<p>The Foothills are characterized by rolling hills, exposed rock faces, and the entrances to abandoned mines that dot the landscape. These mines -- remnants of earlier settlement and extraction -- now serve as lairs for creatures that prefer the dark. Cave systems riddle the hills, connecting surface entrances to deeper underground passages.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"encounter-table\">Encounter Table</h2>\n<p>Roll <strong>1d8</strong> for each encounter:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Roll</th>\n<th>Encounter</th>\n<th>Number</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">beastmen</td>\n<td>Beastman Goblins</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>Cave Bears</td>\n<td>1d2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>Giant Bats</td>\n<td>1d10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Skeletons</td>\n<td>3d4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Brigands</td>\n<td>1d6+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Giant Centipedes</td>\n<td>2d4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Grave Ghouls</td>\n<td>1d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Ogre</td>\n<td>1d2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>The encounter table reflects the Foothills&#39; nature as mining territory gone feral. The heavy skeleton presence (3d4) suggests the mines and surrounding hills are thick with the remains of miners, soldiers, and settlers who died here over the centuries. <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastman</a> goblins use the caves and mines as warrens. Cave bears, giant bats, and giant centipedes are the natural fauna of the underground spaces. Brigands shelter in the hills where pursuit is difficult. Ghouls haunt the deeper places. Ogres -- solitary, territorial, and brutal -- claim the most defensible positions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province containing the Foothills</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The nearest settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a> -- The wasteland bordering the Foothills</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- Goblins who use the mines as warrens</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- Gangs who sometimes venture into the Foothills</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-gilded-vigil","title":"The Gilded Vigil","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["dungeon","cairnhill","kharai","gilded-oath","elvora","tomb-crawl","adventure-module","cairnhill-breaks","veranthas","thune","argollean-brotherhood","undead","seals","binding"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-gilded-vigil\">The Gilded Vigil</h1>\n<p><strong>The Gilded Vigil</strong> is a tomb-crawl adventure module set in the <strong>Cairnhill Breaks</strong>, the fractured limestone foothills three miles east of <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a>. It is one station in a network of <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> guardian tombs that reinforce the seals binding a <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> beneath Cairnhill. The guardian of this station -- <strong>Veranthas</strong>, whose vigil-name translates as &quot;He Who Holds the Middle Line&quot; -- has broken his covenant. Three factions have converged on the site. The seals have weakened but not broken. The Kharai has not escaped.</p>\n<p><strong>Levels:</strong> 4--7\n<strong>Approximate XP:</strong> 6,400</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-themes\">Key Themes</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Oath and betrayal</strong> -- the cost of vows made across millennia, and what happens when a guardian decides his oath was wrong</li>\n<li><strong>The cost of eternal vigilance</strong> -- what two thousand years of silent duty does to a mind, even an undead one</li>\n<li><strong>The ambiguous prisoner</strong> -- the Kharai sealed beneath Cairnhill may be innocent. It may not be. The module deliberately refuses to answer this question.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"new-monsters\">New Monsters</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Monster</th>\n<th>Notes</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Oath-Bound Remains</strong></td>\n<td>Lesser guardian undead; remnants of the Gilded Oath who did not achieve full sentinel status</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gilded Sentinel</strong></td>\n<td>Standard guardian construct of the tomb network</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gilded Warden</strong></td>\n<td>Elite guardian undead; protectors of reliquaries and sacred chambers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gilded Revenant</strong></td>\n<td>A specific type of undead manifestation -- in this module, the &quot;skin&quot; Veranthas shed when he broke the oath</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>The Gilded Vigil (unique)</strong></td>\n<td>Veranthas himself -- the unique entity at the heart of the module</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-cairnhill-breaks\">The Cairnhill Breaks</h3>\n<p>Three miles east of <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a>, the scrubland gives way to broken grey limestone ridges -- the <strong>Cairnhill Breaks</strong>. The terrain rises toward the eastern horizon where <strong><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill#mount-argolle\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mount Argolle</a></strong> stands, its white volcanic plume visible for miles. The lower gullies are choked with maquis scrub. The upper cliffs are bare limestone, carved by the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire#first-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> into terraces, archways, and inscription panels -- remnants of a civilization that once considered these hills worth marking and maintaining.</p>\n<p><strong>Harpies</strong> nest in the highest crags, making aerial approach dangerous and establishing the Breaks as a place avoided by sensible travelers.</p>\n<p>Among the lower ruins dwell the <strong>Thune remnant</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">lizard-folk</a> descendants of Argollean slave-soldiers who never left after the First Empire&#39;s collapse. They have inhabited these ruins for centuries, maintaining their own relationship with the landscape and the things buried within it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-gilded-oath\">The Gilded Oath</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Gilded Oath</strong> was a cohort of <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> warrior-priests who underwent a ritual of partial undeath called <strong>the Sevenfold Wounding</strong>. The process was as follows:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Seven wounds were taken with a <strong>gold-threaded blade</strong></li>\n<li>Through each wound, <strong>molten gold</strong> was slowly introduced into the bloodstream</li>\n<li>The gold hardened into a <strong>lattice beneath the skin</strong>, suffusing the body with a web of consecrated metal</li>\n<li>The process was <strong>agonizing and irreversible</strong></li>\n<li>At completion, the priests <strong>died their living deaths</strong> and entered the guardian tombs</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The Gilded Oath have maintained the seals <strong>in silence</strong> for over two thousand years. They do not speak. They do not communicate. They simply hold the line -- station after station, tomb after tomb, across a network of seal-points threaded through the Cairnhill Breaks. Each guardian tomb is one node in a circuit of binding that reinforces the imprisonment of the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> beneath Cairnhill.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-gold-weave-mechanic\">The Gold Weave Mechanic</h3>\n<p>The gold woven into the guardians&#39; bodies resonates with the <strong>Gnostic Geometry</strong> of the seals. It registers as <strong>faintly arcane</strong> to detection magic. When a guardian is destroyed, the gold can be removed from the body: <strong>1 turn per HD</strong> to extract. The gold itself has both material and occult value -- it is part of the seal-circuit, and its removal weakens the network incrementally.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"veranthas-the-gilded-vigil\">Veranthas -- The Gilded Vigil</h2>\n<p><strong>Veranthas</strong> is the unique entity at the heart of this module. His vigil-name -- <strong>&quot;He Who Holds the Middle Line&quot;</strong> -- designates his station as the Second Seal in the guardian tomb network.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-breaking-of-the-covenant\">The Breaking of the Covenant</h3>\n<p>Sometime in the last year, Veranthas <strong>ceased his vigil</strong>. The sequence of his apostasy:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>He <strong>desecrated his own oath-altar</strong> -- the sacred center of Room 5, where the covenant was physically anchored</li>\n<li>He <strong>retreated to his private chamber</strong> deep in Tier Two</li>\n<li>He <strong>began communicating</strong> with the entity sealed beneath the hill</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The seals have weakened but <strong>not broken</strong>. The Kharai has not escaped. But the effects of the weakening are felt:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dreams have grown strange in Cairnhill</strong> -- the already-unusual shared dream-geography of the town&#39;s residents has intensified, shifted, become disturbing in ways it was not before</li>\n<li><strong>The Thune remnant have grown bolder</strong> -- emboldened by the weakening of the seal-pressure they have always felt, pushing further from their usual territory</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> dispatched a cell</strong> -- sensing opportunity in the disturbance, <a href=\"#/page/arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Arannis Venn</a> sent operatives to investigate</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-central-mystery\">The Central Mystery</h3>\n<p>Veranthas communicated with the Kharai through the <strong>seal-membrane</strong> -- the metaphysical barrier that separates the imprisoned entity from the material world. Through this communication, Veranthas became <strong>convinced</strong> that the creature was:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sane</strong> -- not the mindless, ravening thing that two thousand years of silence had led him to assume</li>\n<li><strong>Not hostile</strong> -- not pressing against the seals with malicious intent but with the desperation of a conscious being trapped in darkness</li>\n<li><strong>Politically imprisoned</strong> -- sealed away not because it was dangerous to the world but because it was dangerous to the powers that ruled the world at the time of its imprisonment</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Veranthas reduced the sealing pressure to allow the Kharai to <strong>&quot;breathe&quot;</strong> -- to exist in something less than total sensory deprivation.</p>\n<p><strong>He may be right. He may be wrong. This is deliberately left ambiguous.</strong></p>\n<p>The module does not resolve whether the Kharai is truly innocent, truly sane, or truly non-hostile. Veranthas believes it. The evidence he presents in Room 16 is compelling but not conclusive. The party must make their own judgment -- and their judgment will have consequences that extend far beyond this tomb.</p>\n<p><strong>Room 14 opens with a CONVERSATION, not a boss fight.</strong> Veranthas wants to talk. He has been alone with his doubt for a year. He wants someone to hear his case.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-three-factions\">The Three Factions</h2>\n<p>Three factions have converged on the Gilded Vigil, each with different goals, different methods, and different dispositions toward the party.</p>\n<h3 id=\"1-the-covenant-of-the-open-hand\">1. The Covenant of the Open Hand</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#thune</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>leader</strong></td>-<td><strong>grakath</strong>-(thune-shaman)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>goal</strong></td>-<td>weaken-the-seals,-free-their-&quot;sleeping-god&quot;</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>disposition</strong></td>-<td>wary;-will-parley</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>arrival</strong></td>-<td>3-days-ago</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>base</strong></td>-<td>room-7-(fractured-gallery)</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>the-covenant-of-the-open-hand-is-a-thune-religious-faction-that-regards-the-sealed-kharai-as-a-<strong>sleeping-god</strong>----a-divine-being-imprisoned-by-the-enemies-of-their-people.-they-have-arrived-at-the-gilded-vigil-with-the-intention-of-weakening-the-seals-and-ultimately-freeing-the-entity.-they-have-<strong>defaced-inscription-work-in-tier-one</strong>----scratching-out-elvoran-glyphs-and-carving-their-own-symbols-over-the-seal-circuit-markers.-they-are-attempting-to-<strong>descend-into-tier-two</strong>-but-have-not-yet-succeeded.</p>-<p>grakath-and-his-followers-are-<strong>wary-but-willing-to-parley</strong>.-they-are-not-mindless-zealots.-they-have-their-own-understanding-of-what-is-imprisoned-beneath-the-hill,-and-they-believe-their-cause-is-just.-whether-their-understanding-is-correct-is-another-question-the-module-does-not-answer.</p>-<h3-id=\"2-the-interred-dead\">2.-the-interred-dead</h3>-<div-class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>-<th>detail</th>-<th>description</th>-</tr>-</thead><tbody><tr>-<td><strong>type</strong></td>-<td>guardian-undead</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>composition</strong></td>-<td>oath-bound-remains,-gilded-warden,-gilded-revenant</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>goal</strong></td>-<td>defend-the-tomb,-enforce-the-covenant</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>disposition</strong></td>-<td>hostile-unless-given-the-correct-elvoran-passphrase</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>the-interred-dead-are-the-remaining-guardians-of-the-tomb----the-gilded-oath-members-who-did-<strong>not</strong>-break-their-covenant.-they-continue-to-enforce-the-oath-as-they-have-for-two-millennia:-silently,-relentlessly,-and-without-discrimination.-they-attack-anyone-who-enters-the-tomb-without-authorization.</p>-<p>the-correct-<strong>elvoran-passphrase</strong>----<em>&quot;veranthas-holds-the-line;-the-kharai-does-not-wake&quot;</em>----will-cause-them-to-stand-down.-this-passphrase-is-bitterly-ironic-given-current-circumstances:-veranthas-no-longer-holds-the-line,-and-the-kharai-is-closer-to-waking-than-it-has-been-in-two-thousand-years.</p>-<p>the-guardian-types-encountered-in-the-tomb:</p>-<ul>-<li><strong>oath-bound-remains</strong>----lesser-undead,-the-remnants-of-oath-takers-whose-binding-was-less-complete</li>-<li><strong>gilded-warden</strong>----elite-guardian-stationed-in-the-reliquary-(room-6)</li>-<li><strong>gilded-revenant</strong>----in-room-5,-this-is-specifically-the-<strong>&quot;skin&quot;-veranthas-shed</strong>-when-he-broke-his-oath.-the-desecration-of-the-oath-altar-caused-a-portion-of-his-consecrated-form-to-separate-and-manifest-as-an-independent,-hostile-entity-that-still-enforces-the-covenant-its-creator-abandoned.</li>-</ul>-<h3-id=\"3-the-argollean-brotherhood\">3.-the-argollean-brotherhood</h3>-<div-class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>-<th>detail</th>-<th>description</th>-</tr>-</thead><tbody><tr>-<td><strong>type</strong></td>-<td>[[argollean-brotherhood</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>leader</strong></td>-<td>**[[arannis-venn</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>scouts</strong></td>-<td><strong>martovar</strong>-and-<strong>sitha</strong></td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>goal</strong></td>-<td>loot-elvoran-relics,-learn-what-the-seals-protect</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>disposition</strong></td>-<td>hostile-if-discovered;-will-negotiate-if-cornered</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>the-brotherhood-cell-was-dispatched-when-the-weakening-of-the-seals-was-detected.-[[arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Arannis Venn</a> leads the operation personally -- a measure of how significant the Brotherhood considers this site.</p>\n<p>Two scouts -- <strong>Martovar</strong> and <strong>Sitha</strong> -- are stripping relics from Tier One, operating from a camp in Room 4 (the Warden&#39;s Cell). Arannis himself has already penetrated into <strong>Tier Two</strong>, moving ahead of his scouts to reach whatever the deeper tomb contains.</p>\n<p>The Brotherhood&#39;s disposition is <strong>hostile if discovered</strong> -- they do not want witnesses to their looting operation. However, they will <strong>negotiate if cornered</strong>. Arannis is pragmatic. If fighting is more costly than talking, he will talk.</p>\n<p><strong>Stolen relics in the Brotherhood camp (Room 4):</strong></p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Relic</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>Golden wreath</td>\n<td>800 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ceremonial longsword</td>\n<td>550 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Veranthas hair relic</td>\n<td>Historical/occult significance</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Passphrase codex fragment</td>\n<td>Contains the Elvoran passphrase</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-two-tiers\">The Two Tiers</h2>\n<p>The Gilded Vigil is divided into two tiers -- an upper tomb that has been breached by the intruding factions, and a deeper tomb that remains Veranthas&#39;s domain.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tier-one-the-upper-tomb-rooms-1-8\">Tier One -- The Upper Tomb (Rooms 1--8)</h3>\n<p>Tier One is the portion of the tomb that has been breached. Evidence of both the Covenant of the Open Hand and the Argollean Brotherhood is visible throughout. The Interred Dead patrol these corridors with increasing agitation.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-1-the-shattered-portico\">Room 1: The Shattered Portico</h4>\n<p>The entrance to the tomb. The portico has been broken open -- whether by the Covenant, the Brotherhood, or time itself is unclear. <strong>2 Thune Sentinels</strong> guard the approach. A <strong>pit trap</strong> protects the inner threshold.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-2-the-antechamber-of-names\">Room 2: The Antechamber of Names</h4>\n<p>The walls of this chamber bear the <strong>full roster of the Gilded Oath</strong> -- every warrior-priest who underwent the Sevenfold Wounding and entered a guardian tomb in the Cairnhill Breaks network. The names are inscribed in Elvoran script, each accompanied by a vigil-name and a station designation. This is the definitive record of the seal-circuit: how many guardians, how many stations, how many seals.</p>\n<p>The inscriptions have been partially <strong>defaced by the Covenant</strong> -- Thune markings scratched over Elvoran glyphs.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-3-the-hall-of-ascension\">Room 3: The Hall of Ascension</h4>\n<p>The Sevenfold Wounding is depicted in <strong>relief carvings</strong> along the walls of this long hall -- a step-by-step visual record of the ritual that created the Gilded Oath. The carvings are detailed, clinical, and deeply unsettling: the seven wounds, the gold-threaded blade, the introduction of molten gold, the hardening of the lattice, the moment of living death.</p>\n<p><strong>2 Oath-Bound Remains</strong> patrol this hall. A <strong>stone arm trap</strong> -- a mechanical device disguised as part of the relief work -- guards the far end.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-4-the-wardens-cell\">Room 4: The Warden&#39;s Cell</h4>\n<p>The Brotherhood camp. <strong>Martovar</strong> and <strong>Sitha</strong> have established a base here, using the room&#39;s defensible position to store their stolen relics. The room contains:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Golden wreath</strong> (800 gp) -- a ceremonial piece stripped from a guardian&#39;s resting alcove</li>\n<li><strong>Ceremonial longsword</strong> (550 gp) -- Elvoran craftsmanship, consecrated but no longer enchanted</li>\n<li><strong>Veranthas hair relic</strong> -- a personal effect of the guardian, of historical and occult significance</li>\n<li><strong>Passphrase codex fragment</strong> -- contains the Elvoran passphrase that will pacify the Interred Dead: <em>&quot;Veranthas holds the line; the Kharai does not wake&quot;</em></li>\n</ul>\n<h4 id=\"room-5-the-oath-chamber\">Room 5: The Oath Chamber</h4>\n<p>The heart of Tier One. The <strong>oath-altar</strong> at the center of this chamber was the physical anchor of Veranthas&#39;s covenant -- the point where the Gilded Oath&#39;s binding was strongest. Veranthas <strong>desecrated</strong> it when he broke his covenant. The altar now bears patterns of <strong>Gnostic Geometry</strong> -- the mathematical language of the seal-circuit, now disrupted and rearranged.</p>\n<p>A <strong>sealed passage to Tier Two</strong> is visible but locked behind mechanisms that respond to the oath-altar&#39;s state.</p>\n<p>The <strong>Gilded Revenant</strong> haunts this chamber -- the <strong>&quot;skin&quot; Veranthas shed</strong> when he desecrated the altar. This entity is a manifestation of the broken covenant itself: the portion of Veranthas&#39;s consecrated form that refused to follow him into apostasy. It still enforces the oath. It is hostile and dangerous.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-6-the-reliquary\">Room 6: The Reliquary</h4>\n<p>A treasury of <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> relics -- items of historical, religious, and monetary value placed here as part of the tomb&#39;s original consecration. A <strong>Gilded Warden</strong> guards the chamber. A <strong>contact poison trap</strong> protects the primary reliquary cases.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-7-the-fractured-gallery\">Room 7: The Fractured Gallery</h4>\n<p>The Covenant of the Open Hand&#39;s <strong>base camp</strong>. <strong>Grakath</strong> and his Thune followers have established themselves here, using the gallery&#39;s multiple exits as escape routes. The walls bear evidence of the Covenant&#39;s defacement -- Thune symbols carved over Elvoran inscription work.</p>\n<p>Grakath is willing to parley. He believes the party may be useful -- or may need to be eliminated. His assessment will depend on how the encounter unfolds.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-8\">Room 8</h4>\n<p>Continuation of the upper tomb complex -- transitional space connecting the Fractured Gallery to the deeper architecture.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tier-two-the-deeper-tomb-rooms-9\">Tier Two -- The Deeper Tomb (Rooms 9+)</h3>\n<p>Tier Two is Veranthas&#39;s domain -- the portion of the tomb that the guardian retreated to after breaking his covenant. The Interred Dead are thicker here. The seal-circuit&#39;s geometry is more intense, the Gnostic patterns more complex. The air itself feels pressured, as though the proximity to the sealed Kharai exerts a physical force.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Arannis Venn</a> has already penetrated into Tier Two, moving ahead of his scouts.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-14-veranthas\">Room 14: Veranthas</h4>\n<p><strong>This room opens with a CONVERSATION, not a boss fight.</strong></p>\n<p>Veranthas -- the Gilded Vigil himself -- is here. He has been alone with his doubt for a year. He has broken a two-thousand-year oath based on his conviction that the entity he was guarding is not what he was told it was. He wants to talk. He wants someone to hear his case. He wants to know if he was right.</p>\n<p>The encounter with Veranthas is the module&#39;s central dramatic moment. He is not a raving madman. He is not a corrupted puppet of the Kharai. He is a being of enormous age and experience who has come to a conclusion that terrifies him -- that his entire existence, his two-thousand-year vigil, his agonizing transformation through the Sevenfold Wounding, may have been in service to a lie.</p>\n<p>How the party responds to Veranthas -- whether they fight him, listen to him, help him, or destroy him -- determines the module&#39;s outcome.</p>\n<h4 id=\"room-16-the-inscriptions\">Room 16: The Inscriptions</h4>\n<p>This chamber contains the <strong>inscriptions presenting Veranthas&#39;s case</strong> -- the evidence he has gathered through his communication with the Kharai. This is the <strong>central mystery payoff</strong>: the accumulated argument that the Kharai&#39;s imprisonment was political rather than necessary, that the entity is sane and non-hostile, that the seals were built not to protect the world but to silence a rival.</p>\n<p>The inscriptions are compelling. They are not conclusive. The module leaves the truth deliberately unresolved.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-treasure\">Key Treasure</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-passphrase\">The Passphrase</h3>\n<p><em>&quot;Veranthas holds the line; the Kharai does not wake.&quot;</em></p>\n<p>This passphrase pacifies the Interred Dead throughout the tomb, transforming a hostile dungeon into a navigable (if still dangerous) space. It is found in the <strong>passphrase codex fragment</strong> in Room 4.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Worth <strong>300 gp</strong> to a scholar of Elvoran history</li>\n<li><strong>Priceless</strong> to a party entering Tier Two, where the Interred Dead are thicker and more dangerous</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"connections-to-the-wider-campaign\">Connections to the Wider Campaign</h2>\n<p>The Gilded Vigil connects to multiple ongoing threads in the Fallen Empire campaign:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> and the nature of their imprisonment -- the central question of whether the Kharai are truly dangerous or politically inconvenient beings</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> psychic bleed -- the weakening of the seals has intensified the bleed effects on the town&#39;s residents</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood&#39;s</a> ongoing interest in ancient binding structures and Elvoran artifacts</li>\n<li>The nature of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire#first-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire&#39;s</a> relationship with the elder races and the decisions they made about what to seal and what to destroy</li>\n<li>The Thune remnant and their claim to the Cairnhill Breaks as ancestral territory</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a> -- The town shaped by the Kharai&#39;s psychic bleed, three miles west</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- The Imprisoned Ones; the entity sealed beneath Cairnhill</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The faction looting the tomb</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">arannis-venn</a> -- Brotherhood leader, present in Tier Two</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> -- The civilization that created the Gilded Oath</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> -- The lizard-folk whose descendants form the Covenant of the Open Hand</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The broader theological context of seals and imprisonment</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- A related binding tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- Another guardian maintaining vigil over a Kharai prison</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">lake-silverhead</a> -- The other known cairnhouse in Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history referencing the Gilded Oath discovery</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-heartwood","title":"The Heartwood","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["wilderness","forest","ancient","backlands","uncharted"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-heartwood\">The Heartwood</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The Heartwood is old. It doesn&#39;t know you&#39;re there. You could die in it and the forest wouldn&#39;t notice.&quot; -- Rika Sorn, woodsman</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Heartwood</strong> is the oldest forest in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> and possibly the oldest forest anyone has mapped -- though &quot;mapped&quot; is a generous term, as no survey of the Heartwood has ever been completed. The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> sent survey parties in. Some came back. None agreed on what they saw or where they had been.</p>\n<p>The Heartwood is not hostile in the way the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a> is hostile. The Gallowswood watches you. The Heartwood does not know you are there. You can disappear in the Heartwood without doing anything wrong.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography-and-zones\">Geography and Zones</h2>\n<p>The Heartwood divides into three concentric zones of increasing age, size, and danger. The boundaries are not sharp -- the forest transitions gradually, and by the time you realize you have entered a deeper zone, you have been in it for some time.</p>\n<h3 id=\"outer-heartwood\">Outer Heartwood</h3>\n<p>Dense deciduous forest dominated by <strong>beech, hornbeam, sessile oak, and hazel</strong>. The canopy is thick but not impenetrable. Light reaches the forest floor in patches. Undergrowth is heavy -- brambles, ferns, and fallen deadwood.</p>\n<p>The outer Heartwood is navigable with standard skill and provides reliable foraging: hazelnuts, beech mast, wild garlic (spring), and blackberries (late summer). It resembles a large, dense, ordinary forest. This resemblance is deceptive.</p>\n<h3 id=\"middle-heartwood\">Middle Heartwood</h3>\n<p>Reached after approximately <strong>one day of travel</strong> into the forest. The trees grow older and larger. The understory thins as the canopy above becomes more complete, starving the forest floor of light. The character of the forest changes -- the human-scale familiarity of the outer Heartwood gives way to something that does not acknowledge human scale.</p>\n<p><strong>Owlbeasts</strong> are territorial in the middle Heartwood. They hunt by both sound and smell -- masking one sense does not protect against the other. Deep claw marks scored into tree trunks are territory markers. If you see these marks, you are in an owlbeast&#39;s range. Move through quickly and quietly.</p>\n<p><strong>Navigation</strong>: <strong>14+ per half-day</strong> to maintain bearing. Landmarks become unreliable. Trees that seemed distinctive begin to resemble one another.</p>\n<h3 id=\"deep-heartwood\">Deep Heartwood</h3>\n<p>The trees are enormous beyond reckoning. The silence is absolute -- not the loaded, watchful silence of the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a>, which feels like something holding its breath, but the silence of a world that existed before human sound and expects to exist after it.</p>\n<p>The deep Heartwood contains things that woodsmen do not describe with precision. Not because they are being evasive or dramatic, but because precision fails them:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tracks</strong> that do not match any known animal. Not beastman, not bear, not owlbeast. Something else.</li>\n<li><strong>A sense of being assessed.</strong> Not hunted. Not threatened. Evaluated by something that has not yet decided what you are.</li>\n<li>The feeling that the forest has noticed you -- not with alarm or hostility, but with the slow attention of something immeasurably old turning a fraction of its awareness toward a small, brief, warm-blooded thing that has wandered into its presence.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Navigation</strong>: <strong>17+ per half-day</strong>. There are no reliable landmarks. The forest defeats orientation through sheer scale and uniformity.</p>\n<p><strong>Critical warning</strong>: &quot;If you think you are on a path in the deep Heartwood, you are not.&quot; There are no paths in the deep Heartwood. Anything that looks like a path was not made by human feet and does not lead where a human would want to go.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"navigation\">Navigation</h2>\n<p>The Heartwood <strong>will</strong> get you lost. This is not a function of poor skill. It is a property of the place.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Zone</th>\n<th>Navigation Throw</th>\n<th>Failure Consequence</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Outer</strong></td>\n<td>Standard</td>\n<td>Normal disorientation. Retrace and try again.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Middle</strong></td>\n<td><strong>14+ per half-day</strong></td>\n<td>Lost. Random direction of travel until next successful check.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Deep</strong></td>\n<td><strong>17+ per half-day</strong></td>\n<td>Lost in territory where being lost can be fatal.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"following-streams\">Following Streams</h3>\n<p><strong>Following streams out always works.</strong> Every stream in the Heartwood flows outward toward the forest&#39;s edge eventually. The method is reliable but slow -- it takes approximately <strong>twice as long</strong> as direct navigation to reach the outer Heartwood by following water.</p>\n<p>This is the recommended emergency navigation method. If lost in the middle or deep Heartwood, find a stream and follow it downstream. Do not attempt to shortcut across ridges or through dense growth. The stream will get you out. Your sense of direction will not.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"flora\">Flora</h2>\n<p>The Heartwood provides several plants of significant practical and medicinal value:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Zone</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Hazelnuts</strong></td>\n<td>Outer</td>\n<td>Seasonal nut crop</td>\n<td>Edible, reliable autumn food</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Beech Mast</strong></td>\n<td>Outer</td>\n<td>Small triangular nuts</td>\n<td>Edible, seasonal</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Wild Garlic</strong></td>\n<td>Outer</td>\n<td>Spring herb, identifiable by smell</td>\n<td>Edible, nutritious</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Blackberries</strong></td>\n<td>Outer</td>\n<td>Late summer berry crop in clearings</td>\n<td>Edible, abundant</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Comfrey / Bruisewort</strong></td>\n<td>All (near streams)</td>\n<td>Broad-leaved herb found near running water</td>\n<td>Poultice: <strong>heals 1d3 damage, once per day per patient</strong>. The most reliable healing herb in the Backlands.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Blessed Thistle</strong></td>\n<td>Middle / Deep</td>\n<td>Spiny herb with yellow flowers</td>\n<td><strong>Doubles hit points recovered from rest.</strong> Rare and exceptionally valuable.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dreamgrass</strong></td>\n<td>Middle / Deep</td>\n<td>Pale-leaved sedge found around old beech roots</td>\n<td>Sedative. <strong>Small doses</strong>: calms panic, aids sleep, useful for field surgery. <strong>Large doses</strong>: deep unconsciousness, respiratory depression, potentially fatal. Dosage is critical.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Insect-Repellent Vine</strong></td>\n<td>Middle / Deep (on older oaks)</td>\n<td>Vine growing on mature oak bark</td>\n<td>Crushed and applied to skin, repels biting insects. Practical value in a forest where insects are relentless. Also useful in the <span class=\"dead-link\">Empire</span> has sent parties in on multiple occasions. The results were consistent only in their inconsistency -- returning members could not agree on the forest&#39;s geography, on what they had encountered, or on how long they had been inside.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> appear to have some relationship with the outer Heartwood but do not enter the deep forest. Whether this represents respect, fear, or a prohibition from their own tradition is not clear.</p>\n<p>The Heartwood may be connected to whatever force or presence underlies the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood&#39;s</a> curse and the <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a> stirring in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>. Or it may be something entirely separate -- something older than the conflicts between <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> and <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a>, older than the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>, older than anything that has a name in human languages.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier province containing the Heartwood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> -- The other great forest of the Backlands, cursed and watchful</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a> -- The wasteland east of the forests</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> -- The nearest settlement to the Heartwood&#39;s southern edge</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> -- The people with the longest relationship to the Heartwood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/backlands-field-guide\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-field-guide</a> -- Comprehensive survival reference including Heartwood flora</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- Not present in the deep Heartwood (a notable absence)</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-slog","title":"The Slog","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["wilderness","slog","backlands","encounters","borderlands","foraging","wild-hunt"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-slog\">The Slog</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>Wind stinks of alkali and rot. Insects bite and burrow. Things cry out in the distance. Nothing answers.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Slog</strong> is the primary hunting ground of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> -- a broad wasteland stretching north and east of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, between the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a> and the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. It is where <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek&#39;s</a> <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalpers</a> and <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> warbands pressing south from <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> most frequently clash.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"geography\">Geography</h2>\n<p>A flat, bleak expanse scabbed with thorn scrub and split stone. Few trees grow here. Little shade lingers. The ground is hard-packed and alkaline, broken at intervals by dry gulches and rocky outcroppings choked with thorn thickets.</p>\n<p>The Slog was once farmland -- productive agricultural territory broken by the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> collapse and centuries of war. The land remembers what it was. Old Imperial stone markers still stand at intervals along road cuts, mute witnesses to a time when this territory was settled and cultivated. When the rains come, the bones of unlucky men push out of the ground -- the residue of battles, massacres, and lonely deaths stretching back generations.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"terrain-and-travel\">Terrain and Travel</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Territory Type</strong></td>\n<td>Borderlands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Movement (open scrub)</strong></td>\n<td>x3/4 normal movement rate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Movement (gully/rocky terrain)</strong></td>\n<td>x1/2 normal movement rate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Navigation (clear day)</strong></td>\n<td>Straightforward, no check required</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Navigation (dust storm / night)</strong></td>\n<td>Navigation throw required (6+)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Encounter Frequency</strong></td>\n<td>Once per 6-mile hex traveled; once per 12 hours resting/stationary</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>The terrain is open enough to spot enemies at distance, which provides some warning to alert travelers. But the dry gulches and thorn thickets provide abundant ambush cover for those who know how to use them -- and the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> warbands and <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">hostile Scalper gangs</a> know how to use them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"encounter-table\">Encounter Table</h2>\n<p>Roll <strong>1d8</strong> for each encounter:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Roll</th>\n<th>Encounter</th>\n<th>Number</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">beastmen</td>\n<td>Beastman Orcs</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">beastmen</td>\n<td>Beastman Goblins</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>Brigands / Hostile <span class=\"dead-link\">scalper-gangs</td>\n<td>Scalpers</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Giant Hyenas</td>\n<td>1d4+1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Stirges</td>\n<td>1d10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Ghouls (risen from unmarked battlefield graves)</td>\n<td>1d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Wight (fallen Imperial soldier, still at his post)</td>\n<td>1d2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Giant Scorpion</td>\n<td>1d2</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>The encounter table reflects the Slog&#39;s character: a killing ground layered with the detritus of centuries. The <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> presence (orcs and goblins) represents warbands pushing south from <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. The brigands and hostile Scalpers are a reminder that not all human activity in the Slog is sanctioned or friendly. The undead -- ghouls rising from unmarked battlefield graves and wights of Imperial soldiers who never left their posts -- speak to the land&#39;s long, violent history. The natural predators (hyenas, stirges, scorpions) are simply what thrives in a place like this.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"strategic-significance\">Strategic Significance</h2>\n<p>The Slog is the primary operational theater for <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek&#39;s</a> <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper gangs</a>. It is where the bounty economy plays out in practice -- gangs ranging into the wasteland to hunt <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a>, collect scalps, and bring them back to the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Exchange</a> for redemption. The terrain favors neither side decisively: open ground allows detection but gulches allow ambush. Engagements in the Slog tend to be sharp, brutal, and short.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastman</a> warbands -- primarily orcs and goblins -- press south from <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> through the Slog with increasing frequency. Whether this represents organized military pressure or simply the overflow of the ruined city&#39;s teeming population is a matter of debate among the Scalpers. The practical effect is the same: the Slog is never safe.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"flora-and-foraging\">Flora and Foraging</h2>\n<p>The Slog is a wasteland, but it yields to those who know what to look for. See <a href=\"#/page/backlands-field-guide\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-field-guide</a> for the full regional flora reference.</p>\n<h3 id=\"edible-and-useful-plants\">Edible and Useful Plants</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Crowsthorn / Ironweed</strong></td>\n<td>Grey-green scrub thorn, chest-height, dominant Slog vegetation</td>\n<td>Bark mildly toxic. Dry catches fire easily (excellent tinder). Boiled thorn-tips produce a weak antiseptic wash.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dustwort</strong></td>\n<td>Low flat-rosette plant, pale green fleshy leaves, near old water sources</td>\n<td>Edible raw but bitter. <strong>BEWARE:</strong> Saltweed closely resembles dustwort but has a waxy sheen -- causes heavy vomiting within 1 hour.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Goldenrod</strong></td>\n<td>Sheltered gullies, dense yellow flower heads in late summer</td>\n<td>Dried: <strong>+2 on proficiency throws to cure disease</strong> (requires Healing proficiency). Seasonal.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Horsetail / Snake Grass</strong></td>\n<td>Segmented reed-like plant near water</td>\n<td>As poultice: <strong>+2 on Mortal Wounds table rolls</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Both goldenrod and horsetail are forageable on <strong>Survival 7+</strong>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"water-sources\">Water Sources</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Old wells</strong> with Imperial stone markers are scattered across the Slog, dating to the Argollean farming period. Some still hold water.</li>\n<li><strong>Dry gulch bends</strong>: Dig approximately 2 feet into the bend of a dry gulch to find subsurface water.</li>\n<li><strong>Survival throws</strong>: <strong>14+</strong> in summer, <strong>10+</strong> in other seasons to locate water.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"argollean-tombs\">Argollean Tombs</h2>\n<p>Scattered across the Slog are mound graves marked with angular <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> script on stone markers. The undead population in these tombs predates the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> presence by centuries -- these dead are old, remnants of the Argollean civilization that once farmed this land.</p>\n<p><strong>Identifying a tomb</strong>: A low, grass-covered rise with even sides and a depression at its crown. The geometric regularity distinguishes a tomb from a natural hill or outcropping.</p>\n<p><strong>Warning</strong>: Give tombs respectful distance at night. The ghouls and wights on the Slog&#39;s encounter table did not appear from nowhere -- many of them emerge from these ancient burial sites.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"lakandi-sign\">Lakandi Sign</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> who range through the Slog leave distinctive fieldcraft markers. Learning to read them is a survival advantage:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fire sign</strong>: Small, efficient fires on a tripod arrangement -- not the sprawling campfires of Imperial soldiers or <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalpers</a></li>\n<li><strong>Bone markers</strong>: Scraped bone left at campsites or along trails</li>\n<li><strong>Knot-patterns</strong>: Specific knot-patterns in cordage carrying encoded meaning, though the full system is not widely understood outside Lakandi culture</li>\n<li><strong>Stone stacks at water sources</strong>: Small stone stacks placed at water sources indicate the water is <strong>clean and safe to drink</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"weather-and-seasons\">Weather and Seasons</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Season</th>\n<th>Conditions</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Summer</strong></td>\n<td>Brutal heat. Move at dawn and dusk only. Daytime travel risks heat exhaustion. Water scarce (Survival 14+).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lightning Season</strong></td>\n<td>Violent electrical storms. Get low -- the flat terrain makes anything upright a target.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Spring</strong></td>\n<td>Flooding. Dry gulches become rushing channels without warning. A gulch that was bone-dry at dawn can be a torrent by afternoon. Camp on high ground.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Winter</strong></td>\n<td>The easiest season. Cold but manageable. Reduced insect activity. Water more accessible.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"tracking-beastmen\">Tracking Beastmen</h2>\n<p>Reading <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> sign in the Slog:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Broken crowsthorn at chest-height</strong>: Standard beastman patrol. They push through the scrub without attempting concealment.</li>\n<li><strong>Crowsthorn bent at 4 feet or below</strong>: A scout or rearguard moving carefully, deliberately keeping a low profile. More dangerous -- this is a beastman that knows it is being hunted, or is hunting you.</li>\n<li><strong>30-foot-wide flattened lanes through the scrub</strong>: <strong>Hill giant.</strong> Nothing else leaves a track like that. Hill giants accompanying beastman warbands are rare but devastating.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-wild-hunt\">The Wild Hunt</h2>\n<p>On certain nights -- specifically when the eight-starred Wolf constellation climbs high -- something else moves through the Slog.</p>\n<p>Riders on the horizon that move too fast and too silently, trailing mist behind them. The dead found in their wake <strong>cannot be raised by clerics</strong>. The bodies are intact but the souls are simply gone.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalpers</a> call it the <strong>Wild Hunt</strong>. They do not discuss it with newcomers. Experienced Scalpers who have survived encounters refuse to describe what they saw in detail. The Wild Hunt is not a beastman warband, not an undead incursion, not a natural phenomenon. It is something else entirely, and the Slog&#39;s veterans treat it with a fear they do not extend to trolls, wights, or beastman war-chiefs.</p>\n<p>When the Wolf constellation rides high, experienced Scalpers make camp, bank their fires, and do not move until dawn.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The settlement whose economy depends on hunting in the Slog</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city from which beastman warbands press south</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> -- The cursed forest bordering the Slog to the west</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-heartwood\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-heartwood</a> -- The ancient forest beyond the Gallowswood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings-hinterlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings-hinterlands</a> -- The more dangerous territory closer to the Crossings ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The gangs who hunt beastmen in the Slog</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The primary targets and threats in the Slog</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province containing the Slog</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The Argollean civilization whose tombs dot the Slog</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> -- Wasteland warriors whose sign can be read in the Slog</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/backlands-field-guide\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-field-guide</a> -- Comprehensive survival reference including Slog flora</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-undercity","title":"The Undercity","category":"locations","status":"active","tags":["location","megadungeon","aodahn","sanctuary","eladra","undercity","constructs","empyrean","threshold","ascension","mystery"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-undercity\">The Undercity</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Undercity</strong> is the vast network of ruins beneath <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the remains of ancient <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> harbor-city upon which Sanctuary was built. It is a <strong>three-tier megadungeon</strong> of escalating danger and mystery, descending from mundane vermin-infested warrens into the preserved heart of an alien civilization and, ultimately, to the place where the Eladra attempted something that may have destroyed them -- or transformed them into something beyond mortal comprehension.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>Beneath <span class=\"dead-link\">Laced Hand</span> or other criminal enterprises -- treat the Warrens as infrastructure, not as the surface layer of something vastly older and more dangerous than they comprehend.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"tier-2-old-aodahn-levels-3-7\">Tier 2: Old Aodahn (Levels 3-7)</h2>\n<p>Below the Warrens lies the <strong>preserved heart of the Eladran city</strong>. This is not ruin -- this is a civilization suspended in amber.</p>\n<h3 id=\"inhabitants\">Inhabitants</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Construct guardians</strong> -- Eladran-built automatons that still patrol their ancient routes, enforcing security protocols for masters who vanished millennia ago</li>\n<li><strong>Doppelgangers</strong> -- shapeshifters that have infiltrated the preserved city, mimicking Eladran forms</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> energy</strong> -- the metaphysical residue of Eladran sorcery still saturates this tier, creating unpredictable magical effects</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"character\">Character</h3>\n<p>Old Aodahn is the archaeological and metaphysical heart of the Undercity. The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> of Aodahn vanished without explanation -- their belongings remained, their constructs continued to function, but the people simply ceased to be present. No evidence of war, plague, or flight. Whatever happened to them happened all at once, and it happened here.</p>\n<p>The construct guardians are a particular danger. They are not mindless -- they follow programmed directives with Eladran precision. They do not distinguish between explorers, looters, and threats. Anything that is not Eladran is, by their programming, an intruder.</p>\n<p>The doppelgangers raise disturbing questions. What are they mimicking? Who are they pretending to be? And for whom are they performing?</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"tier-3-foundations-of-the-spires-levels-7\">Tier 3: Foundations of the Spires (Levels 7+)</h2>\n<p>The deepest level -- the foundations of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn&#39;s</a> five ivory spires that rise over 300 feet above Sanctuary. This is where the Eladra&#39;s greatest works were undertaken, and where their greatest mystery resides.</p>\n<h3 id=\"inhabitants\">Inhabitants</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Masterwork constructs</strong> -- the most sophisticated Eladran automatons, far more dangerous and intelligent than the guardians of Old Aodahn</li>\n<li><strong>Major elementals</strong> -- beings of pure elemental force, either summoned or attracted by the metaphysical energies that saturate the Foundations</li>\n<li><strong>The Threshold</strong> -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened, and <strong>the door has not fully closed</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-threshold\">The Threshold</h3>\n<p>The Threshold is the defining mystery of the Undercity and possibly of the entire <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. This is the site where the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> of Aodahn attempted -- or achieved -- their <strong>ascension</strong>. The nature of this ascension is unknown:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Did they transcend physical existence?</li>\n<li>Did they pass through <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> into <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Beyond</a>?</li>\n<li>Did they merge with <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Aurelion</a>?</li>\n<li>Did they destroy themselves?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>What is known is that <strong>the door has not fully closed</strong>. Whatever the Eladra opened at the Threshold remains ajar. <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> energy bleeds through the crack. The constructs guard it with lethal devotion. The elementals are drawn to it like moths to flame.</p>\n<p>The Threshold may connect to the broader mysteries of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> disappearance, the <a href=\"#/page/the-womb-curse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Womb Curse</a>, and the question of whether the Eladra&#39;s ascension and the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora&#39;s</a> corruption are two sides of the same metaphysical event.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-sanctuary\">Relationship to Sanctuary</h2>\n<p>The Undercity is not merely beneath Sanctuary -- it is the foundation upon which Sanctuary rests, literally and metaphysically. The city above was named after the Eladran word for the city below: Aodahn means &quot;sanctuary&quot; or &quot;refuge.&quot; The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrians</a> preserved the name without understanding its origin.</p>\n<p>Multiple access points exist throughout Sanctuary&#39;s districts, and the boundaries between the modern city and the ancient one are permeable in ways that the surface population does not fully appreciate. The <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> criminal syndicate, various smuggling operations, and occasional adventuring parties all make use of the Undercity&#39;s upper reaches, but few venture beyond the Warrens into the eerie preservation of Old Aodahn.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a> -- The ancient Eladran city whose ruins form the Undercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- The modern city built above</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The race that built Aodahn and vanished at the Threshold</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The boundary the Threshold may breach</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-beyond</a> -- What lies on the other side</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-aurelion</a> -- The cosmic being the Eladra may have sought</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> -- The corrupted branch of the Eladra</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-womb-curse\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-womb-curse</a> -- Possibly connected to the Eladran disappearance</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">laced-hand</a> -- Criminal syndicate that uses the Warrens</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">gnostic-geometry</a> -- Eladran sorcerous tradition preserved in Aodahn&#39;s ruins</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"thornasse","title":"Thornasse","category":"locations","status":"destroyed","tags":["location","avari","erenthis","cynar","cultural-execution","black-tree","crossings","ruins","argolle","backlands","imperial-academy"],"html":"<h1 id=\"thornasse\">Thornasse</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Cynar did not burn a tree. He burned a people. The Erenthis was the heart of the Avari Confederation -- their sacred center, their living covenant with the world. When it burned, the Avari did not simply lose a symbol. They lost the axis around which their civilization turned. The collapse that followed was not military. It was spiritual.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Thornasse</strong> is the site where <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> burned the great <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis tree</a> thirty years ago, constituting a cultural execution of the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> people. The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation&#39;s</a> will to resist collapsed within months of the burning. The scorched stump -- known as <strong>the Black Tree</strong> -- still stands at the center of the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>.</p>\n<p>Something endures.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td>At or near <span class=\"dead-link\">High Mage Cynar</span> -- acting with the authority and power of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> -- burned the great <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis tree</a> at Thornasse. The Erenthis was not merely a tree. It was the sacred center of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a>, the living axis around which their civilization, their spiritual identity, and their collective will turned. The tree was covenant, symbol, and anchor -- its destruction was not an act of war but an act of cultural annihilation.</p>\n<p>The burning was deliberate, calculated, and devastating in its effect. The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation&#39;s</a> will to resist the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> collapsed within months. Military defeat had not achieved what a single act of cultural execution accomplished -- the destruction of the thing that held the Avari together as a people.</p>\n<p>This act remains one of the most consequential uses of <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> power in living memory, and one of the most morally contested.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-black-tree\">The Black Tree</h2>\n<p>The scorched stump of the Erenthis -- called <strong>the Black Tree</strong> -- still stands at the center of the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. It has not been removed. It has not decayed. It stands as monument and wound, marking the site where the Avari Confederation died as a political and spiritual entity.</p>\n<h3 id=\"something-endures\">Something Endures</h3>\n<p>The roots of the Erenthis have not fully died.</p>\n<p>The ground around the Black Tree is warm to the touch -- not from sunlight or geothermal activity, but from something deeper, older, and more deliberate. The tree was burned, the Confederation was broken, and the Avari were scattered -- but the roots persist. Whatever the Erenthis was connected to -- whatever power, presence, or living covenant it embodied -- has not been entirely extinguished.</p>\n<p>What this persistence means -- whether it represents hope for the Avari, a threat to the Empire, or something beyond either interpretation -- is not yet understood.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"consequences\">Consequences</h2>\n<p>The destruction of the Erenthis accomplished what decades of military campaigns could not:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a> fragmented within months of the burning</li>\n<li>Organized Avari resistance to the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> effectively ceased</li>\n<li>The Avari people were scattered, their cultural center destroyed, their collective identity shattered</li>\n<li>The ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> became a monument to imperial power and Avari loss</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy&#39;s</a> role in the destruction cemented its reputation as both indispensable and dangerous</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The sacred tree that was burned</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a> -- The High Mage who burned the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a> -- The civilization destroyed by the burning</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> -- The people whose cultural center was annihilated</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruins where the Black Tree still stands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The underground complex beneath Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution that authorized and executed the burning</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that benefited from the Avari collapse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province containing Thornasse</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"log","title":"Wiki Log","category":"overview","status":"unknown","tags":[],"html":"<h1 id=\"wiki-log\">Wiki Log</h1>\n<p>Chronological record of wiki operations. Newest entries first.</p>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-11-update-missing-entity-pages-created\">[2026-04-11] update | Missing Entity Pages Created</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Pages created (12): <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a>, <a href=\"#/page/anaya\" class=\"wiki-link\">anaya</a>, <a href=\"#/page/antonius\" class=\"wiki-link\">antonius</a>, <a href=\"#/page/lynara\" class=\"wiki-link\">lynara</a>, <a href=\"#/page/crackback\" class=\"wiki-link\">crackback</a>, <a href=\"#/page/doc-quinten\" class=\"wiki-link\">doc-quinten</a>, <a href=\"#/page/irontoe\" class=\"wiki-link\">irontoe</a>, <a href=\"#/page/theo\" class=\"wiki-link\">theo</a>, <a href=\"#/page/argoll-river\" class=\"wiki-link\">argoll-river</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-undercity</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-womb-curse\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-womb-curse</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-black-tree\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-black-tree</a></li>\n<li>People (8): Rook (dead bandit king at Fort Ikenvar), Anaya (henchman with Gallowswood visions), Antonius (henchman with Rendson vision), Lynara (Eladran Nightblade, Malyn&#39;s apprentice), Crackback (Targ thief, Marr&#39;s enforcer), Doc Quinten (Kolani barber-surgeon), Irontoe (Mithrian smith, lost leg fighting Lakandi), Theo (Thrassian Flophouse owner, Marr&#39;s informant)</li>\n<li>Locations (2): Argoll River (major river of the Backlands), The Undercity (three-tier megadungeon beneath Sanctuary)</li>\n<li>Lore (2): The Womb Curse (Eladra/Elvora mystery mentioned by Eolande), The Black Tree (scorched Erenthis at Thornasse, roots endure)</li>\n<li>Index updated: 12 new pages, page count 178 -&gt; 190</li>\n<li>Notes: Red link cleanup. All 12 pages were entities referenced via wikilinks in existing pages but lacking their own wiki pages. Full stat blocks included for Lynara, Crackback, Doc Quinten, Irontoe, and Theo. Maximum detail and cross-referencing throughout.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-next-session-reference-fort-meade-to-sanctuary\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Next Session Reference (Fort Meade to Sanctuary)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>Fallen Empire/next_session_reference.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (4): <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">eolande</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-stone-of-sakkara</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-next-session-reference\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-next-session-reference</a></li>\n<li>Pages updated (4): <a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> (Arc V: three scenes added), <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> (Stone of Sakkara moral crisis and escalation), <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> (Eolande revelation, interrogation, dispatch, expedition plans), <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> (charter proposal details, political transformation)</li>\n<li>Index updated: 1 new person, 2 new lore pages, 1 new source page, page count 173 -&gt; 178</li>\n<li>Notes: MAJOR plot revelations. Eolande -- an Eladran general from ~3000 BE -- is still present at the Black Tree (scorched Erenthis at Thornasse). The Reclaimers encountered him there. Malachor&#39;s most significant dispatch ever sent to his secret third-party contact, revealing Eolande&#39;s existence. The Stone of Sakkara is amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward innocence as the party moves south -- escalating trail of violence (farm animals, a horse, a child). Theodotus faces the moral crisis: killing the Guzzler resolves nothing, the Stone will reach through something else. Legate Marcellus proposes a formal charter: exclusive salvage rights to Crossings/Nethercity, vault/warehouse, quarterly market fairs, 15% (negotiable to 10%) of recovered value. Unspoken agenda: political independence from Governor Drussus.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-woodsmans-field-notes\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Woodsman&#39;s Field Notes</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>THE BACKLANDS/PLAYER MATERIALS/Woodsmans_Field_Notes.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (3): <a href=\"#/page/backlands-field-guide\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-field-guide</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-heartwood\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-heartwood</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-woodsmans-field-notes\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-woodsmans-field-notes</a></li>\n<li>Pages updated (2): <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> (flora table, crab spiders, the Dome, abominations with combat stats, Avari warning stones, burial mounds, navigation hazards, the loaded silence), <a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a> (flora/foraging with mechanics, Argollean tombs, Lakandi sign reading, weather/seasons, beastman tracking guide, hill giants, the Wild Hunt)</li>\n<li>Index updated: 1 new location, 1 new lore page, 1 new source page, page count 170 -&gt; 173</li>\n<li>Notes: Major survival content ingest. Introduces the Heartwood as a completely new major location -- oldest forest in the Backlands, three zones of increasing danger, no survey ever completed, unidentifiable entities in the deep forest. New creature types: abominations (three attacks/round, paralytic venom, immune to sleep/charm/hold) at the Gallowswood Dome, crab spiders (dog-sized, paralytic, -2 surprise). New phenomenon: the Wild Hunt (riders when the Wolf constellation is high, dead cannot be raised). Extensive herbal medicine mechanics across all four regions. Backlands-field-guide serves as the master survival reference page cross-linking all regional content.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-backlands-regional-overview-multiple-source-pages\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Backlands Regional Overview + Multiple Source Pages</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Sources: <code>THE BACKLANDS/Backlands_Regional_Overview.docx</code>, Crossings Adventure Supplement, The Gilded Vigil, Random Notes, Backlands Timeline, History of the First Empire</li>\n<li>Pages created (8): <a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-foothills\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-foothills</a>, <a href=\"#/page/crossings-hinterlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings-hinterlands</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-crossings-supplement\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-crossings-supplement</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-gilded-vigil</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-backlands-regional-overview\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-backlands-regional-overview</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-random-notes\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-random-notes</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-backlands-timeline\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-backlands-timeline</a>, <a href=\"#/page/src-first-empire-history\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-first-empire-history</a></li>\n<li>Pages updated (3): <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> (full rewrite with encounter table, black heart, Outlands classification), <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> (MAJOR: criminal enterprise — bandit ops from Fort Ikenvar, beastman trafficking via Malyn, fraudulent scalp manufacturing), <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> (Fort Caldras alias added, naming discrepancy noted)</li>\n<li>Index updated: 3 new location pages, 5 new source pages, page count 162 -&gt; 170</li>\n<li>Notes: Four wilderness regions now fully documented with terrain rules and encounter tables: the Slog (Borderlands), Gallowswood (Outlands, cursed), the Foothills (mines), Crossings Hinterlands (highest danger). Key revelation: Varro&#39;s criminal enterprise exposes the Lord Merchant as running banditry, beastman slavery, and bounty fraud. Gallowswood rewrite includes the pulsating black heart beneath the granite dome from session notes. Five new source pages cataloged for previously untracked documents.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-campaign-recap-session-history\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Campaign Recap + Session History</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>THE BACKLANDS/SESSION MATERIALS/Campaign Recap Document.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (8): <a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a>, <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a>, <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a>, <a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a>, <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a>, <a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a>, <a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon</a></li>\n<li>Pages updated (1): <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a></li>\n<li>Notes: Campaign session history populated. All 5 active PCs and 1 deceased PC (Tancred) have individual pages. Sessions category now active.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-timelines-fort-harvald-history-of-the-first-empire\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Timelines + Fort Harvald + History of the First Empire</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Sources: <code>THE BACKLANDS/SETTING LORE/Timelines.docx</code>, <code>THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/fort_harvald_acks.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (2): <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-voss</a>, <a href=\"#/page/noma\" class=\"wiki-link\">noma</a></li>\n<li>Pages rewritten (2): <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> (expanded from 663 BE to full 4100 BE timeline), <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> (complete settlement reference with 11 NPCs)</li>\n<li>Notes: History now covers deep pre-imperial era: Eladran city-states, Great Teacher awakening in Krysea, Thune creation, Bitter War, Argollean Empire, Thune rebellion, Massar rise, and full imperial chronology. Fort Harvald fully detailed with bayou frontier atmosphere.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-update-created-82-missing-entity-pages\">[2026-04-10] update | Created 82 missing entity pages</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Filled all broken wikilinks with standalone pages</li>\n<li>Created: 21 race/culture pages, 23 deity/concept pages, 24 house/NPC/event pages, 14 location/concept pages</li>\n<li>Notes: Every wikilinks in the wiki should now resolve to a page with real content. No more empty nodes.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-sanctuary-city-supplement\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Sanctuary City Supplement</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/Sanctuary_City_Supplement.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (6): <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a>, <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a>, <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">governor-drussus</a>, <a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">prelate-voth</a>, <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">laced-hand</a>, <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">drussine-guard</a></li>\n<li>Source page: <a href=\"#/page/src-sanctuary-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-sanctuary-city</a></li>\n<li>Notes: Massive city supplement. Provincial capital with 8 districts and 80+ keyed locations. Key NPCs: Governor Drussus (Fighter 12, building something), Prelate Voth (Cleric 13, Temple leader 20 years), Castellan Thibaud (Master Thief 7, Laced Hand boss). Three-tier megadungeon beneath city (ruins of Aodahn/Eladra city). Five ivory spires may be engineered Erenthis analogues. Eladra vanished mysteriously from Aodahn before Mithrian arrival.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-faiths-of-argolle\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Faiths of Argolle</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>Faiths of Argolle.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (10): <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a>, <a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel-earth-hunger</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a>, <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a>, <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a>, <a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a></li>\n<li>Pages updated (1): <a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a> (rewritten with Shaw&#39;s full theology)</li>\n<li>Source page: <a href=\"#/page/src-faiths-of-argolle\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-faiths-of-argolle</a></li>\n<li>Notes: Deep theological document. Major new concepts: Erenthis trees (Eladran living Empyrean monuments, root network hostile to Cthonic corruption), the Nethercity (Eladran necropolis beneath Crossings, vessel for the Awakening, Great Teacher entity dormant in depths), the Kharai (ancient imprisoned beings in Ygrathen cairnhouses), Convergence Problem (Empyrean and Cthonic gods may be same divided powers), Bel earth-hunger (agricultural blood cult in Dunwick area), Lakandi demon-binding, Varek Ashstone (Ygrathen hermit at Lake Silverhead), Shaw&#39;s Hollow Sun theology (Seros has been stolen, salvation through suffering).</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-crossings-points-of-interest\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Crossings Points of Interest</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/Crossings Points of Interest.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (1): <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a></li>\n<li>Source page: <a href=\"#/page/src-crossings-poi\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-crossings-poi</a></li>\n<li>Notes: Ruined city gazetteer with 10 POIs including ghouls, undead Elvoran mummy, deranged dryad, corrupted giant crocodile, and beastman neutral ground. Encounter table included.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-dramatis-personae-npc-reference\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Dramatis Personae &amp; NPC Reference</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Sources: <code>THE BACKLANDS/CHARACTERS &amp; NPCS/DRAMATIS PERSONAE.docx</code>, <code>THE BACKLANDS/CHARACTERS &amp; NPCS/NPCS.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (11): <a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</a>, <a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a>, <a href=\"#/page/skinner\" class=\"wiki-link\">skinner</a>, <a href=\"#/page/arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">arannis-venn</a>, <a href=\"#/page/bottlecap-juno\" class=\"wiki-link\">bottlecap-juno</a>, <a href=\"#/page/wekko\" class=\"wiki-link\">wekko</a>, <a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">marcos-varanes</a>, <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-gallus\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-gallus</a>, <a href=\"#/page/kael-baldric\" class=\"wiki-link\">kael-baldric</a>, <a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a>, <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a></li>\n<li>Source page: <a href=\"#/page/src-dramatis-personae\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-dramatis-personae</a></li>\n<li>Notes: Full NPC roster with ACKS II stat blocks, secrets, and allegiances. All Scalper gang leaders and factions documented. Kael Baldric listed as missing.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-fort-meade-gm-reference\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Fort Meade GM Reference</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/fort_meade.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (5): <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a>, <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a>, <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-crull</a>, <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a>, <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a></li>\n<li>Pages updated (1): <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a></li>\n<li>Source page: <a href=\"#/page/src-fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-fort-meade</a></li>\n<li>Notes: Fort Meade garrison with trade route dynamics, political leverage, Rook aftermath, Fort Ikenvar/Guzzler threat. Detailed profiles for all key NPCs with secrets. Argollean Brotherhood introduced as covert faction.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-update-enriched-all-wiki-pages-with-maximum-detail\">[2026-04-10] update | Enriched all wiki pages with maximum detail</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Rewrote <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic-and-sorcery</a>, <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a>, <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a>, <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> with exhaustive detail, all flavor quotes, all named individuals</li>\n<li>Rewrote <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a>, <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-measure-and-the-scale</a> with full theological detail and all source quotes</li>\n<li>Notes: User requested maximum detail. All pages now include every available quote, every named person, every cultural/mechanical detail from the source documents.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-the-backlands\">[2026-04-10] ingest | The Backlands</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>THE BACKLANDS/SETTING LORE/THE BACKLANDS.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (8): <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a>, <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a>, <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a>, <a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">tolliver-watts</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a>, <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a>, <a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a>, <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a></li>\n<li>Source page: <a href=\"#/page/src-the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-the-backlands</a></li>\n<li>Notes: Second ingest. Backlands province overview, Bone Creek gazetteer with all 9 locations, 5 NPC pages, Red River Consortium faction page. Bone Creek includes 16+ named NPCs with their secrets and allegiances.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-ingest-fallen-empire-primer\">[2026-04-10] ingest | Fallen Empire Primer</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Source: <code>THE BACKLANDS/SETTING LORE/FALLEN EMPIRE PRIMER FINAL.docx</code></li>\n<li>Pages created (21): <a href=\"#/page/overview\" class=\"wiki-link\">overview</a>, <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a>, <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">great-houses</a>, <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a>, <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic-and-sorcery</a>, <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a>, <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-calendar\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-calendar</a>, <a href=\"#/page/languages-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">languages-of-mithrapos</a>, <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a>, <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a>, <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-pantheon</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-pantheon</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-mystical\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-mystical</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-measure-and-the-scale</a>, <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a>, <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a>, <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-talons</a>, <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">thousand-temples</a>, <a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">burnished-scale</a>, <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithra-city</a></li>\n<li>Source page: <a href=\"#/page/src-fallen-empire-primer\" class=\"wiki-link\">src-fallen-empire-primer</a></li>\n<li>Notes: First ingest. Foundational setting document covering empire, houses, military, history, religions, magic, races, calendar, languages. Seeded all major wiki categories except people/ and sessions/.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"2026-04-10-init-wiki-scaffolding-created\">[2026-04-10] init | Wiki scaffolding created</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Created directory structure: people/, locations/, factions/, faiths/, lore/, sessions/, sources/</li>\n<li>Created index.md, log.md, overview.md (stub)</li>\n<li>Created CLAUDE.md schema at vault root</li>\n<li>Notes: Wiki initialized using the LLM Wiki pattern. Ready for first ingest.</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"argollean-empire","title":"The Argollean Empire (The First Empire)","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["first-empire","eladra","argolle","history","great-teacher","cthonic","empyrean","thune","massaran","ygrathen","nethercity","krysea","transmogrification"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-argollean-empire-the-first-empire\">The Argollean Empire (The First Empire)</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Argollean Empire</strong> -- commonly called the <strong>First Empire</strong> -- was the earliest large-scale civilization in the known history of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. Founded and governed by the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>, it arose in the region of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, expanded through conquest and theological transformation, and endured for millennia before its decline gave rise to the successor states that eventually produced the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>.</p>\n<p>As Magister Callistrus Vellex observed in his lecture on the subject: the name &quot;First Empire&quot; is itself an error of convenience. It was not the first civilization, nor the first to rule others. It was, however, the first to believe that its dominion was permanent.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"origins-of-the-eladra\">Origins of the Eladra</h2>\n<p>At the time of the First Empire&#39;s founding, humanity existed in scattered tribes. The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>, by contrast, appear in the historical record with their cities already standing, their metaphysical systems already articulated, and their theology presuming intimate knowledge of creation itself. There is no archaeological record of an Eladran &quot;rise&quot; -- no primitive settlements, no gradual urbanization, no evidence of the slow accumulation of knowledge that characterizes every other known civilization. They simply appear, fully formed, as if placed.</p>\n<p>Documents predating the <strong>Day-Without-Night</strong> -- a cataclysmic event in early Eladran mythos whose precise nature is debated -- are extremely rare. What survives suggests a civilization already ancient at the time of the catastrophe, already possessed of knowledge that other peoples would not approach for millennia.</p>\n<p>The Eladra claim they were <strong>fashioned as divine images of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></strong> -- the greater gods whose nature and number are contested across theological traditions. Whether this claim is literal truth, metaphorical self-understanding, or propaganda is one of the foundational questions of Mithraposi theology. What is not disputed is that the Eladra behaved as if it were true, and built their civilization accordingly.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"creation-through-loss\">Creation Through Loss</h2>\n<p>Eladran culture reflects a profound preoccupation with what Vellex calls <strong>&quot;creation through loss&quot;</strong> -- the belief that to create was an act of surrender. Every act of making required a corresponding act of giving up. This is not merely an aesthetic principle. It is a metaphysical claim about the nature of reality: that creation is not additive but transformative, that nothing can be brought into being without something being consumed in the process.</p>\n<p>This philosophical foundation is crucial to understanding the Argollean Empire&#39;s later trajectory -- its embrace of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition, the practice of [[#transmogrification|Transmogrification]], and the construction of the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. The Eladra did not stumble into darkness. They walked toward it with theological conviction, believing that what they surrendered in the process was the price of what they were building.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"timeline-of-the-first-empire\">Timeline of the First Empire</h2>\n<h3 id=\"4100-be-eladran-city-states-arise-in-argolle\">4100 BE -- Eladran City-States Arise in Argolle</h3>\n<p>The first recorded Eladran settlements appear in the region of Argolle, centered around what will become the city of <strong>Krysea</strong>. These are not villages. They are cities -- planned, fortified, and built with materials and techniques that suggest a civilization already in possession of advanced knowledge. The city-states govern independently but share language, theology, and cultural institutions.</p>\n<h3 id=\"3900-be-encounter-with-the-ygrathen\">3900 BE -- Encounter with the Ygrathen</h3>\n<p>The Eladra encounter the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> in the <strong>Meniri Mountains</strong>. The two peoples become immediate and enduring enemies. The nature of the enmity is not purely territorial -- it appears to be theological, rooted in fundamentally incompatible understandings of the divine order. The Ygrathen-Eladran conflict will persist for nearly two millennia before its resolution.</p>\n<h3 id=\"3800-be-discovery-of-the-lakan-humans\">3800 BE -- Discovery of the Lakan (Humans)</h3>\n<p>The Eladra discover humans -- whom they call <strong>the Lakan</strong> -- living in tribal societies on the margins of Eladran territory. The encounter is not between equals. The Eladra introduce the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan</a> to the <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a></strong> -- the divine tradition that the Eladra claim as their birthright. This is not merely cultural exchange; it is theological colonization. The Lakan receive gods, and in receiving them, become subordinate to the civilization that brought them.</p>\n<h3 id=\"3200-be-expansion-of-krysea-and-the-great-teacher\">3200 BE -- Expansion of Krysea and the Great Teacher</h3>\n<p>Krysea expands from city-state to regional power. During this period of growth, the entity known as <strong>the Great Teacher</strong> is awakened -- the circumstances and mechanism of this awakening are not recorded in surviving texts. The Great Teacher introduces the <strong><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a></strong> to Eladran civilization, establishing a second divine tradition alongside the existing Empyrean worship.</p>\n<p>The introduction of the Cthonic tradition is the pivotal event of Eladran history. The Empyrean gods represent the divine order as the Eladra have always understood it -- creation from above, authority descending. The Cthonic gods represent something else: power rising from below, transformation through surrender, creation through loss made literal and operational. The Great Teacher does not replace the Empyrean tradition. It offers an alternative, and the Eladra -- already philosophically prepared by their theology of sacrificial creation -- embrace it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"3000-be-general-eolande-and-the-conquests\">3000 BE -- General Eolande and the Conquests</h3>\n<p><strong>General <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a></strong>, tutored directly by the Great Teacher, begins a campaign of territorial expansion that will transform the Eladran city-states into a true empire. Eolande&#39;s military campaigns are not merely territorial -- they are theological, extending the reach of the Cthonic tradition alongside the boundaries of Eladran power. The conquests bring vast territories under Eladran control and establish the political framework that will become the Argollean Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2800-be-transmogrification-begins\">2800 BE -- Transmogrification Begins</h3>\n<p>The practice of <strong>Transmogrification</strong> is introduced -- the deliberate magical alteration of living beings, reshaping flesh and spirit according to principles derived from the Cthonic tradition. This is the theology of &quot;creation through loss&quot; made flesh: beings are transformed, surrendering what they were to become something the Empire requires. The process is applied to subject populations, prisoners of war, and -- in some accounts -- willing Eladran volunteers.</p>\n<p>Transmogrification is not merely a weapon. It is an industrial process, a theological practice, and a tool of governance. It produces soldiers, laborers, and entities designed for specific purposes. It also produces the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Slog</a> -- the creatures that will haunt the margins of every subsequent civilization to occupy this territory.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2700-be-first-crescent-rebellion-and-the-creation-of-the-thune\">2700 BE -- First Crescent Rebellion and the Creation of the Thune</h3>\n<p>The first major internal revolt against the Empire. The rebellion is suppressed, but the crisis prompts a significant response: the creation of the <strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a></strong> -- a servitor race engineered through Transmogrification to serve as the Empire&#39;s slave-soldiers. The Thune are purpose-built for loyalty and warfare, designed to provide the Empire with a military force that cannot rebel because rebellion has been bred out of them.</p>\n<p>The creation of the Thune is the logical endpoint of &quot;creation through loss&quot; applied to governance. The Empire surrenders the humanity of an entire people to gain an army that serves without question. That this army will eventually rebel anyway is one of history&#39;s more pointed ironies.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2600-be-empire-declared-the-bitter-war-begins\">2600 BE -- Empire Declared; The Bitter War Begins</h3>\n<p>The Argollean Empire is formally declared, consolidating the Eladran city-states and conquered territories under a single imperial authority. The declaration coincides with the beginning of the <strong>Bitter War</strong> -- a prolonged conflict whose parties, objectives, and boundaries are not fully preserved in surviving records. What is known is that the war is devastating, long-lasting, and shapes the Empire&#39;s military and administrative institutions for centuries.</p>\n<p>During this period, construction of the <strong>Grand Cthonic Temple</strong> begins beneath what will become the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- the vast subterranean complex that the Great Teacher designs as a prepared vessel for a future event the builders call <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Awakening</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2400-be-doom-temple-of-dirgion\">2400 BE -- Doom Temple of Dirgion</h3>\n<p>Construction of the <strong>Doom Temple of Dirgion</strong> begins within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>, expanding the subterranean complex with a structure dedicated to purposes that surviving records describe in language more suggestive of containment than worship.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2100-be-the-ygrathen-crushed-the-great-teacher-enters-cryostasis\">2100 BE -- The Ygrathen Crushed; The Great Teacher Enters Cryostasis</h3>\n<p>The warlord <strong>Marcan</strong> finally crushes the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a>, ending nearly two millennia of conflict. The Ygrathen are broken as a people and driven into the deep places of the Meniri Mountains, where remnants persist into the present era.</p>\n<p>Construction of the <strong>Hallowed Halls of Heroes</strong> begins within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>, honoring the Empire&#39;s greatest military figures.</p>\n<p>Following the victory over the Ygrathen, the Great Teacher <strong>enters cryostasis</strong> within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>, in a chamber that will come to be known as the <strong>Secret Sepulcher</strong>. The Great Teacher does not die. It does not depart. It enters a state of preserved dormancy -- waiting, as the Nethercity was built to wait, for the event it was constructed to serve.</p>\n<p>The Great Teacher is also known as a <strong>Chemosh (Khepri) Hierarch</strong>. Later sources -- particularly the <strong>Codex of Ninefold Stillness</strong> -- identify the Great Teacher&#39;s true name as <strong>Sen&#39;Zorath, the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues</strong>, and describe a chamber called the <strong>Hall of the Teacher</strong> where Sen&#39;Zorath rests in the <strong>Chrysalis-Urn</strong>. See <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Nethercity</a> for further detail on these locations.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2000-be-great-king-tomb\">2000 BE -- Great King Tomb</h3>\n<p>The warlord <strong>Marcan</strong> -- conqueror of the Ygrathen -- is interred within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> in the structure known as the <strong>Great King Tomb</strong>. The scale and elaboration of the tomb reflects Marcan&#39;s status as the Empire&#39;s greatest military hero.</p>\n<h3 id=\"1800-be-orthanach-becomes-the-first-mummy-lord\">1800 BE -- Orthanach Becomes the First Mummy Lord</h3>\n<p>The hierophant <strong>Orthanach</strong> becomes the <strong>first mummy lord</strong> -- the first being to achieve a form of undeath through Cthonic ritual that preserves consciousness, will, and power beyond bodily death. This is &quot;creation through loss&quot; taken to its ultimate conclusion: the surrender of mortality in exchange for perpetual existence in a transformed state.</p>\n<p>Orthanach&#39;s <strong>Secret Tomb</strong> within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> houses not only the hierophant but also his wife <strong>Sonya</strong> and his guard <strong>Cassair</strong> -- whether they accompanied him willingly into undeath is not recorded.</p>\n<h3 id=\"1700-be-eladran-decline-and-thune-rebellion\">1700 BE -- Eladran Decline and Thune Rebellion</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> enter a period of irreversible decline. The causes are debated -- demographic collapse, theological exhaustion, the accumulated cost of millennia of Transmogrification and Cthonic practice. Whatever the cause, the Eladra can no longer maintain the institutions that sustain their empire.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> -- the slave-soldiers created to serve without question -- rebel. The rebellion is successful. <strong>Krysea</strong> -- the founding city of Eladran civilization, the seat of the Great Teacher&#39;s awakening -- is razed. The Argollean Empire, as a political entity, ceases to exist.</p>\n<p>What follows is not a return to the pre-imperial order but a succession of inheritor states, each built on the ruins of what came before.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"successor-states\">Successor States</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-thunean-empire-1700-1075-be\">The Thunean Empire (1700-1075 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> establish their own empire on the foundations of the Argollean state they destroyed. The Thunean Empire inherits the administrative structures, the military traditions, and much of the theology of its predecessor -- including, critically, elements of the Cthonic tradition that created the Thune themselves. The empire endures for over six centuries before its own collapse.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-massaran-empire-1075-651-be\">The Massaran Empire (1075-651 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> succeeds the Thunean state, representing the third iteration of imperial power in the Argolle region. The Massarans build on and adapt the institutions of both preceding empires. Their collapse in 651 BE creates the conditions from which the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> will eventually emerge -- the current imperial power, which conquered Argolle in 349 IY and renamed the region&#39;s greatest city <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>The Argollean Empire&#39;s most enduring legacy is not its political institutions, which died with it, but the physical and metaphysical infrastructure it left behind:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a></strong> -- the vast subterranean complex beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, built to house the Empire&#39;s greatest figures in states of ritual readiness for <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Awakening</a>. The Nethercity remains intact. Its purpose remains unfulfilled.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Slog</a></strong> -- the products of Transmogrification, still present in the wilderness of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> millennia after the Empire that created them ceased to exist.</li>\n<li>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic tradition</a></strong> -- introduced by the Great Teacher and woven into the fabric of Argolle&#39;s deep history. The tradition persists in corrupted forms, in the Nethercity&#39;s stirring, and in the forces that destroyed <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> thirty years ago.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/mount-argolle\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mount Argolle</a></strong> -- whose upper cliffs bear the carved terraces, archways, and inscription panels of the First Empire, still legible after millennia of erosion.</li>\n<li>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a></strong> -- created as slave-soldiers, now a remnant people living among the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/mount-argolle\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mount Argolle</a>, descendants of the army that destroyed the empire that made them.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The First Empire believed its dominion was permanent. It was wrong. But what it built -- beneath the earth, in the flesh of its subjects, in the theological structures that outlived every political institution -- endures.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The founding civilization of the First Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- The subterranean complex built during the Empire&#39;s height</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-awakening</a> -- The event the Nethercity was constructed to facilitate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The theological tradition introduced by the Great Teacher</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-aurelion</a> -- The Empyrean gods the Eladra claim as their creators</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> -- The slave-soldiers created through Transmogrification</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> -- The ancient enemies of the Eladra</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> -- The Lakan, humans introduced to the Empyrean gods by the Eladra</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The enduring products of Transmogrification</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">massaran-empire</a> -- The third successor state to arise in Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mount-argolle\" class=\"wiki-link\">mount-argolle</a> -- The volcanic mountain bearing First Empire ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The city built above the Nethercity, later sacked</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- Broader historical context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/backlands-provincial-history\" class=\"wiki-link\">backlands-provincial-history</a> -- The modern provincial timeline of Argolle under the Mithrian Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The current imperial power occupying former Argollean territory</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"avari","title":"Avari","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","avari","naming","human","conquered","erenthis","backlands","argolle","crossings","ashward","sanctuary","cynar","thornasse","elder-sarnath"],"html":"<h1 id=\"avari\">Avari</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Avari</strong> are a people shaped by loss and remembrance. Once tall, fair-haired, and formerly warlike seafarers, they were conquered and subjugated by the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> through campaigns of extraordinary brutality. Their culture places great emphasis on honoring the dead, preserving the memory of those who have fallen, and maintaining identity in the face of systematic dispossession.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Avari are tall and fair-haired, with the builds of a people whose heritage lies in seafaring and warfare. Their appearance is distinctive among the peoples of the Empire -- lighter in complexion and hair color than the Mithrian norm, a visible marker of their separate cultural identity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Avari were formerly a warlike seafaring people with a proud and independent culture. Their conquest by the Empire was not a simple military defeat but a sustained campaign of subjugation that included <strong>brutal pogroms against resisters</strong>. Those who fought back were met with extreme violence, and the memory of these pogroms has left a <strong>quiet resentment</strong> that simmers beneath the surface of Avari life -- never extinguished, never openly expressed, always present.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-erenthis-and-avari-spirituality\">The Erenthis and Avari Spirituality</h3>\n<p>The Avari built their culture around <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis trees</a></strong> found in the ruins of the older <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> civilization. They did not fully understand what they were tending -- they did not possess the Eladran theological vocabulary, the cosmological framework, or the metaphysical traditions that had produced the trees in the first place. But they understood enough. They understood that the tree was sacred. They understood that it sustained them. They understood that rites performed in its presence carried weight.</p>\n<p>The Avari built their holiest traditions around the Erenthis as a <strong>living spiritual anchor</strong>. The tree was the center of community, the site of their most important ceremonies, the physical expression of everything they held sacred. The Avari do not use the vocabulary of <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> or <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> classification. They do not need to.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-burning-of-the-erenthis-at-thornasse\">The Burning of the Erenthis at Thornasse</h3>\n<p><strong>High Mage <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a></strong> burned the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at <strong>Thornasse</strong> -- an act understood by everyone as <strong>cultural execution</strong>. The Erenthis at Thornasse was not merely a tree. It was the spiritual center of the Avari Confederation, the living heart of their religious and cultural identity. Cynar did not merely destroy a symbol. He destroyed the thing itself -- the anchor around which an entire people had built their deepest understanding of the sacred.</p>\n<p>The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist collapsed within months. The Avari were defeated, assimilated, and their culture systematically marginalized. What Cynar accomplished with fire at Thornasse, no army had managed in generations of warfare. He understood what the Erenthis meant to the Avari, and he burned it precisely because he understood.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"ancestral-homelands\">Ancestral Homelands</h2>\n<p>The Avari&#39;s ancestral homelands are the <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a></strong> (Province of Argolle). This war-scarred frontier province was once Avari territory, and the ruins, place names, and cultural traces of their former dominion are still visible throughout the region.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-sacking-of-crossings-and-the-ashward\">The Sacking of Crossings and the Ashward</h2>\n<p>When <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> sacked the city of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> in 377 IY, thousands of Avari refugees fled south to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. They were given marginal land on the city&#39;s edge -- the <strong>Ashward</strong> quarter -- and left largely to their own devices.</p>\n<p>The Ashward is desperate, impoverished, and dangerous, but it is also dignified. The Avari have maintained their own community leadership, their own traditions, and their own identity. They have <strong>not assimilated</strong> into Sanctuary&#39;s Mithrian culture. They remain distinct -- their own language, customs, and governance structures intact.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elder Sarnath of the Crossings</a></strong> leads the Avari community in the Ashward. Age 71, respected, stubborn, and determined to preserve Avari identity and culture in the face of displacement and marginalization. The Ashward is policed primarily by the Avari themselves -- the City Watch rarely enters, and the <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> never.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Avari children are <strong>named after a fallen relative or hero</strong>, ensuring that the names of the honored dead continue to live in the present generation. This naming practice is both an act of remembrance and a declaration of continuity -- the dead are not gone so long as their names are carried by the living.</p>\n<p>The patronymic suffix <strong>-sson</strong> is used to denote descent (e.g., Bjornsson, meaning &quot;son of Bjorn&quot;).</p>\n<p>Many Avari have <strong>adopted Mithrian names</strong> over the centuries of Imperial rule, blending their ancestral naming traditions with those of the dominant culture. This adoption is not always willing -- it is sometimes a practical concession to a world that rewards Mithrian conformity and punishes visible difference.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-varek-ashstone\">Relationship with Varek Ashstone</h2>\n<p>The Avari communities near <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a> have coexisted with the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> hermit <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a> for generations beyond counting. They call him <strong>the Old One</strong> or simply <strong>Varek</strong> -- familiar names, not titles of awe. He is part of their landscape, as much as the lake itself. They do not worship him. They do not fear him. They respect him in the way one respects a mountain.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The sacred trees central to Avari spirituality</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The Avari ancestral homeland</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The sacked city from which Avari refugees fled</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- The city where Avari refugees now live</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">elder-sarnath</a> -- The leader of the Avari community in the Ashward</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- The Ygrathen hermit the Avari call the Old One</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a> -- The High Mage who burned the Erenthis at Thornasse</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"backlands-field-guide","title":"Backlands Field Guide","category":"lore","status":"active","tags":["survival","flora","fauna","field-guide","herbs","backlands","foraging","hazards"],"html":"<h1 id=\"backlands-field-guide\">Backlands Field Guide</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;What they don&#39;t tell you is that the Backlands teaches. It kills half the people it teaches, but the rest come out knowing things you can&#39;t learn in a garrison or a schoolroom. You learn what the birds mean. You learn what the silence means. You learn to read the ground the way a scholar reads a page. The ones who make it are the ones who paid attention.&quot; -- Hessa Vayne, <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>A comprehensive survival reference covering the flora, fauna, hazards, and fieldcraft of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>, compiled from the practical experience of woodsmen, <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalpers</a>, and frontier survivors. This guide covers four major wilderness regions: <a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Slog</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a>, <a href=\"#/page/the-heartwood\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Heartwood</a>, and the River Delta near <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-slog-flora-and-foraging\">The Slog -- Flora and Foraging</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Slog</a> is a flat, alkaline wasteland of thorn scrub and split stone. Foraging here requires knowledge and caution -- the land yields what it has, but punishes the careless.</p>\n<h3 id=\"edible-and-useful-plants\">Edible and Useful Plants</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Use</th>\n<th>Notes</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Crowsthorn / Ironweed</strong></td>\n<td>Grey-green scrub thorn, chest-height</td>\n<td>Bark mildly toxic but dry catches fire easily (excellent tinder). Boiled thorn-tips produce a weak antiseptic wash.</td>\n<td>Dominant vegetation of the Slog.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dustwort</strong></td>\n<td>Low flat-rosette plant with pale green fleshy leaves, found near old water sources</td>\n<td>Edible raw but bitter.</td>\n<td><strong>BEWARE:</strong> Saltweed closely resembles dustwort but has a waxy sheen on its leaves. Saltweed causes heavy vomiting within 1 hour of consumption.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Goldenrod</strong></td>\n<td>Found in sheltered gullies; dense yellow flower heads in late summer</td>\n<td>Dried goldenrod grants <strong>+2 on proficiency throws to cure disease</strong> (requires Healing proficiency).</td>\n<td>Seasonal -- late summer only.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Horsetail / Snake Grass</strong></td>\n<td>Segmented reed-like plant found near water</td>\n<td>Applied as a poultice: <strong>+2 on Mortal Wounds table rolls</strong>.</td>\n<td>Both goldenrod and horsetail are forageable on <strong>Survival 7+</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"water-sources\">Water Sources</h3>\n<p>Finding water in the Slog is a survival skill in itself:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Old wells</strong> with Imperial stone markers are scattered across the Slog. These date to the Argollean period when the land was farmed. Some still hold water.</li>\n<li><strong>Dry gulch bends</strong>: Dig approximately 2 feet into the bend of a dry gulch to find subsurface water.</li>\n<li><strong>Survival throws to locate water</strong>: <strong>14+</strong> in summer, <strong>10+</strong> in other seasons. Summer is brutal and water is scarce.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"argollean-tombs\">Argollean Tombs</h3>\n<p>Scattered across the Slog are mound graves marked with angular <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> script on stone markers. The undead population in these tombs predates the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> presence by centuries -- these dead are old.</p>\n<p><strong>Identifying a tomb</strong>: A low, grass-covered rise with even sides and a depression at its crown. The geometric regularity distinguishes a tomb from a natural feature.</p>\n<p><strong>Warning</strong>: Give tombs respectful distance at night. The dead walk in the Slog, and many of them emerge from these ancient burial sites.</p>\n<h3 id=\"lakandi-sign\">Lakandi Sign</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> who range through the Slog leave distinctive fieldcraft markers. Learning to read them is a survival advantage:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fire sign</strong>: Small, efficient fires on a tripod arrangement (not the sprawling campfires of Imperial soldiers or Scalpers)</li>\n<li><strong>Bone markers</strong>: Scraped bone left at campsites or along trails</li>\n<li><strong>Knot-patterns</strong>: Specific knot-patterns in cordage -- these carry meaning, though the full system is not widely understood outside Lakandi culture</li>\n<li><strong>Stone stacks at water sources</strong>: Small stone stacks placed at water sources indicate the water is <strong>clean and safe to drink</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"weather-and-seasons\">Weather and Seasons</h3>\n<p>The Slog&#39;s weather is as much a hazard as its inhabitants:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Season</th>\n<th>Conditions</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Summer</strong></td>\n<td>Brutal heat. Move at dawn and dusk only. Daytime travel risks heat exhaustion. Water is scarce (Survival 14+ to locate).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lightning Season</strong></td>\n<td>Violent electrical storms. Get low -- the flat terrain makes anything upright a lightning target.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Spring</strong></td>\n<td>Flooding. Dry gulches become rushing channels without warning. A gulch that was bone-dry at dawn can be a torrent by afternoon. Camp on high ground.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Winter</strong></td>\n<td>The easiest season for travel. Cold but manageable. Reduced insect activity. Water more accessible.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"tracking-beastmen\">Tracking Beastmen</h3>\n<p>Reading <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> sign in the Slog:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Broken crowsthorn at chest-height</strong>: Standard beastman patrol. They push through the scrub without attempting concealment.</li>\n<li><strong>Crowsthorn bent at 4 feet or below</strong>: A scout or rearguard moving carefully, deliberately keeping a low profile. More dangerous -- this is a beastman that knows it is being hunted, or is hunting you.</li>\n<li><strong>30-foot-wide flattened lanes through the scrub</strong>: Hill giant. Nothing else leaves a track like that.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-wild-hunt\">The Wild Hunt</h3>\n<p>On certain nights -- specifically when the eight-starred Wolf constellation climbs high -- something else moves through the Slog.</p>\n<p>Riders on the horizon that move too fast and too silently, trailing mist behind them. The dead found in their wake <strong>cannot be raised by clerics</strong>. The bodies are intact but the souls are simply gone.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalpers</a> call it the <strong>Wild Hunt</strong>. They do not discuss it with newcomers. Experienced Scalpers who have survived encounters refuse to describe what they saw in detail. The Wild Hunt is not a beastman warband or a natural phenomenon. It is something else entirely, and the Slog&#39;s veterans treat it with a fear they do not extend to trolls, wights, or beastman war-chiefs.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-gallowswood-flora-and-fauna\">The Gallowswood -- Flora and Fauna</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;There is a quality of silence in the Gallowswood. A specific silence, like the forest holding its breath. When that silence comes, something is watching. Something is waiting.&quot; -- Unnamed woodsman</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a> is not merely old in tree terms. It is old in the way places remember things. The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> knew it as sacred and dangerous before the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolleans</a> arrived. Avari warnings are still carved on stones at its border -- and the Avari do not waste effort on warnings they do not mean.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-forest\">The Forest</h3>\n<p>The canopy is thick enough to turn noon into dusk. The light that reaches the forest floor is green and uncertain. The dominant trees are ancient oaks, grey ash, and black-barked hawthorn. The undergrowth is dense, tangled, and disorienting.</p>\n<h3 id=\"flora\">Flora</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Use</th>\n<th>Notes</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Black Hawthorn</strong></td>\n<td>Dark bark, pale flowers in spring, red berries in fall</td>\n<td>Berries are edible but bitter.</td>\n<td>One of the Gallowswood&#39;s defining trees.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Belladonna</strong></td>\n<td>Found near old Argollean burial mounds; purple berries</td>\n<td><strong>Poison.</strong> Do not consume. However, belladonna serves as a marker -- where belladonna clusters, an <span class=\"dead-link\">eladra</td>\n<td>Argollean</span> burial mound is nearby.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gravemoss</strong></td>\n<td>Grey-green lichen found on ash trees</td>\n<td>Scraped and dried, gravemoss serves as wound-packing material for field dressing injuries.</td>\n<td>Abundant in the deep wood.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Wolfsbane</strong></td>\n<td>Tall plant with dark hooded purple-blue flowers</td>\n<td>A dried sprig presented to a lycanthrope forces a <strong>Death save or flee</strong>. If consumed within 1 hour of a lycanthropic bite: <strong>Death save -- success shakes off the lycanthropy entirely; failure = death.</strong></td>\n<td>The cure is as dangerous as the disease. Wolfsbane is the only known field treatment for lycanthropy.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Woundwort / Heal-All</strong></td>\n<td>Small pale purple flowers</td>\n<td><strong>+2 on proficiency throws to cure injury.</strong></td>\n<td>Common enough to be reliable if you know what to look for.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Bracket Fungus</strong></td>\n<td>Shelf fungus on deadfall</td>\n<td>Edible if boiled. Bitter but nutritious.</td>\n<td>Emergency food source.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"fauna-and-hazards\">Fauna and Hazards</h3>\n<p><strong>No foxes</strong> inhabit the deep Gallowswood. No one has satisfactorily explained why. Every other forest in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> has foxes. The Gallowswood does not. The absence is information -- what killed the foxes, or what keeps them out, is unknown.</p>\n<p><strong>Deer</strong> are present but extremely skittish. If deer are running, do <strong>not</strong> pause to assess what they are fleeing from. Run with them. Whatever flushed the deer is worse than the deer think you are.</p>\n<h3 id=\"crab-spiders\">Crab Spiders</h3>\n<p>Dog-sized ambush predators that match the texture of bark. They position themselves at chest-height on tree trunks and wait motionless for prey to pass within striking distance.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Venom</strong>: Paralytic. A bitten victim is immobilized while the spider feeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Surprise</strong>: Check at <strong>-2 for surprise</strong> when entering areas of dense tree cover. The <strong>Alertness</strong> proficiency negates this penalty.</li>\n<li>Crab spiders are solitary hunters. They do not swarm. But a single spider is enough to kill an armored man if it achieves surprise.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-dome\">The Dome</h3>\n<p>A massive clearing approximately half a day&#39;s travel into the deep wood. Before the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> horde was broken at the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a>, beastman tribes congregated here around an artifact of unknown origin and nature. The beastmen are gone now.</p>\n<p><strong>Something remains.</strong></p>\n<p>Creatures wander out of the Dome&#39;s vicinity -- things the woodsmen call <strong>abominations</strong>. They are described as loose bags of shifting flesh, their surfaces constantly growing and absorbing mouths, eyes, and tentacles in a nauseating cycle of formation and dissolution.</p>\n<p><strong>Abomination Combat Statistics:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Speed</strong>: Fast. Faster than they look, which is already unsettling.</li>\n<li><strong>Attacks</strong>: <strong>Three attacks per round</strong> (the shifting flesh generates multiple appendages simultaneously).</li>\n<li><strong>Venom</strong>: Paralytic toxin. On a failed save, the victim is paralyzed for <strong>1d3 turns</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Immunities</strong>: <strong>Immune to sleep, charm, and hold</strong> effects. Whatever intelligence drives them is not a mind that can be influenced by such magic.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The relationship between the Dome, the abominations, and the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood#the-black-heart\" class=\"wiki-link\">pulsating black heart</a> beneath the granite dome described in session accounts is unclear but almost certainly connected.</p>\n<h3 id=\"navigation\">Navigation</h3>\n<p>Navigation in the Gallowswood is treacherous:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Moss grows on ALL sides of trees.</strong> The thick canopy diffuses light so completely that the standard &quot;moss grows on the north side&quot; rule is useless.</li>\n<li><strong>Compass unreliable.</strong> Something in the forest interferes with magnetic navigation. Whether this is a natural mineral deposit or something else is unknown.</li>\n<li><strong>Follow water downhill.</strong> This is the most reliable method of finding your way out. Streams flow downhill and eventually leave the forest.</li>\n<li><strong>Old Avari path markers</strong> exist -- carved stones and wooden poles placed centuries ago. Some sequences of markers are intact and navigable. However, <strong>some marker sequences were not intended for outsiders</strong> and may lead to places the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> considered sacred, dangerous, or both.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"avari-warning-stones\">Avari Warning Stones</h3>\n<p>Carved stones at the Gallowswood&#39;s borders bear <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> warnings. These predate the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> arrival in the region. The Avari did not carve warnings lightly -- their tradition is oral, and committing a warning to stone indicates something they considered important enough to outlast their own memory. The warnings have not been fully translated, but their intent is clear: do not enter.</p>\n<h3 id=\"burial-mounds\">Burial Mounds</h3>\n<p>Old <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> burial mounds are scattered through the Gallowswood. They are identifiable by the clustering of belladonna around their bases. The mounds predate the forest&#39;s current cursed state -- the dead were buried here during the Argollean period, and whatever happened to the Gallowswood afterward was not kind to them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-heartwood-flora-and-survival\">The Heartwood -- Flora and Survival</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The Heartwood is old. It doesn&#39;t know you&#39;re there. You could die in it and the forest wouldn&#39;t notice.&quot; -- Rika Sorn, woodsman</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/the-heartwood\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Heartwood</a> is the oldest forest in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> and possibly the oldest forest anyone has mapped -- though no survey has ever been completed. The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire</a> sent survey parties in. Some came back. None agreed on what they saw or where they had been.</p>\n<p>The Heartwood is not hostile in the way the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a> is hostile. The Gallowswood is aware of you. The Heartwood simply does not care. You can disappear in the Heartwood without doing anything wrong.</p>\n<h3 id=\"flora\">Flora</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Use</th>\n<th>Notes</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Hazelnuts</strong></td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood, seasonal</td>\n<td>Edible. Reliable food source in autumn.</td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood only.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Beech Mast</strong></td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood, seasonal</td>\n<td>Edible. Small triangular nuts from beech trees.</td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood only.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Wild Garlic</strong></td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood, spring</td>\n<td>Edible. Recognizable by smell.</td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood only.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Blackberries</strong></td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood, late summer</td>\n<td>Edible. Abundant in clearings and edges.</td>\n<td>Outer Heartwood only.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Comfrey / Bruisewort</strong></td>\n<td>Found near streams throughout the Heartwood</td>\n<td>Applied as a poultice: <strong>heals 1d3 damage, once per day per patient.</strong></td>\n<td>The most reliable healing herb in the Backlands.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Blessed Thistle</strong></td>\n<td>Middle and deep Heartwood</td>\n<td><strong>Doubles hit points recovered from rest.</strong></td>\n<td>Rare and valuable. Worth gathering when found.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dreamgrass</strong></td>\n<td>Pale-leaved sedge found around old beech roots</td>\n<td>Sedative. <strong>Useful in small doses</strong> (calms panic, aids sleep). <strong>Dangerous in large doses</strong> (deep unconsciousness, respiratory depression).</td>\n<td>Dosage is critical.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Insect-Repellent Vine</strong></td>\n<td>Found on older oaks, middle and deep Heartwood</td>\n<td>Crushed and applied to skin, repels biting insects.</td>\n<td>Practical value in a forest where insects are relentless.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"fauna\">Fauna</h3>\n<p><strong>Owlbeasts</strong> inhabit the middle Heartwood. They are territorial and hunt by both sound and smell -- covering one sense does not protect against the other.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Territory markers</strong>: Deep claw marks scored into tree trunks. If you see these marks, you are in an owlbeast&#39;s territory. Move through quickly and quietly.</li>\n<li>Owlbeasts are ambush predators. They are large, fast, and aggressive when defending territory or hunting.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-deep-heartwood\">The Deep Heartwood</h3>\n<p>The deep Heartwood contains things that woodsmen do not describe with precision. Not because they are being dramatic, but because precision fails them:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tracks</strong> that do not match any known animal</li>\n<li><strong>A sense of being assessed</strong> -- not hunted, not threatened, but evaluated by something that has not yet decided what you are</li>\n<li>The silence in the deep Heartwood is not the Gallowswood&#39;s loaded, watchful silence. It is absolute -- the silence of a world that existed before human sound and expects to exist after it.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"navigation\">Navigation</h3>\n<p>The Heartwood <strong>will</strong> get you lost. This is not a matter of skill -- it is a property of the place.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Zone</th>\n<th>Navigation Throw</th>\n<th>Notes</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Outer Heartwood</strong></td>\n<td>Standard</td>\n<td>Dense but navigable with normal skill.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Middle Heartwood</strong></td>\n<td><strong>14+ per half-day</strong></td>\n<td>Trees grow older and larger. The understory thins. Landmarks become unreliable.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Deep Heartwood</strong></td>\n<td><strong>17+ per half-day</strong></td>\n<td>Trees enormous beyond reckoning. No reliable landmarks. Absolute silence.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p><strong>Following streams out always works.</strong> Every stream in the Heartwood flows to the outer forest eventually. It takes twice as long as direct navigation, but it is reliable.</p>\n<p><strong>Critical warning</strong>: &quot;If you think you are on a path in the deep Heartwood, you are not.&quot; There are no paths in the deep Heartwood. Anything that looks like a path was not made by human feet and does not lead where a human would want to go.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-river-delta-flora-and-survival\">The River Delta -- Flora and Survival</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Everything in the delta wants to eat you or breed in your ears.&quot; -- <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aldric Voss</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The river delta near <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> is a tidal wetland of reed beds taller than a man, channels that split and rejoin unpredictably, and an ecosystem that is indifferent to human survival.</p>\n<h3 id=\"flora\">Flora</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Use</th>\n<th>Notes</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Common Reed</strong></td>\n<td>Dominant vegetation, taller than a man</td>\n<td>Not edible raw, but practical: excellent thatch and tinder. Young shoots are edible if boiled in spring.</td>\n<td>The delta is defined by its reed beds.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Watercress</strong></td>\n<td>Found in clearly fresh water channels</td>\n<td>Edible raw. Nutritious.</td>\n<td><strong>Only harvest from clearly fresh water.</strong> Brackish or tidal watercress may carry parasites.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Marsh Samphire / Glasswort</strong></td>\n<td>Small pale-green succulent on tidal flats</td>\n<td>Edible. Tastes of salt.</td>\n<td>A reliable food source on the tidal flats.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sea Lavender</strong></td>\n<td>Purple flowers marking the tidal boundary</td>\n<td><strong>Not edible.</strong> Functions as a warning marker -- sea lavender marks where the tide reaches. Camp above it.</td>\n<td>Not decoration. Information.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lungwort</strong></td>\n<td>Spotted leaves, purple-pink flowers</td>\n<td>A tincture of lungwort relieves lung complaints. Specifically: <strong>temporarily relieves permanent wound penalties for 4 hours.</strong></td>\n<td>Valuable for characters carrying respiratory damage from combat or disease.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Bitterwood</strong></td>\n<td>Bark and inner wood</td>\n<td>Field treatment for poisoning. Induces vomiting. <strong>Death save: success neutralizes the poison; failure = purging with no benefit</strong> (the poison remains).</td>\n<td>Desperate measure, but better than no treatment.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"reading-the-birds\">Reading the Birds</h3>\n<p>The delta is always full of birds. Once you learn to read them, they constitute the best information system available:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Herons flushing without resettling</strong>: A genuine disturbance. Something moved through the reed bed that herons do not tolerate -- a predator, a beastman patrol, or something larger.</li>\n<li><strong>Multiple marsh harriers going up at once</strong>: Something <strong>large</strong> is moving through the reed beds. Marsh harriers are apex predators in the delta; they do not flush easily. If several go up simultaneously, whatever disturbed them is bigger than a harrier is willing to confront.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"hazards\">Hazards</h3>\n<p><strong>Crocodilians</strong>: Ambush predators that resemble floating wood. Most active at dawn and dusk. They are patient, fast over short distances, and capable of dragging an armored man underwater.</p>\n<p><strong>Insect-Borne Fever</strong>: Unprotected sleep in summer requires a <strong>Constitution check at 9+</strong> or the sleeper loses <strong>1d3 hit points</strong> to insect-borne fever. Protective measures (netting, the insect-repellent vine from the Heartwood, smudge fires) reduce or eliminate this risk.</p>\n<p><strong>Tidal Channels</strong>: The delta&#39;s channels are treacherous:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Probe with a staff</strong> before stepping. The mud can swallow a man.</li>\n<li><strong>Know the tide schedule.</strong> A passable channel at low tide becomes a drowning hazard at high tide.</li>\n<li><strong>Acoustic distortion</strong>: The reed beds create acoustic distortion. Sounds bounce, echo, and mislead. A voice that seems to come from the left may originate from the right. Navigation by sound is unreliable.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cross-regional-notes\">Cross-Regional Notes</h2>\n<h3 id=\"herb-summary-table\">Herb Summary Table</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Herb</th>\n<th>Region</th>\n<th>Mechanical Benefit</th>\n<th>Foraging Difficulty</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>Goldenrod</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the-slog</td>\n<td>Slog</span></td>\n<td>+2 proficiency throw to cure disease</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Horsetail</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the-slog</td>\n<td>Slog</span></td>\n<td>+2 Mortal Wounds table</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Wolfsbane</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">gallowswood</td>\n<td>Gallowswood</span></td>\n<td>Lycanthrope: Death save or flee (presented) / cure or death (consumed within 1hr of bite)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Woundwort</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">gallowswood</td>\n<td>Gallowswood</span></td>\n<td>+2 proficiency throw to cure injury</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Comfrey</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the-heartwood</td>\n<td>Heartwood</span></td>\n<td>Heals 1d3 damage as poultice (1/day)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Blessed Thistle</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the-heartwood</td>\n<td>Heartwood</span></td>\n<td>Doubles HP from rest</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Lungwort</td>\n<td>River Delta</td>\n<td>Relieves permanent wound penalty for 4 hours</td>\n<td>Uncommon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bitterwood</td>\n<td>River Delta</td>\n<td>Death save to neutralize poison</td>\n<td>Common</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"poisondanger-plants\">Poison/Danger Plants</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Plant</th>\n<th>Region</th>\n<th>Effect</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>Saltweed</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the-slog</td>\n<td>Slog</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Belladonna</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">gallowswood</td>\n<td>Gallowswood</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dreamgrass</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the-heartwood</td>\n<td>Heartwood</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-slog\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-slog</a> -- Primary hunting ground, alkaline wasteland</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> -- Cursed forest, dead walk beneath the roots</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-heartwood\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-heartwood</a> -- Oldest forest in the Backlands, uncharted depths</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> -- River delta settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The gangs whose survival depends on this knowledge</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The primary threat tracked across these regions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> -- Ancient people whose warnings mark the Gallowswood borders</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The Argollean civilization whose tombs dot the Slog</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> -- Wasteland warriors whose sign can be read in the Slog</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"backlands-provincial-history","title":"Backlands Provincial History","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["backlands","argolle","timeline","provincial-history","avari","lakandi","sanctuary","crossings","frontier-war","sacking"],"html":"<h1 id=\"backlands-provincial-history\">Backlands Provincial History</h1>\n<p>A granular provincial timeline of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> from 283 IY to 380 IY, covering the region&#39;s transformation from independent <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> territory to contested imperial frontier. This supplements the broader <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a> with local events, administrative decisions, and the lived consequences of empire at its furthest edge.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"before-the-empire-pre-349-iy\">Before the Empire (Pre-349 IY)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"c-283-iy-sanctuary-established\">c. 283 IY -- Sanctuary Established</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire</a> licenses a fortified trading post at the mouth of the Argoll River under treaty with the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a>. The post -- later known as <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- functions as a waystation and customs point. Primary trade goods include furs, salt, and river amber. The arrangement is commercial, not territorial; the Confederation retains sovereignty over the interior. The Empire gains a foothold.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-283-340-iy-the-long-accommodation\">c. 283-340 IY -- The Long Accommodation</h3>\n<p>An informal boundary centered on the Argoll River governs relations between the Empire and the Avari Confederation for nearly six decades. <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> grows steadily during this period, expanding from trading post to permanent settlement. Imperial cartographers survey the interior under the guise of trade expeditions -- mapping terrain, river systems, and resource deposits that have no relevance to commerce but considerable relevance to future military operations.</p>\n<p>Periodic border skirmishes occur but are settled through compensation rather than escalation. The Confederation&#39;s internal disputes -- particularly between the river clans (who benefit from trade with the Empire) and the highland clans (who do not) -- are noted in imperial records with what later historians describe as &quot;evident interest.&quot; The Empire does not cause this division, but it recognizes the opportunity it represents.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-338-iy-hartwells-crossing-vol-kessar-the-silencing\">c. 338 IY -- Hartwell&#39;s Crossing (vol-Kessar / &quot;the Silencing&quot;)</h3>\n<p>Tribune Aldric Hartwell leads an unauthorized surveying column into Avari territory. At a ford on an upper tributary of the Issavar River, the column encounters Avari clans. Imperial records describe the incident as &quot;armed resistance to a lawful survey party.&quot; Avari oral tradition calls it <strong>vol-Kessar</strong> -- the Silencing -- a name that suggests something more violent and more deliberate than a skirmish over boundary markers.</p>\n<p>Hartwell is recalled and reassigned. Compensation is paid to the affected clans. No criminal proceedings are brought against Hartwell or any member of his column. The highland clans -- whose territory was surveyed, whose people were silenced -- regard the compensation as insufficient and the lack of punishment as confirmation that the Empire does not consider Avari sovereignty binding.</p>\n<h3 id=\"338-349-iy-failure-of-the-border-councils\">338-349 IY -- Failure of the Border Councils</h3>\n<p>Three separate Avari delegations travel to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> seeking formal censure of Tribune Hartwell and revision of the border treaty. Each delegation is received. Each is deliberated upon. Each is dismissed without binding outcome. The mechanisms of imperial diplomacy function precisely as designed: they absorb grievance without producing change.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>344 IY</strong>: The highland clans withdraw from the border council, declaring the process a performance without substance.</li>\n<li><strong>347 IY</strong>: Diplomatic contact between the Avari Confederation and the Empire ceases entirely. The river clans lack the authority or the will to speak for the highlands, and the highlands no longer recognize any reason to speak to the Empire at all.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The eleven years between Hartwell&#39;s Crossing and the conquest are a period of diplomatic silence in which both sides understand what is coming. The Confederation fractures further. The Empire surveys the routes its legions will use.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"conquest-and-consolidation-349-365-iy\">Conquest and Consolidation (349-365 IY)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"349-iy-conquest-of-argolle\">349 IY -- Conquest of Argolle</h3>\n<p>Imperial legions cross the Argoll River in force. The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a>, weakened by decades of internal division between river and highland factions, cannot mount a unified defense. <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a> -- the seat of Avari governance -- falls. <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> burns the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> tree at the city that was Erenthis. The city is renamed <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. The Avari Confederation ceases to exist as a political entity.</p>\n<p>The conquest is swift. The Confederation&#39;s fracture along the lines the Empire had observed for decades -- river clans versus highland clans, trade interests versus territorial sovereignty -- ensures that no coordinated resistance materializes. What follows is not a war but a collapse.</p>\n<h3 id=\"350-360-iy-pacification-period\">350-360 IY -- Pacification Period</h3>\n<p>Imperial administration is established at <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, which becomes the provincial capital. Irregular suppression of highland resistance continues throughout this period, though the campaigns are not formally documented as military operations. Communities beyond the river valleys are largely undisturbed -- not from mercy but from irrelevance. The Empire governs where it profits; the rest can wait.</p>\n<p>Road construction begins, connecting Sanctuary to the newly renamed Crossings. The roads serve the dual purpose of commerce and force projection -- they enable trade, but they also enable legions to move quickly through terrain that previously required weeks of travel.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-353-iy-argollean-land-grants\">c. 353 IY -- Argollean Land Grants</h3>\n<p>Retiring legionaries and minor imperial families receive land grants throughout the conquered territory. The grants are generous. The maps on which they are based are not.</p>\n<p>Imperial surveyors have drawn property boundaries without accounting for Avari migration routes, seasonal hunting grounds, or <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> territorial ranges. The grants create a patchwork of imperial claims overlaid on a landscape that is already occupied by peoples the Empire has chosen not to see. The <strong>Red River Consortium</strong> receives a mining and transport charter covering the northern tributaries -- a commercial concession that will prove significant in the decades to come.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-355-365-iy-the-quiet-decade\">c. 355-365 IY -- The Quiet Decade</h3>\n<p>A period of relative stability during which the physical infrastructure of imperial control is established:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a></strong> and <strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a></strong> are constructed, establishing a defensive line beyond which settlement is theoretically discouraged.</li>\n<li>The road between <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> is completed.</li>\n<li>Census data shows steady population growth along river routes.</li>\n<li>Market towns develop, including <strong><a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a></strong> and <strong><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a></strong>, serving as commercial hubs for the surrounding agricultural settlements.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Quiet Decade earns its name from what it lacks: significant military engagement. The highland resistance has been suppressed or scattered. The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> beyond the fort line have not yet been provoked in sufficient numbers. The Empire&#39;s administrators write optimistic reports about provincial development. They are correct about the growth. They are wrong about its security.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-frontier-war-362-370-iy\">The Frontier War (362-370 IY)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"c-362-iy-first-lakandi-contacts\">c. 362 IY -- First Lakandi Contacts</h3>\n<p>Settlers who have pushed past the fort line -- lured by land grants and the promise of unclaimed territory -- begin reporting hostile contact with unknown forces. Provincial administration classifies these reports as &quot;opportunistic incursion by irregular <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Slog</a> elements.&quot; This classification is convenient. It frames the contact as criminal rather than military, avoiding the administrative burden of requesting legionary reinforcement. It is also wrong.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-364-iy-the-millhaven-burning\">c. 364 IY -- The Millhaven Burning</h3>\n<p>A settler cluster of approximately fifty families is destroyed overnight. There are no survivors. The investigation notes &quot;organization uncharacteristic of prior Slog contacts&quot; -- coordinated assault, multiple approach vectors, systematic elimination of escape routes. This is not banditry. This is warfare conducted by an enemy the provincial administration has refused to acknowledge.</p>\n<p>A formal request for legionary reinforcement is submitted to the imperial capital. The request is denied. The province is expected to manage its own frontier problems.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-365-368-iy-reprisal-raids-and-settler-militias\">c. 365-368 IY -- Reprisal Raids and Settler Militias</h3>\n<p>In the absence of imperial military support, informal militias organize among the frontier settlements. These militias conduct reprisal operations into the territory beyond the fort line without official sanction. Several actions target non-combatant encampments -- camps of women, children, and elderly who bear no direct connection to the attacks on settler homesteads.</p>\n<p>The provincial administration neither endorses nor censures these operations. The militias serve a function the Empire will not pay for, and the administration prefers ambiguity to accountability. The reprisals escalate the conflict without resolving it. The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> respond in kind.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-368-iy-the-dunwick-compact\">c. 368 IY -- The Dunwick Compact</h3>\n<p>The growing instability of the frontier forces a restructuring of local governance. <strong><a href=\"#/page/great-houses#house-thane\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Thane</a></strong> and <strong><a href=\"#/page/great-houses#house-cael\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Cael</a></strong> are formally recognized as civic authorities in <a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a>. Similar arrangements are established in <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> and other settlements. The terms are straightforward: local judicial authority and tax collection in exchange for maintaining order.</p>\n<p>The Compact acknowledges what the provincial administration cannot say publicly -- that imperial governance has failed to reach the frontier, and that local power has filled the vacuum. The Great Houses gain legitimacy. The Empire gains the appearance of control. Neither gains security.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-370-iy-retreat-of-the-farsteads\">c. 370 IY -- Retreat of the Farsteads</h3>\n<p>Coordinated <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> strikes force the abandonment of settlements beyond the fort line in a single season. The speed and simultaneity of the attacks exceed all prior Lakandi activity by a significant margin. This is not raiding. This is a territorial offensive executed with discipline and strategic coordination.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a></strong> -- already marginal -- loses most of its population. The fort line becomes not a forward position but a final one.</p>\n<h3 id=\"370-374-iy-the-hollow-years\">370-374 IY -- The Hollow Years</h3>\n<p>The northern interior of the province is functionally abandoned. Settlements beyond the fort line are empty or destroyed. <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> endures as a waystation -- a place people pass through on their way to somewhere safer, sustained by those too stubborn or too poor to leave.</p>\n<p>The provincial administration does not acknowledge the loss of territory. The maps in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> still show settlements that no longer exist, roads that are no longer safe, and a frontier that has contracted by dozens of miles. The Hollow Years are a period of administrative fiction, in which the gap between what the Empire claims and what the Empire controls grows wider with each passing season.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-sacking-and-aftermath-374-380-iy\">The Sacking and Aftermath (374-380 IY)</h2>\n<h3 id=\"374-iy-sacking-of-crossings\">374 IY -- Sacking of Crossings</h3>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><strong>Note:</strong> The backlands_timeline.docx dates the Sacking to 374 IY. The Backlands Primer dates it to 377 IY. This discrepancy has not been resolved. Both dates appear in source material. See <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> for full details.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> is attacked in a coordinated assault involving multiple approach routes and a disciplined withdrawal. This is not a raid. The attackers demonstrate strategic planning -- simultaneous pressure on multiple defensive positions, exploitation of known weaknesses in the city&#39;s fortifications, and organized retreat before reinforcement can arrive.</p>\n<p>A relief column fails to arrive. <strong>Senator Cassius</strong> raises questions in the imperial capital about the failure of the provincial garrison to receive reinforcement. The questions are noted. They are not answered.</p>\n<h3 id=\"374-iy-imperial-bounty-declared\">374 IY -- Imperial Bounty Declared</h3>\n<p>In the aftermath of the Sacking, the Empire declares an <strong>Imperial Bounty</strong>: one mark per <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> scalp. The bounty transforms the conflict from a military problem into a commercial opportunity. It attracts a particular kind of settler -- not farmers seeking land but hunters seeking profit.</p>\n<h3 id=\"374-378-iy-the-scalper-years\">374-378 IY -- The Scalper Years</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> grows rapidly, fueled by the Bounty. The town becomes the primary staging point for scalp-hunting expeditions into the northern interior. The <strong>Red River Consortium</strong> -- already holding mining and transport charters from the Argollean Land Grants -- gains the legal right to administer the Bounty, processing scalps, verifying kills, and distributing payment. The Consortium&#39;s commercial reach extends deep into what was recently abandoned territory.</p>\n<p>The Scalper Years create a brutal economy. The Bounty does not distinguish between combatants and non-combatants, between <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> warriors and Lakandi civilians. The scalp-hunters do not make these distinctions either. The violence is profitable, indiscriminate, and officially sanctioned.</p>\n<h3 id=\"c-375-380-iy-post-sacking-migration\">c. 375-380 IY -- Post-Sacking Migration</h3>\n<p>Refugees from the Sacking redistribute throughout the province. The destruction of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> displaces a significant population, and the survivors scatter to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, <a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a>, and smaller settlements. Settlers holding suspended land grants -- claims to territory that is now functionally part of the hostile frontier -- create contention wherever they arrive, demanding recognition of titles to land they cannot occupy.</p>\n<h3 id=\"380-iy-present-day\">380 IY -- Present Day</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> in 380 IY are a province defined by contraction, improvisation, and unresolved violence. The official map and the actual territory diverge sharply. The <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a> govern where the Empire cannot. The Bounty economy sustains <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> but poisons everything it touches. The <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> was burned thirty years ago, and the consequences of that act are still unfolding.</p>\n<p>Recent reports from <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> note <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> attacks of coordination and scale not seen since the Sacking. Whether this represents a resurgence of the forces that destroyed Crossings, or something new entirely, remains to be determined.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- Overview of the province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- Broader imperial timeline</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> -- The Avari Confederation displaced by conquest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> -- The indigenous people beyond the fort line</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">sacking-of-crossings</a> -- The destruction of the provincial capital</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- The imperial trading post turned provincial capital</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The former Erenthis, renamed and later sacked</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">dunwick</a> -- Market town and seat of House Thane / House Cael</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a> -- Market town in the eastern foothills</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- Frontier waystation and center of the Bounty economy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- Western anchor of the fort line</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-harvald</a> -- Eastern anchor of the fort line</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">great-houses</a> -- The local power structures that filled the imperial vacuum</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The forces behind the frontier violence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The tree burned by Cynar during the conquest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-empire</a> -- The First Empire that preceded all of this</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"battle-of-blue-mound","title":"The Battle of Blue Mound","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["event","history","battle","sorcery","lakan-campaigns","lakandi","imperial-academy","mutual-annihilation"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-battle-of-blue-mound\">The Battle of Blue Mound</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Battle of Blue Mound</strong> was the catastrophic culmination of the <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a> (360-368 IY). It pitted Imperial forces led by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> against the army of <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a> of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a>. The climax of the battle -- a direct sorcerous duel between the two most powerful magic users on the field -- escalated beyond all control, unleashing cataclysmic energies that annihilated <strong>both armies entirely</strong>. Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived. The battlefield was left a blasted and lifeless wasteland.</p>\n<p>The Battle of Blue Mound stands as the most devastating demonstration of sorcerous power in recent Imperial history and fundamentally reshaped the Empire&#39;s approach to warfare.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-battle\">The Battle</h2>\n<p>Imperial armies had marched deep into <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> territory during the <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a>, backed by the devastating magical firepower of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>. The Lakandi, led by <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a>, assembled a formidable army to resist the invasion. The two forces met at Blue Mound.</p>\n<p>The battle proceeded along conventional lines until <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> and <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Jarn Murky-Eye</a> engaged in direct sorcerous combat. What began as a duel between two powerful practitioners escalated into something far worse. The energies unleashed -- Cynar&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> colliding with Jarn&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil-born sorcery</a> -- spiraled beyond the capacity of either combatant to control. The resulting cataclysm consumed everything: both armies, both sorcerers, and the landscape itself.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"consequences\">Consequences</h2>\n<h3 id=\"military-doctrine\">Military Doctrine</h3>\n<p>The Battle of Blue Mound prompted the most significant reform in Imperial military doctrine since the founding of the Empire. It demonstrated conclusively that deploying high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was not merely dangerous but potentially suicidal -- a strategy that could destroy the user&#39;s own forces as completely as the enemy&#39;s.</p>\n<p>In response, the Empire adopted a model of <strong>combined arms warfare</strong>, integrating squad mages into conventional military formations rather than relying on individual sorcerers to decide the outcome of battles. This doctrinal shift reduced the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s singular importance in warfare, a change that the Academy has never fully accepted.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-frontier\">The Frontier</h3>\n<p>The Empire retreated from Lakandi territory and erected a line of <strong>border forts</strong> that marks the current frontier. The Empire abandoned its ambitions of conquest in the region, adopting a purely defensive posture.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-lakandi\">The Lakandi</h3>\n<p>The Lakandi were broken by the campaigns but remained <strong>unbowed</strong>. The destruction of their army at Blue Mound was devastating, but the simultaneous destruction of the Imperial army gave them a claim to something resembling victory. The Lakandi vowed revenge against the Empire, and the border forts that line the frontier stand as testimony to the fact that the Empire takes that vow seriously.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"significance\">Significance</h2>\n<p>The Battle of Blue Mound demonstrates the devastating and uncontrollable power of sorcery when wielded at its highest levels. It is cited by military theorists, Academy scholars, and political commentators as proof that magical power, no matter how great, cannot be deployed without risk of catastrophic consequences. The battle has become a cautionary tale -- a reminder that the forces sorcerers command are not tools but living energies with their own dynamics, capable of consuming their wielders as readily as their targets.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> -- Imperial sorcerer who died in the duel</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a> -- Lakandi sorcerer who died in the duel</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Lakan Campaigns</a> -- the broader military campaign</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a> -- institution whose doctrine was reshaped</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi Binding Tradition</a> -- the sorcerous tradition Jarn embodied</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a> -- the forces unleashed at Blue Mound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Military</a> -- the armed forces that lost an entire army</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"beastmen","title":"Beastmen","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["race","beastmen","massaran-empire","massar","monstrous","sacking-of-crossings","scalper","bounty","mutated","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"beastmen\">Beastmen</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Beastmen</strong> are a collection of species of monstrous humans -- not a single race but a diverse array of twisted, mutated beings united only by their shared origin and their universal reputation for savagery. They were created by the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> as the core of its armies, purpose-bred for war through sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding. After the defeat of the Massaran Empire, the Beastmen were scattered, left without purpose or direction, and they have since devolved into one of the most feared threats in <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The appearances of Beastmen <strong>differ wildly</strong> from one individual to the next, but <strong>all carry a twisted and mutated animal aspect</strong> -- horns, fangs, claws, fur, scales, or other bestial features grafted onto a roughly humanoid frame. No two Beastmen are exactly alike, and the variety of their mutations reflects the chaotic and uncontrolled nature of the sorcery that created them.</p>\n<p>Some resemble twisted versions of specific animals -- bull-headed brutes, wolf-faced hunters, serpent-scaled skulkers. Others combine features from multiple creatures into combinations that defy natural classification. The one constant is the wrongness of their appearance -- the sense that something human has been warped beyond recognition into something that is neither fully animal nor fully human.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Beastmen are <strong>exceedingly cruel and violent</strong>, feared and reviled by all other peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. Whatever culture they may have possessed during the height of the Massaran Empire has long since degraded into something more primal -- warbands organized around strength, packs held together by dominance and fear, and a way of life built around raiding, killing, and consuming.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"creation-by-the-massaran-empire\">Creation by the Massaran Empire</h3>\n<p>The Beastmen were created by the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> as the <strong>core of its armies</strong>. The sorcerer-kings of Massar employed sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding to produce living weapons -- soldiers that were stronger, more savage, and more expendable than human troops. The Beastmen served this purpose with brutal effectiveness, and the Massaran Empire&#39;s military power was built in large part on their backs.</p>\n<h3 id=\"scattering\">Scattering</h3>\n<p>After the defeat of the Massaran Empire in the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos#empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a>, the Beastmen were <strong>scattered</strong> across the wilds of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. Without the sorcerer-kings to command them, the Beastmen fragmented into roving warbands and feral packs, preying on the weak and the unwary. They have never been fully eradicated, and they remain a persistent threat to frontier communities across the known world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-sacking-of-crossings-377-iy\">The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY)</h2>\n<p>The Beastmen <strong>sacked the city of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a></strong> in 377 IY. A massive horde emerged from the wilderness and descended on the settlement, razing it to the ground. The beastmen committed untold atrocity and violence upon the citizens -- the few refugees who escaped tell stories of horrors that defy description.</p>\n<p>The fall of Crossings was one of the most devastating events in recent Imperial history. It destroyed the principal <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> settlement in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, driving thousands of refugees south to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> where they now crowd the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary#ashward\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a> quarter.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-scalper-economy\">The Scalper Economy</h3>\n<p>In response to the sacking, <strong>Emperor <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a></strong> issued an <strong>Imperial scalp bounty</strong> on all Beastmen, offering imperial gold marks for their scalps. This decree created an entirely new economy -- the <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a></strong> trade -- and drew hard men and women from every walk of life to the Backlands, seeking fortune in violence. The outpost of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> became the epicenter of this grim industry.</p>\n<h3 id=\"current-situation\">Current Situation</h3>\n<p>The Beastmen have <strong>settled in the ruins of Crossings</strong> and begun to <strong>push farther south</strong>, kidnapping farmers, raiding settlements, and worse. They represent an active and growing threat to every settlement in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, and the skeletal Imperial garrison left after the withdrawal of 378 IY is ill-equipped to contain them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">massar</a> -- The empire that created the Beastmen</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The city the Beastmen sacked</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier province where Beastmen are active</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- Where Avari refugees from the sacking now live</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The bounty hunters created by the Imperial response</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The Scalper outpost on the northern frontier</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The Empyrean War and the Sacking of Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> -- The people most affected by the Sacking of Crossings</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"bel-earth-hunger","title":"Bel-Tharach: The Earth-Hunger","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["bel","bel-tharach","earth-hunger","slaughterprince","cthonic","agriculture","blood-rites","avari","farming","sacrifice","dunwick","brother-cavin","seros","coastal-plain","argolle"],"html":"<h1 id=\"bel-tharach-the-earth-hunger\">Bel-Tharach: The Earth-Hunger</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The field and the battlefield are not as different as they appear. Both require sacrifice. Both produce abundance through death.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Bel-tharach</strong> is an old <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> word meaning <strong>&quot;the appetite of the earth&quot;</strong> or <strong>&quot;the hunger of the field.&quot;</strong> The farmers who use it do not remember where it comes from. They use it to mean a good harvest -- a season of abundance, a field that gives generously. It is a word of celebration, of gratitude, of plenty.</p>\n<p>It shares a name with <strong>Bel the Slaughterprince</strong> -- the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> war-god of blood, conquest, and slaughter.</p>\n<p>This is the question that several generations of scholars have quietly failed to answer: <strong>whether Bel the Slaughterprince and the agricultural earth-hunger are the same entity.</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-agricultural-blood-rites\">The Agricultural Blood Rites</h2>\n<p>The agricultural blood rites practiced in the farming villages of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle&#39;s</a> coastal plain predate <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> administration by centuries. They are old -- older than the Empire, older than the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, older than any institution that might claim authority to regulate them. They follow a cycle tied to the agricultural year:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Blood offering at planting.</strong> At the beginning of the growing season, blood is given to the earth. The specifics vary by community -- an animal slaughtered over the first-turned furrow, a cut palm pressed into fresh soil, something older and less easily described. The offering is made to ensure the field will produce.</li>\n<li><strong>Petition at harvest.</strong> At the gathering of the crop, a petition is made -- gratitude for what the earth has given, acknowledgment of what the earth has taken, and a request for continued favor. The petition is not prayer in the Empyrean sense. It is transaction. Something was given; something was received; the arrangement continues.</li>\n<li><strong>Sacrifice at the year&#39;s close.</strong> At the end of the agricultural cycle, a sacrifice is made. This is the most significant of the three rites, and the one about which outsiders know the least. The sacrifice closes the cycle, settles the account, and prepares the ground for the next year&#39;s exchange.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These rites share a name with the Cthonic war-god. They share more than a name.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-core-of-the-question\">The Core of the Question</h2>\n<p>What Bel requires in both expressions -- the Slaughterprince on the battlefield and the earth-hunger in the field -- is <strong>consumption</strong>. The Slaughterprince demands blood on the battlefield. The earth-hunger demands blood in the field. The domain differs. The appetite is the same. The same divine hunger manifests differently depending on the community that feeds it -- warriors feed it war, farmers feed it harvest, but both are feeding the same mouth.</p>\n<p>Two interpretations exist, and neither has been definitively established:</p>\n<h3 id=\"interpretation-one-same-entity-different-manifestations\">Interpretation One: Same Entity, Different Manifestations</h3>\n<p>Bel the Slaughterprince and the agricultural earth-hunger are the <strong>same entity</strong>, manifested differently through different communities over time. The agricultural prosperity of Argolle&#39;s farming villages is the favor of a genuine <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> power. The blood-price is a legitimate transaction -- blood given, abundance received, an arrangement that has endured for centuries because both parties honor it.</p>\n<p>Under this interpretation, the farmers of Argolle&#39;s coastal plain are engaged in Cthonic worship -- not the dramatic, self-conscious Cthonic worship of blood-priests and war-cults, but the quiet, practical, transactional worship of people who need their fields to produce and have found something that answers when they ask.</p>\n<h3 id=\"interpretation-two-different-entities-shared-name\">Interpretation Two: Different Entities, Shared Name</h3>\n<p>The Slaughterprince and the earth-hunger are <strong>genuinely different</strong> -- separate entities, separate traditions, separate powers that merely share a name through accident of ancient <a href=\"#/page/languages-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari language</a>. The agricultural rites are not Cthonic worship but folk practice, inherited tradition, superstition that happens to work because the land is fertile and the farmers are skilled.</p>\n<p>Under this interpretation, the shared name is a linguistic coincidence, and the scholars who see a connection are finding patterns where none exist.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"what-is-not-in-question\">What Is Not in Question</h2>\n<p>Whatever the answer to the theological question, several things are <strong>not in question</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Something answers the agricultural rites.</strong> The blood is given; the harvest comes. The petition is made; the fields produce. This is not coincidence and it is not skill. Something responds to the rites -- something real, old, and still being fed.</li>\n<li><strong>It produces extraordinary harvests.</strong> The farming villages of Argolle&#39;s coastal plain are prosperous beyond what soil and climate alone can explain. Their fields produce abundance that neighboring regions -- with comparable land, comparable skill, comparable investment -- cannot match.</li>\n<li><strong>It communicates in abundance and absence.</strong> When the rites are performed correctly, the harvests are extraordinary. When the rites are neglected or performed incorrectly, the harvests fail. The communication is clear: the arrangement has terms, and both parties are expected to honor them.</li>\n<li><strong>It is real, old, and still being fed.</strong> Whatever the farmers of Argolle&#39;s coastal plain are feeding -- whether it is a Cthonic war-god, an ancient earth-spirit, or something that defies either classification -- it has been receiving blood offerings for centuries, and it has not stopped being hungry.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-escalating-demand\">The Escalating Demand</h2>\n<p>The demands have grown proportionally to the prosperity provided over generations. What begins as a modest exchange between desperate farmers and something that answers -- a few drops of blood for a good harvest, a slaughtered animal for an exceptional one -- becomes, over time, something that cannot be unmade without cost.</p>\n<p>Each generation inherits a more prosperous arrangement and a more demanding patron. The blood-price increases. The expectations deepen. The transaction that sustained great-grandparents requires more from their descendants, and the cost of breaking the arrangement -- of refusing to pay what has been paid for generations -- grows with each passing year. The earth-hunger has been fed for centuries. It has grown accustomed to being fed. It will not accept less.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-coastal-plain-communities\">The Coastal Plain Communities</h2>\n<p>The wealthier farming communities of the coastal plain appear, to the casual visitor, entirely normal. They are <strong>hospitable, well-stocked, remarkable in the quality of their fields</strong>. A Temple of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> stands in the town square. The people attend services. Everything appears in order.</p>\n<p>It is the <strong>absences</strong> that accumulate.</p>\n<p>Certain families do not attend temple on certain days. Certain fields are not worked at certain times. Certain questions are not answered. Certain topics produce a silence that is not evasive but simply final -- the silence of people who know what they know and have decided, collectively and without discussion, that outsiders do not need to know it.</p>\n<p>The prosperity is real. The temple attendance is real. The hospitality is real. And beneath all of it, something else is also real, and has been real for longer than anyone living can remember, and will not stop being real simply because the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> would prefer it did not exist.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"brother-cavin-at-dunwick\">Brother Cavin at Dunwick</h2>\n<p><strong>Brother Cavin</strong> is a young priest of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> assigned to the temple at <strong><a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a></strong>, one of the farming communities on the coastal plain. He is a man of genuine piety -- sincere, earnest, and committed to his calling. He has been at his posting for two years.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>deeply uncomfortable</strong>.</p>\n<p>Brother Cavin has heard disturbing confessions -- not dramatic revelations of dark worship, but fragmentary, reluctant admissions that something in Dunwick&#39;s spiritual life does not align with the faith he was trained to serve. He has noticed absences in his congregation at specific times -- particular holy days, planting days, harvest days, when certain families simply do not appear, and no explanation is offered.</p>\n<p>He has begun asking questions of the wrong people.</p>\n<p>Brother Cavin has not yet been harmed. This is not because he is safe. It is not because the community is harmless. It is not because his questions have gone unnoticed. He has not been harmed, though <strong>not for the reasons he believes</strong>. Whether his safety is the product of indifference, calculation, protection, or something else entirely is a question whose answer may determine whether Brother Cavin survives his posting.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- The Empyrean god whose domain mirrors Bel&#39;s</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological crisis of Empyrean/Cthonic mirroring</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The tradition to which Bel belongs</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> -- The culture from which bel-tharach originates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">dunwick</a> -- The farming community where Brother Cavin serves</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">thousand-temples</a> -- The institution that would condemn the agricultural rites</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- A contrasting sacred tradition rooted in the living world</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The official faith of the Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a> -- Another heterodox religious movement in Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- Another tradition engaging with powers outside Empyrean orthodoxy</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"corcanoan","title":"Corcanoan","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","corcanoan","naming","human","seafaring","matrilineal","cthonic","corcano"],"html":"<h1 id=\"corcanoan\">Corcanoan</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Corcanoans</strong> hail from a chain of volcanic islands known as <strong>Corcano</strong>, and their culture is shaped by the dramatic and dangerous landscape they call home. Corcanoan society is matriarchal in structure, with lineage traced through the mother&#39;s line and women holding positions of authority in both domestic and public life.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>Corcanoans are characterized by dark hair and light eyes -- a striking combination that sets them apart from many other peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. Their skin is weathered and tan, bearing the marks of a life spent in the salt wind and harsh sun of the volcanic islands. They are a lean, sinewy people, shaped by the physical demands of seafaring and fishing in treacherous waters.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Corcanoans are <strong>famous sailors and fishermen</strong>. The volcanic islands of Corcano offer little arable land, and the sea has always been the Corcanoan people&#39;s primary source of sustenance, livelihood, and identity. Corcanoan seamanship is legendary throughout the Empire, and Corcanoan captains and navigators are sought after by merchant fleets and naval commands alike.</p>\n<p>Corcanoan society is <strong>matriarchal</strong>. Lineage is traced through the mother&#39;s line, and women hold positions of authority in both domestic and public life. The matriarchal structure shapes every aspect of Corcanoan culture, from inheritance customs to political organization to the naming of children.</p>\n<h3 id=\"religion\">Religion</h3>\n<p>Some Corcanoans <strong>worship Cthonic gods or primal spirits</strong> rather than -- or in addition to -- the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods recognized by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>. The volcanic landscape of Corcano, with its geothermal vents, sulfurous pools, and the ever-present threat of eruption, has produced a spiritual tradition that acknowledges the raw, dangerous power of the natural world in ways that the formalized Empyrean faith does not. These <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> practices are tolerated uneasily by Imperial authorities, who regard them as heterodox but not overtly heretical.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Corcanoan names are <strong>melodic and flowing</strong>, characteristically ending in vowels or soft consonants. The language of Corcano produces names that are pleasant to the ear and easy to speak -- a quality that reflects the musical traditions of Corcanoan culture.</p>\n<p><strong>Children are named after their mothers</strong> or matriarchal ancestors, reinforcing the matrilineal nature of Corcanoan kinship. A Corcanoan&#39;s name is a living record of their maternal lineage, connecting them to generations of women who came before. This practice means that certain names recur across generations, carried forward as acts of remembrance and continuity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that incorporates Corcano</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The Cthonic traditions some Corcanoans follow</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The dominant Empyrean faith</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"cthonic-corruption","title":"Cthonic Corruption","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["cthonic","corruption","empyrean","veil","elvora","erenthis","animals","perception","flesh","mind","decay","transformation","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"cthonic-corruption\">Cthonic Corruption</h1>\n<p><strong>Cthonic corruption</strong> is the practical, observable effect of prolonged exposure to <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> energies on living beings, objects, and environments. It is not metaphor, not theology, not moral judgment. It is what happens -- physically, cognitively, spiritually -- when the material world is subjected to sustained contact with the powers that dwell beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"effects-on-animals\">Effects on Animals</h2>\n<p>Animals exposed to prolonged Cthonic energies develop an awareness that <strong>transcends their nature</strong>. The change is visible and unmistakable to those who know what to look for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eyes that hold something beyond ordinary hunger.</strong> A wolf is hungry. A Cthonic-corrupted wolf is hungry in a way that is not entirely animal -- its eyes hold an intelligence, an appetite, a purpose that does not belong to a creature of instinct and survival. Something looks out through eyes that should contain only predatory focus, and what looks out is aware in a way that the animal alone could never be.</li>\n<li><strong>Behavioral changes.</strong> Corrupted animals do not behave as their uncorrupted counterparts do. Their movements are more purposeful. Their aggression is more directed. They coordinate in ways that exceed natural pack behavior. They target with discrimination that suggests awareness rather than instinct.</li>\n<li><strong>Physical alteration.</strong> Prolonged exposure produces physical changes -- thickened hide, darkened eyes, bone spurs, unusual growths. The corruption reshapes flesh as readily as it reshapes awareness, though the progression is gradual and varies by species and intensity of exposure.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"effects-on-humans\">Effects on Humans</h2>\n<p>Humans carrying Cthonic-saturated items or spending prolonged time in Cthonic-influenced environments experience changes that progress from subtle to profound:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Changes in perception.</strong> The corrupted individual begins to perceive things that others cannot -- presences, energies, dimensions of the world that are normally invisible. This expanded perception is not a gift. It is an intrusion. The boundaries of normal human awareness exist for reasons, and their erosion is not comfortable.</li>\n<li><strong>Changes in relationships.</strong> Prolonged Cthonic exposure affects how the corrupted individual relates to others. Bonds weaken or transform. Empathy erodes or redirects. The corrupted individual&#39;s sense of connection to other people shifts in ways that are difficult to articulate but impossible to miss.</li>\n<li><strong>Changes in what they regard as worth preserving.</strong> This is the subtlest and most dangerous effect. The corrupted individual&#39;s values shift. What once seemed important -- family, community, safety, the ordinary goods of human life -- begins to seem less significant. What replaces these values varies, but the direction is consistent: toward something older, deeper, and less human.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>What happens to a mortal carrying a fragment of a dead god too long without understanding it differs in degree but not in kind from what happened to <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-elvoran-precedent\">The Elvoran Precedent</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> experience is the most thoroughly documented case of civilization-scale Cthonic corruption. Prolonged Veil contact corrupted the Elvora at every level:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eyes blacken.</strong> The iris darkens progressively, eventually turning the eyes wholly black. This is the most visible and iconic sign of deep Cthonic corruption, and it is permanent. The Warlock King <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Jarn Murky-Eye</a> of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> bore a name that was not metaphorical -- his eyes were the color of what he had touched.</li>\n<li><strong>Bones warp.</strong> The skeletal structure deforms under sustained Cthonic pressure, producing distortions that are not illness and not injury but transformation. The body reshapes itself in response to energies it was not designed to contain.</li>\n<li><strong>Voices change.</strong> The corrupted voice acquires qualities that are difficult to describe -- resonances, harmonics, undertones that do not originate in human vocal anatomy. Those who have heard it do not forget it.</li>\n<li><strong>The cost was total.</strong> The Elvora went all the way. They bound something unbindable. The result was the destruction of their civilization: females rendered barren, males rendered immortal, eyes turned black, society shattered. The Elvora are the warning against which all other Cthonic engagement is measured. (See: <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-lakandi-experience\">The Lakandi Experience</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> engage with Cthonic entities at the individual scale rather than the civilizational scale, and their corruption is correspondingly more contained -- but it is not absent. Lakandi practitioners who repeatedly tear open <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> and reach through it to bind demons, spirits, and Beyond-entities accumulate the marks of their engagement:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eyes darkening at the iris</strong> -- progressive, permanent, visible</li>\n<li><strong>A quality of stillness beyond patience</strong> -- the stillness of something that has been touched by entities operating on inhuman timescales</li>\n<li><strong>Awareness of things not normally visible</strong> -- expanded perception that does not fade</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Lakandi treat these marks not as failing but as the <strong>visible record of genuine engagement</strong>. To be corrupted is to have done something real. To be unmarked is to have risked nothing. The corruption is the credential.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"natural-defenses\">Natural Defenses</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> root network is the most reliable natural defense against Cthonic corruption. Creatures touched by Cthonic influence avoid Erenthis root systems entirely -- not because of a physical barrier, but because of a <strong>deep incompatibility below the level of choice</strong>. The corruption and the roots cannot coexist. They are oriented toward fundamentally opposed principles, and the roots hold.</p>\n<p>This defense operates consistently and without active maintenance. Communities centered on living Erenthis trees have survived generations of frontier pressure, Cthonic incursion, and the slow erosion of normalcy that prolonged Cthonic exposure produces. The roots do not merely repel corrupted creatures -- they reinforce the metaphysical integrity of the space they occupy, providing a zone where Cthonic influence cannot gain purchase.</p>\n<p>The Black Tree at <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- the scorched stump of the Erenthis burned by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> thirty years ago -- still extends roots that Cthonic-corrupted creatures avoid. Even dead, even burned, the Erenthis holds.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-spectrum-of-corruption\">The Spectrum of Corruption</h2>\n<p>Cthonic corruption is not binary. It is a spectrum:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Incidental exposure</strong> -- proximity to Cthonic-saturated objects or environments for brief periods. Effects are minimal and usually reversible: unease, disturbed sleep, a sense of being observed.</li>\n<li><strong>Sustained exposure</strong> -- prolonged contact with Cthonic energies. Effects are progressive and increasingly difficult to reverse: perceptual changes, relationship shifts, value erosion.</li>\n<li><strong>Active engagement</strong> -- deliberate interaction with Cthonic entities through <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> or other means. Effects are permanent and cumulative: physical marks, cognitive alterations, fundamental changes in identity and orientation. The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> operate at this level.</li>\n<li><strong>Total immersion</strong> -- civilization-scale binding of Cthonic power. Effects are catastrophic and irreversible. The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> operated at this level, and they were destroyed by it.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The most reliable natural defense against Cthonic corruption</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The barrier through which Cthonic entities are reached</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> -- The civilization destroyed by total Cthonic immersion</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- A tradition that engages with Cthonic entities directly</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a> -- A Lakandi practitioner bearing the marks of binding</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">jarn-murky-eye</a> -- The Warlock King whose corruption was legendary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological crisis that complicates understanding of Cthonic power</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The tradition that opposes Cthonic influence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- A Cthonic construct of enormous scale beneath Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- Ancient beings that exist outside both Empyrean and Cthonic frameworks</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- Where the Black Tree&#39;s roots still resist Cthonic corruption</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"dog-soldier-war","title":"The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY)","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["event","history","warfare","kolani","don-kolani","guerrilla-war","general-darius-jute","kolani-munitions"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-dog-soldier-war-272-291-iy\">The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY)</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Dog Soldier War</strong> (272-291 IY) was a prolonged guerrilla conflict between the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and the <strong>don&#39;Kolani</strong> -- the forest-dwelling branch of the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> people. Spanning nearly two decades, the war proved extraordinarily costly for the Empire and ended not in conquest but in a hard-won peace brokered by <a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a>. The peace treaty included a provision of enormous strategic significance: the Empire gained access to <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-conflict\">The Conflict</h2>\n<p>The don&#39;Kolani launched a relentless guerrilla war against Imperial occupation of their ancestral forest lands. Unlike conventional warfare -- where the Empire&#39;s legions and sorcerous firepower could be brought to bear decisively -- the don&#39;Kolani fought on their own terms. They used the dense forests as both fortress and weapon, striking from cover, dissolving into the wilderness, and refusing to give the Imperial forces the pitched battle they needed to achieve a decisive victory.</p>\n<p>For nearly two decades, the conflict ground on. Imperial casualties mounted. Supply lines were harassed. Garrisons were besieged, relieved, and besieged again. The war became a quagmire -- too costly to sustain, too politically embarrassing to abandon, and impossible to win through conventional military means.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"mutual-respect\">Mutual Respect</h2>\n<p>Over the long years of fighting, something unexpected developed between the combatants: <strong>mutual respect</strong>. The Imperial soldiers who fought in the forests came to recognize the don&#39;Kolani as formidable warriors -- fierce, disciplined, and unyielding in defense of their homeland. The don&#39;Kolani, for their part, came to respect the endurance and courage of the Imperial legionaries who fought far from home in unfamiliar terrain against an enemy they could barely see.</p>\n<p>This mutual respect -- born of shared hardship and the grudging acknowledgment of an enemy&#39;s worth -- would prove critical when peace was finally negotiated.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-peace\">The Peace</h2>\n<p>Peace was brokered by <strong><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a></strong>, one of the most capable military commanders in recent Imperial history. Jute recognized that the war could not be won and that continued fighting served no one&#39;s interests. His diplomacy was informed by the respect that had developed between the soldiers of both sides.</p>\n<p>The peace treaty included provisions of enormous significance:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Access to <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> munitions</strong> -- The Empire gained access to explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology had been developed by the Kolani independently of Mithrian sorcery. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, reducing the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s exclusive importance in warfare and contributing to the ongoing transformation of Imperial military doctrine.</li>\n<li><strong>Formal incorporation of Kolani warriors</strong> -- The treaty led to the establishment of the <a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a>, a military formation composed entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors who serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry within the Imperial military structure.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"strategic-impact\">Strategic Impact</h2>\n<p>The Dog Soldier War&#39;s most lasting impact was technological. The acquisition of Kolani munitions fundamentally altered the balance of power within the Empire&#39;s military establishment. Before the war, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> held a near-monopoly on battlefield firepower -- only sorcerers could deliver the kind of devastating ranged destruction that won battles. The introduction of explosive devices and incendiary weapons gave conventional military commanders an alternative, reducing their dependence on the Academy and shifting the political dynamics of imperial warfare.</p>\n<p>This shift continues to generate tension between the military establishment and the Academy, which views the proliferation of non-sorcerous firepower as a threat to its institutional relevance and authority.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a> -- the commander who brokered peace</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a> -- the military formation established by the treaty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a> -- institution whose monopoly was challenged</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Military</a> -- the armed forces that fought the war</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a> -- broader historical context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"eladra","title":"Eladra","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["race","eladra","argollean","empyrean","aurelion","sorcery","erenthis","aodahn","sanctuary","ancient","spires","gnostic-geometry"],"html":"<h1 id=\"eladra\">Eladra</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Eladra</strong> were once part of the advanced <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>, where they played a central role in the discovery of the secrets of the cosmos, the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods. They were the original practitioners of the sorcerous arts that would later be systematized as <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, and their scholarship laid the foundations for much of what the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> teaches today. Their civilization fell to ruin through the influence of the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> and the creeping corruption of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> power.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Eladra are <strong>taller than humans</strong>, with <strong>lithe but muscular</strong> builds that combine grace with surprising physical strength. Their appearance is distinctly non-human -- proportions that are slightly wrong by human standards, features that are beautiful but alien, a quality of presence that sets them apart from even the most striking human specimen.</p>\n<p>They possess a <strong>natural affinity for sorcery</strong> -- an innate sensitivity to the metaphysical axioms that govern reality. This affinity is not learned but inborn, a fundamental aspect of Eladran biology that made them the foremost sorcerers of the ancient world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-argollean-empire\">The Argollean Empire</h3>\n<p>The Eladra were central to <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> civilization, serving as its foremost scholars and sorcerers. It was the Eladra who discovered the secrets of the cosmos, the nature of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>, and the existence of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods. Their research laid the foundations for <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> and established the metaphysical framework that all subsequent sorcerous traditions would either build upon or react against.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-fall\">The Fall</h3>\n<p>The fall of Eladran civilization was not a single catastrophic event but a long, slow collapse driven by internal decay and the transformation of some Eladra into the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>. As Eladran scholars delved deeper into the chaotic energies of the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a>, they were changed by what they found -- achieving immortality at a terrible cost and bringing ruin upon the civilization they had once sustained.</p>\n<p>The precise nature of the fall is debated by scholars, but the result was the near-total destruction of Eladran culture and the scattering of its people.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-status\">Current Status</h2>\n<p>Those claiming Eladran heritage in the present day are <strong>almost invariably of mixed blood</strong> -- the product of centuries of intermarriage with humans and other peoples. Only a <strong>handful of full-blooded Eladra still live</strong>, and these survivors are <strong>extremely old and deeply reclusive</strong>, withdrawing from the affairs of the mortal world into isolation and silence.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-erenthis-trees\">The Erenthis Trees</h2>\n<p>The Eladra <strong>built the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis trees</a></strong> -- vast, sacred growths whose Eladran spiritual traditions were woven through with <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> vitality. The Erenthis are living expressions of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> distributed essence, cultivated by the Eladra as monuments that would endure long after their civilization fell. The Erenthis root network functions as the most reliable natural defense against <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic corruption</a> in the known world.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> later built their culture around Erenthis found in the ruins of Eladran civilization. They did not fully understand what they were tending, but they understood enough -- that the tree was sacred, that it sustained them, that rites performed in its presence carried weight.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"aodahn-the-city-beneath-sanctuary\">Aodahn -- The City Beneath Sanctuary</h2>\n<p>The Eladra built <strong><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a></strong> -- the ancient harbor-city upon whose ruins <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> now stands. Aodahn was built by the true, uncorrupted Eladra -- possibly the last community of their kind in the world. The city featured <strong>five ivory spires</strong>, each carved from a single stone so white it seems to emit light, each rising three hundred feet or more above the harbor. Modern <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> scholars suspect the spires are <strong>engineered conduits of Empyrean vitality</strong>, analogous to Erenthis trees but constructed rather than grown.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-vanishing\">The Vanishing</h3>\n<p>The Eladra of Aodahn <strong>vanished mysteriously</strong>. When the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrians</a> arrived, they found the city completely abandoned. No evidence of war, plague, siege, or flight. Belongings remained in homes. Workshops stood open. Food rotted on tables. The people were simply gone.</p>\n<p>The chronicler <strong>Varro Silk</strong> wrote that the city felt &quot;as though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned.&quot;</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> has proposed several theories: the Threshold Hypothesis (the Eladra stepped through a door to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a>), the Ascension Model (transcendence of physical form), the Catastrophic Severance Theory (accidental destruction), and the Recall (summoned by their gods). None are proven.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-threshold\">The Threshold</h3>\n<p>At the deepest level of the Undercity beneath Sanctuary -- the Foundations of the Spires -- lies the <strong>Threshold</strong>: the place where the Eladra ascension happened. The door has <strong>not fully closed</strong>. Whatever process the Eladra used to depart left a permanent weakness in the boundary between the physical world and the Empyrean. This is the source of the phenomena that pervade all of Aodahn -- sounds in unknown languages, fleeting visions, the sensation of being watched.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"eladra-agents-in-sanctuary\">Eladra Agents in Sanctuary</h2>\n<p>At least <strong>one Eladra agent is believed to be present in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> at any given time</strong>, watching and guarding secrets about what lies below. These agents are subtle, patient, and nearly impossible to identify. Their purpose is unknown -- whether they guard the Threshold, monitor human activity, or pursue some deeper agenda is a matter of speculation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood\">The Argollean Brotherhood</h2>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a></strong> is a criminal network <strong>connected to old Eladran noble houses</strong> that survived the fall of the First Empire. They exist marginally and resentfully within Mithrian society, executing plans and deeds on behalf of these houses: intelligence work, artifact acquisition, and the occasional removal of obstacles. Their primary interest is relics and artifacts of the First Empire, which they regard as cultural inheritance rather than state property.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> -- The corrupted Eladra who destroyed their civilization</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a> -- The Eladra city beneath Sanctuary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The sacred trees planted by the Eladra</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- The city built on Eladra ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The criminal network connected to Eladran noble houses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> -- The divine essence the Eladra discovered</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- The ancient empire the Eladra were part of</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution that studies Eladra heritage</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic-and-sorcery</a> -- The sorcerous traditions the Eladra founded</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> -- The people who inherited the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> -- The ancient race the Argolleans warred against</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"elvora","title":"Elvora","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["race","elvora","eladra","veil","beyond","immortal","barren","binding","cthonic","corruption","ancient"],"html":"<h1 id=\"elvora\">Elvora</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Elvora</strong> are of <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> descent, but they have been fundamentally changed by exposure to the chaotic energies of the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a>. Where the Eladra sought to understand and codify the laws of reality, the Elvora plunged into the raw chaos that lies beneath those laws, and they were transformed by the experience. They achieved eternal life, but at a cost that is destroying them as a people.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Elvora are <strong>taller than humans and extremely muscular</strong>, their bodies hardened by centuries of existence and the transformative effects of chaotic energy. Their physical characteristics are striking and unsettling:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pale white skin</strong> -- drained of natural pigmentation by centuries of Veil contact</li>\n<li><strong>Solid black eyes</strong> -- lacking iris, pupil, or sclera. The eyes blackened from centuries of <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a> contact, the visible mark of what the Elvora touched and what touched them back</li>\n<li><strong>Tend to be hairless</strong> -- another consequence of the chaotic energies that remade them</li>\n<li><strong>Many lack consideration for modesty or clothing</strong> -- regarding such conventions as meaningless affectations of mortal culture, vestiges of a way of life they have long since transcended</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-price-of-immortality\">The Price of Immortality</h2>\n<p>The Elvora achieved eternal life, but at a terrible cost that ensures their extinction:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>All females are barren</strong> -- unable to bear children, cutting off the possibility of natural reproduction entirely</li>\n<li><strong>All males are immortal</strong> -- unable to die of natural causes, condemned to endure the endless passage of time</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Elvora are thus a <strong>slowly dying race</strong>, their numbers dwindling with each passing century as attrition, violence, and madness claim those who cannot be replaced. Every Elvoran who falls to violence, accident, or the slow erosion of sanity is a permanent loss -- one fewer member of a people who can never grow.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-weight-of-ages\">The Weight of Ages</h2>\n<p>The surviving Elvora are <strong>impossibly old</strong>, and the weight of millennia has taken a devastating toll on their minds. Their memories are <strong>fractured</strong>, their personalities <strong>splintered</strong> by the sheer duration of their existence. An Elvoran who has lived for thousands of years may speak of ancient events with crystalline clarity while being unable to remember their own name from one day to the next. They are beings for whom time has become a burden rather than a resource -- each century adding another layer of experience to minds that were never designed to contain so much.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-binding\">The Binding</h2>\n<p>The Elvora <strong>discovered the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a></strong> -- the barrier between the material world and the chaotic energies of the Beyond. They did not merely study it. They tore it open, reached through, and attempted to bind the powers they found on the other side.</p>\n<p>Their <strong>binding destroyed them even as it succeeded</strong>. The Elvoran binding tradition is the same essential practice as the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a>, but at a <strong>civilizational scale</strong> rather than an individual one. Where a Lakandi practitioner binds a single demon or spirit, the Elvora attempted to bind powers that could reshape civilizations. The cost was total: females rendered barren, males rendered immortal, eyes turned black, civilization destroyed.</p>\n<p>The Elvora are the <strong>cautionary tale</strong>, the warning against ambition unchecked by wisdom. Their fate demonstrates that the scale of a binding matters -- that there are things that should not be bound, not because binding is immoral but because the cost of binding them exceeds what any individual or civilization can pay.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-the-eladra\">Relationship to the Eladra</h2>\n<p>The Elvora and the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> share a common origin but diverged catastrophically. The Eladra maintained their connection to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> -- the divine order, the distributed essence of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>. The Elvora turned instead to the chaos beyond the Veil, seeking power through contact with forces that the Empyrean tradition holds in opposition.</p>\n<p>The builders of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> were <strong>not</strong> Elvora. They were the true, uncorrupted Eladra -- something older and purer, a people who maintained their connection to the Empyrean when others fell away. The distinction matters: the Eladra and the Elvora may share an origin, but they are not the same people, and conflating them obscures the nature of both.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The ancestor civilization from which the Elvora diverged</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- The individual-scale binding tradition related to Elvoran practice</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The barrier the Elvora tore open</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The corruption that marks those who contact the Beyond</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a> -- The Eladra city (built by true Eladra, not Elvora)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> -- Another ancient race with binding traditions</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"empyrean-war","title":"The Empyrean War (663 BE)","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["event","history","empyrean","bellasarius","enador","massaran-empire","beastmen","founding-event"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-empyrean-war-663-be\">The Empyrean War (663 BE)</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Empyrean War</strong> (663 BE) was the foundational conflict that gave birth to the civilization that would become the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. The <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> and the war-chief <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> raised an alliance of peoples against the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its sorcerer-kings. The tyrant-sorcerer <strong>Sebek</strong> was driven into exile, the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> legions that formed the core of the Massaran military were scattered, and centuries of darkness came to an end.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> was a formidable power sustained by <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a> sorcery and the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> legions that served as its military backbone. The Massaran sorcerer-kings ruled through fear, arcane domination, and the deployment of beastman armies -- monstrous warriors whose origins lay in the dark experiments of a bygone age. The peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> lived under Massaran tyranny, their lands occupied, their cultures suppressed, their lives subject to the whims of sorcerer-tyrants.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-alliance\">The Alliance</h2>\n<p>The Empyrean War was made possible by two extraordinary individuals:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a></strong> -- A spiritual leader who rediscovered the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>, the sacred texts that would become the moral and legal foundation of the civilization that followed. Enador provided the spiritual framework -- the shared identity and purpose -- that united disparate peoples into a coherent alliance. He also recovered the <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a>, the ancient Argollean grimoire that restored access to sorcerous power.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a></strong> -- The war-chief who served as the military architect of the alliance. Bellasarius organized, trained, and led the armies that fought the Massaran forces. His tactical brilliance and personal courage made him a figure of legend whose name would echo through the centuries.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Together, the prophet and the general forged an alliance that combined spiritual conviction with military competence -- a combination that proved devastating against the Massaran order.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-war\">The War</h2>\n<p>The Empyrean War was a prolonged and brutal conflict. The Massaran sorcerer-kings commanded powerful magic and the loyalty of the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> legions, making them formidable opponents. The alliance led by Enador and Bellasarius fought a campaign of liberation across <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, breaking Massaran power piece by piece.</p>\n<p>The war culminated in the overthrow of the Massaran order. The tyrant-sorcerer <strong>Sebek</strong> -- the most powerful of the sorcerer-kings -- was driven into exile rather than killed, a detail that has fueled centuries of speculation about whether the Massaran threat was truly ended or merely driven underground. The Beastmen legions were scattered across the wilds of Mithrapos, where they remain a persistent threat to this day -- their descendants are the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> that continue to plague frontier settlements and wilderness regions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"consequences\">Consequences</h2>\n<p>The victory in the Empyrean War had consequences that reshaped the world:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a></strong> -- The alliance transformed into a confederation of free city-states governed by a <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Senate</a>, establishing the political framework that would eventually become the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></strong> -- Enador&#39;s rediscovered texts became the moral and legal foundation of the new order, establishing the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> as the dominant spiritual tradition of Mithrapos.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></strong> -- The founding of the city that would become the capital of the Empire.</li>\n<li><strong>The Valerian Legacy</strong> -- Bellasarius Valerian&#39;s descendants would claim the Imperial throne, with <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> declaring himself the first Emperor in 1 IY. <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>&#39;s prestige rests entirely on this ancestral connection.</li>\n<li><strong>The Beastman Threat</strong> -- The scattered Beastmen legions were never fully destroyed. Their descendants persist in the wilderness, and their periodic resurgence -- most notably the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> in 377 IY -- demonstrates that the consequences of the Empyrean War continue to shape the present.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> -- spiritual leader of the alliance</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian / Marcus Valerian</a> -- war-chief and ancestor of the first Emperor</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> -- the dynasty founded on Bellasarius&#39;s legacy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a> -- the sacred texts rediscovered by Enador</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean Faith</a> -- the faith born from the war&#39;s victory</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a> -- the civilization that emerged from the war</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a> -- broader historical context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> -- the Beastmen&#39;s return, centuries later</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"gnostic-geometry","title":"Gnostic Geometry","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["gnostic-geometry","magic","sorcery","anthyllium","nine-fold","sigils","imperial-academy","argolle","enador","axioms"],"html":"<h1 id=\"gnostic-geometry\">Gnostic Geometry</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The world is built on hidden mathematics.&quot;\n— High Mage Marius</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Gnostic Geometry is the most powerful, most structured, and most carefully controlled form of magic practiced in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. It is the science of the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality — the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout the cosmos by <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice, accessed and directed through mental discipline, geometric diagrams (sigils), and resonance (the spoken word). Once practiced by the ancient Argolleans in the time before the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>, the formulae of Gnostic Geometry were lost for thousands of years after the fall of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, only to be rediscovered when the Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> found <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a> alongside the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"theoretical-foundation\">Theoretical Foundation</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-nine-fold-patterns\">The Nine-Fold Patterns</h3>\n<p>The fundamental premise of Gnostic Geometry is that reality is structured according to nine-fold geometric patterns — mathematical relationships woven into the fabric of the cosmos by <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice. These patterns are not merely descriptions of reality but its actual underlying architecture: the cosmos is, at its deepest level, a geometric construct, and the laws of nature, physics, and metaphysics are all expressions of these nine foundational geometries.</p>\n<p>The nine-fold patterns govern everything from the behavior of matter and energy to the movement of souls, the flow of time, the structure of <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a>, and the relationship between the material world and the Beyond. A gnostic geometer who understands these patterns — who can perceive, reproduce, and manipulate them — can alter the fundamental properties of reality within the scope of their knowledge and power.</p>\n<h3 id=\"manipulation-of-metaphysical-axioms\">Manipulation of Metaphysical Axioms</h3>\n<p>According to <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a>, sorcery through Gnostic Geometry is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms — the foundational rules upon which reality is built. This is a critical distinction from other forms of magic. Hedge-mages manipulate natural forces through instinct and tradition. Warlocks draw power from entities beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a> through negotiated pacts. Practitioners of <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a> channel the divine spark within their own souls. Gnostic geometers manipulate the rules themselves — the underlying mathematical relationships that determine how matter behaves, how energy flows, how space is structured, and how time progresses.</p>\n<p>This gives Gnostic Geometry enormous power but also enormous danger. The axioms that gnostic geometers manipulate are the same axioms that maintain the structural integrity of reality itself. A poorly constructed sigil, an incorrectly resonated formula, a failure of mental discipline at the critical moment — any of these can produce consequences ranging from the sorcerer&#39;s immediate death to localized reality distortions that may persist for decades.</p>\n<h3 id=\"a-structured-lawful-cosmos\">A Structured, Lawful Cosmos</h3>\n<p>The philosophy underlying Gnostic Geometry assumes a structured, lawful cosmos — a universe that operates according to consistent, discoverable rules rather than arbitrary divine whim or chaotic chance. This assumption is grounded in the Empyrean understanding of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice: the supreme designer created a cosmos of order, meaning, and purpose, and the geometric patterns that govern reality are the mathematical expression of that order. Gnostic Geometry is therefore not merely a magical practice but a philosophical commitment — a declaration that the cosmos is rational, that its rules can be understood, and that understanding those rules confers the power to modify them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-three-disciplines\">The Three Disciplines</h2>\n<h3 id=\"mental-discipline\">Mental Discipline</h3>\n<p>The practice of Gnostic Geometry begins with mental discipline — the rigorous training of the mind to perceive, hold, and manipulate the nine-fold patterns without error. The human mind was not designed to process the kind of mathematical complexity that the nine-fold patterns represent, and untrained minds that attempt to engage with them directly risk madness, cognitive dissolution, or the kind of reality-distorting accidents that give sorcery its fearsome reputation.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> subjects its students to years of mental conditioning before permitting them to attempt even the simplest geometric manipulations. This conditioning involves meditation, mathematical study, memory training, and a series of increasingly complex cognitive exercises designed to expand the mind&#39;s capacity to hold multiple geometric relationships simultaneously. The process is grueling, and the dropout rate is high — not all minds are capable of the flexibility and precision that Gnostic Geometry demands.</p>\n<h3 id=\"diagrams-sigils\">Diagrams (Sigils)</h3>\n<p>Sigils are the geometric diagrams through which gnostic geometers access and manipulate the nine-fold patterns. A sigil is not merely a drawing but a precision instrument — a geometric construction whose proportions, angles, and relationships must be exact to within tolerances that would challenge the finest draftsman. Each sigil encodes a specific manipulation of one or more metaphysical axioms, and the act of constructing the sigil — whether drawn on paper, inscribed in stone, traced in the air with a gesture, or held entirely within the mind — is the act that initiates the manipulation.</p>\n<p>The relationship between the sigil&#39;s geometry and its effect is not arbitrary but lawful: specific geometric relationships produce specific metaphysical effects, and these relationships are consistent, reproducible, and predictable. This is what distinguishes Gnostic Geometry from the intuitive, unpredictable magic of hedge-mages and the negotiated, transactional power of warlock pacts.</p>\n<h3 id=\"resonance-spoken-word\">Resonance (Spoken Word)</h3>\n<p>Resonance is the vocal component of Gnostic Geometry — the spoken words, tones, and harmonic patterns that activate the sigils and direct the manipulated axioms toward their intended effects. The words themselves are not magical incantations in the folkloric sense; they are precisely calibrated vibrations that interact with the geometric patterns of the sigils to produce specific metaphysical resonances. The relationship between sound and geometry is one of the deepest mysteries of Gnostic Geometry — the understanding that the cosmos responds not only to visual patterns but to auditory ones, and that the combination of the two produces effects that neither could achieve alone.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"ancient-argollean-practice\">Ancient Argollean Practice</h3>\n<p>Gnostic Geometry was first developed — or first discovered — by the ancient Argolleans, the civilization that flourished in what is now the Province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> long before the rise of the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>. The Argolleans achieved a level of sophistication in geometric sorcery that has never been equaled, and the ruins of their civilization — the temples, fortifications, and arcane infrastructure that dot the Argollean landscape — testify to the power they wielded. The nature of the ancient Argollean civilization and the circumstances of its fall remain subjects of intense scholarly debate and archaeological investigation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-lost-centuries\">The Lost Centuries</h3>\n<p>When <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> fell, the formulae of Gnostic Geometry were lost — destroyed, hidden, or suppressed by the forces that brought the Argollean civilization to an end. For thousands of years, the nine-fold patterns that the Argolleans had mastered were unknown to the wider world. Magic continued to be practiced during this period — through hedge-magic, warlock pacts, and the intuitive sorcery of naturally gifted individuals — but the structured, systematic power of Gnostic Geometry was gone, and the world was immeasurably diminished by its absence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"rediscovery\">Rediscovery</h3>\n<p>The formulae of Gnostic Geometry were rediscovered when the Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> found <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a> — the ancient grimoire that described the nine-fold geometric patterns — alongside the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>. This dual discovery was the intellectual foundation of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> and the civilization that followed: the Measure and the Scale provided the moral framework, and the Anthyllium provided the arcane knowledge, and together they gave the Empyrean faithful both the spiritual authority and the practical power to overthrow the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"imperial-academy-control\">Imperial Academy Control</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> retains strict control over the practice of Gnostic Geometry within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. This control is justified on both practical and political grounds. Practically, Gnostic Geometry is extraordinarily dangerous to untrained practitioners — the manipulation of metaphysical axioms by those who lack the mental discipline, geometric precision, and theoretical understanding to do so safely can result in catastrophic accidents that endanger not only the practitioner but everyone and everything in their vicinity. Politically, the concentration of arcane power in the hands of the Academy ensures that the most potent form of magic in the known world remains under the control of the Imperial government rather than distributed among private practitioners, rogue sorcerers, or hostile powers.</p>\n<p>Unsanctioned practice of Gnostic Geometry is a serious criminal offense throughout the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, and the Academy maintains a corps of investigators — colloquially known as witch-hunters, though the term is imprecise — whose task is to identify, apprehend, and either recruit or suppress unlicensed practitioners.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-other-magical-traditions\">Relationship to Other Magical Traditions</h2>\n<p>Gnostic Geometry is more powerful than hedge-magic, warlock pacts, or any other form of sorcery practiced in the known world — a claim that the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> makes openly and that the evidence supports. Hedge-magic operates through instinct and tradition, achieving modest effects through methods that its practitioners do not fully understand. Warlock pacts achieve power through negotiation with entities beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a>, but the power comes at a cost determined by the entity rather than the practitioner. <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a> channels divine power through virtue, but its effects are unpredictable and its practitioners are vanishingly rare.</p>\n<p>Gnostic Geometry manipulates the axioms of reality itself — the foundational rules upon which all other forms of magic ultimately depend. A gnostic geometer does not petition an entity for power, does not rely on instinct or tradition, and does not need to be virtuous. What a gnostic geometer needs is knowledge, precision, and discipline — and within the scope of those qualities, the power available is limited only by the practitioner&#39;s understanding of the nine-fold patterns and their capacity to manipulate them without destroying themselves.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"grathar","title":"Grathar","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","grathar","naming","human","ygrathen","grathe-steppe","reclusive","tall"],"html":"<h1 id=\"grathar\">Grathar</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Grathar</strong> are a physically imposing and culturally austere people, renowned for their extraordinary size, strength, and directness. They are notable for carrying <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> blood in their veins -- a heritage that manifests in their exceptional physical power and in subtle qualities that set them apart from ordinary humans.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Grathar are <strong>extraordinarily tall and strong</strong> -- the most physically imposing of the human peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. They have dark hair and light eyes, with skin that ranges from <strong>ochre to slightly green</strong> -- a faint but visible echo of their <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> ancestry. The greenish tint to Grathar skin is the most obvious marker of their inhuman heritage, and it sets them apart immediately from all other human cultures.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Grathar are <strong>mostly peaceful and reclusive</strong>, inhabiting the vast <strong>Grathe Steppe</strong> alongside -- but largely separate from -- the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> horse warriors who share the same territory. Where the Skiothans are aggressive, expansionist, and convinced of their own superiority, the Grathar are withdrawn, contemplative, and content to be left alone.</p>\n<p><strong>Few Grathar have assimilated into Mithrian society</strong>. Their extraordinary size, their distinctive appearance, and their reclusive temperament make integration difficult, and most Grathar see no reason to seek it. Those who do venture into Imperial civilization tend to be solitary individuals -- traders, mercenaries, scholars -- rather than communities.</p>\n<h3 id=\"ygrathen-heritage\">Ygrathen Heritage</h3>\n<p>The Grathar <strong>carry <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> blood</strong> -- the oldest race of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, beings of tremendous size and powerful sorcery. This heritage accounts for the Grathar&#39;s exceptional size and physical strength, but it may carry deeper implications as well. The Ygrathen were solitary beings of enormous power who never formed their own civilization; the Grathar&#39;s reclusive nature may reflect this same inclination, inherited across generations of diluted blood.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Grathar use <strong>singular, short, hard-sounding names</strong> that convey brute strength and natural force. Names like <strong>Krug</strong>, <strong>Brak</strong>, or <strong>Thond</strong> are typical -- monosyllabic, percussive, and utterly without ornamentation.</p>\n<p>The Grathar see no need for patronymics, clan names, or honorifics. A Grathar&#39;s name is their name, and <strong>it is enough</strong>. This simplicity in naming reflects the broader Grathar aesthetic: direct, unadorned, and unconcerned with the elaborate social signaling that other cultures invest in their naming practices.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> -- The ancient race whose blood the Grathar carry</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">skiothan</a> -- The nomadic horse warriors who share the Grathe Steppe</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- A full-blooded Ygrathen hermit</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"great-houses","title":"The Great Houses","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["houses","nobility","politics","empire","factions"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-great-houses\">The Great Houses</h1>\n<p>The Great Houses are the noble families whose wealth, military power, and patronage networks dominate the political landscape of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Each house commands vast estates, legions of clients, and tributary lesser houses. The competition between them -- sometimes open warfare, more often intrigue and maneuvering -- shapes the fate of the Empire as much as any decree from the throne.</p>\n<h2 id=\"house-decimus\">House Decimus</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td>Emperor <span class=\"dead-link\">War of Three Emperors</span> (270 IY), when <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> emerged victorious from the civil war that followed the assassination of the mad Emperor <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a>. Since that time, the Decimus line has held the Imperial seat without interruption.</p>\n<p>The house enforces its will through the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a>, an elite cadre of spies, informants, and assassins who serve the Emperor directly. The Talons operate outside normal Imperial law and are feared throughout the Empire as instruments of the throne&#39;s displeasure.</p>\n<p>The succession of House Decimus has not always been smooth. <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Julian Decimus</a>, a previous Emperor, named his son <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Diometian</a> as heir -- a decision that triggered civil war when rival claimants and discontented houses refused to accept the appointment. The resulting conflict reshaped the political order of the Empire.</p>\n<h2 id=\"house-valerian\">House Valerian</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</span> -- the legendary general who, alongside the prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a>, overthrew the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a>. For centuries, the Valerians held the Imperial throne as a near-birthright.</p>\n<p>The house&#39;s fortunes declined after a succession of poor Emperors culminated in the reign of <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a>, whose madness and cruelty brought the Empire to the brink. Aurex was assassinated by his own sister, ending the Valerian dynasty&#39;s hold on power. Today, House Valerian retains immense prestige and wealth but lacks the political muscle to reclaim the throne -- though many believe the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration.</p>\n<h2 id=\"house-kalomenes\">House Kalomenes</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrian League</span>, wielding unrivaled influence in the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a>. When <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> declared himself Emperor, the Kalomenes were among those defeated and forced to bend the knee. The house has never forgotten this humiliation, nor has it ever truly accepted subordination.</p>\n<p>Today, House Kalomenes commands tremendous power in the courts and political institutions of the Empire. The house sponsors dozens of tributary houses and maintains an extensive network of clients, lawyers, and political operatives. Where other houses wield swords, the Kalomenes wield patronage, precedent, and procedural manipulation with lethal precision.</p>\n<h2 id=\"house-malventi\">House Malventi</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Massaran Kingdoms</span> and <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoa</a>, trafficking in exotic goods, rare materials, and -- by persistent rumor -- slaves. The Malventi are cosmopolitan, pragmatic, and largely indifferent to the ideological concerns that animate other houses.</p>\n<p>Their foreign connections make them invaluable as intermediaries and intelligence sources, but also invite suspicion. Many in the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> view the Malventi as dangerously unpatriotic, more loyal to profit than to the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"house-drussus\">House Drussus</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Thousand Temples</span> and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>, promoting cultural purity, religious orthodoxy, and the divine authority of the Emperor. They view the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> not merely as law but as sacred revelation, and they regard any deviation from tradition as heresy.</p>\n<p>The house&#39;s influence is strongest among the priesthood, the rural aristocracy, and the traditional military families who see the Empire as a divinely ordained institution. House Aurel is frequently at odds with the more cosmopolitan houses, particularly <a href=\"#/page/house-malventi\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Malventi</a> and <a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"house-severian\">House Severian</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th></th>\n<th></th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Patriarch</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">house-severian</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Distinction</strong></td>\n<td>Ancient, secretive, rumored [[Eladra</span> blood</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>House Severian is among the oldest houses in the Empire, yet also the most enigmatic. The Severians operate through hidden channels, preferring shadow influence to open political contest. Their true wealth and the full extent of their networks are unknown even to the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a>.</p>\n<p>Persistent rumors hold that the Severian bloodline carries <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> ancestry -- a claim that, if true, would link the house to the ancient <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> civilization and its arcane legacy. The Severians neither confirm nor deny these rumors, and their occasional displays of uncanny insight and influence do nothing to dispel them.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"history-of-mithrapos","title":"History of Mithrapos","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["history","timeline","mithrapos","mithrian-empire","argolle","eladra","elvora","ygrathen","thune","massar","enador","bellasarius","backlands","sorcery","warfare","cthonic","empyrean","krysea","nethercity","lakan","beastmen","targ","crossings"],"html":"<h1 id=\"history-of-mithrapos\">History of Mithrapos</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;Mithrapos is a cradle and a coffin, a boneyard of Empires.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Savron</strong>, Imperial Chronicler, <em>The Last Argument of Kings</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The world of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> has endured the rise and fall of civilizations spanning thousands of years. Each empire has built upon the ruins of the last, inheriting fragments of knowledge, power, and ambition from its predecessors while carrying forward the scars of their failures. The history of Mithrapos is not a story of progress but of cycles -- of greatness achieved and squandered, of knowledge discovered and lost, of empires that blazed with brilliance before collapsing into ash.</p>\n<p>What follows is the definitive chronological record of the principal events and eras that have shaped the world as it exists today, drawn from the earliest surviving accounts of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> city-states through to the present day.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"pre-imperial-era-deep-history\">Pre-Imperial Era: Deep History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-rise-of-the-eladran-city-states-4100-be\">The Rise of the Eladran City-States (4100 BE)</h3>\n<p>The earliest recorded civilization in <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> emerged circa 4100 BE, when the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> city-states arose in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- the region known in the present day as the northern <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. These city-states were centers of scholarship, sorcery, and governance, establishing the cultural and intellectual foundations upon which all subsequent civilizations would build. The Eladra were the foremost scholars and sorcerers of their age, and their discoveries concerning the nature of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>, the cosmos, and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods laid the groundwork for all sorcerous and theological traditions that followed.</p>\n<h3 id=\"first-contact-with-the-ygrathen-3900-be\">First Contact with the Ygrathen (3900 BE)</h3>\n<p>Around 3900 BE, the expanding <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> encountered loose tribes of <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> inhabiting the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Meniri Mountains</a>. Initial contact between the two peoples led to brief but violent conflict. The Ygrathen -- the oldest race of Mithrapos, solitary by nature and possessed of formidable sorcerous power -- and the Eladra became enemies. This enmity would endure for millennia and culminate in wars of annihilation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"discovery-of-the-lakan-3800-be\">Discovery of the Lakan (3800 BE)</h3>\n<p>In 3800 BE, the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> discovered primitive human settlements in the fertile highlands beyond their city-states. The Eladra established trade and friendship with these peoples, introducing them to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods and the theological framework that accompanied Eladran culture. These humans adopted the name <strong><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan</a></strong> -- a designation that would persist through the ages and eventually define one of the most significant human cultures in <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-awakening-of-the-great-teacher-3200-be\">The Awakening of the Great Teacher (3200 BE)</h3>\n<p>The city-state of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Krysea</a> expanded aggressively, becoming one of the most powerful of the Eladran polities. During this expansion, the Eladra discovered a vast network of caves and tunnels beneath the city. In exploring these subterranean passages, they accidentally awakened a slumbering <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Chemosh</a> (<a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Khepri</a>) Hierarch -- a being of immense age and power who had lain dormant beneath Krysea for an unknown span of time.</p>\n<p>Calling himself the <strong>Great Teacher</strong>, the Hierarch introduced the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> gods to the Eladra of Krysea. Where the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods offered law, order, and transcendence, the Cthonic gods offered power, transformation, and the allure of forbidden knowledge. The Great Teacher&#39;s arrival marked a turning point in Eladran civilization -- a spiritual fissure that would widen over the centuries into an unbridgeable chasm.</p>\n<h3 id=\"excavation-of-the-ruins-below-krysea-3100-be\">Excavation of the Ruins Below Krysea (3100 BE)</h3>\n<p>At the instruction of the Great Teacher, the Eladra of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Krysea</a> began a secret excavation of the ancient ruins that lay beneath the city. These ruins predated even the Eladran city-states, and their origins remain a subject of speculation and dread. The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> gods were worshipped as mystery cults during this period -- secretive, initiatory, and confined to a small number of devoted adherents. The seeds of what would become the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> were planted in these excavations.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-rise-of-eolande-and-the-conquest-of-humans-3000-be\">The Rise of Eolande and the Conquest of Humans (3000 BE)</h3>\n<p>The Eladran general <strong><a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a></strong>, tutored personally by the Great Teacher in matters of strategy, sorcery, and statecraft, began conquering nearby human populations. This marked the first systematic subjugation of humans by the Eladra -- a departure from the earlier pattern of trade and friendship. The Great Teacher&#39;s influence was transforming Eladran culture from within, replacing its older values of scholarship and cooperation with ambition, domination, and the pursuit of power.</p>\n<h3 id=\"transmogrification-and-the-creation-of-monsters-2800-be\">Transmogrification and the Creation of Monsters (2800 BE)</h3>\n<p>By 2800 BE, increasing wealth and influence flowed into the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> cults of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Krysea</a>. The Great Teacher and his acolytes began exploring <strong>transmogrification</strong> -- the practice of splicing humans with chaotic energies drawn from the <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a> to create monsters. These experiments represented a fundamental violation of the natural order, and their products were creatures of terrible power and suffering. Transmogrification would become one of the defining practices of Cthonic sorcery and one of the most reviled arts in the history of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-first-crescent-rebellion-and-the-creation-of-the-thune-2700-be\">The First Crescent Rebellion and the Creation of the Thune (2700 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> cults within Eladran society were appalled by the transmogrifiers and their monstrous creations. Attempts to suppress the Cthonic cults led to the martyrdom of Cthonic cultists, which paradoxically increased the movement&#39;s appeal and captured more worshippers for the Cthonic cause.</p>\n<p>Simultaneously, the <strong>First Crescent Rebellion</strong> erupted among the subjugated human populations. This uprising -- the first organized human resistance against Eladran rule -- convinced the Eladran nobility of the need for a purpose-built warrior caste. The result was the creation of the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> -- slave soldiers forged through sorcery and designed for war. The Thune were not born but made, and their creation marked a further step in the moral descent of Eladran civilization.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-argollean-empire-declared-2600-be\">The Argollean Empire Declared (2600 BE)</h3>\n<p>By 2600 BE, open <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> worship had become commonplace throughout Eladran society. Construction of the <strong>Great Temple of the Awakening</strong> began in <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Krysea</a>, a monumental edifice dedicated to the Cthonic gods and the Great Teacher&#39;s vision of spiritual transformation. The enslaved servitor races and the decadent pleasures offered by Cthonic worship seduced the Eladran nobility, who converted in increasing numbers.</p>\n<p>Eladran warlords led armies of <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> to conquer the entirety of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> and the territories beyond. The <strong><a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a></strong> -- the First Empire -- was formally declared. Construction of the <strong>Grand Cthonic Temple</strong> in the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> began, establishing the subterranean complex that would grow over the centuries into one of the most dangerous and significant sites in all of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<p>In this same period, the <strong>Bitter War</strong> erupted. A powerful <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> alliance, influenced by <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> priests who had been driven from the Eladran city-states, sought to stop the Argollean expansion by force. The Bitter War would rage for centuries and consume untold lives.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-burning-of-the-empyrean-temples-2400-be\">The Burning of the Empyrean Temples (2400 BE)</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> disciples of <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a> burned <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> temples across the Argollean Empire and slaughtered their worshippers. This campaign of religious persecution marked the effective destruction of organized Empyrean worship within Argollean territory and the triumph of Cthonic faith among the Eladra.</p>\n<p>On the military front, the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> won several significant battles against the Argolleans during this period, though at catastrophic cost to their own forces. The relentless violence of the Bitter War drove a rise in the worship of <a href=\"#/page/dirgion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dirgion</a>, the Cthonic god of death and entropy. Construction of the <strong>Doom Temple of Dirgion</strong> began.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-thune-ascendant-2300-be\">The Thune Ascendant (2300 BE)</h3>\n<p>The transmogrifiers created new, deadlier versions of the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> slave-soldiers, incorporating lessons learned from centuries of warfare. The tide of the Bitter War turned decisively in Argollean favor. The Argollean economy became entirely dependent on servitor races and enslaved populations to sustain itself -- a structural weakness that would eventually prove fatal. During this period, the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan</a> -- the human peoples who had once been friends and trading partners of the Eladra -- converted to <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> worship, completing the spiritual transformation of the region.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-crushing-of-the-ygrathen-2100-be\">The Crushing of the Ygrathen (2100 BE)</h3>\n<p>Under the command of the Eladran warlord <strong>Marcan</strong>, the Argollean armies crushed the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> alliance and razed their ancestral homeland. The war that had raged for five centuries ended in genocide. Most Ygrathen were killed; the survivors were driven into hiding in the remote and inaccessible places of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, where their descendants remain to this day -- solitary, formidable, and implacable in their hatred.</p>\n<p>Construction of the <strong>Hallowed Halls of Heroes</strong> began in <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Krysea</a> to commemorate the victory. The Great Teacher, his work apparently complete, entered <strong>cryostasis</strong> in the <strong>Secret Sepulcher</strong> deep within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- a chamber whose location was known to only a handful of the most senior Cthonic priests.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-entombment-of-marcan-2000-be\">The Entombment of Marcan (2000 BE)</h3>\n<p>The warlord <strong>Marcan</strong>, conqueror of the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a>, was interred in the <strong>Great King Tomb</strong> within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. His tomb became one of the most revered sites in Argollean culture -- a monument to military glory and the apex of Eladran imperial power.</p>\n<h3 id=\"orthanach-the-mummy-lord-1800-be\">Orthanach the Mummy Lord (1800 BE)</h3>\n<p>The Eladran hierophant <strong>Orthanach</strong> became the first Argollean to successfully transform himself into a <strong>mummy lord</strong> -- achieving a form of undead immortality through Cthonic ritual. Upon his death, Orthanach was interred in the <strong>Secret Tomb</strong> within the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>, accompanied by his wife <strong>Sonya</strong> and his guard <strong>Cassair</strong>. The creation of a mummy lord represented the pinnacle of Cthonic necromantic achievement and a further step into the darkness that was consuming Eladran civilization from within.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-fall-of-argolle-1700-be\">The Fall of Argolle (1700 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> population had been in decline for centuries, their culture increasingly decadent, their birthrate falling, their vitality consumed by Cthonic excess. The <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> -- the slave-soldiers who had fought and won the Empire&#39;s wars -- rose in rebellion. The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan</a>, seeing an opportunity, joined the uprising.</p>\n<p>The Thune slaughtered the Argolleans and <strong>razed <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Krysea</a></strong> to the ground. The city that had been the heart of the First Empire was reduced to rubble, its temples pulled down, its libraries burned, its inhabitants put to the sword. The Eladra who survived the destruction were scattered, many eventually transforming into the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> as they delved deeper into chaotic energies in their desperation to survive. The Lakan retreated into the wastes, their role in the rebellion earning them nothing but further suffering.</p>\n<p>The fall of Argolle was not a single catastrophic event but the culmination of centuries of internal decay -- the inevitable end of a civilization that had traded its soul for power and its future for pleasure.</p>\n<h3 id=\"thune-dominion-1400-be\">Thune Dominion (1400 BE)</h3>\n<p>By 1400 BE, the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> had conquered much of the former Argollean holdings and established their own brutal dominion, subjugating the human populations who had so recently been their allies. The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a>-worshipping humans known as the <strong><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Masserai</a></strong> (or <strong><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a></strong>) functioned as an upper caste within Thune society, assisting in the administration and enforcement of human enslavement. The cycle of subjugation continued -- only the masters had changed.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-rise-of-the-massar-1075-be\">The Rise of the Massar (1075 BE)</h3>\n<p>In 1075 BE, the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a> overthrew their <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> overlords and established their own sorcerer-empire. Over the next five hundred years, the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> expanded steadily, building a civilization sustained by the very sorcerous traditions the Massar had inherited from the Argolleans.</p>\n<h3 id=\"massar-sorcery-unleashed-1070-be\">Massar Sorcery Unleashed (1070 BE)</h3>\n<p>Almost immediately after seizing power, the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a> uncovered ancient <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> secrets -- including the arts of <strong>transmogrification</strong>, <strong>demon-binding</strong>, and <strong>necromancy</strong>. Drawing on these forbidden traditions, the Massar created the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> -- hybrid creatures fused from human and animal stock through chaotic sorcery -- to fuel their war machine. The Beastmen would become one of the most enduring and devastating legacies of Massaran rule, persisting as a threat to civilization long after the empire that created them had fallen.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-empyrean-war-684-652-be\">The Empyrean War (684--652 BE)</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;The Prophet Enador did not bring the gods to man -- he reminded man of the gods they had buried beneath centuries of silence and sin.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Savron</strong>, Imperial Historian, <em>Collected Commentaries</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In 684 BE, the <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> emerged as one of the most transformative figures in the history of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. Enador received the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> -- the sacred texts that would become the foundation of <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith and the moral and legal framework of the civilization that followed. Along with the Measure and the Scale, Enador recovered the <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a>, the ancient Argollean grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality -- the formulae that would be systematized as <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> by later scholars.</p>\n<p>Enador preached the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith across the subjugated lands, gathering followers and igniting a spiritual revolution. Enador and the general <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> raised an alliance of peoples against the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its sorcerer-kings. The sorcerer-king <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sebek</a> attempted to suppress the new faith, triggering the <strong>Second Crescent Rebellion</strong> -- an echo of the First Crescent Rebellion that had shaken the Argollean Empire over two thousand years earlier.</p>\n<p>In 651 BE, the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> armies of the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a> were routed in a series of decisive engagements. The sorcerer-kings were hunted down and slaughtered. <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sebek</a> alone escaped, fleeing into the desert where his fate remains unknown. The Massaran Empire descended into anarchy, its power broken, its sorcerous traditions scattered but not destroyed.</p>\n<p>The victory established the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a>, a confederation of free city-states governed by a Senate, and introduced the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> as the moral and legal foundation of the new order. This was the crucible from which the future Empire would be forged.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-beastman-wars-244-219-be\">The Beastman Wars (244--219 BE)</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> -- the monstrous legacy of <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran</a> transmogrification -- had never been eradicated. In the centuries following the fall of the Massar, the beastman hordes bred, multiplied, and organized in the wilderness. By 244 BE, massive beastman hordes threatened the civilized lands of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a>, launching raids and incursions that overwhelmed local defenses.</p>\n<p>The conflict, known as the <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastman Wars</a></strong>, raged for twenty-five years. The hordes were eventually defeated by <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a> forces led by <strong>Consul Servius of Mithra</strong>, whose military leadership unified the fractious city-states into a coherent fighting force. The Beastman Wars demonstrated both the enduring danger posed by the beastmen and the necessity of unified military command -- lessons that would inform the political transformation to come.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"imperial-era\">Imperial Era</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-founding-of-the-mithrian-empire-0-17-iy\">The Founding of the Mithrian Empire (0--17 IY)</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a></strong>, claiming descent from <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a>, seized power from the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> and declared himself the first Emperor of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. He defeated loyalist Senator armies and consolidated authority under a single throne. The Senate was preserved as a deliberative body but stripped of binding legislative power.</p>\n<p>Marcus Valerian reigned from the founding until 17 IY, establishing the political, military, and administrative structures that would sustain the Empire for centuries. The founding marked the beginning of a new era -- the Imperial Year (IY) calendar -- and established <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> as the seat of power, governance, and sorcerous learning that it remains today. The <a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a> people trace their lineage directly to Bellasarius Valerian, a claimed descent that gives them an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny.</p>\n<h3 id=\"consolidation-and-the-creation-of-the-targ-17-214-iy\">Consolidation and the Creation of the Targ (17--214 IY)</h3>\n<p>The period following Marcus Valerian&#39;s death was one of consolidation, expansion, and institutional development. The Empire extended its reach, pacified its borders, and built the administrative apparatus necessary to govern a multi-ethnic, continental power.</p>\n<p>During this era, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> created the <a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">Targ</a> -- a new race, magically engineered as laborers and soldiers to serve the Empire&#39;s growing needs. The creation of the Targ echoed the Argollean creation of the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> millennia earlier -- a parallel that would not be lost on later historians. The Targ were designed to be stronger, more durable, and more obedient than human workers and warriors. They were also, crucially, regarded as property rather than people.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-reign-of-titus-valerian-the-empire-at-its-greatest-extent-215-257-iy\">The Reign of Titus Valerian: The Empire at Its Greatest Extent (215--257 IY)</h3>\n<p>Emperor <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Titus Valerian</a></strong> presided over the golden age of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Under his rule, the Empire reached its greatest territorial extent, controlling <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kesh</a>, <a href=\"#/page/shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shent</a>, <a href=\"#/page/tet\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tezerat</a>, and the vast heartlands that connected them. Trade flourished, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> expanded, and Mithrian culture and law spread to the farthest provinces. The reign of Titus Valerian represents the high-water mark of Imperial power -- the moment before the tide began to turn.</p>\n<h3 id=\"rebellions-civil-wars-and-the-targ-rebellion-258-269-iy\">Rebellions, Civil Wars, and the Targ Rebellion (258--269 IY)</h3>\n<p>The death of <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Titus Valerian</a> ushered in a period of instability. Rebellions erupted in the provinces, and civil wars fractured the Imperial core. <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kesh</a> was lost -- the first major territorial contraction since the Empire&#39;s founding.</p>\n<p>In 261 IY, the <a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">Targ</a> -- the race created by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> as laborers and soldiers -- rose in violent revolt. Their leader, known only as <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Eater</a></strong>, led a devastating campaign that reached <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> itself. The Eater sacked the capital and slew <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Antonius</a></strong>, an act of violence that shook the Empire to its foundations. The Eater&#39;s name has been preserved in infamy as one of the most feared figures in Imperial history -- a ruler whose reign was a period of madness, cruelty, and excess that tested the Empire&#39;s institutions to their breaking point.</p>\n<p>Peace was eventually brokered by <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Symander</a></strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>. Symander was a towering figure whose diplomatic skill matched his sorcerous ability. Under the terms of the settlement he negotiated, the creation of further Targ was <strong>permanently forbidden</strong>, and the existing Targ were granted full citizenship under the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>, transforming them from property into people in the eyes of Imperial law. Symander also offered the Targ citizenship and lands of their own -- a settlement that averted further bloodshed but left deep scars on both sides.</p>\n<p>The rebellion remains one of the most traumatic events in Imperial history. <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Antonius</a> himself represents a particular kind of failure -- not madness but weakness. Under Antonius, the power of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> had grown unchecked, and the Emperor became little more than a figurehead, rubber-stamping the decisions of ambitious senators and their factional allies. The concentration of power in the Senate led to rampant corruption, political paralysis, and a neglect of the Empire&#39;s military and provincial defenses -- conditions that allowed the Targ Rebellion to escalate to the point of sacking the capital itself.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-year-of-three-emperors-270-iy\">The Year of Three Emperors (270 IY)</h3>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;We traded madness for cowardice, then cowardice for coin. Of all our emperors, it was the one who ruled for 87 days who showed the greatest strength.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Claudius Decimus</strong>, on accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The mad Emperor <strong><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a></strong> of House Valerian was assassinated by his own sister, ending years of increasingly erratic and cruel rule. In the power vacuum that followed, the scholar <strong><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">Numerius</a></strong> was briefly installed as Emperor. Numerius&#39;s reign lasted a mere <strong>87 days</strong> before he was murdered -- a span so brief and so poignant that it has become a byword for the Empire&#39;s inability to sustain principled leadership.</p>\n<p>The resulting chaos was compounded when the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Custodians</a> -- the Imperial bodyguard -- auctioned the office of Emperor to the highest bidder. The grotesque spectacle of the throne being sold like merchandise at market laid bare the depth of the Empire&#39;s institutional rot. <strong>Senator Quintus Soladius</strong> purchased the title, but his reign was immediately contested.</p>\n<p><strong>Governor Persinius Septimus</strong>, commanding loyal legions in the provinces, marched on <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> to claim the throne by force. The resulting civil war, known as the <strong>War of Three Emperors</strong>, drew in multiple Great Houses and threatened to tear the Empire apart.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian</a></strong> ultimately emerged as the power behind the resolution, backing <strong><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a></strong> as a compromise candidate. Claudius Decimus triumphed, establishing <strong>House Decimus</strong> as the ruling dynasty. The Valerian claim to the throne was permanently broken, though House Valerian retained its prestige and wealth.</p>\n<p>Claudius Decimus is one of the most paradoxical figures in Imperial history -- an Emperor who is remembered as one of the most courageous and principled leaders the Empire has ever known. His own words upon accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate reveal a man acutely aware of the Empire&#39;s long decline: a trajectory from madness (The Eater and Aurex) to cowardice (Antonius and his successors) to the naked pursuit of wealth and power. What Claudius Decimus accomplished in his brief reign, and the circumstances of his eventual removal from power, remain subjects of intense historical debate.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-dog-soldier-war-272-291-iy\">The Dog Soldier War (272--291 IY)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>don&#39;Kolani</strong> -- the forest-dwelling branch of the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> people -- launched a prolonged guerrilla war against Imperial occupation of their ancestral lands. The conflict, known as the <a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a>, dragged on for nearly two decades and proved extraordinarily costly for the Empire.</p>\n<p>Peace was eventually brokered by <a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a>, one of the most capable military commanders in recent Imperial history. The peace treaty included a provision of enormous strategic significance: the Empire gained access to <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, reducing the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s exclusive importance in warfare and contributing to the ongoing transformation of Imperial military doctrine.</p>\n<p>The treaty also led to the formal incorporation of Kolani warriors into the Imperial military structure, most notably through the establishment of the <a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a> -- a formation composed entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors who serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-mithrian-marines-297-iy\">The Mithrian Marines (297 IY)</h3>\n<p>In 297 IY, the <strong><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a></strong> were formally established as a distinct branch of the Imperial military. Their creation was a direct response to the proliferation of sorcery on the battlefield -- a growing threat that conventional infantry formations were ill-equipped to counter. The Marines were trained and equipped specifically to operate in environments saturated with hostile magic, combining conventional martial discipline with counter-sorcerous tactics. Their formation marked a significant evolution in Imperial military doctrine and an acknowledgment that the age of the sole sorcerer-as-weapon-of-war was giving way to a more complex and integrated approach to combat.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-fall-of-shent-298-iy\">The Fall of Shent (298 IY)</h3>\n<p>In 298 IY, barbarian tribes invaded and conquered <a href=\"#/page/shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shent</a>, stripping the Empire of another major province. The loss of Shent -- following the earlier loss of <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kesh</a> -- represented a further contraction of Imperial territory and a further blow to Imperial prestige. The Empire was shrinking, and its capacity to defend its periphery was visibly deteriorating.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-heresy-of-the-flame-304-iy\">The Heresy of the Flame (304 IY)</h3>\n<p>A rogue High Priest in <a href=\"#/page/corcanoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Corcanoa</a> declared a new interpretation of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith, challenging the authority of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> hierarchy. The resulting schism threatened to fracture the religious order of the Empire.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Burnished Scale</a> -- the militant arm of the Thousand Temples -- launched an unauthorized purge against the heretical movement and its sympathizers. The violence exceeded any mandate the Temples had been given, and when Lord-Penitent <a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lucan Vargas</a> of the Burnished Scale proved unwilling to cease operations, he was assassinated by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a> on orders from the throne. The incident established a clear precedent: the Emperor&#39;s authority supersedes the Temples&#39; in matters of internal security.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-tet-rebellion-the-second-crescent-rebellion-342-iy\">The Tet Rebellion: The Second Crescent Rebellion (342 IY)</h3>\n<p>In 342 IY, the <a href=\"#/page/tet\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tet</a> people rebelled against Imperial rule and gained their independence in what became known as the <strong>Second Crescent Rebellion</strong> -- the third uprising to bear the name &quot;Crescent Rebellion&quot; in the long history of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, following the First Crescent Rebellion of 2700 BE and the rebellion during the Empyrean War. The Tet&#39;s successful secession further contracted Imperial territory and demonstrated that the Empire&#39;s grip on its provinces was weakening.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-death-of-usil-and-the-storms-of-348-iy\">The Death of Usil and the Storms of 348 IY</h3>\n<p>In 348 IY, the sorcerer-kingdom of <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoa</a> resumed hostilities against the Empire. The sorcerer-king <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Abbu-Marru</a></strong> disappeared under mysterious circumstances -- whether killed, fled, or consumed by his own sorcery, none can say.</p>\n<p>Simultaneously, violent storms and earthquakes of unprecedented ferocity wracked <strong>nearly every province</strong> of the Empire, causing widespread destruction, loss of life, and panic. The event became known as the <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Death of Usil</a></strong>.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> attributed the catastrophe to fluctuations in the gnostic patterns that govern the metaphysical reality of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> -- a scientific explanation rooted in their understanding of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> and the axioms that underpin reality. The priests of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faiths offered a starkly different explanation: an Empyrean god had died. <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Usil</a>, they claimed, had perished -- and the earthquakes and storms were the death throes of a divine being, the cosmos itself convulsing in grief and upheaval. This theological interpretation was rejected by the Academy but embraced by the faithful, and the event became a defining moment in the ongoing tension between sorcerous and religious authority within the Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-burning-of-erenthis-at-thornasse-349-iy\">The Burning of Erenthis at Thornasse (349 IY)</h3>\n<p>In 349 IY, <strong><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a></strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> -- known as <strong>Cynar of the Black Tree</strong> -- burned the city of <strong><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a></strong> at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a>, annihilating it in an act of sorcerous devastation that horrified even the Empire&#39;s own commanders. The destruction of Erenthis broke the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> Confederation, and many of the surviving Avari were enslaved. The event demonstrated the terrifying destructive potential of high-level sorcery and foreshadowed the catastrophe that would follow at <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Blue Mound</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-lakan-campaigns-and-the-battle-of-blue-mound-360-368-iy\">The Lakan Campaigns and the Battle of Blue Mound (360--368 IY)</h3>\n<p>The Empire launched a major military expedition into <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> territory, seeking to pacify the warlike <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan</a> tribes and extend Imperial control. The campaigns dragged on for eight years, culminating in the catastrophic <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a>.</p>\n<p>The battle pitted Imperial forces, led by <strong><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a></strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> -- <strong>Cynar of the Black Tree</strong> -- against the forces of <strong><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a></strong>, a powerful Lakan sorcerer who commanded an army of considerable size and ferocity. The climax of the conflict came when High Mage Cynar and Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye engaged in a direct sorcerous duel -- a confrontation of such magnitude that it escalated beyond all control. The cataclysmic energies unleashed by the two combatants annihilated both armies entirely, leaving the battlefield a blasted and lifeless wasteland. Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived.</p>\n<p>The Battle of Blue Mound had profound consequences for the Empire&#39;s approach to warfare. It demonstrated that the deployment of high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was not merely dangerous but potentially suicidal, and it prompted significant reforms in military doctrine. The Empire subsequently adopted a model of combined arms warfare, integrating squad mages into conventional military formations rather than relying on individual sorcerers to decide the outcome of battles. The Empire retreated to a defensive posture in Lakandi territory, constructing a line of border forts that marks the current frontier.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-second-war-of-morn-371-iy\">The Second War of Morn (371 IY)</h3>\n<p>In 371 IY, the <strong>Second War of <a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">Morn</a></strong> erupted. At its center was a cult of <strong>Lycandites</strong> -- fanatical worshippers of <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lycandaeus</a> the Living God</strong>, a <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> tyrant who had seized control of a significant territory in Morn and declared himself a deity. Lycandaeus practiced both <strong>transmogrification</strong> and <strong>demon-binding</strong> -- the twin abominations that had defined the darkest chapters of Argollean and Massaran sorcery -- and his forces included creatures of horrifying power.</p>\n<p>The Imperial <strong>14th Army</strong> was shattered in the initial engagements, suffering catastrophic losses against Lycandaeus&#39;s sorcerously enhanced forces. The situation appeared desperate until the <strong>8th Marine Company</strong>, led by <strong>Captain <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Pollimer Motts</a></strong>, was deployed. Captain Motts and his Marines fought their way to Lycandaeus himself and destroyed the Ygrathen tyrant, breaking the power of the Lycandite cult and ending the war.</p>\n<p>The Second War of Morn demonstrated both the enduring threat posed by the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> and the effectiveness of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a> as a counter-sorcerous force. Captain Pollimer Motts became one of the most celebrated military figures of the current era.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-sacking-of-crossings-377-iy\">The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY)</h3>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;Crossings did not fall in a day. It fell in the silence of senators, in the turning away of eyes, in the fortunes of the governor rising even as the gates were breached.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Senator Cassius</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> in 377 IY was one of the most devastating and consequential events in recent Imperial history. A massive <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> horde emerged from the wilderness and descended on the town of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, razing it to the ground.</p>\n<p>As Senator Cassius&#39;s damning words make clear, the sacking was not the result of an overwhelming external threat alone. It was enabled by the corruption, negligence, and complicity of Imperial officials -- senators who looked the other way, governors who enriched themselves while their defenses crumbled. The fall of Crossings was a failure of the Empire&#39;s institutions as much as it was a failure of its armies.</p>\n<p>The consequences of the Sacking of Crossings were immediate and far-reaching. The destruction of this settlement led directly to the collapse of Imperial authority in the surrounding region, giving rise to the <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a> economy</strong> -- a brutal system born of Emperor <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a>&#39;s Imperial scalp bounty on beastmen. The bounty unleashed a wave of mercenaries, deserters, and killers into the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> to hunt them. While beastman activity near settled areas has decreased, the influx of violent fortune-seekers has created new and terrible problems for the frontier provinces. The Backlands descend into their current lawless and anarchic state as a direct result of the vacuum left by the fall of Crossings -- a frontier region where Imperial law is a distant memory and survival is the only currency that matters.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-recall-of-the-garrisons-378-iy\">The Recall of the Garrisons (378 IY)</h3>\n<p>In 378 IY, the Emperor recalled the frontier garrisons to fight the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> raiders threatening the Imperial heartland. The provinces -- already strained, already bleeding -- were left defenseless. The recall was a strategic decision born of desperation: the Skiothan threat was existential, and the resources to fight on two fronts simultaneously no longer existed. But the consequences for the frontier were catastrophic. Senators plotted openly in the corridors of <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, and civil war loomed on the horizon.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-present-day-380-iy\">The Present Day (380 IY)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> endures, but it is an empire under strain. Emperor <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> rules from <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, facing threats on multiple fronts: <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> raiders on the western frontier, lingering unrest in <a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">Morn</a>, and the ever-present political maneuvering of the Great Houses. The proliferation of sorcerous knowledge beyond the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s control, the corruption of the Senate, the restlessness of the provinces, and the persistent threats along its borders all test the Empire&#39;s capacity to survive.</p>\n<p>The lessons of history -- the fall of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, the madness of <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Eater</a> and <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a>, the weakness of <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Antonius</a>, the brief courage of <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a>, and the catastrophe of <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- weigh heavily on those who study the past and fear that the patterns of decline may be repeating themselves.</p>\n<p>Mithrapos remains what it has always been: a cradle and a coffin, a boneyard of Empires.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"chronological-reference\">Chronological Reference</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Year</th>\n<th>Event</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>4100 BE</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Eladra</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3900 BE</td>\n<td>Eladra encounter [[Ygrathen</span> in the <span class=\"dead-link\">races-and-cultures</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3800 BE</td>\n<td>Eladra discover [[lakandi</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3200 BE</td>\n<td>[[crossings</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3100 BE</td>\n<td>Secret excavation of ruins below [[crossings</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3000 BE</td>\n<td>General [[eolande</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2800 BE</td>\n<td>Transmogrification experiments begin; splicing humans with chaotic energies</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2700 BE</td>\n<td>First Crescent Rebellion; [[Thune</span> created as slave soldiers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2600 BE</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">argollean-empire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2400 BE</td>\n<td>Disciples of [[Bel</span> burn Empyrean temples; worship of <a href=\"#/page/dirgion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dirgion</a> rises</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2300 BE</td>\n<td>New Thune variants created; Bitter War turns in Argollean favor; <span class=\"dead-link\">lakandi</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2100 BE</td>\n<td>Warlord Marcan crushes [[Ygrathen</span> alliance; Great Teacher enters cryostasis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2000 BE</td>\n<td>Marcan interred in Great King Tomb in <span class=\"dead-link\">the-nethercity</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1800 BE</td>\n<td>Hierophant Orthanach becomes first mummy lord; interred in Secret Tomb</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1700 BE</td>\n<td>Fall of [[the-backlands</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1400 BE</td>\n<td>Thune dominion; [[massar</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1075 BE</td>\n<td>[[Massar</span> overthrow Thune; establish sorcerer-empire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1070 BE</td>\n<td>Massar uncover <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> secrets; create <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>684 BE</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">enador</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>652 BE</td>\n<td>[[massaran-empire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>651 BE</td>\n<td>Massar armies routed; sorcerer-kings slaughtered; Sebek escapes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>244--219 BE</td>\n<td>[[history-of-mithrapos</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>0 IY</td>\n<td>[[marcus-valerian</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17 IY</td>\n<td>Death of Marcus Valerian; consolidation era begins</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17--214 IY</td>\n<td>Imperial consolidation; [[imperial-academy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>215--257 IY</td>\n<td>Emperor [[history-of-mithrapos</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>258--269 IY</td>\n<td>Rebellions and civil wars; [[history-of-mithrapos</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>270 IY</td>\n<td>Year of Three Emperors; [[claudius-decimus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>272--291 IY</td>\n<td>[[dog-soldier-war</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>297 IY</td>\n<td>[[mithrian-marines</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>298 IY</td>\n<td>Barbarian tribes conquer [[shenti</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>304 IY</td>\n<td>[[burnished-scale</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>342 IY</td>\n<td>[[Tet</span> rebel; gain independence (Second Crescent Rebellion)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>348 IY</td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrian Empire</span></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Krysea</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Titus Valerian</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">Targ</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Eater</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Antonius</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">Numerius</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Symander</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lycandaeus</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Pollimer Motts</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lucan Vargas</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Abbu-Marru</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sebek</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Chemosh</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Khepri</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dirgion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dirgion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Usil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastman Wars</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Death of Usil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Marines</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kesh</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shent</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tet\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tezerat</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">Morn</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/corcanoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Corcanoa</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Meniri Mountains</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/burnished-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Burnished Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"kolani-munitions","title":"Kolani Munitions","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["lore","military","kolani","munitions","explosives","weapons","dog-soldier-war","darius-jute","combined-arms","imperial-academy","technology"],"html":"<h1 id=\"kolani-munitions\">Kolani Munitions</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Before the Kolani treaty, the Academy held a monopoly on battlefield destruction. After it, they held a grudge. The generals preferred explosives they could stockpile to mages they had to negotiate with.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Kolani munitions</strong> are deadly and dangerous weapons and explosives originating from the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> people. The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> gained access to these weapons through a peace treaty brokered by <strong><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a></strong>, ending the <strong>Dog Soldier War</strong> (272-291 IY). Kolani munitions are now supplied to the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian military</a> as part of their combined arms doctrine and have partially diminished the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy&#39;s</a> former monopoly on battlefield destruction.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Military weapons and explosives</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Origin</strong></td>\n<td>The <span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrian Empire&#39;s</span> history -- not through conquest, but through diplomacy. The <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> people developed weapons and explosives of extraordinary lethality, and the Empire&#39;s access to these munitions transformed its military doctrine by providing an alternative to the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy&#39;s</a> arcane capabilities for battlefield destruction.</p>\n<p>The munitions are dangerous to manufacture, transport, and deploy. They are not elegant weapons. They are instruments of destruction that do not discriminate, do not require arcane training, and do not answer to the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy&#39;s</a> institutional authority. This combination of qualities made them both invaluable to the military and deeply threatening to the Academy&#39;s position.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-dog-soldier-war-272-291-iy\">The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY)</h2>\n<p>The Dog Soldier War was a protracted conflict between the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> people, lasting nearly two decades (272-291 IY). The war demonstrated the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani&#39;s</a> capacity for sustained, effective resistance against imperial military power -- resistance that the Empire could not overcome through conventional means within an acceptable timeframe or cost.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a></strong> brokered the peace treaty that ended the conflict. The terms of this treaty included the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> supply of munitions to the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian military</a> -- a pragmatic exchange that converted a dangerous enemy into a valuable supplier. The Empire gained access to weapons it could not produce on its own; the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> gained peace, autonomy, and a permanent economic relationship with the dominant power in <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"impact-on-imperial-military-doctrine\">Impact on Imperial Military Doctrine</h2>\n<p>The introduction of Kolani munitions into the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian military</a> altered the Empire&#39;s combined arms doctrine in fundamental ways:</p>\n<h3 id=\"before-kolani-munitions\">Before Kolani Munitions</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> held a near-monopoly on battlefield destruction at scale. When the military needed fortifications reduced, formations shattered, or terrain reshaped, they required Academy-trained <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">mages</a> -- specialists whose training, institutional loyalty, and political interests were controlled by the Academy rather than the military chain of command.</p>\n<p>This monopoly gave the Academy extraordinary political leverage. Generals who needed arcane support had to negotiate with an institution that had its own agenda, its own priorities, and its own price.</p>\n<h3 id=\"after-kolani-munitions\">After Kolani Munitions</h3>\n<p>Kolani munitions provided the military with an alternative source of destructive capability -- one that could be manufactured, stockpiled, transported, and deployed without the Academy&#39;s involvement or permission. Explosives do not require years of arcane training. They do not have institutional loyalties. They do not negotiate.</p>\n<p>The Academy&#39;s monopoly on battlefield destruction was not eliminated but was <strong>partially diminished</strong>. The military now has options it did not previously possess, and the Academy&#39;s bargaining position has weakened accordingly. This shift in the balance of power between the military and the Academy remains a source of institutional tension.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">kolani</a> -- The people who developed the munitions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Darius Jute</a> -- The general who brokered the peace treaty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution whose monopoly was diminished</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that acquired the munitions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> -- The military that deploys them</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">sorcery</a> -- The arcane alternative the munitions partially replaced</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-marines\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-marines</a> -- Another specialist element of Mithrian combined arms doctrine</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"kolani","title":"Kolani","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","kolani","naming","human","tribal","ton-kolani","don-kolani","dog-soldier-war","kolani-irregulars","munitions"],"html":"<h1 id=\"kolani\">Kolani</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Kolani</strong> are a diverse tribal people divided into two principal groups defined by their ancestral homeland and way of life. Their culture is deeply spiritual, rooted in ancestral memory and the natural world, and their martial traditions have proven invaluable to the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> -- but only after decades of bloody conflict.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-two-peoples\">The Two Peoples</h2>\n<h3 id=\"tonkolani-people-of-the-plains\">ton&#39;Kolani -- People of the Plains</h3>\n<p>The <strong>ton&#39;Kolani</strong> are seminomadic pastoralists and warriors who roam the vast grasslands and plains. They are renowned horsemen, and their light cavalry tactics -- swift raids, feigned retreats, encirclement -- have confounded heavier Imperial formations for generations. The ton&#39;Kolani are the backbone of the <a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a>, the Empire&#39;s most effective irregular warfare formation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"donkolani-people-of-the-forest\">don&#39;Kolani -- People of the Forest</h3>\n<p>The <strong>don&#39;Kolani</strong> are settled communities with deep ties to the <strong>Great Kolan Forest</strong>. Their way of life is rooted in the woodland -- they are hunters, trappers, herbalists, and woodworkers whose knowledge of the forest is encyclopedic. The don&#39;Kolani launched the <a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a> against Imperial occupation, a guerrilla campaign that demonstrated the devastating effectiveness of woodland warfare against conventional armies.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>Kolani culture is deeply spiritual, with the natural world and ancestral memory occupying central roles in daily life. The village seer is among the most important figures in any Kolani community, serving as spiritual intermediary, naming authority, and keeper of tribal memory.</p>\n<h3 id=\"totemic-titles\">Totemic Titles</h3>\n<p><strong>Honorific and totemic titles</strong> play an important role in Kolani culture. These titles, earned through deeds of valor, spiritual achievement, or community service, <strong>can replace a Kolani&#39;s given name entirely</strong>. A warrior who earns a totemic title may be known by that title alone for the rest of their life, their birth name set aside in favor of the identity their deeds have earned them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Kolani names are <strong>bestowed by the village seer</strong>, who invokes spirits, natural forces, and ancestral memory to determine the name that best suits the child. This naming ceremony is a sacred ritual, and the name given is believed to carry spiritual significance and power. The name is not chosen arbitrarily -- it is divined, revealed through communion with forces beyond ordinary human perception.</p>\n<p><strong>Clan names serve as surnames</strong>, tying the individual to their broader kinship group. A Kolani introduced by clan name is understood to carry the weight and reputation of that entire kinship network.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"historical-events\">Historical Events</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-dog-soldier-war-272-291-iy\">The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Dog Soldier War</strong> was a prolonged guerrilla campaign launched by the <strong>don&#39;Kolani</strong> against Imperial occupation of their ancestral lands in the Great Kolan Forest. The conflict dragged on for nearly two decades and proved extraordinarily costly for the Empire. The don&#39;Kolani&#39;s mastery of woodland warfare -- ambushes, traps, hit-and-run raids, the exploitation of terrain the Imperial forces could not navigate -- made conventional military operations nearly impossible.</p>\n<p>Peace was eventually brokered by <strong><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">General Darius Jute</a></strong>, one of the most capable military commanders in recent Imperial history. The peace treaty included a provision of enormous strategic significance: the Empire gained access to <strong>Kolani munitions and weaponry</strong> -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, reducing the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy&#39;s</a> exclusive importance in warfare and contributing to the ongoing transformation of Imperial military doctrine.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-kolani-irregulars\">The Kolani Irregulars</h3>\n<p>The peace brokered by General Darius Jute also led to the formal incorporation of Kolani warriors into the Imperial military structure. The <strong><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a></strong> are a notable military formation composed <strong>entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors</strong>. They serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry, and their unconventional tactics have proven invaluable in the Empire&#39;s frontier campaigns. The Kolani Irregulars represent one of the most successful examples of integrating conquered peoples into the Imperial military -- a formation whose effectiveness derives precisely from the cultural traditions the Empire once tried to suppress.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that fought and then integrated the Kolani</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> -- The military that includes the Kolani Irregulars</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The Dog Soldier War in broader context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution whose monopoly Kolani munitions challenge</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"lakan-campaigns","title":"The Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY)","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["event","history","warfare","lakandi","imperial-academy","border-forts","military-campaign"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-lakan-campaigns-360-368-iy\">The Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY)</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Lakan Campaigns</strong> (360-368 IY) were a major Imperial military expedition into <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> territory, launched with the goal of pacifying the warlike Lakandi tribes and extending Imperial control. The campaigns dragged on for eight years and culminated in the catastrophic <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> -- a sorcerous cataclysm that annihilated both armies and killed the commanders of both sides. The Empire retreated, erected a line of border forts, and abandoned its ambitions of conquest in the region.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> are a warlike people whose territory lies beyond the Empire&#39;s established frontier. Their sorcerous traditions -- the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi Binding Tradition</a>, rooted in Veil contact and demon-binding -- made them a persistent concern for Imperial strategists. The decision to launch a major campaign against them reflected both strategic ambition and the confidence of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> in its sorcerous superiority.</p>\n<p>The campaigns were backed by devastating magical firepower. The Academy deployed its most powerful battle-sorcerers, including <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a>, in support of conventional military forces. The expectation was that Imperial sorcery would overwhelm the Lakandi&#39;s more primitive magical traditions and deliver a decisive victory.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-campaigns\">The Campaigns</h2>\n<p>Imperial armies marched deep into Lakandi territory over the course of eight years. The campaigns were costly, grinding affairs. The Lakandi proved far more formidable than expected:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Their warriors were fierce, disciplined, and intimately familiar with the terrain</li>\n<li>Their sorcerers -- practitioners of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi Binding Tradition</a> -- wielded Veil-born power that, while different from the Academy&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, was no less dangerous</li>\n<li>Their resistance was relentless. The Lakandi fought not for territory or resources but for survival and honor, and they would not submit</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The campaigns consumed men, money, and magical resources at a rate that tested the Empire&#39;s capacity to sustain a distant war. Support for the expedition eroded over time as the costs mounted and decisive victory remained elusive.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-battle-of-blue-mound\">The Battle of Blue Mound</h2>\n<p>The campaigns culminated in the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a>, where Imperial forces under <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> engaged the army of <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a>. The climactic sorcerous duel between the two combatants escalated beyond all control, unleashing cataclysmic energies that annihilated both armies entirely. Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived. The battlefield was left a blasted wasteland.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"aftermath\">Aftermath</h2>\n<h3 id=\"imperial-retreat\">Imperial Retreat</h3>\n<p>The destruction of the entire expeditionary force at Blue Mound ended the Empire&#39;s campaign immediately and permanently. There was no army left to continue the fight. The Empire retreated to a defensive posture, constructing a line of <strong>border forts</strong> along the frontier that marks the current boundary between Imperial territory and Lakandi lands. These forts remain manned and maintained to this day, a permanent reminder of the campaign&#39;s failure.</p>\n<h3 id=\"lakandi-response\">Lakandi Response</h3>\n<p>The Lakandi were broken by the campaigns but remained <strong>unbowed</strong>. The loss of their army and their Warlock King at Blue Mound was devastating, but the simultaneous destruction of the Imperial army gave them a claim to victory of a different kind. The Lakandi vowed revenge against the Empire -- a vow that the border forts are designed to deter.</p>\n<h3 id=\"military-reform\">Military Reform</h3>\n<p>The Lakan Campaigns and the Battle of Blue Mound prompted the most significant reform in Imperial military doctrine since the founding of the Empire. The deployment of individual high-level sorcerers as decisive weapons was abandoned in favor of <strong>combined arms warfare</strong>, integrating squad mages into conventional formations. This shift reduced the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s singular importance in warfare.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> -- the catastrophic final battle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> -- the Imperial sorcerer who died at Blue Mound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a> -- the Lakandi sorcerer who died at Blue Mound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi Binding Tradition</a> -- the sorcerous tradition of the Lakandi</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a> -- institution whose doctrine was reshaped</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Military</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"lakandi-binding-tradition","title":"The Lakandi Binding Tradition","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["lakandi","binding","cthonic","demons","veil","corruption","elvora","greta","jarn-murky-eye","cynar","warlock-king","blue-mound","magic","tradition"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-lakandi-binding-tradition\">The Lakandi Binding Tradition</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Lakandi binding tradition</strong> is the practice by which <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> practitioners engage directly with demonic entities, spirits, and Beyond-beings -- not through petition, worship, or prayer, but through <strong>binding, contest, and mutual obligation</strong>. Imperial scholars classify it as <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> demon worship. This classification is not entirely wrong, but it is not entirely right.</p>\n<p>The Lakandi do <strong>not</strong> merely petition demonic powers. They <strong>bind</strong> them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-essential-tradition\">The Essential Tradition</h2>\n<p>The Lakandi binding tradition is, in its essential nature, the same tradition that the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> practiced -- but at a vastly lower scale. The Elvora went all the way. They bound something unbindable, and the cost was total: females rendered barren, males rendered immortal, eyes turned black, civilization destroyed. The Elvora are the cautionary tale, the warning against ambition unchecked by wisdom.</p>\n<p>The Lakandi operate at the <strong>individual scale</strong>. Where the Elvora attempted to bind powers that could reshape civilizations, the Lakandi engage with individual demons, spirits, and entities from beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>. The scale is smaller. The risks are more contained. The costs are personal rather than civilizational. But the essential mechanism is the same: a mortal practitioner tears open the Veil, reaches through, contacts an entity, and enters into an arrangement.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-process-of-binding\">The Process of Binding</h2>\n<p>The binding process follows a consistent pattern, though the specifics vary by practitioner, entity, and circumstance:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>The practitioner tears open the Veil.</strong> This is not a metaphor. The <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a> is the barrier between the material world and whatever lies beyond it. The Lakandi practitioner creates a breach -- temporary, controlled, but real -- through which contact with Beyond-entities becomes possible.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>The practitioner reaches the entity.</strong> Through the breach, the practitioner contacts a specific demon, spirit, or other Beyond-being. This is not summoning in the conventional sense -- the entity is not pulled into the material world. The practitioner extends their awareness, their will, and their power through the breach to meet the entity on its own terms.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>The practitioner negotiates or overpowers the entity into an arrangement.</strong> This is the critical step. The arrangement is not worship. It is not prayer. It is <strong>contest</strong> -- a negotiation conducted from a position of power (if the practitioner is strong enough) or a position of desperate need (if they are not). The result is a binding: a relationship of mutual obligation in which both parties give and both parties receive.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The binding that results is not absolute containment. It is not imprisonment in the sense that the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> are imprisoned in their cairnhouses. It is a <strong>working relationship</strong> -- volatile, dangerous, and sustained only by the practitioner&#39;s will, skill, and the terms of the original arrangement.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-key-distinction-service-vs-holding\">The Key Distinction: Service vs. Holding</h2>\n<p>The Lakandi tradition recognizes a fundamental distinction between two types of binding:</p>\n<h3 id=\"binding-in-service\">Binding in Service</h3>\n<p>In this arrangement, the practitioner is placed in <strong>service</strong> to the Cthonic power. The entity is the dominant partner. The practitioner petitions, the entity grants, and over time the practitioner becomes increasingly dependent -- a servant, a vessel, a tool. The power flows downward. The entity commands; the practitioner obeys.</p>\n<p>This is what imperial scholars imagine when they hear &quot;demon worship,&quot; and it is what many Cthonic practitioners actually practice. It is the path of least resistance: the entity is powerful, the practitioner is desperate, and submission is easier than contest.</p>\n<h3 id=\"binding-where-the-practitioner-holds\">Binding Where the Practitioner Holds</h3>\n<p>In this arrangement, the practitioner <strong>holds</strong> the entity. The practitioner is the dominant partner. The entity has been contested, compelled, or negotiated into a position where it serves the practitioner&#39;s purposes rather than its own. The power flows upward. The practitioner commands; the entity serves.</p>\n<p>This is far more difficult, far more dangerous, and far more impressive. It requires not merely power but will -- the sustained, unbroken determination to hold a being that does not want to be held, that will test the binding constantly, that will exploit any weakness or lapse in attention.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">Greta</a> of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> holds something.</strong> What she gave for it she has not said. But she holds it -- she is not in service to it. The distinction matters more than any other consideration in evaluating a Lakandi practitioner.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cost-corruption\">The Cost: Corruption</h2>\n<p>Repeated contact with the Beyond corrupts. This is the inescapable price of the Lakandi tradition. Every practitioner who tears open <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>, every binding that connects mortal will to demonic power, leaves a mark. The marks are cumulative, permanent, and visible:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eyes darkening at the iris.</strong> The most iconic sign of Lakandi practice. The iris darkens progressively with repeated Veil contact, eventually turning the eyes wholly dark. The degree of darkening reflects the depth and frequency of engagement.</li>\n<li><strong>A quality of stillness beyond patience.</strong> Not the stillness of someone waiting, but the stillness of something that has been touched by entities operating on timescales that dwarf human comprehension. The corrupted practitioner carries something of their bound entity&#39;s relationship to time -- a patience, a weight, a density of presence that is not human.</li>\n<li><strong>Awareness of things not normally visible.</strong> Perception that extends beyond the ordinary human range. Those who have torn open the Veil and reached through it carry an expanded awareness that does not fade -- an ability to perceive presences, energies, and dimensions of reality that most people never access.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Lakandi treat corruption not as failing but as the <strong>visible record of genuine engagement</strong>. To be marked is to have done something real. To be unmarked is to have risked nothing. The corruption is the credential, the proof of practice, the visible testament to a life spent engaging with powers that most people are too frightened or too prudent to touch.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-warlock-king-jarn-murky-eye\">The Warlock King: Jarn Murky-Eye</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Jarn Murky-Eye</a></strong> was the legendary Warlock King of the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> -- the greatest practitioner of the binding tradition in recorded history. His name was <strong>not metaphorical</strong>. His eyes were the color of what he had touched, what he had bound, what he had held through decades of Veil contact and demonic engagement.</p>\n<p>Jarn Murky-Eye fought <strong><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a></strong> at the <strong>Battle of Blue Mound</strong>. The result was <strong>mutual annihilation</strong> -- both the greatest Lakandi binder and the greatest Mithrian war-mage destroyed each other in a confrontation that leveled the battlefield and left nothing living within a significant radius. The Battle of Blue Mound is the definitive demonstration of what the Lakandi binding tradition can produce at its apex: a practitioner capable of meeting the Empire&#39;s most powerful war-mage on equal terms.</p>\n<p>Cynar burned the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a>. Jarn killed him for it. Neither survived the exchange.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-other-traditions\">Relationship to Other Traditions</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-elvoran-tradition\">The Elvoran Tradition</h3>\n<p>The Lakandi binding tradition is the same essential practice as the Elvoran tradition, differing only in scale. The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> bound at the civilizational level; the Lakandi bind at the individual level. The Elvora were destroyed by their ambition; the Lakandi survive by their restraint. The lesson is not that binding is wrong but that scale matters -- that there are things that should not be bound, not because binding is immoral but because the cost of binding them exceeds what any individual or civilization can pay.</p>\n<h3 id=\"imperial-classification\">Imperial Classification</h3>\n<p>Imperial scholars classify the Lakandi tradition as Cthonic demon worship. This classification captures something true -- the Lakandi do engage with <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> entities, do tear open <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>, do accumulate the marks of corruption that Cthonic contact produces. But the classification misses something essential: the Lakandi are not worshippers. They are practitioners. The difference between petitioning a god and binding a demon is the difference between kneeling and wrestling. Both involve contact with power. Only one involves submission.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-ygrathen-tradition\">The Ygrathen Tradition</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> binding tradition -- exemplified by <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a> and the cairnhouses that contain the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> -- is related to but distinct from the Lakandi tradition. The Ygrathen bind at a scale that exceeds even the Elvora: they imprisoned beings that cannot be destroyed, using structures designed to endure for millennia. The Lakandi operate at the opposite end of the spectrum -- individual practitioners binding individual entities for personal use. The traditions share a common root but have diverged enormously in scope and application.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a> -- A Lakandi practitioner who holds a bound entity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">jarn-murky-eye</a> -- The Warlock King, apex of the Lakandi tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a> -- The High Mage who killed and was killed by Jarn at Blue Mound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The corruption that marks Lakandi practitioners</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The barrier that Lakandi practitioners tear open</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> -- The civilization that practiced binding at catastrophic scale</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> -- The culture that sustains the binding tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- A Ygrathen binder operating at much larger scale</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- Entities bound by the related Ygrathen tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological framework within which binding traditions must be understood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- Where Greta practices the tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> -- The site whose destruction prompted Jarn&#39;s final battle</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"lakandi","title":"Lakandi","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","lakandi","naming","human","warrior","wasteland","cthonic","binding","demon-binding","nameless","lakan-campaigns","blue-mound","cynar","jarn-murky-eye","rebellion"],"html":"<h1 id=\"lakandi\">Lakandi</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Lakandi</strong> are a fierce and uncompromising warrior culture in which personal honor, martial prowess, and the ability to endure hardship are the measures of an individual&#39;s worth. Reclusive and warlike, they inhabit a harsh wasteland they fiercely defend against all comers -- including each other.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Lakandi have tan skin and dark hair. Their builds are lean and hardened by the unforgiving environment of their wasteland homeland -- a landscape that strips away everything unnecessary and leaves only what can survive.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Lakandi are <strong>reclusive and warlike</strong>. Their harsh wasteland homeland has shaped a culture that prizes above all else the ability to endure, to fight, and to prevail against impossible odds. The wasteland is not merely where the Lakandi live -- it is what defines them. They <strong>fiercely defend</strong> this territory, not because it is comfortable or bountiful, but because it is theirs and because the act of defending it proves their worth.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tribal-warfare-and-honor\">Tribal Warfare and Honor</h3>\n<p>Lakandi <strong>tribes war amongst themselves</strong> with a <strong>bizarre sense of honor and revenge</strong> that outsiders find nearly incomprehensible. Feuds, vendettas, and blood debts follow elaborate protocols that the Lakandi take with absolute seriousness. What appears to outsiders as senseless violence is, to the Lakandi, a carefully structured system of obligation, retaliation, and the ongoing demonstration of tribal strength.</p>\n<h3 id=\"religion\">Religion</h3>\n<p>Many Lakandi <strong>worship <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> gods, demons, and spirits</strong> rather than the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods recognized by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>. This is not mere heterodoxy -- it is a fundamentally different spiritual orientation, one that engages with the dangerous powers that dwell beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> rather than with the divine order the Empyrean tradition upholds.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-lakandi-binding-tradition\">The Lakandi Binding Tradition</h3>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a></strong> is a form of demon-binding distinct from the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> tradition but sharing the same essential mechanism. Lakandi practitioners tear open the Veil, contact demonic entities, and enter into binding arrangements -- not worship, not petition, but <strong>contest and mutual obligation</strong>. The practitioner who holds their bound entity is the dominant partner; the practitioner who serves their entity has submitted.</p>\n<p>Imperial scholars classify the Lakandi tradition as Cthonic demon worship. This classification captures something true but misses something essential: the Lakandi are not worshippers. They are practitioners. The difference between petitioning a god and binding a demon is the difference between kneeling and wrestling.</p>\n<p>Repeated contact with the Beyond <strong>corrupts</strong>. Every practitioner who tears open the Veil accumulates marks: eyes darkening at the iris, a quality of stillness beyond patience, awareness of things not normally visible. The Lakandi treat corruption not as failing but as the <strong>visible record of genuine engagement</strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Lakandi names are built from <strong>short, harsh consonants and open vowels</strong>, producing names that are as blunt and direct as the people themselves.</p>\n<p>Uniquely among the cultures of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, Lakandi names are <strong>not fixed at birth</strong> -- they <strong>change after trials</strong>. Individuals earn new names through feats of combat, endurance, or survival. These <strong>earned names</strong> typically depict violence, strength, or the natural forces the bearer has overcome. A Lakandi warrior&#39;s name is a compressed history of their most notable achievements.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-nameless\">The Nameless</h3>\n<p>The Lakandi practice of naming carries a dark counterpart: cowards and oathbreakers are stripped of their names entirely, becoming <strong>Nameless</strong>. The Nameless are <strong>exiled from Lakandi society</strong>, cast out to <strong>wander the wastes until death</strong> -- without identity, kinship, or honor. To be made Nameless is considered a fate worse than death, for death at least preserves the memory of what one was. The Nameless are erased.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"historical-events\">Historical Events</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-lakan-campaigns-360-368-iy\">The Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY)</h3>\n<p>The Empire launched a major military expedition into Lakandi territory, seeking to pacify the warlike tribes and extend Imperial control. The <strong>Lakan Campaigns</strong> dragged on for <strong>eight years</strong>, proving extraordinarily costly for the Empire and demonstrating that the Lakandi&#39;s knowledge of their wasteland homeland made them nearly impossible to defeat on their own ground.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-battle-of-blue-mound\">The Battle of Blue Mound</h3>\n<p>The campaigns culminated in the catastrophic <strong><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a></strong>. The battle pitted Imperial forces, led by <strong><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a></strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, against the forces of <strong><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a></strong> -- the greatest practitioner of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a> in recorded history. Jarn&#39;s name was not metaphorical: his eyes were the color of what he had touched, what he had bound, what he had held through decades of Veil contact.</p>\n<p>The climax of the conflict came when Cynar and Jarn engaged in a direct sorcerous duel -- a confrontation of such magnitude that it <strong>annihilated both armies entirely</strong>, leaving the battlefield a blasted and lifeless wasteland. Neither Cynar nor Jarn survived.</p>\n<p>Cynar had burned the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at Thornasse. Jarn killed him for it. Neither survived the exchange.</p>\n<p>The Battle of Blue Mound had profound consequences for Imperial military doctrine, demonstrating that the deployment of high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was potentially suicidal. The Empire subsequently retreated to a defensive posture in Lakandi territory, constructing a line of <strong>border forts</strong> that marks the current frontier.</p>\n<h3 id=\"current-situation\">Current Situation</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Lakandi in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> are stirring</strong>. Whispers of rebellion circulate through the wasteland, and the reduction of the Imperial garrison to skeletal levels has made the threat of a Lakandi uprising more dangerous than ever. The border forts built after the Lakan Campaigns, now commanded by <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a>, are the thin, crumbling line between the Empire&#39;s frontier and whatever the Lakandi are planning.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- The binding tradition practiced by Lakandi sorcerers</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">jarn-murky-eye</a> -- The Warlock King, greatest Lakandi binder</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a> -- The High Mage who fought Jarn at Blue Mound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- Where Lakandi unrest is growing</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Commander of the border forts facing Lakandi territory</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The Cthonic traditions many Lakandi follow</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The Lakan Campaigns in broader context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a> -- A Lakandi practitioner in Bone Creek who holds a bound entity</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"languages-of-mithrapos","title":"Languages of Mithrapos","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["languages","culture","linguistics","mithrapos","argollean"],"html":"<h1 id=\"languages-of-mithrapos\">Languages of Mithrapos</h1>\n<p>The linguistic landscape of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> reflects millennia of conquest, migration, trade, and cultural exchange. Languages range from dead scholarly tongues preserved only in ancient texts to the living dialects spoken across the Empire&#39;s many provinces and beyond its borders.</p>\n<h2 id=\"dead-languages\">Dead Languages</h2>\n<p>These languages are no longer spoken natively but remain important for scholarship, magic, and religious practice.</p>\n<h3 id=\"ancient-argollean\">Ancient Argollean</h3>\n<p>The oldest known written language, belonging to the original <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> civilization. Ancient Argollean survives only in fragmentary inscriptions, ruins, and the most archaic sections of the <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a>. It is studied by scholars of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> but is understood by very few living people. The formulae of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> are partially derived from Ancient Argollean phonetic structures.</p>\n<h3 id=\"classical-argollean\">Classical Argollean</h3>\n<p>The language of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>, a descendant of Ancient Argollean that was the dominant tongue of the Argollean civilization at its height. Classical Argollean is better attested than its ancient ancestor, with surviving texts, poetry, and philosophical works. The verbal components (resonance) used in <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> are spoken in Classical Argollean, and the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> requires its students to achieve fluency.</p>\n<h2 id=\"living-languages\">Living Languages</h2>\n<h3 id=\"argollean-common\">Argollean (Common)</h3>\n<p>The modern descendant of <a href=\"#/page/languages-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Classical Argollean</a>, heavily simplified and influenced by centuries of contact with other languages. Argollean serves as the <em>lingua franca</em> of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> -- the common tongue used for trade, diplomacy, and communication between peoples who share no other language. Nearly everyone in the Empire speaks at least rudimentary Argollean.</p>\n<h3 id=\"high-mithric\">High Mithric</h3>\n<p>The formal language of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>&#39;s elite. High Mithric is spoken by the nobility, the clergy of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, and the scholarly class. It is the language of law, theology, official Imperial documents, and formal oratory. High Mithric is grammatically complex and laden with honorifics and status markers that reflect the Empire&#39;s rigid social hierarchy under the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"low-mithric\">Low Mithric</h3>\n<p>The common Imperial tongue spoken by the vast majority of the Empire&#39;s population. Low Mithric is a simplified, colloquial form of High Mithric blended with Argollean loanwords and regional vocabulary. It varies significantly by province but remains mutually intelligible across most of the Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"old-vestari\">Old Vestari</h3>\n<p>An archaic form of the <a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a> language, now spoken only in formal religious and ceremonial contexts among Vestari nobility. Old Vestari preserves linguistic features that trace back to the earliest days of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"vestari\">Vestari</h3>\n<p>The modern language of the <a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a> people. As one of the first cultures to join the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a>, the Vestari have been deeply integrated into Imperial culture, and their language shows heavy Mithric and Argollean influence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"lyseani\">Lyseani</h3>\n<p>The language of the <a href=\"#/page/lysean\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lysean</a> people. Lyseani is a conservative tongue that has changed relatively little over the centuries, reflecting the Lyseans&#39; agricultural stability and cultural continuity -- even through the devastating drought and the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> Wars that ravaged their homeland.</p>\n<h3 id=\"mornish\">Mornish</h3>\n<p>The language of the Peninsula of <a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">Morn</a>. Mornish is fiercely preserved by its speakers as a marker of cultural identity and resistance to Imperial assimilation. The language features a rich oral literary tradition, including epic poetry and war songs.</p>\n<h3 id=\"thrassian\">Thrassian</h3>\n<p>The language of the <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> mountain people. Thrassian is widely spoken within the Imperial military due to the disproportionate number of Thrassian soldiers in the legions. Many Imperial officers learn at least basic Thrassian to communicate with their troops.</p>\n<h3 id=\"kolani\">Kolani</h3>\n<p>The language of both the ton&#39;Kolani and don&#39;Kolani branches of the <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> people. Kolani is an agglutinative language with a complex system of verbal prefixes that encode speaker intent, emotional state, and social relationship to the listener. It is particularly difficult for non-native speakers to master.</p>\n<h3 id=\"eastern-rinoic\">Eastern Rinoic</h3>\n<p>A dialectal branch of <a href=\"#/page/rinoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rinoic</a> spoken by the eastern tribes of the <a href=\"#/page/rinoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rinoan</a> confederation. Eastern Rinoic has diverged enough from western Rinoic to be considered a distinct language by Imperial scholars, though speakers of both varieties can usually understand each other with effort.</p>\n<h3 id=\"avaric\">Avaric</h3>\n<p>The language of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> people. Avaric belongs to a different linguistic family than most Mithraposian languages and is notably difficult for speakers of Mithric or Argollean to learn. The Avari maintain their language as one of the few cultural traditions not suppressed during their conquest.</p>\n<h3 id=\"lakandic\">Lakandic</h3>\n<p>The language of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> tribes. Lakandic is rarely encountered outside Lakandi territory, as the Lakandi are deeply reclusive and hostile to outsiders. Imperial scholars who have studied the language note its unusual tonal system and its extensive vocabulary for describing terrain, weather, and combat.</p>\n<h3 id=\"rinoic\">Rinoic</h3>\n<p>The primary language of the <a href=\"#/page/rinoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rinoan</a> tribal confederation. Rinoic features a strong oral tradition and a system of kennings -- metaphorical compound words -- that make its poetry dense and allusive.</p>\n<h3 id=\"shentic\">Shentic</h3>\n<p>The language of the <a href=\"#/page/shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shenti</a> people. Shentic shows heavy <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massarai</a> influence, reflecting the Shenti&#39;s long history as subjects of the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>. With the fall of the Shenti province to the <a href=\"#/page/shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tulmuk</a>, Shentic is increasingly spoken by refugee communities within the Empire&#39;s interior.</p>\n<h3 id=\"ancient-massarai\">Ancient Massarai</h3>\n<p>The older form of the Massaran language, associated with the height of the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its sorcerer-kings. Ancient Massarai is the language of many surviving Massaran magical texts and is studied by scholars interested in <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a> sorcery -- though such study is forbidden within the Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"massarai\">Massarai</h3>\n<p>The modern descendant of Ancient Massarai, spoken in the surviving <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Kingdoms</a> and by Massar communities within the Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"urgathai\">Urgathai</h3>\n<p>The language of <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoa</a>, the most prominent surviving Massaran kingdom. Urgathai is a distinct language from Massarai, though the two share a common ancestor. It serves as the language of court, commerce, and diplomacy within Urgathoa&#39;s sphere of influence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"ranka\">Ranka</h3>\n<p>The guttural, simplified language spoken by the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a>. Ranka is less a true language than a pidgin -- a basic communication system cobbled together from fragments of Massarai, animal vocalizations, and improvised vocabulary. Different beastman tribes speak mutually unintelligible variants. Ranka has no written form.</p>\n<h3 id=\"proto-skiothan\">Proto-Skiothan</h3>\n<p>An older form of the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> language, preserved in oral epics, war chants, and ritual formulae among the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> horse tribes. Proto-Skiothan is used primarily in ceremonial contexts.</p>\n<h3 id=\"skiothan\">Skiothan</h3>\n<p>The living language of the <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> nomadic horse warriors of the <a href=\"#/page/grathe-steppe\" class=\"wiki-link\">Grathe Steppe</a>. Skiothan is aggressively maintained by its speakers, who view linguistic purity as an expression of cultural superiority.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Races and Cultures of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"lysean","title":"Lysean","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","lysean","naming","human","religious","scholarly","drought","beastman-wars"],"html":"<h1 id=\"lysean\">Lysean</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Lyseans</strong> are a deeply religious and scholarly people whose culture is suffused with spiritual devotion and intellectual inquiry. Among the earliest members of the Mithrian League, the Lyseans have a long tradition of loyalty to the Empire -- a loyalty that has been repaid with suffering, as their homeland has been devastated by both natural disaster and war.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>Lyseans are tall with fair skin and fair hair. Their lighter coloring distinguishes them from the darker-haired Mithrian norm, and their height is notable even among the taller peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Lyseans were among the <strong>early Mithrian League members</strong>, joining the confederation in its formative years and maintaining a <strong>long tradition of loyalty</strong> to the institutions that grew from it. This loyalty is not blind obedience but a deeply held conviction that the League -- and later the Empire -- represents the best hope for civilization in a dangerous world.</p>\n<p>Lysean culture is suffused with spiritual devotion and intellectual inquiry. Lysean scholars, theologians, and priests are respected throughout the Empire, and Lysean institutions of learning have produced some of the most influential thinkers in Imperial history.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-devastation-of-the-homeland\">The Devastation of the Homeland</h3>\n<p>The Lysean homeland was once the <strong>breadbasket</strong> of the region -- fertile fields that fed not only Lysea but surrounding provinces as well. Approximately <strong>200 years ago</strong>, a prolonged and devastating <strong>drought</strong> ravaged these fields, destroying the agricultural foundation of Lysean prosperity. The drought transformed the breadbasket into dust, and Lysea has never fully recovered.</p>\n<p>The same fields that once fed an empire became the <strong>primary battleground for the Beastman Wars</strong>. Soldiers who were promised fertile farmland as a reward for service found instead <strong>fields of dust</strong> -- the broken promise of a homeland that no longer existed in the form they had been told to expect. This cruel irony -- fighting and dying for land that had already been destroyed -- has left a deep mark on Lysean culture and on the soldiers who serve in Lysean formations.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Lysean names characteristically end in <strong>-an</strong>, <strong>-ur</strong>, <strong>-ik</strong>, or <strong>-el</strong>, giving them a distinctive cadence that sets them apart from the naming traditions of other Imperial peoples.</p>\n<p>The patronymic suffixes <strong>-ian</strong> or <strong>-yan</strong> denote descent (e.g., Gregorian, meaning &quot;son of Gregor&quot;; Toryan, meaning &quot;son of Tor&quot;).</p>\n<p>Lyseans also employ <strong>honorific and religious earned names</strong>, bestowed upon individuals who achieve distinction in spiritual or scholarly pursuits. These earned names carry great prestige and may supplement or replace the bearer&#39;s birth name. A Lysean scholar known by their earned name is understood to have achieved something of lasting significance in their field.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire the Lyseans have long served</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The creatures whose wars ravaged Lysean fields</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The faith that shapes Lysean spiritual life</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"magic-and-sorcery","title":"Magic and Sorcery","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["magic","sorcery","gnostic-geometry","veil","flame","imperial-academy","argolle","elvora","empyrean"],"html":"<h1 id=\"magic-and-sorcery\">Magic and Sorcery</h1>\n<p>The civilizations of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> have long used sorcery as part of their society, whether that be through assisting with vast construction projects or through destruction on the battlefield. Sorcery is not a single unified discipline but rather a collection of competing traditions, each with its own philosophy, methodology, and dangers. The three principal traditions -- <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">Flame</a> -- represent fundamentally different understandings of the nature of reality and the mortal&#39;s place within it. The institutional seat of sorcerous learning in the present age is the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, located in <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, which enforces strict control over the practice of magic throughout the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gnostic-geometry\">Gnostic Geometry</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;The world is built on hidden mathematics -- the sorcerer seeks to learn the metaphysical equation.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>High Mage Marius</strong>, <em>On Axioms</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Gnostic geometry is a form of magic that was once practiced by the ancient <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolleans</a>, thousands of years ago. Within the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>, magic was common -- a part of everyday life. Sorcery was woven into the fabric of Argollean civilization, employed in construction, governance, warfare, and scholarship alike. After the fall of Argolle, the formulae were lost for thousands of years, buried beneath the ruin of that once-great civilization and the long ages of darkness that followed.</p>\n<p>It was not until the <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> rediscovered the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> that these ancient arts were recovered. Along with those sacred texts was the lesser known <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a>, an ancient grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality. The Anthyllium is a work of extraordinary complexity, laying out a system of interlocking mathematical and metaphysical principles that, when properly understood and applied, allow a trained sorcerer to reshape the world around them. The formulae within the Anthyllium are still used in present times by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, forming the foundational curriculum of its sorcerous instruction.</p>\n<p>According to the Anthyllium, sorcery is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout reality -- a structured, lawful cosmos established by the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>. The universe, in this view, is not chaotic or arbitrary but ordered according to deep mathematical principles laid down at the moment of creation. The geometric incantations taught by the Imperial Academy can alter these axioms through three interconnected methods:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Mental discipline</strong> -- the rigorous training of the sorcerer&#39;s mind to perceive and manipulate the underlying axioms</li>\n<li><strong>Diagrams (sigils)</strong> -- precisely drawn geometric patterns that serve as physical anchors for metaphysical manipulation</li>\n<li><strong>Resonance (spoken word)</strong> -- verbal incantations that activate and direct the power channeled through sigils and mental focus</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This form of sorcery is rigid and codified, demanding years of intensive study and practice. It is also extremely dangerous to the untrained mind. An improperly drawn sigil, a mispronounced incantation, or a lapse in mental discipline can produce catastrophic and unpredictable results. Because of this inherent danger, and because the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> seeks to keep all sorcerous knowledge firmly under its own control, the Academy retains strict authority over the teaching and practice of gnostic geometry throughout the Empire. Unsanctioned practice is punishable by imprisonment or death.</p>\n<p>The cataclysmic potential of gnostic geometry was demonstrated during the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> (360--368 IY), in which a duel between <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> and <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a> escalated to such destructive magnitude that it annihilated both armies entirely. This event remains one of the most dramatic illustrations of what sorcery is capable of when wielded without restraint.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> also offered a characteristically scientific explanation for the catastrophic earthquakes and storms that accompanied the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Death of Usil</a> in 348 IY, attributing the devastation to &quot;fluctuations in the gnostic patterns that govern the metaphysical reality of Mithrapos.&quot; Priests of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faiths, by contrast, claimed that an Empyrean god had died -- a theological explanation that the Academy rejected but could not entirely disprove.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-veil\">The Veil</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;Magic is not of this world, it bleeds in from Beyond.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Logos</strong>, <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> Apostate</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> discovery of the Veil reshaped understanding of how magic and sorcery work, challenging the orderly geometric model promoted by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> and its <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> predecessors. The Veil is not merely a boundary between two worlds, but a kind of living membrane between the realm of the mortals and the <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a> -- a multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten and ancient gods, and raw metaphysical potential. It breathes, shifts, and responds to those who touch it.</p>\n<p>When the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> sacrificed himself, it created a cosmic wound -- a fundamental rupture in the fabric of existence -- allowing the realities on either side of the Veil to influence each other. The sorcerer opens these wounds further, siphoning energies from other realities and drawing them into the mortal world. Every act of sorcery, in this understanding, is an act of tearing -- a deliberate reopening of the primordial wound left by the Aurelion&#39;s death.</p>\n<p>While the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> and their predecessors, the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>, see magic as a manipulation of lawful axioms -- an orderly, mathematical process governed by rules and formulae -- the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> know that such order is merely the outer crust of a primordial chaotic stew. Beneath the thin veneer of geometric law lies a seething, alien chaos that defies comprehension. The Elvora believe that true sorcerous power comes not from manipulating the surface patterns but from plunging one&#39;s will into the raw chaos beneath.</p>\n<p>This act of sorcery is inherently violent, as the sorcerer is contesting with the fabric of reality itself, unmaking it and reshaping it according to their will. There is no gentleness in Veil magic -- it is an act of force, of domination over the natural order. Over time, repeated contact with the Beyond corrupts both the flesh and the mind. The physical and psychological toll of Veil sorcery is well documented:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eyes may blacken</strong> -- nearly all Elvora display this characteristic, their eyes becoming solid pools of darkness</li>\n<li><strong>Bones warp</strong> -- skeletal structure may twist and deform under the sustained influence of chaotic energies</li>\n<li><strong>Voices change</strong> -- the sorcerer&#39;s voice may deepen, echo, or take on alien harmonics</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These are not merely cosmetic changes but markers of a fundamental transformation wrought by prolonged exposure to the Beyond. The Elvora, who have practiced Veil sorcery for millennia, bear these marks most prominently.</p>\n<p>Contact with the Veil also permits communion with things from the Beyond: <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> gods, demons, forgotten titans, and other alien intelligences that dwell within the multiversal tangle. This contact is perilous in the extreme, for these entities possess desires, agendas, and hungers of their own. To those who venerate such powers, however, this communion is not a danger but an opportunity -- the true path to apotheosis. Cthonic cults and demon-binders view the Veil not as a barrier to be feared but as a gateway to transcendence.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-flame\">The Flame</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;Each living being carries a spark of the Aurelion within its soul. To embody the Measure and the Scale you can reshape the world with your soul&#39;s fire.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Saint Euphrosyne</strong>, <em>the Measure and the Scale</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The priests of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, and other <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faiths, believe that by aligning one&#39;s will with the virtues of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scale</a> you can channel portions of your divine spark into the mortal realm. This tradition stands apart from both gnostic geometry and Veil sorcery in a fundamental way: the Flame is not drawn from diagrams or summoned from alien realms. Instead, it burns within the soul of every mortal -- a remnant of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice, a shard of divine fire passed down through all living things.</p>\n<p>The faithful of Seros channel this Flame through virtue, sacrifice, and righteous purpose. It is not a power that can be seized or demanded but one that must be earned through the constant practice of moral and spiritual discipline. To walk the path of the Measure and the Scale is to unlock one&#39;s inner radiance. Only through discipline, humility, and devotion can the Flame be kindled into miracles.</p>\n<p>The priests and clerics of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> do little to teach the Flame in any formal or academic sense. It cannot be taught -- it must be lived. The Flame does not respond to formulae or incantations but to the quality of the soul that seeks to wield it. To the faithful, the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> is more than a moral code, a religious doctrine, or a legal treatise -- it is the kindling by which one&#39;s Flame is awakened. A life lived in accordance with its principles is itself the incantation, the sigil, and the resonance all at once.</p>\n<p>This understanding places the Flame tradition in direct philosophical opposition to both gnostic geometry (which treats sorcery as an intellectual and mathematical exercise) and Veil sorcery (which treats it as an act of violent will imposed upon reality). To the priests of Seros, sorcery is neither calculation nor conquest -- it is communion with the divine spark that dwells within.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-imperial-academy\">The Imperial Academy</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;The Emperor rules the world of men, but the Academy governs what is possible within it.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Archmage Thoss</strong>, <em>On the Bounds of Sovereignty</em>, banned in three provinces</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> is the official state-sanctioned seat of sorcerous learning within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Located in <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, its towering spires are the highest structures within the city, able to be seen from leagues away -- a deliberate architectural statement of the Academy&#39;s power and prestige. It is both a prestigious university of learning and a political power in its own right, operating outside the traditional structure of Imperial ministries. The Academy answers to the Emperor, but in practice it exercises a degree of autonomy that few other institutions can claim.</p>\n<p>The Academy is a pillar of imperial stability and ambition, but also a hotbed of secrecy, rivalry, and experimentation. Behind its alabaster walls, Archmages pursue research both sanctioned and clandestine, and political maneuvering among the faculty is as ruthless as anything found in the Imperial Senate.</p>\n<p>Citizens of the Empire hold the Academy in fear and contempt, for its <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seekers</a> prowl the provinces, searching for those who possess the power of sorcery, and enrolling those individuals within its alabaster halls. The Seekers are agents of the Academy who travel the length and breadth of the Empire, testing children and young adults for sorcerous aptitude. When talent is discovered, enrollment is not optional. If a family cannot afford the pricey tuition, the Seekers will enslave the future student as a <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">servus</a>, until such a time that they can pay their tuition through service. This practice, while legal under Imperial law, is deeply resented by the common people. Some of these servus, however, have risen through sheer talent and determination to become some of the most powerful High Mages to ever live -- a fact the Academy is fond of citing in its own defense.</p>\n<p>A conclave of <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Archmages</a> forms a ruling council of the Academy. This is a lifelong appointment, decided by the Emperor himself, making each seat on the council a matter of intense political significance. Every seven years the council will vote on one of their members to become the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Primarch</a>, a figurehead of some executive power within the Academy and a direct advisor to the Emperor. The Primarch serves as the public face of the Academy and wields considerable influence in matters of state, particularly those concerning sorcery, warfare, and the regulation of magical practice.</p>\n<p>The Academy teaches and practices a form of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">geometric gnostic sorcery</a>. The formulae and incantations are difficult to master, requiring years of rigorous study, but they are much more powerful than those employed by a hedge-mage or warlock working outside the Academy&#39;s traditions. Other forms of sorcery are strictly prohibited by the Academy, and the following disciplines are expressly forbidden:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Necromancy</strong> -- the animation or manipulation of the dead</li>\n<li><strong>Transmogrification</strong> -- the fundamental alteration of living flesh</li>\n<li><strong>Demon-binding</strong> -- the summoning and enslavement of entities from the <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Violations of these prohibitions are punishable by death, as demonstrated by the fate of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magistrate Verna Astell</a>, who was executed for practicing forbidden transmogrification rituals.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;The Scale may weigh the soul, but it is the Academy that defines what a soul can be.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Magistrate Verna Astell</strong>, executed for practicing forbidden transmogrification rituals</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Despite these prohibitions, rumors persist of clandestine research conducted within the Academy&#39;s deepest laboratories -- experiments that push against or outright violate the Academy&#39;s own stated rules.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-academy-and-warfare\">The Academy and Warfare</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> once held a near-monopoly on sorcery, ensuring battlefield dominance across its many campaigns of conquest and defense. The Academy was central to this advantage, training and deploying battle-mages whose geometric sorcery could devastate enemy formations, shatter fortifications, and turn the tide of entire wars. However, over time the destructive powers of mages have proliferated beyond the Academy&#39;s control. Hedge-mages, warlocks, and sorcerers trained in rival traditions have appeared in increasing numbers among the Empire&#39;s enemies.</p>\n<p>This proliferation has transformed warfare. The military now uses squad mages as part of combined arms tactics, integrating sorcerers into conventional military formations rather than relying on them as singular weapons of mass destruction. Additionally, <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons gained as part of the peace treaty following the <a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a> -- now supplement magical firepower, further reducing the Academy&#39;s exclusive importance on the battlefield.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> (360--368 IY) stands as a grim testament to the catastrophic potential of sorcerous warfare. The duel between <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> of the Imperial Academy and <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a> escalated beyond all control, annihilating both armies and leaving the battlefield a blasted wasteland. This event prompted significant reforms in how the Empire deploys its mages in combat.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Anthyllium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Death of Usil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"massar","title":"Massar","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","massar","naming","human","massaran-empire","sorcerer-kings","cthonic","argollean","thunean-empire","urgathoan"],"html":"<h1 id=\"massar\">Massar</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Massar</strong> are a culturally sophisticated people whose traditions bear the deep imprint of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> influence. They once ruled the <strong><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></strong> -- a formidable dominion sustained by powerful sorcerer-kings and <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> legions -- that enslaved much of the known world before being overthrown by the forces of <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> and <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> in the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos#empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Massaran Empire was shattered and its armies scattered, but the Massar people endure, and <strong>several kingdoms survive</strong> as successor states to the old empire. The most well-known of these successor states are the <strong>Urgathoans</strong>, who maintain the cultural traditions and political ambitions of the old Massaran order.</p>\n<p>The Massar civilization rose from the ruins of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>, and their language, art, and naming conventions all reflect this heritage. They are a people of <strong>cultural sophistication</strong> -- their art, architecture, and scholarship bear the marks of a civilization that once ruled the known world and has not forgotten that it did.</p>\n<h3 id=\"religion\">Religion</h3>\n<p>The Massar <strong>still worship <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> gods</strong>. While the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and its <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith have become dominant across much of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, the Massar have maintained their older Cthonic traditions -- the worship of the hungry gods, the powers that dwell beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>. This continued devotion to the Cthonic faith is both a spiritual choice and a political statement: a refusal to adopt the religious framework of the empire that overthrew them.</p>\n<h3 id=\"role-in-the-thunean-empire\">Role in the Thunean Empire</h3>\n<p>The Massar are also notable for their historical role as <strong>advisors within the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a></strong>. Massar counselors were brought into the Thunean court and used their position to <strong>orchestrate the overthrow of their Thune overlords</strong> from within. This achievement -- the destruction of an empire through patient manipulation rather than military force -- is one of the most remarkable feats of political warfare in the history of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-beastmen\">The Beastmen</h3>\n<p>The Massar created the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> as the <strong>core of their armies</strong> -- purpose-bred for war through sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding. After the defeat of the Massaran Empire, the Beastmen were scattered, left without purpose or direction. They remain a persistent threat to civilization across <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, a living legacy of Massaran ambition.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Massar names are <strong>Argollean-influenced</strong>, characterized by <strong>elongated vowels</strong> and a flowing, musical cadence that reflects their cultural heritage from the old Argollean Empire.</p>\n<p>Naming particles include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>net</strong> -- meaning &quot;house of&quot; (e.g., Amara net Solenn)</li>\n<li><strong>sah</strong> -- meaning &quot;blood of&quot; (e.g., Kassim sah Durai)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The army the Massar created</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> -- The empire the Massar overthrew from within</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- The ancient empire that influenced Massar culture</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The Empyrean War that overthrew the Massaran Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">shenti</a> -- A people formerly subject to Massaran rule</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tet\" class=\"wiki-link\">tet</a> -- A people formerly enslaved by Massar</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The faith the Massar still follow</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"massaran-empire","title":"The Massaran Empire","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["lore","history","massaran","massar","sorcerer-kings","empyrean-war","sebek","enador","bellasarius-valerian","beastmen","cthonic","urgathoans","thune","slavery","ancient-empire"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-massaran-empire\">The Massaran Empire</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;The Massar ruled as gods and were obeyed as gods and punished as gods punish. Their sorcerer-kings remade the flesh of beasts into armies and the will of men into obedience. When the Prophet broke their power, the world did not celebrate -- it exhaled. The breath it had been holding for centuries.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Massaran Empire</strong> was an ancient empire ruled by the <strong>Massar</strong> -- a dynasty of sorcerer-kings who enslaved much of the known world through a combination of overwhelming arcane power, beastman legions, and systematic domination. It was the defining tyranny of the pre-imperial age, and its shadow falls across every civilization that followed.</p>\n<p>The Massaran Empire was overthrown in the <strong><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a></strong> (663 BE) by <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> and <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a>. The tyrant-sorcerer <strong><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sebek</a></strong> was driven into exile. The beastman legions that formed the core of the Massaran armies were scattered. The Empire shattered -- but it did not entirely die.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Ancient empire, pre-imperial age</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rulers</strong></td>\n<td>The Massar -- sorcerer-kings wielding immense arcane power</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Defining Feature</strong></td>\n<td>Enslaved much of the known world</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Military Core</strong></td>\n<td>Beastman legions -- creatures of reshaped flesh serving as the backbone of Massaran armies</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Fall</strong></td>\n<td>Overthrown in the <span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrapos</span> had known before the rise of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. The Massar sorcerer-kings wielded arcane power on a scale that has not been replicated since -- power sufficient to reshape living flesh into the beastman legions that formed the core of their armies, to bend the will of conquered peoples into obedience, and to maintain dominion over much of the known world for generations.</p>\n<p>Their empire was built on slavery -- not merely the economic exploitation of labor, but the total subjugation of peoples, cultures, and civilizations. The Massar did not merely conquer. They consumed. Nations that fell under their rule were absorbed, their identities erased, their populations converted into raw material for the empire&#39;s needs.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-beastman-legions\">The Beastman Legions</h2>\n<p>The beastman legions were the core of Massaran military power -- creatures of reshaped flesh, created through sorcerous processes that transformed living beings into weapons of war. These legions were the instrument of Massaran conquest, the force that broke the armies of free peoples, and the visible symbol of the sorcerer-kings&#39; power over life itself.</p>\n<p>When the Massaran Empire shattered, the beastman legions were scattered across <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. Without the sorcerer-kings to command them, the beastmen fragmented into warbands, tribes, and feral populations. They persist in the present day -- a living legacy of Massaran power, found in wilderness regions, frontier territories, and the margins of civilization. The <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> beastman population is one such remnant.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-thune-connection\">The Thune Connection</h2>\n<p>The relationship between the Massar and the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> is one of history&#39;s great ironies of power and succession:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a></strong> were originally advisors to an earlier power. They rose to become rulers in their own right, establishing the <strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a></strong>.</li>\n<li>The <strong>Massar</strong> were originally Thune advisors -- subordinates who served the Thunean court. They followed the same pattern as their masters, rising from service to dominance.</li>\n<li>The Massar overthrew the Thune and established the Massaran Empire on the ruins of the Thunean one.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The cycle of advisor-becomes-ruler repeated itself across generations -- a pattern that historians have noted with varying degrees of irony and alarm.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-empyrean-war-and-the-fall\">The Empyrean War and the Fall</h2>\n<p>The Massaran Empire was overthrown in the <strong><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a></strong> of 663 BE -- a conflict that reshaped the world and established the foundations of the current age.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a></strong> -- the founder of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a> -- provided the spiritual and ideological framework for resistance against the Massar</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a></strong> -- the military leader who translated that framework into victory on the battlefield</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sebek</a></strong> -- the last and greatest of the Massar sorcerer-kings -- was driven into exile rather than killed</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The war broke the Massaran Empire, scattered the beastman legions, and liberated the enslaved peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. From the wreckage of the Massaran order, the foundations of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> were laid -- an empire that defined itself, in part, by opposition to everything the Massar had represented.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"surviving-remnants\">Surviving Remnants</h2>\n<p>The Massaran Empire shattered, but it did not entirely die. Several Massaran kingdoms survive in the present day, maintaining elements of the old order -- the worship of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, the traditions of sorcerous power, and the cultural memory of an empire that once ruled the world.</p>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoans</a></strong> are the most well-known of these surviving Massaran successor states. They maintain the worship of the Cthonic gods and preserve traditions that the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> regards as abhorrent -- living proof that the Massaran legacy endures despite the Empire&#39;s best efforts to consign it to history.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>The Massaran Empire&#39;s legacy pervades the present:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Beastman populations</strong> across <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> are the scattered remnants of the legions</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic worship</a></strong> in its various forms traces its institutional roots to Massaran religious practice</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a></strong> defines itself in opposition to the Massaran order</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></strong> claims legitimacy as the successor state to the liberation -- the power that replaced tyranny with civilization</li>\n<li><strong>The fear of sorcery</strong> -- the deep cultural suspicion that pervades imperial society -- is rooted in the memory of what sorcerer-kings did when they held unchecked power</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-war</a> -- The conflict that overthrew the Massaran Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">enador</a> -- The Prophet who provided the spiritual framework for resistance</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> -- The military leader of the liberation</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sebek</a> -- The last sorcerer-king, driven into exile</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The religious tradition of the Massar</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The scattered remnants of Massaran legions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> -- The predecessors the Massar overthrew</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a> -- The empire the Massar replaced</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Urgathoans</a> -- The most well-known surviving Massaran successor state</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that rose from the Massaran collapse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The faith born in opposition to Massaran tyranny</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrapos</a> -- The known world the Massar once dominated</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The broader historical context</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mithrapos","title":"Mithrapos","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["lore","world","geography","mithrapos","middle-sea","empires","setting","cosmology"],"html":"<h1 id=\"mithrapos\">Mithrapos</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;A cradle and a coffin, a boneyard of Empires.&quot; -- Savron</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Mithrapos</strong> is the known world -- the region encircling the <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Middle Sea</a> that has seen the rise and fall of numerous empires, civilizations, and peoples. It is the setting of the Fallen Empire campaign, a world shaped by millennia of conquest, collapse, and the persistent ambitions of mortals and gods alike.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> is the dominant power in Mithrapos in the present age. It will not be the last.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>The known world</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Central Feature</strong></td>\n<td>The <span class=\"dead-link\">Middle Sea</span> have served as the cradle and the grave of civilization after civilization -- each building on the ruins of its predecessor, each believing itself permanent, each eventually joining the wreckage beneath its successors&#39; foundations.</p>\n<p>The current dominant power -- the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> -- is merely the latest in this sequence. It rose from the ashes of the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>, which rose from the ashes of the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a>, which rose from the ashes of something older still. The pattern is not lost on the Empire&#39;s scholars, though they prefer to believe their civilization will be the exception.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-middle-sea\">The Middle Sea</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Middle Sea</a> is the central geographic feature of Mithrapos -- the body of water around which civilizations cluster, trade routes converge, and empires project their power. It connects the disparate lands and peoples of Mithrapos through commerce, war, and cultural exchange. Control of the Middle Sea has been a defining ambition of every empire that has risen to dominance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cycle-of-empires\">The Cycle of Empires</h2>\n<p>Mithrapos has witnessed the rise and fall of numerous empires, each leaving its mark on the landscape, the peoples, and the metaphysical fabric of the world:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thunean Empire</a></strong> -- An early power whose advisors (the Massar) eventually overthrew them</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Massaran Empire</a></strong> -- The tyranny of sorcerer-kings who enslaved much of the known world, overthrown in the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> (663 BE)</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">The First Empire (Eladran)</a></strong> -- An empire whose cultural legacy persists through the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> and the artifacts they seek to reclaim</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></strong> -- The current dominant power, built on the foundations of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a> and the military legacy of <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Each empire has left ruins, artifacts, displaced peoples, and unresolved powers in its wake. The world of Mithrapos is layered with the residue of these successive civilizations -- their temples, their gods, their weapons, and their mistakes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-metaphysical-landscape\">The Metaphysical Landscape</h2>\n<p>Mithrapos exists in relationship to forces that extend beyond the material world:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></strong> -- The barrier between the mortal world and <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Beyond</a>, weakened by the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> sacrifice</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Beyond</a></strong> -- The multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten gods, and raw metaphysical potential beyond the Veil</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean gods</a></strong> -- The divine powers worshipped by the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Cthonic gods</a></strong> -- Older, darker powers that predate the Empyrean faith and persist in hidden worship</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcery</a></strong> -- The practice of opening wounds in the Veil to siphon energies from the Beyond</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The metaphysical landscape of Mithrapos is not stable. The Veil has been damaged, the old gods have not departed, and the new gods have not fully secured their dominion. The world exists in a state of spiritual tension that mirrors its political instability.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Middle Sea</a> -- The central geographic feature of the known world</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The current dominant power</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">massaran-empire</a> -- The ancient tyranny that preceded the current order</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a> -- The empire the Massar overthrew</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> -- The First Empire whose legacy persists</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-war</a> -- The conflict that reshaped the world</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The dominant religious tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The older religious tradition that persists</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The barrier between worlds</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-beyond</a> -- The metaphysical reality beyond the Veil</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The detailed historical timeline</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- The peoples of Mithrapos</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mithrian-calendar","title":"The Mithrian Calendar","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["calendar","time","holidays","culture","empire"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-mithrian-calendar\">The Mithrian Calendar</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Valerian Calendar</strong> is the official timekeeping system of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, instituted after <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> declared himself Emperor in 1 IY. The calendar structures the Imperial year into thirteen months of twenty-eight days each, plus one intercalary day, for a total of <strong>365 days</strong>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"structure\">Structure</h2>\n<p>The year consists of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>13 months</strong> of 28 days each (364 days)</li>\n<li><strong>1 intercalary day</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-calendar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dies Solaris</a> -- which falls after the final day of <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-calendar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aeternitas</a> and before the first day of <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-calendar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Virtus</a>, sitting outside the monthly cycle</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"months\">Months</h2>\n<p>The thirteen months of the Valerian Calendar are named for virtues central to the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Month</th>\n<th>Season</th>\n<th>Virtue</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Virtus</strong></td>\n<td>Winter</td>\n<td>Courage / Manliness</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Decus</strong></td>\n<td>Winter</td>\n<td>Honor / Dignity</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Fides</strong></td>\n<td>Spring</td>\n<td>Faith / Loyalty</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pietas</strong></td>\n<td>Spring</td>\n<td>Duty / Devotion</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Fortuna</strong></td>\n<td>Spring</td>\n<td>Fortune / Fate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Justica</strong></td>\n<td>Summer</td>\n<td>Justice</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Concordia</strong></td>\n<td>Summer</td>\n<td>Harmony / Unity</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Aequitas</strong></td>\n<td>Summer</td>\n<td>Equity / Fairness</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Celementia</strong></td>\n<td>Autumn</td>\n<td>Mercy / Clemency</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Victoria</strong></td>\n<td>Autumn</td>\n<td>Victory</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Spes</strong></td>\n<td>Autumn</td>\n<td>Hope</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Pax</strong></td>\n<td>Autumn</td>\n<td>Peace</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Aeternitas</strong></td>\n<td>Winter</td>\n<td>Eternity / Immortality</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Each month contains exactly 28 days, making the calendar remarkably regular. Weeks are seven days long, and every month begins on the same day of the week.</p>\n<h2 id=\"holidays-and-observances\">Holidays and Observances</h2>\n<h3 id=\"dies-solaris\">Dies Solaris</h3>\n<p><strong>Dies Solaris</strong> is the intercalary day that falls after Aeternitas 28 and before Virtus 1. It exists outside the monthly cycle -- it belongs to no month and no week. Dies Solaris is the most significant holiday in the Imperial calendar.</p>\n<p>The day is marked by:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Feasts</strong> -- Communal meals hosted by patrons for their clients, reinforcing the bonds of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><strong>Games</strong> -- Athletic and martial competitions, chariot races, and public spectacles sponsored by the <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a> and wealthy citizens</li>\n<li><strong>Rites for the Fallen</strong> -- Solemn religious ceremonies conducted by the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> to honor the dead, particularly soldiers who fell in service to the Empire</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Dies Solaris is simultaneously a day of celebration and mourning -- a liminal moment between the old year and the new, when the living acknowledge their debts to those who came before.</p>\n<h3 id=\"ludi-gloriae\">Ludi Gloriae</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Ludi Gloriae</strong> (Games of Glory) occupy the first week of <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-calendar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fides</a>, marking the transition from winter into spring. The festival is both martial and mournful in character.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Mock Battles</strong> -- Organized military exhibitions, war games, and staged combats performed by soldiers and gladiators. These are not mere entertainment but are considered acts of devotion, demonstrating martial virtue before the gods and the people.</li>\n<li><strong>Mourning Lamps</strong> -- On each night of the Ludi Gloriae, citizens light oil lamps and place them in windows, doorways, and public spaces to honor the war dead. The effect transforms Imperial cities into seas of flickering light.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Ludi Gloriae serve a dual purpose: they celebrate the military strength of the Empire while reminding citizens of its human cost.</p>\n<h3 id=\"dies-justicae\">Dies Justicae</h3>\n<p><strong>Dies Justicae</strong> falls on Justica 14, the midpoint of the summer month of Justice. It is a day of legal and moral reflection.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A priest of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> publicly recites the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> -- the full text, which can take several hours -- in the central forum or temple of every Imperial city and town</li>\n<li><strong>No work</strong> is permitted. All commerce, legal proceedings, and military operations (except those deemed essential) cease for the day</li>\n<li>Citizens are expected to reflect on their obligations under the Measure and their moral standing under the Scale</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Dies Justicae reinforces the centrality of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> to Imperial identity. It is the one day of the year when every citizen, from the Emperor to the lowest freedman, is reminded of the code that binds them all.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mithrian-culture","title":"Mithrian Culture","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","mithrian","naming","human","patronage","social-status"],"html":"<h1 id=\"mithrian-culture\">Mithrian Culture</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Mithrians</strong> are the dominant culture of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and the people from whom the Empire takes its name. Mithrian culture is urban, bureaucratic, and deeply hierarchical, with an emphasis on law, order, and civic duty. It is the cultural standard against which all other peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> are measured -- not because Mithrians are inherently superior, but because the Empire&#39;s institutions, laws, and social expectations are built upon Mithrian assumptions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>Mithrians are typically fair to olive-skinned, with dark hair and dark eyes. Centuries of imperial expansion and cultural intermixing have produced considerable variation, but the archetype of the Mithrian remains recognizable: Mediterranean in complexion, with features that reflect the urban sophistication their culture prizes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>Mithrian culture is cosmopolitan by necessity and inclination. The Empire&#39;s vast territorial extent means that Mithrians have been in contact with dozens of peoples for centuries, and their culture reflects this -- absorbing, adapting, and incorporating elements from conquered and allied peoples while maintaining a core identity rooted in certain unshakeable values:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Honor</strong> -- A Mithrian&#39;s word is their bond. Oaths, contracts, and promises carry tremendous weight in Mithrian society, and the breaking of a sworn oath is one of the gravest social transgressions.</li>\n<li><strong>Tradition</strong> -- Mithrians revere the customs and institutions of their ancestors. Innovation is valued, but it must be justified against the weight of precedent.</li>\n<li><strong>Family</strong> -- The family unit is the foundation of Mithrian society. Loyalty to family supersedes nearly all other obligations, and the family name is a source of both pride and responsibility.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-patronage-system\">The Patronage System</h3>\n<p>The patronage system is the engine of Mithrian social mobility and the organizing principle of all social interaction. Every Mithrian exists within a web of patron-client relationships that defines their social standing, their opportunities, and their obligations. A citizen&#39;s worth is measured not only by their own achievements but by the quality and power of the patrons who vouch for them. Conversely, a patron&#39;s prestige is enhanced by the number and quality of their clients.</p>\n<p><strong>Fathers wield tremendous power</strong> within the Mithrian family structure. The paterfamilias -- the male head of household -- holds authority over the family&#39;s fortunes, alliances, and social standing. This patriarchal authority is not merely customary but deeply embedded in the legal and moral framework of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Mithrians use a distinctive <strong>three-part naming system</strong> consisting of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Praenomen</strong> -- The personal or given name, used among intimates and family. Examples: Marcus, Gaius, Titus, Lucius, Justinian, Valerios.</li>\n<li><strong>Nomen</strong> -- The family or clan name, indicating lineage and heritage. Examples: Valerian, Claudius, Drussus, Kalomenes, Severian.</li>\n<li><strong>Cognomen</strong> -- A distinguishing epithet, often earned through deed or inherited through a family branch. Examples: Decimus, Marcellus, Aurel.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Among the <strong>nobility</strong>, the cognomen is favored and carries the greatest social weight, serving as a marker of distinguished lineage or personal accomplishment. A noble introduced by cognomen alone is understood to be claiming the full weight of that branch&#39;s reputation and history.</p>\n<p>Among the <strong>peasantry</strong>, who may lack a formal cognomen, profession often serves in its place. A farmer named Marcus of the Varro family who works as a smith might be known simply as <strong>Marcus Varro the Smith</strong>.</p>\n<p>The naming system reflects the Mithrian obsession with lineage, status, and the public declaration of identity. To know a Mithrian&#39;s full name is to know their family, their branch, and -- if the cognomen is earned rather than inherited -- their most notable achievement.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"religion\">Religion</h2>\n<p>Mithrians follow the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> as codified in the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>, with the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> serving as the institutional expression of their spiritual life. The <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> -- the distributed divine essence -- is the theological foundation, and the Empyrean gods (chief among them the Unconquered Sun) are the objects of public devotion.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-the-empire\">Role in the Empire</h2>\n<p>As the founding culture of the Empire, Mithrians occupy a position of cultural dominance that shapes every institution, law, and social expectation. The Imperial bureaucracy operates in Mithrian language and according to Mithrian legal precedent. The military follows Mithrian command structures. The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> preach in Mithrian theological vocabulary. Even peoples who have been part of the Empire for centuries find themselves navigating a world built on Mithrian assumptions.</p>\n<p>This dominance is not enforced through explicit racial hierarchy -- the Empire&#39;s social system cares far more about status than ethnicity -- but the structural advantages of being born into the culture that designed the system are real and significant.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that bears this culture&#39;s name</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> -- The legal and moral framework of Mithrian civilization</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> -- The institutional expression of Mithrian faith</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a> -- The noble families that dominate Mithrian politics</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a> -- Early allies who follow Mithrian naming conventions</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mithrian-empire","title":"The Mithrian Empire","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["empire","government","politics","mithra","mithrapos"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-mithrian-empire\">The Mithrian Empire</h1>\n<p>The Mithrian Empire is the dominant power of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> region, centered on the great capital of <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>. It is a vast, sprawling dominion governed by an Emperor who rules with supreme authority as codified by the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> -- the foundational legal and moral framework of Imperial civilization. The current year is <strong>380 IY</strong> (Imperial Year), and the reigning Emperor is <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"origins-the-mithrian-league\">Origins: The Mithrian League</h2>\n<p>The Empire traces its roots to the <strong>Mithrian League</strong>, a confederation of city-states united under a governing <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a>. The League was forged in the aftermath of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a>, when the prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> and the general <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> overthrew the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its sorcerer-kings. The League prospered for centuries under senatorial rule, but internal rivalries, corruption, and the ambitions of powerful houses eventually tore the old order apart.</p>\n<h2 id=\"rise-of-the-emperors\">Rise of the Emperors</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a>, claiming descent from <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> himself, seized power and declared himself the first Emperor in <strong>1 IY</strong>. He defeated the armies raised by loyalist Senators and consolidated authority under a single throne. The Senate was not abolished but was stripped of meaningful legislative power, becoming a largely performative body -- a forum for speeches, petitions, and political theater rather than genuine governance.</p>\n<h2 id=\"imperial-government\">Imperial Government</h2>\n<p>The Emperor rules with supreme authority, but does not govern alone. He is advised and supported by several key institutions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a></strong> -- The remnant of the old League&#39;s governing body. Senators hold prestige and can influence policy through rhetoric and patronage, but lack binding authority. Seats are hereditary or appointed.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></strong> -- The scholarly and arcane institution responsible for the study and regulation of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, the primary sanctioned form of magic. The Academy also serves as an advisory body on matters of science, history, and metaphysics.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></strong> -- The organized priesthood of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>, devoted to the worship of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> and the virtues of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>. The Temples wield enormous cultural influence and serve as moral arbiters across the Empire.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ministers</a></strong> -- Senior officials appointed by the Emperor to oversee specific domains of governance such as war, finance, law, and foreign affairs.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Below the Emperor, provincial authority is delegated to <strong><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governors</a></strong> (civilian administrators) and <strong><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legates</a></strong> (military commanders), both appointed directly by the throne.</p>\n<h2 id=\"social-order-the-measure-and-the-scale\">Social Order: The Measure and the Scale</h2>\n<p>Imperial society is governed by a rigid patronage system known as the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>. This legal and philosophical code dictates obligations between patrons and clients, defines social rank, and establishes the moral expectations of citizens. Social status within the Empire matters far more than race or ethnicity -- a <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> general or a <a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">Targ</a> merchant can rise to positions of tremendous influence if they navigate the patronage system effectively, while a <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-culture\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> of poor standing may find themselves with no more rights than a freedman.</p>\n<p>The Measure defines law and civic duty. The Scale defines virtue and moral conduct. Together they form the bedrock of Imperial identity.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-great-houses\">The Great Houses</h2>\n<p>Political power is concentrated among the <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a>, noble families whose wealth, military strength, and patronage networks shape the direction of the Empire. The current ruling house is <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a>, which secured dominance after the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> in 270 IY. Other major houses include <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-malventi\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Malventi</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-aurel\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Aurel</a>, and <a href=\"#/page/house-severian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Severian</a>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"current-state-of-the-empire\">Current State of the Empire</h2>\n<p>Under <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a>, the Empire endures but faces mounting pressures. The frontier provinces contend with <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> raids, <a href=\"#/page/skiothan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skiothan</a> incursions, and the lingering aftermath of the <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a>. Internal tensions simmer between the <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> grow increasingly assertive, and the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> guards its arcane monopoly with paranoid vigilance. The Empire remains the mightiest power in the known world, but cracks in the edifice grow wider with each passing year.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-calendar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Calendar</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Races and Cultures of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"mornish","title":"Mornish","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","mornish","naming","human","rebellious","morn","honorific","lycandite","second-war-of-morn","8th-undying"],"html":"<h1 id=\"mornish\">Mornish</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Mornish</strong> are a hardy and practical people from the <strong>Peninsula of Morn</strong>, a region comprising dozens of fiercely independent cultures united more by geography and temperament than by any central authority. The Mornish place great emphasis on personal honor, earned reputation, and the deeds by which an individual distinguishes themselves. Mornish society values action over birth, and a person&#39;s standing is determined more by what they have done than by who their parents were.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Mornish are tall with fair skin and dark hair. Their builds tend toward the robust and practical -- a people shaped by the demands of a peninsula where life is hard, competition is fierce, and softness is a liability.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Peninsula of Morn contains <strong>dozens of fiercely independent cultures</strong>, each with its own customs, traditions, and rivalries. What unites the Mornish is not uniformity but a shared temperament: direct, uncompromising, and possessed of a deep <strong>rebellious streak</strong> that has made the province a persistent thorn in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire&#39;s</a> side.</p>\n<p>The province of Morn has <strong>caused trouble for the Empire throughout its existence</strong>. The Mornish temperament -- independent, honor-driven, suspicious of distant authority -- is fundamentally incompatible with the centralized control the Empire demands. Every generation produces new grievances, new uprisings, and new reasons for Imperial administrators to dread assignment to Morn.</p>\n<h3 id=\"honorific-titles\">Honorific Titles</h3>\n<p><strong>Honorific titles</strong> are a distinctive feature of Mornish culture. These titles are earned through battle, trade, or notable deed and are appended to the bearer&#39;s name as a mark of respect. Crucially, honorific titles are <strong>never self-given</strong> -- they must be bestowed by one&#39;s peers or community. To claim an unearned title is considered a grave dishonor, one of the few transgressions that can permanently destroy a Mornish person&#39;s reputation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Mornish names reflect the culture&#39;s blunt and direct character:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Male names</strong> tend to be guttural and forceful</li>\n<li><strong>Female names</strong> are strong and simple</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Mornish naming includes several patronymic and locative particles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>bar</strong> -- meaning &quot;descended from&quot; (e.g., Tormund bar Hagen)</li>\n<li><strong>von</strong> -- meaning &quot;of a place&quot; (e.g., Elsa von Greyhold)</li>\n<li><strong>sen</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (e.g., Erik Torvaldsen)</li>\n<li><strong>ric</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (alternative form)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"historical-events\">Historical Events</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-second-war-of-morn-371-iy\">The Second War of Morn (371 IY)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Second War of Morn</strong> in 371 IY was one of the most devastating conflicts the Empire has fought on the peninsula. The war was driven by <strong>Lycandite fanatics</strong> -- religious extremists whose fervor and willingness to die for their cause made them extraordinarily dangerous opponents.</p>\n<p>During the Second War of Morn, the <strong>14th Army was shattered</strong> -- destroyed as a fighting force by the ferocity of the Lycandite resistance. The catastrophe of the 14th Army stands as one of the most significant Imperial military defeats of the century.</p>\n<p>From the same conflict, the <strong><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">8th Undying</a></strong> became legendary. Their exploits during the Second War of Morn have passed into military legend, and their name is invoked as a standard of valor and sacrifice within the ranks of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Military</a>. The 8th Undying earned their name through deeds that proved the Empire could produce soldiers equal to even the most fanatical resistance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire Morn has troubled throughout its existence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> -- The military that produced the 8th Undying</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The broader historical context</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"races-and-cultures","title":"Races and Cultures","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["races","cultures","humans","eladra","elvora","ygrathen","thune","beastmen","social-status","naming-conventions","mithrian-empire"],"html":"<h1 id=\"races-and-cultures\">Races and Cultures</h1>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> is a large and cosmopolitan collection of different people. Race, ethnicity, and cultural backgrounds matter very little to Mithrians of all walks of life. The Empire&#39;s vast territorial extent and centuries of conquest, migration, and trade have produced a society in which cultural intermixing is the norm rather than the exception. What matters more -- what all Mithrians are aware of almost instinctively -- is social status.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"social-status\">Social Status</h2>\n<p>Within Mithrian culture a strict adherence to social status is followed. Status is the organizing principle of Mithrian life, the lens through which all social interactions are understood and conducted. Citizenship brings numerous benefits including:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The ability to <strong>own land and slaves</strong></li>\n<li>The right to <strong>vote in elections</strong></li>\n<li>The right to <strong>hold office</strong></li>\n<li>And most importantly -- the ability to <strong>gain patronage</strong> of someone more powerful than you</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The patronage system is the engine of Mithrian social mobility. A citizen&#39;s worth is measured not only by their own achievements but by the quality and power of the patrons who vouch for them. Conversely, a patron&#39;s prestige is enhanced by the number and quality of their clients. This web of mutual obligation binds Mithrian society together from the lowest citizen to the Emperor himself.</p>\n<p>Those who lack citizenship -- foreigners, slaves, and the dispossessed -- exist outside this system, with few legal protections and no formal avenue for advancement except through the acquisition of citizenship itself.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"human-cultures\">Human Cultures</h2>\n<p>The following sixteen human cultures comprise the principal ethnic and cultural groups found within and around the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Each possesses its own distinct naming conventions, traditions, and social structures, though centuries of Imperial rule have blurred many boundaries.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"mithrian\">Mithrian</h3>\n<p>The Mithrians are the dominant culture of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and the people from whom the Empire takes its name. Mithrian culture is urban, bureaucratic, and deeply hierarchical, with an emphasis on law, order, and civic duty.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Mithrians use a three-part naming system consisting of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Praenomen</strong> -- the personal or given name, used among intimates and family</li>\n<li><strong>Nomen</strong> -- the family or clan name, indicating lineage and heritage</li>\n<li><strong>Cognomen</strong> -- a distinguishing epithet, often earned through deed or inherited through a family branch</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Among the nobility, the cognomen is favored and carries the greatest social weight, serving as a marker of distinguished lineage or personal accomplishment. Among the peasantry, who may lack a formal cognomen, profession often serves in its place -- a farmer named Marcus of the Varro family who works as a smith might be known simply as Marcus Varro the Smith.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"thrassian\">Thrassian</h3>\n<p>The Thrassians are a proud and warlike people whose ancient tribal system persists within the framework of the Empire. Though formally incorporated into the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, Thrassian communities maintain strong tribal identities, and old loyalties to clan and chief often compete with obligations to the Imperial state.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Thrassians employ a patronymic system:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Men</strong> use the suffixes <strong>-ides</strong> or <strong>-ion</strong> (e.g., Alexandrides, meaning &quot;son of Alexander&quot;)</li>\n<li><strong>Women</strong> use the suffixes <strong>-aia</strong> or <strong>-essa</strong> (e.g., Helenaia, meaning &quot;daughter of Helen&quot;)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The tribal system persists within the Empire, and a Thrassian&#39;s tribal affiliation remains a critical component of their identity, often appended informally to their name.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"corcanoan\">Corcanoan</h3>\n<p>The Corcanoans hail from a chain of volcanic islands, and their culture is shaped by the dramatic and dangerous landscape they call home. Corcanoan society is matriarchal in structure, with lineage traced through the mother&#39;s line and women holding positions of authority in both domestic and public life.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Corcanoan names are melodic and flowing, characteristically ending in vowels or soft consonants. Children are named after their mothers or matriarchal ancestors, reinforcing the matrilineal nature of Corcanoan kinship. A Corcanoan&#39;s name is thus a living record of their maternal lineage, connecting them to generations of women who came before.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"mornish\">Mornish</h3>\n<p>The Mornish are a hardy and practical people who place great emphasis on personal honor, earned reputation, and the deeds by which an individual distinguishes themselves. Mornish society values action over birth, and a person&#39;s standing is determined more by what they have done than by who their parents were.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Mornish names reflect the culture&#39;s blunt and direct character:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Male names</strong> tend to be guttural and forceful</li>\n<li><strong>Female names</strong> are strong and simple</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Mornish naming includes several patronymic and locative particles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>bar</strong> -- meaning &quot;descended from&quot; (e.g., Tormund bar Hagen)</li>\n<li><strong>von</strong> -- meaning &quot;of a place&quot; (e.g., Elsa von Greyhold)</li>\n<li><strong>sen</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (e.g., Erik Torvaldsen)</li>\n<li><strong>ric</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (alternative form)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Honorific titles</strong> are a distinctive feature of Mornish culture. These titles are earned through battle, trade, or notable deed and are appended to the bearer&#39;s name as a mark of respect. Crucially, honorific titles are <strong>never self-given</strong> -- they must be bestowed by one&#39;s peers or community. To claim an unearned title is considered a grave dishonor.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"kolani\">Kolani</h3>\n<p>The Kolani are a diverse people divided into two principal groups defined by their ancestral homeland:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>ton&#39;Kolani</strong> -- the people of the plains, seminomadic pastoralists and warriors</li>\n<li><strong>don&#39;Kolani</strong> -- the people of the forest, settled communities with deep ties to the woodland</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Kolani names are bestowed by the village seer, who invokes spirits, natural forces, and ancestral memory to determine the name that best suits the child. This naming ceremony is a sacred ritual, and the name given is believed to carry spiritual significance and power. Clan names serve as surnames, tying the individual to their broader kinship group.</p>\n<p><strong>Honorific and totemic titles</strong> play an important role in Kolani culture. These titles, earned through deeds of valor, spiritual achievement, or community service, can replace a Kolani&#39;s given name entirely. A warrior who earns a totemic title may be known by that title alone for the rest of their life.</p>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a></strong> are a notable military formation within the Imperial army, composed entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors. They serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry, and their unconventional tactics have proven invaluable in the Empire&#39;s frontier campaigns.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"avari\">Avari</h3>\n<p>The Avari are a people shaped by loss and remembrance. Their culture places great emphasis on honoring the dead and preserving the memory of those who have fallen.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Avari children are named after a fallen relative or hero, ensuring that the names of the honored dead continue to live in the present generation. The patronymic suffix <strong>-sson</strong> is used to denote descent (e.g., Bjornsson, meaning &quot;son of Bjorn&quot;). Many Avari have adopted Mithrian names over the centuries of Imperial rule, blending their ancestral naming traditions with those of the dominant culture.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"lysean\">Lysean</h3>\n<p>The Lyseans are a deeply religious and scholarly people whose culture is suffused with spiritual devotion and intellectual inquiry.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Lysean names characteristically end in <strong>-an</strong>, <strong>-ur</strong>, <strong>-ik</strong>, or <strong>-el</strong>, giving them a distinctive cadence. The patronymic suffixes <strong>-ian</strong> or <strong>-yan</strong> denote descent (e.g., Gregorian, meaning &quot;son of Gregor&quot;). Lyseans also employ <strong>honorific and religious earned names</strong>, bestowed upon individuals who achieve distinction in spiritual or scholarly pursuits. These earned names carry great prestige and may supplement or replace the bearer&#39;s birth name.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"targ\">Targ</h3>\n<p>The Targ are a secretive and insular people whose naming practices reflect a deep cultural suspicion of external knowledge and power.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> The Targ have no traditional naming system in the conventional sense. Instead, each Targ possesses a <strong>secret true name</strong> known only to themselves and, in some traditions, to their closest family members. This true name is believed to hold power over the individual, and its revelation to outsiders is considered an act of profound vulnerability or betrayal. In daily life, Targ use <strong>simple nicknames</strong> -- short, functional appellations that carry no spiritual weight and can be discarded or changed at will.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"shenti\">Shenti</h3>\n<p>The Shenti are a passionate and expressive people whose culture draws heavily on celestial imagery, martial virtue, and the symbolism of fire and light.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Shenti names are rich in vowels and draw their inspiration from:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Celestial bodies</strong> -- sun, moon, stars, and constellations</li>\n<li><strong>Virtues</strong> -- courage, wisdom, justice, and mercy</li>\n<li><strong>Lions</strong> -- the lion being a central symbol in Shenti culture</li>\n<li><strong>Fire</strong> -- representing passion, purification, and divine power</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Shenti naming includes the following particles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>ibn</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (e.g., Rashid ibn Khalil)</li>\n<li><strong>satra</strong> -- meaning &quot;of the house of&quot; (e.g., Farah satra Amani)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"tet\">Tet</h3>\n<p>The Tet are a devout people whose culture is deeply intertwined with religious tradition and the veneration of saints, prophets, and sacred virtues.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Tet names reflect a connection to a saint, prophet, or virtue, serving as a constant reminder of the spiritual ideals the bearer is expected to embody. Naming particles include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>ben</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (e.g., David ben Solomon)</li>\n<li><strong>bat</strong> -- meaning &quot;daughter of&quot; (e.g., Miriam bat Sarah)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"lakandi\">Lakandi</h3>\n<p>The Lakandi are a fierce and uncompromising warrior culture in which personal honor, martial prowess, and the ability to endure hardship are the measures of an individual&#39;s worth.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Lakandi names are built from short, harsh consonants and open vowels, producing names that are as blunt and direct as the people themselves. Uniquely among the cultures of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, Lakandi names are not fixed at birth -- they <strong>change after trials</strong>, with individuals earning new names through feats of combat, endurance, or survival. These <strong>earned names</strong> typically depict violence, strength, or the natural forces the bearer has overcome.</p>\n<p>The Lakandi practice of naming carries a dark counterpart: cowards and oathbreakers are stripped of their names entirely, becoming <strong>Nameless</strong>. The Nameless are exiled from Lakandi society, cast out to wander without identity, kinship, or honor. To be made Nameless is considered a fate worse than death.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"skiothan\">Skiothan</h3>\n<p>The Skiothans are a mystical and introspective people whose culture revolves around the concept of dreams, the afterlife, and the hidden nature of the self.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Skiothan given names are short and vowel-rich, easy to speak and pleasant to the ear. However, beneath every Skiothan&#39;s public name lies a <strong>secret True Name</strong>, uttered only twice in the bearer&#39;s life -- once at birth and once at death. The True Name is believed to be the key by which the soul navigates the afterlife, known to the Skiothans as the <strong>Infinite Dream</strong>. To speak a Skiothan&#39;s True Name at any other time is to endanger their soul&#39;s passage into the Dream, and is considered an unspeakable violation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"grathar\">Grathar</h3>\n<p>The Grathar are a physically imposing and culturally austere people, renowned for their strength, endurance, and directness. They are notable for carrying <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> blood in their veins -- a heritage that manifests in their exceptional size and physical power.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Grathar use singular, short, hard-sounding names that convey brute strength and natural force. Names like Krug, Brak, or Thond are typical -- monosyllabic, percussive, and utterly without ornamentation. The Grathar see no need for patronymics, clan names, or honorifics; a Grathar&#39;s name is their name, and it is enough.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"massar\">Massar</h3>\n<p>The Massar are a culturally sophisticated people whose traditions bear the deep imprint of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> influence. Their civilization rose from the ruins of the Argollean Empire, and their language, art, and naming conventions all reflect this heritage.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Massar names are Argollean-influenced, characterized by elongated vowels and a flowing, musical cadence. Naming particles include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>net</strong> -- meaning &quot;house of&quot; (e.g., Amara net Solenn)</li>\n<li><strong>sah</strong> -- meaning &quot;blood of&quot; (e.g., Kassim sah Durai)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Massar are also notable for their historical role as advisors within the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a>, where Massar counselors eventually orchestrated the overthrow of their Thune overlords.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"vestari\">Vestari</h3>\n<p>The Vestari are a proud and aristocratic people who trace their lineage to <a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a>, the legendary founder of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. This claimed descent from the Empire&#39;s greatest hero gives the Vestari an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny.</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Appearance:</strong> The Vestari are tall and narrow-faced with heavy brows and black hair, which is characteristically slicked back. Men carry heavy, well-groomed beards as a mark of dignity and status. Their skin ranges from olive to pale, and they favor ornate jewelry -- rings, chains, clasps, and brooches -- as expressions of wealth, lineage, and personal accomplishment.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Vestari names are ornate and multi-syllabic, frequently incorporating references to virtues, ancestors, and religious concepts. A Vestari&#39;s full name is a declaration of heritage, a compressed genealogy that connects the bearer to their illustrious forebears and the spiritual ideals they are expected to uphold.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"rinoan\">Rinoan</h3>\n<p>The Rinoans are a northern people -- tall, pale, and hardened by the harsh conditions of their homeland. They are organized into clans and warbands, and their culture values martial prowess, loyalty, and endurance above all else.</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Appearance:</strong> Rinoans are pale and tall, with long pleated hair and beards. Their most striking feature is their <strong>piercing blue eyes</strong>, which are almost universal among the Rinoan people. A few rare individuals are born with <strong>pale yellow eyes</strong>, a trait that is regarded with superstition and awe -- such individuals are often believed to possess unusual gifts or to be marked by fate.</p>\n<p><strong>Naming Conventions:</strong> Rinoan names are short and curt, reflecting the culture&#39;s no-nonsense character. Clan and warband names serve as identifiers of allegiance and kinship, and are appended to the individual&#39;s given name.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"ancillary-races\">Ancillary Races</h2>\n<p>Beyond the sixteen human cultures, the world of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> is home to several non-human races, each with its own ancient history, biology, and relationship to the mortal world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"eladra\">Eladra</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> were once part of the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>, where they played a central role in the discovery of the secrets of the cosmos, the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> gods. The Eladra were the original practitioners of the sorcerous arts that would later be systematized as <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, and their scholarship laid the foundations for much of what the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> teaches today.</p>\n<p>Their civilization fell to ruin through the influence of the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> and the creeping corruption of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> power. The precise nature of this fall is debated by scholars, but the result was the near-total destruction of Eladran culture and the scattering of its people.</p>\n<p>Those claiming Eladran heritage in the present day are almost invariably of mixed blood -- the product of centuries of intermarriage with humans and other peoples. Only a handful of full-blooded Eladra still live, and these survivors are extremely old and deeply reclusive, withdrawing from the affairs of the mortal world into isolation and silence.</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Appearance:</strong> The Eladra are taller than humans, with lithe but muscular builds that combine grace with surprising physical strength. They possess a natural affinity for sorcery -- an innate sensitivity to the metaphysical axioms that govern reality -- which made them the foremost sorcerers of the ancient world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"elvora\">Elvora</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> are of <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> descent, but they have been fundamentally changed by exposure to the chaotic energies of the <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a>. Where the Eladra sought to understand and codify the laws of reality, the Elvora plunged into the raw chaos that lies beneath those laws, and they were transformed by the experience.</p>\n<p>The Elvora achieved eternal life, but at a terrible cost:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Females are barren</strong> -- unable to bear children, cutting off the possibility of natural reproduction</li>\n<li><strong>Males are immortal</strong> -- unable to die of natural causes, condemned to endure the endless passage of time</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Elvora are thus a slowly dying race, their numbers dwindling with each passing century as attrition, violence, and madness claim those who cannot be replaced. They are impossibly old, and the weight of millennia has left many with fractured memories and splintered personalities. An Elvoran who has lived for thousands of years may speak of ancient events with crystalline clarity while being unable to remember their own name from one day to the next.</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Appearance:</strong> The Elvora are taller than humans and extremely muscular, their bodies hardened by centuries of existence and the transformative effects of chaotic energy. Their skin is pale white, and their eyes are solid black -- lacking iris, pupil, or sclera. They tend to be hairless, and many lack consideration for modesty or clothing, regarding such conventions as meaningless affectations of mortal culture.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"ygrathen\">Ygrathen</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> are the oldest of all the races of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> -- ancient beyond reckoning, predating even the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>. They are solitary beings by nature, coming together only to breed, which occurs every 33 years under specific cosmological conditions tied to the alignment of celestial bodies.</p>\n<p>The Ygrathen never formed their own civilization in any conventional sense. They are too solitary, too individualistic, and too prone to conflict with their own kind. Throughout their long history, the Ygrathen clashed amongst themselves as often as they fought against other races, preventing any lasting social organization from taking root.</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Appearance:</strong> The Ygrathen are massive -- standing approximately 12 feet tall, with greenish or ochre skin and small tusks protruding from their lower jaws. Despite their brutish appearance, the Ygrathen possess powerful sorcery, and their magical abilities are among the most formidable in the world.</p>\n<p>The Ygrathen&#39;s war against the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> was a cataclysmic conflict that left most of their kind dead or driven into hiding. The few survivors retreated into the most remote and inaccessible regions of Mithrapos, where they remain to this day -- hidden, diminished, but not extinct. The <a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Grathar</a> people carry Ygrathen blood in their veins, a heritage that accounts for their exceptional size and strength.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"thune\">Thune</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> were created by the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolleans</a> as slave soldiers to fight against the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> -- living weapons bred for war. They are reptilian in appearance and possess an alien cunning and intellect that sets them apart from the other races of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. The Thune are wicked and violent by nature and by design, embodying the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> faith in its most brutal form: the strongest consume and rule the weakest.</p>\n<p>The Thune once ruled the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a>, a dominion built on conquest, cruelty, and the subjugation of all other peoples within their reach. This empire was eventually overthrown by <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a> advisors -- counselors who had been brought into the Thunean court and who used their position to orchestrate the empire&#39;s downfall from within.</p>\n<p>In the present day, the Thune are found only in rare pockets -- scattered remnants of their former empire, hiding in remote and inhospitable regions. They are savage but patient, biding their time for what they call the <strong>Awakening</strong> -- a prophesied event in which the Thune will rise again to reclaim their former dominion.</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Appearance:</strong> The Thune come in various shapes and sizes, the product of extensive breeding programs conducted over millennia. Some are small and swift, bred for scouting and infiltration; others are massive and heavily armored, designed for frontline combat. All share the fundamental reptilian characteristics of scaled skin, cold blood, and predatory instinct.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"beastmen\">Beastmen</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> are a collection of species of monstrous humans -- not a single race but a diverse array of twisted, mutated beings united only by their shared origin and their universal reputation for savagery. They were created by the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> as the core of its armies, purpose-bred for war through sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding.</p>\n<p>After the defeat of the Massaran Empire, the Beastmen were scattered, left without purpose or direction. They have since devolved into roving warbands and feral packs, preying on the weak and the unwary. They are exceedingly cruel and violent, feared and reviled by all other peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Appearance:</strong> The appearances of Beastmen differ wildly from one individual to the next, but all carry a twisted and mutated animal aspect -- horns, fangs, claws, fur, scales, or other bestial features grafted onto a roughly humanoid frame. No two Beastmen are exactly alike, and the variety of their mutations reflects the chaotic and uncontrolled nature of the sorcery that created them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani-munitions\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani Irregulars</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"rinoan","title":"Rinoan","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","rinoan","naming","human","tribal","warrior","northern","mercenary","mithrapos","confederation"],"html":"<h1 id=\"rinoan\">Rinoan</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Rinoans</strong> are a fierce, warlike confederation of tribal peoples who inhabit the northern shores of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. Organized into clans and warbands, their culture values martial prowess, loyalty, and endurance above all else. Few Rinoans are seen outside their homelands, though some mercenary bands have made a name for themselves in the wider world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>Rinoans are <strong>pale and tall</strong>, with <strong>long pleated hair and beards</strong> worn in elaborate styles that denote clan affiliation, status, and personal achievement. Their most striking feature is their <strong>piercing blue eyes</strong>, which are almost universal among the Rinoan people.</p>\n<p>A few rare individuals are born with <strong>pale yellow eyes</strong> -- a trait that is regarded with superstition and awe. Such individuals are often believed to possess unusual gifts or to be marked by fate, and they occupy a special place in Rinoan culture -- respected, feared, and watched with particular attention.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Rinoans are organized into <strong>clans and warbands</strong>, and their culture revolves around martial prowess, loyalty to one&#39;s sworn companions, and the ability to endure hardship without complaint. The harsh conditions of their northern homeland -- cold seas, rocky shores, and unforgiving winters -- have produced a people who regard comfort as weakness and struggle as the natural condition of life.</p>\n<p><strong>Few Rinoans are seen outside their homelands.</strong> They are an insular people, suspicious of outsiders and contemptuous of softer civilizations. Those who do venture beyond Rinoan territory tend to be warriors -- <strong>mercenary bands</strong> that have made a name for themselves through ferocity, discipline, and absolute reliability. A Rinoan mercenary who gives their word will keep it unto death; this reputation makes Rinoan warriors highly sought after despite their limited numbers.</p>\n<p>The Rinoan confederation is not a unified state but a loose alliance of clans that cooperate against external threats while maintaining fierce internal rivalries. Clan warfare is a constant feature of Rinoan life, though it follows elaborate codes of conduct that outsiders rarely understand.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Rinoan names are <strong>short and curt</strong>, reflecting the culture&#39;s no-nonsense character. Names are functional, direct, and stripped of ornamentation -- a Rinoan name says what it needs to say and nothing more.</p>\n<p><strong>Clan and warband names</strong> serve as identifiers of allegiance and kinship, and are appended to the individual&#39;s given name. A Rinoan warrior introduced by both given name and clan name is declaring not only their identity but their loyalties -- whom they fight with, whom they answer to, and whom they will die for.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire beyond Rinoan borders</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"sacking-of-crossings","title":"The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY)","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["event","history","beastmen","backlands","crossings","scalpers","imperial-bounty","catastrophe"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-sacking-of-crossings-377-iy\">The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY)</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Sacking of Crossings</strong> (377 IY) was one of the most devastating and consequential events in recent Imperial history. A massive <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> horde descended on the northern town of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, overwhelming its defenders, razing the settlement, and slaughtering or scattering its people. The destruction of Crossings led directly to the collapse of Imperial authority in the surrounding region and set in motion the chain of events that has plunged the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> into their current state of lawlessness and anarchy.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;Crossings did not fall in a day. It fell in the silence of senators, in the turning away of eyes, in the fortunes of the governor rising even as the gates were breached.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Senator Cassius</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-sacking\">The Sacking</h2>\n<p>The Beastmen horde that descended on <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> was of a size and ferocity that overwhelmed the town&#39;s defenses. The <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> -- descendants of the legions scattered during the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> -- had gathered in unprecedented numbers, driven by forces and motivations that remain poorly understood. The town&#39;s garrison, already undermanned and under-supplied, could not hold.</p>\n<p>Crossings was razed. Its people were slaughtered or driven into the wilderness. The town that had served as a trading hub and frontier outpost for generations was destroyed in a matter of days.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"institutional-failure\">Institutional Failure</h2>\n<p>As Senator Cassius&#39;s damning words make clear, the Sacking was not the result of an overwhelming external threat alone. It was enabled by the corruption, negligence, and complicity of Imperial officials:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Senators who looked the other way</strong> -- Warnings about frontier defenses were ignored by a <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Senate</a> preoccupied with factional politics and personal enrichment</li>\n<li><strong>Governors who enriched themselves</strong> -- Provincial officials who diverted military resources and tax revenue to their own benefit while defenses crumbled</li>\n<li><strong>The turning away of eyes</strong> -- A systematic failure of institutional responsibility at every level, from the court in <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> to the provincial bureaucracy</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The fall of Crossings was a failure of the Empire&#39;s institutions as much as it was a failure of its armies. Senator Cassius&#39;s accusation -- that the governor&#39;s fortune rose &quot;even as the gates were breached&quot; -- points to a level of corruption that borders on complicity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-imperial-bounty\">The Imperial Bounty</h2>\n<p>In response to the Sacking, Emperor <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> issued an <strong>Imperial scalp bounty</strong> on <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a>. The bounty was intended to suppress the beastman threat by unleashing the profit motive against them. Anyone who delivered beastman scalps to Imperial agents would be paid from the treasury.</p>\n<p>The consequences were catastrophic. The bounty unleashed a wave of <strong>mercenaries, deserters, and killers</strong> into the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. These individuals -- collectively known as <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalpers</a> -- poured into the frontier provinces in pursuit of bounty money. While beastman activity near settled areas has decreased, the influx of violent fortune-seekers has created new and terrible problems:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Scalper gangs prey on travelers and settlers as readily as on beastmen</li>\n<li>The bounty economy attracts the worst elements of Imperial society</li>\n<li>Fraud is rampant -- human and non-beastman scalps are passed off as legitimate claims</li>\n<li>The violence of the Scalpers has made large areas of the Backlands more dangerous, not less</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"consequences\">Consequences</h2>\n<p>The Sacking of Crossings and its aftermath have fundamentally reshaped the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Collapse of Imperial authority</strong> -- The destruction of Crossings destroyed the last pretense of effective imperial governance in the region</li>\n<li><strong>The Scalper economy</strong> -- The Imperial Bounty created an entire economic ecosystem built on violence</li>\n<li><strong>Power vacuum</strong> -- The absence of imperial authority has allowed local strongmen like <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> to consolidate independent power bases</li>\n<li><strong>Refugee crisis</strong> -- Survivors of Crossings scattered across the Backlands, adding to the displaced populations that strain the resources of remaining settlements</li>\n<li><strong>The garrison recall</strong> -- The Emperor&#39;s subsequent recall of armies to face the Skiothan threat (378 IY) compounded the crisis, stripping the Backlands of whatever military protection remained</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Backlands have never recovered. The region remains a lawless frontier where Imperial law is a distant memory and survival is the only currency that matters.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- the town that was destroyed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> -- issued the Imperial Bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper Gangs</a> -- consequence of the bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> -- provincial strongman</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- the region devastated by the aftermath</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean War</a> -- the war that created the Beastmen threat</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"shenti","title":"Shenti","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","shenti","naming","human","massar","celestial","shent","tulmuk","cthonic"],"html":"<h1 id=\"shenti\">Shenti</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Shenti</strong> are a passionate and expressive people whose culture draws heavily on celestial imagery, martial virtue, and the symbolism of fire and light. Former subjects of the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>, the Shenti bear the imprint of Massar influence even centuries after that empire&#39;s fall -- in their art, their architecture, their spiritual traditions, and their naming conventions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Shenti are characterized by tan skin and dark eyes. Their complexion reflects their homeland&#39;s climate -- warmer and more arid than the Imperial heartland -- and their dark eyes are a near-universal feature that gives Shenti faces a distinctive intensity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Shenti were once subjects of the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>, and <strong>Massar influence is still felt</strong> in every aspect of Shenti culture. The sorcerer-kings of Massar left a deep imprint on the peoples they ruled, and the Shenti have never fully shed the cultural inheritance of that older civilization -- its aesthetic sensibilities, its hierarchical instincts, its relationship to power and authority.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-fall-of-shent\">The Fall of Shent</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Province of Shent</strong> has <strong>fallen to Cthonic Tulmuk barbarian tribes</strong>. These <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a>-worshipping invaders have overrun the Shenti homeland, driving its people from their ancestral territory and destroying or corrupting the institutions that once defined Shenti life. The fall of Shent is one of the Empire&#39;s most significant territorial losses, and it represents a catastrophe for the Shenti people -- the destruction of everything they built over centuries.</p>\n<p>Despite this catastrophe, <strong>many Shenti still live within the Empire</strong>. Displaced from their homeland, Shenti communities have established themselves in cities and provinces throughout Imperial territory. They carry their culture with them -- their traditions, their naming practices, their spiritual devotion -- maintaining identity in exile in much the same way the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> have done in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary#ashward\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ashward</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Shenti names are rich in vowels and draw their inspiration from:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Celestial bodies</strong> -- the sun, moon, stars, and constellations, reflecting the Shenti fascination with the heavens</li>\n<li><strong>Virtues</strong> -- courage, wisdom, justice, and mercy, naming children after the qualities they are expected to embody</li>\n<li><strong>Lions</strong> -- the lion being a central symbol in Shenti culture, representing strength, nobility, and royal authority</li>\n<li><strong>Fire</strong> -- representing passion, purification, and divine power</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Shenti naming includes the following particles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>ibn</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (e.g., Rashid ibn Khalil)</li>\n<li><strong>satra</strong> -- meaning &quot;of the house of&quot; (e.g., Farah satra Amani)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">massar</a> -- The empire that once ruled the Shenti</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire where Shenti now live</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The faith of the Tulmuk invaders who took Shent</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"skiothan","title":"Skiothan","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","skiothan","naming","human","nomadic","horse-warriors","grathe-steppe","true-name","infinite-dream","raiders"],"html":"<h1 id=\"skiothan\">Skiothan</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Skiothans</strong> are a mystical and introspective people whose culture revolves around the concept of dreams, the afterlife, and the hidden nature of the self. Despite their philosophical depth, they are also fearsome <strong>nomadic horse warriors</strong> who raid the western provinces of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> from the vast <strong>Grathe Steppe</strong>, and who believe themselves superior to all other races.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Skiothans are tall with dark hair and dark eyes. Their builds are lean and powerful, shaped by a lifetime in the saddle -- the horse is not merely a tool of Skiothan warfare but an extension of Skiothan identity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Skiothans are nomadic horse warriors who roam the <strong>Grathe Steppe</strong>, the vast grassland that lies beyond the Empire&#39;s western frontier. They <strong>raid the western provinces</strong> with devastating effectiveness, their mounted tactics overwhelming the heavier but less mobile Imperial formations sent to stop them.</p>\n<p>The Skiothans <strong>believe themselves superior to all other races</strong> -- a conviction that is not mere arrogance but a deeply held spiritual belief rooted in their cosmology. In the Skiothan worldview, they are the chosen people, the riders who will gallop through the Infinite Dream when all other peoples have been forgotten.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-infinite-dream\">The Infinite Dream</h3>\n<p>The Skiothan afterlife is called the <strong>Infinite Dream</strong> -- a spiritual realm that the soul enters upon death. The passage into the Infinite Dream is not automatic; it requires navigation, and the key to that navigation is the bearer&#39;s True Name. Without their True Name, a Skiothan soul wanders lost, unable to find its way into the Dream. With it, the passage is assured.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Skiothan given names are <strong>short and vowel-rich</strong>, easy to speak and pleasant to the ear. These public names are used in daily life and carry no particular spiritual weight.</p>\n<p>However, beneath every Skiothan&#39;s public name lies a <strong>secret True Name</strong>, uttered only <strong>twice</strong> in the bearer&#39;s life -- once at <strong>birth</strong> and once at <strong>death</strong>. The True Name is believed to be the key by which the soul navigates the afterlife. To speak a Skiothan&#39;s True Name at any other time is to <strong>endanger their soul&#39;s passage</strong> into the Infinite Dream, and is considered an <strong>unspeakable violation</strong> -- an act of spiritual murder more heinous than physical killing.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-skiothan-threat\">The Skiothan Threat</h2>\n<p>The Skiothan raids on the western provinces have escalated to the point of existential threat. In <strong>378 IY</strong>, the <strong>Emperor recalled armies</strong> from the provinces -- including the garrisons of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> -- to fight the Skiothan threat. This withdrawal left frontier provinces like <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> undermanned and poorly defended, effectively abandoning them to their fate in order to address the Skiothan danger closer to the Imperial heartland.</p>\n<p>The Emperor&#39;s decision reflects the severity of the Skiothan threat: the raids are not merely border skirmishes but a sustained military campaign that threatens the Empire&#39;s core territories. The Skiothans&#39; mobility, their knowledge of the Grathe Steppe, and their willingness to fight a war of maneuver against an empire built for siege and occupation make them one of the most dangerous enemies the Empire currently faces.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire the Skiothans raid</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">grathar</a> -- The other people of the Grathe Steppe</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- A province abandoned due to the Skiothan threat</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The broader context of the Skiothan wars</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"targ","title":"Targ","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["race","culture","targ","naming","magically-created","imperial-academy","the-eater","rebellion","slaves","citizens"],"html":"<h1 id=\"targ\">Targ</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Targ</strong> are a magically created race, brought into existence by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial College</a> to supplement the armies of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Once slaves, now citizens, the Targ occupy a unique and often uncomfortable position within Imperial society -- a people who were designed as tools and who fought a bloody war to be recognized as persons.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Targ are tall with ochre to grey skin and light eyes. They are <strong>stronger than men</strong>, with powerful builds that reflect the martial purpose for which they were created. Their appearance is distinctive and immediately recognizable -- the skin coloration, the light eyes set against darker features, the sheer physical mass that sets them apart from baseline humans.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Targ possess a <strong>vicious streak and hot tempers</strong> -- traits that were deliberately bred into them by their creators at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, who wanted soldiers, not scholars. These characteristics remain even now, generations after emancipation, and they continue to shape Targ culture and the way other peoples perceive them.</p>\n<p>Once slaves, the Targ are now <strong>citizens with their own communities</strong> within the Empire. The road from property to personhood was paved with blood -- the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos#targ-rebellion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Targ Rebellion</a> of 261 IY was one of the most traumatic events in Imperial history, and its resolution fundamentally changed the legal and moral landscape of the Empire.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-targ-rebellion-261-iy\">The Targ Rebellion (261 IY)</h3>\n<p>The Targ rose in violent revolt against the Empire that had enslaved them. Their leader, known only as <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Eater</a></strong>, led a devastating campaign that reached <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> itself. The Eater sacked the capital and slew <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Antonius</a>, an act of violence that shook the Empire to its foundations.</p>\n<p>Peace was eventually brokered by <strong><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Symander</a></strong> of the Imperial Academy. Under the terms of the settlement, the Targ were granted <strong>full citizenship under the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></strong>, transforming them from property into people in the eyes of Imperial law.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>The Targ have <strong>no traditional naming system</strong> in the conventional sense. Their naming practices reflect a deep cultural suspicion of external knowledge and power -- a suspicion born from generations of enslavement during which their creators held absolute authority over every aspect of their existence, including their identities.</p>\n<p>Each Targ possesses a <strong>secret true name</strong> known only to themselves and, in some traditions, to their closest family members. This true name is believed to hold power over the individual, and its revelation to outsiders is considered an act of profound vulnerability or betrayal. The true name is guarded with fierce intensity -- to know a Targ&#39;s true name is to hold a weapon against them.</p>\n<p>In daily life, Targ use <strong>simple nicknames</strong> -- short, functional appellations that carry no spiritual weight and can be discarded or changed at will. These nicknames serve the practical purpose of identification without exposing the bearer to the risks associated with their true name&#39;s revelation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire that created and then emancipated the Targ</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution that created the Targ</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The Targ Rebellion in broader context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> -- The legal framework that granted Targ citizenship</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"tet","title":"Tet","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","tet","naming","human","tezerat","massar","superstitious","enador","crescent-rebellion","measure-and-scale"],"html":"<h1 id=\"tet\">Tet</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Tet</strong> are a devout people from the <strong>Tezerat Plateau</strong>, whose culture is deeply intertwined with religious tradition and the veneration of saints, prophets, and sacred virtues. Former slaves of the <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>, the Tet carry the marks of that subjugation in their fierce independence and deep superstition -- a people shaped by suffering who found meaning through faith.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Tet have tan skin, variable eyes (ranging across a wider spectrum than most peoples of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>), and dark hair. Their appearance reflects the harsh, elevated terrain of the Tezerat Plateau -- a landscape that demands endurance and produces a resilient, weather-hardened people.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Tet are <strong>deeply superstitious</strong>, a trait that pervades every aspect of daily life. Signs, omens, prophecies, and portents carry tremendous weight in Tet culture, and decisions -- from the mundane to the momentous -- are often guided by interpretations of the supernatural rather than by purely rational calculation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"former-massar-slaves\">Former Massar Slaves</h3>\n<p>The Tet were <strong>former <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a> slaves</strong>, subjugated by the sorcerer-kings of the Massaran Empire and held in bondage for generations. The experience of enslavement has left an indelible mark on Tet culture -- a fierce determination never to be subjugated again, combined with a spiritual framework that interprets suffering as a test of faith and liberation as divine reward.</p>\n<h3 id=\"enador-and-the-measure-and-the-scale\">Enador and the Measure and the Scale</h3>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a></strong> discovered the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> on the Tezerat Plateau -- the sacred texts that would become the foundation of <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith and the moral and legal framework of the civilization that followed. This discovery gives the Tezerat Plateau and its people a unique significance in the religious history of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. The Tet regard themselves as the people among whom the divine truth was revealed, and this belief shapes their sense of spiritual identity.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-second-crescent-rebellion\">The Second Crescent Rebellion</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Second Crescent Rebellion</strong> led to the Tet achieving <strong>independence from the Empire</strong>. This rebellion -- driven by the Tet&#39;s fierce independence, their religious convictions, and their unwillingness to submit to distant imperial authority -- resulted in the Tezerat Plateau being granted a degree of autonomy that few other Imperial provinces have achieved. The rebellion demonstrated that the Tet&#39;s devotion to their faith and their freedom exceeded their willingness to submit to Imperial control.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Tet names reflect a <strong>connection to a saint, prophet, or virtue</strong>, serving as a constant reminder of the spiritual ideals the bearer is expected to embody. Every Tet name is a declaration of faith -- an invocation of the sacred that the bearer carries with them through life.</p>\n<p>Naming particles include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>ben</strong> -- meaning &quot;son of&quot; (e.g., David ben Solomon)</li>\n<li><strong>bat</strong> -- meaning &quot;daughter of&quot; (e.g., Miriam bat Sarah)</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">massar</a> -- The empire that once enslaved the Tet</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> -- The sacred texts discovered on the Tezerat Plateau</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> -- The prophet who discovered the Measure and the Scale</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The faith that arose from the Tet homeland</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire from which the Tet won independence</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-anthyllium","title":"The Anthyllium","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["anthyllium","grimoire","gnostic-geometry","nine-fold","enador","imperial-academy","measure-and-the-scale","sorcery","axioms","aurelion"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-anthyllium\">The Anthyllium</h1>\n<p>The Anthyllium is the ancient grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality — the foundational text of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> and one of the most important documents in the history of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Discovered alongside the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> by the Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a>, the Anthyllium contains the formulae still used by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> to train its gnostic geometers and to regulate the practice of structured sorcery throughout the Empire.</p>\n<p>If the Measure and the Scale is the moral constitution of Mithrian civilization — the document that tells the faithful how to live — the Anthyllium is its arcane constitution — the document that tells sorcerers how to reshape reality without destroying it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"contents\">Contents</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-nine-fold-geometric-patterns\">The Nine-Fold Geometric Patterns</h3>\n<p>The Anthyllium describes in meticulous detail the nine-fold geometric patterns that underlie the structure of reality. These patterns are not mere mathematical abstractions but the actual architectural blueprints of the cosmos — the geometric relationships that <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> embedded in the fabric of reality during its sacrifice, and that determine how matter, energy, space, time, and metaphysical forces interact.</p>\n<p>Each of the nine patterns governs a different aspect of reality, and the relationships between them — the ways in which they combine, intersect, reinforce, and counteract each other — determine the full complexity of the natural and supernatural world. The Anthyllium maps these relationships with a precision that has never been equaled, providing the theoretical framework that makes the systematic practice of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> possible.</p>\n<h3 id=\"formulae-of-sorcery\">Formulae of Sorcery</h3>\n<p>Beyond the theoretical description of the nine-fold patterns, the Anthyllium contains practical formulae — specific geometric constructions (sigils), resonance patterns (spoken formulae), and mental disciplines that allow trained practitioners to manipulate the metaphysical axioms encoded in the patterns. These formulae are the working tools of gnostic geometers — the specific techniques by which abstract geometric knowledge is translated into practical magical effect.</p>\n<p>The formulae in the Anthyllium are not spells in the folkloric sense. They are more analogous to engineering specifications — precise, technical documents that describe exactly how to construct a sigil, exactly how to calibrate a resonance, exactly how to discipline the mind for a specific manipulation, and exactly what effects will result if the procedure is followed correctly. They are also explicit about the consequences of error, which can range from the merely painful to the catastrophically destructive.</p>\n<h3 id=\"a-structured-lawful-cosmos\">A Structured, Lawful Cosmos</h3>\n<p>The Anthyllium&#39;s deepest teaching — the philosophical foundation upon which all its practical formulae rest — is that the cosmos is a structured, lawful creation. According to the Anthyllium, sorcery is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout reality — axioms that exist because <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> designed the cosmos with intention and purpose. The cosmos is not chaotic, arbitrary, or random; it is a mathematical construct, built on principles that can be discovered, understood, and applied.</p>\n<p>This teaching aligns the Anthyllium closely with the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a>&#39;s understanding of the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice — the belief that the supreme designer created a cosmos of order, meaning, and purpose. The Anthyllium does not explicitly endorse Empyrean theology, but its foundational assumption — that reality is structured and lawful — is compatible with the Empyrean worldview and incompatible with the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a>&#39;s emphasis on chaos, contest, and the ultimate primacy of will over law.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"discovery\">Discovery</h2>\n<p>The Anthyllium was discovered by the Prophet <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a> alongside the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> — the sacred scripture of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. The dual discovery is one of the pivotal moments in the history of the known world. Enador&#39;s recovery of the Measure and the Scale provided the spiritual authority and moral framework that united the Empyrean faithful. His simultaneous recovery of the Anthyllium provided the arcane knowledge and practical power that enabled those faithful to challenge and ultimately overthrow the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a> and its <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a>.</p>\n<p>The circumstances of the discovery — where the texts were found, how they came to be in the same location, whether they were deliberately placed together or whether their proximity was coincidental — are the subject of extensive debate among scholars and theologians. The orthodox position of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> holds that <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> guided Enador to both texts, that their co-location was divinely arranged, and that the Aurelion intended for moral wisdom and arcane knowledge to be reunited at the moment when the world most needed both.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-status\">Current Status</h2>\n<p>The Anthyllium is held by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, which treats it as both a sacred text and a state secret. Access to the original document is restricted to the highest-ranking members of the Academy&#39;s faculty, and the formulae contained within it are disseminated to students only in carefully controlled portions, calibrated to each student&#39;s level of training and demonstrated competence.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> retains strict control over the Anthyllium and the knowledge it contains for both practical and political reasons. Practically, the formulae of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> are extraordinarily dangerous in untrained hands, and unrestricted access to the Anthyllium would inevitably lead to catastrophic magical accidents. Politically, the Academy&#39;s monopoly on gnostic geometric knowledge is one of the pillars of Imperial power — a monopoly that the Academy, the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, and the Imperial government all have strong incentives to maintain.</p>\n<p>Copies of portions of the Anthyllium exist in various forms — student texts, reference manuals, classified military documents — but the complete, original text is singular and irreplaceable. Its security is a matter of the highest Imperial priority, and the measures taken to protect it are among the most sophisticated in the Empire.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-the-measure-and-the-scale\">Relationship to the Measure and the Scale</h2>\n<p>The Anthyllium and the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> were discovered together and are understood together — the twin pillars of Mithrian civilization, one moral and one arcane. The Measure and the Scale tells the faithful how the cosmos should be inhabited — with virtue, justice, duty, and devotion. The Anthyllium tells them how the cosmos is constructed — with geometry, axioms, and mathematical relationships that can be perceived and manipulated.</p>\n<p>Together, the two texts provide a complete framework for engaging with reality: the Measure and the Scale addresses the soul, and the Anthyllium addresses the mind. The Empyrean faithful believe that both are necessary — that arcane knowledge without moral guidance leads to the kind of tyranny practiced by the <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a>, and that moral conviction without practical power leads to helplessness in the face of evil.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Enador</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerer Kings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-aurelion","title":"The Aurelion","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["aurelion","cosmology","creation","sacrifice","sorcery","souls","empyrean","cthonic","empty-throne"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-aurelion\">The Aurelion</h1>\n<p>The Aurelion is the supreme designer of the cosmos — the singular, transcendent being whose self-sacrifice created all of reality. Both the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a> agree on the fundamental fact of the Aurelion&#39;s existence and sacrifice, making this one of the very few points of theological consensus between the two irreconcilable traditions. Where they diverge — profoundly and irreconcilably — is in their interpretation of why the Aurelion sacrificed itself, what the sacrifice was intended to achieve, and what obligations the sacrifice places upon living beings.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-sacrifice\">The Sacrifice</h2>\n<p>The Aurelion&#39;s self-sacrifice is the foundational event of the cosmos — the singular act from which all of reality proceeds. Before the sacrifice, there was the Aurelion alone. After the sacrifice, there was everything else: matter, energy, space, time, souls, gods, and the living beings that populate the cosmos. The Aurelion did not create the world through an act of will or craftsmanship, as a potter shapes clay. The Aurelion became the world — its essence, its substance, its animating force — by destroying itself utterly and allowing its own being to diffuse throughout the void, transforming formless potential into structured, living reality.</p>\n<p>This is the central mystery of all theology in the known world: the Aurelion is simultaneously absent and omnipresent. It no longer exists as a discrete entity — it sacrificed that existence irrevocably — and yet its essence permeates every particle of the cosmos, every living being, every natural law, every metaphysical axiom. The Aurelion is the cosmos, and the cosmos is the Aurelion&#39;s corpse, its legacy, its final gift.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-essence\">The Essence</h2>\n<p>The Aurelion&#39;s essence permeates the cosmos and all living things. This is not a metaphor but a metaphysical reality with measurable consequences. Every living being possesses a soul — a fragment of the Aurelion&#39;s original being, a spark of the divine substance that animated the supreme designer before the sacrifice. This soul is what distinguishes the living from the dead, the conscious from the inert, the being capable of moral choice from the object that simply exists.</p>\n<p>The presence of the Aurelion&#39;s essence throughout the cosmos is also what makes sorcery possible. The practice of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, the channeling of <a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a>, the manipulation of <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a> — all forms of magic ultimately derive their power from the Aurelion&#39;s essence, which permeates the fabric of reality and can be accessed, channeled, and directed by those with the knowledge and will to do so. Sorcery is, in a very real sense, the manipulation of the Aurelion&#39;s remains.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"interpretations-of-the-sacrifice\">Interpretations of the Sacrifice</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-empyrean-interpretation\">The Empyrean Interpretation</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed itself to purge the cosmos of entropy and evil — to separate light from darkness, order from chaos, virtue from vice. In this interpretation, the sacrifice was an act of supreme moral purpose: the Aurelion saw that the original state of the cosmos was a formless tangle of good and evil, light and dark, order and chaos, and chose to destroy itself in order to impose a moral structure upon reality. The separation of light from darkness — the foundational act that <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> completed and maintains — is the direct consequence of the Aurelion&#39;s sacrificial purpose.</p>\n<p>In the Empyrean understanding, the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice places a moral obligation upon all living beings. Because the cosmos was created through an act of supreme selflessness, the beings who inhabit it are called to emulate that selflessness — to orient their lives toward order, virtue, and the service of others, to resist the entropy and chaos that the sacrifice was designed to overcome. The <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> is the codification of this obligation, the moral law that translates the Aurelion&#39;s sacrificial purpose into practical guidance for daily life.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-cthonic-interpretation\">The Cthonic Interpretation</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a> teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed itself to eliminate weakness — to create a cosmos defined by contest, where only the powerful survive and the weak are rightfully consumed. In this interpretation, the sacrifice was not an act of compassion but an act of refinement: the Aurelion destroyed itself to create a crucible, a testing ground where the strong would prove their worth through struggle, conquest, and the domination of the weak. The cosmos is not a garden to be tended but an arena to be fought in, and the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice created that arena deliberately.</p>\n<p>In the Cthonic understanding, the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice places no moral obligation upon living beings — it places a test. The cosmos rewards strength, cunning, and the will to dominate, and punishes weakness, mercy, and submission. The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a> are the divine exemplars of this principle — beings who have achieved power through contest and who demand that their followers do the same. The Aurelion did not sacrifice itself so that its children could be gentle; it sacrificed itself so that its children could be strong.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-mystical-interpretation\">The Mystical Interpretation</h3>\n<p>A third interpretation, less widely held but persistent among certain philosophical and mystical traditions, holds that the Aurelion sacrificed itself to experience the full spectrum of existence — to become All. In this reading, the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice was neither moral nor competitive but experiential: the supreme designer, existing alone in perfect unity, chose to shatter itself into infinite fragments so that it could experience reality from every possible perspective simultaneously — as light and darkness, as predator and prey, as the saint and the sinner, as every living being that has ever existed or will ever exist.</p>\n<p>In the mystical understanding, every soul is the Aurelion experiencing itself from a unique vantage point. Every act of kindness and every act of cruelty, every moment of joy and every moment of suffering, is the Aurelion&#39;s experience. The cosmos is not a creation but a self-exploration — the Aurelion&#39;s attempt to know itself through the infinite diversity of lived experience. This interpretation is embraced by followers of <a href=\"#/page/the-mystical\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mystical</a> tradition and exists at the margins of both Empyrean and Cthonic orthodoxy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-empty-throne\">The Empty Throne</h2>\n<p>Central to all theological discussion of the Aurelion is the image of the Empty Throne — the seat of cosmic authority that the Aurelion occupied before the sacrifice and that has remained vacant ever since. The Empty Throne is perhaps the most powerful theological symbol in the known world, because both the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a> acknowledge it, and both draw fundamentally different conclusions from its emptiness.</p>\n<p>For the Empyrean faithful, the Empty Throne is a symbol of the Aurelion&#39;s supreme sacrifice — the seat from which the supreme designer ruled the cosmos, voluntarily abandoned so that the cosmos could exist. The emptiness of the throne is sacred, a permanent reminder that the highest power in the universe chose service over dominion, self-destruction over self-preservation. <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> guards the throne but does not sit in it — he is the steward of the Aurelion&#39;s legacy, not its replacement.</p>\n<p>For the Cthonic faithful, the Empty Throne is an invitation — a vacancy waiting to be filled by whoever proves strong enough to claim it. The Aurelion destroyed itself, and its throne stands empty. The cosmos has no ruler, no supreme authority, no final arbiter — and the contest to fill that void is the fundamental drama of existence. The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a> compete for the throne, and the <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a> — the prophesied return of the Cthonic gods to the material world — may be understood as the opening move in the final contest for cosmic supremacy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Awakening</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-mystical\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mystical</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Pantheon</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-awakening","title":"The Awakening","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["awakening","cthonic","prophecy","resurrection","argolle","nethercity","crossings","great-teacher","erenthis","cthonic-corruption"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-awakening\">The Awakening</h1>\n<p>The Awakening is the prophesied future event in <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> theology when the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a> will return to the material world and the faithful will enjoy true bodily resurrection — not the spiritual afterlife promised by the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> but a physical, corporeal restoration of the flesh, a triumphant reversal of death itself. For most of the known world, the Awakening is a theological concept — a distant eschatological promise that motivates Cthonic worship but has no immediate, observable reality.</p>\n<p>In the Province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, in the year 380 IY, it is an event in progress.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"cthonic-theology-of-the-awakening\">Cthonic Theology of the Awakening</h2>\n<p>In Cthonic eschatology, the current state of the cosmos is not the final state. The separation of light from darkness accomplished by <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, the moral order codified in the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a>, the political dominion of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> — all of these are temporary arrangements, impositions of Empyrean order upon a cosmos that is fundamentally Cthonic in nature. The Awakening is the prophesied moment when these impositions will be swept away, when the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a> will break free of whatever constraints bind them, return to the material world in their full divine power, and establish a new cosmic order based on strength, contest, and the triumph of the will.</p>\n<p>For the Cthonic faithful, the Awakening is not a catastrophe but a liberation — the long-awaited reversal of the cosmic injustice perpetrated by <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and the Empyrean order. The faithful who have endured persecution, who have kept the old rites alive in secret, who have refused to bow before the Winged Sun despite centuries of suppression — these are the ones who will be rewarded when the Cthonic gods return. True bodily resurrection — not the vague spiritual afterlife of Empyrean theology but the actual, physical restoration of the dead — is the Awakening&#39;s ultimate promise.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-awakening-in-argolle\">The Awakening in Argolle</h2>\n<h3 id=\"an-event-in-progress\">An Event in Progress</h3>\n<p>What makes the Awakening uniquely terrifying in the current era is that it is no longer merely a theological concept. In the Province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, 380 IY, the signs of the Awakening are not prophetic speculation but observable phenomena. The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a> that permeates the region — the twisted creatures, the corrupted landscapes, the palpable sense of wrongness that hangs over the backlands — is not random or natural. It is the leading edge of the Awakening, the first tremors of a cosmic event that threatens to tear the fabric of the material world and permit the return of forces that have been absent for millennia.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-nethercity\">The Nethercity</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> is a prepared vessel for the Awakening — a vast, ancient subterranean complex that was designed or adapted to serve as the physical infrastructure through which the Awakening will occur. The Nethercity is not merely an archaeological curiosity or a dungeon to be explored; it is a machine, a metaphysical engine whose purpose is to facilitate the return of the Cthonic gods or their agents to the material world. The exact mechanisms by which the Nethercity accomplishes this purpose are not fully understood, but the scale and sophistication of the complex — along with the intensity of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a> emanating from its depths — leave little doubt about its function.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-great-teacher\">The Great Teacher</h3>\n<p>The Great Teacher rests dormant in the depths of the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> — an entity of immense power and unknown nature whose slumber is the thin barrier between the current state of affairs and the full realization of the Awakening. The Great Teacher&#39;s identity is unclear — whether it is one of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a> themselves, an avatar, a herald, or something else entirely remains a matter of speculation and dread. What is known is that it is there, that it is stirring, and that the increasing urgency of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic-corrupted</a> creatures in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> correlates with its restless slumber.</p>\n<h3 id=\"erenthis-disturbance\">Erenthis Disturbance</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> root network — the vast, living mycorrhizal web that connects the forests of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> and serves as a sensory and communication system for the natural world — has sensed increasing disturbance for two years. The Erenthis is not a conscious entity in the way that mortal beings are conscious, but it is aware in its own fashion, and the signals it transmits through its network have grown increasingly agitated, urgent, and distressed. Druids and naturalists who commune with the Erenthis report a consistent message: something is waking up beneath the ground, and the natural world is afraid.</p>\n<h3 id=\"cthonic-creature-urgency\">Cthonic Creature Urgency</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic-corrupted</a> creatures throughout <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> have begun behaving with increasing urgency — not merely the mindless aggression that characterizes corrupted wildlife but directed, purposeful behavior that suggests coordination, intelligence, or at the very least a shared imperative driving them toward a common goal. Corrupted beasts are moving toward <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> beneath it. Nests of corrupted creatures are growing larger and more organized. Attacks on settlements are increasing in frequency and ferocity. The pattern is unmistakable to those with eyes to see it: the corrupted world is preparing for something.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-convergence\">The Convergence</h2>\n<p>The Awakening is intimately connected to <a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Convergence</a> — the multi-layered crisis currently unfolding in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> that threatens to overwhelm the province&#39;s capacity to respond. The political instability, the military overextension, the religious tensions, the economic pressures — all of these are either caused by or exacerbated by the approaching Awakening, and all of them conspire to ensure that when the Awakening reaches its crisis point, the province will be at its most vulnerable and least prepared.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Nethercity</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Erenthis</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Convergence Problem</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-beyond","title":"The Beyond","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["lore","cosmology","metaphysics","beyond","veil","aurelion","sorcery","cthonic","demons","planes","gods"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-beyond\">The Beyond</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;What lies beyond the Veil is not another world. It is every other world -- tangled together, pressing against the membrane of reality like fingers against wet cloth. When the Aurelion died, it tore a hole in that cloth. The fingers came through.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Beyond</strong> is the multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten and ancient gods, and raw metaphysical potential that exists on the other side of <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>. It is not a single place but a vast, incomprehensible expanse of realities that press against the mortal world, seeking entry, seeking worship, seeking consumption.</p>\n<p>When the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> sacrificed itself, it created a cosmic wound in the Veil, allowing the realities of the Beyond to influence the mortal world in ways that were not previously possible.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>The totality of reality beyond <span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrapos</span> and the material plane. It is not ordered, not comprehensible in mortal terms, and not safe. The entities that inhabit the Beyond range from mindless currents of raw metaphysical energy to ancient gods whose worship predates recorded history to alien intelligences that defy classification.</p>\n<p>The mortal world is separated from the Beyond by <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> -- a metaphysical barrier that once maintained a cleaner division between realities. That division was compromised when the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> sacrificed itself, creating a cosmic wound that has never fully healed. Through that wound, the Beyond exerts influence on the mortal world -- sometimes subtle, sometimes catastrophic, always dangerous.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cosmic-wound\">The Cosmic Wound</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> sacrifice created a wound in <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> that fundamentally altered the relationship between the mortal world and the Beyond. Before the wound, the Veil was a more effective barrier -- not impermeable, but sufficient to maintain a functional separation between realities. After the wound, the Beyond presses against the mortal world with greater force, and the points where the Veil is thin have become more numerous and more unstable.</p>\n<p>This wound is the foundational metaphysical fact of the current age. It explains:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Why <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">sorcery</a> is possible -- sorcerers exploit the wound, opening further tears in the Veil to siphon energies from the Beyond</li>\n<li>Why <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic worship</a> persists -- the Cthonic gods exist in or draw power from the Beyond, and the wound gives them greater access to mortal worshippers</li>\n<li>Why demonic entities can cross into the mortal world -- the wound permits passage that would not otherwise be possible</li>\n<li>Why the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean faith</a> emphasizes the maintenance of cosmic order -- the gods of the Empyrean pantheon stand, in part, as guardians against the incursion of the Beyond</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"sorcery-and-the-beyond\">Sorcery and the Beyond</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sorcerers</a> access the Beyond by opening wounds in <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> -- deliberate tears in the barrier between realities through which they siphon energies, knowledge, and power. Every act of sorcery is, in a meaningful sense, an act of further damaging the Veil -- widening the cosmic wound that the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> sacrifice created, inviting more of the Beyond into the mortal world.</p>\n<p>The energies siphoned from the Beyond are potent but dangerous. They do not obey the natural laws of the mortal world. They carry the character of their origin -- alien, unstable, and hungry. Sorcerers who draw too deeply or too frequently from the Beyond risk corruption, madness, and the attention of entities that exist on the other side.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"communion-with-the-beyond\">Communion with the Beyond</h2>\n<p>The Beyond permits communion with entities that mortal religions, philosophies, and classifications struggle to categorize:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a></strong> -- Powers of immense age and appetite that exist in or draw sustenance from the Beyond. They predate the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean gods</a> and persist despite centuries of imperial suppression.</li>\n<li><strong>Demons</strong> -- Entities that cross from the Beyond into the mortal world through tears in the Veil. They range from mindless hunger (like <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a>) to intelligent malice.</li>\n<li><strong>Forgotten titans</strong> -- Beings of immense power whose worship has ceased but whose existence has not. They persist in the Beyond, waiting, sleeping, or simply enduring.</li>\n<li><strong>Alien intelligences</strong> -- Entities that defy mortal classification entirely. They are not gods, not demons, not spirits -- they are something else, something that the mortal mind was not designed to comprehend.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The barrier separating the mortal world from the Beyond</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> -- The entity whose sacrifice created the cosmic wound</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">sorcery</a> -- The practice of opening tears in the Veil to access the Beyond</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The religious tradition connected to powers of the Beyond</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The faith that stands in opposition to the Beyond&#39;s influence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- A demonic entity that crossed from the Beyond</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrapos</a> -- The mortal world the Beyond presses against</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-black-tree","title":"The Black Tree","category":"lore","status":"active","tags":["erenthis","avari","crossings","thornasse","eolande","dryad","cynar","womb-curse","malachor","reclaimers","spiritual","magic"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-black-tree\">The Black Tree</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Black Tree</strong> is the scorched stump of the great <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a>, near <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. It was burned by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> in <strong>349 IY</strong> as an act of cultural execution against the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a>. The burning was intended to destroy the spiritual heart of the Avari people -- and it succeeded in breaking their will to resist. But the roots have <strong>not fully died</strong>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>What It Is</strong></td>\n<td>The scorched stump of the great <span class=\"dead-link\">High Mage Cynar</span> -- acting on imperial authority -- burned the great <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at Thornasse. The Erenthis trees are living monuments of <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> origin, hostile to <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic corruption</a> and sacred to the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> people. The Thornasse Erenthis was the spiritual axis of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a> -- their sacred center, their living covenant with the world.</p>\n<p>Cynar did not burn a tree. He burned a people. The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist collapsed within months. The subsequent imperial campaigns in Argolle faced a broken, scattered population rather than an organized resistance.</p>\n<p>Cynar himself would die at the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a>, where he and <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Jarn Murky-Eye</a> destroyed each other in mutual annihilation. Whether there is cosmic justice in the death of the man who burned the Erenthis is a matter of theological debate.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"something-endures\">Something Endures</h2>\n<p>The roots have <strong>not fully died</strong>. The ground around the Black Tree is <strong>warm to the touch</strong> -- not from fire (the burning was thirty years ago) but from something beneath. The Erenthis was not merely a tree but a living <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> monument, a creation of ancient sorcery and spiritual significance. Whatever power animated it has not been fully extinguished.</p>\n<p>This persistence is significant. The <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis trees</a> are described as hostile to <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic corruption</a>. If the Black Tree&#39;s roots still live, they may still serve as a bulwark against the Cthonic forces that are clearly active in the Backlands -- the <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a>, the corruption spreading through <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a> and beyond.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-dryad\">The Dryad</h2>\n<p>A <strong>deranged and twisted dryad</strong> desperately tries to lure a fitting man to <strong>rebirth the dead tree</strong>. The dryad is the spiritual guardian of the Erenthis -- a being whose existence is bound to the tree. With the Erenthis burned, the dryad has been driven mad, twisted by the trauma of her tree&#39;s destruction.</p>\n<p>Her attempts to find a &quot;fitting man&quot; to rebirth the tree suggest that the Erenthis can be restored -- but the process requires a specific kind of sacrifice or union. What constitutes &quot;fitting&quot; is unclear, and the dryad&#39;s deranged state makes her judgment on the matter unreliable and her methods dangerous.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"eolande-at-the-black-tree\">Eolande at the Black Tree</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> encountered <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a> at the Black Tree -- an ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> general from approximately <strong>3000 BE</strong>, still present at the site over five millennia later. Eolande was tutored by the Great Teacher, led the military campaigns that built the Eladran empire, and extended the reach of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic tradition</a> alongside Eladran power.</p>\n<p>Why Eolande is at the Black Tree -- an Eladran general from the deep past, present at the scorched stump of an Eladran monument -- is itself a profound mystery. Is he bound to the tree as the dryad is? Is he guarding something? Waiting for something?</p>\n<p>During this encounter, Eolande mentioned the <a href=\"#/page/the-womb-curse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Womb Curse</a> -- a term that provoked an urgent reaction from <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> agent at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>. Malachor wants <strong>every detail</strong> of what the Reclaimers learned at the Black Tree.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"metaphysical-properties\">Metaphysical Properties</h2>\n<p>The Black Tree and its surroundings exhibit unusual metaphysical effects:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Warm ground</strong> -- the earth around the stump radiates heat from below, suggesting living roots or active magical energy</li>\n<li><strong>Dreams</strong> -- characters who sleep near the Black Tree <strong>dream of crystalline towers and wrong stars</strong>. The crystalline towers may be visions of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn&#39;s</a> ivory spires or of the Eladran civilization that created the Erenthis. The &quot;wrong stars&quot; suggest a vision of a different time -- a sky from millennia past, or a sky from <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Beyond</a></li>\n<li><strong>Magical enhancement</strong> -- mages and clerics who sleep near the Black Tree <strong>wake with a bonus cantrip</strong>, a temporary gift of arcane or divine power granted by proximity to the Erenthis&#39;s enduring energy</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These effects confirm that the Black Tree is not merely a historical site but an active source of metaphysical power. The Erenthis tradition is alive here, diminished but not destroyed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"significance\">Significance</h2>\n<p>The Black Tree sits at the intersection of multiple critical mysteries:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>The Avari</strong> -- It was their spiritual axis. Its destruction broke them. Its persistence offers hope.</li>\n<li><strong>The Eladra</strong> -- It is an Eladran creation. Eolande -- an Eladran general -- is present. The Womb Curse was mentioned here.</li>\n<li><strong>The Cthonic</strong> -- The Erenthis trees are hostile to Cthonic corruption. With the <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">Awakening</a> in progress in Argolle, the Black Tree may be one of the few remaining defenses.</li>\n<li><strong>The Academy</strong> -- <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> urgently wants every detail, suggesting the Academy recognizes the Black Tree&#39;s importance to their investigations.</li>\n<li><strong>The Reclaimers</strong> -- Their encounter with Eolande here has given them knowledge that powerful factions desperately want.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The living Eladran monuments, of which the Black Tree is a scorched remnant</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> -- The site where the Erenthis was burned</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city near Thornasse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">eolande</a> -- The ancient Eladran general encountered at the Black Tree</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">high-mage-cynar</a> -- The man who burned the Erenthis in 349 IY</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">avari</a> -- The people whose spiritual center was destroyed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-womb-curse\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-womb-curse</a> -- Mentioned by Eolande at the Black Tree</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- The Academy agent who urgently seeks information from this encounter</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-awakening</a> -- The Cthonic event the Erenthis may resist</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a> -- The Eladran city whose spires may appear in Black Tree dreams</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- What the Erenthis tradition opposes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party that encountered Eolande here</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-convergence-problem","title":"The Convergence Problem","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["theology","empyrean","cthonic","convergence","seros","bel","andraste","nasga","sagramore","ravanor","aurelion","eladra","elvora","veil","mirror","divine","cosmic"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-convergence-problem\">The Convergence Problem</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Convergence Problem</strong> is the theological crisis that emerges from the observation that the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> and <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> gods are <strong>mirrors of each other</strong>. Each Empyrean deity has a Cthonic analogue governing the same domain but oriented toward opposite moral ends. The structural mirror is too precise to be accidental, and its implications threaten the foundations of both traditions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-mirror-pairs\">The Mirror Pairs</h2>\n<h3 id=\"seros-and-bel\">Seros and Bel</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></strong> (light, law, civilization) and <strong><a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a></strong> (war, conquest, blood) -- both claim sovereignty over the <strong>will to impose order</strong>. Seros imposes order through law, justice, and the structures of civilization. Bel imposes order through conquest, dominance, and the spilling of blood. The domain is identical. The method differs. The moral orientation is opposite. But the underlying impulse -- the drive to shape the world according to a singular will -- is the same.</p>\n<h3 id=\"andraste-and-nasga\">Andraste and Nasga</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/andraste\" class=\"wiki-link\">Andraste</a></strong> (compassion, strength) and <strong><a href=\"#/page/nasga\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nasga</a></strong> (pain, desire) -- both operate in the domain of <strong>the body&#39;s experience</strong>. Andraste sanctifies the body&#39;s capacity for endurance, compassion, and protective strength. Nasga sanctifies the body&#39;s capacity for suffering, hunger, and consuming desire. Both traditions claim authority over what the body feels and what that feeling means. The difference is whether the body&#39;s experience is oriented toward the protection of others or the satisfaction of the self.</p>\n<h3 id=\"sagramore-and-ravanor\">Sagramore and Ravanor</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/sagramore\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sagramore</a></strong> (loyalty, sacrifice) and <strong><a href=\"#/page/ravanor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ravanor</a></strong> (rulership, tyranny) -- both concern the <strong>relationship between individual will and power structures</strong>. Sagramore asks: what are you willing to sacrifice for something greater than yourself? Ravanor asks: what are you willing to take from those beneath you? Both address the same fundamental question -- how does the individual relate to power? -- but from opposite positions within the hierarchy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-structural-mirror\">The Structural Mirror</h2>\n<p>The precision of the mirror is what produces the theological crisis. If Empyrean and Cthonic gods merely shared some superficial similarities, the mirror could be dismissed as coincidence, convergent evolution of divine archetypes, or the natural tendency of mortal minds to organize the divine into symmetrical categories.</p>\n<p>But the mirror is <strong>too precise</strong> to be accidental. Every Empyrean god has its Cthonic counterpart. Every domain is shared. Every moral axis is exactly inverted. The system is not approximate -- it is exact. This precision demands explanation, and every available explanation is uncomfortable for at least one tradition.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-most-disturbing-theory\">The Most Disturbing Theory</h2>\n<p>The most disturbing theory -- one advanced by <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> scholars whose work survives only in fragments -- proposes that the Empyrean and Cthonic gods are <strong>not separate beings at all</strong>. They are a single set of primal powers, <strong>divided by the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> sacrifice</strong>.</p>\n<p>What the Empyrean calls divine principle and the Cthonic calls divine hunger are the <strong>same cosmic forces</strong>, seen from different sides of the wound that the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice opened in the fabric of reality.</p>\n<p>If this theory is correct:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Worshipping an Empyrean god and its Cthonic counterpart may be less different than either tradition prefers to acknowledge.</strong> The priest of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> who calls upon the Unconquered Sun for justice and the blood-priest of <a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a> who calls upon the Slaughterprince for victory may be addressing the same power -- or two halves of what was once a single power -- through different rituals, different vocabularies, and different moral frameworks.</li>\n<li><strong>The Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice did not merely create the distinction between Empyrean and Cthonic -- it may have CREATED the Empyrean and Cthonic as separate categories.</strong> Before the sacrifice, there may have been only primal forces, undivided, neither good nor evil in the senses those terms now carry.</li>\n<li><strong>The moral distinction between the traditions may be a function of perspective rather than ontology.</strong> The Empyrean tradition is not inherently superior to the Cthonic tradition -- or vice versa. Both are fragments of something that was once whole, each claiming to represent the truth while possessing only half of it.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-veil-complication\">The Veil Complication</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> discovery of <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> complicates the Convergence Problem further.</p>\n<p>The Elvora demonstrated that the Cthonic gods are reachable through the Veil -- they are not wholly immanent, not purely present in the material world, but accessible through a barrier that separates the material from something beyond it. This means the Cthonic gods have a transcendent dimension that their theology does not emphasize.</p>\n<p>Meanwhile, the Empyrean gods are increasingly understood as expressions of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> distributed essence -- present in the world through the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice, active in the material realm through the structures and living things (such as the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a>) that carry that essence. This means the Empyrean gods have an immanent dimension that their theology does not emphasize.</p>\n<p>The boundaries between transcendent and immanent -- between Empyrean and Cthonic -- are <strong>less fixed than either theology suggests</strong>. The Cthonic gods are not purely of this world. The Empyrean gods are not purely beyond it. Both traditions have been simplifying a reality that is more complex, more intertwined, and more troubling than either is comfortable admitting.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"theological-responses\">Theological Responses</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-empyrean-response\">The Empyrean Response</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> tradition -- particularly the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> -- finds the Convergence Problem <strong>anathema</strong>. The suggestion that Empyrean gods and Cthonic gods are aspects of the same primal forces is, from the Empyrean perspective, not merely wrong but dangerous. It undermines the moral authority on which the entire Empyrean tradition is built. If <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and <a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a> are two faces of the same power, then the distinction between justice and conquest is not cosmic but interpretive -- a matter of human choice rather than divine mandate.</p>\n<p>The Thousand Temples have consistently suppressed, ignored, or condemned scholarship that advances the Convergence theory. This suppression has been effective but not total. The theory persists because the evidence for it is structural and persistent -- it does not depend on any single text or tradition but on the observable architecture of the divine.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-cthonic-response\">The Cthonic Response</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition finds the Convergence Problem <strong>flattering and probably correct</strong>. If the Cthonic gods are not inferior to the Empyrean gods but their equals -- or their other halves -- then the Cthonic tradition is not a corruption of the divine but an equally valid expression of it. The moral condemnation that the Empyrean tradition heaps upon Cthonic worship is revealed as self-serving propaganda rather than cosmic truth.</p>\n<p>The Cthonic tradition has never been as invested in the separation of Empyrean and Cthonic as the Empyrean tradition has. For the Cthonic, power is power. The source matters less than the result. The Convergence Problem, if accepted, validates a position the Cthonic tradition has held all along.</p>\n<h3 id=\"neither-has-resolved-it\">Neither Has Resolved It</h3>\n<p>The Empyrean find the Convergence Problem anathema. The Cthonic find it flattering and probably correct. Neither tradition has resolved it. Neither tradition can, because resolution would require one side to concede something fundamental about the nature of the divine -- and neither side is willing to concede anything at all.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- Empyrean god of light, law, and civilization</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel-earth-hunger</a> -- Cthonic god of war, and the agricultural earth-hunger</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/andraste\" class=\"wiki-link\">andraste</a> -- Empyrean goddess of compassion and strength</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/nasga\" class=\"wiki-link\">nasga</a> -- Cthonic goddess of pain and desire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sagramore\" class=\"wiki-link\">sagramore</a> -- Empyrean god of loyalty and sacrifice</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ravanor\" class=\"wiki-link\">ravanor</a> -- Cthonic god of rulership and tyranny</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> -- Whose sacrifice may have created the Empyrean/Cthonic divide</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The barrier through which Cthonic gods are reachable</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- Living expression of Aurelion&#39;s distributed essence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> -- The scholars who advanced the most disturbing theory</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> -- Whose discovery of the Veil complicated the problem</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">thousand-temples</a> -- The Empyrean institution that suppresses convergence scholarship</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The tradition that finds convergence anathema</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The tradition that finds convergence flattering</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- A tradition that engages Cthonic entities without Empyrean frameworks</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-erenthis","title":"The Erenthis","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["erenthis","eladra","avari","aurelion","empyrean","cthonic","mystical","tree","sacred","thornasse","crossings","cynar","black-tree","root-network","spiritual-anchor"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-erenthis\">The Erenthis</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Erenthis</strong> are not merely trees. To call them trees is to describe a cathedral as a pile of stones. The Erenthis are <strong>living monuments</strong> planted by the ancient <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> civilization -- vast, sacred growths whose <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> spiritual traditions were woven through with <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> vitality. They are the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> distributed essence expressed through cultivation and the living world -- a divine presence made manifest not in scripture or temple but in bark, root, warmth, and fruit.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"nature-and-properties\">Nature and Properties</h2>\n<p>The Erenthis are living expressions of a spiritual tradition older than any surviving institution in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Their properties defy natural explanation:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Perpetual warmth.</strong> An Erenthis generates warmth year-round, regardless of season or climate. The ground around a living Erenthis is warm to the touch even in the depths of winter. Communities centered on a living Erenthis have endured generations of frontier pressure in part because the tree itself sustains them against cold, famine, and despair.</li>\n<li><strong>All-season fruit.</strong> The Erenthis bears fruit in all seasons -- not merely in the growing months, but continuously, providing sustenance to those who tend it through every turning of the year.</li>\n<li><strong>Metaphysical root network.</strong> The root system of an Erenthis extends a metaphysical charge that is <strong>actively hostile</strong> to entities of <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic corruption</a>. This is not a physical barrier. Creatures touched by Cthonic influence avoid Erenthis root systems entirely -- not because they cannot pass, but because of a deep incompatibility below the level of choice. The roots do not repel. They are simply fundamentally, structurally incompatible with what Cthonic corruption is. The effect is consistent, reliable, and operates without any action on the part of those the roots protect.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Erenthis root network is the <strong>most reliable natural defense against <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic corruption</a></strong> known in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. Communities centered on living Erenthis have survived generations of frontier pressure that destroyed settlements without such protection. The roots hold. They have always held.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-eladran-origin\">The Eladran Origin</h2>\n<p>The Erenthis were planted by the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> civilization -- the ancient precursor culture whose ruins dot the landscape of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> and beyond. The Eladra understood what they were planting. Their spiritual traditions were not separate from the Empyrean vitality that animates the Erenthis; the trees were cultivated expressions of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> distributed presence in the material world. The Eladra wove their deepest practices into the living wood, creating monuments that would endure long after their civilization fell.</p>\n<p>The Erenthis are what remain.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-avari-and-the-erenthis\">The Avari and the Erenthis</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> built their culture around Erenthis found in the ruins of the older <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> civilization. They did not fully understand what they were tending -- they did not possess the Eladran theological vocabulary, the cosmological framework, or the metaphysical traditions that had produced the trees in the first place. But they understood enough. They understood that the tree was sacred. They understood that it sustained them. They understood that rites performed in its presence carried weight -- that prayers spoken beneath its branches were not empty, that ceremonies conducted among its roots connected to something real.</p>\n<p>The Avari built their holiest traditions around the Erenthis as a <strong>living spiritual anchor</strong>. The tree was the center of community, the site of their most important ceremonies, the physical expression of everything they held sacred. They did not need to name what they felt in its presence. They did not need the vocabulary of Empyrean theology or Cthonic classification. They knew what the tree was because they lived with it, generation after generation, and it sustained them.</p>\n<p>The Avari do not use the vocabulary of <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> or <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> classification. They do not need to.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-burning-of-the-erenthis-at-thornasse\">The Burning of the Erenthis at Thornasse</h2>\n<p>Thirty years ago, <strong>High Mage <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a></strong> burned the Erenthis at <strong><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a></strong>.</p>\n<p>This act was understood by everyone -- Avari, Mithrian, scholar, soldier, priest -- as <strong>cultural execution</strong>. The Erenthis at Thornasse was not merely a tree. It was the spiritual center of the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari Confederation</a>, the living heart of their religious and cultural identity. Cynar did not merely destroy a symbol. He destroyed the thing itself -- the anchor around which an entire people had built their deepest understanding of the sacred.</p>\n<p>The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist collapsed within months. The Avari were defeated, assimilated, and their culture was systematically marginalized. What Cynar accomplished with fire at Thornasse, no army had managed in generations of warfare. He understood what the Erenthis meant to the Avari, and he burned it precisely because he understood.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-black-tree\">The Black Tree</h2>\n<p>The scorched stump of the Erenthis at Thornasse -- <strong>the Black Tree</strong> -- still stands at the center of the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. Cynar burned the trunk and branches. He killed what grew above the earth. But the roots have not fully died.</p>\n<p>The ground around the Black Tree is warm to the touch. Thirty years after the burning, something endures. The roots extend beneath the ruins, beneath the rubble, beneath the beastman occupation and the blood and the ruin of what was once the heart of Avari civilization. Whatever the Erenthis is -- whatever the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> distributed essence means when expressed in living wood -- it has not been wholly extinguished.</p>\n<p>The Black Tree is a wound. It is also, possibly, a promise.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"defense-against-cthonic-corruption\">Defense Against Cthonic Corruption</h2>\n<p>The Erenthis root network functions as the most reliable natural defense against <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic corruption</a> in the known world. The mechanism is not physical. There is no wall, no ward, no visible barrier. Creatures touched by Cthonic influence simply avoid the root systems entirely. The incompatibility operates at a level below conscious choice -- below instinct, below awareness. The corruption and the roots cannot coexist. They are oriented toward fundamentally opposed principles, and the roots win.</p>\n<p>This defense has proven itself over centuries. Communities centered on living Erenthis have survived where others have fallen. The root network holds against Cthonic-corrupted creatures, against the subtle warping influence of prolonged Cthonic exposure, against the slow erosion of will and identity that the corruption produces. The roots do not merely resist. They actively reinforce whatever stands within their reach.</p>\n<p>In the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, Cthonic-corrupted creatures behave with increasing urgency -- but they avoid the areas where the Black Tree&#39;s root network still extends. Even in death, even as a scorched stump, the Erenthis holds.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"theological-classification\">Theological Classification</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> priests have been notably inconsistent in their classification of the Erenthis. Some have called it a <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> construct -- a product of the dark traditions, to be regarded with suspicion or hostility. This classification is, by every measurable indicator, wrong. The Erenthis is <strong>actively hostile</strong> to Cthonic corruption. Its root network repels Cthonic entities. Its properties align with the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> tradition by every standard the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> themselves apply.</p>\n<p>The most honest categorization may be <strong>Mystical</strong> -- the third tradition. The Erenthis is a living expression of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion&#39;s</a> distributed presence: not god or demon, but what both Empyrean and Cthonic seek, present here and now in bark, root, warmth, and fruit. It is not transcendent in the way the Empyrean gods are transcendent. It is not immanent in the way the Cthonic gods are immanent. It is simply here -- real, alive, sustaining, and sacred in a way that does not require any theology to justify.</p>\n<p>The Avari do not use this vocabulary. They do not need to.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-status\">Current Status</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The Erenthis at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a> was burned thirty years ago by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a>. The Black Tree -- the scorched stump -- remains at the center of the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. Its roots have not fully died.</li>\n<li>Other Erenthis are believed to exist in remote locations throughout <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> and beyond, though their locations are not widely known.</li>\n<li>The root network beneath the ruins of Crossings has been responding to something -- those with access to the network have sensed increasing disturbance over the past two years. The Erenthis have oriented themselves in response: to resist, to reinforce, to hold. (See: <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Nethercity</a>)</li>\n<li>Communities centered on living Erenthis continue to survive where others have fallen to frontier pressure, beastman raids, and Cthonic corruption.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city where the Black Tree stands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> -- The site of the Erenthis burning</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cynar</a> -- The High Mage who burned the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> -- The people who built their culture around the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> -- The ancient civilization that planted the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a> -- The divine presence expressed through the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The corruption the Erenthis root network resists</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- The subterranean complex beneath Crossings, whose stirring the roots have sensed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological problem that complicates classification of the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The tradition the Erenthis most closely aligns with</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- Another tradition operating outside standard Empyrean/Cthonic classification</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-flame","title":"The Flame","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["flame","priestly-magic","empyrean","aurelion","measure-and-the-scale","virtue","divine-spark","euphrosyne","thousand-temples"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-flame\">The Flame</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;Each living being carries a spark of the Aurelion within its soul. To embody the Measure and the Scale you can reshape the world with your soul&#39;s fire.&quot;\n— <a href=\"#/page/euphrosyne\" class=\"wiki-link\">Euphrosyne</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Flame is the priestly magic of the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> — the divine power channeled through virtue, sacrifice, and righteous purpose. Unlike <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, which manipulates the metaphysical axioms of reality through mental discipline, geometric diagrams, and spoken resonance, and unlike the warlock pacts and hedge-magic traditions that draw power from entities beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a>, the Flame draws its power from within the soul itself. It is the spark of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> — the fragment of the supreme designer&#39;s essence that resides within every living being — ignited through alignment with the virtues of the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> and directed outward as an act of divine will.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"theological-foundation\">Theological Foundation</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-divine-spark\">The Divine Spark</h3>\n<p>The foundational principle of the Flame is that every living being carries a spark of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> within its soul. This is not a metaphor or a poetic conceit but a literal metaphysical reality: when the Aurelion sacrificed itself to create the cosmos, its essence diffused throughout all of reality, and every soul is a fragment of that essence — a tiny piece of the divine fire that once animated the supreme designer of the cosmos.</p>\n<p>This spark is present in all living beings, but in most it remains dormant — a potential that is never realized, a fire that never burns. The vast majority of people live their entire lives without ever touching the divine fire within them, without ever knowing that the power to reshape reality lies coiled within their own souls, waiting to be awakened.</p>\n<h3 id=\"channeled-through-virtue\">Channeled Through Virtue</h3>\n<p>The Flame cannot be ignited through study, through technique, or through the acquisition of arcane knowledge. It is not a skill that can be taught in the way that <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> is taught at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>. The Flame is activated through the alignment of the will with the virtues encoded in the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a> — the moral and spiritual disciplines that the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a> holds as the path to divine truth. Compassion, justice, courage, hope, sacrifice, duty, steadfastness — these are not merely moral qualities but metaphysical keys that unlock the divine spark and allow the Flame to burn.</p>\n<p>This means that the Flame cannot be faked. A sorcerer can learn the geometric formulae of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> without believing in the divine order; a warlock can negotiate a pact with a demonic entity without any moral conviction whatsoever. But the Flame demands authenticity. The priest who channels the Flame must genuinely embody the virtues of the Scale — must truly feel compassion, truly seek justice, truly possess the courage and hope that the Empyrean faith demands. Hypocrisy extinguishes the spark. Self-interest smothers it. Only genuine, lived virtue can fan the spark into a flame capable of reshaping reality.</p>\n<h3 id=\"not-drawn-from-external-sources\">Not Drawn from External Sources</h3>\n<p>The Flame is fundamentally different from all other forms of magic in the known world because it does not draw power from external sources. <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> draws power from the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded in reality — ultimately from the Aurelion&#39;s essence, but indirectly, through the medium of geometric patterns and spoken resonance. Sorcery through <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a> draws power from the alien energies of the Beyond. Hedge-magic draws on natural forces, ley lines, and local spiritual conditions. All of these involve reaching outside the self to access power that exists in the external world.</p>\n<p>The Flame burns within. It is the sorcerer&#39;s own soul — or more precisely, the Aurelion&#39;s spark within the sorcerer&#39;s soul — that provides the power. This makes the Flame simultaneously the most intimate and the most demanding form of magic: intimate because it requires the practitioner to reach into the deepest part of their own being, and demanding because the quality of the power is directly proportional to the quality of the soul that channels it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"practice-and-expression\">Practice and Expression</h2>\n<h3 id=\"miracles-not-spells\">Miracles, Not Spells</h3>\n<p>The manifestations of the Flame are typically described as miracles rather than spells — a linguistic distinction that reflects a genuine theological and practical difference. Spells, in the tradition of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, are reproducible, formulaic procedures: given the correct diagram, the correct resonance, and the correct mental discipline, any trained sorcerer can produce the same result. Miracles are not reproducible in this way. Each miracle is a unique expression of the channeler&#39;s virtue, responding to the specific circumstances of the moment and the specific state of the channeler&#39;s soul.</p>\n<p>The Flame can heal wounds, purify corruption, banish undead, shield the faithful from harm, reveal hidden truths, and accomplish other feats that defy natural explanation. The specific miracles that a Flame-channeler can perform are not drawn from a catalogue or learned from a textbook but emerge organically from the interaction between the channeler&#39;s virtues, the situation at hand, and the divine spark within.</p>\n<h3 id=\"cannot-be-taught-must-be-lived\">Cannot Be Taught, Must Be Lived</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> barely teach the Flame in the current era. This is partly a matter of institutional decline — the living tradition of Flame-channeling has atrophied over centuries as the Temples have become increasingly bureaucratic, political, and concerned with temporal power rather than spiritual development. But it is also a reflection of the Flame&#39;s fundamental nature: it cannot be taught in the way that <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> can be taught, through lectures, textbooks, and supervised practice.</p>\n<p>The Flame must be lived. A priest who wishes to channel the divine fire must cultivate genuine virtue through years of discipline, sacrifice, and spiritual development. There are no shortcuts, no techniques, no secret methods. The only way to ignite the spark is to become the kind of person in whom the spark naturally burns — and this requires a lifetime of moral and spiritual effort that few are willing to undertake and fewer still are capable of sustaining.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-flame-and-other-magical-traditions\">The Flame and Other Magical Traditions</h2>\n<p>The Flame exists in tension with the other magical traditions of the known world. Practitioners of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> view the Flame with a mixture of respect and skepticism — respect because its effects are undeniable, skepticism because its mechanisms resist systematic analysis. Warlocks and hedge-mages view it with fear, because the Flame is one of the few powers capable of directly countering <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a> and banishing the entities that these practitioners traffic with.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> officially maintain that the Flame is the only truly legitimate form of supernatural power — that <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> is a tolerated but spiritually inferior practice, and that all other forms of magic are varying degrees of heresy. In practice, however, the rarity of genuine Flame-channelers means that the Temples rely heavily on the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> and its gnostic geometers for practical magical needs, and the official theological position exists more as aspiration than reality.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/euphrosyne\" class=\"wiki-link\">Euphrosyne</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Veil</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-guzzler","title":"The Guzzler","category":"lore","status":"active","tags":["demon","guzzler","fort-ikenvar","stone-of-sakkara","theodotus","backlands","sanctuary","demonic-entity"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-guzzler\">The Guzzler</h1>\n<p><strong>The Guzzler</strong> is a demonic entity of unknown origin currently occupying the ruined <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>, the marsh fort east of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>. It is not intelligent in any meaningful sense -- it just hungers and eats what it finds. It does not discriminate. It has no agenda beyond feeding. It is a mouth with legs, a consuming force that devours whatever crosses its path without preference or plan.</p>\n<p>The Guzzler is being drawn southward from Fort Ikenvar by the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>, carried by <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. Its approach toward populated areas represents a growing humanitarian catastrophe.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Demonic entity</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Intelligence</strong></td>\n<td>Minimal -- pure hunger, no agenda</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Origin</strong></td>\n<td>Unknown</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Lair</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Fort Ikenvar</span> for weeks, drawn by the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>. It cannot locate the Stone precisely -- it feels it the way an animal senses weather before it turns. The pull is ambient, not directional. A pressure gradient rather than a beacon.</p>\n<p>When the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> were at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, the Guzzler followed toward the garrison. When the party moved south toward <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, the Guzzler followed south. The Stone&#39;s influence is reshaping the Guzzler&#39;s behavior in two critical ways:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Range:</strong> The Guzzler is no longer contained by the marshes around Fort Ikenvar. It is moving through open territory, along roads, past settlements -- terrain it would not naturally traverse without the Stone&#39;s pull.</li>\n<li><strong>Target selection:</strong> The Stone is amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent. The creature&#39;s already indiscriminate appetite is being bent toward the most vulnerable prey -- children, livestock, the undefended. This is not the Guzzler&#39;s doing. It is the Stone&#39;s.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"trail-of-violence\">Trail of Violence</h2>\n<p>As the Guzzler follows the Stone south along the route from <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, it has left an escalating trail of predation:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>A farm three miles south of Fort Meade:</strong> Goats taken, fence posts crushed in. The farmer reported it two days late, embarrassed he had waited.</li>\n<li><strong>The Sanctuary road:</strong> A merchant&#39;s draft horse found half-consumed at the roadside. The merchant saw nothing. Heard nothing. The horse was simply gone.</li>\n<li><strong>Near Sanctuary:</strong> A child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The escalation tracks the party&#39;s southward movement precisely. The Guzzler is not attacking settlements randomly. It is following the Stone, and the Stone is amplifying its hunger toward innocence. The incidents are a consequence of <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> carrying the Stone through populated territory.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"military-assessment\">Military Assessment</h2>\n<p>The approximately one hundred soldiers at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> under <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> command are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The garrison was built to hold a frontier chokepoint against mortal threats -- <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a>, <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> raiders, bandits like <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a>. A demonic entity is a categorically different problem requiring capabilities the garrison does not possess.</p>\n<p>If the Guzzler arrives near <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, the consequences would be catastrophic. Sanctuary is a city of 28,000 people. The Guzzler in an urban-adjacent environment is a vastly different problem than the Guzzler in the marshes around Fort Ikenvar. The density of potential victims, the difficulty of evacuation, and the political fallout of a demonic entity attacking civilians near the provincial capital would be devastating.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-futility-of-killing-it\">The Futility of Killing It</h2>\n<p><strong>Killing the Guzzler resolves nothing.</strong> The Guzzler is a symptom, not the disease. The <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> drew this creature. If the Guzzler is destroyed, the Stone will reach through something else. Another entity will be attracted. Another vessel for hunger will be found. The Stone&#39;s influence does not end when one manifestation of it is eliminated.</p>\n<p>Fighting the Guzzler in an urban-adjacent environment near <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> is a different tactical problem than fighting it in the marshes. The terrain, the civilian population, the political implications -- all change. But even a successful engagement only buys time. The Stone remains. The pull remains. The next entity drawn by the Stone may be worse.</p>\n<p>The problem is the Stone, not the Guzzler. <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> knows this, somewhere beneath the philosophical distance he maintains from the violence around him. The scene ends when he decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<p>The Guzzler occupied <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> before the events of the campaign. The ruined marsh fort east of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> was also the base of operations for <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a>, the bandit whose destruction was the Reclaimers&#39; first major accomplishment. Whether the Guzzler was present during Rook&#39;s occupation, whether Rook&#39;s people coexisted with it or avoided it, and whether the Guzzler&#39;s arrival at Fort Ikenvar was connected to any other event in the Backlands&#39; recent history are all unclear.</p>\n<p>What is clear is that the Guzzler was contained -- naturally or by circumstance -- within the marshes around Fort Ikenvar until the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> pulled it free.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-stone-of-sakkara</a> -- The artifact drawing the Guzzler southward</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- The Reclaimer carrying the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- The Guzzler&#39;s lair</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison threatened by the Guzzler&#39;s movement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- The city toward which the Guzzler is being drawn</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party whose movements are guiding the Guzzler&#39;s path</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Commander of the garrison not equipped to face it</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- Former occupant of Fort Ikenvar</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history documenting the Guzzler&#39;s approach</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-kharai","title":"The Kharai","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["kharai","imprisoned-ones","cairnhouse","ygrathen","eladra","cairnhill","lake-silverhead","psychic-bleed","dreams","ancient","cosmic","binding","varek-ashstone","gilded-oath","elvora","veranthas","seal-circuit"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-kharai\">The Kharai</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Kharai</strong> -- the <strong>Imprisoned Ones</strong> -- are beings of enormous will and appetite, ancient beyond reckoning. The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> civilizations already regarded them as predating the current age of the world. They are not gods. They are not demons. They were never part of any divine order. They do not fit within the cosmic architecture of either the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> or <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition. They are simply what they are: vast, patient, and impossible to destroy.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;It does not threaten. It waits. It has more time than anything built to contain it.&quot; -- Attributed to the <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen hermit of Lake Silverhead</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"nature\">Nature</h2>\n<p>The Kharai defy classification within the theological frameworks that govern understanding of the supernatural in the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and beyond. They are not <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> -- they serve no divine principle, uphold no cosmic order, express no distributed essence of the <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurelion</a>. They are not <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> -- they are not hungry gods reaching through the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a>, not entities of corruption and appetite seeking to consume the material world.</p>\n<p>They are <strong>outside</strong> the system entirely. Beings of enormous will and appetite that simply exist -- have always existed -- with a patience and persistence that exceeds anything built to contain them.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> imprisoned the Kharai rather than destroying them. The most straightforward explanation is that they <strong>could not</strong> be destroyed. But there is another possibility, one that scholars and theologians have debated without resolution: perhaps the Ygrathen understood something about the Kharai that has since been forgotten. Perhaps destruction was possible but unwise. Perhaps the Kharai serve a function in the deep structure of the world that would be disrupted by their annihilation. The Ygrathen chose imprisonment, and the reasons for that choice may matter as much as the choice itself.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cairnhouses\">The Cairnhouses</h2>\n<p>The Kharai are contained within structures called <strong>cairnhouses</strong> -- constructions of <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> design, built specifically to imprison the Kharai using binding traditions that predate the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> by an unknown span of time. The cairnhouses were not improvised. They were engineered with precision and sustained intention, designed to hold beings that cannot be killed and will never stop pressing against their confinement.</p>\n<p>At least two cairnhouses are known to exist in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>The cairnhouse on the island in <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a></strong> (far north of the province) -- watched over by the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> hermit <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a>, who has maintained his vigil for centuries.</li>\n<li><strong>The cairnhouse at <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a></strong> (on the scrubland edge of the province) -- the structure that has shaped the town and its people through generations of psychic bleed.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Others may exist. The Ygrathen built what was necessary, and the Kharai are not few.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-psychic-bleed\">The Psychic Bleed</h2>\n<p>A cairnhouse does not perfectly contain what is inside. The beings imprisoned within press against the walls of their binding constantly, with the patience of something that has more time than the dam. The pressure leaks. This leakage -- the <strong>psychic bleed</strong> -- is not dramatic. It does not manifest as madness, mutation, or catastrophe. It is subtle, persistent, and cumulative.</p>\n<p>Over six to seven generations, the psychic bleed from the cairnhouse at <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> has shaped the people who live near it. The changes are consistent across the population, suggesting not random corruption but a slow, steady pressure that molds human consciousness into something slightly -- but distinctly -- different from the norm.</p>\n<h3 id=\"effects-on-cairnhill-residents\">Effects on Cairnhill Residents</h3>\n<p>The people of <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> display the following characteristics, all attributable to generations of exposure to the psychic bleed:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Too-complete attention.</strong> Cairnhill residents do not merely notice things -- they attend to them with a focus and thoroughness that is subtly unsettling to outsiders. Their gaze does not wander. Their awareness does not drift. They are present in a way that exceeds ordinary human attentiveness.</li>\n<li><strong>Tolerance for enclosed spaces and darkness.</strong> What would produce claustrophobia or discomfort in others produces no distress in Cairnhill residents. They are comfortable in tight spaces, in darkness, in conditions that would unnerve most people. This is not courage -- it is genuine comfort, as if enclosed darkness is a natural environment rather than a threatening one.</li>\n<li><strong>A different relationship to time.</strong> Cairnhill residents experience time differently. They are patient beyond ordinary patience -- not in the way of disciplined or stoic individuals, but in the way of people for whom the passage of time carries a different weight. Hours, days, seasons move through their awareness at a different pace.</li>\n<li><strong>Perceptiveness below normal awareness.</strong> Cairnhill residents perceive things that others do not -- not supernatural visions or mystical insight, but a baseline awareness of their environment that operates below the level of conscious attention. They notice what others miss. They feel what others cannot. This perceptiveness is not a skill; it is a condition of their existence.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-dreams\">The Dreams</h2>\n<p>Every resident of <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> dreams of vast enclosed spaces.</p>\n<p>The dreams are consistent across the population. They feature halls, corridors, and chambers of impossible scale -- structures too large to exist beneath any hill, lit by no visible source, built in geometries that are not quite wrong but not quite right. The spaces are not threatening. They are not nightmares. They are simply <strong>immense</strong>, deeply <strong>other</strong>, and entirely <strong>real</strong> in the way that only the most vivid and persistent dreams can be.</p>\n<p>The residents of Cairnhill discuss the geography of their shared dreams with the casual familiarity of people discussing shared weather. They know the corridors. They recognize the chambers. They have navigated the impossible halls in sleep since childhood, as their parents did, and their parents&#39; parents before them. It has never occurred to them that outsiders do not share the same dreams.</p>\n<p>This is the most telling indicator of how thoroughly the psychic bleed has shaped the community. The dreams are not aberrant to those who have them. They are simply part of life -- as natural and unremarkable as the hill itself, as the enclosed spaces they do not fear, as the patience that runs deeper in them than in anyone else.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood-and-the-cairnhouses\">The Argollean Brotherhood and the Cairnhouses</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> seeks access to the cairnhouses -- not to free what is imprisoned within, but to study the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> binding structures themselves. The binding tradition that produced the cairnhouses represents an achievement of containment magic that the Brotherhood considers invaluable: techniques for sealing and holding beings of power that no contemporary practitioner can replicate.</p>\n<p>The town of <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> does not allow anyone near the hill.</p>\n<p>This tension has been building for years. The Brotherhood wants what the cairnhouse contains -- not the Kharai, but the knowledge of how to bind them. Cairnhill wants to be left alone, to continue the quiet existence they have maintained for generations, shaped by the bleed but sustained by their own stubborn refusal to let outsiders interfere with what they have learned to live with. The Brotherhood sees an invaluable research opportunity. Cairnhill sees a threat to the only equilibrium they have ever known.</p>\n<p>Neither side has yielded. Neither side is likely to.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-guardian-tomb-network-and-the-gilded-oath\">The Guardian Tomb Network and the Gilded Oath</h2>\n<p>The cairnhouses are not the only means by which the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> are contained. In the <strong>Cairnhill Breaks</strong> -- the fractured limestone foothills east of <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> -- a network of <strong>Elvoran guardian tombs</strong> forms a <strong>seal-circuit</strong>: a chain of binding stations that reinforces the imprisonment of the Kharai beneath the hill. Each station is manned by a member of the <strong>Gilded Oath</strong>, a cohort of <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> warrior-priests who underwent a ritual of partial undeath called the <strong>Sevenfold Wounding</strong>.</p>\n<p>The Sevenfold Wounding was a process of agonizing transformation: seven wounds taken with a gold-threaded blade, through which molten gold was introduced into the bloodstream and hardened into a lattice beneath the skin. At the ritual&#39;s completion, the warrior-priests died their living deaths and entered the guardian tombs, where they have maintained the seals <strong>in silence</strong> for over two thousand years. The gold woven into their bodies resonates with the <strong>Gnostic Geometry</strong> of the seal-circuit, binding their vigil to the mathematical structure of the containment itself.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-breaking-of-the-second-seal\">The Breaking of the Second Seal</h3>\n<p>At the <strong>Second Seal</strong> station -- the tomb known as <a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Gilded Vigil</a> -- the guardian <strong>Veranthas</strong> (vigil-name: &quot;He Who Holds the Middle Line&quot;) has <strong>broken his covenant</strong>. Sometime in the last year, Veranthas:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Ceased his vigil</li>\n<li>Desecrated his own oath-altar</li>\n<li>Retreated to his private chamber</li>\n<li>Began <strong>communicating with the imprisoned entity</strong> through the seal-membrane</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Veranthas claims that through this communication he has become convinced the Kharai sealed beneath Cairnhill is <strong>sane, not hostile, and politically imprisoned</strong> -- sealed away not because it was dangerous to the world but because it was dangerous to the powers that ruled the world at the time of its imprisonment. He reduced the sealing pressure to allow the entity to &quot;breathe.&quot;</p>\n<p>The seals have weakened but not broken. The Kharai has not escaped. But the effects are felt: dreams have grown strange in Cairnhill, the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> remnant in the Breaks have grown bolder, and the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> has dispatched a cell to investigate.</p>\n<p><strong>The central question -- whether Veranthas is right or wrong about the Kharai&#39;s nature -- is deliberately unresolved.</strong> If the Ygrathen chose imprisonment rather than destruction because the Kharai serve a function in the deep structure of the world, then Veranthas&#39;s claim that the imprisonment was political rather than necessary may carry more weight than first appears. The possibility that the Kharai are misunderstood -- that they are prisoners rather than monsters -- is the most dangerous idea in the setting, precisely because it cannot be definitively confirmed or denied.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- The Ygrathen hermit who watches over the Lake Silverhead cairnhouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a> -- The town shaped by generations of psychic bleed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">lake-silverhead</a> -- The lake whose island holds a cairnhouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The faction seeking access to cairnhouse binding structures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> -- The ancient people who built the cairnhouses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> -- The civilization that already regarded the Kharai as ancient</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- Another ancient subterranean structure with imprisoned power</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- A related but distinct binding tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The Cthonic tradition, from which the Kharai are notably distinct</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The Empyrean tradition, from which the Kharai are equally distinct</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-gilded-vigil</a> -- The guardian tomb where Veranthas broke his covenant</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> -- The civilization that created the Gilded Oath</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-nethercity-codex","title":"The Codex of Ninefold Stillness","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["nethercity","codex","in-world-document","cthonic","varn-ka-morath","sen-zorath","great-teacher","quiet-ones","awakening","eladra","soul-lanterns","dream-masks","leylines","binding"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-codex-of-ninefold-stillness\">The Codex of Ninefold Stillness</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;When the world above dims -- and it shall -- the world below will shine with remembered light.&quot;</em>\n-- Seer-Historian Vharul Sen-Ka</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The <strong>Codex of Ninefold Stillness</strong> is an in-world document attributed to <strong>Seer-Historian Vharul Sen-Ka</strong>, describing the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> in terms that far exceed what contemporary explorers have been able to confirm. Where modern accounts describe a subterranean complex of tomb-palaces and vault-temples, the Codex describes a <strong>city in every sense</strong> -- a metropolis of the dead built not as a graveyard but as a vessel for a civilization that expects to resume.</p>\n<p>The Codex calls the Nethercity by its original name: <strong>Varn-Ka&#39;Morath</strong>, which translates as <strong>&quot;the House of Becoming.&quot;</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-city-described\">The City Described</h2>\n<h3 id=\"scale-and-architecture\">Scale and Architecture</h3>\n<p>The Codex insists that the Nethercity is not a mere catacomb. Vharul Sen-Ka describes it as a city in every functional sense:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Vaultways as wide as rivers</strong> -- the primary corridors of the Nethercity are not cramped tomb-passages but broad avenues of monumental scale, built to accommodate movement, procession, and the traffic of a functioning urban center</li>\n<li><strong>Avenues marked by soul-lanterns</strong> -- fixed light sources whose flames <strong>feed on remembrance</strong>. The soul-lanterns do not burn fuel. They burn memory. The mechanism by which this functions is not explained, but the implication is that the lanterns are sustained by the accumulated memories of the dead interred nearby -- a perpetual light source powered by the psychic residue of the deceased</li>\n<li><strong>Entire districts shaped around sarcophagal towers</strong> -- the Nethercity is organized into districts, each centered on towering structures that house the interred. These are not individual tombs but collective monuments -- vertical necropoli within the horizontal necropolis</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-quiet-ones\">The Quiet Ones</h3>\n<p>The sarcophagal towers house the <strong>Quiet Ones</strong> -- those who gave themselves to the <strong>Long Sleep</strong> to await the <strong>Unsealing of the Final Door</strong>. The Codex describes them not as the dead but as the <strong>waiting</strong> -- beings who chose to enter a state of suspended existence in anticipation of a future event that would require their return.</p>\n<p>The Long Sleep is not death. It is not undeath. It is a third state -- a deliberate cessation of activity that preserves the sleeper in readiness for a purpose that has not yet arrived. The Quiet Ones did not die and were not killed. They <strong>chose</strong> to stop, and they can, according to the Codex, choose to start again.</p>\n<h3 id=\"death-as-a-chamber\">Death as a Chamber</h3>\n<p>The Codex articulates a theology of death that is profoundly different from both <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> and standard <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> understanding:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>Death is understood as <strong>a chamber, not a wall</strong>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In this framework, death is not an ending (the Empyrean view) or a consumption (the Cthonic view) but a <strong>transition space</strong> -- a room one passes through on the way to somewhere else. The Nethercity was built as the physical expression of this theology: a literal chamber of death through which the faithful would pass on their way to whatever lay beyond the Unsealing of the Final Door.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-honored-dead\">The Honored Dead</h3>\n<p>The honored dead are arrayed in splendor within the Nethercity, equipped not with offerings but with <strong>tools for the age to come</strong>:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Item</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Mirrors of black glass</strong></td>\n<td>Reflective surfaces of unknown material and purpose; possibly scrying devices, possibly instruments of self-recognition for beings who will wake after millennia of sleep</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Scepters of memory-copper</strong></td>\n<td>Implements made of an alloy called &quot;memory-copper&quot; -- a material that apparently retains impressions of its wielder&#39;s thoughts and experiences</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Dream-masks still humming with soul-echoes</strong></td>\n<td>Facial coverings that continue to resonate with the psychic impressions of their wearers, even after centuries of interment</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>The Codex is emphatic that these are <strong>not offerings</strong>. They are not grave goods placed to honor the dead or comfort them in an afterlife. They are <strong>equipment</strong> -- tools the Quiet Ones will need when they wake. The distinction matters: offerings imply finality. Equipment implies a future.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-hall-of-the-teacher\">The Hall of the Teacher</h2>\n<p>At the city&#39;s heart lies the <strong>Hall of the Teacher</strong>, containing the slumbering form of the <strong>Great Architect Sen&#39;Zorath the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues</strong>. This is the entity referred to elsewhere as <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity#the-great-teacher\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Great Teacher</a> -- the being who directed the construction of the Nethercity under the authority of whatever Cthonic power animated the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire#first-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> era.</p>\n<p>Sen&#39;Zorath rests within the <strong>Chrysalis-Urn</strong> -- a vessel whose name implies transformation rather than mere containment. The Great Teacher is not stored. It is <strong>gestating</strong>. The Chrysalis-Urn is not a coffin but a cocoon.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-chamber-of-the-still-light\">The Chamber of the Still Light</h3>\n<p>Adjacent to or within the Hall of the Teacher is the <strong>Chamber of the Still Light</strong> -- a space defined by a <strong>veil of cold gold</strong> through which the Great Teacher&#39;s presence can be felt. The Codex describes the experience:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>His thought presses like gravity upon the soul.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The Chamber of the Still Light is not a place of communication. The Great Teacher does not speak. It does not instruct. It simply <strong>exists</strong> with such intensity that proximity to it exerts a force on the consciousness of the living -- a weight of thought so massive that it bends the psychic landscape around it like a star bends light.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-invisible-architecture\">The Invisible Architecture</h2>\n<p>The Codex describes the Nethercity as constructed along <strong>invisible axes</strong> -- structural principles that are not visible to the eye but are essential to the city&#39;s function:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Aetheric leylines</strong> -- currents of metaphysical energy that flow through the Nethercity&#39;s architecture, connecting its districts, its towers, and its sleepers into a single integrated system</li>\n<li><strong>Resonance lattices</strong> -- geometric structures embedded in the city&#39;s design that harmonize the psychic frequencies of the interred Quiet Ones, keeping them aligned even across millennia of dormancy</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The purpose of this invisible architecture is explicitly stated in the Codex: so that when the Quiet Ones awaken, they will rise <strong>aligned, harmonized, and prepared</strong>. The Long Sleep is not merely preservation -- it is <strong>calibration</strong>. The sleepers are being tuned, over centuries, into a collective instrument that will function as a unified whole when the Unsealing occurs.</p>\n<p>The slumbering minds of the Quiet Ones are not simply dormant. They are being <strong>worked upon</strong> by the resonance lattices -- slowly, imperceptibly adjusted so that when they wake, they will think in concert, act in concert, and serve whatever purpose the Great Teacher designed them to serve.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-prophecy\">The Prophecy</h2>\n<p>The Codex concludes with what reads as either prophecy or promise:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;When the world above dims -- and it shall -- the world below will shine with remembered light.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is the eschatological core of the Nethercity&#39;s purpose. The builders of Varn-Ka&#39;Morath did not merely expect the surface world to decline -- they regarded it as <strong>inevitable</strong>. The Nethercity was built as a replacement, a successor, a continuation of civilization that would outlast whatever catastrophe consumed the world above. The &quot;remembered light&quot; of the soul-lanterns -- the flames that feed on memory -- would illuminate a new age built on the accumulated wisdom and experience of the old.</p>\n<p>Whether this prophecy is genuine foreknowledge, self-fulfilling design, or the grandiose ambition of a Cthonic architect is left for the reader to determine.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-known-accounts\">Relationship to Known Accounts</h2>\n<p>The Codex of Ninefold Stillness describes the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> in terms that significantly expand upon what contemporary sources have documented. The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers&#39;</a> exploration of the complex has confirmed its immense scale and First Empire provenance, but they have not penetrated to the depths the Codex describes. The Hall of the Teacher, the Chamber of the Still Light, and the sarcophagal districts remain beyond current reach.</p>\n<p>The Codex&#39;s description of <strong>Sen&#39;Zorath</strong> as the &quot;Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues&quot; suggests the Great Teacher may have been a polyglot, a linguist, or a being whose power operated through language itself -- shaping reality through the mastery of every tongue that existed in the First Empire&#39;s vast, multicultural dominion.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- The subterranean complex the Codex describes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The theological tradition that animated the Nethercity&#39;s construction</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> -- The civilization that built the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- Other ancient imprisoned entities with parallels to the Quiet Ones</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city above the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The root network responding to the Nethercity&#39;s stirring</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The group currently exploring the complex</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological framework within which the Nethercity&#39;s purpose must be understood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The contrasting theology of death as finality</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-gilded-vigil</a> -- Another ancient site where the sealed and the guardians exist in tension</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-nethercity","title":"The Nethercity","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["nethercity","crossings","eladra","cthonic","necropolis","great-teacher","first-empire","awakening","reclaimers","erenthis","subterranean","tomb","dungeon","varn-ka-morath","sen-zorath","quiet-ones"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-nethercity\">The Nethercity</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Nethercity</strong> -- known in the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity-codex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Codex of Ninefold Stillness</a> by its original name <strong>Varn-Ka&#39;Morath</strong>, &quot;the House of Becoming&quot; -- is a vast subterranean complex beneath the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, built by the ancient <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> civilization. It is not a graveyard. It is not a ruin. It is a <strong>prepared vessel</strong> -- a necropolis of tomb-palaces, vault-temples, and ritual chambers constructed with a purpose that has not yet been fulfilled.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"architecture-and-scale\">Architecture and Scale</h2>\n<p>The Nethercity is immense. Its construction predates the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> by centuries, possibly millennia. The complex comprises:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tomb-palaces</strong> -- elaborate burial chambers designed not merely to house the dead but to preserve them in states of ritual readiness. These are not modest crypts. They are palatial in scale, decorated with the symbolic language of the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> civilization, built to endure until they are needed.</li>\n<li><strong>Vault-temples</strong> -- sacred spaces combining the functions of temple and treasury. Whatever was worshipped or honored in these chambers was considered too important to be entrusted to surface structures. The vault-temples are deep, reinforced, and built to withstand catastrophe.</li>\n<li><strong>Ritual chambers</strong> -- purpose-built spaces for ceremonies whose nature can only be inferred from their architecture. The geometry of these chambers suggests rites of enormous scale and significance -- not daily worship but singular events, prepared for over generations.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Hundreds of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire#first-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire&#39;s</a> greatest figures are interred within the Nethercity. They were placed here not merely to rest but <strong>to await</strong>. The distinction matters. A graveyard honors the dead. The Nethercity holds them in reserve.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"named-locations\">Named Locations</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> Timelines and the <strong>Codex of Ninefold Stillness</strong> preserve the names and approximate construction dates of the Nethercity&#39;s principal structures. These are not rooms in a dungeon. They are monuments of state religion, built over centuries according to a design that the Great Teacher articulated before entering dormancy.</p>\n<h3 id=\"great-temple-of-the-awakening-construction-began-c-2600-be\">Great Temple of the Awakening (construction began c. 2600 BE)</h3>\n<p>The central and earliest major structure of the Nethercity, the <strong>Great Temple of the Awakening</strong> was begun during the period when the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> was formally declared and the Bitter War commenced. Its name is its purpose: this is the temple built for <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Awakening</a> -- the future event that the entire Nethercity was constructed to facilitate. The temple is the architectural heart of the complex, and all other structures are oriented in relation to it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"doom-temple-of-dirgion-construction-began-c-2400-be\">Doom Temple of Dirgion (construction began c. 2400 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Doom Temple of Dirgion</strong> was begun approximately two centuries after the Great Temple. Surviving records describe it in language more suggestive of containment than worship -- a structure built not to honor a deity but to hold something in readiness, or to keep something bound. The name &quot;Dirgion&quot; does not correspond to any known <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> or <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> deity in modern theological catalogs. Whether it names a god, an entity, or a principle is unknown.</p>\n<h3 id=\"hallowed-halls-of-heroes-construction-began-c-2100-be\">Hallowed Halls of Heroes (construction began c. 2100 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Hallowed Halls of Heroes</strong> were begun during the period of the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> defeat under warlord Marcan. The Halls serve as the interment complex for the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire&#39;s</a> greatest military figures -- the generals, champions, and warlords whose victories built the Empire. These are the figures held in reserve, placed in states of ritual readiness for whatever the Awakening requires of them.</p>\n<h3 id=\"great-king-tomb-c-2000-be\">Great King Tomb (c. 2000 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Great King Tomb</strong> houses the remains of the warlord <strong>Marcan</strong> -- conqueror of the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> and the Empire&#39;s greatest military hero. His interment within a purpose-built tomb of exceptional scale reflects his status. The Great King Tomb is among the most elaborate single structures in the Nethercity.</p>\n<h3 id=\"secret-tomb-c-1800-be\">Secret Tomb (c. 1800 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Secret Tomb</strong> houses the hierophant <strong>Orthanach</strong> -- the <strong>first mummy lord</strong>, the first being to achieve undeath through <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> ritual that preserves consciousness, will, and power beyond bodily death. Interred alongside Orthanach are his wife <strong>Sonya</strong> and his guard <strong>Cassair</strong>. Whether they accompanied him willingly into undeath is not recorded. The tomb is designated &quot;secret&quot; in the records, suggesting it was deliberately concealed within the Nethercity&#39;s deeper levels.</p>\n<h3 id=\"secret-sepulcher-c-2100-be\">Secret Sepulcher (c. 2100 BE)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Secret Sepulcher</strong> is the chamber in which the <strong>Great Teacher</strong> entered cryostasis following the defeat of the Ygrathen. Like the Secret Tomb, the Sepulcher was deliberately hidden within the complex. The Great Teacher chose dormancy rather than death or departure -- entering a state of preserved waiting that mirrors the Nethercity&#39;s own purpose. The Sepulcher is the most closely guarded location in the Nethercity, and its precise position within the complex is not recorded in any surviving document accessible to modern scholars.</p>\n<h3 id=\"hall-of-the-teacher-from-the-codex-of-ninefold-stillness\">Hall of the Teacher (from the Codex of Ninefold Stillness)</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Codex of Ninefold Stillness</strong> describes a chamber called the <strong>Hall of the Teacher</strong>, which may be another name for the Secret Sepulcher or an adjacent ritual space. The Codex identifies the Great Teacher by name: <strong>Sen&#39;Zorath, the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues</strong>. According to the Codex, Sen&#39;Zorath rests within the <strong>Chrysalis-Urn</strong> -- a vessel whose name implies not mere preservation but ongoing transformation. The Chrysalis-Urn suggests that the Great Teacher&#39;s dormancy is not static but developmental -- that whatever Sen&#39;Zorath is becoming, the process has been underway for millennia.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-great-teacher\">The Great Teacher</h2>\n<p>An entity called <strong>the Great Teacher</strong> directed the construction of the Nethercity. This being operated under the direct instruction of whatever power animated the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition during the First Empire era. The Great Teacher is not a title given in retrospect -- it is the name by which the entity was known to those who built what it designed.</p>\n<p>The Great Teacher <strong>rests dormant</strong> in the deepest levels of the Nethercity, within the [[#secret-sepulcher-c-2100-be|Secret Sepulcher]]. It has not died. It has not departed. It waits, as the Nethercity was built to wait, for whatever it was constructed to receive.</p>\n<p>The nature of the Great Teacher -- whether it is a being of flesh, spirit, or something else entirely -- is not known with certainty. What is known is that it possessed sufficient authority and power to direct the construction of one of the most ambitious subterranean projects in the history of the known world, and that the power it served was Cthonic in origin.</p>\n<h3 id=\"identity\">Identity</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> Timelines identify the Great Teacher as a <strong>Chemosh (Khepri) Hierarch</strong> -- a title that places the entity within the Cthonic theological hierarchy but does not clarify its species, origin, or the precise nature of its authority.</p>\n<p>The <strong>Codex of Ninefold Stillness</strong> provides a name: <strong>Sen&#39;Zorath, the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues</strong>. The Codex describes Sen&#39;Zorath resting within the <strong>Chrysalis-Urn</strong> in the [[#hall-of-the-teacher-from-the-codex-of-ninefold-stillness|Hall of the Teacher]]. The title &quot;Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues&quot; suggests a being whose power operated through language, command, and the reshaping of others -- consistent with an entity that directed the creation of the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> through <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire#transmogrification\" class=\"wiki-link\">Transmogrification</a> and the construction of a necropolis designed to outlast the civilization that built it.</p>\n<p>The name &quot;Chrysalis-Urn&quot; implies that the Great Teacher&#39;s dormancy is not static preservation but <strong>ongoing transformation</strong> -- that Sen&#39;Zorath is not merely sleeping but becoming something else, and has been becoming it for millennia. This connects directly to <a href=\"#/page/the-awakening\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Awakening</a>: the Nethercity anticipates not a metaphorical event but a <strong>literal</strong> one. Something will emerge from the Chrysalis-Urn, and whatever emerges may not be what entered it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"purpose-the-awakening\">Purpose: The Awakening</h2>\n<p>The Nethercity was not built as a monument to the past. It was built as <strong>preparation for a future event</strong>. The hundreds of interred figures, the ritual chambers, the vault-temples -- all of it was constructed in anticipation of something the builders called, or what scholars have come to call, <strong>the Awakening</strong>.</p>\n<p>The Awakening it anticipates is not metaphorical.</p>\n<p>Something is changing in the world&#39;s deeper metaphysical substrate. Those with access to the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> root network have sensed it for two years: an increasing disturbance, a presence in the deep energies that was not there before. The Erenthis trees have oriented themselves in response -- to resist, to reinforce, to hold. The trees feel what is stirring below, and they are bracing against it.</p>\n<p>In the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> above, <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic-corrupted</a> creatures behave with increasing urgency, as if something below is beginning to call. Their patterns have shifted. Their movements have purpose where before there was only territorial aggression. Something in the Nethercity is exerting influence, and the corrupted creatures above are responding.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-erenthis-response\">The Erenthis Response</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> root network beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- the roots of the Black Tree, the scorched stump of the Erenthis that <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> burned thirty years ago -- has not fully died. These roots extend into the earth around and above the Nethercity, and for two years they have been responding to whatever is stirring below.</p>\n<p>The Erenthis roots have <strong>oriented themselves</strong> in response to the Nethercity&#39;s increasing activity:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>To resist</strong> -- pushing back against the metaphysical pressure emanating from below</li>\n<li><strong>To reinforce</strong> -- strengthening whatever barriers exist between the Nethercity and the surface</li>\n<li><strong>To hold</strong> -- maintaining the boundary between what sleeps below and what lives above</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The fact that the Erenthis roots are responding at all confirms that what is happening in the Nethercity is real, significant, and perceived as a threat by the oldest and most reliable defense against Cthonic influence in the region.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-reclaimers\">The Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> have been exploring the Nethercity. The extent of their penetration, what they have found, and what they intend to do with their discoveries are not fully known. The Nethercity is vast, dangerous, and actively defended by whatever Cthonic influences persist within its depths. Exploration is not merely a matter of mapping corridors -- it is an engagement with forces that have been accumulating power in darkness for centuries.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-status\">Current Status</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The Great Teacher rests dormant in the deepest levels</li>\n<li>Cthonic-corrupted creatures in the <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> ruins above behave with increasing urgency and purpose</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> root network has been responding for approximately two years</li>\n<li>The metaphysical disturbance is intensifying</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> are actively exploring the complex</li>\n<li>The Awakening the Nethercity was built to facilitate has not yet occurred -- but the signs suggest it is approaching</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city above the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The root network responding to the Nethercity&#39;s stirring</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The tradition that animated the Nethercity&#39;s construction</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> -- The civilization that built the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The group exploring the complex</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- Other ancient imprisoned entities predating the current age</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-convergence-problem\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-convergence-problem</a> -- The theological framework within which the Nethercity&#39;s Cthonic origins must be understood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-empire</a> -- The First Empire that built the Nethercity and its named structures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mount-argolle\" class=\"wiki-link\">mount-argolle</a> -- The volcanic mountain bearing additional First Empire ruins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> -- The slave-soldiers created by the Great Teacher&#39;s Transmogrification</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> -- The ancient enemies whose defeat preceded the Great Teacher&#39;s cryostasis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity-codex\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity-codex</a> -- The Codex of Ninefold Stillness: Seer-Historian Vharul Sen-Ka&#39;s in-world account of Varn-Ka&#39;Morath</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-reclaimers","title":"The Reclaimers","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["lore","party","player-characters","reclaimers","backlands","fort-meade","legate-marcellus","lady-severina","nethercity","rook","fort-ikenvar","argollean-brotherhood","scalpers","crossings","campaign-history"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-reclaimers\">The Reclaimers</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;They came to the Backlands as carrion comes, drawn to rot. This was the northern province of Argolle where the land lay charred with old wars and the bones of empires still pushed from the dirt when the rains came. Six years gone the border city of Crossings was put to the torch by a horde of beastmen vast beyond counting and the people were butchered in their homes and the Emperor in his distant hall decreed then that a man might trade death for coin and a gold mark was set for every beast&#39;s scalp and so the land filled with killers.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;They arrived as hired swords. They destroyed Rook when the garrison could not. They carry artifacts the Brotherhood wants and the Academy covets. They are formally part of the Legate&#39;s household but answer to his wife. Whatever they are, they are no longer simply adventurers.&quot;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>The Reclaimers</strong> are the player character party -- a group of adventurers operating in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>, the northern province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>. They arrived individually in the aftermath of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>&#39; destruction, drawn by the <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor&#39;s</a> scalp bounty on beastmen -- a gold mark for every beast&#39;s scalp. They were killers among killers, indistinguishable from the <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper gangs</a> that filled the province. They are now formally part of <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> household at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> and hold his writ of tax exemption. Their true patron is <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a>, who went behind her husband&#39;s back to hire them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td>Adventuring party (player characters)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Base of Operations</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Shatzi</span> -- Merchant (Organizer)</h3>\n<p>A merchant failed and cast down, but sly -- never finished. Shatzi seeks some angle, always, to claw back what the world took from her. She is the Reclaimers&#39; organizer and de facto leader: the one who manages logistics, negotiates terms, handles finances, and holds a band of misfits together as a functioning enterprise in hostile territory. Her merchant&#39;s instinct is always working -- assessing, calculating, looking for the deal others have missed.</p>\n<p>Shatzi has been invited to <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina&#39;s</a> social gatherings at Fort Meade, reflecting Severina&#39;s recognition of a kindred operator. Both women understand the mechanics of influence and operate through practical intelligence rather than brute force.</p>\n<h3 id=\"theodotustheodotus-philosopher-bard-thrassian\"><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> -- Philosopher-Bard (Thrassian)</h3>\n<p>A <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> whose books had soured him. Years of study and contemplation had left Theodotus hollow, unconvinced that the truths he sought could be found in libraries or lecture halls. He came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands -- not as a soldier or a scalper, but as something stranger: a philosopher who had decided that the lecture hall was a lie and the battlefield might be honest.</p>\n<p>Theodotus carries the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>, an artifact of terrible and uncertain power. The Stone&#39;s presence at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> draws <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a> -- the demonic entity occupying <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> -- toward the garrison. The approximately one hundred soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The Stone makes Theodotus and the entire party a danger to the garrison that shelters them.</p>\n<h3 id=\"tiberiustiberius-mage-necromancer\"><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> -- Mage (Necromancer)</h3>\n<p>Schooled at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> in <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, the Empire&#39;s preeminent institution of sorcerous learning. Tiberius was cast out for the blackness of his studies -- necromantic research sufficiently transgressive that even the Academy, which tolerates considerable clandestine experimentation behind its alabaster walls, could not permit him to remain. His exile was stayed only by his noble bloodlines; a man of lesser birth would have been executed.</p>\n<p>Tiberius came to the Backlands because the frontier&#39;s institutional structures are too weak to monitor or regulate sorcerous practice. The constant supply of death provides ample material for a necromancer&#39;s work. He is the party&#39;s most potent member in terms of raw sorcerous ability, but also the most dangerous -- to enemies, bystanders, and potentially to his companions.</p>\n<h3 id=\"imaniman-bladedancer\"><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> -- Bladedancer</h3>\n<p>Driven from the <a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</a> for speaking too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons. The Order -- a militant religious institution connected to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith -- trained bladedancers in the martial and devotional arts. Its priestesses maintained relationships with noble patrons that blurred the boundary between spiritual authority and secular power. Everyone within the Order understood this corruption. No one named it. Iman named it, and for this honesty she was expelled.</p>\n<p>Iman has developed a close personal relationship with <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a>. Severina told Iman privately that she considers herself the real political engine of the Marcellus household -- a confidence suggesting trust that extends beyond the merely professional. Through Iman, the Reclaimers have a direct and personal line to their patron.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"former-members\">Former Members</h2>\n<h3 id=\"tancredtancred-crusader-of-seros-deceased\"><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred</a> -- Crusader of Seros (Deceased)</h3>\n<p>A crusader bearing the fire of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> who sought baptism in the blood of beasts. Tancred&#39;s martial calling was indistinguishable from his religious devotion -- the act of destroying the monstrous was itself an act of worship, a prayer spoken in steel and blood. He came to the Backlands because the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty had transformed the frontier into a crusade by another name.</p>\n<p>Tancred was the Reclaimers&#39; spiritual center -- the member whose convictions were absolute and whose purpose was unambiguous. His certainty steadied the group when doubt crept in.</p>\n<p><strong>Tancred died during the campaign.</strong> He sought baptism in blood, and the frontier obliged him. His death left a void in the Reclaimers that has not been filled -- the party lost its spiritual certainty, the member who never doubted that the killing was righteous.</p>\n<h3 id=\"rendson-avari-gambler-departed\">Rendson -- Avari Gambler (Departed)</h3>\n<p>An Avari gambler, whoremonger, and fugitive from debts whose past was soiled and unrevealed. Rendson was an early member of the Reclaimers during their initial period as scalpers in the Backlands. His debts were considerable and his habits worse. He departed the group early and vanished into the frontier. His fate is unknown.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"origin-and-hiring\">Origin and Hiring</h2>\n<p>The Reclaimers did not begin as a coherent group. They arrived in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> individually -- each drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty, by desperation, or by some private motive they did not share. The Backlands in the sixth year after the fall of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> was a land of ash and opportunity, filled with killers drawn by the promise of a gold mark for every beast&#39;s scalp. The Reclaimers were among these killers, initially indistinguishable from the other <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper gangs</a> roaming the province.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shatzi</a> organized the disparate individuals into a functioning group. Where <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> brought philosophical curiosity and <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> brought arcane power, Shatzi brought the thing the group actually needed: someone who could make it work. Her merchant&#39;s understanding of logistics, negotiation, and the management of unreliable people transformed a collection of misfits into an operational enterprise.</p>\n<p>The Reclaimers came to the attention of <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a> at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, the garrison commanded by her husband <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</a>. Severina hired them without the Legate&#39;s knowledge -- acting on her own political judgment rather than waiting for her husband&#39;s approval. They were formally absorbed into the Marcellus household with a writ of tax exemption.</p>\n<p>This fact -- that the Reclaimers were Severina&#39;s initiative, not the Legate&#39;s -- colors their position within the household. They are formally part of Marcellus&#39;s household, but their true patron is Severina. The Legate is aware of this dynamic and tolerates it because the Reclaimers have proven useful, though the arrangement is not without tension.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"destruction-of-rook\">Destruction of Rook</h2>\n<p>The Reclaimers&#39; most significant accomplishment to date is the destruction of <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>. Rook&#39;s campaign of banditry had terrorized the settlements and trade routes of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> for months -- targeted attacks on residents, disappeared travelers, deliberate intimidation. The garrison at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> could not resolve the threat.</p>\n<p>The Reclaimers tracked Rook to his base at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> -- the ruined marsh fort east of Fort Meade -- and destroyed him there. This victory delivered what the garrison could not, a fact experienced by <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> as both a professional humiliation and a political opportunity.</p>\n<p>It was during this period of the campaign that <a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred</a> fell in battle -- the crusader of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> who had sought baptism in the blood of beasts and found instead the death he had always courted.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-stone-of-sakkara\">The Stone of Sakkara</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> carries the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> -- an artifact of significant and dangerous properties. The Stone&#39;s presence at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> has drawn <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a> -- the demonic entity occupying <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> -- toward the garrison. The Guzzler cannot precisely locate the Stone but can sense its pull, compromising the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature.</p>\n<p>The ~100 soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The Stone&#39;s presence creates a threat that the garrison was never designed to counter. By carrying the Stone, the Reclaimers have inadvertently made themselves a danger to the very community that shelters them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-nethercity\">The Nethercity</h2>\n<p>The Reclaimers are currently exploring the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- an underground complex of significant scope and danger. The Nethercity has begun producing artifacts of genuine <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> provenance, drawing the attention of multiple factions.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> is monitoring what the Reclaimers recover from the Nethercity. Whether the Brotherhood approaches as buyers, competitors, or hostile actors depends entirely on what comes up and how the Reclaimers handle it. <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a>, representing the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, has a competing interest in the same artifacts. The presence of <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> -- a disgraced Academy mage -- in the same party that is recovering artifacts the Academy covets adds an additional layer of tension to this dynamic.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"political-position\">Political Position</h2>\n<p>The Reclaimers occupy a complicated and increasingly dangerous political position:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Formally</strong> part of <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> household, holding his writ of tax exemption</li>\n<li><strong>Actually</strong> hired by and loyal to <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina</a>, who engaged them without her husband&#39;s approval</li>\n<li><strong>Socially</strong> connected to Severina through both <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> (close personal relationship) and <a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shatzi</a> (invited to her gatherings)</li>\n<li><strong>Professionally</strong> useful enough that the Legate tolerates the arrangement, despite the implicit humiliation</li>\n<li><strong>Monitored</strong> by the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a>, who want what they find in the Nethercity</li>\n<li><strong>Of interest</strong> to <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, who want the same artifacts for different reasons</li>\n<li><strong>Carrying</strong> the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>, which creates a demonic threat to the garrison that shelters them</li>\n<li><strong>Harboring</strong> a disgraced Academy necromancer (<a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a>) whose former institution is now competing with them for Nethercity artifacts</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"who-they-are\">Who They Are</h2>\n<p>The Reclaimers are not heroes. They are the kind of people the scalp bounty was designed to attract -- expendable, desperate, and willing to kill for coin. A failed merchant. A disillusioned philosopher. A disgraced necromancer whose noble blood saved him from execution. A bladedancer expelled for honesty. A dead crusader. A gambler who vanished.</p>\n<p>They came to the Backlands as carrion comes, drawn to rot. What they became -- the destroyers of Rook, the bearers of the Stone of Sakkara, the explorers of the Nethercity, the instruments of Lady Severina&#39;s political ambitions -- was not planned. It accumulated, the way mud accumulates on boots in the Backlands. One thing led to another, and now they are entangled in factional politics, demonic threats, and archaeological discoveries that extend far beyond the frontier scalp trade that brought them here.</p>\n<p>They are formally part of the Legate&#39;s household. They answer to his wife. They carry artifacts the Brotherhood wants and the Academy covets. Whatever they are, they are no longer simply adventurers.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- The session-by-session chronicle of the campaign</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where the Reclaimers are based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Their formal patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- Their actual patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- The bandit they destroyed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- Where they destroyed Rook; where the Guzzler dwells</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The underground complex they are currently exploring</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruins above the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> -- The dangerous artifact Theodotus carries</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The faction monitoring their Nethercity recoveries</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- The Imperial Academy historian competing for the same artifacts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution Malachor represents and Tiberius was expelled from</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon</a> -- The militant order from which Iman was expelled</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- The faith Tancred served</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The other killers drawn by the bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province in which they operate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> -- Party organizer, Merchant</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- Party member, Philosopher-Bard</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> -- Party member, Necromancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- Party member, Bladedancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- Former party member, Crusader (deceased)</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-stone-of-sakkara","title":"The Stone of Sakkara","category":"lore","status":"active","tags":["artifact","stone-of-sakkara","theodotus","guzzler","corruption","fort-meade","fort-ikenvar","sanctuary","moral-crisis"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-stone-of-sakkara\">The Stone of Sakkara</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Stone of Sakkara</strong> is an artifact of terrible and uncertain power currently carried by <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> Philosopher-Bard of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. The Stone&#39;s nature is not fully understood, but its effects are becoming catastrophically clear: it draws <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a> -- the demonic entity at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> -- toward whoever carries it, and when its bearer refuses to feed it, the Stone reaches further, amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"properties\">Properties</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-pull\">The Pull</h3>\n<p>The Stone of Sakkara exerts an influence that can be sensed by demonic entities. <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Guzzler</a> at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> has been drawn toward it for weeks, ranging further and further from its lair in the ruined marsh fort. The Guzzler cannot locate the Stone precisely -- it feels it the way an animal senses weather before it turns. The pull is not a beacon. It is a pressure, a gradient, an ambient wrongness that the Guzzler follows without understanding.</p>\n<p>When the Reclaimers were at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, the Guzzler followed. When the party moved south toward <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, the Guzzler followed south. The Stone&#39;s influence is not bounded by distance in any obvious way -- it simply pulls, and what it pulls toward itself is hunger.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-amplification\">The Amplification</h3>\n<p>The Stone is not directing the Guzzler with intelligence. It has no agenda, no consciousness, no plan. But it is <strong>amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent</strong>. This is not a targeting mechanism -- it is a distortion of the Guzzler&#39;s already indiscriminate appetite, bending it toward the most vulnerable prey. Farm animals. Horses. Children.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> refused to feed the Stone. The Stone&#39;s response was not retribution -- it is not capable of retribution. It simply reached further. The refusal to feed it did not stop the hunger. It redirected it. The Stone found other sources of sustenance by amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s predatory range and focusing its appetite on easier, softer, more innocent targets.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-wrongness\">The Wrongness</h3>\n<p>Theodotus does not perceive the Stone&#39;s influence clearly. He feels it as a <strong>wrongness</strong> -- a sense that the suffering he hears about along the road is somehow adjacent to the weight in his pack. Not a voice. Not a compulsion. Just a persistent, gnawing awareness that the violence happening around him is not random, that its proximity to his path is not coincidence, and that the artifact he carries is somehow the center of gravity around which the suffering orbits.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-trail-of-incidents\">The Trail of Incidents</h2>\n<p>As the Reclaimers move south from <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> toward <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, the Guzzler follows, and the Stone&#39;s amplification produces an escalating trail of violence along the road:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>A farm three miles south of Fort Meade:</strong> Goats taken. Fence posts crushed in. The farmer reports it two days late, embarrassed he waited.</li>\n<li><strong>A merchant on the Sanctuary road:</strong> His draft horse found half-consumed at the roadside. He saw nothing. Heard nothing. The horse was simply gone.</li>\n<li><strong>Closer to Sanctuary:</strong> A child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The escalation is not coincidence. The Stone amplifies hunger toward innocence, and each incident is more devastating than the last. Farm animals. A horse. A child. The trajectory is clear and terrible.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"theodotuss-moral-crisis\">Theodotus&#39;s Moral Crisis</h2>\n<p>When the child&#39;s disappearance reaches <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> -- by rumor, or by encountering the family directly on the road -- the wrongness crystallizes. The ambient unease becomes certainty. This is the test.</p>\n<p>Not a combat encounter. A question. Several questions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Does he tell the party what he suspects?</strong> The Stone&#39;s influence has been his burden alone. Sharing it means admitting that the deaths along the road may be his fault -- not through action, but through possession.</li>\n<li><strong>Does he try to destroy the Stone?</strong> And does he know how? The Stone&#39;s nature is not understood. Destruction may not be possible, or may release something worse.</li>\n<li><strong>Does he draw the Guzzler away from the road deliberately?</strong> Leading it into wilderness, away from settlements and travelers -- a sacrifice of convenience for the sake of innocent lives.</li>\n<li><strong>Does he realize the geometry of innocence does not change?</strong> Putting distance between himself and the Stone means it simply calls the creature further. The Guzzler&#39;s range extends. The innocents along the new path are no safer than the ones along the old. The problem is not location. The problem is the Stone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-core-truth\">The Core Truth</h3>\n<p><strong>Killing the Guzzler resolves nothing.</strong> The Stone will reach through something else. The Guzzler is a symptom, not the disease. Whatever hunger the Stone amplifies, whatever demonic attention it attracts, destroying one vessel of that hunger does not eliminate the hunger itself. Another entity will be drawn. Another predator will be bent toward innocence. The Stone is the problem.</p>\n<p>The scene ends when Theodotus decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"factional-interest\">Factional Interest</h2>\n<p>The Stone of Sakkara has drawn attention from multiple factions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Argollean Brotherhood</a></strong> is aware of the Stone and has an interest in it -- likely viewing it as an artifact of <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> or <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean</a> provenance that belongs to the descendants of its creators.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a></strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> has a competing interest -- the Academy would view the Stone as a subject of scholarly study and, ultimately, imperial property.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a></strong> carries it, and the moral weight of that carrying is growing heavier with every incident along the road.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"unresolved-questions\">Unresolved Questions</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What is the Stone of Sakkara?</strong> Its origin, its purpose, and the nature of its power remain unknown.</li>\n<li><strong>Can it be destroyed?</strong> And what would happen if it were?</li>\n<li><strong>Is the Stone sentient?</strong> Its behavior suggests something more than inert enchantment -- the amplification of hunger toward innocence implies a will, or at least a preference. But Theodotus&#39;s perception of it as a wrongness rather than a voice suggests it operates below the threshold of consciousness.</li>\n<li><strong>What does &quot;feeding the Stone&quot; mean?</strong> Theodotus refused to feed it. What would feeding it look like? What would it require?</li>\n<li><strong>What will the Stone reach through next?</strong> If the Guzzler is destroyed, what entity or force will the Stone attract next?</li>\n<li><strong>Who or what is Sakkara?</strong> The name itself is unexplored.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- The Reclaimer who carries the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- The Guzzler&#39;s lair</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison endangered by the Stone&#39;s pull</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- The city the Reclaimers are traveling toward, where the Guzzler&#39;s arrival would be catastrophic</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party implicated in the Stone&#39;s trail of violence</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- Faction interested in the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Academy historian with competing interest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- Institution that would claim the Stone for study</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history documenting the Stone&#39;s effects</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-veil","title":"The Veil","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["veil","beyond","sorcery","corruption","membrane","multiverse","elvoran","cthonic","demons","lakandi","magic"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-veil\">The Veil</h1>\n<p>The Veil is the living membrane between the mortal realm and the Beyond — the barrier, boundary, and point of contact that separates the material world from the vast, alien expanse of other planes, forgotten gods, and raw metaphysical potential that lies on the other side. The Veil is not a wall or a border in any conventional sense. It is a living thing — a dynamic, responsive, semi-permeable membrane that was created as a cosmic wound when <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a> sacrificed itself, and that has pulsed, shifted, and fluctuated ever since.</p>\n<p>The Veil was first discovered — or first understood — by the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a>, who perceived it through senses and cognitive frameworks that other races lack. The Elvoran understanding of the Veil remains the most sophisticated in the known world, though human sorcerers, particularly those trained in <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, have developed their own theoretical frameworks for understanding and interacting with the membrane.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"nature-of-the-veil\">Nature of the Veil</h2>\n<h3 id=\"a-living-membrane\">A Living Membrane</h3>\n<p>The Veil is not static. It breathes, contracts, expands, thins, and thickens in response to forces both natural and artificial. Certain locations are naturally thin — places where the membrane between the mortal realm and the Beyond is so attenuated that entities, energies, or perceptions can pass between the two with relative ease. Other locations are thick, reinforced by centuries of Empyrean worship, consecrated ground, or simple distance from sources of metaphysical stress. The <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> have long understood that temples and consecrated sites serve a practical function beyond the spiritual — they reinforce the Veil, thickening the membrane and making it harder for the forces beyond to penetrate.</p>\n<h3 id=\"not-merely-a-boundary\">Not Merely a Boundary</h3>\n<p>The Veil is not merely a dividing line between &quot;here&quot; and &quot;there&quot; but a point of contact — a multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten gods, and raw metaphysical potential. The Beyond is not a single place but an infinite expanse of realities, dimensions, and states of being that human minds were not designed to comprehend. Some of these planes are inhabited by intelligences — demons, titans, forgotten gods, entities that defy categorization — and the Veil is the only thing preventing direct contact between these intelligences and the mortal world.</p>\n<h3 id=\"created-as-a-cosmic-wound\">Created as a Cosmic Wound</h3>\n<p>The Veil came into existence as a consequence of <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>&#39;s sacrifice — the cosmic wound left behind when the supreme designer tore itself apart to create the cosmos. In this sense, the Veil is a scar — the boundary between the reality that the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice created and the void that existed before. It is simultaneously a consequence of creation and a reminder of the violence that creation required. The Veil is the place where the ordered cosmos meets the unordered void, and the tension between these two states is what gives the membrane its dynamic, living quality.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"sorcery-and-the-veil\">Sorcery and the Veil</h2>\n<h3 id=\"opening-wounds\">Opening Wounds</h3>\n<p>The fundamental act of sorcery — whether practiced through <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>, warlock pacts, hedge-magic, or any other tradition — involves opening wounds in the Veil to siphon energies from the Beyond into the material world. This process is inherently violent. The sorcerer is not gently parting a curtain or opening a door; he is tearing a hole in a living membrane, contesting with the very fabric of reality to create an opening through which power can flow. The Veil resists, the energies beyond are hostile or at best indifferent to mortal purposes, and the act of sorcery leaves both the sorcerer and the membrane damaged.</p>\n<p>This is why sorcery is dangerous, why it is regulated, and why even the most disciplined practitioners of <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> treat their art with caution and respect. The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> teaches that sorcery is the controlled manipulation of metaphysical axioms — a structured, lawful practice governed by the nine-fold geometric patterns described in <a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a>. But even the most structured sorcery still involves wounding the Veil, and every wound, no matter how carefully controlled, carries risk.</p>\n<h3 id=\"corruption-of-flesh-and-mind\">Corruption of Flesh and Mind</h3>\n<p>Prolonged contact with the Veil — or more precisely, prolonged exposure to the energies that flow through the wounds sorcerers create in it — corrupts both flesh and mind. The physical signs are unmistakable and well-documented: eyes blacken, filling with darkness as the sclera darkens to the color of pitch. Bones warp, bending and growing in unnatural configurations. Voices change, taking on harmonics and resonances that no human throat should be able to produce. Skin may harden, crack, or develop patterns that resemble the sigils used in <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a>.</p>\n<p>The mental corruption is equally severe and far more insidious. Sorcerers who draw too heavily or too frequently from the Veil report hearing voices, experiencing alien perceptions, losing time, and finding that their thought patterns have been altered in ways they cannot identify or reverse. The boundary between the sorcerer&#39;s own consciousness and the entities or energies beyond the Veil begins to blur, and in extreme cases, the sorcerer may lose the ability to distinguish between their own thoughts and the whisperings of the Beyond.</p>\n<p>This corruption is a physical and spiritual reality, not merely a metaphor or a moral judgment. It is the price that the mortal body and mind pay for contesting with forces that were never meant to flow through human flesh.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-beyond\">The Beyond</h2>\n<h3 id=\"alien-planes\">Alien Planes</h3>\n<p>The Beyond encompasses an unknown and potentially infinite number of alien planes — realities that operate according to laws fundamentally different from those governing the material world. Some of these planes are hostile environments where mortal life cannot survive. Others are habitable but profoundly alien, governed by physics, biology, and metaphysics that bear no resemblance to anything in the material world. The geography, if it can be called that, of the Beyond is poorly mapped and potentially unmappable — the planes shift, merge, divide, and reconfigure in ways that defy cartographic discipline.</p>\n<h3 id=\"forgotten-gods-and-titans\">Forgotten Gods and Titans</h3>\n<p>Among the inhabitants of the Beyond are entities of immense power — forgotten gods, primordial titans, and beings of such alien nature that the words &quot;god&quot; and &quot;titan&quot; are only approximate labels. These entities predate the current cosmic order, or emerged from realities parallel to it, and their relationship to <a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a>, <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a> is poorly understood. Some may be the remnants of cosmological systems that the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice overwrote or displaced. Others may be native to the void that existed before creation. Their intentions toward the material world, if they have intentions at all, are rarely benign.</p>\n<h3 id=\"communion-with-cthonic-powers\">Communion with Cthonic Powers</h3>\n<p>The Veil permits communion with the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic gods</a>, demons, and the forgotten titans described above. The <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a> has long used the Veil as a medium of communication and transaction — rituals performed at thin points in the membrane can reach across the divide and establish contact with Cthonic entities, receiving guidance, power, or direct supernatural intervention in exchange for offerings, oaths, or the creation of conditions favorable to the entity&#39;s interests. This practice is the foundation of Cthonic priestly power and the mechanism by which Cthonic cults maintain their connection to their divine patrons.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"lakandi-demon-binding\">Lakandi Demon-Binding</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> practice a distinctive form of interaction with the Veil: individual-scale demon-binding. Rather than the communal rituals and priestly hierarchies that characterize most Cthonic interactions with the Veil, the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a> involves individual practitioners establishing personal relationships with specific demonic entities, binding them through negotiated contracts and using them as sources of power, knowledge, or direct supernatural service.</p>\n<p>This practice is conducted at the individual scale — each Lakandi binder negotiates their own contract, bears their own risks, and reaps their own rewards. The tradition is ancient, deeply embedded in <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> culture, and operated with a degree of openness and social acceptance that would be unthinkable in most Mithrian communities. The Lakandi do not view demon-binding as evil or corrupting but as a practical skill — dangerous, certainly, but no more inherently immoral than any other form of commerce or negotiation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-aurelion\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Aurelion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-anthyllium\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Anthyllium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-flame\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Flame</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Faith</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-pantheon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Pantheon</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi Binding Tradition</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Races and Cultures</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"the-womb-curse","title":"The Womb Curse","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["eladra","elvora","mystery","womb-curse","eolande","malachor","black-tree","barren","immortal","veil"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-womb-curse\">The Womb Curse</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Womb Curse</strong> is a term mentioned by <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a> -- the ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> general from approximately 3000 BE -- during his encounter with <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a> at the Black Tree at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a>. Its full nature has not yet been revealed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>First Mentioned By</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">eolande</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Context</strong></td>\n<td>Discussion of the [[eladra</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Urgently Sought By</strong></td>\n<td>[[malachor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Mystery -- nature unclear</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Likely Connection</strong></td>\n<td>The [[elvora</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"what-is-known\">What Is Known</h2>\n<p>[[Eolande</span> mentioned the Womb Curse at the Black Tree during his encounter with the Reclaimers. The specific context of his remarks is not fully recorded, but the mention was significant enough to provoke an <strong>urgent reaction from <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a></strong>, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> agent stationed at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>.</p>\n<p>Malachor&#39;s response was immediate and intense: <strong>&quot;What did he say about the Womb Curse? About the Eladra?&quot;</strong> -- the urgency of a scholar who has been searching for this information and recognizes its importance the moment it surfaces.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"probable-connections\">Probable Connections</h2>\n<p>The Womb Curse likely relates to one or both of the following:</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-elvora-condition\">The Elvora Condition</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> -- the corrupted descendants of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> who plunged into the chaos of <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Beyond</a> -- suffer a specific and devastating biological curse:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>All Elvora females are barren</strong> -- they cannot bear children</li>\n<li><strong>All Elvora males are immortal</strong> -- they do not age or die of natural causes</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This combination is a slow-motion extinction event. The Elvora cannot reproduce. Their numbers can only decrease. Their immortality is not a gift but a sentence -- eternal life for a dying race. The term &quot;Womb Curse&quot; aligns precisely with this condition: a curse that strikes at the womb, at reproduction, at the continuation of the species.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-eladran-disappearance\">The Eladran Disappearance</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> vanished without explanation. Their belongings remained. Their constructs continued to function. But the people simply ceased to be present. The Womb Curse may be connected to whatever metaphysical event caused this disappearance -- perhaps the same force that rendered the Elvora barren also destroyed or transformed the Eladra of Aodahn.</p>\n<p>The Threshold in the <a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Undercity</a> beneath <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened and the door has not fully closed -- may be the site where the Womb Curse originated or was enacted.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"malachors-interest\">Malachor&#39;s Interest</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor&#39;s</a> urgent interest in the Womb Curse reveals that the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> has prior knowledge of the concept -- enough to recognize the term immediately and understand its significance. The Academy has clearly been investigating the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> mystery, and the Womb Curse is a piece of that puzzle they have been seeking.</p>\n<p>That an Academy agent stationed in the remote Backlands reacts with such urgency suggests the Womb Curse is not merely an academic curiosity but a matter of active strategic or metaphysical importance to the Academy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"eolandes-knowledge\">Eolande&#39;s Knowledge</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a> dates from approximately 3000 BE -- over five thousand years before the current campaign date. If the Womb Curse was known in his time, it predates the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora&#39;s</a> corruption, the fall of the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>, and the rise of human civilization in Argolle. This would mean the Womb Curse is an ancient phenomenon -- not a recent corruption but something woven into the deep history of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> race.</p>\n<p>Alternatively, Eolande&#39;s millennia of existence at the Black Tree may have given him knowledge of events that occurred long after his own era. A being who has persisted for five thousand years has had time to witness -- or learn of -- the Elvora&#39;s transformation and the Eladran disappearance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"open-questions\">Open Questions</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Is the Womb Curse the same phenomenon that rendered the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a> barren and immortal?</li>\n<li>Did the Womb Curse cause the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> to vanish?</li>\n<li>Is the Womb Curse connected to the Threshold in the <a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Undercity</a>?</li>\n<li>Why does the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> consider this information urgent?</li>\n<li>What does <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a> know that <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> does not?</li>\n<li>Is the Womb Curse a natural consequence of contact with <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>, or was it deliberately inflicted?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">eolande</a> -- The ancient Eladran general who mentioned the Womb Curse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- The Imperial Academy agent urgently seeking information about it</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The race the Womb Curse concerns</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> -- Corrupted Eladra whose barrenness may be the Womb Curse manifest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">aodahn</a> -- The Eladran city whose inhabitants vanished</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-undercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-undercity</a> -- The megadungeon beneath Sanctuary, site of the Threshold</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-black-tree\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-black-tree</a> -- Where Eolande mentioned the Womb Curse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> -- Site of the Black Tree encounter</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The metaphysical boundary possibly connected to the Curse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution investigating the Eladran mystery</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"thrassian","title":"Thrassian","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","thrassian","naming","human","tribal","warrior","military"],"html":"<h1 id=\"thrassian\">Thrassian</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Thrassians</strong> are a proud and warlike mountain people whose ancient tribal system persists within the framework of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Though formally incorporated into the Empire, Thrassian communities maintain strong tribal identities, and old loyalties to clan and chief often compete with obligations to the Imperial state.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>Thrassians are characterized by their curly dark hair and dark eyes. Their mountain heritage gives them sturdy, weathered builds suited to the harsh terrain of Thrassia. They are a physically imposing people, shaped by generations of highland warfare and pastoral life.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>Thrassian culture is fundamentally tribal and warrior-oriented. The tribe is the primary unit of Thrassian identity, superseding even family in matters of loyalty and obligation. Thrassian tribes are led by chiefs whose authority derives from martial prowess, demonstrated wisdom, and the consent of the tribal council.</p>\n<p>The Thrassians are the <strong>backbone of the Mithrian military</strong>. Their warrior traditions, physical toughness, and fierce loyalty to comrades make them natural soldiers, and Thrassian recruits have filled the ranks of Imperial legions since the earliest days of the Empire. A disproportionate number of the Empire&#39;s most decorated soldiers and most feared units are of Thrassian origin.</p>\n<p>Thrassian tribes <strong>clash and assist each other</strong> with equal fervor. Intertribal rivalries are fierce and sometimes violent, but when an external threat appears, the same tribes that were raiding each other&#39;s herds will fight shoulder to shoulder without hesitation. This duality -- fierce internal competition combined with absolute solidarity against outsiders -- is the defining characteristic of Thrassian social life.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Thrassians employ a <strong>patronymic system</strong> that ties each individual directly to their parent:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Men</strong> use the suffixes <strong>-ides</strong> or <strong>-ion</strong> (e.g., Alexandrides, meaning &quot;son of Alexander&quot;; Demetrion, meaning &quot;son of Demetrios&quot;)</li>\n<li><strong>Women</strong> use the suffixes <strong>-aia</strong> or <strong>-essa</strong> (e.g., Helenaia, meaning &quot;daughter of Helen&quot;; Sophiessa, meaning &quot;daughter of Sophia&quot;)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A Thrassian&#39;s <strong>tribal affiliation</strong> remains a critical component of their identity and is often appended informally to their name. A Thrassian warrior might introduce himself not merely as &quot;Leonides&quot; but as &quot;Leonides of the Hawk Tribe&quot; -- the tribal identity carrying as much weight as the patronymic itself.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire the Thrassians serve</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> -- The military institution Thrassians form the backbone of</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- Where Thrassian sailors fill the harbor taverns</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"thune","title":"Thune","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["race","thune","reptilian","argollean","ygrathen","slave-soldiers","cthonic","thunean-empire","massar","awakening","breeding"],"html":"<h1 id=\"thune\">Thune</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Thune</strong> were created by the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolleans</a> as slave soldiers to fight against the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> -- living weapons bred for war. They are reptilian in appearance and possess an alien cunning and intellect that sets them apart from the other races of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>. The Thune are wicked and violent by nature and by design, and their patience is as formidable as their savagery.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Thune come in <strong>various shapes and sizes</strong>, the product of <strong>extensive breeding programs</strong> conducted over millennia. The Argolleans engineered the Thune for specific military roles, and the results of that engineering persist:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Some are <strong>small and swift</strong>, bred for scouting and infiltration</li>\n<li>Others are <strong>massive and heavily armored</strong>, designed for frontline combat</li>\n<li>All share the fundamental <strong>reptilian characteristics</strong> of scaled skin, cold blood, and predatory instinct</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The variety of Thune physiology reflects the thoroughness of their creators&#39; design -- the Argolleans did not create a single type of soldier but an entire ecosystem of war-forms, each optimized for a specific purpose.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Thune possess an <strong>alien cunning and intellect</strong> that is not fully understood by human scholars. Their minds do not work like human minds -- their priorities, their patience, their relationship to time and planning all operate on principles that human psychology struggles to model.</p>\n<p>The Thune <strong>embody the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> faith</strong> in its most brutal form: <strong>the strongest consume and rule the weakest</strong>. This is not merely a philosophical position but the organizing principle of Thune society. Power is absolute, hierarchy is determined by force, and the weak exist to serve or be devoured by the strong. There is no mercy in Thune culture because mercy is a concept that has no place in their understanding of the world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"creation\">Creation</h3>\n<p>The Thune were created by the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> as slave soldiers to fight the <a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> -- the oldest race of Mithrapos, whose solitary nature and formidable sorcerous power made them a persistent threat. The Thune were designed to be expendable, replaceable, and absolutely obedient. They were tools, not people, and the Argolleans treated them accordingly.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-thunean-empire\">The Thunean Empire</h3>\n<p>The Thune eventually broke free of Argollean control and built the <strong><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thunean Empire</a></strong> -- a dominion built on conquest, cruelty, and the subjugation of all other peoples within their reach. The Thunean Empire was a brutal regime even by the harsh standards of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a>, and its legacy of violence and oppression has colored the way all other peoples regard the Thune to this day.</p>\n<h3 id=\"overthrow-by-the-massar\">Overthrow by the Massar</h3>\n<p>The Thunean Empire was eventually <strong>overthrown by <a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massar</a> advisors</strong> -- counselors who had been brought into the Thunean court and who used their position to orchestrate the empire&#39;s downfall from within. The Massar accomplished through patient political manipulation what no army had managed through force of arms: the destruction of the Thunean Empire from the inside out.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-status\">Current Status</h2>\n<p>In the present day, the Thune are found only in <strong>rare pockets</strong> -- scattered remnants of their former empire, hiding in remote and inhospitable regions. They are <strong>savage but biding their time</strong> for what they call the <strong>Awakening</strong> -- a prophesied event in which the Thune will rise again to reclaim their former dominion.</p>\n<p>The Awakening is not a vague hope but a fixed certainty in Thune culture. They do not question whether it will come -- they prepare for when it comes. The patience of the Thune is measured in generations, and their plans operate on timescales that human strategists cannot easily comprehend.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- The empire that created the Thune</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">ygrathen</a> -- The ancient race the Thune were created to fight</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/massar\" class=\"wiki-link\">massar</a> -- The people who overthrew the Thunean Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The faith the Thune embody</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The broader historical context</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"vestari","title":"Vestari","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["culture","vestari","naming","human","bellasarius","mithrian-league","cosmopolitan","aristocratic","nobility"],"html":"<h1 id=\"vestari\">Vestari</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Vestari</strong> are a proud and aristocratic people who trace their lineage to <strong><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a></strong>, the legendary general who co-founded the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a> alongside the <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a>. This claimed descent from the Empire&#39;s greatest hero gives the Vestari an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Vestari are <strong>tall and narrow-faced with heavy brows and black hair</strong>, which is characteristically <strong>slicked back</strong>. Men carry <strong>heavy, well-groomed beards</strong> as a mark of dignity and status -- a Vestari man&#39;s beard is a statement of identity, and its care and presentation are matters of serious concern.</p>\n<p>Their skin ranges from <strong>olive to pale</strong>, and they favor <strong>ornate jewelry</strong> -- rings, chains, clasps, and brooches -- as expressions of wealth, lineage, and personal accomplishment. Vestari clothing is similarly ornate, with rich fabrics and elaborate detailing that reflect the wearer&#39;s status and heritage.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-values\">Culture and Values</h2>\n<p>The Vestari are <strong>cosmopolitan allies of Mithra</strong> and were the <strong>first city-state to join the Mithrian League</strong>. Uniquely among the peoples incorporated into the League, the Vestari <strong>joined without bloodshed</strong> -- a distinction they have never let anyone forget. Where other peoples were conquered, subjugated, or coerced, the Vestari came willingly, recognizing in the League the fulfillment of the vision their ancestor Bellasarius had fought for.</p>\n<p>The Vestari <strong>nobility traces its lineage to Bellasarius</strong> himself. Whether this descent is historically accurate or a product of centuries of genealogical invention is a matter that no one raises in polite Vestari company. The claim is the foundation of Vestari identity, and to challenge it is to challenge the Vestari sense of self.</p>\n<p>The Vestari&#39;s sense of cultural superiority is not aggressive but pervasive. They regard themselves as the truest heirs of the League&#39;s founding ideals, the people most closely connected to the heroic age that produced the Empire. This conviction shapes their politics, their art, their social expectations, and their interactions with every other culture in the Empire.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"naming-conventions\">Naming Conventions</h2>\n<p>Vestari names are <strong>ornate and multi-syllabic</strong>, frequently incorporating references to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Virtues</strong> -- names that invoke courage, wisdom, justice, and honor</li>\n<li><strong>Ancestors</strong> -- names that connect the bearer to illustrious forebears</li>\n<li><strong>Religious concepts</strong> -- names drawn from <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> theology and the <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Measure and the Scale</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>A Vestari&#39;s full name is a declaration of heritage -- a compressed genealogy that connects the bearer to their illustrious forebears and the spiritual ideals they are expected to uphold.</p>\n<p>The Vestari <strong>follow Mithrian naming conventions</strong>, employing the same three-part system (praenomen, nomen, cognomen) used by the dominant culture. This is not imitation but a shared inheritance -- the Vestari regard the naming conventions not as borrowed from Mithrian culture but as a tradition they helped create.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bellasarius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bellasarius Valerian</a> -- The legendary ancestor of the Vestari</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire the Vestari helped found</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-culture\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-culture</a> -- The culture whose naming conventions the Vestari share</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The founding of the Mithrian League</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> -- The faith that shapes Vestari spiritual life</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"war-of-three-emperors","title":"The War of Three Emperors (270 IY)","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["event","history","civil-war","house-decimus","house-valerian","succession-crisis","aurex","claudius-decimus"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-war-of-three-emperors-270-iy\">The War of Three Emperors (270 IY)</h1>\n<p>The <strong>War of Three Emperors</strong> (270 IY) was the devastating civil war that erupted following the assassination of the mad Emperor <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a> of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>. The conflict ended the Valerian dynasty&#39;s centuries-long hold on the Imperial throne and established <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> as the ruling house of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> -- a position it retains to this day.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;We traded madness for cowardice, then cowardice for coin. Of all our emperors, it was the one who ruled for 87 days who showed the greatest strength.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a></strong>, on accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"causes\">Causes</h2>\n<p>Emperor <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a> of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> had brought the Empire to the brink of collapse through madness and cruelty. When his own sister assassinated him -- an act of desperate necessity -- he died without naming an heir. The Valerian dynasty, which had held the throne for centuries, ended not with a battle but with a knife in the dark and an empty succession.</p>\n<p>The absence of a clear successor created a power vacuum that drew in every ambitious general, governor, and noble house in the Empire.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-scholar-emperor-numerius\">The Scholar-Emperor Numerius</h2>\n<p>In the immediate aftermath of Aurex&#39;s assassination, the scholar <strong>Numerius</strong> was installed as Emperor -- a principled and learned man who attempted to restore order through reason, law, and good governance. Numerius ruled for only <strong>87 days</strong> before he was murdered.</p>\n<p>His brief reign is remembered as a tragedy. <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> himself would later eulogize Numerius as the Emperor who &quot;showed the greatest strength&quot; -- a man whose virtues were precisely the qualities the Imperial system was least equipped to sustain. Numerius&#39;s murder demonstrated that the Empire did not reward wisdom or principle; it rewarded power.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-civil-war\">The Civil War</h2>\n<p>Following Numerius&#39;s death, the Empire descended into open civil war. Multiple claimants raised armies, forged alliances, and fought for the throne. The conflict was brutal and widespread, drawing in the Great Houses and their tributary networks, threatening to tear the Empire apart entirely.</p>\n<p>The details of the war -- which claimants fought, which alliances formed and collapsed, which battles decided the outcome -- are recorded in Imperial chronicles. What matters for the present is the result: <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> emerged victorious from the chaos, defeating his rivals through military competence, strategic patience, and the ruthlessness that civil wars demand.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"consequences\">Consequences</h2>\n<p>The War of Three Emperors reshaped the political order of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a></strong> was established as the ruling dynasty. The Decimus line has held the throne without interruption from 270 IY to the present day.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a></strong> lost the throne permanently. The house retained its prestige and wealth but was stripped of political supremacy. Many believe the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration.</li>\n<li><strong>The precedent of violent succession</strong> was reinforced. The Empire has no stable mechanism for the peaceful transfer of power, and the War of Three Emperors demonstrated -- again -- that the throne ultimately belongs to whoever can take it by force.</li>\n<li><strong>Claudius Decimus&#39;s legacy</strong> -- His words upon accepting the title of Imperator revealed a man acutely aware of the Empire&#39;s decline: a trajectory from madness to cowardice to greed that had corroded the foundations of imperial governance.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"later-succession-crisis\">Later Succession Crisis</h2>\n<p>The Decimus dynasty&#39;s own history has not been free of succession violence. <strong>Julian Decimus</strong>, a later Emperor, named his son <strong>Diometian</strong> as heir -- a decision that triggered civil war when rival claimants and discontented houses refused to accept the appointment. The resulting conflict demonstrated that the problems of succession that destroyed the Valerian dynasty had not been solved by replacing it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> -- the victor and dynasty founder</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a> -- the mad Emperor whose death triggered the crisis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> -- the dynasty that emerged from the war</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> -- the dynasty that fell</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> -- the current Emperor</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a> -- broader historical context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"ygrathen","title":"Ygrathen","category":"lore","status":"unknown","tags":["race","ygrathen","ancient","sorcery","solitary","cairnhouse","kharai","binding","grathar","varek-ashstone","argollean"],"html":"<h1 id=\"ygrathen\">Ygrathen</h1>\n<p>The <strong>Ygrathen</strong> are the oldest of all the races of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> -- ancient beyond reckoning, predating even the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>. They are solitary beings by nature, possessed of tremendous physical and sorcerous power, and they embody one of the most profound insights in the world&#39;s history: <strong>some things cannot be ended, only contained.</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"physical-appearance\">Physical Appearance</h2>\n<p>The Ygrathen are <strong>massive</strong> -- standing approximately <strong>12 feet tall</strong>, with <strong>greenish or ochre skin</strong> and <strong>small tusks</strong> protruding from their lower jaws. Despite their brutish appearance, they are beings of tremendous intelligence and sorcerous ability. Their size, their coloring, and their tusks make them immediately recognizable -- and immediately formidable. There is nothing subtle about an Ygrathen&#39;s presence.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"culture-and-nature\">Culture and Nature</h2>\n<p>The Ygrathen <strong>never formed their own civilization</strong> in any conventional sense. They are too solitary, too individualistic, and too prone to conflict with their own kind. Throughout their long history, the Ygrathen <strong>clashed amongst themselves</strong> as often as they fought against other races, preventing any lasting social organization from taking root.</p>\n<h3 id=\"breeding\">Breeding</h3>\n<p>The Ygrathen are solitary beings who come together only to <strong>breed every 33 years</strong> under specific cosmological conditions tied to the alignment of celestial bodies. This extremely infrequent reproduction, combined with their solitary nature and the devastating losses of their war against the Argollean Empire, has reduced their numbers to near-extinction.</p>\n<h3 id=\"sorcery\">Sorcery</h3>\n<p>The Ygrathen possess <strong>powerful sorcery</strong> -- their magical abilities are among the most formidable in the world. Ygrathen sorcery is not learned from books or academies but is an expression of their fundamental nature, refined over lifespans that may stretch for centuries or millennia.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history\">History</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-war-against-the-argollean-empire\">The War Against the Argollean Empire</h3>\n<p>The Ygrathen&#39;s war against the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> was a cataclysmic conflict that left <strong>most of their kind dead or driven into hiding</strong>. The Argolleans created the <a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thune</a> specifically as slave soldiers to fight the Ygrathen -- a testament to how formidable the Ygrathen were as opponents. The war drained the Empire&#39;s resources and weakened its foundations even as it drove the Ygrathen to the edge of extinction.</p>\n<p>The few survivors retreated into the most remote and inaccessible regions of Mithrapos, where they remain to this day -- hidden, diminished, but not extinct.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-cairnhouses-and-the-kharai\">The Cairnhouses and the Kharai</h2>\n<p>The Ygrathen built <strong>cairnhouses</strong> -- structures of Ygrathen design, engineered with precision and sustained intention, designed to imprison the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> (the Imprisoned Ones). The Kharai are beings of enormous will and appetite, ancient beyond reckoning, that defy classification within either <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> or <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> frameworks. They are simply what they are: vast, patient, and <strong>impossible to destroy</strong>.</p>\n<p>The Ygrathen imprisoned the Kharai rather than destroying them. The most straightforward explanation is that they could not be destroyed. But there is another possibility: perhaps the Ygrathen understood something about the Kharai that has since been forgotten -- that destruction was possible but unwise, that the Kharai serve a function in the deep structure of the world.</p>\n<p>This is the central Ygrathen insight: <strong>some things cannot be ended, only contained.</strong> The cairnhouses are the physical expression of this understanding -- structures designed to hold beings that will never stop pressing against their confinement, maintained by practitioners whose vigil may last centuries.</p>\n<p>At least two cairnhouses are known to exist in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The cairnhouse on the island of <strong>Kantar</strong> in <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a> -- watched over by <a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a></li>\n<li>The cairnhouse at <strong><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a></strong> -- whose psychic bleed has shaped the town&#39;s population over six to seven generations</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-grathar\">The Grathar</h2>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Grathar</a></strong> people carry Ygrathen blood in their veins -- a heritage that accounts for their exceptional size and strength, their ochre-to-greenish skin tone, and their reclusive temperament. The Grathar are the most visible legacy of the Ygrathen in the modern world, living proof that the oldest race of Mithrapos has not been entirely lost.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"varek-ashstone\">Varek Ashstone</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">Varek Ashstone</a></strong> is a known Ygrathen hermit who built the cairnhouse at Kantar and has maintained a solitary vigil over it for centuries. He lives in a stone dwelling on the northern shore of <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a>. The <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> call him the Old One or simply Varek. He is very large, very old, very tired, and very capable. His vigil is penance for something that went wrong during the cairnhouse&#39;s construction -- people died, and Varek has spent the centuries since as atonement.</p>\n<p>Varek&#39;s power is the <strong>binding tradition</strong>: the art of sealing and containing powerful entities. He is one of the last living practitioners of this tradition at its full scale. His capabilities are demonstrated not in dramatic displays of force but in what does not happen near Lake Silverhead -- things from the outlands that have approached Kantar have been turned away, bound, redirected, or persuaded that the cost was greater than the return.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-ygrathen-binding-tradition\">The Ygrathen Binding Tradition</h2>\n<p>The Ygrathen binding tradition is related to but distinct from the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a>. The Ygrathen bind at a scale that exceeds even the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>: they imprisoned beings that cannot be destroyed, using structures designed to endure for millennia. The Lakandi operate at the opposite end of the spectrum -- individual practitioners binding individual entities for personal use. The traditions share a common root but have diverged enormously in scope and application.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> -- Overview of all races and cultures</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/varek-ashstone\" class=\"wiki-link\">varek-ashstone</a> -- The Ygrathen hermit of Lake Silverhead</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- The Imprisoned Ones the Ygrathen built cairnhouses to contain</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a> -- A town shaped by a cairnhouse&#39;s psychic bleed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/grathar\" class=\"wiki-link\">grathar</a> -- The human people who carry Ygrathen blood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- The empire that warred against the Ygrathen</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thune\" class=\"wiki-link\">thune</a> -- The slave soldiers created to fight the Ygrathen</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- The ancient race that postdates the Ygrathen</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> -- A race whose binding tradition parallels the Ygrathen&#39;s</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- The individual-scale binding tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The faction seeking access to cairnhouse binding structures</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"overview","title":"The Fallen Empire — Campaign Overview","category":"overview","status":"unknown","tags":["overview","backlands","fallen-empire"],"html":"<h1 id=\"the-fallen-empire-campaign-overview\">The Fallen Empire — Campaign Overview</h1>\n<h2 id=\"the-setting\">The Setting</h2>\n<p>The world of Mithrapos is a region encircling the Middle Sea, shaped by the rise and fall of empires. The ancient <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> (the First Empire) fell long ago, but its echoes still influence the modern <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> — the dominant power of the region, now in what many believe to be its twilight.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> is ruled by Emperor <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> from the alabaster walls of <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>. Imperial power rests on four pillars: the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">military</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> of sorcery, the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a> of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">Great Houses</a> that dominate politics through patronage.</p>\n<p>The sacred text <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Measure and the Scale</a> serves as both religious doctrine and legal framework. Three traditions of <a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic</a> exist: the Academy&#39;s gnostic geometry, the Elvoran art of piercing the Veil, and the Flame channeled by the faithful of Seros.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> and <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> faiths offer competing visions of the cosmos — one of reincarnation and purification, the other of consumption and the prophesied Awakening. The Empire outlaws Cthonic worship, but its cults persist in shadow.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-backlands\">The Backlands</h2>\n<p>The Backlands is a remote northern province of the Mithrian Empire — the frontier. In 377 IY, a beastman horde sacked the town of Crossings, and the Emperor&#39;s response (a scalp bounty that drew mercenaries, deserters, and killers into the region) left the Backlands in a state of simmering chaos. The current year is <strong>380 IY</strong>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"current-campaign\">Current Campaign</h2>\n<p><em>The Reclaimers</em> — a party of adventurers operating in the Backlands.</p>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> — Political structure and governance</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">great-houses</a> — The noble houses that shape imperial politics</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> — Timeline of key events</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic-and-sorcery</a> — The three traditions of sorcery</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">races-and-cultures</a> — Peoples of Mithrapos</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> — The state religion</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> — The outlawed dark cults</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"anaya","title":"Anaya","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["henchman","reclaimers","corruption","wounded","visions","gallowswood","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"anaya\">Anaya</h1>\n<p><strong>Anaya</strong> is a henchman serving <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. She suffered a critical wound from a <strong>zombie beastman</strong> and has since been afflicted with fever and infection -- but what troubles those around her is not the wound itself but what has followed it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Role</strong></td>\n<td>Henchman of <span class=\"dead-link\">the-reclaimers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Active -- wounded, feverish, possibly corrupted</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Wound</strong></td>\n<td>Critical injury from a zombie beastman</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Condition</strong></td>\n<td>Feverish, wound infected, experiencing disturbing visions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Threat</strong></td>\n<td>Possible [[cthonic-corruption</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-wound\">The Wound</h2>\n<p>Anaya was critically wounded by a <strong>zombie beastman</strong> -- an undead creature combining the savagery of [[beastmen</span> with the horror of necromantic animation. The wound has become infected and she is feverish, but the physical injury may be the least of her problems.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-visions\">The Visions</h2>\n<p>Since her wounding, Anaya speaks of a <strong>pulsating black heart beneath the mound</strong> in the <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a>. She describes it as calling to her, beckoning her forth -- a psychic pull from whatever entity or force lies beneath the granite dome in the cursed forest.</p>\n<p>The Gallowswood is a place where the dead walk beneath the roots, and a pulsating black heart beats beneath a granite dome. Anaya&#39;s visions suggest a direct connection between her zombie beastman wound and whatever <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> power animates the Gallowswood&#39;s undead.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gretas-reaction\">Greta&#39;s Reaction</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">Greta of Bone Creek</a> -- the old <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> witch who holds a bound demon and practices the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a> -- is <strong>visibly disturbed</strong> by Anaya&#39;s visions. Greta does not share why she is disturbed, which is itself alarming. Greta is not a woman given to visible emotion without cause. Whatever she recognizes in Anaya&#39;s descriptions, she is not willing to speak of it openly.</p>\n<p>This silence from a woman who traffics with entities from beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> suggests that what calls to Anaya from beneath the Gallowswood is something Greta understands -- and fears.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"implications\">Implications</h2>\n<p>Anaya&#39;s condition raises urgent questions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Is the zombie beastman wound a vector for <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic corruption</a>?</li>\n<li>Is the pulsating black heart beneath the Gallowswood actively reaching out to the wounded, the dying, or the corruptible?</li>\n<li>Does Greta&#39;s silence indicate she knows what the heart is -- and that the knowledge is too dangerous to share?</li>\n<li>Can Anaya be saved, or is the beckoning already too deep?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party Anaya serves as henchman</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> -- The cursed forest whose black heart calls to her</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/greta\" class=\"wiki-link\">greta</a> -- The Lakandi witch disturbed by Anaya&#39;s visions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The corruption that may be taking hold</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The zombie beastman that wounded her</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"antonius","title":"Antonius","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["henchman","reclaimers","vision","rendson","loyalty","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"antonius\">Antonius</h1>\n<p><strong>Antonius</strong> is a henchman serving <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. He nearly died in the field and, as he neared death, experienced a <strong>vision of <a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rendson</a></strong> -- the dead former Reclaimer, the Avari gambler and fugitive known as the Grim Sleeper.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Role</strong></td>\n<td>Henchman of <span class=\"dead-link\">Rendson</span> -- the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> gambler, whoremonger, and fugitive who died alongside <a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred</a> fighting a necropede in the Backlands. Rendson was known as the &quot;Grim Sleeper&quot; for his talent of killing beasts where they lay.</p>\n<p>The nature and content of the vision are not fully known. Whether Rendson appeared as a warning, a comfort, a guide, or something else entirely is unclear. What is clear is that the experience has shaken Antonius enough to raise concerns about his continued loyalty and mental state.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"loyalty-concerns\">Loyalty Concerns</h2>\n<p>A loyalty check is needed. Near-death visions of fallen comrades can break a henchman&#39;s resolve or twist their priorities in unpredictable ways. The Backlands are a place where the boundary between the living and the dead is thin, where <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> frays, and where visions cannot be dismissed as mere hallucination.</p>\n<p>Whether Antonius saw Rendson through the natural delirium of blood loss or through something more metaphysical -- a genuine contact with the dead, a Cthonic lure, or a glimpse beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> -- remains to be determined.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party Antonius serves as henchman</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">rendson</a> -- The dead Reclaimer who appeared in Antonius&#39;s vision</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- Died alongside Rendson fighting a necropede</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The boundary between the living and the dead</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"arannis-venn","title":"Arannis Venn","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","spellsword","eladran","scholar","argollean-brotherhood","criminal","backlands","artifacts","lore"],"html":"<h1 id=\"arannis-venn\">Arannis Venn</h1>\n<p><strong>Arannis Venn</strong> is an <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> spellsword and scholar who serves as the leader of the <strong>Argollean Brotherhood</strong> in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. Reserved and intensely focused, Venn is a figure of quiet authority who commands respect through intellect, competence, and the weight of ancient <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> heritage. He is a <strong>source of lore and artifacts</strong> for those who seek knowledge of the old world, but he is also <strong>morally gray</strong> — willing to deal in shadows, secrets, and criminal enterprise when it serves his purposes.</p>\n<p>Venn leads a <strong>criminal network</strong> connected to old Eladran noble houses, blending scholarly pursuit with underworld operations in a way that makes him both invaluable and dangerous to those who deal with him.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Spellsword 6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>2</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>33</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+4-(longsword,-1d8+1)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>int</strong></td>-<td>16</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>venn&#39;s-statistics-reflect-a-warrior-scholar-of-considerable-ability.-his-ac-of-2-indicates-heavy-armor-—-likely-enchanted-or-of-exceptional-eladran-craftsmanship-—-while-his-33-hit-points-and-+4-attack-bonus-make-him-a-dangerous-combatant-in-melee.-his-intelligence-of-16-supports-both-his-spellcasting-and-his-role-as-a-master-of-lore-and-strategy.-as-a-spellsword,-venn-blends-martial-prowess-with-arcane-power,-making-him-a-versatile-and-unpredictable-opponent.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"spells\">spells</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>magic-missile</strong>-—-unerring-bolts-of-arcane-force;-a-reliable-and-unavoidable-offensive-spell-that-reflects-venn&#39;s-pragmatic-approach-to-combat</li>-<li><strong>dispel-magic</strong>-—-the-ability-to-unravel-and-neutralize-magical-effects;-essential-for-a-scholar-who-deals-in-ancient-artifacts-and-may-encounter-wards,-curses,-and-enchantments</li>-<li><strong>knock</strong>-—-magical-opening-of-locks-and-barriers;-a-practical-spell-for-a-man-who-leads-a-criminal-network-and-frequently-needs-access-to-places-he-is-not-welcome</li>-</ul>-<p>venn&#39;s-spell-selection-is-notably-<strong>practical-and-utilitarian</strong>-—-no-flashy-destructive-magic,-but-instead-a-toolkit-designed-for-precision,-access,-and-control.-this-mirrors-his-personality:-reserved,-focused,-and-efficient.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>engineering</strong>-—-knowledge-of-structures,-fortifications,-and-mechanical-systems;-useful-for-both-exploring-ancient-eladran-ruins-and-planning-the-operations-of-his-criminal-network</li>-<li><strong>loremastery</strong>-—-deep-and-broad-scholarly-knowledge-spanning-history,-magic,-culture,-and-the-accumulated-wisdom-of-the-eladran-people;-this-is-venn&#39;s-defining-skill-and-the-foundation-of-his-value-as-a-source-of-information</li>-<li><strong>command</strong>-—-the-ability-to-lead,-organize,-and-direct-subordinates;-essential-for-running-the-argollean-brotherhood&#39;s-operations-across-the-backlands</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">appearance-and-demeanor</h2>-<p>venn-is-<strong>reserved</strong>-and-<strong>scholarly</strong>-—-a-man-who-measures-his-words-carefully-and-reveals-nothing-by-accident.-he-does-not-engage-in-idle-conversation-or-emotional-display.-every-interaction-with-venn-is-a-transaction,-whether-the-currency-is-information,-coin,-or-favor.</p>-<p>he-is-<strong>intensely-focused</strong>,-pursuing-his-goals-with-a-single-mindedness-that-can-make-him-seem-cold-or-distant.-this-focus-is-not-cruelty-—-it-is-the-discipline-of-a-scholar-who-has-spent-decades-honing-his-craft-and-who-does-not-have-time-or-patience-for-distractions.</p>-<p>his-most-notable-physical-feature-is-a-<strong>bone-inlaid-ring</strong>-inscribed-with-<strong>eladran-script</strong>.-this-ring-is-likely-of-ancient-provenance,-possibly-a-badge-of-office-within-the-argollean-brotherhood-or-a-relic-of-the-old-eladran-noble-houses-his-network-is-connected-to.-the-bone-inlay-suggests-a-funerary-or-memorial-function-—-the-ring-may-commemorate-a-fallen-house,-a-dead-mentor,-or-a-lost-homeland.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood\">the-argollean-brotherhood</h2>-<p>venn-leads-the-<strong>argollean-brotherhood</strong>-in-the-backlands,-a-<strong>criminal-network</strong>-with-deep-connections-to-old-[[races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> noble houses. The Brotherhood is not a common street gang — it is an organized, disciplined operation run by an Eladran spellsword with a scholar&#39;s intellect and a commander&#39;s authority.</p>\n<p>The Brotherhood&#39;s connection to <strong>old Eladran noble houses</strong> suggests several things:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Heritage</strong> — The Brotherhood may trace its origins to the fall of Eladran civilization, preserving the interests and assets of noble families that lost their power and influence</li>\n<li><strong>Artifacts</strong> — The old houses likely possessed significant magical artifacts, texts, and treasures that the Brotherhood now seeks to recover, protect, or trade</li>\n<li><strong>Political Ambition</strong> — The connection to noble houses implies the Brotherhood may have political goals beyond mere profit — perhaps the restoration of Eladran influence or the recovery of lost Eladran territories</li>\n<li><strong>Network</strong> — Old noble houses had networks of allies, agents, and contacts that the Brotherhood may still draw upon, giving it reach and resources far beyond what a frontier criminal organization would normally possess</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-the-backlands\">Role in the Backlands</h2>\n<p>Venn occupies a unique position in the Backlands as a <strong>source of lore and artifacts</strong>. In a frontier region where knowledge of the old world is scarce and ancient ruins dot the landscape, Venn&#39;s expertise is invaluable. He can identify artifacts, translate ancient texts, provide historical context for discoveries, and connect seekers with the resources they need.</p>\n<p>However, Venn is <strong>morally gray</strong>. His willingness to deal with anyone — Scalpers, criminals, imperial officials, fellow Eladran — and his leadership of a criminal network mean that every transaction with Venn comes with strings attached. He does not give anything for free, and his favors always come with an expectation of reciprocity.</p>\n<p>This moral ambiguity makes Venn a versatile figure in the Backlands: he can be an ally, a patron, a rival, or an adversary depending on how his interests align with those who seek him out.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eladran Ruins</strong> — Venn&#39;s loremastery and engineering proficiency make him the ideal guide or patron for expeditions into ancient Eladran ruins scattered across the Backlands</li>\n<li><strong>The Bone Ring</strong> — What is the significance of Venn&#39;s bone-inlaid ring? It may be a key to an ancient vault, a badge of a secret order, or a memorial to a tragedy Venn seeks to avenge</li>\n<li><strong>The Noble Houses</strong> — The Argollean Brotherhood&#39;s connection to old Eladran noble houses opens up a web of intrigue, politics, and ancient rivalries that could draw players into a world far beyond the frontier</li>\n<li><strong>Artifact Trade</strong> — Venn is a buyer, seller, and broker of ancient artifacts. Players who discover relics in the field may find Venn their best — or only — option for identification and sale</li>\n<li><strong>Criminal Network</strong> — The Brotherhood&#39;s criminal operations in the Backlands may intersect with other power players in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, creating opportunities for alliance or conflict</li>\n<li><strong>Morally Gray Patron</strong> — Venn makes an excellent patron for adventurers — knowledgeable, well-resourced, and willing to hire outsiders for dangerous work. But his goals are his own, and his agents may find themselves serving purposes they did not anticipate.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province where Venn and the Brotherhood operate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement; a hub of activity in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> — Venn&#39;s race and the cultural heritage of the Argollean Brotherhood</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/great-houses\" class=\"wiki-link\">great-houses</a> — The noble houses of the Empire; the Eladran houses connected to the Brotherhood may have parallels or rivalries here</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic-and-sorcery</a> — The magical traditions Venn practices as a spellsword</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — The Scalper gangs that Venn and the Brotherhood may interact with</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — The ruined city; a potential source of Eladran artifacts</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"bottlecap-juno","title":"Bottlecap Juno","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","barbarian","scalper","the-dregs","unpredictable","wild-card","backlands","bone-creek"],"html":"<h1 id=\"bottlecap-juno\">Bottlecap Juno</h1>\n<p><strong>Bottlecap Juno</strong> is a barbarian warrior and the leader of <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-dregs\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Dregs</a></strong>, one of the Scalper gangs operating in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. Unpredictable, grinning, and possibly mad, Juno is a <strong>wild card faction leader</strong> whose behavior defies easy prediction or manipulation. He leads the Dregs with a chaotic energy that keeps rivals off balance and allies perpetually uncertain.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Barbarian 4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td>—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>AC</strong></td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>HP</strong></td>\n<td>34</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>ATK</strong></td>\n<td>+4 (Great Axe, 1d10+1)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Str</strong></td>\n<td>15</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Juno&#39;s statistics reveal a formidable melee combatant. His 34 hit points — the highest among the Scalper gang leaders — make him exceptionally durable, and his great axe deals devastating 1d10+1 damage per swing. His AC of 3 provides solid protection, likely through a combination of armor and natural toughness. His Strength of 15 supports his barbarian fighting style: direct, powerful, and relentless.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"proficiencies\">Proficiencies</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Berserkergang</strong> — The ability to enter a berserk frenzy in combat, gaining enhanced strength and ferocity at the cost of tactical discipline and self-preservation. When Juno rages, he becomes a whirlwind of destruction that is as dangerous to those nearby as it is to his enemies. This proficiency defines Juno&#39;s fighting style and his personality — a man who lives on the edge of control.</li>\n<li><strong>Intimidation</strong> — The art of frightening and coercing others through force of personality, physical presence, or implied violence. Juno&#39;s unpredictable nature makes his intimidation uniquely effective — people fear what they cannot predict, and Juno is nothing if not unpredictable.</li>\n<li><strong>Survival</strong> — The practical skills needed to endure in the wilderness of the Backlands: finding food and water, building shelter, reading weather, navigating terrain. This proficiency keeps the Dregs alive in the field between hunts.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">Appearance and Demeanor</h2>\n<p>Juno is defined by his <strong>unpredictability</strong>. He shifts between moods with unsettling speed — laughing one moment, deadly serious the next, then laughing again at something no one else finds funny. This volatility is not an act; it is the genuine expression of a mind that does not operate within normal boundaries.</p>\n<p>He is always <strong>grinning</strong> — a wide, unsettling smile that rarely leaves his face, even in combat, even in danger, even in moments where any sane person would show fear. The grin is a mask of madness, a signal to everyone around him that Juno plays by different rules.</p>\n<p>Juno is <strong>possibly mad</strong>. The Scalper saying — <em>&quot;The Bounty takes its toll&quot;</em> — may find its truest expression in Juno, who seems to have crossed a threshold from which there is no return. Whether his madness was caused by the horrors of beastman hunting, was always present, or stems from some other source is unclear. What is clear is that it makes him extraordinarily dangerous.</p>\n<p>His most notable physical feature is a <strong>necklace of bent coins</strong> — bottlecaps, bent marks, and crushed currency strung together as a trophy necklace. The origin of this affectation, and whether it is the source of his name, is unclear. Each bent coin may represent a kill, a victory, or simply something that amused Juno in the moment.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-dregs\">The Dregs</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-dregs\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Dregs</a></strong> are a Scalper gang that reflects their leader&#39;s chaotic nature. Where the <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#skin-eaters\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters</a> are brutally efficient and the <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-bleak-sons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bleak Sons</a> are zealously disciplined, the Dregs are <strong>wild and unpredictable</strong> — a loose collection of fighters bound together by Juno&#39;s force of personality rather than any formal structure or ideology.</p>\n<p>The Dregs represent the <strong>wild card faction</strong> in Backlands politics. They cannot be easily bought, threatened, or reasoned with, because their leader operates on instinct and impulse rather than rational calculation. This makes them unreliable allies and terrifying enemies — but also potentially useful to anyone clever enough to point Juno&#39;s chaos in the right direction.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Wild Card</strong> — Juno&#39;s unpredictability makes him a volatile element in any conflict. Convincing him to support one side or another could tip the balance of power in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> — but controlling him is another matter entirely.</li>\n<li><strong>The Bent Coins</strong> — What is the significance of Juno&#39;s necklace? Each coin may have a story, and the necklace itself may be more than a simple trophy.</li>\n<li><strong>Berserkergang</strong> — Juno&#39;s berserk frenzy is his greatest weapon and his greatest vulnerability. In a rage, he is devastating but uncontrollable — a threat to everyone in his vicinity, friend and foe alike.</li>\n<li><strong>Madness or Method</strong> — Is Juno truly mad, or is his apparent insanity a carefully cultivated persona designed to keep his enemies off balance? The answer changes everything about how to deal with him.</li>\n<li><strong>The Dregs&#39; Loyalty</strong> — What holds the Dregs together? If Juno were killed or incapacitated, would the gang splinter, rally around a new leader, or descend into chaos?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-dregs\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Dregs</a> — Juno&#39;s gang</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures the Dregs hunt</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/skinner\" class=\"wiki-link\">skinner</a> — Leader of the rival Skin Eaters</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/marcos-varanes\" class=\"wiki-link\">marcos-varanes</a> — Leader of the Bleak Sons; a contrasting figure of zealous discipline</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"brother-marco","title":"Brother Marco","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","bone-creek","priest","seros","house-of-silence","faith","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"brother-marco\">Brother Marco</h1>\n<p><strong>Brother Marco</strong> is a young priest of <strong><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></strong> who serves at the <strong>House of Silence</strong>, the church of Seros in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>. He took over the church after the previous priest, <strong>Father Draven</strong>, succumbed to disease.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"arrival-in-bone-creek\">Arrival in Bone Creek</h2>\n<p>Brother Marco claims to have received a <strong>vision from <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a></strong> — a divine calling that compelled him to journey to the distant frontier outpost of Bone Creek. He made the <strong>long trek alone</strong>, a remarkable feat given the dangers of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. When he arrived, he was <strong>malnourished and wounded</strong>, bearing the marks of a harrowing journey.</p>\n<p>Despite his battered condition, Marco&#39;s conviction was unshaken. He immediately took over the House of Silence and began ministering to the people of Bone Creek.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"ministry\">Ministry</h2>\n<p>Marco&#39;s ministry has been unexpectedly successful in a settlement as godless and violent as Bone Creek. His <strong>weekly service</strong> now draws enough attendees that <strong>many must stand</strong>, spending hours in silent prayer in accordance with the rites of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>.</p>\n<p>In a place where men bear the marks of corruption openly, where the Bounty takes its toll on body and soul alike, Marco&#39;s quiet devotion has struck a deep chord. Whether this is genuine spiritual hunger among the Scalpers or something else entirely remains to be seen.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"predecessor-father-draven\">Predecessor: Father Draven</h2>\n<p>Marco&#39;s predecessor, <strong>Father Draven</strong>, was a far cry from the pious young priest who replaced him. Draven was known as a drunkard and eventually succumbed to disease. Before his death, he offered one of the most memorable descriptions of the Backlands:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;There is no soil out here, only the ash of Empires. The trees breathe rot and the water tastes of the dead. I seen it, I seen what waits beneath the ground. This land is not cursed — no, no, no — it remembers. Every war, every broken oath, every forgotten god — it sings them back into the marrow of the earth. That&#39;s why we can&#39;t leave. We&#39;re not stuck. We&#39;ve been claimed.&quot;</em>\n— <strong>Father Draven</strong>, drunken priest</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Marco is described as <strong>young</strong> — a stark contrast to the hardened veterans, criminals, and desperate fortune-seekers who populate Bone Creek. His willingness to trek alone through the dangerous Backlands on nothing more than a vision speaks to either extraordinary faith, extraordinary foolishness, or both. His arrival malnourished and wounded suggests the journey nearly killed him, yet he persevered.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The settlement where Marco ministers</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> — The god Marco serves</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province Marco journeyed through</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"cassian-varro","title":"Cassian Varro","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","bone-creek","red-river-consortium","merchant","lord-merchant","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"cassian-varro\">Cassian Varro</h1>\n<p><strong>Cassian Varro</strong> is the <strong>Lord Merchant</strong> of the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium&#39;s</a> <strong>Red River Exchange</strong> in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> — the largest building in town and the economic heart of the settlement. A polished and shrewd businessman, Varro is deeply involved in the local economy and political dealings of Bone Creek.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role\">Role</h2>\n<p>As Lord Merchant, Varro oversees the operations of the Red River Exchange, which serves two critical functions in Bone Creek:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Loot and Treasure Sales</strong> — Scalpers sell their plundered loot and treasure to the Exchange&#39;s merchants, who are shrewd negotiators.</li>\n<li><strong>Beastman Scalp Redemption</strong> — The Exchange is where <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastman</a> scalps are sold in exchange for the Imperial Bounty, minus a <strong>transaction fee</strong> that the Consortium takes as profit.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The Exchange employs an <strong>army of hardened guardsmen and bodyguards</strong>, making it both the most secure and most imposing building in Bone Creek.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"alliances\">Alliances</h2>\n<p>Varro is a <strong>close ally</strong> of <strong><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a></strong>, proprietor of Double Sevens. Together, they represent the most powerful political and economic bloc in Bone Creek — one oriented toward commerce, development, and the gradual civilization of the frontier settlement. The Varro-Watts alliance stands in contrast to the rough, lawless influence of <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a> and his network.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Varro is described as <strong>polished and shrewd</strong> — a businessman first and foremost, but one who understands that in a place like Bone Creek, politics and economics are inseparable. His deep involvement in local dealings suggests he is not merely a Consortium functionary following orders from distant superiors, but an active player shaping the settlement&#39;s future.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"criminal-enterprise-secret-gm-only\">Criminal Enterprise (SECRET — GM ONLY)</h2>\n<p>Beneath the polished exterior of a legitimate merchant, Cassian Varro operates a <strong>sophisticated criminal enterprise</strong> that undermines the very bounty economy he publicly administers. This is not petty corruption -- it is a calculated, multi-layered operation:</p>\n<h3 id=\"bandit-operations-fort-ikenvar\">Bandit Operations — Fort Ikenvar</h3>\n<p>Varro <strong>funds a bandit operation out of <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a></strong>. The ruined marsh fort -- formerly <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook&#39;s</a> base of operations before the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> destroyed him -- is now being used as a base for Varro&#39;s criminal activities. This means Varro is actively destabilizing the trade routes and frontier settlements that his legitimate business depends on, profiting from both sides of the equation.</p>\n<h3 id=\"beastman-trafficking-malyn-and-the-withered-craw\">Beastman Trafficking — Malyn and the Withered Craw</h3>\n<p>Varro uses <strong><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn the Misshapen</a></strong> to <strong>traffic enslaved <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a></strong> to buyers in <strong><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a></strong>. Rather than killing beastmen for scalps as the bounty system intends, Varro&#39;s operation captures them alive and sells them as slaves. Malyn -- an exiled Mage 7 who already enslaves beastmen through sorcery -- and his gang, the <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Withered Craw</a>, serve as the operational arm of this trafficking pipeline.</p>\n<p>This is a critical revelation about the nature of the Withered Craw: they are not a conventional Scalper gang. They are a slaving operation, and Varro is their patron.</p>\n<h3 id=\"fraudulent-scalp-manufacturing\">Fraudulent Scalp Manufacturing</h3>\n<p>Varro has <strong>arrangements with at least one <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper gang</a> to manufacture scalps without the inconvenience of a hunt</strong>. This means scalps are being produced and redeemed at the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Exchange</a> that do not represent actual beastman kills. The Imperial Bounty is being defrauded.</p>\n<p>The implications are severe:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The bounty numbers reported to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empire</a> are inflated</li>\n<li>The actual beastman threat is not being reduced as the scalp counts suggest</li>\n<li>Imperial funds are being siphoned through fraudulent redemptions</li>\n<li>Varro profits from the transaction fees on scalps he knows are fake</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"strategic-implications\">Strategic Implications</h3>\n<p>Varro&#39;s criminal enterprise means that the <strong>most powerful economic figure in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a></strong> is actively:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Funding banditry that destabilizes the region</li>\n<li>Running a slave trade in the very creatures the bounty system is designed to eliminate</li>\n<li>Defrauding the Imperial Bounty that funds the settlement&#39;s existence</li>\n<li>Using his legitimate position at the Exchange to launder the proceeds</li>\n</ol>\n<p>His alliance with <strong><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a></strong> takes on a darker cast in this light -- does Watts know? Is he complicit, or is he being used as a respectable front?</p>\n<p>The contrast with <strong><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr&#39;s</a></strong> petty rackets is stark. Marr runs card games and a protection scheme. Varro runs a regional criminal enterprise that touches banditry, slavery, and fraud at an institutional level.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> — The trading consortium Varro represents</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The settlement where Varro operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">tolliver-watts</a> — Varro&#39;s close ally and proprietor of Double Sevens</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> — The rival power in Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures whose scalps fuel the Exchange&#39;s business</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> — Ruined fort where Varro funds bandit operations</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</a> — Varro&#39;s agent for beastman trafficking</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — At least one gang manufactures scalps for Varro</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> — Destination for Varro&#39;s enslaved beastman trafficking</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"castellan-thibaud","title":"Castellan Thibaud","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","criminal","laced-hand","thief","sanctuary","underworld"],"html":"<h1 id=\"castellan-thibaud\">Castellan Thibaud</h1>\n<p><strong>Castellan Thibaud</strong> is the boss of the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a>, the dominant criminal syndicate in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. At age 52, he has spent over 30 years rising through the organization&#39;s ranks to become its undisputed leader. Intelligent, cautious, and remarkably well-read for a criminal boss, Thibaud runs the Laced Hand less like a gang and more like a corporation -- focused on profit, stability, and the long-term viability of his enterprise.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Thibaud (the &quot;Castellan&quot; is a title, not a name)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>52</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Master Thief 7</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Affiliation</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Laced Hand</span> over the course of three decades -- a remarkable feat in an organization where ambition typically outpaces lifespan. His survival and ascent owe less to violence (though he is capable of it) than to intelligence, patience, and an instinct for reading people and situations that borders on the preternatural.</p>\n<p>He operates from multiple hideouts throughout <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and is rarely seen in public. His anonymity is both a security measure and a management tool -- the less visible the boss, the more difficult he is to target, and the more his reputation grows in the telling.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Thibaud is more like a <strong>crime CEO</strong> than a traditional gang leader. He is:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Intelligent</strong> -- His strategic thinking rivals that of the political operators in the Governor&#39;s administration. He understands markets, logistics, human psychology, and the subtle dynamics of power.</li>\n<li><strong>Cautious</strong> -- He does not take unnecessary risks, does not make impulsive decisions, and does not allow emotion to drive policy. Every significant action by the Laced Hand is calculated for its impact on the organization&#39;s long-term interests.</li>\n<li><strong>Remarkably well-read</strong> -- An unusual trait for a criminal boss. Thibaud reads widely -- history, philosophy, political theory -- and applies what he learns to the management of his organization. He is capable of quoting imperial historians and making the quotation relevant to the discussion at hand.</li>\n<li><strong>Focused on profit and stability</strong> -- Thibaud&#39;s primary goals are the continued profitability and operational stability of the Laced Hand. He is not interested in revolution, ideology, or personal glory. He wants the organization to thrive, and he understands that thriving requires a stable environment in which to operate.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-arrangement-with-the-governor\">The Arrangement with the Governor</h2>\n<p>Thibaud maintains a <strong>tacit arrangement</strong> with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a>. The arrangement is transactional:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Laced Hand provides intelligence from the docks, subtle removal of inconvenient individuals, and a criminal safety valve that keeps the underworld organized rather than chaotic</li>\n<li>In exchange, the Governor does not interfere with Laced Hand operations</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Thibaud understands that this arrangement exists at Drussus&#39;s pleasure and can be revoked at any time. He is therefore careful to remain useful without becoming threatening -- a balance that requires constant attention and occasional sacrifice.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a> -- the organization he leads</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- the power he accommodates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city where he operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"claudius-decimus","title":"Claudius Decimus","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["historical","emperor","house-decimus","war-of-three-emperors","dynasty-founder","scholar-emperor"],"html":"<h1 id=\"claudius-decimus\">Claudius Decimus</h1>\n<p><strong>Claudius Decimus</strong> emerged victorious from the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> (270 IY) and founded the <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Decimus dynasty</a> that rules the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> to this day. He is one of the most paradoxical figures in Imperial history -- a man who triumphed in a brutal civil war yet is remembered as one of the most courageous and principled leaders the Empire has ever known.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;We traded madness for cowardice, then cowardice for coin. Of all our emperors, it was the one who ruled for 87 days who showed the greatest strength.&quot;</em>\n-- <strong>Claudius Decimus</strong>, on accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Claudius Decimus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>Imperator; founder of the Decimus dynasty</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>House</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Aurex</span> of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>, the Empire plunged into chaos. With no clear heir, generals and governors vied for the throne. The scholar-emperor <strong>Numerius</strong> was briefly installed -- a principled and learned man who attempted to restore order through reason and law. Numerius ruled for only 87 days before he was murdered, his brief reign a testament to the Empire&#39;s inability to sustain the qualities it most needed in its leaders.</p>\n<p>The civil war that followed Numerius&#39;s death was devastating. Multiple claimants raised armies, alliances shifted and collapsed, and the Empire tore itself apart in a contest of ambition and violence. From this crucible, Claudius Decimus emerged triumphant -- not through superior bloodline or political connections, but through military competence, strategic patience, and a ruthlessness tempered by genuine principle.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character-and-legacy\">Character and Legacy</h2>\n<p>Claudius Decimus&#39;s own words upon accepting the title of Imperator reveal a man acutely aware of the Empire&#39;s long decline. His reference to the Emperor who &quot;ruled for 87 days&quot; -- Numerius -- is a tribute to the scholar-emperor&#39;s courage and a tacit admission that the system that produced Claudius Decimus as victor was the same system that murdered the only genuinely good man to hold the throne.</p>\n<p>The trajectory Claudius described -- from madness (<a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aurex</a> and <a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Eater</a>) to cowardice (<a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Antonius</a> and his successors) to the naked pursuit of wealth and power -- was not merely rhetoric. It was a diagnosis of the Empire&#39;s fundamental sickness, delivered by the man who had just fought his way through its most violent symptom.</p>\n<p>What Claudius Decimus accomplished in his own reign, and the circumstances of his eventual removal from power, remain subjects of intense historical debate. His founding of the Decimus dynasty established a new ruling house, but the question that haunts his legacy is whether the dynasty he created has been any better than the one it replaced.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-decimus-dynasty\">The Decimus Dynasty</h2>\n<p>The dynasty Claudius founded has held the Imperial throne without interruption from 270 IY to the present day. The current Emperor, <a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Justinian Claudius Decimus</a>, bears his ancestor&#39;s name and rules from <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>. Whether the Decimus line has fulfilled Claudius&#39;s implicit promise -- to be better than what came before -- is a matter of perspective and politics.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> -- the dynasty he founded</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> -- the civil war he won</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a> -- the mad Emperor whose death triggered the crisis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/justinian-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</a> -- current Emperor and descendant</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> -- the dynasty he replaced</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"colonel-vex","title":"Colonel Marcian Vex","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","military","fighter","drussine-guard","sanctuary","house-drussus"],"html":"<h1 id=\"colonel-marcian-vex\">Colonel Marcian Vex</h1>\n<p><strong>Colonel Marcian Vex</strong> is the commander of the <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a>, the personal army of <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. A grim and efficient officer, Vex handles the day-to-day military operations of the Guard and is loyal to the Governor personally -- not to the city, not to the province, and not to the Emperor.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Marcian Vex</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Rank</strong></td>\n<td>Colonel</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Fighter 9</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Affiliation</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Drussine Guard</span>. While <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> sets strategy and makes political decisions, it is Vex who translates those decisions into military reality. He manages training, deployment, discipline, logistics, and the thousand daily details that keep a force of 2,000 soldiers functioning as a cohesive military unit.</p>\n<p>His competence is beyond question. The Drussine Guard is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, and Vex&#39;s hand is visible in every aspect of its operation -- from the quality of its equipment to the precision of its drill to the speed of its response to threats.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Vex is <strong>grim and efficient</strong> -- a man who wastes no words, tolerates no excuses, and measures people by their usefulness. He is not cruel, but he is entirely without sentiment. He does not inspire loyalty through charisma or warmth; he inspires it through competence and the knowledge that under his command, the Guard functions like a machine.</p>\n<p>His personal loyalty to <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> is absolute. This is not the loyalty of a subordinate who follows orders because he must, but the loyalty of a man who has chosen his commander and committed to that choice without reservation. Whether this loyalty stems from shared history, personal obligation, ideological alignment, or simple recognition that Drussus is the most competent leader available is not clear -- and Vex is not the kind of man who explains his motivations.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a></strong> -- His commander and the object of his absolute loyalty. Vex serves as the Governor&#39;s military right hand.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Drussine Guard</a></strong> -- The force he commands and has shaped into the premier military unit in the province.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a></strong> -- The other significant military authority in the Backlands. Vex&#39;s relationship with Marcellus is defined by the Governor&#39;s policy of strategic containment.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- his commander</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Drussine Guard</a> -- the force he commands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a> -- the Great House he serves</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city where he is stationed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"crackback","title":"Crackback","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","thief","mornish","targ","bone-creek","pretty-peach","thaddeus-marr","enforcer","pimp","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"crackback\">Crackback</h1>\n<p><strong>Crackback</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">targ</a> Thief (level 2) of <a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mornish</a> extraction who serves as the pimp at <strong>The Pretty Peach</strong> in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, working directly under <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a>. He is a crude, opportunistic enforcer and gossip source -- the kind of man who thrives in frontier squalor.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Crackback</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Thaddeus Marr&#39;s</span> operation:</p>\n<h3 id=\"enforcer\">Enforcer</h3>\n<p>He keeps order at The Pretty Peach through intimidation and, when necessary, violence. In a town full of Scalpers, brawlers, and frontier desperadoes, this requires a certain baseline of menace that Crackback possesses in abundance.</p>\n<h3 id=\"gossip-source\">Gossip Source</h3>\n<p>Crackback&#39;s position as pimp gives him access to the intimate secrets and drunken confessions of Bone Creek&#39;s population. Men talk freely to working girls, and working girls talk to their pimp. This makes Crackback a valuable intelligence asset for Marr&#39;s racket -- a stream of information gathered through proximity to vulnerability.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> -- Crackback&#39;s boss, proprietor of The Pretty Peach</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The frontier outpost where Crackback operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">targ</a> -- Crackback&#39;s race, former slaves magically created</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">mornish</a> -- Cultural background</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"doc-quinten","title":"Doc Quinten","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","explorer","kolani","bone-creek","surgeon","neutral","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"doc-quinten\">Doc Quinten</h1>\n<p><strong>Doc Quinten</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> Explorer (level 3) who serves as <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek&#39;s</a> barber-surgeon. Everyone calls him &quot;Doc&quot; despite his lack of formal medical credentials. He ran field surgery for <strong>three separate armies</strong> during his career before washing up on the frontier, and his hands are steady enough that no one cares about credentials.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Doc Quinten</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Scalper gangs</span>, <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr&#39;s</a> operation, <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro&#39;s</a> <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> interests, <a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw&#39;s</a> <a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">Congregation</a>, <a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn&#39;s</a> hidden network -- all of them need a surgeon, and none of them are willing to jeopardize the only competent one in town by dragging him into their feuds.</p>\n<p>This neutrality makes Doc Quinten one of the few truly safe people to talk to in Bone Creek. He will not betray a confidence -- not out of moral principle, but because doing so would compromise his neutrality and, therefore, his survival.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<p>Doc Quinten&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> heritage and Explorer training mark him as a man of the frontier and the wilderness, not the city. The <a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">kolani</a> are plains and forest tribes who fought the <a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dog Soldier War</a> against the Empire -- a guerrilla campaign of legendary ferocity. Doc&#39;s service as field surgeon to three separate armies likely included time on both sides of various Kolani conflicts, which explains both his skill and his absolute refusal to take sides.</p>\n<p>His Beast Lore specialization in dogs is notable -- in a frontier where tracking, hunting, and survival matter, a man who understands dogs understands the frontier.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The frontier outpost where Doc Quinten practices</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">kolani</a> -- His people, plains and forest tribes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/dog-soldier-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">dog-soldier-war</a> -- The Kolani guerrilla war, possibly part of his military background</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The gangs whose members he patches up without prejudice</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"elder-sarnath","title":"Elder Sarnath","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","avari","elder","sanctuary","ashward","community-leader","refugee","crossings"],"html":"<h1 id=\"elder-sarnath\">Elder Sarnath</h1>\n<p><strong>Sarnath of the Crossings</strong> (age 71) is a former merchant and the community elder of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> population in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>&#39;s Ashward district. Wise and diplomatic, Sarnath has devoted his later years to ensuring the survival and dignity of his people in a city that tolerates them but does not embrace them. He is not powerful in the conventional sense -- he commands no soldiers, controls no wealth, and holds no title. But he is respected, and in the precarious world of the Ashward, respect is the currency that matters most.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Sarnath of the Crossings</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>71</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Role</strong></td>\n<td>Community elder</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Crossings</span>, the settlement destroyed in the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> (377 IY). Whether he was present during the sacking or had already departed before the beastman horde arrived is not widely known. What is known is that the destruction of Crossings and the burning of the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at Thornasse by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> are wounds that define the Avari community&#39;s identity -- and Sarnath carries both.</p>\n<p>Before becoming a community leader, Sarnath was a merchant. His commercial experience gave him an understanding of how power works in practical terms -- contracts, obligations, favors, relationships. He has applied this understanding to the task of keeping the Avari community alive in a city where they are marginalized, distrusted, and largely powerless.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-the-ashward\">Role in the Ashward</h2>\n<p>The Ashward is the poorest district of <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, home to refugees, displaced peoples, and communities that exist at the margins of the city&#39;s economic and political life. The Avari community within the Ashward looks to Sarnath for guidance -- not because he holds any formal authority, but because he has earned trust through decades of steady, patient work on their behalf.</p>\n<p>Sarnath&#39;s approach is focused on two priorities:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Survival</strong> -- Ensuring the Avari community has access to food, shelter, and the basic necessities of life in a city that does not prioritize their welfare</li>\n<li><strong>Dignity</strong> -- Preserving the Avari identity, traditions, and sense of self-worth in the face of marginalization and the lingering trauma of the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a>&#39;s destruction</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<p>Sarnath has cultivated relationships with various city factions -- not from a position of power but from a position of usefulness and trust:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a></strong> -- Sarnath is not a political player, but he is aware that the Governor&#39;s tolerance of the Ashward depends on the district remaining quiet and manageable</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Thousand Temples</a></strong> -- The Avari&#39;s relationship with the dominant faith is complex, given the cultural wounds inflicted by Imperial religious institutions</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a></strong> -- Sarnath&#39;s merchant background gives him some connection to the commercial world, though the Avari community&#39;s economic resources are minimal</li>\n<li><strong>Other community leaders</strong> -- Sarnath&#39;s diplomacy extends to the non-Avari populations of the Ashward, where cooperation between marginalized groups is essential for survival</li>\n</ul>\n<p>He is not powerful, but he is <strong>respected</strong> -- a distinction that, in the Ashward, carries its own weight.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city where he lives</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- the town associated with his name</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> -- the event that devastated the Avari</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Erenthis</a> -- the Avari tradition destroyed by the Empire</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> -- the sorcerer who burned the Erenthis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures\" class=\"wiki-link\">Races and Cultures of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"emperor-aurex","title":"Emperor Aurex","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["historical","emperor","house-valerian","mad-emperor","assassination","war-of-three-emperors"],"html":"<h1 id=\"emperor-aurex\">Emperor Aurex</h1>\n<p><strong>Emperor Aurex</strong> was the last Emperor of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> to sit upon the Imperial throne. His reign was defined by madness and cruelty that brought the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> to the brink of collapse. Aurex was assassinated by his own sister -- an act of desperate necessity that left no heir and ended the Valerian dynasty&#39;s hold on power forever. His death triggered the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> (270 IY), the brutal civil war from which <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> emerged victorious, founding the <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Decimus dynasty</a> that rules to this day.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Aurex (of House Valerian)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>Emperor of the <span class=\"dead-link\">Decimus dynasty</span> to paint the Emperor they replaced in the darkest possible terms. What is beyond dispute is that Aurex&#39;s rule was disastrous for the Empire and that his removal was regarded as necessary by virtually everyone who survived it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-assassination\">The Assassination</h2>\n<p>Aurex was killed by his own sister. The precise circumstances of the assassination -- whether it was a spontaneous act of desperation or the culmination of a carefully planned conspiracy -- are not fully known. What is known is that Aurex died without naming an heir, and his sister either could not or would not claim the throne in her own right.</p>\n<p>The absence of a clear successor plunged the Empire into chaos. The resulting power vacuum drew in generals, governors, and ambitious nobles, each claiming legitimacy and marshaling forces. The scholar <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Numerius</a> was briefly installed as Emperor -- only to be murdered within 87 days. The ensuing civil war, known as the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a>, was the most devastating internal conflict the Empire had experienced since its founding.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>Aurex&#39;s legacy is one of destruction and cautionary example. His reign is cited by historians as proof that the concentration of absolute power in a single individual -- without adequate checks or mechanisms for removal -- makes the Empire vulnerable to catastrophic failure when that individual proves unfit. The Valerian dynasty, which had held power for centuries, was destroyed in a generation by a single ruler&#39;s madness.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a>, upon accepting the title of Imperator, spoke directly to the trajectory that Aurex represented: a decline from madness to cowardice to naked greed that had corroded the Empire&#39;s foundations.</p>\n<p>Aurex also serves as a defining wound in the identity of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a>. The house retains its ancient prestige and its wealth, but the stain of Aurex&#39;s reign -- the madness, the cruelty, the inglorious end -- hangs over every Valerian ambition. Whether the house can ever truly escape this legacy is an open question.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> -- the dynasty that ended with Aurex</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> -- the civil war his death triggered</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> -- the Emperor who emerged from the chaos</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> -- the dynasty that replaced the Valerians</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"eolande","title":"Eolande, the Eladran General","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["eladra","first-empire","black-tree","crossings","ancient","argollean-empire","great-teacher","thornasse","sword","dryad","womb-curse"],"html":"<h1 id=\"eolande-the-eladran-general\">Eolande, the Eladran General</h1>\n<p><strong>Eolande</strong> is an ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> general from approximately 3000 BE -- over five thousand years before the current campaign date of 380 IY. He was tutored personally by the <strong>Great Teacher</strong> in matters of strategy, sorcery, and statecraft, and led the military campaigns that transformed the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> city-states into a true empire. His conquests marked the first systematic subjugation of humans by the Eladra, extending the reach of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition alongside the boundaries of Eladran power.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>still present</strong> at the Black Tree -- the scorched <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> stump at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a>, near <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> encountered him there. An Eladran general from 3000 BE, still alive and present over five millennia later, is an event of staggering historical and metaphysical significance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Eolande</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">History of Mithrapos</span>. Tutored personally by the Great Teacher -- the enigmatic figure who transformed Eladran culture from scholarship and cooperation into ambition, domination, and the pursuit of power -- Eolande began a campaign of territorial expansion that brought vast human populations under Eladran control.</p>\n<p>His military campaigns were not merely territorial. They were theological, extending the reach of the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition alongside the boundaries of Eladran power. The conquests established the political framework that would become the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> -- the great pre-human civilization whose ruins now litter the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> and whose buried cities, including the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> beneath <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, remain among the most significant archaeological and sorcerous sites in the known world.</p>\n<p>Eolande&#39;s era predates the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> (663 BE), the rise of <a href=\"#/page/marcus-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcus Valerian</a> and the founding of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, and the entire recorded history of human civilization as the Mithrian world understands it. He is a figure from the deep past -- from the age when the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a> ruled and humans were subjects.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-black-tree-encounter\">The Black Tree Encounter</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-reclaimers-meet-eolande-380-iy\">The Reclaimers Meet Eolande (380 IY)</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> encountered Eolande at the Black Tree -- the scorched stump of the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thornasse</a>. The Erenthis was one of the great living monuments of the Eladran civilization, burned by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> in an act of destruction whose consequences still ripple through the Backlands. The Black Tree endures as a dead stump, charred and massive, at the site where the living tree once stood.</p>\n<p>That Eolande is present at this site -- alive, or in some state resembling life -- after more than five thousand years raises questions of extraordinary magnitude.</p>\n<h3 id=\"malachors-interrogation\">Malachor&#39;s Interrogation</h3>\n<p>When <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> learned of the encounter through garrison talk, he approached the Reclaimers with barely-composed urgency. His questions reveal the scope of what the party witnessed and the details that remain unclear:</p>\n<p><strong>On Eolande&#39;s state of mind:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>What language did Eolande speak? Did he understand Mithrian, or only the old tongue? -- This question probes whether Eolande has had any contact with the post-imperial world or whether he exists in a bubble of deep antiquity, speaking only the Eladran language of five millennia past.</li>\n<li>How coherent was he? Did he seem aware of time passing? Does he know the First Empire has fallen? -- The question of temporal awareness is critical. An Eladran general who does not know his empire fell is a man preserved in amber. One who does know is something far stranger -- a being who has watched five thousand years of history unfold from the foot of a dead tree.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>On what Eolande revealed:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>What did he say about the Womb Curse? -- The &quot;Womb Curse&quot; is referenced in connection with the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora&#39;s</a> barrenness or possibly the broader <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> disappearance. That Eolande spoke of it suggests he has knowledge of the catastrophe that ended Eladran fertility and doomed the race to extinction -- knowledge that predates any surviving written record.</li>\n<li>What did he say about the Eladra? -- Any testimony from a living witness of the Eladran civilization at its height is of incalculable scholarly value. The Eladra are gone. Their cities are ruins. Their language is dead. Eolande may be the last primary source in existence.</li>\n<li>What did he say about <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a>? -- That Eolande mentioned the Slaughterprince by name connects the ancient Eladran general to the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> theological framework. Bel&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/bel-earth-hunger\" class=\"wiki-link\">earth-hunger</a> cult is active in modern <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>. Whatever Eolande knows about Bel predates the Empyrean faith entirely.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>On the sword:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The sword. Every detail. Does it bear any inscription? -- There is a sword associated with Eolande or found at the Black Tree. Malachor&#39;s intensity about this object suggests it may be an artifact of First Empire provenance -- possibly a weapon carried by Eolande himself during the conquests, which would make it over five thousand years old and of immense sorcerous, historical, and monetary value.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>On the dryad and the tree:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Is the tree alive? Is she bound to the dead wood, or to something that remains in it? -- There is a dryad associated with the Black Tree. The Erenthis was a living monument -- a creation of Eladran sorcery that bridged the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a> and served as a conduit of power. That a dryad persists at the site of the scorched stump suggests the Erenthis is not entirely dead, or that something within it -- some residue of the original sorcery, some fragment of the living tree -- still sustains a bound spirit. The dryad&#39;s relationship to the dead wood is a question of metaphysical importance: is she a ghost of what the tree was, or a guardian of what it still contains?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"significance\">Significance</h2>\n<p>Eolande&#39;s survival -- or persistence, or whatever state describes a five-thousand-year-old Eladran general standing at the foot of a burned tree -- is the most significant discovery the Reclaimers have made. <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> recognizes this immediately. His questions are not idle scholarship. They are the questions of a man who understands that a living witness to the Eladran civilization changes the entire calculus of imperial history, Academy research, and the theological understanding of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition, and the fall of the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>.</p>\n<p>Malachor&#39;s response to the encounter was to write the most significant dispatch of his career -- a report to his secret third-party contact, the unnamed buyer who has been receiving copies of his academic reports for years. Whatever that contact represents, they now know about Eolande. Malachor sent the dispatch before fully considering what he had set in motion.</p>\n<h3 id=\"malachors-proposed-expedition\">Malachor&#39;s Proposed Expedition</h3>\n<p>Malachor is already planning a return expedition to the Black Tree. His proposed party: two <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> assistants he intends to summon to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, himself, and the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> as escort into <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. He presents this as something to finalize after the party returns from Sanctuary. He will push on every subsequent encounter.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"unresolved-questions\">Unresolved Questions</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What state is Eolande in?</strong> Alive in the biological sense? Preserved by sorcery? Sustained by the Erenthis remnant? A revenant? Something else entirely?</li>\n<li><strong>What language does he speak?</strong> If only the old Eladran tongue, communication is limited. If he understands Mithrian, that implies contact with the post-imperial world.</li>\n<li><strong>What does he know about the Womb Curse?</strong> This may be the single most important piece of information he possesses -- the cause of the Eladran race&#39;s extinction.</li>\n<li><strong>What is the sword?</strong> An artifact of the conquests? A weapon of the Great Teacher? Something else?</li>\n<li><strong>What is the dryad&#39;s nature?</strong> Bound to dead wood or to a living remnant? Guardian or prisoner?</li>\n<li><strong>Who is Malachor&#39;s third-party contact?</strong> And what will they do with the knowledge of Eolande&#39;s existence?</li>\n<li><strong>What did Eolande say about Bel?</strong> Any pre-Empyrean testimony about a Cthonic deity could reshape theological understanding.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- Eolande&#39;s race, the ancient builders of Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-empire</a> -- The empire Eolande&#39;s conquests helped create</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> -- Site of the Black Tree where Eolande was found</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- The living Eladran monuments, one of which stood at Thornasse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city near the Black Tree</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- The Academy historian desperate for details about Eolande</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party that encountered Eolande</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">history-of-mithrapos</a> -- The historical timeline documenting Eolande&#39;s conquests</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">high-mage-cynar</a> -- Burned the Erenthis at Thornasse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> -- The corrupted Eladra, possibly connected to the Womb Curse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">bel</a> -- The Cthonic deity Eolande spoke of</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> -- The theological tradition Eolande&#39;s conquests spread</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-nethercity</a> -- Eladran ruins beneath Crossings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution that will covet Eolande&#39;s testimony</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history recording the encounter</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"ezekiel-shaw","title":"Ezekiel Shaw","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","cleric","mithrian","preacher","fanatical","congregation-of-the-hollow-sun","bone-creek","backlands","long-term-threat","prophet"],"html":"<h1 id=\"ezekiel-shaw\">Ezekiel Shaw</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;Mysterious preacher who speaks of divine trials and hidden light. Some call him a prophet. Others call him mad.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Ezekiel Shaw</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> cleric of the sixth circle and the charismatic leader of the <strong><a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">Congregation of the Hollow Sun</a></strong>, a secretive religious group operating in the <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> area of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. Shaw is a figure of contradiction — radiating warmth and sincerity while harboring fanaticism that borders on madness. He speaks of <strong>divine trials</strong> and <strong>hidden light</strong>, drawing followers with his magnetic presence and unsettling conviction.</p>\n<p>Shaw is identified as a <strong>long-term threat</strong> — not an immediate antagonist, but a slowly building danger whose true intentions and the full scope of his Congregation&#39;s activities may not become apparent until it is too late.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Cleric 6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>2</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>30</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+3-(mace,-1d6+1)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>wis</strong></td>-<td>16</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>shaw&#39;s-statistics-reveal-a-dangerous-combatant-as-well-as-a-spiritual-leader.-his-ac-of-2-indicates-heavy-armor-—-likely-plate-or-splint-mail-—-marking-him-as-someone-prepared-for-violence-despite-his-role-as-a-preacher.-his-30-hit-points-and-+3-attack-bonus-make-him-a-formidable-physical-threat,-and-his-wisdom-of-16-reflects-a-powerful-connection-to-whatever-divine-(or-profane)-source-empowers-his-magic.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"spells\">spells</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>bless</strong>-—-bolstering-the-faithful;-strengthening-his-followers-in-body-and-spirit,-reinforcing-their-devotion-through-tangible-divine-favor</li>-<li><strong>hold-person</strong>-—-paralyzing-the-unfaithful-or-those-who-oppose-him;-a-spell-of-control-and-subjugation-that-reveals-shaw&#39;s-willingness-to-impose-his-will-by-force</li>-<li><strong>cure-disease</strong>-—-healing-the-sick;-a-powerful-tool-for-building-a-following-among-the-desperate-and-suffering-people-of-the-backlands,-where-disease-is-rampant-and-healers-are-scarce</li>-</ul>-<p>shaw&#39;s-spell-selection-paints-a-picture-of-a-man-who-<strong>rewards-loyalty</strong>-(bless,-cure-disease)-and-<strong>punishes-defiance</strong>-(hold-person).-his-ability-to-cure-disease-alone-would-make-him-one-of-the-most-valuable-individuals-in-the-backlands-—-and-he-knows-it.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>leadership</strong>-—-the-ability-to-command,-inspire,-and-organize-followers;-shaw-is-not-merely-a-preacher-but-a-leader-of-men,-capable-of-building-and-directing-an-organization</li>-<li><strong>prophecy</strong>-—-the-art-of-divination-and-foretelling;-shaw-claims-to-receive-visions-and-divine-revelations,-and-this-proficiency-suggests-those-claims-may-have-some-genuine-basis-—-or-at-least-that-he-is-skilled-enough-in-the-practice-to-be-convincing</li>-<li><strong>black-lore</strong>-—-forbidden-knowledge-of-dark-and-proscribed-traditions;-a-deeply-troubling-proficiency-for-a-cleric,-suggesting-that-shaw&#39;s-theology-draws-from-sources-that-orthodox-faiths-would-condemn.-this-proficiency,-combined-with-his-secretive-congregation,-raises-serious-questions-about-the-true-nature-of-the-&quot;hidden-light&quot;-he-preaches</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">appearance-and-demeanor</h2>-<p>shaw-<strong>radiates-warmth</strong>-—-a-quality-that-makes-him-immediately-disarming-and-compelling.-people-are-drawn-to-him-instinctively,-feeling-a-sense-of-comfort-and-trust-in-his-presence-that-is-difficult-to-resist.-his-eyes-are-described-as-<strong>shimmering</strong>,-possessing-an-unusual,-almost-supernatural-quality-that-reinforces-his-aura-of-otherworldly-connection.</p>-<p>beneath-this-warmth-lies-<strong>fanaticism</strong>.-shaw-is-not-a-moderate-or-a-compromiser-—-he-is-a-true-believer,-utterly-convinced-of-the-righteousness-of-his-cause-and-the-truth-of-his-visions.-whether-this-conviction-stems-from-genuine-divine-contact,-madness,-or-something-darker-is-unclear.-the-combination-of-charisma,-warmth,-and-fanaticism-makes-shaw-exceptionally-dangerous-—-he-can-draw-people-in-with-his-presence-and-bind-them-with-his-conviction-before-they-realize-what-they-have-committed-to.</p>-<p>shaw-is-<strong>possibly-mad</strong>.-the-line-between-prophecy-and-madness-is-thin,-and-shaw-walks-it-with-unsettling-confidence.-his-certainty-in-his-own-divine-mandate,-combined-with-his-proficiency-in-black-lore,-suggests-a-man-who-may-have-opened-doors-in-his-mind-that-cannot-be-closed.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"the-congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\">the-congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</h2>-<p>shaw-leads-the-<strong>[[congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">Congregation of the Hollow Sun</a></strong>, a secretive religious group whose full membership, beliefs, and goals are not publicly known. The name itself is evocative and disturbing — a &quot;hollow sun&quot; suggests a light that is empty, false, or corrupted. Whether the Congregation worships a legitimate deity, a corrupted aspect of an existing faith, or something entirely alien is a mystery.</p>\n<p>What is known:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Congregation operates <strong>in secret</strong>, suggesting its beliefs or practices would not be tolerated if widely known</li>\n<li>Shaw is its <strong>undisputed leader</strong>, with his charisma and divine power serving as the foundation of the group&#39;s cohesion</li>\n<li>The Congregation represents a <strong>long-term threat</strong> — it is growing, organizing, and building toward something</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Shaw&#39;s proficiency in <strong>Prophecy</strong> suggests the Congregation may be oriented around a prophetic vision — a foretold event or transformation that Shaw believes is coming. His <strong>Black Lore</strong> proficiency raises the possibility that this prophecy involves dark or forbidden elements.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"threat-assessment\">Threat Assessment</h2>\n<p>Shaw is categorized as a <strong>long-term threat</strong>, distinguishing him from the more immediate dangers of the Backlands. This designation suggests several things:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Shaw is patient.</strong> He is not planning an imminent attack or confrontation. He is building something — a following, a power base, a ritual framework — that will take time to mature.</li>\n<li><strong>Shaw is growing stronger.</strong> The Congregation is presumably expanding, recruiting from the desperate and disillusioned population of the Backlands. Each new follower adds to Shaw&#39;s power and influence.</li>\n<li><strong>Shaw&#39;s endgame is unknown.</strong> Whatever the Congregation is building toward — a mass ritual, a prophetic fulfillment, an uprising, a summoning — it has not yet been revealed.</li>\n<li><strong>Early intervention is possible.</strong> As a long-term threat, Shaw can potentially be investigated, confronted, or undermined before his plans reach fruition — but only if someone recognizes the danger he represents.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Hidden Light</strong> — What is the &quot;hidden light&quot; Shaw preaches? Is it a corrupted deity, a forgotten power, or something from beyond the mortal world?</li>\n<li><strong>The Hollow Sun</strong> — The name of the Congregation is deeply symbolic. What does it mean? Is it a reference to an eclipse, a dead god, or a void that hungers?</li>\n<li><strong>Shaw&#39;s Visions</strong> — Are Shaw&#39;s prophecies genuine? If so, what do they foretell? If not, what is the source of his power and conviction?</li>\n<li><strong>Black Lore</strong> — Shaw&#39;s proficiency in Black Lore is deeply concerning for a cleric. What forbidden knowledge does he possess, and how does it inform his theology?</li>\n<li><strong>Recruitment</strong> — The Congregation is recruiting from the desperate population of the Backlands. Tracking its members and understanding its structure could reveal Shaw&#39;s true intentions.</li>\n<li><strong>The Shimmering Eyes</strong> — Shaw&#39;s unusual, shimmering eyes may be a sign of supernatural influence, corruption, or transformation. Are they a mark of divine favor — or something else entirely?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a> — The secretive religious group Shaw leads</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The settlement where Shaw operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> — The orthodox faith of the Balanced Scale; potentially in tension with Shaw&#39;s teachings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> — The priest of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> at the House of Silence; a potential rival or target for Shaw</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> — Dark religious traditions; potentially connected to Shaw&#39;s Black Lore</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">empyrean-faith</a> — The state religion; Shaw&#39;s Congregation may represent a heretical offshoot or a rival tradition</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"governor-drussus","title":"Governor Valerios Drussus","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","governor","politician","military","fighter","sanctuary","citadel","drussine-guard","backlands","house-drussus","great-houses"],"html":"<h1 id=\"governor-valerios-drussus\">Governor Valerios Drussus</h1>\n<p><strong>Governor Valerios Drussus</strong> is the provincial governor of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, commanding from the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Citadel</a> in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. He is the most powerful individual in the province -- holding military, bureaucratic, and economic supremacy through fifteen years of methodical consolidation. Patriarch of <a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a>, the newest of the Great Houses, his intentions remain deliberately opaque. Every faction fears him. Every faction courts him. No one knows what he is building.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Valerios Drussus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td>Mithrian male</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>48</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>House</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">House Drussus</span> is the newest of the Great Houses, built on his accomplishments rather than inherited from a lineage of power. Before his appointment as Governor, he was already wealthy and well-connected, having parlayed military success into political capital with a precision that made older houses nervous.</p>\n<p>He was appointed Governor of the Backlands in <strong>365 IY</strong>, fifteen years ago. At the time, the appointment was seen as semi-exile -- the Backlands is a provincial backwater, far from the imperial court, and the posting was considered a dead end for an ambitious officer. Whether Drussus accepted it willingly or was maneuvered into it is unknown. What is certain is that he has made the most of it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"consolidation-of-power\">Consolidation of Power</h2>\n<p>Since taking the post, Drussus has executed a systematic consolidation of power with a patience and thoroughness that borders on the obsessive:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Gifts to the military</strong> -- Generous pay, excellent equipment, and personal attention have ensured that the <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> (his private army, ~2,000 strong) is loyal to <strong>him personally</strong>, not to the city or the Empire</li>\n<li><strong>Careful marriages for his daughters</strong> -- Strategic alliances through marriage, binding merchant families and minor nobility to <a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a></li>\n<li><strong>Steady acquisition of merchant houses and estates</strong> -- Drussus has bought, inherited, or pressured his way into ownership of significant economic assets throughout the province</li>\n<li><strong>Gradual placement of loyalists throughout the bureaucracy</strong> -- Every tax collector, magistrate, and functionary in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> was either appointed by Drussus or knows they serve at his pleasure</li>\n<li><strong>Control over the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">City Watch</a></strong> (~600 strong) -- Ostensibly independent, in practice answerable to the Governor</li>\n<li><strong>Tacit arrangement with the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a></strong> -- The criminal syndicate provides intelligence, removes inconvenient people, and keeps the underworld organized. In exchange, Drussus does not interfere.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>His personal wealth now competes with the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>. His control over the bureaucracy is absolute. The <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the Backlands.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"combat-ability\">Combat Ability</h2>\n<p>Those who have faced Drussus in combat describe him as <strong>preternaturally calm</strong>, adjusting tactics mid-battle with disconcerting speed. He does not fight with fury or passion. He fights the way he governs -- with cold precision, exploiting weaknesses the moment they appear, never overextending, never losing control.</p>\n<p>At Fighter 12 with 96 HP and AC 2, he is one of the most dangerous combatants in the province. His Leader ability (+4 reaction from loyal troops) means that the <a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussine Guard</a> fights with exceptional morale and coordination when he is present.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-relationships\">Key Relationships</h2>\n<h3 id=\"prelate-severan-voth\">Prelate Severan Voth</h3>\n<p>The relationship between Drussus and <a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Voth</a> is <strong>cold and formal</strong>. They do not trust each other, but they maintain an equilibrium born of mutual recognition:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drussus does not interfere with Temple internal affairs</li>\n<li>Voth does not publicly oppose the Governor&#39;s authority</li>\n<li>Both recognize that either could seriously damage the other</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This is not friendship or alliance. It is a standoff between two powers who have calculated that open conflict would be mutually destructive. The balance holds, but it is fragile.</p>\n<h3 id=\"legate-marcellus\">Legate Marcellus</h3>\n<p>From the surface, Drussus &quot;seems content to rest on his laurels in Sanctuary.&quot; But the <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> records reveal that he is engaged in a <strong>silent political war</strong> with <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a>. Drussus has blocked every request Marcellus has made for reinforcements, recognition, or transfer. He has isolated the Legate at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, denying him the resources and political support he needs to challenge the Governor&#39;s authority or to build an independent power base.</p>\n<p>This is not personal animosity. It is strategic containment. Marcellus represents the only other significant military authority in the province, and Drussus will not tolerate a rival.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-laced-hand\">The Laced Hand</h3>\n<p>Drussus maintains a tacit arrangement with the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> criminal syndicate. The arrangement is transactional:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Laced Hand provides intelligence from the docks, subtle removal of inconvenient individuals, and a criminal safety valve that keeps the underworld organized rather than chaotic</li>\n<li>In exchange, the Governor does not interfere with Laced Hand operations</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/castellan-thibaud\" class=\"wiki-link\">Castellan Thibaud</a> understands that this arrangement exists at Drussus&#39;s pleasure and can be revoked at any time.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-red-river-consortium\">The Red River Consortium</h3>\n<p>The Sanctuary branch of the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>, led by Directrix <a href=\"#/page/valeria-thorne\" class=\"wiki-link\">Valeria Thorne</a> (age 58), is <strong>politically aligned with the Governor</strong>. This alliance gives Drussus access to the Consortium&#39;s commercial networks and wealth, while the Consortium benefits from favorable treatment in provincial trade policy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Drussus is a man of few words and enormous patience. He does not make threats. He does not bluster. He does not negotiate from emotion. Every decision he makes is calculated, every concession is temporary, and every gift comes with an invisible ledger entry.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>immune to most social manipulation</strong>. Appeals to honor fall on deaf ears. Invocations of tradition are met with polite indifference. Sentimental arguments are dismissed without comment. He respects only <strong>competence and strength</strong> -- those who demonstrate both may earn his attention, if not his trust.</p>\n<p>His loyalty is to <strong>Sanctuary and his vision for it</strong>, not to the Emperor. He would not betray the Empire directly -- he is too pragmatic for open rebellion -- but he would act independently without hesitation if he judged it necessary.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gm-notes\">GM Notes</h2>\n<p>Drussus is <strong>not a villain by default</strong>. He is a dangerous man doing dangerous things for reasons that are deliberately left ambiguous. His methods are cold. His ambition is vast. But his goals could be:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A personal empire</strong> -- naked ambition, using the province as a power base</li>\n<li><strong>A check against imperial decline</strong> -- preparing the Backlands for a future where the Empire can no longer protect it</li>\n<li><strong>A grand conspiracy</strong> -- serving some hidden agenda that has not yet been revealed</li>\n<li><strong>Something else entirely</strong> -- the GM should decide, or leave it ambiguous</li>\n</ul>\n<p>What is clear:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>He is building something. The consolidation of power is too systematic, too thorough, to be mere bureaucratic ambition.</li>\n<li>He is not sentimental. People are tools, alliances are temporary, and loyalty is currency.</li>\n<li>He is extremely difficult to manipulate or deceive. PCs who attempt social approaches will find a wall of calm intelligence.</li>\n<li>He can be worked with, but never controlled. Adventurers who prove competent and useful may find him a valuable patron -- but they should never forget who holds the leash.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- provincial capital</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Citadel</a> -- Governor&#39;s fortress-seat</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/drussine-guard\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Drussine Guard</a> -- the Governor&#39;s personal army</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a> -- the newest Great House</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/prelate-voth\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prelate Severan Voth</a> -- head of the Temple</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> -- military rival at Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a> -- criminal syndicate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> -- trading company</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/colonel-vex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Colonel Marcian Vex</a> -- Drussine Guard commander</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- the province</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"greta","title":"Greta of Bone Creek","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","witch","lakandi","bone-creek","demonic-pact","herbalism","alchemy","cthonic","binding","backlands","scalper"],"html":"<h1 id=\"greta-of-bone-creek\">Greta of Bone Creek</h1>\n<p><strong>Greta</strong> is an old <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> woman who has lived in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> longer than anyone can remember. She is a practitioner of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a> -- one of a handful of people in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> who engages directly with entities from beyond <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a>, not through petition or worship but through binding, contest, and mutual obligation.</p>\n<p>She wears a <strong>bird-skull necklace</strong>. She smells of herbs. She is <strong>blunt, secretive, and earthy</strong> -- a woman who has survived decades of frontier life not through charm or diplomacy but through competence, knowledge, and whatever arrangement she has made with the thing she does not discuss.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Witch 3 (<a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#lakandi</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>7</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>11</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>wis</strong></td>-<td>16</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<h3-id=\"spells\">spells</h3>-<ul>-<li><strong>charm-animal</strong>----control-over-the-natural-world;-the-ability-to-bend-animal-will-to-her-own,-reflecting-the-lakandi-tradition&#39;s-emphasis-on-binding-and-domination-rather-than-cooperation</li>-<li><strong>sleep</strong>----the-power-to-impose-unconsciousness;-a-spell-of-control-that-echoes-the-binding-tradition&#39;s-fundamental-premise:-the-practitioner-imposes,-the-target-submits</li>-<li><strong>cure-light-wounds</strong>----healing;-the-practical-magic-that-has-kept-greta-valued-and-alive-in-bone-creek-for-decades,-the-reason-the-community-tolerates-what-they-know-about-her-and-does-not-ask-about-what-they-suspect</li>-</ul>-<h3-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h3>-<ul>-<li><strong>alchemy</strong>----the-preparation-of-substances-with-supernatural-properties;-the-practical-application-of-knowledge-that-bridges-the-mundane-and-the-arcane</li>-<li><strong>herbalism-2</strong>----advanced-knowledge-of-plants,-their-properties,-and-their-uses;-greta&#39;s-primary-visible-trade-and-the-reason-most-of-bone-creek-interacts-with-her-at-all</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"the-pact\">the-pact</h2>-<p>greta-has-made-a-pact-with-a-demonic-entity-she-does-not-discuss.-most-of-[[bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> treats this as her private business, because she has never harmed anyone and her medicines have genuinely saved lives. This is the practical morality of the frontier: what matters is not what you believe or what you have done in private, but whether you are useful and whether you are dangerous. Greta is useful. She has not, thus far, been dangerous to anyone in Bone Creek.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-key-distinction\">The Key Distinction</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi tradition</a> distinguishes between two fundamentally different types of demonic engagement:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Binding that places the practitioner in SERVICE to a Cthonic power.</strong> The practitioner petitions, the entity grants, and the practitioner becomes increasingly dependent -- a servant, a vessel, a tool. The power flows downward. The entity commands; the practitioner obeys.</li>\n<li><strong>Binding where the practitioner HOLDS the entity.</strong> The practitioner contests, the entity yields (or is compelled to yield), and the relationship is one of controlled obligation rather than servitude. The power flows upward. The practitioner commands; the entity serves.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Greta holds something.</strong> She is not in service to a Cthonic power. She has bound an entity into an arrangement where she maintains control -- or at least, where the balance of the arrangement favors her. What she gave for this binding she has not said. The cost of holding a demonic entity is always real, always personal, and always visible to those who know what to look for.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"history-in-bone-creek\">History in Bone Creek</h2>\n<p>Greta has operated through every phase of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek&#39;s</a> existence:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The silver rush</strong> -- when Bone Creek was a booming mining settlement and fortune-seekers flooded the region. Greta was there, providing medicines, remedies, and services that the miners needed and could not get elsewhere.</li>\n<li><strong>The decline</strong> -- when the silver ran out and Bone Creek contracted from a boom town to a dying settlement. Greta remained when others left, sustained by whatever she is and whatever she knows.</li>\n<li><strong>The current Scalper economy</strong> -- when the imperial bounty on <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> scalps transformed Bone Creek into the epicenter of the Scalper trade. Greta adapted, as she has always adapted, providing her services to a new clientele of bounty hunters, mercenaries, and desperate frontier people.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Through every phase, Greta has been a constant -- an anchor of continuity in a place defined by volatility. She was here before the silver. She was here before the Scalpers. She will be here after them, if anything is.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"knowledge-and-watching\">Knowledge and Watching</h2>\n<p>Greta knows the region&#39;s pre-imperial history better than anyone in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>. She is not forthcoming about this knowledge. She does not volunteer information. She does not educate. She does not share what she knows unless she has a reason -- and her reasons are her own, as opaque and guarded as everything else about her.</p>\n<p>She is <strong>watching</strong>. What she watches for, what she expects, what she anticipates -- none of this is clear. But the quality of her attention -- the way her gaze lingers on certain visitors, certain events, certain shifts in the balance of power in Bone Creek and beyond -- suggests that Greta is not merely surviving the frontier but monitoring it. She is waiting for something, or watching for something, and when it arrives she will know it before anyone else does.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-marks-of-binding\">The Marks of Binding</h2>\n<p>Repeated contact with the Beyond corrupts. This is not speculation or theology -- it is observable fact. The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi tradition</a> treats the signs of corruption not as failing but as the <strong>visible record of genuine engagement</strong>. To be marked is to have done something real.</p>\n<p>The marks of binding include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eyes darkening at the iris</strong> -- a gradual deepening of color that progresses with prolonged Cthonic contact, eventually turning the eyes fully dark. The legendary Warlock King <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Jarn Murky-Eye</a> bore a name that was not metaphorical.</li>\n<li><strong>A quality of stillness beyond patience</strong> -- not the stillness of someone waiting, but the stillness of something that has been touched by entities that operate on timescales beyond human comprehension. A person who has held a demon carries something of that demon&#39;s relationship to time.</li>\n<li><strong>Awareness of things not normally visible</strong> -- perception that extends beyond the ordinary human range, into frequencies and dimensions that most people never access. Those who have torn open <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Veil</a> and reached through it carry an expanded awareness that does not fade.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Lakandi treat these marks as credentials. To be corrupted is to have engaged. To be engaged is to have risked. To have risked is to have done something real with power that most people are too frightened to touch.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The settlement where Greta has lived for decades</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- The tradition Greta practices</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> -- Greta&#39;s culture and people</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-veil</a> -- The barrier through which Lakandi practitioners reach</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-corruption</a> -- The corruption that marks those who engage with the Beyond</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">jarn-murky-eye</a> -- The legendary Warlock King of the Lakandi binding tradition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a> -- Another heterodox spiritual movement in Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> -- The preacher of the Hollow Sun, also operating in Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> -- The priest of Seros in Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier province</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"high-mage-cynar","title":"High Mage Cynar","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["historical","imperial-academy","high-mage","sorcerer","battle-of-blue-mound","lakan-campaigns","erenthis","avari","thornasse"],"html":"<h1 id=\"high-mage-cynar\">High Mage Cynar</h1>\n<p><strong>High Mage Cynar</strong> was the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s foremost battle-sorcerer during the <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a> (360-368 IY). He is remembered for two acts that define his legacy: the cataclysmic sorcerous duel with <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a> at the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> -- which annihilated both armies and killed both combatants -- and the burning of the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at Thornasse, the cultural execution of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> people. Both acts demonstrated the devastating and irreversible consequences of concentrating overwhelming power in a single individual.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Cynar</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>High Mage of the <span class=\"dead-link\">Lakan Campaigns</span>, Imperial armies marched deep into <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> territory, backed by devastating magical firepower. The campaign culminated in the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a>, where Imperial forces under Cynar&#39;s command engaged the army of <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a>.</p>\n<p>The climax of the battle came when Cynar and Jarn Murky-Eye engaged in a direct sorcerous duel -- a confrontation of such magnitude that it escalated beyond all control. The cataclysmic energies unleashed by the two combatants annihilated <strong>both armies entirely</strong>, leaving the battlefield a blasted and lifeless wasteland. Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived.</p>\n<p>The Battle of Blue Mound had profound consequences for Imperial military doctrine. It demonstrated that the deployment of high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was not merely dangerous but potentially suicidal. The Empire subsequently adopted a model of combined arms warfare, integrating squad mages into conventional military formations rather than relying on individual sorcerers to decide the outcome of battles.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-burning-of-the-erenthis\">The Burning of the Erenthis</h2>\n<p>Approximately 30 years ago, High Mage Cynar committed what many consider a cultural atrocity: the burning of the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a> at Thornasse. The Erenthis was the sacred oral and written tradition of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> people -- their history, their songs, their identity as a people preserved across generations.</p>\n<p>Cynar&#39;s destruction of the Erenthis at Thornasse was a deliberate act of cultural execution. By destroying the physical records and killing or scattering the keepers of the oral tradition, the Empire attempted to erase the Avari as a distinct people. The consequences of this act continue to reverberate: the Avari communities that survive -- such as the community in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>&#39;s Ashward, led by <a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elder Sarnath</a> -- carry the wound of this destruction as a defining element of their identity.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>Cynar&#39;s legacy is one of overwhelming power wielded without adequate restraint. In war, his duel with <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Jarn Murky-Eye</a> destroyed everything it was meant to protect. In peace, his burning of the Erenthis inflicted a wound that can never be fully healed. He embodied the dangers of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s doctrine of sorcerous supremacy -- the belief that magical power, properly applied, could solve any problem. The Battle of Blue Mound proved that some problems, when met with overwhelming force, simply consume everything.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> -- the catastrophic battle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Lakan Campaigns</a> -- the broader military campaign</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</a> -- his opponent in the duel</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Erenthis</a> -- the Avari tradition he destroyed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elder-sarnath\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elder Sarnath</a> -- Avari community elder in Sanctuary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a> -- the institution he served</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a> -- the forces he wielded</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"iman","title":"Iman","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["pc","player-character","reclaimers","bladedancer","order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon","empyrean","lady-severina","backlands","fort-meade"],"html":"<h1 id=\"iman\">Iman</h1>\n<p><strong>Iman</strong> is a Bladedancer and a member of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. She was driven from the <a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</a> for speaking too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons -- for naming aloud the corruption that others chose to tolerate in silence. Exiled from the only institution that had given her purpose, she came to <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> and found new allegiances among the killers drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty. She has developed a close relationship with <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Iman</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Bladedancer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Active PC</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Party</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</span> -- a militant order connected to the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> faith. The Order trained bladedancers in the martial and devotional arts, combining blade-work with religious discipline in service to the Empyrean temples and their patrons.</p>\n<p>The Order, however, was not the pure institution its public face suggested. The priestesses of the Order maintained relationships with noble patrons -- relationships that blurred the boundary between spiritual authority and secular power, between devotion and transaction. These arrangements were understood by everyone within the Order but spoken of by no one. They were the open secret upon which the institution&#39;s funding, political protection, and social standing depended.</p>\n<p>Iman spoke too plainly. She named what others chose not to name. She identified the corruption -- the exchange of spiritual authority for noble patronage, the priestesses who served their patrons&#39; interests rather than their faith&#39;s teachings -- and she said it aloud, in terms that could not be misunderstood or politely ignored.</p>\n<p>For this, she was driven from the Order. Not for being wrong, but for being honest in a place where honesty was the one unforgivable sin.</p>\n<h3 id=\"coming-to-the-backlands\">Coming to the Backlands</h3>\n<p>Stripped of her place in the Order, Iman came to <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> as so many others did -- drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty, by the promise of coin for killing, by the frontier&#39;s indifference to a person&#39;s past. The Backlands did not care what she had said or whom she had offended. It cared only whether she could fight, and she could.</p>\n<p>She fell in with the group that would become <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>, finding among these killers and misfits a kind of belonging that the Order had revoked. Her bladedancer training made her one of the party&#39;s most capable combatants. Her directness -- the same quality that had gotten her expelled -- made her a forthright companion, if sometimes an uncomfortable one.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-lady-severina\">Relationship with Lady Severina</h2>\n<p>Iman has developed a close personal relationship with <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a>, the wife of <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> and the Reclaimers&#39; true patron. The precise nature of this relationship is multilayered -- Severina is the party&#39;s patron, a political operator of considerable sophistication, and a woman who recognizes in Iman a directness that she values precisely because it is so rare in her world of courtly maneuvering.</p>\n<p>Severina told Iman privately that she considers herself the real political engine of the Marcellus household. This confidence suggests a level of trust between the two women that extends beyond the merely professional. Iman, expelled from one institution for her honesty, has found in Severina someone who values that quality rather than punishing it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-among-the-reclaimers\">Role Among the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Iman is one of the party&#39;s front-line combatants -- a trained bladedancer whose martial skills were honed in the <a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</a>. She brings religious discipline and martial precision to a group that is otherwise composed of scholars, merchants, and outcasts.</p>\n<p>Her connection to <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina</a> gives her a political dimension within the party that extends beyond her combat role. Through Iman, the Reclaimers have a direct and personal line to their patron -- a relationship that is not merely transactional but built on genuine mutual regard.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"personality\">Personality</h2>\n<p>Iman is direct, plain-spoken, and unwilling to tolerate the kind of comfortable lies that most institutions depend upon. This quality got her expelled from the <a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">Order of the Scarlet Ribbon</a>, and it remains her defining characteristic. She says what she sees. She names what others choose to leave unnamed. In an order of priestesses and nobles, this made her dangerous. Among the Reclaimers, it makes her trustworthy.</p>\n<p>She carries the weight of her expulsion without self-pity. The Order cast her out for telling the truth, and she has not forgiven them for it, but neither has she allowed it to embitter her entirely. She found new purpose in the Backlands, new companions among the Reclaimers, and a new patron in Lady Severina who values honesty rather than punishing it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The adventuring party she belongs to</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon</a> -- The militant order from which she was expelled</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- Her close relationship and the Reclaimers&#39; patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Severina&#39;s husband and the Reclaimers&#39; formal patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where she is based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The underground complex currently being explored</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruins above the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history of the campaign</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"irontoe","title":"Irontoe","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","fighter","mithrian","bone-creek","smith","veteran","lakandi","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"irontoe\">Irontoe</h1>\n<p><strong>Pontus &quot;Irontoe&quot; Draega</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-culture\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> Fighter (level 2) who serves as <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek&#39;s</a> smith. He lost his leg fighting the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> and wears an <strong>iron foot on a wooden leg</strong> -- the prosthetic that earned him his name. Despite the disability, he is one of the most productive and loudest men in the settlement.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Pontus &quot;Irontoe&quot; Draega</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Lakandi</span></strong>, most likely during the <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a> (360-368 IY) -- the eight-year war that ended with the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> and the mutual annihilation of <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> and <a href=\"#/page/jarn-murky-eye\" class=\"wiki-link\">Jarn Murky-Eye</a>. His Fighter training and Manual of Arms proficiency mark him as a trained imperial soldier, not a militia conscript.</p>\n<p>A man who survived the Lakan Campaigns and lost only a leg came out ahead of many. The Lakandi fought with <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">bound demons</a> and dark sorcery -- losing a limb to such enemies and living to forge iron in a frontier town is, by any measure, a victory.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-bone-creek\">Role in Bone Creek</h2>\n<p>As the settlement&#39;s only skilled smith, Irontoe is essential infrastructure. <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalpers</a> need weapons maintained, armor repaired, and tools forged. The frontier consumes metal at a prodigious rate. Irontoe&#39;s forge is one of the few things standing between Bone Creek and complete material collapse.</p>\n<p>His Craft (Smithing) proficiency makes him the man who keeps the Scalper economy&#39;s tools sharp and functional. His Manual of Arms proficiency means he understands what he&#39;s making and for whom -- a soldier-smith, not merely a tradesman.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The frontier outpost where Irontoe works his forge</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> -- The enemy who took his leg</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakan-campaigns</a> -- The likely war in which he served</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-culture\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-culture</a> -- His cultural background</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The primary customers for his smithing</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"jarn-murky-eye","title":"Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["historical","warlock-king","lakandi","sorcerer","battle-of-blue-mound","lakan-campaigns","veil","demon-binding"],"html":"<h1 id=\"warlock-king-jarn-murky-eye\">Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</h1>\n<p><strong>Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye</strong> was the most powerful sorcerer-warlord of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> people, a warlock whose name was not metaphorical -- he bore the physical marks of extensive contact with the <a href=\"#/page/the-veil\" class=\"wiki-link\">Veil</a> and demon-binding practices that defined Lakandi sorcerous tradition. He fought <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> at the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> during the <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a> (360-368 IY). The cataclysmic sorcerous duel between the two annihilated both armies and killed both combatants.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Jarn Murky-Eye</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>Warlock King of the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Affiliation</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> tribes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sorcerous Tradition</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Veil</span>, the boundary between the physical world and the chaotic energies of the <a href=\"#/page/the-beyond\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beyond</a>. Among the Lakandi, such physical corruption is not viewed as a curse or a mark of shame. It is treated as a <strong>visible record of genuine engagement</strong> -- proof that the sorcerer has touched the Veil, bargained with entities beyond it, and returned bearing the marks of that contact.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi binding tradition</a> holds that a sorcerer who has not been changed by the Veil has not truly engaged with it. Corruption -- physical transformation, discoloration, asymmetry, or more profound alterations -- is evidence of authenticity. A warlock whose body shows no marks is either a fraud or a coward. Jarn&#39;s murky eye was thus a badge of authority as much as a physical affliction.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-battle-of-blue-mound\">The Battle of Blue Mound</h2>\n<p>When Imperial armies marched deep into Lakandi territory during the <a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakan Campaigns</a>, Jarn Murky-Eye assembled an army of considerable size and ferocity to resist the invasion. The campaign culminated in the <a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a>, where Jarn&#39;s forces clashed with the Imperial army led by <a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a>.</p>\n<p>The climax of the battle was a direct sorcerous duel between the two most powerful magic users on the field. The confrontation escalated beyond all control -- the energies unleashed by Cynar&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/gnostic-geometry\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gnostic Geometry</a> and Jarn&#39;s Veil-born sorcery combined into a cataclysm that annihilated both armies entirely. Neither Jarn nor Cynar survived.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>Jarn Murky-Eye&#39;s death did not end the Lakandi as a people. The Empire, having lost its entire expeditionary force, retreated and erected a line of border forts that marks the current frontier. The Lakandi were broken by the campaign but remained unbowed -- vowing revenge against the Empire that had invaded their lands and, in the process of being defeated, destroyed everything.</p>\n<p>Among the Lakandi, Jarn is remembered as a hero -- a warlock king who met the Empire&#39;s most powerful sorcerer in single combat and, though he died, ensured that the enemy did not survive either. The mutual annihilation at Blue Mound is viewed not as a defeat but as a victory of a different kind: proof that the Lakandi will never submit, even at the cost of their own destruction.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/battle-of-blue-mound\" class=\"wiki-link\">Battle of Blue Mound</a> -- the catastrophic battle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakan-campaigns\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Lakan Campaigns</a> -- the broader military campaign</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/high-mage-cynar\" class=\"wiki-link\">High Mage Cynar</a> -- his opponent in the duel</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi Binding Tradition</a> -- the sorcerous tradition he embodied</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-corruption\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic Corruption</a> -- the forces of the Veil</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"justinian-decimus","title":"Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["emperor","house-decimus","ruler","mithrian-empire","mithra-city","imperial-bounty","skiothan"],"html":"<h1 id=\"emperor-justinian-claudius-decimus\">Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</h1>\n<p><strong>Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</strong> is the current Emperor of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> and patriarch of <a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a>, the ruling dynasty founded by his ancestor <a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> in 270 IY. He firmly holds the Empire in his grasp, ruling from <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> and facing threats on multiple fronts.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Justinian Claudius Decimus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>Emperor of the <span class=\"dead-link\">War of Three Emperors</span>, and the current Emperor maintains his grip through the same instruments that have sustained his house for over a century: the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Talons</a> (spies and assassins who answer only to the throne), the legions, and the vast bureaucratic apparatus of imperial governance.</p>\n<p>The Emperor&#39;s authority is absolute in theory, though in practice it is constrained by the power of the Great Houses, the influence of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thousand Temples</a>, the independence of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, and the practical limits of governing an empire that spans a continent.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-decisions\">Key Decisions</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-garrison-recall-378-iy\">The Garrison Recall (378 IY)</h3>\n<p>Two years ago, when the great <strong>Skiothan</strong> host threatened the Empire&#39;s western frontier, the Emperor recalled the local armies and garrisons from the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> to reinforce the defenses against this existential threat. This strategic decision left the frontier provinces undermanned and poorly defended, contributing directly to the current lawlessness and chaos in the Backlands. The recall stranded officers like <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> at skeleton garrisons like <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, and shifted the balance of power in the provinces toward local strongmen like <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-bounty-377-378-iy\">The Imperial Bounty (377-378 IY)</h3>\n<p>Following the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> in 377 IY -- when a <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> horde razed the northern town and slaughtered its people -- the Emperor issued an Imperial scalp bounty on beastmen. The bounty was intended to suppress the beastman threat, but its consequences were catastrophic. It unleashed a wave of mercenaries, deserters, and killers into the Backlands, creating the <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a> economy that has plunged the frontier into anarchy. While beastman activity near settled areas has decreased, the influx of violent fortune-seekers has created problems arguably worse than the threat they were sent to address.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"threats\">Threats</h2>\n<p>The Emperor faces challenges on multiple fronts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a></strong> in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> -- a persistent threat to frontier settlements</li>\n<li><strong>Skiothan raiders</strong> on the western frontier -- the existential threat that prompted the garrison recall</li>\n<li><strong>Lingering unrest in <a href=\"#/page/mornish\" class=\"wiki-link\">Morn</a></strong> -- provincial instability</li>\n<li><strong>The Great Houses</strong> -- the ever-present political maneuvering of <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Valerian</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kalomenes</a>, <a href=\"#/page/house-severian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severian</a>, and the others</li>\n<li><strong>The proliferation of sorcerous knowledge</strong> beyond the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>&#39;s control</li>\n<li><strong>Corruption of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Senate</a></strong></li>\n<li><strong>Provincial restlessness</strong> -- the Backlands in particular are sliding toward a state of de facto independence under <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a></li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Decimus</a> -- the ruling dynasty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/claudius-decimus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Claudius Decimus</a> -- ancestor and dynasty founder</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-talons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Talons</a> -- the Emperor&#39;s spies and assassins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> -- the disaster that prompted the Imperial Bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper Gangs</a> -- consequence of the bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> -- provincial strongman in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> -- military commander stranded by the recall</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"kael-baldric","title":"Kael Baldric","category":"people","status":"missing","tags":["npc","fighter","avari","scalper","baldric-brothers","missing","investigation-hook","backlands","bone-creek"],"html":"<h1 id=\"kael-baldric\">Kael Baldric</h1>\n<p><strong>Kael Baldric</strong> is an <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> fighter and the leader of the <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-baldric-brothers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Baldric Brothers</a></strong>, a Scalper gang composed of five Avari brothers with a fearsome reputation in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. Stern, protective, and fiercely loyal to his family, Kael is the eldest and most formidable of the brothers — the one who holds the group together and directs their violent efficiency.</p>\n<p>Kael is currently <strong>MISSING</strong>. His disappearance is unexplained and deeply troubling, both for his brothers and for the balance of power among the Scalper gangs of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>. The Baldric Brothers are rarely seen apart, and Kael&#39;s absence suggests something has gone catastrophically wrong. His disappearance serves as a potential <strong>investigation or rescue hook</strong> — a mystery that could lead into the dangerous wilderness of the Backlands or into the web of intrigue that entangles Bone Creek&#39;s power players.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Fighter 4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>3</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>30</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+4-(bastard-sword,-1d10+1)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>str</strong></td>-<td>15</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>kael&#39;s-statistics-reflect-a-seasoned-warrior-of-considerable-ability.-his-30-hit-points-provide-strong-durability,-and-his-+4-attack-bonus-with-a-bastard-sword-dealing-1d10+1-damage-makes-him-a-powerful-melee-combatant.-his-strength-of-15-supports-his-fighting-style:-direct,-forceful,-and-unrelenting.-his-ac-of-3-indicates-solid-armor,-likely-well-maintained-—-kael-is-a-professional-who-takes-his-equipment-seriously.</p>-<p>the-bastard-sword-is-a-versatile-weapon-that-can-be-wielded-in-one-or-two-hands,-reflecting-kael&#39;s-adaptability-in-combat.-it-is-a-weapon-of-reach-and-power,-suitable-for-a-leader-who-fights-at-the-front-of-his-brothers&#39;-formation.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>leadership</strong>-—-the-ability-to-command,-inspire,-and-organize-a-fighting-force.-for-kael,-this-proficiency-is-exercised-within-the-tight-knit-structure-of-the-baldric-brothers-—-five-siblings-who-fight-as-a-single,-coordinated-unit.-kael&#39;s-leadership-is-not-the-broad,-political-command-of-a-general-but-the-intimate,-familial-authority-of-an-eldest-brother-who-has-kept-his-family-alive-through-years-of-violence.</li>-<li><strong>survival</strong>-—-the-practical-skills-of-wilderness-endurance-in-the-harsh-environment-of-the-backlands.-tracking-prey,-finding-water,-reading-the-land,-navigating-hostile-terrain-—-these-are-the-skills-that-keep-the-baldric-brothers-operational-in-the-field-between-bounty-hunts.</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">appearance-and-demeanor</h2>-<p>kael-is-<strong>completely-bald</strong>-—-a-striking-physical-feature-that-makes-him-instantly-recognizable.-combined-with-his-<strong>black-chain-tattoos</strong>,-which-wind-across-his-scalp-and-presumably-down-his-neck-and-body,-kael-presents-an-intimidating-and-memorable-figure.-the-black-chain-tattoos-may-be-cultural-markers-of-his-[[races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> heritage, symbols of his bond with his brothers, or marks earned through combat and survival.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>stern</strong> — a man of few words and direct action. Kael does not waste time on pleasantries, negotiation, or unnecessary conversation. He assesses situations quickly, makes decisions firmly, and expects his brothers to follow without question. This sternness is not cruelty — it is the discipline of a man who knows that hesitation and weakness get people killed on the frontier.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>protective</strong> — fiercely and absolutely devoted to the safety and well-being of his brothers. This protectiveness is the core of Kael&#39;s identity. Everything he does — every fight, every hunt, every decision — is filtered through the question of whether it serves or endangers his family. This makes Kael predictable in one crucial way: threatening his brothers is the surest way to earn his undying enmity, and protecting them is the surest path to his gratitude.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>family-loyal</strong> to an extreme degree. The Baldric Brothers are not merely a Scalper gang — they are a family unit, and Kael&#39;s loyalty to that unit is absolute. He would die for his brothers without hesitation, and he would kill anyone who threatened them without remorse.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-baldric-brothers\">The Baldric Brothers</h2>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-baldric-brothers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Baldric Brothers</a></strong> are five <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> brothers who operate as a single, cohesive Scalper gang in the Backlands. They have a <strong>fearsome reputation</strong> earned through effectiveness and violence:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>They are <strong>rarely seen apart</strong> — the brothers operate as a unit at almost all times, fighting together, eating together, sleeping in shifts to protect each other. This unity is their greatest strength, as five coordinated warriors fighting as one are far more dangerous than five individuals.</li>\n<li>They <strong>get jobs done quickly and violently</strong> — the Baldric Brothers are known for brutal efficiency. They do not linger, they do not hesitate, and they do not leave survivors among their beastman prey. This reputation means they are sought after for difficult or dangerous bounties that other Scalper groups would avoid.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The four unnamed brothers presumably share Kael&#39;s Avari heritage and martial capabilities, though their individual classes, levels, and personalities are not detailed. What is clear is that they form a tightly bonded fighting unit whose coordination and mutual loyalty make them far more dangerous than their individual statistics would suggest.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"current-status-missing\">Current Status: MISSING</h2>\n<p>Kael Baldric is currently <strong>missing</strong>. This is an extraordinary and alarming situation for several reasons:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>The brothers are never apart.</strong> For Kael to be separated from his brothers implies that something extraordinary — a battle, a trap, a betrayal, a disaster — has occurred. The Baldric Brothers do not simply wander off alone.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>Kael is the leader.</strong> Without Kael, the remaining four brothers lose their commander, their decision-maker, and their emotional anchor. The gang&#39;s effectiveness and cohesion are severely compromised.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>No explanation has been offered.</strong> Kael&#39;s disappearance is unexplained, which means the brothers either do not know what happened to him or are not willing to share that information. Either possibility is deeply troubling.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><strong>Foul play is likely.</strong> Given the dangerous nature of the Backlands and the number of enemies a successful Scalper gang inevitably accumulates, Kael&#39;s disappearance is more likely the result of violence than accident.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"possible-explanations\">Possible Explanations</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Captured by beastmen</strong> — Kael may have been taken alive during a hunt gone wrong. If so, he is likely being held in or near <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> or another beastman settlement.</li>\n<li><strong>Betrayed by a rival</strong> — One of the other Scalper gangs or a power player in Bone Creek may have orchestrated Kael&#39;s disappearance to weaken the Baldric Brothers.</li>\n<li><strong>Lost in the wilderness</strong> — The Backlands are vast and dangerous. Kael may be injured, trapped, or lost in hostile terrain.</li>\n<li><strong>Imprisoned</strong> — Kael may have been captured by imperial forces, by the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>, or by some other organized power.</li>\n<li><strong>Voluntary departure</strong> — It is possible, though unlikely given his character, that Kael left of his own accord for reasons unknown to his brothers.</li>\n<li><strong>Dead</strong> — The simplest and most grim explanation. Kael may have been killed, and his body has not yet been found.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Search for Kael</strong> — The Baldric Brothers&#39; search for their missing leader is a ready-made adventure hook. They would pay handsomely — or offer violent services — to anyone who could provide information about Kael&#39;s whereabouts.</li>\n<li><strong>The Brothers Without a Leader</strong> — How do the four remaining brothers cope without Kael? Do they fragment, lash out, seek help, or become even more dangerous in their desperation?</li>\n<li><strong>Who Took Kael?</strong> — If Kael&#39;s disappearance was orchestrated, identifying the responsible party opens up a web of intrigue involving Scalper gangs, beastmen, or Bone Creek&#39;s power players.</li>\n<li><strong>The Rescue</strong> — If Kael is alive and captive, a rescue mission into beastman-held territory or a rival&#39;s stronghold would be a high-stakes operation.</li>\n<li><strong>The Avari Bond</strong> — The Baldric Brothers&#39; extreme loyalty to each other is both a strength and a vulnerability. Anyone who threatens the remaining brothers controls the most powerful lever in the situation.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-baldric-brothers\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Baldric Brothers</a> — Kael&#39;s gang of five Avari brothers</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> — The Baldric Brothers&#39; cultural heritage</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — Potential captors if Kael was taken during a hunt</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — The ruined city; a possible location for a captive Kael</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"lady-severina","title":"Lady Severina Marcellus","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","noble","political","fort-meade","house-valerian","backlands","mithrian"],"html":"<h1 id=\"lady-severina-marcellus\">Lady Severina Marcellus</h1>\n<p><strong>Lady Severina Marcellus</strong> (nee Severina) is the wife of <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</a> and the more politically sophisticated half of the Marcellus household at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>. She operates through warmth, curiosity, and social intelligence that most people underestimate.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Lady Severina Marcellus (nee Severina)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td>Mithrian female</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>Early 40s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Noble 2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Backlands</span> with diminishing external leverage.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Severina is genuinely interested in people -- not as performance, but as method. Understanding people is how she moves them. Where her husband commands through cold authority and implied threat, Severina operates through warmth, curiosity, and a social intelligence that most people underestimate until it is too late.</p>\n<p>She is the more politically sophisticated of the two Marcellus, and she knows it. She told <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> privately that she considers herself the real political engine of the household. She is probably correct.</p>\n<p>She wears <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> jewelry and is often seen alone.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-rook-situation\">The Rook Situation</h2>\n<p>During the worst of <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook&#39;s</a> banditry, Severina saw that her husband&#39;s pride was going to cost them everything. The garrison could not resolve the situation, and Marcellus would not admit it. So she went behind his back and hired the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> to deal with Rook.</p>\n<p>She was right. The Reclaimers destroyed Rook at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> and broke the bandit threat.</p>\n<p>Marcellus publicly humiliated her for it afterward -- a cold, controlled display staged for the garrison&#39;s benefit. She accepted it with visible grace. The political reality is that her decision saved them, and both of them know it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<h3 id=\"legate-marcellus-husband\">Legate Marcellus (Husband)</h3>\n<p>A complex marriage of political convenience that has calcified under years of frontier hardship. Severina respects her husband&#39;s competence but recognizes his limitations -- his pride, his coldness, his inability to adapt politically. He publicly humiliated her over the Reclaimer hiring, and she absorbed it without breaking. The power dynamic between them is less straightforward than it appears from the outside.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-reclaimers\">The Reclaimers</h3>\n<p>Warmer and more personal than her husband&#39;s relationship with them. Severina has invited <a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shatzi</a> and <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> to gatherings repeatedly. She is genuinely curious about them as people. She views the Reclaimers as her investment -- she hired them, they delivered, and that connection belongs to her more than to her husband.</p>\n<h3 id=\"malachor\">Malachor</h3>\n<p>Severina is fully aware of <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor&#39;s</a> feelings for her. She has made a careful study of how to use them without encouraging enough to create a problem. She values his <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> access and the information it provides. She does not value him beyond that. Malachor&#39;s infatuation is a tool she maintains with precision -- enough warmth to keep him useful, never enough to make him bold.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"political-role\">Political Role</h2>\n<p>Severina is the diplomatic face of the Marcellus household. While the Legate manages the garrison and the trade route, Severina manages relationships -- with visiting officials, with merchant contacts, with anyone whose goodwill might be converted into political capital.</p>\n<p>Her judgment on the Rook situation demonstrated that she sees threats and opportunities faster than her husband, and is willing to act on them even at personal cost. This makes her one of the most capable political operators at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, and one of the most underestimated.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Her husband, commanding officer of Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where the Marcellus household is based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The party she hired to resolve the Rook situation</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Imperial historian whose feelings she exploits strategically</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- The bandit threat she acted to resolve</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- Where the Reclaimers destroyed Rook</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-valerian</a> -- The Legate&#39;s noble house</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- Reclaimer she has cultivated a personal relationship with</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> -- Reclaimer she has invited to social gatherings</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution whose access she values through Malachor</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"legate-marcellus","title":"Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","military","legate","mithrian-military","backlands","border-forts","lakan-campaigns","house-valerian","fort-meade"],"html":"<h1 id=\"legate-titus-valerian-marcellus\">Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</h1>\n<p><strong>Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</strong> is the military commander of the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> and commanding officer of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, holding the rank of <strong>Legate</strong> within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian military</a>. He commands a garrison of approximately 100 soldiers and controls the most strategically significant chokepoint between the imperial interior and the frontier.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Titus Valerian Marcellus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td>Mithrian male</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>Late 40s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>House</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">House Valerian</span> carried weight, but it was his competence that earned his postings and his reputation.</p>\n<p>His life has been a sequence of near-achievements. Before the Emperor&#39;s garrison recall, he was positioned to parlay military success on the frontier into a Senate seat. His wife, <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severina</a>, came from wealth and influence. The Valerian name carried weight. Everything was aligned.</p>\n<p>Then the recall came. <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> blocked every request Marcellus made for reinforcements, recognition, or transfer. Severina&#39;s father died, leaving her brother -- who cares nothing for his sister -- as head of household. The political support structure that was supposed to carry Marcellus to the Senate evaporated, and he was left holding a crumbling frontier with a skeleton garrison and no path forward.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-withdrawal-378-iy\">The Withdrawal (378 IY)</h2>\n<p>Two years ago, when the great <strong>Skiotha</strong> host threatened the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, the Emperor <strong>Justinian Claudius Decimus</strong> recalled the local armies and garrisons from the Backlands. This left the province undermanned and poorly defended, and left Marcellus holding the frontier with a skeleton force.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-border-forts\">The Border Forts</h2>\n<p>The border forts under Marcellus&#39;s command were originally constructed after the failed <strong>Lakan Campaigns</strong> -- the imperial wars of subjugation against the <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> barbarians of the wastes. These fortifications were built to hold the line against future Lakandi aggression. Now, with the garrison stripped down to a fraction of its intended strength, they serve as a thin and crumbling barrier.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Cold, calculating, quietly cruel. Marcellus does not raise his voice. He does not need to. The garrison&#39;s mean streak reflects his own -- eleven years under his command have shaped <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Crull</a> and every soldier beneath him into instruments of his temperament.</p>\n<p>He is capable of genuine respect but extends it rarely and withdraws it without warning. He is not performatively harsh -- he is simply indifferent to discomfort he does not share, and efficient in applying pressure where it serves his purposes.</p>\n<p>He spends his own coin to eliminate threats and delay imperial scrutiny, understanding that every problem he solves quietly is one less excuse for the Governor to intervene in his domain.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"threats\">Threats</h2>\n<p>Marcellus faces threats on multiple fronts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> have sacked <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and are pushing farther south</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lakandi</a> are stirring in the wastes, with whispers of rebellion</li>\n<li>His forces are too few to adequately defend the border forts, let alone project power into the province</li>\n<li>No reinforcements are forthcoming from the imperial heartland</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-rook-situation-and-the-reclaimers\">The Rook Situation and the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>The resolution of the <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> situation partially restored Marcellus&#39;s position. <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severina</a> hired the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> behind his back because she saw his pride was going to cost them everything. She was right -- the Reclaimers delivered what his garrison could not, destroying Rook at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>.</p>\n<p>Marcellus publicly humiliated Severina for going behind his back -- a cold, controlled display staged for the garrison&#39;s benefit. But he is experienced enough to recognize a useful asset when he sees one. He no longer plans to discard the Reclaimers. He plans to use them for career rehabilitation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"political-position\">Political Position</h2>\n<p>Marcellus is engaged in a silent war with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- his direct superior. The Governor sits in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, content to rest on his laurels while the frontier crumbles. Marcellus uses the trade route leverage carefully: enough pressure to remind the Governor of his dependence on Fort Meade&#39;s chokepoint, not enough to justify formal reprisal.</p>\n<p>The trade route revenue funds his soldiers&#39; loyalty, his intelligence operations against the Governor, and his household expenses. The food dependency of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> on the supply caravans passing through Fort Meade is his most significant political weapon.</p>\n<h3 id=\"chain-of-command\">Chain of Command</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus</strong> -- The Emperor who recalled the armies</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a></strong> (<a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a>) -- Civil governor of the Backlands, seated in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a></li>\n<li><strong>Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus</strong> -- Military commander on the frontier</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The disconnect between the distant, inactive Governor and the embattled Legate represents one of the core tensions in the Backlands&#39; power structure.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-the-reclaimers\">Relationship with the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Professional and transactional, but with a longer horizon than before. Marcellus sees the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> as capable irregular assets -- people who can accomplish what his garrison cannot, operating outside formal military channels.</p>\n<p>He will honor agreements precisely as written and exploit any ambiguity ruthlessly. He is not an enemy, but he is not a friend. Every interaction is evaluated through the lens of what the Reclaimers can do for his career rehabilitation and what it will cost him.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-charter-proposal\">The Charter Proposal</h3>\n<p>Before the Reclaimers depart for <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, Marcellus requests a formal meeting. The message is delivered by his steward -- not <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crull</a>, not a soldier. This deliberate choice of messenger signals the nature of the conversation: this is business, not military command. Crull is not in the room. <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severina</a> is present, seated slightly to the side -- not beside him.</p>\n<p>Marcellus opens by noting the Reclaimers brought four thousand gold worth of goods through his market in a single visit. Tax exempt. He lets that sit, then presents his proposal without theatrics -- a business arrangement between parties who have worked together three weeks:</p>\n<p><strong>The Terms:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A formal charter:</strong> The Reclaimers are his licensed salvagers with exclusive territorial claim to the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. No other party operates there without their sanction.</li>\n<li><strong>A secure vault and warehouse</strong> at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, constructed at his expense, for the Reclaimers&#39; exclusive use.</li>\n<li><strong>A quarterly market fair</strong> at Fort Meade, drawing merchants from <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and <a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a>. He funds the first three years.</li>\n<li><strong>In exchange:</strong> Fifteen percent of recovered value, payable in goods or coin at their discretion. And continued availability as his agents -- tasks specified as they arise.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Negotiation Parameters:</strong></p>\n<p>Marcellus will not move on the structure. He will negotiate specifics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Percentage:</strong> Floor is ten percent. He opened at fifteen.</li>\n<li><strong>Timeline for vault construction:</strong> Movable.</li>\n<li><strong>Specifics of &quot;available when required&quot;:</strong> He will accept definition. He will also use any vagueness left in the final language.</li>\n<li><strong>He will honor exactly what is agreed. He will exploit any ambiguity in exactly what is agreed.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Severina&#39;s Role:</strong></p>\n<p>After Marcellus finishes, <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severina</a> speaks. She frames it as opportunity rather than contract -- the charter carries weight in Sanctuary as well as Fort Meade, the formalization protects what the Reclaimers have already built, the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> introductions <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> can arrange become more credible under the Legate&#39;s seal. She is warm, interested, and precise beneath the warmth. She is not selling. She is clarifying. The difference is hard to pin down.</p>\n<p><strong>What He Doesn&#39;t Say:</strong></p>\n<p>He does not say this is about <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussus</a>. He does not say that a Fort Meade with a functioning market, a growing merchant quarter, and documented gold output is a Fort Meade that no longer needs the Governor&#39;s goodwill to survive. He does not say the Reclaimers are the engine he needs to change his political position. None of this needs saying. It is all visible to anyone paying attention.</p>\n<p>Three weeks ago Marcellus was a frustrated legate using irregular assets to solve a bandit problem. He has moved faster than that framing suggests because he has been calculating since the <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> situation ended. This meeting is the result -- and the beginning of a dependency that runs in both directions. The party is becoming essential to his ambitions in a way that makes them harder to walk away from. The political transformation of Fort Meade from a crumbling frontier garrison into an independent economic power is now his project, and the Reclaimers are the engine that makes it possible.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-severina\">Relationship with Severina</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a> is the more politically sophisticated half of the household, and Marcellus is not unaware of this fact. Their marriage is a political partnership that functions despite -- or perhaps because of -- the fundamental tension between his authority and her judgment. She was right about Rook. He punished her for being right. Both of them understand what that means.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison Marcellus commands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- His wife and the household&#39;s political engine</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-crull</a> -- His senior NCO and enforcer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Imperial historian stationed at Fort Meade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province Marcellus is tasked with defending</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> -- The imperial military structure</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> -- The empire Marcellus serves</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-valerian</a> -- Marcellus&#39;s noble house</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">governor-drussus</a> -- His political rival and nominal superior</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The party he now considers a useful irregular asset</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- The bandit whose destruction partially restored Marcellus&#39;s position</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- Where the Reclaimers destroyed Rook</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi</a> -- The barbarian threat the border forts were built to contain</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- The creatures threatening the province from the north</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The sacked city whose fall worsened the frontier crisis</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">sanctuary</a> -- Where Governor Drussus sits idle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The frontier settlement dependent on Fort Meade&#39;s supply route</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">house-drussus</a> -- The governor&#39;s noble house</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"lynara","title":"Lynara","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","eladra","nightblade","malyn","apprentice","backlands","conflicted","stealth","sorcery"],"html":"<h1 id=\"lynara\">Lynara</h1>\n<p><strong>Lynara</strong> is an <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> Nightblade (level 3) and the apprentice of <a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn the Misshapen</a>. She is one of the few true Eladra encountered in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> -- golden-skinned and pale-eyed in the manner of her ancient race -- and serves as a potential gateway to understanding Malyn&#39;s secret operations.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Lynara</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Eladran</span> heritage:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Golden skin</strong> -- the warm metallic complexion of the uncorrupted Eladra, distinct from the pale white skin of the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a></li>\n<li><strong>Pale Eladran eyes</strong> -- the characteristic eyes of her kind, without the solid black of Elvora Veil-corruption</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Her appearance alone marks her as extraordinary. True Eladra are vanishingly rare in the current age. The <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> vanished without explanation. The <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> are corrupted beyond recognition. For an Eladran of apparently uncorrupted lineage to be operating in the Backlands -- as the apprentice of a reclusive, crippled mage who enslaves <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> -- raises profound questions about where she came from and what she knows.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"personality\">Personality</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Curious</strong> -- genuinely interested in the world around her, not merely following orders</li>\n<li><strong>Conflicted</strong> -- morally torn about her role serving Malyn and whatever dark purposes he pursues</li>\n<li><strong>Intelligent</strong> -- perceptive and thoughtful, capable of independent judgment</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Lynara&#39;s moral conflict is her defining characteristic. She serves <a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn the Misshapen</a> -- a mage who practices forbidden arts including alchemy and black lore, who enslaves beastmen through the <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-withered-craw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Withered Craw</a>, and who operates from paranoid seclusion. Lynara is aware enough to be troubled by this, which suggests she is neither fully complicit nor fully trapped.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role\">Role</h2>\n<p>Lynara is the <strong>gateway to Malyn&#39;s secret operations</strong>. Her conflicted nature makes her a potential point of leverage -- someone who might be turned, persuaded, or simply listened to in order to understand what Malyn is truly doing with enslaved beastmen in his hidden laboratory.</p>\n<p>Her Nightblade training makes her Malyn&#39;s eyes and hands in the field -- capable of stealth, infiltration, and sorcery in equal measure. She is the operative he sends when he cannot go himself, which, given his crippled state and reliance on illusions to move, is frequently.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</a> -- Her master, the exiled mage who enslaves beastmen</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">eladra</a> -- Her ancient race, builders of <a href=\"#/page/aodahn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Aodahn</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">Erenthis</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">elvora</a> -- The corrupted branch of her people</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The Withered Craw, Malyn&#39;s front operation</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The settlement nearest Malyn&#39;s operations</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"magister-shale","title":"Magister Cornelius Shale","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","wizard","imperial-academy","sanctuary","scholar","administrator","spires"],"html":"<h1 id=\"magister-cornelius-shale\">Magister Cornelius Shale</h1>\n<p><strong>Magister Cornelius Shale</strong> (age 64) is the Academy Regent in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, overseeing the local branch of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> housed within the Spires. A brilliant scholar and careful administrator, Shale maintains the Academy&#39;s independence through a combination of imperial protection, useful services to <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a>, and the practical fact that antagonizing a major center of magical learning is unwise.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Cornelius Shale</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>Magister; Academy Regent in <span class=\"dead-link\">Imperial Academy</span> in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and the surrounding <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. He oversees the Academy&#39;s local operations -- research, education, the provision of magical services to the provincial government, and the maintenance of the Spires as a center of sorcerous learning.</p>\n<p>The position requires a delicate balance. The Academy answers to <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>, not to the provincial governor, but Shale operates far from the capital in a province where <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a>&#39;s authority is effectively absolute. Maintaining Academy independence requires constant diplomatic skill.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-balance-of-power\">The Balance of Power</h2>\n<p>Shale maintains the Academy&#39;s autonomy through three pillars:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Imperial protection</strong> -- The Academy is an imperial institution, and its authority derives from the Emperor. Even <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> must consider the consequences of openly defying an institution that answers to <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Useful services</strong> -- Shale ensures that the Academy provides valuable magical services to the Governor and the city -- healing, divination, enchantment, and the occasional demonstration of power that reminds everyone of what a center of magical learning can do when motivated.</li>\n<li><strong>Practical deterrence</strong> -- Antagonizing a major concentration of wizards is simply unwise. The Academy may not have an army, but it has power of a different kind, and Shale ensures that this reality is understood without ever making explicit threats.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This balance is fragile. Shale walks a tightrope between institutional loyalty to the Academy, practical accommodation of the Governor, and the preservation of his own authority within the Spires.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-foundations\">The Foundations</h2>\n<p>Shale has <strong>privately sealed several passages</strong> in the Foundations of the Spires that the previous Regent left open. The Foundations -- the deep substructure beneath the Academy&#39;s towers -- contain passages, chambers, and connections whose full extent is not publicly known. The previous Regent&#39;s decision to leave certain passages accessible was either negligent or deliberate; Shale&#39;s decision to seal them suggests he discovered something in those passages that he judged too dangerous, too sensitive, or too politically inconvenient to leave accessible.</p>\n<p>What lies in the sealed passages, and why the previous Regent left them open, are questions that Shale does not discuss.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Shale is a <strong>brilliant scholar</strong> whose intellectual interests range across multiple disciplines of sorcerous study. He is also a <strong>careful administrator</strong> -- a man who understands that maintaining the Academy&#39;s position in a province ruled by a military strongman requires patience, diplomacy, and the occasional strategic concession.</p>\n<p>He is not a confrontational man. He does not make threats, does not engage in political theatrics, and does not seek public attention. He manages through competence, quiet authority, and the understanding that the best way to preserve institutional power is to make that power indispensable.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Imperial Academy</a> -- the institution he represents</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- the provincial power he must navigate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city where he is stationed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magic and Sorcery</a> -- the forces he studies and wields</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Nethercity</a> -- the deep structures beneath Sanctuary</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"malachor","title":"Malachor, Imperial Historian","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","scholar","imperial-academy","fort-meade","backlands","mithrian","artifacts"],"html":"<h1 id=\"malachor-imperial-historian\">Malachor, Imperial Historian</h1>\n<p><strong>Malachor</strong> is a member of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> stationed at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, sent to the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> to document the province&#39;s history and catalogue recovered artifacts. He is a man of genuine intelligence operating in service of poor judgment.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Malachor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td>Mithrian male</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>50s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Scholar 4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Backlands</span> by the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> to document the province&#39;s history and catalogue recovered artifacts. His knowledge of the First Empire and the Argollean period is deep and real -- this is not contested by anyone who has worked with him. The Academy&#39;s interest in the Backlands centers on the ruins at <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>, both of which contain artifacts of significant historical and political value.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"severina\">Severina</h2>\n<p>The complication in Malachor&#39;s life -- the one that distorts everything else -- is <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a>, whom he loves with the particular desperation of a man who has talked himself into believing the feeling is mutual when it is entirely strategic on her part.</p>\n<p>Severina is fully aware of his feelings. She has made a careful study of how to use them without encouraging enough to create a problem. She values his <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> access and the information it provides. She does not value him beyond that.</p>\n<p>During the worst of the <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> situation, Malachor privately hoped that <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Legate</a> would be killed. He did nothing to prevent it, either. He told himself this was neutrality. It was not.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood\">The Argollean Brotherhood</h2>\n<p>Malachor is aware of the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood&#39;s</a> presence in <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>. He finds them deeply objectionable. Both he and the Brotherhood are interested in the same artifacts -- relics of the First Empire recovered from <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>.</p>\n<p>The Brotherhood regards the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> as a body that believes ancient <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> heritage belongs to the Empire rather than to its descendants. Malachor considers their perspective provincial and ungrateful.</p>\n<p>The two factions want the same things. They will not cooperate. Neither will move openly against the other -- for now.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-the-reclaimers\">Relationship with the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Complex and potentially very useful -- for Malachor. He wants everything the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> recover from the <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> ruins and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. He will be charming. He will be generous with information. He will be entirely focused on what he can extract from the relationship.</p>\n<p>The Reclaimers represent access to sites and artifacts Malachor cannot reach on his own. His approach will be to make himself indispensable as an expert while positioning himself to claim or copy everything of value.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-eolande-revelation\">The Eolande Revelation</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-urgency\">The Urgency</h3>\n<p>When the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> returned from <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Black Tree</a>, Malachor approached within hours -- not through a steward, not through <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcellus</a>. Directly, and with barely-composed urgency. He had heard enough from garrison talk to know something significant happened. He needed confirmation. Then everything.</p>\n<p>His questions reveal the scope of what the party witnessed and the scholarly priorities of a man who recognizes a discovery of civilizational importance:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What language did <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a> speak? Did he understand Mithrian, or only the old tongue?</li>\n<li>How coherent was he -- did he seem aware of time passing? Does he know the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> has fallen?</li>\n<li>What did he say about the <strong>Womb Curse</strong>? About the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>? About <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a>?</li>\n<li><strong>The sword.</strong> Every detail. Does it bear any inscription?</li>\n<li><strong>The dryad</strong> -- is the tree alive? Is she bound to the dead wood, or to something that remains in it?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These are not idle questions. A living witness to the Eladran civilization at its height -- a general who served the Great Teacher -- changes the entire calculus of <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> research, imperial history, and the theological understanding of the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>, the <a href=\"#/page/elvora\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvora</a>, and the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> tradition.</p>\n<h3 id=\"his-ask\">His Ask</h3>\n<p>Malachor wants to accompany the party to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. He frames this as mutual convenience -- he has contacts at the Academy chapter there, and what the party has witnessed constitutes academic testimony of enormous value.</p>\n<p>For <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> specifically: Malachor offers an introduction to senior Academy figures, vouched by him, with the Reclaimers&#39; testimony behind it. For a man expelled from the Academy for the blackness of his studies, a vouched introduction from an active Academy member with testimony of a discovery like Eolande behind it -- that is not nothing. Malachor is careful about how he phrases this, but the offer is clear.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-expedition\">The Expedition</h3>\n<p>Malachor is already forming an expedition to return to the Black Tree: two Academy assistants he intends to summon to Sanctuary, himself, and the Reclaimers as escort into <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. He presents this as something to finalize after they return from Sanctuary. He will push on every subsequent encounter. The man is driven now in a way his earlier scholarly work never drove him. This is the discovery of a lifetime, and he knows it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-dispatch\">The Dispatch</h3>\n<p>That night, Malachor writes the most significant dispatch of his career. His secret third-party contact has received dry academic reports for years. This is different, and he knows it the moment he finishes writing. He sends it before fully considering what he has set in motion.</p>\n<p>Whatever that contact represents -- and their identity remains unknown -- they now know about <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a>. An Eladran general from 3000 BE, still present at the Black Tree after five thousand years. Malachor&#39;s report to this buyer has always been a transaction: information for money, with leverage accumulating on both sides. This dispatch is qualitatively different. This is the kind of intelligence that changes relationships, realigns priorities, and draws attention Malachor may not be prepared to manage.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"secrets\">Secrets</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><strong>SECRET:</strong> Malachor has been selling copies of his academic reports to a third party -- not the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a>, someone else -- for reasons that began as financial and have become something he is no longer fully in control of. The identity of this buyer and the nature of their leverage over Malachor remain unknown. <strong>His most recent dispatch -- the Eolande report -- is the most significant piece of intelligence he has ever transmitted. He sent it before fully considering the consequences.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><strong>SECRET:</strong> Malachor knows that <a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn</a> is practicing magic. He has not reported this. He plans to use the knowledge as leverage against Malyn when the time is right.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where Malachor is stationed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The scholarly institution he represents</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- The woman he loves, who uses him strategically</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Severina&#39;s husband, whom Malachor secretly hoped would die</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The rival faction interested in the same artifacts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The party whose discoveries he intends to exploit</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- Ruins containing artifacts of interest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- Underground site containing artifacts of significant value</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn</a> -- Reclaimer whose secret magic practice Malachor knows about</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">eolande</a> -- The ancient Eladran general whose existence Malachor has now reported</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> -- Site of the Black Tree where Eolande was found</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> -- Reclaimer offered Academy introductions as leverage</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province Malachor was sent to document</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"malyn-the-misshapen","title":"Malyn the Misshapen","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","mage","mithrian","exiled","reclusive","backlands","scalpers","withered-craw","alchemy","illusion","beastmen"],"html":"<h1 id=\"malyn-the-misshapen\">Malyn the Misshapen</h1>\n<p><strong>Malyn the Misshapen</strong> is an exiled <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> mage of considerable power, operating in secret from a hidden location in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. Bitter, paranoid, and deeply reclusive, Malyn was crippled by a failed spell that left his body twisted and broken. He compensates for his physical deformity through the use of <strong>illusions to move</strong>, masking his true, wretched appearance and projecting false images of mobility where his ruined body cannot carry him.</p>\n<p>Malyn is a practitioner of forbidden arts, including <strong>alchemy</strong> and <strong>black lore</strong>, and has turned his intellect toward the enslavement of <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> rather than their destruction. He secretly controls the <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-withered-craw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Withered Craw</a></strong> Scalper group, using them as a front to capture and enslave beastmen for his own dark purposes — a stark contrast to the other Scalper gangs, who hunt beastmen for the Imperial Bounty.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Mage 7</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>8</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>18</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+2-(staff,-1d6)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>int</strong></td>-<td>17</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"spells\">spells</h2>-<p>malyn-commands-a-dangerous-repertoire-of-arcane-magic,-including:</p>-<ul>-<li><strong>charm</strong>-—-bending-the-will-of-others-to-his-command</li>-<li><strong>shield</strong>-—-a-defensive-ward-of-magical-force</li>-<li><strong>invisibility</strong>-—-concealment-from-sight,-useful-for-his-reclusive-operations</li>-<li><strong>fireball</strong>-—-raw-destructive-power;-his-most-dangerous-offensive-spell</li>-</ul>-<p>his-spell-list-reflects-a-mage-who-values-control,-concealment,-and-devastating-retaliation-when-cornered.-combined-with-his-high-intelligence-of-17,-malyn-is-a-formidable-magical-threat-despite-his-physical-frailty.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>alchemy</strong>-—-malyn-is-a-skilled-alchemist,-likely-producing-concoctions-that-aid-in-the-subjugation-and-control-of-beastmen,-as-well-as-compounds-for-his-own-sustenance-and-survival</li>-<li><strong>beast-lore</strong>-—-deep-knowledge-of-beastman-physiology,-behavior,-and-weaknesses;-essential-to-his-enslavement-operations</li>-<li><strong>black-lore</strong>-—-forbidden-knowledge-of-dark-and-proscribed-magical-traditions;-marks-malyn-as-someone-who-has-crossed-lines-that-most-mages-would-not-dare-approach</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"personality-and-demeanor\">personality-and-demeanor</h2>-<p>malyn-is-defined-by-three-core-traits:-<strong>bitterness</strong>,-<strong>paranoia</strong>,-and-<strong>reclusiveness</strong>.-the-failed-spell-that-crippled-him-appears-to-have-broken-more-than-his-body-—-it-shattered-whatever-social-bonds-or-moral-restraints-he-once-possessed.-he-trusts-no-one-fully,-keeps-his-location-secret,-and-operates-entirely-through-intermediaries-and-proxies.</p>-<p>his-use-of-illusions-to-mask-his-deformity-and-simulate-movement-suggests-a-deep-vanity-or-shame-about-his-condition.-he-is-not-a-man-who-has-accepted-his-fate-—-he-is-one-who-rages-against-it,-using-every-tool-at-his-disposal-to-maintain-power-and-relevance-despite-his-broken-form.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"operations\">operations</h2>-<h3-id=\"the-withered-craw\">the-withered-craw</h3>-<p>malyn-secretly-controls-the-<strong>[[scalper-gangs#the-withered-craw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Withered Craw</a></strong>, a Scalper group that operates under the guise of hunting beastmen for the Imperial Bounty. In reality, the Withered Craw <strong>enslaves beastmen</strong> rather than killing them, capturing them alive and delivering them to Malyn for purposes unknown. This operation is a closely guarded secret — if it were discovered, it would draw the wrath of every other Scalper gang in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, as well as the attention of imperial authorities.</p>\n<p>The enslavement operation suggests Malyn has a use for live beastmen — whether as subjects for magical experimentation, labor for some hidden project, or components in alchemical processes. Whatever the purpose, it is almost certainly forbidden.</p>\n<h3 id=\"malachors-leverage\">Malachor&#39;s Leverage</h3>\n<p><strong>Malachor</strong> is aware that Malyn is practicing magic — a dangerous secret in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, where unlicensed sorcery is viewed with deep suspicion and hostility. Malachor <strong>plans to use this knowledge as leverage</strong> against Malyn, creating a volatile dynamic between the two. Malyn&#39;s paranoia is not unfounded; there are those who know his secrets and intend to exploit them.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"lynara-apprentice\">Lynara — Apprentice</h2>\n<p>Malyn has taken an apprentice: <strong>Lynara</strong>, a young <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> Nightblade who serves as his eyes, hands, and agent in the world beyond his hidden sanctum. Lynara is the <strong>gateway to Malyn&#39;s secret operations</strong> — anyone seeking to uncover or interact with Malyn&#39;s network will almost certainly encounter Lynara first.</p>\n<h3 id=\"lynaras-statistics\">Lynara&#39;s Statistics</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Nightblade 3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>4</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>13</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>dex</strong></td>-<td>16</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<h3-id=\"lynaras-spells\">lynara&#39;s-spells</h3>-<ul>-<li><strong>sleep</strong>-—-incapacitating-targets-without-bloodshed;-ideal-for-capturing-beastmen-alive</li>-<li><strong>darkness</strong>-—-tactical-concealment;-creating-zones-of-impenetrable-shadow</li>-</ul>-<h3-id=\"lynaras-skills\">lynara&#39;s-skills</h3>-<ul>-<li><strong>stealth</strong>-—-10+-(highly-proficient;-capable-of-moving-unseen-in-most-environments)</li>-<li><strong>trap-find</strong>-—-12+-(skilled-at-detecting-and-disarming-traps;-useful-in-dungeon-and-ruin-exploration)</li>-</ul>-<h3-id=\"lynaras-proficiencies\">lynara&#39;s-proficiencies</h3>-<ul>-<li><strong>skulduggery</strong>-—-the-arts-of-deception,-infiltration,-and-criminal-enterprise</li>-<li><strong>engineering</strong>-—-practical-knowledge-of-structures,-mechanisms,-and-construction;-unusual-for-a-nightblade-and-likely-reflecting-malyn&#39;s-influence</li>-</ul>-<h3-id=\"lynaras-appearance-and-personality\">lynara&#39;s-appearance-and-personality</h3>-<p>lynara-possesses-the-distinctive-features-of-the-[[races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> race: <strong>golden skin</strong> and <strong>pale Eladran eyes</strong> that mark her as unmistakably non-human. She is <strong>curious</strong>, <strong>intelligent</strong>, and <strong>conflicted</strong> — drawn to Malyn&#39;s knowledge and power but <strong>morally torn</strong> by the nature of his work. This internal conflict makes her a complex figure who could potentially be turned against her master, or who might grow deeper into his dark practices depending on outside influence.</p>\n<p>Lynara represents the most accessible point of contact with Malyn&#39;s operations. She is the face of the Withered Craw in the field, and her moral uncertainty makes her a potential ally, informant, or adversary depending on how she is approached.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Enslaved Beastmen</strong> — What is Malyn doing with the beastmen captured by the Withered Craw? Investigation into disappearing beastman captives could lead back to Malyn&#39;s operation.</li>\n<li><strong>Malachor&#39;s Gambit</strong> — Malachor&#39;s plan to leverage Malyn&#39;s secret magic practice creates a three-way tension that players could exploit or be caught in.</li>\n<li><strong>Lynara&#39;s Conflict</strong> — Lynara&#39;s moral uncertainty makes her a potential point of leverage. A party that earns her trust could gain access to Malyn&#39;s secrets — or turn her against him entirely.</li>\n<li><strong>The Failed Spell</strong> — What spell did Malyn attempt that crippled him? The answer could lead to lost magical knowledge, a cursed artifact, or a dangerous location.</li>\n<li><strong>Forbidden Alchemy</strong> — Malyn&#39;s combination of alchemy, beast lore, and black lore suggests he may be attempting something unprecedented and deeply dangerous.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — Overview of Scalper gangs, including the Withered Craw</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-withered-craw\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Withered Craw</a> — Malyn&#39;s secretly controlled Scalper group</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement nearest to Malyn&#39;s operations</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province where Malyn operates in hiding</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures Malyn enslaves through the Withered Craw</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran</a> — Lynara&#39;s race</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/magic-and-sorcery\" class=\"wiki-link\">magic-and-sorcery</a> — The magical traditions Malyn practices</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — The ruined city that spawned the Scalper trade</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"marcos-varanes","title":"Marcos Varanes (\"The Measure\")","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","paladin","mithrian","zealot","bleak-sons","seros","scalper","backlands","bone-creek","militant"],"html":"<h1 id=\"marcos-varanes-the-measure\">Marcos Varanes (&quot;The Measure&quot;)</h1>\n<p><strong>Marcos Varanes</strong>, known as <strong>&quot;The Measure,&quot;</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> paladin and the leader of the <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-bleak-sons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bleak Sons</a></strong>, a Scalper gang driven not by profit but by <strong>zealous religious conviction</strong>. Varanes is a fanatical militant of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, the god of justice, law, and the balanced scale. He views the hunting of <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> not as a mercenary enterprise but as a <strong>holy crusade</strong> — a divine mandate to purge the unclean from the lands of the Empire.</p>\n<p>Varanes is a <strong>possible ally or fanatic adversary</strong> — his rigid devotion to his faith makes him a powerful and reliable partner for those who share his cause, but an implacable and terrifying enemy for those who fall short of his exacting moral standards or stand in the way of his divine mission.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Paladin 5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>1</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>38</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+5-(morning-star,-1d8+2)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>str</strong></td>-<td>17</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>varanes-is-the-most-formidable-physical-combatant-among-the-scalper-gang-leaders.-his-ac-of-1-—-the-best-armor-class-of-any-npc-in-this-tier-—-indicates-full-plate-armor-or-its-equivalent,-likely-maintained-with-religious-devotion-as-a-symbol-of-his-faith.-his-38-hit-points-make-him-extraordinarily-durable,-his-+5-attack-bonus-is-the-highest-among-the-gang-leaders,-and-his-morning-star-dealing-1d8+2-damage-makes-every-swing-a-bone-crushing-blow.-his-strength-of-17-is-the-raw-physical-power-of-a-man-built-for-war-in-the-name-of-his-god.</p>-<p>as-a-paladin,-varanes-likely-possesses-additional-abilities-beyond-his-listed-statistics-—-including-the-ability-to-detect-evil,-lay-on-hands-for-healing,-and-project-an-aura-of-courage-that-bolsters-his-followers.-these-abilities,-combined-with-his-raw-combat-power,-make-him-a-nearly-unstoppable-force-on-the-battlefield.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>intimidation</strong>-—-the-ability-to-cow-and-coerce-through-force-of-presence-and-implied-violence.-varanes-does-not-use-intimidation-for-criminal-purposes-—-he-uses-it-as-a-weapon-of-righteous-authority,-compelling-the-wicked-to-submit-or-flee.-when-a-seven-foot-paladin-in-full-plate-armor-points-a-blood-stained-morning-star-at-you-and-invokes-the-judgment-of-[[seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, intimidation comes naturally.</li>\n<li><strong>Theology</strong> — Deep knowledge of religious doctrine, scripture, and divine law. Varanes is not merely a warrior who prays — he is a scholar of his faith, capable of citing chapter and verse to justify his actions and condemn his enemies. His theological knowledge gives him the authority to lead the Bleak Sons as both a military and spiritual commander.</li>\n<li><strong>Divine Blessing</strong> — The ability to invoke divine favor upon allies and followers. This proficiency marks Varanes as a true conduit of divine power — not merely a devout believer, but a man through whom the power of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> flows. His blessings strengthen his followers and reinforce their conviction that they fight in the service of a just god.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">Appearance and Demeanor</h2>\n<p>Varanes is <strong>zealous</strong>, <strong>righteous</strong>, and <strong>commanding</strong> — three qualities that, in combination, produce a leader of terrible conviction and absolute certainty. He does not doubt. He does not hesitate. He does not compromise. The Measure sees the world in stark terms of justice and injustice, purity and corruption, the righteous and the damned — and he has appointed himself the instrument of divine reckoning.</p>\n<p>His epithet — <strong>&quot;The Measure&quot;</strong> — refers to <a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Measure and the Scale</a>, the central symbol of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. Varanes sees himself as the living embodiment of divine judgment: he weighs the deeds of men and finds them wanting or worthy, and he acts accordingly. This is not arrogance in his mind — it is duty, a burden placed upon him by his god.</p>\n<p>Varanes wears a <strong>bronze scale fetish</strong> — an amulet bearing the image of the balanced scale of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. This amulet is both a symbol of his faith and a focus for his divine power. It likely serves as his holy symbol, and its bronze construction suggests durability, weight, and permanence — qualities Varanes embodies.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-bleak-sons\">The Bleak Sons</h2>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-bleak-sons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bleak Sons</a></strong> are a Scalper gang unlike the others. Where most gangs are motivated by gold, survival, or personal ambition, the Bleak Sons are driven by <strong>religious fanaticism</strong>. They are followers of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> who believe that the hunting of beastmen is a sacred duty — a divine trial set before them by their god to test their faith and purify the land.</p>\n<p>Under Varanes&#39;s leadership, the Bleak Sons operate with <strong>military discipline</strong> and <strong>religious fervor</strong>. They are organized, methodical, and absolutely committed to their cause. They do not drink to excess, they do not consort with the working girls of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, and they do not engage in the casual brutality and debauchery that characterizes many Scalper gangs. They are, in many ways, the most disciplined and effective fighting force in the Backlands.</p>\n<p>However, their fanaticism is also their greatest weakness. The Bleak Sons&#39; rigid moral code makes them inflexible and judgmental — they view other Scalpers as sinners and degenerates, and they have no tolerance for moral ambiguity. This alienates potential allies and creates friction with every other faction in the Backlands.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"faith-and-fanaticism\">Faith and Fanaticism</h2>\n<p>Varanes&#39;s devotion to <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> is absolute and uncompromising. He believes that:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>The beastman scourge is a divine trial</strong> — a test set by Seros to separate the worthy from the unworthy</li>\n<li><strong>The hunting of beastmen is a sacred duty</strong> — not merely a profitable enterprise, but a holy crusade ordained by the god of justice</li>\n<li><strong>Those who do not meet the standard of righteousness are complicit in evil</strong> — moral neutrality is a form of sin, and those who tolerate corruption enable it</li>\n<li><strong>He is the instrument of divine judgment</strong> — The Measure by which all are weighed</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This fanaticism makes Varanes both admirable and terrifying. His courage is genuine, his conviction is unshakeable, and his dedication to his cause is absolute. But his inability to tolerate imperfection, his certainty in his own righteousness, and his willingness to use force against anyone he judges unworthy make him a danger to friend and foe alike.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-the-house-of-silence\">Relationship to the House of Silence</h2>\n<p>The <strong>House of Silence</strong> in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a> is the church of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>, currently led by the young priest <strong><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a></strong>. Varanes&#39;s relationship with Marco is potentially complex — both serve the same god, but their approaches to faith could not be more different. Marco is a quiet, devoted priest who draws followers through sincerity and suffering. Varanes is a militant crusader who draws followers through strength and conviction.</p>\n<p>Whether these two servants of Seros will find common cause or come into conflict is a question of significant importance for the spiritual future of Bone Creek.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ally or Adversary</strong> — The Bleak Sons are the most disciplined and effective Scalper gang. An alliance with Varanes could be enormously valuable — but the price is conformity to his exacting moral standards. Failure to meet those standards turns a powerful ally into a righteous enemy.</li>\n<li><strong>The Crusade</strong> — Varanes views the beastman hunts as a holy war. What happens when his crusade extends beyond beastmen to include humans he judges unworthy? The Scalper gangs, the criminals, the corrupt — all could fall under his wrathful gaze.</li>\n<li><strong>The Measure and the Scale</strong> — Varanes&#39;s epithet and his bronze scale amulet connect him directly to the deepest doctrines of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a>. Does he truly embody the god&#39;s will, or has his fanaticism distorted the faith into something its founder would not recognize?</li>\n<li><strong>Brother Marco</strong> — Two servants of Seros in the same settlement, with radically different approaches to their faith. Will they unite or divide? Will Varanes accept Marco&#39;s gentle authority, or will he see the young priest as weak and unworthy?</li>\n<li><strong>Corruption</strong> — The veteran Scalpers bear marks of corruption. What happens when a paladin of Seros — a man dedicated to purity and righteousness — discovers signs of corruption in his own followers? Or in himself?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-bleak-sons\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Bleak Sons</a> — Varanes&#39;s fanatical Scalper gang</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> — The god of justice and the balanced scale; Varanes&#39;s patron deity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-measure-and-the-scale\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-measure-and-the-scale</a> — The central doctrine of Seros&#39;s faith</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> — The priest of Seros at the House of Silence in Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures the Bleak Sons hunt as a holy crusade</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> — The empire whose bounty the Bleak Sons view as divinely ordained</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"marcus-valerian","title":"Marcus Valerian","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["historical","emperor","first-emperor","founder","house-valerian","bellasarius","mithrian-empire","mithra-city"],"html":"<h1 id=\"marcus-valerian\">Marcus Valerian</h1>\n<p><strong>Marcus Valerian</strong> was the first Emperor of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>, claiming descent from the legendary war-chief [[#Bellasarius Valerian]]. In 1 IY, Marcus seized power from the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a>, defeated loyalist Senator armies on the battlefield, and consolidated authority under a single throne. The Senate was preserved as a deliberative body but stripped of binding legislative power. His coup transformed the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian League</a> -- a confederation of free city-states -- into an empire, and established <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> as the seat of power, governance, and sorcerous learning that it remains to this day.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Marcus Valerian</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>First Emperor of Mithra</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>House</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">house-valerian</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Claimed Descent</strong></td>\n<td>[[</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Ascension</strong></td>\n<td>1 IY</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Dead</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-founding-of-the-empire\">The Founding of the Empire</h2>\n<p>Marcus Valerian&#39;s seizure of power was not a peaceful transition. The <a href=\"#/page/imperial-senate\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Senate</a> of the Mithrian League was a powerful institution, and many Senators refused to accept the abolition of their authority. Marcus defeated the armies raised by loyalist Senators in a series of campaigns that demonstrated both his military ability and his political ruthlessness. Those who submitted were brought into the new order. Those who did not were destroyed.</p>\n<p>The founding of the Empire marked the beginning of a new era -- the Imperial Year (IY) calendar -- and established the political framework that has endured for nearly four centuries. The Senate was preserved but neutered, allowed to deliberate but stripped of the power to bind the Emperor&#39;s decisions. Real authority resided in the throne, enforced by the legions and the bureaucracy that Marcus constructed.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"bellasarius-valerian\">Bellasarius Valerian</h2>\n<p>Marcus claimed descent from <strong>Bellasarius Valerian</strong>, the war-chief who fought alongside the <a href=\"#/page/enador\" class=\"wiki-link\">Prophet Enador</a> during the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean War</a> (663 BE). Bellasarius was the military architect of the alliance that overthrew the <a href=\"#/page/massaran-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Massaran Empire</a>, scattered the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> legions, and drove the tyrant-sorcerer Sebek into exile. His name is among the most revered in Mithrian history.</p>\n<p>Whether Marcus&#39;s claimed descent was genuine or fabricated is a matter of historical debate. What is beyond dispute is that the claim gave Marcus a legitimacy that no other aspirant to power could match. The Valerian name -- synonymous with the liberation of Mithrapos from Massaran tyranny -- was the foundation upon which the Empire was built.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/vestari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Vestari</a> people trace their lineage directly to Bellasarius Valerian, a claimed descent that gives them an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>Marcus Valerian&#39;s legacy is the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> itself. For centuries after his founding, <a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> held the Imperial throne as a near-birthright, producing a long line of Emperors who ruled with varying degrees of competence and virtue. The dynasty&#39;s decline -- culminating in the madness of <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> -- eventually broke the Valerian hold on power, but the Empire Marcus built endures.</p>\n<p>The founding of the Empire also set the template for the tension between imperial authority and senatorial power that has defined Mithrian politics ever since. Every subsequent Emperor has had to navigate the same fundamental question that Marcus answered with force: who truly rules -- the one who wears the crown, or the many who surround the throne?</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-valerian\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Valerian</a> -- the dynasty Marcus founded</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/empyrean-war\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Empyrean War</a> -- the war fought by his ancestor Bellasarius</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Mithrian Empire</a> -- the state he created</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> -- the capital he established</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor Aurex</a> -- the mad Emperor who ended the Valerian dynasty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/war-of-three-emperors\" class=\"wiki-link\">War of Three Emperors</a> -- the civil war that followed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/history-of-mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">History of Mithrapos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-kalomenes\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Kalomenes</a> -- the house he defeated to seize power</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"noma","title":"Noma of the Shallows","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","fort-harvald","mystery","backlands","nethercity","hermit","supernatural","corcanoa"],"html":"<h1 id=\"noma-of-the-shallows\">Noma of the Shallows</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;On a foggy morning the towers of Crossings rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man. The old ones say you can hear it breathing.&quot;</em>\n-- local saying from <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Noma of the Shallows</strong> is a solitary figure who lives apart from the settlement of <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a>, on a platform structure built over a backwater channel in the marshes of the delta. She is one of the most enigmatic and potentially significant individuals in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> -- a person whose very existence raises questions that the settlement around her is not equipped to answer.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"overview\">Overview</h2>\n<p>Noma&#39;s race is unknown. Her age is unknown. She speaks with what might be a <a href=\"#/page/corcanoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Corcanoan</a> accent -- though even this is uncertain, as accents blur and shift in the frontier, and Noma&#39;s speech patterns may be archaic rather than regional.</p>\n<p>She worships something old. Something that has <strong>no name</strong>. Her devotional practices do not fit within the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> theological framework, nor within the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> traditions, nor within any of the folk religions or syncretic cults that populate the margins of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. Whatever Noma prays to, whatever she communes with, it predates the organized religions of <a href=\"#/page/mithrapos\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrapos</a> -- or exists outside them entirely.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-problem-of-time\">The Problem of Time</h2>\n<p>Noma has lived at the shallows <strong>longer than anyone can remember</strong>. The people of <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> speak of her as though she has always been there -- as though the marshes and Noma are inseparable, as though the platform over the backwater channel is as permanent a feature of the landscape as the delta itself.</p>\n<p>This is a problem, because Fort Harvald is only <strong>a few years old</strong>. The settlement coalesced after the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> in 377 IY. Before that, there was nothing here but the abandoned border fort and the marshes. Noma was here before the refugees came, before the settlement existed, before the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">sacking</a>. She was here when there was no one and nothing to be here for.</p>\n<p>How long Noma has lived in the shallows is unknown. What sustained her alone in the delta marshes, with the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> on the horizon and the <a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Beastmen</a> herds in the wilderness, is unknown. Why she chose this place -- or whether she chose it at all -- is unknown.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"knowledge-of-the-nethercity\">Knowledge of the Nethercity</h2>\n<p>Noma <strong>knows what lies in the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a></strong> -- the vast subterranean complex beneath the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> that dates back to the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a>, thousands of years before the founding of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. The Nethercity contains the Grand Cthonic Temple, the Great King Tomb of the warlord Marcan, the Secret Sepulcher where the Great Teacher entered cryostasis, the Secret Tomb of the mummy lord Orthanach, the Doom Temple of <a href=\"#/page/dirgion\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dirgion</a>, and the Hallowed Halls of Heroes -- among untold other chambers, passages, and horrors that have accumulated over millennia.</p>\n<p>How Noma possesses this knowledge is unknown. Whether she has been inside the Nethercity, whether she has communed with something within it, or whether her knowledge comes from a source entirely outside the understanding of the settlement&#39;s inhabitants is unclear.</p>\n<p>Noma <strong>may not say freely</strong> what she knows. Those who seek her out may find that her knowledge comes at a price, or with conditions, or wrapped in riddles and warnings that only make sense when it is too late to act on them. She is not hostile. She is not helpful. She is something else -- something that does not map onto the categories that the people of Fort Harvald use to understand the world.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"dwelling\">Dwelling</h2>\n<p>Noma&#39;s home is a platform structure built over a backwater channel, separated from the main settlement by water and marsh. The construction is rough but sturdy -- built for permanence in a landscape that erodes everything. The platform sits above the waterline, accessible by boat or by picking a careful path through the shallows. The surrounding marsh is thick with reeds, still water, and the ambient sounds of the delta.</p>\n<p>The isolation is deliberate. Noma lives apart. She does not come into the settlement. Those who wish to speak with her must come to her.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-fort-harvald\">Role in Fort Harvald</h2>\n<p>Noma occupies no formal role in the settlement of <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a>. She holds no position, exercises no authority, and participates in none of the settlement&#39;s social or economic structures. She is known to the people of Fort Harvald in the way that a landmark is known -- as something that is simply there, that was there before you arrived, and that will be there after you leave.</p>\n<p>Some of the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> in the Refugee Quarter regard her with superstitious unease. Others treat her with a wary respect that borders on reverence. <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Voss</a> is aware of her existence but has not investigated -- he has enough problems without adding a mysterious hermit to his concerns. <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Ossian</a> at the Shrine of the Unnamed has never spoken with her, though the supernatural events at his shrine and Noma&#39;s presence in the marshes may not be unrelated.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"significance\">Significance</h2>\n<p>Noma of the Shallows represents several converging mysteries:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Temporal anomaly</strong> -- She has been here longer than the settlement, in a place that had no reason to sustain a solitary inhabitant. Her presence predates the context that would explain it.</li>\n<li><strong>Religious mystery</strong> -- She worships something with no name, outside all known theological frameworks. This suggests a tradition older than the <a href=\"#/page/empyrean-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Empyrean</a> and <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> systems -- or something that exists outside the theological spectrum entirely.</li>\n<li><strong>Knowledge of the Nethercity</strong> -- She knows what lies beneath <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, knowledge that should be inaccessible to anyone outside the most senior circles of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> or the <a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cthonic</a> cults. The source of this knowledge is unknown.</li>\n<li><strong>Connection to something deeper</strong> -- Her presence, her knowledge, and her worship point toward something beneath the surface of the world -- something that the ruins of Crossings, the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>, and the ancient history of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> are all connected to.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> -- The settlement near which Noma lives</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- The ruined city visible from the shallows</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The ancient subterranean complex Noma knows of</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> -- The catastrophe that created the settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-voss\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sergeant Aldric Voss</a> -- Fort Harvald&#39;s commanding officer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Ossian</a> -- Keeper of the Shrine of the Unnamed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Empire</a> -- The ancient civilization that built the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/corcanoan\" class=\"wiki-link\">Corcanoa</a> -- Possible origin of Noma&#39;s accent</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- The frontier region</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"prelate-voth","title":"Prelate Severan Voth","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","cleric","religious-leader","temple","thousand-temples","unconquered-sun","sanctuary","sunward","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"prelate-severan-voth\">Prelate Severan Voth</h1>\n<p><strong>Prelate Severan Voth</strong> is the head of the <a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple of the Unconquered Sun</a> in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and the highest-ranking religious authority in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. At 73, he has led the Temple for twenty years, shaping it into a political force that serves as the primary check on the Governor&#39;s secular power. He is widely respected even by non-followers -- and widely feared by those who have crossed him.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Severan Voth</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td>Mithrian male</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>73</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Cleric 13</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Hit Points</strong></td>\n<td>76</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Armor Class</strong></td>\n<td>4 (plate + shield)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Attack</strong></td>\n<td>+9</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Damage</strong></td>\n<td>1d8+3 (mace)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Special</strong></td>\n<td>7th level casting, Turn Undead, Divine Authority</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>Prelate of the <span class=\"dead-link\">Sanctuary</span>, behind only <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus&#39;s</a> apparatus. The Grand Temple in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sunward</a> seats 3,000 worshippers. The monastic orders are disciplined and well-funded. The Healing House provides essential services to the poor. And the Temple&#39;s intelligence network -- built on confessionals, charitable works, and the simple fact that people trust priests -- rivals the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand&#39;s</a> in reach and surpasses it in reliability.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Voth is <strong>not a moral absolutist</strong>, despite what his enemies claim. He is a <strong>pragmatist</strong> who believes the Temple&#39;s role is to serve as a check on secular power, to maintain standards of justice and decency, and to preserve the faith. He will compromise when necessary -- but carefully and strategically, never in haste and never in public.</p>\n<p>His moral framework is <strong>the Temple&#39;s welfare</strong>, not universal justice. He will protect the institution, advance its interests, and preserve its authority. If that means tolerating a degree of corruption in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> or turning a blind eye to the Governor&#39;s more questionable methods, he will do so -- provided the balance of power is maintained and the Temple&#39;s position is not diminished.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>not corrupt</strong>. He does not enrich himself. He does not abuse his position for personal gain. But he is deeply, thoroughly <strong>political</strong>. Every decision he makes is filtered through the lens of institutional survival and institutional power.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-temples-intelligence-network\">The Temple&#39;s Intelligence Network</h2>\n<p>Voth has access to information rivaling the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand&#39;s</a> network. His sources include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Confessionals</strong> -- The faithful share their sins, their fears, and their knowledge of others&#39; sins and fears</li>\n<li><strong>Charitable works</strong> -- The Healing House, Pilgrim&#39;s House, and Temple alms-giving put Temple agents in contact with every stratum of society</li>\n<li><strong>Monastic orders</strong> -- Disciplined, loyal, and discreet, the monks serve as eyes and ears throughout the city</li>\n<li><strong>Agents throughout the city</strong> -- Lay members of the faith who report to the Temple hierarchy</li>\n<li><strong>Diplomatic contacts</strong> -- The Temple&#39;s network extends beyond <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> to other temples and religious institutions across the region</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This intelligence capability is one of Voth&#39;s greatest assets. He often knows about events before the Governor does, and he uses this advantage judiciously -- never revealing his sources, never overplaying his hand.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"key-relationships\">Key Relationships</h2>\n<h3 id=\"governor-drussus\">Governor Drussus</h3>\n<p>The relationship between Voth and <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> is based on <strong>mutual respect mixed with wariness</strong>. Neither trusts the other. Neither can afford to ignore the other. The equilibrium they maintain is simple:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drussus does not interfere with Temple internal affairs</li>\n<li>Voth does not publicly oppose the Governor&#39;s authority</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Both recognize that either could seriously damage the other. Drussus has the military power. Voth has the moral authority and the intelligence network. Open conflict would be mutually destructive. So they maintain a cold peace, watching each other across a gap that neither dares to cross.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-laced-hand\">The Laced Hand</h3>\n<p>Voth regards the <a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">Laced Hand</a> as a necessary evil at best, a moral rot at worst. He tolerates their existence because eliminating them would require the Governor&#39;s cooperation (which would come at too high a political price) and because the alternative -- unorganized, chaotic crime -- would be worse. But he does not approve, and he maintains agents in the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Harbor</a> specifically to monitor Laced Hand activities.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-imperial-academy\">The Imperial Academy</h3>\n<p>Voth&#39;s relationship with the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Academy</a> is one of <strong>cautious cooperation</strong>. The Temple and the Academy represent different kinds of authority -- spiritual and intellectual -- and they occasionally clash on matters of doctrine or policy. But <a href=\"#/page/magister-shale\" class=\"wiki-link\">Magister Shale</a> and Voth share a common interest in maintaining institutional independence from the Governor, and this creates a basis for cooperation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-in-play\">Role in Play</h2>\n<p>Voth will <strong>work with adventurers</strong> if doing so serves the Temple&#39;s interests. He can provide:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Healing and divine services</li>\n<li>Information from the Temple&#39;s intelligence network</li>\n<li>Political support or protection within the <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sunward</a></li>\n<li>Moral authority (which carries real weight in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>)</li>\n<li>Access to the Temple&#39;s resources (monastic warriors, safe houses, diplomatic channels)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>He will <strong>move against adventurers</strong> if they threaten the Temple&#39;s position, undermine its authority, or destabilize the carefully maintained balance of power in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. He is not vindictive -- but he is thorough.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"gm-notes\">GM Notes</h2>\n<p>Voth should be played as a man who has been making hard choices for decades and has developed a deep, unshakeable conviction that the Temple must survive above all else. He is kind when kindness costs nothing. He is generous when generosity serves the Temple. He is merciless when the Temple is threatened.</p>\n<p>Key principles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>He is never the first to act.</strong> He watches, gathers information, and responds. Rash action is beneath him.</li>\n<li><strong>He is not fooled by flattery or deception.</strong> Seventy-three years of hearing confessions have given him an almost supernatural ability to detect lies.</li>\n<li><strong>He remembers everything.</strong> Every favor, every slight, every broken promise. His ledger is long and his memory is perfect.</li>\n<li><strong>He is afraid of the Governor.</strong> Not in a craven way -- in the way that a chess player fears a superior opponent. He respects Drussus&#39;s ability and knows that if their equilibrium ever breaks, the outcome is uncertain.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- provincial capital</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Sunward</a> -- the Temple district</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thousand-temples\" class=\"wiki-link\">Temple of the Unconquered Sun</a> -- the faith</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- secular counterweight</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/laced-hand\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Laced Hand</a> -- criminal syndicate</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> -- scholarly institution</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- the province</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"rendson","title":"Rendson","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["pc","player-character","reclaimers","avari","gambler","deceased","backlands","necropede","grim-sleeper"],"html":"<h1 id=\"rendson\">Rendson</h1>\n<p><strong>Rendson</strong> was an <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> gambler, whoremonger, and fugitive who served as a member of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a> during the early days of the campaign. His past was soiled and unrevealed, his debts considerable, and his habits worse. He earned the name <strong>&quot;Grim Sleeper&quot;</strong> for striking beasts where they lay -- a talent for killing things in their dens, in their nests, in the places where they thought they were safe. He died alongside <a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred</a> fighting a <strong>necropede</strong>, a vile undead abomination, in the Backlands.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Rendson</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>class</strong></td>-<td>gambler</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>status</strong></td>-<td><strong>dead</strong></td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>epithet</strong></td>-<td>&quot;the-grim-sleeper&quot;</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>party</strong></td>-<td>[[the-reclaimers</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>cause-of-death</strong></td>-<td>killed-fighting-a-necropede-alongside-[[tancred</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>base-of-operations</strong></td>-<td>[[fort-meade</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"background\">background</h2>-<h3-id=\"an-avari-fugitive\">an-avari-fugitive</h3>-<p>rendson-was-[[races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> -- a member of the nomadic people whose reputation for cunning, commerce, and moral flexibility precedes them across the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a>. He embodied the worst of every stereotype the settled peoples applied to his kind: a gambler who cheated, a whoremonger who spent what he stole, a fugitive running from debts he had no intention of repaying. His past was a trail of burned bridges, broken promises, and creditors who would have preferred to collect in flesh.</p>\n<p>He came to <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> because the frontier does not ask questions. The Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty drew killers and fugitives in equal measure, and Rendson was both. Whatever he was running from, the Backlands offered distance and the possibility of coin earned through violence rather than fraud -- though Rendson was not above fraud when the opportunity presented itself.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-grim-sleeper\">The Grim Sleeper</h3>\n<p>Rendson earned the name <strong>&quot;Grim Sleeper&quot;</strong> for his particular talent: <strong>striking beasts where they lay</strong>. While other scalpers tracked their quarry across open ground or fought in desperate skirmishes on the march, Rendson preferred to find where the creatures slept, where they denned, where they felt safe -- and kill them there. It was not brave work. It was not honorable work. It was efficient, ruthless, and effective, and it earned him a reputation among the scalper gangs as a man who would go into dark places that others avoided.</p>\n<p>The name carried an edge of dark humor and grudging respect. &quot;Grim Sleeper&quot; suggested both the nature of his work -- killing sleeping things -- and something about the man himself. There was a grimness to Rendson that his gambling and whoring did not fully mask. Beneath the vice and the running, there was a man who understood darkness intimately, who was comfortable in it, who used it as a tool.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"among-the-reclaimers\">Among the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Rendson joined <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a> in the early days of the campaign, when the party was still a loose collection of individuals drawn together by the scalp bounty rather than any shared purpose. He was the group&#39;s least reputable member -- the one whose presence lowered the moral average, whose habits drew disapproval, whose past no one wanted to examine too closely.</p>\n<p>And yet he fought. When it mattered, when the beasts came and the steel was drawn, Rendson stood with his companions. His skills -- honed in the dark dens of the Backlands&#39; worst creatures -- proved invaluable in the close quarters and underground spaces where the Reclaimers increasingly found themselves. The Grim Sleeper was in his element when the rest of the party was not.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"death\">Death</h2>\n<p>Rendson died alongside <a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred</a> fighting a <strong>necropede</strong> -- a vile undead abomination encountered during the campaign. The necropede was a creature of horrifying scale and lethality, and the battle that killed Rendson and Tancred was one of the defining moments of the Reclaimers&#39; history.</p>\n<p>Where Tancred held fast with shield and faith so that others might live, Rendson&#39;s death was the death of a fighter -- not a saint, not a martyr, but a man who lifted his blade when the moment demanded it and did not run. For a gambler and a fugitive, that was enough.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-eulogies\">The Eulogies</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a> gave the eulogy for both Tancred and Rendson. Marco&#39;s words for Rendson acknowledged the man&#39;s flaws without flinching from them, but found grace in how he died:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;He lifted his blade beside his brothers and sisters. He died in the fight, as a warrior. There is grace in that. There is redemption in that.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Marco&#39;s eulogy was a deliberate act of mercy -- the insistence that a man&#39;s death could redeem a life that the man himself had done little to redeem. Rendson was a gambler, a whoremonger, a fugitive. But he died fighting beside his companions, and Marco chose to make that the final word.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a> also spoke at the funeral, though his words were directed more at <a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred&#39;s</a> death and its political utility. Shaw used the occasion to advance his movement, turning a warrior&#39;s sacrifice into rhetorical fuel. Whether Shaw acknowledged Rendson at all is unclear -- the Grim Sleeper was not the kind of man whose death served Shaw&#39;s purposes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>Rendson&#39;s legacy among the Reclaimers is complicated. He was not beloved. He was not admired. He was tolerated because he was useful, and remembered because he died well. In the brutal arithmetic of the Backlands, that is a more honest epitaph than most men receive.</p>\n<p>The campaign chronicle originally recorded Rendson as having &quot;departed&quot; the group -- vanished into the frontier, fate unknown. His death alongside Tancred corrects that record. He did not vanish. He did not run. In the end, the Grim Sleeper stood his ground.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The adventuring party he belonged to</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- The crusader who died beside him</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> -- The priest who gave his eulogy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> -- The preacher who spoke at the funeral</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where he was based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier where he fought and fell</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> -- His people</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The trade that brought him to the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history of the campaign</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"rook","title":"Rook","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["npc","bandit","fort-ikenvar","backlands","reclaimers","deceased"],"html":"<h1 id=\"rook\">Rook</h1>\n<p><strong>Rook</strong> was a bandit king who operated from the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>, using the decayed marsh fort as his base of operations to terrorize the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> supply routes and the garrison at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Dead -- destroyed by <span class=\"dead-link\">Fort Meade</span> and the surrounding territory. His operations included:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Targeted attacks on residents</strong> of Fort Meade and the surrounding settlements</li>\n<li><strong>Disappearances of travelers</strong> along the supply routes between <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, Fort Meade, and <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a></li>\n<li><strong>Deliberate intimidation</strong> -- Rook did not simply rob; he made examples, ensuring the population understood that the roads were his domain</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Legate&#39;s soldiers at Fort Meade were unable to deal with Rook. Whether through insufficient manpower, the difficulty of assaulting a fortified position in treacherous marshland, or the competing demands on <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> garrison, the imperial military failed to neutralize the threat.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"destruction\">Destruction</h2>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Reclaimers</a> delivered what the Legate&#39;s soldiers could not. They assaulted Fort Ikenvar and destroyed Rook, ending months of banditry that had terrorized the region. This action was one of the early demonstrations of the Reclaimers&#39; capacity to solve problems that the official imperial apparatus could not -- or would not -- address.</p>\n<p>After Rook&#39;s elimination, <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> did not remain empty for long. The ruins are now occupied by <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a>, a demonic entity of unknown origin drawn south by <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Stone of Sakkara</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>Rook&#39;s banditry and the Reclaimers&#39; destruction of him served as a key moment in establishing the party&#39;s reputation in the Backlands. The Legate could not do it. The Reclaimers could. That distinction matters in the political calculus of <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- Rook&#39;s base of operations, now occupied by the Guzzler</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison Rook terrorized</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The party that destroyed him</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Military commander who could not eliminate the threat</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- The demonic entity that now occupies Fort Ikenvar</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"sergeant-crull","title":"Sergeant Davan Crull","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","military","soldier","fort-meade","backlands","mithrian-military","garrison"],"html":"<h1 id=\"sergeant-davan-crull\">Sergeant Davan Crull</h1>\n<p><strong>Sergeant Davan Crull</strong> is the senior non-commissioned officer at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, serving as <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> enforcer at ground level. Eleven years under Marcellus and five on the frontier have compressed him into something harder than the man he started as.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Davan Crull</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td>Mithrian male</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>Mid-30s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Fighter 2 equivalent (senior NCO)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Location</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">the Legate&#39;s</span> will at ground level. He has served under Marcellus for eleven years. He understands his commander the way a hammer understands a nail: completely and without complexity.</p>\n<p>He does not question orders. He does not soften them. He is efficient and unsentimental.</p>\n<p>The garrison&#39;s mean streak runs through Crull like a seam of iron. He was not always this way. Eleven years under Marcellus and five on the frontier compressed him into something harder. The man who arrived at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> is not the man who serves there now.</p>\n<p>Crull is not sadistic -- cruelty for its own sake bores him. But he has no particular objection to it when it serves a purpose. The distinction is real but functionally narrow.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"service-record\">Service Record</h2>\n<p>Common born. Rose through the ranks on competence and a willingness to do what officers ask without questions. This combination -- ability paired with unquestioning obedience -- is what drew <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcellus&#39;s</a> attention and what has kept Crull in his position for over a decade.</p>\n<p>Crull does not aspire to command. He does not think about the political dimensions of his commander&#39;s decisions. He receives orders, he executes them, and he does so with a precision that has made him indispensable to a Legate who values instruments that do not require explanation.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-the-reclaimers\">Relationship with the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Watchful and neutral. Crull was told to extend professional courtesy to the <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a>, and he does so precisely -- no more, no less. He does not like outsiders in his garrison&#39;s area of operations. This is not personal animosity but professional territoriality.</p>\n<p>He respects demonstrated competence. The Reclaimers destroyed <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> when the garrison could not, and that earns a measure of grudging acknowledgment. But trust is a different currency, and Crull has not extended it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"secret\">Secret</h2>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><strong>SECRET:</strong> Crull was present at an incident during the <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> campaign that the official record does not reflect. Three civilians were killed. He followed orders. He thinks about it more than he expected to.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where Crull serves</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- His commanding officer for eleven years</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-military\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-military</a> -- The military structure he serves within</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">Reclaimers</a> -- The outsiders he watches with professional neutrality</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- The bandit campaign during which Crull&#39;s secret incident occurred</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- The Legate&#39;s wife</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"sergeant-gallus","title":"Sergeant Gallus","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","fighter","mithrian","law-enforcement","corrupt","lazy","bone-creek","backlands","imperial-decay"],"html":"<h1 id=\"sergeant-gallus\">Sergeant Gallus</h1>\n<p><strong>Sergeant Gallus</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> fighter and the nominal <strong>law enforcer of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a></strong>. In theory, Gallus represents the authority of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> in this frontier settlement — the long arm of imperial law extending to the edge of civilization. In practice, Gallus is a <strong>lazy, corrupt, conflict-averse</strong> excuse for a lawman who embodies everything wrong with the Empire&#39;s grip on its distant provinces. He is a <strong>symbol of imperial decay</strong> — a man who wears the title of authority without any of its substance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Fighter 2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#mithrian</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>3</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>11</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+1-(short-sword,-1d6+1)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>cha</strong></td>-<td>7</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>gallus&#39;s-statistics-tell-the-story-of-a-man-who-was-never-particularly-capable-and-has-allowed-even-those-modest-abilities-to-atrophy.-as-a-fighter-2,-he-is-barely-above-a-common-soldier-in-skill-and-experience.-his-11-hit-points-make-him-fragile-—-a-single-solid-blow-from-any-of-the-scalper-gang-leaders-would-drop-him.-his-+1-attack-bonus-is-the-lowest-of-any-named-npc-in-the-backlands,-and-his-short-sword-is-the-weapon-of-a-man-who-fights-only-when-cornered.</p>-<p>most-telling-is-his-charisma-of-7-—-well-below-average.-gallus-inspires-neither-respect,-loyalty,-nor-fear.-he-cannot-command-a-room,-rally-defenders,-or-project-authority.-in-a-settlement-full-of-hardened-killers,-veteran-warriors,-and-charismatic-leaders,-gallus-is-a-joke-—-and-everyone-knows-it.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>gambling</strong>-—-gallus&#39;s-primary-pastime-and-likely-his-primary-source-of-supplemental-income.-he-gambles-in-the-taverns-and-flophouses-of-bone-creek,-rubbing-shoulders-with-the-very-scalpers-he-is-theoretically-responsible-for-policing.-his-gambling-habit-reinforces-his-image-as-a-man-more-interested-in-personal-pleasure-than-public-duty.</li>-<li><strong>intimidation</strong>-—-a-sad-irony.-gallus-possesses-the-proficiency-to-intimidate,-but-his-low-charisma,-poor-combat-abilities,-and-universally-known-cowardice-make-his-attempts-at-intimidation-laughable-to-anyone-with-real-power-in-bone-creek.-he-may-be-able-to-bully-the-weakest-and-most-vulnerable-residents-—-drunks,-beggars,-newly-arrived-scalpers-who-haven&#39;t-yet-learned-the-lay-of-the-land-—-but-any-established-figure-in-town-would-simply-laugh-in-his-face.</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">appearance-and-demeanor</h2>-<p>gallus-wears-a-<strong>rusting-breastplate</strong>-—-the-single-most-telling-detail-about-his-character.-a-breastplate-that-rusts-is-a-breastplate-that-is-not-maintained,-not-oiled,-not-cared-for.-it-is-the-armor-of-a-soldier-who-has-given-up.-the-rust-is-a-visible-metaphor-for-everything-gallus-represents:-authority-that-has-corroded,-duty-that-has-decayed,-and-standards-that-have-been-abandoned.</p>-<p>gallus-<strong>smells-of-wine-and-grease</strong>-—-the-scent-of-a-man-who-spends-his-days-drinking-cheap-wine-and-eating-greasy-food-in-the-taverns-of-bone-creek-rather-than-patrolling,-investigating,-or-enforcing-the-law.-he-is-perpetually-slightly-drunk,-slightly-disheveled,-and-wholly-unimpressive.</p>-<p>he-is-<strong>lazy</strong>-—-avoiding-work,-avoiding-conflict,-avoiding-anything-that-might-require-effort-or-risk.-his-laziness-is-not-mere-indolence;-it-is-a-survival-strategy.-gallus-understands,-consciously-or-instinctively,-that-he-is-hopelessly-outmatched-by-every-significant-power-player-in-bone-creek,-and-his-solution-is-to-simply-not-engage.-he-does-the-bare-minimum-to-maintain-his-position-and-collect-whatever-meager-pay-or-bribes-come-his-way.</p>-<p>he-is-<strong>corrupt</strong>-—-easily-bribed-and-willing-to-look-the-other-way-for-the-right-price.-his-corruption-is-petty-rather-than-grand-—-he-does-not-orchestrate-criminal-enterprises-or-broker-power-deals.-he-simply-accepts-coin-to-ignore-things-he-would-have-ignored-anyway.-his-corruption-is-the-corruption-of-weakness,-not-ambition.</p>-<p>he-<strong>avoids-conflict</strong>-at-all-costs.-in-a-settlement-where-violence-is-the-primary-currency-of-power,-gallus&#39;s-aversion-to-conflict-is-both-understandable-and-damning.-he-will-not-confront-scalper-gangs,-he-will-not-investigate-crimes-committed-by-anyone-with-the-power-to-retaliate,-and-he-will-not-enforce-laws-that-might-put-him-in-danger.-he-is,-for-all-practical-purposes,-a-law-enforcer-who-enforces-nothing.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"role-in-bone-creek\">role-in-bone-creek</h2>-<p>gallus&#39;s-presence-in-bone-creek-serves-several-narrative-functions:</p>-<h3-id=\"symbol-of-imperial-decay\">symbol-of-imperial-decay</h3>-<p>gallus-is-what-happens-when-an-empire-stretches-too-far,-cares-too-little,-and-sends-its-worst-to-guard-its-most-distant-outposts.-he-represents-the-[[mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire&#39;s</a> failure to maintain meaningful authority in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. The fact that Gallus is the best the Empire can muster for law enforcement in its most volatile frontier settlement speaks volumes about the state of imperial governance.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-path-of-least-resistance\">The Path of Least Resistance</h3>\n<p>For players and power brokers in Bone Creek, Gallus is the path of least resistance. He can be <strong>easily bribed</strong> to ignore activities, provide information, or lend the thin veneer of official sanction to otherwise illegal operations. He can be <strong>pushed around</strong> by anyone with strength, wealth, or reputation — which means everyone of consequence in Bone Creek.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-vacuum-of-authority\">The Vacuum of Authority</h3>\n<p>Gallus&#39;s ineffectiveness creates a <strong>power vacuum</strong> that the real powers of Bone Creek — <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a>, <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a>, <a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a>, and the various Scalper gang leaders — rush to fill. The absence of legitimate law enforcement is what allows Bone Creek to function as a lawless frontier settlement, and Gallus&#39;s continued presence ensures that no one feels the need to establish real authority.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Bribable Badge</strong> — Gallus can be bribed for information, access, or official blind eyes. He is the cheapest and most accessible source of semi-official cooperation in Bone Creek.</li>\n<li><strong>Pushed Too Far</strong> — What happens if someone pushes Gallus past his breaking point? Even a coward can become dangerous when cornered, and Gallus does carry a sword and wear armor — rusted though it may be.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperial Report</strong> — Does Gallus report back to anyone in the imperial hierarchy? If so, what does he report? His reports could be a source of misinformation, deliberate deception, or accidental revelation.</li>\n<li><strong>Replacement</strong> — What would happen if the Empire sent a competent replacement for Gallus? A real law enforcer in Bone Creek would disrupt every power dynamic in the settlement.</li>\n<li><strong>Witness</strong> — Gallus&#39;s laziness and ubiquity in the taverns of Bone Creek mean he sees and hears a great deal. He may possess information he doesn&#39;t even realize is valuable — overheard conversations, patterns of behavior, movements of key figures.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The settlement Gallus nominally polices</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">mithrian-empire</a> — The empire whose authority Gallus theoretically represents</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> — The real power in Bone Creek&#39;s underworld</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> — The Lord Merchant who wields economic authority</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">tolliver-watts</a> — The merchant seeking to civilize Bone Creek</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> — A higher-ranking imperial official; potential contrast to Gallus&#39;s incompetence</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"sergeant-voss","title":"Sergeant Aldric Voss","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","fort-harvald","military","sergeant","mithrian","backlands","garrison","border-forts"],"html":"<h1 id=\"sergeant-aldric-voss\">Sergeant Aldric Voss</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;On a foggy morning the towers of Crossings rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man. The old ones say you can hear it breathing.&quot;</em>\n-- local saying from <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Sergeant Aldric Voss</strong> is the commanding officer of the garrison at <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a>, a small imperial border fort in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> located mere miles from the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. He commands a garrison of ten soldiers and is the highest-ranking imperial military authority in the settlement.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"overview\">Overview</h2>\n<p>Voss is a <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> male in his late 40s. He was once a capable and promising soldier -- the kind of career officer whose talent and discipline should have carried him to command of a company, a significant garrison, or a staff position in the provincial hierarchy. Instead, a single political mistake destroyed his career and buried him in the most remote, neglected, and strategically insignificant posting the Empire could find.</p>\n<p>He runs Fort Harvald with the same professionalism he would bring to a posting of genuine importance. He runs a tight ship. His garrison of ten soldiers is disciplined, functional, and loyal -- loyal to Voss personally, more than to the Empire that abandoned him. In a frontier where corruption is the norm and imperial authority is a polite fiction, Voss is <strong>not corrupt</strong>. This makes him a rarity in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> -- and possibly a liability.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<p>Voss&#39;s career was ended by a political miscalculation. He supported the wrong Senator in a dispute with the <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate-Governor</a> -- the kind of factional mistake that is commonplace in the politics of the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> but fatal to those who lack the connections to survive the consequences. He was passed over for promotion. The posting to <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> followed -- not as a temporary assignment but as a permanent exile. There is no path forward from Fort Harvald. There is no promotion coming. Voss knows this.</p>\n<p>Whether the years of isolation, neglect, and proximity to the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> have eroded his principles or hardened them is a question that has not yet been answered. He has not broken. He has not compromised. But he has also not been tested -- not truly, not in the way that the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> eventually tests everyone.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-orro-problem\">The Orro Problem</h2>\n<p>Voss knows that <strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Silvan Orro</a></strong> -- the trader who operates the River Trade Post at <a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> -- reports to the Governor. Orro is too polished, too connected, and too well-resourced for a bayou frontier posting. His connections to <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> mark him as a man with interests far beyond the fur trade. Voss has identified Orro as a probable <strong>intelligence asset</strong> but has said nothing about it.</p>\n<p>The reasons for this silence are ambiguous. Voss may be waiting to see what Orro reports and to whom. He may be calculating whether exposing Orro would improve his position or simply make a powerful enemy. He may be exhausted by the futility of fighting a system that has already discarded him. Or he may be waiting for the right moment -- the moment when the information becomes leverage rather than just knowledge.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"personality\">Personality</h2>\n<p>Voss is professional, competent, and quietly bitter. He does not complain about his posting -- not because he accepts it, but because complaints would be an admission that the system&#39;s judgment matters to him. He treats his soldiers fairly and expects discipline in return. He is respected by his garrison and by the civilian community of Fort Harvald, though his relationship with the <a href=\"#/page/avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> refugees is complicated by the fact that he represents the same Empire that many of them blame for the <a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a>.</p>\n<p>He is not a warm man. He is not an approachable man. But he is a reliable one -- and in the Backlands, reliability is worth more than warmth.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationships\">Relationships</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Garrison</strong> -- Voss&#39;s ten soldiers are loyal to him personally. This is a significant distinction in a frontier where imperial authority has effectively collapsed.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Maren Ashfoot</a></strong> -- The unofficial leader of Fort Harvald&#39;s civilian community. Voss and Maren have a functional, respectful working relationship -- the military and civilian spheres of the settlement cooperating out of necessity rather than affection.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Silvan Orro</a></strong> -- Voss knows Orro is the Governor&#39;s man. Orro does not know Voss knows. This asymmetry is one of the most significant political dynamics in Fort Harvald.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Havar bar-Kessian</a></strong> -- The elder of the Refugee Quarter suspects imperial complicity in the fall of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. Voss represents the Empire. The tension is obvious.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Harvald</a> -- The settlement Voss commands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- The ruined city visible from the fort</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sacking-of-crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sacking of Crossings</a> -- The catastrophe that created the settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Silvan Orro</a> -- River trader and probable intelligence asset</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-harvald\" class=\"wiki-link\">Maren Ashfoot</a> -- Civilian leader of Fort Harvald</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a> -- The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> -- Trade organization connected to Orro</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate-Governor</a> -- The political authority whose displeasure ended Voss&#39;s career</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"shatzi","title":"Shatzi","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["pc","player-character","reclaimers","merchant","organizer","lady-severina","backlands","fort-meade"],"html":"<h1 id=\"shatzi\">Shatzi</h1>\n<p><strong>Shatzi</strong> is a Merchant and a member of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a> -- their organizer, negotiator, and the closest thing the party has to a leader. She is a merchant failed and cast down, but sly -- never finished. She seeks some angle, always, to claw back what the world took from her. She was invited to <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina&#39;s</a> social gatherings, a distinction that reflects both her political usefulness and Severina&#39;s recognition of a kindred operator.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Shatzi</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Merchant</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Active PC</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Party</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Backlands</span> drew Shatzi for the same reason it drew everyone: opportunity born from catastrophe. The destruction of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty created a frontier economy where the old hierarchies did not apply, where a failed merchant could reinvent herself, where capital could be accumulated through means that polite society would not sanction but the frontier did not care about.</p>\n<p>She did not come to kill beasts. She came because the Backlands was a market -- chaotic, violent, and ungoverned, but a market nonetheless. And markets are where Shatzi lives.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-organizer\">The Organizer</h2>\n<p>Shatzi is the Reclaimers&#39; organizer. Not their commander -- the Reclaimers do not have a formal command structure -- but the person who holds the group together as a functioning enterprise. She manages logistics, negotiates terms, handles the party&#39;s finances, and makes the practical decisions that keep a band of misfits operational in hostile territory.</p>\n<p>This role is a natural extension of her merchant training. A merchant understands supply chains, profit margins, risk assessment, and the management of people who are fundamentally unreliable. All of these skills transfer directly to running an adventuring party in the Backlands.</p>\n<p>She was the one who organized the disparate individuals who would become the Reclaimers into a coherent group. Where <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> brought philosophical curiosity and <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> brought arcane power, Shatzi brought the thing the group actually needed: someone who could make it work.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-with-lady-severina\">Relationship with Lady Severina</h2>\n<p>Shatzi has been invited to <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina&#39;s</a> social gatherings at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> -- an invitation that carries considerable significance in the political ecosystem of the garrison. Severina&#39;s gatherings are not merely social events. They are the arena in which the Legate&#39;s wife exercises her political influence, cultivates relationships, and manages the web of obligations and favors that sustains her household&#39;s position.</p>\n<p>That Shatzi is invited suggests that Severina recognizes in her a kindred mind -- someone who understands the mechanics of influence, who thinks in terms of leverage and opportunity, who operates through practical intelligence rather than brute force. Shatzi and Severina are both women who have learned to operate within systems that were not designed for them, and they recognize each other&#39;s competence.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"personality\">Personality</h2>\n<p>Shatzi is pragmatic, calculating, and relentlessly opportunistic -- but not cruel. Her merchant&#39;s instinct is always working, always assessing, always looking for the deal, the advantage, the angle that others have missed. She was cast down, and she will claw her way back up, and she does not much care about the niceties of how she does it.</p>\n<p>She is sly. In the Backlands, this is a compliment. Slyness means survival. It means seeing the trap before it closes. It means understanding that every transaction has a hidden cost and every alliance has an expiration date. Shatzi understands these things instinctively, and this understanding is what makes her the Reclaimers&#39; indispensable member.</p>\n<p>She is never finished. This is perhaps her most defining quality. No matter what happens -- no matter what she loses, what setback she suffers, what scheme collapses -- Shatzi is already thinking about the next move. She was failed and cast down, and she did not accept it. She came to the Backlands instead, and she is still working, still scheming, still clawing.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The adventuring party she organizes</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- Her social patron and the Reclaimers&#39; true patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Severina&#39;s husband and the Reclaimers&#39; formal patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where she is based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The underground complex currently being explored</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruins above the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history of the campaign</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"skinner","title":"Skinner","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","assassin","kolani","scalper","skin-eaters","brutal","backlands","bone-creek"],"html":"<h1 id=\"skinner\">Skinner</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;Notoriously brutal Scalper captain. Covered in scars and never seen without a blade. Rumors say he&#39;s not entirely sane.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Skinner</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> assassin and the feared leader of the <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#skin-eaters\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters</a></strong>, one of the most brutal Scalper gangs operating in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. He is the <strong>embodiment of Scalper brutality</strong> — a cold, intense killer whose reputation for savagery precedes him wherever he goes. Covered in scars from countless encounters, Skinner is never seen without a blade within reach, and the rumors that surround him suggest a man whose sanity has been eroded by years of violence and the corrupting influence of the beastman hunts.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Assassin 5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>4</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>28</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+4-(hooked-axe,-1d8+2)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>dex</strong></td>-<td>15</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>skinner&#39;s-statistics-reveal-a-lethal-combatant-optimized-for-killing.-his-ac-of-4-—-achieved-in-part-through-his-distinctive-<strong>beastman-hide-armor</strong>-—-provides-solid-protection,-while-his-28-hit-points-give-him-the-durability-to-survive-prolonged-engagements.-his-+4-attack-bonus-with-a-hooked-axe-dealing-1d8+2-damage-makes-him-a-devastating-melee-fighter,-and-his-dexterity-of-15-supports-his-assassin&#39;s-trade-of-stealth-and-precision.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"skills\">skills</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>surprise</strong>-—-10+-(skinner-excels-at-catching-his-enemies-unaware;-his-ability-to-appear-from-nowhere-and-strike-without-warning-is-a-key-part-of-both-his-combat-effectiveness-and-his-fearsome-reputation)</li>-<li><strong>backstab</strong>-—-+4-(when-skinner-strikes-from-concealment-or-surprise,-his-damage-is-multiplied-devastatingly;-this-is-the-hallmark-of-a-trained-killer-who-fights-not-with-honor-but-with-lethal-efficiency)</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"proficiencies\">proficiencies</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>tracking</strong>-—-the-ability-to-follow-prey-across-any-terrain;-essential-for-hunting-beastmen-in-the-wilderness-of-the-backlands,-and-equally-useful-for-hunting-men</li>-<li><strong>ambushing</strong>-—-the-art-of-setting-and-executing-ambushes;-skinner-does-not-fight-fair-—-he-chooses-his-ground,-sets-his-trap,-and-strikes-when-his-prey-is-most-vulnerable</li>-<li><strong>torture</strong>-—-the-deliberate-infliction-of-pain-for-the-purpose-of-extracting-information,-punishing-enemies,-or-simple-cruelty;-this-proficiency,-combined-with-skinner&#39;s-reputation-for-brutality,-makes-him-one-of-the-most-feared-individuals-in-the-backlands</li>-</ul>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">appearance-and-demeanor</h2>-<p>skinner-is-<strong>cold</strong>-and-<strong>intense</strong>-—-a-man-of-few-words-whose-presence-fills-a-room-with-dread.-he-does-not-posture-or-threaten-unnecessarily;-his-reputation-does-that-work-for-him.-when-skinner-speaks,-people-listen,-because-the-alternative-is-to-discover-firsthand-why-his-name-precedes-him.</p>-<p>he-is-<strong>covered-in-scars</strong>,-each-one-a-testament-to-a-life-spent-in-close-quarters-violence.-these-are-not-the-scars-of-a-soldier-who-fights-in-formation-—-they-are-the-marks-of-a-killer-who-fights-in-the-dark,-in-the-mud,-in-the-places-where-civilized-rules-do-not-apply.</p>-<p>skinner-is-<strong>never-seen-without-a-blade</strong>.-his-weapon-of-choice-is-a-<strong>hooked-axe</strong>-—-a-cruel,-purpose-built-instrument-designed-not-merely-to-kill-but-to-tear-and-maim.-the-hook-allows-him-to-catch-shields,-drag-opponents-off-balance,-and-inflict-ragged,-difficult-to-heal-wounds.</p>-<p>his-most-distinctive-feature-is-his-<strong>beastman-hide-armor</strong>-—-armor-crafted-from-the-tanned-skins-of-the-very-creatures-he-hunts.-this-is-a-statement-of-dominance,-contempt,-and-identity.-skinner-does-not-merely-kill-beastmen;-he-wears-them-as-trophies,-a-walking-testament-to-the-volume-of-his-kills-and-the-depth-of-his-savagery.</p>-<p>rumors-persist-that-<strong>skinner-is-not-entirely-sane</strong>.-the-years-of-hunting,-killing,-and-skinning-beastmen-have-taken-their-toll,-and-there-are-those-who-whisper-that-the-line-between-skinner-and-the-creatures-he-hunts-has-grown-dangerously-thin.-the-old-scalper-saying-—-<em>&quot;the-bounty-takes-its-toll&quot;</em>-—-finds-its-most-vivid-expression-in-skinner.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"the-skin-eaters\">the-skin-eaters</h2>-<p>skinner-leads-the-<strong>[[scalper-gangs#skin-eaters\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters</a></strong>, a Scalper gang whose name alone is enough to inspire fear and revulsion. The Skin Eaters are the most <strong>notoriously brutal</strong> of the Scalper gangs, known for methods that go far beyond what is necessary to collect the Imperial Bounty. Under Skinner&#39;s leadership, the gang has become an instrument of pure, efficient violence — feared by beastmen and humans alike.</p>\n<p>The Skin Eaters&#39; reputation serves a practical purpose: it deters rivals, intimidates potential enemies, and ensures that few dare to cross them. But it also isolates them — even among the hardened Scalpers of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, the Skin Eaters are regarded with a mixture of respect and horror.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"kolani-heritage\">Kolani Heritage</h2>\n<p>As a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a>, Skinner comes from a culture that values strength, survival, and martial prowess. The Kolani are a people shaped by hardship, and Skinner is a product of that heritage taken to its most extreme expression. His skills in tracking, ambushing, and torture reflect a warrior tradition refined into something altogether more predatory.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Thin Line</strong> — Is Skinner still sane? His years of brutal violence may have pushed him past a breaking point, and his behavior could become increasingly erratic and dangerous.</li>\n<li><strong>Beastman-Hide Armor</strong> — Skinner&#39;s armor is a provocation and a trophy. It could attract the attention of beastman leaders seeking revenge, or it could be a valuable item if Skinner falls.</li>\n<li><strong>The Torture Master</strong> — Skinner&#39;s proficiency in torture makes him a potential source of information about beastman activities, rival gangs, or hidden locations — for those willing to deal with him.</li>\n<li><strong>Gang War</strong> — The Skin Eaters&#39; brutality puts them at odds with more moderate Scalper groups. A confrontation between the Skin Eaters and another gang could destabilize the entire Scalper economy of Bone Creek.</li>\n<li><strong>Corruption</strong> — The veteran Scalpers bear &quot;marks of corruption.&quot; Has Skinner been affected? Is his instability a sign of something supernatural rather than merely psychological?</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#skin-eaters\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters</a> — Skinner&#39;s gang</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures Skinner hunts and skins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> — Skinner&#39;s cultural heritage</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> — The ruined city that spawned the Scalper trade</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"tancred","title":"Tancred","category":"people","status":"dead","tags":["pc","player-character","reclaimers","crusader","seros","deceased","backlands","necropede","eulogies"],"html":"<h1 id=\"tancred\">Tancred</h1>\n<p><strong>Tancred</strong> was a Crusader bearing the fire of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> and a former member of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. He sought baptism in the blood of beasts -- a holy war made personal, a faith expressed through violence against the monstrous. He came to <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> because the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty had transformed the frontier into a crusade by another name, and Tancred intended to fight it as one. He died during the campaign.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Tancred</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Crusader</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Dead</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Faith</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Seros</span>, the faith of the burning god whose light purifies and whose flame consumes. For Tancred, violence was not merely a means to an end but a sacrament -- the act of destroying the monstrous was itself an act of worship, a prayer spoken in steel and blood.</p>\n<p>The faith of Seros demands action. It does not reward contemplation, compromise, or restraint. Seros is a god of the forge and the pyre, and his crusaders are the instruments of his cleansing fire. Tancred embodied this theology without reservation or doubt. He did not question whether the beasts of the Backlands deserved destruction. They were abominations, and Seros demanded their purification. The question was not whether to fight but how much of himself to pour into the fighting.</p>\n<h3 id=\"coming-to-the-backlands\">Coming to the Backlands</h3>\n<p>The destruction of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> by the beastman horde was, for a crusader of Seros, an obscenity that demanded answer. A border city put to the torch. Its people butchered in their homes. The beastmen vast beyond counting, unburned and unbroken, still roaming the province that they had despoiled. The Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty was a mercenary response to a spiritual crisis, but for Tancred it served: it drew fighting men to the frontier, and among fighting men a crusader could find purpose.</p>\n<p>He sought baptism in the blood of beasts. This phrase captures Tancred&#39;s theology and his psychology in equal measure. He wanted to be immersed in the holy violence of the crusade -- not merely to participate but to be transformed by it, to be washed clean in the act of destroying Seros&#39;s enemies. The beastmen were the baptismal font. Their blood was the consecrating water. Every kill was a step deeper into the faith.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"among-the-reclaimers\">Among the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Tancred was the Reclaimers&#39; spiritual center -- the member whose convictions were absolute and whose purpose was unambiguous. While <a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shatzi</a> sought wealth, <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> sought truth, <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> pursued forbidden knowledge, and <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> sought purpose after exile, Tancred knew exactly why he was in the Backlands and exactly what he intended to do there. His certainty was both an anchor and a liability -- it steadied the group when doubt crept in, but it also made him inflexible in situations that demanded compromise.</p>\n<p>His relationship with <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> was necessarily complicated. Tancred bore the fire of a purifying god; Tiberius practiced necromancy. The theological tension between a crusader who sought to cleanse the world of abomination and a mage who trafficked in the manipulation of death itself must have been considerable. That they fought alongside each other despite this tension speaks to the pragmatism that even zealotry must sometimes adopt in the Backlands.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"death\">Death</h2>\n<p>Tancred died fighting a <strong>necropede</strong> -- a vile undead abomination -- alongside <a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rendson</a>, the Avari gambler known as &quot;the Grim Sleeper.&quot; The necropede was a creature of horrifying scale and lethality, and the battle that killed both men was one of the defining moments of the Reclaimers&#39; history.</p>\n<p>Tancred faced the creature with <strong>nothing but shield and faith</strong>. He held fast so that others might live. This was not a desperate last stand born of panic but a deliberate choice -- the choice of a crusader who believed that his life was worth spending in the defense of others, that the fire of <a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros</a> burned brightest in sacrifice. He held the line. Others survived because he did.</p>\n<p>His death left a void in the Reclaimers that has not been filled. The party lost its spiritual certainty -- the member who never doubted, who always knew that what they were doing mattered, who fought with the absolute conviction that the beasts were evil and the killing was righteous. Without Tancred, the Reclaimers are a more pragmatic group, but also a more uncertain one.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-eulogies\">The Eulogies</h3>\n<p>Two eulogies were given for Tancred, and the contrast between them reveals the political fault lines that his death exposed.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a></strong> spoke first, giving eulogies for both Tancred and <a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rendson</a>. Marco&#39;s words for Tancred honored the crusader&#39;s sacrifice without embellishment -- a warrior of faith who died as he lived, in service to his god and his companions. Marco also spoke for Rendson, acknowledging the gambler&#39;s flaws but finding grace in his death.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a></strong> gave a competing eulogy -- and &quot;competing&quot; is the operative word. Shaw used Tancred&#39;s death <strong>politically</strong>, turning the crusader&#39;s sacrifice into rhetorical fuel for his movement. Where Marco honored Tancred as a man, Shaw claimed him as a symbol. Where Marco spoke of faith and sacrifice, Shaw spoke of causes and movements. Shaw&#39;s eulogy was not about Tancred. It was about Shaw.</p>\n<p>The fact that Shaw felt comfortable using a dead man&#39;s sacrifice to advance his political ambitions -- at the man&#39;s own funeral -- speaks to both Shaw&#39;s ambition and the growing influence of his movement in the Backlands.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"legacy\">Legacy</h2>\n<p>Tancred&#39;s death is part of the Reclaimers&#39; history -- a reminder that the Backlands kills zealots and cynics alike, that faith does not make a man invulnerable, and that the blood-baptism Tancred sought was real in ways he may not have intended. He found what he was looking for. It killed him.</p>\n<p>Among the surviving Reclaimers, Tancred&#39;s memory serves as a marker of what the campaign has cost them. He and <a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rendson</a> fell together -- the crusader and the gambler, the most devout and the least reputable members of the party, united in death as they had been unlikely allies in life. Their absence changes the group&#39;s character in ways that are felt even if they are not always spoken.</p>\n<p>The henchman <strong>Antonius</strong> had a <strong>vision of Rendson</strong> near the point of death -- a detail that suggests the deaths of both men may carry metaphysical significance beyond the merely physical. Whether the vision was divine communication, psychic residue, or the desperate hallucination of a grieving companion is unresolved.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The adventuring party he belonged to</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- The faith he served</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where he was based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The frontier where he fought and fell</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined city whose destruction called him to the frontier</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">rendson</a> -- The Avari gambler who died beside him</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> -- The priest who gave his eulogy</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> -- The preacher who used his death politically</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history of the campaign</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"thaddeus-marr","title":"Thaddeus Marr","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","bone-creek","pretty-peach","racketeer","frontiersman","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"thaddeus-marr\">Thaddeus Marr</h1>\n<p><strong>Thaddeus Marr</strong> is the proprietor of <strong>The Pretty Peach</strong> tavern and inn in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>, and one of the most powerful and dangerous figures in the settlement. A hardened frontiersman with a storied reputation, Marr is far more than a simple tavern keeper — he secretly operates a <strong>racket</strong> within town, using his network of informants and enforcers to maintain control over Bone Creek&#39;s underworld.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"operations\">Operations</h2>\n<h3 id=\"the-pretty-peach\">The Pretty Peach</h3>\n<p>Marr&#39;s primary base of operations. The Pretty Peach serves watered-down ale, cheap wine, and decent food. Hard beds are available for a few marks, though decent rooms are in high demand. It is the rough-and-tumble heart of Bone Creek&#39;s social life, catering to the Scalper trade.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-flophouse-via-theo\">The Flophouse (via Theo)</h3>\n<p>Marr has <strong>Theo</strong>, the proprietor of the Flophouse, secretly in his pocket. Theo feeds Marr information on Scalper gangs, rumors, and activities within town. Since the Flophouse is the first stop for most newly arrived Scalpers, this gives Marr intelligence on every new arrival before they even set foot in the Peach. Theo carries a brutal cudgel and no one dares cross him — but his true loyalty is to Marr.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-racket\">The Racket</h3>\n<p>Marr secretly operates a racket within town. The exact nature and full extent of this criminal enterprise is not publicly known, but it is clear that Marr&#39;s influence extends well beyond the walls of the Pretty Peach.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"associates\">Associates</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Theo</strong> — Proprietor of the Flophouse. Secret informant feeding Marr intelligence on Scalpers, gangs, and town activity.</li>\n<li><strong>Crackback</strong> — A brutish <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#targ\" class=\"wiki-link\">targ</a> who serves as the local pimp and Marr&#39;s right-hand man. Crackback employs several working girls and provides muscle for Marr&#39;s operations.</li>\n<li><strong>Trixie</strong> — A young and beautiful slave girl at the Pretty Peach.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"rivalries\">Rivalries</h2>\n<p>Marr is locked in a <strong>simmering rivalry</strong> with <strong><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tolliver Watts</a></strong> and his establishment, <strong>Double Sevens</strong>, which sits directly across the street from the Pretty Peach. This rivalry has already resulted in large-scale brawls between the two factions. The conflict represents a deeper tension — Marr embodies the lawless, rough frontier culture of Bone Creek, while Watts and his ally <a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a> seek to bring civilization and order to the settlement.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Marr is described as a <strong>hardened frontiersman with a storied reputation</strong>. He is cunning, well-connected, and not to be underestimated. His control over both the Pretty Peach and the Flophouse (through Theo) gives him eyes and ears across the settlement, and his racket extends his reach into the criminal underworld of Bone Creek.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The settlement where Marr operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tolliver-watts\" class=\"wiki-link\">tolliver-watts</a> — Marr&#39;s rival across the street</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> — Lord Merchant allied with Watts against Marr&#39;s interests</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> — The trading consortium backing Watts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"theo","title":"Theo","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","fighter","thrassian","bone-creek","flophouse","informant","thaddeus-marr","backlands"],"html":"<h1 id=\"theo\">Theo</h1>\n<p><strong>Theo</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> Fighter (level 3) and the proprietor of <strong>The Flophouse</strong> in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>. A gruff, no-nonsense mountain tribesman who commands respect through fear, Theo runs the cheapest lodging in town with an iron fist and a brutal cudgel. He is also a <strong>secret informant</strong>, reporting on <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a> activities to <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Theo</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Bone Creek</span> -- a step above sleeping in the mud, but only just. Theo runs it with absolute authority:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Carries a brutal cudgel</strong> -- and has clearly used it</li>\n<li><strong>Never extends credit</strong> -- pay up front or sleep outside</li>\n<li><strong>Respected through fear</strong> -- no one causes trouble in The Flophouse because no one wants to find out exactly how brutal that cudgel gets</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Flophouse caters to the lowest rung of Bone Creek society -- broke Scalpers between hunts, drifters, and anyone too poor or too new to afford a room at The Pretty Peach or the Double Sevens.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"personality\">Personality</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Gruff</strong> -- communication reduced to essential words and meaningful silences</li>\n<li><strong>No-nonsense</strong> -- zero tolerance for trouble, excuses, or conversation</li>\n<li><strong>Respected through fear</strong> -- not charisma, not diplomacy, not reputation; plain, simple fear</li>\n</ul>\n<p>His <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> mountain tribesman background explains the approach. The Thrassians are warriors from the peaks -- direct, physical, and uninterested in the elaborate social games of lowland <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-culture\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian</a> culture.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"secret-marrs-informant\">Secret: Marr&#39;s Informant</h2>\n<p>Theo <strong>secretly reports on <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Scalper</a> activities to <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr</a></strong>. His position as Flophouse proprietor makes him an ideal intelligence asset:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Flophouse is where Scalpers talk freely -- they are drunk, exhausted, and among their own kind</li>\n<li>Theo&#39;s Alertness proficiency means he misses nothing</li>\n<li>His gruff, disinterested demeanor means no one suspects he is listening</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This makes Theo part of Marr&#39;s broader intelligence network in Bone Creek, alongside <a href=\"#/page/crackback\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crackback</a> at The Pretty Peach. Between the two establishments, Marr has ears on virtually every Scalper who passes through town -- those who can afford the Peach talk to Crackback&#39;s girls, and those who cannot afford it talk in Theo&#39;s Flophouse.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> -- The frontier outpost where Theo runs The Flophouse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> -- The man Theo secretly reports to</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crackback\" class=\"wiki-link\">crackback</a> -- Fellow informant in Marr&#39;s network</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">thrassian</a> -- Theo&#39;s cultural background, mountain tribal warriors</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The gangs Theo monitors for Marr</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"theodotus","title":"Theodotus","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["pc","player-character","reclaimers","philosopher-bard","thrassian","stone-of-sakkara","backlands","fort-meade","the-guzzler"],"html":"<h1 id=\"theodotus\">Theodotus</h1>\n<p><strong>Theodotus</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/thrassian\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thrassian</a> Philosopher-Bard and a member of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. His books had soured him -- years of study and contemplation had left him hollow, unconvinced that the truths he sought could be found in libraries or lecture halls. He came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands. He is currently the bearer of the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>, an artifact of terrible power whose presence draws <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a> toward <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Theodotus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Mithrian Empire</span> by millennia. Unlike most of his kind encountered in the Backlands, Theodotus is educated, articulate, and driven by intellectual curiosity rather than territorial instinct or predatory hunger.</p>\n<p>He was a scholar. His books had soured him. The precise nature of this souring is not entirely clear -- whether it was a specific disillusionment, a philosophical crisis, or simply the accumulated weight of learning without understanding. What is clear is that Theodotus reached a point where the written word no longer satisfied. The truths he sought were not in texts. They were carried by men who lived and died violently, men who acted rather than contemplated, men whose understanding was bought with blood rather than study.</p>\n<p>And so he came to <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> -- not as a soldier or a scalper, but as something stranger: a philosopher who had decided that the lecture hall was a lie and the battlefield might be honest. He joined the killers drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty, not because he wanted gold, but because he wanted to stand among men who knew things his books could not teach him.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-stone-of-sakkara\">The Stone of Sakkara</h2>\n<p>Theodotus carries the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> -- an artifact of significant and dangerous properties whose full nature is not yet understood. The Stone&#39;s presence at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> has drawn <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a> -- the demonic entity currently occupying <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> -- toward the garrison. The Guzzler cannot precisely locate the Stone but can sense its pull, compromising the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature.</p>\n<p>The approximately one hundred soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. By carrying the Stone, Theodotus has inadvertently made himself and his companions a threat to the very garrison that shelters them. The Stone draws the Guzzler. The Guzzler&#39;s approach endangers everyone at Fort Meade. The Reclaimers live at Fort Meade. The logic is inescapable.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> is aware of the Stone, and <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> of the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> has a competing interest in it. Theodotus&#39;s possession of this artifact places him at the center of multiple factional interests that extend far beyond the Backlands.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-stones-escalation-the-road-to-sanctuary\">The Stone&#39;s Escalation -- The Road to Sanctuary</h3>\n<p>As the Reclaimers travel south from <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, the Stone&#39;s influence has escalated catastrophically. Theodotus refused to feed the Stone. So the Stone reached further.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">Guzzler</a> has followed the party south from <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>, drawn by the Stone&#39;s pull. But the Stone is not merely drawing the Guzzler -- it is <strong>amplifying the creature&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent</strong>. The result is an escalating trail of violence along the road:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>A farm three miles south of Fort Meade: goats taken, fence posts crushed in.</li>\n<li>A merchant on the Sanctuary road: his draft horse found half-consumed. He saw nothing. Heard nothing.</li>\n<li>Near Sanctuary: a child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Theodotus does not perceive the Stone&#39;s influence clearly. He feels it as a <strong>wrongness</strong> -- a sense that the suffering he hears about along the road is somehow adjacent to the weight in his pack. Not a voice. Not a compulsion. Just a persistent, gnawing awareness that the violence around him is not random, that its proximity to his path is not coincidence.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-test\">The Test</h3>\n<p>When the child&#39;s disappearance reaches Theodotus -- by rumor, or by encountering the family directly -- the wrongness crystallizes. This is the moral crisis the Stone has been building toward. Not a combat encounter. A question:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Does he tell the party what he suspects? Sharing means admitting the deaths may be his fault -- not through action, but through possession.</li>\n<li>Does he try to destroy the Stone? And does he know how?</li>\n<li>Does he draw the Guzzler away from the road deliberately, leading it into wilderness?</li>\n<li>Does he realize the geometry of innocence does not change? Putting distance between himself and the Stone means it simply calls the creature further. The innocents along the new path are no safer.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The core truth Theodotus must confront: <strong>killing the Guzzler resolves nothing</strong>. The Stone will reach through something else. The Guzzler is a symptom, not the disease. The scene ends when Theodotus decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies.</p>\n<p>This is the test the Stone has been building toward since Theodotus first refused to feed it. A philosopher who came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands is now carrying an artifact that turns his proximity into a weapon against the innocent. The books never prepared him for this. The battlefield didn&#39;t either.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-among-the-reclaimers\">Role Among the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Theodotus serves as a kind of chronicler and observer within the party -- a man who watches, considers, and occasionally speaks in ways that unsettle his companions. He is not the group&#39;s leader (that role falls more naturally to <a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shatzi</a>) nor its spiritual center (that was <a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred&#39;s</a> role, before his death). Theodotus is the one who asks why, who notices patterns, who considers what the violence means rather than simply participating in it.</p>\n<p>This does not mean he is passive. He came to the Backlands specifically to be among violent men, and he has proven willing to act when action is required. But his motivations remain philosophical in a way that sets him apart from his companions. <a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shatzi</a> wants wealth. <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> wants knowledge of a darker kind. <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> wants purpose after exile. Theodotus wants truth -- and he has not yet decided whether he has found it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"personality\">Personality</h2>\n<p>Theodotus is contemplative, measured, and occasionally unsettling. His Thrassian heritage gives him a perspective on the world that differs fundamentally from his human companions -- he sees things through a longer lens, with less urgency and more patience. His manner of speaking tends toward the philosophical, though he is capable of blunt directness when the situation demands it.</p>\n<p>His decision to abandon scholarship for the company of killers suggests a man who reached the end of one kind of patience and found another. He is not disillusioned in the bitter sense -- he has not given up on truth. He has simply concluded that truth lives in a different place than he was looking.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The adventuring party he belongs to</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> -- The dangerous artifact he carries</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where he is based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- Where the Guzzler dwells</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The underground complex currently being explored</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruins above the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- Faction interested in the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Academy representative with competing interest</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history of the campaign</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"tiberius","title":"Tiberius","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["pc","player-character","reclaimers","mage","necromancer","imperial-academy","noble","exile","backlands","fort-meade"],"html":"<h1 id=\"tiberius\">Tiberius</h1>\n<p><strong>Tiberius</strong> is a Mage and a member of <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>. He was schooled at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> -- the official state-sanctioned seat of sorcerous learning within the <a href=\"#/page/mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire</a> -- and cast out for the blackness of his studies. His exile was stayed only by his noble bloodlines; a man of lesser birth would have been executed or worse. He is a necromancer, and the nature of his research at the Academy was sufficiently transgressive that even that institution -- which tolerates a great deal of clandestine experimentation -- could not permit him to remain.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Tiberius</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Mage (Necromancer)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Status</strong></td>\n<td>Active PC</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Party</strong></td>\n<td><span class=\"dead-link\">Imperial Academy</span> in <a href=\"#/page/mithra-city\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithra City</a> -- the Empire&#39;s preeminent institution of sorcerous learning. The Academy is a place of immense prestige and equally immense danger, where the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Archmages</a> of the Conclave govern the boundaries of permissible research and the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seekers</a> scour the provinces for sorcerous talent. To be admitted to the Academy is to enter a world of power, politics, and experimentation that operates by rules entirely its own.</p>\n<p>Tiberius excelled there. His aptitude for sorcery was genuine, his intellectual capacity considerable, and his ambition -- the ambition that the Academy both cultivates and fears -- was considerable. But his interests drew him toward the forbidden arts. Necromancy. The manipulation of death itself. The boundaries between life and unlife, the mechanics of the soul&#39;s departure, the possibility of reversal or corruption of that departure.</p>\n<p>The Academy tolerates a great deal. Behind its alabaster walls, Archmages pursue research both sanctioned and clandestine. The institution&#39;s official prohibitions are understood to be somewhat elastic, particularly for those with sufficient talent, political protection, or discretion. But Tiberius&#39;s studies crossed a line that even the Academy&#39;s elastic standards could not accommodate. The blackness of his studies -- the specific nature of which is not fully revealed -- was sufficient to warrant his expulsion.</p>\n<h3 id=\"noble-bloodlines-and-exile\">Noble Bloodlines and Exile</h3>\n<p>What saved Tiberius from execution was his blood. He comes from noble lineage -- a family of sufficient standing within the Empire&#39;s aristocratic hierarchy that the Academy and the Imperial authorities could not simply destroy him without political consequence. A commoner or a <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">servus</a> caught pursuing the same research would have been put to death without ceremony. Tiberius&#39;s noble bloodlines made that politically inconvenient.</p>\n<p>Instead, he was exiled. Cast out from the Academy, stripped of his institutional standing, but permitted to live. The exile was a compromise -- a way for the Academy to enforce its prohibitions without creating a political crisis with a powerful noble house. Tiberius was removed from the institution where his research posed an institutional danger, but he was not removed from the world.</p>\n<p>This distinction matters. Tiberius is an exile, not a prisoner. He retains his knowledge, his abilities, and his noble connections (however strained). He was cast out, but he was not destroyed. And the Backlands -- the frontier where the Empire&#39;s authority is thin and its institutions distant -- is precisely the kind of place where a disgraced noble mage might continue his work with minimal oversight.</p>\n<h3 id=\"coming-to-the-backlands\">Coming to the Backlands</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a> offered Tiberius what the Empire&#39;s heartlands could not: distance from the institutions that had expelled him and proximity to the kind of death -- violent, abundant, and uncatalogued -- that his studies required. The beastman threat, the scalp bounty, the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>, and the untamed wilderness of the northern frontier all provided a landscape rich in the raw materials of necromantic research.</p>\n<p>He joined the group that would become <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>, bringing arcane power of a kind that none of his companions could match. His necromancy makes him the party&#39;s most potent member in terms of raw sorcerous ability, but it also makes him the most dangerous -- to his enemies, to bystanders, and potentially to his companions.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"necromancy\">Necromancy</h2>\n<p>Tiberius is a practicing necromancer. The full scope of his abilities and research is not revealed, but the blackness of his studies at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> was sufficient to warrant expulsion from an institution that tolerates considerable clandestine experimentation. This suggests that his necromantic practice goes beyond the merely academic or theoretical -- that he has crossed boundaries of taste, ethics, or metaphysical safety that even the Academy&#39;s elastic standards could not accommodate.</p>\n<p>In the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, Tiberius operates with relative freedom. The frontier&#39;s institutional structures are too weak to monitor or regulate sorcerous practice with any effectiveness, and the constant supply of death -- from beastman encounters, from the hazards of the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>, from the general violence of frontier life -- provides ample material for a necromancer&#39;s work.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"role-among-the-reclaimers\">Role Among the Reclaimers</h2>\n<p>Tiberius serves as the party&#39;s primary arcane practitioner -- the member whose sorcerous abilities represent the group&#39;s most significant tactical asset. In a world where magic is rare, regulated, and feared, having a trained Academy mage (even a disgraced one) in the party provides capabilities that no amount of martial skill can replicate.</p>\n<p>His companions tolerate his necromancy because they must. The Backlands is not a place where moral squeamishness is a survival trait, and whatever Tiberius does with the dead is less immediately threatening than the beastmen, bandits, and demonic entities that populate the frontier. The calculus is simple: Tiberius&#39;s magic keeps them alive, and the means by which he maintains and extends that magic are best not examined too closely.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"personality\">Personality</h2>\n<p>Tiberius is intelligent, ambitious, and fundamentally unrepentant. He was cast out of the Academy not because he regretted his research but because he was caught -- or because the research reached a point where it could no longer be concealed. He has not abandoned the blackness of his studies. He has simply moved them to a place where no one has the authority or the ability to stop him.</p>\n<p>His noble bearing persists despite his exile. He carries himself with the confidence of a man who was born to privilege and educated at the Empire&#39;s most prestigious institution. The Backlands have not humbled him. If anything, the frontier&#39;s lawlessness has liberated him -- freed him from the institutional constraints that the Academy imposed and that his noble family&#39;s reputation once demanded.</p>\n<p>He is not evil in the simple sense. He is a man whose intellectual curiosity has carried him past boundaries that most people -- including most sorcerers -- would not cross. The blackness of his studies is a darkness of inquiry, not necessarily of intent. But the distinction between dark inquiry and dark intent is one that matters less in practice than in theory.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The adventuring party he belongs to</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- The institution that educated and expelled him</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where he is based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The underground complex currently being explored</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruins above the Nethercity</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Academy representative operating in the Backlands (potential point of tension)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/campaign-chronicle\" class=\"wiki-link\">campaign-chronicle</a> -- Session history of the campaign</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"tolliver-watts","title":"Tolliver Watts","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","bone-creek","double-sevens","merchant","backlands","civilizer"],"html":"<h1 id=\"tolliver-watts\">Tolliver Watts</h1>\n<p><strong>Tolliver Watts</strong> is a wealthy merchant and the proprietor of <strong>Double Sevens</strong>, a relatively new and upscale establishment in <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a>. Unlike most in the frontier settlement, Watts harbors ambitions beyond mere profit — he ultimately seeks to <strong>bring civilization to Bone Creek</strong>, transforming it from a lawless outpost into a proper town.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"double-sevens\">Double Sevens</h2>\n<p>Watts&#39; establishment sits <strong>directly across the street</strong> from <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr&#39;s</a> Pretty Peach, and the contrast between the two is deliberate. Double Sevens caters to the <strong>more successful Scalpers</strong> and the <strong>burgeoning burgher class</strong> of Bone Creek, offering a notable step up in quality.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Serves <strong>imported spirits, wines, and ales</strong> (not the watered-down swill of the Peach)</li>\n<li>Hosts <strong>gambling tables</strong></li>\n<li>Employs its own prostitutes, who are <strong>&quot;held to a higher standard than Peach girls&quot;</strong></li>\n<li>Represents Watts&#39; vision of what Bone Creek could become</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"associates\">Associates</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Madame Selka</strong> — A young and beautiful <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#shenti\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shenti</a> woman who oversees the working girls at Double Sevens. She and Watts have <strong>frequent, public arguments</strong>, suggesting a complicated relationship.</li>\n<li><strong>Frog</strong> — Watts&#39; assistant and advisor. A lifelong slave who is an expert with administration and numbers. Frog handles the business details that keep Double Sevens running smoothly.</li>\n<li><strong>Three-Finger Kanos</strong> — Bodyguard and head of security for Double Sevens. Provides the muscle Watts needs to protect his investment and his person.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"alliances\">Alliances</h2>\n<p>Watts is a <strong>close ally</strong> of <strong><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cassian Varro</a></strong>, the Lord Merchant of the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium&#39;s</a> Red River Exchange. This alliance between Watts&#39; wealth and the Consortium&#39;s economic power represents the strongest political bloc in Bone Creek, one oriented toward commerce, order, and development.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"rivalries\">Rivalries</h2>\n<p>The <strong>simmering rivalry</strong> between Double Sevens and <a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">Thaddeus Marr&#39;s</a> Pretty Peach has already resulted in <strong>large-scale brawls</strong>. This conflict is more than a business dispute — it reflects a fundamental disagreement about what Bone Creek should be. Marr represents the rough, lawless frontier; Watts represents the push toward civilization.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Watts is described as a <strong>wealthy merchant</strong> — polished enough to attract a higher class of clientele, ambitious enough to envision a civilized Bone Creek, and pragmatic enough to ally with the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> to make it happen. His willingness to employ slaves (Frog) and prostitutes while simultaneously championing &quot;civilization&quot; suggests a complex, possibly hypocritical character.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The settlement Watts seeks to civilize</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thaddeus-marr\" class=\"wiki-link\">thaddeus-marr</a> — Watts&#39; rival across the street</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cassian-varro\" class=\"wiki-link\">cassian-varro</a> — Watts&#39; ally and Lord Merchant of the Red River Exchange</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">red-river-consortium</a> — The trading consortium allied with Watts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"valeria-thorne","title":"Valeria Thorne","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","merchant","red-river-consortium","sanctuary","politician","commerce"],"html":"<h1 id=\"valeria-thorne\">Valeria Thorne</h1>\n<p><strong>Valeria Thorne</strong> (age 58) is the Directrix of the <a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a>&#39;s <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> branch. She has held the rotating leadership position for an unprecedented <strong>three consecutive terms</strong>, a testament to both her competence and her political acumen. Shrewd and ruthless when necessary, Thorne has aligned the Consortium politically with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> -- an alliance that critics argue has made her the Governor&#39;s creature rather than an independent commercial leader.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"at-a-glance\">At a Glance</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Detail</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Full Name</strong></td>\n<td>Valeria Thorne</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Age</strong></td>\n<td>58</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Title</strong></td>\n<td>Directrix, <span class=\"dead-link\">Red River Consortium</span> operates on a system of rotating leadership, designed to prevent any single individual from accumulating too much power within the organization. Thorne has held the Directrix position for three consecutive terms -- a feat without precedent in the Consortium&#39;s history. Her continued tenure reflects several factors:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Competence</strong> -- Under her leadership, the Sanctuary branch has been profitable and well-managed</li>\n<li><strong>Political connections</strong> -- Her alignment with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> gives the Consortium favorable treatment in provincial trade policy</li>\n<li><strong>Strategic marriages</strong> -- Thorne married her niece to one of the Governor&#39;s subordinates, creating a personal bond between her family and the Drussus power structure</li>\n<li><strong>Ruthlessness</strong> -- Those who have challenged her leadership within the Consortium have found their opposition quietly and effectively neutralized</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-drussus-alliance\">The Drussus Alliance</h2>\n<p>Thorne&#39;s political alignment with <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a> is the defining feature of her leadership. The alliance gives Drussus access to the Consortium&#39;s commercial networks, wealth, and intelligence, while the Consortium benefits from favorable treatment in provincial trade policy, tax assessments, and contract allocation.</p>\n<p>Critics within the Consortium whisper that Thorne has become <strong>Drussus&#39;s creature</strong> -- that her loyalty to the Governor has compromised the Consortium&#39;s independence and turned what should be a commercial organization into an extension of the Governor&#39;s political machine. Whether this criticism is fair or merely the complaints of rivals who lack her political instinct is a matter of perspective.</p>\n<p>The marriage of her niece to one of the Governor&#39;s subordinates has deepened the personal ties between Thorne and the Drussus power structure, making any future separation of interests increasingly difficult.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"character\">Character</h2>\n<p>Thorne is <strong>shrewd</strong> above all else. She reads people and situations with the precision of a woman who has spent four decades in the competitive world of frontier commerce. She is pleasant when pleasantness serves her interests, accommodating when accommodation is profitable, and ruthless when ruthlessness is required. She does not waste energy on sentimentality, ideology, or personal grudges.</p>\n<p>Her critics may call her the Governor&#39;s creature, but Thorne would likely argue that she has positioned the Consortium to thrive in the only political environment that matters -- the one that exists right now, in <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, under <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Drussus</a>&#39;s authority.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/red-river-consortium\" class=\"wiki-link\">Red River Consortium</a> -- the organization she leads</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Governor Valerios Drussus</a> -- her political patron/ally</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> -- the city where she operates</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/house-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">House Drussus</a> -- the Great House she is aligned with</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Backlands</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"varek-ashstone","title":"Varek Ashstone","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","ygrathen","kharai","cairnhouse","lake-silverhead","hermit","binding","ancient","vigil","kantar","avari","penance"],"html":"<h1 id=\"varek-ashstone\">Varek Ashstone</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p>&quot;It does not threaten. It waits. It has more time than anything built to contain it.&quot; -- Attributed to Varek Ashstone</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Varek Ashstone</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> hermit who built the cairnhouse at <strong><a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead#kantar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kantar</a></strong> -- the island in <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a> in the far north of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a> -- and who has maintained a solitary vigil over it for centuries. He lives in a stone dwelling on the lake&#39;s northern shore. He has been there longer than the oldest memory of the village.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> call him <strong>the Old One</strong>, or simply <strong>Varek</strong>. They speak of him with careful respect -- not fear, not reverence, but the particular regard one gives to something that has endured long enough to warrant it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"appearance-and-bearing\">Appearance and Bearing</h2>\n<p>Varek is <strong>very large</strong> and <strong>very old</strong>. He carries a sorrow that the elders of the nearby Avari village speak of with careful respect -- not as gossip or curiosity but as something they recognize and do not presume to understand. Whatever happened to Varek, whatever price he paid, whatever loss he carries, it is not a subject for casual inquiry. The elders know enough to know that.</p>\n<p>He is <strong>very tired</strong> and <strong>very capable</strong>. The two qualities coexist without contradiction. Varek has been doing what he does for a very long time, and the weight of that duration is visible in him -- but the power that sustains his vigil has not diminished. He endures because he must, and because he can.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-vigil\">The Vigil</h2>\n<p>Varek will not leave the lake. His vigil is not optional. It is not a choice he makes each morning and could unmake each evening. It is the fixed point around which his existence has been organized for centuries.</p>\n<p>The cairnhouse at Kantar holds something -- one or more of the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a>, the Imprisoned Ones -- that required sustained attention for the duration of its imprisonment. The binding is not passive. It does not simply hold and endure. It requires monitoring, maintenance, and the ongoing presence of someone capable of responding to changes in the binding&#39;s integrity. Varek is that someone. He has been that someone for longer than any living memory extends.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-went-wrong\">What Went Wrong</h3>\n<p>Something went wrong during the construction of the cairnhouse at Kantar. <strong>People died.</strong> The details are not widely known -- Varek does not speak of it, and the Avari elders refer to it only obliquely, with the careful indirection that marks a wound too deep for direct address. Whatever happened, the cost was real and the loss was grievous.</p>\n<p>Varek has spent the centuries since as <strong>penance</strong>. His vigil is not merely duty -- it is atonement. He watches the island. He monitors the binding&#39;s output for signs of change. He endures because the alternative is to abandon what he built at a cost he has never forgiven himself for paying.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"power-and-tradition\">Power and Tradition</h2>\n<p>Varek&#39;s power is the <strong>binding tradition</strong>: the art of sealing and containing powerful entities. This is the same tradition that the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> used to construct all the cairnhouses -- the structures that hold the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> across the world. Varek is one of the last living practitioners of this tradition at its full scale.</p>\n<p>His capabilities are demonstrated not in dramatic displays of force but in what does not happen near <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Things from the outlands that have approached Kantar have been <strong>turned away</strong>. They were not destroyed. They were <strong>bound, redirected, or persuaded</strong> that the cost of Kantar was greater than the return. The distinction matters. Varek does not kill what comes. He contains it, deflects it, or convinces it -- through means that do not rely on violence -- that it does not want what it thinks it wants.</li>\n<li>The binding at Kantar has held for centuries. The cairnhouse functions. The <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a> within remain imprisoned. This is not the result of a good design left to run on its own -- it is the result of constant, sustained attention by someone who understands the binding at a level no contemporary scholar can replicate.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"relationship-to-the-avari\">Relationship to the Avari</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> communities near <a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lake Silverhead</a> have coexisted with Varek for generations beyond counting. They call him <strong>the Old One</strong> or <strong>Varek</strong> -- familiar names, not titles of awe. He is part of their landscape, as much as the lake itself or the hills beyond it. They do not worship him. They do not fear him. They respect him in the way one respects a mountain: it was there before you, it will be there after you, and it is not your place to question why.</p>\n<p>The elders speak of Varek&#39;s sorrow with careful respect. They do not pry. They do not speculate. They acknowledge what they see and leave the rest to him.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-argollean-brotherhood\">The Argollean Brotherhood</h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> seeks access to the cairnhouse at Kantar for the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> binding structures it contains. Varek&#39;s response to such interest is not recorded, but the Brotherhood&#39;s inability to gain access to the <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> cairnhouse -- where the town itself stands in their way -- suggests that Varek&#39;s vigil at Kantar presents an equally impassable obstacle. A man who has spent centuries guarding a binding is unlikely to permit academic tourists to examine it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-kharai</a> -- The Imprisoned Ones, one or more of whom Varek guards</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lake-silverhead\" class=\"wiki-link\">lake-silverhead</a> -- The lake where Varek maintains his vigil</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">cairnhill</a> -- The other known cairnhouse in Argolle</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#ygrathen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ygrathen</a> -- Varek&#39;s people and the builders of the cairnhouses</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- The faction seeking cairnhouse access</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lakandi-binding-tradition\" class=\"wiki-link\">lakandi-binding-tradition</a> -- A related binding tradition operating at smaller scale</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-erenthis\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-erenthis</a> -- Another ancient defense against Cthonic corruption</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari</a> -- The people who live near Varek and call him the Old One</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"wekko","title":"Wekko","category":"people","status":"active","tags":["npc","witch-doctor","kolani","scalper","hollow-men","ritualistic","ominous","backlands","bone-creek","prophecy","cult"],"html":"<h1 id=\"wekko\">Wekko</h1>\n<p><strong>Wekko</strong> is a <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> witch-doctor and the enigmatic leader of the <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-hollow-men\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hollow Men</a></strong>, a Scalper group that operates with an <strong>ominous, ritualistic, and alien</strong> quality that sets them apart from every other gang in the <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>. Always masked and perpetually silent, Wekko is a figure of dread and mystery — a <strong>cultic presence</strong> whose true goals and methods remain shrouded in secrecy. Where other Scalper leaders are defined by greed, violence, or ideology, Wekko is defined by an unsettling otherness that defies easy categorization.</p>\n<p>Wekko represents the potential for either <strong>prophecy or violence</strong> — or both. The Hollow Men are not merely hunters; they are practitioners of something older and darker than the Imperial Bounty, and Wekko stands at their center like a silent idol.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"statistics\">Statistics</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Attribute</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Class</strong></td>\n<td>Witch-Doctor 6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Race</strong></td>\n<td><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>ac</strong></td>-<td>5</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>hp</strong></td>-<td>24</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>atk</strong></td>-<td>+3-(bone-spear,-1d6+1)</td>-</tr>-<tr>-<td><strong>wis</strong></td>-<td>16</td>-</tr>-</tbody></table></div>-<p>wekko&#39;s-statistics-reflect-a-spiritual-leader-rather-than-a-front-line-warrior.-his-ac-of-5-and-24-hit-points-provide-moderate-protection,-while-his-bone-spear-—-a-weapon-as-ritualistic-as-it-is-practical-—-deals-respectable-damage.-his-true-power-lies-in-his-wisdom-of-16,-which-fuels-his-spellcasting-and-his-connection-to-whatever-spiritual-forces-he-channels.-as-a-witch-doctor-6,-wekko-commands-significant-supernatural-power,-making-him-far-more-dangerous-than-his-physical-statistics-might-suggest.</p>-<hr>-<h2-id=\"spells\">spells</h2>-<ul>-<li><strong>cause-fear</strong>-—-invoking-supernatural-terror-in-a-target,-forcing-them-to-flee-in-mindless-panic.-this-spell-reflects-wekko&#39;s-mastery-of-psychological-warfare-and-his-understanding-that-the-mind-is-the-most-vulnerable-target.-for-a-leader-who-never-speaks-and-always-wears-a-mask,-the-ability-to-weaponize-fear-is-grimly-appropriate.</li>-<li><strong>curse</strong>-—-inflicting-a-lasting-supernatural-affliction-upon-a-target.-curses-are-among-the-most-feared-forms-of-magic-—-lingering,-insidious,-and-often-resistant-to-conventional-healing.-wekko&#39;s-ability-to-curse-his-enemies-makes-him-a-figure-to-be-avoided-rather-than-confronted.</li>-<li><strong>speak-with-dead</strong>-—-communing-with-the-spirits-of-the-deceased.-this-spell-reveals-the-deepest-layer-of-wekko&#39;s-practice:-he-walks-between-the-worlds-of-the-living-and-the-dead,-drawing-knowledge-and-perhaps-power-from-those-who-have-passed-beyond.-in-the-[[the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands</a>, where death is a constant companion, this ability gives Wekko access to secrets that no living person could provide.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Wekko&#39;s spell selection paints a picture of a practitioner who deals in <strong>fear, suffering, and death</strong> — the three constants of life in the Backlands. His magic is not flashy or destructive; it is insidious, personal, and deeply unsettling.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"proficiencies\">Proficiencies</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Terror</strong> — The systematic use of fear as a tool of control, intimidation, and psychological warfare. This goes beyond simple intimidation — Terror as a proficiency suggests a methodical, almost academic understanding of how to break the human mind through dread. Wekko does not merely frighten people; he dismantles their courage at a fundamental level.</li>\n<li><strong>Prophecy</strong> — The art of divination and foretelling. Like <a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a>, Wekko possesses the ability to peer into the future or claim divine revelation. Whether Wekko&#39;s prophecies are genuine, whether they align with or conflict with Shaw&#39;s, and what they foretell are all matters of grave importance.</li>\n<li><strong>Healing</strong> — The ability to mend wounds and cure ailments through spiritual or herbal means. This proficiency provides a striking counterpoint to Wekko&#39;s otherwise ominous profile. The witch-doctor who deals in fear, curses, and the dead also possesses the power to heal — suggesting a figure who understands the full cycle of life and death, and who can offer salvation as easily as damnation.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"appearance-and-demeanor\">Appearance and Demeanor</h2>\n<p>Wekko is <strong>always masked</strong>. The mask is not a disguise — it is an identity. Whether it is carved wood, bone, animal hide, or something stranger, the mask transforms Wekko from a person into a symbol, a vessel, a thing that exists between the human and the supernatural. No one in the Backlands has seen Wekko&#39;s face, and this absence of a face is itself a source of power and dread.</p>\n<p>Wekko is <strong>perpetually silent</strong>. He does not speak — not in greeting, not in negotiation, not in combat. Whether this silence is a vow, a consequence of some ritual or injury, or simply a choice, it amplifies the alien quality of his presence. A masked, silent figure leading a band of ritualistic hunters through the Backlands is a vision from a nightmare, and Wekko cultivates that impression deliberately or instinctively.</p>\n<p>His demeanor is described as <strong>ominous</strong>, <strong>ritualistic</strong>, and <strong>alien</strong>. These are not the qualities of a frontier mercenary — they are the qualities of a priest, a shaman, or a conduit for forces that most people in the Backlands do not understand and cannot confront. Wekko exists in a space between the mundane world of Scalpers and bounties and a spiritual realm of visions, curses, and communion with the dead.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-hollow-men\">The Hollow Men</h2>\n<p>The <strong><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-hollow-men\" class=\"wiki-link\">Hollow Men</a></strong> are a Scalper gang unlike any other. While other gangs are defined by their brutality (<a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#skin-eaters\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters</a>), their chaos (<a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-dregs\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dregs</a>), or their ideology (<a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-bleak-sons\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bleak Sons</a>), the Hollow Men are defined by their <strong>ritualistic nature</strong> and their leader&#39;s cultic authority.</p>\n<p>The name &quot;Hollow Men&quot; itself is evocative and disturbing. Are the followers hollow — emptied of their former selves by Wekko&#39;s rituals? Have they been hollowed out to serve as vessels for something else? Or does the name refer to a spiritual state — men who have looked into the void and found themselves empty? The name resonates with themes of loss, transformation, and the surrender of individual identity to a greater (or darker) purpose.</p>\n<p>The Hollow Men&#39;s presence in the Backlands represents a <strong>cultic element</strong> in the Scalper trade — a reminder that the beastman hunts attract not only mercenaries and soldiers but also those drawn by darker motivations. Wekko and his followers may hunt beastmen for the bounty, but they also appear to be engaged in practices that have nothing to do with imperial gold.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"dual-nature-prophecy-and-violence\">Dual Nature: Prophecy and Violence</h2>\n<p>Wekko&#39;s role in the Backlands is characterized by the potential for <strong>prophecy or violence</strong> — and the two may be inseparable. His proficiency in Prophecy suggests he receives visions or insights about the future, and his proficiency in Terror suggests he is capable of inflicting devastating psychological and physical harm.</p>\n<p>This duality makes Wekko one of the most dangerous and unpredictable figures in the Backlands. He could:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Deliver a prophecy</strong> that reshapes the political and spiritual landscape of <a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek</a></li>\n<li><strong>Unleash violence</strong> through curses, fear, and the fanatical devotion of his followers</li>\n<li><strong>Do both simultaneously</strong>, using prophetic authority to justify or motivate acts of ritualistic violence</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The intersection of prophecy and violence is a potent and terrifying combination, and Wekko embodies it in a way that no other figure in the Backlands can match.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"plot-hooks\">Plot Hooks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Mask</strong> — What lies beneath Wekko&#39;s mask? Removing it — willingly or by force — could reveal a face, a void, a brand, or something worse.</li>\n<li><strong>The Silence</strong> — Why does Wekko never speak? Is it a vow, a curse, a ritual requirement, or a choice? Breaking the silence could have profound consequences.</li>\n<li><strong>Speak with Dead</strong> — Wekko can commune with the dead. In a place as steeped in death as the Backlands, this ability gives him access to secrets that could shake the foundations of power in Bone Creek. What has he learned from the dead?</li>\n<li><strong>Competing Prophets</strong> — Both Wekko and <a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a> possess the Prophecy proficiency. Do their visions align, conflict, or complement each other? A meeting between these two prophetic figures could be explosive.</li>\n<li><strong>The Hollow Men&#39;s Rituals</strong> — What do the Hollow Men do when they are not hunting beastmen? Their ritualistic nature suggests practices that go beyond the bounty trade — practices that could involve the dead, the cursed, or forces from beyond the mortal world.</li>\n<li><strong>Healing and Harm</strong> — Wekko&#39;s combination of Healing and Terror makes him a figure who can save or destroy with equal facility. Those who seek his healing may find themselves indebted to a power they do not understand.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs#the-hollow-men\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Hollow Men</a> — Wekko&#39;s gang</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">bone-creek</a> — The Scalper settlement</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> — The frontier province</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#kolani\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kolani</a> — Wekko&#39;s cultural heritage</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> — Another prophetic figure in the Backlands; potential rival or counterpart</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">congregation-of-the-hollow-sun</a> — Shaw&#39;s secretive religious group; possible parallels with the Hollow Men</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/cthonic-faith\" class=\"wiki-link\">cthonic-faith</a> — Dark religious traditions that may relate to Wekko&#39;s practices</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/beastmen\" class=\"wiki-link\">beastmen</a> — The creatures the Hollow Men hunt</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"slug":"campaign-chronicle","title":"Campaign Chronicle","category":"sessions","status":"unknown","tags":["sessions","chronicle","reclaimers","backlands","campaign-history","crossings","fort-meade","scalpers","beastmen","necropede","gilded-oath","cairnhill","gallowswood","nagrand","eolande","stone-of-sakkara","guzzler","charter","sanctuary"],"html":"<h1 id=\"campaign-chronicle\">Campaign Chronicle</h1>\n<blockquote class=\"flavor-text\"><p><em>&quot;They came to the Backlands as carrion comes, drawn to rot. This was the northern province of Argolle where the land lay charred with old wars and the bones of empires still pushed from the dirt when the rains came. Six years gone the border city of Crossings was put to the torch by a horde of beastmen vast beyond counting and the people were butchered in their homes and the Emperor in his distant hall decreed then that a man might trade death for coin and a gold mark was set for every beast&#39;s scalp and so the land filled with killers.&quot;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This page serves as the master chronicle of the Fallen Empire campaign -- a record of the sessions, arcs, and events as they unfolded at the table. The campaign is set in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a>, the northern province of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argolle</a>, six years after the fall of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> to a beastman horde of unprecedented scale. The <a href=\"#/page/emperor-aurex\" class=\"wiki-link\">Emperor</a>&#39;s scalp bounty drew a tide of killers, fugitives, and opportunists to the frontier, and among them came the adventurers who would become known as <a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Reclaimers</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-reclaimers-cast-of-player-characters\">The Reclaimers -- Cast of Player Characters</h2>\n<p>The Reclaimers are the player character party. They arrived in the Backlands individually -- each drawn by the scalp bounty, by desperation, or by some private motive they did not share. They are formally part of <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> household at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> and hold his writ of tax exemption. Their true patron is <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a>, who hired them without her husband&#39;s knowledge.</p>\n<h3 id=\"active-members\">Active Members</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Character</th>\n<th>Class</th>\n<th>Player Summary</th>\n<th>Status</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>**<span class=\"dead-link\">shatzi</td>\n<td>Shatzi</span>**</td>\n<td>Merchant</td>\n<td>Failed and cast down, but sly -- never finished. Seeks some angle to claw back what the world took. Organizer of the Reclaimers.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**<span class=\"dead-link\">theodotus</td>\n<td>Theodotus</span>**</td>\n<td>Philosopher-Bard (Thrassian)</td>\n<td>Books had soured him. Came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands. Carries the <span class=\"dead-link\">the-stone-of-sakkara</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**[[tiberius</td>\n<td>Tiberius</span>**</td>\n<td>Mage (Necromancer)</td>\n<td>Schooled at the <span class=\"dead-link\">imperial-academy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**[[iman</td>\n<td>Iman</span>**</td>\n<td>Bladedancer</td>\n<td>Driven from the <span class=\"dead-link\">order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3 id=\"former-members\">Former Members</h3>\n<div class=\"table-wrapper\"><table><thead><tr>\n<th>Character</th>\n<th>Class</th>\n<th>Player Summary</th>\n<th>Status</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody><tr>\n<td>**[[tancred</td>\n<td>Tancred</span>**</td>\n<td>Crusader</td>\n<td>Bore the fire of <span class=\"dead-link\">seros</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>**[[rendson</td>\n<td>Rendson</span>**</td>\n<td>Avari Gambler</td>\n<td>Whoremonger, fugitive from debts, past soiled and unrevealed. Earned the name &quot;Grim Sleeper.&quot; Died alongside Tancred.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"campaign-arcs\">Campaign Arcs</h2>\n<p>The campaign has progressed through several distinct phases, each defined by the threats faced, the territory explored, and the political entanglements deepened.</p>\n<h3 id=\"arc-i-arrival-and-the-scalp-trade\">Arc I -- Arrival and the Scalp Trade</h3>\n<p>The Reclaimers arrived in <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> as individual scalpers -- killers drawn by the Emperor&#39;s bounty on beastman scalps. The Backlands at this time were a lawless frontier province, charred by the destruction of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> six years prior. The scalp trade attracted a brutal class of opportunists: soldiers of fortune, debtors fleeing their past, exiles, and the desperate. The Reclaimers were among them, and in those early days they were indistinguishable from the other <a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper gangs</a> roaming the province.</p>\n<p>During this period, <strong>Rendson</strong> -- an Avari gambler and fugitive -- was among the party&#39;s number. His past was soiled and unrevealed, his debts considerable, and his habits worse. He departed the group early and vanished into the frontier. His fate is unknown.</p>\n<h3 id=\"arc-ii-fort-meade-and-the-destruction-of-rook\">Arc II -- Fort Meade and the Destruction of Rook</h3>\n<p>The Reclaimers came to the attention of <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina Marcellus</a> at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, the garrison commanded by her husband <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a>. Severina hired them without the Legate&#39;s knowledge, and they were formally absorbed into the Marcellus household with a writ of tax exemption.</p>\n<p>Their first major undertaking was the destruction of <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> -- the bandit whose campaign of terror had paralyzed the settlements and trade routes of the Backlands. The garrison at Fort Meade could not resolve the threat. The Reclaimers tracked Rook to his base at <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>, the ruined marsh fort east of Fort Meade, and destroyed him there. This victory was both a vindication and a humiliation -- it delivered what the Legate&#39;s own soldiers could not.</p>\n<p>It was during this period that <strong><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred</a></strong> and <strong><a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rendson</a></strong> fell in battle against a <strong>necropede</strong> -- a vile undead abomination. Tancred held fast with nothing but shield and faith so that others might live. Rendson, the &quot;Grim Sleeper,&quot; lifted his blade beside his brothers and sisters and died in the fight. Both were given eulogies: <a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a> spoke for both men, acknowledging Rendson&#39;s flaws but praising his courage in the end. <a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a> also gave a competing eulogy, using Tancred&#39;s death to advance his movement -- turning a warrior&#39;s sacrifice into rhetorical fuel for his political ambitions.</p>\n<h3 id=\"arc-iii-the-stone-of-sakkara-and-the-guzzler\">Arc III -- The Stone of Sakkara and the Guzzler</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> came into possession of the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a> -- an artifact of terrible and uncertain power. The Stone&#39;s presence at <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> drew <a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Guzzler</a>, the demonic entity occupying <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a>, toward the garrison. The Guzzler cannot precisely locate the Stone but can sense its pull, compromising the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature. The approximately one hundred soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The Stone&#39;s presence creates a threat the garrison was never designed to counter.</p>\n<h3 id=\"arc-iv-the-nethercity\">Arc IV -- The Nethercity</h3>\n<p>The Reclaimers are currently exploring the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> beneath the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> -- an underground complex of vast scope and mortal danger. The Nethercity has begun yielding artifacts of genuine <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> provenance, drawing the attention of multiple competing factions. The <a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Argollean Brotherhood</a> monitors what the Reclaimers recover. <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a>, representing the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a>, has a competing interest in the same relics.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"political-context\">Political Context</h2>\n<p>The Reclaimers operate within a web of political relationships that has grown more complex as the campaign has progressed:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina</a></strong> hired them and remains their true patron. <a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">Shatzi</a> is invited to her gatherings. <a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">Iman</a> has developed a close personal relationship with her.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a></strong> tolerates them because they are useful, though their existence within his household is a reminder of his wife&#39;s independent political judgment.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Argollean Brotherhood</a></strong> watches what they bring up from the Nethercity with acquisitive interest.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a></strong> and the <strong><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a></strong> compete for the same artifacts the Brotherhood wants.</li>\n<li><strong>The <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a></strong> makes them a danger to the garrison that shelters them.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"the-world-they-entered\">The World They Entered</h2>\n<p>The Backlands in the sixth year after the fall of Crossings is a land of ash and opportunity. The beastman horde that sacked the border city was vast beyond counting -- an event that shattered the province&#39;s northern defenses and depopulated entire districts. The Emperor&#39;s response was not to send legions but to set a price: a gold mark for every beast&#39;s scalp. This edict transformed the province into a hunting ground, drawing killers from across the Empire.</p>\n<p>The land itself bears the scars. Old wars have charred the earth. The bones of earlier empires push from the dirt when the rains come. The infrastructure of civilization -- roads, watchtowers, garrison forts -- exists in various states of ruin and partial repair. <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> is one such outpost, maintained by the Legate&#39;s garrison as a fragile point of order in a landscape that has largely reverted to wilderness and violence.</p>\n<p>Into this world came the Reclaimers: a failed merchant, a disillusioned philosopher, a disgraced mage, an expelled bladedancer, a zealous crusader, and a gambler on the run. They were not heroes. They were the kind of people the scalp bounty was designed to attract -- expendable, desperate, and willing to kill for coin. What they became is the subject of this chronicle.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"session-prep-notes-recent-developments\">Session Prep Notes -- Recent Developments</h2>\n<p>The following details are drawn from recent session preparation materials and reflect events at or near the current point in the campaign.</p>\n<h3 id=\"the-necropede-battle-and-the-deaths-of-tancred-and-rendson\">The Necropede Battle and the Deaths of Tancred and Rendson</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tancred</a> and <a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rendson</a> both died fighting a <strong>necropede</strong> -- a vile undead abomination encountered during operations in the Backlands. Tancred faced the creature with nothing but shield and faith, holding fast so that others might live. Rendson, who had earned the name &quot;Grim Sleeper&quot; for striking beasts where they lay, fought beside him and fell. Both deaths were confirmed.</p>\n<p><strong>The Eulogies:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">Brother Marco</a> gave the eulogy for both men. His words for Rendson were an act of mercy: acknowledging the man&#39;s flaws -- gambler, whoremonger, fugitive -- while insisting that his death redeemed what his life had not.</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Ezekiel Shaw</a> gave a <strong>competing eulogy</strong>, using Tancred&#39;s death to advance his movement. Shaw turned the crusader&#39;s sacrifice into political rhetoric, claiming the death as evidence for his cause rather than honoring it on its own terms.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"henchmen-status\">Henchmen Status</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Antonius</strong> -- Had a <strong>vision of Rendson</strong> near the point of death. The nature and significance of this vision is unresolved.</li>\n<li><strong>Anaya</strong> -- Suffered a <strong>critical wound from a zombie beastman</strong>. She is feverish, the wound infected. In her delirium she speaks of a <strong>pulsating black heart beneath a mound in <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a></strong> -- a vision or a memory, the distinction unclear.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"tiberiuss-discovery-the-gilded-oath-documents\">Tiberius&#39;s Discovery -- The Gilded Oath Documents</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> found documents in <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill</a> written in <strong>Argollean</strong> script. The documents point to <strong>four locations in the hills east of Cairnhill</strong> containing burial spots of <strong>Gilded Oath</strong> beings -- the <a href=\"#/page/races-and-cultures#elvoran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Elvoran</a> warrior-priests who underwent the Sevenfold Wounding and entered guardian tombs to maintain the seals binding the <a href=\"#/page/the-kharai\" class=\"wiki-link\">Kharai</a>. This discovery connects directly to <a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Gilded Vigil</a> and the guardian tomb network in the <a href=\"#/page/cairnhill#the-cairnhill-breaks\" class=\"wiki-link\">Cairnhill Breaks</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"malyns-findings-beastmen-origins\">Malyn&#39;s Findings -- Beastmen Origins</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malyn&#39;s</a> research has revealed critical information about the beastmen:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Beastmen are <strong>more prone to the corrupting influence of chaotic/Cthonic energy</strong> than other beings</li>\n<li>They were <strong>created during the First Empire as slave soldiers</strong>, produced by infusing man with beast -- a deliberate act of magical engineering, not natural evolution</li>\n<li>They were originally located in an <strong>ancient temple dedicated to &quot;Nagrand&quot;</strong> -- a name not previously documented in the campaign&#39;s theological records</li>\n<li>The connection between beastmen, Cthonic corruption, and First Empire slave-soldier programs suggests the beastman horde that destroyed <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> may not have been a natural disaster but the consequence of ancient imperial engineering coming undone</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"the-gallowswood-dreams\">The Gallowswood Dreams</h3>\n<p>Multiple sources report dreams of a <strong>black pulsating heart beating beneath a granite dome</strong> in <a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">Gallowswood</a>. The dreams feature:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Twisted crimson veins</strong> radiating from the heart</li>\n<li>An <strong>awakened lust for power</strong> in the dreamer</li>\n<li>A sense of something vast and hungry stirring beneath the earth</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Anaya&#39;s feverish descriptions of the pulsating heart beneath a mound in Gallowswood echo these dreams. Whether the dreams are prophetic, the product of Cthonic influence, or the psychic bleed of another sealed entity is unknown.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"arc-v-fort-meade-to-sanctuary-three-scenes\">Arc V -- Fort Meade to Sanctuary: Three Scenes</h2>\n<p>The following arc covers the Reclaimers&#39; journey south from <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a> to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, encompassing three critical developments: the revelation of <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a> at the Black Tree, the escalating crisis of the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>, and <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus&#39;s</a> formal charter proposal.</p>\n<h3 id=\"scene-1-malachor-wants-everything\">Scene 1: Malachor Wants Everything</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> approaches the Reclaimers within hours of their return from <a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Black Tree</a> -- not through a steward, not through <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Marcellus</a>. Directly, and with barely-composed urgency. He has heard enough from garrison talk to know something significant happened at the Black Tree. He needs confirmation. Then everything.</p>\n<p><strong>Malachor&#39;s Questions:</strong></p>\n<p>His questions function as interrogation prompts, not a script. He will return to any the party deflects:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What language did <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a> speak? Did he understand Mithrian, or only the old tongue?</li>\n<li>How coherent was he -- did he seem aware of time passing? Does he know the <a href=\"#/page/argollean-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">First Empire</a> has fallen?</li>\n<li>What did he say about the <strong>Womb Curse</strong>? About the <a href=\"#/page/eladra\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladra</a>? About <a href=\"#/page/bel\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bel</a>?</li>\n<li><strong>The sword.</strong> Every detail. Does it bear any inscription?</li>\n<li><strong>The dryad</strong> -- is the tree alive? Is she bound to the dead wood, or to something that remains in it?</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Malachor&#39;s Ask:</strong></p>\n<p>He wants to accompany the party to <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>. He frames this as mutual convenience -- he has contacts at the <a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">Imperial Academy</a> chapter there, and what the party has witnessed constitutes academic testimony of enormous value.</p>\n<p>For <a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">Tiberius</a> specifically: Malachor offers an introduction to senior Academy figures, vouched by him, with the Reclaimers&#39; testimony behind it. For a man looking to recover lost standing after expulsion from the Academy, that is not nothing.</p>\n<p><strong>The expedition he is already forming:</strong> Two Academy assistants he intends to summon to Sanctuary, himself, and the Reclaimers as escort into <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a>. He presents this as something to finalize after they return from Sanctuary. He will push on every subsequent encounter.</p>\n<p><strong>GM Note -- The Dispatch:</strong></p>\n<p>That night Malachor writes the most significant dispatch of his career. His secret third-party contact -- the unnamed buyer who has received dry academic reports for years -- receives something fundamentally different. Malachor knows it the moment he finishes writing. He sends it before fully considering what he has set in motion. Whatever that contact represents, they now know about <a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eolande</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"scene-2-the-stone-and-the-guzzler\">Scene 2: The Stone and the Guzzler</h3>\n<p><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">The Guzzler</a> has been ranging further from <a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Ikenvar</a> for weeks, drawn by the <a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">Stone of Sakkara</a>. It cannot locate the Stone precisely -- it feels it the way an animal senses weather before it turns. When the party moved to <a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">Fort Meade</a>, it followed. Now it follows south toward <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Trail of Incidents</strong> (delivered as rumors, reports, and roadside encounters -- not all at once):</p>\n<ol>\n<li>A farm three miles south of Fort Meade: goats taken, fence posts crushed in. The farmer reports it two days late, embarrassed he waited.</li>\n<li>A merchant on the Sanctuary road: his draft horse found half-consumed at the roadside. He saw nothing. Heard nothing. The horse was simply gone.</li>\n<li>Closer to Sanctuary: a child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>The Stone&#39;s Influence:</strong></p>\n<p>The Stone is not directing the Guzzler with intelligence. But it is amplifying its hunger toward the soft and the innocent. <a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Theodotus</a> will not perceive this clearly -- he will feel it as a wrongness, a sense that the suffering he is hearing about is somehow adjacent to the weight in his pack. He refused to feed the Stone. So the Stone reached further.</p>\n<p><strong>Theodotus&#39;s Moment:</strong></p>\n<p>When the child&#39;s disappearance reaches him, the wrongness crystallizes. This is the test. Not a combat encounter. A question:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Does he tell the party what he suspects?</li>\n<li>Does he try to destroy the Stone -- and does he know how?</li>\n<li>Does he draw the Guzzler away from the road deliberately?</li>\n<li>Does he realize that putting distance between himself and the Stone means it simply calls the creature further, and the geometry of innocence does not change?</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>GM Note:</strong> The Guzzler arriving near Sanctuary is a consequence, not an encounter. Killing it resolves nothing -- the Stone will reach through something else. If the party fights it in an urban-adjacent environment, that is a very different problem than the marsh. The scene ends when Theodotus decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies.</p>\n<h3 id=\"scene-3-the-legates-proposal\">Scene 3: The Legate&#39;s Proposal</h3>\n<p>Before the party departs for <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a>, <a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Legate Marcellus</a> requests a formal meeting. The message is delivered by his steward -- not <a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crull</a>, not a soldier. This is deliberate, and the party may notice it.</p>\n<p><strong>The Room:</strong> The Legate&#39;s meeting room. A map of <a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the Backlands</a> dominates one wall. Marcellus stands. <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Lady Severina</a> is present, seated slightly to the side -- not beside him. Crull is not in the room.</p>\n<p><strong>The Proposal:</strong></p>\n<p>Marcellus opens by noting the Reclaimers brought four thousand gold worth of goods through his market in a single visit. Tax exempt. He lets that sit, then presents a formal business arrangement:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A formal charter:</strong> The Reclaimers are his licensed salvagers with exclusive territorial claim to the ruins of <a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">Crossings</a> and the <a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a>. No other party operates there without their sanction.</li>\n<li><strong>A secure vault and warehouse</strong> at Fort Meade, constructed at his expense, for the Reclaimers&#39; exclusive use.</li>\n<li><strong>A quarterly market fair</strong> at Fort Meade, drawing merchants from <a href=\"#/page/sanctuary\" class=\"wiki-link\">Sanctuary</a> and <a href=\"#/page/dunwick\" class=\"wiki-link\">Dunwick</a>. He funds the first three years.</li>\n<li><strong>In exchange:</strong> Fifteen percent of recovered value, payable in goods or coin at their discretion. And continued availability as his agents -- tasks specified as they arise.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>What He Doesn&#39;t Say:</strong></p>\n<p>He does not say this is about <a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">Drussus</a>. He does not say that a Fort Meade with a functioning market, a growing merchant quarter, and documented gold output is a Fort Meade that no longer needs the Governor&#39;s goodwill to survive. He does not say the Reclaimers are the engine he needs to change his political position. None of this needs saying. It is all visible to anyone paying attention.</p>\n<p><strong>Severina&#39;s Role:</strong></p>\n<p>After Marcellus finishes, <a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">Severina</a> speaks. She frames it as opportunity rather than contract -- the charter carries weight in Sanctuary as well as Fort Meade, the formalization protects what they have already built, the Academy introductions <a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">Malachor</a> can arrange become more credible under the Legate&#39;s seal. She is warm, interested, and precise beneath the warmth. She is not selling. She is clarifying. The difference is hard to pin down.</p>\n<p><strong>Negotiation Parameters:</strong></p>\n<p>Marcellus will not move on the structure. He will negotiate specifics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Percentage:</strong> Floor is ten percent. He opened at fifteen.</li>\n<li><strong>Timeline for vault construction:</strong> Movable.</li>\n<li><strong>Specifics of &quot;available when required&quot;:</strong> He will accept definition. He will also use any vagueness left in the final language.</li>\n<li><strong>He will honor exactly what is agreed. He will exploit any ambiguity in exactly what is agreed.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>GM Note:</strong> Three weeks ago he was a frustrated legate using irregular assets to solve a bandit problem. He has moved faster than that framing suggests because he has been calculating since the <a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">Rook</a> situation ended. This meeting is the result -- and the beginning of a dependency that runs in both directions. The party is becoming essential to his ambitions in a way that makes them harder to walk away from.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"see-also\">See Also</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-reclaimers\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-reclaimers</a> -- The player character party</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-backlands</a> -- The province where the campaign takes place</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/crossings\" class=\"wiki-link\">crossings</a> -- The ruined border city</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-meade\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-meade</a> -- The garrison where the Reclaimers are based</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/legate-marcellus\" class=\"wiki-link\">legate-marcellus</a> -- Their formal patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/lady-severina\" class=\"wiki-link\">lady-severina</a> -- Their actual patron</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-nethercity\" class=\"wiki-link\">Nethercity</a> -- The underground complex currently being explored</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-stone-of-sakkara\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-stone-of-sakkara</a> -- The dangerous artifact carried by Theodotus</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-guzzler\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-guzzler</a> -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/eolande\" class=\"wiki-link\">eolande</a> -- Ancient Eladran general encountered at the Black Tree</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/thornasse\" class=\"wiki-link\">thornasse</a> -- Site of the Black Tree encounter</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rook\" class=\"wiki-link\">rook</a> -- The bandit the Reclaimers destroyed</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/fort-ikenvar\" class=\"wiki-link\">fort-ikenvar</a> -- Where Rook was destroyed and the Guzzler dwells</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/scalper-gangs\" class=\"wiki-link\">scalper-gangs</a> -- The other killers drawn by the bounty</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/argollean-brotherhood\" class=\"wiki-link\">argollean-brotherhood</a> -- Faction monitoring Nethercity recoveries</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/imperial-academy\" class=\"wiki-link\">imperial-academy</a> -- Faction competing for artifacts</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malachor\" class=\"wiki-link\">malachor</a> -- Academy representative, writing dispatches about Eolande</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/governor-drussus\" class=\"wiki-link\">governor-drussus</a> -- The political rival Marcellus is maneuvering against</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/shatzi\" class=\"wiki-link\">shatzi</a> -- PC, Merchant</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/theodotus\" class=\"wiki-link\">theodotus</a> -- PC, Philosopher-Bard, bearer of the Stone</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tiberius\" class=\"wiki-link\">tiberius</a> -- PC, Necromancer, offered Academy introductions</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/iman\" class=\"wiki-link\">iman</a> -- PC, Bladedancer</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/tancred\" class=\"wiki-link\">tancred</a> -- PC, Crusader (deceased)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/rendson\" class=\"wiki-link\">rendson</a> -- PC, Avari Gambler (deceased)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon\" class=\"wiki-link\">order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon</a> -- The order from which Iman was expelled</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">seros</a> -- The faith Tancred served</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/the-gilded-vigil\" class=\"wiki-link\">the-gilded-vigil</a> -- The guardian tomb connected to Tiberius&#39;s discovery</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/gallowswood\" class=\"wiki-link\">gallowswood</a> -- Location of the pulsating heart dreams</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/malyn-the-misshapen\" class=\"wiki-link\">malyn-the-misshapen</a> -- Scholar whose research revealed beastmen origins</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/brother-marco\" class=\"wiki-link\">brother-marco</a> -- Gave eulogies for Tancred and Rendson</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/ezekiel-shaw\" class=\"wiki-link\">ezekiel-shaw</a> -- Gave competing eulogy, used Tancred&#39;s death politically</li>\n<li><a href=\"#/page/sergeant-crull\" class=\"wiki-link\">sergeant-crull</a> -- Notably absent from the Legate&#39;s charter meeting</li>\n</ul>\n"}];
window.WIKI_SEARCH = [{"slug":"argollean-brotherhood","title":"The Argollean Brotherhood","category":"factions","tags":"faction criminal eladran first-empire artifacts intelligence fort-meade backlands","text":"The Argollean Brotherhood The Argollean Brotherhood is a criminal network connected to old Eladran noble houses that survived the fall of the First Empire. They exist marginally and resentfully within Mithrian imperial society, executing plans and deeds on behalf of these houses: intelligence work, artifact acquisition, and the occasional removal of obstacles. Overview The Brotherhood are not common criminals. They are criminals with a lineage, which makes them more dangerous and harder to prosecute. Their operations are disciplined, their motivations are ideological as much as financial, and their networks extend through the remnants of the old Eladran aristocracy. They execute plans and deeds on behalf of the old Eladran noble houses: intelligence work, artifact acquisition, and occasional removal of obstacles. Their members are trained, discreet, and motivated by a sense of cultural grievance that gives their work a conviction ordinary criminal enterprise lacks. Primary Interest: First Empire Artifacts The Brotherhood&#39;s primary commercial interest is relics and artifacts of the First Empire -- items that the old Eladran houses regard as cultural inheritance, and which the Mithrian Empire regards as state property. They move these items through networks that bypass official channels, returning them to the Eladran houses they consider their rightful owners. This trade is lucrative, but it is not purely mercenary -- the Brotherhood genuinely believes these artifacts belong to the descendants of those who created them, not to the empire that conquered their makers. Presence in Fort Meade Fort Meade&#39;s position on the trade route between Sanctuary and Bone Creek makes it a natural waypoint for Brotherhood operations. Members are embedded in the settlement, though they remain unidentified. They are not aggressive toward the general population. Their interest is focused on the flow of artifacts from the Crossings ruins and the Nethercity -- sites that have begun producing relics of genuine First Empire provenance. Relationship with Malachor and the Imperial Academy The Brotherhood and Malachor share a mutual distaste maintained at professional distance. Both want the same things -- the artifacts flowing out of the Crossings ruins and the Nethercity . The Brotherhood regards the Imperial Academy as a body that believes ancient Eladran heritage belongs to the Empire rather than to its descendants. Malachor considers their perspective provincial and ungrateful. They will not cooperate. Neither will move openly against the other -- for now. The equilibrium is maintained by the fact that neither faction has enough leverage or manpower at Fort Meade to risk open confrontation. Hook for the Reclaimers The Brotherhood will become aware of what the Reclaimers recover from the Nethercity . Whether they approach as buyers, competitors, or hostile actors depends entirely on what comes up and how the Reclaimers handle it. If the Reclaimers recover artifacts the Brotherhood considers Eladran cultural property and attempt to sell them through official channels (or to Malachor ), the relationship will turn adversarial. If the Reclaimers are willing to deal, the Brotherhood can offer coin, information, and access to networks the party cannot reach on their own. Local Leadership: Arannis Venn The Brotherhood&#39;s local operations at Fort Meade are led by Arannis Venn . Detail Description Full Name Arannis Venn Race Eladran script, marks him to those who know what to look for. See Also fort-meade -- The garrison settlement where the Brotherhood operates covertly malachor -- Imperial Academy historian and rival artifact hunter imperial-academy -- The scholarly institution the Brotherhood opposes ideologically Eladran -- The ancient civilization whose heritage the Brotherhood claims to protect crossings -- Ruins producing First Empire artifacts Nethercity -- Underground site producing artifacts of significant value Reclaimers -- The party whose discoveries may draw Brotherhood attention mithrian-empire -- The empire the Brotherhood exists within, resentfully sanctuary -- Southern terminus of the trade route the Brotherhood uses bone-creek -- Northern terminus of the trade route arannis-venn -- Local Brotherhood leader at Fort Meade"},{"slug":"burnished-scale","title":"The Burnished Scale","category":"factions","tags":"religion militant-order heresy-of-the-flame","text":"The Burnished Scale The Burnished Scale is a militant religious order within the Mithrian Empire , defined by its role in one of the most dangerous internal crises the Empire has ever faced -- the Heresy of the Flame in 304 IY. The Heresy of the Flame (304 IY) Under the leadership of Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas , the Burnished Scale launched an unauthorized purge targeting those they deemed heretics, apostates, and enemies of the true faith. The purge was conducted without the sanction of the Thousand Temples or the authority of the Emperor, representing a direct challenge to both religious and secular governance. Vargas and his followers believed they were acting in defense of doctrinal purity, but the violence and scope of the purge rapidly destabilized entire provinces. What began as a campaign of religious enforcement threatened to ignite full-scale civil war within the Empire. The Assassination and Its Aftermath The crisis reached its breaking point when the Imperial Talons , acting on the Emperor&#39;s orders, assassinated Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas . The killing of the Burnished Scale&#39;s leader decapitated the movement but did not immediately quell the unrest. Vargas&#39;s followers viewed his death as martyrdom, and the Empire teetered dangerously close to open conflict. It fell to the Thousand Temples to intervene, brokering a resolution that pulled the Empire back from the brink. The Heresy of the Flame left deep scars on imperial politics and religious life, and the events of 304 IY remain a cautionary tale about the dangers of unchecked zealotry. Legacy The Burnished Scale&#39;s purge and its aftermath reshaped the relationship between the Empire&#39;s religious and secular authorities. The crisis demonstrated both the fragility of imperial unity and the necessity of institutional checks on militant faith. The memory of Lord-Pentient Vargas remains a divisive subject -- reviled by some as a fanatic, venerated by others as a martyr who died for the purity of the Flame. See Also The Thousand Temples The Imperial Talons Mithra City"},{"slug":"congregation-of-the-hollow-sun","title":"Congregation of the Hollow Sun","category":"factions","tags":"faction religious secretive cult bone-creek backlands long-term-threat hollow-sun heresy shaw seros thousand-temples refugees avari scalpers scarification suffering purification","text":"Congregation of the Hollow Sun The temples speak of fire, brothers. They speak of flame as if it warms. But I have seen the flame that burns in silence. I have heard it speak in the dark, where no sun can reach. -- Ezekiel Shaw , Sermon of the Hollow Light What they worship in their temples is not the Sun, but its shadow! They weigh you with false scales, built by cowards in golden robes. -- Ezekiel Shaw The Congregation of the Hollow Sun is a secretive religious movement operating across the Province of Argolle , led by the charismatic cleric Ezekiel Shaw , who calls himself the Prophet of the True Dawn . The Congregation represents a long-term threat -- a slowly building movement whose full theology, membership, and ultimate trajectory remain contested even by those who study it. While the other power players in Bone Creek and beyond struggle over gold, territory, and influence, Shaw is building something far more dangerous: a community of true believers who feel -- perhaps for the first time in their lives -- that someone has told them the truth about their suffering. Shaw&#39;s Theology The Stolen Sun Shaw&#39;s theology begins with a claim that the official church has suppressed: that Seros -- or whatever the Unconquered Sun truly is -- has been stolen . The faith of the Thousand Temples is a shadow of the original truth -- a flattering lie designed to keep the wealthy comfortable and the poor compliant. The scales have been weighted from the beginning. The justice that the Thousand Temples preach is justice for those who can afford it. The light they worship is not the Sun but its reflection, distorted by centuries of institutional corruption, political accommodation, and deliberate suppression of truths that would threaten the comfort of those who benefit from the lie. This is not merely theological criticism. Shaw does not argue that the Thousand Temples are imperfect or in need of reform. He argues that they are fundamentally false -- that the entire institutional structure of Empyrean worship as practiced in the Mithrian Empire is built on a foundation of deliberate deception. The Hollow Sun In place of the warm, distant, benevolent light of orthodox Seros worship, Shaw proposes the Hollow Sun -- not the comfortable divine radiance that the Thousand Temples preach, but something colder, more total, and radically egalitarian . The Hollow Sun sees through you . It does not care about birth, coin, silk on your tongue, or the endorsement of senators. It wants your weight -- your pain, your purity, the thing that remains when everything false has been scraped away. It demands not wealth or status but authenticity -- the raw, unadorned truth of what you are when pretension, comfort, and self-deception have been stripped away. Salvation Through Suffering Shaw&#39;s theology of salvation is built on suffering. Salvation is not granted to the comfortable or the powerful. It is available to those who have been reduced to what cannot be taken away -- who have been stripped of everything except the irreducible core of their being by the grinding weight of frontier life, poverty, violence, and despair. This salvation is available to the refugee and the slave as fully as to the magistrate . In fact, it is more available to them -- because they have already been stripped, already been reduced, already been scraped clean of the pretensions and comforts that insulate the wealthy from the Hollow Sun&#39;s gaze. The poor, the desperate, the broken -- they are closer to the truth than any senator in his marble hall. This is an enormously appealing message in a province full of people the Empire has failed. Recruitment and Following Who Follows Shaw The Congregation draws from the populations that the Empire has most thoroughly abandoned: Refugee quarters -- the displaced, the dispossessed, the people who have lost everything to beastman raids, imperial neglect, and frontier violence. Shaw tells them their suffering has meaning. No one else has. The Scalper population -- bounty hunters, mercenaries, and frontier desperadoes who kill beastmen for gold and carry trauma that no temple has addressed. Shaw offers them a framework for understanding what they have done and what has been done to them. Avari communities -- the marginalized survivors of the Avari Confederation, whose culture was systematically destroyed after High Mage Cynar burned the Erenthis at Thornasse . Shaw&#39;s critique of imperial institutions resonates with people who have experienced the Empire&#39;s power at its most destructive. Shaw&#39;s Charisma Shaw is eloquent, genuinely charismatic, and capable of a self-effacement that makes his followers feel they are discovering truth for themselves . He does not preach at people. He does not demand conversion. He speaks, and what he says lands with the weight of something his listeners have always suspected but never heard articulated. His followers do not feel recruited. They feel recognized. This is what makes Shaw dangerous. A demagogue can be exposed. A fraud can be revealed. But Shaw may not be either. He may be exactly what he appears to be -- a man who has seen something true and cannot stop telling people about it. Whether that truth is divine, demonic, or merely the natural product of a brilliant mind operating in a broken world is the question that no one has answered. Shaw&#39;s Methods Shaw moves . He appears, preaches, converts, and moves on before the Thousand Temples can engage. He does not establish permanent facilities or visible infrastructure. He does not challenge the Temples directly. He arrives in a community, speaks to the people the Temples have failed, says something that sounds unbearably true, and leaves behind a community of poor people who feel that something real has been said about their lives. By the time the Temples learn he was there, he is gone. By the time they send a representative to assess the situation, the converts are already meeting, already praying, already organizing around the theology Shaw planted. The Congregation grows not through institutional machinery but through the propagation of an idea -- and ideas, once planted, are difficult to uproot. Shaw calls himself the Prophet of the True Dawn . The Unease of the Thousand Temples What makes the Thousand Temples uneasy about the Congregation is not merely its heterodox theology. Heterodoxy is common enough on the frontier, and the Temples have dealt with heretics before. What disturbs the institutional church is the undercurrent of suffering and purification language in Shaw&#39;s preaching. Shaw speaks of: Pain -- not as affliction to be endured but as instrument of transformation. Pain purifies. Pain reveals. Pain strips away everything false and leaves only what is real. Blood -- not as sacrifice in the Cthonic sense but as proof of commitment. To bleed for the Hollow Sun is to demonstrate the sincerity of your devotion in a way that words and wealth cannot match. Being scraped clean -- the process of purification through which the believer is reduced to their essential self. The language is violent. The imagery is not comfortable. Burning -- the fire that burns in silence, the flame that illuminates by consuming. Shaw&#39;s fire does not warm. It transforms, and transformation is not painless. The Congregation performs rites of physical endurance and ritual scarification . Whether these represent genuine asceticism -- the disciplined mortification of the flesh in pursuit of spiritual purity, a practice with precedent in legitimate Empyrean traditions -- or the beginning of something darker is an unanswered question. The line between asceticism and blood-cult is thin, and Shaw walks it with the confidence of someone who either does not see it or does not care. Leadership Ezekiel Shaw -- Cleric 6 The Congregation is led by Ezekiel Shaw , a Mithrian Cleric 6 who serves as its founder, preacher, and spiritual authority. Attribute Value Class Cleric 6 Race - - - ac - 2 - - - hp - 30 - - - atk - +3-(mace,-1d6+1) - - - wis - 16 - - - shaw-possesses-proficiencies-in- leadership ,- prophecy ,-and----most-troublingly---- black-lore ,-the-knowledge-of-dark-and-forbidden-traditions.-his-spells-include- bless ,- hold-person ,-and- cure-disease . - his-ability-to-heal-disease-alone-makes-him-one-of-the-most-valuable-individuals-in-the-[[the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands , where disease is rampant and qualified healers are almost nonexistent. This gives him enormous leverage -- the grateful sick become the faithful, and the faithful become the Congregation. For Shaw&#39;s full statistics, spells, and detailed profile, see ezekiel-shaw . The Name: Hollow Sun The name carries layered significance within Shaw&#39;s theology: Hollow -- The Sun as preached by the Thousand Temples is hollow because it has been emptied of its true content. The real Sun -- the Hollow Sun -- is the void that remains when the false light is stripped away. It is not empty. It is cleared. The hollowness is not absence but preparation. Sun -- Shaw does not reject the solar imagery of Seros worship. He claims it. The Hollow Sun is the true Sun, and what the Temples worship is its shadow. This appropriation of orthodox imagery makes the Congregation&#39;s theology difficult to combat -- Shaw speaks in the same language as the faith he opposes. Congregation -- Not cult, not brotherhood, not cabal. A congregation: an assembly of ordinary faithful gathered around shared belief. The framing is deliberate and effective. Threat Assessment The Congregation is classified as a long-term threat based on: Growing membership from populations the Empire has failed -- refugee quarters, Scalper communities, marginalized Avari Secretive operations that obscure the movement&#39;s true size and capabilities Shaw&#39;s significant personal power -- Cleric 6 with combat capability and healing magic Black Lore proficiency suggesting engagement with forbidden knowledge Prophetic claims that may foretell an event the Congregation is working to bring about The suffering/purification theology whose endpoint remains unclear -- asceticism or blood-cult Shaw&#39;s mobility -- his ability to appear, convert, and vanish before institutions can respond The genuine appeal of the message -- Shaw says things that sound true to people whose lives confirm them Relationship to Other Faiths Seros / Thousand Temples -- Direct opposition. Shaw accuses the Thousand Temples of suppressing the truth about the Unconquered Sun. The Temples regard Shaw as a heretic at best, a Cthonic agent at worst. Brother Marco at the House of Silence in Bone Creek -- A priest of genuine faith who represents the orthodox tradition Shaw attacks. A potential flashpoint. Marcos Varanes and the Bleak Sons -- Militant followers of Seros whose fanatical devotion could drive direct confrontation with Shaw if they become aware of his activities. Empyrean Faith -- The state religion. Shaw&#39;s theology exists in opposition to the institutional Empyrean, though his relationship to the underlying Empyrean tradition is more ambiguous. Cthonic Tradition -- Shaw&#39;s Black Lore proficiency and the suffering-oriented theology raise questions about Cthonic influence. Whether the Hollow Sun is an Empyrean heresy or a Cthonic deception disguised in solar language is unanswered. Plot Hooks The True Dawn -- Shaw calls himself Prophet of the True Dawn. What is the dawn he prophesies? A literal event? A spiritual transformation? Something worse? The Scarification Rites -- What is the full extent of the Congregation&#39;s ritual practices? Where does asceticism end and something darker begin? Infiltration -- Joining the Congregation risks falling under Shaw&#39;s magnetic influence, but it may be the only way to learn its true scope and goals. Competing Faiths -- The Congregation, the House of Silence, and the Bleak Sons represent three radically different expressions of faith in the same region. Their intersection could produce theological debate, political maneuvering, or open violence. The Hidden Light -- Shaw speaks of hidden light and silent flame. Is this metaphor, prophecy, or reference to a specific supernatural force? Shaw&#39;s Madness -- Is Shaw truly mad, genuinely prophetic, or something more dangerous than either? See Also ezekiel-shaw -- The Prophet of the True Dawn bone-creek -- The settlement where the Congregation operates the-backlands -- The frontier province where Shaw recruits seros -- The Empyrean god whose worship Shaw challenges thousand-temples -- The institution Shaw accuses of suppressing truth brother-marco -- The orthodox priest; potential rival marcos-varanes -- The militant of Seros; potential confrontation empyrean-faith -- The state religion Shaw opposes cthonic-corruption -- The dark tradition that may influence Shaw&#39;s theology the-convergence-problem -- The theological crisis underlying Shaw&#39;s claims bel-earth-hunger -- Another heterodox religious tradition in Argolle greta -- Another practitioner operating outside orthodox frameworks the-erenthis -- The sacred tradition Shaw&#39;s Avari followers may still revere wekko -- Another prophetic figure; parallels with the Congregation"},{"slug":"drussine-guard","title":"The Drussine Guard","category":"factions","tags":"faction military private-army drussine-guard sanctuary citadel governor-drussus backlands","text":"The Drussine Guard The Drussine Guard is Governor Valerios Drussus&#39;s personal army -- approximately 2,000 soldiers stationed in Sanctuary . It is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the Backlands , and its loyalty is to the Governor personally , not to the city, the province, or the Mithrian Empire . At a Glance Detail Description Type Private military force / personal army Strength ~2,000 soldiers Commander Skiothan crisis). It is not the City Watch . It is Governor Drussus&#39;s private army -- a legal distinction that matters enormously in imperial politics and not at all in practice. In practice, the Drussine Guard is the dominant military force in the Backlands . With ~2,000 soldiers -- compared to Legate Marcellus&#39;s ~100 at Fort Meade and the City Watch&#39;s ~600 -- the Guard outnumbers every other armed force in the province combined. It is better trained, better equipped, and better paid than any of them. The Guard serves multiple functions simultaneously: Police force -- maintaining order in Sanctuary , supplementing and often superseding the City Watch Security apparatus -- protecting the Governor, the Citadel , and critical infrastructure Garrison -- defending the city against external threats Political insurance -- ensuring that no faction in Sanctuary can challenge the Governor&#39;s authority through force Recruitment Training Recruitment into the Drussine Guard is selective . Candidates are drawn from the professional military class -- veterans, career soldiers, and men with proven martial ability. But martial skill alone is not sufficient. Every recruit is screened for loyalty to the Governor. This screening is thorough. Family connections, personal history, political associations, and character are all evaluated. Men with divided loyalties -- to the Emperor, to other patrons, to ideological causes -- are quietly rejected. The Guard recruits soldiers who will follow the Governor&#39;s orders without hesitation, without question, and without regret. Training is rigorous and ongoing. The Guard drills regularly, maintains high standards of physical fitness, and practices formation fighting, urban combat, and counter-insurgency techniques. They are professional soldiers in every sense. Pay Equipment Pay in the Drussine Guard is excellent -- significantly above the imperial standard for equivalent rank. This serves multiple purposes: It attracts the best available soldiers It creates economic dependence on the Governor (soldiers who leave the Guard take a significant pay cut) It reinforces loyalty (well-paid soldiers are less susceptible to bribery or recruitment by rivals) It generates gratitude and personal attachment to Drussus Equipment is the best available in the Backlands. The Guard is outfitted with quality arms, armor, and supplies. They look professional because they are professional, and the visual impression reinforces their authority. Command Structure Colonel Marcian Vex -- Commander Colonel Marcian Vex commands the Drussine Guard. Fighter 9, he is loyal to Drussus personally -- not merely professionally obedient but genuinely devoted to the Governor&#39;s cause. Vex is grim and efficient, a man who does not waste words, does not tolerate incompetence, and does not second-guess his orders. Vex was handpicked by Drussus for the command. His loyalty has been tested and proven over years of service. He is the mechanism through which the Governor&#39;s will becomes military action. Below Vex, the Guard operates through a standard military hierarchy: Senior Officers -- Company and battalion commanders, responsible for specific sectors or functions Junior Officers -- Platoon leaders and specialists Non-Commissioned Officers -- Sergeants and corporals who manage day-to-day operations Rank and file -- The soldiers themselves Deployment The Drussine Guard maintains presence throughout Sanctuary : The Citadel -- Primary barracks and headquarters. The largest concentration of Guard forces. In an emergency, the Citadel can be sealed and held indefinitely. Garrison posts throughout the city -- Guard stations in every district except the Ashward , providing visible presence and rapid response capability Gate posts -- Guard detachments at the city&#39;s major entrances Escort details -- Protection for the Governor, senior officials, and important shipments Patrol routes -- Regular patrols through all major districts The Guard does not patrol the Ashward refugee quarter. This is policy, not oversight -- the Avari community polices itself, and Guard presence would provoke rather than stabilize. Relationship with Other Forces The City Watch The City Watch (~600 strong) is the nominal municipal police force. In theory, the Watch handles civil law enforcement while the Guard handles military security. In practice, the Guard supersedes the Watch whenever it chooses. Watch officers know this and generally defer to Guard authority without resistance. The Watch is ostensibly independent but in practice answers to the Governor through the chain of command. It is a secondary force -- useful for routine policing but politically subordinate to the Guard in every way that matters. Legate Marcellus The Drussine Guard&#39;s existence is one of the reasons Legate Marcellus at Fort Meade is so politically isolated. With ~100 soldiers under his command compared to the Guard&#39;s ~2,000, Marcellus cannot challenge the Governor&#39;s military supremacy. The Guard ensures that the only significant military power in the Backlands belongs to Drussus. The Laced Hand The Drussine Guard is the implicit threat that keeps the Laced Hand in line. Castellan Thibaud understands that if the Governor ever decides the criminal syndicate is more trouble than it is worth, the Guard will dismantle it. This knowledge shapes the Laced Hand&#39;s behavior -- they remain useful, profitable, and never provocative enough to warrant destruction. Political Significance The Drussine Guard is the physical expression of Governor Drussus&#39;s power. Its existence transforms him from a political appointee into a military strongman. Key implications: Provincial autonomy -- With the imperial legions recalled to fight Skiothan incursions, the Guard is the only significant military force in the Backlands. This makes the Governor effectively autonomous. Factional balance -- No other faction in Sanctuary can challenge the Governor through force. The Temple , the Academy , and the Consortium must compete through politics, economics, and influence -- domains where the Governor also excels. Imperial tension -- A provincial governor maintaining a 2,000-strong personal army is, at minimum, unusual. Whether the Emperor is aware, concerned, or simply too occupied with the Skiothan wars to act is unknown. GM Notes The Drussine Guard should be played as a professional, efficient, and intimidating military force. Key principles: They are not bullies. They do not harass civilians for sport. They enforce the Governor&#39;s will with the minimum force necessary -- but they will use maximum force if required, without hesitation. They are everywhere. PCs operating in Sanctuary will encounter Guard patrols, guard posts, and Guard checkpoints regularly. The Guard&#39;s presence is a constant reminder of who holds power. They are loyal. Attempts to bribe, subvert, or recruit individual Guard members will almost always fail. The screening process and the excellent pay ensure that most soldiers are genuinely committed. They are the ceiling. The Guard represents the upper limit of what force can accomplish in Sanctuary without the Governor&#39;s approval. Any plan that involves fighting the Guard is a plan that involves fighting 2,000 professional soldiers and the full weight of the Governor&#39;s apparatus. Colonel Vex is the face of the Guard. Interactions with Guard leadership go through Vex, and Vex is not interested in negotiations, excuses, or appeals. He follows orders. See Also Governor Valerios Drussus -- patron and commander-in-chief Colonel Marcian Vex -- Guard commander Sanctuary -- the city they garrison The Citadel -- headquarters City Watch -- subordinate civil police force Legate Marcellus -- military rival at Fort Meade The Laced Hand -- criminal syndicate kept in line by Guard presence The Backlands -- the province"},{"slug":"house-aurel","title":"House Aurel","category":"factions","tags":"great-house conservative thousand-temples empyrean-faith religious-orthodoxy politics","text":"House Aurel House Aurel is the most doctrinally conservative of the Great Houses. The Aurels maintain deep and longstanding ties to the Thousand Temples and the Empyrean Faith , promoting cultural purity, religious orthodoxy, and the divine authority of the Emperor. They view the Measure and the Scale not merely as law but as sacred revelation, and they regard any deviation from tradition as heresy. At a Glance Patriarch Empyrean Faith . Where other houses treat religion as one element of political life among many, the Aurels view it as the foundation of all legitimate authority. Their core convictions include: The Measure and the Scale as sacred revelation -- Not merely a legal code or moral framework, but the direct word of the divine, to be followed without compromise or reinterpretation Divine authority of the Emperor -- The Emperor rules by divine mandate. His authority is not merely political but spiritual, granted by the Empyrean gods through the institutions of the faith Cultural purity -- The traditions, customs, and practices of the Mithrian people are sacred and must be preserved against foreign contamination, cosmopolitan dilution, and heretical innovation Religious orthodoxy -- The Thousand Temples are the guardians of spiritual truth, and their authority in matters of faith is absolute Influence The house&#39;s influence is strongest among three constituencies: The priesthood -- House Aurel&#39;s deep ties to the Thousand Temples give them unparalleled access to the Empire&#39;s religious hierarchy. Aurel-aligned priests serve in temples across the Empire, and the house&#39;s patronage supports seminaries, shrines, and religious institutions. The rural aristocracy -- Provincial nobles who view the capital&#39;s cosmopolitanism with suspicion find in House Aurel a champion of traditional values and hierarchies. Traditional military families -- Officers and soldiers who see the Empire as a divinely ordained institution, not merely a political entity, are naturally drawn to the Aurel worldview. Rivalries House Aurel is frequently at odds with the more cosmopolitan houses: House Malventi -- The Aurels view the Malventi as morally compromised and dangerously cosmopolitan. The Malventi&#39;s foreign trade connections, rumored involvement in the slave trade, and indifference to the Empyrean Faith are anathema to everything the Aurels stand for. House Kalomenes -- The Kalomenes&#39; procedural gamesmanship and institutional manipulation strike the Aurels as a perversion of the sacred order. The Aurels believe in hierarchy, duty, and obedience -- not loopholes and legal technicalities. Conversely, House Aurel generally supports House Decimus &#39;s hold on the throne, provided the Emperor continues to uphold the faith and its institutions. See Also The Thousand Temples -- religious institution deeply tied to House Aurel The Empyrean Faith -- the faith House Aurel champions The Measure and the Scale -- the sacred texts The Great Houses -- overview of all noble houses House Malventi -- ideological opponents House Kalomenes -- political rivals The Burnished Scale -- militant arm of the Temples The Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"house-decimus","title":"House Decimus","category":"factions","tags":"great-house ruling-house imperial-throne politics mithra-city imperial-talons","text":"House Decimus House Decimus is the ruling house of the Mithrian Empire , the most powerful of the Great Houses by virtue of holding the Imperial throne itself. The house secured its dominance during the War of Three Emperors in 270 IY, when Claudius Decimus emerged victorious from the brutal civil war that followed the assassination of the mad Emperor Aurex . Since that time, the Decimus line has held the Imperial seat without interruption. At a Glance Patriarch Emperor Aurex of House Valerian . Aurex&#39;s madness and cruelty had brought the Empire to the brink of collapse, and when his own sister killed him -- leaving no heir -- the resulting power vacuum plunged the Empire into civil war. The scholar-emperor Numerius was briefly installed on the throne but was murdered after only 87 days. Generals and governors vied for supremacy. From this crucible, Claudius Decimus emerged triumphant, founding the dynasty that rules to this day. The Succession Crisis The succession of House Decimus has not always been smooth. Julian Decimus , a previous Emperor, named his son Diometian as heir -- a decision that triggered civil war when rival claimants and discontented houses refused to accept the appointment. The resulting conflict reshaped the political order of the Empire and demonstrated that even the ruling house is not immune to the factional violence that defines Mithrian politics. Power and Influence House Decimus enforces its will through the Imperial Talons , an elite cadre of spies, informants, and assassins who serve the Emperor directly. The Talons operate outside normal Imperial law and are feared throughout the Empire as instruments of the throne&#39;s displeasure. Their existence is an open secret among the imperial elite -- their reputation alone serves as a deterrent against those who would move against the ruling house. Beyond the Talons, House Decimus commands the full apparatus of imperial governance: the legions, the bureaucracy, the treasury, and the legal authority of the throne. The Emperor&#39;s word is law, and while the Imperial Senate retains deliberative power, it has been stripped of binding legislative authority since Marcus Valerian founded the Empire in 1 IY. Current Status Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus firmly holds the Empire in his grasp. In 378 IY, he recalled armies from the Backlands to face the Skiothan threat on the western frontier -- a strategic decision that left the frontier provinces undermanned and contributed to the current lawlessness of the Backlands. Following the Sacking of Crossings in 377 IY, the Emperor issued an Imperial Bounty on beastmen, unleashing a wave of mercenaries and killers into the frontier provinces. The Decimus dynasty faces threats on multiple fronts: beastmen in the Backlands, Skiothan raiders to the west, lingering unrest in Morn, and the ever-present political maneuvering of rival Great Houses. The question that haunts the Empire is whether the Decimus line can hold what Claudius Decimus won -- or whether the patterns of decline that destroyed the Valerian dynasty will repeat themselves. Relationships House Valerian -- The house whose throne the Decimus line took. Relations are defined by the Valerians&#39; smoldering resentment and persistent rumors of restoration schemes. House Kalomenes -- Wields tremendous institutional power and has never truly accepted subordination to any ruling house. House Severian -- Enigmatic and difficult to read. The Talons cannot fully penetrate their networks, which makes them a persistent concern. House Aurel -- Aligned with the throne on matters of tradition and divine authority, but their deep ties to the Thousand Temples give them an independent power base. House Drussus -- Newest Great House. Close ties to the legions make them a potential ally or a potential threat. House Malventi -- Foreign connections make them invaluable but invite suspicion of disloyalty. See Also Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus -- current Emperor and patriarch Claudius Decimus -- founder of the dynasty The Imperial Talons -- elite spies and assassins War of Three Emperors -- the civil war that brought House Decimus to power Emperor Aurex -- the mad Emperor whose assassination created the power vacuum The Great Houses -- overview of all noble houses The Mithrian Empire Mithra City"},{"slug":"house-drussus","title":"House Drussus","category":"factions","tags":"great-house military newest-house backlands sanctuary drussine-guard politics","text":"House Drussus House Drussus is the youngest of the Great Houses, having risen to prominence through the battlefield accomplishments of its founder and current patriarch, Valerios Drussus . The house was built on military excellence rather than inherited from a lineage of power. House Drussus maintains close ties to the Imperial legions and is widely seen as the house of soldiers. Their rise is resented by older houses who view them as upstarts, but the Drussus name commands genuine respect among the officer corps and the common soldiery. At a Glance Patriarch Valerios Drussus made his name as a competent and aggressive general, earning glory and wealth in the Empire&#39;s many frontier campaigns. He was not born to the purple -- he built his house from nothing, parlaying military success into political capital with a precision that made older houses nervous. The house has since leveraged military wealth and reputation into broader political power. Strategic marriages, acquisition of merchant houses and estates, and the systematic placement of loyalists throughout the provincial bureaucracy have given House Drussus a power base that extends far beyond the battlefield. The Backlands Governor Drussus was appointed to the Backlands in 365 IY -- a posting initially seen as semi-exile. Whether he accepted it willingly or was maneuvered into it is unknown. What is certain is that he has made the most of it. Over fifteen years, he has executed a systematic consolidation of power in Sanctuary that includes: Personal command of the Drussine Guard , approximately 2,000 soldiers loyal to him personally Control over the City Watch (~600 strong) Strategic marriages binding merchant families and minor nobility to House Drussus Steady acquisition of economic assets throughout the province Gradual placement of loyalists throughout the bureaucracy A tacit arrangement with the Laced Hand criminal syndicate His personal wealth now competes with the Red River Consortium . His control over the bureaucracy is absolute. The Drussine Guard is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the Backlands. Reputation Among the Great Houses The older houses -- Valerian , Kalomenes , Aurel , Severian -- view House Drussus with varying degrees of contempt, wariness, and grudging respect. The Drussus name carries no ancient lineage, no storied ancestors, no centuries of accumulated prestige. What it carries is the loyalty of soldiers, the wealth of a province, and the ruthless competence of its patriarch. Whether House Drussus will endure beyond its founder -- whether it can establish the institutional depth and dynastic continuity that defines a true Great House -- remains to be seen. See Also Governor Valerios Drussus -- patriarch and founder Colonel Marcian Vex -- Drussine Guard commander The Drussine Guard -- the Governor&#39;s personal army Sanctuary -- provincial capital and seat of power The Citadel -- Governor&#39;s fortress-seat The Backlands -- the province The Great Houses -- overview of all noble houses The Laced Hand -- criminal syndicate with tacit arrangement Red River Consortium -- commercial rival/ally"},{"slug":"house-kalomenes","title":"House Kalomenes","category":"factions","tags":"great-house politics mithrian-league imperial-senate patronage institutional-power","text":"House Kalomenes House Kalomenes was once the most powerful house in the old Mithrian League , wielding unrivaled influence in the Imperial Senate before the rise of the Empire. When Marcus Valerian declared himself Emperor in 1 IY, the Kalomenes were among those defeated and forced to bend the knee. The house has never forgotten this humiliation, nor has it ever truly accepted subordination. Today, House Kalomenes commands tremendous power in the courts and political institutions of the Empire. Where other houses wield swords, the Kalomenes wield patronage, precedent, and procedural manipulation with lethal precision. At a Glance Patriarch Mithrian League -- the confederation of free city-states that preceded the Empire -- House Kalomenes was the dominant political force. They controlled the Senate , shaped legislation, and wielded the kind of institutional power that made them effectively the rulers of the League in all but name. The Humiliation When Marcus Valerian seized power and declared himself the first Emperor, the Kalomenes were among the houses that resisted. They raised armies, marshaled their allies, and fought to preserve the old order. They lost. Defeated on the battlefield, House Kalomenes was forced to bend the knee to the new Emperor -- a humiliation that has defined the house&#39;s character and ambitions for centuries. The Kalomenes have never forgotten. Every subsequent generation has been raised with the memory of what was lost and the conviction that the current order is illegitimate -- or, at the very least, that the Kalomenes&#39; rightful place is far higher than any Emperor has been willing to grant. Power and Methods House Kalomenes does not rely on military force or direct confrontation. Their power lies in the Empire&#39;s institutions themselves: Patronage networks -- The house sponsors dozens of tributary houses, creating a web of obligation and loyalty that extends across the Empire Legal and procedural expertise -- Kalomenes lawyers, advocates, and political operatives are the most skilled in the Empire. They can delay, obstruct, or redirect imperial policy through the courts and the Senate with devastating effectiveness Institutional memory -- The house maintains archives and precedent records that give them an encyclopedic knowledge of imperial law, senatorial procedure, and bureaucratic process. They know every loophole, every exception, every obscure ruling that can be weaponized Client networks -- An extensive network of clients, operatives, and informants embedded throughout the imperial bureaucracy The Kalomenes do not need to overthrow the Emperor. They can accomplish their goals by making governance impossible without their cooperation. Relationships House Decimus -- The ruling house. The Kalomenes accept the throne&#39;s authority publicly while undermining it institutionally whenever their interests require. House Valerian -- Both houses share the experience of having been displaced by imperial power, though the Kalomenes lost their position to the Valerians&#39; ancestor in the first place. The dynamic is complex. House Malventi -- The Kalomenes&#39; institutional conservatism sometimes clashes with Malventi cosmopolitanism, though both houses are pragmatic enough to cooperate when interests align. House Aurel -- Frequently at odds. The Aurels view the Kalomenes&#39; procedural games as undermining the sacred order of the Empire. See Also The Great Houses -- overview of all noble houses Marcus Valerian -- the Emperor who defeated them The Imperial Senate The Mithrian Empire House Decimus -- the ruling house"},{"slug":"house-malventi","title":"House Malventi","category":"factions","tags":"great-house commerce trade massaran-kingdoms urgathoa foreign-connections politics","text":"House Malventi House Malventi derives its power from commerce, particularly trade connections that extend far beyond the borders of the Mithrian Empire . The house maintains deep ties to the Massaran Kingdoms and Urgathoa , trafficking in exotic goods, rare materials, and -- by persistent and credible rumor -- slaves. The Malventi are cosmopolitan, pragmatic, and largely indifferent to the ideological concerns that animate other houses. Their foreign connections make them invaluable as intermediaries and intelligence sources, but also invite suspicion of disloyalty. Many in the Imperial Senate and the Thousand Temples view the Malventi as dangerously unpatriotic, more loyal to profit than to the Measure and the Scale . At a Glance Patriarch Massaran Kingdoms -- The remnants of the old Massaran Empire that was overthrown in the Empyrean War . Most Mithrians view the Massaran successor states with deep distrust. The Malventi view them as customers. Urgathoa -- A distant and poorly understood power. Malventi traders are among the few Mithrians who maintain regular contact with Urgathoan merchants and officials. Exotic goods and rare materials -- The Malventi traffic in substances, artifacts, and commodities that cannot be obtained within the Empire&#39;s borders. This trade is enormously profitable and gives the house access to resources that other houses cannot match. Slaves -- The most damaging accusation leveled against House Malventi is their alleged involvement in the slave trade. The house neither confirms nor denies these rumors, which persist because the Malventi&#39;s trading partners in the Massaran Kingdoms and Urgathoa are known to practice slavery openly. Character and Philosophy The Malventi are defined by pragmatism. They do not care about bloodlines, traditions, or theological disputes except insofar as these things affect commerce. They are cosmopolitan in outlook, comfortable dealing with foreigners, and deeply skeptical of the ideological rigidity that characterizes houses like House Aurel . This pragmatism makes them effective negotiators, reliable trading partners, and valuable intelligence sources. It also makes them deeply suspect in the eyes of those who believe that loyalty to the Empire and the Empyrean Faith should take precedence over profit. Relationships House Aurel -- Frequent antagonists. The Aurels view the Malventi as morally compromised and dangerously cosmopolitan. The Malventi view the Aurels as provincial zealots. House Kalomenes -- Both houses are pragmatic enough to cooperate when interests align, despite their very different approaches to power. House Decimus -- The ruling house values Malventi intelligence and commercial connections while distrusting their foreign loyalties. House Severian -- Both houses operate in shadows and trade in information. The relationship is opaque. See Also The Great Houses -- overview of all noble houses The Mithrian Empire The Empyrean War -- the war that overthrew the Massaran Empire The Measure and the Scale The Thousand Temples House Aurel -- ideological opponents"},{"slug":"house-severian","title":"House Severian","category":"factions","tags":"great-house ancient enigmatic eladra shadow-politics secrets politics","text":"House Severian House Severian is among the oldest houses in the Mithrian Empire , yet also the most enigmatic. The Severians operate through hidden channels, preferring shadow influence to open political contest. Their true wealth and the full extent of their networks are unknown even to the Imperial Talons . Persistent rumors hold that the Severian bloodline carries Eladra ancestry -- a claim that, if true, would link the house to the ancient Argollean Empire and its arcane legacy. The Severians neither confirm nor deny these rumors, and their occasional displays of uncanny insight and influence do nothing to dispel them. At a Glance Patriarch house-severian Distinction Ancient, secretive, rumored [[Eladra blood Power Base Hidden networks, shadow influence, unknown wealth Approach Operates through hidden channels; avoids open political contest Mystery and Reputation House Severian is defined by what is not known about them. Other Great Houses -- even those that operate through intrigue and maneuvering -- maintain visible power structures: estates, armies, patronage networks, tributary houses. The Severians maintain all of these, but their true assets are hidden. Their wealth cannot be accurately assessed. Their agents cannot be reliably identified. Their goals cannot be confidently predicted. The Imperial Talons -- the Emperor&#39;s own spies and assassins -- have been unable to fully penetrate Severian networks. This fact alone speaks volumes. The Talons are the most feared intelligence apparatus in the Empire, and their inability to map the Severian organization suggests either extraordinary operational security or resources that exceed what any noble house should possess. The Eladra Question The most persistent and troubling rumor about House Severian concerns their bloodline. Whispers have circulated for centuries that the Severians carry Eladra ancestry -- that somewhere in their family tree, the blood of the ancient Argollean Empire &#39;s foremost scholars and sorcerers was introduced. If true, this would be a matter of enormous significance. The Eladra were the architects of Argollean civilization, the discoverers of Gnostic Geometry , and the builders of wonders that have never been equaled. Their transformation into the Elvora -- corrupted by Cthonic power into something no longer human -- was one of the defining tragedies of Mithrapos&#39;s history. Eladra blood in a Great House would raise questions about arcane ability, longevity, and loyalties that no amount of political maneuvering could answer. The Severians neither confirm nor deny these rumors. Their occasional displays of uncanny insight -- knowing things they should not know, predicting events before they unfold, moving with a precision that suggests foreknowledge -- do nothing to put the whispers to rest. Political Position House Severian does not compete openly for political power. They do not sponsor legislation, they do not make public alliances, and they do not engage in the theatrical rivalries that define relationships between other Great Houses. Instead, they influence events from the shadows -- a word here, a favor there, a piece of information delivered at precisely the right moment to precisely the right person. This makes them difficult to oppose, difficult to ally with, and difficult to trust. Other houses deal with the Severians cautiously, aware that any interaction may be only the visible surface of a much deeper game. Relationships House Decimus -- The ruling house views the Severians with wariness. The Talons&#39; inability to penetrate their networks is a source of ongoing concern. House Valerian -- Both ancient houses, both diminished from former heights, but in very different ways. The Valerians lost their throne openly; the Severians&#39; losses -- if any -- are invisible. All other houses -- Treat the Severians with caution. No house can confidently claim to understand Severian motivations or to predict their actions. See Also The Great Houses -- overview of all noble houses The Imperial Talons -- unable to fully penetrate Severian networks Eladra -- the ancient race whose blood the Severians may carry Races and Cultures of Mithrapos The Mithrian Empire History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"house-valerian","title":"House Valerian","category":"factions","tags":"great-house ancient-lineage bellasarius politics prestigious-bloodline","text":"House Valerian House Valerian possesses the most prestigious bloodline in the Mithrian Empire , claiming direct descent from Bellasarius Valerian -- the legendary general who, alongside the prophet Enador , overthrew the Massaran Empire in the Empyrean War (663 BE). For centuries, the Valerians held the Imperial throne as a near-birthright. Today, the house retains immense prestige and wealth but lacks the political muscle to reclaim the throne -- though many believe the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration. At a Glance Patriarch Bellasarius Valerian was the war-chief who fought alongside the Prophet Enador to overthrow the Massaran Empire and its sorcerer-kings in the Empyrean War . His descendant Marcus Valerian seized power in 1 IY, declaring himself the first Emperor of Mithra and founding the imperial dynasty. For centuries thereafter, the Valerian name was synonymous with the throne. The Decline The house&#39;s fortunes declined after a succession of poor Emperors who squandered the legacy of their ancestors. This trajectory of decay culminated in the reign of Emperor Aurex , whose madness and cruelty brought the Empire to the very brink of destruction. Aurex was assassinated by his own sister, an act of desperate necessity that left no heir and ended the Valerian dynasty&#39;s hold on power forever. The ensuing chaos -- the War of Three Emperors (270 IY) -- saw Claudius Decimus triumph in the civil war and establish House Decimus as the new ruling dynasty. The Valerian claim to the throne was permanently broken. Current Standing House Valerian retains enormous wealth and the prestige of its ancient name. The Valerian bloodline is still regarded with reverence by traditionalists, historians, and those who remember that the Empire was built by Valerian hands. However, the house lacks the political muscle, military power, and institutional leverage to challenge House Decimus directly. Many believe -- and many fear -- that the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration. Whether this is true or merely the paranoia of rival houses is impossible to say with certainty. The Valerians maintain their dignity, their wealth, and their silence on the subject. Notable Members Basilios Valerian -- Current patriarch of the house Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus -- Military commander of the Backlands and commanding officer of Fort Meade . A career soldier of the Valerian line, now isolated at the frontier by Governor Drussus &#39;s political containment. Bellasarius Valerian -- Legendary founder and ancestor (deceased) Marcus Valerian -- First Emperor (deceased) Emperor Aurex -- The mad Emperor whose assassination ended the dynasty (deceased) Relationships House Decimus -- The house that took the throne from them. The relationship is defined by Valerian resentment and Decimus wariness. House Kalomenes -- Both houses share a history of having been displaced. The Kalomenes lost power when Marcus Valerian declared himself Emperor; the dynamic between these two ancient houses is complex. House Aurel -- Traditionalists who respect the Valerian bloodline but support the divine authority of whoever holds the throne. See Also Marcus Valerian / Bellasarius Valerian -- founder and first Emperor Emperor Aurex -- the mad Emperor who ended the dynasty Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus -- prominent living member War of Three Emperors -- the civil war that ended Valerian rule The Empyrean War -- the war that made the Valerian name House Decimus -- the ruling house that replaced them The Great Houses -- overview of all noble houses The Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"imperial-academy","title":"The Imperial Academy","category":"factions","tags":"imperial-academy sorcery gnostic-geometry mithrian-empire archmages seekers primarch mithra-city","text":"The Imperial Academy The Emperor rules the world of men, but the Academy governs what is possible within it. -- Archmage Thoss , On the Bounds of Sovereignty , banned in three provinces The Imperial Academy is the official state-sanctioned seat of sorcerous learning within the Mithrian Empire . It is both a prestigious university of learning and a political power in its own right, operating outside the traditional structure of Imperial ministries. The Academy answers nominally to the Emperor, but in practice it exercises a degree of autonomy that few other institutions within the Empire can match. Its influence extends into military strategy, state policy, provincial governance, and the regulation of all sorcerous activity across the Empire&#39;s vast territories. The Academy is a pillar of imperial stability and ambition, but also a hotbed of secrecy, rivalry, and experimentation. Behind its alabaster walls, Archmages pursue research both sanctioned and clandestine, political factions maneuver for influence, and the boundaries of what is possible are tested -- sometimes in defiance of the Academy&#39;s own stated prohibitions. Location and Architecture The Imperial Academy is located in Mithra City , the capital of the Mithrian Empire . Its towering spires are the highest structures within the city, able to be seen from leagues away -- a deliberate architectural statement of the Academy&#39;s power, prestige, and ambition. The spires serve both practical and symbolic purposes: their height aids in certain sorcerous observations and experiments, while their visibility from such great distance ensures that every citizen of Mithra City lives within sight of the Academy&#39;s dominion. The Academy&#39;s grounds are extensive, encompassing lecture halls, libraries, laboratories, dormitories, administrative chambers, and the private quarters of the Archmages. The walls are of alabaster, and the overall impression is one of austere, forbidding magnificence. Governance and Leadership The Conclave of Archmages A conclave of Archmages forms the ruling council of the Academy. Appointment to the conclave is a lifelong position, decided by the Emperor himself. This makes each seat on the council a matter of intense political significance -- not only within the Academy but within the broader Imperial power structure. The Emperor&#39;s ability to appoint Archmages gives the throne a measure of control over the Academy, while the lifelong nature of the appointment ensures that individual Archmages can accumulate considerable independent power over the course of their tenure. The conclave deliberates on matters of curriculum, research policy, institutional governance, and the Academy&#39;s relationship with the Imperial state. Decisions are reached through a combination of formal voting, factional negotiation, and -- according to persistent rumor -- sorcerous coercion. The Primarch Every seven years, the conclave will vote on one of their members to become the Primarch . The Primarch serves as a figurehead of some executive power within the Academy and holds the position of direct advisor to the Emperor. The Primarch is the public face of the Academy, representing it in state ceremonies, Imperial councils, and diplomatic negotiations. While the Primarch&#39;s executive authority within the Academy is formally limited -- they are first among equals, not an absolute ruler -- the combination of institutional prestige and direct access to the Emperor gives the Primarch considerable informal power. The seven-year election cycle ensures a degree of turnover in the Academy&#39;s leadership while the lifelong nature of the Archmages&#39; appointments provides institutional continuity. The tension between these two principles -- change and stability -- is a defining feature of the Academy&#39;s internal politics. The Seekers Citizens of the Empire hold the Academy in fear and contempt, and much of this animosity is directed at the Academy&#39;s Seekers . The Seekers are agents of the Academy who prowl the provinces, searching for those who possess the power of sorcery. They travel the length and breadth of the Empire, testing children and young adults for sorcerous aptitude. When talent is discovered, enrollment is not optional -- the individual is taken to the Academy whether they or their family consent or not. If a family cannot afford the pricey tuition required for formal enrollment, the Seekers will enslave the future student, designating them as a servus -- a bonded servant of the Academy. The servus serves in this capacity until such a time that they can pay their tuition through service. This practice, while entirely legal under Imperial law, is deeply resented by the common people. Parents dread the arrival of Seekers in their communities, and stories of families hiding talented children or fleeing their homes to avoid the Seekers are common throughout the provinces. Despite the cruelty of the system, the Academy is fond of pointing out that some of its most powerful and distinguished graduates rose from the ranks of the servus. These individuals, born into poverty and enslaved by the institution that would educate them, ascended through sheer talent, determination, and ruthlessness to become some of the most powerful High Mages to ever live. The Academy cites these examples as proof that the system is meritocratic at its core -- a claim that its critics regard with considerable skepticism. Sorcerous Tradition The Academy teaches and practices a form of geometric gnostic sorcery , rooted in the ancient formulae of the Anthyllium -- the Argollean grimoire recovered by the Prophet Enador along with the Measure and the Scale . This tradition holds that sorcery is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout reality -- a structured, lawful cosmos established by the Aurelion . The formulae and incantations of gnostic geometry are difficult to master, requiring years of rigorous study, intense mental discipline, and precise execution. However, the power they confer is much greater than that available to a hedge-mage or warlock working outside the Academy&#39;s traditions. Academy-trained sorcerers can achieve feats of destruction, construction, divination, and transmutation that are simply beyond the reach of self-taught practitioners. Prohibited Disciplines Other forms of sorcery are strictly prohibited by the Academy. The following disciplines are expressly forbidden, and their practice is punishable by death: Necromancy -- the animation, summoning, or manipulation of the dead Transmogrification -- the fundamental alteration of living flesh, including self-modification Demon-binding -- the summoning, communication with, or enslavement of entities from the Beyond The Scale may weigh the soul, but it is the Academy that defines what a soul can be. -- Magistrate Verna Astell , executed for practicing forbidden transmogrification rituals The fate of Magistrate Verna Astell serves as a stark reminder of the consequences of violating the Academy&#39;s prohibitions. Astell, a magistrate of some standing, was discovered to have been conducting transmogrification experiments -- altering living flesh in ways the Academy deemed an abomination. She was arrested, tried before the conclave, and executed. Her final words, quoted above, are frequently cited by critics of the Academy as evidence that the institution&#39;s true concern is not the protection of the public but the preservation of its own monopoly on power. Clandestine Research Despite the severity of these prohibitions, rumors persist of clandestine research conducted within the Academy&#39;s deepest laboratories -- experiments that push against or outright violate the Academy&#39;s own stated rules. The nature of this research is unknown to outsiders, but whispered speculation includes forbidden transmogrification, communication with entities from the Beyond, and experiments with necromantic energy. Whether these rumors reflect reality or are merely the product of public suspicion and the Academy&#39;s culture of secrecy is impossible to determine from the outside. The Academy and Warfare The Mithrian Empire once held a near-monopoly on sorcery, and the Imperial Academy was the instrument of that monopoly. For centuries, the Academy&#39;s trained battle-mages ensured Mithrian battlefield dominance, their geometric sorcery capable of devastating enemy formations, shattering fortifications, and deciding the outcome of entire wars. No rival power could field sorcerers of comparable skill or power, and this advantage was a cornerstone of Imperial military strategy. Over time, however, the destructive powers of mages have proliferated beyond the Academy&#39;s control. Hedge-mages, warlocks, and sorcerers trained in rival traditions have appeared in increasing numbers among the Empire&#39;s enemies. The Academy&#39;s monopoly has eroded, and with it the Empire&#39;s guaranteed battlefield superiority. The Battle of Blue Mound (360--368 IY) The consequences of uncontrolled sorcerous warfare were demonstrated with devastating finality at the Battle of Blue Mound (360--368 IY). The conflict pitted Imperial forces led by High Mage Cynar , one of the Academy&#39;s most powerful battle-mages, against the army of Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye , a sorcerer of formidable power operating outside any institutional framework. The war dragged on for eight years before culminating in a direct sorcerous duel between Cynar and Jarn Murky-Eye. The duel escalated beyond all control, unleashing cataclysmic energies that annihilated both armies entirely and left the battlefield a blasted wasteland. Neither combatant survived. The Battle of Blue Mound prompted significant reforms in how the Empire deploys its mages in combat. The model of the singular, all-powerful battle-mage was abandoned in favor of combined arms tactics -- integrating squad mages into conventional military formations, where their sorcery supplements rather than replaces conventional weapons and tactics. The Death of Usil (348 IY) The Academy&#39;s role as the Empire&#39;s foremost authority on metaphysical matters was tested by the Death of Usil in 348 IY, when violent earthquakes and storms of unprecedented ferocity struck across Mithrapos . The Academy attributed the catastrophe to fluctuations in the gnostic patterns that govern the metaphysical reality of Mithrapos -- a scientific explanation consistent with their understanding of the axioms that underpin reality. The priests of the Empyrean faiths offered a competing explanation: an Empyrean god -- Usil -- had died, and the cosmic upheaval was the consequence of that divine death. The Academy rejected this interpretation but could not disprove it, and the event became a defining moment in the ongoing rivalry between sorcerous and religious authority within the Empire. Kolani Munitions The peace treaty that ended the Dog Soldier War included a provision that further diminished the Academy&#39;s exclusive military importance: the Empire gained access to Kolani munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, providing Imperial commanders with destructive capabilities that do not depend on the Academy&#39;s sorcerers. This development has been a source of quiet resentment within the Academy, which views the adoption of non-sorcerous weapons technology as a diminishment of its institutional importance. Public Perception The Academy occupies an ambivalent position in the public imagination of the Mithrian Empire . It is respected for its power and feared for its authority, but it is also resented for its arrogance, its secrecy, and the predatory practices of its Seekers . Common citizens regard the Academy as a necessary evil at best -- an institution that provides the Empire with essential sorcerous capability while extracting a heavy toll in freedom, dignity, and trust. The Academy&#39;s critics -- and they are numerous, though few dare to speak openly -- accuse it of hoarding knowledge, suppressing rival traditions, enslaving the talented, and conducting forbidden research in defiance of its own rules. Its defenders counter that without the Academy&#39;s discipline and control, sorcery would be an unregulated catastrophe, as dangerous to its practitioners and bystanders as to any enemy. See Also Mithrian Empire Mithra City Gnostic Geometry Anthyllium Measure and the Scale Prophet Enador Argolle Aurelion Archmages Primarch Seekers Eladra Elvora Veil Beyond Battle of Blue Mound Death of Usil Dog Soldier War Kolani Irregulars High Mage Cynar Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye Magistrate Verna Astell Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"imperial-senate","title":"The Imperial Senate","category":"factions","tags":"faction political mithrian-league senate governance performative hereditary patronage imperial","text":"The Imperial Senate The Senate is where speeches are given, petitions are heard, and nothing is decided. It is a theater of governance -- the costumes are magnificent, the performances are impassioned, and the audience left long ago. The Imperial Senate is a remnant of the old Mithrian League governing body. Once a powerful institution with genuine legislative and executive authority, the Senate has declined into a largely performative body -- a forum for speeches, petitions, and political theater that retains the trappings of power without its substance. At a Glance Detail Description Type Legislative/advisory body (nominal) Status Active, but largely performative Origin Remnant of the old Mithrian Empire&#39;s political structure -- it is an institution that everyone acknowledges, many attend, and no one obeys. Its origins in the Mithrian League gave it genuine authority in an earlier age, when the League was a confederation of equals and the Senate was the forum where those equals negotiated, legislated, and governed. The transformation of the League into the Empire changed the Senate&#39;s function without abolishing its form. As imperial power concentrated in the Emperor and the bureaucratic apparatus of the state, the Senate&#39;s authority was progressively hollowed out. What remains is a body that retains the architecture, the ceremony, and the rhetoric of governance without the binding authority that once gave those things meaning. Membership Seats in the Imperial Senate are hereditary or appointed : Hereditary seats pass through the Great Houses and old families that held them during the League era. These seats carry the prestige of lineage and the weight of tradition, though the authority they represent has long since migrated to other institutions. Appointed seats are granted by the Emperor or through the mechanisms of imperial patronage. These appointments are tools of political management -- rewards for loyalty, incentives for cooperation, or consolation prizes for those who might otherwise cause trouble. Senators hold prestige . They are addressed with deference, consulted with the appearance of seriousness, and treated as persons of consequence. This prestige is genuine within the social hierarchy of the Empire, even if the legislative authority it once accompanied has evaporated. Function The Senate&#39;s practical function in the current imperial order is threefold: Political Theater The Senate floor is a stage. Senators deliver speeches on matters of policy, morality, and imperial direction. These speeches are often eloquent, sometimes brilliant, and rarely consequential. The audience is not the Senate itself but the broader political class -- the speeches signal positions, establish alliances, and advance or undermine reputations. Petitions and Patronage The Senate receives petitions from citizens, provinces, and institutions seeking imperial favor, redress, or attention. The Senate&#39;s ability to act on these petitions is limited, but the act of petitioning -- and the Senate&#39;s response to petitions -- creates a mechanism of patronage that Senators use to build and maintain political networks. Influence Through Rhetoric Senators can influence policy through rhetoric and patronage, even without binding authority. A sufficiently persuasive speech, a well-timed petition, or a strategic alliance of Senatorial voices can create political pressure that the Emperor and the imperial bureaucracy must acknowledge, if not obey. The Senate&#39;s power is the power of opinion, reputation, and social pressure -- real in its effects, even if informal in its mechanisms. Relationship to Imperial Power The Senate lacks binding authority . It cannot legislate, cannot tax, cannot command armies, and cannot compel the Emperor or the imperial administration to act. Its resolutions are advisory at best, ignored at worst. This arrangement suits the imperial order. The Senate provides a venue for political expression that might otherwise find less manageable outlets. Ambitious nobles, frustrated provinces, and aggrieved parties can bring their grievances to the Senate floor, where they are heard, debated, and -- crucially -- contained. The Senate functions as a pressure valve, allowing the political class to feel heard without granting them the power to act. See Also Mithrian League -- The original governing body from which the Senate descends mithrian-empire -- The empire the Senate nominally advises great-houses -- The noble families that hold hereditary Senate seats Emperor -- The actual locus of imperial authority"},{"slug":"imperial-talons","title":"The Imperial Talons","category":"factions","tags":"espionage imperial-institution house-decimus","text":"The Imperial Talons The Imperial Talons are an elite order of spies and assassins operating within the Mithrian Empire . They answer to no ministry, no senate committee, and no military chain of command -- their loyalty belongs solely and absolutely to the Emperor. The Talons serve as the hidden hand of House Decimus , enforcing the ruling dynasty&#39;s power through intelligence gathering, covert operations, and targeted killings. Role and Purpose Where the Mithrian Military projects imperial power openly and the Imperial Academy controls the arcane, the Talons operate in shadow. They are the Emperor&#39;s instrument for dealing with threats that cannot be addressed through conventional means -- internal conspiracies, disloyal nobles, heretical movements, and foreign agents operating within imperial borders. The Talons&#39; existence is an open secret among the imperial elite. Their reputation alone serves as a deterrent: those who move against House Decimus know that the Emperor&#39;s reach extends far beyond the legions and the law. The Heresy of the Flame The Talons&#39; most historically significant operation was the assassination of Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas during the Heresy of the Flame in 304 IY. Vargas, the leader of the Burnished Scale , had launched an unauthorized religious purge that threatened to tear the Empire apart. When the crisis reached a point where diplomatic resolution seemed impossible, the Talons were dispatched. The assassination of Vargas eliminated the figurehead of the heretical movement, but it did not immediately resolve the crisis. The Empire teetered on the brink of civil war until the Thousand Temples intervened to broker a fragile peace. See Also House Decimus The Burnished Scale The Thousand Temples The Mithrian Military"},{"slug":"laced-hand","title":"The Laced Hand","category":"factions","tags":"faction criminal syndicate thieves-guild sanctuary harbor smuggling black-market backlands","text":"The Laced Hand The Laced Hand is Sanctuary&#39;s criminal syndicate -- an organized, hierarchical underworld operation that controls the docks, smuggling, the black market, protection rackets, gambling dens, and information brokerage throughout the city. Operating with Governor Drussus&#39;s tacit approval , the Laced Hand occupies a unique position: simultaneously criminal and quasi-institutional, feared and relied upon, illegal and essential. At a Glance Detail Description Type Criminal syndicate Base of Operations Sanctuary for generations, surviving changes in governors, shifts in imperial policy, and periodic crackdowns by adapting, compromising, and -- when necessary -- eliminating threats with surgical precision. The organization is not universally hated . It provides services the city needs: Docking assistance -- Ships entering Sanctuary&#39;s harbor navigate the Laced Hand&#39;s system. Dock assignments, loading/unloading crews, and cargo security all flow through Laced Hand-controlled unions. Dispute resolution -- In the Harbor and parts of the Commons , the Laced Hand settles disputes faster and more reliably than the City Watch . Their judgments are enforced. Moving goods quietly -- Not all smuggling is contraband. Merchants who need to avoid customs duties, move sensitive cargo, or bypass bureaucratic delays turn to the Laced Hand. Criminal safety valve -- By keeping the underworld organized, the Laced Hand prevents the chaos of competing gangs, random violence, and uncontrolled crime. The Governor understands this. Leadership Castellan Thibaud -- Boss Castellan Thibaud is the current boss of the Laced Hand. Master Thief 7, age 52. Thibaud rose through the organization&#39;s ranks over thirty years , beginning as a dockside pickpocket and advancing through every level of the hierarchy. He is intelligent, cautious, and remarkably well-read -- more like a crime CEO than a typical underworld boss. He does not swagger, threaten, or posture. He manages. Key traits: Operates from multiple hideouts throughout the city, rarely using the same location twice in succession Rarely seen in public -- most of Sanctuary&#39;s population would not recognize him on the street Runs the Laced Hand as a hierarchical, quasi-legal operation with clear chains of command, standardized procedures, and something approaching corporate discipline Focused on profit and stability , not flash or violence. Violence is a tool, not a policy. When it is used, it is precise and purposeful. Understands that his organization exists at the Governor&#39;s pleasure and could be destroyed if Drussus ever decided the arrangement was no longer useful Thibaud&#39;s greatest asset is his patience . He does not react to provocations. He does not make emotional decisions. He calculates, waits, and acts when the moment is right. Operations The Dockworkers&#39; Union The Laced Hand&#39;s most visible operation. Control of the dockworkers&#39; union gives them effective control over the Harbor district. Nothing enters or leaves Sanctuary by sea without the Laced Hand&#39;s knowledge and, implicitly, their permission. Warehousing Smuggling The Laced Hand controls a network of warehouses throughout the Harbor and parts of the Commons . These serve dual purposes: legitimate storage for merchants and concealed storage for contraband, stolen goods, and items that need to disappear for a while. The Black Market Goods that cannot be sold through legitimate channels -- stolen property, restricted items, contraband -- flow through the Laced Hand&#39;s black market. This is not a single location but a network of dealers, brokers, and contacts operating throughout the city. Protection Rackets Merchants and business owners in the Harbor and parts of the Commons pay regular fees to the Laced Hand. In exchange, they receive genuine protection -- from theft, from competitors, from random violence, and from the Laced Hand itself. Gambling Dens The Laced Hand operates gambling establishments throughout Sanctuary , ranging from upscale houses catering to wealthy merchants to dockside dice games for sailors. All pay a cut to the organization. Discretion Houses The Laced Hand maintains discretion houses in most districts. These serve triple duty: Information brokers -- where intelligence is bought and sold Meeting places -- neutral ground for negotiations between parties who cannot be seen meeting publicly Safe houses -- temporary shelter for those who need to disappear The discretion houses are the backbone of the Laced Hand&#39;s intelligence network and one of their most valuable services. The Crimson Anchor Tavern The Crimson Anchor Tavern in the Harbor is the Laced Hand&#39;s primary operations hub . On the surface, it is a busy dockside tavern -- loud, crowded, smelling of salt and beer. Beneath that surface, it is the nerve center of the organization&#39;s daily operations. Proprietor: Mara -- Has worked at the Crimson Anchor for 20 years . Knows everyone worth knowing in Sanctuary&#39;s underworld. Functions as an informal intelligence clearinghouse, message drop, and first point of contact for those seeking to do business with the Laced Hand. Mara is not Laced Hand leadership -- she is infrastructure. Without her, the organization&#39;s communication network would be significantly degraded. The Arrangement with the Governor The Laced Hand operates with Governor Drussus&#39;s tacit approval . This arrangement is unspoken but understood by both parties: What the Laced Hand provides: Intelligence from the docks -- who is arriving, what they carry, who they meet Subtle removal of individuals who are inconvenient to the Governor but cannot be openly dealt with A criminal safety valve -- organized crime is predictable and manageable; disorganized crime is not Economic lubrication -- the black market moves goods and services that the legitimate economy cannot What the Governor provides: Non-interference -- the City Watch does not aggressively pursue Laced Hand operations Stability -- the Governor does not allow rival criminal organizations to challenge the Laced Hand&#39;s dominance Implicit protection -- the Laced Hand&#39;s position is secure so long as it remains useful Thibaud understands the fragility of this arrangement. It exists because Drussus finds it useful. The moment it becomes more trouble than it is worth, the Drussine Guard will crush the Laced Hand without hesitation. Thibaud manages accordingly -- keeping his operations profitable but not provocative, useful but not indispensable enough to demand concessions. Structure The Laced Hand is organized hierarchically: The Boss ( Castellan Thibaud ) -- overall leadership and strategic direction Lieutenants -- each controls a specific district or operation (docks, smuggling, gambling, protection, etc.) Captains -- manage day-to-day operations within their lieutenant&#39;s territory Operatives -- skilled thieves, enforcers, smugglers, and information brokers Associates -- dockworkers, lookouts, messengers, and others who work with the Laced Hand but are not full members Advancement is based on reliability, profit generation, and discretion. Violence is not rewarded unless it was necessary and executed cleanly. Relationship with Other Factions Prelate Voth the Temple Prelate Voth regards the Laced Hand as a moral rot. The Temple monitors Laced Hand activities through its own intelligence network and occasionally interferes when criminal operations become too brazen or impact Temple interests. The Laced Hand, in turn, avoids operating in the Sunward and treats Temple property and personnel as off-limits. The Imperial Academy The Academy is largely indifferent to the Laced Hand, and the Laced Hand treats Academy matters as outside its scope. Occasional transactions occur -- an antiquarian who needs an artifact moved quietly, a scholar who needs information from the docks -- but there is no formal relationship. The Avari Community The Laced Hand has limited presence in the Ashward . The Avari community polices itself, and the Laced Hand has calculated that the profit potential of the refugee quarter does not justify the difficulty of operating there. GM Notes The Laced Hand should be played as a professional organization, not a street gang. Key principles: They are businesspeople first. Profit, stability, and institutional survival drive their decisions, not ego or territoriality. Violence is a tool, not a culture. When the Laced Hand uses violence, it is precise, purposeful, and designed to send a specific message. Random violence is bad for business. They are a useful resource for PCs. Need information? Need something moved? Need someone found? The Laced Hand can provide -- for a price. They are not enemies by default. They are dangerous when crossed. The same professionalism that makes them reasonable also makes them methodical in retribution. Crossing the Laced Hand means dealing with an organization that has been eliminating problems for generations. Thibaud is the key. If PCs interact with Laced Hand leadership, they interact with Thibaud -- and he is smarter, more patient, and better informed than they expect. See Also Sanctuary -- the city The Harbor -- primary territory The Crimson Anchor Tavern -- operations hub Castellan Thibaud -- boss Governor Valerios Drussus -- tacit patron Prelate Severan Voth -- moral opponent The Drussine Guard -- the threat that enforces good behavior The Commons -- secondary territory City Watch -- nominal law enforcement"},{"slug":"mithrian-marines","title":"The Mithrian Marines","category":"factions","tags":"faction military marines mithrian elite shroud empyrean 8th-undying second-war-of-morn lycandite ferocity","text":"The Mithrian Marines Send the Regulars if you want to win the battle. Send the Marines if you want the enemy stacked like firewood. -- Captain Pollimer Motts, 8th Company Marines, 14th Army The Mithrian Marines are an elite branch of the Mithrian military, famous for their ferocity in combat and their distinctive religious practice -- the worship of Shroud , the Empyrean god of crossing and passage. At a Glance Detail Description Type Elite military branch Allegiance Shroud -- the Empyrean god of crossing and passage. Where most imperial soldiers observe the broader Empyrean pantheon with varying degrees of sincerity, the Marines have adopted Shroud as their patron with particular devotion. Shroud presides over transitions -- the crossing of thresholds, the passage from one state to another, the boundary between the living and the dead. For the Marines, this domain has specific and practical meaning: they are the ones who carry enemies across that boundary, and they worship the god who stands at the gate. This devotion gives Marine units a spiritual cohesion that supplements their military discipline. They do not merely fight together -- they share a religious identity that frames their violence as sacred function, their casualties as offerings, and their survival as evidence of divine favor. The 8th Undying The most famous Marine unit is the 8th Undying -- the 8th Company Marines of the 14th Army, who earned their epithet during the Second War of Morn in 371 IY. The Second War of Morn (371 IY) During the Second War of Morn, the 14th Army was shattered by Lycandite fanatics -- an enemy whose religious fervor and physical transformation made them exceptionally dangerous opponents. The 14th Army broke. Its regular formations collapsed under the pressure of an enemy that did not retreat, did not negotiate, and did not die easily. The 8th Company Marines did not break. What the 8th Company did in the aftermath of the 14th Army&#39;s destruction earned them the name Undying -- a title that speaks to both their refusal to die and their capacity to inflict death on an enemy that had already destroyed a conventional army. The 8th Undying became legendary, a unit whose name carried weight sufficient to alter the calculations of enemies who heard it. Captain Pollimer Motts of the 8th Company Marines summarized the distinction between regular forces and Marines with characteristic bluntness: the Regulars win battles; the Marines leave nothing standing. Role in Imperial Military Doctrine The Marines serve a specific function within the Mithrian Empire&#39;s combined arms doctrine. They are not a general-purpose formation -- they are a specialist instrument deployed when conventional forces are insufficient or when the political and military situation demands a particular kind of result. Their deployment signals escalation. When the Marines are committed, the Empire has decided that the situation requires not merely military resolution but the kind of resolution that discourages future resistance. This makes them both invaluable and politically sensitive -- their use carries implications that extend beyond the immediate tactical situation. See Also mithrian-empire -- The empire the Marines serve shroud -- The Empyrean god of crossing/passage worshipped by the Marines empyrean-faith -- The broader religious tradition to which Shroud belongs Lycandite -- The fanatics who shattered the 14th Army mithrian-military -- The broader military structure kolani-munitions -- Another specialist element of Mithrian combined arms doctrine"},{"slug":"mithrian-military","title":"The Mithrian Military","category":"factions","tags":"military mithrian-empire imperial-institution","text":"The Mithrian Military The Mithrian Military is the vast, structured, and brutally efficient professional army of the Mithrian Empire . Born from the citizen-soldier ideals enshrined in the Measure and the Scale, the military has served as both the instrument of imperial expansion and the shield against the Empire&#39;s many enemies. Origins and the Legionary Tradition The military was originally built around vast legions of heavy infantry -- disciplined formations of citizen soldiers who carved the Empire out of a hostile world. As Mithra conquered new peoples, the defeated were enlisted as auxiliaries , fighting alongside the legions in exchange for the promise of full citizenship upon completion of their service. Military service has long been the surest path to land ownership, the core aspiration of every Mithrian citizen. Transformation by Sorcery The proliferation of destructive sorcery on the battlefield fundamentally transformed the Mithrian way of war. Where once Mithra held a near-monopoly on organized sorcerous power through the Imperial Academy , rival nations and elder civilizations have since developed their own devastating magical capabilities. Elder sorcery in particular is devastatingly destructive, capable of shattering formations and reducing fortifications to rubble. In response, the military has evolved from a force built around massed heavy infantry into a combined arms, highly mobile, and adaptable fighting force. The rigid legion structure has given way to more flexible doctrines suited to surviving and prevailing on a battlefield shaped by magic. Modern Composition The contemporary Mithrian Military integrates a wide array of specialized units: Line infantry -- still the backbone, though deployed in looser, more adaptive formations Squad mages -- Academy-trained sorcerers embedded at the tactical level Scouts and assassins -- operating ahead of and behind enemy lines Sappers -- combat engineers specializing in fortification and demolition Kolani munitions teams -- employing advanced explosive and incendiary weapons acquired from the Kolani as part of the peace settlement following the Dog Soldier War The Mithrian Marines Among the most feared elements of the military are the Mithrian Marines , a seaborne fighting force with a fearsome reputation. The Marines are notable for their worship of Shroud , an Empyrean god associated with death, the sea, and the passage between worlds -- an unusual devotion that sets them apart from the broader imperial religious culture centered on the Thousand Temples . The 8th Undying The 8th Undying are legendary heroes whose fame dates to the Second War of Morn in 371 IY. Their exploits during that conflict have passed into military legend, and their name is invoked as a standard of valor and sacrifice within the ranks. Strategic Challenges Despite its formidable capabilities, the Mithrian Military is stretched dangerously thin. On the Empire&#39;s borders, Skiothan and Lakan barbarian forces continually test the legions&#39; ability to hold the line. The combination of vast frontier commitments, the rising threat of elder sorcery, and the logistical demands of maintaining a professional army across a continent-spanning empire has placed the military under mounting strain. See Also The Imperial Academy The Imperial Talons Mithra City The Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon","title":"Order of the Scarlet Ribbon","category":"factions","tags":"faction religious-order empyrean bladedancer iman militant-order priestesses noble-patrons","text":"Order of the Scarlet Ribbon The Order of the Scarlet Ribbon is a militant religious order connected to the Empyrean faith. The Order trains bladedancers -- warrior-devotees who combine martial discipline with religious devotion in service to the Empyrean temples and their patrons. It is the order from which Iman was driven for speaking too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons. At a Glance Detail Description Type Militant religious order Faith Empyrean faith, producing warriors who fight as an act of worship and worship through the act of fighting. The Order is led by its priestesses, who serve as both spiritual authorities and institutional administrators. They govern the training of initiates, maintain the Order&#39;s relationship with the Empyrean temples, and manage the political connections that sustain the institution&#39;s funding and social standing. The Corruption Beneath the Order&#39;s public face of religious devotion and martial discipline lies a more complicated reality. The priestesses of the Order maintain relationships with noble patrons -- relationships that blur the boundary between spiritual authority and secular power, between religious service and political transaction. These arrangements are the open secret of the Order. Everyone within the institution understands them. The noble patrons provide funding, political protection, and social standing. In return, the priestesses provide services that extend beyond the merely spiritual -- access, influence, the prestige of association with a respected religious order, and other accommodations that are understood but not named. This exchange is tolerated because it is necessary. The Order cannot sustain itself on faith alone. It requires resources, and resources come from patrons, and patrons expect returns on their investment. The priestesses who serve their patrons&#39; interests rather than their faith&#39;s teachings do so because the alternative -- institutional poverty and political irrelevance -- is worse. Or so the reasoning goes. The corruption is not dramatic or violent. It is the ordinary, grinding corruption of an institution that has learned to survive by compromising its stated principles. It is the kind of corruption that everyone sees and no one names, because naming it would require confronting the gap between what the Order claims to be and what it actually is. Iman&#39;s Expulsion Iman was a bladedancer of the Order -- trained in its martial and devotional traditions, shaped by its discipline, loyal to its stated ideals. She was also honest in a way that the Order could not tolerate. Iman spoke too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons. She named the corruption -- the exchange of spiritual authority for secular patronage, the priestesses who served their benefactors rather than their faith. She said it aloud, in terms that could not be misunderstood or politely ignored. For this, she was driven from the Order. Not for being wrong -- the corruption she identified was real and widely known -- but for being honest about it. The Order could tolerate the corruption itself. What it could not tolerate was someone saying so. Iman&#39;s expulsion was not a punishment for falsehood but for truth -- the one unforgivable sin in an institution built on comfortable lies. Iman subsequently came to the Backlands and joined the Reclaimers , where her bladedancer training and her directness found a more welcoming context. Relationship with the Empyrean Faith The Order of the Scarlet Ribbon is connected to the Empyrean faith -- one of the major religious traditions of the Mithrian Empire . The precise nature of this connection -- whether the Order is an official arm of the Empyrean temples, an independent order operating under Empyrean auspices, or a semi-autonomous institution with its own governance -- is not fully clarified in available sources. What is clear is that the Order draws its spiritual authority from the Empyrean tradition and its martial practice from the bladedancer discipline associated with that tradition. The priestesses who lead the Order derive their legitimacy from their religious role, even as their actual function has become increasingly entangled with secular patronage. See Also iman -- Former member, expelled for honesty the-reclaimers -- The party Iman joined after her expulsion Empyrean -- The faith to which the Order is connected lady-severina -- Iman&#39;s current close relationship, who values the directness the Order punished the-backlands -- Where Iman went after her expulsion campaign-chronicle -- Session history of the campaign"},{"slug":"red-river-consortium","title":"Red River Consortium","category":"factions","tags":"faction trading-company consortium bone-creek backlands commerce scalpers","text":"Red River Consortium The Red River Consortium is a trading company operating in the Backlands , most notably through its Red River Exchange in Bone Creek . The Consortium has positioned itself as the economic backbone of the Scalper trade, profiting from the Imperial Bounty by serving as the intermediary between Scalpers and the imperial treasury. The Red River Exchange The Red River Exchange is the largest building in Bone Creek — a physical testament to the Consortium&#39;s wealth and power in the settlement. It serves two primary functions: Loot and Treasure Sales Scalpers sell their plundered loot and treasure to the Exchange. The Consortium&#39;s merchants are shrewd negotiators , ensuring that the Exchange profits handsomely from every transaction. Scalpers fresh from the field, desperate for coin, are often at a disadvantage when haggling with the Exchange&#39;s experienced traders. Beastman Scalp Redemption The Exchange is where beastman scalps are sold in exchange for the Imperial Bounty of one imperial gold mark per scalp. The Consortium takes a transaction fee on every scalp redeemed — a cut of the Emperor&#39;s own bounty that flows directly into Consortium coffers. Given the volume of scalps passing through Bone Creek, this fee represents an enormous and steady revenue stream. Security The Consortium employs an army of hardened guardsmen and bodyguards to protect the Exchange, its merchants, its inventory, and its gold. In a settlement as lawless as Bone Creek, this private security force makes the Red River Exchange one of the few places where violence is reliably punished. It also makes the Consortium a military power in its own right within the settlement. Leadership Cassian Varro — Lord Merchant Cassian Varro serves as the Lord Merchant of the Red River Exchange — the Consortium&#39;s chief representative in Bone Creek. He is described as a polished and shrewd businessman who is deeply involved in the local economy and political dealings of the settlement. Varro is not merely an administrator; he is an active political player shaping Bone Creek&#39;s future through his alliance with Tolliver Watts . Alliances The Consortium, through Varro, is a close ally of Tolliver Watts , proprietor of Double Sevens. Together, they represent the strongest power bloc in Bone Creek — one oriented toward commerce, order, and the gradual civilization of the frontier. This alliance stands in opposition to the rougher, more lawless influence of Thaddeus Marr and his network. Role in the Scalper Economy The Red River Consortium sits at the center of the entire Scalper economy in Bone Creek: Scalpers risk their lives hunting beastmen for scalps The Exchange buys the scalps and redeems the Imperial Bounty (taking a transaction fee) The Exchange also buys any loot or treasure Scalpers recover (at negotiated — often unfavorable — prices) The Consortium profits from both the transaction fees and the markup on resold goods This position gives the Consortium enormous economic leverage. Every mark that flows through Bone Creek passes through the Exchange at some point, and the Consortium takes its cut each time. See Also cassian-varro — Lord Merchant and local leader of the Consortium bone-creek — The settlement where the Exchange operates tolliver-watts — Close ally of the Consortium thaddeus-marr — Rival power in Bone Creek the-backlands — The frontier province beastmen — The creatures whose scalps fuel the Consortium&#39;s business mithrian-empire — The empire whose bounty the Consortium profits from"},{"slug":"scalper-gangs","title":"Scalper Gangs","category":"factions","tags":"faction scalpers gangs bounty beastmen bone-creek backlands violence frontier","text":"Scalper Gangs The Scalper gangs are organized groups of bounty hunters operating in the Backlands , drawn to the frontier by Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus&#39;s decree offering one imperial gold mark for every beastman scalp delivered to an authorized exchange point. These gangs represent the organized edge of the Scalper trade — bands of fighters who have banded together under charismatic or powerful leaders to hunt beastmen more effectively, claim territory, and survive in one of the most dangerous regions of the Mithrian Empire . Those who seek the Imperial Bounty are called Scalpers . Hard men and women who come from every walk of life, drawn by the allure of imperial gold, a Scalper&#39;s life is one of chaos, violence, and peril . For whatever reason, each Scalper has left their former life behind and journeyed to the edge of civilization. The veteran Scalpers are unlike any men one might encounter elsewhere — their eyes dulled from the horrors they have seen and endured, or tinged with a glint of madness . Some even bear the marks of corruption openly. They say, those who hunt the beastmen are changed. They say: The Bounty takes its toll. The Gangs Skin Eaters Leader: Skinner — Assassin 5 ( Kolani ) The most notoriously brutal of the Scalper gangs. The Skin Eaters are defined by their leader&#39;s savage reputation and their willingness to engage in methods that go far beyond what is necessary to collect the Imperial Bounty. Skinner wears beastman-hide armor crafted from the skins of his kills — a walking trophy and a statement of absolute dominance over his prey. Skinner is cold, intense, and feared throughout the Backlands. Covered in scars and never seen without a blade, rumors say he is not entirely sane. His proficiencies in Tracking , Ambushing , and Torture paint a picture of a methodical predator who hunts with lethal efficiency and dispatches his prey with deliberate cruelty. The Skin Eaters embody the darkest extreme of the Scalper trade — the point where hunting becomes butchery and survival becomes savagery. Key Stats: AC 4, HP 28, ATK +4 (Hooked Axe 1d8+2), Dex 15 For Skinner&#39;s full profile, see skinner . The Dregs Leader: Bottlecap Juno — Barbarian 4 The wild card faction of the Scalper gangs. The Dregs are as unpredictable as their leader — a grinning, possibly mad barbarian who leads through raw charisma and physical intimidation rather than any coherent strategy or ideology. Juno wears a necklace of bent coins and fights with a great axe and berserker fury. The Dregs cannot be easily bought, threatened, or reasoned with. Their unpredictability makes them unreliable allies and terrifying enemies. Where other gangs can be anticipated, the Dregs operate on instinct and impulse, making them a chaotic element in any conflict they enter. Juno&#39;s proficiencies in Berserkergang , Intimidation , and Survival reflect a leader who fights in a frenzy, terrifies his enemies, and keeps his people alive in the wilderness through sheer stubborn resilience. Key Stats: AC 3, HP 34, ATK +4 (Great Axe 1d10+1), Str 15 For Juno&#39;s full profile, see bottlecap-juno . The Baldric Brothers Leader: Kael Baldric — Fighter 4 ( Avari ) — CURRENTLY MISSING Five Avari brothers with a fearsome reputation in the Backlands. The Baldric Brothers are rarely seen apart — they operate as a single, cohesive fighting unit, and their coordination and mutual loyalty make them far more dangerous than their individual capabilities would suggest. They are known for getting jobs done quickly and violently . Kael , the eldest, is the leader — stern, protective, and fiercely family-loyal. He is completely bald with black-chain tattoos and fights with a bastard sword. His proficiencies in Leadership and Survival reflect his role as the group&#39;s commander and guide. Kael is currently missing . His unexplained disappearance is deeply troubling — the brothers are never apart, and Kael&#39;s absence suggests something has gone catastrophically wrong. This creates an immediate investigation or rescue hook for anyone who encounters the remaining four brothers. Key Stats: AC 3, HP 30, ATK +4 (Bastard Sword 1d10+1), Str 15 For Kael&#39;s full profile, see kael-baldric . The Hollow Men Leader: Wekko — Witch-Doctor 6 ( Kolani ) The most ominous and alien of the Scalper gangs. The Hollow Men are defined by their ritualistic nature and the unsettling, cultic authority of their masked, silent leader. Wekko is always masked and perpetually silent — a figure who exists in the space between the human and the supernatural, commanding his followers through force of presence and spiritual power rather than words. The Hollow Men are not merely bounty hunters — they are practitioners of something older and darker than the Imperial Bounty. Wekko&#39;s spells include Cause Fear , Curse , and Speak with Dead , and his proficiencies in Terror , Prophecy , and Healing suggest a witch-doctor who wields the full spectrum of spiritual power — from healing the living to commanding the dead. The Hollow Men represent a cultic presence in the Scalper trade, and Wekko&#39;s prophetic abilities give them the potential to shape events through foretelling as well as violence. Key Stats: AC 5, HP 24, ATK +3 (Bone Spear 1d6+1), Wis 16 For Wekko&#39;s full profile, see wekko . The Bleak Sons Leader: Marcos Varanes The Measure — Paladin 5 ( Mithrian ) The most disciplined and ideologically driven of the Scalper gangs. The Bleak Sons are zealous militant followers of Seros , the god of justice and the balanced scale. Under Varanes&#39;s leadership, they treat the beastman hunts not as a mercenary enterprise but as a holy crusade — a sacred duty imposed by divine will. Varanes — The Measure — is the most formidable physical combatant among the gang leaders. Clad in full armor (AC 1) with 38 hit points and a +5 attack bonus, he is a devastating warrior. His bronze scale fetish amulet marks him as a devoted servant of Seros , and his proficiencies in Intimidation , Theology , and Divine Blessing make him both a military and spiritual commander. The Bleak Sons are a possible ally or fanatic adversary . Their discipline and combat effectiveness make them the most valuable potential partners in the Backlands, but their rigid moral code and Varanes&#39;s absolute certainty in his own righteousness make them inflexible and judgmental. Those who do not meet their standards are viewed not as neutral parties but as sinners. Key Stats: AC 1, HP 38, ATK +5 (Morning Star 1d8+2), Str 17 For Varanes&#39;s full profile, see marcos-varanes . The Withered Craw Secret Controller: Malyn the Misshapen — Mage 7 ( Mithrian ) The most secretive of the Scalper gangs — and for good reason. The Withered Craw operates under the guise of a standard bounty-hunting operation, but is in reality secretly controlled by Malyn the Misshapen , an exiled, crippled mage who uses the gang to enslave beastmen rather than kill them . While other Scalper gangs bring back scalps, the Withered Craw brings back living captives — delivering them to Malyn for purposes that are unknown and almost certainly forbidden. Malyn himself never appears publicly. His apprentice Lynara — an Eladran Nightblade 3 with golden skin and pale Eladran eyes — serves as the gateway to Malyn&#39;s operations. She is curious, intelligent, and morally torn by the nature of her master&#39;s work, making her a potential point of leverage for anyone investigating the Withered Craw&#39;s true activities. The Withered Craw&#39;s existence is a closely guarded secret. If it were discovered that they enslave beastmen rather than kill them, the reaction from other Scalper gangs, the Red River Consortium , and imperial authorities would be swift and violent. Key Stats (Malyn): AC 8, HP 18, ATK +2 (Staff 1d6), Int 17 Key Stats (Lynara): AC 4, HP 13, Dex 16 For Malyn&#39;s full profile, see malyn-the-misshapen . Comparative Overview Gang Leader Class HP Best Stat Defining Trait Skin Eaters skinner Skinner Assassin 5 28 Dex 15 The Dregs bottlecap-juno Bottlecap Juno Barbarian 4 34 Str 15 Baldric Brothers kael-baldric Kael Baldric Fighter 4 30 Str 15 Hollow Men wekko Wekko Witch-Doctor 6 24 Wis 16 Bleak Sons marcos-varanes Marcos Varanes Paladin 5 38 Str 17 Withered Craw malyn-the-misshapen Malyn the Misshapen Mage 7 18 Int 17 The Scalper Economy The Scalper gangs exist within an economic ecosystem centered on Bone Creek : The Hunt — Gangs venture north into beastman territory, risking their lives to kill (or, in the Withered Craw&#39;s case, capture) beastmen The Scalps — Beastman scalps are brought back to Bone Creek as proof of kills The Exchange — Scalps are sold at the Red River Exchange , operated by the Red River Consortium , in exchange for imperial gold marks (minus a transaction fee) The Spend — Gold flows into Bone Creek&#39;s taverns, shops, and services — the Pretty Peach ( Thaddeus Marr ), Double Sevens ( Tolliver Watts ), Tackle and Harness, and other establishments The Cycle — Scalpers resupply, recover, and head back out to hunt again This cycle keeps Bone Creek alive and profitable, but it also ensures a constant flow of violence, trauma, and corruption through the settlement. The veteran Scalpers&#39; dulled eyes and marks of corruption are the human cost of this economy. Inter-Gang Dynamics The six Scalper gangs exist in a state of competitive coexistence — they are not allies, but outright gang warfare would be counterproductive when there are beastmen to hunt and bounties to collect. Tensions exist along several axes: Brutality vs. Discipline — The Skin Eaters and the Bleak Sons represent opposite approaches to the Scalper trade. Skinner&#39;s savage methods and Varanes&#39;s righteous zeal could easily spark a confrontation. Chaos vs. Order — The Dregs&#39; unpredictability is anathema to the Bleak Sons&#39; rigid discipline and the Baldric Brothers&#39; family cohesion. Secrecy vs. Transparency — The Withered Craw&#39;s hidden agenda, the Hollow Men&#39;s ritualistic secrecy, and the Congregation of the Hollow Sun&#39;s covert recruitment all create layers of hidden activity beneath the surface of the Scalper trade. Leadership Vacuum — Kael Baldric&#39;s disappearance creates instability among the Baldric Brothers, potentially shifting the balance of power among the gangs. See Also bone-creek — The Scalper settlement and economic hub the-backlands — The frontier province where the gangs operate beastmen — The creatures the gangs hunt for the Imperial Bounty crossings — The ruined city whose fall created the Scalper trade red-river-consortium — The trading company that profits from the scalp bounty mithrian-empire — The empire that issued the bounty skinner — Leader of the Skin Eaters bottlecap-juno — Leader of the Dregs kael-baldric — Leader of the Baldric Brothers (missing) wekko — Leader of the Hollow Men marcos-varanes — Leader of the Bleak Sons malyn-the-misshapen — Secret controller of the Withered Craw ezekiel-shaw — Leader of the Congregation of the Hollow Sun (not a Scalper gang, but operates within the same ecosystem) congregation-of-the-hollow-sun — Secretive religious group connected to the Scalper community sergeant-gallus — The nominal law enforcer who does nothing about gang activities thaddeus-marr — Power broker who interacts with all the gangs cassian-varro — Lord Merchant who controls the bounty exchange"},{"slug":"thousand-temples","title":"The Thousand Temples","category":"factions","tags":"religion imperial-institution the-flame","text":"The Thousand Temples The Thousand Temples is the official religious institution of the Mithrian Empire , serving as the organized body through which the faith of the Flame is administered, interpreted, and protected. Headquartered in Mithra City , the Thousand Temples holds authority over religious doctrine, priestly ordination, and the sacred process of canonization. The Flame and Its Priests The priests of the Thousand Temples are able to channel the Flame , drawing upon its divine power to perform miracles, heal, and ward against darkness. However, the nature of this gift is mysterious even to those who wield it -- priests can channel the Flame, but they cannot truly teach it . The ability appears to be granted rather than learned, setting it apart from the formulaic sorcery of the Imperial Academy . This distinction places the Flame outside the Academy&#39;s regulatory authority and has been a source of tension between the two institutions. Sainthood One of the Thousand Temples&#39; most significant functions is the anointing of Saints . Sainthood is typically granted posthumously to individuals who exhibited the seven virtues of the Scale during their lifetime -- a rigorous standard that ensures the sanctity of the honor. However, the process is not entirely insulated from politics. Some Emperors have pressured the Thousand Temples to grant Sainthood to living individuals , a practice that blurs the line between spiritual recognition and political propaganda. The Temples have historically resisted such pressure, though not always successfully. The Heresy of the Flame The Thousand Temples played a critical role during the Heresy of the Flame in 304 IY. When the Burnished Scale launched an unauthorized religious purge under Lord-Pentient Lucan Vargas, and the Imperial Talons assassinated Vargas in response, the Empire was driven to the edge of civil war. It was the Thousand Temples that intervened to prevent open conflict , brokering a resolution that preserved imperial unity -- though the scars of the crisis persisted for generations. Notable Figures High Priest Anton -- a prominent figure within the current leadership of the Thousand Temples, whose influence extends across both religious and political spheres. See Also The Burnished Scale The Imperial Talons The Imperial Academy Mithra City"},{"slug":"andraste","title":"Andraste, the Holy Dancer","category":"faiths","tags":"andraste empyrean deity saint holy-dancer compassion strength joy heron twin-swords nasga","text":"Andraste, the Holy Dancer Andraste is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title of the Holy Dancer. Her spheres of divine influence encompass compassion, strength, and joy — a trinity of virtues that reflects the Empyrean understanding that true strength is not cold or joyless but is expressed through the fullness of lived experience. She is the goddess who teaches that the body is not merely a vessel for the soul but an instrument through which divine virtue is enacted in the world. To dance is to move with purpose, to feel deeply, and to endure — and so the Holy Dancer embodies all three. Symbol and Sacred Animal Twin Swords Andraste&#39;s holy symbol is a pair of twin swords, crossed at the blade. The twin swords represent the duality at the heart of her nature — compassion and strength, gentleness and ferocity, the capacity to comfort and the capacity to defend. A single sword is a weapon; twin swords are a dance. The symbol reminds the faithful that compassion without the strength to act upon it is mere sentiment, and strength without compassion to guide it is mere violence. The Holy Dancer carries both, and her followers are called to do the same. The Heron The heron is Andraste&#39;s sacred animal. Herons are creatures of extraordinary grace and patience — they stand motionless in still water for hours before striking with sudden, decisive precision. This mirrors Andraste&#39;s teaching that joy and compassion are not passive states but require discipline, awareness, and the willingness to act decisively when the moment demands it. The heron is also a creature of liminality, dwelling at the boundary between water and land, sky and earth — a fitting companion for a goddess whose domain spans the full range of bodily experience. Spheres of Influence Compassion Andraste&#39;s compassion is not a soft or sentimental thing. It is the fierce, active compassion of one who sees suffering and moves to address it — not through prayer alone but through direct action. The Holy Dancer teaches that to witness pain and do nothing is a failure of virtue, that compassion demands the courage to intervene, to protect, to heal. Her followers are called to be present in moments of suffering, to offer not merely words of comfort but the strength of their hands and the resolve of their hearts. Strength Strength, in Andraste&#39;s teaching, is inseparable from compassion. It is the physical and spiritual capacity to act upon one&#39;s convictions, to stand firm when others falter, to carry burdens that would crush lesser wills. The Holy Dancer does not teach passive endurance but active, joyful engagement with the challenges of existence. Her strength is the strength of the dancer — not the brute force of the battering ram but the controlled, purposeful power of a body trained to move with intention and grace. Joy Joy is the third and perhaps most distinctive of Andraste&#39;s spheres. In the theology of the Empyrean Faith , joy is not mere happiness or pleasure but a profound spiritual state — the recognition that life, with all its suffering and struggle, is fundamentally beautiful and worthy of celebration. The Holy Dancer teaches that joy is an act of defiance against the entropy and despair that the Cthonic powers seek to spread, that to dance in the face of darkness is itself a form of worship and resistance. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros himself, Andraste is no longer worshipped as a goddess in her own right within the orthodox practice of the Thousand Temples . Following the theological consolidation that elevated Seros to the position of supreme and singular deity, the lesser Empyrean gods were reinterpreted as Saints — mortal exemplars of divine virtue who achieved transcendence through their embodiment of the Measure and the Scale . Andraste is now venerated as Saint Andraste, the patron saint of compassion, dancers, healers, and those who serve others through physical labor and bodily sacrifice. Despite this formal demotion, devotion to Andraste remains deeply embedded in the popular religion of the Mithrian Empire . Shrines to the Holy Dancer can be found in healing houses, dance halls, and the quarters of midwives and surgeons. Soldiers pray to her before battle — not for victory, which belongs to Seros and Hector , but for the strength to show mercy to the defeated and compassion to the wounded. Her feast day is celebrated with communal dances, charitable acts, and the ritual crossing of twin swords above the heads of the faithful. Cthonic Mirror: Nasga Andraste&#39;s Cthonic counterpart is Nasga , the Mistress of Pain and Pleasure. Both deities operate within the domain of the body&#39;s experience — sensation, physicality, the raw immediacy of flesh and nerve. Where Andraste teaches that bodily experience is sanctified through compassion, strength, and joy, Nasga teaches that the body is an instrument of desire and domination, that pain and pleasure are the only truths that matter, and that the strongest are those who can both inflict and endure the most extreme sensations. The mirror between Andraste and Nasga is one of the most theologically significant pairings in the Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology. It illustrates the fundamental Empyrean teaching that every virtue has a shadow, every divine truth a dark reflection. The same raw material of bodily experience that Andraste sanctifies through compassion, Nasga corrupts through obsession. The faithful are warned that the line between Andraste&#39;s joy and Nasga&#39;s pleasure is thinner than most would like to admit. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros Nasga The Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples Hector"},{"slug":"bel","title":"Bel, the Slaughterprince","category":"faiths","tags":"bel cthonic deity slaughterprince lord-of-war war conquest blood manticore black-gauntlet bel-tharach earth-hunger argolle dunwick seros","text":"Bel, the Slaughterprince Bel is one of the seven Cthonic gods , known by the titles of the Slaughterprince and the Lord of War. His spheres of divine influence encompass war, conquest, and blood — the raw, unrestrained violence that the Cthonic Faith celebrates as the purest expression of will and the ultimate arbiter of truth. Where the Empyrean war-gods Damocles and Hector teach that warfare must be governed by discipline, honor, and moral purpose, Bel teaches that war is its own purpose — that the strong have the right to take what they can hold, that conquest is the natural state of existence, and that blood spilled in battle is the most sacred offering any being can make. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Black Gauntlet Bel&#39;s unholy symbol is a black gauntlet — a mailed fist of dark iron, clenched and ready to strike. The black gauntlet is a deliberate inversion of Damocles &#39;s burning gauntlet: where Damocles&#39;s fist burns with the divine flame of righteous purpose, Bel&#39;s fist is dark, cold, and purposeless save for the act of striking itself. The black gauntlet represents war stripped of all moral justification — violence as an end in itself, power exercised for no reason other than the capacity to exercise it. The Manticore The manticore is Bel&#39;s sacred animal — a monstrous predator combining the body of a great cat, the wings of a bat, and a tail bearing venomous spines. The manticore is not a natural creature but a thing of Cthonic origin , a being designed for nothing but killing. It hunts not for food or territory but for the pleasure of the hunt itself. In Cthonic theology, the manticore represents the ideal warrior in Bel&#39;s image: a perfect engine of destruction, unburdened by mercy, honor, or any purpose beyond the next kill. Spheres of Influence War War, in Bel&#39;s teaching, is the fundamental state of the cosmos — the natural condition from which peace is merely a temporary and unnatural deviation. The Slaughterprince teaches that The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice did not create a cosmos of order and harmony but a cosmos of contest, where the strong destroy the weak and the survivors inherit a world shaped by their victory. War is not a failure of civilization but the truth that civilization was built to conceal. Every law, every treaty, every declaration of peace is merely a pause in the eternal war — a moment of exhaustion before the next round of bloodshed. Conquest Conquest is war directed toward a specific end: the subjugation of the defeated by the victorious. Bel teaches that conquest is the natural right of the strong — that those who can take territory, enslave populations, and impose their will upon others have earned the right to do so by virtue of their strength alone. This teaching places Bel in direct theological opposition to Seros , who holds that authority derives from divine mandate and moral fitness rather than mere power. Both gods claim sovereignty over the will to impose order, but where Seros builds, Bel subjugates. Blood Blood is the sacred substance of Bel&#39;s worship — the physical medium through which the Slaughterprince&#39;s power flows and the offering most pleasing to him. Blood spilled in battle is the highest form of sacrifice in Bel&#39;s theology, but blood shed in any context of dominance and submission — ritual sacrifice, blood sport, even the blood of the harvest — carries spiritual significance. The centrality of blood to Bel&#39;s worship connects him to some of the most ancient and persistent religious practices in the known world, including the agricultural blood rites that predate the formal theology of the Cthonic Faith . Cthonic Mirror of Seros Bel is the Cthonic mirror of Seros — both gods claim sovereignty over the will to impose order upon the cosmos, but they represent diametrically opposed understandings of what order means and how it should be achieved. Seros imposes order through law, justice, and the cultivation of virtue — he builds, he judges, he illuminates. Bel imposes order through force, conquest, and the elimination of all who resist — he conquers, he subjugates, he dominates. The mirror between Bel and Seros is the deepest and most consequential in the entire Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology. It reflects the fundamental question at the heart of all theology and all politics: is order best achieved through justice or through power? Through the consent of the governed or the force of the conqueror? Seros and Bel give opposite answers, and the conflict between those answers has shaped the history of the world. The Bel-Tharach: Agricultural Blood Rites In the rural villages of Argolle , particularly in the agricultural communities of the backlands, a form of Bel worship persists that differs dramatically from the martial cult of the Slaughterprince. Known as the bel-tharach — the earth-hunger — these rites involve the offering of blood to the soil itself, in the belief that the earth is hungry, that the land demands blood to remain fertile, and that the refusal to feed the earth with blood will result in crop failure, blight, and famine. The bel-tharach is ancient — far older than the formal theology of the Cthonic Faith , older perhaps than the Empyrean Faith itself. It is a primal, visceral form of religious practice rooted in the intimate relationship between farming communities and the land they work. The blood offerings are typically animal — a chicken, a goat, a pig slaughtered at planting or harvest time and its blood poured directly onto the fields — but darker traditions persist in isolated communities, and rumors of human sacrifice in service of the earth-hunger have circulated for as long as anyone can remember. The fundamental question — whether the agricultural Bel of the bel-tharach and the Slaughterprince of the Cthonic war-cult are the same entity — remains unanswered. Some theologians argue that the earth-hunger is a debased survival of an even older deity whose identity has been absorbed by Bel over the centuries. Others hold that Bel is Bel, that war and harvest are both forms of the same cosmic transaction — the exchange of blood for power — and that the farmer who feeds the earth and the warrior who feeds the battlefield are both, in the end, serving the same hungry god. Bel Worship in Dunwick Bel worship has been documented in Dunwick , where his cult operates with varying degrees of secrecy depending on local conditions and the vigilance of Temple authorities. The presence of Bel worship in settled communities represents a persistent challenge to the Empyrean order — a reminder that the Slaughterprince&#39;s theology of strength and blood resonates with those who feel abandoned by the promises of Seros and unprotected by the justice of the Mithrian Empire . See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon Seros Damocles Hector Bel-Earth Hunger Argolle Dunwick Cthonic Corruption The Awakening Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"bellasarius","title":"Bellasarius, the Father","category":"faiths","tags":"bellasarius empyrean deity saint the-father courage service fatherhood horse eagle valerian vestari empyrean-war mithrian-empire","text":"Bellasarius, the Father In the name of the Father, the spear finds its mark, and the faithless are made to kneel. — Vestari oath of service Bellasarius is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title of the Father. His spheres of divine influence encompass courage, service, and fatherhood — the protective, sacrificial virtues of the patriarch who places himself between his family and the dangers of the world. Bellasarius is the god of those who lead not from behind but from the front, who demand nothing of their followers that they would not first demand of themselves, and who understand that true authority is not a privilege to be enjoyed but a burden to be borne. Bellasarius holds a unique position in the Empyrean Pantheon because the historical figure who bears his name — Bellasarius Valerian — is one of the most important mortals in the history of the Mithrian Empire . The relationship between the god Bellasarius and the mortal Bellasarius Valerian is a subject of theological debate, but the prevailing orthodoxy of the Thousand Temples holds that the mortal was an avatar or vessel of the divine Bellasarius, chosen to enact the god&#39;s will in the material world at the most critical moment in human history. Symbol and Sacred Animal Eagle Clutching a Spear Bellasarius&#39;s holy symbol is an eagle clutching a spear in its talons — a martial and regal emblem that combines the imagery of divine vision (the eagle, which sees all from above) with the imagery of martial action (the spear, the weapon of the infantry commander who leads from the front). The eagle represents the Father&#39;s watchfulness, his capacity to see threats before they arrive and to act decisively to protect those in his care. The spear represents his willingness to fight, to place himself in harm&#39;s way, to be the first point of contact between his charges and the forces that threaten them. The Horse The horse is Bellasarius&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its strength, loyalty, and the intimate partnership it forms with its rider. The war horse carries its rider into battle, bears the weight of armor and rider without complaint, and charges into danger at the command of its master. In Empyrean theology, the horse represents the ideal of partnership in service — the understanding that the greatest deeds are accomplished not by individuals acting alone but by partners who trust each other absolutely and work together toward a common purpose. The horse also represents the virtue of noble bearing — the capacity to carry oneself with dignity and purpose even in the most desperate circumstances. Spheres of Influence Courage Courage is the foundational virtue of Bellasarius&#39;s teaching — not the reckless bravery that charges blindly into danger but the considered, purposeful courage of the leader who assesses the threat, weighs the cost, and then acts decisively despite his fear. The Father teaches that true courage is not the absence of fear but the refusal to allow fear to override duty. A father who does not fear for his children is a fool; a father who allows his fear to prevent him from protecting them is a coward. Bellasarius demands that his followers feel their fear fully and then act anyway. Service Service, in Bellasarius&#39;s teaching, is the essence of leadership. The Father does not reign — he serves. His authority exists not for his own benefit but for the protection and welfare of those in his care. Bellasarius teaches that the leader who uses his position for personal gain has betrayed the most sacred trust that can be placed upon a mortal soul, and that the truest measure of a father&#39;s worth is not what he accumulates for himself but what he provides for his family. This teaching has profound political implications within the Mithrian Empire , where Bellasarius&#39;s theology serves as the moral foundation for the obligation of the nobility to serve the common good. Fatherhood Fatherhood is both literal and metaphorical in Bellasarius&#39;s teaching. Literally, the Father is the patron of fathers, husbands, and all who bear the responsibility of providing for and protecting a family. Metaphorically, fatherhood encompasses any relationship in which one person assumes responsibility for the welfare of others — the commander and his soldiers, the lord and his vassals, the teacher and his students. Bellasarius teaches that fatherhood is the highest calling available to a mortal soul, and that the father who faithfully discharges his duties participates in the same divine act of protection and provision that Seros performs for all of creation. The Historical Bellasarius Valerian The historical Bellasarius Valerian was the great general who, alongside the Prophet Enador , led the Empyrean War that overthrew the Massaran Empire in 663 BE (Before Empire). While Enador provided the spiritual vision and prophetic authority that united the Empyrean faithful, it was Bellasarius who provided the military genius and personal courage that translated that vision into victory on the battlefield. Together, they broke the power of the Sorcerer Kings and liberated the peoples who had lived under Massaran tyranny for generations. Following the victory in the Empyrean War, Bellasarius Valerian founded the Mithrian state — the political entity that would eventually grow into the Mithrian Empire . He established the principles of governance, military organization, and civic duty that continue to define Mithrian civilization centuries later. His legacy is not merely military but institutional: the Mithrian state is, in a very real sense, his creation. House Valerian House Valerian , one of the Great Houses of the Mithrian Empire, claims direct descent from Bellasarius Valerian himself. This claim gives House Valerian an unparalleled legitimacy among the nobility — they are the bloodline of the Father, the living legacy of the man who founded the Empire and whose divine patron is one of the nine Empyrean gods. The political implications of this lineage are immense, and House Valerian has leveraged its ancestral connection to Bellasarius throughout the Empire&#39;s history. The Vestari The Vestari — the elite warrior-aristocrats of the Mithrian Empire — trace their nobility to Bellasarius Valerian. The Vestari tradition holds that Bellasarius established the first Vestari order from among his most trusted companions during the Empyrean War, creating a martial aristocracy bound by oaths of service, courage, and paternal responsibility. To be Vestari is to be a spiritual descendant of Bellasarius, to carry forward the traditions he established, and to embody the virtues of the Father in every aspect of one&#39;s life. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Bellasarius is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Bellasarius is the patron saint of fathers, commanders, founders, and all who bear the weight of leadership. His feast day is one of the most important holidays in the Mithrian calendar — a day of family gatherings, military parades, and the renewal of oaths of service. Devotion to Saint Bellasarius is perhaps the most politically significant of all the Empyrean saint cults. His eagle-and-spear emblem adorns the banners of House Valerian , the shields of the Vestari , and the gates of every military fortress in the Empire. Invocation of Saint Bellasarius is a standard element of coronation ceremonies, military commissions, and the swearing of feudal oaths. He is the patron saint of the Mithrian Empire itself — the spiritual father of the nation. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros Enador Empyrean War Massaran Empire Mithrian Empire House Valerian Vestari Great Houses The Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"cthonic-faith","title":"The Cthonic Faith","category":"faiths","tags":"cthonic religion theology dark-gods aurelion cults massaran undeath awakening human-sacrifice thune veil","text":"The Cthonic Faith You are limited by your senses, which pin you to this place, to this time. Your sorrows, your angers, your love — it divides you from what your heart of hearts knows. You are a stranger to yourself. Inside you resides a mote of the Aurellion, implanted within you at the moment of atomic creation. In the end you will find yourself at the beginning. When the Awakening occurs and we stand before Him, at last you will finally know yourself — know him. And the warmth that encompasses you will be the warm blood of the afterbirth of a True Resurrection. — A Cthonic cultist, burned at the stake The Cthonic faith is not a religion in any sense that a citizen of the Mithrian Empire would recognize. It has no central authority, no unified scripture, no ordained priesthood bound by shared doctrine. It is, instead, a tangled web of dark cults, secret traditions, ancient heresies, and forbidden practices — a sprawling, hydra-headed constellation of beliefs united only by their devotion to forgotten and hungering gods and other malevolent primal beings older than memory. Where the Empyrean Faith builds temples of stone and gold, the Cthonic faithful worship in caves, crypts, and ruins. Where the Empyrean faith preaches order, light, and the sanctity of life, the Cthonic traditions embrace darkness, power, consumption, and the annihilation of the weak. The Cthonic faith is strictly illegal under Mithrian law. Its practitioners, when discovered, face execution — typically by burning, a grim irony given the Empyrean theology of cremation. And yet, despite centuries of persecution, the Cthonic traditions endure. They persist in the Massar Kingdoms , where they remain the dominant spiritual practice. They survive among the Urgathoans , who carry their dark rites across borders and boundaries. They fester in the forgotten places of the Empire itself — in the deep cellars beneath old cities, in the crypts of ancient families, in the ruins of civilizations that predate the Mithrian Empire by millennia. The documented worship of Bel in Dunwick is only the most recent and most visible reminder that the Cthonic faith is not a relic of the past but a living, hungry presence within the Empire&#39;s own borders. The Aurelion: A Shared Origin, A Divided Interpretation Both Empyrean and Cthonic traditions agree on the fundamental nature of the Aurelion . He was the supreme designer of the cosmos, who sacrificed himself in the act of creation. His essence permeates the cosmos and all living things. It is his sacrifice that gives beings their souls and makes the practice of sorcery possible. But where the Empyrean Faith teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed himself out of love — to purge the universe of entropy and evil, to separate light from darkness — the Cthonic faith holds a radically different interpretation. In Cthonic theology, the Aurelion sacrificed himself to eliminate weakness. The act of cosmic creation was not an expression of compassion but of dominance — a violent pruning of all that was soft, fragile, and unworthy. The universe that resulted is not a garden tended by benevolent gods but a battleground, a crucible of competition where only the powerful survive and only the strongest are worthy of the Aurelion&#39;s legacy. This fundamental theological divergence — sacrifice as love versus sacrifice as dominion — is the fault line upon which the entire spiritual history of the known world has fractured. The Soul in Cthonic Theology The Cthonic understanding of the soul is perhaps the most profoundly disturbing aspect of the faith to Empyrean sensibilities, and the one that most clearly illustrates the irreconcilable gulf between the two traditions. In Cthonic theology, the soul is not a sacred spark destined for peaceful reunion with the divine. It is fuel. It is raw material. It is meat for the grinding. Death and Consumption Upon death, the Cthonic faith teaches that the soul is consumed — devoured as fuel for new life. There is no gentle weighing, no merciful judgment, no peaceful halls of rest. The soul is seized, broken apart, and fed into the churning engine of creation. Each new life that enters the world contains within it not a single, pristine soul but the remnants of thousands, perhaps millions, of other souls — fragments of the dead, shards of the consumed, sent screaming into the world to feed something more powerful than itself. This is not viewed as tragedy by the Cthonic faithful. It is viewed as truth — as the fundamental operating principle of a cosmos designed by a god who valued strength above all else. The strong consume the weak. The powerful grow more powerful by devouring the essence of the less powerful. This is not cruelty; it is the natural order. It is the Aurelion&#39;s design. No Paradise, No Reincarnation The Cthonic faith offers no paradise, no peaceful afterlife, no comforting promise of reunion with the divine. For the vast majority of souls, death brings only one of two fates: consumption — the dissolution of identity as the soul is broken apart and fed into the cycle of predatory creation — or oblivion, the utter annihilation of self. The only alternative is undeath — the forcible retention of the soul within the material world through necromantic arts, a practice that the Cthonic traditions regard not as abomination but as a legitimate exercise of power. To cheat death through undeath is to demonstrate the kind of strength and will that the Aurelion himself embodied in the act of creation. Soul Consolidation and Apotheosis The ultimate aspiration of the most devoted and powerful Cthonic practitioners is singular apotheosis — the consolidation of enough consumed souls into a single being that it achieves a form of godhood, a restoration of the Aurelion&#39;s original, undivided power. This is the theological justification for centuries of human sacrifice, soul harvesting, and necromantic experimentation: every soul consumed brings the practitioner one step closer to becoming, in essence, a new Aurelion. The cosmos, in this view, is not a place of harmony and balance but an arena of cosmic competition, and the ultimate prize is the throne of creation itself. The Rites of the Dead: Preservation and the Awakening In direct and deliberate opposition to the Empyrean practice of cremation, the Cthonic faith mandates the preservation of the body after death. Bodies are kept intact — buried, interred in crypts, sealed in tombs — so that the physical identity of the deceased is maintained. The corpse is not a discarded husk to be burned; it is a vessel, a repository, a container that must be kept whole for the day of reckoning. This practice is rooted in the Cthonic doctrine of the Awakening — the prophesied future event in which the Cthonic gods will return to the material world, the barriers between life and death will shatter, and the faithful will enjoy a true, bodily resurrection. Not a spiritual ascension, not a metaphorical reunion with the divine, but a literal, physical resurrection of the flesh. The dead will rise from their crypts. The bones will re-clothe themselves in flesh. The faithful who preserved their bodies will stand again in the light of their hungering gods and be rewarded for their devotion with eternal, embodied life. The Awakening is the central eschatological promise of the Cthonic faith — the event toward which all Cthonic practice and sacrifice is ultimately directed. It is the reason bodies are preserved. It is the reason crypts are tended. It is the reason the Cthonic faithful endure persecution, torture, and death at the hands of the Mithrian Empire without renouncing their beliefs. To be burned — to have one&#39;s body destroyed in the Empyrean fashion — is, in Cthonic theology, to be annihilated utterly, denied the possibility of resurrection, cast out from the Awakening forever. This is why the Empyrean practice of burning captured Cthonic cultists is regarded not merely as execution but as a form of spiritual genocide. Human Sacrifice Human sacrifice is a common practice among the Cthonic faithful. It is not an aberration, not a corruption of the faith by extremists, but a central and theologically justified component of Cthonic worship. The logic is brutally consistent with Cthonic theology: if the strong are meant to consume the weak, if souls are fuel for the powerful, then the deliberate sacrifice of living beings to the hungering gods is simply the most direct and honest expression of the cosmic order. Sacrificial rites vary enormously among the different Cthonic cults and traditions, reflecting the faith&#39;s fractured and decentralized nature. Some cults practice elaborate ritual murders with complex symbolic frameworks. Others engage in mass sacrifices. Some reserve the practice for captured enemies; others sacrifice willing devotees who believe their deaths will accelerate their own gods&#39; return. The common thread is the offering of life — of soul, of essence, of the mote of the Aurelion that resides within every living being — to powers that are hungry, ancient, and patient. The Cthonic Gods The gods of the Cthonic faith are not the orderly, comprehensible deities of the Empyrean pantheon. They are forgotten and hungering gods — primal beings older than memory, entities that predate the ordered cosmos and perhaps predate the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice itself. They are worshipped not out of love or gratitude but out of fear, ambition, and the desperate hope that service to these powers will grant the faithful a share of their terrible strength. Among the Cthonic gods whose worship has been documented within or near the borders of the Mithrian Empire : Bel — The Slaughterprince, whose worship has been documented in Dunwick and whose cult represents one of the most persistent Cthonic presences within Imperial territory. The full extent of the Cthonic pantheon is unknown and perhaps unknowable, given the faith&#39;s secretive and fragmented nature. New gods — or very old ones — seem to surface with disturbing regularity, emerging from ancient ruins, forgotten texts, and the fevered visions of those who peer too deeply beyond the Veil . The Cthonic Faith and the Veil The relationship between the Cthonic faith and the Veil — the metaphysical barrier between the material world and the realm Beyond — is intimate, dangerous, and theologically central. Elvoran sorcery, the most powerful and feared form of magic in the known world, draws its power from Beyond the Veil, from the chaotic and alien energies that exist outside the ordered cosmos. For Cthonic practitioners, this is not merely a magical technique but a spiritual practice: communion with the Cthonic gods and demons that dwell beyond the Veil is understood as the path to apotheosis, the means by which a mortal soul can transcend its limitations and achieve the kind of singular, consuming power that the Cthonic faith venerates above all else. This theological connection between Cthonic worship and Veil-sorcery is one of the reasons the Mithrian Empire regards all unregulated sorcery with deep suspicion. To draw power from Beyond is, in the Empyrean understanding, to traffic with the very forces of darkness and entropy that the Aurelion sacrificed himself to contain. The line between a scholar studying the Veil and a Cthonic cultist seeking communion with hungering gods is, in the eyes of the Thousand Temples , vanishingly thin. The Thune and the Cthonic Way The Thune are perhaps the purest living embodiment of Cthonic theology in practice. Thune society is organized around the principle that the strongest consume and rule the weakest — a social order that mirrors the Cthonic understanding of the cosmos itself. Among the Thune, might is not merely right; it is the only right. Power is its own justification. The weak exist to serve the strong, and the strong exist to consume the weak and grow stronger still. This is not cruelty in the Thune understanding; it is fidelity to the Aurelion&#39;s design, the honest and unflinching acceptance of a universe built on predation and dominance. Cthonic Worship in the Modern Era Despite the Mithrian Empire &#39;s centuries-long campaign of suppression, the Cthonic faith remains a living force in the world. It is still openly worshipped in the Massar Kingdoms , where the fall of the Massaran Empire did not extinguish the old traditions but merely scattered them into a patchwork of competing kingdoms, each with its own Cthonic practices and patron deities. The Urgathoans carry Cthonic rites and beliefs across the known world, their nomadic existence making them nearly impossible to suppress. And within the Empire itself, Cthonic cults persist in the shadows — patient, hidden, and waiting for the Awakening that their faith promises will come. See Also Empyrean Faith Aurelion The Veil Seros The Awakening Bel Thune Massar Kingdoms Massaran Empire Urgathoan Magic and Sorcery Thousand Temples Dunwick Mithrian Empire Elvoran"},{"slug":"cthonic-pantheon","title":"Cthonic Pantheon","category":"faiths","tags":"cthonic pantheon dark-gods dirgion iskara bel","text":"Cthonic Pantheon The Cthonic faith worships a collection of forgotten, hungering gods and malevolent primal beings older than memory. Unlike the Empyrean pantheon , which has been consolidated under the singular worship of Seros , the Cthonic gods remain distinct and competitive -- each commanding their own cults, rites, and sacrificial traditions. There is no unified church, no central authority, and no orthodoxy. The Cthonic pantheon is as fractured and predatory as the worldview it represents. The Cthonic Gods Name Titles Spheres Holy Symbol Sacred Animal Dirgion Doombringer, Lord of Death Death, undeath Fiery eye skull Vulture Iskara Mother of Monsters, Demon Queen Chaos, darkness Ouroboros Hydra Kaleth Dark Watcher, Elder Eye Madness, knowledge, entropy An eye Fungus Bel The Slaughterprince, Lord of War War, conquest, blood Black gauntlet Manticore Galmorm The Poisoner, The Trickster Treachery, poison, thievery Horned rat Rat Nasga Mistress of Pain and Pleasure Beauty, pain, lust A rose Snake Ravanor The Bitter Prince, Horned One Rulership, power, tyranny Antlered crown Stag Dirgion, the Doombringer Dirgion is the Lord of Death and the patron of undeath. His followers seek to defy the annihilation that awaits all souls by binding themselves to the mortal world through necromantic rites. Of all the Cthonic gods, Dirgion&#39;s influence is perhaps the most feared -- his cults operate in crypts and ossuaries, raising the dead and preserving the bodies of the faithful for the Awakening . His symbol, the fiery eye skull, is a mark of dread wherever it is found. Iskara, the Demon Queen Iskara is the Mother of Monsters, a primordial force of chaos and darkness. She is credited with the creation of many of the world&#39;s most terrible creatures, and her cults are devoted to the unleashing of entropy upon the ordered world. The ouroboros -- the serpent consuming its own tail -- serves as her holy symbol, representing the endless cycle of destruction and creation that she embodies. Kaleth, the Dark Watcher Kaleth is the Elder Eye, the god of madness, forbidden knowledge, and entropy. His worshippers seek truths that mortal minds were not meant to contain, and many are driven insane by what they discover. Kaleth&#39;s cults are among the most secretive and intellectually dangerous of the Cthonic traditions. His sacred animal is not an animal at all but fungus -- a reflection of his association with decay, parasitism, and the slow dissolution of order. Bel, the Slaughterprince Bel is the Lord of War in his most brutal and unrestrained form. Where Damocles of the Empyrean represents war as strategy and cunning, Bel represents war as slaughter, conquest, and the spilling of blood for its own sake. His black gauntlet is raised by warlords and berserkers, and his manticore symbolizes the fusion of predatory cunning with raw destructive force. Galmorm, the Poisoner Galmorm is the Trickster, the god of treachery, poison, and thievery. His worshippers operate in the shadows -- assassins, poisoners, thieves, and those who prefer to win through deception rather than strength. The horned rat is his symbol, a creature of cunning survival thriving in the margins of civilization. Nasga, Mistress of Pain and Pleasure Nasga governs beauty, pain, and lust -- the intoxicating overlap of pleasure and suffering. Her cults are seductive and cruel, drawing followers with promises of ecstasy and binding them with agony. The rose is her symbol, beautiful and thorned, and the snake her sacred animal, hypnotic and venomous. Ravanor, the Bitter Prince Ravanor is the Horned One, the god of rulership, power, and tyranny. He represents dominion not earned through virtue but seized through force and held through fear. His antlered crown symbolizes the raw, primal claim to sovereignty, and the stag -- proud, territorial, and violent in its contests for dominance -- is his sacred animal. Ravanor&#39;s worship appeals to those who desire power above all else. See Also The Cthonic Faith Empyrean Pantheon and Saints The Empyrean Faith The Massar Kingdoms Aurelion"},{"slug":"damocles","title":"Damocles, Victor of One Hundred Stratagems","category":"faiths","tags":"damocles empyrean deity saint victor war cunning victory fox burning-gauntlet","text":"Damocles, Victor of One Hundred Stratagems Damocles is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title Victor of One Hundred Stratagems. His spheres of divine influence encompass war, cunning, and victory — not the brutal, indiscriminate slaughter glorified by the Cthonic war-god Bel , but the disciplined, intelligent application of force in pursuit of righteous ends. Damocles is the god of the general who wins through superior planning, the strategist who turns an enemy&#39;s strength against him, the commander who achieves victory without unnecessary bloodshed. His hundred stratagems are not merely military tactics but metaphors for the hundred ways that wisdom, applied with courage and cunning, can overcome seemingly insurmountable obstacles. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Burning Gauntlet Damocles&#39;s holy symbol is a burning gauntlet — an armored fist wreathed in flame. The gauntlet represents martial power, the closed fist of disciplined force, while the flame signifies the divine fire of righteous purpose that transforms mere violence into sanctified action. A fist without flame is brutality; flame without a fist is impotent rage. The burning gauntlet is both — controlled, directed, purposeful force illuminated by the light of Seros and guided by the virtues of the Measure and the Scale . The Fox The fox is Damocles&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its legendary cunning, adaptability, and resourcefulness. The fox does not charge its prey head-on as a lion might; it observes, waits, adapts, and strikes when the moment is most favorable. In Empyrean theology, the fox represents the virtue of strategic thinking — the understanding that the greatest victories are won not by the strongest army but by the wisest commander. Fox imagery is common in Mithrian Military heraldry, particularly among scout companies and intelligence officers. Spheres of Influence War Damocles&#39;s domain over war is distinct from the domains of other war-associated deities in the Empyrean and Cthonic pantheons. Where Hector embodies the disciplined valor of the individual warrior and Bel glorifies war as conquest and slaughter, Damocles presides over the art of warfare itself — the grand strategy, the operational planning, the logistical mastery that determines the outcome of campaigns. He is the patron of generals, tacticians, and military theorists, the god invoked not in the chaos of the melee but in the quiet of the command tent where battles are won before the first sword is drawn. Cunning Cunning, in Damocles&#39;s teaching, is not deception but intelligence applied with moral purpose. The Victor of One Hundred Stratagems does not advocate lying, treachery, or dishonorable conduct — these are the domain of Galmorm , the Cthonic Trickster. Rather, Damocles teaches that wisdom demands flexibility, that rigid thinking is the enemy of victory, and that the truly virtuous commander uses every resource at his disposal — including misdirection, feints, and unconventional tactics — to achieve righteous ends with minimum loss of life. Victory Victory is the ultimate purpose of Damocles&#39;s teachings — not victory for its own sake, which is the corruption preached by Bel , but victory in service of justice, order, and the protection of the innocent. Damocles teaches that true victory is achieved when the enemy is defeated, the innocent are protected, and the cost in blood and suffering is minimized. A victory that destroys what it sought to protect is no victory at all. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Damocles is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Damocles is the patron saint of military commanders, strategists, diplomats, and all who seek to resolve conflicts through intelligence and skill rather than brute force. His feast day is marked by war games, strategic competitions, and the recitation of famous stratagems from Mithrian military history. Within the Mithrian Military , devotion to Saint Damocles remains exceptionally strong. Officers are expected to study the Hundred Stratagems — a collection of tactical and strategic principles attributed to the god — as part of their formal training. Temples dedicated to Saint Damocles often double as military academies, and his burning gauntlet is displayed alongside the Winged Sun of Seros in war rooms and command posts throughout the Empire. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros Hector Bel Galmorm The Measure and the Scale Mithrian Military Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"dirgion","title":"Dirgion, the Doombringer","category":"faiths","tags":"dirgion cthonic deity doombringer death undeath necromancy vulture fiery-eye-skull","text":"Dirgion, the Doombringer Dirgion is one of the seven Cthonic gods , known by the titles of the Doombringer and the Lord of Death. His spheres of divine influence encompass death and undeath — the twin aspects of mortality that the Cthonic Faith reinterprets not as natural transitions to be accepted but as enemies to be conquered through will, power, and forbidden knowledge. Dirgion teaches that death is not the passage to divine judgment that the Empyrean Faith proclaims but an annihilation to be resisted by any means necessary — and that undeath, far from being an abomination, is the ultimate expression of the will to survive. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Fiery Eye Skull Dirgion&#39;s unholy symbol is a skull with a single fiery eye blazing in its socket — the death&#39;s head that refuses to die, the consciousness that persists beyond the dissolution of the flesh. The fiery eye represents awareness, will, and power maintained even after the body has decayed and crumbled. It is the central image of Dirgion&#39;s theology: that death is not an ending but a transformation, and that those with sufficient will and knowledge can pass through death and emerge on the other side with their consciousness intact and their power magnified. The skull is the reality of mortality; the fiery eye is the refusal to accept that reality. The Vulture The vulture is Dirgion&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its intimate association with death and its capacity to derive sustenance from what others abandon as dead and worthless. The vulture does not kill; it waits for death to occur and then transforms the dead into fuel for the living. In Cthonic theology, the vulture represents the principle that death is not waste but raw material — that the corpse, properly handled, is not refuse to be buried but a resource to be utilized. This theology provides the spiritual foundation for the necromantic practices that are Dirgion&#39;s most notorious legacy. Spheres of Influence Death Death, in Dirgion&#39;s teaching, is the supreme enemy — the final annihilation that all living beings instinctively resist and that the strongest and wisest among them can learn to overcome. The Doombringer rejects the Empyrean teaching that death is a natural and divinely ordained passage to judgment and reward. Instead, Dirgion teaches that death is the ultimate expression of cosmic entropy — the force of dissolution that seeks to unmake everything The Aurelion created — and that resisting death is not a sin but the highest possible act of will and self-assertion. This teaching places Dirgion in direct theological opposition to Seros , who holds the role of judge of the dead, and to Shroud , who serves as psychopomp and guide of souls across the threshold. For Dirgion&#39;s followers, the soul that submits to Seros&#39;s judgment and allows Shroud to carry it across the threshold has surrendered — has accepted annihilation and called it salvation. The true warrior against death refuses the crossing entirely. Undeath Undeath is the practical application of Dirgion&#39;s resistance to death — the state achieved by those who have passed through death and emerged on the other side with their consciousness, power, and will intact. Dirgion&#39;s followers seek undeath through a variety of necromantic rites, the specific practices of which vary among different cults and traditions but which share a common theological foundation: the belief that the soul can be anchored to the material world beyond the natural span of mortal life through the application of forbidden knowledge and sufficient will. Undeath, in Dirgion&#39;s theology, is not a curse but a triumph — the ultimate victory over the entropy that The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice was meant (in the Cthonic interpretation) to impose upon the universe. The lich, the vampire, the revenant — these are not abominations but exemplars, beings who have achieved what Dirgion demands of all his followers: the refusal to die. Cult Activities Dirgion&#39;s cults are among the most feared and reviled religious organizations in the Mithrian Empire and beyond. They operate in secret, gathering in crypts, ossuaries, catacombs, and any other spaces associated with death and the dead. Their activities center on necromantic rites — the raising and binding of the dead, the creation of undead servants, the research into lichdom and other forms of self-directed undeath, and the study of death&#39;s mechanisms in pursuit of methods to circumvent them. The discovery of a Dirgion cult is considered a mark of dread wherever it occurs. The Thousand Temples treat Dirgion worship as one of the most serious spiritual offenses, and the secular authorities of the Mithrian Empire deal with confirmed Dirgion cultists with extreme severity. Despite this, the cults persist — because Dirgion&#39;s central promise, the conquest of death, is perhaps the most seductive promise any deity has ever made. See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon Seros Shroud The Aurelion The Awakening The Veil Cthonic Corruption Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"empyrean-faith","title":"The Empyrean Faith","category":"faiths","tags":"empyrean religion theology seros aurelion flame thousand-temples reincarnation cremation enador","text":"The Empyrean Faith As the flame gives light, so too does it burn. Thus is the soul weighed beneath the eyes of Seros, the Winged Sun, who watches all with measure unerring. — Anton, High Priest of the Thousand Temples The Empyrean faith is the dominant religious tradition of the Mithrian Empire , a monotheistic-pantheistic theology centered on the worship of the Aurelion — the supreme designer of the cosmos — and the veneration of Seros , the Winged Sun, as the principal deity of the Empyrean pantheon. It teaches that all existence flows from a single act of divine sacrifice, that the cosmos is a battleground between light and darkness, and that the soul of every living being carries within it a sacred spark destined for eventual reunification with the divine. The Empyrean faith is the state religion of the Mithrian Empire , enshrined in law, enforced by the Thousand Temples , and woven into every facet of Mithrian civic, military, and cultural life. The Aurelion and the Cosmic Sacrifice At the heart of Empyrean theology lies the doctrine of the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice. The Aurelion is understood not as a god among gods, but as the supreme and singular architect of all reality — a being of such incomprehensible totality that the cosmos itself is merely the residue of his self-destruction. Both Empyrean and Cthonic traditions agree on the fundamental nature of the Aurelion: he was the supreme designer of the cosmos, who sacrificed himself in the act of creation. His essence permeates the cosmos and all living things. It is the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice that gives beings their souls and makes the practice of sorcery possible. Where the two faiths diverge — violently and irreconcilably — is in their interpretation of the purpose and meaning of that sacrifice. The Empyrean faith teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed himself to purge the universe of entropy and evil, separating light from darkness in the first and most fundamental act of cosmic ordering. Before the sacrifice, all things existed in a state of undifferentiated chaos — a roiling, formless void in which creation and destruction, good and evil, order and entropy were indistinguishable. The Aurelion, in his infinite wisdom and compassion, chose to unmake himself so that light could be divided from shadow, so that life could be distinguished from death, and so that the forces of order and civilization could have a foundation upon which to build. This act of supreme selflessness is the theological model for all Empyrean virtue — the belief that sacrifice in service of something greater than oneself is the highest possible expression of the divine spark within. The Empyrean gods — Seros chief among them — are understood as emanations or aspects of the Aurelion&#39;s will, fragments of his divine intention given form and purpose in the aftermath of the sacrifice. They are the architects of order, the advocates of life and civilization, the shepherds who guide living souls toward spiritual purity and eventual reunification with the Aurelion through the great cycles of existence. The Soul and Its Journey Empyrean theology posits a detailed and carefully ordered cosmology of the soul. Every living being possesses a soul — a mote of the Aurelion&#39;s essence, implanted at the moment of creation. This soul is not merely a metaphysical abstraction; it is the literal substance of divine light, the fragment of the Aurelion that connects each mortal creature to the cosmic whole. It is the soul that allows sentient beings to reason, to love, to create, and — for those with the gift — to channel the Flame . Death and the Weighing When a living being dies, the Empyrean faith teaches that its soul is ushered to the afterlife, a process overseen by Seros himself. In the afterlife, the soul&#39;s valor and deeds are weighed — literally measured against the virtues of The Measure and the Scale . This is not a metaphorical process in Empyrean theology but a literal cosmic event: the soul stands before the divine judgment, and its worth is assessed against the totality of its earthly life. Noble and heroic souls — those who embodied the seven virtues of the Scale, who lived with honor, courage, compassion, and purpose — pass through this judgment and enter the Halls of Seros , a place of peace, radiance, and communion with the divine. In the Halls, these worthy souls rest in serene contemplation, awaiting the ultimate reunification with the Aurelion that the faith teaches will come at the end of all cycles. These souls are not idle; they are venerated as heroes and legends, and many are found to be widely worshipped as Saints in their own right, their names invoked in prayer, their deeds recounted in liturgy, their intercession sought by the living. Reincarnation Souls that are found wanting — not wicked, but incomplete, unfinished in their journey toward spiritual perfection — are returned to the cycle of mortal life through reincarnation. The Empyrean faith does not view reincarnation as punishment but as opportunity: each new life is a chance to grow closer to the divine ideal, to better embody the virtues of the Scale, to refine the soul&#39;s inner light until it shines brightly enough to pass the weighing and enter the Halls. The number of cycles a soul might endure is unspecified in Empyrean doctrine; some theologians of the Academy have debated whether the process is infinite or bounded, but no consensus has ever been reached. This cyclical understanding of the soul creates a profound Empyrean reverence for life in all its forms. Every living creature, no matter how humble, may carry within it a soul on its journey toward the divine. This is one of the theological foundations for the Empyrean emphasis on compassion, mercy, and the protection of the innocent — any being might be a soul on the cusp of its final incarnation. Cremation and the Rites of the Dead The practice of cremation is one of the most visible and non-negotiable tenets of the Empyrean faith. The Empyrean faith instructs that bodies be burned upon death, so that the soul can more quickly enter the afterlife where it will be judged. The theological reasoning is precise: the soul, upon departing the body, must journey to the afterlife for its weighing, and the destruction of the physical vessel by fire accelerates this process, freeing the soul from its material anchor and allowing it to ascend unimpeded toward the judgment of Seros . To allow a body to decay naturally — to leave it unburned, to permit the slow dissolution of flesh — is considered a minor sacrilege, a sign of negligence or ignorance. But to actively prevent the body&#39;s destruction through mummification, embalming, or other methods of preservation is a far graver sin. The Empyrean faith teaches that such practices trap the soul, binding it to the material world and preventing it from completing its journey. This theological position places the Empyrean faith in direct and irreconcilable opposition to the Cthonic Faith , which mandates the preservation of the body in anticipation of the prophesied Awakening . The cremation rites are performed by priests of the Thousand Temples , who recite passages from The Measure and the Scale as the body is consumed by flame. In military contexts, particularly among the Mithrian Marines , the rites may be performed by a commanding officer if no priest is available, and mass cremations on the battlefield are a grim but common occurrence in the Empire&#39;s many wars. The ashes of the dead are typically scattered or interred in family urns, though the ashes of particularly revered individuals may be preserved in reliquaries within temples. Centuries of Secret Worship The Empyrean faith as it exists today is the product of millennia of persecution, secrecy, and eventual triumphant revolution. For thousands of years, the followers of the Empyrean gods congregated in secret for fear of subjugation from their Cthonic masters. The worship of Seros and the other Empyrean gods was forbidden under the Massaran Empire , driven underground, and punished with death. Empyrean believers met in hidden cellars, in remote caves, in the shadows of the very crypts and ruins that the Cthonic cults claimed as their own sacred spaces. During this long period of oppression, the Empyrean faith survived through oral tradition, whispered prayers, and the fierce devotion of a scattered and persecuted community. The gods of the Empyrean pantheon were invoked in hushed tones, their names passed from parent to child in secret, their rites performed in darkness for fear of the Sorcerer Kings and their Cthonic priesthoods. The faith&#39;s survival through these centuries of subjugation is regarded by modern Empyrean theologians as proof of its divine truth — that the light of Seros could not be extinguished even by the deepest darkness of Cthonic tyranny. The Prophet Enador and the Revolution The turning point in the history of the Empyrean faith — and indeed in the history of the known world — came with the emergence of the Prophet Enador . Enador is the single most important figure in Empyrean religious history. It was Enador who retrieved the sacred text known as The Measure and the Scale , a document of immense theological and legal significance that outlined the core beliefs, virtues, and laws of the Empyrean faith. Alongside the Measure and the Scale, Enador also recovered the Anthyllium grimoire, though the precise relationship between these two texts and the circumstances of their discovery are subjects of intense scholarly debate at the Academy . Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end. — The Prophet Enador to the Sorcerer King Sebek Armed with the divine mandate of the Measure and the Scale, Enador launched a holy war against the Massaran Empire and its Cthonic rulers. This was not merely a military campaign but a religious revolution — a cosmic struggle between the forces of light and darkness, order and entropy, civilization and barbarism. Enador&#39;s war was long, brutal, and transformative. Its eventual success — the overthrow of the Massaran Empire and the destruction or scattering of its Cthonic priesthoods — led directly to the founding of Mithra City and, in time, the establishment of the Mithrian Empire itself. Enador&#39;s revolution established the Empyrean faith not merely as one religion among many but as the foundational ideology of an entire civilization. The Mithrian Empire is, in a very real sense, the political and military expression of Empyrean theology — a civilization built on the principles of the Measure and the Scale, governed by the light of Seros , and dedicated to the eternal war against the forces of darkness and entropy that the Cthonic faiths represent. The Empyrean Pantheon and the Rise of Saints Throughout the Mithrian Empire , the worship of Empyrean gods besides Seros is extremely rare. In the centuries since the founding of the Empire, the Mithrians have effectively supplanted most of the Empyrean mythological tradition with the singular worship of Seros, the Winged Sun, the Unconquered Sun, the Silent One. The other gods of the Empyrean pantheon — once vibrant figures of worship and devotion — have been largely forgotten, relegated to ancient texts and the debate halls of the Academy , where they are discussed as subjects of historical and philosophical interest rather than objects of living faith. In their place, a pantheon of Saints has arisen. Saints are mortal individuals, posthumously anointed by the Thousand Temples , who in life exhibited the seven virtues of The Measure and the Scale to an extraordinary degree. These Saints have become, in practice, minor gods to the Serosian faithful — their names invoked in prayer, their intercession sought in times of need, their lives held up as models of virtue and devotion. Several militant orders have been founded in the names of particular Saints, and the cult of the Saints is one of the most vibrant and dynamic aspects of contemporary Empyrean worship. The one significant exception to the dominance of Seros worship is the veneration of the Empyrean god Shroud among the Mithrian Military , particularly the Mithrian Marines . Shroud&#39;s worship persists in military culture as a patron of soldiers, of those who walk in the shadow of death, and of those who must do grim and necessary work in the service of the light. The Flame The Flame is the priestly magic of the Empyrean faith — a manifestation of divine power channeled through the virtue and spiritual purity of the practitioner. Unlike the arcane sorcery drawn from the Veil , the Flame is not a learned skill in any conventional sense. It cannot be studied from textbooks, memorized from formulae, or acquired through intellectual effort alone. The Flame is channeled through virtue — through the living embodiment of the principles outlined in The Measure and the Scale . This creates a profound tension within the institutional structure of the Thousand Temples . The Flame is the most visible and dramatic proof of the Empyrean faith&#39;s divine truth — when a priest of Seros calls upon the Flame and light answers, it is taken as direct evidence of the god&#39;s favor and the practitioner&#39;s worthiness. And yet the Thousand Temples barely teach the Flame in any formal sense, because the consensus among Empyrean theologians is that it cannot be taught — it must be lived. A priest who walks the path of the Measure and the Scale, who genuinely embodies the seven virtues, who burns with sincere devotion and righteous purpose, may find the Flame answering their call. A priest who merely memorizes the words and performs the rituals without inner transformation will find only silence. This doctrine means that the ability to channel the Flame is, in practice, vanishingly rare even among the ordained clergy of the Thousand Temples. Many priests serve their entire lives without ever manifesting it. Those who do are regarded with tremendous reverence and are often fast-tracked to positions of authority within the Temple hierarchy, or held up as candidates for eventual Sainthood. See Also Seros The Measure and the Scale Cthonic Faith Aurelion Enador Thousand Temples Saints The Flame Shroud Mithrian Empire Mithra City Massaran Empire Magic and Sorcery The Veil Anthyllium"},{"slug":"empyrean-pantheon","title":"Empyrean Pantheon and Saints","category":"faiths","tags":"empyrean pantheon gods saints seros","text":"Empyrean Pantheon and Saints The Empyrean faith originally encompassed a full pantheon of gods, each governing distinct aspects of mortal life and the cosmic order. In the modern Mithrian Empire , Seros has risen to overwhelming dominance, and most of the other Empyrean gods are now venerated as Saints rather than actively worshipped as deities. Their divine origins have been reframed by the Thousand Temples as legendary mortal lives of extraordinary virtue. The Empyrean Gods Name Titles Spheres Holy Symbol Sacred Animal seros Seros The Silent One, The Unconquered Sun Light, law, civilization Winged sun Andraste The Holy Dancer Compassion, strength, joy Twin swords Heron Damocles Victor of One Hundred Stratagems War, cunning, victory Burning gauntlet Fox Eramus The Shepherd Wisdom, duty, steadfastness Shepherd&#39;s crook Dog Euphrosyne The Candle Hope, willpower, resolve A candle Gazelle Hector The Bronze Lord Discipline, martial prowess, justice Crossed swords Lion Mina The Hand Grace, art, beauty A chisel Swan Sagramore The Martyr Loyalty, endurance, sacrifice Broken manacles Ox Bellasarius The Father Courage, service, fatherhood Eagle clutching spear Horse enador Enador The Light in the Dark Vision, journey, time Open scroll From Gods to Saints The transition from active godhood to saintly veneration was not sudden or violent. As Mithrian culture centralized its religious identity around Seros , the other Empyrean gods were gradually absorbed into a framework of sainthood administered by the Thousand Temples . Their myths were reinterpreted as hagiographies -- tales of mortal individuals whose lives so perfectly embodied the virtues of the Scale that they earned a place of honor in the afterlife and the devotion of the faithful. Saints are posthumously anointed by the Thousand Temples. To qualify, an individual must have exhibited the seven virtues of the Scale to an extraordinary and well-documented degree. The process of canonization involves extensive theological review, testimony from witnesses, and approval by the senior clergy. Notable Saints Many of the figures listed above now hold the title of Saint within the Thousand Temples. Andraste is invoked by those seeking courage tempered with compassion. Damocles is the patron of military strategists. Eramus is beloved by scholars, magistrates, and teachers. Sagramore is honored by prisoners, laborers, and all who endure suffering with dignity. Enador , the Light in the Dark, holds a unique position as both a saint and a historical prophet. It was Enador who rediscovered the Measure and the Scale along with the Anthyllium grimoire, fundamentally shaping the religious and legal foundations of the Mithrian Empire. Bellasarius, the Father, is widely venerated as a model of paternal duty -- courage wielded in service to family, community, and the state. His eagle-and-spear symbol is common in households and military barracks alike. The Living Tradition While the old gods may no longer command the fervent worship they once did, their influence persists. Their symbols adorn temples and armor. Their stories are told to children. Their virtues shape the moral framework of Mithrian society through the Scale . In this sense, the Empyrean pantheon has not died -- it has been transformed, its divine fire redistributed across a constellation of saintly exemplars orbiting the singular radiance of Seros . See Also Seros, the Winged Sun The Empyrean Faith The Measure and the Scale The Thousand Temples Cthonic Pantheon Prophet Enador"},{"slug":"enador","title":"Enador, the Light in the Dark","category":"faiths","tags":"enador empyrean deity saint prophet light-in-the-dark vision journey time owl scroll empyrean-war measure-and-the-scale anthyllium massaran-empire sorcerer-kings","text":"Enador, the Light in the Dark Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end. — The Prophet Enador to Sorcerer King Sebek Enador is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title the Light in the Dark. His spheres of divine influence encompass vision, journey, and time — the prophetic virtues of those who see what others cannot, who venture into darkness to retrieve what the world has lost, and who understand the long arc of time as a force that shapes the destiny of nations and souls alike. Enador is the god of prophets, pilgrims, scholars, and seekers — those who leave the safety of the known world to pursue truth in places where truth has been buried, forgotten, or deliberately hidden. Enador occupies a singular position in the Empyrean Pantheon because the historical Enador was not merely a mortal vessel of the divine but the Prophet of Seros himself — the individual chosen by the Unconquered Sun to retrieve the most sacred artifacts of the faith and to lead the holy war that would reshape the world. No other figure in Empyrean history, save perhaps Bellasarius Valerian, has had so direct and measurable an impact on the course of civilization. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Open Scroll Enador&#39;s holy symbol is an open scroll — a document unrolled and ready to be read. The scroll represents knowledge recovered, wisdom revealed, truth brought from darkness into light. It is deliberately distinguished from a closed or sealed scroll, which would represent hidden or forbidden knowledge. Enador&#39;s scroll is open — his truth is meant to be shared, studied, and applied. The symbol also references Enador&#39;s most famous act: the recovery of The Anthyllium , the ancient grimoire that contained the formulae of Gnostic Geometry , alongside The Measure and the Scale , the sacred text of Seros . The Owl The owl is Enador&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its association with wisdom, night-vision, and the ability to see clearly in darkness. The owl hunts when others sleep, perceives what others cannot, and moves through the night with silent, purposeful precision. In Empyrean theology, the owl represents the prophet&#39;s gift — the capacity to perceive truths hidden from ordinary sight, to navigate the darkness of ignorance and deception, and to bring back knowledge that illuminates the path forward for those who cannot see it themselves. Spheres of Influence Vision Vision, in Enador&#39;s teaching, is the capacity to perceive truth beyond the surface of things — to see the hidden patterns, the buried connections, the long-term consequences that escape ordinary perception. Enador&#39;s vision is not merely physical sight but spiritual and intellectual penetration: the ability to discern The Aurelion &#39;s design in the apparent chaos of the world, to read the signs of the times, and to understand what must be done when others are paralyzed by confusion or fear. The Prophet teaches that vision is both a gift and a discipline — some are born with keener sight than others, but all can sharpen their perception through study, contemplation, and the cultivation of inner silence. Journey The journey is central to Enador&#39;s mythology and theology. His greatest act — the recovery of the Measure and the Scale and The Anthyllium — was accomplished through a physical and spiritual journey of immense difficulty and danger. Enador teaches that truth is not found in comfort and safety but in the willingness to leave the known behind, to venture into hostile territory, and to endure the hardships of the road in pursuit of something greater than personal security. Every pilgrimage undertaken by the Empyrean faithful is, in some sense, a recapitulation of Enador&#39;s original journey. Time Time is the most esoteric of Enador&#39;s spheres — the understanding that the cosmos unfolds according to patterns and rhythms that operate on scales far beyond the span of a single human life. The Prophet teaches that patience is not passivity but the recognition that some truths can only be revealed through the passage of time, that some victories can only be won by those willing to plan and labor across generations, and that the ultimate triumph of light over darkness is not a single decisive battle but a long, patient process of recovery, restoration, and renewal. The Prophet&#39;s Great Work Recovery of the Sacred Texts Enador&#39;s defining act was the recovery of two texts of immeasurable importance: The Measure and the Scale — the sacred scripture of Seros that codifies the moral and theological foundations of the Empyrean Faith — and The Anthyllium — the ancient grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality, the foundational text of Gnostic Geometry . These texts had been lost, hidden, or suppressed during the long centuries of the Massaran Empire &#39;s dominion, and their recovery was essential to the spiritual and intellectual renewal that made the Empyrean War possible. The circumstances of the recovery — where the texts were found, what Enador endured to retrieve them, what forces opposed him — are the subject of extensive hagiographic literature within the Thousand Temples , though the precise historical details are debated by scholars. The Empyrean War Armed with the recovered texts and the prophetic authority of Seros himself, Enador led the Empyrean War alongside the general Bellasarius Valerian. This was the great holy war that overthrew the Massaran Empire and its Sorcerer Kings in 663 BE (Before Empire). Enador provided the spiritual vision, the prophetic legitimacy, and the theological framework that united the diverse peoples suffering under Massaran tyranny into a single, unified force. Bellasarius provided the military genius to translate that vision into battlefield victory. The Empyrean War was not merely a political revolution but a cosmic event — the moment when the forces of Empyrean light decisively broke the power of the sorcerer-tyrants who had ruled through Cthonic bargains and arcane oppression. Enador&#39;s famous warning to Sorcerer King Sebek — that mercy has its end — is one of the most quoted passages in Empyrean scripture. Founding of Mithra City The victory in the Empyrean War led directly to the founding of Mithra City and, eventually, the Mithrian Empire . Enador&#39;s holy war created the conditions for Bellasarius Valerian to establish the Mithrian state, and the theological and legal principles articulated by Enador in the Measure and the Scale became the moral and legal foundation of the new civilization. In this sense, Enador is not merely a prophet but the co-founder of Mithrian civilization itself. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Enador is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Enador is the patron saint of prophets, scholars, pilgrims, and seekers of lost knowledge. His feast day is marked by scholarly gatherings, the reading of sacred texts, and the departure of pilgrimages to holy sites associated with his journey. Devotion to Saint Enador is particularly strong among the clergy of the Thousand Temples , among scholars and mages of the Imperial Academy , and among those who undertake pilgrimages. His open scroll is displayed in libraries, scriptoriums, and lecture halls, and students of Gnostic Geometry traditionally offer a prayer to the Prophet before beginning their studies — for it was Enador who recovered the knowledge they seek to master. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros Bellasarius The Measure and the Scale The Anthyllium Gnostic Geometry Empyrean War Massaran Empire Sorcerer Kings Mithra City Mithrian Empire Thousand Temples Imperial Academy"},{"slug":"eramus","title":"Eramus, the Shepherd","category":"faiths","tags":"eramus empyrean deity saint shepherd wisdom duty steadfastness dog shepherds-crook","text":"Eramus, the Shepherd Eramus is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title of the Shepherd. His spheres of divine influence encompass wisdom, duty, and steadfastness — the quiet, unglamorous virtues that hold civilizations together long after the heroes and conquerors have passed into legend. Eramus is not the god of great deeds or dramatic revelations but the god of the long watch, the patient hand, the steady voice that guides the faithful through the ordinary trials of daily life. He is the god of magistrates and teachers, of farmers and parents, of all who bear the weight of responsibility without complaint and carry it faithfully to the end. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Shepherd&#39;s Crook Eramus&#39;s holy symbol is a shepherd&#39;s crook — the simple, curved staff used by herders to guide and protect their flocks. The crook is simultaneously a tool of gentle guidance and firm correction: it can draw a wandering sheep back to the flock, and it can fend off a wolf at the gate. This duality is central to Eramus&#39;s teaching — that wisdom without the willingness to enforce it is mere philosophizing, and that authority without wisdom is tyranny. The shepherd&#39;s crook is one of the humblest symbols in the Empyrean Pantheon , deliberately eschewing the martial imagery of swords and gauntlets for a tool associated with common labor. The Dog The dog is Eramus&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its loyalty, vigilance, and devotion to duty. The sheepdog does not seek glory or recognition; it works tirelessly, endures hardship without complaint, and places the safety of the flock above its own comfort. In Empyrean theology, the dog represents the ideal of selfless service — the willingness to serve not because service brings reward but because service is its own justification. Dogs are welcomed in temples dedicated to Saint Eramus, and it is considered deeply auspicious for a stray dog to appear at a threshold during times of uncertainty. Spheres of Influence Wisdom Eramus&#39;s wisdom is practical rather than esoteric. It is not the arcane knowledge of Kaleth or the visionary insight of Enador but the accumulated, hard-won understanding that comes from years of patient observation, careful thought, and honest engagement with the world as it is. The Shepherd teaches that true wisdom begins with the acknowledgment of one&#39;s own ignorance and grows through the disciplined practice of listening, questioning, and reflecting. His followers are counselors, teachers, and judges — those whose wisdom serves others rather than aggrandizing themselves. Duty Duty is the cornerstone of Eramus&#39;s teaching. The Shepherd holds that every living being has obligations — to family, to community, to the divine order established by The Aurelion and maintained by Seros . These obligations are not burdens to be resented but callings to be embraced, for it is through the faithful performance of duty that the individual soul aligns itself with the cosmic order and earns its place in the divine plan. Eramus teaches that the smallest duty faithfully performed is more pleasing to the gods than the grandest gesture undertaken for selfish reasons. Steadfastness Steadfastness is the virtue that binds wisdom and duty together. It is the refusal to abandon one&#39;s post, to betray one&#39;s principles, to surrender to despair when the task grows difficult and the end seems far away. The Shepherd endures. He does not flee when the wolves come; he does not falter when the storm breaks. He stands, crook in hand, and does what must be done. In a cosmos threatened by the entropy and chaos of the Cthonic powers, steadfastness is perhaps the most necessary of all virtues. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Eramus is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Eramus is the patron saint of teachers, magistrates, shepherds, farmers, and all who serve in positions of quiet authority. His feast day is celebrated with community gatherings, the settling of disputes, and the recognition of those who have served their communities with distinction. Devotion to Saint Eramus is particularly strong in rural areas of the Mithrian Empire , where his practical, duty-centered theology resonates with the rhythms of agricultural life. Village priests often model their ministry on Eramus&#39;s example, serving as counselors, mediators, and educators as much as spiritual leaders. The Shepherd&#39;s crook is a common sight above the doors of schoolhouses, courtrooms, and village halls throughout the Empire&#39;s provinces. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros The Aurelion The Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples Enador"},{"slug":"euphrosyne","title":"Euphrosyne, the Candle","category":"faiths","tags":"euphrosyne empyrean deity saint candle hope willpower resolve gazelle flame","text":"Euphrosyne, the Candle Each living being carries a spark of the Aurelion within its soul. To embody the Measure and the Scale you can reshape the world with your soul&#39;s fire. — Euphrosyne Euphrosyne is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title of the Candle. Her spheres of divine influence encompass hope, willpower, and resolve — the inner virtues that sustain the faithful when external circumstances offer no comfort, when the darkness is total and the path forward invisible. Euphrosyne is the goddess of the single flame that refuses to be extinguished, the last light burning in the deepest night. She teaches that the spark of the divine — the fragment of The Aurelion that resides within every living soul — is sufficient to overcome any darkness, provided the will to carry it forward does not falter. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Candle Euphrosyne&#39;s holy symbol is a single lit candle — the simplest, most fragile source of light imaginable. A candle can be extinguished by a gust of wind, drowned by a splash of water, smothered by a careless hand. And yet a single candle, carefully tended, can illuminate a room, guide a traveler through darkness, or kindle a bonfire that warms a hundred souls. The candle represents the Empyrean teaching that the smallest spark of divine virtue, nurtured through willpower and resolve, can overcome seemingly infinite darkness. The symbol is deliberately humble — not a blazing sun or a roaring fire but a single, quiet flame that burns because someone chose to light it and refuses to let it die. The Gazelle The gazelle is Euphrosyne&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its grace, speed, and remarkable endurance. Gazelles are creatures of the open plain — exposed, vulnerable, with no armor or weapons save their speed and their unbreakable will to survive. They do not fight their predators; they outrun them, outlast them, refuse to surrender to exhaustion or despair. In Empyrean theology, the gazelle represents the virtue of hope in action — not passive wishing but the active, tireless pursuit of survival and freedom against overwhelming odds. Spheres of Influence Hope Hope, in Euphrosyne&#39;s teaching, is not optimism — it is not the belief that things will improve or that circumstances will change. Hope is the decision to act as though the light matters even when the darkness seems total. It is a choice, not a feeling, and it requires the same discipline and courage as any martial virtue. The Candle teaches that despair is the ultimate victory of the Cthonic powers — that to surrender hope is to extinguish the spark of The Aurelion within one&#39;s own soul and to hand that territory to the forces of entropy and darkness without a fight. Willpower Willpower is the fuel that keeps the candle burning. Euphrosyne teaches that the divine spark within every soul is not self-sustaining — it must be actively maintained through an act of will, through the conscious decision to align oneself with the virtues of the Measure and the Scale and to resist the temptations of despair, apathy, and surrender. Willpower is not stubbornness or obstinacy; it is the directed, purposeful application of inner strength toward righteous ends. It is what separates the saint from the merely pious, the hero from the merely brave. Resolve Resolve is willpower sustained over time — the commitment to continue when hope is thin and the will is exhausted. Euphrosyne&#39;s resolve is not the dramatic courage of the battlefield but the quiet, grinding determination of the long siege, the endless march, the years of patient labor toward a goal that may never be reached. She teaches that the greatest acts of virtue are not the spectacular ones but the sustained ones — the faithful who keep the candle lit not for a moment but for a lifetime. The Flame Euphrosyne&#39;s teachings are intimately connected to the priestly magic known as The Flame — the divine power channeled through virtue, sacrifice, and righteous purpose. Her famous declaration that every living being carries a spark of The Aurelion within its soul is one of the foundational texts of Flame theology. It is Euphrosyne who articulated the principle that divine magic is not drawn from external sources — not from the geometric patterns of Gnostic Geometry or the alien energies beyond The Veil — but from the fire that burns within the soul itself. To embody the Measure and the Scale is to fan that spark into a conflagration capable of reshaping reality. The Thousand Temples barely teach The Flame in the current era, but Euphrosyne&#39;s words remain the theological cornerstone for those rare priests and paladins who still wield it. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Euphrosyne is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a goddess in her own right. Saint Euphrosyne is the patron saint of the desperate, the imprisoned, the besieged, and all who endure suffering with unbroken will. Her feast day is celebrated by the lighting of candles in windows — one for each member of the household — and by prayers for those who suffer in darkness. Devotion to Saint Euphrosyne is especially common among prisoners, refugees, and those facing terminal illness. Her candle appears in the cells of those condemned to execution, in the windows of plague-houses, and in the hands of soldiers marching into battles they do not expect to survive. She is the last saint invoked, the final prayer offered, the light carried into the darkness when all other lights have failed. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros The Aurelion The Flame The Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"galmorm","title":"Galmorm, the Poisoner","category":"faiths","tags":"galmorm cthonic deity poisoner trickster treachery poison thievery rat horned-rat","text":"Galmorm, the Poisoner Galmorm is one of the seven Cthonic gods , known by the titles of the Poisoner and the Trickster. His spheres of divine influence encompass treachery, poison, and thievery — the arts of the weak who survive and prosper through cunning, deception, and the willingness to strike from the shadows when a direct confrontation would mean certain defeat. Galmorm is the god of those who cannot win fairly and so refuse to play fairly — the liar, the assassin, the thief, the poisoner who slips death into a cup of wine and watches with quiet satisfaction as the strong choke on it. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Horned Rat Galmorm&#39;s unholy symbol is a horned rat — a rat bearing small, curving horns, an image that combines the association of rats with disease, filth, and secret infestation with the supernatural menace of horns, traditionally a marker of Cthonic power. The horned rat represents Galmorm&#39;s central teaching: that the weak, the despised, and the overlooked are the true inheritors of power. The rat thrives where other creatures perish — in the walls, in the sewers, in the refuse heaps of civilization. It is everywhere, it is indestructible, and it operates entirely outside the notice and control of those who consider themselves its masters. The Rat The rat is also Galmorm&#39;s sacred animal in its natural form — the common rat that infests every city, every ship, every granary and warehouse in the known world. Rats are survivors. They adapt to any environment, exploit any resource, and reproduce with a speed that renders extermination campaigns futile. In Cthonic theology, the rat represents the principle that survival and proliferation, not honor and virtue, are the true measures of success. The Empyrean gods may claim the lion and the eagle, but it is the rat that has conquered the world. Spheres of Influence Treachery Treachery is Galmorm&#39;s primary virtue — the willingness to betray trust, break oaths, and exploit the loyalty of others for personal advantage. The Trickster teaches that trust is a vulnerability, that oaths are chains worn by the foolish, and that the only truly free being is the one who refuses to be bound by any commitment that does not serve their own interests. This teaching is anathema to the Empyrean Faith , which holds loyalty, honor, and the keeping of oaths as fundamental virtues — and Galmorm&#39;s followers take particular pleasure in exploiting those virtues against the faithful. Poison Poison is Galmorm&#39;s preferred instrument — the weapon of the weak against the strong, the tool that renders martial prowess, armor, and fortification irrelevant. A single drop in a cup, a smear on a doorknob, a dusting of powder on a letter&#39;s seal — poison strikes where swords cannot reach, bypasses every defense, and kills with a efficiency that no battlefield can match. Galmorm&#39;s followers are students of toxicology, herbalism, and alchemy, experts in the identification, preparation, and deployment of substances that kill, incapacitate, or manipulate. Thievery Thievery is the redistribution of resources from those who have them to those with the skill and daring to take them — and in Galmorm&#39;s theology, this is not a crime but a correction. The Trickster teaches that property, like power, belongs to whoever is clever enough to acquire it, and that the wealthy and powerful who believe their possessions are secure are simply waiting to be educated. Galmorm&#39;s followers are thieves, burglars, pickpockets, and confidence artists — practitioners of an art that the Empyrean order condemns but that the Cthonic faith celebrates as a demonstration of the principle that cunning is superior to strength. Cult Activities Galmorm&#39;s cults are among the most difficult to detect and eradicate, precisely because deception and concealment are the fundamental skills that define his worship. Where the cults of Bel or Dirgion can be identified by their blood-soaked altars and necromantic horrors, Galmorm&#39;s followers leave no trace — or, more accurately, they leave traces designed to mislead. A Galmorm cult might operate for years within a city&#39;s thieves&#39; guild, a merchant house, or even a Temple chapter without detection, its members indistinguishable from their legitimate neighbors. The Trickster&#39;s cults are organized in cells, with no member knowing the identities of more than a handful of others. Information is compartmentalized, loyalty is maintained through mutual blackmail rather than genuine devotion, and betrayal — the supreme Galmorm virtue — is simultaneously the cult&#39;s greatest tool and its greatest vulnerability. Galmorm cults frequently self-destruct as members betray each other, only to reform elsewhere with new members and new configurations. See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon Damocles The Measure and the Scale Cthonic Corruption Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"hector","title":"Hector, the Bronze Lord","category":"faiths","tags":"hector empyrean deity saint bronze-lord discipline martial-prowess justice lion crossed-swords","text":"Hector, the Bronze Lord Hector is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title of the Bronze Lord. His spheres of divine influence encompass discipline, martial prowess, and justice — the warrior virtues that the Empyrean Faith holds as essential to the maintenance of cosmic order. Where Damocles presides over the art of war at the strategic level, Hector embodies the personal virtues of the warrior: the discipline to train relentlessly, the skill to fight with lethal precision, and the justice to wield deadly force only in righteous cause. He is the god of the soldier in the line, the knight on the field, the individual who stands between the innocent and those who would harm them. Symbol and Sacred Animal Crossed Swords Hector&#39;s holy symbol is a pair of crossed swords — an ancient martial emblem representing the readiness to fight and the discipline to fight with honor. Unlike the twin swords of Andraste , which signify the duality of compassion and strength, Hector&#39;s crossed swords represent the intersection of martial skill and moral purpose. The crossing point is the moment of decision — where the blade meets the cause, where violence becomes justice or justice becomes violence. The symbol reminds the faithful that the sword is morally neutral; it is the hand that holds it and the cause that guides it that determine whether its use is righteous. The Lion The lion is Hector&#39;s sacred animal, chosen as the supreme symbol of martial courage, strength, and nobility. The lion does not hunt through cunning or ambush — it confronts its prey directly, openly, with raw power and unyielding aggression. In Empyrean theology, the lion represents the ideal warrior: brave without recklessness, powerful without cruelty, dominant without tyranny. Lion imagery is ubiquitous in Mithrian Military heraldry, and the lion&#39;s roar is invoked in battle cries across the Empire&#39;s legions. Spheres of Influence Discipline Discipline is the foundation upon which all of Hector&#39;s other virtues are built. The Bronze Lord teaches that martial prowess without discipline is mere savagery, and justice without discipline is mere vengeance. Discipline is the daily practice of training the body and mind to respond correctly under the most extreme pressure — to hold formation when every instinct screams retreat, to show mercy when rage demands blood, to maintain honor when dishonor would be easier and more expedient. Hector&#39;s discipline is not the cold, mechanical obedience of a mindless automaton but the hard-won self-mastery of a warrior who has chosen to subordinate personal desire to the demands of duty and justice. Martial Prowess Martial prowess is the practical application of discipline — the ability to fight effectively, to defend the innocent, and to defeat the enemies of order and light. Hector does not glorify violence for its own sake; he teaches that martial skill is a sacred trust, a talent cultivated through years of training and sacrifice that must be employed only in service of righteous cause. The Bronze Lord demands excellence from his followers — not merely adequate competence but relentless pursuit of mastery. A warrior who stops training has betrayed the trust placed in him. Justice Justice is the moral compass that directs Hector&#39;s martial virtues toward righteous ends. Without justice, discipline becomes oppression and martial prowess becomes tyranny. The Bronze Lord teaches that the warrior&#39;s ultimate purpose is not victory but justice — that the sword exists to protect the innocent, punish the wicked, and maintain the order established by Seros and codified in the Measure and the Scale . Hector&#39;s justice is direct and uncompromising: guilt is punished, innocence is defended, and the strong are held to a higher standard than the weak. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Hector is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Hector is the patron saint of soldiers, knights, guards, and all who bear arms in defense of the innocent. His feast day is marked by martial tournaments, weapons inspections, and the swearing of oaths of service. Devotion to Saint Hector is the most widespread of all the Empyrean saints within the Mithrian Military . Every barracks has a shrine to the Bronze Lord, every regiment carries his crossed swords alongside the Winged Sun of Seros , and every recruit is taught that martial prowess without honor is an abomination. The military courts of the Empire invoke Saint Hector&#39;s name when passing judgment on soldiers accused of dishonorable conduct, and his crossed swords are displayed prominently in every court-martial chamber. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros Damocles Andraste The Measure and the Scale Mithrian Military Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"iskara","title":"Iskara, the Mother of Monsters","category":"faiths","tags":"iskara cthonic deity mother-of-monsters demon-queen chaos darkness ouroboros hydra","text":"Iskara, the Mother of Monsters Iskara is one of the seven Cthonic gods , known by the titles of the Mother of Monsters and the Demon Queen. Her spheres of divine influence encompass chaos and darkness — the primordial forces that existed before The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice imposed order upon the cosmos and that continue to press against the boundaries of reality, seeking to reclaim what was taken from them. Iskara is the goddess of things that should not be — creatures born from the corruption of natural forms, monstrosities that defy the categories and laws established by the Empyrean order, beings that exist in defiance of the cosmic design and draw their power from that very defiance. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Ouroboros Iskara&#39;s unholy symbol is the ouroboros — the serpent that devours its own tail, the ancient symbol of cyclical destruction and renewal, of entropy feeding upon itself to generate new forms of chaos. The ouroboros represents Iskara&#39;s fundamental teaching: that creation and destruction are not opposites but aspects of the same process, that the ordered cosmos is not a stable structure but a temporary arrangement constantly being consumed and reconstituted by the forces of chaos that underlie it. The serpent eating itself is simultaneously self-destruction and self-creation — the perfect emblem of Iskara&#39;s domain. The Hydra The hydra is Iskara&#39;s sacred animal — the many-headed serpent that cannot be killed through conventional means, whose severed heads regenerate and multiply. The hydra represents Iskara&#39;s central principle: that chaos is unkillable, that the forces of disorder cannot be permanently defeated because they are woven into the fabric of reality itself. Cut off one head and two grow in its place. Destroy one monstrous incursion and three more emerge from the darkness. The hydra is a theological statement about the futility of the Empyrean project — the impossible dream of permanently ordering a cosmos that is, at its foundation, chaotic. Spheres of Influence Chaos Chaos is Iskara&#39;s primary domain — not the colloquial chaos of mere disorder or confusion but the metaphysical chaos that predates creation itself. In Cthonic theology, the cosmos was originally a formless void of infinite potential, and The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice imposed structure, law, and limitation upon that void. Iskara represents the void&#39;s refusal to be fully tamed — the persistent pressure of infinite possibility against the finite structures of ordered reality. Her followers believe that the order imposed by the Aurelion is a cage, that the laws of nature are chains, and that true liberation lies in the dissolution of all structure and the return to the primordial chaos from which all things arose. Darkness Darkness, in Iskara&#39;s teaching, is not merely the absence of light but a positive, active force — the original state of the cosmos before Seros separated light from dark, the womb from which all things were born and to which all things will eventually return. Iskara&#39;s darkness is creative, fertile, and dangerous — it is the space where new forms gestate, where mutations and monstrosities take shape, where the rigid categories of the Empyrean order break down and recombine into something unprecedented. The Mother of Monsters does not merely dwell in darkness; she uses it as her workshop, her laboratory, her birthing chamber. The Mother of Monsters Iskara&#39;s most feared aspect is her role as the creator and patron of monsters — beings that violate the natural order established by The Aurelion and maintained by Seros . In Cthonic theology, monsters are not errors or corruptions but deliberate creations — living arguments against the Empyrean claim that the cosmos is ordered, lawful, and good. Every chimera, every aberration, every creature that defies natural classification is a child of Iskara, a proof that chaos cannot be fully contained and that the boundaries between species, between forms, between the possible and the impossible, are more permeable than the Thousand Temples would like to admit. Iskara&#39;s cult is feared throughout the Mithrian Empire and beyond for its involvement in the creation of monstrous beings through Cthonic rituals , the breeding of unnatural creatures, and the summoning of entities from beyond The Veil . The Demon Queen&#39;s followers view these acts not as abominations but as sacred works — contributions to Iskara&#39;s ongoing project of demonstrating that order is an illusion and that the true nature of reality is chaos. See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon The Aurelion Seros The Veil Cthonic Corruption The Awakening Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"kaleth","title":"Kaleth, the Dark Watcher","category":"faiths","tags":"kaleth cthonic deity dark-watcher elder-eye madness knowledge entropy eye fungus","text":"Kaleth, the Dark Watcher Kaleth is one of the seven Cthonic gods , known by the titles of the Dark Watcher and the Elder Eye. His spheres of divine influence encompass madness, knowledge, and entropy — a triad that reflects the Cthonic teaching that ultimate knowledge is inseparable from the dissolution of the mind that contains it. Kaleth is the god of the truth that destroys the knower, the revelation that shatters sanity, the understanding so complete and so terrible that the mind cannot contain it and breaks apart under its weight. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Eye Kaleth&#39;s unholy symbol is a single eye — open, unblinking, staring without context or expression. The eye has no face around it, no lid to close, no tears to shed. It simply watches. It sees everything. And in the act of seeing, it unmakes what it observes. The eye represents Kaleth&#39;s central teaching: that observation is not passive but active, that to truly see something is to change it, and that the ultimate act of seeing — the comprehension of the totality of reality — would destroy reality itself. The eye is both a warning and a promise: a warning to those who seek knowledge without understanding the price, and a promise to those who are willing to pay it. Fungus Kaleth&#39;s sacred organism is not an animal but a fungus — the vast, patient, decentralized networks of mycelium that grow through darkness, decompose the dead, and break down the structures of the living world into their constituent elements. Fungus represents Kaleth&#39;s domain of entropy in its most literal form: the slow, inexorable dissolution of organized matter into formless substrate. But fungus is also a network of information — mycorrhizal webs that connect trees across forests, transmitting chemical signals and nutrients through underground channels invisible to the naked eye. In Cthonic theology, the fungal network is a metaphor for Kaleth&#39;s own consciousness: vast, decentralized, patient, and present everywhere that decay occurs. Spheres of Influence Madness Madness, in Kaleth&#39;s teaching, is not a disease but a state of perception — the condition that results when a finite mind encounters infinite truth. The Dark Watcher teaches that sanity is a defense mechanism, a set of cognitive walls that the mind erects to protect itself from the unbearable totality of reality. These walls are necessary for survival, but they are also limitations — they prevent the mind from perceiving the true nature of the cosmos, which is vastly more complex, more terrifying, and more beautiful than any sane mind can comprehend. Kaleth&#39;s madness is the demolition of those walls, the flooding of consciousness with raw, unfiltered reality. It is simultaneously destruction and enlightenment. Knowledge Knowledge is the substance that drives the mind to madness — the actual content of the revelations that Kaleth offers to those who seek him out. Kaleth&#39;s knowledge is not the practical wisdom of Eramus or the prophetic vision of Enador but something far more fundamental: knowledge of the underlying structure of reality, of the hidden mathematics that govern the cosmos, of the true nature of The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice and what it actually created. This knowledge is related to, but distinct from, the formulae of Gnostic Geometry — where gnostic geometers work with carefully controlled portions of metaphysical truth, Kaleth offers the whole, unmediated, and uncontrolled. Entropy Entropy is the physical manifestation of Kaleth&#39;s domain — the universal tendency toward disorder, dissolution, and the breakdown of organized structures. In Cthonic theology, entropy is not a flaw in the cosmos but its fundamental nature — the truth that the Empyrean Faith refuses to acknowledge, the reality that all order is temporary, all structures are provisional, and all things will eventually return to the formless potential from which they arose. Kaleth does not cause entropy; he embodies the awareness of it. He is the god who watches everything fall apart and who understands, with perfect clarity, why it must. Cult Activities Kaleth&#39;s cults are among the most intellectually dangerous religious organizations in the known world. Unlike the blood-soaked rites of Bel or the necromantic horrors of Dirgion , Kaleth&#39;s worship often begins with genuine scholarly inquiry — the desire to understand the nature of reality more deeply than the Thousand Temples or the Imperial Academy permit. Seekers who push too far into forbidden knowledge, who question the comfortable certainties of Empyrean theology, who look too deeply into The Veil and the entities beyond it — these are the souls most vulnerable to Kaleth&#39;s call. The result is a cult composed not of thugs and madmen but of scholars, mages, and seekers who have been broken by what they learned. Kaleth&#39;s followers often retain extraordinary intellectual capabilities even as their sanity erodes — they can perceive patterns invisible to others, solve problems that baffle conventional minds, and access knowledge that no living being should possess. But this capability comes at a terrible price: the progressive dissolution of identity, empathy, and connection to the human world. The most advanced of Kaleth&#39;s followers become something barely recognizable as human — vessels of knowledge without the emotional or moral framework to use it responsibly. See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon The Aurelion The Veil Gnostic Geometry Cthonic Corruption Imperial Academy Eramus Enador"},{"slug":"mina","title":"Mina, the Hand","category":"faiths","tags":"mina empyrean deity saint the-hand grace art beauty swan chisel","text":"Mina, the Hand Mina is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title of the Hand. Her spheres of divine influence encompass grace, art, and beauty — the creative virtues through which the divine order is made manifest in the material world. Mina teaches that beauty is not frivolity but a fundamental expression of cosmic truth, that the impulse to create is a reflection of The Aurelion &#39;s original act of creation, and that the artist who shapes stone, paint, music, or word into something beautiful participates in the ongoing work of bringing order and meaning to an imperfect world. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Chisel Mina&#39;s holy symbol is a chisel — the sculptor&#39;s fundamental tool, the instrument by which raw stone is transformed into art. The chisel represents the principle that beauty does not emerge from nothing but is carved from the rough material of the world through skill, patience, and vision. Every block of stone contains a statue; it requires the Hand to reveal it. The chisel also carries a subtle theological message: creation requires destruction. To sculpt is to remove, to cut away, to sacrifice the superfluous in service of the essential. Mina&#39;s art is not additive but reductive — the pursuit of the truth that lies hidden within. The Swan The swan is Mina&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its extraordinary grace and beauty. The swan moves through water with effortless elegance, its visible serenity concealing the ceaseless, powerful motion beneath the surface. In Empyrean theology, the swan represents the ideal of art — the appearance of effortless beauty that in reality demands enormous discipline, training, and labor. The swan also symbolizes transformation: the ugly duckling that becomes the most beautiful of birds, mirroring the artist&#39;s capacity to transform base materials into transcendent works. Spheres of Influence Grace Grace, in Mina&#39;s teaching, is the quality of moving through the world with awareness, intention, and beauty. It is not mere physical elegance but a spiritual discipline — the practice of bringing conscious attention and aesthetic sensibility to every action, every word, every gesture. The Hand teaches that grace is available to all, not merely to the talented or the privileged, and that the farmer who plows a straight furrow, the mason who lays a true wall, and the mother who braids her daughter&#39;s hair all participate in the same divine impulse toward beauty and order. Art Art is the highest expression of Mina&#39;s teaching — the creation of works that embody divine truth in material form. The Hand does not distinguish between high art and craft, between the sculptor&#39;s marble masterpiece and the potter&#39;s functional bowl. All creation undertaken with skill, care, and devotion to beauty is sacred. Mina teaches that the cosmos itself is the ultimate work of art — The Aurelion &#39;s masterpiece, the original creative act from which all subsequent creation flows — and that every artist, in however small a way, continues the work that the Aurelion began. Beauty Beauty, for Mina, is not subjective preference but objective reality — a fundamental property of the cosmos as real and measurable as mass or distance. The Empyrean cosmology holds that beauty is the visible manifestation of divine order, the sensory evidence that the cosmos is structured, meaningful, and purposeful. Ugliness, decay, and entropy are the marks of Cthonic influence — the corruption of form and meaning that the forces of darkness spread wherever they gain purchase. To create beauty is therefore an act of spiritual warfare, a direct challenge to the entropic forces that seek to unmake the world. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Mina is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a goddess in her own right. Saint Mina is the patron saint of artists, sculptors, architects, musicians, poets, and all who create beauty through skilled labor. Her feast day is celebrated with exhibitions of art, musical performances, and the dedication of new public works. Devotion to Saint Mina is particularly strong among the artisan guilds of Mithra City and other major urban centers of the Mithrian Empire . Guild halls are decorated with her chisel emblem, and apprentices traditionally offer prayers to the Hand before beginning their first major work. Architects invoke her blessing before laying foundation stones, and it is considered deeply inauspicious to begin construction on a significant building without first dedicating the work to Saint Mina&#39;s grace. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros The Aurelion The Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples Mithra City"},{"slug":"nasga","title":"Nasga, Mistress of Pain and Pleasure","category":"faiths","tags":"nasga cthonic deity mistress-of-pain pleasure beauty pain lust snake rose andraste","text":"Nasga, Mistress of Pain and Pleasure Nasga is one of the seven Cthonic gods , known as the Mistress of Pain and Pleasure. Her spheres of divine influence encompass beauty, pain, and lust — the domains of sensation, desire, and the body&#39;s capacity for both ecstasy and agony. Nasga teaches that the body is the only truth, that sensation is the only knowledge worth possessing, and that the ultimate expression of power is the ability to control what others feel — to be the source of their pleasure and the author of their pain. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Rose Nasga&#39;s unholy symbol is a single rose — beautiful, fragrant, and armed with thorns that draw blood from the hand that reaches for it. The rose represents the inseparability of beauty and pain in Nasga&#39;s theology: the flower cannot be possessed without the wound, the pleasure cannot be enjoyed without the price. The rose is a trap — it lures with beauty and punishes with pain, and Nasga&#39;s followers believe this is the fundamental mechanism of the cosmos itself. Every pleasure carries a hidden thorn; every beauty conceals a blade. Those who understand this truth control the transaction. Those who do not are its victims. The Snake The snake is Nasga&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its sinuous beauty, its venomous bite, and its ancient association with temptation, sensuality, and forbidden knowledge. The snake moves with a grace that is both mesmerizing and threatening, its beauty and its danger coexisting in a single, fluid form. In Cthonic theology, the snake represents the principle that attraction and danger are the same force — that the most beautiful things are the most dangerous, and that the impulse to reach for beauty despite knowing the danger is the most powerful drive in mortal nature. Spheres of Influence Beauty Beauty, in Nasga&#39;s teaching, is not the wholesome, virtue-aligned beauty celebrated by Mina in the Empyrean Pantheon but a weaponized force — the capacity to compel desire, to override rational judgment, and to draw the observer into a transaction they do not fully understand. Nasga&#39;s beauty is the beauty of the lure, the bait, the trap that is irresistible precisely because it is beautiful. Her followers cultivate physical beauty with obsessive dedication, not as an expression of divine order but as an instrument of power and control. Pain Pain is the other face of Nasga&#39;s domain — the counterweight to beauty and pleasure, the thorn on the rose. The Mistress teaches that pain is not merely suffering but information — the most honest, most immediate, most undeniable form of communication between one being and another. Pain cannot be ignored, cannot be misinterpreted, cannot be denied. It cuts through all pretense, all social convention, all the elaborate fictions that civilized beings construct to protect themselves from reality. Nasga&#39;s followers study pain with the same devotion that scholars bring to books — learning to inflict it with precision, to modulate it with artistry, and to use it as a tool of domination and transformation. Lust Lust is desire stripped of sentiment — the raw, consuming hunger for another person&#39;s body, attention, or submission. Nasga teaches that lust is the most fundamental drive in mortal nature, more powerful than fear, more persistent than ambition, more honest than love. Her followers do not merely indulge lust but weaponize it, using desire as a mechanism of control — both their own desire, which they learn to master and direct with ruthless discipline, and the desire of others, which they learn to provoke, manipulate, and exploit. Cthonic Mirror of Andraste Nasga is the Cthonic mirror of Andraste , the Holy Dancer. Both deities operate within the domain of the body&#39;s experience — sensation, physicality, the raw immediacy of flesh and nerve. Where Andraste teaches that bodily experience is sanctified through compassion, strength, and joy, Nasga teaches that the body is an instrument of desire and domination, that pain and pleasure are the only truths that matter, and that the strongest are those who can both inflict and endure the most extreme sensations. The mirror between Andraste and Nasga illuminates the Empyrean-Cthonic theology&#39;s understanding of physicality. The body is the same — the nerve endings, the muscles, the capacity for sensation — but the meaning assigned to bodily experience is diametrically opposed. Andraste sanctifies the body through compassion; Nasga weaponizes it through desire. The same dance that Andraste performs as worship, Nasga performs as seduction. The same strength that Andraste directs toward protection, Nasga directs toward domination. See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon Andraste Mina Cthonic Corruption The Awakening Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"ravanor","title":"Ravanor, the Bitter Prince","category":"faiths","tags":"ravanor cthonic deity bitter-prince horned-one rulership power tyranny stag antlered-crown sagramore","text":"Ravanor, the Bitter Prince Ravanor is one of the seven Cthonic gods , known by the titles of the Bitter Prince and the Horned One. His spheres of divine influence encompass rulership, power, and tyranny — the domains of political authority exercised without moral constraint, of dominion pursued as an end in itself, of the will to rule elevated to the status of a divine imperative. Ravanor is the god of kings who answer to no one, of lords who rule through fear rather than consent, of every form of authority that exists to serve the ruler rather than the ruled. Symbol and Sacred Animal The Antlered Crown Ravanor&#39;s unholy symbol is an antlered crown — a circlet of royal authority surmounted not by jewels or crosses but by the branching antlers of a great stag. The antlered crown combines the imagery of civilized authority (the crown) with the imagery of primal, natural dominance (the antlers of the stag in rut, which fights other males for supremacy through raw physical contest). The symbol represents Ravanor&#39;s teaching that all political authority, no matter how elaborately dressed in law and custom, ultimately rests on the same foundation as the stag&#39;s dominance over its herd: the willingness and ability to destroy rivals through superior force. The Stag The stag is Ravanor&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for the yearly contest of rut in which males fight for dominance, the right to mate, and supremacy over the herd. The stag&#39;s antlers — which grow, are used in combat, and are shed only to regrow larger the following year — represent the cyclical nature of power: the constant contest, the inevitable challenge, the perpetual need to defend one&#39;s position against rivals. In Cthonic theology, the stag represents the principle that power must be constantly fought for and defended, that authority unchallenged becomes weak, and that the true ruler is the one who can defeat all challengers and maintain supremacy through force of will. Spheres of Influence Rulership Rulership, in Ravanor&#39;s teaching, is the natural right of the strong — not a sacred trust conferred by the gods (as the Empyrean Faith teaches) but a prize seized by those with the power and will to take it. The Bitter Prince rejects the Empyrean concept of legitimate authority — the idea that rulers govern by divine mandate, that their authority is conditional upon the faithful discharge of duty, and that the ruled have a right to just governance. In Ravanor&#39;s theology, the only legitimate authority is the authority of the strongest, and the only check on a ruler&#39;s power is the emergence of someone stronger. Power Power is the substance of Ravanor&#39;s domain — the raw capacity to impose one&#39;s will upon others, to shape the world according to one&#39;s desires, to stand above the mass of ordinary beings and direct their lives according to one&#39;s own vision. The Horned One teaches that power is not a means to an end but the end itself — that the accumulation and exercise of power is the highest possible achievement of the mortal soul, and that those who possess power are under no obligation to use it for any purpose other than the maintenance and expansion of their own dominion. Tyranny Tyranny is power freed from moral constraint — rulership without accountability, authority without obligation, dominion without limit. In the Empyrean understanding, tyranny is the corruption of legitimate authority, the perversion of the sacred trust of governance. In Ravanor&#39;s teaching, tyranny is authority in its purest form — the state in which the ruler&#39;s will is unimpeded by law, custom, conscience, or the competing claims of the governed. The Bitter Prince does not merely permit tyranny; he demands it, teaching that a ruler who submits to moral constraint has voluntarily surrendered the power that makes him a ruler in the first place. Cthonic Mirror of Sagramore Ravanor is the Cthonic mirror of Sagramore , the Martyr. Both deities preside over the relationship between individual will and power structures, but they represent diametrically opposed understandings of that relationship. Sagramore teaches that the individual finds meaning and transcendence through willing sacrifice to a just cause — that power is legitimized by the willingness to spend it in service of others. Ravanor teaches that the individual finds meaning through the accumulation and exercise of power — that rulership is its own justification and that those strong enough to seize power have earned the right to wield it without limit. The mirror between Sagramore and Ravanor asks the most fundamental political question in the Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology: does the ruler exist to serve the people, or do the people exist to serve the ruler? Sagramore answers with sacrifice — the leader who gives his life for his followers. Ravanor answers with dominion — the ruler who takes from his subjects whatever he has the power to take. The history of the Mithrian Empire — and indeed of all civilizations in the known world — can be read as the ongoing contest between these two answers. See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon Sagramore Seros Bel The Measure and the Scale Cthonic Corruption Thousand Temples Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"sagramore","title":"Sagramore, the Martyr","category":"faiths","tags":"sagramore empyrean deity saint martyr loyalty endurance sacrifice ox broken-manacles ravanor","text":"Sagramore, the Martyr Sagramore is one of the nine Empyrean gods , known by the title of the Martyr. His spheres of divine influence encompass loyalty, endurance, and sacrifice — the virtues of those who give themselves wholly to a cause greater than their own survival. Sagramore is the god of the last stand, the broken shield, the soldier who holds the pass so others may escape. He teaches that the highest expression of the soul is not triumph but willing sacrifice — the decision to spend one&#39;s own life in service of something worth more than any individual existence. Symbol and Sacred Animal Broken Manacles Sagramore&#39;s holy symbol is a pair of broken manacles — shattered chains that once bound wrists or ankles. The symbol operates on multiple levels. At its most literal, the broken manacles represent liberation through sacrifice — the idea that Sagramore&#39;s willing death shattered the chains of oppression, ignorance, or spiritual bondage that held others captive. More theologically, the broken manacles signify the ultimate freedom that comes through perfect sacrifice: the soul that gives itself entirely is no longer bound by fear, desire, or self-interest and achieves a liberation more complete than any earthly freedom. The Ox The ox is Sagramore&#39;s sacred animal, chosen for its extraordinary endurance, its capacity for sustained labor, and its willingness to bear burdens without complaint. The ox does not seek glory or recognition; it pulls the plow, carries the load, endures the yoke, and serves until its strength is spent. In Empyrean theology, the ox represents the ideal of selfless endurance — the virtue of continuing to serve when the work is thankless, the burden is crushing, and the end is nowhere in sight. The ox also represents the quiet, uncelebrated strength that makes civilization possible — the understanding that the world is held together not by heroes but by those who endure. Spheres of Influence Loyalty Loyalty, in Sagramore&#39;s teaching, is the commitment to a cause, a person, or a principle that transcends self-interest. It is not blind obedience — the Cthonic god Ravanor demands that — but a conscious, freely chosen dedication that persists even when loyalty becomes costly. The Martyr teaches that loyalty must be earned and freely given, that it flows upward from love and respect rather than downward from fear and compulsion. True loyalty is tested not in times of prosperity but in times of crisis, when the loyal servant must choose between their own safety and their sworn duty. Endurance Endurance is the capacity to sustain loyalty and sacrifice over time — to continue bearing the burden when the body fails and the spirit falters. Sagramore&#39;s endurance is not stoic indifference to suffering but the active, conscious decision to keep going despite suffering. The Martyr does not teach his followers to deny their pain but to acknowledge it and choose to endure it anyway, because the cause they serve is worth the price they pay. This teaching resonates powerfully with the common people of the Mithrian Empire — farmers, laborers, soldiers, and servants whose lives are defined by endurance. Sacrifice Sacrifice is the culmination of loyalty and endurance — the moment when the faithful give not merely their effort or their comfort but their lives in service of the greater good. Sagramore teaches that sacrifice is the highest act of which a mortal soul is capable, the closest a living being can come to replicating The Aurelion &#39;s original sacrifice that created the cosmos. This does not mean that Sagramore demands death from his followers — rather, he teaches that the willingness to sacrifice, the readiness to give everything, is itself a form of spiritual perfection that transforms even the most ordinary life into something sacred. Cthonic Mirror: Ravanor Sagramore&#39;s Cthonic counterpart is Ravanor , the Bitter Prince, the Horned One. Both deities preside over the relationship between individual will and power structures, but from diametrically opposed perspectives. Sagramore teaches that the individual finds meaning and transcendence through willing sacrifice to a just cause — that power is legitimized by the willingness to spend it in service of others. Ravanor teaches that the individual finds meaning through the accumulation and exercise of power — that rulership is its own justification and that those strong enough to seize power have earned the right to wield it without limit. The mirror between Sagramore and Ravanor illuminates one of the deepest tensions in the Empyrean-Cthonic cosmology: the question of whether power exists to serve or to rule. Sagramore answers that power exists to serve, even unto death. Ravanor answers that power exists to dominate, and that those who sacrifice themselves are fools who deserve their fate. Current Veneration Like all members of the Empyrean Pantheon save Seros , Sagramore is now venerated as a Saint rather than worshipped as a god in his own right. Saint Sagramore is the patron saint of martyrs, prisoners, slaves, and all who suffer unjustly. His feast day is marked by solemn remembrance of those who gave their lives in service of the Empire, the faith, or the innocent. Devotion to Saint Sagramore is particularly strong among the lower classes of the Mithrian Empire and among soldiers who have seen heavy combat. His broken manacles are a symbol of hope for the oppressed and a reminder to the powerful that their authority is legitimized only by their willingness to sacrifice for those they lead. Condemned prisoners are offered a final prayer to Saint Sagramore before execution, and his image is carved into the walls of dungeons and prison cells throughout the Empire. See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros Ravanor The Aurelion The Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"seros","title":"Seros, the Winged Sun","category":"faiths","tags":"seros empyrean deity winged-sun unconquered-sun silent-one saints thousand-temples flame shroud","text":"Seros, the Winged Sun As the flame gives light, so too does it burn. Thus is the soul weighed beneath the eyes of Seros, the Winged Sun, who watches all with measure unerring. — Anton, High Priest of the Thousand Temples Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end. — The Prophet Enador to the Sorcerer King Sebek Seros is the principal deity of the Empyrean Faith , the supreme god of light, judgment, and cosmic order, and the single most important religious figure in the Mithrian Empire . Known by many titles — the Winged Sun, the Unconquered Sun, the Silent One — Seros is the divine force that separated light from darkness in the wake of the Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice, the judge who weighs every soul upon death, and the eternal adversary of the Cthonic powers that seek to drag the cosmos back into primordial entropy. His worship is the state religion of the Mithrian Empire, administered by the Thousand Temples , and his name is invoked in every courtroom, on every battlefield, and at every hearth where the Empyrean faithful gather. Titles and Epithets The Silent One Seros is called the Silent One because he does not speak — he acts. This is not a deficiency but a theological statement of the highest order. In Empyrean theology, Seros does not issue commandments from on high, does not whisper prophecies into the ears of priests, does not engage in the kind of direct divine communication that characterizes the relationship between mortal worshippers and many other deities across the known world. His light reveals truth without commentary. The sun does not explain the shadows it casts; it simply illuminates, and the truth becomes self-evident to those with eyes to see. This silence is both a comfort and a challenge to the faithful. It means that Seros&#39;s will must be discerned through contemplation, through the study of The Measure and the Scale , through the cultivation of inner virtue rather than the reception of external revelation. The silence of Seros places the burden of moral reasoning squarely upon the shoulders of the faithful — they cannot wait for divine instruction but must actively seek the light through their own effort and devotion. The Unconquered Sun The title of the Unconquered Sun reflects both Seros&#39;s cosmic role as the bringer of light and his theological position as the force that cannot be overcome by darkness, entropy, or the Cthonic powers. The sun rises every morning. The light returns after every night. No matter how deep the darkness, no matter how long the shadow, the Unconquered Sun endures and prevails. This title is a statement of absolute theological confidence — a declaration that the forces of order and light are not merely equal to the forces of darkness but ultimately, inevitably, irresistibly superior to them. For the soldiers of the Mithrian Military , the title carries an additional, more martial significance. The Unconquered Sun is the patron of victory, the divine guarantor that righteous force will triumph over wickedness. The Imperial legions march under the banner of the Winged Sun, and their battle hymns invoke Seros as the unconquerable force that guides their blades and shields their hearts. The Winged Sun The most common iconographic representation of Seros — a radiant sun with outstretched wings — is both his most recognizable symbol and his most frequently used title. The wings signify his role as a psychopomp, a guide of souls: it is Seros who carries the souls of the dead from the material world to the afterlife, Seros who bears them aloft on wings of light to face their judgment. The sun represents his nature as the source of illumination, warmth, and life. Together, the winged sun is a comprehensive symbol of Seros&#39;s dual role as sustainer of the living and judge of the dead. The Measure and the Scale: Seros as Judge At the heart of Seros&#39;s theological function is his role as the divine judge of souls. When a living being dies, it is Seros who measures each soul and sets it upon the Scale. The Measure is the standard against which the soul is assessed — the codified virtues and laws of the Empyrean faith. The Scale is the instrument of judgment — the cosmic balance upon which the soul&#39;s worth is weighed against the totality of its earthly deeds. This is not a process of arbitrary divine whim. Seros judges according to fixed and knowable principles — the seven virtues of the Scale, which are documented, studied, debated, and taught throughout the Mithrian Empire . The faithful know the standard by which they will be judged, and they are expected to spend their lives striving to meet it. In this sense, Seros&#39;s judgment is the most transparent form of divine justice imaginable: the rules are written, the standard is public, and the judge is incorruptible. Souls that meet the standard enter the Halls of Seros , where they rest in peace and radiance, awaiting the ultimate reunification with the Aurelion . Souls that fall short are returned to the cycle of reincarnation, given another chance to refine their virtue and try again. The Supplanting of the Empyrean Pantheon One of the most significant theological developments in the history of the Mithrian Empire has been the gradual, nearly complete supplanting of the broader Empyrean pantheon by the singular worship of Seros. In the early centuries of the faith, the Empyrean tradition encompassed a full pantheon of gods — deities of war, wisdom, mercy, craft, nature, and countless other domains. These gods were worshipped alongside Seros, each with their own rites, their own priests, their own sacred traditions. Over time, as the Mithrian Empire consolidated its power and the Thousand Temples codified Empyrean worship into a more unified institutional framework, the worship of the other Empyrean gods faded. The Mithrians supplanted most Empyrean myth with Seros. The other gods were not formally repudiated or declared false — they were simply eclipsed. Forgotten. Allowed to slip from living worship into the pages of ancient texts and the debate halls of the Academy , where they are discussed as subjects of historical curiosity and theological speculation rather than objects of active devotion. This process was not entirely organic. The centralization of religious authority in the Thousand Temples , the political utility of a single state deity, and the sheer gravitational pull of Seros&#39;s theological importance all contributed to the eclipse of the broader pantheon. Some scholars at the Academy have argued that the loss of the other Empyrean gods represents a genuine impoverishment of the faith, a narrowing of spiritual vision that has left the Mithrian people less spiritually resilient than their ancestors. These arguments, needless to say, are not popular with the Thousand Temples. The Exception: Shroud The one significant exception to the total dominance of Seros worship within the Mithrian Empire is the continued veneration of the Empyrean god Shroud among the Mithrian Military , particularly the Mithrian Marines . Shroud is a deity of shadows, of stealth, of the grim and necessary work that must be done in darkness so that the light may prevail. His worship persists in military culture because soldiers understand, in a way that civilians and priests often do not, that the defense of civilization sometimes requires acts that the comfortable virtues of the Scale cannot easily encompass. The Thousand Temples tolerates the worship of Shroud within the military without formally endorsing it — a pragmatic accommodation that reflects the Empire&#39;s recognition that the men and women who fight and die in its name deserve some latitude in their spiritual practices. Shroud&#39;s priests, such as they exist, operate largely within military structures rather than civilian temples. The Saints: A New Pantheon In the vacuum left by the eclipse of the Empyrean pantheon, a new form of veneration has arisen: the cult of the Saints . Saints are mortal individuals, posthumously anointed by the Thousand Temples , who in life exhibited the seven virtues of The Measure and the Scale to an extraordinary and exemplary degree. They are not gods in the Empyrean theological sense — they are human souls who passed through the judgment of Seros with such radiant virtue that they were elevated to a special status in the Halls of Seros, from which they can intercede on behalf of the living. In practice, however, the Saints have become minor gods to the Serosian faithful. Their names are invoked in prayer. Their relics are venerated. Their feast days are celebrated with processions, liturgies, and acts of devotion. Specific Saints are associated with specific domains — a Saint of healers, a Saint of soldiers, a Saint of sailors, a Saint of the poor — in a pattern that closely mirrors the diversified worship of the old Empyrean pantheon. Whether this represents a healthy evolution of the faith or a tacit admission that the singular worship of Seros is insufficient to meet the spiritual needs of a diverse civilization is a subject of lively debate at the Academy . The Anointing of Saints The process by which a Saint is anointed is controlled exclusively by the Thousand Temples . A candidate for Sainthood must be deceased — the faith is firm on this point, though a few Emperors throughout history have pressured High Priests to declare living Saints, with varying degrees of success and controversy. The candidate&#39;s life is examined in exhaustive detail, and they must be found to have exhibited all seven virtues of the Scale in exemplary fashion. The process can take years or even decades, and the theological and political debates surrounding individual candidates are often intense. Several militant orders have been founded in the names of particular Saints — orders of knights, warrior-priests, and holy soldiers who dedicate themselves to embodying the specific virtues that their patron Saint exemplified. These orders represent some of the most formidable military forces in the Empire, motivated not merely by duty or pay but by a fierce and burning devotion to a spiritual ideal. Seros and the Flame The Flame — the priestly magic of the Empyrean Faith — is intimately connected to the worship of Seros. The Flame is understood as a direct emanation of Seros&#39;s divine light, channeled through the virtue and spiritual purity of the faithful. To call upon the Flame is not to cast a spell but to open oneself as a vessel for the light of the Unconquered Sun, to become a conduit through which Seros&#39;s power flows into the material world. Seros&#39;s faithful who channel the Flame do so not through study or technique but through the quality of their devotion and the depth of their virtue. A priest who genuinely walks the path of The Measure and the Scale , who embodies the seven virtues not merely in word but in the marrow of their being, may find the Flame answering their call — a warm, golden light that heals, protects, purifies, and, when necessary, destroys. Those who merely perform the outward forms of devotion without inner transformation find only silence. This connection between virtue and power is one of the most theologically significant aspects of Seros worship. It means that the Flame is, in essence, a form of divine validation — proof that the wielder has been found worthy in the eyes of the Unconquered Sun. When a priest of Seros manifests the Flame on the battlefield or in the temple, it is understood not merely as a display of magical power but as a visible, tangible expression of Seros&#39;s judgment: this soul burns brightly enough to carry my light. See Also Empyrean Faith The Measure and the Scale Aurelion Enador Thousand Temples Saints The Flame Shroud Cthonic Faith Mithrian Empire Mithrian Military Mithrian Marines Academy Magic and Sorcery"},{"slug":"shroud","title":"Shroud, God of Crossing and Passage","category":"faiths","tags":"shroud empyrean deity crossing passage death marines mithrian-military thousand-temples","text":"Shroud, God of Crossing and Passage Shroud is one of the Empyrean gods , the deity of crossing and passage — the divine power who presides over thresholds, transitions, and the boundary between the living world and whatever lies beyond. Where Seros judges the dead and weighs their souls against the Measure and the Scale , Shroud is the god who carries them across — the psychopomp, the ferryman, the guide who walks beside the dying in their final moments and leads them through the passage from mortal existence to the afterlife. Shroud occupies a unique position in the modern Empyrean Faith . Unlike the other Empyrean gods who have been fully subsumed into the cult of Seros and reinterpreted as Saints, Shroud retains an active, devoted following — particularly among the Mithrian Military , and most especially among the Imperial Marines. The Thousand Temples tolerate this practice, though it exists in an acknowledged tension with the theological orthodoxy that holds Seros as the singular, supreme deity. Spheres of Influence Crossing Crossing is the moment of transition — the liminal instant between one state and another. Shroud presides over all crossings: birth, death, the passage from childhood to adulthood, the departure from home, the crossing of thresholds both literal and metaphorical. His domain is the space between — the doorway, the bridge, the ford, the passage through the mountains — and his followers invoke him whenever they stand at the boundary between the known and the unknown. Passage Passage is crossing extended through time — the journey from one state to another that is not instantaneous but sustained. Shroud is the companion of those who travel through darkness, through danger, through the long and uncertain road between departure and arrival. He is invoked by soldiers before battle (the passage from peace to war), by sailors before voyages (the passage across uncertain waters), and by the dying in their final hours (the passage from life to whatever comes after). Worship Among the Mithrian Marines Shroud&#39;s most devoted followers are found among the Mithrian Marines — the elite amphibious and expeditionary forces of the Mithrian Empire . Marines face death more frequently and more intimately than most soldiers, operating in small units far from reinforcement, conducting landings on hostile shores, and fighting in the chaotic, close-quarters environments where the line between the living and the dead is thinnest. For the Marines, Shroud is not an abstract theological concept but a practical, immediate spiritual necessity. They pray to Shroud before every operation — not for victory (that belongs to Seros and Damocles ) or for courage (that belongs to Bellasarius and Hector ) but for safe passage. They ask Shroud to guide them across the threshold of battle and, if they fall, to carry them safely to the judgment of Seros . The Marine prayer to Shroud — whispered on beaches before dawn assaults, in landing craft approaching hostile shores, in the silence before the order to advance — is one of the most intimate expressions of faith in the entire Empyrean tradition. Shroud&#39;s presence in Marine culture extends beyond prayer. Marine units carry small shroud-tokens — strips of dark cloth blessed by chaplains — which are placed over the eyes of fallen comrades as a symbolic gesture of commending the dead to Shroud&#39;s care. Marine chaplains perform crossing rites before every major operation, invoking Shroud&#39;s protection for the passage ahead. When a Marine dies in the field, the words spoken over the body invoke Shroud by name, not merely as a saint but with the respect and urgency due to a god. Tension with Seros&#39;s Supremacy The active worship of Shroud exists in a state of acknowledged theological tension with the orthodox position of the Thousand Temples , which holds that Seros is the singular supreme deity and that all other Empyrean gods are properly understood as Saints — mortal exemplars of divine virtue who achieved transcendence, not independent divine beings worthy of worship in their own right. Shroud&#39;s case is complicated by several factors. First, the theological function he serves — guide of the dead, companion of the dying — is not easily subsumed into Seros&#39;s portfolio. Seros judges the dead; Shroud carries them. These are distinct roles, and collapsing them into one deity creates theological awkwardness that even orthodox scholars acknowledge. Second, Shroud&#39;s following among the Marines is ancient, deeply embedded in military culture, and practically useful — Marine morale and unit cohesion are measurably enhanced by the crossing rites, and the Thousand Temples are pragmatic enough to recognize the value of this. The result is an uneasy accommodation. The Thousand Temples do not formally endorse Shroud worship, but they do not actively suppress it. Marine chaplains are permitted to invoke Shroud by name in crossing rites, and Shroud-tokens are tolerated as legitimate devotional objects. The theological compromise holds that Shroud, even if properly understood as a Saint, serves a legitimate devotional function that complements rather than competes with the worship of Seros . This makes Shroud the only Empyrean god besides Seros with active, organized worship in the current era — a distinction that sets him apart from all the other members of the Empyrean Pantheon . See Also Empyrean Faith Empyrean Pantheon Seros Mithrian Military Thousand Temples The Measure and the Scale The Veil"},{"slug":"the-measure-and-the-scale","title":"The Measure and the Scale","category":"faiths","tags":"measure scale law virtues empyrean theology philosophy enador patronage justice sainthood flame","text":"The Measure and the Scale Know this: mercy guides the hand of Seros, but mercy has its end. — The Prophet Enador to the Sorcerer King Sebek It is not enough to simply embody a virtue of the Scale. All virtues must be balanced, to achieve harmony&#39;s ultimate form: justice. — From the text of the Measure and the Scale The Measure and the Scale is the foundational sacred text of the Empyrean Faith , the bedrock of Imperial legal and philosophical tradition, and the single most influential document in the history of the known world. It is simultaneously a theological treatise, a legal code, a philosophical framework, and a guide to personal moral conduct — a text so comprehensive in its ambitions and so pervasive in its influence that virtually no aspect of Mithrian life remains untouched by its principles. Every law in the Empire traces its authority back to the Measure. Every moral judgment invokes the Scale. Every citizen, from the lowest laborer to the Emperor himself, is expected to live by its precepts and will be judged — both in life and after death — by its standard. Origins and Recovery The Measure and the Scale was not composed by any mortal hand — or so the Thousand Temples teaches. It is understood as a divinely inspired text, a record of the cosmic principles established by the Aurelion at the moment of creation and preserved through the ages for the eventual edification of the faithful. Its precise origins are lost in the murk of prehistory, but its recovery is one of the most celebrated events in Empyrean religious history. The text was rediscovered by the Prophet Enador , the towering figure whose holy war against the Massaran Empire and its Cthonic rulers would reshape the world. Enador retrieved the Measure and the Scale alongside the Anthyllium grimoire — the circumstances of this discovery are debated endlessly at the Academy , with some scholars arguing that the two texts were found together in a single cache, others insisting they were recovered from separate locations, and a minority suggesting that the Measure and the Scale was not found at all but divinely revealed to Enador in a moment of prophetic vision. Regardless of the precise circumstances, the recovery of the Measure and the Scale provided the theological and legal foundation for Enador&#39;s revolution. It gave the scattered, persecuted followers of the Empyrean Faith a unified creed, a shared code of conduct, and — critically — a divinely sanctioned legal framework that could replace the Cthonic laws of the Massaran Empire . When Enador overthrew the Sorcerer Kings and founded Mithra City , it was the Measure and the Scale that became the constitution of the new civilization. The Two Components The text is divided into two distinct but interlocking parts, each addressing a different dimension of human existence. The Measure The Measure is the external component — the codified laws and structure for civilized society. It is concerned with the ordering of communities, the regulation of commerce, the administration of justice, the duties of rulers and subjects, and the framework within which human beings live together in organized society. The Measure emphasizes three cardinal social virtues: duty , honor , and loyalty . The Measure is not merely a set of abstract principles; it is a detailed and practical legal code. It specifies the obligations of citizens to their families, their patrons, and the state. It establishes the rights and responsibilities of different social classes. It codifies the relationship between the Thousand Temples and secular authority. It outlines the procedures for judicial proceedings, the penalties for various crimes, and the principles by which disputes are to be resolved. Every judicial matter within the Mithrian Empire — from the most trivial property dispute to the most serious capital case — is ultimately adjudicated by reference to the Measure. The Scale The Scale is the internal component — the moral fiber of individuals. Where the Measure governs the external ordering of society, the Scale governs the internal ordering of the soul. It is concerned with personal virtue, spiritual development, and the cultivation of the qualities that will determine the soul&#39;s fate when it stands before Seros in the afterlife. The Scale seeks the ultimate balance and harmony between all virtues — not the maximization of any single quality but the integration of all of them into a unified, harmonious whole. The distinction between the Measure and the Scale is fundamental to Empyrean theology and legal philosophy. The Measure tells you what to do; the Scale tells you who to be. The Measure can be enforced by external authority — by courts, by soldiers, by priests. The Scale can only be cultivated from within. A person may obey every law of the Measure and still fail the Scale, because obedience without inner virtue is hollow. Conversely, a person of profound inner virtue may, in extreme circumstances, find themselves in tension with the letter of the Measure — a theological paradox that has fueled countless debates at the Academy and occasional crises within the Thousand Temples . The Seven Virtues of the Scale The Scale identifies seven virtues that together constitute the ideal of human spiritual development. These virtues are not presented as independent qualities to be pursued in isolation but as paired and balanced attributes, each tempering and completing the others. The paired structure is deliberate and theologically essential: a virtue without its counterbalance becomes a vice. 1. Justice Tempered by Wisdom Justice without wisdom is cruelty. Wisdom without justice is cowardice. The first virtue demands that the faithful pursue what is right and fair, but always through the lens of understanding, discernment, and compassion for the complexity of mortal existence. A just person who lacks wisdom will enforce the letter of the law while violating its spirit. A wise person who lacks justice will understand the world perfectly and do nothing to improve it. 2. Discipline Forged through Self-Mastery Discipline is not merely the capacity to obey orders or follow rules; it is the mastery of the self — the ability to govern one&#39;s own desires, impulses, and weaknesses. Self-mastery is the forge through which discipline is created: not the suppression of the inner life but its ordering, its harnessing, its transformation from chaotic impulse into directed purpose. A disciplined person who lacks self-mastery is merely rigid. A self-mastered person who lacks discipline has refined their nature but never directed it outward. 3. Courage Wielded in Service Courage without service is recklessness. Service without courage is timidity. The third virtue demands bravery — not the absence of fear, but the willingness to act in spite of it — but insists that bravery must always be directed toward a purpose greater than the self. The soldier who charges into battle for personal glory has courage but not service. The priest who serves the community but will not speak truth to power has service but not courage. 4. Loyalty to One&#39;s Father, in Body, Soul, and State The fourth virtue is the most socially significant and the most frequently debated. Father in this context is understood in three dimensions: the literal biological father (body), the divine father — the Aurelion and by extension Seros (soul), and the paternal authority of the state and its institutions (state). This triad of loyalties — familial, spiritual, and civic — is the foundation of Mithrian social order. The faithful owe obedience and devotion to their family, their god, and their Empire, and the proper ordering of these loyalties is one of the central challenges of Empyrean moral life. This virtue is the theological foundation of the Mithrian patronage system. The father wields tremendous power within the family, extending outward into a social order where powerful families extend patronage — protection, resources, opportunities — to lesser families and individuals in exchange for loyalty and service. The patronage system is not merely a social convention; it is a divinely ordained structure, codified in the Measure and rooted in the Scale&#39;s understanding of loyalty as a fundamental virtue. 5. Compassion Leveled by Strength Compassion without strength is weakness. Strength without compassion is tyranny. The fifth virtue demands that the faithful feel for the suffering of others and act to alleviate it — but always from a position of capability, resolve, and the willingness to make hard decisions. Compassion that cannot act is mere sentiment. Strength that does not feel is mere brutality. The ideal is a fierce and active mercy — the compassion of a healer who sets broken bones, not the compassion of a bystander who weeps at the sight of blood. 6. Truth Tempered by Grace Truth without grace is cruelty. Grace without truth is deception. The sixth virtue demands honesty — a commitment to seeing and speaking the world as it is — but insists that truth must always be delivered with care for the humanity of those who receive it. A person who speaks the truth without consideration for its impact is not virtuous but merely blunt. A person who prioritizes others&#39; feelings over honesty is not kind but merely dishonest. The ideal is a truth that illuminates without destroying, that reveals without cruelty. 7. Sacrifice Anchored by Purpose Sacrifice without purpose is waste. Purpose without sacrifice is vanity. The seventh and final virtue — which mirrors the Aurelion &#39;s own supreme act — demands that the faithful be willing to give of themselves for something greater, but insists that this giving must be directed, intentional, and meaningful. The martyr who dies for no reason has sacrificed but served no purpose. The leader who pursues grand ambitions without personal cost has purpose but makes no sacrifice. The ideal is a giving of self that creates something real, lasting, and good — the echo of the Aurelion&#39;s own sacrifice in the mortal life of every faithful soul. Harmony: The Ultimate Form It is not enough to simply embody a virtue of the Scale. All virtues must be balanced, to achieve harmony&#39;s ultimate form: justice. The seven virtues are not a checklist to be completed but a dynamic, living system of balance. The ultimate aspiration of the Scale is not the perfection of any single virtue but the achievement of harmony — the state in which all seven virtues exist in perfect equilibrium, each supporting and being supported by the others. This harmonious state is identified with justice itself — not justice in the narrow legal sense, but justice as the cosmic principle of right order, the alignment of the individual soul with the divine intention of the Aurelion . This understanding of harmony as the ultimate form of justice has profound implications for Empyrean theology and practice. It means that a person who excels in courage but neglects compassion has not achieved the ideal. A person who embodies truth but lacks discipline has not reached harmony. Only the soul that holds all seven virtues in balanced integration — each tempering the others, each preventing the others from becoming distorted into vice — has achieved the fullness of the Scale&#39;s demands. It is this standard — this demanding, comprehensive, almost impossibly high ideal of perfect moral harmony — against which Seros weighs every soul upon death. Legal and Social Implications The Measure and the Scale is not merely a religious text; it is the living legal code of the Mithrian Empire . Its influence on Mithrian law and society is total and pervasive. The Judicial System All judicial matters within the Empire are adjudicated by reference to the Measure and the Scale. Judges, magistrates, and legal scholars are trained in the interpretation of the text, and legal arguments are framed in terms of its principles. The most contentious legal cases often hinge on competing interpretations of the Measure&#39;s provisions — debates that can draw in theologians from the Thousand Temples , philosophers from the Academy , and political factions from across the Empire. Legal and philosophical debates over the interpretation of the Measure and the Scale are frequent and vigorous in Mithrian society. The text&#39;s dual nature as both divine revelation and practical legal code ensures that its interpretation remains a living, contested, and deeply consequential enterprise. Dies Justicae The importance of the Measure and the Scale to Mithrian society is most dramatically expressed in the annual holiday of Dies Justicae — the Day of Justice. On this day, all work throughout the Empire is forbidden. The entire text of the Measure and the Scale is recited aloud by a priest of the Thousand Temples — a marathon of liturgical reading that can take many hours. Citizens gather to listen, and the recitation is treated as both a civic duty and a sacred rite. Dies Justicae serves as an annual reminder that the laws of the Empire are not merely human conventions but divine principles, and that every citizen — from the Emperor to the lowest serf — lives under the same cosmic standard. The Patronage System The Measure codifies the patronage system that structures Mithrian social order. The fourth virtue of the Scale — Loyalty to One&#39;s Father, in Body, Soul, and State — establishes the theological justification for a society organized around hierarchical relationships of obligation and protection. The father wields tremendous power within the family: authority over children, management of family assets, representation of the family in civic and religious life. This familial authority extends outward into a broader social framework in which powerful families extend patronage to lesser families and individuals. The patronage system is simultaneously a source of social stability and social tension. It ensures that even the poorest and most vulnerable members of Mithrian society have a patron to whom they can appeal for protection and assistance. But it also concentrates enormous power in the hands of the great families and creates a web of obligations that can constrain individual freedom and perpetuate entrenched hierarchies. Connection to the Flame The Measure and the Scale is intimately connected to the Flame — the priestly magic of the Empyrean Faith . To walk the path of the Measure and the Scale — to genuinely embody the seven virtues in balanced harmony — is to unlock the inner radiance that allows the faithful to channel the Flame. The Flame is not a reward for obedience but a natural consequence of spiritual transformation: when the soul achieves the harmony that the Scale demands, it burns with the light of Seros , and that light can be directed outward into the material world as a force of healing, protection, and righteous destruction. This connection between virtue and magical power is one of the most theologically significant aspects of the Empyrean faith, and it gives the Measure and the Scale a practical importance that transcends its legal and philosophical functions. The text is not merely a guide to good behavior or a legal code for social organization; it is, literally, the key to unlocking divine power. Connection to Sainthood The Saints of the Empyrean Faith are those individuals who, in life, exhibited the seven virtues of the Scale to an extraordinary and exemplary degree. The process of anointing a Saint — controlled exclusively by the Thousand Temples — involves an exhaustive examination of the candidate&#39;s life against the standard of the seven virtues. Did they embody justice tempered by wisdom? Discipline forged through self-mastery? Courage wielded in service? The candidate must be found to have achieved the harmony that the Scale demands — not perfection in any single virtue, but balanced excellence across all seven. This connection between the Scale and Sainthood means that the Measure and the Scale is not merely a historical or legal document but a living, active standard by which the holiness of individuals continues to be assessed. Every generation produces new candidates for Sainthood, and every candidacy is a renewed engagement with the text&#39;s demands. See Also Empyrean Faith Seros Aurelion Enador Thousand Temples Saints The Flame Anthyllium Mithrian Empire Massaran Empire Sorcerer Kings Academy Cthonic Faith Magic and Sorcery"},{"slug":"the-mystical","title":"The Mystical","category":"faiths","tags":"mystical religion aurelion tribal philosophy","text":"The Mystical The Mystical is the third and rarest of the great cosmological traditions, standing apart from both the Empyrean faith and the Cthonic cults . It has no organized church, no priesthood, no holy texts, and no codified doctrine. It is less a religion than a philosophical orientation -- a way of understanding the cosmos that resists the binary moral framework imposed by the other two faiths. The Mystical Interpretation of Aurelion Where the Empyrean faith teaches that Aurelion sacrificed himself to purge evil and the Cthonic faith holds that he sacrificed himself to eliminate weakness, the Mystical tradition offers a third reading. In this view, Aurelion sought to experience the full spectrum of existence -- light and darkness, creation and destruction, joy and suffering -- and sacrificed himself not to separate these forces but to become All. His death was not an act of purification or culling but an act of total immersion in the fabric of reality. The Struggle as Purpose The Mystical perspective reframes the eternal conflict between Empyrean and Cthonic forces not as a war to be won but as a necessary process. The struggle between light and darkness, order and chaos, is itself the mechanism through which Aurelion experiences the fullness of existence. Both sides serve a purpose. Both contribute to the eventual rebirth of the divine whole. To declare one side righteous and the other evil is, in the Mystical view, to misunderstand the nature of the cosmos. This emphasis on lived experience over strict moral dichotomies sets the Mystical tradition apart from the rigid ethical frameworks of the Measure and the Scale and the brutal survival doctrine of the Cthonic cults. The Mystical does not ask is this good or evil? but rather what does this reveal about the nature of All? Practitioners and Adherents The Mystical is not widely recognized within the Mithrian Empire . It has no temples, no clergy, and no political influence. Those who hold Mystical beliefs tend to be solitary thinkers, wandering ascetics, or individuals who have arrived at their conclusions through personal spiritual experience rather than institutional instruction. Various tribal peoples beyond the borders of the Empire follow versions of the Mystical tradition, though their practices and beliefs vary enormously. Many of these groups do not even believe in Aurelion as such -- their cosmologies may use different names, different stories, and different frameworks while arriving at a similar philosophical destination. The Mystical is less a defined creed than a convergence of independent insights, and it resists the kind of systematization that would make it legible to the institutional religions. Relationship with Other Faiths The Thousand Temples generally regard the Mystical as a harmless eccentricity at best and a subtle heresy at worst. It does not attract the violent persecution directed at Cthonic cults, but neither does it receive any form of official sanction. Cthonic worshippers tend to dismiss the Mystical as naive -- a refusal to accept the hard truths of a predatory cosmos. See Also The Empyrean Faith The Cthonic Faith Aurelion The Measure and the Scale"},{"slug":"index","title":"Wiki Index","category":"overview","tags":"","text":"Wiki Index 190 pages across 7 categories. Last updated 2026-04-11. Overview overview — Campaign setting front page: the Fallen Empire and the Backlands People (48) Player Characters theodotus — Thrassian Philosopher-Bard, carries the Stone of Sakkara iman — Bladedancer, expelled from the Order of the Scarlet Ribbon shatzi — Merchant, organizer of the Reclaimers tiberius — Necromancer, expelled from the Imperial Academy tancred — Crusader of Seros, DECEASED Sanctuary governor-drussus — Valerios Drussus, Fighter 12, Governor of the Backlands prelate-voth — Severan Voth, Cleric 13, Temple of the Unconquered Sun colonel-vex — Marcian Vex, Fighter 9, Drussine Guard commander castellan-thibaud — Master Thief 7, boss of the Laced Hand valeria-thorne — Red River Consortium Directrix in Sanctuary magister-shale — Cornelius Shale, Wizard 11, Academy Regent elder-sarnath — Sarnath of the Crossings, Avari community elder Reclaimers Henchmen anaya — Henchman, critically wounded by zombie beastman, experiencing visions of the Gallowswood&#39;s black heart antonius — Henchman, had a vision of Rendson as he neared death Fort Meade legate-marcellus — Titus Valerian Marcellus, Fighter 6, Backlands military commander lady-severina — Lady Severina Marcellus, Noble 2, the Legate&#39;s wife sergeant-crull — Davan Crull, senior NCO, the Legate&#39;s enforcer malachor — Imperial Historian, Scholar 4, Academy agent rook — Bandit king, operated from Fort Ikenvar, DECEASED Fort Harvald sergeant-voss — Aldric Voss, garrison commander, politically buried noma — Noma of the Shallows, ageless river witch Bone Creek thaddeus-marr — Thief 4 (Mornish), Pretty Peach proprietor, secret racket tolliver-watts — Venturer 5, Double Sevens owner cassian-varro — Venturer 6, Red River Consortium Lord Merchant brother-marco — Cleric 2, priest of Seros sergeant-gallus — Fighter 2, corrupt law enforcer crackback — Thief 2 (Targ/Mornish), pimp at The Pretty Peach, Marr&#39;s enforcer doc-quinten — Explorer 3 (Kolani), barber-surgeon, universally neutral irontoe — Pontus Irontoe Draega, Fighter 2 (Mithrian), smith, lost leg fighting the Lakandi theo — Fighter 3 (Thrassian), Flophouse proprietor, secret informant for Marr greta — Witch 3 (Lakandi), holds a bound demon malyn-the-misshapen — Mage 7, exiled, enslaves beastmen lynara — Eladran Nightblade 3, Malyn&#39;s apprentice, morally conflicted ezekiel-shaw — Cleric 6, Congregation of the Hollow Sun leader Scalper Gang Leaders skinner — Assassin 5 (Kolani), Skin Eaters bottlecap-juno — Barbarian 4, the Dregs kael-baldric — Fighter 4 (Avari), Baldric Brothers, MISSING wekko — Witch-Doctor 6, Hollow Men marcos-varanes — Paladin 5, Bleak Sons arannis-venn — Eladran Spellsword 6, Argollean Brotherhood Historical Figures eolande — Ancient Eladran general (~3000 BE), still present at the Black Tree at Thornasse marcus-valerian — First Emperor of Mithra emperor-aurex — Mad Emperor, assassinated by his sister claudius-decimus — Victor of the War of Three Emperors justinian-decimus — Current Emperor high-mage-cynar — Burned the Erenthis, died at Blue Mound jarn-murky-eye — Lakandi Warlock King, died at Blue Mound varek-ashstone — Ygrathen hermit, cairnhouse guardian at Lake Silverhead Locations (21) mithra-city — Capital of the Mithrian Empire sanctuary — Provincial capital, port city of 28,000, 8 districts the-undercity — Ancient Aodahn beneath Sanctuary, three-tier megadungeon: Warrens, Old Aodahn, Foundations of the Spires aodahn — Ancient Eladra city beneath Sanctuary, three-tier megadungeon the-backlands — Province of Argolle, the forgotten frontier bone-creek — Scalper outpost, 9 keyed locations fort-meade — Strategic garrison on the Sanctuary–Bone Creek supply route fort-harvald — Settlement near Crossings ruins, bayou frontier fort-ikenvar — Ruined marsh fort, lair of the Guzzler argoll-river — Major river of the Backlands, flows from interior to Turquoise Sea at Sanctuary crossings — Ruined river city, 10 points of interest, beastman-occupied cairnhill — Town shaped by psychic bleed from imprisoned Kharai dunwick — Farming town, Bel earth-hunger cult activity gallowswood — Cursed forest, dead walk beneath the roots, pulsating black heart beneath granite dome the-slog — Primary hunting ground, wasteland between Bone Creek and Crossings, Borderlands encounter table the-foothills — Hills and abandoned mines, cave bears and skeletons crossings-hinterlands — Territory surrounding Crossings ruins, highest beastman activity lake-silverhead — Far northern lake with Ygrathen cairnhouse thornasse — Site of the burned Erenthis, the Black Tree endures the-heartwood — Oldest forest in the Backlands, uncharted depths, owlbeasts, unidentifiable deep entities grathe-steppe — Skiothan homeland, vast grasslands Factions (21) Imperial Institutions imperial-academy — State seat of sorcerous learning mithrian-military — The imperial armed forces mithrian-marines — Elite branch, Shroud worship, the 8th Undying imperial-talons — Emperor&#39;s spies and assassins imperial-senate — Remnant of the Mithrian League, largely performative thousand-temples — Official religious institution burnished-scale — Disgraced militant religious order Great Houses house-decimus — Ruling house, Emperor Justinian house-valerian — Ancient lineage to Bellasarius house-kalomenes — Court power, patronage mastery house-malventi — Foreign trade, Massaran connections house-drussus — Newest house, Governor Drussus house-aurel — Conservative, Thousand Temples ties house-severian — Enigmatic, rumored Eladra blood Backlands Factions red-river-consortium — Trading company, Bone Creek and Sanctuary argollean-brotherhood — Criminal network of old Eladran noble houses congregation-of-the-hollow-sun — Populist heretical cult, Ezekiel Shaw scalper-gangs — Six gangs: Skin Eaters, Dregs, Baldric Brothers, Hollow Men, Bleak Sons, Withered Craw laced-hand — Sanctuary&#39;s criminal syndicate drussine-guard — Governor&#39;s 2,000-strong private army order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon — Militant Empyrean order, Iman&#39;s former order Faiths (24) The Empyrean empyrean-faith — State religion: reincarnation, purification, the Aurelion seros — The Winged Sun, dominant deity empyrean-pantheon — Overview table of all Empyrean gods/saints andraste — The Holy Dancer: compassion, strength, joy damocles — Victor of One Hundred Stratagems: war, cunning, victory eramus — The Shepherd: wisdom, duty, steadfastness euphrosyne — The Candle: hope, willpower, resolve hector — The Bronze Lord: discipline, martial prowess, justice mina — The Hand: grace, art, beauty sagramore — The Martyr: loyalty, endurance, sacrifice bellasarius — The Father: courage, service, fatherhood enador — The Light in the Dark: vision, journey, time; Prophet of Seros shroud — God of crossing and passage, worshipped by Marines The Cthonic cthonic-faith — Outlawed dark cults: undeath, the Awakening cthonic-pantheon — Overview table of all Cthonic gods dirgion — Doombringer: death, undeath iskara — Mother of Monsters: chaos, darkness kaleth — Dark Watcher: madness, knowledge, entropy bel — The Slaughterprince: war, conquest, blood; also earth-hunger galmorm — The Poisoner: treachery, poison, thievery nasga — Mistress of Pain and Pleasure: beauty, pain, lust ravanor — The Bitter Prince: rulership, power, tyranny Other the-mystical — The rare third faith: Aurelion as All the-measure-and-the-scale — Sacred text, legal framework, seven virtues Lore (57) The World mithrapos — The known world, region encircling the Middle Sea mithrian-empire — Political structure, governance, social order great-houses — The seven Great Houses overview massaran-empire — Ancient sorcerer-king empire, overthrown in the Empyrean War History Events history-of-mithrapos — Complete timeline from 4100 BE to 380 IY empyrean-war — 663 BE: Enador and Bellasarius vs the Massaran Empire war-of-three-emperors — 270 IY: Aurex&#39;s death, Numerius&#39;s 87 days, Decimus rises dog-soldier-war — 272-291 IY: don&#39;Kolani guerrilla war, Jute&#39;s peace lakan-campaigns — 360-368 IY: Eight-year war against Lakandi battle-of-blue-mound — Cynar vs Jarn Murky-Eye, mutual annihilation sacking-of-crossings — 377 IY: Beastman horde destroys Crossings Magic Metaphysics magic-and-sorcery — Overview of the three traditions gnostic-geometry — Nine-fold geometric patterns, Academy sorcery the-veil — Living membrane between mortal realm and the Beyond the-flame — Empyrean priestly magic, divine spark the-anthyllium — Ancient grimoire of gnostic formulae the-aurelion — Supreme cosmic being, three interpretations of the sacrifice the-beyond — The multiversal reality beyond the Veil the-awakening — Cthonic prophecy, event in progress in Argolle the-convergence-problem — Are Empyrean and Cthonic gods the same divided powers? cthonic-corruption — Effects of Cthonic influence on living creatures the-erenthis — Living Eladran monuments, hostile to Cthonic corruption the-black-tree — Scorched Erenthis stump at Thornasse, roots endure, Eolande encountered here, dryad, dreams the-womb-curse — Mystery mentioned by Eolande, connected to Eladra/Elvora, urgently sought by Malachor the-nethercity — Eladran necropolis beneath Crossings the-kharai — Ancient imprisoned beings, Ygrathen cairnhouses bel-earth-hunger — Agricultural blood cult in Argolle farming villages the-stone-of-sakkara — Artifact carried by Theodotus, amplifies demonic hunger toward innocence, draws the Guzzler the-guzzler — Demonic entity at Fort Ikenvar, drawn south by the Stone of Sakkara, escalating trail of violence lakandi-binding-tradition — Demon-binding sorcery kolani-munitions — Deadly Kolani weapons, gained via Dog Soldier War backlands-field-guide — Comprehensive survival reference: flora, fauna, hazards for all Backlands regions Races Cultures races-and-cultures — Overview of all peoples mithrian-culture — Dominant imperial culture, three-part naming thrassian — Mountain tribal warriors corcanoan — Volcanic island seafarers mornish — Peninsula of Morn, rebellious kolani — Plains/forest tribes, Kolani Irregulars avari — Conquered seafarers, Erenthis tradition, Crossings refugees lysean — Loyal breadbasket, drought-devastated targ — Magically created race, former slaves shenti — Former Massaran subjects tet — Tezerat Plateau, Enador found the Measure here lakandi — Wasteland warriors, demon-binders skiothan — Nomadic horse warriors, True Names grathar — Tall reclusive people, Ygrathen blood massar — Former sorcerer-king culture vestari — Cosmopolitan allies, Bellasarius lineage rinoan — Northern tribal confederation, blue/yellow eyes eladra — Ancient Argollean race, built Erenthis and Aodahn elvora — Immortal, corrupted by the Veil thune — Reptilian slave soldiers, await the Awakening beastmen — Massaran-created monstrous humans ygrathen — Oldest race, cairnhouse builders Reference mithrian-calendar — Valerian Calendar: 13 months, holidays languages-of-mithrapos — Dead and living languages the-reclaimers — The player character party Sessions (1) campaign-chronicle — Campaign session history and PC roster Sources (14) src-fallen-empire-primer — Foundational setting document src-the-backlands — Backlands province and Bone Creek src-fort-meade — Fort Meade garrison and political dynamics src-dramatis-personae — Full NPC roster with stat blocks src-crossings-poi — Crossings ruins points of interest src-faiths-of-argolle — Religious traditions, Erenthis, Kharai, Nethercity src-sanctuary-city — Sanctuary city supplement, 8 districts src-crossings-supplement — Crossings Adventure Supplement, 32 keyed locations, 7 districts, 5 beastman factions src-gilded-vigil — The Gilded Vigil tomb crawl, Cairnhill Breaks, Kharai innocence question src-backlands-regional-overview — Backlands Regional Overview, 4 wilderness regions, Varro&#39;s criminal enterprise src-random-notes — Shaw&#39;s Sermon, Codex of Ninefold Stillness, eulogies, session prep src-backlands-timeline — Backlands provincial timeline 283-380 IY src-first-empire-history — History of the First Empire, Eladra, Argollean Empire src-next-session-reference — Session prep: Eolande at the Black Tree, Stone of Sakkara crisis, Legate&#39;s charter proposal src-woodsmans-field-notes — Woodsman&#39;s Field Notes: flora, fauna, survival across four Backlands regions"},{"slug":"aodahn","title":"Aodahn","category":"locations","tags":"location ruins ancient eladra empyrean megadungeon undercity sanctuary aodahn mystery spires argollean","text":"Aodahn As though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned. -- Chronicler Varro Silk Aodahn is the ancient Eladra harbor-city upon whose ruins Sanctuary was built. The name is an Argollean word meaning sanctuary or refuge -- a name the Mithrians unconsciously preserved when they founded their own city atop the ruins. Aodahn was built by the true, uncorrupted Eladra -- possibly the last community of their kind in the world -- and its remnants represent one of the greatest archaeological mysteries and most dangerous adventuring environments in the Backlands . At a Glance Detail Description Name Aodahn (Argollean: sanctuary or refuge ) Built By The Elvora -- the corrupted elven peoples known elsewhere in the world. The Eladra were something older and purer , a people who maintained their connection to the Empyrean when others fell away. They were true children of the Empyrean gods, and their works reflected a level of craft and understanding that the Mithrian Empire has never approached. Aodahn may have been the last Eladra community in the world . If so, its loss -- or transformation, or ascension, or whatever occurred -- represents the final chapter of a civilization that existed before human history began. At least one Eladra agent is believed to be present in Sanctuary at any given time, watching and guarding secrets about what lies below. These agents are subtle, patient, and nearly impossible to identify. Their purpose is unknown -- whether they guard the Threshold, monitor human activity, or pursue some deeper agenda is a matter of speculation. The Five Ivory Spires The most visible remnants of Aodahn are the five ivory spires that punctuate Sanctuary&#39;s skyline. Each spire is carved from a single stone so white it seems to emit light. Each rises three hundred feet or more above the harbor. Their proportions are calculated in ratios that trouble human perception -- they appear simultaneously too tall and too slender, too massive and too delicate, as though human geometry and Eladra geometry do not quite overlap. Theories of Purpose Modern Academy scholars suspect that the spires are engineered conduits of Empyrean vitality , analogous to Erenthis trees but constructed rather than grown. If this theory is correct, the implications are enormous: Aodahn was not simply a city. It was a project -- an engineered environment designed to channel, concentrate, or amplify Empyrean energy for a specific purpose. The nature of that purpose remains unknown. Theories include: Ascension preparation -- the spires were infrastructure for a planned transcendence Defensive array -- the spires protected the city from metaphysical threats Communication network -- the spires connected Aodahn to other Eladra sites or to the Empyrean itself Energy harvest -- the spires gathered Empyrean vitality for unknown applications Documented Phenomena The spires cause documented sensory phenomena in their vicinity: Sounds in unknown languages -- whispered conversations in tongues no living scholar can identify, heard most clearly at dawn and dusk Sensation of being observed -- a persistent, unmistakable feeling of attention from an unseen source Fleeting images -- momentary visions of non-existent people and places, glimpsed at the edge of perception and gone when looked at directly Emotional resonance -- feelings of profound peace, terrible grief, or desperate urgency that arise without cause and pass without trace Several cults have formed around the spires over the centuries, each interpreting the phenomena differently. The Temple of the Unconquered Sun monitors these cults and suppresses those that become destabilizing. Individual Spires The Academy Spire -- One spire was incorporated into the Imperial Academy Tower , which was constructed around it rather than breaking it down. The spire rises through the Tower&#39;s interior, serving as both architectural centerpiece and object of continuous study. Magister Cornelius Shale and his scholars have spent decades attempting to understand its properties. The Garden Spire -- Another spire stands in the Eladra Spire Garden , a public space in the Ivory Quarter . The Garden produces particularly vivid visions at sunset, drawing curious scholars, devoted cultists, and occasional madmen in equal measure. Three additional spires -- distributed across Sanctuary , each surrounded by varying degrees of development, superstition, and restricted access. The Abandonment When the Mithrians first arrived at the site, they found Aodahn completely abandoned . This was not the aftermath of war, plague, siege, or flight. There was no evidence of catastrophe of any kind. The city was simply empty . Belongings remained in homes Workshops stood open, tools laid out as if in mid-use Food rotted on tables Personal effects -- clothing, jewelry, documents -- were undisturbed No bodies, no blood, no signs of struggle No defensive preparations, no evidence of evacuation The chronicler Varro Silk , among the first Mithrian scholars to examine the site, wrote that Aodahn felt as though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned. Academic Theories The Imperial Academy has proposed several theories to explain the Abandonment: The Threshold Hypothesis -- The Eladra used the spires to open a door to the Empyrean or to another plane of existence and stepped through, leaving the physical world behind The Ascension Model -- The Eladra transcended physical form, shedding their bodies (which dissolved) and becoming something non-corporeal The Catastrophic Severance Theory -- An accident or external force severed the Eladra&#39;s connection to the Empyrean, destroying them instantly and completely The Recall -- The Eladra were summoned by their gods and departed willingly, leaving everything behind because nothing material would be needed None of these theories are proven. The truth, if it can be determined at all, likely lies in the Foundations of the Spires -- the deepest level of the Undercity , where the Threshold is said to exist. The Undercity -- Three-Tier Megadungeon Below the surface streets of Sanctuary , the ruins of Aodahn extend downward in three distinct tiers, forming one of the most extensive and dangerous dungeon environments in the Backlands . Tier 1: The Warrens (Levels 1--3) The uppermost levels, accessible through numerous known entrances throughout the city. The Warrens are a transition zone between the surface world and the true ruins -- partially settled by smugglers, outcasts, and those with reason to avoid the light, but increasingly dangerous as one descends. Inhabitants: Giant vermin (rats, spiders, centipedes) -- thriving in the darkness and refuse Oozes -- drawn to the moisture and organic waste Smuggler gangs -- using the tunnels as hidden routes between Sanctuary&#39;s districts Outcast settlements -- small communities of those who cannot or will not live on the surface Features: Collapsed tunnels and flooded passages Hidden caches left by smugglers and previous explorers Smuggler routes connecting the Harbor , Commons , and other districts Occasional Eladra architecture visible through natural collapse Danger Level: Low to moderate. Manageable by experienced adventurers. Tier 2: Old Aodahn (Levels 3--7) Below the Warrens, the character of the ruins changes dramatically. Here, the preserved heart of the ancient Eladra city lies largely intact. The architecture becomes alien -- proportions shift, materials defy identification, spaces exist that should not be possible given the geometry above. The area is saturated with Empyrean energy, producing persistent strange phenomena. Inhabitants: Construct guardians -- Eladra -built automatons still operational after centuries, maintaining patrol routes and responding to intrusion with mechanical precision Doppelgangers -- entities of unknown origin that have taken up residence in the abandoned city Minotaurs -- drawn to the labyrinthine passages Minor elementals -- manifesting spontaneously from the concentrated Empyrean energy Features: Preserved Eladra workshops, libraries, and living spaces -- still containing artifacts, documents, and equipment Empyrean energy saturation causes minor reality distortions: lights without source, sounds without origin, time moving at inconsistent rates Strange phenomena: flickering illumination in sealed chambers, conversations in unknown languages echoing through empty halls, fleeting images of Eladra going about lives that ended centuries ago Architecture that does not obey human geometric conventions Danger Level: Significant. Requires well-equipped and experienced parties. The constructs alone are dangerous, and the environmental effects of Empyrean saturation add unpredictability. Tier 3: Foundations of the Spires (Levels 7+) The deepest known level of the Undercity. Here, at the roots of the great spires, the Eladra built something extraordinary -- the infrastructure of whatever process they ultimately used to depart the physical world. The Empyrean energy is overwhelming. Reality itself becomes unreliable. Inhabitants: Masterwork constructs -- far more powerful than those found in Old Aodahn, designed to protect the most critical installations Major elementals -- powerful beings manifesting from the extreme concentration of Empyrean energy Entities of unknown origin -- things that exist in the space between the physical world and whatever lies beyond the Threshold Features: The Threshold -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened. The door has not fully closed . Whatever process the Eladra used to depart left a permanent weakness in the boundary between the physical world and the Empyrean . This is the source of the phenomena that pervade all of Aodahn -- the sounds, the visions, the sensation of being watched. It is a wound in reality, and it has not healed. Empyrean energy so concentrated that mortal flesh reacts unpredictably -- healing, harming, transforming, or simply refusing to behave as expected Magical effects are amplified, distorted, or inverted in the Threshold&#39;s vicinity The roots of the spires themselves, visible as massive pillars of white stone descending into the bedrock, still humming with energy after centuries Danger Level: Extreme. Few have reached this level and returned. Those who have describe experiences that they struggle to articulate -- as though the language for what they witnessed does not yet exist. Significance Aodahn is not merely an archaeological curiosity or an adventuring site. It is a living mystery -- a place where the past has not fully become the past, where the Eladra&#39;s departure left a mark that the world has not yet absorbed. For the Academy , it represents the greatest unsolved puzzle in the Backlands -- perhaps in the world. For the Temple , it is a potential theological crisis: if the Eladra achieved a form of ascension outside the framework of the Unconquered Sun&#39;s theology, what does that imply about the faith? For the Governor , it is a resource -- artifacts from the Undercity are valuable, and knowledge of the spires could be leveraged politically. For the Eladra agents who still watch from the shadows, it is something else entirely -- a trust, a burden, a promise kept across centuries. GM Notes Aodahn should be treated as the deep background mystery of Sanctuary . Key principles: It does not need to be the focus. The mystery of the Eladra and the Threshold can exist as atmosphere and background for dozens of sessions before becoming directly relevant. It should always be felt. The spires are visible from anywhere in the city. The phenomena are documented. The Undercity is always below. Even in political adventures that never go underground, Aodahn is present. The Threshold is real. Whatever the Eladra did, it left a permanent mark. The door has not fully closed. This is the source of the phenomena -- and potentially a source of much greater threats or opportunities. The megadungeon scales with the campaign. The Warrens are appropriate for low-level parties. Old Aodahn challenges experienced adventurers. The Foundations of the Spires are endgame content. The Eladra agents are watching. At least one is likely in Sanctuary at any time. They are subtle, nearly impossible to identify, and their agenda is unknown. They are a wild card that the GM can deploy when the time is right. See Also Sanctuary -- the city built upon Aodahn&#39;s ruins The Eladra -- the builders The Empyrean -- the divine source of the spires&#39; power Erenthis Trees -- natural analogues to the spires&#39; function The Ivory Quarter -- district built atop the ruins Imperial Academy -- institution studying the ruins Magister Cornelius Shale -- Academy Regent The Undercity -- the megadungeon The Backlands -- the province The Elvora -- the corrupted elven peoples (distinct from the Eladra)"},{"slug":"argoll-river","title":"Argoll River","category":"locations","tags":"location river backlands crossings sanctuary fort-harvald argent-bay trade-route neglect beastmen","text":"Argoll River The Argoll River is the major waterway of the Backlands , flowing from the interior highlands to the Turquoise Sea at Sanctuary . It is the primary geographic artery of the province -- the feature around which settlement, trade, and military strategy have organized for millennia. At a Glance Detail Description Type Major river Region the-backlands Source Interior highlands Mouth [[sanctuary Delta [[crossings Key Crossings The Stone Yoke Bridge (at [[crossings Key Settlements [[sanctuary Current Condition Clogged, neglected, slow, brown, stinking Geography The Argoll River flows from the interior of the Backlands toward the coast, passing through or near several key locations: [[Sanctuary -- The provincial capital sits at the river&#39;s mouth where it empties into the Turquoise Sea . The ancient Eladran city of Aodahn was built at this same location, suggesting the river has been a center of civilization for millennia. Fort Harvald -- Located on the river delta, this settlement serves as a forward base near the ruins of Crossings. Crossings -- The ruined river city sits at the delta where the Argoll empties into Argent Bay . The city&#39;s name reflects its historical role as a crossing point -- the convergence of seven imperial roads at the river. The Stone Yoke Bridge -- Spans the river&#39;s widest channel at Crossings, serving as the primary entry point into the ruined city. Current Condition The Argoll River is clogged with six years of neglect and beastman filth . Since the Sacking of Crossings in 377 IY (or 374 IY per the alternate timeline), the river has deteriorated from a navigable trade artery into a sluggish, foul waterway: Slow -- choked by debris, silt, and years without maintenance Brown -- muddied by uncontrolled erosion and contamination Stinking -- polluted by beastman habitation, rotting vegetation, and the general decay of an untended watershed Before the fall of Crossings, the Argoll was a vital trade route connecting the interior settlements to the coast and, through Sanctuary&#39;s harbor, to the broader Mithrian Empire . Its degradation is a physical manifestation of the Backlands&#39; collapse -- a river that once carried commerce now carries filth. Historical Significance The Argoll River has been the spine of civilization in the Backlands across three distinct eras: The Eladran Era -- The Eladra built Aodahn at the river&#39;s mouth, recognizing its strategic value as the gateway between sea and interior. The Argollean / Avari Era -- The Avari Confederation centered their civilization along the river, with Crossings/Thornasse as their cultural heart and the great Erenthis planted at the river delta. The Mithrian Era -- The Empire built its Backlands infrastructure along the river corridor, with Sanctuary as the capital and Crossings as the major interior trade hub, connected by seven imperial roads. The river&#39;s name likely derives from Argolle , the imperial province in which it flows. Strategic Importance Control of the Argoll River means control of the Backlands. Whoever holds Sanctuary at the mouth and can project power upriver to Crossings controls the province&#39;s economic and military lifeline. The current situation -- where Sanctuary is held by Governor Drussus but Crossings is occupied by 800 beastmen -- represents a fractured strategic picture. The river connects two worlds: imperial civilization at the coast and beastman-occupied ruins in the interior. See Also sanctuary -- Provincial capital at the river&#39;s mouth crossings -- Ruined city at the river delta fort-harvald -- Settlement on the river delta Argent Bay -- Bay where the Argoll meets the sea at Crossings the-backlands -- The province the river defines sacking-of-crossings -- The event that led to the river&#39;s neglect aodahn -- Ancient Eladran city at the river&#39;s mouth"},{"slug":"bone-creek","title":"Bone Creek","category":"locations","tags":"settlement outpost bone-creek backlands scalpers frontier bounty","text":"Bone Creek Deep in the Northern Backlands , as far as any man is willing to go, sits the outpost of Bone Creek . A ramshackle frontier settlement that has reinvented itself as the epicenter of the Scalper trade, Bone Creek is a place of desperate ambition, casual violence, and hard-won survival. It&#39;s far too cold, you&#39;re always hungry, and you&#39;re just as likely to get shanked in the streets as you are to meet your doom on the Slog. With a little luck you might be able to kill a few of the fucking beastmen and make enough coin to put some food in your belly. But here, in Bone Creek, luck can only get you so far. The veteran Scalpers are unlike any men you have ever encountered, their eyes dulled from the horrors they have seen and endured, or tinged with a glint of madness. Some even bear the marks of corruption openly. They say, those who hunt the beastmen are changed. They say, The Bounty takes its toll. History The Silver Rush Years ago, a silver rush in the nearby foothills led to an influx of prospectors, speculators, and miners. Those days are long gone. The mines are barren and forgotten, and until recently the outpost was in decline, nearly abandoned — a ghost of its former self slowly dying on the frontier. The Scalper Rush Two years ago, a great horde of beastmen attacked and sacked the city of Crossings . The few refugees who managed to escape with their lives tell stories of the horrors the beastmen inflicted upon the citizens of the Empire that day. Now, those same beastmen have settled in the ruin of the city and begun to push farther south, kidnapping farmers, raiding, and worse. By the decree of the Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus , the beastmen are to be culled. Vile subhumanoid creatures, the beastmen have an unnatural propensity for violence and are responsible for committing unspeakable atrocities. The price of a beastman scalp is one imperial gold mark , creating an entirely new rush for Bone Creek — not for silver, but for blood. Scalpers Those who seek the Imperial Bounty are called Scalpers . Hard men and women who come from every walk of life, drawn by the allure of the Imperial Bounty, a Scalper&#39;s life is one of chaos, violence, and peril. For whatever reason, each Scalper has left their former life behind and journeyed to the edge of civilization. The veteran Scalpers are unlike any men one might encounter elsewhere — their eyes dulled from the horrors they have seen and endured, or tinged with a glint of madness. Some even bear the marks of corruption openly. Locations in Bone Creek The Flophouse A former barn converted into a single large room filled with straw mattresses, blankets, and a community pot of stew. The food is not very good, the floor is hard, and it can be bitterly cold in winter. It is the cheapest accommodation in town and the first stop for most newly arrived Scalpers. Theo , the proprietor, does not suffer delinquent payments. He carries a brutal cudgel, and no one dares cross him. Beneath his gruff exterior, however, Theo is secretly in Thaddeus Marr&#39;s pocket — feeding him information on Scalper gangs, rumors, and activities within town. The Flophouse serves as Marr&#39;s eyes and ears on the newest and most vulnerable arrivals. Key NPCs: Theo — Proprietor. Carries a brutal cudgel. Secret informant for Thaddeus Marr . The Pretty Peach A tavern and inn serving watered-down ale, cheap wine, and decent food. Hard beds are available for a few marks, though decent rooms are in high demand. The Pretty Peach is the domain of Thaddeus Marr , its proprietor — a hardened frontiersman with a storied reputation. Thaddeus has a deal with the local pimp Crackback , a brutish targ who employs several working girls. A simmering rivalry with Double Sevens directly across the street has resulted in large-scale brawls on more than one occasion. Thaddeus secretly operates a racket within town, using the Pretty Peach as his base of operations and Theo at the Flophouse as his informant network. Key NPCs: Thaddeus Marr — Proprietor. Hardened frontiersman. Secret racketeer. Crackback — A brutish targ . Local pimp and Marr&#39;s right-hand man. Employs several working girls. Trixie — A young and beautiful slave girl. Double Sevens Located directly across the street from the Pretty Peach, Double Sevens is a relatively new establishment operated by the wealthy merchant Tolliver Watts . It caters to the more successful Scalpers and the burgeoning burgher class of Bone Creek, offering a notable step up in quality from the Peach. Double Sevens serves imported spirits, wines, and ales. It hosts gambling tables and employs its own prostitutes, who are held to a higher standard than Peach girls. Madame Selka , a young and beautiful Shenti woman, oversees the working girls and has frequent, public arguments with Watts. Watts is a close ally of Cassian Varro of the Red River Consortium , and ultimately seeks to bring civilization to Bone Creek — transforming it from a lawless outpost into something resembling a proper town. Key NPCs: Tolliver Watts — Proprietor. Wealthy merchant. Ally of Cassian Varro . Seeks to civilize Bone Creek. Madame Selka — Young, beautiful Shenti woman. Oversees the working girls. Has frequent public arguments with Watts. Frog — Watts&#39; assistant and advisor. A lifelong slave. Expert with administration and numbers. Three-Finger Kanos — Bodyguard and head of security for Double Sevens. Tackle and Harness An all-purpose general shop and small stable run by Royce and Rhoda Harbecke and their children. The shop caters specifically to Scalper needs, carrying a wide inventory of goods useful for hunting ranka or exploring the wilderness. A small, newly built stable is attached. The Harbeckes are honest and hard-working Mithrian citizens — a rare breed in Bone Creek. One of their children could potentially be hired as a henchman. Key NPCs: Royce Harbecke — Co-owner. Honest Mithrian citizen. Rhoda Harbecke — Co-owner. Wife of Royce. Harbecke children — Help run the shop. Potential henchman hires. Greta&#39;s Tinctures An old recluse named Greta sells minor alchemical items and herbs from this small shop. Greta has lived in Bone Creek longer than almost anyone else in the settlement. She is strange and eccentric, with no known family. Rumors persist that Greta is a witch who serves a demonic being. Whether these rumors hold any truth is unknown, but few are willing to test them. Key NPCs: Greta — Old recluse. Alchemist and herbalist. Rumored witch who may serve a demonic being. One of the longest residents of Bone Creek. Bone Creek Surgery The local barber surgeon, known simply as Doc (real name Quinten ), operates out of this establishment. Services include bloodletting, amputations, and minor dentistry. Doc also offers baths, hair cutting, shaving, and enemas. He is hardly the most talented barber surgeon in the land, but he is the only one in Bone Creek, and that counts for something on the frontier. Key NPCs: Doc (Quinten) — Barber surgeon. Mediocre talent, but the only medical professional in town. Irontoe Smithing Pontus Irontoe lost his leg fighting the Lakandi and now walks on an iron foot attached to a wooden leg — hence his name. He is a skilled smith capable of both weapon and armor smithing, though he is often too busy for serious commissions. Irontoe has recently taken on several apprentices. His loud voice can frequently be heard chastising his students from across town. Key NPCs: Pontus Irontoe — Smith. Lost his leg fighting the Lakandi . Iron foot on wooden leg. Skilled but perpetually busy. Loud and demanding taskmaster. The House of Silence The church of Seros in Bone Creek. It was recently taken over by a young priest named Brother Marco after the previous priest, Father Draven , succumbed to disease. Brother Marco made the long trek to Bone Creek alone after claiming to have received a vision from Seros . He arrived malnourished and wounded, but undeterred. His weekly service now draws enough attendees that many must stand, spending hours in silent prayer. In a place as godless as Bone Creek, Marco&#39;s devotion has struck a chord. Key NPCs: Brother Marco — Young priest of Seros . Arrived alone after a vision. Malnourished and wounded on arrival. Services are standing-room-only. Father Draven (deceased) — Previous priest. Succumbed to disease. Known as a drunkard. Red River Exchange The largest building in town , owned and operated by the Red River Consortium . This is where Scalpers sell their plundered loot and treasure, and critically, where beastman scalps are sold in exchange for the Imperial Bounty (minus a transaction fee). The merchants of the Exchange are shrewd negotiators who employ an army of hardened guardsmen and bodyguards. The Exchange is both the economic heart of Bone Creek and the Consortium&#39;s seat of power in the settlement. Cassian Varro serves as Lord Merchant — a polished, shrewd businessman deeply involved in the local economy and political dealings of Bone Creek. He is a close ally of Tolliver Watts . Key NPCs: Cassian Varro — Lord Merchant. Red River Consortium representative. Polished and shrewd. Deeply involved in local politics and economy. Numerous hardened guardsmen and bodyguards (unnamed). Power Dynamics Bone Creek&#39;s politics revolve around three interconnected power blocs: Thaddeus Marr — Controls the Pretty Peach and the Flophouse (through Theo). Operates a secret racket. Backed by Crackback and street-level muscle. Represents the old, rough frontier way of doing things. Tolliver Watts — Controls Double Sevens. Backed by wealth, Madame Selka&#39;s operation, and Three-Finger Kanos&#39;s security. Allied with Cassian Varro. Represents the push toward civilization and order. Cassian Varro / Red River Consortium — Controls the Red River Exchange and the flow of money. The economic backbone of Bone Creek. Allied with Watts. The simmering rivalry between the Pretty Peach and Double Sevens has already resulted in large-scale brawls and shows no signs of cooling. This conflict mirrors a deeper tension in Bone Creek: whether the settlement will remain a lawless frontier outpost or evolve into something more civilized. Complete NPC Registry Name Location Role Theo The Flophouse Proprietor; secret informant for Marr ** thaddeus-marr Thaddeus Marr ** The Pretty Peach Crackback The Pretty Peach Targ pimp; Marr&#39;s right-hand man Trixie The Pretty Peach Young slave girl ** tolliver-watts Tolliver Watts ** Double Sevens Madame Selka Double Sevens Shenti madam; oversees working girls Frog Double Sevens Slave; assistant/advisor; expert administrator Three-Finger Kanos Double Sevens Bodyguard; head of security Royce Harbecke Tackle and Harness Shop co-owner Rhoda Harbecke Tackle and Harness Shop co-owner Greta Greta&#39;s Tinctures Alchemist; rumored witch Doc (Quinten) Bone Creek Surgery Barber surgeon Pontus Irontoe Irontoe Smithing Smith; lost leg fighting Lakandi ** brother-marco Brother Marco ** House of Silence Father Draven (deceased) House of Silence Former priest; drunkard ** cassian-varro Cassian Varro ** Red River Exchange See Also the-backlands — The province in which Bone Creek is located crossings — The sacked city whose fall created the Scalper trade beastmen — The creatures hunted for the Imperial Bounty red-river-consortium — The trading consortium that runs the Exchange thaddeus-marr — Proprietor of the Pretty Peach and local power broker tolliver-watts — Proprietor of Double Sevens and would-be civilizer cassian-varro — Lord Merchant of the Red River Exchange brother-marco — Priest of Seros at the House of Silence seros — The god worshipped at the House of Silence lakandi — The barbarians Irontoe fought before losing his leg mithrian-empire — The empire whose bounty drives the Scalper economy sanctuary — The nearest major port city in the Backlands"},{"slug":"cairnhill","title":"Cairnhill","category":"locations","tags":"location town cairnhouse kharai psychic-bleed dreams ygrathen argollean-brotherhood scrubland argolle backlands cairnhill-breaks mount-argolle thune harpies gilded-oath elvora","text":"Cairnhill Cairnhill is a town on the scrubland edge of the Province of Argolle , built around -- or rather, near -- a cairnhouse containing one or more of the Kharai , the Imprisoned Ones. The town and its people have been shaped by six to seven generations of exposure to the psychic bleed emanating from the cairnhouse: a slow, persistent pressure that has molded human consciousness into something subtly but distinctly different from the norm. Cairnhill is not a cursed place. Its people are not corrupted, damaged, or diminished. They are changed -- adapted, over generations, to a presence that most people cannot perceive and would not survive unchanged. The residents of Cairnhill are what happens when human beings live in close proximity to something vast and patient and fundamentally other for long enough that the otherness becomes part of who they are. The Cairnhouse The cairnhouse stands on the hill from which the town takes its name. It is a Ygrathen construction -- built using binding traditions that predate the Mithrian Empire by an unknown span of time, designed to imprison one or more of the Kharai using techniques no contemporary practitioner can replicate. The town does not allow anyone near the hill. This prohibition is not law in the Mithrian sense. It is not enforced by guards or fortifications. It is simply understood -- by the residents of Cairnhill, by the few outsiders who have reason to visit, by everyone who has learned what the hill is and what happens to those who approach it without the understanding that comes from having lived with it for generations. The people of Cairnhill protect the cairnhouse not because they worship what is inside, but because they know what it is and what would happen if the binding were disturbed. The Psychic Bleed The cairnhouse does not perfectly contain what is inside. The beings imprisoned within press against the walls of their binding constantly, with the patience of something that has more time than the dam. The pressure leaks. Over six to seven generations, this leakage -- the psychic bleed -- has shaped the people of Cairnhill. Effects on Residents Too-complete attention. Cairnhill residents attend to their surroundings with a focus and thoroughness that unsettles outsiders. Their gaze does not wander. Their awareness does not drift. They are present with an intensity that exceeds ordinary human attentiveness -- not hostile, not aggressive, simply fully, completely aware. Tolerance for enclosed spaces and darkness. Conditions that produce claustrophobia or discomfort in others are comfortable -- genuinely comfortable -- for Cairnhill residents. Tight spaces, deep darkness, the absence of sky and light -- these are not threatening environments. They are natural. This tolerance is not learned or cultivated. It is inherited, bred into the population by generations of proximity to something that exists in enclosed darkness. A different relationship to time. Cairnhill residents are patient in a way that exceeds discipline or temperament. They experience the passage of time at a different weight. Hours and days and seasons move through their awareness with a cadence that outsiders find difficult to match. They are not slow -- they are calibrated to a timescale that is not human. Perceptiveness below normal awareness. Cairnhill residents perceive things that others do not -- not visions or supernatural insight, but a baseline environmental awareness that operates below conscious attention. They notice what others miss. They feel shifts in atmosphere, mood, and presence that register nowhere in ordinary human perception. This is not a skill. It is a condition of their existence, shaped by generations of living beside something that communicates in pressures too subtle for normal senses. The Dreams Every resident of Cairnhill dreams of vast enclosed spaces . The dreams feature halls, corridors, and chambers of impossible scale -- structures too large to exist beneath any hill, lit by no visible source, built in geometries that are not quite wrong but not quite right. The spaces are immense, deeply other, and entirely real. They are not nightmares. They do not frighten. They simply are -- as present and persistent as the waking world, as familiar as the streets of the town itself. Residents of Cairnhill discuss the geography of their shared dreams with the casual familiarity of people discussing shared weather . They know the corridors. They recognize the chambers. They have navigated the impossible halls in sleep since childhood, and their parents before them, and their parents&#39; parents before them. The dream geography is as real to them as the physical geography of the town. It has never occurred to them that outsiders do not share the same dreams. This is perhaps the most telling indicator of how thoroughly the psychic bleed has shaped the community. The dreams are not aberrant. They are not discussed as unusual or remarkable. They are simply part of life -- as natural and unremarkable as the hill, as the darkness they do not fear, as the patience that runs deeper in them than it does in anyone else. The Argollean Brotherhood The Argollean Brotherhood seeks access to the cairnhouse for the Ygrathen binding structures it contains. The Brotherhood is not interested in the Kharai themselves -- they want the knowledge of how to bind them. The binding tradition that produced the cairnhouses represents an achievement of containment magic that no contemporary institution can replicate, and the Brotherhood considers this knowledge invaluable. The town of Cairnhill does not allow anyone near the hill. This tension has been building for years. The Brotherhood sends scholars, petitioners, negotiators. Cairnhill refuses them -- not with violence, not with argument, but with the implacable patience of people who have been shaped by something that has more time than anything built to contain it. The Brotherhood wants what it wants. Cairnhill will not give it. Neither side has yielded. The Brotherhood&#39;s frustration is compounded by the fact that the other known cairnhouse in Argolle -- the one at Lake Silverhead -- is watched over by Varek Ashstone , a Ygrathen hermit who has guarded his charge for centuries and is even less likely to permit access. The Cairnhill Breaks Three miles east of Cairnhill, the scrubland gives way to broken grey limestone ridges known as the Cairnhill Breaks . The terrain rises toward the eastern horizon where Mount Argolle stands, its white volcanic plume visible for miles across the province. The Breaks are a landscape of layered history: Lower gullies choked with maquis scrub -- dense, thorny Mediterranean-type vegetation that makes ground-level navigation slow and difficult Upper cliffs of bare limestone, carved by the First Empire into terraces, archways, and inscription panels -- monumental stonework that has survived centuries of weathering and neglect Highest crags occupied by harpy nests -- the winged predators have claimed the most inaccessible peaks, making aerial approach dangerous and establishing the Breaks as territory that sensible travelers avoid Mount Argolle Mount Argolle dominates the eastern horizon beyond the Cairnhill Breaks -- a volcanic peak whose white plume is a constant presence in the sky above the province. The mountain gives its name to the broader region of Argolle and serves as a geographic landmark visible from most of the surrounding territory. The volcanic activity is ongoing but not immediately threatening; the plume is a steady exhalation rather than an eruption. The Thune Remnant Among the lower ruins of the Cairnhill Breaks dwell the Thune remnant -- lizard-folk descendants of Argollean slave-soldiers who served the First Empire and never left after its collapse. They have inhabited the ruins of the Breaks for centuries, maintaining their own culture, their own relationship with the landscape, and their own understanding of what lies buried beneath the hills. The Thune remnant are not hostile by default, but they are territorial and wary. They regard the Cairnhill Breaks as ancestral ground -- not because their ancestors built the ruins (they did not) but because their ancestors were brought here as soldiers and never given anywhere else to go. The Breaks are the only home they have known for generations. Their relationship with the sealed Kharai is distinct from that of the Cairnhill townsfolk. While the human residents of Cairnhill have been shaped by the psychic bleed into something subtly other, the Thune remnant have developed a religious relationship with the imprisoned entity. Some among them regard the Kharai as a sleeping god -- a divine being imprisoned by the enemies of their people. This belief has produced factions like the Covenant of the Open Hand , a Thune group that seeks to weaken the seals and free what they consider a deity unjustly imprisoned. The weakening of the seals at the Gilded Vigil has emboldened the Thune remnant. They have grown bolder in recent months, pushing further from their usual territory and taking a more active interest in the guardian tomb network that threads through the Breaks. The Guardian Tomb Network The Cairnhill Breaks contain a network of Elvoran guardian tombs -- stations on a seal-circuit that reinforces the imprisonment of the Kharai beneath the hill. Each tomb houses a member of the Gilded Oath , warrior-priests who underwent the Sevenfold Wounding and entered a state of partial undeath to maintain the seals in perpetuity. The guardian tomb known as the Gilded Vigil -- the Second Seal station -- is the site where the guardian Veranthas has broken his covenant, weakening the seal network and drawing multiple factions to the Breaks. See Also the-kharai -- The Imprisoned Ones contained within the cairnhouse varek-ashstone -- The Ygrathen hermit guarding the other known cairnhouse lake-silverhead -- The location of the other cairnhouse in Argolle argollean-brotherhood -- The faction seeking cairnhouse access Ygrathen -- The builders of the cairnhouses the-backlands -- The province where Cairnhill is located cthonic-corruption -- The tradition from which the Kharai are notably distinct the-gilded-vigil -- The guardian tomb in the Cairnhill Breaks where the Second Seal has been compromised Elvoran -- The civilization that created the Gilded Oath and the seal-circuit Thune -- The lizard-folk remnant inhabiting the Breaks"},{"slug":"crossings-hinterlands","title":"The Crossings Hinterlands","category":"locations","tags":"wilderness hinterlands crossings backlands encounters","text":"The Crossings Hinterlands The Crossings Hinterlands are the territory immediately surrounding the ruined city of Crossings in the Backlands . This region is significantly more dangerous than the Slog -- beastman activity is dramatically higher here, and the encounter table reflects the proximity to a major beastman population center. The undead presence is also more severe, with wraiths and wights stalking alongside the living threats. Geography The Hinterlands form a ring of increasingly dangerous territory around the Crossings ruins. As travelers approach the ruined city, the frequency and lethality of encounters escalates sharply. The landscape transitions from the open scrub of the Slog into terrain marked by the ruins of outlying settlements, overgrown roads, and the detritus of the 377 IY sacking . Access Fort Harvald is the staging point for entering the Crossings Hinterlands. Parties venturing into this territory typically provision and gather intelligence at Fort Harvald before pushing into the Hinterlands and ultimately into Crossings itself. Encounter Table Roll 1d8 for each encounter: Roll Encounter Number 1 beastmen Beastman Orcs 2 beastmen Beastman Gnolls 3 beastmen Beastman Ogre 4 Grave Ghouls 1d6 5 Stirges 1d10 6 Wight 1d2 7 Wraith 1 8 Troll 1 The Hinterlands encounter table is notably more dangerous than the Slog&#39;s . Key differences: Beastman gnolls replace goblins -- gnolls are a more formidable threat than the goblin warbands of the Slog. Beastman ogres appear as a standalone encounter -- a single ogre is a serious threat to an unprepared party. Wraiths are present -- incorporeal undead that do not appear in the Slog&#39;s table. Their presence near Crossings may be connected to the Nethercity or the Awakening . Trolls cap the table, same as the Gallowswood . No brigands or human hostiles -- this territory is too deep into beastman country for human bandits to operate. See Also crossings -- The ruined city at the center of the Hinterlands fort-harvald -- The staging point for entering the Hinterlands the-slog -- The less dangerous wasteland south of the Hinterlands the-backlands -- The province containing the Hinterlands beastmen -- The dominant threat in the Hinterlands sacking-of-crossings -- The 377 IY event that created this wasteland the-nethercity -- The Eladran necropolis beneath Crossings the-awakening -- The Cthonic prophecy connected to the region"},{"slug":"crossings","title":"Crossings","category":"locations","tags":"ruins beastmen crossings nethercity erenthis krysea thornasse","text":"Crossings Crossings is a ruined Mithrian river city in the Backlands , located west of Fort Harvald at the delta of the Argoll River where it empties into Argent Bay . Once a major trade hub sitting at the convergence of seven imperial roads, the city was sacked by a vast, organized horde of beastmen in 377 IY (per the Fallen Empire Primer ; the Backlands timeline places this event at 374 IY -- note this discrepancy). The sacking prompted Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus to issue the imperial scalp bounty of one gold mark per beastman scalp, creating the entire Scalper trade and transforming Bone Creek from a dying silver-rush outpost into the epicenter of the bounty economy. Today, approximately 800 beastmen occupy the ruins, divided among five mutually hostile factions . The city is classified as Outlands (Ruins) -- a shattered monument to imperial failure, a haunted labyrinth crawling with beastmen, undead, and beasts, and a treasure trove of lost wealth from three distinct civilizations layered one atop another. At a Glance Detail Value Former Names Thornasse (Avari) / Krysea (First Empire / Eladran) Location West of Eladra when Mithra City was still a fishing village. High towers rose above the river delta. Krysea fell when its people were destroyed by the Thune slave soldiers they had created. The ruins were buried and forgotten -- but they are still down there, beneath the Avari foundations, beneath the Mithrian pavement. The Nethercity entrance at Location 32 leads down into what remains. Thornasse (Avari) The Avari built Thornasse around the great Erenthis trees left behind by the Eladra. The fruit of a single Erenthis could feed a dozen men. The roots ran down into something old and warm beneath the earth. The trees were sacred -- the largest, at the city center, served as the spiritual axis of the Avari Confederation for generations. Crossings (Mithrian, 349 IY onward) In 349 IY , the Mithrian High Mage Cynar burned the great Erenthis at the city center. Avari resistance collapsed. The Mithrians renamed the settlement Crossings , paved over the Avari foundations, and built baths, forums, and temples in the imperial style. The city thrived for 28 years before the sacking. The Sacking (377 IY) The sacking of Crossings was unlike anything the Backlands had seen. This was not the usual goblin warband or orc raider -- it was an organized, coordinated, vast assault. Three gates were breached simultaneously. The harbor was sealed before a single ship could flee. The killing lasted three days . Senator Cassius named the Governor directly: the relief force was delayed, recalled, or never existed. The Governor&#39;s only response was the scalp bounty. Who organized the horde? No one has answered this question. The beastmen in the ruins now are fractured, territorial, and mutually hostile -- nothing like the disciplined force that broke the gates. Something drove them together. Whatever it was, it does not appear to be doing so anymore. The City Today The Approaches For two miles in every direction from the walls, the landscape has been stripped bare. Beastmen scavenged all timber for fuel and crude palisades. The former dense river-forest is now a grey waste of stumps and bracken. Nothing grows above knee height. The sky sits large and cold. The river is clogged with filth -- six years of neglect. Fallen timber, detritus, and the occasional bloated body turning in the current. The smell reaches travelers a full mile out. First Sight The road ends at open wasteland. Where forest stood, stumps run to the horizon in every direction. The ruins of Crossings rise ahead across the river -- towers broken and scorched black. The great bridge still stands. Below it, the river runs slow and brown, carrying things you do not want to look at directly. The city behind the bridge is dark even in morning light. You can hear the aqueduct running somewhere inside. You can also hear drums. The Aqueduct The Mithrian aqueduct still functions . Water flows through channels beneath the streets -- a running, eerie constant throughout the ruins. The aqueduct serves as both a navigation tool and a hazard : the channels have destabilized several districts, and the [[#the-drowned-market|Drowned Market]] floods deeper every year. Underground or in enclosed spaces, the sound of running water imposes -1 to all Hear Noise throws . The main channels serve as reliable navigation landmarks throughout the city. The Lights At night, lights move in the Temple District . No one who investigated has returned with an explanation. The light comes from the eyes of the [[#the-hollow-father|Hollow Father]]. The Drum-Lullaby Sung by mothers in the Backlands: Don&#39;t look out, child, don&#39;t look at the window. Lay your head down; let me hum the drum. Count the night-fires -- one and two and three now. Head down, eyes closed, till the morning comes. What they take by night, they leave by morning. What is lost is lost, and gone is gone. But you are here, and I am here beside you. Head down, eyes closed, to the drum. Five Beastman Factions Approximately 800 beastmen inhabit the ruins, divided among five factions that are mutually hostile but share a wariness of armed unknowns. The organized force that broke the gates no longer exists -- what remains is a fractured, territorial patchwork. Goblins of the Scale Territory : Temple District Leader : The [[#the-hollow-father|Hollow Father]] Details : The goblins worship and obey an undead Elvoran mummy wrapped in cloth that speaks in a language no beastman should know. The lights that move at night in the Temple District come from the Hollow Father&#39;s eyes. The goblins carry maps and are more organized than typical goblin bands. Gnolls of the Governor Territory : The [[#the-governors-palace|Governor&#39;s Palace]] Leader : A gnoll war-chief Details : The gnoll war-chief holds a Mithrian noblewoman prisoner , captured six months ago. She may still be alive. Orcs of the Scar Territory : Old Quarter and Forum Details : The orcs roam the Old Quarter and the area around the Forum. Orc scavengers encountered in the deeper ruins are often lost and frightened -- separated from their warband and desperate. Hobgoblins of the Iron Ring Territory : The [[#the-iron-ring|Arena]] Details : The hobgoblins occupy the arena and demand tolls from anyone passing through their territory. The bridge tax is 1d6 gold marks per person . They keep the arena crypts locked and will not say why -- they have lost four of their own down there. Ghouls of the Bridge Territory : Beneath the [[#the-stone-yoke-bridge|Stone Yoke Bridge]] Details : Not truly a faction. They simply eat whoever falls. Ghouls beneath the Stone Yoke Bridge will not attack a person carrying Avari grave-goods -- the reason has been forgotten, but grandmothers in the Backlands still remember. Neutral Ground: The Forum of Seven Roads In the [[#the-forum-of-seven-roads|Forum of Seven Roads]], all beastmen observe the Neutral Ground rule -- no violence. Three factions trade there every tenday . This is the best place to talk to a beastman without being attacked on sight. Special Rules Structural Collapse When charging, ramming, or casting area spells in roofed structures, roll 1d6 . On a 1 , a roof or wall section becomes unstable and collapses the next round , dealing 2d8 damage (save vs. Petrification for half). Aqueduct Noise Running water imposes -1 to all Hear Noise throws when underground or in enclosed spaces. Main channels serve as reliable navigation landmarks. Beastman Reactions Five factions are mutually hostile but share wariness of armed unknowns. The Neutral Ground rule at the Forum of Seven Roads is universally observed. The Warm Ground In the Old Quarter near the [[#the-blackened-stump|Blackened Stump]], the ground is noticeably warm . Characters who sleep here experience vivid dreams of crystalline towers and a vast dark sky of wrong stars -- visions of ancient Krysea. Mages and Clerics who sleep on the warm ground recover spells normally but wake with one additional non-memorized cantrip lodged in their mind. Seven Districts and Thirty-Two Keyed Locations The Adventure Supplement maps the city into districts with level-appropriate content. The Approaches and Old Quarter (Locations 1-11) Level Range : 1st-3rd level This district covers the Stone Yoke Bridge, the Blackened Stump, and the ruined outskirts. It is the entry point for parties approaching from the south. Location 1: The Stone Yoke Bridge A massive Mithrian stone bridge of three arches , still intact, spanning the widest channel of the river delta. Built to endure centuries, it has survived the sacking where lesser structures crumbled. Its stones are stained dark with old smoke and river silt. Chains that once supported harbor gates now clatter in the wind like bones -- a haunting sound that echoes across the delta. A tribe of ghouls lives underneath the bridge, feeding on corpses dumped by the beastmen above. The ghouls are not interested in fighting -- they have a reliable food source and see no reason to risk conflict with the living. They will not attack anyone carrying Avari grave-goods . The bridge is the primary entry point into the ruins and could serve as a defensible position. The Blackened Stump A raised mound of overgrown vegetation choked with thick thorns, weeds, and thistle, from which the scorched stump of the great Erenthis juts into the air. A squat, ruined Mithrian barracks sits nearby, half-consumed by encroaching vegetation. The surrounding area radiates unnatural warmth -- the [[#the-warm-ground|Warm Ground]] effect described in Special Rules. A deranged and twisted dryad resides here, desperately trying to lure a fitting man to rebirth the dead tree. Her madness is driven by the death of her Erenthis -- the core of her being, the anchor of her existence. She is not evil in the traditional sense; she is broken, desperate, and willing to do terrible things to restore what she has lost. The Black Tree is not dead. Its roots still move. Whatever Cynar burned in 349 IY, he did not kill -- only changed it. Temple District and Civic Heart (Locations 12-22) Level Range : 3rd-5th level This district encompasses the territory of the Goblins of the Scale , the Forum of Seven Roads, and the Governor&#39;s Palace. It is the political and spiritual center of both the old city and the new beastman occupation. The Temple of the Balanced Scale A temple within the ruins, now occupied by the Goblins of the Scale and their master, the Hollow Father . The temple may be connected to the faith of Seros , the Balanced Scale. The Hollow Father The Hollow Father is an undead Elvoran mummy -- wrapped in cloth, speaking in a language no beastman should know. The lights that move through the Temple District at night come from its eyes. It commands the goblins absolutely. The combination of beastman muscle and ancient undead intelligence makes this one of the most dangerous locations in the ruins. The Hollow Father&#39;s presence raises critical questions: What is an Elvoran mummy doing in a Mithrian city built on Avari foundations built on Eladran ruins? How old is it? What does it want? The Forum of Seven Roads A wide stone plaza where seven paved imperial roads converged -- the physical and symbolic heart of Crossings. Broken columns ring the space, inscribed with distances, tolls, and imperial decrees. Statues of Mithrian magistrates lie toppled, faces shattered. The beastmen use the Forum as neutral ground . Three factions trade here every tenday . No violence is permitted -- a rule observed since the Sacking itself. This is the best place to talk to a beastman without immediate combat. The Forum floor is cracked. The ground beneath is hollow -- ancient tunnels, some say Eladran, some say older. The Governor&#39;s Palace Occupied by the Gnolls of the Governor . The gnoll war-chief holds a Mithrian noblewoman prisoner , captured six months ago. She may still be alive. The rumor of a governor&#39;s safe room in the palace basement, stocked for siege, is false . The Governor&#39;s Walk A raised colonnade overlooking the river delta, once used for processions and civic announcements. Statues of lawgivers line the colonnade -- heads smashed, torsos scarred by beastman desecration. The wind whistles through the columns like low voices -- a haunting acoustic effect created by the architecture interacting with river breezes. Harbor, Drowned Market, and Iron Ring District (Locations 23-32) Level Range : 4th-6th level This district covers the hobgoblin-controlled arena, the flooded commercial district, and the harbor ruins. The Drowned Market Once the commercial heart of Crossings, now knee- to waist-deep in water fed by the still-functioning aqueduct. Stone stalls and counting houses stand half-submerged. The district floods deeper every year. A corrupted giant crocodile has moved into the flooded district -- size of a boat, twisted by evil energies. It has eaten three scalpers in the last season alone. The Broken Harbor Rotting piers, capsized ships, and shattered cranes define the Broken Harbor. The harbor silted up after the sacking , trapping ship hulls in the mud. Tar and pitch still cling to the harbor stones. A colony of giant crabs has moved into the harbor, nesting among the wrecked ships. The Iron Ring A half-collapsed stone arena with tiered seating. The sands are dark with old blood. Rusted portcullises beneath the arena floor still grind open when disturbed -- the mechanical systems are partially functional. Bones litter the edges of the arena floor, carefully stacked in places -- someone or something has been organizing the dead. The Hobgoblins of the Iron Ring occupy the arena and control access. They keep the arena crypts locked and will not say why. They have lost four of their own down there. The Salt Baths Once a vast public bath complex fed by the aqueduct. The roof has collapsed , exposing steaming basins crusted with white salt and lime. Broken mosaics on remaining walls depict scenes of civic life -- citizens bathing, merchants trading, officials deliberating. These are among the best-preserved artistic remnants of the pre-sacking city. The Counting Halls A row of long stone buildings once used by guilds and trade houses. Vault doors hang open -- contents long looted. Shelves of ledgers rot in the damp air. Counting tables remain, covered in meaningless tally marks scratched by beastmen. A sealed vault exists beneath the Counting Halls. The combination is cut into the underside of the Registrar&#39;s desk . Location 32: The Nethercity Entrance The deepest point in the mapped ruins. This entrance connects to a deeper dungeon -- the remains of ancient Krysea and whatever lies beneath it. Appropriate for any level willing to face what waits below. The Forum floor cracks hint at what is down there: ancient tunnels, some Eladran, some older. The aqueduct taps the same water table. That is why the water tastes of iron. Rumors (d12) Roll Rumor Truth 1 Goblins worship something old wrapped in cloth that speaks in an unknown language. Light at night comes from its eyes. True 2 The Black Tree is not dead. Roots move. Whatever Cynar burned, he did not kill -- only changed it. True 3 Gnoll war-chief in Governor&#39;s Palace has a Mithrian noblewoman prisoner, captured 6 months ago, may still be alive. True 4 Sealed vault under the Counting Halls. Combination cut into underside of Registrar&#39;s desk. Partly true 5 Forum floor is cracked -- ground hollow beneath. Ancient tunnels, some say Eladran, some say older. Partly true 6 Crocodile in the flooded market is the size of a boat. Ate three scalpers last season. Partly true 7 Hobgoblins keep the arena crypts locked. Won&#39;t say why. Lost four of their own down there. Partly true 8 Whole district on east side beastmen never go near. Streets perfectly clean. Like nothing happened. False 9 Ghouls under Stone Yoke Bridge will not attack a person carrying Avari grave-goods. Grandmother knew why. True 10 Governor&#39;s safe room still intact in palace basement, stocked for siege. False 11 Beastmen don&#39;t fight in the Forum -- neutral ground since the Sacking. Three factions trade every tenday. True 12 Crossings sits on Krysea. Krysea sits on something with no name. Aqueduct taps same water table. That&#39;s why water tastes of iron. Partly true Encounter Tables Table A: Open Ruins (d20) Roll Encounter 1-2 Goblin Patrols 3-4 Orc Raiders 5-6 Hobgoblin Toll Parties 7-8 Gnoll Hunters 9 Warg Packs 10 Grave Ghouls 11 Zombies 12 Skeleton Patrols 13 Strix 14 Giant Crab Spiders 15-16 Rival Scalpers 17 Beastman Duels 18 Structural Collapse 19 Aqueduct Burst 20 Wights Table B: Old Quarter and Temple District (d20) Roll Encounter 1-2 Goblin Gangs (carry maps) 3-4 Skeleton Sentinels (immune to fire, wearing Thune-era armor) 5-6 Orc Scavengers (lost and frightened) 7-8 Goblin Champions 9-10 Zombie Congregations (shuffle toward Temple District in procession) 11-12 Wights 13-14 Hollow Father&#39;s Eye (goblin shaman observer) 15 Dryad&#39;s Lure 16-17 Corrupted Ground (revealing Krysean stairs) 18-19 Skeleton Throngs 20 The Hollow Father itself (with honor guard) Strategic Significance Crossings remains strategically vital despite its destruction: Forward Base : The beastmen use the ruins as a forward base for pushing south into imperial territory. As long as they hold Crossings, they have a fortified position from which to launch raids. Seven Roads : The seven paved imperial roads that once brought trade now provide beastmen with routes of advance into the Backlands. River Crossing : The Stone Yoke Bridge controls movement across the delta. Whoever holds the bridge controls the river. Lost Wealth : The ruins contain Mithrian wealth -- the sealed vault beneath the Counting Halls, the treasures of the Temple, the cargo of the Broken Harbor -- along with Eladran artifacts in the Nethercity below. Recapture : Taking Crossings back would deal a devastating blow to beastman power in the Backlands and restore imperial control over a critical trade route. The Nethercity : Whatever lies beneath the ruins -- Krysea, and whatever Krysea sits on -- represents a deeper mystery and a deeper danger than the surface occupation. See Also the-backlands -- The frontier province where Crossings is located fort-harvald -- The nearest imperial fortification, east of the ruins argoll-river -- The river at whose delta Crossings stands bone-creek -- The Scalper settlement that exists because of Crossings&#39; fall beastmen -- The creatures who sacked and now occupy the city mithrian-empire -- The empire that built and lost Crossings Cynar -- The High Mage who burned the great Erenthis in 349 IY Erenthis -- The sacred Avari trees, one of which still lives beneath the Blackened Stump Nethercity -- The ancient Eladran ruins beneath the city scalper-gangs -- The gangs that hunt beastmen in response to the fall of Crossings red-river-consortium -- The trading company that profits from the scalp bounty cassian-varro -- The Lord Merchant who oversees bounty redemption races-and-cultures -- The Eladran, Avari, and Mithrian peoples connected to Crossings&#39; history seros -- The faith of the Balanced Scale; the Temple may be connected to this tradition thune -- The slave soldiers who destroyed Krysea"},{"slug":"dunwick","title":"Dunwick","category":"locations","tags":"location town backlands coastal-plain seros bel earth-hunger farming argolle brother-cavin cthonic","text":"Dunwick A fine town. Good fields. Good people. The temple is well-attended and the harvest is generous. One might almost call it blessed -- if one did not look too carefully at who is absent on which days, and why. Dunwick is a farming town on the coastal plain of the Backlands , in the province of Argolle . It is one of the wealthier agricultural communities in the region -- prosperous, hospitable, and unremarkable to the casual visitor. Its fields produce harvests that exceed what soil and climate alone can explain. Beneath the surface, Dunwick is entangled in the ancient agricultural blood rites of Bel-tharach -- the earth-hunger . At a Glance Detail Description Location Coastal plain of Backlands can be civilized. The prosperity is real. It is also sustained by something that predates the Mithrian Empire , the Thousand Temples , and the faith of Seros by centuries. The farming villages of the coastal plain -- Dunwick among them -- practice agricultural blood rites tied to the cycle of planting, petition, and sacrifice. These rites share a name and possibly an identity with Bel the Slaughterprince , the Cthonic war-god of blood, conquest, and slaughter. The community does not discuss these rites with outsiders. Questions about them are met not with evasion but with silence -- the silence of people who have decided, collectively and without discussion, that outsiders do not need to know. The Temple of Seros Dunwick maintains a Temple of Seros in the town square. It is well-built, well-attended, and entirely orthodox in its public presentation. The people come to services. They observe the holy days. They tithe. Everything appears in order. It is the absences that accumulate. Certain families do not attend temple on certain days. Certain holy days, planting days, and harvest days see particular members of the congregation simply vanish from the pews. No explanation is offered. None is expected. The temple stands as a genuine institution of the Empyrean faith -- but it exists alongside something older, and the two have reached an accommodation that the Thousand Temples would condemn if it understood its nature. Brother Cavin Brother Cavin is a young priest of Seros assigned to Dunwick&#39;s temple. He is a man of genuine piety -- sincere, earnest, and committed to his calling. He has been at his posting for two years. He is deeply uncomfortable. Detail Description Role Priest of Bel-tharach -- the earth-hunger. These rites follow the agricultural year: Blood offering at planting -- Blood is given to the earth at the beginning of the growing season. The specifics vary by community. Petition at harvest -- Gratitude for what the earth has given, acknowledgment of what the earth has taken, a request for continued favor. This is not prayer -- it is transaction. Sacrifice at the year&#39;s close -- The most significant of the three rites, and the one about which outsiders know the least. The sacrifice closes the cycle, settles the account, and prepares the ground for the next year&#39;s exchange. The demands have grown over generations. What begins as modest exchange becomes, over time, something that cannot be unmade without cost. Each generation inherits a more prosperous arrangement and a more demanding patron. See Also bel-earth-hunger -- The agricultural blood rites practiced in Dunwick&#39;s surrounding villages seros -- The Empyrean god whose temple stands in Dunwick the-backlands -- The province in which Dunwick is located Argolle -- The province containing Dunwick&#39;s coastal plain cthonic-corruption -- The tradition to which the earth-hunger may belong thousand-temples -- The institution that would condemn Dunwick&#39;s rites empyrean-faith -- The official faith Dunwick publicly observes the-convergence-problem -- The theological crisis of Empyrean/Cthonic mirroring relevant to Dunwick"},{"slug":"fort-harvald","title":"Fort Harvald","category":"locations","tags":"location settlement fort backlands border-forts frontier crossings avari refugees bayou beastmen nethercity argolle","text":"Fort Harvald On a foggy morning the towers of Crossings rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man. The old ones say you can hear it breathing. -- local saying Fort Harvald is a small, battered frontier settlement in the Backlands , built around the remains of an imperial border fort. It sits mere miles from the ruins of Crossings -- close enough that the broken skyline of the destroyed city is visible on the horizon. Fort Harvald is not a garrison in any meaningful strategic sense. It is a place where people come to be forgotten -- Avari refugees who lost everything in the Sacking of Crossings , loggers, trappers, river folk, and scalpers drawn by the beastman bounty. The tone of the settlement is one of suspended grief: a bayou frontier outpost living in the permanent shadow of catastrophe. At a Glance Detail Description Population Low hundreds Inhabitants Avari refugees, loggers, trappers, river folk, scalper-gangs Garrison 10 soldiers Commanding Officer [[sergeant-voss Dominant Powers Voss (military), [[fort-harvald Proximity to Crossings Miles -- ruins visible on horizon Beastman Threat High -- enormous herds near [[Crossings , far more dangerous than northern Backlands Tone Suspended grief. Bayou frontier. A place for the forgotten. The Fort Fort Harvald is built on solid Argollean -era stone foundations -- ancient masonry that has endured for millennia -- with later Mithrian additions in varying states of disrepair. The walls hold. The interior buildings do not. Leaking roofs, rotted barracks, and a collapsed storehouse define the garrison&#39;s physical condition. The garrison flag has faded to near-white -- a detail that says everything about the Empire&#39;s investment in this posting. The fort was never meant to be a settlement. It was a military installation, part of the chain of border forts constructed after the failed Lakan Campaigns . But after the Sacking of Crossings , refugees, drifters, and opportunists gathered around it, and a community of sorts coalesced in the shadow of its walls. The fort is now the administrative and military center of a settlement that has no formal charter, no imperial recognition, and no future that anyone here cares to discuss. Salvage from Crossings has been built into Fort Harvald&#39;s walls and structures. Crossings is literally underfoot -- its stones, its timbers, its memory woven into the fabric of the place that replaced it. Garrison The garrison of Fort Harvald consists of ten soldiers under the command of Sergeant Aldric Voss . This is not a prestigious posting. It is a punishment, a dead end, or a first assignment for those who drew the shortest straw. Despite this, the garrison functions -- largely due to Voss&#39;s stubborn competence. Sergeant Aldric Voss Main article: Sergeant Aldric Voss Aldric Voss is a Mithrian male in his late 40s. He was once a capable and promising soldier -- the kind of career officer who should have risen to command a company or a fort of actual strategic significance. One political mistake buried him here permanently: he supported the wrong Senator in a dispute with the Legate-Governor , and his career was over. He was passed over for promotion and assigned to Fort Harvald, where he has remained ever since. Voss runs a tight ship. He is not corrupt -- a rarity in the Backlands . He knows that Silvan Orro reports to the Governor, but he has said nothing about it yet. Whether this silence represents calculation, resignation, or simply the exhaustion of a man who has spent years fighting battles he cannot win is unclear. Garrison Personnel Corin bar-Aldric -- Avari local. His family lives in the Refugee Quarter. His loyalty to the garrison is conditional on the garrison&#39;s treatment of his people. He serves because it puts food on the table and gives his family a measure of protection, not because he believes in the Empire. Essa von-Halvard -- Avari local, Corin&#39;s sister. Quieter and more watchful than her brother. She knows the delta paths -- the waterways, the mud tracks, the routes through the marshland that no map records. An invaluable asset for anyone venturing into the wilderness. Tomas Fides -- Young. This is his first posting. He is visibly terrified -- of the beastmen, of the ruins, of the sounds that carry across the delta at night, of everything. He will attach himself to any courageous figure who shows him kindness or leadership. He has written four unsent letters home. Old Brek -- Veteran. Was in Crossings when it fell. He never speaks of it. He knows the ruins of Crossings intimately -- their layout, their dangers, their secrets. Getting him to share that knowledge would require extraordinary trust or extraordinary need. The Other Six -- Reliable, professional, unremarkable. They are loyal to Voss personally more than to the Empire -- a distinction that matters in a place where the Empire has effectively abandoned its own. Key Locations The Fur Shed The social heart of Fort Harvald. Not a tavern in any formal sense -- more of a trading post, gathering place, and community center rolled into one. The Fur Shed is where news is exchanged, deals are struck, disputes are mediated, and the settlement&#39;s fragile social fabric is maintained. Maren Ashfoot -- Avari female, 50s -- runs the Fur Shed. She was born in Crossings , lost everything in the sacking, and rebuilt herself here through sheer force of will. Maren knows everyone in Fort Harvald and most of what happens within it. She is the settlement&#39;s unofficial leader in all matters not involving the garrison. Maren maintains a hidden stash of Crossings salvage -- artifacts, valuables, and personal effects recovered from the ruins. The nature and significance of this stash are known to very few. Whether she keeps it as a memorial, as insurance, or for some other purpose, only Maren knows. The Refugee Quarter The largest concentration of Avari in Fort Harvald. The Quarter was built almost entirely from salvage scavenged from Crossings -- timber, stone, ironwork, and domestic objects carried across the delta by refugees who had nothing else. The architecture is improvised and ramshackle, but there is a fierce dignity to it -- the refusal of a displaced people to simply disappear. Elder Havar bar-Kessian -- Avari male, 70s -- is the unofficial leader of the Refugee Quarter. He remembers Crossings in its prime, before the sacking, when it was a thriving settlement with markets, temples, and a future. Havar maintains a ledger of every Crossings dead, recorded by name -- a labor of grief and memory that he has pursued with obsessive dedication since the sacking. The ledger is the most complete record of the dead that exists. Havar suspects imperial complicity in the Sacking of Crossings . He believes -- though he cannot prove -- that the destruction was enabled not merely by negligence but by deliberate betrayal: that someone in the Imperial hierarchy profited from the fall of Crossings or allowed it to happen to serve a political end. He has no proof. The suspicion eats at him. River Trade Post The commercial hub of Fort Harvald, located on the waterfront where river traffic connects the settlement to the broader trade networks of the Backlands . Silvan Orro -- Mithrian male, 40s -- operates the River Trade Post. He is too polished for this posting. His manners, his dress, his connections, and his resources all suggest a man who belongs in a provincial capital, not a bayou frontier settlement. Orro is connected to Cassian Varro and the Red River Consortium , and he almost certainly functions as an intelligence asset for the Governor -- reporting on conditions, personalities, and activities in Fort Harvald and the surrounding region. Sergeant Voss knows what Orro is. He has said nothing about it yet. Skinning Grounds The processing area where scalpers bring their kills and where beastman hides, teeth, claws, and scalps are weighed, graded, and prepared for transport. The smell is indescribable. Pek -- Targ male, heavily scarred, missing his right ear -- runs the weighing station at the Skinning Grounds. Pek keeps private shorthand records of the transactions that pass through his station -- records written in a notation that no one else in Fort Harvald can read. Someone pays for this information. Who, and what they do with it, is unknown. Shrine of the Unnamed A small, rough-built shrine at the edge of the settlement where the Avari of Fort Harvald gather for worship, remembrance, and grief. Brother Ossian -- Avari male, 30s -- tends the shrine. He has no formal religious training. His rites are syncretic -- a blend of Empyrean worship, older Avari traditions, and a folk cult of remembrance for the dead of Crossings . The shrine serves a community that has lost its temples, its priests, and its certainties, and Ossian has improvised a spiritual practice from the wreckage. Small supernatural events have been occurring at the shrine. Candles light themselves. Names appear on the memorial wall that Ossian did not write. These events are subtle, infrequent, and deeply unsettling. Ossian has noticed. He has told no one . Noma of the Shallows Main article: Noma of the Shallows Noma lives apart from the settlement, on a platform structure built over a backwater channel in the marshes. Her race and age are unknown. She speaks with what might be a Corcanoan accent. She worships something old -- something that has no name and predates the Empyrean and Cthonic theological frameworks. Noma has lived here longer than anyone can remember -- which is a problem, because the settlement of Fort Harvald is only a few years old. She was here before the settlement existed, before the refugees came, before the Sacking of Crossings . How long she has been here, and what sustained her in the marshes alone, is unknown. Noma knows what lies in the Nethercity . She may not say freely. Those who seek her out may find that her knowledge comes at a price, or with conditions, or wrapped in riddles that only make sense when it is too late. The Shadow of Crossings Fort Harvald exists in the permanent shadow of Crossings -- physically, psychologically, and spiritually. The ruins of the destroyed city are close enough to shape every aspect of life in the settlement. On clear days , the broken skyline of Crossings is visible on the horizon. The people of Fort Harvald have learned not to look too long. On foggy mornings , the tower silhouettes rise from the mist -- somehow worse than seeing them clearly. The local saying captures it precisely: the towers rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man. At night , lights move in the ruins. No one investigates. No one has investigated for a long time. Whatever moves in Crossings after dark, the people of Fort Harvald have made their peace with not knowing. Sounds carry across the delta at night. They are not always identifiable. They are always wrong. The Skin Eaters recently killed 300 Beastmen in the ruins of Crossings and report that terrifying monsters lurk deeper within -- things worse than beastmen, things that suggest the ruins connect to something far older and more dangerous than a razed frontier town. Salvage from Crossings is built into the walls, structures, and foundations of Fort Harvald. Crossings is literally underfoot. The dead city&#39;s bones are the living settlement&#39;s skeleton. Hooks and Tensions Voss and Orro : The sergeant knows the trader is a spy. The spy does not know he has been identified. This standoff cannot last. Havar&#39;s Suspicion : The elder believes the Empire let Crossings fall on purpose. If he finds proof, the consequences for Fort Harvald -- and for the Governor -- could be severe. The Shrine : Something supernatural is happening at the Shrine of the Unnamed. Brother Ossian is keeping it secret, but the events are escalating. Noma : A woman of unknown race and age who predates the settlement she lives beside and who knows the secrets of the Nethercity . Her presence raises questions that no one in Fort Harvald is equipped to answer. The Ruins : Crossings is not empty. It is not safe. The monsters within are worse than beastmen. And the ruins may connect to the Nethercity -- to the ancient Argollean underworld that predates the Empire by millennia. Pek&#39;s Records : Someone is paying the Targ at the Skinning Grounds for intelligence. Who, and why? See Also Crossings -- The destroyed city whose shadow defines Fort Harvald Sacking of Crossings -- The catastrophe that created the settlement Sergeant Aldric Voss -- Commanding officer of the garrison Noma of the Shallows -- The mysterious hermit of the marshes Maren Ashfoot -- Unofficial leader of the civilian community Silvan Orro -- River trader and probable intelligence asset Havar bar-Kessian -- Elder of the Refugee Quarter Brother Ossian -- Keeper of the Shrine of the Unnamed Cassian Varro -- Lord Merchant of the Red River Consortium Red River Consortium -- Trade organization connected to Orro Skin Eaters -- Scalper company active in the Crossings ruins Nethercity -- The ancient Argollean underworld beneath Crossings The Backlands -- The frontier province Avari -- The displaced people of Crossings Lakan Campaigns -- The failed campaigns that prompted the border forts Scalper -- The bounty economy that draws killers to the frontier"},{"slug":"fort-ikenvar","title":"Fort Ikenvar","category":"locations","tags":"location military fort ruin marsh backlands border-forts rook the-guzzler demonic stone-of-sakkara frontier","text":"Fort Ikenvar There is nothing left of Fort Ikenvar that resembles a fort. The walls have slumped into the bog. The gates are gone. The barracks are flooded to the eaves. What remains is a ruin in the process of being swallowed by the earth -- and something in that ruin that swallows everything else. Fort Ikenvar is a ruined imperial marsh fort east of Fort Meade in the Backlands . Once a functional outpost in the chain of border forts constructed after the failed Lakan Campaigns , it has collapsed into the wetland and is now little more than a half-sunken ruin in a bog. It is occupied by the Guzzler -- a demonic entity of unknown origin that hungers without intelligence, purpose, or agenda. At a Glance Detail Description Location East of Backlands frontier. It formed part of the chain of border forts alongside Fort Meade and Fort Harvald , constructed after the failed Lakan Campaigns to secure the Empire&#39;s frontier. At some point, the fort&#39;s foundations gave way to the marsh beneath them, and the structure began its slow collapse into the wetland. The garrison was withdrawn and the fort was abandoned. What remains is a ruin in the process of being consumed by the earth -- walls slumped into bog, gates gone, barracks flooded. The marsh has reclaimed most of the structure, and what stands above the waterline is unstable, rotting, and treacherous. Rook&#39;s Base of Operations The bandit leader Rook used Fort Ikenvar as his base of operations during his campaign of terror against the settlements and trade routes of the Backlands . The ruin&#39;s remote location in the marsh made it difficult for the garrison at Fort Meade to locate and assault -- the approach was treacherous, the terrain favored the defender, and the fort&#39;s very ruination made it an unlikely place for anyone to look. Rook&#39;s banditry grew increasingly violent over time -- targeted attacks on residents, disappeared travelers, deliberate intimidation campaigns. The garrison at Fort Meade could not resolve the threat. The Reclaimers ultimately tracked Rook to Fort Ikenvar and destroyed him there, ending the bandit crisis that had terrorized the region for months. This victory was experienced by Legate Marcellus as both a professional humiliation and a political opportunity. The Guzzler Following Rook&#39;s destruction, the Guzzler -- a demonic entity of unknown origin -- took up residence in the ruins of Fort Ikenvar. Detail Description Nature Demonic entity Intelligence None in any meaningful sense Motivation Hunger. It eats what it finds. It does not discriminate. Containment Generally contained to the marsh, but this containment is not absolute Current Threat Drawn toward Fort Meade by the presence of the Stone of Sakkara , which Theodotus carries. The entity cannot precisely locate the Stone, but it can sense its pull. This attraction has compromised the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature. The ~100 soldiers garrisoned at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. If the Guzzler is drawn out of the marsh in force, the garrison will face a threat it was never designed to counter. Strategic Significance Fort Ikenvar&#39;s destruction removed the eastern anchor from the chain of border forts. Where three forts once provided overlapping coverage -- Harvald on the west, Meade in the center, Ikenvar on the east -- only two remain functional. The eastern approach to the Backlands is now undefended by permanent fortification, covered only by patrols and the natural barrier of the marsh itself. The marsh that consumed the fort now serves as the primary barrier on the eastern approach -- an unreliable substitute for stone walls and a garrison. See Also fort-meade -- The central garrison west of Fort Ikenvar fort-harvald -- The western border fort, still functional the-guzzler -- The demonic entity occupying the ruins rook -- The bandit who used Fort Ikenvar as his base Reclaimers -- The party that destroyed Rook at Fort Ikenvar Stone of Sakkara -- The artifact drawing the Guzzler toward Fort Meade theodotus -- The Reclaimer who carries the Stone of Sakkara legate-marcellus -- Commander of the Backlands garrison the-backlands -- The province in which Fort Ikenvar stands lakan-campaigns -- The failed campaigns that prompted construction of the border forts"},{"slug":"fort-meade","title":"Fort Meade (Fort Caldras)","category":"locations","tags":"location military garrison fort backlands trade-route frontier border-forts","text":"Fort Meade (Fort Caldras) Naming Note: The Backlands Regional Overview uses Fort Caldras consistently for this location. All other sources use Fort Meade. These are the same installation. The wiki uses Fort Meade as the primary name with Fort Caldras as an alias. The road to Bone Creek runs through Fort Meade. Every coin, every crust of bread, every soldier who ever held that frontier passed through these gates. Marcellus knows it. The Governor knows it. The difference is only one of them acts on it. Fort Meade is the most strategically significant military installation in the Backlands . It controls the flow of food, goods, soldiers, information, and coin between the imperial interior and the frontier. The settlement around the fort exists to support it, not the other way around. At a Glance Detail Description Location South of Backlands . It controls the flow of food, goods, soldiers, information, and coin between the imperial interior and the frontier. Bone Creek cannot survive long without supply caravans passing through Fort Meade. The settlement around the fort exists to support the garrison, not the other way around. There is no entertainment district, no gambling hall, no brothel quarter. Vice is informal and tolerated so long as it does not interfere with garrison function. The garrison&#39;s mean streak -- a reflection of Legate Marcellus himself -- sets the tone. People here are practical, cautious, and not inclined to involve themselves in affairs that are not their own. The Trade Route Fort Meade sits astride the central trade route between Sanctuary and Bone Creek , making it the primary chokepoint for all commerce and supply flowing to and from the frontier. Northbound to Bone Creek Food staples Salt Tools Rope Lamp oil Manufactured goods Replacement soldiers (rarely) Correspondence Coin Southbound to Sanctuary Beastman scalps Relics and salvage Furs and pelts Raw timber Occasional prisoners Reports to the Governor Revenue and Political Leverage Fort Meade levies taxes and fees on all goods passing in both directions -- this generates considerable revenue. Legate Marcellus uses this revenue to: Maintain his soldiers&#39; loyalty Fund intelligence operations against the Governor Support household expenses The food dependency of Bone Creek is Fort Meade&#39;s most significant political weapon. If the Legate embargoed caravans, Bone Creek would feel it within weeks. The political war between the Legate and the Governor has remained cold precisely because of this mutual awareness -- the Legate applies enough pressure to remind the Governor of dependence, but not enough to justify formal reprisal. Rook&#39;s Banditry -- The Wounds That Remain Months of Rook&#39;s banditry left deep wounds on Fort Meade and its surroundings. The bandits grew increasingly violent over time -- targeted attacks on residents, disappeared travelers, deliberate intimidation campaigns. The anxiety of that period has not fully lifted. People are relieved that Rook is dead, but they remember how close things came to breaking. The Reclaimers ultimately delivered what the garrison could not -- the destruction of Rook at Fort Ikenvar . This fact is not lost on the Legate, who experienced it as both a professional humiliation and a political opportunity. Fort Ikenvar -- Nearby Threat Fort Ikenvar sits east of Fort Meade in a sunken marsh. It was once a functional imperial outpost but is now a ruin sinking into a bog. Rook used it as his base of operations before the Reclaimers destroyed him there. The Guzzler The Guzzler -- a demonic entity of unknown origin -- now occupies Fort Ikenvar. It is not intelligent in any meaningful sense. It simply hungers and eats what it finds. It does not discriminate and has no agenda beyond feeding. Residents of Fort Meade fear the Guzzler with particular dread. The entity is generally contained to the marsh, but this containment is not absolute. The Guzzler has been drawn toward Fort Meade by the presence of the Stone of Sakkara , which Theodotus carries. It cannot precisely locate the Stone, but it can sense its pull. Key Figures Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus -- Commanding officer. Cold, calculating, quietly cruel. Commands ~100 soldiers. House Valerian. Lady Severina Marcellus -- The Legate&#39;s wife. More politically sophisticated than her husband. The real political engine of the household. Malachor -- Imperial Academy historian. Scholarly, manipulative, in love with Severina. Cataloguing artifacts from the frontier. Sergeant Davan Crull -- The Legate&#39;s enforcer at ground level. Eleven years of service have compressed him into something hard and efficient. Arannis Venn -- Local leader of the Argollean Brotherhood (covert). Power Factions The Legate&#39;s Household Marcellus and Severina operate as a political unit, though their methods differ sharply. The Legate commands through cold authority; Severina moves people through warmth, curiosity, and social intelligence. Between them, they control the garrison, the trade route revenue, and the flow of information. The Argollean Brotherhood (Covert) The Argollean Brotherhood has members embedded in the settlement, though they remain unidentified. Their primary interest is the flow of artifacts from the Crossings ruins and the Nethercity . They are not aggressive toward the general population. Fort Meade&#39;s position on the trade route makes it a natural waypoint for their operations. The Imperial Academy (Malachor) Malachor represents the Imperial Academy&#39;s interests -- documenting the province&#39;s history and cataloguing recovered artifacts. His presence creates friction with the Brotherhood , as both factions want the same relics for very different reasons. See Also bone-creek -- The frontier settlement dependent on Fort Meade&#39;s supply route sanctuary -- Southern terminus of the trade route legate-marcellus -- Commanding officer of Fort Meade lady-severina -- The Legate&#39;s wife and political partner malachor -- Imperial Academy historian stationed at Fort Meade sergeant-crull -- Senior NCO and the Legate&#39;s enforcer fort-ikenvar -- Ruined marsh fort east of Fort Meade, lair of the Guzzler the-guzzler -- Demonic entity occupying Fort Ikenvar rook -- The bandit whose campaign terrorized the region argollean-brotherhood -- Covert criminal network with presence in Fort Meade imperial-academy -- The scholarly institution Malachor represents the-backlands -- The province in which Fort Meade stands governor-drussus -- The Legate&#39;s political rival Stone of Sakkara -- Artifact drawing the Guzzler toward Fort Meade Reclaimers -- The party who destroyed Rook and resolved the bandit crisis"},{"slug":"gallowswood","title":"Gallowswood","category":"locations","tags":"wilderness forest cursed backlands encounters outlands abominations","text":"Gallowswood Men who enter the Gallowswood armed come back afraid. Men who enter unarmed do not come back. Gallowswood is a vast, cursed deciduous forest west of Bone Creek in the Backlands . Dense with ancient oaks whose boughs choke the moonlight, the Gallowswood is a place where the dead walk beneath the roots. It is classified as Outlands territory -- a step beyond the Borderlands, deeper into the wild, and significantly more dangerous than the Slog . Geography There is a quality of silence in the Gallowswood. A specific silence, like the forest holding its breath. When that silence comes, something is watching. Something is waiting. -- Unnamed woodsman The Gallowswood is a vast deciduous forest of ancient oaks, grey ash, and black-barked hawthorn. The canopy is thick enough to turn noon into dusk -- a green, uncertain light filters to the forest floor even at midday, and by evening the interior is pitch black. The undergrowth is thick with tangled roots, moss-covered deadfall, and thickets of bramble that make movement slow and navigation difficult. This is not merely an old forest in tree terms. It is old in the way places remember things. The Avari knew it as sacred and dangerous before the Argolleans arrived. Avari warnings are still carved on stones at its borders -- and the Avari do not waste effort on warnings they do not mean. The forest represents the untamed character of the Backlands frontier -- territory that the Mithrian Empire claims on maps but does not control in practice. The chain of border forts defends against incursions from the wilderness beyond, but regions like the Gallowswood exist within the nominal borders of the province, reminders that imperial authority thins rapidly beyond the trade routes and garrison towns. Terrain and Travel Detail Description Territory Type Outlands Encounter Frequency Once per 6-mile hex traveled; once per 12 hours resting/stationary (day or night) Night Travel Shift one column right on encounter table (more dangerous encounters) Travel through the Gallowswood is not undertaken lightly. Those who enter without preparation, arms, and numbers may not return. The dense canopy and tangled undergrowth make it easy to become disoriented, and the things that live beneath the trees are actively hostile. Encounter Table Roll 1d8 for each encounter: Roll Encounter Number 1 Common Wolves 2d4 2 beastmen Beastman Goblins 3 Bandits 1d6+1 4 Grave Ghouls 1d6 5 Dire Wolves 1d4 6 Wight 1d2 7 Lycanthrope / Werewolf 1d4 8 Troll 1 Night travel shifts one column right , meaning encounters skew toward the more dangerous end of the table. A party traveling through the Gallowswood at night is more likely to encounter dire wolves, wights, werewolves, and trolls than wolves and goblins. The encounter table reflects the forest&#39;s cursed nature. The undead presence (ghouls and wights) is not incidental -- the dead walk here. Wolves and dire wolves hunt in packs beneath the canopy. Beastman goblins use the forest as cover for their movements. Bandits shelter in the deep woods where the law cannot reach. The werewolves and the troll represent the deeper, older threats -- things that have always been in the Gallowswood, things that predate the Empire&#39;s claim on this land. Flora The Gallowswood supports several plants of significant practical and medicinal value. See backlands-field-guide for the full regional flora reference. Plant Description Use Black Hawthorn Dark bark, pale spring flowers, red fall berries Berries edible but bitter. One of the Gallowswood&#39;s defining trees. Belladonna Found near old Argollean burial mounds; purple berries Poison. Do not consume. Serves as a marker -- where belladonna clusters, an the Backlands has foxes. The Gallowswood does not. The absence is information -- what killed the foxes, or what keeps them out, is unknown. Deer Deer are present but extremely skittish. If deer are running, do not pause to assess what they are fleeing from. Run with them. Whatever flushed the deer is worse than the deer think you are. Crab Spiders Dog-sized ambush predators that match the texture of bark. They position themselves at chest-height on tree trunks and wait motionless for prey to pass within striking distance. Venom : Paralytic. A bitten victim is immobilized while the spider feeds. Surprise : Check at -2 for surprise when entering areas of dense tree cover. The Alertness proficiency negates this penalty. Crab spiders are solitary hunters. They do not swarm. But a single crab spider is enough to kill an armored man if it achieves surprise. Argollean Burial Mounds Old Argollean burial mounds are scattered through the Gallowswood. They are identifiable by the clustering of belladonna around their bases. The mounds predate the forest&#39;s current cursed state -- the dead were buried here during the Argollean period, and whatever happened to the Gallowswood afterward was not kind to them. The relationship between the burial mounds and the Gallowswood&#39;s undead population (ghouls and wights on the encounter table) is likely not coincidental. Avari Warning Stones Carved stones at the Gallowswood&#39;s borders bear Avari warnings. These predate the Argollean arrival in the region. The Avari did not carve warnings lightly -- their tradition is oral, and committing a warning to stone indicates something they considered important enough to outlast their own memory. The warnings have not been fully translated, but their intent is unmistakable: do not enter. Navigation Navigation in the Gallowswood is exceptionally treacherous: Moss grows on ALL sides of trees. The thick canopy diffuses light so completely that the standard moss grows on the north side rule is useless here. Compass unreliable. Something in the forest interferes with magnetic navigation. Whether this is a natural mineral deposit or something else is unknown. Follow water downhill. The most reliable method of finding your way out. Streams flow downhill and eventually leave the forest. Old Avari path markers exist -- carved stones and wooden poles placed centuries ago. Some sequences of markers are intact and navigable. However, some marker sequences were not intended for outsiders and may lead to places the Avari considered sacred, dangerous, or both. The Dome and the Abominations A massive clearing approximately half a day&#39;s travel into the deep wood. Before the beastman horde was broken at the Sacking of Crossings , beastman tribes congregated here around an artifact of unknown origin and nature. The beastmen are gone now. Something remains. Creatures wander out of the Dome&#39;s vicinity -- things the woodsmen call abominations . They are described as loose bags of shifting flesh, their surfaces constantly growing and absorbing mouths, eyes, and tentacles in a nauseating cycle of formation and dissolution. They are not natural creatures. They are not undead. They are something else. Abomination Combat Profile Attribute Detail Speed Fast -- faster than they appear, which is already unsettling Attacks Three attacks per round (shifting flesh generates multiple appendages simultaneously) Venom Paralytic toxin. Failed save = paralysis for 1d3 turns Immunities Immune to sleep, charm, and hold effects. Whatever intelligence drives them is not a mind that can be influenced by such magic. The Dome&#39;s connection to the pulsating black heart beneath the granite dome (see below) is unclear but almost certainly significant. The beastman artifact, the abominations, and the black heart may be three manifestations of the same phenomenon -- or three separate horrors that happen to share the same cursed ground. The Black Heart From session accounts: there is a pulsating black heart beneath a granite dome somewhere deep in the Gallowswood. Twisted crimson veins grow from it, spreading through the earth like roots. Characters have experienced dreams about this heart -- sensing malevolent evil radiating from the cancerous ball of flesh, but also an awakened lust for power . The heart calls to those who have been touched by darkness. Anaya (henchman) speaks of this heart calling to her after being wounded by a zombie beastman. She describes the pull as something beyond mere temptation -- a voice beneath thought, an ache in the blood. Greta is visibly disturbed by Anaya&#39;s visions but does not share why. Greta&#39;s silence on this matter is conspicuous given her knowledge of binding traditions and Cthonic phenomena. The nature of the black heart is unknown. It may be connected to the Awakening , to the Nethercity beneath Crossings , or to something older still. Its presence beneath the Gallowswood may explain why the dead walk here -- why this forest, of all the forests in the Backlands , is cursed. See Also the-backlands -- The frontier province containing the Gallowswood bone-creek -- The frontier settlement east of the Gallowswood the-slog -- The wasteland bordering the Gallowswood to the east the-heartwood -- The older, deeper forest beyond the Gallowswood fort-meade -- The nearest major garrison greta -- Witch who is disturbed by visions of the black heart the-awakening -- The Cthonic prophecy that may be connected to the black heart the-nethercity -- The Eladran necropolis that may share a connection with the heart beastmen -- Goblins who use the forest for cover avari -- Ancient people whose warning stones mark the Gallowswood borders eladra -- The Argollean civilization whose burial mounds dot the forest backlands-field-guide -- Comprehensive survival reference including Gallowswood flora mithrian-empire -- The empire that claims but does not control this territory"},{"slug":"grathe-steppe","title":"Grathe Steppe","category":"locations","tags":"location steppe skiotha grathar nomadic horse-warriors raids slavery frontier wilderness","text":"Grathe Steppe The steppe does not end. It simply becomes something else -- farther east, farther north, beyond the reach of maps and the patience of empires. The Skiotha do not conquer it. They move through it, as natural to the grass sea as the wind. The Grathe Steppe is a vast grassland expanse that serves as the homeland of the Skiothan nomadic horse warriors. It also hosts small communities of Grathar people. The steppe lies beyond the effective reach of the Mithrian Empire , and the Skiotha who ride it are a persistent threat to the Empire&#39;s western provinces. At a Glance Detail Description Location East and north of the Mithrian Empire , inhospitable to the settled agriculture and permanent fortification that define imperial civilization. The steppe does not support cities, garrisons, or the administrative apparatus of empire. It supports movement -- and the Skiotha have mastered movement across it as no other people have. The steppe resists conquest not through military strength but through geography. It is too vast to garrison, too open to fortify, and too sparse to sustain the supply lines that imperial armies require. Campaigns into the steppe have historically exhausted themselves -- armies march in, find no fixed positions to assault, and are harassed by mounted raiders who refuse set-piece battle until the invaders are weakened by distance and deprivation. The Skiotha The Skiothan nomadic horse warriors are the dominant people of the Grathe Steppe. They are raiders, herders, and warriors who live by the rhythm of the grasslands -- moving with their herds, fighting from horseback, and striking the settled provinces of the Mithrian Empire when opportunity presents. The Skiotha raid the Empire&#39;s western provinces, taking slaves and treasure. These raids are not the sporadic violence of disorganized bandits -- they are the systematic economic activity of a warrior culture that views the settled lands as a resource to be harvested. Slaves taken in raids serve the Skiothan economy; treasure funds the acquisition of goods the steppe cannot produce. The Empire has never fully pacified the Skiothan threat. The chain of border forts and frontier garrisons exists in part to contain and deter these incursions, but the steppe is too vast and the Skiotha too mobile for permanent military solutions. The Grathar Small Grathar communities also inhabit the Grathe Steppe, coexisting with the dominant Skiothan population. The relationship between the Grathar and the Skiotha on the steppe -- whether cooperative, subordinate, or merely tolerated -- reflects the broader dynamics of peoples who share territory without sharing culture. See Also Skiotha -- The nomadic horse warriors who dominate the steppe grathar -- The secondary inhabitants of the Grathe Steppe mithrian-empire -- The empire whose western provinces suffer Skiothan raids races-and-cultures -- The peoples of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"lake-silverhead","title":"Lake Silverhead","category":"locations","tags":"location lake argolle ygrathen kharai cairnhouse varek-ashstone imprisoned far-north vigil","text":"Lake Silverhead The lake is still. The island is silent. The cairnhouse has stood for centuries, and the thing inside it has not moved. Varek watches from the northern shore. He has watched for longer than any human life should allow. He does not speak of what happens if the vigil ends. Lake Silverhead is a lake in the far north of Argolle province. At its center lies an island holding a cairnhouse of Ygrathen construction. Within the cairnhouse, a Kharai is imprisoned. On the northern shore, the Ygrathen hermit Varek Ashstone maintains a centuries-long vigil over the site. At a Glance Detail Description Location Far north of Argolle , remote from the garrison towns and trade routes that define life in the Backlands . It is not a site of commerce, settlement, or strategic interest. It is a site of containment. The island at the center of the lake holds a cairnhouse -- a structure of Ygrathen construction, built with the characteristic methods and materials of that ancient and enduring people. Within the cairnhouse, a Kharai is imprisoned. The nature of the imprisonment -- whether physical, magical, spiritual, or some combination -- reflects Ygrathen methods of containment that predate the Mithrian Empire by centuries. The Cairnhouse The cairnhouse on the island is of Ygrathen construction -- built to contain, to endure, and to hold what is placed within it for as long as the structure stands. The Ygrathen built to last, and their containment structures are among the most durable works of any civilization in Mithrapos . The Kharai imprisoned within represents a threat sufficient to justify centuries of continuous vigil by a single Ygrathen guardian. The specific nature of the Kharai -- its identity, its power, the circumstances of its imprisonment -- are known to Varek Ashstone and perhaps to no one else living. Varek Ashstone Varek Ashstone is a Ygrathen hermit who lives on the northern shore of Lake Silverhead. He maintains a centuries-long vigil over the cairnhouse and its prisoner -- a duration that speaks to either the extraordinary longevity of the Ygrathen people or to methods of life-extension that are not widely understood. Varek&#39;s vigil is solitary, deliberate, and unbroken. He does not seek company, does not welcome visitors, and does not explain his purpose to those who stumble upon him. He watches the island. He has watched for a very long time. The implication is clear: if the vigil ends, something happens -- and whatever that something is, Varek has judged it worth spending centuries to prevent. See Also varek-ashstone -- The Ygrathen hermit maintaining vigil on the northern shore Kharai -- The imprisoned entity within the cairnhouse ygrathen -- The ancient people who built the cairnhouse Argolle -- The province in which Lake Silverhead is located the-backlands -- The broader frontier region mithrapos -- The known world in which Lake Silverhead exists"},{"slug":"mithra-city","title":"Mithra City","category":"locations","tags":"capital mithrian-empire","text":"Mithra City Mithra City is the capital of the Mithrian Empire and the seat of imperial power. Encircled by alabaster white walls , the city stands as the political, religious, and sorcerous heart of the known world. From within its boundaries, the Emperor rules over the vast territories of the Empire, supported by a dense concentration of institutions that together form the machinery of imperial governance. Landmarks and Institutions The Imperial Palace The Emperor governs from the imperial palace at the city&#39;s center, the symbolic and literal seat of House Decimus authority. The palace complex houses the imperial court, the Emperor&#39;s personal guard, and the chambers from which edicts are issued to every corner of the Empire. The Imperial Academy The towering spires of the Imperial Academy are the highest structures in the city , visible from miles beyond the walls. The Academy serves as the state-sanctioned center of sorcerous learning and a political power in its own right, its Archmages wielding influence that rivals that of the imperial ministries. The Imperial Senate The Imperial Senate convenes in Mithra City, serving as the deliberative body through which the noble houses, provincial governors, and civic leaders participate in imperial governance. While the Emperor holds ultimate authority, the Senate remains a significant forum for political negotiation and factional maneuvering. The Thousand Temples The headquarters of the Thousand Temples are located within the city, making Mithra City the spiritual capital of the Empire as well as its political one. The Temples&#39; presence ensures that religious authority remains physically proximate to the throne -- a deliberate arrangement that reflects the intertwining of faith and governance in Mithrian society. Significance Mithra City is more than a capital -- it is the embodiment of the Empire itself. The concentration of the Academy, the Senate, the Thousand Temples, and the imperial throne within its walls means that every major current of imperial life -- political, military, religious, and arcane -- flows through and from this single city. Control of Mithra City is, in practical terms, control of the Empire. See Also The Imperial Academy The Thousand Temples The Mithrian Military The Imperial Talons The Burnished Scale"},{"slug":"mount-argolle","title":"Mount Argolle","category":"locations","tags":"mount-argolle argolle volcano first-empire eladra thune harpies gilded-oath cairnhill-breaks cairnhill","text":"Mount Argolle Mount Argolle is an active volcanic mountain east of Cairnhill , the geographical and historical heart of the region that bears its name. Its white volcanic plume is visible from the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]] and serves as a perpetual landmark for travelers, settlers, and the creatures that inhabit its slopes. The mountain is simultaneously a natural wonder, a ruin of the First Empire , and a living ecosystem of predators and remnant peoples. Geography Mount Argolle rises from the eastern edge of the Backlands , beyond the fractured limestone foothills known as the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]]. The mountain is volcanic -- not dormant but active, venting a persistent white plume from its summit that can be seen for dozens of miles in clear weather. The plume serves as a navigational reference point throughout the eastern Backlands, a column of pale smoke marking the boundary between settled territory and the deep interior. The mountain&#39;s lower slopes are traversable, though difficult. The upper reaches are sheer cliffs, carved and shaped by the Eladra of the First Empire into architectural forms that blur the line between natural formation and deliberate construction. Above the carved levels, the highest crags are bare volcanic rock -- wind-scoured, sulfur-stained, and inhabited by creatures that tolerate the heat and fumes. The Cairnhill Breaks The Cairnhill Breaks are a region of fractured limestone foothills lying between Cairnhill and Mount Argolle. The terrain is broken, irregular, and difficult to navigate -- a landscape of shattered ridgelines, collapsed sinkholes, narrow defiles, and exposed rock faces where the limestone has cracked and tilted under geological stress. The Breaks are not empty. The fractured terrain provides shelter and concealment for a variety of inhabitants: [[#gilded-oath-guardian-tombs|Gilded Oath guardian tombs]] are scattered throughout the Breaks, built into the rock faces and ridge crests by the First Empire to watch over the approaches to Mount Argolle. Predators and territorial creatures use the defiles and sinkholes as hunting grounds. The terrain itself is hazardous -- unstable footing, hidden drops, and narrow passages that can trap the unwary. Travel through the Cairnhill Breaks requires either local knowledge or considerable caution. The route from Cairnhill to Mount Argolle passes through the Breaks by necessity, and every mile of the journey is contested terrain. First Empire Ruins The upper cliffs of Mount Argolle were carved by the First Empire into monumental architectural forms: Terraces -- broad, level platforms cut into the cliff face, connected by carved stairways. These terraces served purposes that combined the residential, the ceremonial, and the military. Their scale suggests they were built to accommodate large numbers of people -- or beings -- and their positioning provides commanding views of the surrounding landscape. Archways -- massive carved openings in the rock, framing passages that lead deeper into the mountain&#39;s interior. Some archways are purely decorative, marking boundaries between zones of the carved complex. Others are functional, providing access to chambers and corridors within the mountain itself. Inscription panels -- carved surfaces bearing text and imagery in the Eladran script. The panels are weathered but legible in places, recording histories, dedications, and ritual formulae from the height of the First Empire. The content of these inscriptions has not been systematically studied by modern scholars -- the mountain&#39;s current inhabitants discourage academic visitation. The ruins are extensive. The First Empire did not merely build on Mount Argolle -- it reshaped the mountain&#39;s upper third into a complex that integrated natural volcanic rock with carved architecture on a scale that rivals the Nethercity in ambition, if not in subterranean depth. Current Inhabitants Harpies The highest crags of Mount Argolle are home to nesting harpies -- predatory creatures that exploit the mountain&#39;s thermal updrafts and inaccessible perches. The harpies are territorial and aggressive, defending their nesting sites against any intrusion. Their presence makes the upper reaches of the mountain extremely dangerous for any creature that cannot fly, and their hunting range extends into the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]] below. Thune Remnant The lower ruins of Mount Argolle are inhabited by a Thune remnant -- descendants of the Argollean slave-soldiers who were created through Transmogrification to serve the First Empire. When the Thune rebelled and destroyed the Empire that made them (c. 1700 BE), not all Thune joined the successor civilization that became the Thunean Empire . Some remained in the ruins of their creation, in the carved mountain where they had served. These remnant Thune have lived among the lower ruins of Mount Argolle for millennia. They are not the Thune of the historical empires -- they are a people shaped by long isolation, by the volcanic mountain&#39;s harsh environment, and by proximity to the First Empire&#39;s abandoned architecture and whatever lingers within it. Their relationship with the ruins is complex -- they inhabit structures built by the civilization that created and enslaved their ancestors, and they guard them with a possessiveness that combines territorial instinct with something deeper. The Thune remnant&#39;s attitude toward outsiders ranges from suspicious to hostile. They do not welcome visitors, they do not trade, and they do not explain themselves. Gilded Oath Guardian Tombs The Gilded Oath guardian tombs are scattered throughout the [[#the-cairnhill-breaks|Cairnhill Breaks]] between Cairnhill and Mount Argolle. These are not conventional burial sites. They are guardian installations -- tombs built to house warriors interred with the expectation that they would continue to serve in death as they served in life. The tombs were constructed by the First Empire to protect the approaches to Mount Argolle. Each tomb is a fortified structure built into the limestone terrain of the Breaks, positioned to watch over passes, defiles, and routes of approach. The interred guardians were placed according to a defensive scheme that treated the entire Cairnhill Breaks as a layered security perimeter around the mountain. Whether the guardians within these tombs remain active -- whether the Cthonic preservation that sustained them has endured across millennia -- is a question that travelers through the Breaks sometimes answer involuntarily. Significance Mount Argolle is the physical anchor of the region&#39;s deep history. The mountain predates every civilization that has claimed this territory. The Eladra carved it. The Thune inherited it. The Mithrian Empire has never controlled it. The mountain stands at the intersection of geological time and historical time -- a volcano that was sacred before recorded history and remains inhabited by the descendants of the civilization that carved its cliffs. For adventurers and scholars, Mount Argolle represents one of the most significant -- and most dangerous -- First Empire sites accessible from the settled Backlands . The Nethercity beneath Crossings may be larger, but Mount Argolle&#39;s ruins are exposed, visible, and guarded by inhabitants who have had millennia to learn every carved passage and hidden chamber. See Also cairnhill -- The nearest settlement, gateway to the Cairnhill Breaks argollean-empire -- The First Empire that carved the mountain&#39;s upper cliffs eladra -- The civilization that built the original mountain complex thune -- The slave-soldiers whose descendants inhabit the lower ruins the-nethercity -- The subterranean complex beneath Crossings, built by the same civilization beastmen -- Other products of First Empire Transmogrification in the region the-backlands -- The province in which Mount Argolle stands backlands-provincial-history -- The modern history of the region Gilded Oath -- The guardian tradition that produced the tombs in the Cairnhill Breaks"},{"slug":"sanctuary","title":"Sanctuary","category":"locations","tags":"location city capital provincial-capital backlands port harbor sanctuary aodahn eladra megadungeon market","text":"Sanctuary The bones of what came before are visible everywhere. Impossible geometry of Eladra spires, strange angles of ruined streets, names lingering in Imperial bureaucracy like ghosts of a language no one speaks anymore. Sanctuary is not built on ruins. Sanctuary is ruins, with a city draped over them like a shroud. Sanctuary is the provincial capital of the Backlands and the last true city in the province. A metropolitan port built upon the ruins of Aodahn , the great Argollean harbor-city, Sanctuary is the economic, political, religious, and scholarly center of the Backlands. It is a city built on tension -- between factions, between past and present, between the Empire&#39;s fading reach and the ambitions of those who would fill the vacuum. At a Glance Detail Description Location Mouth of the Backlands . Everything else -- Bone Creek , Fort Meade , Cairnhill , the Crossings (now destroyed) -- is a town, settlement, or outpost by comparison. Sanctuary is metropolitan. It has districts, institutions, guilds, temples, academies, a functioning port, and a population measured in tens of thousands. The city is ethnically diverse. Mithrian bureaucrats and soldiers form the ruling class. Merchants from Morn haggle in the markets. Sailors from Thrassia fill the harbor taverns. Avari refugees from the sacking of the Crossings crowd the Ashward . Lakandi traders pass through with goods from the wastes. Scholars from across the known world come to study at the Imperial Academy . The bones of what came before are visible everywhere. The impossible geometry of Eladra spires, the strange angles of ruined streets, names lingering in Imperial bureaucracy like ghosts of a language no one speaks. Five ivory spires -- each carved from a single stone so white it seems to emit light, each three hundred feet or more above the harbor -- dominate the skyline. They are not Mithrian. They predate the Empire by centuries, perhaps millennia. They are remnants of Aodahn , and they are a reminder that Sanctuary is not built on ruins. Sanctuary is ruins, with a city draped over them. History Aodahn -- The City Before The ruins upon which Sanctuary stands are called Aodahn -- an Argollean word meaning sanctuary or refuge. The name predates the Mithrian city by centuries, and the Mithrians kept it, perhaps unconsciously recognizing its aptness. Aodahn was built by the true children of the Empyrean gods -- the Eladra , who were not corrupted Elvora . The Eladra were something older and purer, a people who maintained their connection to the Empyrean when others fell away. Their city reflected this. The five ivory spires, each carved from a single stone and proportioned in ratios that trouble human perception, rose over three hundred feet above the harbor. Modern Academy scholars suspect the spires are engineered conduits of Empyrean vitality , analogous to Erenthis trees but constructed rather than grown. If true, Aodahn was not simply a city -- it was a project . The Abandonment When the Mithrians arrived, they found Aodahn abandoned . No records of war or catastrophe. No evidence of plague, siege, or flight. The city was simply empty. The Eladra had vanished. Belongings remained. Workshops stood open. Food rotted on tables. The people were gone. The chronicler Varro Silk wrote that the city felt as though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned. No satisfactory explanation has ever been offered. The Academy has theories -- the Threshold hypothesis, the Ascension model, the Catastrophic Severance theory -- but none are proven. What is known is that the Eladra are not entirely gone. At least one Eladra agent is believed to be present in Sanctuary at any given time, watching, guarding secrets about what lies below. Imperial Foundation Sanctuary was formally established as an imperial trading post in 283 IY , taking advantage of the natural harbor and the Argoll River&#39;s navigability inland. The existing ruins provided building material and shelter. The spires, too massive and too strange to demolish, were incorporated into the growing city. By 350 IY , Sanctuary had grown large enough and become strategically important enough to be designated the provincial capital of the Backlands. The governor&#39;s seat was established in the Citadel , the Imperial Academy was chartered, and the Temple of the Unconquered Sun raised its Grand Temple in the Sunward . Geography Sanctuary sits at the mouth of the Argoll River where it empties into the Turquoise Sea . The city rises from the waterfront in tiers, with the Harbor at the lowest elevation and the Citadel at the highest. The Eladra spires punctuate the skyline at irregular intervals, their white stone catching the light at all hours. Below the surface streets, the ruins of Aodahn extend downward in three tiers, forming a vast Undercity that has never been fully explored. Current Situation (380 IY) The Emperor&#39;s attention has turned westward, fighting Skiothan incursions that threaten the imperial heartland. Legions have been recalled from the provinces. The Backlands garrison has been stripped to skeletal levels. The province is effectively autonomous, and everyone knows it. Governor Valerios Drussus has used this vacuum ruthlessly. He has consolidated personal power with frightening efficiency over the fifteen years of his tenure. The Drussine Guard -- his private army , not technically the provincial military -- now numbers 2,000 strong . His control over the bureaucracy is absolute. His personal wealth competes with the Red River Consortium . Every faction fears him. Every faction courts him. No one knows what he intends. The balance of power in Sanctuary is a web of mutual suspicion and careful accommodation: Governor Drussus holds military and bureaucratic supremacy but must maintain appearances of imperial loyalty Prelate Voth and the Temple hold moral authority and extensive intelligence networks The Laced Hand controls the underworld with the Governor&#39;s tacit approval The Imperial Academy guards ancient knowledge and maintains independence through scholarly prestige The Red River Consortium holds economic leverage through trade monopolies The Avari community survives in the Ashward , led by Elder Sarnath of the Crossings The Eight Districts 1. The Citadel The fortress-seat of the Governor. Occupies the highest ground in the city, behind walls-within-walls. The architecture is a mix of austere military-functional construction and grand palatial display -- the Governor lives here, and his power radiates outward from this point. Key Locations (9 keyed): Governor&#39;s Palace -- Seat of Valerios Drussus . Administrative heart of the province. Drussine Guard Barracks -- Housing and training facilities for the ~2,000 soldiers of the Drussine Guard Provincial Archive -- Imperial records, census data, tax rolls, legal precedent Military Mint -- Where the province&#39;s coinage is struck Prisoner&#39;s Vault -- The Governor&#39;s personal prison, separate from civil gaols Citadel Gate -- Primary entrance, heavily fortified War Room -- Strategic planning center Officer&#39;s Quarters -- Housing for senior Drussine Guard officers, including Colonel Marcian Vex Armory -- Arsenal for the garrison The Citadel is effectively a self-contained military installation within the city. In the event of civil unrest, the Governor could hold the Citadel indefinitely with the forces at his disposal. 2. The Ivory Quarter Built atop the ruins of ancient Aodahn , the Ivory Quarter takes its name from the Eladra spires that rise here. The atmosphere is scholarly and watchful -- students, researchers, and antiquarians fill the streets, but there is always the sense of being observed, whether by Academy security or by something older. Key Locations (9 keyed): Academy Tower -- The central structure of the Imperial Academy , constructed around one of the Eladra spires rather than demolishing it. The spire rises through the Tower&#39;s interior, over 300 feet tall, and serves as both architectural centerpiece and object of study. Regent: Magister Cornelius Shale , Wizard 11. Artifact Vault -- Secured repository for recovered relics and Eladra artifacts Academy Library -- One of the largest collections of texts in the Backlands Antiquarians Guild -- Organization of relic-hunters, scholars, and collectors Eladra Spire Garden -- Public gardens surrounding another Eladra spire. Documented phenomena at sunset: visions, sounds in unknown languages, sensation of being watched. Several cults have formed around the spires. Scholar&#39;s Row -- Boarding houses, bookshops, and scriptoria catering to students Academy Security Post -- The Academy maintains its own security force, independent of the City Watch Alchemist&#39;s Corner -- Cluster of alchemical shops and workshops The Cartographer -- Map shop specializing in Backlands geography and Undercity surveys 3. The Sunward The religious heart of Sanctuary. Dominated by the Temple of the Unconquered Sun and its associated structures. Prelate Severan Voth&#39;s influence is absolute here -- the Temple functions as a state within a state in this district. Key Locations (8 keyed): Grand Temple of the Unconquered Sun -- The largest religious structure in the Backlands. Seats 3,000 worshippers. Center of Prelate Voth&#39;s authority. Monastic Complex -- Housing and training for the Temple&#39;s monastic orders Pilgrim&#39;s House -- Shelter and services for pilgrims traveling to Sanctuary Temple of Mitra -- Secondary temple dedicated to Mitra Shrine of Seros -- Smaller shrine to Seros Healing House -- Temple-run hospital and healing center. Free healing for the faithful, subsidized for others. Scriptorum -- Where Temple scribes copy, preserve, and produce religious texts Temple Guard Post -- The Temple maintains its own guards within the Sunward 4. The Harbor The economic engine of Sanctuary. The wharves, warehouses, and shipyards of the Harbor generate the wealth that keeps the city functioning. The district smells of salt, tar, and exotic goods. It is loud, boisterous, and dangerous. The Laced Hand controls the Harbor through the dockworkers&#39; union. Nothing moves through the port without their knowledge and often their approval. Key Locations (9 keyed): The Crimson Anchor Tavern -- Laced Hand operations hub. Proprietor Mara has worked here 20 years and knows everyone worth knowing. Public house on the surface, nerve center of criminal operations beneath. Customs House -- Imperial customs authority (now largely controlled by the Governor&#39;s apparatus) Shipyard -- Construction and repair of sailing vessels Maritime Guild -- Association of captains, navigators, and ship owners Merchant&#39;s Exchange -- Where large-scale commercial deals are brokered Salt Warehouses -- Storage for one of the Backlands&#39; most valuable commodities Dockworkers&#39; Union Hall -- Nominally a labor organization, effectively a Laced Hand front Harbor Watch Post -- City Watch station, often compromised by Laced Hand influence Fishmarket -- Daily market for the harbor&#39;s catch, active before dawn 5. The Commons Where most of Sanctuary&#39;s population lives. Dense, crowded, teeming with humanity. Tenements rise five and six stories. The Grand Market sprawls through the center. Every craft, trade, and profession is represented. The district is ethnically and economically diverse -- Mithrian tradespeople live alongside Lakandi merchants, foreign sailors, and everyone in between. City Watch presence is regular but authority is distributed among local strongmen and neighborhood bosses. The Laced Hand maintains order in their own fashion -- protection rackets double as informal policing. Key Locations (12+ keyed): Grand Market -- The largest open market in the Backlands. Daily trading in goods from across the known world. Crafters&#39; Quarter -- Smiths, tanners, weavers, potters, carpenters clustered by trade The Tenements -- Dense residential blocks, 5-6 stories, housing thousands Commons Watch Station -- City Watch headquarters for the district The Brass Lamp -- Popular tavern and gathering place Moneylenders&#39; Row -- Financiers, moneylenders, and pawnbrokers Bathhouse -- Public bathing and social gathering Courier&#39;s Hall -- Where messages, packages, and small goods are dispatched throughout the city and beyond Butcher&#39;s Lane -- Food market and slaughterhouse district Weavers&#39; Hall -- Guild hall for the textile trades Apothecary Row -- Herbalists, healers, and medicine sellers The Rag Market -- Secondhand goods, salvage, and bargain traders 6. The Ashward The refugee quarter. When the Crossings was sacked, thousands of Avari fled south to Sanctuary. They were given marginal land on the city&#39;s edge -- the Ashward -- and left largely to their own devices. The district is desperate, impoverished, and dangerous, but it is also dignified. The Avari have maintained their own community leadership, their own traditions, and their own identity. Key Details: Population: 8,000--10,000 (mostly Avari refugees) Elder Sarnath of the Crossings -- Age 71, community leader. Respected, stubborn, determined to preserve Avari identity and culture Avari have not assimilated into Sanctuary&#39;s Mithrian culture. They remain distinct -- their own language, customs, governance Shanty settlements on marginal land -- flooding, poor sanitation, inadequate infrastructure Camp markets selling Avari goods, food, and crafts Makeshift temples to Avari gods The Ashward is policed primarily by Avari themselves -- City Watch rarely enters, Drussine Guard never Dangerous for outsiders unfamiliar with Avari customs and community structures 7. The Undercity -- Ruins of Aodahn Beneath Sanctuary lies the true Aodahn -- the ancient Eladra city, only partially explored, extending downward in three tiers. This is a three-tier megadungeon that represents one of the most significant adventuring environments in the Backlands . Tier 1: The Warrens (Levels 1--3) The uppermost levels of the Undercity, accessible through numerous known entrances throughout the city. The Warrens are partially settled -- smugglers, outcasts, and those with reason to avoid the surface maintain hidden communities here. Beyond the settled areas, the Warrens become increasingly dangerous. Inhabitants: Giant vermin (rats, spiders, centipedes), oozes, smuggler gangs, outcast settlements Features: Collapsed tunnels, flooded passages, hidden caches, smuggler routes connecting districts Danger Level: Low to moderate. Manageable by experienced adventurers. Tier 2: Old Aodahn (Levels 3--7) Below the Warrens lies the preserved heart of the ancient Eladra city. Here, the architecture becomes alien -- proportions shift, materials defy identification, spaces exist that should not be possible given the geometry above. The area is saturated with Empyrean energy, producing strange phenomena: lights without source, sounds without origin, time moving at inconsistent rates. Inhabitants: Construct guardians (still operational after centuries), doppelgangers, minotaurs, minor elementals Features: Preserved Eladra workshops, libraries, and living spaces. Empyrean energy saturation causes minor reality distortions. Strange phenomena -- flickering lights, sounds in unknown languages, fleeting images of people and places that do not exist. Danger Level: Significant. Requires well-equipped and experienced parties. Tier 3: Foundations of the Spires (Levels 7+) The deepest known level of the Undercity. Here, at the roots of the great spires, the Eladra built something extraordinary. This is where scholars believe the Ascension -- whatever it was -- actually occurred. The Empyrean energy is overwhelming. Reality itself becomes unreliable. Inhabitants: Masterwork constructs (far more powerful than those above), major elementals, entities of unknown origin Features: The Threshold -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened. The door has not fully closed. Empyrean energy is so concentrated that mortal flesh reacts unpredictably. Magical effects are amplified, distorted, or inverted. Danger Level: Extreme. Few have reached this level and returned. 8. (Outer Districts / Outskirts) Beyond the walls, the outskirts of Sanctuary include farms, small settlements, and the sprawl of the Ashward refugee camps. These areas are nominally under the Governor&#39;s authority but in practice are loosely governed. Key Organizations The Governor&#39;s Apparatus The machinery of Governor Drussus&#39;s power. This includes: The Drussine Guard (~2,000 soldiers) -- the Governor&#39;s personal army, loyal to him personally The Provincial Bureaucracy -- Tax collectors, magistrates, record-keepers, functionaries, all screened for loyalty to the Governor The City Watch (~600) -- Ostensibly independent municipal police, in practice answerable to the Governor through the chain of command Together, these institutions give Drussus near-total control over the city&#39;s administrative, military, and law enforcement functions. Temple of the Unconquered Sun Led by Prelate Severan Voth , Cleric 13. The Temple is the most significant religious institution in the Backlands and functions as a check on secular power. It operates from the Grand Temple in the Sunward and maintains monastic orders, a healing house, and an extensive intelligence network. The Laced Hand Sanctuary&#39;s criminal syndicate , operating with the Governor&#39;s tacit approval. Led by Castellan Thibaud (Master Thief 7). Controls the docks, smuggling, black market, protection rackets, and gambling dens. Operations hub: The Crimson Anchor Tavern in the Harbor . See The Laced Hand for full details. The Imperial Academy of Sanctuary The Backlands&#39; premier institution of learning and magical research. Regent: Magister Cornelius Shale , Wizard 11. Housed partially around one of the Eladra spires. Maintains its own security force and artifact vault. See Imperial Academy for full details. The Red River Consortium (Sanctuary Branch) The great trading company&#39;s Sanctuary operations. Directrix: Valeria Thorne , age 58. Politically aligned with Governor Drussus . The Consortium&#39;s wealth in Sanctuary competes with the Governor&#39;s own. See Red River Consortium for full details. The Avari Community The Avari refugee population of the Ashward , led by Elder Sarnath of the Crossings (age 71). A distinct community within Sanctuary that has not assimilated into Mithrian culture. Maintains its own leadership, customs, language, and traditions. Economy Trade Sanctuary is the largest market in the Backlands (Market Class III). Its port connects the province to maritime trade routes across the Turquoise Sea , while the Argoll River provides access to the interior. Major exports: Salt, relics and artifacts from the Undercity , processed goods, administrative services Major imports: Food staples, manufactured goods, luxury items, soldiers (formerly), scholars The Red River Consortium and the Laced Hand between them control most of the city&#39;s commerce -- the former through legitimate trade monopolies, the latter through the docks, smuggling, and the black market. Power Dynamics The political landscape of Sanctuary is defined by the relationships between its major factions: Drussus vs. Voth : Cold and formal. They do not trust each other but maintain equilibrium. Drussus does not interfere with Temple internal affairs; Voth does not publicly oppose the Governor&#39;s authority. Both recognize that either could seriously damage the other. Drussus and the Laced Hand : Tacit arrangement. The Laced Hand provides intelligence, removes inconvenient people, and keeps the underworld organized. In exchange, the Governor does not interfere with their operations. Drussus vs. Legate Marcellus : A silent political war fought at a distance. Marcellus at Fort Meade represents the only other significant military authority in the province. Academy independence: The Academy maintains neutrality through scholarly prestige and the value of its services. It cooperates with all factions and is beholden to none. Avari marginalization: The Ashward community is largely ignored by Sanctuary&#39;s power brokers, which is both a source of suffering and a form of protection. Adventure Hooks The Undercity megadungeon offers exploration from the relatively safe Warrens down to the reality-warping Foundations of the Spires Factional intrigue between the Governor, Temple, Laced Hand, and Academy provides endless political adventure The mystery of the Eladra disappearance and the Threshold remains unsolved Avari refugee politics and the community&#39;s desperate situation offer moral complexity The Governor&#39;s true intentions remain unknown -- is he building a personal empire, preparing for imperial collapse, or something else? Trade disputes, smuggling operations, and Harbor politics provide economic adventure The spires&#39; documented phenomena -- visions, sounds, sensations -- offer supernatural mystery GM Notes Sanctuary is the Backlands&#39; urban hub. It should feel like a real city -- complex, layered, contradictory. Key principles: Every faction has legitimate grievances and legitimate strengths. There are no simple villains here. The Undercity is always present. Even in political adventures, the ancient ruins beneath the streets are a constant reminder that Sanctuary is built on something older and stranger than the Empire. The Governor is the linchpin. Every major plot in Sanctuary passes through Drussus at some point. His intentions are deliberately ambiguous. The Eladra mystery is the deep background. It does not need to be the focus of any given session, but it should always be felt -- in the spires, in the phenomena, in the occasional Eladra agent glimpsed and then gone. See Also Aodahn -- the ancient Eladra city beneath Sanctuary Governor Valerios Drussus -- provincial governor Prelate Severan Voth -- head of the Temple of the Unconquered Sun The Laced Hand -- criminal syndicate The Drussine Guard -- the Governor&#39;s personal army Imperial Academy -- scholarly institution Red River Consortium -- trading company The Backlands -- the province Fort Meade -- military installation to the north Bone Creek -- frontier settlement The Crossings -- destroyed Avari settlement Legate Marcellus -- military commander at Fort Meade"},{"slug":"the-backlands","title":"The Backlands (Province of Argolle)","category":"locations","tags":"province backlands argolle frontier mithrian-empire avari setting","text":"The Backlands (Province of Argolle) The province of Argolle , commonly known as the Backlands , is the forgotten frontier of the Mithrian Empire . Once the ancestral homelands of the Avari people, this war-scarred region exists at the very edge of imperial civilization, a place where the Empire&#39;s grip has grown so weak that law, order, and hope have all but evaporated. There is no soil out here, only the ash of Empires. The trees breathe rot and the water tastes of the dead. I seen it, I seen what waits beneath the ground. This land is not cursed — no, no, no — it remembers. Every war, every broken oath, every forgotten god — it sings them back into the marrow of the earth. That&#39;s why we can&#39;t leave. We&#39;re not stuck. We&#39;ve been claimed. — Father Draven , drunken priest Overview The Backlands carries a legacy of violence and war stretching back centuries, having been the site of numerous conflicts since the days of the ancient Argollean Empire . It is a land defined by its suffering — every generation brings new wars, new atrocities, and new reasons for the earth to remember. Today, the Backlands is a sparsely populated, poorly defended frontier territory. Its settlements cling to existence against a tide of threats both external and internal. The land itself seems hostile to civilization, as if the accumulated trauma of ages has seeped into the very soil. Current Political Situation The Withdrawal (378 IY) Two years ago, as the great Skiotha host threatened the very yoke of the Empire , the Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus recalled the local armies and garrisons from the Backlands, leaving the province undermanned and poorly defended. This single act effectively abandoned the Backlands to its fate, stripping it of the military strength needed to maintain order and defend its borders. Military Command Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus commands what remains — a small force of men tasked with guarding several border forts. These fortifications were originally constructed after the failed Lakan Campaigns years past, built to hold back the Lakandi threat from the wastes. Now they serve as the thin, crumbling line between the Empire&#39;s frontier and whatever lies beyond. Civil Governance Governor Valerios Drussus of House Drussus is the imperial governor of the Backlands. He seems content to rest on his laurels in Sanctuary , the only major port city left in the province. His inaction and distance from the frontier&#39;s problems have left settlements like Bone Creek and the ruins of Crossings to fend for themselves. The Sacking of Crossings Six years ago (approximately 374 IY), a horde of beastmen , wild and savage monsters long thought defeated, sacked the city of Crossings . The beastmen committed untold atrocity and violence upon the citizens there. The few refugees who managed to escape with their lives tell stories of the horrors inflicted that day. Note: There is a discrepancy in the sources regarding the date of the Sacking of Crossings. The Backlands source document places it six years ago (374 IY), while the campaign primer dates it to 377 IY. The exact date remains uncertain. In response to the sacking, the Emperor declared an Imperial Bounty upon all beastmen, offering imperial gold marks for their scalps. This decree created an entirely new economy — the Scalper trade — and drew hard men and women from every walk of life to the Backlands, seeking fortune in violence. The outpost of Bone Creek became the epicenter of this grim new industry. The beastmen, for their part, have settled in the ruin of Crossings and begun to push farther south, kidnapping farmers, raiding settlements, and worse. The Lakandi Threat The Lakandi of the wastes stir once more. These savage barbarians have long been enemies of both the Empire and the Avari . They were brutally subjugated in several wars against the Empire — the Lakan Campaigns — and the border forts now commanded by Legate Marcellus were built in their aftermath. But subjugation has not broken them. The Lakandi silently stew beneath the surface, and whispers of rebellion are not uncommon. With the imperial garrison reduced to a skeleton force, the threat of a Lakandi uprising is more dangerous than ever. Key Features Ancestral homeland of the Avari people Province of Argolle — a formal province of the Mithrian Empire Located on the forgotten frontier , as far from the imperial heartland as one can get Left undermanned and poorly defended since 378 IY when armies were recalled Legacy of violence stretching back to the Argollean Empire The beastmen threat emanating from the ruins of Crossings The Imperial Bounty on beastmen scalps, fueling the Scalper economy The Lakandi stirring in the wastes, with whispers of rebellion Sanctuary as the only major port city remaining Bone Creek as the primary Scalper outpost on the northern frontier Border forts from the Lakan Campaigns era, now undermanned Notable Figures Name Role Location ** legate-marcellus Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus ** Military commander of the Backlands Governor Valerios Drussus Imperial Governor (of house-drussus House Drussus ) Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus Emperor of the mithrian-empire Mithrian Empire Father Draven Drunken priest (deceased — succumbed to disease) bone-creek See Also [[mithrian-empire — The empire that claims dominion over the Backlands avari — The people whose ancestral homeland is Argolle bone-creek — The Scalper outpost on the northern frontier crossings — The sacked city, now occupied by beastmen sanctuary — The only major port city in the Backlands house-drussus — The noble house of the provincial governor mithrian-military — The imperial military, now largely withdrawn beastmen — The subhumanoid creatures terrorizing the frontier lakandi — The barbarians of the wastes, stirring toward rebellion red-river-consortium — The trading consortium operating in the Backlands"},{"slug":"the-foothills","title":"The Foothills","category":"locations","tags":"wilderness foothills mines backlands encounters","text":"The Foothills The Foothills are a rugged region of hills and abandoned mines in the Backlands . The terrain is rough, broken by old mine shafts, cave systems, and rocky ridgelines that provide shelter to a variety of dangerous inhabitants -- from beastman goblins and brigands to the undead that stir in the deep places. Geography The Foothills are characterized by rolling hills, exposed rock faces, and the entrances to abandoned mines that dot the landscape. These mines -- remnants of earlier settlement and extraction -- now serve as lairs for creatures that prefer the dark. Cave systems riddle the hills, connecting surface entrances to deeper underground passages. Encounter Table Roll 1d8 for each encounter: Roll Encounter Number 1 beastmen Beastman Goblins 2 Cave Bears 1d2 3 Giant Bats 1d10 4 Skeletons 3d4 5 Brigands 1d6+1 6 Giant Centipedes 2d4 7 Grave Ghouls 1d6 8 Ogre 1d2 The encounter table reflects the Foothills&#39; nature as mining territory gone feral. The heavy skeleton presence (3d4) suggests the mines and surrounding hills are thick with the remains of miners, soldiers, and settlers who died here over the centuries. Beastman goblins use the caves and mines as warrens. Cave bears, giant bats, and giant centipedes are the natural fauna of the underground spaces. Brigands shelter in the hills where pursuit is difficult. Ghouls haunt the deeper places. Ogres -- solitary, territorial, and brutal -- claim the most defensible positions. See Also the-backlands -- The province containing the Foothills bone-creek -- The nearest settlement the-slog -- The wasteland bordering the Foothills beastmen -- Goblins who use the mines as warrens scalper-gangs -- Gangs who sometimes venture into the Foothills"},{"slug":"the-gilded-vigil","title":"The Gilded Vigil","category":"locations","tags":"dungeon cairnhill kharai gilded-oath elvora tomb-crawl adventure-module cairnhill-breaks veranthas thune argollean-brotherhood undead seals binding","text":"The Gilded Vigil The Gilded Vigil is a tomb-crawl adventure module set in the Cairnhill Breaks , the fractured limestone foothills three miles east of Cairnhill . It is one station in a network of Elvoran guardian tombs that reinforce the seals binding a Kharai beneath Cairnhill. The guardian of this station -- Veranthas , whose vigil-name translates as He Who Holds the Middle Line -- has broken his covenant. Three factions have converged on the site. The seals have weakened but not broken. The Kharai has not escaped. Levels: 4--7 Approximate XP: 6,400 Key Themes Oath and betrayal -- the cost of vows made across millennia, and what happens when a guardian decides his oath was wrong The cost of eternal vigilance -- what two thousand years of silent duty does to a mind, even an undead one The ambiguous prisoner -- the Kharai sealed beneath Cairnhill may be innocent. It may not be. The module deliberately refuses to answer this question. New Monsters Monster Notes Oath-Bound Remains Lesser guardian undead; remnants of the Gilded Oath who did not achieve full sentinel status Gilded Sentinel Standard guardian construct of the tomb network Gilded Warden Elite guardian undead; protectors of reliquaries and sacred chambers Gilded Revenant A specific type of undead manifestation -- in this module, the skin Veranthas shed when he broke the oath The Gilded Vigil (unique) Veranthas himself -- the unique entity at the heart of the module Background The Cairnhill Breaks Three miles east of Cairnhill , the scrubland gives way to broken grey limestone ridges -- the Cairnhill Breaks . The terrain rises toward the eastern horizon where Mount Argolle stands, its white volcanic plume visible for miles. The lower gullies are choked with maquis scrub. The upper cliffs are bare limestone, carved by the First Empire into terraces, archways, and inscription panels -- remnants of a civilization that once considered these hills worth marking and maintaining. Harpies nest in the highest crags, making aerial approach dangerous and establishing the Breaks as a place avoided by sensible travelers. Among the lower ruins dwell the Thune remnant -- lizard-folk descendants of Argollean slave-soldiers who never left after the First Empire&#39;s collapse. They have inhabited these ruins for centuries, maintaining their own relationship with the landscape and the things buried within it. The Gilded Oath The Gilded Oath was a cohort of Elvoran warrior-priests who underwent a ritual of partial undeath called the Sevenfold Wounding . The process was as follows: Seven wounds were taken with a gold-threaded blade Through each wound, molten gold was slowly introduced into the bloodstream The gold hardened into a lattice beneath the skin , suffusing the body with a web of consecrated metal The process was agonizing and irreversible At completion, the priests died their living deaths and entered the guardian tombs The Gilded Oath have maintained the seals in silence for over two thousand years. They do not speak. They do not communicate. They simply hold the line -- station after station, tomb after tomb, across a network of seal-points threaded through the Cairnhill Breaks. Each guardian tomb is one node in a circuit of binding that reinforces the imprisonment of the Kharai beneath Cairnhill. The Gold Weave Mechanic The gold woven into the guardians&#39; bodies resonates with the Gnostic Geometry of the seals. It registers as faintly arcane to detection magic. When a guardian is destroyed, the gold can be removed from the body: 1 turn per HD to extract. The gold itself has both material and occult value -- it is part of the seal-circuit, and its removal weakens the network incrementally. Veranthas -- The Gilded Vigil Veranthas is the unique entity at the heart of this module. His vigil-name -- He Who Holds the Middle Line -- designates his station as the Second Seal in the guardian tomb network. The Breaking of the Covenant Sometime in the last year, Veranthas ceased his vigil . The sequence of his apostasy: He desecrated his own oath-altar -- the sacred center of Room 5, where the covenant was physically anchored He retreated to his private chamber deep in Tier Two He began communicating with the entity sealed beneath the hill The seals have weakened but not broken . The Kharai has not escaped. But the effects of the weakening are felt: Dreams have grown strange in Cairnhill -- the already-unusual shared dream-geography of the town&#39;s residents has intensified, shifted, become disturbing in ways it was not before The Thune remnant have grown bolder -- emboldened by the weakening of the seal-pressure they have always felt, pushing further from their usual territory The Argollean Brotherhood dispatched a cell -- sensing opportunity in the disturbance, Arannis Venn sent operatives to investigate The Central Mystery Veranthas communicated with the Kharai through the seal-membrane -- the metaphysical barrier that separates the imprisoned entity from the material world. Through this communication, Veranthas became convinced that the creature was: Sane -- not the mindless, ravening thing that two thousand years of silence had led him to assume Not hostile -- not pressing against the seals with malicious intent but with the desperation of a conscious being trapped in darkness Politically imprisoned -- sealed away not because it was dangerous to the world but because it was dangerous to the powers that ruled the world at the time of its imprisonment Veranthas reduced the sealing pressure to allow the Kharai to breathe -- to exist in something less than total sensory deprivation. He may be right. He may be wrong. This is deliberately left ambiguous. The module does not resolve whether the Kharai is truly innocent, truly sane, or truly non-hostile. Veranthas believes it. The evidence he presents in Room 16 is compelling but not conclusive. The party must make their own judgment -- and their judgment will have consequences that extend far beyond this tomb. Room 14 opens with a CONVERSATION, not a boss fight. Veranthas wants to talk. He has been alone with his doubt for a year. He wants someone to hear his case. The Three Factions Three factions have converged on the Gilded Vigil, each with different goals, different methods, and different dispositions toward the party. 1. The Covenant of the Open Hand Detail Description Type - - - leader - grakath -(thune-shaman) - - - goal - weaken-the-seals,-free-their- sleeping-god - - - disposition - wary;-will-parley - - - arrival - 3-days-ago - - - base - room-7-(fractured-gallery) - - - the-covenant-of-the-open-hand-is-a-thune-religious-faction-that-regards-the-sealed-kharai-as-a- sleeping-god ----a-divine-being-imprisoned-by-the-enemies-of-their-people.-they-have-arrived-at-the-gilded-vigil-with-the-intention-of-weakening-the-seals-and-ultimately-freeing-the-entity.-they-have- defaced-inscription-work-in-tier-one ----scratching-out-elvoran-glyphs-and-carving-their-own-symbols-over-the-seal-circuit-markers.-they-are-attempting-to- descend-into-tier-two -but-have-not-yet-succeeded. - grakath-and-his-followers-are- wary-but-willing-to-parley .-they-are-not-mindless-zealots.-they-have-their-own-understanding-of-what-is-imprisoned-beneath-the-hill,-and-they-believe-their-cause-is-just.-whether-their-understanding-is-correct-is-another-question-the-module-does-not-answer. - 2.-the-interred-dead - - detail - description - - - type - guardian-undead - - - composition - oath-bound-remains,-gilded-warden,-gilded-revenant - - - goal - defend-the-tomb,-enforce-the-covenant - - - disposition - hostile-unless-given-the-correct-elvoran-passphrase - - - the-interred-dead-are-the-remaining-guardians-of-the-tomb----the-gilded-oath-members-who-did- not -break-their-covenant.-they-continue-to-enforce-the-oath-as-they-have-for-two-millennia:-silently,-relentlessly,-and-without-discrimination.-they-attack-anyone-who-enters-the-tomb-without-authorization. - the-correct- elvoran-passphrase ---- veranthas-holds-the-line;-the-kharai-does-not-wake ----will-cause-them-to-stand-down.-this-passphrase-is-bitterly-ironic-given-current-circumstances:-veranthas-no-longer-holds-the-line,-and-the-kharai-is-closer-to-waking-than-it-has-been-in-two-thousand-years. - the-guardian-types-encountered-in-the-tomb: - - oath-bound-remains ----lesser-undead,-the-remnants-of-oath-takers-whose-binding-was-less-complete - gilded-warden ----elite-guardian-stationed-in-the-reliquary-(room-6) - gilded-revenant ----in-room-5,-this-is-specifically-the- skin -veranthas-shed -when-he-broke-his-oath.-the-desecration-of-the-oath-altar-caused-a-portion-of-his-consecrated-form-to-separate-and-manifest-as-an-independent,-hostile-entity-that-still-enforces-the-covenant-its-creator-abandoned. - - 3.-the-argollean-brotherhood - - detail - description - - - type - [[argollean-brotherhood - - - leader - **[[arannis-venn - - - scouts - martovar -and- sitha - - - goal - loot-elvoran-relics,-learn-what-the-seals-protect - - - disposition - hostile-if-discovered;-will-negotiate-if-cornered - - - the-brotherhood-cell-was-dispatched-when-the-weakening-of-the-seals-was-detected.-[[arannis-venn\" class=\"wiki-link\">Arannis Venn leads the operation personally -- a measure of how significant the Brotherhood considers this site. Two scouts -- Martovar and Sitha -- are stripping relics from Tier One, operating from a camp in Room 4 (the Warden&#39;s Cell). Arannis himself has already penetrated into Tier Two , moving ahead of his scouts to reach whatever the deeper tomb contains. The Brotherhood&#39;s disposition is hostile if discovered -- they do not want witnesses to their looting operation. However, they will negotiate if cornered . Arannis is pragmatic. If fighting is more costly than talking, he will talk. Stolen relics in the Brotherhood camp (Room 4): Relic Value Golden wreath 800 gp Ceremonial longsword 550 gp Veranthas hair relic Historical/occult significance Passphrase codex fragment Contains the Elvoran passphrase The Two Tiers The Gilded Vigil is divided into two tiers -- an upper tomb that has been breached by the intruding factions, and a deeper tomb that remains Veranthas&#39;s domain. Tier One -- The Upper Tomb (Rooms 1--8) Tier One is the portion of the tomb that has been breached. Evidence of both the Covenant of the Open Hand and the Argollean Brotherhood is visible throughout. The Interred Dead patrol these corridors with increasing agitation. Room 1: The Shattered Portico The entrance to the tomb. The portico has been broken open -- whether by the Covenant, the Brotherhood, or time itself is unclear. 2 Thune Sentinels guard the approach. A pit trap protects the inner threshold. Room 2: The Antechamber of Names The walls of this chamber bear the full roster of the Gilded Oath -- every warrior-priest who underwent the Sevenfold Wounding and entered a guardian tomb in the Cairnhill Breaks network. The names are inscribed in Elvoran script, each accompanied by a vigil-name and a station designation. This is the definitive record of the seal-circuit: how many guardians, how many stations, how many seals. The inscriptions have been partially defaced by the Covenant -- Thune markings scratched over Elvoran glyphs. Room 3: The Hall of Ascension The Sevenfold Wounding is depicted in relief carvings along the walls of this long hall -- a step-by-step visual record of the ritual that created the Gilded Oath. The carvings are detailed, clinical, and deeply unsettling: the seven wounds, the gold-threaded blade, the introduction of molten gold, the hardening of the lattice, the moment of living death. 2 Oath-Bound Remains patrol this hall. A stone arm trap -- a mechanical device disguised as part of the relief work -- guards the far end. Room 4: The Warden&#39;s Cell The Brotherhood camp. Martovar and Sitha have established a base here, using the room&#39;s defensible position to store their stolen relics. The room contains: Golden wreath (800 gp) -- a ceremonial piece stripped from a guardian&#39;s resting alcove Ceremonial longsword (550 gp) -- Elvoran craftsmanship, consecrated but no longer enchanted Veranthas hair relic -- a personal effect of the guardian, of historical and occult significance Passphrase codex fragment -- contains the Elvoran passphrase that will pacify the Interred Dead: Veranthas holds the line; the Kharai does not wake Room 5: The Oath Chamber The heart of Tier One. The oath-altar at the center of this chamber was the physical anchor of Veranthas&#39;s covenant -- the point where the Gilded Oath&#39;s binding was strongest. Veranthas desecrated it when he broke his covenant. The altar now bears patterns of Gnostic Geometry -- the mathematical language of the seal-circuit, now disrupted and rearranged. A sealed passage to Tier Two is visible but locked behind mechanisms that respond to the oath-altar&#39;s state. The Gilded Revenant haunts this chamber -- the skin Veranthas shed when he desecrated the altar. This entity is a manifestation of the broken covenant itself: the portion of Veranthas&#39;s consecrated form that refused to follow him into apostasy. It still enforces the oath. It is hostile and dangerous. Room 6: The Reliquary A treasury of Elvoran relics -- items of historical, religious, and monetary value placed here as part of the tomb&#39;s original consecration. A Gilded Warden guards the chamber. A contact poison trap protects the primary reliquary cases. Room 7: The Fractured Gallery The Covenant of the Open Hand&#39;s base camp . Grakath and his Thune followers have established themselves here, using the gallery&#39;s multiple exits as escape routes. The walls bear evidence of the Covenant&#39;s defacement -- Thune symbols carved over Elvoran inscription work. Grakath is willing to parley. He believes the party may be useful -- or may need to be eliminated. His assessment will depend on how the encounter unfolds. Room 8 Continuation of the upper tomb complex -- transitional space connecting the Fractured Gallery to the deeper architecture. Tier Two -- The Deeper Tomb (Rooms 9+) Tier Two is Veranthas&#39;s domain -- the portion of the tomb that the guardian retreated to after breaking his covenant. The Interred Dead are thicker here. The seal-circuit&#39;s geometry is more intense, the Gnostic patterns more complex. The air itself feels pressured, as though the proximity to the sealed Kharai exerts a physical force. Arannis Venn has already penetrated into Tier Two, moving ahead of his scouts. Room 14: Veranthas This room opens with a CONVERSATION, not a boss fight. Veranthas -- the Gilded Vigil himself -- is here. He has been alone with his doubt for a year. He has broken a two-thousand-year oath based on his conviction that the entity he was guarding is not what he was told it was. He wants to talk. He wants someone to hear his case. He wants to know if he was right. The encounter with Veranthas is the module&#39;s central dramatic moment. He is not a raving madman. He is not a corrupted puppet of the Kharai. He is a being of enormous age and experience who has come to a conclusion that terrifies him -- that his entire existence, his two-thousand-year vigil, his agonizing transformation through the Sevenfold Wounding, may have been in service to a lie. How the party responds to Veranthas -- whether they fight him, listen to him, help him, or destroy him -- determines the module&#39;s outcome. Room 16: The Inscriptions This chamber contains the inscriptions presenting Veranthas&#39;s case -- the evidence he has gathered through his communication with the Kharai. This is the central mystery payoff : the accumulated argument that the Kharai&#39;s imprisonment was political rather than necessary, that the entity is sane and non-hostile, that the seals were built not to protect the world but to silence a rival. The inscriptions are compelling. They are not conclusive. The module leaves the truth deliberately unresolved. Key Treasure The Passphrase Veranthas holds the line; the Kharai does not wake. This passphrase pacifies the Interred Dead throughout the tomb, transforming a hostile dungeon into a navigable (if still dangerous) space. It is found in the passphrase codex fragment in Room 4. Worth 300 gp to a scholar of Elvoran history Priceless to a party entering Tier Two, where the Interred Dead are thicker and more dangerous Connections to the Wider Campaign The Gilded Vigil connects to multiple ongoing threads in the Fallen Empire campaign: The Kharai and the nature of their imprisonment -- the central question of whether the Kharai are truly dangerous or politically inconvenient beings The Cairnhill psychic bleed -- the weakening of the seals has intensified the bleed effects on the town&#39;s residents The Argollean Brotherhood&#39;s ongoing interest in ancient binding structures and Elvoran artifacts The nature of the First Empire&#39;s relationship with the elder races and the decisions they made about what to seal and what to destroy The Thune remnant and their claim to the Cairnhill Breaks as ancestral territory See Also cairnhill -- The town shaped by the Kharai&#39;s psychic bleed, three miles west the-kharai -- The Imprisoned Ones; the entity sealed beneath Cairnhill argollean-brotherhood -- The faction looting the tomb arannis-venn -- Brotherhood leader, present in Tier Two Elvoran -- The civilization that created the Gilded Oath Thune -- The lizard-folk whose descendants form the Covenant of the Open Hand cthonic-faith -- The broader theological context of seals and imprisonment lakandi-binding-tradition -- A related binding tradition varek-ashstone -- Another guardian maintaining vigil over a Kharai prison lake-silverhead -- The other known cairnhouse in Argolle campaign-chronicle -- Session history referencing the Gilded Oath discovery"},{"slug":"the-heartwood","title":"The Heartwood","category":"locations","tags":"wilderness forest ancient backlands uncharted","text":"The Heartwood The Heartwood is old. It doesn&#39;t know you&#39;re there. You could die in it and the forest wouldn&#39;t notice. -- Rika Sorn, woodsman The Heartwood is the oldest forest in the Backlands and possibly the oldest forest anyone has mapped -- though mapped is a generous term, as no survey of the Heartwood has ever been completed. The Mithrian Empire sent survey parties in. Some came back. None agreed on what they saw or where they had been. The Heartwood is not hostile in the way the Gallowswood is hostile. The Gallowswood watches you. The Heartwood does not know you are there. You can disappear in the Heartwood without doing anything wrong. Geography and Zones The Heartwood divides into three concentric zones of increasing age, size, and danger. The boundaries are not sharp -- the forest transitions gradually, and by the time you realize you have entered a deeper zone, you have been in it for some time. Outer Heartwood Dense deciduous forest dominated by beech, hornbeam, sessile oak, and hazel . The canopy is thick but not impenetrable. Light reaches the forest floor in patches. Undergrowth is heavy -- brambles, ferns, and fallen deadwood. The outer Heartwood is navigable with standard skill and provides reliable foraging: hazelnuts, beech mast, wild garlic (spring), and blackberries (late summer). It resembles a large, dense, ordinary forest. This resemblance is deceptive. Middle Heartwood Reached after approximately one day of travel into the forest. The trees grow older and larger. The understory thins as the canopy above becomes more complete, starving the forest floor of light. The character of the forest changes -- the human-scale familiarity of the outer Heartwood gives way to something that does not acknowledge human scale. Owlbeasts are territorial in the middle Heartwood. They hunt by both sound and smell -- masking one sense does not protect against the other. Deep claw marks scored into tree trunks are territory markers. If you see these marks, you are in an owlbeast&#39;s range. Move through quickly and quietly. Navigation : 14+ per half-day to maintain bearing. Landmarks become unreliable. Trees that seemed distinctive begin to resemble one another. Deep Heartwood The trees are enormous beyond reckoning. The silence is absolute -- not the loaded, watchful silence of the Gallowswood , which feels like something holding its breath, but the silence of a world that existed before human sound and expects to exist after it. The deep Heartwood contains things that woodsmen do not describe with precision. Not because they are being evasive or dramatic, but because precision fails them: Tracks that do not match any known animal. Not beastman, not bear, not owlbeast. Something else. A sense of being assessed. Not hunted. Not threatened. Evaluated by something that has not yet decided what you are. The feeling that the forest has noticed you -- not with alarm or hostility, but with the slow attention of something immeasurably old turning a fraction of its awareness toward a small, brief, warm-blooded thing that has wandered into its presence. Navigation : 17+ per half-day . There are no reliable landmarks. The forest defeats orientation through sheer scale and uniformity. Critical warning : If you think you are on a path in the deep Heartwood, you are not. There are no paths in the deep Heartwood. Anything that looks like a path was not made by human feet and does not lead where a human would want to go. Navigation The Heartwood will get you lost. This is not a function of poor skill. It is a property of the place. Zone Navigation Throw Failure Consequence Outer Standard Normal disorientation. Retrace and try again. Middle 14+ per half-day Lost. Random direction of travel until next successful check. Deep 17+ per half-day Lost in territory where being lost can be fatal. Following Streams Following streams out always works. Every stream in the Heartwood flows outward toward the forest&#39;s edge eventually. The method is reliable but slow -- it takes approximately twice as long as direct navigation to reach the outer Heartwood by following water. This is the recommended emergency navigation method. If lost in the middle or deep Heartwood, find a stream and follow it downstream. Do not attempt to shortcut across ridges or through dense growth. The stream will get you out. Your sense of direction will not. Flora The Heartwood provides several plants of significant practical and medicinal value: Plant Zone Description Use Hazelnuts Outer Seasonal nut crop Edible, reliable autumn food Beech Mast Outer Small triangular nuts Edible, seasonal Wild Garlic Outer Spring herb, identifiable by smell Edible, nutritious Blackberries Outer Late summer berry crop in clearings Edible, abundant Comfrey / Bruisewort All (near streams) Broad-leaved herb found near running water Poultice: heals 1d3 damage, once per day per patient . The most reliable healing herb in the Backlands. Blessed Thistle Middle / Deep Spiny herb with yellow flowers Doubles hit points recovered from rest. Rare and exceptionally valuable. Dreamgrass Middle / Deep Pale-leaved sedge found around old beech roots Sedative. Small doses : calms panic, aids sleep, useful for field surgery. Large doses : deep unconsciousness, respiratory depression, potentially fatal. Dosage is critical. Insect-Repellent Vine Middle / Deep (on older oaks) Vine growing on mature oak bark Crushed and applied to skin, repels biting insects. Practical value in a forest where insects are relentless. Also useful in the Empire has sent parties in on multiple occasions. The results were consistent only in their inconsistency -- returning members could not agree on the forest&#39;s geography, on what they had encountered, or on how long they had been inside. The Avari appear to have some relationship with the outer Heartwood but do not enter the deep forest. Whether this represents respect, fear, or a prohibition from their own tradition is not clear. The Heartwood may be connected to whatever force or presence underlies the Gallowswood&#39;s curse and the Awakening stirring in the Backlands . Or it may be something entirely separate -- something older than the conflicts between Empyrean and Cthonic , older than the Eladra , older than anything that has a name in human languages. See Also the-backlands -- The frontier province containing the Heartwood gallowswood -- The other great forest of the Backlands, cursed and watchful the-slog -- The wasteland east of the forests fort-harvald -- The nearest settlement to the Heartwood&#39;s southern edge avari -- The people with the longest relationship to the Heartwood backlands-field-guide -- Comprehensive survival reference including Heartwood flora beastmen -- Not present in the deep Heartwood (a notable absence)"},{"slug":"the-slog","title":"The Slog","category":"locations","tags":"wilderness slog backlands encounters borderlands foraging wild-hunt","text":"The Slog Wind stinks of alkali and rot. Insects bite and burrow. Things cry out in the distance. Nothing answers. The Slog is the primary hunting ground of the Backlands -- a broad wasteland stretching north and east of Bone Creek , between the Gallowswood and the ruins of Crossings . It is where Bone Creek&#39;s Scalpers and beastman warbands pressing south from Crossings most frequently clash. Geography A flat, bleak expanse scabbed with thorn scrub and split stone. Few trees grow here. Little shade lingers. The ground is hard-packed and alkaline, broken at intervals by dry gulches and rocky outcroppings choked with thorn thickets. The Slog was once farmland -- productive agricultural territory broken by the Argollean collapse and centuries of war. The land remembers what it was. Old Imperial stone markers still stand at intervals along road cuts, mute witnesses to a time when this territory was settled and cultivated. When the rains come, the bones of unlucky men push out of the ground -- the residue of battles, massacres, and lonely deaths stretching back generations. Terrain and Travel Detail Description Territory Type Borderlands Movement (open scrub) x3/4 normal movement rate Movement (gully/rocky terrain) x1/2 normal movement rate Navigation (clear day) Straightforward, no check required Navigation (dust storm / night) Navigation throw required (6+) Encounter Frequency Once per 6-mile hex traveled; once per 12 hours resting/stationary The terrain is open enough to spot enemies at distance, which provides some warning to alert travelers. But the dry gulches and thorn thickets provide abundant ambush cover for those who know how to use them -- and the beastman warbands and hostile Scalper gangs know how to use them. Encounter Table Roll 1d8 for each encounter: Roll Encounter Number 1 beastmen Beastman Orcs 2 beastmen Beastman Goblins 3 Brigands / Hostile scalper-gangs Scalpers 4 Giant Hyenas 1d4+1 5 Stirges 1d10 6 Ghouls (risen from unmarked battlefield graves) 1d6 7 Wight (fallen Imperial soldier, still at his post) 1d2 8 Giant Scorpion 1d2 The encounter table reflects the Slog&#39;s character: a killing ground layered with the detritus of centuries. The beastman presence (orcs and goblins) represents warbands pushing south from Crossings . The brigands and hostile Scalpers are a reminder that not all human activity in the Slog is sanctioned or friendly. The undead -- ghouls rising from unmarked battlefield graves and wights of Imperial soldiers who never left their posts -- speak to the land&#39;s long, violent history. The natural predators (hyenas, stirges, scorpions) are simply what thrives in a place like this. Strategic Significance The Slog is the primary operational theater for Bone Creek&#39;s Scalper gangs . It is where the bounty economy plays out in practice -- gangs ranging into the wasteland to hunt beastmen , collect scalps, and bring them back to the Red River Exchange for redemption. The terrain favors neither side decisively: open ground allows detection but gulches allow ambush. Engagements in the Slog tend to be sharp, brutal, and short. Beastman warbands -- primarily orcs and goblins -- press south from Crossings through the Slog with increasing frequency. Whether this represents organized military pressure or simply the overflow of the ruined city&#39;s teeming population is a matter of debate among the Scalpers. The practical effect is the same: the Slog is never safe. Flora and Foraging The Slog is a wasteland, but it yields to those who know what to look for. See backlands-field-guide for the full regional flora reference. Edible and Useful Plants Plant Description Use Crowsthorn / Ironweed Grey-green scrub thorn, chest-height, dominant Slog vegetation Bark mildly toxic. Dry catches fire easily (excellent tinder). Boiled thorn-tips produce a weak antiseptic wash. Dustwort Low flat-rosette plant, pale green fleshy leaves, near old water sources Edible raw but bitter. BEWARE: Saltweed closely resembles dustwort but has a waxy sheen -- causes heavy vomiting within 1 hour. Goldenrod Sheltered gullies, dense yellow flower heads in late summer Dried: +2 on proficiency throws to cure disease (requires Healing proficiency). Seasonal. Horsetail / Snake Grass Segmented reed-like plant near water As poultice: +2 on Mortal Wounds table rolls . Both goldenrod and horsetail are forageable on Survival 7+ . Water Sources Old wells with Imperial stone markers are scattered across the Slog, dating to the Argollean farming period. Some still hold water. Dry gulch bends : Dig approximately 2 feet into the bend of a dry gulch to find subsurface water. Survival throws : 14+ in summer, 10+ in other seasons to locate water. Argollean Tombs Scattered across the Slog are mound graves marked with angular Argollean script on stone markers. The undead population in these tombs predates the beastman presence by centuries -- these dead are old, remnants of the Argollean civilization that once farmed this land. Identifying a tomb : A low, grass-covered rise with even sides and a depression at its crown. The geometric regularity distinguishes a tomb from a natural hill or outcropping. Warning : Give tombs respectful distance at night. The ghouls and wights on the Slog&#39;s encounter table did not appear from nowhere -- many of them emerge from these ancient burial sites. Lakandi Sign The Lakandi who range through the Slog leave distinctive fieldcraft markers. Learning to read them is a survival advantage: Fire sign : Small, efficient fires on a tripod arrangement -- not the sprawling campfires of Imperial soldiers or Scalpers Bone markers : Scraped bone left at campsites or along trails Knot-patterns : Specific knot-patterns in cordage carrying encoded meaning, though the full system is not widely understood outside Lakandi culture Stone stacks at water sources : Small stone stacks placed at water sources indicate the water is clean and safe to drink Weather and Seasons Season Conditions Summer Brutal heat. Move at dawn and dusk only. Daytime travel risks heat exhaustion. Water scarce (Survival 14+). Lightning Season Violent electrical storms. Get low -- the flat terrain makes anything upright a target. Spring Flooding. Dry gulches become rushing channels without warning. A gulch that was bone-dry at dawn can be a torrent by afternoon. Camp on high ground. Winter The easiest season. Cold but manageable. Reduced insect activity. Water more accessible. Tracking Beastmen Reading beastman sign in the Slog: Broken crowsthorn at chest-height : Standard beastman patrol. They push through the scrub without attempting concealment. Crowsthorn bent at 4 feet or below : A scout or rearguard moving carefully, deliberately keeping a low profile. More dangerous -- this is a beastman that knows it is being hunted, or is hunting you. 30-foot-wide flattened lanes through the scrub : Hill giant. Nothing else leaves a track like that. Hill giants accompanying beastman warbands are rare but devastating. The Wild Hunt On certain nights -- specifically when the eight-starred Wolf constellation climbs high -- something else moves through the Slog. Riders on the horizon that move too fast and too silently, trailing mist behind them. The dead found in their wake cannot be raised by clerics . The bodies are intact but the souls are simply gone. The Scalpers call it the Wild Hunt . They do not discuss it with newcomers. Experienced Scalpers who have survived encounters refuse to describe what they saw in detail. The Wild Hunt is not a beastman warband, not an undead incursion, not a natural phenomenon. It is something else entirely, and the Slog&#39;s veterans treat it with a fear they do not extend to trolls, wights, or beastman war-chiefs. When the Wolf constellation rides high, experienced Scalpers make camp, bank their fires, and do not move until dawn. See Also bone-creek -- The settlement whose economy depends on hunting in the Slog crossings -- The ruined city from which beastman warbands press south gallowswood -- The cursed forest bordering the Slog to the west the-heartwood -- The ancient forest beyond the Gallowswood crossings-hinterlands -- The more dangerous territory closer to the Crossings ruins scalper-gangs -- The gangs who hunt beastmen in the Slog beastmen -- The primary targets and threats in the Slog the-backlands -- The province containing the Slog eladra -- The Argollean civilization whose tombs dot the Slog lakandi -- Wasteland warriors whose sign can be read in the Slog backlands-field-guide -- Comprehensive survival reference including Slog flora"},{"slug":"the-undercity","title":"The Undercity","category":"locations","tags":"location megadungeon aodahn sanctuary eladra undercity constructs empyrean threshold ascension mystery","text":"The Undercity The Undercity is the vast network of ruins beneath Sanctuary -- the remains of ancient Aodahn , the Eladran harbor-city upon which Sanctuary was built. It is a three-tier megadungeon of escalating danger and mystery, descending from mundane vermin-infested warrens into the preserved heart of an alien civilization and, ultimately, to the place where the Eladra attempted something that may have destroyed them -- or transformed them into something beyond mortal comprehension. At a Glance Detail Description Location Beneath Laced Hand or other criminal enterprises -- treat the Warrens as infrastructure, not as the surface layer of something vastly older and more dangerous than they comprehend. Tier 2: Old Aodahn (Levels 3-7) Below the Warrens lies the preserved heart of the Eladran city . This is not ruin -- this is a civilization suspended in amber. Inhabitants Construct guardians -- Eladran-built automatons that still patrol their ancient routes, enforcing security protocols for masters who vanished millennia ago Doppelgangers -- shapeshifters that have infiltrated the preserved city, mimicking Eladran forms Empyrean energy -- the metaphysical residue of Eladran sorcery still saturates this tier, creating unpredictable magical effects Character Old Aodahn is the archaeological and metaphysical heart of the Undercity. The Eladra of Aodahn vanished without explanation -- their belongings remained, their constructs continued to function, but the people simply ceased to be present. No evidence of war, plague, or flight. Whatever happened to them happened all at once, and it happened here. The construct guardians are a particular danger. They are not mindless -- they follow programmed directives with Eladran precision. They do not distinguish between explorers, looters, and threats. Anything that is not Eladran is, by their programming, an intruder. The doppelgangers raise disturbing questions. What are they mimicking? Who are they pretending to be? And for whom are they performing? Tier 3: Foundations of the Spires (Levels 7+) The deepest level -- the foundations of Aodahn&#39;s five ivory spires that rise over 300 feet above Sanctuary. This is where the Eladra&#39;s greatest works were undertaken, and where their greatest mystery resides. Inhabitants Masterwork constructs -- the most sophisticated Eladran automatons, far more dangerous and intelligent than the guardians of Old Aodahn Major elementals -- beings of pure elemental force, either summoned or attracted by the metaphysical energies that saturate the Foundations The Threshold -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened, and the door has not fully closed The Threshold The Threshold is the defining mystery of the Undercity and possibly of the entire Backlands . This is the site where the Eladra of Aodahn attempted -- or achieved -- their ascension . The nature of this ascension is unknown: Did they transcend physical existence? Did they pass through the Veil into the Beyond ? Did they merge with the Aurelion ? Did they destroy themselves? What is known is that the door has not fully closed . Whatever the Eladra opened at the Threshold remains ajar. Empyrean energy bleeds through the crack. The constructs guard it with lethal devotion. The elementals are drawn to it like moths to flame. The Threshold may connect to the broader mysteries of the Eladran disappearance, the Womb Curse , and the question of whether the Eladra&#39;s ascension and the Elvora&#39;s corruption are two sides of the same metaphysical event. Relationship to Sanctuary The Undercity is not merely beneath Sanctuary -- it is the foundation upon which Sanctuary rests, literally and metaphysically. The city above was named after the Eladran word for the city below: Aodahn means sanctuary or refuge. The Mithrians preserved the name without understanding its origin. Multiple access points exist throughout Sanctuary&#39;s districts, and the boundaries between the modern city and the ancient one are permeable in ways that the surface population does not fully appreciate. The Laced Hand criminal syndicate, various smuggling operations, and occasional adventuring parties all make use of the Undercity&#39;s upper reaches, but few venture beyond the Warrens into the eerie preservation of Old Aodahn. See Also aodahn -- The ancient Eladran city whose ruins form the Undercity sanctuary -- The modern city built above eladra -- The race that built Aodahn and vanished at the Threshold the-veil -- The boundary the Threshold may breach the-beyond -- What lies on the other side the-aurelion -- The cosmic being the Eladra may have sought elvora -- The corrupted branch of the Eladra the-womb-curse -- Possibly connected to the Eladran disappearance laced-hand -- Criminal syndicate that uses the Warrens gnostic-geometry -- Eladran sorcerous tradition preserved in Aodahn&#39;s ruins"},{"slug":"thornasse","title":"Thornasse","category":"locations","tags":"location avari erenthis cynar cultural-execution black-tree crossings ruins argolle backlands imperial-academy","text":"Thornasse Cynar did not burn a tree. He burned a people. The Erenthis was the heart of the Avari Confederation -- their sacred center, their living covenant with the world. When it burned, the Avari did not simply lose a symbol. They lost the axis around which their civilization turned. The collapse that followed was not military. It was spiritual. Thornasse is the site where High Mage Cynar burned the great Erenthis tree thirty years ago, constituting a cultural execution of the Avari people. The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist collapsed within months of the burning. The scorched stump -- known as the Black Tree -- still stands at the center of the ruins of Crossings . Something endures. At a Glance Detail Description Location At or near High Mage Cynar -- acting with the authority and power of the Imperial Academy -- burned the great Erenthis tree at Thornasse. The Erenthis was not merely a tree. It was the sacred center of the Avari Confederation , the living axis around which their civilization, their spiritual identity, and their collective will turned. The tree was covenant, symbol, and anchor -- its destruction was not an act of war but an act of cultural annihilation. The burning was deliberate, calculated, and devastating in its effect. The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist the Mithrian Empire collapsed within months. Military defeat had not achieved what a single act of cultural execution accomplished -- the destruction of the thing that held the Avari together as a people. This act remains one of the most consequential uses of Imperial Academy power in living memory, and one of the most morally contested. The Black Tree The scorched stump of the Erenthis -- called the Black Tree -- still stands at the center of the ruins of Crossings . It has not been removed. It has not decayed. It stands as monument and wound, marking the site where the Avari Confederation died as a political and spiritual entity. Something Endures The roots of the Erenthis have not fully died. The ground around the Black Tree is warm to the touch -- not from sunlight or geothermal activity, but from something deeper, older, and more deliberate. The tree was burned, the Confederation was broken, and the Avari were scattered -- but the roots persist. Whatever the Erenthis was connected to -- whatever power, presence, or living covenant it embodied -- has not been entirely extinguished. What this persistence means -- whether it represents hope for the Avari, a threat to the Empire, or something beyond either interpretation -- is not yet understood. Consequences The destruction of the Erenthis accomplished what decades of military campaigns could not: The Avari Confederation fragmented within months of the burning Organized Avari resistance to the Mithrian Empire effectively ceased The Avari people were scattered, their cultural center destroyed, their collective identity shattered The ruins of Crossings became a monument to imperial power and Avari loss The Imperial Academy&#39;s role in the destruction cemented its reputation as both indispensable and dangerous See Also the-erenthis -- The sacred tree that was burned Cynar -- The High Mage who burned the Erenthis Avari Confederation -- The civilization destroyed by the burning Avari -- The people whose cultural center was annihilated crossings -- The ruins where the Black Tree still stands Nethercity -- The underground complex beneath Crossings imperial-academy -- The institution that authorized and executed the burning mithrian-empire -- The empire that benefited from the Avari collapse the-backlands -- The province containing Thornasse"},{"slug":"log","title":"Wiki Log","category":"overview","tags":"","text":"Wiki Log Chronological record of wiki operations. Newest entries first. [2026-04-11] update | Missing Entity Pages Created Pages created (12): rook , anaya , antonius , lynara , crackback , doc-quinten , irontoe , theo , argoll-river , the-undercity , the-womb-curse , the-black-tree People (8): Rook (dead bandit king at Fort Ikenvar), Anaya (henchman with Gallowswood visions), Antonius (henchman with Rendson vision), Lynara (Eladran Nightblade, Malyn&#39;s apprentice), Crackback (Targ thief, Marr&#39;s enforcer), Doc Quinten (Kolani barber-surgeon), Irontoe (Mithrian smith, lost leg fighting Lakandi), Theo (Thrassian Flophouse owner, Marr&#39;s informant) Locations (2): Argoll River (major river of the Backlands), The Undercity (three-tier megadungeon beneath Sanctuary) Lore (2): The Womb Curse (Eladra/Elvora mystery mentioned by Eolande), The Black Tree (scorched Erenthis at Thornasse, roots endure) Index updated: 12 new pages, page count 178 - 190 Notes: Red link cleanup. All 12 pages were entities referenced via wikilinks in existing pages but lacking their own wiki pages. Full stat blocks included for Lynara, Crackback, Doc Quinten, Irontoe, and Theo. Maximum detail and cross-referencing throughout. [2026-04-10] ingest | Next Session Reference (Fort Meade to Sanctuary) Source: Fallen Empire/next_session_reference.docx Pages created (4): eolande , the-stone-of-sakkara , the-guzzler , src-next-session-reference Pages updated (4): campaign-chronicle (Arc V: three scenes added), theodotus (Stone of Sakkara moral crisis and escalation), malachor (Eolande revelation, interrogation, dispatch, expedition plans), legate-marcellus (charter proposal details, political transformation) Index updated: 1 new person, 2 new lore pages, 1 new source page, page count 173 - 178 Notes: MAJOR plot revelations. Eolande -- an Eladran general from ~3000 BE -- is still present at the Black Tree (scorched Erenthis at Thornasse). The Reclaimers encountered him there. Malachor&#39;s most significant dispatch ever sent to his secret third-party contact, revealing Eolande&#39;s existence. The Stone of Sakkara is amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward innocence as the party moves south -- escalating trail of violence (farm animals, a horse, a child). Theodotus faces the moral crisis: killing the Guzzler resolves nothing, the Stone will reach through something else. Legate Marcellus proposes a formal charter: exclusive salvage rights to Crossings/Nethercity, vault/warehouse, quarterly market fairs, 15% (negotiable to 10%) of recovered value. Unspoken agenda: political independence from Governor Drussus. [2026-04-10] ingest | Woodsman&#39;s Field Notes Source: THE BACKLANDS/PLAYER MATERIALS/Woodsmans_Field_Notes.docx Pages created (3): backlands-field-guide , the-heartwood , src-woodsmans-field-notes Pages updated (2): gallowswood (flora table, crab spiders, the Dome, abominations with combat stats, Avari warning stones, burial mounds, navigation hazards, the loaded silence), the-slog (flora/foraging with mechanics, Argollean tombs, Lakandi sign reading, weather/seasons, beastman tracking guide, hill giants, the Wild Hunt) Index updated: 1 new location, 1 new lore page, 1 new source page, page count 170 - 173 Notes: Major survival content ingest. Introduces the Heartwood as a completely new major location -- oldest forest in the Backlands, three zones of increasing danger, no survey ever completed, unidentifiable entities in the deep forest. New creature types: abominations (three attacks/round, paralytic venom, immune to sleep/charm/hold) at the Gallowswood Dome, crab spiders (dog-sized, paralytic, -2 surprise). New phenomenon: the Wild Hunt (riders when the Wolf constellation is high, dead cannot be raised). Extensive herbal medicine mechanics across all four regions. Backlands-field-guide serves as the master survival reference page cross-linking all regional content. [2026-04-10] ingest | Backlands Regional Overview + Multiple Source Pages Sources: THE BACKLANDS/Backlands_Regional_Overview.docx , Crossings Adventure Supplement, The Gilded Vigil, Random Notes, Backlands Timeline, History of the First Empire Pages created (8): the-slog , the-foothills , crossings-hinterlands , src-crossings-supplement , src-gilded-vigil , src-backlands-regional-overview , src-random-notes , src-backlands-timeline , src-first-empire-history Pages updated (3): gallowswood (full rewrite with encounter table, black heart, Outlands classification), cassian-varro (MAJOR: criminal enterprise — bandit ops from Fort Ikenvar, beastman trafficking via Malyn, fraudulent scalp manufacturing), fort-meade (Fort Caldras alias added, naming discrepancy noted) Index updated: 3 new location pages, 5 new source pages, page count 162 - 170 Notes: Four wilderness regions now fully documented with terrain rules and encounter tables: the Slog (Borderlands), Gallowswood (Outlands, cursed), the Foothills (mines), Crossings Hinterlands (highest danger). Key revelation: Varro&#39;s criminal enterprise exposes the Lord Merchant as running banditry, beastman slavery, and bounty fraud. Gallowswood rewrite includes the pulsating black heart beneath the granite dome from session notes. Five new source pages cataloged for previously untracked documents. [2026-04-10] ingest | Campaign Recap + Session History Source: THE BACKLANDS/SESSION MATERIALS/Campaign Recap Document.docx Pages created (8): campaign-chronicle , theodotus , iman , shatzi , tiberius , tancred , order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon Pages updated (1): the-reclaimers Notes: Campaign session history populated. All 5 active PCs and 1 deceased PC (Tancred) have individual pages. Sessions category now active. [2026-04-10] ingest | Timelines + Fort Harvald + History of the First Empire Sources: THE BACKLANDS/SETTING LORE/Timelines.docx , THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/fort_harvald_acks.docx Pages created (2): sergeant-voss , noma Pages rewritten (2): history-of-mithrapos (expanded from 663 BE to full 4100 BE timeline), fort-harvald (complete settlement reference with 11 NPCs) Notes: History now covers deep pre-imperial era: Eladran city-states, Great Teacher awakening in Krysea, Thune creation, Bitter War, Argollean Empire, Thune rebellion, Massar rise, and full imperial chronology. Fort Harvald fully detailed with bayou frontier atmosphere. [2026-04-10] update | Created 82 missing entity pages Filled all broken wikilinks with standalone pages Created: 21 race/culture pages, 23 deity/concept pages, 24 house/NPC/event pages, 14 location/concept pages Notes: Every wikilinks in the wiki should now resolve to a page with real content. No more empty nodes. [2026-04-10] ingest | Sanctuary City Supplement Source: THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/Sanctuary_City_Supplement.docx Pages created (6): sanctuary , aodahn , governor-drussus , prelate-voth , laced-hand , drussine-guard Source page: src-sanctuary-city Notes: Massive city supplement. Provincial capital with 8 districts and 80+ keyed locations. Key NPCs: Governor Drussus (Fighter 12, building something), Prelate Voth (Cleric 13, Temple leader 20 years), Castellan Thibaud (Master Thief 7, Laced Hand boss). Three-tier megadungeon beneath city (ruins of Aodahn/Eladra city). Five ivory spires may be engineered Erenthis analogues. Eladra vanished mysteriously from Aodahn before Mithrian arrival. [2026-04-10] ingest | Faiths of Argolle Source: Faiths of Argolle.docx Pages created (10): the-erenthis , the-nethercity , the-kharai , the-convergence-problem , bel-earth-hunger , cthonic-corruption , lakandi-binding-tradition , varek-ashstone , greta , cairnhill Pages updated (1): congregation-of-the-hollow-sun (rewritten with Shaw&#39;s full theology) Source page: src-faiths-of-argolle Notes: Deep theological document. Major new concepts: Erenthis trees (Eladran living Empyrean monuments, root network hostile to Cthonic corruption), the Nethercity (Eladran necropolis beneath Crossings, vessel for the Awakening, Great Teacher entity dormant in depths), the Kharai (ancient imprisoned beings in Ygrathen cairnhouses), Convergence Problem (Empyrean and Cthonic gods may be same divided powers), Bel earth-hunger (agricultural blood cult in Dunwick area), Lakandi demon-binding, Varek Ashstone (Ygrathen hermit at Lake Silverhead), Shaw&#39;s Hollow Sun theology (Seros has been stolen, salvation through suffering). [2026-04-10] ingest | Crossings Points of Interest Source: THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/Crossings Points of Interest.docx Pages created (1): crossings Source page: src-crossings-poi Notes: Ruined city gazetteer with 10 POIs including ghouls, undead Elvoran mummy, deranged dryad, corrupted giant crocodile, and beastman neutral ground. Encounter table included. [2026-04-10] ingest | Dramatis Personae NPC Reference Sources: THE BACKLANDS/CHARACTERS NPCS/DRAMATIS PERSONAE.docx , THE BACKLANDS/CHARACTERS NPCS/NPCS.docx Pages created (11): malyn-the-misshapen , ezekiel-shaw , skinner , arannis-venn , bottlecap-juno , wekko , marcos-varanes , sergeant-gallus , kael-baldric , congregation-of-the-hollow-sun , scalper-gangs Source page: src-dramatis-personae Notes: Full NPC roster with ACKS II stat blocks, secrets, and allegiances. All Scalper gang leaders and factions documented. Kael Baldric listed as missing. [2026-04-10] ingest | Fort Meade GM Reference Source: THE BACKLANDS/LOCATIONS/fort_meade.docx Pages created (5): fort-meade , lady-severina , sergeant-crull , malachor , argollean-brotherhood Pages updated (1): legate-marcellus Source page: src-fort-meade Notes: Fort Meade garrison with trade route dynamics, political leverage, Rook aftermath, Fort Ikenvar/Guzzler threat. Detailed profiles for all key NPCs with secrets. Argollean Brotherhood introduced as covert faction. [2026-04-10] update | Enriched all wiki pages with maximum detail Rewrote magic-and-sorcery , races-and-cultures , history-of-mithrapos , imperial-academy with exhaustive detail, all flavor quotes, all named individuals Rewrote empyrean-faith , cthonic-faith , seros , the-measure-and-the-scale with full theological detail and all source quotes Notes: User requested maximum detail. All pages now include every available quote, every named person, every cultural/mechanical detail from the source documents. [2026-04-10] ingest | The Backlands Source: THE BACKLANDS/SETTING LORE/THE BACKLANDS.docx Pages created (8): the-backlands , bone-creek , thaddeus-marr , tolliver-watts , cassian-varro , legate-marcellus , brother-marco , red-river-consortium Source page: src-the-backlands Notes: Second ingest. Backlands province overview, Bone Creek gazetteer with all 9 locations, 5 NPC pages, Red River Consortium faction page. Bone Creek includes 16+ named NPCs with their secrets and allegiances. [2026-04-10] ingest | Fallen Empire Primer Source: THE BACKLANDS/SETTING LORE/FALLEN EMPIRE PRIMER FINAL.docx Pages created (21): overview , mithrian-empire , great-houses , history-of-mithrapos , magic-and-sorcery , races-and-cultures , mithrian-calendar , languages-of-mithrapos , empyrean-faith , seros , empyrean-pantheon , cthonic-faith , cthonic-pantheon , the-mystical , the-measure-and-the-scale , imperial-academy , mithrian-military , imperial-talons , thousand-temples , burnished-scale , mithra-city Source page: src-fallen-empire-primer Notes: First ingest. Foundational setting document covering empire, houses, military, history, religions, magic, races, calendar, languages. Seeded all major wiki categories except people/ and sessions/. [2026-04-10] init | Wiki scaffolding created Created directory structure: people/, locations/, factions/, faiths/, lore/, sessions/, sources/ Created index.md, log.md, overview.md (stub) Created CLAUDE.md schema at vault root Notes: Wiki initialized using the LLM Wiki pattern. Ready for first ingest."},{"slug":"argollean-empire","title":"The Argollean Empire (The First Empire)","category":"lore","tags":"first-empire eladra argolle history great-teacher cthonic empyrean thune massaran ygrathen nethercity krysea transmogrification","text":"The Argollean Empire (The First Empire) The Argollean Empire -- commonly called the First Empire -- was the earliest large-scale civilization in the known history of Mithrapos . Founded and governed by the Eladra , it arose in the region of Argolle , expanded through conquest and theological transformation, and endured for millennia before its decline gave rise to the successor states that eventually produced the Mithrian Empire . As Magister Callistrus Vellex observed in his lecture on the subject: the name First Empire is itself an error of convenience. It was not the first civilization, nor the first to rule others. It was, however, the first to believe that its dominion was permanent. Origins of the Eladra At the time of the First Empire&#39;s founding, humanity existed in scattered tribes. The Eladra , by contrast, appear in the historical record with their cities already standing, their metaphysical systems already articulated, and their theology presuming intimate knowledge of creation itself. There is no archaeological record of an Eladran rise -- no primitive settlements, no gradual urbanization, no evidence of the slow accumulation of knowledge that characterizes every other known civilization. They simply appear, fully formed, as if placed. Documents predating the Day-Without-Night -- a cataclysmic event in early Eladran mythos whose precise nature is debated -- are extremely rare. What survives suggests a civilization already ancient at the time of the catastrophe, already possessed of knowledge that other peoples would not approach for millennia. The Eladra claim they were fashioned as divine images of the Aurelion -- the greater gods whose nature and number are contested across theological traditions. Whether this claim is literal truth, metaphorical self-understanding, or propaganda is one of the foundational questions of Mithraposi theology. What is not disputed is that the Eladra behaved as if it were true, and built their civilization accordingly. Creation Through Loss Eladran culture reflects a profound preoccupation with what Vellex calls creation through loss -- the belief that to create was an act of surrender. Every act of making required a corresponding act of giving up. This is not merely an aesthetic principle. It is a metaphysical claim about the nature of reality: that creation is not additive but transformative, that nothing can be brought into being without something being consumed in the process. This philosophical foundation is crucial to understanding the Argollean Empire&#39;s later trajectory -- its embrace of the Cthonic tradition, the practice of [[#transmogrification|Transmogrification]], and the construction of the Nethercity . The Eladra did not stumble into darkness. They walked toward it with theological conviction, believing that what they surrendered in the process was the price of what they were building. Timeline of the First Empire 4100 BE -- Eladran City-States Arise in Argolle The first recorded Eladran settlements appear in the region of Argolle, centered around what will become the city of Krysea . These are not villages. They are cities -- planned, fortified, and built with materials and techniques that suggest a civilization already in possession of advanced knowledge. The city-states govern independently but share language, theology, and cultural institutions. 3900 BE -- Encounter with the Ygrathen The Eladra encounter the Ygrathen in the Meniri Mountains . The two peoples become immediate and enduring enemies. The nature of the enmity is not purely territorial -- it appears to be theological, rooted in fundamentally incompatible understandings of the divine order. The Ygrathen-Eladran conflict will persist for nearly two millennia before its resolution. 3800 BE -- Discovery of the Lakan (Humans) The Eladra discover humans -- whom they call the Lakan -- living in tribal societies on the margins of Eladran territory. The encounter is not between equals. The Eladra introduce the Lakan to the Empyrean gods -- the divine tradition that the Eladra claim as their birthright. This is not merely cultural exchange; it is theological colonization. The Lakan receive gods, and in receiving them, become subordinate to the civilization that brought them. 3200 BE -- Expansion of Krysea and the Great Teacher Krysea expands from city-state to regional power. During this period of growth, the entity known as the Great Teacher is awakened -- the circumstances and mechanism of this awakening are not recorded in surviving texts. The Great Teacher introduces the Cthonic gods to Eladran civilization, establishing a second divine tradition alongside the existing Empyrean worship. The introduction of the Cthonic tradition is the pivotal event of Eladran history. The Empyrean gods represent the divine order as the Eladra have always understood it -- creation from above, authority descending. The Cthonic gods represent something else: power rising from below, transformation through surrender, creation through loss made literal and operational. The Great Teacher does not replace the Empyrean tradition. It offers an alternative, and the Eladra -- already philosophically prepared by their theology of sacrificial creation -- embrace it. 3000 BE -- General Eolande and the Conquests General Eolande , tutored directly by the Great Teacher, begins a campaign of territorial expansion that will transform the Eladran city-states into a true empire. Eolande&#39;s military campaigns are not merely territorial -- they are theological, extending the reach of the Cthonic tradition alongside the boundaries of Eladran power. The conquests bring vast territories under Eladran control and establish the political framework that will become the Argollean Empire. 2800 BE -- Transmogrification Begins The practice of Transmogrification is introduced -- the deliberate magical alteration of living beings, reshaping flesh and spirit according to principles derived from the Cthonic tradition. This is the theology of creation through loss made flesh: beings are transformed, surrendering what they were to become something the Empire requires. The process is applied to subject populations, prisoners of war, and -- in some accounts -- willing Eladran volunteers. Transmogrification is not merely a weapon. It is an industrial process, a theological practice, and a tool of governance. It produces soldiers, laborers, and entities designed for specific purposes. It also produces the Slog -- the creatures that will haunt the margins of every subsequent civilization to occupy this territory. 2700 BE -- First Crescent Rebellion and the Creation of the Thune The first major internal revolt against the Empire. The rebellion is suppressed, but the crisis prompts a significant response: the creation of the Thune -- a servitor race engineered through Transmogrification to serve as the Empire&#39;s slave-soldiers. The Thune are purpose-built for loyalty and warfare, designed to provide the Empire with a military force that cannot rebel because rebellion has been bred out of them. The creation of the Thune is the logical endpoint of creation through loss applied to governance. The Empire surrenders the humanity of an entire people to gain an army that serves without question. That this army will eventually rebel anyway is one of history&#39;s more pointed ironies. 2600 BE -- Empire Declared; The Bitter War Begins The Argollean Empire is formally declared, consolidating the Eladran city-states and conquered territories under a single imperial authority. The declaration coincides with the beginning of the Bitter War -- a prolonged conflict whose parties, objectives, and boundaries are not fully preserved in surviving records. What is known is that the war is devastating, long-lasting, and shapes the Empire&#39;s military and administrative institutions for centuries. During this period, construction of the Grand Cthonic Temple begins beneath what will become the Nethercity -- the vast subterranean complex that the Great Teacher designs as a prepared vessel for a future event the builders call the Awakening . 2400 BE -- Doom Temple of Dirgion Construction of the Doom Temple of Dirgion begins within the Nethercity , expanding the subterranean complex with a structure dedicated to purposes that surviving records describe in language more suggestive of containment than worship. 2100 BE -- The Ygrathen Crushed; The Great Teacher Enters Cryostasis The warlord Marcan finally crushes the Ygrathen , ending nearly two millennia of conflict. The Ygrathen are broken as a people and driven into the deep places of the Meniri Mountains, where remnants persist into the present era. Construction of the Hallowed Halls of Heroes begins within the Nethercity , honoring the Empire&#39;s greatest military figures. Following the victory over the Ygrathen, the Great Teacher enters cryostasis within the Nethercity , in a chamber that will come to be known as the Secret Sepulcher . The Great Teacher does not die. It does not depart. It enters a state of preserved dormancy -- waiting, as the Nethercity was built to wait, for the event it was constructed to serve. The Great Teacher is also known as a Chemosh (Khepri) Hierarch . Later sources -- particularly the Codex of Ninefold Stillness -- identify the Great Teacher&#39;s true name as Sen&#39;Zorath, the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues , and describe a chamber called the Hall of the Teacher where Sen&#39;Zorath rests in the Chrysalis-Urn . See The Nethercity for further detail on these locations. 2000 BE -- Great King Tomb The warlord Marcan -- conqueror of the Ygrathen -- is interred within the Nethercity in the structure known as the Great King Tomb . The scale and elaboration of the tomb reflects Marcan&#39;s status as the Empire&#39;s greatest military hero. 1800 BE -- Orthanach Becomes the First Mummy Lord The hierophant Orthanach becomes the first mummy lord -- the first being to achieve a form of undeath through Cthonic ritual that preserves consciousness, will, and power beyond bodily death. This is creation through loss taken to its ultimate conclusion: the surrender of mortality in exchange for perpetual existence in a transformed state. Orthanach&#39;s Secret Tomb within the Nethercity houses not only the hierophant but also his wife Sonya and his guard Cassair -- whether they accompanied him willingly into undeath is not recorded. 1700 BE -- Eladran Decline and Thune Rebellion The Eladra enter a period of irreversible decline. The causes are debated -- demographic collapse, theological exhaustion, the accumulated cost of millennia of Transmogrification and Cthonic practice. Whatever the cause, the Eladra can no longer maintain the institutions that sustain their empire. The Thune -- the slave-soldiers created to serve without question -- rebel. The rebellion is successful. Krysea -- the founding city of Eladran civilization, the seat of the Great Teacher&#39;s awakening -- is razed. The Argollean Empire, as a political entity, ceases to exist. What follows is not a return to the pre-imperial order but a succession of inheritor states, each built on the ruins of what came before. Successor States The Thunean Empire (1700-1075 BE) The Thune establish their own empire on the foundations of the Argollean state they destroyed. The Thunean Empire inherits the administrative structures, the military traditions, and much of the theology of its predecessor -- including, critically, elements of the Cthonic tradition that created the Thune themselves. The empire endures for over six centuries before its own collapse. The Massaran Empire (1075-651 BE) The Massaran Empire succeeds the Thunean state, representing the third iteration of imperial power in the Argolle region. The Massarans build on and adapt the institutions of both preceding empires. Their collapse in 651 BE creates the conditions from which the Mithrian Empire will eventually emerge -- the current imperial power, which conquered Argolle in 349 IY and renamed the region&#39;s greatest city Crossings . Legacy The Argollean Empire&#39;s most enduring legacy is not its political institutions, which died with it, but the physical and metaphysical infrastructure it left behind: The Nethercity -- the vast subterranean complex beneath Crossings , built to house the Empire&#39;s greatest figures in states of ritual readiness for the Awakening . The Nethercity remains intact. Its purpose remains unfulfilled. The Slog -- the products of Transmogrification, still present in the wilderness of the Backlands millennia after the Empire that created them ceased to exist. The Cthonic tradition -- introduced by the Great Teacher and woven into the fabric of Argolle&#39;s deep history. The tradition persists in corrupted forms, in the Nethercity&#39;s stirring, and in the forces that destroyed Crossings thirty years ago. Mount Argolle -- whose upper cliffs bear the carved terraces, archways, and inscription panels of the First Empire, still legible after millennia of erosion. The Thune -- created as slave-soldiers, now a remnant people living among the ruins of Mount Argolle , descendants of the army that destroyed the empire that made them. The First Empire believed its dominion was permanent. It was wrong. But what it built -- beneath the earth, in the flesh of its subjects, in the theological structures that outlived every political institution -- endures. See Also eladra -- The founding civilization of the First Empire the-nethercity -- The subterranean complex built during the Empire&#39;s height the-awakening -- The event the Nethercity was constructed to facilitate cthonic-corruption -- The theological tradition introduced by the Great Teacher the-aurelion -- The Empyrean gods the Eladra claim as their creators thune -- The slave-soldiers created through Transmogrification ygrathen -- The ancient enemies of the Eladra lakandi -- The Lakan, humans introduced to the Empyrean gods by the Eladra beastmen -- The enduring products of Transmogrification massaran-empire -- The third successor state to arise in Argolle mount-argolle -- The volcanic mountain bearing First Empire ruins crossings -- The city built above the Nethercity, later sacked history-of-mithrapos -- Broader historical context backlands-provincial-history -- The modern provincial timeline of Argolle under the Mithrian Empire mithrian-empire -- The current imperial power occupying former Argollean territory"},{"slug":"avari","title":"Avari","category":"lore","tags":"culture avari naming human conquered erenthis backlands argolle crossings ashward sanctuary cynar thornasse elder-sarnath","text":"Avari The Avari are a people shaped by loss and remembrance. Once tall, fair-haired, and formerly warlike seafarers, they were conquered and subjugated by the Mithrian Empire through campaigns of extraordinary brutality. Their culture places great emphasis on honoring the dead, preserving the memory of those who have fallen, and maintaining identity in the face of systematic dispossession. Physical Appearance The Avari are tall and fair-haired, with the builds of a people whose heritage lies in seafaring and warfare. Their appearance is distinctive among the peoples of the Empire -- lighter in complexion and hair color than the Mithrian norm, a visible marker of their separate cultural identity. Culture and Values The Avari were formerly a warlike seafaring people with a proud and independent culture. Their conquest by the Empire was not a simple military defeat but a sustained campaign of subjugation that included brutal pogroms against resisters . Those who fought back were met with extreme violence, and the memory of these pogroms has left a quiet resentment that simmers beneath the surface of Avari life -- never extinguished, never openly expressed, always present. The Erenthis and Avari Spirituality The Avari built their culture around Erenthis trees found in the ruins of the older Eladran civilization. They did not fully understand what they were tending -- they did not possess the Eladran theological vocabulary, the cosmological framework, or the metaphysical traditions that had produced the trees in the first place. But they understood enough. They understood that the tree was sacred. They understood that it sustained them. They understood that rites performed in its presence carried weight. The Avari built their holiest traditions around the Erenthis as a living spiritual anchor . The tree was the center of community, the site of their most important ceremonies, the physical expression of everything they held sacred. The Avari do not use the vocabulary of Empyrean or Cthonic classification. They do not need to. The Burning of the Erenthis at Thornasse High Mage Cynar burned the Erenthis at Thornasse -- an act understood by everyone as cultural execution . The Erenthis at Thornasse was not merely a tree. It was the spiritual center of the Avari Confederation, the living heart of their religious and cultural identity. Cynar did not merely destroy a symbol. He destroyed the thing itself -- the anchor around which an entire people had built their deepest understanding of the sacred. The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist collapsed within months. The Avari were defeated, assimilated, and their culture systematically marginalized. What Cynar accomplished with fire at Thornasse, no army had managed in generations of warfare. He understood what the Erenthis meant to the Avari, and he burned it precisely because he understood. Ancestral Homelands The Avari&#39;s ancestral homelands are the Backlands (Province of Argolle). This war-scarred frontier province was once Avari territory, and the ruins, place names, and cultural traces of their former dominion are still visible throughout the region. The Sacking of Crossings and the Ashward When Beastmen sacked the city of Crossings in 377 IY, thousands of Avari refugees fled south to Sanctuary . They were given marginal land on the city&#39;s edge -- the Ashward quarter -- and left largely to their own devices. The Ashward is desperate, impoverished, and dangerous, but it is also dignified. The Avari have maintained their own community leadership, their own traditions, and their own identity. They have not assimilated into Sanctuary&#39;s Mithrian culture. They remain distinct -- their own language, customs, and governance structures intact. Elder Sarnath of the Crossings leads the Avari community in the Ashward. Age 71, respected, stubborn, and determined to preserve Avari identity and culture in the face of displacement and marginalization. The Ashward is policed primarily by the Avari themselves -- the City Watch rarely enters, and the Drussine Guard never. Naming Conventions Avari children are named after a fallen relative or hero , ensuring that the names of the honored dead continue to live in the present generation. This naming practice is both an act of remembrance and a declaration of continuity -- the dead are not gone so long as their names are carried by the living. The patronymic suffix -sson is used to denote descent (e.g., Bjornsson, meaning son of Bjorn ). Many Avari have adopted Mithrian names over the centuries of Imperial rule, blending their ancestral naming traditions with those of the dominant culture. This adoption is not always willing -- it is sometimes a practical concession to a world that rewards Mithrian conformity and punishes visible difference. Relationship with Varek Ashstone The Avari communities near Lake Silverhead have coexisted with the Ygrathen hermit Varek Ashstone for generations beyond counting. They call him the Old One or simply Varek -- familiar names, not titles of awe. He is part of their landscape, as much as the lake itself. They do not worship him. They do not fear him. They respect him in the way one respects a mountain. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures the-erenthis -- The sacred trees central to Avari spirituality the-backlands -- The Avari ancestral homeland crossings -- The sacked city from which Avari refugees fled sanctuary -- The city where Avari refugees now live elder-sarnath -- The leader of the Avari community in the Ashward varek-ashstone -- The Ygrathen hermit the Avari call the Old One Cynar -- The High Mage who burned the Erenthis at Thornasse"},{"slug":"backlands-field-guide","title":"Backlands Field Guide","category":"lore","tags":"survival flora fauna field-guide herbs backlands foraging hazards","text":"Backlands Field Guide What they don&#39;t tell you is that the Backlands teaches. It kills half the people it teaches, but the rest come out knowing things you can&#39;t learn in a garrison or a schoolroom. You learn what the birds mean. You learn what the silence means. You learn to read the ground the way a scholar reads a page. The ones who make it are the ones who paid attention. -- Hessa Vayne, Scalper A comprehensive survival reference covering the flora, fauna, hazards, and fieldcraft of the Backlands , compiled from the practical experience of woodsmen, Scalpers , and frontier survivors. This guide covers four major wilderness regions: the Slog , the Gallowswood , the Heartwood , and the River Delta near Fort Harvald . The Slog -- Flora and Foraging The Slog is a flat, alkaline wasteland of thorn scrub and split stone. Foraging here requires knowledge and caution -- the land yields what it has, but punishes the careless. Edible and Useful Plants Plant Description Use Notes Crowsthorn / Ironweed Grey-green scrub thorn, chest-height Bark mildly toxic but dry catches fire easily (excellent tinder). Boiled thorn-tips produce a weak antiseptic wash. Dominant vegetation of the Slog. Dustwort Low flat-rosette plant with pale green fleshy leaves, found near old water sources Edible raw but bitter. BEWARE: Saltweed closely resembles dustwort but has a waxy sheen on its leaves. Saltweed causes heavy vomiting within 1 hour of consumption. Goldenrod Found in sheltered gullies; dense yellow flower heads in late summer Dried goldenrod grants +2 on proficiency throws to cure disease (requires Healing proficiency). Seasonal -- late summer only. Horsetail / Snake Grass Segmented reed-like plant found near water Applied as a poultice: +2 on Mortal Wounds table rolls . Both goldenrod and horsetail are forageable on Survival 7+ . Water Sources Finding water in the Slog is a survival skill in itself: Old wells with Imperial stone markers are scattered across the Slog. These date to the Argollean period when the land was farmed. Some still hold water. Dry gulch bends : Dig approximately 2 feet into the bend of a dry gulch to find subsurface water. Survival throws to locate water : 14+ in summer, 10+ in other seasons. Summer is brutal and water is scarce. Argollean Tombs Scattered across the Slog are mound graves marked with angular Argollean script on stone markers. The undead population in these tombs predates the beastman presence by centuries -- these dead are old. Identifying a tomb : A low, grass-covered rise with even sides and a depression at its crown. The geometric regularity distinguishes a tomb from a natural feature. Warning : Give tombs respectful distance at night. The dead walk in the Slog, and many of them emerge from these ancient burial sites. Lakandi Sign The Lakandi who range through the Slog leave distinctive fieldcraft markers. Learning to read them is a survival advantage: Fire sign : Small, efficient fires on a tripod arrangement (not the sprawling campfires of Imperial soldiers or Scalpers) Bone markers : Scraped bone left at campsites or along trails Knot-patterns : Specific knot-patterns in cordage -- these carry meaning, though the full system is not widely understood outside Lakandi culture Stone stacks at water sources : Small stone stacks placed at water sources indicate the water is clean and safe to drink Weather and Seasons The Slog&#39;s weather is as much a hazard as its inhabitants: Season Conditions Summer Brutal heat. Move at dawn and dusk only. Daytime travel risks heat exhaustion. Water is scarce (Survival 14+ to locate). Lightning Season Violent electrical storms. Get low -- the flat terrain makes anything upright a lightning target. Spring Flooding. Dry gulches become rushing channels without warning. A gulch that was bone-dry at dawn can be a torrent by afternoon. Camp on high ground. Winter The easiest season for travel. Cold but manageable. Reduced insect activity. Water more accessible. Tracking Beastmen Reading beastman sign in the Slog: Broken crowsthorn at chest-height : Standard beastman patrol. They push through the scrub without attempting concealment. Crowsthorn bent at 4 feet or below : A scout or rearguard moving carefully, deliberately keeping a low profile. More dangerous -- this is a beastman that knows it is being hunted, or is hunting you. 30-foot-wide flattened lanes through the scrub : Hill giant. Nothing else leaves a track like that. The Wild Hunt On certain nights -- specifically when the eight-starred Wolf constellation climbs high -- something else moves through the Slog. Riders on the horizon that move too fast and too silently, trailing mist behind them. The dead found in their wake cannot be raised by clerics . The bodies are intact but the souls are simply gone. The Scalpers call it the Wild Hunt . They do not discuss it with newcomers. Experienced Scalpers who have survived encounters refuse to describe what they saw in detail. The Wild Hunt is not a beastman warband or a natural phenomenon. It is something else entirely, and the Slog&#39;s veterans treat it with a fear they do not extend to trolls, wights, or beastman war-chiefs. The Gallowswood -- Flora and Fauna There is a quality of silence in the Gallowswood. A specific silence, like the forest holding its breath. When that silence comes, something is watching. Something is waiting. -- Unnamed woodsman The Gallowswood is not merely old in tree terms. It is old in the way places remember things. The Avari knew it as sacred and dangerous before the Argolleans arrived. Avari warnings are still carved on stones at its border -- and the Avari do not waste effort on warnings they do not mean. The Forest The canopy is thick enough to turn noon into dusk. The light that reaches the forest floor is green and uncertain. The dominant trees are ancient oaks, grey ash, and black-barked hawthorn. The undergrowth is dense, tangled, and disorienting. Flora Plant Description Use Notes Black Hawthorn Dark bark, pale flowers in spring, red berries in fall Berries are edible but bitter. One of the Gallowswood&#39;s defining trees. Belladonna Found near old Argollean burial mounds; purple berries Poison. Do not consume. However, belladonna serves as a marker -- where belladonna clusters, an eladra Argollean burial mound is nearby. Gravemoss Grey-green lichen found on ash trees Scraped and dried, gravemoss serves as wound-packing material for field dressing injuries. Abundant in the deep wood. Wolfsbane Tall plant with dark hooded purple-blue flowers A dried sprig presented to a lycanthrope forces a Death save or flee . If consumed within 1 hour of a lycanthropic bite: Death save -- success shakes off the lycanthropy entirely; failure = death. The cure is as dangerous as the disease. Wolfsbane is the only known field treatment for lycanthropy. Woundwort / Heal-All Small pale purple flowers +2 on proficiency throws to cure injury. Common enough to be reliable if you know what to look for. Bracket Fungus Shelf fungus on deadfall Edible if boiled. Bitter but nutritious. Emergency food source. Fauna and Hazards No foxes inhabit the deep Gallowswood. No one has satisfactorily explained why. Every other forest in the Backlands has foxes. The Gallowswood does not. The absence is information -- what killed the foxes, or what keeps them out, is unknown. Deer are present but extremely skittish. If deer are running, do not pause to assess what they are fleeing from. Run with them. Whatever flushed the deer is worse than the deer think you are. Crab Spiders Dog-sized ambush predators that match the texture of bark. They position themselves at chest-height on tree trunks and wait motionless for prey to pass within striking distance. Venom : Paralytic. A bitten victim is immobilized while the spider feeds. Surprise : Check at -2 for surprise when entering areas of dense tree cover. The Alertness proficiency negates this penalty. Crab spiders are solitary hunters. They do not swarm. But a single spider is enough to kill an armored man if it achieves surprise. The Dome A massive clearing approximately half a day&#39;s travel into the deep wood. Before the beastman horde was broken at the Sacking of Crossings , beastman tribes congregated here around an artifact of unknown origin and nature. The beastmen are gone now. Something remains. Creatures wander out of the Dome&#39;s vicinity -- things the woodsmen call abominations . They are described as loose bags of shifting flesh, their surfaces constantly growing and absorbing mouths, eyes, and tentacles in a nauseating cycle of formation and dissolution. Abomination Combat Statistics: Speed : Fast. Faster than they look, which is already unsettling. Attacks : Three attacks per round (the shifting flesh generates multiple appendages simultaneously). Venom : Paralytic toxin. On a failed save, the victim is paralyzed for 1d3 turns . Immunities : Immune to sleep, charm, and hold effects. Whatever intelligence drives them is not a mind that can be influenced by such magic. The relationship between the Dome, the abominations, and the pulsating black heart beneath the granite dome described in session accounts is unclear but almost certainly connected. Navigation Navigation in the Gallowswood is treacherous: Moss grows on ALL sides of trees. The thick canopy diffuses light so completely that the standard moss grows on the north side rule is useless. Compass unreliable. Something in the forest interferes with magnetic navigation. Whether this is a natural mineral deposit or something else is unknown. Follow water downhill. This is the most reliable method of finding your way out. Streams flow downhill and eventually leave the forest. Old Avari path markers exist -- carved stones and wooden poles placed centuries ago. Some sequences of markers are intact and navigable. However, some marker sequences were not intended for outsiders and may lead to places the Avari considered sacred, dangerous, or both. Avari Warning Stones Carved stones at the Gallowswood&#39;s borders bear Avari warnings. These predate the Argollean arrival in the region. The Avari did not carve warnings lightly -- their tradition is oral, and committing a warning to stone indicates something they considered important enough to outlast their own memory. The warnings have not been fully translated, but their intent is clear: do not enter. Burial Mounds Old Argollean burial mounds are scattered through the Gallowswood. They are identifiable by the clustering of belladonna around their bases. The mounds predate the forest&#39;s current cursed state -- the dead were buried here during the Argollean period, and whatever happened to the Gallowswood afterward was not kind to them. The Heartwood -- Flora and Survival The Heartwood is old. It doesn&#39;t know you&#39;re there. You could die in it and the forest wouldn&#39;t notice. -- Rika Sorn, woodsman The Heartwood is the oldest forest in the Backlands and possibly the oldest forest anyone has mapped -- though no survey has ever been completed. The Empire sent survey parties in. Some came back. None agreed on what they saw or where they had been. The Heartwood is not hostile in the way the Gallowswood is hostile. The Gallowswood is aware of you. The Heartwood simply does not care. You can disappear in the Heartwood without doing anything wrong. Flora Plant Description Use Notes Hazelnuts Outer Heartwood, seasonal Edible. Reliable food source in autumn. Outer Heartwood only. Beech Mast Outer Heartwood, seasonal Edible. Small triangular nuts from beech trees. Outer Heartwood only. Wild Garlic Outer Heartwood, spring Edible. Recognizable by smell. Outer Heartwood only. Blackberries Outer Heartwood, late summer Edible. Abundant in clearings and edges. Outer Heartwood only. Comfrey / Bruisewort Found near streams throughout the Heartwood Applied as a poultice: heals 1d3 damage, once per day per patient. The most reliable healing herb in the Backlands. Blessed Thistle Middle and deep Heartwood Doubles hit points recovered from rest. Rare and valuable. Worth gathering when found. Dreamgrass Pale-leaved sedge found around old beech roots Sedative. Useful in small doses (calms panic, aids sleep). Dangerous in large doses (deep unconsciousness, respiratory depression). Dosage is critical. Insect-Repellent Vine Found on older oaks, middle and deep Heartwood Crushed and applied to skin, repels biting insects. Practical value in a forest where insects are relentless. Fauna Owlbeasts inhabit the middle Heartwood. They are territorial and hunt by both sound and smell -- covering one sense does not protect against the other. Territory markers : Deep claw marks scored into tree trunks. If you see these marks, you are in an owlbeast&#39;s territory. Move through quickly and quietly. Owlbeasts are ambush predators. They are large, fast, and aggressive when defending territory or hunting. The Deep Heartwood The deep Heartwood contains things that woodsmen do not describe with precision. Not because they are being dramatic, but because precision fails them: Tracks that do not match any known animal A sense of being assessed -- not hunted, not threatened, but evaluated by something that has not yet decided what you are The silence in the deep Heartwood is not the Gallowswood&#39;s loaded, watchful silence. It is absolute -- the silence of a world that existed before human sound and expects to exist after it. Navigation The Heartwood will get you lost. This is not a matter of skill -- it is a property of the place. Zone Navigation Throw Notes Outer Heartwood Standard Dense but navigable with normal skill. Middle Heartwood 14+ per half-day Trees grow older and larger. The understory thins. Landmarks become unreliable. Deep Heartwood 17+ per half-day Trees enormous beyond reckoning. No reliable landmarks. Absolute silence. Following streams out always works. Every stream in the Heartwood flows to the outer forest eventually. It takes twice as long as direct navigation, but it is reliable. Critical warning : If you think you are on a path in the deep Heartwood, you are not. There are no paths in the deep Heartwood. Anything that looks like a path was not made by human feet and does not lead where a human would want to go. The River Delta -- Flora and Survival Everything in the delta wants to eat you or breed in your ears. -- Aldric Voss The river delta near Fort Harvald is a tidal wetland of reed beds taller than a man, channels that split and rejoin unpredictably, and an ecosystem that is indifferent to human survival. Flora Plant Description Use Notes Common Reed Dominant vegetation, taller than a man Not edible raw, but practical: excellent thatch and tinder. Young shoots are edible if boiled in spring. The delta is defined by its reed beds. Watercress Found in clearly fresh water channels Edible raw. Nutritious. Only harvest from clearly fresh water. Brackish or tidal watercress may carry parasites. Marsh Samphire / Glasswort Small pale-green succulent on tidal flats Edible. Tastes of salt. A reliable food source on the tidal flats. Sea Lavender Purple flowers marking the tidal boundary Not edible. Functions as a warning marker -- sea lavender marks where the tide reaches. Camp above it. Not decoration. Information. Lungwort Spotted leaves, purple-pink flowers A tincture of lungwort relieves lung complaints. Specifically: temporarily relieves permanent wound penalties for 4 hours. Valuable for characters carrying respiratory damage from combat or disease. Bitterwood Bark and inner wood Field treatment for poisoning. Induces vomiting. Death save: success neutralizes the poison; failure = purging with no benefit (the poison remains). Desperate measure, but better than no treatment. Reading the Birds The delta is always full of birds. Once you learn to read them, they constitute the best information system available: Herons flushing without resettling : A genuine disturbance. Something moved through the reed bed that herons do not tolerate -- a predator, a beastman patrol, or something larger. Multiple marsh harriers going up at once : Something large is moving through the reed beds. Marsh harriers are apex predators in the delta; they do not flush easily. If several go up simultaneously, whatever disturbed them is bigger than a harrier is willing to confront. Hazards Crocodilians : Ambush predators that resemble floating wood. Most active at dawn and dusk. They are patient, fast over short distances, and capable of dragging an armored man underwater. Insect-Borne Fever : Unprotected sleep in summer requires a Constitution check at 9+ or the sleeper loses 1d3 hit points to insect-borne fever. Protective measures (netting, the insect-repellent vine from the Heartwood, smudge fires) reduce or eliminate this risk. Tidal Channels : The delta&#39;s channels are treacherous: Probe with a staff before stepping. The mud can swallow a man. Know the tide schedule. A passable channel at low tide becomes a drowning hazard at high tide. Acoustic distortion : The reed beds create acoustic distortion. Sounds bounce, echo, and mislead. A voice that seems to come from the left may originate from the right. Navigation by sound is unreliable. Cross-Regional Notes Herb Summary Table Herb Region Mechanical Benefit Foraging Difficulty Goldenrod the-slog Slog +2 proficiency throw to cure disease Horsetail the-slog Slog +2 Mortal Wounds table Wolfsbane gallowswood Gallowswood Lycanthrope: Death save or flee (presented) / cure or death (consumed within 1hr of bite) Woundwort gallowswood Gallowswood +2 proficiency throw to cure injury Comfrey the-heartwood Heartwood Heals 1d3 damage as poultice (1/day) Blessed Thistle the-heartwood Heartwood Doubles HP from rest Lungwort River Delta Relieves permanent wound penalty for 4 hours Uncommon Bitterwood River Delta Death save to neutralize poison Common Poison/Danger Plants Plant Region Effect Saltweed the-slog Slog Belladonna gallowswood Gallowswood Dreamgrass the-heartwood Heartwood See Also the-slog -- Primary hunting ground, alkaline wasteland gallowswood -- Cursed forest, dead walk beneath the roots the-heartwood -- Oldest forest in the Backlands, uncharted depths fort-harvald -- River delta settlement the-backlands -- The frontier province scalper-gangs -- The gangs whose survival depends on this knowledge beastmen -- The primary threat tracked across these regions avari -- Ancient people whose warnings mark the Gallowswood borders eladra -- The Argollean civilization whose tombs dot the Slog lakandi -- Wasteland warriors whose sign can be read in the Slog"},{"slug":"backlands-provincial-history","title":"Backlands Provincial History","category":"lore","tags":"backlands argolle timeline provincial-history avari lakandi sanctuary crossings frontier-war sacking","text":"Backlands Provincial History A granular provincial timeline of the Backlands from 283 IY to 380 IY, covering the region&#39;s transformation from independent Avari territory to contested imperial frontier. This supplements the broader History of Mithrapos with local events, administrative decisions, and the lived consequences of empire at its furthest edge. Before the Empire (Pre-349 IY) c. 283 IY -- Sanctuary Established The Empire licenses a fortified trading post at the mouth of the Argoll River under treaty with the Avari Confederation . The post -- later known as Sanctuary -- functions as a waystation and customs point. Primary trade goods include furs, salt, and river amber. The arrangement is commercial, not territorial; the Confederation retains sovereignty over the interior. The Empire gains a foothold. c. 283-340 IY -- The Long Accommodation An informal boundary centered on the Argoll River governs relations between the Empire and the Avari Confederation for nearly six decades. Sanctuary grows steadily during this period, expanding from trading post to permanent settlement. Imperial cartographers survey the interior under the guise of trade expeditions -- mapping terrain, river systems, and resource deposits that have no relevance to commerce but considerable relevance to future military operations. Periodic border skirmishes occur but are settled through compensation rather than escalation. The Confederation&#39;s internal disputes -- particularly between the river clans (who benefit from trade with the Empire) and the highland clans (who do not) -- are noted in imperial records with what later historians describe as evident interest. The Empire does not cause this division, but it recognizes the opportunity it represents. c. 338 IY -- Hartwell&#39;s Crossing (vol-Kessar / the Silencing ) Tribune Aldric Hartwell leads an unauthorized surveying column into Avari territory. At a ford on an upper tributary of the Issavar River, the column encounters Avari clans. Imperial records describe the incident as armed resistance to a lawful survey party. Avari oral tradition calls it vol-Kessar -- the Silencing -- a name that suggests something more violent and more deliberate than a skirmish over boundary markers. Hartwell is recalled and reassigned. Compensation is paid to the affected clans. No criminal proceedings are brought against Hartwell or any member of his column. The highland clans -- whose territory was surveyed, whose people were silenced -- regard the compensation as insufficient and the lack of punishment as confirmation that the Empire does not consider Avari sovereignty binding. 338-349 IY -- Failure of the Border Councils Three separate Avari delegations travel to Sanctuary seeking formal censure of Tribune Hartwell and revision of the border treaty. Each delegation is received. Each is deliberated upon. Each is dismissed without binding outcome. The mechanisms of imperial diplomacy function precisely as designed: they absorb grievance without producing change. 344 IY : The highland clans withdraw from the border council, declaring the process a performance without substance. 347 IY : Diplomatic contact between the Avari Confederation and the Empire ceases entirely. The river clans lack the authority or the will to speak for the highlands, and the highlands no longer recognize any reason to speak to the Empire at all. The eleven years between Hartwell&#39;s Crossing and the conquest are a period of diplomatic silence in which both sides understand what is coming. The Confederation fractures further. The Empire surveys the routes its legions will use. Conquest and Consolidation (349-365 IY) 349 IY -- Conquest of Argolle Imperial legions cross the Argoll River in force. The Avari Confederation , weakened by decades of internal division between river and highland factions, cannot mount a unified defense. Thornasse -- the seat of Avari governance -- falls. High Mage Cynar burns the Erenthis tree at the city that was Erenthis. The city is renamed Crossings . The Avari Confederation ceases to exist as a political entity. The conquest is swift. The Confederation&#39;s fracture along the lines the Empire had observed for decades -- river clans versus highland clans, trade interests versus territorial sovereignty -- ensures that no coordinated resistance materializes. What follows is not a war but a collapse. 350-360 IY -- Pacification Period Imperial administration is established at Sanctuary , which becomes the provincial capital. Irregular suppression of highland resistance continues throughout this period, though the campaigns are not formally documented as military operations. Communities beyond the river valleys are largely undisturbed -- not from mercy but from irrelevance. The Empire governs where it profits; the rest can wait. Road construction begins, connecting Sanctuary to the newly renamed Crossings. The roads serve the dual purpose of commerce and force projection -- they enable trade, but they also enable legions to move quickly through terrain that previously required weeks of travel. c. 353 IY -- Argollean Land Grants Retiring legionaries and minor imperial families receive land grants throughout the conquered territory. The grants are generous. The maps on which they are based are not. Imperial surveyors have drawn property boundaries without accounting for Avari migration routes, seasonal hunting grounds, or Lakandi territorial ranges. The grants create a patchwork of imperial claims overlaid on a landscape that is already occupied by peoples the Empire has chosen not to see. The Red River Consortium receives a mining and transport charter covering the northern tributaries -- a commercial concession that will prove significant in the decades to come. c. 355-365 IY -- The Quiet Decade A period of relative stability during which the physical infrastructure of imperial control is established: Fort Meade and Fort Harvald are constructed, establishing a defensive line beyond which settlement is theoretically discouraged. The road between Sanctuary and Crossings is completed. Census data shows steady population growth along river routes. Market towns develop, including Dunwick and Cairnhill , serving as commercial hubs for the surrounding agricultural settlements. The Quiet Decade earns its name from what it lacks: significant military engagement. The highland resistance has been suppressed or scattered. The Lakandi beyond the fort line have not yet been provoked in sufficient numbers. The Empire&#39;s administrators write optimistic reports about provincial development. They are correct about the growth. They are wrong about its security. The Frontier War (362-370 IY) c. 362 IY -- First Lakandi Contacts Settlers who have pushed past the fort line -- lured by land grants and the promise of unclaimed territory -- begin reporting hostile contact with unknown forces. Provincial administration classifies these reports as opportunistic incursion by irregular Slog elements. This classification is convenient. It frames the contact as criminal rather than military, avoiding the administrative burden of requesting legionary reinforcement. It is also wrong. c. 364 IY -- The Millhaven Burning A settler cluster of approximately fifty families is destroyed overnight. There are no survivors. The investigation notes organization uncharacteristic of prior Slog contacts -- coordinated assault, multiple approach vectors, systematic elimination of escape routes. This is not banditry. This is warfare conducted by an enemy the provincial administration has refused to acknowledge. A formal request for legionary reinforcement is submitted to the imperial capital. The request is denied. The province is expected to manage its own frontier problems. c. 365-368 IY -- Reprisal Raids and Settler Militias In the absence of imperial military support, informal militias organize among the frontier settlements. These militias conduct reprisal operations into the territory beyond the fort line without official sanction. Several actions target non-combatant encampments -- camps of women, children, and elderly who bear no direct connection to the attacks on settler homesteads. The provincial administration neither endorses nor censures these operations. The militias serve a function the Empire will not pay for, and the administration prefers ambiguity to accountability. The reprisals escalate the conflict without resolving it. The Lakandi respond in kind. c. 368 IY -- The Dunwick Compact The growing instability of the frontier forces a restructuring of local governance. House Thane and House Cael are formally recognized as civic authorities in Dunwick . Similar arrangements are established in Cairnhill and other settlements. The terms are straightforward: local judicial authority and tax collection in exchange for maintaining order. The Compact acknowledges what the provincial administration cannot say publicly -- that imperial governance has failed to reach the frontier, and that local power has filled the vacuum. The Great Houses gain legitimacy. The Empire gains the appearance of control. Neither gains security. c. 370 IY -- Retreat of the Farsteads Coordinated Lakandi strikes force the abandonment of settlements beyond the fort line in a single season. The speed and simultaneity of the attacks exceed all prior Lakandi activity by a significant margin. This is not raiding. This is a territorial offensive executed with discipline and strategic coordination. Bone Creek -- already marginal -- loses most of its population. The fort line becomes not a forward position but a final one. 370-374 IY -- The Hollow Years The northern interior of the province is functionally abandoned. Settlements beyond the fort line are empty or destroyed. Bone Creek endures as a waystation -- a place people pass through on their way to somewhere safer, sustained by those too stubborn or too poor to leave. The provincial administration does not acknowledge the loss of territory. The maps in Sanctuary still show settlements that no longer exist, roads that are no longer safe, and a frontier that has contracted by dozens of miles. The Hollow Years are a period of administrative fiction, in which the gap between what the Empire claims and what the Empire controls grows wider with each passing season. The Sacking and Aftermath (374-380 IY) 374 IY -- Sacking of Crossings Note: The backlands_timeline.docx dates the Sacking to 374 IY. The Backlands Primer dates it to 377 IY. This discrepancy has not been resolved. Both dates appear in source material. See Sacking of Crossings for full details. Crossings is attacked in a coordinated assault involving multiple approach routes and a disciplined withdrawal. This is not a raid. The attackers demonstrate strategic planning -- simultaneous pressure on multiple defensive positions, exploitation of known weaknesses in the city&#39;s fortifications, and organized retreat before reinforcement can arrive. A relief column fails to arrive. Senator Cassius raises questions in the imperial capital about the failure of the provincial garrison to receive reinforcement. The questions are noted. They are not answered. 374 IY -- Imperial Bounty Declared In the aftermath of the Sacking, the Empire declares an Imperial Bounty : one mark per beastman scalp. The bounty transforms the conflict from a military problem into a commercial opportunity. It attracts a particular kind of settler -- not farmers seeking land but hunters seeking profit. 374-378 IY -- The Scalper Years Bone Creek grows rapidly, fueled by the Bounty. The town becomes the primary staging point for scalp-hunting expeditions into the northern interior. The Red River Consortium -- already holding mining and transport charters from the Argollean Land Grants -- gains the legal right to administer the Bounty, processing scalps, verifying kills, and distributing payment. The Consortium&#39;s commercial reach extends deep into what was recently abandoned territory. The Scalper Years create a brutal economy. The Bounty does not distinguish between combatants and non-combatants, between Lakandi warriors and Lakandi civilians. The scalp-hunters do not make these distinctions either. The violence is profitable, indiscriminate, and officially sanctioned. c. 375-380 IY -- Post-Sacking Migration Refugees from the Sacking redistribute throughout the province. The destruction of Crossings displaces a significant population, and the survivors scatter to Sanctuary , Dunwick , Cairnhill , and smaller settlements. Settlers holding suspended land grants -- claims to territory that is now functionally part of the hostile frontier -- create contention wherever they arrive, demanding recognition of titles to land they cannot occupy. 380 IY -- Present Day The Backlands in 380 IY are a province defined by contraction, improvisation, and unresolved violence. The official map and the actual territory diverge sharply. The Great Houses govern where the Empire cannot. The Bounty economy sustains Bone Creek but poisons everything it touches. The Erenthis at Crossings was burned thirty years ago, and the consequences of that act are still unfolding. Recent reports from Fort Harvald note beastman attacks of coordination and scale not seen since the Sacking. Whether this represents a resurgence of the forces that destroyed Crossings, or something new entirely, remains to be determined. See Also the-backlands -- Overview of the province history-of-mithrapos -- Broader imperial timeline avari -- The Avari Confederation displaced by conquest lakandi -- The indigenous people beyond the fort line sacking-of-crossings -- The destruction of the provincial capital sanctuary -- The imperial trading post turned provincial capital crossings -- The former Erenthis, renamed and later sacked dunwick -- Market town and seat of House Thane / House Cael cairnhill -- Market town in the eastern foothills bone-creek -- Frontier waystation and center of the Bounty economy fort-meade -- Western anchor of the fort line fort-harvald -- Eastern anchor of the fort line great-houses -- The local power structures that filled the imperial vacuum beastmen -- The forces behind the frontier violence the-erenthis -- The tree burned by Cynar during the conquest argollean-empire -- The First Empire that preceded all of this"},{"slug":"battle-of-blue-mound","title":"The Battle of Blue Mound","category":"lore","tags":"event history battle sorcery lakan-campaigns lakandi imperial-academy mutual-annihilation","text":"The Battle of Blue Mound The Battle of Blue Mound was the catastrophic culmination of the Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY). It pitted Imperial forces led by High Mage Cynar of the Imperial Academy against the army of Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye of the Lakandi . The climax of the battle -- a direct sorcerous duel between the two most powerful magic users on the field -- escalated beyond all control, unleashing cataclysmic energies that annihilated both armies entirely . Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived. The battlefield was left a blasted and lifeless wasteland. The Battle of Blue Mound stands as the most devastating demonstration of sorcerous power in recent Imperial history and fundamentally reshaped the Empire&#39;s approach to warfare. The Battle Imperial armies had marched deep into Lakandi territory during the Lakan Campaigns , backed by the devastating magical firepower of the Imperial Academy . The Lakandi, led by Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye , assembled a formidable army to resist the invasion. The two forces met at Blue Mound. The battle proceeded along conventional lines until High Mage Cynar and Jarn Murky-Eye engaged in direct sorcerous combat. What began as a duel between two powerful practitioners escalated into something far worse. The energies unleashed -- Cynar&#39;s Gnostic Geometry colliding with Jarn&#39;s Veil-born sorcery -- spiraled beyond the capacity of either combatant to control. The resulting cataclysm consumed everything: both armies, both sorcerers, and the landscape itself. Consequences Military Doctrine The Battle of Blue Mound prompted the most significant reform in Imperial military doctrine since the founding of the Empire. It demonstrated conclusively that deploying high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was not merely dangerous but potentially suicidal -- a strategy that could destroy the user&#39;s own forces as completely as the enemy&#39;s. In response, the Empire adopted a model of combined arms warfare , integrating squad mages into conventional military formations rather than relying on individual sorcerers to decide the outcome of battles. This doctrinal shift reduced the Imperial Academy &#39;s singular importance in warfare, a change that the Academy has never fully accepted. The Frontier The Empire retreated from Lakandi territory and erected a line of border forts that marks the current frontier. The Empire abandoned its ambitions of conquest in the region, adopting a purely defensive posture. The Lakandi The Lakandi were broken by the campaigns but remained unbowed . The destruction of their army at Blue Mound was devastating, but the simultaneous destruction of the Imperial army gave them a claim to something resembling victory. The Lakandi vowed revenge against the Empire, and the border forts that line the frontier stand as testimony to the fact that the Empire takes that vow seriously. Significance The Battle of Blue Mound demonstrates the devastating and uncontrollable power of sorcery when wielded at its highest levels. It is cited by military theorists, Academy scholars, and political commentators as proof that magical power, no matter how great, cannot be deployed without risk of catastrophic consequences. The battle has become a cautionary tale -- a reminder that the forces sorcerers command are not tools but living energies with their own dynamics, capable of consuming their wielders as readily as their targets. See Also High Mage Cynar -- Imperial sorcerer who died in the duel Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye -- Lakandi sorcerer who died in the duel The Lakan Campaigns -- the broader military campaign The Imperial Academy -- institution whose doctrine was reshaped Lakandi Binding Tradition -- the sorcerous tradition Jarn embodied Magic and Sorcery -- the forces unleashed at Blue Mound The Mithrian Military -- the armed forces that lost an entire army History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"beastmen","title":"Beastmen","category":"lore","tags":"race beastmen massaran-empire massar monstrous sacking-of-crossings scalper bounty mutated backlands","text":"Beastmen The Beastmen are a collection of species of monstrous humans -- not a single race but a diverse array of twisted, mutated beings united only by their shared origin and their universal reputation for savagery. They were created by the Massaran Empire as the core of its armies, purpose-bred for war through sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding. After the defeat of the Massaran Empire, the Beastmen were scattered, left without purpose or direction, and they have since devolved into one of the most feared threats in Mithrapos . Physical Appearance The appearances of Beastmen differ wildly from one individual to the next, but all carry a twisted and mutated animal aspect -- horns, fangs, claws, fur, scales, or other bestial features grafted onto a roughly humanoid frame. No two Beastmen are exactly alike, and the variety of their mutations reflects the chaotic and uncontrolled nature of the sorcery that created them. Some resemble twisted versions of specific animals -- bull-headed brutes, wolf-faced hunters, serpent-scaled skulkers. Others combine features from multiple creatures into combinations that defy natural classification. The one constant is the wrongness of their appearance -- the sense that something human has been warped beyond recognition into something that is neither fully animal nor fully human. Culture and Values The Beastmen are exceedingly cruel and violent , feared and reviled by all other peoples of Mithrapos . Whatever culture they may have possessed during the height of the Massaran Empire has long since degraded into something more primal -- warbands organized around strength, packs held together by dominance and fear, and a way of life built around raiding, killing, and consuming. History Creation by the Massaran Empire The Beastmen were created by the Massaran Empire as the core of its armies . The sorcerer-kings of Massar employed sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding to produce living weapons -- soldiers that were stronger, more savage, and more expendable than human troops. The Beastmen served this purpose with brutal effectiveness, and the Massaran Empire&#39;s military power was built in large part on their backs. Scattering After the defeat of the Massaran Empire in the Empyrean War , the Beastmen were scattered across the wilds of Mithrapos . Without the sorcerer-kings to command them, the Beastmen fragmented into roving warbands and feral packs, preying on the weak and the unwary. They have never been fully eradicated, and they remain a persistent threat to frontier communities across the known world. The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY) The Beastmen sacked the city of Crossings in 377 IY. A massive horde emerged from the wilderness and descended on the settlement, razing it to the ground. The beastmen committed untold atrocity and violence upon the citizens -- the few refugees who escaped tell stories of horrors that defy description. The fall of Crossings was one of the most devastating events in recent Imperial history. It destroyed the principal Avari settlement in the Backlands , driving thousands of refugees south to Sanctuary where they now crowd the Ashward quarter. The Scalper Economy In response to the sacking, Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus issued an Imperial scalp bounty on all Beastmen, offering imperial gold marks for their scalps. This decree created an entirely new economy -- the Scalper trade -- and drew hard men and women from every walk of life to the Backlands, seeking fortune in violence. The outpost of Bone Creek became the epicenter of this grim industry. Current Situation The Beastmen have settled in the ruins of Crossings and begun to push farther south , kidnapping farmers, raiding settlements, and worse. They represent an active and growing threat to every settlement in the Backlands , and the skeletal Imperial garrison left after the withdrawal of 378 IY is ill-equipped to contain them. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures massar -- The empire that created the Beastmen crossings -- The city the Beastmen sacked the-backlands -- The frontier province where Beastmen are active sanctuary -- Where Avari refugees from the sacking now live scalper-gangs -- The bounty hunters created by the Imperial response bone-creek -- The Scalper outpost on the northern frontier history-of-mithrapos -- The Empyrean War and the Sacking of Crossings avari -- The people most affected by the Sacking of Crossings"},{"slug":"bel-earth-hunger","title":"Bel-Tharach: The Earth-Hunger","category":"lore","tags":"bel bel-tharach earth-hunger slaughterprince cthonic agriculture blood-rites avari farming sacrifice dunwick brother-cavin seros coastal-plain argolle","text":"Bel-Tharach: The Earth-Hunger The field and the battlefield are not as different as they appear. Both require sacrifice. Both produce abundance through death. Bel-tharach is an old Avari word meaning the appetite of the earth or the hunger of the field. The farmers who use it do not remember where it comes from. They use it to mean a good harvest -- a season of abundance, a field that gives generously. It is a word of celebration, of gratitude, of plenty. It shares a name with Bel the Slaughterprince -- the Cthonic war-god of blood, conquest, and slaughter. This is the question that several generations of scholars have quietly failed to answer: whether Bel the Slaughterprince and the agricultural earth-hunger are the same entity. The Agricultural Blood Rites The agricultural blood rites practiced in the farming villages of Argolle&#39;s coastal plain predate Mithrian administration by centuries. They are old -- older than the Empire, older than the Thousand Temples , older than any institution that might claim authority to regulate them. They follow a cycle tied to the agricultural year: Blood offering at planting. At the beginning of the growing season, blood is given to the earth. The specifics vary by community -- an animal slaughtered over the first-turned furrow, a cut palm pressed into fresh soil, something older and less easily described. The offering is made to ensure the field will produce. Petition at harvest. At the gathering of the crop, a petition is made -- gratitude for what the earth has given, acknowledgment of what the earth has taken, and a request for continued favor. The petition is not prayer in the Empyrean sense. It is transaction. Something was given; something was received; the arrangement continues. Sacrifice at the year&#39;s close. At the end of the agricultural cycle, a sacrifice is made. This is the most significant of the three rites, and the one about which outsiders know the least. The sacrifice closes the cycle, settles the account, and prepares the ground for the next year&#39;s exchange. These rites share a name with the Cthonic war-god. They share more than a name. The Core of the Question What Bel requires in both expressions -- the Slaughterprince on the battlefield and the earth-hunger in the field -- is consumption . The Slaughterprince demands blood on the battlefield. The earth-hunger demands blood in the field. The domain differs. The appetite is the same. The same divine hunger manifests differently depending on the community that feeds it -- warriors feed it war, farmers feed it harvest, but both are feeding the same mouth. Two interpretations exist, and neither has been definitively established: Interpretation One: Same Entity, Different Manifestations Bel the Slaughterprince and the agricultural earth-hunger are the same entity , manifested differently through different communities over time. The agricultural prosperity of Argolle&#39;s farming villages is the favor of a genuine Cthonic power. The blood-price is a legitimate transaction -- blood given, abundance received, an arrangement that has endured for centuries because both parties honor it. Under this interpretation, the farmers of Argolle&#39;s coastal plain are engaged in Cthonic worship -- not the dramatic, self-conscious Cthonic worship of blood-priests and war-cults, but the quiet, practical, transactional worship of people who need their fields to produce and have found something that answers when they ask. Interpretation Two: Different Entities, Shared Name The Slaughterprince and the earth-hunger are genuinely different -- separate entities, separate traditions, separate powers that merely share a name through accident of ancient Avari language . The agricultural rites are not Cthonic worship but folk practice, inherited tradition, superstition that happens to work because the land is fertile and the farmers are skilled. Under this interpretation, the shared name is a linguistic coincidence, and the scholars who see a connection are finding patterns where none exist. What Is Not in Question Whatever the answer to the theological question, several things are not in question : Something answers the agricultural rites. The blood is given; the harvest comes. The petition is made; the fields produce. This is not coincidence and it is not skill. Something responds to the rites -- something real, old, and still being fed. It produces extraordinary harvests. The farming villages of Argolle&#39;s coastal plain are prosperous beyond what soil and climate alone can explain. Their fields produce abundance that neighboring regions -- with comparable land, comparable skill, comparable investment -- cannot match. It communicates in abundance and absence. When the rites are performed correctly, the harvests are extraordinary. When the rites are neglected or performed incorrectly, the harvests fail. The communication is clear: the arrangement has terms, and both parties are expected to honor them. It is real, old, and still being fed. Whatever the farmers of Argolle&#39;s coastal plain are feeding -- whether it is a Cthonic war-god, an ancient earth-spirit, or something that defies either classification -- it has been receiving blood offerings for centuries, and it has not stopped being hungry. The Escalating Demand The demands have grown proportionally to the prosperity provided over generations. What begins as a modest exchange between desperate farmers and something that answers -- a few drops of blood for a good harvest, a slaughtered animal for an exceptional one -- becomes, over time, something that cannot be unmade without cost. Each generation inherits a more prosperous arrangement and a more demanding patron. The blood-price increases. The expectations deepen. The transaction that sustained great-grandparents requires more from their descendants, and the cost of breaking the arrangement -- of refusing to pay what has been paid for generations -- grows with each passing year. The earth-hunger has been fed for centuries. It has grown accustomed to being fed. It will not accept less. The Coastal Plain Communities The wealthier farming communities of the coastal plain appear, to the casual visitor, entirely normal. They are hospitable, well-stocked, remarkable in the quality of their fields . A Temple of Seros stands in the town square. The people attend services. Everything appears in order. It is the absences that accumulate. Certain families do not attend temple on certain days. Certain fields are not worked at certain times. Certain questions are not answered. Certain topics produce a silence that is not evasive but simply final -- the silence of people who know what they know and have decided, collectively and without discussion, that outsiders do not need to know it. The prosperity is real. The temple attendance is real. The hospitality is real. And beneath all of it, something else is also real, and has been real for longer than anyone living can remember, and will not stop being real simply because the Thousand Temples would prefer it did not exist. Brother Cavin at Dunwick Brother Cavin is a young priest of Seros assigned to the temple at Dunwick , one of the farming communities on the coastal plain. He is a man of genuine piety -- sincere, earnest, and committed to his calling. He has been at his posting for two years. He is deeply uncomfortable . Brother Cavin has heard disturbing confessions -- not dramatic revelations of dark worship, but fragmentary, reluctant admissions that something in Dunwick&#39;s spiritual life does not align with the faith he was trained to serve. He has noticed absences in his congregation at specific times -- particular holy days, planting days, harvest days, when certain families simply do not appear, and no explanation is offered. He has begun asking questions of the wrong people. Brother Cavin has not yet been harmed. This is not because he is safe. It is not because the community is harmless. It is not because his questions have gone unnoticed. He has not been harmed, though not for the reasons he believes . Whether his safety is the product of indifference, calculation, protection, or something else entirely is a question whose answer may determine whether Brother Cavin survives his posting. See Also seros -- The Empyrean god whose domain mirrors Bel&#39;s the-convergence-problem -- The theological crisis of Empyrean/Cthonic mirroring cthonic-corruption -- The tradition to which Bel belongs Avari -- The culture from which bel-tharach originates dunwick -- The farming community where Brother Cavin serves thousand-temples -- The institution that would condemn the agricultural rites the-erenthis -- A contrasting sacred tradition rooted in the living world empyrean-faith -- The official faith of the Empire congregation-of-the-hollow-sun -- Another heterodox religious movement in Argolle lakandi-binding-tradition -- Another tradition engaging with powers outside Empyrean orthodoxy"},{"slug":"corcanoan","title":"Corcanoan","category":"lore","tags":"culture corcanoan naming human seafaring matrilineal cthonic corcano","text":"Corcanoan The Corcanoans hail from a chain of volcanic islands known as Corcano , and their culture is shaped by the dramatic and dangerous landscape they call home. Corcanoan society is matriarchal in structure, with lineage traced through the mother&#39;s line and women holding positions of authority in both domestic and public life. Physical Appearance Corcanoans are characterized by dark hair and light eyes -- a striking combination that sets them apart from many other peoples of Mithrapos . Their skin is weathered and tan, bearing the marks of a life spent in the salt wind and harsh sun of the volcanic islands. They are a lean, sinewy people, shaped by the physical demands of seafaring and fishing in treacherous waters. Culture and Values The Corcanoans are famous sailors and fishermen . The volcanic islands of Corcano offer little arable land, and the sea has always been the Corcanoan people&#39;s primary source of sustenance, livelihood, and identity. Corcanoan seamanship is legendary throughout the Empire, and Corcanoan captains and navigators are sought after by merchant fleets and naval commands alike. Corcanoan society is matriarchal . Lineage is traced through the mother&#39;s line, and women hold positions of authority in both domestic and public life. The matriarchal structure shapes every aspect of Corcanoan culture, from inheritance customs to political organization to the naming of children. Religion Some Corcanoans worship Cthonic gods or primal spirits rather than -- or in addition to -- the Empyrean gods recognized by the Thousand Temples . The volcanic landscape of Corcano, with its geothermal vents, sulfurous pools, and the ever-present threat of eruption, has produced a spiritual tradition that acknowledges the raw, dangerous power of the natural world in ways that the formalized Empyrean faith does not. These Cthonic practices are tolerated uneasily by Imperial authorities, who regard them as heterodox but not overtly heretical. Naming Conventions Corcanoan names are melodic and flowing , characteristically ending in vowels or soft consonants. The language of Corcano produces names that are pleasant to the ear and easy to speak -- a quality that reflects the musical traditions of Corcanoan culture. Children are named after their mothers or matriarchal ancestors, reinforcing the matrilineal nature of Corcanoan kinship. A Corcanoan&#39;s name is a living record of their maternal lineage, connecting them to generations of women who came before. This practice means that certain names recur across generations, carried forward as acts of remembrance and continuity. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire that incorporates Corcano cthonic-faith -- The Cthonic traditions some Corcanoans follow empyrean-faith -- The dominant Empyrean faith"},{"slug":"cthonic-corruption","title":"Cthonic Corruption","category":"lore","tags":"cthonic corruption empyrean veil elvora erenthis animals perception flesh mind decay transformation backlands","text":"Cthonic Corruption Cthonic corruption is the practical, observable effect of prolonged exposure to Cthonic energies on living beings, objects, and environments. It is not metaphor, not theology, not moral judgment. It is what happens -- physically, cognitively, spiritually -- when the material world is subjected to sustained contact with the powers that dwell beyond the Veil . Effects on Animals Animals exposed to prolonged Cthonic energies develop an awareness that transcends their nature . The change is visible and unmistakable to those who know what to look for: Eyes that hold something beyond ordinary hunger. A wolf is hungry. A Cthonic-corrupted wolf is hungry in a way that is not entirely animal -- its eyes hold an intelligence, an appetite, a purpose that does not belong to a creature of instinct and survival. Something looks out through eyes that should contain only predatory focus, and what looks out is aware in a way that the animal alone could never be. Behavioral changes. Corrupted animals do not behave as their uncorrupted counterparts do. Their movements are more purposeful. Their aggression is more directed. They coordinate in ways that exceed natural pack behavior. They target with discrimination that suggests awareness rather than instinct. Physical alteration. Prolonged exposure produces physical changes -- thickened hide, darkened eyes, bone spurs, unusual growths. The corruption reshapes flesh as readily as it reshapes awareness, though the progression is gradual and varies by species and intensity of exposure. Effects on Humans Humans carrying Cthonic-saturated items or spending prolonged time in Cthonic-influenced environments experience changes that progress from subtle to profound: Changes in perception. The corrupted individual begins to perceive things that others cannot -- presences, energies, dimensions of the world that are normally invisible. This expanded perception is not a gift. It is an intrusion. The boundaries of normal human awareness exist for reasons, and their erosion is not comfortable. Changes in relationships. Prolonged Cthonic exposure affects how the corrupted individual relates to others. Bonds weaken or transform. Empathy erodes or redirects. The corrupted individual&#39;s sense of connection to other people shifts in ways that are difficult to articulate but impossible to miss. Changes in what they regard as worth preserving. This is the subtlest and most dangerous effect. The corrupted individual&#39;s values shift. What once seemed important -- family, community, safety, the ordinary goods of human life -- begins to seem less significant. What replaces these values varies, but the direction is consistent: toward something older, deeper, and less human. What happens to a mortal carrying a fragment of a dead god too long without understanding it differs in degree but not in kind from what happened to Elvora . The Elvoran Precedent The Elvoran experience is the most thoroughly documented case of civilization-scale Cthonic corruption. Prolonged Veil contact corrupted the Elvora at every level: Eyes blacken. The iris darkens progressively, eventually turning the eyes wholly black. This is the most visible and iconic sign of deep Cthonic corruption, and it is permanent. The Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye of the Lakandi bore a name that was not metaphorical -- his eyes were the color of what he had touched. Bones warp. The skeletal structure deforms under sustained Cthonic pressure, producing distortions that are not illness and not injury but transformation. The body reshapes itself in response to energies it was not designed to contain. Voices change. The corrupted voice acquires qualities that are difficult to describe -- resonances, harmonics, undertones that do not originate in human vocal anatomy. Those who have heard it do not forget it. The cost was total. The Elvora went all the way. They bound something unbindable. The result was the destruction of their civilization: females rendered barren, males rendered immortal, eyes turned black, society shattered. The Elvora are the warning against which all other Cthonic engagement is measured. (See: Elvora ) The Lakandi Experience The Lakandi engage with Cthonic entities at the individual scale rather than the civilizational scale, and their corruption is correspondingly more contained -- but it is not absent. Lakandi practitioners who repeatedly tear open the Veil and reach through it to bind demons, spirits, and Beyond-entities accumulate the marks of their engagement: Eyes darkening at the iris -- progressive, permanent, visible A quality of stillness beyond patience -- the stillness of something that has been touched by entities operating on inhuman timescales Awareness of things not normally visible -- expanded perception that does not fade The Lakandi treat these marks not as failing but as the visible record of genuine engagement . To be corrupted is to have done something real. To be unmarked is to have risked nothing. The corruption is the credential. Natural Defenses The Erenthis root network is the most reliable natural defense against Cthonic corruption. Creatures touched by Cthonic influence avoid Erenthis root systems entirely -- not because of a physical barrier, but because of a deep incompatibility below the level of choice . The corruption and the roots cannot coexist. They are oriented toward fundamentally opposed principles, and the roots hold. This defense operates consistently and without active maintenance. Communities centered on living Erenthis trees have survived generations of frontier pressure, Cthonic incursion, and the slow erosion of normalcy that prolonged Cthonic exposure produces. The roots do not merely repel corrupted creatures -- they reinforce the metaphysical integrity of the space they occupy, providing a zone where Cthonic influence cannot gain purchase. The Black Tree at Crossings -- the scorched stump of the Erenthis burned by High Mage Cynar thirty years ago -- still extends roots that Cthonic-corrupted creatures avoid. Even dead, even burned, the Erenthis holds. The Spectrum of Corruption Cthonic corruption is not binary. It is a spectrum: Incidental exposure -- proximity to Cthonic-saturated objects or environments for brief periods. Effects are minimal and usually reversible: unease, disturbed sleep, a sense of being observed. Sustained exposure -- prolonged contact with Cthonic energies. Effects are progressive and increasingly difficult to reverse: perceptual changes, relationship shifts, value erosion. Active engagement -- deliberate interaction with Cthonic entities through the Veil or other means. Effects are permanent and cumulative: physical marks, cognitive alterations, fundamental changes in identity and orientation. The Lakandi operate at this level. Total immersion -- civilization-scale binding of Cthonic power. Effects are catastrophic and irreversible. The Elvora operated at this level, and they were destroyed by it. See Also the-erenthis -- The most reliable natural defense against Cthonic corruption the-veil -- The barrier through which Cthonic entities are reached Elvora -- The civilization destroyed by total Cthonic immersion lakandi-binding-tradition -- A tradition that engages with Cthonic entities directly greta -- A Lakandi practitioner bearing the marks of binding jarn-murky-eye -- The Warlock King whose corruption was legendary the-convergence-problem -- The theological crisis that complicates understanding of Cthonic power empyrean-faith -- The tradition that opposes Cthonic influence the-nethercity -- A Cthonic construct of enormous scale beneath Crossings the-kharai -- Ancient beings that exist outside both Empyrean and Cthonic frameworks crossings -- Where the Black Tree&#39;s roots still resist Cthonic corruption"},{"slug":"dog-soldier-war","title":"The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY)","category":"lore","tags":"event history warfare kolani don-kolani guerrilla-war general-darius-jute kolani-munitions","text":"The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY) The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY) was a prolonged guerrilla conflict between the Mithrian Empire and the don&#39;Kolani -- the forest-dwelling branch of the Kolani people. Spanning nearly two decades, the war proved extraordinarily costly for the Empire and ended not in conquest but in a hard-won peace brokered by General Darius Jute . The peace treaty included a provision of enormous strategic significance: the Empire gained access to Kolani munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces. The Conflict The don&#39;Kolani launched a relentless guerrilla war against Imperial occupation of their ancestral forest lands. Unlike conventional warfare -- where the Empire&#39;s legions and sorcerous firepower could be brought to bear decisively -- the don&#39;Kolani fought on their own terms. They used the dense forests as both fortress and weapon, striking from cover, dissolving into the wilderness, and refusing to give the Imperial forces the pitched battle they needed to achieve a decisive victory. For nearly two decades, the conflict ground on. Imperial casualties mounted. Supply lines were harassed. Garrisons were besieged, relieved, and besieged again. The war became a quagmire -- too costly to sustain, too politically embarrassing to abandon, and impossible to win through conventional military means. Mutual Respect Over the long years of fighting, something unexpected developed between the combatants: mutual respect . The Imperial soldiers who fought in the forests came to recognize the don&#39;Kolani as formidable warriors -- fierce, disciplined, and unyielding in defense of their homeland. The don&#39;Kolani, for their part, came to respect the endurance and courage of the Imperial legionaries who fought far from home in unfamiliar terrain against an enemy they could barely see. This mutual respect -- born of shared hardship and the grudging acknowledgment of an enemy&#39;s worth -- would prove critical when peace was finally negotiated. The Peace Peace was brokered by General Darius Jute , one of the most capable military commanders in recent Imperial history. Jute recognized that the war could not be won and that continued fighting served no one&#39;s interests. His diplomacy was informed by the respect that had developed between the soldiers of both sides. The peace treaty included provisions of enormous significance: Access to Kolani munitions -- The Empire gained access to explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology had been developed by the Kolani independently of Mithrian sorcery. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, reducing the Imperial Academy &#39;s exclusive importance in warfare and contributing to the ongoing transformation of Imperial military doctrine. Formal incorporation of Kolani warriors -- The treaty led to the establishment of the Kolani Irregulars , a military formation composed entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors who serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry within the Imperial military structure. Strategic Impact The Dog Soldier War&#39;s most lasting impact was technological. The acquisition of Kolani munitions fundamentally altered the balance of power within the Empire&#39;s military establishment. Before the war, the Imperial Academy held a near-monopoly on battlefield firepower -- only sorcerers could deliver the kind of devastating ranged destruction that won battles. The introduction of explosive devices and incendiary weapons gave conventional military commanders an alternative, reducing their dependence on the Academy and shifting the political dynamics of imperial warfare. This shift continues to generate tension between the military establishment and the Academy, which views the proliferation of non-sorcerous firepower as a threat to its institutional relevance and authority. See Also General Darius Jute -- the commander who brokered peace Kolani Irregulars -- the military formation established by the treaty The Imperial Academy -- institution whose monopoly was challenged The Mithrian Military -- the armed forces that fought the war History of Mithrapos -- broader historical context The Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"eladra","title":"Eladra","category":"lore","tags":"race eladra argollean empyrean aurelion sorcery erenthis aodahn sanctuary ancient spires gnostic-geometry","text":"Eladra The Eladra were once part of the advanced Argollean Empire , where they played a central role in the discovery of the secrets of the cosmos, the Aurelion , and the Empyrean gods. They were the original practitioners of the sorcerous arts that would later be systematized as Gnostic Geometry , and their scholarship laid the foundations for much of what the Imperial Academy teaches today. Their civilization fell to ruin through the influence of the Elvora and the creeping corruption of Cthonic power. Physical Appearance The Eladra are taller than humans , with lithe but muscular builds that combine grace with surprising physical strength. Their appearance is distinctly non-human -- proportions that are slightly wrong by human standards, features that are beautiful but alien, a quality of presence that sets them apart from even the most striking human specimen. They possess a natural affinity for sorcery -- an innate sensitivity to the metaphysical axioms that govern reality. This affinity is not learned but inborn, a fundamental aspect of Eladran biology that made them the foremost sorcerers of the ancient world. History The Argollean Empire The Eladra were central to Argollean civilization, serving as its foremost scholars and sorcerers. It was the Eladra who discovered the secrets of the cosmos, the nature of the Aurelion , and the existence of the Empyrean gods. Their research laid the foundations for Gnostic Geometry and established the metaphysical framework that all subsequent sorcerous traditions would either build upon or react against. The Fall The fall of Eladran civilization was not a single catastrophic event but a long, slow collapse driven by internal decay and the transformation of some Eladra into the Elvora . As Eladran scholars delved deeper into the chaotic energies of the Beyond , they were changed by what they found -- achieving immortality at a terrible cost and bringing ruin upon the civilization they had once sustained. The precise nature of the fall is debated by scholars, but the result was the near-total destruction of Eladran culture and the scattering of its people. Current Status Those claiming Eladran heritage in the present day are almost invariably of mixed blood -- the product of centuries of intermarriage with humans and other peoples. Only a handful of full-blooded Eladra still live , and these survivors are extremely old and deeply reclusive , withdrawing from the affairs of the mortal world into isolation and silence. The Erenthis Trees The Eladra built the Erenthis trees -- vast, sacred growths whose Eladran spiritual traditions were woven through with Empyrean vitality. The Erenthis are living expressions of the Aurelion&#39;s distributed essence, cultivated by the Eladra as monuments that would endure long after their civilization fell. The Erenthis root network functions as the most reliable natural defense against Cthonic corruption in the known world. The Avari later built their culture around Erenthis found in the ruins of Eladran civilization. They did not fully understand what they were tending, but they understood enough -- that the tree was sacred, that it sustained them, that rites performed in its presence carried weight. Aodahn -- The City Beneath Sanctuary The Eladra built Aodahn -- the ancient harbor-city upon whose ruins Sanctuary now stands. Aodahn was built by the true, uncorrupted Eladra -- possibly the last community of their kind in the world. The city featured five ivory spires , each carved from a single stone so white it seems to emit light, each rising three hundred feet or more above the harbor. Modern Academy scholars suspect the spires are engineered conduits of Empyrean vitality , analogous to Erenthis trees but constructed rather than grown. The Vanishing The Eladra of Aodahn vanished mysteriously . When the Mithrians arrived, they found the city completely abandoned. No evidence of war, plague, siege, or flight. Belongings remained in homes. Workshops stood open. Food rotted on tables. The people were simply gone. The chronicler Varro Silk wrote that the city felt as though its inhabitants had stepped out of the room and simply never returned. The Academy has proposed several theories: the Threshold Hypothesis (the Eladra stepped through a door to the Empyrean ), the Ascension Model (transcendence of physical form), the Catastrophic Severance Theory (accidental destruction), and the Recall (summoned by their gods). None are proven. The Threshold At the deepest level of the Undercity beneath Sanctuary -- the Foundations of the Spires -- lies the Threshold : the place where the Eladra ascension happened. The door has not fully closed . Whatever process the Eladra used to depart left a permanent weakness in the boundary between the physical world and the Empyrean. This is the source of the phenomena that pervade all of Aodahn -- sounds in unknown languages, fleeting visions, the sensation of being watched. Eladra Agents in Sanctuary At least one Eladra agent is believed to be present in Sanctuary at any given time , watching and guarding secrets about what lies below. These agents are subtle, patient, and nearly impossible to identify. Their purpose is unknown -- whether they guard the Threshold, monitor human activity, or pursue some deeper agenda is a matter of speculation. The Argollean Brotherhood The Argollean Brotherhood is a criminal network connected to old Eladran noble houses that survived the fall of the First Empire. They exist marginally and resentfully within Mithrian society, executing plans and deeds on behalf of these houses: intelligence work, artifact acquisition, and the occasional removal of obstacles. Their primary interest is relics and artifacts of the First Empire, which they regard as cultural inheritance rather than state property. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures elvora -- The corrupted Eladra who destroyed their civilization aodahn -- The Eladra city beneath Sanctuary the-erenthis -- The sacred trees planted by the Eladra sanctuary -- The city built on Eladra ruins argollean-brotherhood -- The criminal network connected to Eladran noble houses Aurelion -- The divine essence the Eladra discovered Argolle -- The ancient empire the Eladra were part of imperial-academy -- The institution that studies Eladra heritage magic-and-sorcery -- The sorcerous traditions the Eladra founded avari -- The people who inherited the Erenthis ygrathen -- The ancient race the Argolleans warred against"},{"slug":"elvora","title":"Elvora","category":"lore","tags":"race elvora eladra veil beyond immortal barren binding cthonic corruption ancient","text":"Elvora The Elvora are of Eladran descent, but they have been fundamentally changed by exposure to the chaotic energies of the Beyond . Where the Eladra sought to understand and codify the laws of reality, the Elvora plunged into the raw chaos that lies beneath those laws, and they were transformed by the experience. They achieved eternal life, but at a cost that is destroying them as a people. Physical Appearance The Elvora are taller than humans and extremely muscular , their bodies hardened by centuries of existence and the transformative effects of chaotic energy. Their physical characteristics are striking and unsettling: Pale white skin -- drained of natural pigmentation by centuries of Veil contact Solid black eyes -- lacking iris, pupil, or sclera. The eyes blackened from centuries of Veil contact, the visible mark of what the Elvora touched and what touched them back Tend to be hairless -- another consequence of the chaotic energies that remade them Many lack consideration for modesty or clothing -- regarding such conventions as meaningless affectations of mortal culture, vestiges of a way of life they have long since transcended The Price of Immortality The Elvora achieved eternal life, but at a terrible cost that ensures their extinction: All females are barren -- unable to bear children, cutting off the possibility of natural reproduction entirely All males are immortal -- unable to die of natural causes, condemned to endure the endless passage of time The Elvora are thus a slowly dying race , their numbers dwindling with each passing century as attrition, violence, and madness claim those who cannot be replaced. Every Elvoran who falls to violence, accident, or the slow erosion of sanity is a permanent loss -- one fewer member of a people who can never grow. The Weight of Ages The surviving Elvora are impossibly old , and the weight of millennia has taken a devastating toll on their minds. Their memories are fractured , their personalities splintered by the sheer duration of their existence. An Elvoran who has lived for thousands of years may speak of ancient events with crystalline clarity while being unable to remember their own name from one day to the next. They are beings for whom time has become a burden rather than a resource -- each century adding another layer of experience to minds that were never designed to contain so much. The Binding The Elvora discovered the Veil -- the barrier between the material world and the chaotic energies of the Beyond. They did not merely study it. They tore it open, reached through, and attempted to bind the powers they found on the other side. Their binding destroyed them even as it succeeded . The Elvoran binding tradition is the same essential practice as the Lakandi binding tradition , but at a civilizational scale rather than an individual one. Where a Lakandi practitioner binds a single demon or spirit, the Elvora attempted to bind powers that could reshape civilizations. The cost was total: females rendered barren, males rendered immortal, eyes turned black, civilization destroyed. The Elvora are the cautionary tale , the warning against ambition unchecked by wisdom. Their fate demonstrates that the scale of a binding matters -- that there are things that should not be bound, not because binding is immoral but because the cost of binding them exceeds what any individual or civilization can pay. Relationship to the Eladra The Elvora and the Eladra share a common origin but diverged catastrophically. The Eladra maintained their connection to the Empyrean -- the divine order, the distributed essence of the Aurelion . The Elvora turned instead to the chaos beyond the Veil, seeking power through contact with forces that the Empyrean tradition holds in opposition. The builders of Aodahn were not Elvora. They were the true, uncorrupted Eladra -- something older and purer, a people who maintained their connection to the Empyrean when others fell away. The distinction matters: the Eladra and the Elvora may share an origin, but they are not the same people, and conflating them obscures the nature of both. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures eladra -- The ancestor civilization from which the Elvora diverged lakandi-binding-tradition -- The individual-scale binding tradition related to Elvoran practice the-veil -- The barrier the Elvora tore open cthonic-corruption -- The corruption that marks those who contact the Beyond aodahn -- The Eladra city (built by true Eladra, not Elvora) ygrathen -- Another ancient race with binding traditions"},{"slug":"empyrean-war","title":"The Empyrean War (663 BE)","category":"lore","tags":"event history empyrean bellasarius enador massaran-empire beastmen founding-event","text":"The Empyrean War (663 BE) The Empyrean War (663 BE) was the foundational conflict that gave birth to the civilization that would become the Mithrian Empire . The Prophet Enador and the war-chief Bellasarius Valerian raised an alliance of peoples against the Massaran Empire and its sorcerer-kings. The tyrant-sorcerer Sebek was driven into exile, the Beastmen legions that formed the core of the Massaran military were scattered, and centuries of darkness came to an end. Background The Massaran Empire was a formidable power sustained by Veil sorcery and the Beastmen legions that served as its military backbone. The Massaran sorcerer-kings ruled through fear, arcane domination, and the deployment of beastman armies -- monstrous warriors whose origins lay in the dark experiments of a bygone age. The peoples of Mithrapos lived under Massaran tyranny, their lands occupied, their cultures suppressed, their lives subject to the whims of sorcerer-tyrants. The Alliance The Empyrean War was made possible by two extraordinary individuals: Prophet Enador -- A spiritual leader who rediscovered the Measure and the Scale , the sacred texts that would become the moral and legal foundation of the civilization that followed. Enador provided the spiritual framework -- the shared identity and purpose -- that united disparate peoples into a coherent alliance. He also recovered the Anthyllium , the ancient Argollean grimoire that restored access to sorcerous power. Bellasarius Valerian -- The war-chief who served as the military architect of the alliance. Bellasarius organized, trained, and led the armies that fought the Massaran forces. His tactical brilliance and personal courage made him a figure of legend whose name would echo through the centuries. Together, the prophet and the general forged an alliance that combined spiritual conviction with military competence -- a combination that proved devastating against the Massaran order. The War The Empyrean War was a prolonged and brutal conflict. The Massaran sorcerer-kings commanded powerful magic and the loyalty of the Beastmen legions, making them formidable opponents. The alliance led by Enador and Bellasarius fought a campaign of liberation across Mithrapos , breaking Massaran power piece by piece. The war culminated in the overthrow of the Massaran order. The tyrant-sorcerer Sebek -- the most powerful of the sorcerer-kings -- was driven into exile rather than killed, a detail that has fueled centuries of speculation about whether the Massaran threat was truly ended or merely driven underground. The Beastmen legions were scattered across the wilds of Mithrapos, where they remain a persistent threat to this day -- their descendants are the Beastmen that continue to plague frontier settlements and wilderness regions. Consequences The victory in the Empyrean War had consequences that reshaped the world: The Mithrian League -- The alliance transformed into a confederation of free city-states governed by a Senate , establishing the political framework that would eventually become the Mithrian Empire . The Measure and the Scale -- Enador&#39;s rediscovered texts became the moral and legal foundation of the new order, establishing the Empyrean Faith as the dominant spiritual tradition of Mithrapos. Mithra City -- The founding of the city that would become the capital of the Empire. The Valerian Legacy -- Bellasarius Valerian&#39;s descendants would claim the Imperial throne, with Marcus Valerian declaring himself the first Emperor in 1 IY. House Valerian &#39;s prestige rests entirely on this ancestral connection. The Beastman Threat -- The scattered Beastmen legions were never fully destroyed. Their descendants persist in the wilderness, and their periodic resurgence -- most notably the Sacking of Crossings in 377 IY -- demonstrates that the consequences of the Empyrean War continue to shape the present. See Also Prophet Enador -- spiritual leader of the alliance Bellasarius Valerian / Marcus Valerian -- war-chief and ancestor of the first Emperor House Valerian -- the dynasty founded on Bellasarius&#39;s legacy The Measure and the Scale -- the sacred texts rediscovered by Enador The Empyrean Faith -- the faith born from the war&#39;s victory The Mithrian Empire -- the civilization that emerged from the war History of Mithrapos -- broader historical context Sacking of Crossings -- the Beastmen&#39;s return, centuries later"},{"slug":"gnostic-geometry","title":"Gnostic Geometry","category":"lore","tags":"gnostic-geometry magic sorcery anthyllium nine-fold sigils imperial-academy argolle enador axioms","text":"Gnostic Geometry The world is built on hidden mathematics. — High Mage Marius Gnostic Geometry is the most powerful, most structured, and most carefully controlled form of magic practiced in the Mithrian Empire . It is the science of the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality — the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout the cosmos by The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice, accessed and directed through mental discipline, geometric diagrams (sigils), and resonance (the spoken word). Once practiced by the ancient Argolleans in the time before the Massaran Empire , the formulae of Gnostic Geometry were lost for thousands of years after the fall of Argolle , only to be rediscovered when the Prophet Enador found The Anthyllium alongside the Measure and the Scale . Theoretical Foundation The Nine-Fold Patterns The fundamental premise of Gnostic Geometry is that reality is structured according to nine-fold geometric patterns — mathematical relationships woven into the fabric of the cosmos by The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice. These patterns are not merely descriptions of reality but its actual underlying architecture: the cosmos is, at its deepest level, a geometric construct, and the laws of nature, physics, and metaphysics are all expressions of these nine foundational geometries. The nine-fold patterns govern everything from the behavior of matter and energy to the movement of souls, the flow of time, the structure of The Veil , and the relationship between the material world and the Beyond. A gnostic geometer who understands these patterns — who can perceive, reproduce, and manipulate them — can alter the fundamental properties of reality within the scope of their knowledge and power. Manipulation of Metaphysical Axioms According to The Anthyllium , sorcery through Gnostic Geometry is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms — the foundational rules upon which reality is built. This is a critical distinction from other forms of magic. Hedge-mages manipulate natural forces through instinct and tradition. Warlocks draw power from entities beyond The Veil through negotiated pacts. Practitioners of The Flame channel the divine spark within their own souls. Gnostic geometers manipulate the rules themselves — the underlying mathematical relationships that determine how matter behaves, how energy flows, how space is structured, and how time progresses. This gives Gnostic Geometry enormous power but also enormous danger. The axioms that gnostic geometers manipulate are the same axioms that maintain the structural integrity of reality itself. A poorly constructed sigil, an incorrectly resonated formula, a failure of mental discipline at the critical moment — any of these can produce consequences ranging from the sorcerer&#39;s immediate death to localized reality distortions that may persist for decades. A Structured, Lawful Cosmos The philosophy underlying Gnostic Geometry assumes a structured, lawful cosmos — a universe that operates according to consistent, discoverable rules rather than arbitrary divine whim or chaotic chance. This assumption is grounded in the Empyrean understanding of The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice: the supreme designer created a cosmos of order, meaning, and purpose, and the geometric patterns that govern reality are the mathematical expression of that order. Gnostic Geometry is therefore not merely a magical practice but a philosophical commitment — a declaration that the cosmos is rational, that its rules can be understood, and that understanding those rules confers the power to modify them. The Three Disciplines Mental Discipline The practice of Gnostic Geometry begins with mental discipline — the rigorous training of the mind to perceive, hold, and manipulate the nine-fold patterns without error. The human mind was not designed to process the kind of mathematical complexity that the nine-fold patterns represent, and untrained minds that attempt to engage with them directly risk madness, cognitive dissolution, or the kind of reality-distorting accidents that give sorcery its fearsome reputation. The Imperial Academy subjects its students to years of mental conditioning before permitting them to attempt even the simplest geometric manipulations. This conditioning involves meditation, mathematical study, memory training, and a series of increasingly complex cognitive exercises designed to expand the mind&#39;s capacity to hold multiple geometric relationships simultaneously. The process is grueling, and the dropout rate is high — not all minds are capable of the flexibility and precision that Gnostic Geometry demands. Diagrams (Sigils) Sigils are the geometric diagrams through which gnostic geometers access and manipulate the nine-fold patterns. A sigil is not merely a drawing but a precision instrument — a geometric construction whose proportions, angles, and relationships must be exact to within tolerances that would challenge the finest draftsman. Each sigil encodes a specific manipulation of one or more metaphysical axioms, and the act of constructing the sigil — whether drawn on paper, inscribed in stone, traced in the air with a gesture, or held entirely within the mind — is the act that initiates the manipulation. The relationship between the sigil&#39;s geometry and its effect is not arbitrary but lawful: specific geometric relationships produce specific metaphysical effects, and these relationships are consistent, reproducible, and predictable. This is what distinguishes Gnostic Geometry from the intuitive, unpredictable magic of hedge-mages and the negotiated, transactional power of warlock pacts. Resonance (Spoken Word) Resonance is the vocal component of Gnostic Geometry — the spoken words, tones, and harmonic patterns that activate the sigils and direct the manipulated axioms toward their intended effects. The words themselves are not magical incantations in the folkloric sense; they are precisely calibrated vibrations that interact with the geometric patterns of the sigils to produce specific metaphysical resonances. The relationship between sound and geometry is one of the deepest mysteries of Gnostic Geometry — the understanding that the cosmos responds not only to visual patterns but to auditory ones, and that the combination of the two produces effects that neither could achieve alone. History Ancient Argollean Practice Gnostic Geometry was first developed — or first discovered — by the ancient Argolleans, the civilization that flourished in what is now the Province of Argolle long before the rise of the Massaran Empire . The Argolleans achieved a level of sophistication in geometric sorcery that has never been equaled, and the ruins of their civilization — the temples, fortifications, and arcane infrastructure that dot the Argollean landscape — testify to the power they wielded. The nature of the ancient Argollean civilization and the circumstances of its fall remain subjects of intense scholarly debate and archaeological investigation. The Lost Centuries When Argolle fell, the formulae of Gnostic Geometry were lost — destroyed, hidden, or suppressed by the forces that brought the Argollean civilization to an end. For thousands of years, the nine-fold patterns that the Argolleans had mastered were unknown to the wider world. Magic continued to be practiced during this period — through hedge-magic, warlock pacts, and the intuitive sorcery of naturally gifted individuals — but the structured, systematic power of Gnostic Geometry was gone, and the world was immeasurably diminished by its absence. Rediscovery The formulae of Gnostic Geometry were rediscovered when the Prophet Enador found The Anthyllium — the ancient grimoire that described the nine-fold geometric patterns — alongside the Measure and the Scale . This dual discovery was the intellectual foundation of the Empyrean War and the civilization that followed: the Measure and the Scale provided the moral framework, and the Anthyllium provided the arcane knowledge, and together they gave the Empyrean faithful both the spiritual authority and the practical power to overthrow the Massaran Empire and its Sorcerer Kings . Imperial Academy Control The Imperial Academy retains strict control over the practice of Gnostic Geometry within the Mithrian Empire . This control is justified on both practical and political grounds. Practically, Gnostic Geometry is extraordinarily dangerous to untrained practitioners — the manipulation of metaphysical axioms by those who lack the mental discipline, geometric precision, and theoretical understanding to do so safely can result in catastrophic accidents that endanger not only the practitioner but everyone and everything in their vicinity. Politically, the concentration of arcane power in the hands of the Academy ensures that the most potent form of magic in the known world remains under the control of the Imperial government rather than distributed among private practitioners, rogue sorcerers, or hostile powers. Unsanctioned practice of Gnostic Geometry is a serious criminal offense throughout the Mithrian Empire , and the Academy maintains a corps of investigators — colloquially known as witch-hunters, though the term is imprecise — whose task is to identify, apprehend, and either recruit or suppress unlicensed practitioners. Relationship to Other Magical Traditions Gnostic Geometry is more powerful than hedge-magic, warlock pacts, or any other form of sorcery practiced in the known world — a claim that the Imperial Academy makes openly and that the evidence supports. Hedge-magic operates through instinct and tradition, achieving modest effects through methods that its practitioners do not fully understand. Warlock pacts achieve power through negotiation with entities beyond The Veil , but the power comes at a cost determined by the entity rather than the practitioner. The Flame channels divine power through virtue, but its effects are unpredictable and its practitioners are vanishingly rare. Gnostic Geometry manipulates the axioms of reality itself — the foundational rules upon which all other forms of magic ultimately depend. A gnostic geometer does not petition an entity for power, does not rely on instinct or tradition, and does not need to be virtuous. What a gnostic geometer needs is knowledge, precision, and discipline — and within the scope of those qualities, the power available is limited only by the practitioner&#39;s understanding of the nine-fold patterns and their capacity to manipulate them without destroying themselves. See Also The Anthyllium The Aurelion The Veil The Flame Enador Imperial Academy Magic and Sorcery The Measure and the Scale Argolle Massaran Empire Sorcerer Kings Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"grathar","title":"Grathar","category":"lore","tags":"culture grathar naming human ygrathen grathe-steppe reclusive tall","text":"Grathar The Grathar are a physically imposing and culturally austere people, renowned for their extraordinary size, strength, and directness. They are notable for carrying Ygrathen blood in their veins -- a heritage that manifests in their exceptional physical power and in subtle qualities that set them apart from ordinary humans. Physical Appearance The Grathar are extraordinarily tall and strong -- the most physically imposing of the human peoples of Mithrapos . They have dark hair and light eyes, with skin that ranges from ochre to slightly green -- a faint but visible echo of their Ygrathen ancestry. The greenish tint to Grathar skin is the most obvious marker of their inhuman heritage, and it sets them apart immediately from all other human cultures. Culture and Values The Grathar are mostly peaceful and reclusive , inhabiting the vast Grathe Steppe alongside -- but largely separate from -- the Skiothan horse warriors who share the same territory. Where the Skiothans are aggressive, expansionist, and convinced of their own superiority, the Grathar are withdrawn, contemplative, and content to be left alone. Few Grathar have assimilated into Mithrian society . Their extraordinary size, their distinctive appearance, and their reclusive temperament make integration difficult, and most Grathar see no reason to seek it. Those who do venture into Imperial civilization tend to be solitary individuals -- traders, mercenaries, scholars -- rather than communities. Ygrathen Heritage The Grathar carry Ygrathen blood -- the oldest race of Mithrapos , beings of tremendous size and powerful sorcery. This heritage accounts for the Grathar&#39;s exceptional size and physical strength, but it may carry deeper implications as well. The Ygrathen were solitary beings of enormous power who never formed their own civilization; the Grathar&#39;s reclusive nature may reflect this same inclination, inherited across generations of diluted blood. Naming Conventions Grathar use singular, short, hard-sounding names that convey brute strength and natural force. Names like Krug , Brak , or Thond are typical -- monosyllabic, percussive, and utterly without ornamentation. The Grathar see no need for patronymics, clan names, or honorifics. A Grathar&#39;s name is their name, and it is enough . This simplicity in naming reflects the broader Grathar aesthetic: direct, unadorned, and unconcerned with the elaborate social signaling that other cultures invest in their naming practices. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures ygrathen -- The ancient race whose blood the Grathar carry skiothan -- The nomadic horse warriors who share the Grathe Steppe varek-ashstone -- A full-blooded Ygrathen hermit"},{"slug":"great-houses","title":"The Great Houses","category":"lore","tags":"houses nobility politics empire factions","text":"The Great Houses The Great Houses are the noble families whose wealth, military power, and patronage networks dominate the political landscape of the Mithrian Empire . Each house commands vast estates, legions of clients, and tributary lesser houses. The competition between them -- sometimes open warfare, more often intrigue and maneuvering -- shapes the fate of the Empire as much as any decree from the throne. House Decimus Patriarch Emperor War of Three Emperors (270 IY), when Claudius Decimus emerged victorious from the civil war that followed the assassination of the mad Emperor Aurex . Since that time, the Decimus line has held the Imperial seat without interruption. The house enforces its will through the Imperial Talons , an elite cadre of spies, informants, and assassins who serve the Emperor directly. The Talons operate outside normal Imperial law and are feared throughout the Empire as instruments of the throne&#39;s displeasure. The succession of House Decimus has not always been smooth. Julian Decimus , a previous Emperor, named his son Diometian as heir -- a decision that triggered civil war when rival claimants and discontented houses refused to accept the appointment. The resulting conflict reshaped the political order of the Empire. House Valerian Patriarch Bellasarius Valerian -- the legendary general who, alongside the prophet Enador , overthrew the Massaran Empire in the Empyrean War . For centuries, the Valerians held the Imperial throne as a near-birthright. The house&#39;s fortunes declined after a succession of poor Emperors culminated in the reign of Aurex , whose madness and cruelty brought the Empire to the brink. Aurex was assassinated by his own sister, ending the Valerian dynasty&#39;s hold on power. Today, House Valerian retains immense prestige and wealth but lacks the political muscle to reclaim the throne -- though many believe the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration. House Kalomenes Patriarch Mithrian League , wielding unrivaled influence in the Imperial Senate . When Marcus Valerian declared himself Emperor, the Kalomenes were among those defeated and forced to bend the knee. The house has never forgotten this humiliation, nor has it ever truly accepted subordination. Today, House Kalomenes commands tremendous power in the courts and political institutions of the Empire. The house sponsors dozens of tributary houses and maintains an extensive network of clients, lawyers, and political operatives. Where other houses wield swords, the Kalomenes wield patronage, precedent, and procedural manipulation with lethal precision. House Malventi Patriarch Massaran Kingdoms and Urgathoa , trafficking in exotic goods, rare materials, and -- by persistent rumor -- slaves. The Malventi are cosmopolitan, pragmatic, and largely indifferent to the ideological concerns that animate other houses. Their foreign connections make them invaluable as intermediaries and intelligence sources, but also invite suspicion. Many in the Imperial Senate and the Thousand Temples view the Malventi as dangerously unpatriotic, more loyal to profit than to the Measure and the Scale . House Drussus Patriarch Thousand Temples and the Empyrean Faith , promoting cultural purity, religious orthodoxy, and the divine authority of the Emperor. They view the Measure and the Scale not merely as law but as sacred revelation, and they regard any deviation from tradition as heresy. The house&#39;s influence is strongest among the priesthood, the rural aristocracy, and the traditional military families who see the Empire as a divinely ordained institution. House Aurel is frequently at odds with the more cosmopolitan houses, particularly House Malventi and House Kalomenes . House Severian Patriarch house-severian Distinction Ancient, secretive, rumored [[Eladra blood House Severian is among the oldest houses in the Empire, yet also the most enigmatic. The Severians operate through hidden channels, preferring shadow influence to open political contest. Their true wealth and the full extent of their networks are unknown even to the Imperial Talons . Persistent rumors hold that the Severian bloodline carries Eladra ancestry -- a claim that, if true, would link the house to the ancient Argollean civilization and its arcane legacy. The Severians neither confirm nor deny these rumors, and their occasional displays of uncanny insight and influence do nothing to dispel them. See Also Mithrian Empire Imperial Senate War of Three Emperors Imperial Talons Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"history-of-mithrapos","title":"History of Mithrapos","category":"lore","tags":"history timeline mithrapos mithrian-empire argolle eladra elvora ygrathen thune massar enador bellasarius backlands sorcery warfare cthonic empyrean krysea nethercity lakan beastmen targ crossings","text":"History of Mithrapos Mithrapos is a cradle and a coffin, a boneyard of Empires. -- Savron , Imperial Chronicler, The Last Argument of Kings The world of Mithrapos has endured the rise and fall of civilizations spanning thousands of years. Each empire has built upon the ruins of the last, inheriting fragments of knowledge, power, and ambition from its predecessors while carrying forward the scars of their failures. The history of Mithrapos is not a story of progress but of cycles -- of greatness achieved and squandered, of knowledge discovered and lost, of empires that blazed with brilliance before collapsing into ash. What follows is the definitive chronological record of the principal events and eras that have shaped the world as it exists today, drawn from the earliest surviving accounts of the Eladran city-states through to the present day. Pre-Imperial Era: Deep History The Rise of the Eladran City-States (4100 BE) The earliest recorded civilization in Mithrapos emerged circa 4100 BE, when the Eladran city-states arose in Argolle -- the region known in the present day as the northern Backlands . These city-states were centers of scholarship, sorcery, and governance, establishing the cultural and intellectual foundations upon which all subsequent civilizations would build. The Eladra were the foremost scholars and sorcerers of their age, and their discoveries concerning the nature of the Aurelion , the cosmos, and the Empyrean gods laid the groundwork for all sorcerous and theological traditions that followed. First Contact with the Ygrathen (3900 BE) Around 3900 BE, the expanding Eladra encountered loose tribes of Ygrathen inhabiting the Meniri Mountains . Initial contact between the two peoples led to brief but violent conflict. The Ygrathen -- the oldest race of Mithrapos, solitary by nature and possessed of formidable sorcerous power -- and the Eladra became enemies. This enmity would endure for millennia and culminate in wars of annihilation. Discovery of the Lakan (3800 BE) In 3800 BE, the Eladra discovered primitive human settlements in the fertile highlands beyond their city-states. The Eladra established trade and friendship with these peoples, introducing them to the Empyrean gods and the theological framework that accompanied Eladran culture. These humans adopted the name Lakan -- a designation that would persist through the ages and eventually define one of the most significant human cultures in Mithrapos . The Awakening of the Great Teacher (3200 BE) The city-state of Krysea expanded aggressively, becoming one of the most powerful of the Eladran polities. During this expansion, the Eladra discovered a vast network of caves and tunnels beneath the city. In exploring these subterranean passages, they accidentally awakened a slumbering Chemosh ( Khepri ) Hierarch -- a being of immense age and power who had lain dormant beneath Krysea for an unknown span of time. Calling himself the Great Teacher , the Hierarch introduced the Cthonic gods to the Eladra of Krysea. Where the Empyrean gods offered law, order, and transcendence, the Cthonic gods offered power, transformation, and the allure of forbidden knowledge. The Great Teacher&#39;s arrival marked a turning point in Eladran civilization -- a spiritual fissure that would widen over the centuries into an unbridgeable chasm. Excavation of the Ruins Below Krysea (3100 BE) At the instruction of the Great Teacher, the Eladra of Krysea began a secret excavation of the ancient ruins that lay beneath the city. These ruins predated even the Eladran city-states, and their origins remain a subject of speculation and dread. The Cthonic gods were worshipped as mystery cults during this period -- secretive, initiatory, and confined to a small number of devoted adherents. The seeds of what would become the Nethercity were planted in these excavations. The Rise of Eolande and the Conquest of Humans (3000 BE) The Eladran general Eolande , tutored personally by the Great Teacher in matters of strategy, sorcery, and statecraft, began conquering nearby human populations. This marked the first systematic subjugation of humans by the Eladra -- a departure from the earlier pattern of trade and friendship. The Great Teacher&#39;s influence was transforming Eladran culture from within, replacing its older values of scholarship and cooperation with ambition, domination, and the pursuit of power. Transmogrification and the Creation of Monsters (2800 BE) By 2800 BE, increasing wealth and influence flowed into the Cthonic cults of Krysea . The Great Teacher and his acolytes began exploring transmogrification -- the practice of splicing humans with chaotic energies drawn from the Beyond to create monsters. These experiments represented a fundamental violation of the natural order, and their products were creatures of terrible power and suffering. Transmogrification would become one of the defining practices of Cthonic sorcery and one of the most reviled arts in the history of Mithrapos . The First Crescent Rebellion and the Creation of the Thune (2700 BE) The Empyrean cults within Eladran society were appalled by the transmogrifiers and their monstrous creations. Attempts to suppress the Cthonic cults led to the martyrdom of Cthonic cultists, which paradoxically increased the movement&#39;s appeal and captured more worshippers for the Cthonic cause. Simultaneously, the First Crescent Rebellion erupted among the subjugated human populations. This uprising -- the first organized human resistance against Eladran rule -- convinced the Eladran nobility of the need for a purpose-built warrior caste. The result was the creation of the Thune -- slave soldiers forged through sorcery and designed for war. The Thune were not born but made, and their creation marked a further step in the moral descent of Eladran civilization. The Argollean Empire Declared (2600 BE) By 2600 BE, open Cthonic worship had become commonplace throughout Eladran society. Construction of the Great Temple of the Awakening began in Krysea , a monumental edifice dedicated to the Cthonic gods and the Great Teacher&#39;s vision of spiritual transformation. The enslaved servitor races and the decadent pleasures offered by Cthonic worship seduced the Eladran nobility, who converted in increasing numbers. Eladran warlords led armies of Thune to conquer the entirety of Argolle and the territories beyond. The Argollean Empire -- the First Empire -- was formally declared. Construction of the Grand Cthonic Temple in the Nethercity began, establishing the subterranean complex that would grow over the centuries into one of the most dangerous and significant sites in all of Mithrapos . In this same period, the Bitter War erupted. A powerful Ygrathen alliance, influenced by Empyrean priests who had been driven from the Eladran city-states, sought to stop the Argollean expansion by force. The Bitter War would rage for centuries and consume untold lives. The Burning of the Empyrean Temples (2400 BE) Cthonic disciples of Bel burned Empyrean temples across the Argollean Empire and slaughtered their worshippers. This campaign of religious persecution marked the effective destruction of organized Empyrean worship within Argollean territory and the triumph of Cthonic faith among the Eladra. On the military front, the Ygrathen won several significant battles against the Argolleans during this period, though at catastrophic cost to their own forces. The relentless violence of the Bitter War drove a rise in the worship of Dirgion , the Cthonic god of death and entropy. Construction of the Doom Temple of Dirgion began. The Thune Ascendant (2300 BE) The transmogrifiers created new, deadlier versions of the Thune slave-soldiers, incorporating lessons learned from centuries of warfare. The tide of the Bitter War turned decisively in Argollean favor. The Argollean economy became entirely dependent on servitor races and enslaved populations to sustain itself -- a structural weakness that would eventually prove fatal. During this period, the Lakan -- the human peoples who had once been friends and trading partners of the Eladra -- converted to Cthonic worship, completing the spiritual transformation of the region. The Crushing of the Ygrathen (2100 BE) Under the command of the Eladran warlord Marcan , the Argollean armies crushed the Ygrathen alliance and razed their ancestral homeland. The war that had raged for five centuries ended in genocide. Most Ygrathen were killed; the survivors were driven into hiding in the remote and inaccessible places of Mithrapos , where their descendants remain to this day -- solitary, formidable, and implacable in their hatred. Construction of the Hallowed Halls of Heroes began in Krysea to commemorate the victory. The Great Teacher, his work apparently complete, entered cryostasis in the Secret Sepulcher deep within the Nethercity -- a chamber whose location was known to only a handful of the most senior Cthonic priests. The Entombment of Marcan (2000 BE) The warlord Marcan , conqueror of the Ygrathen , was interred in the Great King Tomb within the Nethercity . His tomb became one of the most revered sites in Argollean culture -- a monument to military glory and the apex of Eladran imperial power. Orthanach the Mummy Lord (1800 BE) The Eladran hierophant Orthanach became the first Argollean to successfully transform himself into a mummy lord -- achieving a form of undead immortality through Cthonic ritual. Upon his death, Orthanach was interred in the Secret Tomb within the Nethercity , accompanied by his wife Sonya and his guard Cassair . The creation of a mummy lord represented the pinnacle of Cthonic necromantic achievement and a further step into the darkness that was consuming Eladran civilization from within. The Fall of Argolle (1700 BE) The Eladran population had been in decline for centuries, their culture increasingly decadent, their birthrate falling, their vitality consumed by Cthonic excess. The Thune -- the slave-soldiers who had fought and won the Empire&#39;s wars -- rose in rebellion. The Lakan , seeing an opportunity, joined the uprising. The Thune slaughtered the Argolleans and razed Krysea to the ground. The city that had been the heart of the First Empire was reduced to rubble, its temples pulled down, its libraries burned, its inhabitants put to the sword. The Eladra who survived the destruction were scattered, many eventually transforming into the Elvora as they delved deeper into chaotic energies in their desperation to survive. The Lakan retreated into the wastes, their role in the rebellion earning them nothing but further suffering. The fall of Argolle was not a single catastrophic event but the culmination of centuries of internal decay -- the inevitable end of a civilization that had traded its soul for power and its future for pleasure. Thune Dominion (1400 BE) By 1400 BE, the Thune had conquered much of the former Argollean holdings and established their own brutal dominion, subjugating the human populations who had so recently been their allies. The Cthonic -worshipping humans known as the Masserai (or Massar ) functioned as an upper caste within Thune society, assisting in the administration and enforcement of human enslavement. The cycle of subjugation continued -- only the masters had changed. The Rise of the Massar (1075 BE) In 1075 BE, the Massar overthrew their Thune overlords and established their own sorcerer-empire. Over the next five hundred years, the Massaran Empire expanded steadily, building a civilization sustained by the very sorcerous traditions the Massar had inherited from the Argolleans. Massar Sorcery Unleashed (1070 BE) Almost immediately after seizing power, the Massar uncovered ancient Elvora secrets -- including the arts of transmogrification , demon-binding , and necromancy . Drawing on these forbidden traditions, the Massar created the Beastmen -- hybrid creatures fused from human and animal stock through chaotic sorcery -- to fuel their war machine. The Beastmen would become one of the most enduring and devastating legacies of Massaran rule, persisting as a threat to civilization long after the empire that created them had fallen. The Empyrean War (684--652 BE) The Prophet Enador did not bring the gods to man -- he reminded man of the gods they had buried beneath centuries of silence and sin. -- Savron , Imperial Historian, Collected Commentaries In 684 BE, the Prophet Enador emerged as one of the most transformative figures in the history of Mithrapos . Enador received the Measure and the Scale -- the sacred texts that would become the foundation of Empyrean faith and the moral and legal framework of the civilization that followed. Along with the Measure and the Scale, Enador recovered the Anthyllium , the ancient Argollean grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality -- the formulae that would be systematized as Gnostic Geometry by later scholars. Enador preached the Empyrean faith across the subjugated lands, gathering followers and igniting a spiritual revolution. Enador and the general Bellasarius Valerian raised an alliance of peoples against the Massaran Empire and its sorcerer-kings. The sorcerer-king Sebek attempted to suppress the new faith, triggering the Second Crescent Rebellion -- an echo of the First Crescent Rebellion that had shaken the Argollean Empire over two thousand years earlier. In 651 BE, the Beastmen armies of the Massar were routed in a series of decisive engagements. The sorcerer-kings were hunted down and slaughtered. Sebek alone escaped, fleeing into the desert where his fate remains unknown. The Massaran Empire descended into anarchy, its power broken, its sorcerous traditions scattered but not destroyed. The victory established the Mithrian League , a confederation of free city-states governed by a Senate, and introduced the Measure and the Scale as the moral and legal foundation of the new order. This was the crucible from which the future Empire would be forged. The Beastman Wars (244--219 BE) The Beastmen -- the monstrous legacy of Massaran transmogrification -- had never been eradicated. In the centuries following the fall of the Massar, the beastman hordes bred, multiplied, and organized in the wilderness. By 244 BE, massive beastman hordes threatened the civilized lands of the Mithrian League , launching raids and incursions that overwhelmed local defenses. The conflict, known as the Beastman Wars , raged for twenty-five years. The hordes were eventually defeated by Mithrian League forces led by Consul Servius of Mithra , whose military leadership unified the fractious city-states into a coherent fighting force. The Beastman Wars demonstrated both the enduring danger posed by the beastmen and the necessity of unified military command -- lessons that would inform the political transformation to come. Imperial Era The Founding of the Mithrian Empire (0--17 IY) Marcus Valerian , claiming descent from Bellasarius Valerian , seized power from the Imperial Senate and declared himself the first Emperor of the Mithrian Empire . He defeated loyalist Senator armies and consolidated authority under a single throne. The Senate was preserved as a deliberative body but stripped of binding legislative power. Marcus Valerian reigned from the founding until 17 IY, establishing the political, military, and administrative structures that would sustain the Empire for centuries. The founding marked the beginning of a new era -- the Imperial Year (IY) calendar -- and established Mithra City as the seat of power, governance, and sorcerous learning that it remains today. The Vestari people trace their lineage directly to Bellasarius Valerian, a claimed descent that gives them an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny. Consolidation and the Creation of the Targ (17--214 IY) The period following Marcus Valerian&#39;s death was one of consolidation, expansion, and institutional development. The Empire extended its reach, pacified its borders, and built the administrative apparatus necessary to govern a multi-ethnic, continental power. During this era, the Imperial Academy created the Targ -- a new race, magically engineered as laborers and soldiers to serve the Empire&#39;s growing needs. The creation of the Targ echoed the Argollean creation of the Thune millennia earlier -- a parallel that would not be lost on later historians. The Targ were designed to be stronger, more durable, and more obedient than human workers and warriors. They were also, crucially, regarded as property rather than people. The Reign of Titus Valerian: The Empire at Its Greatest Extent (215--257 IY) Emperor Titus Valerian presided over the golden age of the Mithrian Empire . Under his rule, the Empire reached its greatest territorial extent, controlling Kesh , Shent , Tezerat , and the vast heartlands that connected them. Trade flourished, the Imperial Academy expanded, and Mithrian culture and law spread to the farthest provinces. The reign of Titus Valerian represents the high-water mark of Imperial power -- the moment before the tide began to turn. Rebellions, Civil Wars, and the Targ Rebellion (258--269 IY) The death of Titus Valerian ushered in a period of instability. Rebellions erupted in the provinces, and civil wars fractured the Imperial core. Kesh was lost -- the first major territorial contraction since the Empire&#39;s founding. In 261 IY, the Targ -- the race created by the Imperial Academy as laborers and soldiers -- rose in violent revolt. Their leader, known only as The Eater , led a devastating campaign that reached Mithra City itself. The Eater sacked the capital and slew Emperor Antonius , an act of violence that shook the Empire to its foundations. The Eater&#39;s name has been preserved in infamy as one of the most feared figures in Imperial history -- a ruler whose reign was a period of madness, cruelty, and excess that tested the Empire&#39;s institutions to their breaking point. Peace was eventually brokered by High Mage Symander of the Imperial Academy . Symander was a towering figure whose diplomatic skill matched his sorcerous ability. Under the terms of the settlement he negotiated, the creation of further Targ was permanently forbidden , and the existing Targ were granted full citizenship under the Measure and the Scale , transforming them from property into people in the eyes of Imperial law. Symander also offered the Targ citizenship and lands of their own -- a settlement that averted further bloodshed but left deep scars on both sides. The rebellion remains one of the most traumatic events in Imperial history. Emperor Antonius himself represents a particular kind of failure -- not madness but weakness. Under Antonius, the power of the Imperial Senate had grown unchecked, and the Emperor became little more than a figurehead, rubber-stamping the decisions of ambitious senators and their factional allies. The concentration of power in the Senate led to rampant corruption, political paralysis, and a neglect of the Empire&#39;s military and provincial defenses -- conditions that allowed the Targ Rebellion to escalate to the point of sacking the capital itself. The Year of Three Emperors (270 IY) We traded madness for cowardice, then cowardice for coin. Of all our emperors, it was the one who ruled for 87 days who showed the greatest strength. -- Claudius Decimus , on accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate The mad Emperor Aurex of House Valerian was assassinated by his own sister, ending years of increasingly erratic and cruel rule. In the power vacuum that followed, the scholar Numerius was briefly installed as Emperor. Numerius&#39;s reign lasted a mere 87 days before he was murdered -- a span so brief and so poignant that it has become a byword for the Empire&#39;s inability to sustain principled leadership. The resulting chaos was compounded when the Imperial Custodians -- the Imperial bodyguard -- auctioned the office of Emperor to the highest bidder. The grotesque spectacle of the throne being sold like merchandise at market laid bare the depth of the Empire&#39;s institutional rot. Senator Quintus Soladius purchased the title, but his reign was immediately contested. Governor Persinius Septimus , commanding loyal legions in the provinces, marched on Mithra City to claim the throne by force. The resulting civil war, known as the War of Three Emperors , drew in multiple Great Houses and threatened to tear the Empire apart. Cassian ultimately emerged as the power behind the resolution, backing Claudius Decimus as a compromise candidate. Claudius Decimus triumphed, establishing House Decimus as the ruling dynasty. The Valerian claim to the throne was permanently broken, though House Valerian retained its prestige and wealth. Claudius Decimus is one of the most paradoxical figures in Imperial history -- an Emperor who is remembered as one of the most courageous and principled leaders the Empire has ever known. His own words upon accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate reveal a man acutely aware of the Empire&#39;s long decline: a trajectory from madness (The Eater and Aurex) to cowardice (Antonius and his successors) to the naked pursuit of wealth and power. What Claudius Decimus accomplished in his brief reign, and the circumstances of his eventual removal from power, remain subjects of intense historical debate. The Dog Soldier War (272--291 IY) The don&#39;Kolani -- the forest-dwelling branch of the Kolani people -- launched a prolonged guerrilla war against Imperial occupation of their ancestral lands. The conflict, known as the Dog Soldier War , dragged on for nearly two decades and proved extraordinarily costly for the Empire. Peace was eventually brokered by General Darius Jute , one of the most capable military commanders in recent Imperial history. The peace treaty included a provision of enormous strategic significance: the Empire gained access to Kolani munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, reducing the Imperial Academy &#39;s exclusive importance in warfare and contributing to the ongoing transformation of Imperial military doctrine. The treaty also led to the formal incorporation of Kolani warriors into the Imperial military structure, most notably through the establishment of the Kolani Irregulars -- a formation composed entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors who serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry. The Mithrian Marines (297 IY) In 297 IY, the Mithrian Marines were formally established as a distinct branch of the Imperial military. Their creation was a direct response to the proliferation of sorcery on the battlefield -- a growing threat that conventional infantry formations were ill-equipped to counter. The Marines were trained and equipped specifically to operate in environments saturated with hostile magic, combining conventional martial discipline with counter-sorcerous tactics. Their formation marked a significant evolution in Imperial military doctrine and an acknowledgment that the age of the sole sorcerer-as-weapon-of-war was giving way to a more complex and integrated approach to combat. The Fall of Shent (298 IY) In 298 IY, barbarian tribes invaded and conquered Shent , stripping the Empire of another major province. The loss of Shent -- following the earlier loss of Kesh -- represented a further contraction of Imperial territory and a further blow to Imperial prestige. The Empire was shrinking, and its capacity to defend its periphery was visibly deteriorating. The Heresy of the Flame (304 IY) A rogue High Priest in Corcanoa declared a new interpretation of the Empyrean faith, challenging the authority of the Thousand Temples hierarchy. The resulting schism threatened to fracture the religious order of the Empire. The Burnished Scale -- the militant arm of the Thousand Temples -- launched an unauthorized purge against the heretical movement and its sympathizers. The violence exceeded any mandate the Temples had been given, and when Lord-Penitent Lucan Vargas of the Burnished Scale proved unwilling to cease operations, he was assassinated by the Imperial Talons on orders from the throne. The incident established a clear precedent: the Emperor&#39;s authority supersedes the Temples&#39; in matters of internal security. The Tet Rebellion: The Second Crescent Rebellion (342 IY) In 342 IY, the Tet people rebelled against Imperial rule and gained their independence in what became known as the Second Crescent Rebellion -- the third uprising to bear the name Crescent Rebellion in the long history of Mithrapos , following the First Crescent Rebellion of 2700 BE and the rebellion during the Empyrean War. The Tet&#39;s successful secession further contracted Imperial territory and demonstrated that the Empire&#39;s grip on its provinces was weakening. The Death of Usil and the Storms of 348 IY In 348 IY, the sorcerer-kingdom of Urgathoa resumed hostilities against the Empire. The sorcerer-king Abbu-Marru disappeared under mysterious circumstances -- whether killed, fled, or consumed by his own sorcery, none can say. Simultaneously, violent storms and earthquakes of unprecedented ferocity wracked nearly every province of the Empire, causing widespread destruction, loss of life, and panic. The event became known as the Death of Usil . The Imperial Academy attributed the catastrophe to fluctuations in the gnostic patterns that govern the metaphysical reality of Mithrapos -- a scientific explanation rooted in their understanding of Gnostic Geometry and the axioms that underpin reality. The priests of the Empyrean faiths offered a starkly different explanation: an Empyrean god had died. Usil , they claimed, had perished -- and the earthquakes and storms were the death throes of a divine being, the cosmos itself convulsing in grief and upheaval. This theological interpretation was rejected by the Academy but embraced by the faithful, and the event became a defining moment in the ongoing tension between sorcerous and religious authority within the Empire. The Burning of Erenthis at Thornasse (349 IY) In 349 IY, High Mage Cynar of the Imperial Academy -- known as Cynar of the Black Tree -- burned the city of Erenthis at Thornasse , annihilating it in an act of sorcerous devastation that horrified even the Empire&#39;s own commanders. The destruction of Erenthis broke the Avari Confederation, and many of the surviving Avari were enslaved. The event demonstrated the terrifying destructive potential of high-level sorcery and foreshadowed the catastrophe that would follow at Blue Mound . The Lakan Campaigns and the Battle of Blue Mound (360--368 IY) The Empire launched a major military expedition into Lakandi territory, seeking to pacify the warlike Lakan tribes and extend Imperial control. The campaigns dragged on for eight years, culminating in the catastrophic Battle of Blue Mound . The battle pitted Imperial forces, led by High Mage Cynar of the Imperial Academy -- Cynar of the Black Tree -- against the forces of Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye , a powerful Lakan sorcerer who commanded an army of considerable size and ferocity. The climax of the conflict came when High Mage Cynar and Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye engaged in a direct sorcerous duel -- a confrontation of such magnitude that it escalated beyond all control. The cataclysmic energies unleashed by the two combatants annihilated both armies entirely, leaving the battlefield a blasted and lifeless wasteland. Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived. The Battle of Blue Mound had profound consequences for the Empire&#39;s approach to warfare. It demonstrated that the deployment of high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was not merely dangerous but potentially suicidal, and it prompted significant reforms in military doctrine. The Empire subsequently adopted a model of combined arms warfare, integrating squad mages into conventional military formations rather than relying on individual sorcerers to decide the outcome of battles. The Empire retreated to a defensive posture in Lakandi territory, constructing a line of border forts that marks the current frontier. The Second War of Morn (371 IY) In 371 IY, the Second War of Morn erupted. At its center was a cult of Lycandites -- fanatical worshippers of Lycandaeus the Living God , a Ygrathen tyrant who had seized control of a significant territory in Morn and declared himself a deity. Lycandaeus practiced both transmogrification and demon-binding -- the twin abominations that had defined the darkest chapters of Argollean and Massaran sorcery -- and his forces included creatures of horrifying power. The Imperial 14th Army was shattered in the initial engagements, suffering catastrophic losses against Lycandaeus&#39;s sorcerously enhanced forces. The situation appeared desperate until the 8th Marine Company , led by Captain Pollimer Motts , was deployed. Captain Motts and his Marines fought their way to Lycandaeus himself and destroyed the Ygrathen tyrant, breaking the power of the Lycandite cult and ending the war. The Second War of Morn demonstrated both the enduring threat posed by the Ygrathen and the effectiveness of the Mithrian Marines as a counter-sorcerous force. Captain Pollimer Motts became one of the most celebrated military figures of the current era. The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY) Crossings did not fall in a day. It fell in the silence of senators, in the turning away of eyes, in the fortunes of the governor rising even as the gates were breached. -- Senator Cassius The Sacking of Crossings in 377 IY was one of the most devastating and consequential events in recent Imperial history. A massive Beastmen horde emerged from the wilderness and descended on the town of Crossings , razing it to the ground. As Senator Cassius&#39;s damning words make clear, the sacking was not the result of an overwhelming external threat alone. It was enabled by the corruption, negligence, and complicity of Imperial officials -- senators who looked the other way, governors who enriched themselves while their defenses crumbled. The fall of Crossings was a failure of the Empire&#39;s institutions as much as it was a failure of its armies. The consequences of the Sacking of Crossings were immediate and far-reaching. The destruction of this settlement led directly to the collapse of Imperial authority in the surrounding region, giving rise to the Scalper economy -- a brutal system born of Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus &#39;s Imperial scalp bounty on beastmen. The bounty unleashed a wave of mercenaries, deserters, and killers into the Backlands to hunt them. While beastman activity near settled areas has decreased, the influx of violent fortune-seekers has created new and terrible problems for the frontier provinces. The Backlands descend into their current lawless and anarchic state as a direct result of the vacuum left by the fall of Crossings -- a frontier region where Imperial law is a distant memory and survival is the only currency that matters. The Recall of the Garrisons (378 IY) In 378 IY, the Emperor recalled the frontier garrisons to fight the Skiothan raiders threatening the Imperial heartland. The provinces -- already strained, already bleeding -- were left defenseless. The recall was a strategic decision born of desperation: the Skiothan threat was existential, and the resources to fight on two fronts simultaneously no longer existed. But the consequences for the frontier were catastrophic. Senators plotted openly in the corridors of Mithra City , and civil war loomed on the horizon. The Present Day (380 IY) The Mithrian Empire endures, but it is an empire under strain. Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus rules from Mithra City , facing threats on multiple fronts: Beastmen in the Backlands , Skiothan raiders on the western frontier, lingering unrest in Morn , and the ever-present political maneuvering of the Great Houses. The proliferation of sorcerous knowledge beyond the Imperial Academy &#39;s control, the corruption of the Senate, the restlessness of the provinces, and the persistent threats along its borders all test the Empire&#39;s capacity to survive. The lessons of history -- the fall of Argolle , the madness of The Eater and Aurex , the weakness of Antonius , the brief courage of Claudius Decimus , and the catastrophe of Crossings -- weigh heavily on those who study the past and fear that the patterns of decline may be repeating themselves. Mithrapos remains what it has always been: a cradle and a coffin, a boneyard of Empires. Chronological Reference Year Event 4100 BE Eladra 3900 BE Eladra encounter [[Ygrathen in the races-and-cultures 3800 BE Eladra discover [[lakandi 3200 BE [[crossings 3100 BE Secret excavation of ruins below [[crossings 3000 BE General [[eolande 2800 BE Transmogrification experiments begin; splicing humans with chaotic energies 2700 BE First Crescent Rebellion; [[Thune created as slave soldiers 2600 BE argollean-empire 2400 BE Disciples of [[Bel burn Empyrean temples; worship of Dirgion rises 2300 BE New Thune variants created; Bitter War turns in Argollean favor; lakandi 2100 BE Warlord Marcan crushes [[Ygrathen alliance; Great Teacher enters cryostasis 2000 BE Marcan interred in Great King Tomb in the-nethercity 1800 BE Hierophant Orthanach becomes first mummy lord; interred in Secret Tomb 1700 BE Fall of [[the-backlands 1400 BE Thune dominion; [[massar 1075 BE [[Massar overthrow Thune; establish sorcerer-empire 1070 BE Massar uncover Elvora secrets; create Beastmen 684 BE enador 652 BE [[massaran-empire 651 BE Massar armies routed; sorcerer-kings slaughtered; Sebek escapes 244--219 BE [[history-of-mithrapos 0 IY [[marcus-valerian 17 IY Death of Marcus Valerian; consolidation era begins 17--214 IY Imperial consolidation; [[imperial-academy 215--257 IY Emperor [[history-of-mithrapos 258--269 IY Rebellions and civil wars; [[history-of-mithrapos 270 IY Year of Three Emperors; [[claudius-decimus 272--291 IY [[dog-soldier-war 297 IY [[mithrian-marines 298 IY Barbarian tribes conquer [[shenti 304 IY [[burnished-scale 342 IY [[Tet rebel; gain independence (Second Crescent Rebellion) 348 IY Mithrian Empire Argolle Krysea Nethercity Prophet Enador Bellasarius Valerian Marcus Valerian Titus Valerian Measure and the Scale Anthyllium Imperial Academy Eladra Elvora Ygrathen Thune Lakan Massar Massaran Empire Beastmen Targ The Eater Emperor Antonius Aurex Numerius Claudius Decimus Justinian Claudius Decimus High Mage Symander High Mage Cynar Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye Lycandaeus Pollimer Motts General Darius Jute Lucan Vargas Abbu-Marru Sebek Chemosh Khepri Cthonic Empyrean Bel Dirgion Usil Battle of Blue Mound Beastman Wars Death of Usil Dog Soldier War Sacking of Crossings Mithrian Marines Backlands Crossings Kesh Shent Tezerat Morn Corcanoa Meniri Mountains Scalper Kolani Irregulars Burnished Scale Imperial Talons Thousand Temples Gnostic Geometry"},{"slug":"kolani-munitions","title":"Kolani Munitions","category":"lore","tags":"lore military kolani munitions explosives weapons dog-soldier-war darius-jute combined-arms imperial-academy technology","text":"Kolani Munitions Before the Kolani treaty, the Academy held a monopoly on battlefield destruction. After it, they held a grudge. The generals preferred explosives they could stockpile to mages they had to negotiate with. Kolani munitions are deadly and dangerous weapons and explosives originating from the Kolani people. The Mithrian Empire gained access to these weapons through a peace treaty brokered by General Darius Jute , ending the Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY). Kolani munitions are now supplied to the Mithrian military as part of their combined arms doctrine and have partially diminished the Imperial Academy&#39;s former monopoly on battlefield destruction. At a Glance Detail Description Type Military weapons and explosives Origin The Mithrian Empire&#39;s history -- not through conquest, but through diplomacy. The Kolani people developed weapons and explosives of extraordinary lethality, and the Empire&#39;s access to these munitions transformed its military doctrine by providing an alternative to the Imperial Academy&#39;s arcane capabilities for battlefield destruction. The munitions are dangerous to manufacture, transport, and deploy. They are not elegant weapons. They are instruments of destruction that do not discriminate, do not require arcane training, and do not answer to the Imperial Academy&#39;s institutional authority. This combination of qualities made them both invaluable to the military and deeply threatening to the Academy&#39;s position. The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY) The Dog Soldier War was a protracted conflict between the Mithrian Empire and the Kolani people, lasting nearly two decades (272-291 IY). The war demonstrated the Kolani&#39;s capacity for sustained, effective resistance against imperial military power -- resistance that the Empire could not overcome through conventional means within an acceptable timeframe or cost. General Darius Jute brokered the peace treaty that ended the conflict. The terms of this treaty included the Kolani supply of munitions to the Mithrian military -- a pragmatic exchange that converted a dangerous enemy into a valuable supplier. The Empire gained access to weapons it could not produce on its own; the Kolani gained peace, autonomy, and a permanent economic relationship with the dominant power in Mithrapos . Impact on Imperial Military Doctrine The introduction of Kolani munitions into the Mithrian military altered the Empire&#39;s combined arms doctrine in fundamental ways: Before Kolani Munitions The Imperial Academy held a near-monopoly on battlefield destruction at scale. When the military needed fortifications reduced, formations shattered, or terrain reshaped, they required Academy-trained mages -- specialists whose training, institutional loyalty, and political interests were controlled by the Academy rather than the military chain of command. This monopoly gave the Academy extraordinary political leverage. Generals who needed arcane support had to negotiate with an institution that had its own agenda, its own priorities, and its own price. After Kolani Munitions Kolani munitions provided the military with an alternative source of destructive capability -- one that could be manufactured, stockpiled, transported, and deployed without the Academy&#39;s involvement or permission. Explosives do not require years of arcane training. They do not have institutional loyalties. They do not negotiate. The Academy&#39;s monopoly on battlefield destruction was not eliminated but was partially diminished . The military now has options it did not previously possess, and the Academy&#39;s bargaining position has weakened accordingly. This shift in the balance of power between the military and the Academy remains a source of institutional tension. See Also kolani -- The people who developed the munitions Darius Jute -- The general who brokered the peace treaty imperial-academy -- The institution whose monopoly was diminished mithrian-empire -- The empire that acquired the munitions mithrian-military -- The military that deploys them sorcery -- The arcane alternative the munitions partially replaced mithrian-marines -- Another specialist element of Mithrian combined arms doctrine"},{"slug":"kolani","title":"Kolani","category":"lore","tags":"culture kolani naming human tribal ton-kolani don-kolani dog-soldier-war kolani-irregulars munitions","text":"Kolani The Kolani are a diverse tribal people divided into two principal groups defined by their ancestral homeland and way of life. Their culture is deeply spiritual, rooted in ancestral memory and the natural world, and their martial traditions have proven invaluable to the Mithrian Empire -- but only after decades of bloody conflict. The Two Peoples ton&#39;Kolani -- People of the Plains The ton&#39;Kolani are seminomadic pastoralists and warriors who roam the vast grasslands and plains. They are renowned horsemen, and their light cavalry tactics -- swift raids, feigned retreats, encirclement -- have confounded heavier Imperial formations for generations. The ton&#39;Kolani are the backbone of the Kolani Irregulars , the Empire&#39;s most effective irregular warfare formation. don&#39;Kolani -- People of the Forest The don&#39;Kolani are settled communities with deep ties to the Great Kolan Forest . Their way of life is rooted in the woodland -- they are hunters, trappers, herbalists, and woodworkers whose knowledge of the forest is encyclopedic. The don&#39;Kolani launched the Dog Soldier War against Imperial occupation, a guerrilla campaign that demonstrated the devastating effectiveness of woodland warfare against conventional armies. Culture and Values Kolani culture is deeply spiritual, with the natural world and ancestral memory occupying central roles in daily life. The village seer is among the most important figures in any Kolani community, serving as spiritual intermediary, naming authority, and keeper of tribal memory. Totemic Titles Honorific and totemic titles play an important role in Kolani culture. These titles, earned through deeds of valor, spiritual achievement, or community service, can replace a Kolani&#39;s given name entirely . A warrior who earns a totemic title may be known by that title alone for the rest of their life, their birth name set aside in favor of the identity their deeds have earned them. Naming Conventions Kolani names are bestowed by the village seer , who invokes spirits, natural forces, and ancestral memory to determine the name that best suits the child. This naming ceremony is a sacred ritual, and the name given is believed to carry spiritual significance and power. The name is not chosen arbitrarily -- it is divined, revealed through communion with forces beyond ordinary human perception. Clan names serve as surnames , tying the individual to their broader kinship group. A Kolani introduced by clan name is understood to carry the weight and reputation of that entire kinship network. Historical Events The Dog Soldier War (272-291 IY) The Dog Soldier War was a prolonged guerrilla campaign launched by the don&#39;Kolani against Imperial occupation of their ancestral lands in the Great Kolan Forest. The conflict dragged on for nearly two decades and proved extraordinarily costly for the Empire. The don&#39;Kolani&#39;s mastery of woodland warfare -- ambushes, traps, hit-and-run raids, the exploitation of terrain the Imperial forces could not navigate -- made conventional military operations nearly impossible. Peace was eventually brokered by General Darius Jute , one of the most capable military commanders in recent Imperial history. The peace treaty included a provision of enormous strategic significance: the Empire gained access to Kolani munitions and weaponry -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons whose technology was previously unknown to Mithrian forces. These munitions now supplement magical firepower on the battlefield, reducing the Imperial Academy&#39;s exclusive importance in warfare and contributing to the ongoing transformation of Imperial military doctrine. The Kolani Irregulars The peace brokered by General Darius Jute also led to the formal incorporation of Kolani warriors into the Imperial military structure. The Kolani Irregulars are a notable military formation composed entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors . They serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry, and their unconventional tactics have proven invaluable in the Empire&#39;s frontier campaigns. The Kolani Irregulars represent one of the most successful examples of integrating conquered peoples into the Imperial military -- a formation whose effectiveness derives precisely from the cultural traditions the Empire once tried to suppress. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire that fought and then integrated the Kolani mithrian-military -- The military that includes the Kolani Irregulars history-of-mithrapos -- The Dog Soldier War in broader context imperial-academy -- The institution whose monopoly Kolani munitions challenge"},{"slug":"lakan-campaigns","title":"The Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY)","category":"lore","tags":"event history warfare lakandi imperial-academy border-forts military-campaign","text":"The Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY) The Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY) were a major Imperial military expedition into Lakandi territory, launched with the goal of pacifying the warlike Lakandi tribes and extending Imperial control. The campaigns dragged on for eight years and culminated in the catastrophic Battle of Blue Mound -- a sorcerous cataclysm that annihilated both armies and killed the commanders of both sides. The Empire retreated, erected a line of border forts, and abandoned its ambitions of conquest in the region. Background The Lakandi are a warlike people whose territory lies beyond the Empire&#39;s established frontier. Their sorcerous traditions -- the Lakandi Binding Tradition , rooted in Veil contact and demon-binding -- made them a persistent concern for Imperial strategists. The decision to launch a major campaign against them reflected both strategic ambition and the confidence of the Imperial Academy in its sorcerous superiority. The campaigns were backed by devastating magical firepower. The Academy deployed its most powerful battle-sorcerers, including High Mage Cynar , in support of conventional military forces. The expectation was that Imperial sorcery would overwhelm the Lakandi&#39;s more primitive magical traditions and deliver a decisive victory. The Campaigns Imperial armies marched deep into Lakandi territory over the course of eight years. The campaigns were costly, grinding affairs. The Lakandi proved far more formidable than expected: Their warriors were fierce, disciplined, and intimately familiar with the terrain Their sorcerers -- practitioners of the Lakandi Binding Tradition -- wielded Veil-born power that, while different from the Academy&#39;s Gnostic Geometry , was no less dangerous Their resistance was relentless. The Lakandi fought not for territory or resources but for survival and honor, and they would not submit The campaigns consumed men, money, and magical resources at a rate that tested the Empire&#39;s capacity to sustain a distant war. Support for the expedition eroded over time as the costs mounted and decisive victory remained elusive. The Battle of Blue Mound The campaigns culminated in the Battle of Blue Mound , where Imperial forces under High Mage Cynar engaged the army of Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye . The climactic sorcerous duel between the two combatants escalated beyond all control, unleashing cataclysmic energies that annihilated both armies entirely. Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived. The battlefield was left a blasted wasteland. Aftermath Imperial Retreat The destruction of the entire expeditionary force at Blue Mound ended the Empire&#39;s campaign immediately and permanently. There was no army left to continue the fight. The Empire retreated to a defensive posture, constructing a line of border forts along the frontier that marks the current boundary between Imperial territory and Lakandi lands. These forts remain manned and maintained to this day, a permanent reminder of the campaign&#39;s failure. Lakandi Response The Lakandi were broken by the campaigns but remained unbowed . The loss of their army and their Warlock King at Blue Mound was devastating, but the simultaneous destruction of the Imperial army gave them a claim to victory of a different kind. The Lakandi vowed revenge against the Empire -- a vow that the border forts are designed to deter. Military Reform The Lakan Campaigns and the Battle of Blue Mound prompted the most significant reform in Imperial military doctrine since the founding of the Empire. The deployment of individual high-level sorcerers as decisive weapons was abandoned in favor of combined arms warfare , integrating squad mages into conventional formations. This shift reduced the Imperial Academy &#39;s singular importance in warfare. See Also Battle of Blue Mound -- the catastrophic final battle High Mage Cynar -- the Imperial sorcerer who died at Blue Mound Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye -- the Lakandi sorcerer who died at Blue Mound Lakandi Binding Tradition -- the sorcerous tradition of the Lakandi The Imperial Academy -- institution whose doctrine was reshaped The Mithrian Military History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"lakandi-binding-tradition","title":"The Lakandi Binding Tradition","category":"lore","tags":"lakandi binding cthonic demons veil corruption elvora greta jarn-murky-eye cynar warlock-king blue-mound magic tradition","text":"The Lakandi Binding Tradition The Lakandi binding tradition is the practice by which Lakandi practitioners engage directly with demonic entities, spirits, and Beyond-beings -- not through petition, worship, or prayer, but through binding, contest, and mutual obligation . Imperial scholars classify it as Cthonic demon worship. This classification is not entirely wrong, but it is not entirely right. The Lakandi do not merely petition demonic powers. They bind them. The Essential Tradition The Lakandi binding tradition is, in its essential nature, the same tradition that the Elvora practiced -- but at a vastly lower scale. The Elvora went all the way. They bound something unbindable, and the cost was total: females rendered barren, males rendered immortal, eyes turned black, civilization destroyed. The Elvora are the cautionary tale, the warning against ambition unchecked by wisdom. The Lakandi operate at the individual scale . Where the Elvora attempted to bind powers that could reshape civilizations, the Lakandi engage with individual demons, spirits, and entities from beyond the Veil . The scale is smaller. The risks are more contained. The costs are personal rather than civilizational. But the essential mechanism is the same: a mortal practitioner tears open the Veil, reaches through, contacts an entity, and enters into an arrangement. The Process of Binding The binding process follows a consistent pattern, though the specifics vary by practitioner, entity, and circumstance: The practitioner tears open the Veil. This is not a metaphor. The Veil is the barrier between the material world and whatever lies beyond it. The Lakandi practitioner creates a breach -- temporary, controlled, but real -- through which contact with Beyond-entities becomes possible. The practitioner reaches the entity. Through the breach, the practitioner contacts a specific demon, spirit, or other Beyond-being. This is not summoning in the conventional sense -- the entity is not pulled into the material world. The practitioner extends their awareness, their will, and their power through the breach to meet the entity on its own terms. The practitioner negotiates or overpowers the entity into an arrangement. This is the critical step. The arrangement is not worship. It is not prayer. It is contest -- a negotiation conducted from a position of power (if the practitioner is strong enough) or a position of desperate need (if they are not). The result is a binding: a relationship of mutual obligation in which both parties give and both parties receive. The binding that results is not absolute containment. It is not imprisonment in the sense that the Kharai are imprisoned in their cairnhouses. It is a working relationship -- volatile, dangerous, and sustained only by the practitioner&#39;s will, skill, and the terms of the original arrangement. The Key Distinction: Service vs. Holding The Lakandi tradition recognizes a fundamental distinction between two types of binding: Binding in Service In this arrangement, the practitioner is placed in service to the Cthonic power. The entity is the dominant partner. The practitioner petitions, the entity grants, and over time the practitioner becomes increasingly dependent -- a servant, a vessel, a tool. The power flows downward. The entity commands; the practitioner obeys. This is what imperial scholars imagine when they hear demon worship, and it is what many Cthonic practitioners actually practice. It is the path of least resistance: the entity is powerful, the practitioner is desperate, and submission is easier than contest. Binding Where the Practitioner Holds In this arrangement, the practitioner holds the entity. The practitioner is the dominant partner. The entity has been contested, compelled, or negotiated into a position where it serves the practitioner&#39;s purposes rather than its own. The power flows upward. The practitioner commands; the entity serves. This is far more difficult, far more dangerous, and far more impressive. It requires not merely power but will -- the sustained, unbroken determination to hold a being that does not want to be held, that will test the binding constantly, that will exploit any weakness or lapse in attention. Greta of Bone Creek holds something. What she gave for it she has not said. But she holds it -- she is not in service to it. The distinction matters more than any other consideration in evaluating a Lakandi practitioner. The Cost: Corruption Repeated contact with the Beyond corrupts. This is the inescapable price of the Lakandi tradition. Every practitioner who tears open the Veil , every binding that connects mortal will to demonic power, leaves a mark. The marks are cumulative, permanent, and visible: Eyes darkening at the iris. The most iconic sign of Lakandi practice. The iris darkens progressively with repeated Veil contact, eventually turning the eyes wholly dark. The degree of darkening reflects the depth and frequency of engagement. A quality of stillness beyond patience. Not the stillness of someone waiting, but the stillness of something that has been touched by entities operating on timescales that dwarf human comprehension. The corrupted practitioner carries something of their bound entity&#39;s relationship to time -- a patience, a weight, a density of presence that is not human. Awareness of things not normally visible. Perception that extends beyond the ordinary human range. Those who have torn open the Veil and reached through it carry an expanded awareness that does not fade -- an ability to perceive presences, energies, and dimensions of reality that most people never access. The Lakandi treat corruption not as failing but as the visible record of genuine engagement . To be marked is to have done something real. To be unmarked is to have risked nothing. The corruption is the credential, the proof of practice, the visible testament to a life spent engaging with powers that most people are too frightened or too prudent to touch. The Warlock King: Jarn Murky-Eye Jarn Murky-Eye was the legendary Warlock King of the Lakandi -- the greatest practitioner of the binding tradition in recorded history. His name was not metaphorical . His eyes were the color of what he had touched, what he had bound, what he had held through decades of Veil contact and demonic engagement. Jarn Murky-Eye fought High Mage Cynar at the Battle of Blue Mound . The result was mutual annihilation -- both the greatest Lakandi binder and the greatest Mithrian war-mage destroyed each other in a confrontation that leveled the battlefield and left nothing living within a significant radius. The Battle of Blue Mound is the definitive demonstration of what the Lakandi binding tradition can produce at its apex: a practitioner capable of meeting the Empire&#39;s most powerful war-mage on equal terms. Cynar burned the Erenthis at Thornasse . Jarn killed him for it. Neither survived the exchange. Relationship to Other Traditions The Elvoran Tradition The Lakandi binding tradition is the same essential practice as the Elvoran tradition, differing only in scale. The Elvora bound at the civilizational level; the Lakandi bind at the individual level. The Elvora were destroyed by their ambition; the Lakandi survive by their restraint. The lesson is not that binding is wrong but that scale matters -- that there are things that should not be bound, not because binding is immoral but because the cost of binding them exceeds what any individual or civilization can pay. Imperial Classification Imperial scholars classify the Lakandi tradition as Cthonic demon worship. This classification captures something true -- the Lakandi do engage with Cthonic entities, do tear open the Veil , do accumulate the marks of corruption that Cthonic contact produces. But the classification misses something essential: the Lakandi are not worshippers. They are practitioners. The difference between petitioning a god and binding a demon is the difference between kneeling and wrestling. Both involve contact with power. Only one involves submission. The Ygrathen Tradition The Ygrathen binding tradition -- exemplified by Varek Ashstone and the cairnhouses that contain the Kharai -- is related to but distinct from the Lakandi tradition. The Ygrathen bind at a scale that exceeds even the Elvora: they imprisoned beings that cannot be destroyed, using structures designed to endure for millennia. The Lakandi operate at the opposite end of the spectrum -- individual practitioners binding individual entities for personal use. The traditions share a common root but have diverged enormously in scope and application. See Also greta -- A Lakandi practitioner who holds a bound entity jarn-murky-eye -- The Warlock King, apex of the Lakandi tradition Cynar -- The High Mage who killed and was killed by Jarn at Blue Mound cthonic-corruption -- The corruption that marks Lakandi practitioners the-veil -- The barrier that Lakandi practitioners tear open Elvora -- The civilization that practiced binding at catastrophic scale Lakandi -- The culture that sustains the binding tradition varek-ashstone -- A Ygrathen binder operating at much larger scale the-kharai -- Entities bound by the related Ygrathen tradition the-convergence-problem -- The theological framework within which binding traditions must be understood bone-creek -- Where Greta practices the tradition thornasse -- The site whose destruction prompted Jarn&#39;s final battle"},{"slug":"lakandi","title":"Lakandi","category":"lore","tags":"culture lakandi naming human warrior wasteland cthonic binding demon-binding nameless lakan-campaigns blue-mound cynar jarn-murky-eye rebellion","text":"Lakandi The Lakandi are a fierce and uncompromising warrior culture in which personal honor, martial prowess, and the ability to endure hardship are the measures of an individual&#39;s worth. Reclusive and warlike, they inhabit a harsh wasteland they fiercely defend against all comers -- including each other. Physical Appearance The Lakandi have tan skin and dark hair. Their builds are lean and hardened by the unforgiving environment of their wasteland homeland -- a landscape that strips away everything unnecessary and leaves only what can survive. Culture and Values The Lakandi are reclusive and warlike . Their harsh wasteland homeland has shaped a culture that prizes above all else the ability to endure, to fight, and to prevail against impossible odds. The wasteland is not merely where the Lakandi live -- it is what defines them. They fiercely defend this territory, not because it is comfortable or bountiful, but because it is theirs and because the act of defending it proves their worth. Tribal Warfare and Honor Lakandi tribes war amongst themselves with a bizarre sense of honor and revenge that outsiders find nearly incomprehensible. Feuds, vendettas, and blood debts follow elaborate protocols that the Lakandi take with absolute seriousness. What appears to outsiders as senseless violence is, to the Lakandi, a carefully structured system of obligation, retaliation, and the ongoing demonstration of tribal strength. Religion Many Lakandi worship Cthonic gods, demons, and spirits rather than the Empyrean gods recognized by the Thousand Temples . This is not mere heterodoxy -- it is a fundamentally different spiritual orientation, one that engages with the dangerous powers that dwell beyond the Veil rather than with the divine order the Empyrean tradition upholds. The Lakandi Binding Tradition The Lakandi binding tradition is a form of demon-binding distinct from the Elvoran tradition but sharing the same essential mechanism. Lakandi practitioners tear open the Veil, contact demonic entities, and enter into binding arrangements -- not worship, not petition, but contest and mutual obligation . The practitioner who holds their bound entity is the dominant partner; the practitioner who serves their entity has submitted. Imperial scholars classify the Lakandi tradition as Cthonic demon worship. This classification captures something true but misses something essential: the Lakandi are not worshippers. They are practitioners. The difference between petitioning a god and binding a demon is the difference between kneeling and wrestling. Repeated contact with the Beyond corrupts . Every practitioner who tears open the Veil accumulates marks: eyes darkening at the iris, a quality of stillness beyond patience, awareness of things not normally visible. The Lakandi treat corruption not as failing but as the visible record of genuine engagement . Naming Conventions Lakandi names are built from short, harsh consonants and open vowels , producing names that are as blunt and direct as the people themselves. Uniquely among the cultures of Mithrapos , Lakandi names are not fixed at birth -- they change after trials . Individuals earn new names through feats of combat, endurance, or survival. These earned names typically depict violence, strength, or the natural forces the bearer has overcome. A Lakandi warrior&#39;s name is a compressed history of their most notable achievements. The Nameless The Lakandi practice of naming carries a dark counterpart: cowards and oathbreakers are stripped of their names entirely, becoming Nameless . The Nameless are exiled from Lakandi society , cast out to wander the wastes until death -- without identity, kinship, or honor. To be made Nameless is considered a fate worse than death, for death at least preserves the memory of what one was. The Nameless are erased. Historical Events The Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY) The Empire launched a major military expedition into Lakandi territory, seeking to pacify the warlike tribes and extend Imperial control. The Lakan Campaigns dragged on for eight years , proving extraordinarily costly for the Empire and demonstrating that the Lakandi&#39;s knowledge of their wasteland homeland made them nearly impossible to defeat on their own ground. The Battle of Blue Mound The campaigns culminated in the catastrophic Battle of Blue Mound . The battle pitted Imperial forces, led by High Mage Cynar of the Imperial Academy , against the forces of Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye -- the greatest practitioner of the Lakandi binding tradition in recorded history. Jarn&#39;s name was not metaphorical: his eyes were the color of what he had touched, what he had bound, what he had held through decades of Veil contact. The climax of the conflict came when Cynar and Jarn engaged in a direct sorcerous duel -- a confrontation of such magnitude that it annihilated both armies entirely , leaving the battlefield a blasted and lifeless wasteland. Neither Cynar nor Jarn survived. Cynar had burned the Erenthis at Thornasse. Jarn killed him for it. Neither survived the exchange. The Battle of Blue Mound had profound consequences for Imperial military doctrine, demonstrating that the deployment of high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was potentially suicidal. The Empire subsequently retreated to a defensive posture in Lakandi territory, constructing a line of border forts that marks the current frontier. Current Situation The Lakandi in the Backlands are stirring . Whispers of rebellion circulate through the wasteland, and the reduction of the Imperial garrison to skeletal levels has made the threat of a Lakandi uprising more dangerous than ever. The border forts built after the Lakan Campaigns, now commanded by Legate Marcellus , are the thin, crumbling line between the Empire&#39;s frontier and whatever the Lakandi are planning. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures lakandi-binding-tradition -- The binding tradition practiced by Lakandi sorcerers jarn-murky-eye -- The Warlock King, greatest Lakandi binder Cynar -- The High Mage who fought Jarn at Blue Mound the-backlands -- Where Lakandi unrest is growing legate-marcellus -- Commander of the border forts facing Lakandi territory cthonic-faith -- The Cthonic traditions many Lakandi follow history-of-mithrapos -- The Lakan Campaigns in broader context greta -- A Lakandi practitioner in Bone Creek who holds a bound entity"},{"slug":"languages-of-mithrapos","title":"Languages of Mithrapos","category":"lore","tags":"languages culture linguistics mithrapos argollean","text":"Languages of Mithrapos The linguistic landscape of Mithrapos reflects millennia of conquest, migration, trade, and cultural exchange. Languages range from dead scholarly tongues preserved only in ancient texts to the living dialects spoken across the Empire&#39;s many provinces and beyond its borders. Dead Languages These languages are no longer spoken natively but remain important for scholarship, magic, and religious practice. Ancient Argollean The oldest known written language, belonging to the original Argollean civilization. Ancient Argollean survives only in fragmentary inscriptions, ruins, and the most archaic sections of the Anthyllium . It is studied by scholars of the Imperial Academy but is understood by very few living people. The formulae of Gnostic Geometry are partially derived from Ancient Argollean phonetic structures. Classical Argollean The language of the Eladra and the Elvora , a descendant of Ancient Argollean that was the dominant tongue of the Argollean civilization at its height. Classical Argollean is better attested than its ancient ancestor, with surviving texts, poetry, and philosophical works. The verbal components (resonance) used in Gnostic Geometry are spoken in Classical Argollean, and the Imperial Academy requires its students to achieve fluency. Living Languages Argollean (Common) The modern descendant of Classical Argollean , heavily simplified and influenced by centuries of contact with other languages. Argollean serves as the lingua franca of Mithrapos -- the common tongue used for trade, diplomacy, and communication between peoples who share no other language. Nearly everyone in the Empire speaks at least rudimentary Argollean. High Mithric The formal language of the Mithrian Empire &#39;s elite. High Mithric is spoken by the nobility, the clergy of the Thousand Temples , and the scholarly class. It is the language of law, theology, official Imperial documents, and formal oratory. High Mithric is grammatically complex and laden with honorifics and status markers that reflect the Empire&#39;s rigid social hierarchy under the Measure and the Scale . Low Mithric The common Imperial tongue spoken by the vast majority of the Empire&#39;s population. Low Mithric is a simplified, colloquial form of High Mithric blended with Argollean loanwords and regional vocabulary. It varies significantly by province but remains mutually intelligible across most of the Empire. Old Vestari An archaic form of the Vestari language, now spoken only in formal religious and ceremonial contexts among Vestari nobility. Old Vestari preserves linguistic features that trace back to the earliest days of the Mithrian League . Vestari The modern language of the Vestari people. As one of the first cultures to join the Mithrian League , the Vestari have been deeply integrated into Imperial culture, and their language shows heavy Mithric and Argollean influence. Lyseani The language of the Lysean people. Lyseani is a conservative tongue that has changed relatively little over the centuries, reflecting the Lyseans&#39; agricultural stability and cultural continuity -- even through the devastating drought and the Beastmen Wars that ravaged their homeland. Mornish The language of the Peninsula of Morn . Mornish is fiercely preserved by its speakers as a marker of cultural identity and resistance to Imperial assimilation. The language features a rich oral literary tradition, including epic poetry and war songs. Thrassian The language of the Thrassian mountain people. Thrassian is widely spoken within the Imperial military due to the disproportionate number of Thrassian soldiers in the legions. Many Imperial officers learn at least basic Thrassian to communicate with their troops. Kolani The language of both the ton&#39;Kolani and don&#39;Kolani branches of the Kolani people. Kolani is an agglutinative language with a complex system of verbal prefixes that encode speaker intent, emotional state, and social relationship to the listener. It is particularly difficult for non-native speakers to master. Eastern Rinoic A dialectal branch of Rinoic spoken by the eastern tribes of the Rinoan confederation. Eastern Rinoic has diverged enough from western Rinoic to be considered a distinct language by Imperial scholars, though speakers of both varieties can usually understand each other with effort. Avaric The language of the Avari people. Avaric belongs to a different linguistic family than most Mithraposian languages and is notably difficult for speakers of Mithric or Argollean to learn. The Avari maintain their language as one of the few cultural traditions not suppressed during their conquest. Lakandic The language of the Lakandi tribes. Lakandic is rarely encountered outside Lakandi territory, as the Lakandi are deeply reclusive and hostile to outsiders. Imperial scholars who have studied the language note its unusual tonal system and its extensive vocabulary for describing terrain, weather, and combat. Rinoic The primary language of the Rinoan tribal confederation. Rinoic features a strong oral tradition and a system of kennings -- metaphorical compound words -- that make its poetry dense and allusive. Shentic The language of the Shenti people. Shentic shows heavy Massarai influence, reflecting the Shenti&#39;s long history as subjects of the Massaran Empire . With the fall of the Shenti province to the Tulmuk , Shentic is increasingly spoken by refugee communities within the Empire&#39;s interior. Ancient Massarai The older form of the Massaran language, associated with the height of the Massaran Empire and its sorcerer-kings. Ancient Massarai is the language of many surviving Massaran magical texts and is studied by scholars interested in Veil sorcery -- though such study is forbidden within the Empire. Massarai The modern descendant of Ancient Massarai, spoken in the surviving Massaran Kingdoms and by Massar communities within the Empire. Urgathai The language of Urgathoa , the most prominent surviving Massaran kingdom. Urgathai is a distinct language from Massarai, though the two share a common ancestor. It serves as the language of court, commerce, and diplomacy within Urgathoa&#39;s sphere of influence. Ranka The guttural, simplified language spoken by the Beastmen . Ranka is less a true language than a pidgin -- a basic communication system cobbled together from fragments of Massarai, animal vocalizations, and improvised vocabulary. Different beastman tribes speak mutually unintelligible variants. Ranka has no written form. Proto-Skiothan An older form of the Skiothan language, preserved in oral epics, war chants, and ritual formulae among the Skiothan horse tribes. Proto-Skiothan is used primarily in ceremonial contexts. Skiothan The living language of the Skiothan nomadic horse warriors of the Grathe Steppe . Skiothan is aggressively maintained by its speakers, who view linguistic purity as an expression of cultural superiority. See Also Races and Cultures of Mithrapos Mithrian Empire Imperial Academy Gnostic Geometry Argollean Massaran Empire"},{"slug":"lysean","title":"Lysean","category":"lore","tags":"culture lysean naming human religious scholarly drought beastman-wars","text":"Lysean The Lyseans are a deeply religious and scholarly people whose culture is suffused with spiritual devotion and intellectual inquiry. Among the earliest members of the Mithrian League, the Lyseans have a long tradition of loyalty to the Empire -- a loyalty that has been repaid with suffering, as their homeland has been devastated by both natural disaster and war. Physical Appearance Lyseans are tall with fair skin and fair hair. Their lighter coloring distinguishes them from the darker-haired Mithrian norm, and their height is notable even among the taller peoples of Mithrapos . Culture and Values The Lyseans were among the early Mithrian League members , joining the confederation in its formative years and maintaining a long tradition of loyalty to the institutions that grew from it. This loyalty is not blind obedience but a deeply held conviction that the League -- and later the Empire -- represents the best hope for civilization in a dangerous world. Lysean culture is suffused with spiritual devotion and intellectual inquiry. Lysean scholars, theologians, and priests are respected throughout the Empire, and Lysean institutions of learning have produced some of the most influential thinkers in Imperial history. The Devastation of the Homeland The Lysean homeland was once the breadbasket of the region -- fertile fields that fed not only Lysea but surrounding provinces as well. Approximately 200 years ago , a prolonged and devastating drought ravaged these fields, destroying the agricultural foundation of Lysean prosperity. The drought transformed the breadbasket into dust, and Lysea has never fully recovered. The same fields that once fed an empire became the primary battleground for the Beastman Wars . Soldiers who were promised fertile farmland as a reward for service found instead fields of dust -- the broken promise of a homeland that no longer existed in the form they had been told to expect. This cruel irony -- fighting and dying for land that had already been destroyed -- has left a deep mark on Lysean culture and on the soldiers who serve in Lysean formations. Naming Conventions Lysean names characteristically end in -an , -ur , -ik , or -el , giving them a distinctive cadence that sets them apart from the naming traditions of other Imperial peoples. The patronymic suffixes -ian or -yan denote descent (e.g., Gregorian, meaning son of Gregor ; Toryan, meaning son of Tor ). Lyseans also employ honorific and religious earned names , bestowed upon individuals who achieve distinction in spiritual or scholarly pursuits. These earned names carry great prestige and may supplement or replace the bearer&#39;s birth name. A Lysean scholar known by their earned name is understood to have achieved something of lasting significance in their field. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire the Lyseans have long served beastmen -- The creatures whose wars ravaged Lysean fields empyrean-faith -- The faith that shapes Lysean spiritual life"},{"slug":"magic-and-sorcery","title":"Magic and Sorcery","category":"lore","tags":"magic sorcery gnostic-geometry veil flame imperial-academy argolle elvora empyrean","text":"Magic and Sorcery The civilizations of Mithrapos have long used sorcery as part of their society, whether that be through assisting with vast construction projects or through destruction on the battlefield. Sorcery is not a single unified discipline but rather a collection of competing traditions, each with its own philosophy, methodology, and dangers. The three principal traditions -- Gnostic Geometry , the Veil , and the Flame -- represent fundamentally different understandings of the nature of reality and the mortal&#39;s place within it. The institutional seat of sorcerous learning in the present age is the Imperial Academy , located in Mithra City , which enforces strict control over the practice of magic throughout the Mithrian Empire . Gnostic Geometry The world is built on hidden mathematics -- the sorcerer seeks to learn the metaphysical equation. -- High Mage Marius , On Axioms Gnostic geometry is a form of magic that was once practiced by the ancient Argolleans , thousands of years ago. Within the Argollean Empire , magic was common -- a part of everyday life. Sorcery was woven into the fabric of Argollean civilization, employed in construction, governance, warfare, and scholarship alike. After the fall of Argolle, the formulae were lost for thousands of years, buried beneath the ruin of that once-great civilization and the long ages of darkness that followed. It was not until the Prophet Enador rediscovered the Measure and the Scale that these ancient arts were recovered. Along with those sacred texts was the lesser known Anthyllium , an ancient grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality. The Anthyllium is a work of extraordinary complexity, laying out a system of interlocking mathematical and metaphysical principles that, when properly understood and applied, allow a trained sorcerer to reshape the world around them. The formulae within the Anthyllium are still used in present times by the Imperial Academy , forming the foundational curriculum of its sorcerous instruction. According to the Anthyllium, sorcery is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout reality -- a structured, lawful cosmos established by the Aurelion . The universe, in this view, is not chaotic or arbitrary but ordered according to deep mathematical principles laid down at the moment of creation. The geometric incantations taught by the Imperial Academy can alter these axioms through three interconnected methods: Mental discipline -- the rigorous training of the sorcerer&#39;s mind to perceive and manipulate the underlying axioms Diagrams (sigils) -- precisely drawn geometric patterns that serve as physical anchors for metaphysical manipulation Resonance (spoken word) -- verbal incantations that activate and direct the power channeled through sigils and mental focus This form of sorcery is rigid and codified, demanding years of intensive study and practice. It is also extremely dangerous to the untrained mind. An improperly drawn sigil, a mispronounced incantation, or a lapse in mental discipline can produce catastrophic and unpredictable results. Because of this inherent danger, and because the Imperial Academy seeks to keep all sorcerous knowledge firmly under its own control, the Academy retains strict authority over the teaching and practice of gnostic geometry throughout the Empire. Unsanctioned practice is punishable by imprisonment or death. The cataclysmic potential of gnostic geometry was demonstrated during the Battle of Blue Mound (360--368 IY), in which a duel between High Mage Cynar and Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye escalated to such destructive magnitude that it annihilated both armies entirely. This event remains one of the most dramatic illustrations of what sorcery is capable of when wielded without restraint. The Imperial Academy also offered a characteristically scientific explanation for the catastrophic earthquakes and storms that accompanied the Death of Usil in 348 IY, attributing the devastation to fluctuations in the gnostic patterns that govern the metaphysical reality of Mithrapos. Priests of the Empyrean faiths, by contrast, claimed that an Empyrean god had died -- a theological explanation that the Academy rejected but could not entirely disprove. The Veil Magic is not of this world, it bleeds in from Beyond. -- Logos , Elvoran Apostate The Elvoran discovery of the Veil reshaped understanding of how magic and sorcery work, challenging the orderly geometric model promoted by the Imperial Academy and its Eladran predecessors. The Veil is not merely a boundary between two worlds, but a kind of living membrane between the realm of the mortals and the Beyond -- a multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten and ancient gods, and raw metaphysical potential. It breathes, shifts, and responds to those who touch it. When the Aurelion sacrificed himself, it created a cosmic wound -- a fundamental rupture in the fabric of existence -- allowing the realities on either side of the Veil to influence each other. The sorcerer opens these wounds further, siphoning energies from other realities and drawing them into the mortal world. Every act of sorcery, in this understanding, is an act of tearing -- a deliberate reopening of the primordial wound left by the Aurelion&#39;s death. While the Imperial Academy and their predecessors, the Eladra , see magic as a manipulation of lawful axioms -- an orderly, mathematical process governed by rules and formulae -- the Elvora know that such order is merely the outer crust of a primordial chaotic stew. Beneath the thin veneer of geometric law lies a seething, alien chaos that defies comprehension. The Elvora believe that true sorcerous power comes not from manipulating the surface patterns but from plunging one&#39;s will into the raw chaos beneath. This act of sorcery is inherently violent, as the sorcerer is contesting with the fabric of reality itself, unmaking it and reshaping it according to their will. There is no gentleness in Veil magic -- it is an act of force, of domination over the natural order. Over time, repeated contact with the Beyond corrupts both the flesh and the mind. The physical and psychological toll of Veil sorcery is well documented: Eyes may blacken -- nearly all Elvora display this characteristic, their eyes becoming solid pools of darkness Bones warp -- skeletal structure may twist and deform under the sustained influence of chaotic energies Voices change -- the sorcerer&#39;s voice may deepen, echo, or take on alien harmonics These are not merely cosmetic changes but markers of a fundamental transformation wrought by prolonged exposure to the Beyond. The Elvora, who have practiced Veil sorcery for millennia, bear these marks most prominently. Contact with the Veil also permits communion with things from the Beyond: Cthonic gods, demons, forgotten titans, and other alien intelligences that dwell within the multiversal tangle. This contact is perilous in the extreme, for these entities possess desires, agendas, and hungers of their own. To those who venerate such powers, however, this communion is not a danger but an opportunity -- the true path to apotheosis. Cthonic cults and demon-binders view the Veil not as a barrier to be feared but as a gateway to transcendence. The Flame Each living being carries a spark of the Aurelion within its soul. To embody the Measure and the Scale you can reshape the world with your soul&#39;s fire. -- Saint Euphrosyne , the Measure and the Scale The priests of Seros , and other Empyrean faiths, believe that by aligning one&#39;s will with the virtues of the Scale you can channel portions of your divine spark into the mortal realm. This tradition stands apart from both gnostic geometry and Veil sorcery in a fundamental way: the Flame is not drawn from diagrams or summoned from alien realms. Instead, it burns within the soul of every mortal -- a remnant of the Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice, a shard of divine fire passed down through all living things. The faithful of Seros channel this Flame through virtue, sacrifice, and righteous purpose. It is not a power that can be seized or demanded but one that must be earned through the constant practice of moral and spiritual discipline. To walk the path of the Measure and the Scale is to unlock one&#39;s inner radiance. Only through discipline, humility, and devotion can the Flame be kindled into miracles. The priests and clerics of the Thousand Temples do little to teach the Flame in any formal or academic sense. It cannot be taught -- it must be lived. The Flame does not respond to formulae or incantations but to the quality of the soul that seeks to wield it. To the faithful, the Measure and the Scale is more than a moral code, a religious doctrine, or a legal treatise -- it is the kindling by which one&#39;s Flame is awakened. A life lived in accordance with its principles is itself the incantation, the sigil, and the resonance all at once. This understanding places the Flame tradition in direct philosophical opposition to both gnostic geometry (which treats sorcery as an intellectual and mathematical exercise) and Veil sorcery (which treats it as an act of violent will imposed upon reality). To the priests of Seros, sorcery is neither calculation nor conquest -- it is communion with the divine spark that dwells within. The Imperial Academy The Emperor rules the world of men, but the Academy governs what is possible within it. -- Archmage Thoss , On the Bounds of Sovereignty , banned in three provinces The Imperial Academy is the official state-sanctioned seat of sorcerous learning within the Mithrian Empire . Located in Mithra City , its towering spires are the highest structures within the city, able to be seen from leagues away -- a deliberate architectural statement of the Academy&#39;s power and prestige. It is both a prestigious university of learning and a political power in its own right, operating outside the traditional structure of Imperial ministries. The Academy answers to the Emperor, but in practice it exercises a degree of autonomy that few other institutions can claim. The Academy is a pillar of imperial stability and ambition, but also a hotbed of secrecy, rivalry, and experimentation. Behind its alabaster walls, Archmages pursue research both sanctioned and clandestine, and political maneuvering among the faculty is as ruthless as anything found in the Imperial Senate. Citizens of the Empire hold the Academy in fear and contempt, for its Seekers prowl the provinces, searching for those who possess the power of sorcery, and enrolling those individuals within its alabaster halls. The Seekers are agents of the Academy who travel the length and breadth of the Empire, testing children and young adults for sorcerous aptitude. When talent is discovered, enrollment is not optional. If a family cannot afford the pricey tuition, the Seekers will enslave the future student as a servus , until such a time that they can pay their tuition through service. This practice, while legal under Imperial law, is deeply resented by the common people. Some of these servus, however, have risen through sheer talent and determination to become some of the most powerful High Mages to ever live -- a fact the Academy is fond of citing in its own defense. A conclave of Archmages forms a ruling council of the Academy. This is a lifelong appointment, decided by the Emperor himself, making each seat on the council a matter of intense political significance. Every seven years the council will vote on one of their members to become the Primarch , a figurehead of some executive power within the Academy and a direct advisor to the Emperor. The Primarch serves as the public face of the Academy and wields considerable influence in matters of state, particularly those concerning sorcery, warfare, and the regulation of magical practice. The Academy teaches and practices a form of geometric gnostic sorcery . The formulae and incantations are difficult to master, requiring years of rigorous study, but they are much more powerful than those employed by a hedge-mage or warlock working outside the Academy&#39;s traditions. Other forms of sorcery are strictly prohibited by the Academy, and the following disciplines are expressly forbidden: Necromancy -- the animation or manipulation of the dead Transmogrification -- the fundamental alteration of living flesh Demon-binding -- the summoning and enslavement of entities from the Beyond Violations of these prohibitions are punishable by death, as demonstrated by the fate of Magistrate Verna Astell , who was executed for practicing forbidden transmogrification rituals. The Scale may weigh the soul, but it is the Academy that defines what a soul can be. -- Magistrate Verna Astell , executed for practicing forbidden transmogrification rituals Despite these prohibitions, rumors persist of clandestine research conducted within the Academy&#39;s deepest laboratories -- experiments that push against or outright violate the Academy&#39;s own stated rules. The Academy and Warfare The Mithrian Empire once held a near-monopoly on sorcery, ensuring battlefield dominance across its many campaigns of conquest and defense. The Academy was central to this advantage, training and deploying battle-mages whose geometric sorcery could devastate enemy formations, shatter fortifications, and turn the tide of entire wars. However, over time the destructive powers of mages have proliferated beyond the Academy&#39;s control. Hedge-mages, warlocks, and sorcerers trained in rival traditions have appeared in increasing numbers among the Empire&#39;s enemies. This proliferation has transformed warfare. The military now uses squad mages as part of combined arms tactics, integrating sorcerers into conventional military formations rather than relying on them as singular weapons of mass destruction. Additionally, Kolani munitions -- explosive devices and incendiary weapons gained as part of the peace treaty following the Dog Soldier War -- now supplement magical firepower, further reducing the Academy&#39;s exclusive importance on the battlefield. The Battle of Blue Mound (360--368 IY) stands as a grim testament to the catastrophic potential of sorcerous warfare. The duel between High Mage Cynar of the Imperial Academy and Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye escalated beyond all control, annihilating both armies and leaving the battlefield a blasted wasteland. This event prompted significant reforms in how the Empire deploys its mages in combat. See Also Imperial Academy Argolle Eladra Elvora Aurelion Measure and the Scale Anthyllium Veil Beyond Empyrean Cthonic Seros Thousand Temples Battle of Blue Mound Death of Usil Prophet Enador Dog Soldier War"},{"slug":"massar","title":"Massar","category":"lore","tags":"culture massar naming human massaran-empire sorcerer-kings cthonic argollean thunean-empire urgathoan","text":"Massar The Massar are a culturally sophisticated people whose traditions bear the deep imprint of Argollean influence. They once ruled the Massaran Empire -- a formidable dominion sustained by powerful sorcerer-kings and Beastmen legions -- that enslaved much of the known world before being overthrown by the forces of Prophet Enador and Bellasarius Valerian in the Empyrean War . Culture and Values The Massaran Empire was shattered and its armies scattered, but the Massar people endure, and several kingdoms survive as successor states to the old empire. The most well-known of these successor states are the Urgathoans , who maintain the cultural traditions and political ambitions of the old Massaran order. The Massar civilization rose from the ruins of the Argollean Empire , and their language, art, and naming conventions all reflect this heritage. They are a people of cultural sophistication -- their art, architecture, and scholarship bear the marks of a civilization that once ruled the known world and has not forgotten that it did. Religion The Massar still worship Cthonic gods . While the Mithrian Empire and its Empyrean faith have become dominant across much of Mithrapos , the Massar have maintained their older Cthonic traditions -- the worship of the hungry gods, the powers that dwell beyond the Veil . This continued devotion to the Cthonic faith is both a spiritual choice and a political statement: a refusal to adopt the religious framework of the empire that overthrew them. Role in the Thunean Empire The Massar are also notable for their historical role as advisors within the Thunean Empire . Massar counselors were brought into the Thunean court and used their position to orchestrate the overthrow of their Thune overlords from within. This achievement -- the destruction of an empire through patient manipulation rather than military force -- is one of the most remarkable feats of political warfare in the history of Mithrapos . The Beastmen The Massar created the Beastmen as the core of their armies -- purpose-bred for war through sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding. After the defeat of the Massaran Empire, the Beastmen were scattered, left without purpose or direction. They remain a persistent threat to civilization across Mithrapos , a living legacy of Massaran ambition. Naming Conventions Massar names are Argollean-influenced , characterized by elongated vowels and a flowing, musical cadence that reflects their cultural heritage from the old Argollean Empire. Naming particles include: net -- meaning house of (e.g., Amara net Solenn) sah -- meaning blood of (e.g., Kassim sah Durai) See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures beastmen -- The army the Massar created thune -- The empire the Massar overthrew from within Argolle -- The ancient empire that influenced Massar culture history-of-mithrapos -- The Empyrean War that overthrew the Massaran Empire shenti -- A people formerly subject to Massaran rule tet -- A people formerly enslaved by Massar cthonic-faith -- The faith the Massar still follow"},{"slug":"massaran-empire","title":"The Massaran Empire","category":"lore","tags":"lore history massaran massar sorcerer-kings empyrean-war sebek enador bellasarius-valerian beastmen cthonic urgathoans thune slavery ancient-empire","text":"The Massaran Empire The Massar ruled as gods and were obeyed as gods and punished as gods punish. Their sorcerer-kings remade the flesh of beasts into armies and the will of men into obedience. When the Prophet broke their power, the world did not celebrate -- it exhaled. The breath it had been holding for centuries. The Massaran Empire was an ancient empire ruled by the Massar -- a dynasty of sorcerer-kings who enslaved much of the known world through a combination of overwhelming arcane power, beastman legions, and systematic domination. It was the defining tyranny of the pre-imperial age, and its shadow falls across every civilization that followed. The Massaran Empire was overthrown in the Empyrean War (663 BE) by Prophet Enador and Bellasarius Valerian . The tyrant-sorcerer Sebek was driven into exile. The beastman legions that formed the core of the Massaran armies were scattered. The Empire shattered -- but it did not entirely die. At a Glance Detail Description Type Ancient empire, pre-imperial age Rulers The Massar -- sorcerer-kings wielding immense arcane power Defining Feature Enslaved much of the known world Military Core Beastman legions -- creatures of reshaped flesh serving as the backbone of Massaran armies Fall Overthrown in the Mithrapos had known before the rise of the Mithrian Empire . The Massar sorcerer-kings wielded arcane power on a scale that has not been replicated since -- power sufficient to reshape living flesh into the beastman legions that formed the core of their armies, to bend the will of conquered peoples into obedience, and to maintain dominion over much of the known world for generations. Their empire was built on slavery -- not merely the economic exploitation of labor, but the total subjugation of peoples, cultures, and civilizations. The Massar did not merely conquer. They consumed. Nations that fell under their rule were absorbed, their identities erased, their populations converted into raw material for the empire&#39;s needs. The Beastman Legions The beastman legions were the core of Massaran military power -- creatures of reshaped flesh, created through sorcerous processes that transformed living beings into weapons of war. These legions were the instrument of Massaran conquest, the force that broke the armies of free peoples, and the visible symbol of the sorcerer-kings&#39; power over life itself. When the Massaran Empire shattered, the beastman legions were scattered across Mithrapos . Without the sorcerer-kings to command them, the beastmen fragmented into warbands, tribes, and feral populations. They persist in the present day -- a living legacy of Massaran power, found in wilderness regions, frontier territories, and the margins of civilization. The Backlands beastman population is one such remnant. The Thune Connection The relationship between the Massar and the Thune is one of history&#39;s great ironies of power and succession: The Thune were originally advisors to an earlier power. They rose to become rulers in their own right, establishing the Thunean Empire . The Massar were originally Thune advisors -- subordinates who served the Thunean court. They followed the same pattern as their masters, rising from service to dominance. The Massar overthrew the Thune and established the Massaran Empire on the ruins of the Thunean one. The cycle of advisor-becomes-ruler repeated itself across generations -- a pattern that historians have noted with varying degrees of irony and alarm. The Empyrean War and the Fall The Massaran Empire was overthrown in the Empyrean War of 663 BE -- a conflict that reshaped the world and established the foundations of the current age. Prophet Enador -- the founder of the Empyrean faith -- provided the spiritual and ideological framework for resistance against the Massar Bellasarius Valerian -- the military leader who translated that framework into victory on the battlefield Sebek -- the last and greatest of the Massar sorcerer-kings -- was driven into exile rather than killed The war broke the Massaran Empire, scattered the beastman legions, and liberated the enslaved peoples of Mithrapos . From the wreckage of the Massaran order, the foundations of the Mithrian Empire were laid -- an empire that defined itself, in part, by opposition to everything the Massar had represented. Surviving Remnants The Massaran Empire shattered, but it did not entirely die. Several Massaran kingdoms survive in the present day, maintaining elements of the old order -- the worship of Cthonic gods , the traditions of sorcerous power, and the cultural memory of an empire that once ruled the world. The Urgathoans are the most well-known of these surviving Massaran successor states. They maintain the worship of the Cthonic gods and preserve traditions that the Mithrian Empire regards as abhorrent -- living proof that the Massaran legacy endures despite the Empire&#39;s best efforts to consign it to history. Legacy The Massaran Empire&#39;s legacy pervades the present: Beastman populations across Mithrapos are the scattered remnants of the legions Cthonic worship in its various forms traces its institutional roots to Massaran religious practice The Empyrean faith defines itself in opposition to the Massaran order The Mithrian Empire claims legitimacy as the successor state to the liberation -- the power that replaced tyranny with civilization The fear of sorcery -- the deep cultural suspicion that pervades imperial society -- is rooted in the memory of what sorcerer-kings did when they held unchecked power See Also empyrean-war -- The conflict that overthrew the Massaran Empire enador -- The Prophet who provided the spiritual framework for resistance Bellasarius Valerian -- The military leader of the liberation Sebek -- The last sorcerer-king, driven into exile cthonic-corruption -- The religious tradition of the Massar beastmen -- The scattered remnants of Massaran legions thune -- The predecessors the Massar overthrew Thunean Empire -- The empire the Massar replaced Urgathoans -- The most well-known surviving Massaran successor state mithrian-empire -- The empire that rose from the Massaran collapse empyrean-faith -- The faith born in opposition to Massaran tyranny mithrapos -- The known world the Massar once dominated history-of-mithrapos -- The broader historical context"},{"slug":"mithrapos","title":"Mithrapos","category":"lore","tags":"lore world geography mithrapos middle-sea empires setting cosmology","text":"Mithrapos A cradle and a coffin, a boneyard of Empires. -- Savron Mithrapos is the known world -- the region encircling the Middle Sea that has seen the rise and fall of numerous empires, civilizations, and peoples. It is the setting of the Fallen Empire campaign, a world shaped by millennia of conquest, collapse, and the persistent ambitions of mortals and gods alike. The Mithrian Empire is the dominant power in Mithrapos in the present age. It will not be the last. At a Glance Detail Description Type The known world Central Feature The Middle Sea have served as the cradle and the grave of civilization after civilization -- each building on the ruins of its predecessor, each believing itself permanent, each eventually joining the wreckage beneath its successors&#39; foundations. The current dominant power -- the Mithrian Empire -- is merely the latest in this sequence. It rose from the ashes of the Massaran Empire , which rose from the ashes of the Thunean Empire , which rose from the ashes of something older still. The pattern is not lost on the Empire&#39;s scholars, though they prefer to believe their civilization will be the exception. The Middle Sea The Middle Sea is the central geographic feature of Mithrapos -- the body of water around which civilizations cluster, trade routes converge, and empires project their power. It connects the disparate lands and peoples of Mithrapos through commerce, war, and cultural exchange. Control of the Middle Sea has been a defining ambition of every empire that has risen to dominance. The Cycle of Empires Mithrapos has witnessed the rise and fall of numerous empires, each leaving its mark on the landscape, the peoples, and the metaphysical fabric of the world: The Thunean Empire -- An early power whose advisors (the Massar) eventually overthrew them The Massaran Empire -- The tyranny of sorcerer-kings who enslaved much of the known world, overthrown in the Empyrean War (663 BE) The First Empire (Eladran) -- An empire whose cultural legacy persists through the Argollean Brotherhood and the artifacts they seek to reclaim The Mithrian Empire -- The current dominant power, built on the foundations of the Empyrean faith and the military legacy of Bellasarius Valerian Each empire has left ruins, artifacts, displaced peoples, and unresolved powers in its wake. The world of Mithrapos is layered with the residue of these successive civilizations -- their temples, their gods, their weapons, and their mistakes. The Metaphysical Landscape Mithrapos exists in relationship to forces that extend beyond the material world: The Veil -- The barrier between the mortal world and the Beyond , weakened by the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice The Beyond -- The multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten gods, and raw metaphysical potential beyond the Veil The Empyrean gods -- The divine powers worshipped by the Mithrian Empire The Cthonic gods -- Older, darker powers that predate the Empyrean faith and persist in hidden worship Sorcery -- The practice of opening wounds in the Veil to siphon energies from the Beyond The metaphysical landscape of Mithrapos is not stable. The Veil has been damaged, the old gods have not departed, and the new gods have not fully secured their dominion. The world exists in a state of spiritual tension that mirrors its political instability. See Also Middle Sea -- The central geographic feature of the known world mithrian-empire -- The current dominant power massaran-empire -- The ancient tyranny that preceded the current order Thunean Empire -- The empire the Massar overthrew Eladran -- The First Empire whose legacy persists empyrean-war -- The conflict that reshaped the world empyrean-faith -- The dominant religious tradition cthonic-corruption -- The older religious tradition that persists the-veil -- The barrier between worlds the-beyond -- The metaphysical reality beyond the Veil history-of-mithrapos -- The detailed historical timeline races-and-cultures -- The peoples of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"mithrian-calendar","title":"The Mithrian Calendar","category":"lore","tags":"calendar time holidays culture empire","text":"The Mithrian Calendar The Valerian Calendar is the official timekeeping system of the Mithrian Empire , instituted after Marcus Valerian declared himself Emperor in 1 IY. The calendar structures the Imperial year into thirteen months of twenty-eight days each, plus one intercalary day, for a total of 365 days . Structure The year consists of: 13 months of 28 days each (364 days) 1 intercalary day -- Dies Solaris -- which falls after the final day of Aeternitas and before the first day of Virtus , sitting outside the monthly cycle Months The thirteen months of the Valerian Calendar are named for virtues central to the Measure and the Scale and the Empyrean Faith . Month Season Virtue Virtus Winter Courage / Manliness Decus Winter Honor / Dignity Fides Spring Faith / Loyalty Pietas Spring Duty / Devotion Fortuna Spring Fortune / Fate Justica Summer Justice Concordia Summer Harmony / Unity Aequitas Summer Equity / Fairness Celementia Autumn Mercy / Clemency Victoria Autumn Victory Spes Autumn Hope Pax Autumn Peace Aeternitas Winter Eternity / Immortality Each month contains exactly 28 days, making the calendar remarkably regular. Weeks are seven days long, and every month begins on the same day of the week. Holidays and Observances Dies Solaris Dies Solaris is the intercalary day that falls after Aeternitas 28 and before Virtus 1. It exists outside the monthly cycle -- it belongs to no month and no week. Dies Solaris is the most significant holiday in the Imperial calendar. The day is marked by: Feasts -- Communal meals hosted by patrons for their clients, reinforcing the bonds of the Measure and the Scale Games -- Athletic and martial competitions, chariot races, and public spectacles sponsored by the Great Houses and wealthy citizens Rites for the Fallen -- Solemn religious ceremonies conducted by the Thousand Temples to honor the dead, particularly soldiers who fell in service to the Empire Dies Solaris is simultaneously a day of celebration and mourning -- a liminal moment between the old year and the new, when the living acknowledge their debts to those who came before. Ludi Gloriae The Ludi Gloriae (Games of Glory) occupy the first week of Fides , marking the transition from winter into spring. The festival is both martial and mournful in character. Mock Battles -- Organized military exhibitions, war games, and staged combats performed by soldiers and gladiators. These are not mere entertainment but are considered acts of devotion, demonstrating martial virtue before the gods and the people. Mourning Lamps -- On each night of the Ludi Gloriae, citizens light oil lamps and place them in windows, doorways, and public spaces to honor the war dead. The effect transforms Imperial cities into seas of flickering light. The Ludi Gloriae serve a dual purpose: they celebrate the military strength of the Empire while reminding citizens of its human cost. Dies Justicae Dies Justicae falls on Justica 14, the midpoint of the summer month of Justice. It is a day of legal and moral reflection. A priest of the Thousand Temples publicly recites the Measure and the Scale -- the full text, which can take several hours -- in the central forum or temple of every Imperial city and town No work is permitted. All commerce, legal proceedings, and military operations (except those deemed essential) cease for the day Citizens are expected to reflect on their obligations under the Measure and their moral standing under the Scale Dies Justicae reinforces the centrality of the Measure and the Scale to Imperial identity. It is the one day of the year when every citizen, from the Emperor to the lowest freedman, is reminded of the code that binds them all. See Also Mithrian Empire Measure and the Scale Thousand Temples Empyrean Faith History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"mithrian-culture","title":"Mithrian Culture","category":"lore","tags":"culture mithrian naming human patronage social-status","text":"Mithrian Culture The Mithrians are the dominant culture of the Mithrian Empire and the people from whom the Empire takes its name. Mithrian culture is urban, bureaucratic, and deeply hierarchical, with an emphasis on law, order, and civic duty. It is the cultural standard against which all other peoples of Mithrapos are measured -- not because Mithrians are inherently superior, but because the Empire&#39;s institutions, laws, and social expectations are built upon Mithrian assumptions. Physical Appearance Mithrians are typically fair to olive-skinned, with dark hair and dark eyes. Centuries of imperial expansion and cultural intermixing have produced considerable variation, but the archetype of the Mithrian remains recognizable: Mediterranean in complexion, with features that reflect the urban sophistication their culture prizes. Culture and Values Mithrian culture is cosmopolitan by necessity and inclination. The Empire&#39;s vast territorial extent means that Mithrians have been in contact with dozens of peoples for centuries, and their culture reflects this -- absorbing, adapting, and incorporating elements from conquered and allied peoples while maintaining a core identity rooted in certain unshakeable values: Honor -- A Mithrian&#39;s word is their bond. Oaths, contracts, and promises carry tremendous weight in Mithrian society, and the breaking of a sworn oath is one of the gravest social transgressions. Tradition -- Mithrians revere the customs and institutions of their ancestors. Innovation is valued, but it must be justified against the weight of precedent. Family -- The family unit is the foundation of Mithrian society. Loyalty to family supersedes nearly all other obligations, and the family name is a source of both pride and responsibility. The Patronage System The patronage system is the engine of Mithrian social mobility and the organizing principle of all social interaction. Every Mithrian exists within a web of patron-client relationships that defines their social standing, their opportunities, and their obligations. A citizen&#39;s worth is measured not only by their own achievements but by the quality and power of the patrons who vouch for them. Conversely, a patron&#39;s prestige is enhanced by the number and quality of their clients. Fathers wield tremendous power within the Mithrian family structure. The paterfamilias -- the male head of household -- holds authority over the family&#39;s fortunes, alliances, and social standing. This patriarchal authority is not merely customary but deeply embedded in the legal and moral framework of the Measure and the Scale . Naming Conventions Mithrians use a distinctive three-part naming system consisting of: Praenomen -- The personal or given name, used among intimates and family. Examples: Marcus, Gaius, Titus, Lucius, Justinian, Valerios. Nomen -- The family or clan name, indicating lineage and heritage. Examples: Valerian, Claudius, Drussus, Kalomenes, Severian. Cognomen -- A distinguishing epithet, often earned through deed or inherited through a family branch. Examples: Decimus, Marcellus, Aurel. Among the nobility , the cognomen is favored and carries the greatest social weight, serving as a marker of distinguished lineage or personal accomplishment. A noble introduced by cognomen alone is understood to be claiming the full weight of that branch&#39;s reputation and history. Among the peasantry , who may lack a formal cognomen, profession often serves in its place. A farmer named Marcus of the Varro family who works as a smith might be known simply as Marcus Varro the Smith . The naming system reflects the Mithrian obsession with lineage, status, and the public declaration of identity. To know a Mithrian&#39;s full name is to know their family, their branch, and -- if the cognomen is earned rather than inherited -- their most notable achievement. Religion Mithrians follow the Empyrean Faith as codified in the Measure and the Scale , with the Thousand Temples serving as the institutional expression of their spiritual life. The Aurelion -- the distributed divine essence -- is the theological foundation, and the Empyrean gods (chief among them the Unconquered Sun) are the objects of public devotion. Role in the Empire As the founding culture of the Empire, Mithrians occupy a position of cultural dominance that shapes every institution, law, and social expectation. The Imperial bureaucracy operates in Mithrian language and according to Mithrian legal precedent. The military follows Mithrian command structures. The Thousand Temples preach in Mithrian theological vocabulary. Even peoples who have been part of the Empire for centuries find themselves navigating a world built on Mithrian assumptions. This dominance is not enforced through explicit racial hierarchy -- the Empire&#39;s social system cares far more about status than ethnicity -- but the structural advantages of being born into the culture that designed the system are real and significant. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire that bears this culture&#39;s name Measure and the Scale -- The legal and moral framework of Mithrian civilization Thousand Temples -- The institutional expression of Mithrian faith Great Houses -- The noble families that dominate Mithrian politics Vestari -- Early allies who follow Mithrian naming conventions"},{"slug":"mithrian-empire","title":"The Mithrian Empire","category":"lore","tags":"empire government politics mithra mithrapos","text":"The Mithrian Empire The Mithrian Empire is the dominant power of the Mithrapos region, centered on the great capital of Mithra City . It is a vast, sprawling dominion governed by an Emperor who rules with supreme authority as codified by the Measure and the Scale -- the foundational legal and moral framework of Imperial civilization. The current year is 380 IY (Imperial Year), and the reigning Emperor is Justinian Claudius Decimus . Origins: The Mithrian League The Empire traces its roots to the Mithrian League , a confederation of city-states united under a governing Imperial Senate . The League was forged in the aftermath of the Empyrean War , when the prophet Enador and the general Bellasarius Valerian overthrew the Massaran Empire and its sorcerer-kings. The League prospered for centuries under senatorial rule, but internal rivalries, corruption, and the ambitions of powerful houses eventually tore the old order apart. Rise of the Emperors Marcus Valerian , claiming descent from Bellasarius Valerian himself, seized power and declared himself the first Emperor in 1 IY . He defeated the armies raised by loyalist Senators and consolidated authority under a single throne. The Senate was not abolished but was stripped of meaningful legislative power, becoming a largely performative body -- a forum for speeches, petitions, and political theater rather than genuine governance. Imperial Government The Emperor rules with supreme authority, but does not govern alone. He is advised and supported by several key institutions: Imperial Senate -- The remnant of the old League&#39;s governing body. Senators hold prestige and can influence policy through rhetoric and patronage, but lack binding authority. Seats are hereditary or appointed. Imperial Academy -- The scholarly and arcane institution responsible for the study and regulation of Gnostic Geometry , the primary sanctioned form of magic. The Academy also serves as an advisory body on matters of science, history, and metaphysics. Thousand Temples -- The organized priesthood of the Empyrean Faith , devoted to the worship of the Aurelion and the virtues of the Measure and the Scale . The Temples wield enormous cultural influence and serve as moral arbiters across the Empire. Ministers -- Senior officials appointed by the Emperor to oversee specific domains of governance such as war, finance, law, and foreign affairs. Below the Emperor, provincial authority is delegated to Governors (civilian administrators) and Legates (military commanders), both appointed directly by the throne. Social Order: The Measure and the Scale Imperial society is governed by a rigid patronage system known as the Measure and the Scale . This legal and philosophical code dictates obligations between patrons and clients, defines social rank, and establishes the moral expectations of citizens. Social status within the Empire matters far more than race or ethnicity -- a Thrassian general or a Targ merchant can rise to positions of tremendous influence if they navigate the patronage system effectively, while a Mithrian of poor standing may find themselves with no more rights than a freedman. The Measure defines law and civic duty. The Scale defines virtue and moral conduct. Together they form the bedrock of Imperial identity. The Great Houses Political power is concentrated among the Great Houses , noble families whose wealth, military strength, and patronage networks shape the direction of the Empire. The current ruling house is House Decimus , which secured dominance after the War of Three Emperors in 270 IY. Other major houses include House Valerian , House Kalomenes , House Malventi , House Drussus , House Aurel , and House Severian . Current State of the Empire Under Justinian Claudius Decimus , the Empire endures but faces mounting pressures. The frontier provinces contend with Beastmen raids, Skiothan incursions, and the lingering aftermath of the Lakan Campaigns . Internal tensions simmer between the Great Houses , the Thousand Temples grow increasingly assertive, and the Imperial Academy guards its arcane monopoly with paranoid vigilance. The Empire remains the mightiest power in the known world, but cracks in the edifice grow wider with each passing year. See Also Great Houses Measure and the Scale Imperial Senate Imperial Academy Thousand Temples Empyrean War History of Mithrapos Mithrian Calendar Races and Cultures of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"mornish","title":"Mornish","category":"lore","tags":"culture mornish naming human rebellious morn honorific lycandite second-war-of-morn 8th-undying","text":"Mornish The Mornish are a hardy and practical people from the Peninsula of Morn , a region comprising dozens of fiercely independent cultures united more by geography and temperament than by any central authority. The Mornish place great emphasis on personal honor, earned reputation, and the deeds by which an individual distinguishes themselves. Mornish society values action over birth, and a person&#39;s standing is determined more by what they have done than by who their parents were. Physical Appearance The Mornish are tall with fair skin and dark hair. Their builds tend toward the robust and practical -- a people shaped by the demands of a peninsula where life is hard, competition is fierce, and softness is a liability. Culture and Values The Peninsula of Morn contains dozens of fiercely independent cultures , each with its own customs, traditions, and rivalries. What unites the Mornish is not uniformity but a shared temperament: direct, uncompromising, and possessed of a deep rebellious streak that has made the province a persistent thorn in the Mithrian Empire&#39;s side. The province of Morn has caused trouble for the Empire throughout its existence . The Mornish temperament -- independent, honor-driven, suspicious of distant authority -- is fundamentally incompatible with the centralized control the Empire demands. Every generation produces new grievances, new uprisings, and new reasons for Imperial administrators to dread assignment to Morn. Honorific Titles Honorific titles are a distinctive feature of Mornish culture. These titles are earned through battle, trade, or notable deed and are appended to the bearer&#39;s name as a mark of respect. Crucially, honorific titles are never self-given -- they must be bestowed by one&#39;s peers or community. To claim an unearned title is considered a grave dishonor, one of the few transgressions that can permanently destroy a Mornish person&#39;s reputation. Naming Conventions Mornish names reflect the culture&#39;s blunt and direct character: Male names tend to be guttural and forceful Female names are strong and simple Mornish naming includes several patronymic and locative particles: bar -- meaning descended from (e.g., Tormund bar Hagen) von -- meaning of a place (e.g., Elsa von Greyhold) sen -- meaning son of (e.g., Erik Torvaldsen) ric -- meaning son of (alternative form) Historical Events The Second War of Morn (371 IY) The Second War of Morn in 371 IY was one of the most devastating conflicts the Empire has fought on the peninsula. The war was driven by Lycandite fanatics -- religious extremists whose fervor and willingness to die for their cause made them extraordinarily dangerous opponents. During the Second War of Morn, the 14th Army was shattered -- destroyed as a fighting force by the ferocity of the Lycandite resistance. The catastrophe of the 14th Army stands as one of the most significant Imperial military defeats of the century. From the same conflict, the 8th Undying became legendary. Their exploits during the Second War of Morn have passed into military legend, and their name is invoked as a standard of valor and sacrifice within the ranks of the Mithrian Military . The 8th Undying earned their name through deeds that proved the Empire could produce soldiers equal to even the most fanatical resistance. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire Morn has troubled throughout its existence mithrian-military -- The military that produced the 8th Undying history-of-mithrapos -- The broader historical context"},{"slug":"races-and-cultures","title":"Races and Cultures","category":"lore","tags":"races cultures humans eladra elvora ygrathen thune beastmen social-status naming-conventions mithrian-empire","text":"Races and Cultures The Mithrian Empire is a large and cosmopolitan collection of different people. Race, ethnicity, and cultural backgrounds matter very little to Mithrians of all walks of life. The Empire&#39;s vast territorial extent and centuries of conquest, migration, and trade have produced a society in which cultural intermixing is the norm rather than the exception. What matters more -- what all Mithrians are aware of almost instinctively -- is social status. Social Status Within Mithrian culture a strict adherence to social status is followed. Status is the organizing principle of Mithrian life, the lens through which all social interactions are understood and conducted. Citizenship brings numerous benefits including: The ability to own land and slaves The right to vote in elections The right to hold office And most importantly -- the ability to gain patronage of someone more powerful than you The patronage system is the engine of Mithrian social mobility. A citizen&#39;s worth is measured not only by their own achievements but by the quality and power of the patrons who vouch for them. Conversely, a patron&#39;s prestige is enhanced by the number and quality of their clients. This web of mutual obligation binds Mithrian society together from the lowest citizen to the Emperor himself. Those who lack citizenship -- foreigners, slaves, and the dispossessed -- exist outside this system, with few legal protections and no formal avenue for advancement except through the acquisition of citizenship itself. Human Cultures The following sixteen human cultures comprise the principal ethnic and cultural groups found within and around the Mithrian Empire . Each possesses its own distinct naming conventions, traditions, and social structures, though centuries of Imperial rule have blurred many boundaries. Mithrian The Mithrians are the dominant culture of the Mithrian Empire and the people from whom the Empire takes its name. Mithrian culture is urban, bureaucratic, and deeply hierarchical, with an emphasis on law, order, and civic duty. Naming Conventions: Mithrians use a three-part naming system consisting of: Praenomen -- the personal or given name, used among intimates and family Nomen -- the family or clan name, indicating lineage and heritage Cognomen -- a distinguishing epithet, often earned through deed or inherited through a family branch Among the nobility, the cognomen is favored and carries the greatest social weight, serving as a marker of distinguished lineage or personal accomplishment. Among the peasantry, who may lack a formal cognomen, profession often serves in its place -- a farmer named Marcus of the Varro family who works as a smith might be known simply as Marcus Varro the Smith. Thrassian The Thrassians are a proud and warlike people whose ancient tribal system persists within the framework of the Empire. Though formally incorporated into the Mithrian Empire , Thrassian communities maintain strong tribal identities, and old loyalties to clan and chief often compete with obligations to the Imperial state. Naming Conventions: Thrassians employ a patronymic system: Men use the suffixes -ides or -ion (e.g., Alexandrides, meaning son of Alexander ) Women use the suffixes -aia or -essa (e.g., Helenaia, meaning daughter of Helen ) The tribal system persists within the Empire, and a Thrassian&#39;s tribal affiliation remains a critical component of their identity, often appended informally to their name. Corcanoan The Corcanoans hail from a chain of volcanic islands, and their culture is shaped by the dramatic and dangerous landscape they call home. Corcanoan society is matriarchal in structure, with lineage traced through the mother&#39;s line and women holding positions of authority in both domestic and public life. Naming Conventions: Corcanoan names are melodic and flowing, characteristically ending in vowels or soft consonants. Children are named after their mothers or matriarchal ancestors, reinforcing the matrilineal nature of Corcanoan kinship. A Corcanoan&#39;s name is thus a living record of their maternal lineage, connecting them to generations of women who came before. Mornish The Mornish are a hardy and practical people who place great emphasis on personal honor, earned reputation, and the deeds by which an individual distinguishes themselves. Mornish society values action over birth, and a person&#39;s standing is determined more by what they have done than by who their parents were. Naming Conventions: Mornish names reflect the culture&#39;s blunt and direct character: Male names tend to be guttural and forceful Female names are strong and simple Mornish naming includes several patronymic and locative particles: bar -- meaning descended from (e.g., Tormund bar Hagen) von -- meaning of a place (e.g., Elsa von Greyhold) sen -- meaning son of (e.g., Erik Torvaldsen) ric -- meaning son of (alternative form) Honorific titles are a distinctive feature of Mornish culture. These titles are earned through battle, trade, or notable deed and are appended to the bearer&#39;s name as a mark of respect. Crucially, honorific titles are never self-given -- they must be bestowed by one&#39;s peers or community. To claim an unearned title is considered a grave dishonor. Kolani The Kolani are a diverse people divided into two principal groups defined by their ancestral homeland: ton&#39;Kolani -- the people of the plains, seminomadic pastoralists and warriors don&#39;Kolani -- the people of the forest, settled communities with deep ties to the woodland Naming Conventions: Kolani names are bestowed by the village seer, who invokes spirits, natural forces, and ancestral memory to determine the name that best suits the child. This naming ceremony is a sacred ritual, and the name given is believed to carry spiritual significance and power. Clan names serve as surnames, tying the individual to their broader kinship group. Honorific and totemic titles play an important role in Kolani culture. These titles, earned through deeds of valor, spiritual achievement, or community service, can replace a Kolani&#39;s given name entirely. A warrior who earns a totemic title may be known by that title alone for the rest of their life. The Kolani Irregulars are a notable military formation within the Imperial army, composed entirely of ton&#39;Kolani tribal warriors. They serve as scouts, skirmishers, and light cavalry, and their unconventional tactics have proven invaluable in the Empire&#39;s frontier campaigns. Avari The Avari are a people shaped by loss and remembrance. Their culture places great emphasis on honoring the dead and preserving the memory of those who have fallen. Naming Conventions: Avari children are named after a fallen relative or hero, ensuring that the names of the honored dead continue to live in the present generation. The patronymic suffix -sson is used to denote descent (e.g., Bjornsson, meaning son of Bjorn ). Many Avari have adopted Mithrian names over the centuries of Imperial rule, blending their ancestral naming traditions with those of the dominant culture. Lysean The Lyseans are a deeply religious and scholarly people whose culture is suffused with spiritual devotion and intellectual inquiry. Naming Conventions: Lysean names characteristically end in -an , -ur , -ik , or -el , giving them a distinctive cadence. The patronymic suffixes -ian or -yan denote descent (e.g., Gregorian, meaning son of Gregor ). Lyseans also employ honorific and religious earned names , bestowed upon individuals who achieve distinction in spiritual or scholarly pursuits. These earned names carry great prestige and may supplement or replace the bearer&#39;s birth name. Targ The Targ are a secretive and insular people whose naming practices reflect a deep cultural suspicion of external knowledge and power. Naming Conventions: The Targ have no traditional naming system in the conventional sense. Instead, each Targ possesses a secret true name known only to themselves and, in some traditions, to their closest family members. This true name is believed to hold power over the individual, and its revelation to outsiders is considered an act of profound vulnerability or betrayal. In daily life, Targ use simple nicknames -- short, functional appellations that carry no spiritual weight and can be discarded or changed at will. Shenti The Shenti are a passionate and expressive people whose culture draws heavily on celestial imagery, martial virtue, and the symbolism of fire and light. Naming Conventions: Shenti names are rich in vowels and draw their inspiration from: Celestial bodies -- sun, moon, stars, and constellations Virtues -- courage, wisdom, justice, and mercy Lions -- the lion being a central symbol in Shenti culture Fire -- representing passion, purification, and divine power Shenti naming includes the following particles: ibn -- meaning son of (e.g., Rashid ibn Khalil) satra -- meaning of the house of (e.g., Farah satra Amani) Tet The Tet are a devout people whose culture is deeply intertwined with religious tradition and the veneration of saints, prophets, and sacred virtues. Naming Conventions: Tet names reflect a connection to a saint, prophet, or virtue, serving as a constant reminder of the spiritual ideals the bearer is expected to embody. Naming particles include: ben -- meaning son of (e.g., David ben Solomon) bat -- meaning daughter of (e.g., Miriam bat Sarah) Lakandi The Lakandi are a fierce and uncompromising warrior culture in which personal honor, martial prowess, and the ability to endure hardship are the measures of an individual&#39;s worth. Naming Conventions: Lakandi names are built from short, harsh consonants and open vowels, producing names that are as blunt and direct as the people themselves. Uniquely among the cultures of Mithrapos , Lakandi names are not fixed at birth -- they change after trials , with individuals earning new names through feats of combat, endurance, or survival. These earned names typically depict violence, strength, or the natural forces the bearer has overcome. The Lakandi practice of naming carries a dark counterpart: cowards and oathbreakers are stripped of their names entirely, becoming Nameless . The Nameless are exiled from Lakandi society, cast out to wander without identity, kinship, or honor. To be made Nameless is considered a fate worse than death. Skiothan The Skiothans are a mystical and introspective people whose culture revolves around the concept of dreams, the afterlife, and the hidden nature of the self. Naming Conventions: Skiothan given names are short and vowel-rich, easy to speak and pleasant to the ear. However, beneath every Skiothan&#39;s public name lies a secret True Name , uttered only twice in the bearer&#39;s life -- once at birth and once at death. The True Name is believed to be the key by which the soul navigates the afterlife, known to the Skiothans as the Infinite Dream . To speak a Skiothan&#39;s True Name at any other time is to endanger their soul&#39;s passage into the Dream, and is considered an unspeakable violation. Grathar The Grathar are a physically imposing and culturally austere people, renowned for their strength, endurance, and directness. They are notable for carrying Ygrathen blood in their veins -- a heritage that manifests in their exceptional size and physical power. Naming Conventions: Grathar use singular, short, hard-sounding names that convey brute strength and natural force. Names like Krug, Brak, or Thond are typical -- monosyllabic, percussive, and utterly without ornamentation. The Grathar see no need for patronymics, clan names, or honorifics; a Grathar&#39;s name is their name, and it is enough. Massar The Massar are a culturally sophisticated people whose traditions bear the deep imprint of Argollean influence. Their civilization rose from the ruins of the Argollean Empire, and their language, art, and naming conventions all reflect this heritage. Naming Conventions: Massar names are Argollean-influenced, characterized by elongated vowels and a flowing, musical cadence. Naming particles include: net -- meaning house of (e.g., Amara net Solenn) sah -- meaning blood of (e.g., Kassim sah Durai) The Massar are also notable for their historical role as advisors within the Thunean Empire , where Massar counselors eventually orchestrated the overthrow of their Thune overlords. Vestari The Vestari are a proud and aristocratic people who trace their lineage to Bellasarius Valerian , the legendary founder of the Mithrian Empire . This claimed descent from the Empire&#39;s greatest hero gives the Vestari an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny. Physical Appearance: The Vestari are tall and narrow-faced with heavy brows and black hair, which is characteristically slicked back. Men carry heavy, well-groomed beards as a mark of dignity and status. Their skin ranges from olive to pale, and they favor ornate jewelry -- rings, chains, clasps, and brooches -- as expressions of wealth, lineage, and personal accomplishment. Naming Conventions: Vestari names are ornate and multi-syllabic, frequently incorporating references to virtues, ancestors, and religious concepts. A Vestari&#39;s full name is a declaration of heritage, a compressed genealogy that connects the bearer to their illustrious forebears and the spiritual ideals they are expected to uphold. Rinoan The Rinoans are a northern people -- tall, pale, and hardened by the harsh conditions of their homeland. They are organized into clans and warbands, and their culture values martial prowess, loyalty, and endurance above all else. Physical Appearance: Rinoans are pale and tall, with long pleated hair and beards. Their most striking feature is their piercing blue eyes , which are almost universal among the Rinoan people. A few rare individuals are born with pale yellow eyes , a trait that is regarded with superstition and awe -- such individuals are often believed to possess unusual gifts or to be marked by fate. Naming Conventions: Rinoan names are short and curt, reflecting the culture&#39;s no-nonsense character. Clan and warband names serve as identifiers of allegiance and kinship, and are appended to the individual&#39;s given name. Ancillary Races Beyond the sixteen human cultures, the world of Mithrapos is home to several non-human races, each with its own ancient history, biology, and relationship to the mortal world. Eladra The Eladra were once part of the Argollean Empire , where they played a central role in the discovery of the secrets of the cosmos, the Aurelion , and the Empyrean gods. The Eladra were the original practitioners of the sorcerous arts that would later be systematized as Gnostic Geometry , and their scholarship laid the foundations for much of what the Imperial Academy teaches today. Their civilization fell to ruin through the influence of the Elvora and the creeping corruption of Cthonic power. The precise nature of this fall is debated by scholars, but the result was the near-total destruction of Eladran culture and the scattering of its people. Those claiming Eladran heritage in the present day are almost invariably of mixed blood -- the product of centuries of intermarriage with humans and other peoples. Only a handful of full-blooded Eladra still live, and these survivors are extremely old and deeply reclusive, withdrawing from the affairs of the mortal world into isolation and silence. Physical Appearance: The Eladra are taller than humans, with lithe but muscular builds that combine grace with surprising physical strength. They possess a natural affinity for sorcery -- an innate sensitivity to the metaphysical axioms that govern reality -- which made them the foremost sorcerers of the ancient world. Elvora The Elvora are of Eladran descent, but they have been fundamentally changed by exposure to the chaotic energies of the Beyond . Where the Eladra sought to understand and codify the laws of reality, the Elvora plunged into the raw chaos that lies beneath those laws, and they were transformed by the experience. The Elvora achieved eternal life, but at a terrible cost: Females are barren -- unable to bear children, cutting off the possibility of natural reproduction Males are immortal -- unable to die of natural causes, condemned to endure the endless passage of time The Elvora are thus a slowly dying race, their numbers dwindling with each passing century as attrition, violence, and madness claim those who cannot be replaced. They are impossibly old, and the weight of millennia has left many with fractured memories and splintered personalities. An Elvoran who has lived for thousands of years may speak of ancient events with crystalline clarity while being unable to remember their own name from one day to the next. Physical Appearance: The Elvora are taller than humans and extremely muscular, their bodies hardened by centuries of existence and the transformative effects of chaotic energy. Their skin is pale white, and their eyes are solid black -- lacking iris, pupil, or sclera. They tend to be hairless, and many lack consideration for modesty or clothing, regarding such conventions as meaningless affectations of mortal culture. Ygrathen The Ygrathen are the oldest of all the races of Mithrapos -- ancient beyond reckoning, predating even the Eladra and the Argollean Empire . They are solitary beings by nature, coming together only to breed, which occurs every 33 years under specific cosmological conditions tied to the alignment of celestial bodies. The Ygrathen never formed their own civilization in any conventional sense. They are too solitary, too individualistic, and too prone to conflict with their own kind. Throughout their long history, the Ygrathen clashed amongst themselves as often as they fought against other races, preventing any lasting social organization from taking root. Physical Appearance: The Ygrathen are massive -- standing approximately 12 feet tall, with greenish or ochre skin and small tusks protruding from their lower jaws. Despite their brutish appearance, the Ygrathen possess powerful sorcery, and their magical abilities are among the most formidable in the world. The Ygrathen&#39;s war against the Argollean Empire was a cataclysmic conflict that left most of their kind dead or driven into hiding. The few survivors retreated into the most remote and inaccessible regions of Mithrapos, where they remain to this day -- hidden, diminished, but not extinct. The Grathar people carry Ygrathen blood in their veins, a heritage that accounts for their exceptional size and strength. Thune The Thune were created by the Argolleans as slave soldiers to fight against the Ygrathen -- living weapons bred for war. They are reptilian in appearance and possess an alien cunning and intellect that sets them apart from the other races of Mithrapos . The Thune are wicked and violent by nature and by design, embodying the Cthonic faith in its most brutal form: the strongest consume and rule the weakest. The Thune once ruled the Thunean Empire , a dominion built on conquest, cruelty, and the subjugation of all other peoples within their reach. This empire was eventually overthrown by Massar advisors -- counselors who had been brought into the Thunean court and who used their position to orchestrate the empire&#39;s downfall from within. In the present day, the Thune are found only in rare pockets -- scattered remnants of their former empire, hiding in remote and inhospitable regions. They are savage but patient, biding their time for what they call the Awakening -- a prophesied event in which the Thune will rise again to reclaim their former dominion. Physical Appearance: The Thune come in various shapes and sizes, the product of extensive breeding programs conducted over millennia. Some are small and swift, bred for scouting and infiltration; others are massive and heavily armored, designed for frontline combat. All share the fundamental reptilian characteristics of scaled skin, cold blood, and predatory instinct. Beastmen The Beastmen are a collection of species of monstrous humans -- not a single race but a diverse array of twisted, mutated beings united only by their shared origin and their universal reputation for savagery. They were created by the Massaran Empire as the core of its armies, purpose-bred for war through sorcerous experimentation and selective breeding. After the defeat of the Massaran Empire, the Beastmen were scattered, left without purpose or direction. They have since devolved into roving warbands and feral packs, preying on the weak and the unwary. They are exceedingly cruel and violent, feared and reviled by all other peoples of Mithrapos . Physical Appearance: The appearances of Beastmen differ wildly from one individual to the next, but all carry a twisted and mutated animal aspect -- horns, fangs, claws, fur, scales, or other bestial features grafted onto a roughly humanoid frame. No two Beastmen are exactly alike, and the variety of their mutations reflects the chaotic and uncontrolled nature of the sorcery that created them. See Also Mithrian Empire Argolle Eladra Elvora Ygrathen Thune Beastmen Bellasarius Valerian Kolani Irregulars Cthonic Empyrean Aurelion Gnostic Geometry Thunean Empire Massaran Empire Measure and the Scale"},{"slug":"rinoan","title":"Rinoan","category":"lore","tags":"culture rinoan naming human tribal warrior northern mercenary mithrapos confederation","text":"Rinoan The Rinoans are a fierce, warlike confederation of tribal peoples who inhabit the northern shores of Mithrapos . Organized into clans and warbands, their culture values martial prowess, loyalty, and endurance above all else. Few Rinoans are seen outside their homelands, though some mercenary bands have made a name for themselves in the wider world. Physical Appearance Rinoans are pale and tall , with long pleated hair and beards worn in elaborate styles that denote clan affiliation, status, and personal achievement. Their most striking feature is their piercing blue eyes , which are almost universal among the Rinoan people. A few rare individuals are born with pale yellow eyes -- a trait that is regarded with superstition and awe. Such individuals are often believed to possess unusual gifts or to be marked by fate, and they occupy a special place in Rinoan culture -- respected, feared, and watched with particular attention. Culture and Values The Rinoans are organized into clans and warbands , and their culture revolves around martial prowess, loyalty to one&#39;s sworn companions, and the ability to endure hardship without complaint. The harsh conditions of their northern homeland -- cold seas, rocky shores, and unforgiving winters -- have produced a people who regard comfort as weakness and struggle as the natural condition of life. Few Rinoans are seen outside their homelands. They are an insular people, suspicious of outsiders and contemptuous of softer civilizations. Those who do venture beyond Rinoan territory tend to be warriors -- mercenary bands that have made a name for themselves through ferocity, discipline, and absolute reliability. A Rinoan mercenary who gives their word will keep it unto death; this reputation makes Rinoan warriors highly sought after despite their limited numbers. The Rinoan confederation is not a unified state but a loose alliance of clans that cooperate against external threats while maintaining fierce internal rivalries. Clan warfare is a constant feature of Rinoan life, though it follows elaborate codes of conduct that outsiders rarely understand. Naming Conventions Rinoan names are short and curt , reflecting the culture&#39;s no-nonsense character. Names are functional, direct, and stripped of ornamentation -- a Rinoan name says what it needs to say and nothing more. Clan and warband names serve as identifiers of allegiance and kinship, and are appended to the individual&#39;s given name. A Rinoan warrior introduced by both given name and clan name is declaring not only their identity but their loyalties -- whom they fight with, whom they answer to, and whom they will die for. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire beyond Rinoan borders"},{"slug":"sacking-of-crossings","title":"The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY)","category":"lore","tags":"event history beastmen backlands crossings scalpers imperial-bounty catastrophe","text":"The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY) The Sacking of Crossings (377 IY) was one of the most devastating and consequential events in recent Imperial history. A massive Beastmen horde descended on the northern town of Crossings , overwhelming its defenders, razing the settlement, and slaughtering or scattering its people. The destruction of Crossings led directly to the collapse of Imperial authority in the surrounding region and set in motion the chain of events that has plunged the Backlands into their current state of lawlessness and anarchy. Crossings did not fall in a day. It fell in the silence of senators, in the turning away of eyes, in the fortunes of the governor rising even as the gates were breached. -- Senator Cassius The Sacking The Beastmen horde that descended on Crossings was of a size and ferocity that overwhelmed the town&#39;s defenses. The Beastmen -- descendants of the legions scattered during the Empyrean War -- had gathered in unprecedented numbers, driven by forces and motivations that remain poorly understood. The town&#39;s garrison, already undermanned and under-supplied, could not hold. Crossings was razed. Its people were slaughtered or driven into the wilderness. The town that had served as a trading hub and frontier outpost for generations was destroyed in a matter of days. Institutional Failure As Senator Cassius&#39;s damning words make clear, the Sacking was not the result of an overwhelming external threat alone. It was enabled by the corruption, negligence, and complicity of Imperial officials: Senators who looked the other way -- Warnings about frontier defenses were ignored by a Senate preoccupied with factional politics and personal enrichment Governors who enriched themselves -- Provincial officials who diverted military resources and tax revenue to their own benefit while defenses crumbled The turning away of eyes -- A systematic failure of institutional responsibility at every level, from the court in Mithra City to the provincial bureaucracy The fall of Crossings was a failure of the Empire&#39;s institutions as much as it was a failure of its armies. Senator Cassius&#39;s accusation -- that the governor&#39;s fortune rose even as the gates were breached -- points to a level of corruption that borders on complicity. The Imperial Bounty In response to the Sacking, Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus issued an Imperial scalp bounty on Beastmen . The bounty was intended to suppress the beastman threat by unleashing the profit motive against them. Anyone who delivered beastman scalps to Imperial agents would be paid from the treasury. The consequences were catastrophic. The bounty unleashed a wave of mercenaries, deserters, and killers into the Backlands . These individuals -- collectively known as Scalpers -- poured into the frontier provinces in pursuit of bounty money. While beastman activity near settled areas has decreased, the influx of violent fortune-seekers has created new and terrible problems: Scalper gangs prey on travelers and settlers as readily as on beastmen The bounty economy attracts the worst elements of Imperial society Fraud is rampant -- human and non-beastman scalps are passed off as legitimate claims The violence of the Scalpers has made large areas of the Backlands more dangerous, not less Consequences The Sacking of Crossings and its aftermath have fundamentally reshaped the Backlands : Collapse of Imperial authority -- The destruction of Crossings destroyed the last pretense of effective imperial governance in the region The Scalper economy -- The Imperial Bounty created an entire economic ecosystem built on violence Power vacuum -- The absence of imperial authority has allowed local strongmen like Governor Drussus to consolidate independent power bases Refugee crisis -- Survivors of Crossings scattered across the Backlands, adding to the displaced populations that strain the resources of remaining settlements The garrison recall -- The Emperor&#39;s subsequent recall of armies to face the Skiothan threat (378 IY) compounded the crisis, stripping the Backlands of whatever military protection remained The Backlands have never recovered. The region remains a lawless frontier where Imperial law is a distant memory and survival is the only currency that matters. See Also Crossings -- the town that was destroyed Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus -- issued the Imperial Bounty Scalper Gangs -- consequence of the bounty Governor Drussus -- provincial strongman The Backlands -- the region devastated by the aftermath The Empyrean War -- the war that created the Beastmen threat History of Mithrapos The Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"shenti","title":"Shenti","category":"lore","tags":"culture shenti naming human massar celestial shent tulmuk cthonic","text":"Shenti The Shenti are a passionate and expressive people whose culture draws heavily on celestial imagery, martial virtue, and the symbolism of fire and light. Former subjects of the Massaran Empire , the Shenti bear the imprint of Massar influence even centuries after that empire&#39;s fall -- in their art, their architecture, their spiritual traditions, and their naming conventions. Physical Appearance The Shenti are characterized by tan skin and dark eyes. Their complexion reflects their homeland&#39;s climate -- warmer and more arid than the Imperial heartland -- and their dark eyes are a near-universal feature that gives Shenti faces a distinctive intensity. Culture and Values The Shenti were once subjects of the Massaran Empire , and Massar influence is still felt in every aspect of Shenti culture. The sorcerer-kings of Massar left a deep imprint on the peoples they ruled, and the Shenti have never fully shed the cultural inheritance of that older civilization -- its aesthetic sensibilities, its hierarchical instincts, its relationship to power and authority. The Fall of Shent The Province of Shent has fallen to Cthonic Tulmuk barbarian tribes . These Cthonic -worshipping invaders have overrun the Shenti homeland, driving its people from their ancestral territory and destroying or corrupting the institutions that once defined Shenti life. The fall of Shent is one of the Empire&#39;s most significant territorial losses, and it represents a catastrophe for the Shenti people -- the destruction of everything they built over centuries. Despite this catastrophe, many Shenti still live within the Empire . Displaced from their homeland, Shenti communities have established themselves in cities and provinces throughout Imperial territory. They carry their culture with them -- their traditions, their naming practices, their spiritual devotion -- maintaining identity in exile in much the same way the Avari have done in the Ashward . Naming Conventions Shenti names are rich in vowels and draw their inspiration from: Celestial bodies -- the sun, moon, stars, and constellations, reflecting the Shenti fascination with the heavens Virtues -- courage, wisdom, justice, and mercy, naming children after the qualities they are expected to embody Lions -- the lion being a central symbol in Shenti culture, representing strength, nobility, and royal authority Fire -- representing passion, purification, and divine power Shenti naming includes the following particles: ibn -- meaning son of (e.g., Rashid ibn Khalil) satra -- meaning of the house of (e.g., Farah satra Amani) See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures massar -- The empire that once ruled the Shenti mithrian-empire -- The empire where Shenti now live cthonic-faith -- The faith of the Tulmuk invaders who took Shent"},{"slug":"skiothan","title":"Skiothan","category":"lore","tags":"culture skiothan naming human nomadic horse-warriors grathe-steppe true-name infinite-dream raiders","text":"Skiothan The Skiothans are a mystical and introspective people whose culture revolves around the concept of dreams, the afterlife, and the hidden nature of the self. Despite their philosophical depth, they are also fearsome nomadic horse warriors who raid the western provinces of the Mithrian Empire from the vast Grathe Steppe , and who believe themselves superior to all other races. Physical Appearance The Skiothans are tall with dark hair and dark eyes. Their builds are lean and powerful, shaped by a lifetime in the saddle -- the horse is not merely a tool of Skiothan warfare but an extension of Skiothan identity. Culture and Values The Skiothans are nomadic horse warriors who roam the Grathe Steppe , the vast grassland that lies beyond the Empire&#39;s western frontier. They raid the western provinces with devastating effectiveness, their mounted tactics overwhelming the heavier but less mobile Imperial formations sent to stop them. The Skiothans believe themselves superior to all other races -- a conviction that is not mere arrogance but a deeply held spiritual belief rooted in their cosmology. In the Skiothan worldview, they are the chosen people, the riders who will gallop through the Infinite Dream when all other peoples have been forgotten. The Infinite Dream The Skiothan afterlife is called the Infinite Dream -- a spiritual realm that the soul enters upon death. The passage into the Infinite Dream is not automatic; it requires navigation, and the key to that navigation is the bearer&#39;s True Name. Without their True Name, a Skiothan soul wanders lost, unable to find its way into the Dream. With it, the passage is assured. Naming Conventions Skiothan given names are short and vowel-rich , easy to speak and pleasant to the ear. These public names are used in daily life and carry no particular spiritual weight. However, beneath every Skiothan&#39;s public name lies a secret True Name , uttered only twice in the bearer&#39;s life -- once at birth and once at death . The True Name is believed to be the key by which the soul navigates the afterlife. To speak a Skiothan&#39;s True Name at any other time is to endanger their soul&#39;s passage into the Infinite Dream, and is considered an unspeakable violation -- an act of spiritual murder more heinous than physical killing. The Skiothan Threat The Skiothan raids on the western provinces have escalated to the point of existential threat. In 378 IY , the Emperor recalled armies from the provinces -- including the garrisons of the Backlands -- to fight the Skiothan threat. This withdrawal left frontier provinces like Argolle undermanned and poorly defended, effectively abandoning them to their fate in order to address the Skiothan danger closer to the Imperial heartland. The Emperor&#39;s decision reflects the severity of the Skiothan threat: the raids are not merely border skirmishes but a sustained military campaign that threatens the Empire&#39;s core territories. The Skiothans&#39; mobility, their knowledge of the Grathe Steppe, and their willingness to fight a war of maneuver against an empire built for siege and occupation make them one of the most dangerous enemies the Empire currently faces. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire the Skiothans raid grathar -- The other people of the Grathe Steppe the-backlands -- A province abandoned due to the Skiothan threat history-of-mithrapos -- The broader context of the Skiothan wars"},{"slug":"targ","title":"Targ","category":"lore","tags":"race culture targ naming magically-created imperial-academy the-eater rebellion slaves citizens","text":"Targ The Targ are a magically created race, brought into existence by the Imperial College to supplement the armies of the Mithrian Empire . Once slaves, now citizens, the Targ occupy a unique and often uncomfortable position within Imperial society -- a people who were designed as tools and who fought a bloody war to be recognized as persons. Physical Appearance The Targ are tall with ochre to grey skin and light eyes. They are stronger than men , with powerful builds that reflect the martial purpose for which they were created. Their appearance is distinctive and immediately recognizable -- the skin coloration, the light eyes set against darker features, the sheer physical mass that sets them apart from baseline humans. Culture and Values The Targ possess a vicious streak and hot tempers -- traits that were deliberately bred into them by their creators at the Imperial Academy , who wanted soldiers, not scholars. These characteristics remain even now, generations after emancipation, and they continue to shape Targ culture and the way other peoples perceive them. Once slaves, the Targ are now citizens with their own communities within the Empire. The road from property to personhood was paved with blood -- the Targ Rebellion of 261 IY was one of the most traumatic events in Imperial history, and its resolution fundamentally changed the legal and moral landscape of the Empire. The Targ Rebellion (261 IY) The Targ rose in violent revolt against the Empire that had enslaved them. Their leader, known only as The Eater , led a devastating campaign that reached Mithra City itself. The Eater sacked the capital and slew Emperor Antonius , an act of violence that shook the Empire to its foundations. Peace was eventually brokered by High Mage Symander of the Imperial Academy. Under the terms of the settlement, the Targ were granted full citizenship under the Measure and the Scale , transforming them from property into people in the eyes of Imperial law. Naming Conventions The Targ have no traditional naming system in the conventional sense. Their naming practices reflect a deep cultural suspicion of external knowledge and power -- a suspicion born from generations of enslavement during which their creators held absolute authority over every aspect of their existence, including their identities. Each Targ possesses a secret true name known only to themselves and, in some traditions, to their closest family members. This true name is believed to hold power over the individual, and its revelation to outsiders is considered an act of profound vulnerability or betrayal. The true name is guarded with fierce intensity -- to know a Targ&#39;s true name is to hold a weapon against them. In daily life, Targ use simple nicknames -- short, functional appellations that carry no spiritual weight and can be discarded or changed at will. These nicknames serve the practical purpose of identification without exposing the bearer to the risks associated with their true name&#39;s revelation. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire that created and then emancipated the Targ imperial-academy -- The institution that created the Targ history-of-mithrapos -- The Targ Rebellion in broader context Measure and the Scale -- The legal framework that granted Targ citizenship"},{"slug":"tet","title":"Tet","category":"lore","tags":"culture tet naming human tezerat massar superstitious enador crescent-rebellion measure-and-scale","text":"Tet The Tet are a devout people from the Tezerat Plateau , whose culture is deeply intertwined with religious tradition and the veneration of saints, prophets, and sacred virtues. Former slaves of the Massaran Empire , the Tet carry the marks of that subjugation in their fierce independence and deep superstition -- a people shaped by suffering who found meaning through faith. Physical Appearance The Tet have tan skin, variable eyes (ranging across a wider spectrum than most peoples of Mithrapos ), and dark hair. Their appearance reflects the harsh, elevated terrain of the Tezerat Plateau -- a landscape that demands endurance and produces a resilient, weather-hardened people. Culture and Values The Tet are deeply superstitious , a trait that pervades every aspect of daily life. Signs, omens, prophecies, and portents carry tremendous weight in Tet culture, and decisions -- from the mundane to the momentous -- are often guided by interpretations of the supernatural rather than by purely rational calculation. Former Massar Slaves The Tet were former Massar slaves , subjugated by the sorcerer-kings of the Massaran Empire and held in bondage for generations. The experience of enslavement has left an indelible mark on Tet culture -- a fierce determination never to be subjugated again, combined with a spiritual framework that interprets suffering as a test of faith and liberation as divine reward. Enador and the Measure and the Scale The Prophet Enador discovered the Measure and the Scale on the Tezerat Plateau -- the sacred texts that would become the foundation of Empyrean faith and the moral and legal framework of the civilization that followed. This discovery gives the Tezerat Plateau and its people a unique significance in the religious history of Mithrapos . The Tet regard themselves as the people among whom the divine truth was revealed, and this belief shapes their sense of spiritual identity. The Second Crescent Rebellion The Second Crescent Rebellion led to the Tet achieving independence from the Empire . This rebellion -- driven by the Tet&#39;s fierce independence, their religious convictions, and their unwillingness to submit to distant imperial authority -- resulted in the Tezerat Plateau being granted a degree of autonomy that few other Imperial provinces have achieved. The rebellion demonstrated that the Tet&#39;s devotion to their faith and their freedom exceeded their willingness to submit to Imperial control. Naming Conventions Tet names reflect a connection to a saint, prophet, or virtue , serving as a constant reminder of the spiritual ideals the bearer is expected to embody. Every Tet name is a declaration of faith -- an invocation of the sacred that the bearer carries with them through life. Naming particles include: ben -- meaning son of (e.g., David ben Solomon) bat -- meaning daughter of (e.g., Miriam bat Sarah) See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures massar -- The empire that once enslaved the Tet Measure and the Scale -- The sacred texts discovered on the Tezerat Plateau Prophet Enador -- The prophet who discovered the Measure and the Scale empyrean-faith -- The faith that arose from the Tet homeland mithrian-empire -- The empire from which the Tet won independence"},{"slug":"the-anthyllium","title":"The Anthyllium","category":"lore","tags":"anthyllium grimoire gnostic-geometry nine-fold enador imperial-academy measure-and-the-scale sorcery axioms aurelion","text":"The Anthyllium The Anthyllium is the ancient grimoire describing the nine-fold geometric patterns that govern reality — the foundational text of Gnostic Geometry and one of the most important documents in the history of the Mithrian Empire . Discovered alongside the Measure and the Scale by the Prophet Enador , the Anthyllium contains the formulae still used by the Imperial Academy to train its gnostic geometers and to regulate the practice of structured sorcery throughout the Empire. If the Measure and the Scale is the moral constitution of Mithrian civilization — the document that tells the faithful how to live — the Anthyllium is its arcane constitution — the document that tells sorcerers how to reshape reality without destroying it. Contents The Nine-Fold Geometric Patterns The Anthyllium describes in meticulous detail the nine-fold geometric patterns that underlie the structure of reality. These patterns are not mere mathematical abstractions but the actual architectural blueprints of the cosmos — the geometric relationships that The Aurelion embedded in the fabric of reality during its sacrifice, and that determine how matter, energy, space, time, and metaphysical forces interact. Each of the nine patterns governs a different aspect of reality, and the relationships between them — the ways in which they combine, intersect, reinforce, and counteract each other — determine the full complexity of the natural and supernatural world. The Anthyllium maps these relationships with a precision that has never been equaled, providing the theoretical framework that makes the systematic practice of Gnostic Geometry possible. Formulae of Sorcery Beyond the theoretical description of the nine-fold patterns, the Anthyllium contains practical formulae — specific geometric constructions (sigils), resonance patterns (spoken formulae), and mental disciplines that allow trained practitioners to manipulate the metaphysical axioms encoded in the patterns. These formulae are the working tools of gnostic geometers — the specific techniques by which abstract geometric knowledge is translated into practical magical effect. The formulae in the Anthyllium are not spells in the folkloric sense. They are more analogous to engineering specifications — precise, technical documents that describe exactly how to construct a sigil, exactly how to calibrate a resonance, exactly how to discipline the mind for a specific manipulation, and exactly what effects will result if the procedure is followed correctly. They are also explicit about the consequences of error, which can range from the merely painful to the catastrophically destructive. A Structured, Lawful Cosmos The Anthyllium&#39;s deepest teaching — the philosophical foundation upon which all its practical formulae rest — is that the cosmos is a structured, lawful creation. According to the Anthyllium, sorcery is the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded throughout reality — axioms that exist because The Aurelion designed the cosmos with intention and purpose. The cosmos is not chaotic, arbitrary, or random; it is a mathematical construct, built on principles that can be discovered, understood, and applied. This teaching aligns the Anthyllium closely with the Empyrean Faith &#39;s understanding of the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice — the belief that the supreme designer created a cosmos of order, meaning, and purpose. The Anthyllium does not explicitly endorse Empyrean theology, but its foundational assumption — that reality is structured and lawful — is compatible with the Empyrean worldview and incompatible with the Cthonic Faith &#39;s emphasis on chaos, contest, and the ultimate primacy of will over law. Discovery The Anthyllium was discovered by the Prophet Enador alongside the Measure and the Scale — the sacred scripture of Seros . The dual discovery is one of the pivotal moments in the history of the known world. Enador&#39;s recovery of the Measure and the Scale provided the spiritual authority and moral framework that united the Empyrean faithful. His simultaneous recovery of the Anthyllium provided the arcane knowledge and practical power that enabled those faithful to challenge and ultimately overthrow the Massaran Empire and its Sorcerer Kings . The circumstances of the discovery — where the texts were found, how they came to be in the same location, whether they were deliberately placed together or whether their proximity was coincidental — are the subject of extensive debate among scholars and theologians. The orthodox position of the Thousand Temples holds that Seros guided Enador to both texts, that their co-location was divinely arranged, and that the Aurelion intended for moral wisdom and arcane knowledge to be reunited at the moment when the world most needed both. Current Status The Anthyllium is held by the Imperial Academy , which treats it as both a sacred text and a state secret. Access to the original document is restricted to the highest-ranking members of the Academy&#39;s faculty, and the formulae contained within it are disseminated to students only in carefully controlled portions, calibrated to each student&#39;s level of training and demonstrated competence. The Imperial Academy retains strict control over the Anthyllium and the knowledge it contains for both practical and political reasons. Practically, the formulae of Gnostic Geometry are extraordinarily dangerous in untrained hands, and unrestricted access to the Anthyllium would inevitably lead to catastrophic magical accidents. Politically, the Academy&#39;s monopoly on gnostic geometric knowledge is one of the pillars of Imperial power — a monopoly that the Academy, the Thousand Temples , and the Imperial government all have strong incentives to maintain. Copies of portions of the Anthyllium exist in various forms — student texts, reference manuals, classified military documents — but the complete, original text is singular and irreplaceable. Its security is a matter of the highest Imperial priority, and the measures taken to protect it are among the most sophisticated in the Empire. Relationship to the Measure and the Scale The Anthyllium and the Measure and the Scale were discovered together and are understood together — the twin pillars of Mithrian civilization, one moral and one arcane. The Measure and the Scale tells the faithful how the cosmos should be inhabited — with virtue, justice, duty, and devotion. The Anthyllium tells them how the cosmos is constructed — with geometry, axioms, and mathematical relationships that can be perceived and manipulated. Together, the two texts provide a complete framework for engaging with reality: the Measure and the Scale addresses the soul, and the Anthyllium addresses the mind. The Empyrean faithful believe that both are necessary — that arcane knowledge without moral guidance leads to the kind of tyranny practiced by the Sorcerer Kings , and that moral conviction without practical power leads to helplessness in the face of evil. See Also Gnostic Geometry The Measure and the Scale Enador The Aurelion Imperial Academy Empyrean Faith Seros Massaran Empire Sorcerer Kings The Veil Magic and Sorcery Mithrian Empire Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"the-aurelion","title":"The Aurelion","category":"lore","tags":"aurelion cosmology creation sacrifice sorcery souls empyrean cthonic empty-throne","text":"The Aurelion The Aurelion is the supreme designer of the cosmos — the singular, transcendent being whose self-sacrifice created all of reality. Both the Empyrean Faith and the Cthonic Faith agree on the fundamental fact of the Aurelion&#39;s existence and sacrifice, making this one of the very few points of theological consensus between the two irreconcilable traditions. Where they diverge — profoundly and irreconcilably — is in their interpretation of why the Aurelion sacrificed itself, what the sacrifice was intended to achieve, and what obligations the sacrifice places upon living beings. The Sacrifice The Aurelion&#39;s self-sacrifice is the foundational event of the cosmos — the singular act from which all of reality proceeds. Before the sacrifice, there was the Aurelion alone. After the sacrifice, there was everything else: matter, energy, space, time, souls, gods, and the living beings that populate the cosmos. The Aurelion did not create the world through an act of will or craftsmanship, as a potter shapes clay. The Aurelion became the world — its essence, its substance, its animating force — by destroying itself utterly and allowing its own being to diffuse throughout the void, transforming formless potential into structured, living reality. This is the central mystery of all theology in the known world: the Aurelion is simultaneously absent and omnipresent. It no longer exists as a discrete entity — it sacrificed that existence irrevocably — and yet its essence permeates every particle of the cosmos, every living being, every natural law, every metaphysical axiom. The Aurelion is the cosmos, and the cosmos is the Aurelion&#39;s corpse, its legacy, its final gift. The Essence The Aurelion&#39;s essence permeates the cosmos and all living things. This is not a metaphor but a metaphysical reality with measurable consequences. Every living being possesses a soul — a fragment of the Aurelion&#39;s original being, a spark of the divine substance that animated the supreme designer before the sacrifice. This soul is what distinguishes the living from the dead, the conscious from the inert, the being capable of moral choice from the object that simply exists. The presence of the Aurelion&#39;s essence throughout the cosmos is also what makes sorcery possible. The practice of Gnostic Geometry , the channeling of The Flame , the manipulation of The Veil — all forms of magic ultimately derive their power from the Aurelion&#39;s essence, which permeates the fabric of reality and can be accessed, channeled, and directed by those with the knowledge and will to do so. Sorcery is, in a very real sense, the manipulation of the Aurelion&#39;s remains. Interpretations of the Sacrifice The Empyrean Interpretation The Empyrean Faith teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed itself to purge the cosmos of entropy and evil — to separate light from darkness, order from chaos, virtue from vice. In this interpretation, the sacrifice was an act of supreme moral purpose: the Aurelion saw that the original state of the cosmos was a formless tangle of good and evil, light and dark, order and chaos, and chose to destroy itself in order to impose a moral structure upon reality. The separation of light from darkness — the foundational act that Seros completed and maintains — is the direct consequence of the Aurelion&#39;s sacrificial purpose. In the Empyrean understanding, the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice places a moral obligation upon all living beings. Because the cosmos was created through an act of supreme selflessness, the beings who inhabit it are called to emulate that selflessness — to orient their lives toward order, virtue, and the service of others, to resist the entropy and chaos that the sacrifice was designed to overcome. The Measure and the Scale is the codification of this obligation, the moral law that translates the Aurelion&#39;s sacrificial purpose into practical guidance for daily life. The Cthonic Interpretation The Cthonic Faith teaches that the Aurelion sacrificed itself to eliminate weakness — to create a cosmos defined by contest, where only the powerful survive and the weak are rightfully consumed. In this interpretation, the sacrifice was not an act of compassion but an act of refinement: the Aurelion destroyed itself to create a crucible, a testing ground where the strong would prove their worth through struggle, conquest, and the domination of the weak. The cosmos is not a garden to be tended but an arena to be fought in, and the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice created that arena deliberately. In the Cthonic understanding, the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice places no moral obligation upon living beings — it places a test. The cosmos rewards strength, cunning, and the will to dominate, and punishes weakness, mercy, and submission. The Cthonic gods are the divine exemplars of this principle — beings who have achieved power through contest and who demand that their followers do the same. The Aurelion did not sacrifice itself so that its children could be gentle; it sacrificed itself so that its children could be strong. The Mystical Interpretation A third interpretation, less widely held but persistent among certain philosophical and mystical traditions, holds that the Aurelion sacrificed itself to experience the full spectrum of existence — to become All. In this reading, the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice was neither moral nor competitive but experiential: the supreme designer, existing alone in perfect unity, chose to shatter itself into infinite fragments so that it could experience reality from every possible perspective simultaneously — as light and darkness, as predator and prey, as the saint and the sinner, as every living being that has ever existed or will ever exist. In the mystical understanding, every soul is the Aurelion experiencing itself from a unique vantage point. Every act of kindness and every act of cruelty, every moment of joy and every moment of suffering, is the Aurelion&#39;s experience. The cosmos is not a creation but a self-exploration — the Aurelion&#39;s attempt to know itself through the infinite diversity of lived experience. This interpretation is embraced by followers of The Mystical tradition and exists at the margins of both Empyrean and Cthonic orthodoxy. The Empty Throne Central to all theological discussion of the Aurelion is the image of the Empty Throne — the seat of cosmic authority that the Aurelion occupied before the sacrifice and that has remained vacant ever since. The Empty Throne is perhaps the most powerful theological symbol in the known world, because both the Empyrean Faith and the Cthonic Faith acknowledge it, and both draw fundamentally different conclusions from its emptiness. For the Empyrean faithful, the Empty Throne is a symbol of the Aurelion&#39;s supreme sacrifice — the seat from which the supreme designer ruled the cosmos, voluntarily abandoned so that the cosmos could exist. The emptiness of the throne is sacred, a permanent reminder that the highest power in the universe chose service over dominion, self-destruction over self-preservation. Seros guards the throne but does not sit in it — he is the steward of the Aurelion&#39;s legacy, not its replacement. For the Cthonic faithful, the Empty Throne is an invitation — a vacancy waiting to be filled by whoever proves strong enough to claim it. The Aurelion destroyed itself, and its throne stands empty. The cosmos has no ruler, no supreme authority, no final arbiter — and the contest to fill that void is the fundamental drama of existence. The Cthonic gods compete for the throne, and the Awakening — the prophesied return of the Cthonic gods to the material world — may be understood as the opening move in the final contest for cosmic supremacy. See Also Empyrean Faith Cthonic Faith Seros The Measure and the Scale The Veil The Flame Gnostic Geometry The Awakening The Mystical Cthonic Pantheon Empyrean Pantheon"},{"slug":"the-awakening","title":"The Awakening","category":"lore","tags":"awakening cthonic prophecy resurrection argolle nethercity crossings great-teacher erenthis cthonic-corruption","text":"The Awakening The Awakening is the prophesied future event in Cthonic theology when the Cthonic gods will return to the material world and the faithful will enjoy true bodily resurrection — not the spiritual afterlife promised by the Empyrean Faith but a physical, corporeal restoration of the flesh, a triumphant reversal of death itself. For most of the known world, the Awakening is a theological concept — a distant eschatological promise that motivates Cthonic worship but has no immediate, observable reality. In the Province of Argolle , in the year 380 IY, it is an event in progress. Cthonic Theology of the Awakening In Cthonic eschatology, the current state of the cosmos is not the final state. The separation of light from darkness accomplished by Seros , the moral order codified in the Measure and the Scale , the political dominion of the Mithrian Empire — all of these are temporary arrangements, impositions of Empyrean order upon a cosmos that is fundamentally Cthonic in nature. The Awakening is the prophesied moment when these impositions will be swept away, when the Cthonic gods will break free of whatever constraints bind them, return to the material world in their full divine power, and establish a new cosmic order based on strength, contest, and the triumph of the will. For the Cthonic faithful, the Awakening is not a catastrophe but a liberation — the long-awaited reversal of the cosmic injustice perpetrated by Seros and the Empyrean order. The faithful who have endured persecution, who have kept the old rites alive in secret, who have refused to bow before the Winged Sun despite centuries of suppression — these are the ones who will be rewarded when the Cthonic gods return. True bodily resurrection — not the vague spiritual afterlife of Empyrean theology but the actual, physical restoration of the dead — is the Awakening&#39;s ultimate promise. The Awakening in Argolle An Event in Progress What makes the Awakening uniquely terrifying in the current era is that it is no longer merely a theological concept. In the Province of Argolle , 380 IY, the signs of the Awakening are not prophetic speculation but observable phenomena. The Cthonic Corruption that permeates the region — the twisted creatures, the corrupted landscapes, the palpable sense of wrongness that hangs over the backlands — is not random or natural. It is the leading edge of the Awakening, the first tremors of a cosmic event that threatens to tear the fabric of the material world and permit the return of forces that have been absent for millennia. The Nethercity The Nethercity beneath Crossings is a prepared vessel for the Awakening — a vast, ancient subterranean complex that was designed or adapted to serve as the physical infrastructure through which the Awakening will occur. The Nethercity is not merely an archaeological curiosity or a dungeon to be explored; it is a machine, a metaphysical engine whose purpose is to facilitate the return of the Cthonic gods or their agents to the material world. The exact mechanisms by which the Nethercity accomplishes this purpose are not fully understood, but the scale and sophistication of the complex — along with the intensity of the Cthonic Corruption emanating from its depths — leave little doubt about its function. The Great Teacher The Great Teacher rests dormant in the depths of the Nethercity — an entity of immense power and unknown nature whose slumber is the thin barrier between the current state of affairs and the full realization of the Awakening. The Great Teacher&#39;s identity is unclear — whether it is one of the Cthonic gods themselves, an avatar, a herald, or something else entirely remains a matter of speculation and dread. What is known is that it is there, that it is stirring, and that the increasing urgency of Cthonic-corrupted creatures in Argolle correlates with its restless slumber. Erenthis Disturbance The Erenthis root network — the vast, living mycorrhizal web that connects the forests of Argolle and serves as a sensory and communication system for the natural world — has sensed increasing disturbance for two years. The Erenthis is not a conscious entity in the way that mortal beings are conscious, but it is aware in its own fashion, and the signals it transmits through its network have grown increasingly agitated, urgent, and distressed. Druids and naturalists who commune with the Erenthis report a consistent message: something is waking up beneath the ground, and the natural world is afraid. Cthonic Creature Urgency Cthonic-corrupted creatures throughout Argolle have begun behaving with increasing urgency — not merely the mindless aggression that characterizes corrupted wildlife but directed, purposeful behavior that suggests coordination, intelligence, or at the very least a shared imperative driving them toward a common goal. Corrupted beasts are moving toward Crossings and the Nethercity beneath it. Nests of corrupted creatures are growing larger and more organized. Attacks on settlements are increasing in frequency and ferocity. The pattern is unmistakable to those with eyes to see it: the corrupted world is preparing for something. The Convergence The Awakening is intimately connected to the Convergence — the multi-layered crisis currently unfolding in Argolle that threatens to overwhelm the province&#39;s capacity to respond. The political instability, the military overextension, the religious tensions, the economic pressures — all of these are either caused by or exacerbated by the approaching Awakening, and all of them conspire to ensure that when the Awakening reaches its crisis point, the province will be at its most vulnerable and least prepared. See Also Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon Argolle Crossings The Nethercity The Erenthis Cthonic Corruption The Convergence Problem Seros The Aurelion Empyrean Faith The Veil"},{"slug":"the-beyond","title":"The Beyond","category":"lore","tags":"lore cosmology metaphysics beyond veil aurelion sorcery cthonic demons planes gods","text":"The Beyond What lies beyond the Veil is not another world. It is every other world -- tangled together, pressing against the membrane of reality like fingers against wet cloth. When the Aurelion died, it tore a hole in that cloth. The fingers came through. The Beyond is the multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten and ancient gods, and raw metaphysical potential that exists on the other side of the Veil . It is not a single place but a vast, incomprehensible expanse of realities that press against the mortal world, seeking entry, seeking worship, seeking consumption. When the Aurelion sacrificed itself, it created a cosmic wound in the Veil, allowing the realities of the Beyond to influence the mortal world in ways that were not previously possible. At a Glance Detail Description Type The totality of reality beyond Mithrapos and the material plane. It is not ordered, not comprehensible in mortal terms, and not safe. The entities that inhabit the Beyond range from mindless currents of raw metaphysical energy to ancient gods whose worship predates recorded history to alien intelligences that defy classification. The mortal world is separated from the Beyond by the Veil -- a metaphysical barrier that once maintained a cleaner division between realities. That division was compromised when the Aurelion sacrificed itself, creating a cosmic wound that has never fully healed. Through that wound, the Beyond exerts influence on the mortal world -- sometimes subtle, sometimes catastrophic, always dangerous. The Cosmic Wound The Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice created a wound in the Veil that fundamentally altered the relationship between the mortal world and the Beyond. Before the wound, the Veil was a more effective barrier -- not impermeable, but sufficient to maintain a functional separation between realities. After the wound, the Beyond presses against the mortal world with greater force, and the points where the Veil is thin have become more numerous and more unstable. This wound is the foundational metaphysical fact of the current age. It explains: Why sorcery is possible -- sorcerers exploit the wound, opening further tears in the Veil to siphon energies from the Beyond Why Cthonic worship persists -- the Cthonic gods exist in or draw power from the Beyond, and the wound gives them greater access to mortal worshippers Why demonic entities can cross into the mortal world -- the wound permits passage that would not otherwise be possible Why the Empyrean faith emphasizes the maintenance of cosmic order -- the gods of the Empyrean pantheon stand, in part, as guardians against the incursion of the Beyond Sorcery and the Beyond Sorcerers access the Beyond by opening wounds in the Veil -- deliberate tears in the barrier between realities through which they siphon energies, knowledge, and power. Every act of sorcery is, in a meaningful sense, an act of further damaging the Veil -- widening the cosmic wound that the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice created, inviting more of the Beyond into the mortal world. The energies siphoned from the Beyond are potent but dangerous. They do not obey the natural laws of the mortal world. They carry the character of their origin -- alien, unstable, and hungry. Sorcerers who draw too deeply or too frequently from the Beyond risk corruption, madness, and the attention of entities that exist on the other side. Communion with the Beyond The Beyond permits communion with entities that mortal religions, philosophies, and classifications struggle to categorize: Cthonic gods -- Powers of immense age and appetite that exist in or draw sustenance from the Beyond. They predate the Empyrean gods and persist despite centuries of imperial suppression. Demons -- Entities that cross from the Beyond into the mortal world through tears in the Veil. They range from mindless hunger (like the Guzzler ) to intelligent malice. Forgotten titans -- Beings of immense power whose worship has ceased but whose existence has not. They persist in the Beyond, waiting, sleeping, or simply enduring. Alien intelligences -- Entities that defy mortal classification entirely. They are not gods, not demons, not spirits -- they are something else, something that the mortal mind was not designed to comprehend. See Also the-veil -- The barrier separating the mortal world from the Beyond Aurelion -- The entity whose sacrifice created the cosmic wound sorcery -- The practice of opening tears in the Veil to access the Beyond cthonic-corruption -- The religious tradition connected to powers of the Beyond empyrean-faith -- The faith that stands in opposition to the Beyond&#39;s influence the-guzzler -- A demonic entity that crossed from the Beyond mithrapos -- The mortal world the Beyond presses against"},{"slug":"the-black-tree","title":"The Black Tree","category":"lore","tags":"erenthis avari crossings thornasse eolande dryad cynar womb-curse malachor reclaimers spiritual magic","text":"The Black Tree The Black Tree is the scorched stump of the great Erenthis at Thornasse , near Crossings . It was burned by High Mage Cynar in 349 IY as an act of cultural execution against the Avari Confederation . The burning was intended to destroy the spiritual heart of the Avari people -- and it succeeded in breaking their will to resist. But the roots have not fully died . At a Glance Detail Description What It Is The scorched stump of the great High Mage Cynar -- acting on imperial authority -- burned the great Erenthis at Thornasse. The Erenthis trees are living monuments of Eladran origin, hostile to Cthonic corruption and sacred to the Avari people. The Thornasse Erenthis was the spiritual axis of the Avari Confederation -- their sacred center, their living covenant with the world. Cynar did not burn a tree. He burned a people. The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist collapsed within months. The subsequent imperial campaigns in Argolle faced a broken, scattered population rather than an organized resistance. Cynar himself would die at the Battle of Blue Mound , where he and Jarn Murky-Eye destroyed each other in mutual annihilation. Whether there is cosmic justice in the death of the man who burned the Erenthis is a matter of theological debate. Something Endures The roots have not fully died . The ground around the Black Tree is warm to the touch -- not from fire (the burning was thirty years ago) but from something beneath. The Erenthis was not merely a tree but a living Eladran monument, a creation of ancient sorcery and spiritual significance. Whatever power animated it has not been fully extinguished. This persistence is significant. The Erenthis trees are described as hostile to Cthonic corruption . If the Black Tree&#39;s roots still live, they may still serve as a bulwark against the Cthonic forces that are clearly active in the Backlands -- the Awakening , the beastmen , the corruption spreading through Gallowswood and beyond. The Dryad A deranged and twisted dryad desperately tries to lure a fitting man to rebirth the dead tree . The dryad is the spiritual guardian of the Erenthis -- a being whose existence is bound to the tree. With the Erenthis burned, the dryad has been driven mad, twisted by the trauma of her tree&#39;s destruction. Her attempts to find a fitting man to rebirth the tree suggest that the Erenthis can be restored -- but the process requires a specific kind of sacrifice or union. What constitutes fitting is unclear, and the dryad&#39;s deranged state makes her judgment on the matter unreliable and her methods dangerous. Eolande at the Black Tree The Reclaimers encountered Eolande at the Black Tree -- an ancient Eladran general from approximately 3000 BE , still present at the site over five millennia later. Eolande was tutored by the Great Teacher, led the military campaigns that built the Eladran empire, and extended the reach of the Cthonic tradition alongside Eladran power. Why Eolande is at the Black Tree -- an Eladran general from the deep past, present at the scorched stump of an Eladran monument -- is itself a profound mystery. Is he bound to the tree as the dryad is? Is he guarding something? Waiting for something? During this encounter, Eolande mentioned the Womb Curse -- a term that provoked an urgent reaction from Malachor , the Imperial Academy agent at Fort Meade . Malachor wants every detail of what the Reclaimers learned at the Black Tree. Metaphysical Properties The Black Tree and its surroundings exhibit unusual metaphysical effects: Warm ground -- the earth around the stump radiates heat from below, suggesting living roots or active magical energy Dreams -- characters who sleep near the Black Tree dream of crystalline towers and wrong stars . The crystalline towers may be visions of Aodahn&#39;s ivory spires or of the Eladran civilization that created the Erenthis. The wrong stars suggest a vision of a different time -- a sky from millennia past, or a sky from the Beyond Magical enhancement -- mages and clerics who sleep near the Black Tree wake with a bonus cantrip , a temporary gift of arcane or divine power granted by proximity to the Erenthis&#39;s enduring energy These effects confirm that the Black Tree is not merely a historical site but an active source of metaphysical power. The Erenthis tradition is alive here, diminished but not destroyed. Significance The Black Tree sits at the intersection of multiple critical mysteries: The Avari -- It was their spiritual axis. Its destruction broke them. Its persistence offers hope. The Eladra -- It is an Eladran creation. Eolande -- an Eladran general -- is present. The Womb Curse was mentioned here. The Cthonic -- The Erenthis trees are hostile to Cthonic corruption. With the Awakening in progress in Argolle, the Black Tree may be one of the few remaining defenses. The Academy -- Malachor urgently wants every detail, suggesting the Academy recognizes the Black Tree&#39;s importance to their investigations. The Reclaimers -- Their encounter with Eolande here has given them knowledge that powerful factions desperately want. See Also the-erenthis -- The living Eladran monuments, of which the Black Tree is a scorched remnant thornasse -- The site where the Erenthis was burned crossings -- The ruined city near Thornasse eolande -- The ancient Eladran general encountered at the Black Tree high-mage-cynar -- The man who burned the Erenthis in 349 IY avari -- The people whose spiritual center was destroyed the-womb-curse -- Mentioned by Eolande at the Black Tree malachor -- The Academy agent who urgently seeks information from this encounter the-awakening -- The Cthonic event the Erenthis may resist aodahn -- The Eladran city whose spires may appear in Black Tree dreams cthonic-corruption -- What the Erenthis tradition opposes the-reclaimers -- The party that encountered Eolande here"},{"slug":"the-convergence-problem","title":"The Convergence Problem","category":"lore","tags":"theology empyrean cthonic convergence seros bel andraste nasga sagramore ravanor aurelion eladra elvora veil mirror divine cosmic","text":"The Convergence Problem The Convergence Problem is the theological crisis that emerges from the observation that the Empyrean and Cthonic gods are mirrors of each other . Each Empyrean deity has a Cthonic analogue governing the same domain but oriented toward opposite moral ends. The structural mirror is too precise to be accidental, and its implications threaten the foundations of both traditions. The Mirror Pairs Seros and Bel Seros (light, law, civilization) and Bel (war, conquest, blood) -- both claim sovereignty over the will to impose order . Seros imposes order through law, justice, and the structures of civilization. Bel imposes order through conquest, dominance, and the spilling of blood. The domain is identical. The method differs. The moral orientation is opposite. But the underlying impulse -- the drive to shape the world according to a singular will -- is the same. Andraste and Nasga Andraste (compassion, strength) and Nasga (pain, desire) -- both operate in the domain of the body&#39;s experience . Andraste sanctifies the body&#39;s capacity for endurance, compassion, and protective strength. Nasga sanctifies the body&#39;s capacity for suffering, hunger, and consuming desire. Both traditions claim authority over what the body feels and what that feeling means. The difference is whether the body&#39;s experience is oriented toward the protection of others or the satisfaction of the self. Sagramore and Ravanor Sagramore (loyalty, sacrifice) and Ravanor (rulership, tyranny) -- both concern the relationship between individual will and power structures . Sagramore asks: what are you willing to sacrifice for something greater than yourself? Ravanor asks: what are you willing to take from those beneath you? Both address the same fundamental question -- how does the individual relate to power? -- but from opposite positions within the hierarchy. The Structural Mirror The precision of the mirror is what produces the theological crisis. If Empyrean and Cthonic gods merely shared some superficial similarities, the mirror could be dismissed as coincidence, convergent evolution of divine archetypes, or the natural tendency of mortal minds to organize the divine into symmetrical categories. But the mirror is too precise to be accidental. Every Empyrean god has its Cthonic counterpart. Every domain is shared. Every moral axis is exactly inverted. The system is not approximate -- it is exact. This precision demands explanation, and every available explanation is uncomfortable for at least one tradition. The Most Disturbing Theory The most disturbing theory -- one advanced by Eladran scholars whose work survives only in fragments -- proposes that the Empyrean and Cthonic gods are not separate beings at all . They are a single set of primal powers, divided by the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice . What the Empyrean calls divine principle and the Cthonic calls divine hunger are the same cosmic forces , seen from different sides of the wound that the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice opened in the fabric of reality. If this theory is correct: Worshipping an Empyrean god and its Cthonic counterpart may be less different than either tradition prefers to acknowledge. The priest of Seros who calls upon the Unconquered Sun for justice and the blood-priest of Bel who calls upon the Slaughterprince for victory may be addressing the same power -- or two halves of what was once a single power -- through different rituals, different vocabularies, and different moral frameworks. The Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice did not merely create the distinction between Empyrean and Cthonic -- it may have CREATED the Empyrean and Cthonic as separate categories. Before the sacrifice, there may have been only primal forces, undivided, neither good nor evil in the senses those terms now carry. The moral distinction between the traditions may be a function of perspective rather than ontology. The Empyrean tradition is not inherently superior to the Cthonic tradition -- or vice versa. Both are fragments of something that was once whole, each claiming to represent the truth while possessing only half of it. The Veil Complication The Elvoran discovery of the Veil complicates the Convergence Problem further. The Elvora demonstrated that the Cthonic gods are reachable through the Veil -- they are not wholly immanent, not purely present in the material world, but accessible through a barrier that separates the material from something beyond it. This means the Cthonic gods have a transcendent dimension that their theology does not emphasize. Meanwhile, the Empyrean gods are increasingly understood as expressions of the Aurelion&#39;s distributed essence -- present in the world through the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice, active in the material realm through the structures and living things (such as the Erenthis ) that carry that essence. This means the Empyrean gods have an immanent dimension that their theology does not emphasize. The boundaries between transcendent and immanent -- between Empyrean and Cthonic -- are less fixed than either theology suggests . The Cthonic gods are not purely of this world. The Empyrean gods are not purely beyond it. Both traditions have been simplifying a reality that is more complex, more intertwined, and more troubling than either is comfortable admitting. Theological Responses The Empyrean Response The Empyrean tradition -- particularly the Thousand Temples -- finds the Convergence Problem anathema . The suggestion that Empyrean gods and Cthonic gods are aspects of the same primal forces is, from the Empyrean perspective, not merely wrong but dangerous. It undermines the moral authority on which the entire Empyrean tradition is built. If Seros and Bel are two faces of the same power, then the distinction between justice and conquest is not cosmic but interpretive -- a matter of human choice rather than divine mandate. The Thousand Temples have consistently suppressed, ignored, or condemned scholarship that advances the Convergence theory. This suppression has been effective but not total. The theory persists because the evidence for it is structural and persistent -- it does not depend on any single text or tradition but on the observable architecture of the divine. The Cthonic Response The Cthonic tradition finds the Convergence Problem flattering and probably correct . If the Cthonic gods are not inferior to the Empyrean gods but their equals -- or their other halves -- then the Cthonic tradition is not a corruption of the divine but an equally valid expression of it. The moral condemnation that the Empyrean tradition heaps upon Cthonic worship is revealed as self-serving propaganda rather than cosmic truth. The Cthonic tradition has never been as invested in the separation of Empyrean and Cthonic as the Empyrean tradition has. For the Cthonic, power is power. The source matters less than the result. The Convergence Problem, if accepted, validates a position the Cthonic tradition has held all along. Neither Has Resolved It The Empyrean find the Convergence Problem anathema. The Cthonic find it flattering and probably correct. Neither tradition has resolved it. Neither tradition can, because resolution would require one side to concede something fundamental about the nature of the divine -- and neither side is willing to concede anything at all. See Also seros -- Empyrean god of light, law, and civilization bel-earth-hunger -- Cthonic god of war, and the agricultural earth-hunger andraste -- Empyrean goddess of compassion and strength nasga -- Cthonic goddess of pain and desire sagramore -- Empyrean god of loyalty and sacrifice ravanor -- Cthonic god of rulership and tyranny Aurelion -- Whose sacrifice may have created the Empyrean/Cthonic divide the-veil -- The barrier through which Cthonic gods are reachable the-erenthis -- Living expression of Aurelion&#39;s distributed essence Eladra -- The scholars who advanced the most disturbing theory Elvora -- Whose discovery of the Veil complicated the problem thousand-temples -- The Empyrean institution that suppresses convergence scholarship empyrean-faith -- The tradition that finds convergence anathema cthonic-corruption -- The tradition that finds convergence flattering lakandi-binding-tradition -- A tradition that engages Cthonic entities without Empyrean frameworks"},{"slug":"the-erenthis","title":"The Erenthis","category":"lore","tags":"erenthis eladra avari aurelion empyrean cthonic mystical tree sacred thornasse crossings cynar black-tree root-network spiritual-anchor","text":"The Erenthis The Erenthis are not merely trees. To call them trees is to describe a cathedral as a pile of stones. The Erenthis are living monuments planted by the ancient Eladran civilization -- vast, sacred growths whose Eladran spiritual traditions were woven through with Empyrean vitality. They are the Aurelion&#39;s distributed essence expressed through cultivation and the living world -- a divine presence made manifest not in scripture or temple but in bark, root, warmth, and fruit. Nature and Properties The Erenthis are living expressions of a spiritual tradition older than any surviving institution in the Mithrian Empire . Their properties defy natural explanation: Perpetual warmth. An Erenthis generates warmth year-round, regardless of season or climate. The ground around a living Erenthis is warm to the touch even in the depths of winter. Communities centered on a living Erenthis have endured generations of frontier pressure in part because the tree itself sustains them against cold, famine, and despair. All-season fruit. The Erenthis bears fruit in all seasons -- not merely in the growing months, but continuously, providing sustenance to those who tend it through every turning of the year. Metaphysical root network. The root system of an Erenthis extends a metaphysical charge that is actively hostile to entities of Cthonic corruption . This is not a physical barrier. Creatures touched by Cthonic influence avoid Erenthis root systems entirely -- not because they cannot pass, but because of a deep incompatibility below the level of choice. The roots do not repel. They are simply fundamentally, structurally incompatible with what Cthonic corruption is. The effect is consistent, reliable, and operates without any action on the part of those the roots protect. The Erenthis root network is the most reliable natural defense against Cthonic corruption known in the Backlands . Communities centered on living Erenthis have survived generations of frontier pressure that destroyed settlements without such protection. The roots hold. They have always held. The Eladran Origin The Erenthis were planted by the Eladran civilization -- the ancient precursor culture whose ruins dot the landscape of Argolle and beyond. The Eladra understood what they were planting. Their spiritual traditions were not separate from the Empyrean vitality that animates the Erenthis; the trees were cultivated expressions of the Aurelion&#39;s distributed presence in the material world. The Eladra wove their deepest practices into the living wood, creating monuments that would endure long after their civilization fell. The Erenthis are what remain. The Avari and the Erenthis The Avari built their culture around Erenthis found in the ruins of the older Eladran civilization. They did not fully understand what they were tending -- they did not possess the Eladran theological vocabulary, the cosmological framework, or the metaphysical traditions that had produced the trees in the first place. But they understood enough. They understood that the tree was sacred. They understood that it sustained them. They understood that rites performed in its presence carried weight -- that prayers spoken beneath its branches were not empty, that ceremonies conducted among its roots connected to something real. The Avari built their holiest traditions around the Erenthis as a living spiritual anchor . The tree was the center of community, the site of their most important ceremonies, the physical expression of everything they held sacred. They did not need to name what they felt in its presence. They did not need the vocabulary of Empyrean theology or Cthonic classification. They knew what the tree was because they lived with it, generation after generation, and it sustained them. The Avari do not use the vocabulary of Empyrean or Cthonic classification. They do not need to. The Burning of the Erenthis at Thornasse Thirty years ago, High Mage Cynar burned the Erenthis at Thornasse . This act was understood by everyone -- Avari, Mithrian, scholar, soldier, priest -- as cultural execution . The Erenthis at Thornasse was not merely a tree. It was the spiritual center of the Avari Confederation , the living heart of their religious and cultural identity. Cynar did not merely destroy a symbol. He destroyed the thing itself -- the anchor around which an entire people had built their deepest understanding of the sacred. The Avari Confederation&#39;s will to resist collapsed within months. The Avari were defeated, assimilated, and their culture was systematically marginalized. What Cynar accomplished with fire at Thornasse, no army had managed in generations of warfare. He understood what the Erenthis meant to the Avari, and he burned it precisely because he understood. The Black Tree The scorched stump of the Erenthis at Thornasse -- the Black Tree -- still stands at the center of the ruins of Crossings . Cynar burned the trunk and branches. He killed what grew above the earth. But the roots have not fully died. The ground around the Black Tree is warm to the touch. Thirty years after the burning, something endures. The roots extend beneath the ruins, beneath the rubble, beneath the beastman occupation and the blood and the ruin of what was once the heart of Avari civilization. Whatever the Erenthis is -- whatever the Aurelion&#39;s distributed essence means when expressed in living wood -- it has not been wholly extinguished. The Black Tree is a wound. It is also, possibly, a promise. Defense Against Cthonic Corruption The Erenthis root network functions as the most reliable natural defense against Cthonic corruption in the known world. The mechanism is not physical. There is no wall, no ward, no visible barrier. Creatures touched by Cthonic influence simply avoid the root systems entirely. The incompatibility operates at a level below conscious choice -- below instinct, below awareness. The corruption and the roots cannot coexist. They are oriented toward fundamentally opposed principles, and the roots win. This defense has proven itself over centuries. Communities centered on living Erenthis have survived where others have fallen. The root network holds against Cthonic-corrupted creatures, against the subtle warping influence of prolonged Cthonic exposure, against the slow erosion of will and identity that the corruption produces. The roots do not merely resist. They actively reinforce whatever stands within their reach. In the ruins of Crossings , Cthonic-corrupted creatures behave with increasing urgency -- but they avoid the areas where the Black Tree&#39;s root network still extends. Even in death, even as a scorched stump, the Erenthis holds. Theological Classification Mithrian priests have been notably inconsistent in their classification of the Erenthis. Some have called it a Cthonic construct -- a product of the dark traditions, to be regarded with suspicion or hostility. This classification is, by every measurable indicator, wrong. The Erenthis is actively hostile to Cthonic corruption. Its root network repels Cthonic entities. Its properties align with the Empyrean tradition by every standard the Thousand Temples themselves apply. The most honest categorization may be Mystical -- the third tradition. The Erenthis is a living expression of the Aurelion&#39;s distributed presence: not god or demon, but what both Empyrean and Cthonic seek, present here and now in bark, root, warmth, and fruit. It is not transcendent in the way the Empyrean gods are transcendent. It is not immanent in the way the Cthonic gods are immanent. It is simply here -- real, alive, sustaining, and sacred in a way that does not require any theology to justify. The Avari do not use this vocabulary. They do not need to. Current Status The Erenthis at Thornasse was burned thirty years ago by High Mage Cynar . The Black Tree -- the scorched stump -- remains at the center of the ruins of Crossings . Its roots have not fully died. Other Erenthis are believed to exist in remote locations throughout Argolle and beyond, though their locations are not widely known. The root network beneath the ruins of Crossings has been responding to something -- those with access to the network have sensed increasing disturbance over the past two years. The Erenthis have oriented themselves in response: to resist, to reinforce, to hold. (See: The Nethercity ) Communities centered on living Erenthis continue to survive where others have fallen to frontier pressure, beastman raids, and Cthonic corruption. See Also crossings -- The ruined city where the Black Tree stands thornasse -- The site of the Erenthis burning Cynar -- The High Mage who burned the Erenthis Avari -- The people who built their culture around the Erenthis Eladra -- The ancient civilization that planted the Erenthis Aurelion -- The divine presence expressed through the Erenthis cthonic-corruption -- The corruption the Erenthis root network resists the-nethercity -- The subterranean complex beneath Crossings, whose stirring the roots have sensed the-convergence-problem -- The theological problem that complicates classification of the Erenthis empyrean-faith -- The tradition the Erenthis most closely aligns with lakandi-binding-tradition -- Another tradition operating outside standard Empyrean/Cthonic classification"},{"slug":"the-flame","title":"The Flame","category":"lore","tags":"flame priestly-magic empyrean aurelion measure-and-the-scale virtue divine-spark euphrosyne thousand-temples","text":"The Flame Each living being carries a spark of the Aurelion within its soul. To embody the Measure and the Scale you can reshape the world with your soul&#39;s fire. — Euphrosyne The Flame is the priestly magic of the Empyrean Faith — the divine power channeled through virtue, sacrifice, and righteous purpose. Unlike Gnostic Geometry , which manipulates the metaphysical axioms of reality through mental discipline, geometric diagrams, and spoken resonance, and unlike the warlock pacts and hedge-magic traditions that draw power from entities beyond The Veil , the Flame draws its power from within the soul itself. It is the spark of The Aurelion — the fragment of the supreme designer&#39;s essence that resides within every living being — ignited through alignment with the virtues of the Measure and the Scale and directed outward as an act of divine will. Theological Foundation The Divine Spark The foundational principle of the Flame is that every living being carries a spark of The Aurelion within its soul. This is not a metaphor or a poetic conceit but a literal metaphysical reality: when the Aurelion sacrificed itself to create the cosmos, its essence diffused throughout all of reality, and every soul is a fragment of that essence — a tiny piece of the divine fire that once animated the supreme designer of the cosmos. This spark is present in all living beings, but in most it remains dormant — a potential that is never realized, a fire that never burns. The vast majority of people live their entire lives without ever touching the divine fire within them, without ever knowing that the power to reshape reality lies coiled within their own souls, waiting to be awakened. Channeled Through Virtue The Flame cannot be ignited through study, through technique, or through the acquisition of arcane knowledge. It is not a skill that can be taught in the way that Gnostic Geometry is taught at the Imperial Academy . The Flame is activated through the alignment of the will with the virtues encoded in the Measure and the Scale — the moral and spiritual disciplines that the Empyrean Faith holds as the path to divine truth. Compassion, justice, courage, hope, sacrifice, duty, steadfastness — these are not merely moral qualities but metaphysical keys that unlock the divine spark and allow the Flame to burn. This means that the Flame cannot be faked. A sorcerer can learn the geometric formulae of Gnostic Geometry without believing in the divine order; a warlock can negotiate a pact with a demonic entity without any moral conviction whatsoever. But the Flame demands authenticity. The priest who channels the Flame must genuinely embody the virtues of the Scale — must truly feel compassion, truly seek justice, truly possess the courage and hope that the Empyrean faith demands. Hypocrisy extinguishes the spark. Self-interest smothers it. Only genuine, lived virtue can fan the spark into a flame capable of reshaping reality. Not Drawn from External Sources The Flame is fundamentally different from all other forms of magic in the known world because it does not draw power from external sources. Gnostic Geometry draws power from the manipulation of metaphysical axioms embedded in reality — ultimately from the Aurelion&#39;s essence, but indirectly, through the medium of geometric patterns and spoken resonance. Sorcery through The Veil draws power from the alien energies of the Beyond. Hedge-magic draws on natural forces, ley lines, and local spiritual conditions. All of these involve reaching outside the self to access power that exists in the external world. The Flame burns within. It is the sorcerer&#39;s own soul — or more precisely, the Aurelion&#39;s spark within the sorcerer&#39;s soul — that provides the power. This makes the Flame simultaneously the most intimate and the most demanding form of magic: intimate because it requires the practitioner to reach into the deepest part of their own being, and demanding because the quality of the power is directly proportional to the quality of the soul that channels it. Practice and Expression Miracles, Not Spells The manifestations of the Flame are typically described as miracles rather than spells — a linguistic distinction that reflects a genuine theological and practical difference. Spells, in the tradition of Gnostic Geometry , are reproducible, formulaic procedures: given the correct diagram, the correct resonance, and the correct mental discipline, any trained sorcerer can produce the same result. Miracles are not reproducible in this way. Each miracle is a unique expression of the channeler&#39;s virtue, responding to the specific circumstances of the moment and the specific state of the channeler&#39;s soul. The Flame can heal wounds, purify corruption, banish undead, shield the faithful from harm, reveal hidden truths, and accomplish other feats that defy natural explanation. The specific miracles that a Flame-channeler can perform are not drawn from a catalogue or learned from a textbook but emerge organically from the interaction between the channeler&#39;s virtues, the situation at hand, and the divine spark within. Cannot Be Taught, Must Be Lived The Thousand Temples barely teach the Flame in the current era. This is partly a matter of institutional decline — the living tradition of Flame-channeling has atrophied over centuries as the Temples have become increasingly bureaucratic, political, and concerned with temporal power rather than spiritual development. But it is also a reflection of the Flame&#39;s fundamental nature: it cannot be taught in the way that Gnostic Geometry can be taught, through lectures, textbooks, and supervised practice. The Flame must be lived. A priest who wishes to channel the divine fire must cultivate genuine virtue through years of discipline, sacrifice, and spiritual development. There are no shortcuts, no techniques, no secret methods. The only way to ignite the spark is to become the kind of person in whom the spark naturally burns — and this requires a lifetime of moral and spiritual effort that few are willing to undertake and fewer still are capable of sustaining. The Flame and Other Magical Traditions The Flame exists in tension with the other magical traditions of the known world. Practitioners of Gnostic Geometry view the Flame with a mixture of respect and skepticism — respect because its effects are undeniable, skepticism because its mechanisms resist systematic analysis. Warlocks and hedge-mages view it with fear, because the Flame is one of the few powers capable of directly countering Cthonic Corruption and banishing the entities that these practitioners traffic with. The Thousand Temples officially maintain that the Flame is the only truly legitimate form of supernatural power — that Gnostic Geometry is a tolerated but spiritually inferior practice, and that all other forms of magic are varying degrees of heresy. In practice, however, the rarity of genuine Flame-channelers means that the Temples rely heavily on the Imperial Academy and its gnostic geometers for practical magical needs, and the official theological position exists more as aspiration than reality. See Also The Aurelion Euphrosyne The Measure and the Scale Empyrean Faith Thousand Temples Gnostic Geometry The Veil Imperial Academy Magic and Sorcery Seros"},{"slug":"the-guzzler","title":"The Guzzler","category":"lore","tags":"demon guzzler fort-ikenvar stone-of-sakkara theodotus backlands sanctuary demonic-entity","text":"The Guzzler The Guzzler is a demonic entity of unknown origin currently occupying the ruined Fort Ikenvar , the marsh fort east of Fort Meade in the Backlands . It is not intelligent in any meaningful sense -- it just hungers and eats what it finds. It does not discriminate. It has no agenda beyond feeding. It is a mouth with legs, a consuming force that devours whatever crosses its path without preference or plan. The Guzzler is being drawn southward from Fort Ikenvar by the Stone of Sakkara , carried by Theodotus of the Reclaimers . Its approach toward populated areas represents a growing humanitarian catastrophe. At a Glance Detail Description Type Demonic entity Intelligence Minimal -- pure hunger, no agenda Origin Unknown Lair Fort Ikenvar for weeks, drawn by the Stone of Sakkara . It cannot locate the Stone precisely -- it feels it the way an animal senses weather before it turns. The pull is ambient, not directional. A pressure gradient rather than a beacon. When the Reclaimers were at Fort Meade , the Guzzler followed toward the garrison. When the party moved south toward Sanctuary , the Guzzler followed south. The Stone&#39;s influence is reshaping the Guzzler&#39;s behavior in two critical ways: Range: The Guzzler is no longer contained by the marshes around Fort Ikenvar. It is moving through open territory, along roads, past settlements -- terrain it would not naturally traverse without the Stone&#39;s pull. Target selection: The Stone is amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent. The creature&#39;s already indiscriminate appetite is being bent toward the most vulnerable prey -- children, livestock, the undefended. This is not the Guzzler&#39;s doing. It is the Stone&#39;s. Trail of Violence As the Guzzler follows the Stone south along the route from Fort Meade to Sanctuary , it has left an escalating trail of predation: A farm three miles south of Fort Meade: Goats taken, fence posts crushed in. The farmer reported it two days late, embarrassed he had waited. The Sanctuary road: A merchant&#39;s draft horse found half-consumed at the roadside. The merchant saw nothing. Heard nothing. The horse was simply gone. Near Sanctuary: A child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go. The escalation tracks the party&#39;s southward movement precisely. The Guzzler is not attacking settlements randomly. It is following the Stone, and the Stone is amplifying its hunger toward innocence. The incidents are a consequence of Theodotus carrying the Stone through populated territory. Military Assessment The approximately one hundred soldiers at Fort Meade under Legate Marcellus&#39;s command are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The garrison was built to hold a frontier chokepoint against mortal threats -- beastmen , Lakandi raiders, bandits like Rook . A demonic entity is a categorically different problem requiring capabilities the garrison does not possess. If the Guzzler arrives near Sanctuary , the consequences would be catastrophic. Sanctuary is a city of 28,000 people. The Guzzler in an urban-adjacent environment is a vastly different problem than the Guzzler in the marshes around Fort Ikenvar. The density of potential victims, the difficulty of evacuation, and the political fallout of a demonic entity attacking civilians near the provincial capital would be devastating. The Futility of Killing It Killing the Guzzler resolves nothing. The Guzzler is a symptom, not the disease. The Stone of Sakkara drew this creature. If the Guzzler is destroyed, the Stone will reach through something else. Another entity will be attracted. Another vessel for hunger will be found. The Stone&#39;s influence does not end when one manifestation of it is eliminated. Fighting the Guzzler in an urban-adjacent environment near Sanctuary is a different tactical problem than fighting it in the marshes. The terrain, the civilian population, the political implications -- all change. But even a successful engagement only buys time. The Stone remains. The pull remains. The next entity drawn by the Stone may be worse. The problem is the Stone, not the Guzzler. Theodotus knows this, somewhere beneath the philosophical distance he maintains from the violence around him. The scene ends when he decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies. History The Guzzler occupied Fort Ikenvar before the events of the campaign. The ruined marsh fort east of Fort Meade was also the base of operations for Rook , the bandit whose destruction was the Reclaimers&#39; first major accomplishment. Whether the Guzzler was present during Rook&#39;s occupation, whether Rook&#39;s people coexisted with it or avoided it, and whether the Guzzler&#39;s arrival at Fort Ikenvar was connected to any other event in the Backlands&#39; recent history are all unclear. What is clear is that the Guzzler was contained -- naturally or by circumstance -- within the marshes around Fort Ikenvar until the Stone of Sakkara pulled it free. See Also the-stone-of-sakkara -- The artifact drawing the Guzzler southward theodotus -- The Reclaimer carrying the Stone fort-ikenvar -- The Guzzler&#39;s lair fort-meade -- The garrison threatened by the Guzzler&#39;s movement sanctuary -- The city toward which the Guzzler is being drawn the-reclaimers -- The party whose movements are guiding the Guzzler&#39;s path legate-marcellus -- Commander of the garrison not equipped to face it rook -- Former occupant of Fort Ikenvar campaign-chronicle -- Session history documenting the Guzzler&#39;s approach"},{"slug":"the-kharai","title":"The Kharai","category":"lore","tags":"kharai imprisoned-ones cairnhouse ygrathen eladra cairnhill lake-silverhead psychic-bleed dreams ancient cosmic binding varek-ashstone gilded-oath elvora veranthas seal-circuit","text":"The Kharai The Kharai -- the Imprisoned Ones -- are beings of enormous will and appetite, ancient beyond reckoning. The Eladran civilizations already regarded them as predating the current age of the world. They are not gods. They are not demons. They were never part of any divine order. They do not fit within the cosmic architecture of either the Empyrean or Cthonic tradition. They are simply what they are: vast, patient, and impossible to destroy. It does not threaten. It waits. It has more time than anything built to contain it. -- Attributed to the Ygrathen hermit of Lake Silverhead Nature The Kharai defy classification within the theological frameworks that govern understanding of the supernatural in the Mithrian Empire and beyond. They are not Empyrean -- they serve no divine principle, uphold no cosmic order, express no distributed essence of the Aurelion . They are not Cthonic -- they are not hungry gods reaching through the Veil , not entities of corruption and appetite seeking to consume the material world. They are outside the system entirely. Beings of enormous will and appetite that simply exist -- have always existed -- with a patience and persistence that exceeds anything built to contain them. The Ygrathen imprisoned the Kharai rather than destroying them. The most straightforward explanation is that they could not be destroyed. But there is another possibility, one that scholars and theologians have debated without resolution: perhaps the Ygrathen understood something about the Kharai that has since been forgotten. Perhaps destruction was possible but unwise. Perhaps the Kharai serve a function in the deep structure of the world that would be disrupted by their annihilation. The Ygrathen chose imprisonment, and the reasons for that choice may matter as much as the choice itself. The Cairnhouses The Kharai are contained within structures called cairnhouses -- constructions of Ygrathen design, built specifically to imprison the Kharai using binding traditions that predate the Mithrian Empire by an unknown span of time. The cairnhouses were not improvised. They were engineered with precision and sustained intention, designed to hold beings that cannot be killed and will never stop pressing against their confinement. At least two cairnhouses are known to exist in Argolle : The cairnhouse on the island in Lake Silverhead (far north of the province) -- watched over by the Ygrathen hermit Varek Ashstone , who has maintained his vigil for centuries. The cairnhouse at Cairnhill (on the scrubland edge of the province) -- the structure that has shaped the town and its people through generations of psychic bleed. Others may exist. The Ygrathen built what was necessary, and the Kharai are not few. The Psychic Bleed A cairnhouse does not perfectly contain what is inside. The beings imprisoned within press against the walls of their binding constantly, with the patience of something that has more time than the dam. The pressure leaks. This leakage -- the psychic bleed -- is not dramatic. It does not manifest as madness, mutation, or catastrophe. It is subtle, persistent, and cumulative. Over six to seven generations, the psychic bleed from the cairnhouse at Cairnhill has shaped the people who live near it. The changes are consistent across the population, suggesting not random corruption but a slow, steady pressure that molds human consciousness into something slightly -- but distinctly -- different from the norm. Effects on Cairnhill Residents The people of Cairnhill display the following characteristics, all attributable to generations of exposure to the psychic bleed: Too-complete attention. Cairnhill residents do not merely notice things -- they attend to them with a focus and thoroughness that is subtly unsettling to outsiders. Their gaze does not wander. Their awareness does not drift. They are present in a way that exceeds ordinary human attentiveness. Tolerance for enclosed spaces and darkness. What would produce claustrophobia or discomfort in others produces no distress in Cairnhill residents. They are comfortable in tight spaces, in darkness, in conditions that would unnerve most people. This is not courage -- it is genuine comfort, as if enclosed darkness is a natural environment rather than a threatening one. A different relationship to time. Cairnhill residents experience time differently. They are patient beyond ordinary patience -- not in the way of disciplined or stoic individuals, but in the way of people for whom the passage of time carries a different weight. Hours, days, seasons move through their awareness at a different pace. Perceptiveness below normal awareness. Cairnhill residents perceive things that others do not -- not supernatural visions or mystical insight, but a baseline awareness of their environment that operates below the level of conscious attention. They notice what others miss. They feel what others cannot. This perceptiveness is not a skill; it is a condition of their existence. The Dreams Every resident of Cairnhill dreams of vast enclosed spaces. The dreams are consistent across the population. They feature halls, corridors, and chambers of impossible scale -- structures too large to exist beneath any hill, lit by no visible source, built in geometries that are not quite wrong but not quite right. The spaces are not threatening. They are not nightmares. They are simply immense , deeply other , and entirely real in the way that only the most vivid and persistent dreams can be. The residents of Cairnhill discuss the geography of their shared dreams with the casual familiarity of people discussing shared weather. They know the corridors. They recognize the chambers. They have navigated the impossible halls in sleep since childhood, as their parents did, and their parents&#39; parents before them. It has never occurred to them that outsiders do not share the same dreams. This is the most telling indicator of how thoroughly the psychic bleed has shaped the community. The dreams are not aberrant to those who have them. They are simply part of life -- as natural and unremarkable as the hill itself, as the enclosed spaces they do not fear, as the patience that runs deeper in them than in anyone else. The Argollean Brotherhood and the Cairnhouses The Argollean Brotherhood seeks access to the cairnhouses -- not to free what is imprisoned within, but to study the Ygrathen binding structures themselves. The binding tradition that produced the cairnhouses represents an achievement of containment magic that the Brotherhood considers invaluable: techniques for sealing and holding beings of power that no contemporary practitioner can replicate. The town of Cairnhill does not allow anyone near the hill. This tension has been building for years. The Brotherhood wants what the cairnhouse contains -- not the Kharai, but the knowledge of how to bind them. Cairnhill wants to be left alone, to continue the quiet existence they have maintained for generations, shaped by the bleed but sustained by their own stubborn refusal to let outsiders interfere with what they have learned to live with. The Brotherhood sees an invaluable research opportunity. Cairnhill sees a threat to the only equilibrium they have ever known. Neither side has yielded. Neither side is likely to. The Guardian Tomb Network and the Gilded Oath The cairnhouses are not the only means by which the Kharai are contained. In the Cairnhill Breaks -- the fractured limestone foothills east of Cairnhill -- a network of Elvoran guardian tombs forms a seal-circuit : a chain of binding stations that reinforces the imprisonment of the Kharai beneath the hill. Each station is manned by a member of the Gilded Oath , a cohort of Elvoran warrior-priests who underwent a ritual of partial undeath called the Sevenfold Wounding . The Sevenfold Wounding was a process of agonizing transformation: seven wounds taken with a gold-threaded blade, through which molten gold was introduced into the bloodstream and hardened into a lattice beneath the skin. At the ritual&#39;s completion, the warrior-priests died their living deaths and entered the guardian tombs, where they have maintained the seals in silence for over two thousand years. The gold woven into their bodies resonates with the Gnostic Geometry of the seal-circuit, binding their vigil to the mathematical structure of the containment itself. The Breaking of the Second Seal At the Second Seal station -- the tomb known as the Gilded Vigil -- the guardian Veranthas (vigil-name: He Who Holds the Middle Line ) has broken his covenant . Sometime in the last year, Veranthas: Ceased his vigil Desecrated his own oath-altar Retreated to his private chamber Began communicating with the imprisoned entity through the seal-membrane Veranthas claims that through this communication he has become convinced the Kharai sealed beneath Cairnhill is sane, not hostile, and politically imprisoned -- sealed away not because it was dangerous to the world but because it was dangerous to the powers that ruled the world at the time of its imprisonment. He reduced the sealing pressure to allow the entity to breathe. The seals have weakened but not broken. The Kharai has not escaped. But the effects are felt: dreams have grown strange in Cairnhill, the Thune remnant in the Breaks have grown bolder, and the Argollean Brotherhood has dispatched a cell to investigate. The central question -- whether Veranthas is right or wrong about the Kharai&#39;s nature -- is deliberately unresolved. If the Ygrathen chose imprisonment rather than destruction because the Kharai serve a function in the deep structure of the world, then Veranthas&#39;s claim that the imprisonment was political rather than necessary may carry more weight than first appears. The possibility that the Kharai are misunderstood -- that they are prisoners rather than monsters -- is the most dangerous idea in the setting, precisely because it cannot be definitively confirmed or denied. See Also varek-ashstone -- The Ygrathen hermit who watches over the Lake Silverhead cairnhouse cairnhill -- The town shaped by generations of psychic bleed lake-silverhead -- The lake whose island holds a cairnhouse argollean-brotherhood -- The faction seeking access to cairnhouse binding structures Ygrathen -- The ancient people who built the cairnhouses Eladra -- The civilization that already regarded the Kharai as ancient the-nethercity -- Another ancient subterranean structure with imprisoned power lakandi-binding-tradition -- A related but distinct binding tradition cthonic-corruption -- The Cthonic tradition, from which the Kharai are notably distinct empyrean-faith -- The Empyrean tradition, from which the Kharai are equally distinct the-gilded-vigil -- The guardian tomb where Veranthas broke his covenant Elvoran -- The civilization that created the Gilded Oath"},{"slug":"the-nethercity-codex","title":"The Codex of Ninefold Stillness","category":"lore","tags":"nethercity codex in-world-document cthonic varn-ka-morath sen-zorath great-teacher quiet-ones awakening eladra soul-lanterns dream-masks leylines binding","text":"The Codex of Ninefold Stillness When the world above dims -- and it shall -- the world below will shine with remembered light. -- Seer-Historian Vharul Sen-Ka The Codex of Ninefold Stillness is an in-world document attributed to Seer-Historian Vharul Sen-Ka , describing the Nethercity in terms that far exceed what contemporary explorers have been able to confirm. Where modern accounts describe a subterranean complex of tomb-palaces and vault-temples, the Codex describes a city in every sense -- a metropolis of the dead built not as a graveyard but as a vessel for a civilization that expects to resume. The Codex calls the Nethercity by its original name: Varn-Ka&#39;Morath , which translates as the House of Becoming. The City Described Scale and Architecture The Codex insists that the Nethercity is not a mere catacomb. Vharul Sen-Ka describes it as a city in every functional sense: Vaultways as wide as rivers -- the primary corridors of the Nethercity are not cramped tomb-passages but broad avenues of monumental scale, built to accommodate movement, procession, and the traffic of a functioning urban center Avenues marked by soul-lanterns -- fixed light sources whose flames feed on remembrance . The soul-lanterns do not burn fuel. They burn memory. The mechanism by which this functions is not explained, but the implication is that the lanterns are sustained by the accumulated memories of the dead interred nearby -- a perpetual light source powered by the psychic residue of the deceased Entire districts shaped around sarcophagal towers -- the Nethercity is organized into districts, each centered on towering structures that house the interred. These are not individual tombs but collective monuments -- vertical necropoli within the horizontal necropolis The Quiet Ones The sarcophagal towers house the Quiet Ones -- those who gave themselves to the Long Sleep to await the Unsealing of the Final Door . The Codex describes them not as the dead but as the waiting -- beings who chose to enter a state of suspended existence in anticipation of a future event that would require their return. The Long Sleep is not death. It is not undeath. It is a third state -- a deliberate cessation of activity that preserves the sleeper in readiness for a purpose that has not yet arrived. The Quiet Ones did not die and were not killed. They chose to stop, and they can, according to the Codex, choose to start again. Death as a Chamber The Codex articulates a theology of death that is profoundly different from both Empyrean and standard Cthonic understanding: Death is understood as a chamber, not a wall . In this framework, death is not an ending (the Empyrean view) or a consumption (the Cthonic view) but a transition space -- a room one passes through on the way to somewhere else. The Nethercity was built as the physical expression of this theology: a literal chamber of death through which the faithful would pass on their way to whatever lay beyond the Unsealing of the Final Door. The Honored Dead The honored dead are arrayed in splendor within the Nethercity, equipped not with offerings but with tools for the age to come : Item Description Mirrors of black glass Reflective surfaces of unknown material and purpose; possibly scrying devices, possibly instruments of self-recognition for beings who will wake after millennia of sleep Scepters of memory-copper Implements made of an alloy called memory-copper -- a material that apparently retains impressions of its wielder&#39;s thoughts and experiences Dream-masks still humming with soul-echoes Facial coverings that continue to resonate with the psychic impressions of their wearers, even after centuries of interment The Codex is emphatic that these are not offerings . They are not grave goods placed to honor the dead or comfort them in an afterlife. They are equipment -- tools the Quiet Ones will need when they wake. The distinction matters: offerings imply finality. Equipment implies a future. The Hall of the Teacher At the city&#39;s heart lies the Hall of the Teacher , containing the slumbering form of the Great Architect Sen&#39;Zorath the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues . This is the entity referred to elsewhere as the Great Teacher -- the being who directed the construction of the Nethercity under the authority of whatever Cthonic power animated the First Empire era. Sen&#39;Zorath rests within the Chrysalis-Urn -- a vessel whose name implies transformation rather than mere containment. The Great Teacher is not stored. It is gestating . The Chrysalis-Urn is not a coffin but a cocoon. The Chamber of the Still Light Adjacent to or within the Hall of the Teacher is the Chamber of the Still Light -- a space defined by a veil of cold gold through which the Great Teacher&#39;s presence can be felt. The Codex describes the experience: His thought presses like gravity upon the soul. The Chamber of the Still Light is not a place of communication. The Great Teacher does not speak. It does not instruct. It simply exists with such intensity that proximity to it exerts a force on the consciousness of the living -- a weight of thought so massive that it bends the psychic landscape around it like a star bends light. The Invisible Architecture The Codex describes the Nethercity as constructed along invisible axes -- structural principles that are not visible to the eye but are essential to the city&#39;s function: Aetheric leylines -- currents of metaphysical energy that flow through the Nethercity&#39;s architecture, connecting its districts, its towers, and its sleepers into a single integrated system Resonance lattices -- geometric structures embedded in the city&#39;s design that harmonize the psychic frequencies of the interred Quiet Ones, keeping them aligned even across millennia of dormancy The purpose of this invisible architecture is explicitly stated in the Codex: so that when the Quiet Ones awaken, they will rise aligned, harmonized, and prepared . The Long Sleep is not merely preservation -- it is calibration . The sleepers are being tuned, over centuries, into a collective instrument that will function as a unified whole when the Unsealing occurs. The slumbering minds of the Quiet Ones are not simply dormant. They are being worked upon by the resonance lattices -- slowly, imperceptibly adjusted so that when they wake, they will think in concert, act in concert, and serve whatever purpose the Great Teacher designed them to serve. The Prophecy The Codex concludes with what reads as either prophecy or promise: When the world above dims -- and it shall -- the world below will shine with remembered light. This is the eschatological core of the Nethercity&#39;s purpose. The builders of Varn-Ka&#39;Morath did not merely expect the surface world to decline -- they regarded it as inevitable . The Nethercity was built as a replacement, a successor, a continuation of civilization that would outlast whatever catastrophe consumed the world above. The remembered light of the soul-lanterns -- the flames that feed on memory -- would illuminate a new age built on the accumulated wisdom and experience of the old. Whether this prophecy is genuine foreknowledge, self-fulfilling design, or the grandiose ambition of a Cthonic architect is left for the reader to determine. Relationship to Known Accounts The Codex of Ninefold Stillness describes the Nethercity in terms that significantly expand upon what contemporary sources have documented. The Reclaimers&#39; exploration of the complex has confirmed its immense scale and First Empire provenance, but they have not penetrated to the depths the Codex describes. The Hall of the Teacher, the Chamber of the Still Light, and the sarcophagal districts remain beyond current reach. The Codex&#39;s description of Sen&#39;Zorath as the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues suggests the Great Teacher may have been a polyglot, a linguist, or a being whose power operated through language itself -- shaping reality through the mastery of every tongue that existed in the First Empire&#39;s vast, multicultural dominion. See Also the-nethercity -- The subterranean complex the Codex describes cthonic-faith -- The theological tradition that animated the Nethercity&#39;s construction Eladra -- The civilization that built the Nethercity the-kharai -- Other ancient imprisoned entities with parallels to the Quiet Ones crossings -- The ruined city above the Nethercity the-erenthis -- The root network responding to the Nethercity&#39;s stirring Reclaimers -- The group currently exploring the complex the-convergence-problem -- The theological framework within which the Nethercity&#39;s purpose must be understood empyrean-faith -- The contrasting theology of death as finality the-gilded-vigil -- Another ancient site where the sealed and the guardians exist in tension"},{"slug":"the-nethercity","title":"The Nethercity","category":"lore","tags":"nethercity crossings eladra cthonic necropolis great-teacher first-empire awakening reclaimers erenthis subterranean tomb dungeon varn-ka-morath sen-zorath quiet-ones","text":"The Nethercity The Nethercity -- known in the Codex of Ninefold Stillness by its original name Varn-Ka&#39;Morath , the House of Becoming -- is a vast subterranean complex beneath the ruins of Crossings , built by the ancient Eladran civilization. It is not a graveyard. It is not a ruin. It is a prepared vessel -- a necropolis of tomb-palaces, vault-temples, and ritual chambers constructed with a purpose that has not yet been fulfilled. Architecture and Scale The Nethercity is immense. Its construction predates the Mithrian Empire by centuries, possibly millennia. The complex comprises: Tomb-palaces -- elaborate burial chambers designed not merely to house the dead but to preserve them in states of ritual readiness. These are not modest crypts. They are palatial in scale, decorated with the symbolic language of the Eladran civilization, built to endure until they are needed. Vault-temples -- sacred spaces combining the functions of temple and treasury. Whatever was worshipped or honored in these chambers was considered too important to be entrusted to surface structures. The vault-temples are deep, reinforced, and built to withstand catastrophe. Ritual chambers -- purpose-built spaces for ceremonies whose nature can only be inferred from their architecture. The geometry of these chambers suggests rites of enormous scale and significance -- not daily worship but singular events, prepared for over generations. Hundreds of the First Empire&#39;s greatest figures are interred within the Nethercity. They were placed here not merely to rest but to await . The distinction matters. A graveyard honors the dead. The Nethercity holds them in reserve. Named Locations The Argollean Empire Timelines and the Codex of Ninefold Stillness preserve the names and approximate construction dates of the Nethercity&#39;s principal structures. These are not rooms in a dungeon. They are monuments of state religion, built over centuries according to a design that the Great Teacher articulated before entering dormancy. Great Temple of the Awakening (construction began c. 2600 BE) The central and earliest major structure of the Nethercity, the Great Temple of the Awakening was begun during the period when the Argollean Empire was formally declared and the Bitter War commenced. Its name is its purpose: this is the temple built for the Awakening -- the future event that the entire Nethercity was constructed to facilitate. The temple is the architectural heart of the complex, and all other structures are oriented in relation to it. Doom Temple of Dirgion (construction began c. 2400 BE) The Doom Temple of Dirgion was begun approximately two centuries after the Great Temple. Surviving records describe it in language more suggestive of containment than worship -- a structure built not to honor a deity but to hold something in readiness, or to keep something bound. The name Dirgion does not correspond to any known Cthonic or Empyrean deity in modern theological catalogs. Whether it names a god, an entity, or a principle is unknown. Hallowed Halls of Heroes (construction began c. 2100 BE) The Hallowed Halls of Heroes were begun during the period of the Ygrathen defeat under warlord Marcan. The Halls serve as the interment complex for the First Empire&#39;s greatest military figures -- the generals, champions, and warlords whose victories built the Empire. These are the figures held in reserve, placed in states of ritual readiness for whatever the Awakening requires of them. Great King Tomb (c. 2000 BE) The Great King Tomb houses the remains of the warlord Marcan -- conqueror of the Ygrathen and the Empire&#39;s greatest military hero. His interment within a purpose-built tomb of exceptional scale reflects his status. The Great King Tomb is among the most elaborate single structures in the Nethercity. Secret Tomb (c. 1800 BE) The Secret Tomb houses the hierophant Orthanach -- the first mummy lord , the first being to achieve undeath through Cthonic ritual that preserves consciousness, will, and power beyond bodily death. Interred alongside Orthanach are his wife Sonya and his guard Cassair . Whether they accompanied him willingly into undeath is not recorded. The tomb is designated secret in the records, suggesting it was deliberately concealed within the Nethercity&#39;s deeper levels. Secret Sepulcher (c. 2100 BE) The Secret Sepulcher is the chamber in which the Great Teacher entered cryostasis following the defeat of the Ygrathen. Like the Secret Tomb, the Sepulcher was deliberately hidden within the complex. The Great Teacher chose dormancy rather than death or departure -- entering a state of preserved waiting that mirrors the Nethercity&#39;s own purpose. The Sepulcher is the most closely guarded location in the Nethercity, and its precise position within the complex is not recorded in any surviving document accessible to modern scholars. Hall of the Teacher (from the Codex of Ninefold Stillness) The Codex of Ninefold Stillness describes a chamber called the Hall of the Teacher , which may be another name for the Secret Sepulcher or an adjacent ritual space. The Codex identifies the Great Teacher by name: Sen&#39;Zorath, the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues . According to the Codex, Sen&#39;Zorath rests within the Chrysalis-Urn -- a vessel whose name implies not mere preservation but ongoing transformation. The Chrysalis-Urn suggests that the Great Teacher&#39;s dormancy is not static but developmental -- that whatever Sen&#39;Zorath is becoming, the process has been underway for millennia. The Great Teacher An entity called the Great Teacher directed the construction of the Nethercity. This being operated under the direct instruction of whatever power animated the Cthonic tradition during the First Empire era. The Great Teacher is not a title given in retrospect -- it is the name by which the entity was known to those who built what it designed. The Great Teacher rests dormant in the deepest levels of the Nethercity, within the [[#secret-sepulcher-c-2100-be|Secret Sepulcher]]. It has not died. It has not departed. It waits, as the Nethercity was built to wait, for whatever it was constructed to receive. The nature of the Great Teacher -- whether it is a being of flesh, spirit, or something else entirely -- is not known with certainty. What is known is that it possessed sufficient authority and power to direct the construction of one of the most ambitious subterranean projects in the history of the known world, and that the power it served was Cthonic in origin. Identity The Argollean Empire Timelines identify the Great Teacher as a Chemosh (Khepri) Hierarch -- a title that places the entity within the Cthonic theological hierarchy but does not clarify its species, origin, or the precise nature of its authority. The Codex of Ninefold Stillness provides a name: Sen&#39;Zorath, the Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues . The Codex describes Sen&#39;Zorath resting within the Chrysalis-Urn in the [[#hall-of-the-teacher-from-the-codex-of-ninefold-stillness|Hall of the Teacher]]. The title Shaper of Ten Thousand Tongues suggests a being whose power operated through language, command, and the reshaping of others -- consistent with an entity that directed the creation of the Thune through Transmogrification and the construction of a necropolis designed to outlast the civilization that built it. The name Chrysalis-Urn implies that the Great Teacher&#39;s dormancy is not static preservation but ongoing transformation -- that Sen&#39;Zorath is not merely sleeping but becoming something else, and has been becoming it for millennia. This connects directly to the Awakening : the Nethercity anticipates not a metaphorical event but a literal one. Something will emerge from the Chrysalis-Urn, and whatever emerges may not be what entered it. Purpose: The Awakening The Nethercity was not built as a monument to the past. It was built as preparation for a future event . The hundreds of interred figures, the ritual chambers, the vault-temples -- all of it was constructed in anticipation of something the builders called, or what scholars have come to call, the Awakening . The Awakening it anticipates is not metaphorical. Something is changing in the world&#39;s deeper metaphysical substrate. Those with access to the Erenthis root network have sensed it for two years: an increasing disturbance, a presence in the deep energies that was not there before. The Erenthis trees have oriented themselves in response -- to resist, to reinforce, to hold. The trees feel what is stirring below, and they are bracing against it. In the ruins of Crossings above, Cthonic-corrupted creatures behave with increasing urgency, as if something below is beginning to call. Their patterns have shifted. Their movements have purpose where before there was only territorial aggression. Something in the Nethercity is exerting influence, and the corrupted creatures above are responding. The Erenthis Response The Erenthis root network beneath Crossings -- the roots of the Black Tree, the scorched stump of the Erenthis that High Mage Cynar burned thirty years ago -- has not fully died. These roots extend into the earth around and above the Nethercity, and for two years they have been responding to whatever is stirring below. The Erenthis roots have oriented themselves in response to the Nethercity&#39;s increasing activity: To resist -- pushing back against the metaphysical pressure emanating from below To reinforce -- strengthening whatever barriers exist between the Nethercity and the surface To hold -- maintaining the boundary between what sleeps below and what lives above The fact that the Erenthis roots are responding at all confirms that what is happening in the Nethercity is real, significant, and perceived as a threat by the oldest and most reliable defense against Cthonic influence in the region. The Reclaimers The Reclaimers have been exploring the Nethercity. The extent of their penetration, what they have found, and what they intend to do with their discoveries are not fully known. The Nethercity is vast, dangerous, and actively defended by whatever Cthonic influences persist within its depths. Exploration is not merely a matter of mapping corridors -- it is an engagement with forces that have been accumulating power in darkness for centuries. Current Status The Great Teacher rests dormant in the deepest levels Cthonic-corrupted creatures in the Crossings ruins above behave with increasing urgency and purpose The Erenthis root network has been responding for approximately two years The metaphysical disturbance is intensifying The Reclaimers are actively exploring the complex The Awakening the Nethercity was built to facilitate has not yet occurred -- but the signs suggest it is approaching See Also crossings -- The ruined city above the Nethercity the-erenthis -- The root network responding to the Nethercity&#39;s stirring cthonic-corruption -- The tradition that animated the Nethercity&#39;s construction Eladra -- The civilization that built the Nethercity Reclaimers -- The group exploring the complex the-kharai -- Other ancient imprisoned entities predating the current age the-convergence-problem -- The theological framework within which the Nethercity&#39;s Cthonic origins must be understood argollean-empire -- The First Empire that built the Nethercity and its named structures mount-argolle -- The volcanic mountain bearing additional First Empire ruins thune -- The slave-soldiers created by the Great Teacher&#39;s Transmogrification ygrathen -- The ancient enemies whose defeat preceded the Great Teacher&#39;s cryostasis the-nethercity-codex -- The Codex of Ninefold Stillness: Seer-Historian Vharul Sen-Ka&#39;s in-world account of Varn-Ka&#39;Morath"},{"slug":"the-reclaimers","title":"The Reclaimers","category":"lore","tags":"lore party player-characters reclaimers backlands fort-meade legate-marcellus lady-severina nethercity rook fort-ikenvar argollean-brotherhood scalpers crossings campaign-history","text":"The Reclaimers They came to the Backlands as carrion comes, drawn to rot. This was the northern province of Argolle where the land lay charred with old wars and the bones of empires still pushed from the dirt when the rains came. Six years gone the border city of Crossings was put to the torch by a horde of beastmen vast beyond counting and the people were butchered in their homes and the Emperor in his distant hall decreed then that a man might trade death for coin and a gold mark was set for every beast&#39;s scalp and so the land filled with killers. They arrived as hired swords. They destroyed Rook when the garrison could not. They carry artifacts the Brotherhood wants and the Academy covets. They are formally part of the Legate&#39;s household but answer to his wife. Whatever they are, they are no longer simply adventurers. The Reclaimers are the player character party -- a group of adventurers operating in the Backlands , the northern province of Argolle . They arrived individually in the aftermath of Crossings &#39; destruction, drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty on beastmen -- a gold mark for every beast&#39;s scalp. They were killers among killers, indistinguishable from the scalper gangs that filled the province. They are now formally part of Legate Marcellus&#39;s household at Fort Meade and hold his writ of tax exemption. Their true patron is Lady Severina Marcellus , who went behind her husband&#39;s back to hire them. At a Glance Detail Description Type Adventuring party (player characters) Base of Operations Shatzi -- Merchant (Organizer) A merchant failed and cast down, but sly -- never finished. Shatzi seeks some angle, always, to claw back what the world took from her. She is the Reclaimers&#39; organizer and de facto leader: the one who manages logistics, negotiates terms, handles finances, and holds a band of misfits together as a functioning enterprise in hostile territory. Her merchant&#39;s instinct is always working -- assessing, calculating, looking for the deal others have missed. Shatzi has been invited to Lady Severina&#39;s social gatherings at Fort Meade, reflecting Severina&#39;s recognition of a kindred operator. Both women understand the mechanics of influence and operate through practical intelligence rather than brute force. Theodotus -- Philosopher-Bard (Thrassian) A Thrassian whose books had soured him. Years of study and contemplation had left Theodotus hollow, unconvinced that the truths he sought could be found in libraries or lecture halls. He came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands -- not as a soldier or a scalper, but as something stranger: a philosopher who had decided that the lecture hall was a lie and the battlefield might be honest. Theodotus carries the Stone of Sakkara , an artifact of terrible and uncertain power. The Stone&#39;s presence at Fort Meade draws the Guzzler -- the demonic entity occupying Fort Ikenvar -- toward the garrison. The approximately one hundred soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The Stone makes Theodotus and the entire party a danger to the garrison that shelters them. Tiberius -- Mage (Necromancer) Schooled at the Imperial Academy in Mithra City , the Empire&#39;s preeminent institution of sorcerous learning. Tiberius was cast out for the blackness of his studies -- necromantic research sufficiently transgressive that even the Academy, which tolerates considerable clandestine experimentation behind its alabaster walls, could not permit him to remain. His exile was stayed only by his noble bloodlines; a man of lesser birth would have been executed. Tiberius came to the Backlands because the frontier&#39;s institutional structures are too weak to monitor or regulate sorcerous practice. The constant supply of death provides ample material for a necromancer&#39;s work. He is the party&#39;s most potent member in terms of raw sorcerous ability, but also the most dangerous -- to enemies, bystanders, and potentially to his companions. Iman -- Bladedancer Driven from the Order of the Scarlet Ribbon for speaking too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons. The Order -- a militant religious institution connected to the Empyrean faith -- trained bladedancers in the martial and devotional arts. Its priestesses maintained relationships with noble patrons that blurred the boundary between spiritual authority and secular power. Everyone within the Order understood this corruption. No one named it. Iman named it, and for this honesty she was expelled. Iman has developed a close personal relationship with Lady Severina Marcellus . Severina told Iman privately that she considers herself the real political engine of the Marcellus household -- a confidence suggesting trust that extends beyond the merely professional. Through Iman, the Reclaimers have a direct and personal line to their patron. Former Members Tancred -- Crusader of Seros (Deceased) A crusader bearing the fire of Seros who sought baptism in the blood of beasts. Tancred&#39;s martial calling was indistinguishable from his religious devotion -- the act of destroying the monstrous was itself an act of worship, a prayer spoken in steel and blood. He came to the Backlands because the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty had transformed the frontier into a crusade by another name. Tancred was the Reclaimers&#39; spiritual center -- the member whose convictions were absolute and whose purpose was unambiguous. His certainty steadied the group when doubt crept in. Tancred died during the campaign. He sought baptism in blood, and the frontier obliged him. His death left a void in the Reclaimers that has not been filled -- the party lost its spiritual certainty, the member who never doubted that the killing was righteous. Rendson -- Avari Gambler (Departed) An Avari gambler, whoremonger, and fugitive from debts whose past was soiled and unrevealed. Rendson was an early member of the Reclaimers during their initial period as scalpers in the Backlands. His debts were considerable and his habits worse. He departed the group early and vanished into the frontier. His fate is unknown. Origin and Hiring The Reclaimers did not begin as a coherent group. They arrived in the Backlands individually -- each drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty, by desperation, or by some private motive they did not share. The Backlands in the sixth year after the fall of Crossings was a land of ash and opportunity, filled with killers drawn by the promise of a gold mark for every beast&#39;s scalp. The Reclaimers were among these killers, initially indistinguishable from the other scalper gangs roaming the province. Shatzi organized the disparate individuals into a functioning group. Where Theodotus brought philosophical curiosity and Tiberius brought arcane power, Shatzi brought the thing the group actually needed: someone who could make it work. Her merchant&#39;s understanding of logistics, negotiation, and the management of unreliable people transformed a collection of misfits into an operational enterprise. The Reclaimers came to the attention of Lady Severina Marcellus at Fort Meade , the garrison commanded by her husband Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus . Severina hired them without the Legate&#39;s knowledge -- acting on her own political judgment rather than waiting for her husband&#39;s approval. They were formally absorbed into the Marcellus household with a writ of tax exemption. This fact -- that the Reclaimers were Severina&#39;s initiative, not the Legate&#39;s -- colors their position within the household. They are formally part of Marcellus&#39;s household, but their true patron is Severina. The Legate is aware of this dynamic and tolerates it because the Reclaimers have proven useful, though the arrangement is not without tension. Destruction of Rook The Reclaimers&#39; most significant accomplishment to date is the destruction of Rook at Fort Ikenvar . Rook&#39;s campaign of banditry had terrorized the settlements and trade routes of the Backlands for months -- targeted attacks on residents, disappeared travelers, deliberate intimidation. The garrison at Fort Meade could not resolve the threat. The Reclaimers tracked Rook to his base at Fort Ikenvar -- the ruined marsh fort east of Fort Meade -- and destroyed him there. This victory delivered what the garrison could not, a fact experienced by Legate Marcellus as both a professional humiliation and a political opportunity. It was during this period of the campaign that Tancred fell in battle -- the crusader of Seros who had sought baptism in the blood of beasts and found instead the death he had always courted. The Stone of Sakkara Theodotus carries the Stone of Sakkara -- an artifact of significant and dangerous properties. The Stone&#39;s presence at Fort Meade has drawn the Guzzler -- the demonic entity occupying Fort Ikenvar -- toward the garrison. The Guzzler cannot precisely locate the Stone but can sense its pull, compromising the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature. The ~100 soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The Stone&#39;s presence creates a threat that the garrison was never designed to counter. By carrying the Stone, the Reclaimers have inadvertently made themselves a danger to the very community that shelters them. The Nethercity The Reclaimers are currently exploring the Nethercity beneath Crossings -- an underground complex of significant scope and danger. The Nethercity has begun producing artifacts of genuine First Empire provenance, drawing the attention of multiple factions. The Argollean Brotherhood is monitoring what the Reclaimers recover from the Nethercity. Whether the Brotherhood approaches as buyers, competitors, or hostile actors depends entirely on what comes up and how the Reclaimers handle it. Malachor , representing the Imperial Academy , has a competing interest in the same artifacts. The presence of Tiberius -- a disgraced Academy mage -- in the same party that is recovering artifacts the Academy covets adds an additional layer of tension to this dynamic. Political Position The Reclaimers occupy a complicated and increasingly dangerous political position: Formally part of Legate Marcellus&#39;s household, holding his writ of tax exemption Actually hired by and loyal to Lady Severina , who engaged them without her husband&#39;s approval Socially connected to Severina through both Iman (close personal relationship) and Shatzi (invited to her gatherings) Professionally useful enough that the Legate tolerates the arrangement, despite the implicit humiliation Monitored by the Argollean Brotherhood , who want what they find in the Nethercity Of interest to Malachor and the Imperial Academy , who want the same artifacts for different reasons Carrying the Stone of Sakkara , which creates a demonic threat to the garrison that shelters them Harboring a disgraced Academy necromancer ( Tiberius ) whose former institution is now competing with them for Nethercity artifacts Who They Are The Reclaimers are not heroes. They are the kind of people the scalp bounty was designed to attract -- expendable, desperate, and willing to kill for coin. A failed merchant. A disillusioned philosopher. A disgraced necromancer whose noble blood saved him from execution. A bladedancer expelled for honesty. A dead crusader. A gambler who vanished. They came to the Backlands as carrion comes, drawn to rot. What they became -- the destroyers of Rook, the bearers of the Stone of Sakkara, the explorers of the Nethercity, the instruments of Lady Severina&#39;s political ambitions -- was not planned. It accumulated, the way mud accumulates on boots in the Backlands. One thing led to another, and now they are entangled in factional politics, demonic threats, and archaeological discoveries that extend far beyond the frontier scalp trade that brought them here. They are formally part of the Legate&#39;s household. They answer to his wife. They carry artifacts the Brotherhood wants and the Academy covets. Whatever they are, they are no longer simply adventurers. See Also campaign-chronicle -- The session-by-session chronicle of the campaign fort-meade -- The garrison where the Reclaimers are based legate-marcellus -- Their formal patron lady-severina -- Their actual patron rook -- The bandit they destroyed fort-ikenvar -- Where they destroyed Rook; where the Guzzler dwells Nethercity -- The underground complex they are currently exploring crossings -- The ruins above the Nethercity Stone of Sakkara -- The dangerous artifact Theodotus carries the-guzzler -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone argollean-brotherhood -- The faction monitoring their Nethercity recoveries malachor -- The Imperial Academy historian competing for the same artifacts imperial-academy -- The institution Malachor represents and Tiberius was expelled from order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon -- The militant order from which Iman was expelled seros -- The faith Tancred served scalper-gangs -- The other killers drawn by the bounty the-backlands -- The province in which they operate shatzi -- Party organizer, Merchant theodotus -- Party member, Philosopher-Bard tiberius -- Party member, Necromancer iman -- Party member, Bladedancer tancred -- Former party member, Crusader (deceased)"},{"slug":"the-stone-of-sakkara","title":"The Stone of Sakkara","category":"lore","tags":"artifact stone-of-sakkara theodotus guzzler corruption fort-meade fort-ikenvar sanctuary moral-crisis","text":"The Stone of Sakkara The Stone of Sakkara is an artifact of terrible and uncertain power currently carried by Theodotus , the Thrassian Philosopher-Bard of the Reclaimers . The Stone&#39;s nature is not fully understood, but its effects are becoming catastrophically clear: it draws the Guzzler -- the demonic entity at Fort Ikenvar -- toward whoever carries it, and when its bearer refuses to feed it, the Stone reaches further, amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent. Properties The Pull The Stone of Sakkara exerts an influence that can be sensed by demonic entities. The Guzzler at Fort Ikenvar has been drawn toward it for weeks, ranging further and further from its lair in the ruined marsh fort. The Guzzler cannot locate the Stone precisely -- it feels it the way an animal senses weather before it turns. The pull is not a beacon. It is a pressure, a gradient, an ambient wrongness that the Guzzler follows without understanding. When the Reclaimers were at Fort Meade , the Guzzler followed. When the party moved south toward Sanctuary , the Guzzler followed south. The Stone&#39;s influence is not bounded by distance in any obvious way -- it simply pulls, and what it pulls toward itself is hunger. The Amplification The Stone is not directing the Guzzler with intelligence. It has no agenda, no consciousness, no plan. But it is amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent . This is not a targeting mechanism -- it is a distortion of the Guzzler&#39;s already indiscriminate appetite, bending it toward the most vulnerable prey. Farm animals. Horses. Children. Theodotus refused to feed the Stone. The Stone&#39;s response was not retribution -- it is not capable of retribution. It simply reached further. The refusal to feed it did not stop the hunger. It redirected it. The Stone found other sources of sustenance by amplifying the Guzzler&#39;s predatory range and focusing its appetite on easier, softer, more innocent targets. The Wrongness Theodotus does not perceive the Stone&#39;s influence clearly. He feels it as a wrongness -- a sense that the suffering he hears about along the road is somehow adjacent to the weight in his pack. Not a voice. Not a compulsion. Just a persistent, gnawing awareness that the violence happening around him is not random, that its proximity to his path is not coincidence, and that the artifact he carries is somehow the center of gravity around which the suffering orbits. The Trail of Incidents As the Reclaimers move south from Fort Meade toward Sanctuary , the Guzzler follows, and the Stone&#39;s amplification produces an escalating trail of violence along the road: A farm three miles south of Fort Meade: Goats taken. Fence posts crushed in. The farmer reports it two days late, embarrassed he waited. A merchant on the Sanctuary road: His draft horse found half-consumed at the roadside. He saw nothing. Heard nothing. The horse was simply gone. Closer to Sanctuary: A child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go. The escalation is not coincidence. The Stone amplifies hunger toward innocence, and each incident is more devastating than the last. Farm animals. A horse. A child. The trajectory is clear and terrible. Theodotus&#39;s Moral Crisis When the child&#39;s disappearance reaches Theodotus -- by rumor, or by encountering the family directly on the road -- the wrongness crystallizes. The ambient unease becomes certainty. This is the test. Not a combat encounter. A question. Several questions: Does he tell the party what he suspects? The Stone&#39;s influence has been his burden alone. Sharing it means admitting that the deaths along the road may be his fault -- not through action, but through possession. Does he try to destroy the Stone? And does he know how? The Stone&#39;s nature is not understood. Destruction may not be possible, or may release something worse. Does he draw the Guzzler away from the road deliberately? Leading it into wilderness, away from settlements and travelers -- a sacrifice of convenience for the sake of innocent lives. Does he realize the geometry of innocence does not change? Putting distance between himself and the Stone means it simply calls the creature further. The Guzzler&#39;s range extends. The innocents along the new path are no safer than the ones along the old. The problem is not location. The problem is the Stone. The Core Truth Killing the Guzzler resolves nothing. The Stone will reach through something else. The Guzzler is a symptom, not the disease. Whatever hunger the Stone amplifies, whatever demonic attention it attracts, destroying one vessel of that hunger does not eliminate the hunger itself. Another entity will be drawn. Another predator will be bent toward innocence. The Stone is the problem. The scene ends when Theodotus decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies. Factional Interest The Stone of Sakkara has drawn attention from multiple factions: The Argollean Brotherhood is aware of the Stone and has an interest in it -- likely viewing it as an artifact of Eladran or Argollean provenance that belongs to the descendants of its creators. Malachor of the Imperial Academy has a competing interest -- the Academy would view the Stone as a subject of scholarly study and, ultimately, imperial property. Theodotus carries it, and the moral weight of that carrying is growing heavier with every incident along the road. Unresolved Questions What is the Stone of Sakkara? Its origin, its purpose, and the nature of its power remain unknown. Can it be destroyed? And what would happen if it were? Is the Stone sentient? Its behavior suggests something more than inert enchantment -- the amplification of hunger toward innocence implies a will, or at least a preference. But Theodotus&#39;s perception of it as a wrongness rather than a voice suggests it operates below the threshold of consciousness. What does feeding the Stone mean? Theodotus refused to feed it. What would feeding it look like? What would it require? What will the Stone reach through next? If the Guzzler is destroyed, what entity or force will the Stone attract next? Who or what is Sakkara? The name itself is unexplored. See Also theodotus -- The Reclaimer who carries the Stone the-guzzler -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone fort-ikenvar -- The Guzzler&#39;s lair fort-meade -- The garrison endangered by the Stone&#39;s pull sanctuary -- The city the Reclaimers are traveling toward, where the Guzzler&#39;s arrival would be catastrophic the-reclaimers -- The party implicated in the Stone&#39;s trail of violence argollean-brotherhood -- Faction interested in the Stone malachor -- Academy historian with competing interest imperial-academy -- Institution that would claim the Stone for study campaign-chronicle -- Session history documenting the Stone&#39;s effects"},{"slug":"the-veil","title":"The Veil","category":"lore","tags":"veil beyond sorcery corruption membrane multiverse elvoran cthonic demons lakandi magic","text":"The Veil The Veil is the living membrane between the mortal realm and the Beyond — the barrier, boundary, and point of contact that separates the material world from the vast, alien expanse of other planes, forgotten gods, and raw metaphysical potential that lies on the other side. The Veil is not a wall or a border in any conventional sense. It is a living thing — a dynamic, responsive, semi-permeable membrane that was created as a cosmic wound when The Aurelion sacrificed itself, and that has pulsed, shifted, and fluctuated ever since. The Veil was first discovered — or first understood — by the Elvoran , who perceived it through senses and cognitive frameworks that other races lack. The Elvoran understanding of the Veil remains the most sophisticated in the known world, though human sorcerers, particularly those trained in Gnostic Geometry at the Imperial Academy , have developed their own theoretical frameworks for understanding and interacting with the membrane. Nature of the Veil A Living Membrane The Veil is not static. It breathes, contracts, expands, thins, and thickens in response to forces both natural and artificial. Certain locations are naturally thin — places where the membrane between the mortal realm and the Beyond is so attenuated that entities, energies, or perceptions can pass between the two with relative ease. Other locations are thick, reinforced by centuries of Empyrean worship, consecrated ground, or simple distance from sources of metaphysical stress. The Thousand Temples have long understood that temples and consecrated sites serve a practical function beyond the spiritual — they reinforce the Veil, thickening the membrane and making it harder for the forces beyond to penetrate. Not Merely a Boundary The Veil is not merely a dividing line between here and there but a point of contact — a multiversal tangle of alien planes, forgotten gods, and raw metaphysical potential. The Beyond is not a single place but an infinite expanse of realities, dimensions, and states of being that human minds were not designed to comprehend. Some of these planes are inhabited by intelligences — demons, titans, forgotten gods, entities that defy categorization — and the Veil is the only thing preventing direct contact between these intelligences and the mortal world. Created as a Cosmic Wound The Veil came into existence as a consequence of The Aurelion &#39;s sacrifice — the cosmic wound left behind when the supreme designer tore itself apart to create the cosmos. In this sense, the Veil is a scar — the boundary between the reality that the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice created and the void that existed before. It is simultaneously a consequence of creation and a reminder of the violence that creation required. The Veil is the place where the ordered cosmos meets the unordered void, and the tension between these two states is what gives the membrane its dynamic, living quality. Sorcery and the Veil Opening Wounds The fundamental act of sorcery — whether practiced through Gnostic Geometry , warlock pacts, hedge-magic, or any other tradition — involves opening wounds in the Veil to siphon energies from the Beyond into the material world. This process is inherently violent. The sorcerer is not gently parting a curtain or opening a door; he is tearing a hole in a living membrane, contesting with the very fabric of reality to create an opening through which power can flow. The Veil resists, the energies beyond are hostile or at best indifferent to mortal purposes, and the act of sorcery leaves both the sorcerer and the membrane damaged. This is why sorcery is dangerous, why it is regulated, and why even the most disciplined practitioners of Gnostic Geometry treat their art with caution and respect. The Imperial Academy teaches that sorcery is the controlled manipulation of metaphysical axioms — a structured, lawful practice governed by the nine-fold geometric patterns described in The Anthyllium . But even the most structured sorcery still involves wounding the Veil, and every wound, no matter how carefully controlled, carries risk. Corruption of Flesh and Mind Prolonged contact with the Veil — or more precisely, prolonged exposure to the energies that flow through the wounds sorcerers create in it — corrupts both flesh and mind. The physical signs are unmistakable and well-documented: eyes blacken, filling with darkness as the sclera darkens to the color of pitch. Bones warp, bending and growing in unnatural configurations. Voices change, taking on harmonics and resonances that no human throat should be able to produce. Skin may harden, crack, or develop patterns that resemble the sigils used in Gnostic Geometry . The mental corruption is equally severe and far more insidious. Sorcerers who draw too heavily or too frequently from the Veil report hearing voices, experiencing alien perceptions, losing time, and finding that their thought patterns have been altered in ways they cannot identify or reverse. The boundary between the sorcerer&#39;s own consciousness and the entities or energies beyond the Veil begins to blur, and in extreme cases, the sorcerer may lose the ability to distinguish between their own thoughts and the whisperings of the Beyond. This corruption is a physical and spiritual reality, not merely a metaphor or a moral judgment. It is the price that the mortal body and mind pay for contesting with forces that were never meant to flow through human flesh. The Beyond Alien Planes The Beyond encompasses an unknown and potentially infinite number of alien planes — realities that operate according to laws fundamentally different from those governing the material world. Some of these planes are hostile environments where mortal life cannot survive. Others are habitable but profoundly alien, governed by physics, biology, and metaphysics that bear no resemblance to anything in the material world. The geography, if it can be called that, of the Beyond is poorly mapped and potentially unmappable — the planes shift, merge, divide, and reconfigure in ways that defy cartographic discipline. Forgotten Gods and Titans Among the inhabitants of the Beyond are entities of immense power — forgotten gods, primordial titans, and beings of such alien nature that the words god and titan are only approximate labels. These entities predate the current cosmic order, or emerged from realities parallel to it, and their relationship to The Aurelion , Seros , and the Cthonic Pantheon is poorly understood. Some may be the remnants of cosmological systems that the Aurelion&#39;s sacrifice overwrote or displaced. Others may be native to the void that existed before creation. Their intentions toward the material world, if they have intentions at all, are rarely benign. Communion with Cthonic Powers The Veil permits communion with the Cthonic gods , demons, and the forgotten titans described above. The Cthonic Faith has long used the Veil as a medium of communication and transaction — rituals performed at thin points in the membrane can reach across the divide and establish contact with Cthonic entities, receiving guidance, power, or direct supernatural intervention in exchange for offerings, oaths, or the creation of conditions favorable to the entity&#39;s interests. This practice is the foundation of Cthonic priestly power and the mechanism by which Cthonic cults maintain their connection to their divine patrons. Lakandi Demon-Binding The Lakandi practice a distinctive form of interaction with the Veil: individual-scale demon-binding. Rather than the communal rituals and priestly hierarchies that characterize most Cthonic interactions with the Veil, the Lakandi binding tradition involves individual practitioners establishing personal relationships with specific demonic entities, binding them through negotiated contracts and using them as sources of power, knowledge, or direct supernatural service. This practice is conducted at the individual scale — each Lakandi binder negotiates their own contract, bears their own risks, and reaps their own rewards. The tradition is ancient, deeply embedded in Lakandi culture, and operated with a degree of openness and social acceptance that would be unthinkable in most Mithrian communities. The Lakandi do not view demon-binding as evil or corrupting but as a practical skill — dangerous, certainly, but no more inherently immoral than any other form of commerce or negotiation. See Also The Aurelion Seros Gnostic Geometry The Anthyllium The Flame Imperial Academy Cthonic Faith Cthonic Pantheon Cthonic Corruption Lakandi Binding Tradition Magic and Sorcery Races and Cultures Thousand Temples"},{"slug":"the-womb-curse","title":"The Womb Curse","category":"lore","tags":"eladra elvora mystery womb-curse eolande malachor black-tree barren immortal veil","text":"The Womb Curse The Womb Curse is a term mentioned by Eolande -- the ancient Eladran general from approximately 3000 BE -- during his encounter with the Reclaimers at the Black Tree at Thornasse . Its full nature has not yet been revealed. At a Glance Detail Description First Mentioned By eolande Context Discussion of the [[eladra Urgently Sought By [[malachor Status Mystery -- nature unclear Likely Connection The [[elvora What Is Known [[Eolande mentioned the Womb Curse at the Black Tree during his encounter with the Reclaimers. The specific context of his remarks is not fully recorded, but the mention was significant enough to provoke an urgent reaction from Malachor , the Imperial Academy agent stationed at Fort Meade . Malachor&#39;s response was immediate and intense: What did he say about the Womb Curse? About the Eladra? -- the urgency of a scholar who has been searching for this information and recognizes its importance the moment it surfaces. Probable Connections The Womb Curse likely relates to one or both of the following: The Elvora Condition The Elvora -- the corrupted descendants of the Eladra who plunged into the chaos of the Beyond -- suffer a specific and devastating biological curse: All Elvora females are barren -- they cannot bear children All Elvora males are immortal -- they do not age or die of natural causes This combination is a slow-motion extinction event. The Elvora cannot reproduce. Their numbers can only decrease. Their immortality is not a gift but a sentence -- eternal life for a dying race. The term Womb Curse aligns precisely with this condition: a curse that strikes at the womb, at reproduction, at the continuation of the species. The Eladran Disappearance The Eladra of Aodahn vanished without explanation. Their belongings remained. Their constructs continued to function. But the people simply ceased to be present. The Womb Curse may be connected to whatever metaphysical event caused this disappearance -- perhaps the same force that rendered the Elvora barren also destroyed or transformed the Eladra of Aodahn. The Threshold in the Undercity beneath Sanctuary -- the place where the Eladra ascension happened and the door has not fully closed -- may be the site where the Womb Curse originated or was enacted. Malachor&#39;s Interest Malachor&#39;s urgent interest in the Womb Curse reveals that the Imperial Academy has prior knowledge of the concept -- enough to recognize the term immediately and understand its significance. The Academy has clearly been investigating the Eladran mystery, and the Womb Curse is a piece of that puzzle they have been seeking. That an Academy agent stationed in the remote Backlands reacts with such urgency suggests the Womb Curse is not merely an academic curiosity but a matter of active strategic or metaphysical importance to the Academy. Eolande&#39;s Knowledge Eolande dates from approximately 3000 BE -- over five thousand years before the current campaign date. If the Womb Curse was known in his time, it predates the Elvora&#39;s corruption, the fall of the Argollean Empire , and the rise of human civilization in Argolle. This would mean the Womb Curse is an ancient phenomenon -- not a recent corruption but something woven into the deep history of the Eladran race. Alternatively, Eolande&#39;s millennia of existence at the Black Tree may have given him knowledge of events that occurred long after his own era. A being who has persisted for five thousand years has had time to witness -- or learn of -- the Elvora&#39;s transformation and the Eladran disappearance. Open Questions Is the Womb Curse the same phenomenon that rendered the Elvora barren and immortal? Did the Womb Curse cause the Eladra of Aodahn to vanish? Is the Womb Curse connected to the Threshold in the Undercity ? Why does the Imperial Academy consider this information urgent? What does Eolande know that Malachor does not? Is the Womb Curse a natural consequence of contact with the Veil , or was it deliberately inflicted? See Also eolande -- The ancient Eladran general who mentioned the Womb Curse malachor -- The Imperial Academy agent urgently seeking information about it eladra -- The race the Womb Curse concerns elvora -- Corrupted Eladra whose barrenness may be the Womb Curse manifest aodahn -- The Eladran city whose inhabitants vanished the-undercity -- The megadungeon beneath Sanctuary, site of the Threshold the-black-tree -- Where Eolande mentioned the Womb Curse thornasse -- Site of the Black Tree encounter the-veil -- The metaphysical boundary possibly connected to the Curse imperial-academy -- The institution investigating the Eladran mystery"},{"slug":"thrassian","title":"Thrassian","category":"lore","tags":"culture thrassian naming human tribal warrior military","text":"Thrassian The Thrassians are a proud and warlike mountain people whose ancient tribal system persists within the framework of the Mithrian Empire . Though formally incorporated into the Empire, Thrassian communities maintain strong tribal identities, and old loyalties to clan and chief often compete with obligations to the Imperial state. Physical Appearance Thrassians are characterized by their curly dark hair and dark eyes. Their mountain heritage gives them sturdy, weathered builds suited to the harsh terrain of Thrassia. They are a physically imposing people, shaped by generations of highland warfare and pastoral life. Culture and Values Thrassian culture is fundamentally tribal and warrior-oriented. The tribe is the primary unit of Thrassian identity, superseding even family in matters of loyalty and obligation. Thrassian tribes are led by chiefs whose authority derives from martial prowess, demonstrated wisdom, and the consent of the tribal council. The Thrassians are the backbone of the Mithrian military . Their warrior traditions, physical toughness, and fierce loyalty to comrades make them natural soldiers, and Thrassian recruits have filled the ranks of Imperial legions since the earliest days of the Empire. A disproportionate number of the Empire&#39;s most decorated soldiers and most feared units are of Thrassian origin. Thrassian tribes clash and assist each other with equal fervor. Intertribal rivalries are fierce and sometimes violent, but when an external threat appears, the same tribes that were raiding each other&#39;s herds will fight shoulder to shoulder without hesitation. This duality -- fierce internal competition combined with absolute solidarity against outsiders -- is the defining characteristic of Thrassian social life. Naming Conventions Thrassians employ a patronymic system that ties each individual directly to their parent: Men use the suffixes -ides or -ion (e.g., Alexandrides, meaning son of Alexander ; Demetrion, meaning son of Demetrios ) Women use the suffixes -aia or -essa (e.g., Helenaia, meaning daughter of Helen ; Sophiessa, meaning daughter of Sophia ) A Thrassian&#39;s tribal affiliation remains a critical component of their identity and is often appended informally to their name. A Thrassian warrior might introduce himself not merely as Leonides but as Leonides of the Hawk Tribe -- the tribal identity carrying as much weight as the patronymic itself. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures mithrian-empire -- The empire the Thrassians serve mithrian-military -- The military institution Thrassians form the backbone of sanctuary -- Where Thrassian sailors fill the harbor taverns"},{"slug":"thune","title":"Thune","category":"lore","tags":"race thune reptilian argollean ygrathen slave-soldiers cthonic thunean-empire massar awakening breeding","text":"Thune The Thune were created by the Argolleans as slave soldiers to fight against the Ygrathen -- living weapons bred for war. They are reptilian in appearance and possess an alien cunning and intellect that sets them apart from the other races of Mithrapos . The Thune are wicked and violent by nature and by design, and their patience is as formidable as their savagery. Physical Appearance The Thune come in various shapes and sizes , the product of extensive breeding programs conducted over millennia. The Argolleans engineered the Thune for specific military roles, and the results of that engineering persist: Some are small and swift , bred for scouting and infiltration Others are massive and heavily armored , designed for frontline combat All share the fundamental reptilian characteristics of scaled skin, cold blood, and predatory instinct The variety of Thune physiology reflects the thoroughness of their creators&#39; design -- the Argolleans did not create a single type of soldier but an entire ecosystem of war-forms, each optimized for a specific purpose. Culture and Values The Thune possess an alien cunning and intellect that is not fully understood by human scholars. Their minds do not work like human minds -- their priorities, their patience, their relationship to time and planning all operate on principles that human psychology struggles to model. The Thune embody the Cthonic faith in its most brutal form: the strongest consume and rule the weakest . This is not merely a philosophical position but the organizing principle of Thune society. Power is absolute, hierarchy is determined by force, and the weak exist to serve or be devoured by the strong. There is no mercy in Thune culture because mercy is a concept that has no place in their understanding of the world. History Creation The Thune were created by the Argollean Empire as slave soldiers to fight the Ygrathen -- the oldest race of Mithrapos, whose solitary nature and formidable sorcerous power made them a persistent threat. The Thune were designed to be expendable, replaceable, and absolutely obedient. They were tools, not people, and the Argolleans treated them accordingly. The Thunean Empire The Thune eventually broke free of Argollean control and built the Thunean Empire -- a dominion built on conquest, cruelty, and the subjugation of all other peoples within their reach. The Thunean Empire was a brutal regime even by the harsh standards of Mithrapos , and its legacy of violence and oppression has colored the way all other peoples regard the Thune to this day. Overthrow by the Massar The Thunean Empire was eventually overthrown by Massar advisors -- counselors who had been brought into the Thunean court and who used their position to orchestrate the empire&#39;s downfall from within. The Massar accomplished through patient political manipulation what no army had managed through force of arms: the destruction of the Thunean Empire from the inside out. Current Status In the present day, the Thune are found only in rare pockets -- scattered remnants of their former empire, hiding in remote and inhospitable regions. They are savage but biding their time for what they call the Awakening -- a prophesied event in which the Thune will rise again to reclaim their former dominion. The Awakening is not a vague hope but a fixed certainty in Thune culture. They do not question whether it will come -- they prepare for when it comes. The patience of the Thune is measured in generations, and their plans operate on timescales that human strategists cannot easily comprehend. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures Argolle -- The empire that created the Thune ygrathen -- The ancient race the Thune were created to fight massar -- The people who overthrew the Thunean Empire cthonic-faith -- The faith the Thune embody history-of-mithrapos -- The broader historical context"},{"slug":"vestari","title":"Vestari","category":"lore","tags":"culture vestari naming human bellasarius mithrian-league cosmopolitan aristocratic nobility","text":"Vestari The Vestari are a proud and aristocratic people who trace their lineage to Bellasarius Valerian , the legendary general who co-founded the Mithrian League alongside the Prophet Enador . This claimed descent from the Empire&#39;s greatest hero gives the Vestari an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny. Physical Appearance The Vestari are tall and narrow-faced with heavy brows and black hair , which is characteristically slicked back . Men carry heavy, well-groomed beards as a mark of dignity and status -- a Vestari man&#39;s beard is a statement of identity, and its care and presentation are matters of serious concern. Their skin ranges from olive to pale , and they favor ornate jewelry -- rings, chains, clasps, and brooches -- as expressions of wealth, lineage, and personal accomplishment. Vestari clothing is similarly ornate, with rich fabrics and elaborate detailing that reflect the wearer&#39;s status and heritage. Culture and Values The Vestari are cosmopolitan allies of Mithra and were the first city-state to join the Mithrian League . Uniquely among the peoples incorporated into the League, the Vestari joined without bloodshed -- a distinction they have never let anyone forget. Where other peoples were conquered, subjugated, or coerced, the Vestari came willingly, recognizing in the League the fulfillment of the vision their ancestor Bellasarius had fought for. The Vestari nobility traces its lineage to Bellasarius himself. Whether this descent is historically accurate or a product of centuries of genealogical invention is a matter that no one raises in polite Vestari company. The claim is the foundation of Vestari identity, and to challenge it is to challenge the Vestari sense of self. The Vestari&#39;s sense of cultural superiority is not aggressive but pervasive. They regard themselves as the truest heirs of the League&#39;s founding ideals, the people most closely connected to the heroic age that produced the Empire. This conviction shapes their politics, their art, their social expectations, and their interactions with every other culture in the Empire. Naming Conventions Vestari names are ornate and multi-syllabic , frequently incorporating references to: Virtues -- names that invoke courage, wisdom, justice, and honor Ancestors -- names that connect the bearer to illustrious forebears Religious concepts -- names drawn from Empyrean theology and the Measure and the Scale A Vestari&#39;s full name is a declaration of heritage -- a compressed genealogy that connects the bearer to their illustrious forebears and the spiritual ideals they are expected to uphold. The Vestari follow Mithrian naming conventions , employing the same three-part system (praenomen, nomen, cognomen) used by the dominant culture. This is not imitation but a shared inheritance -- the Vestari regard the naming conventions not as borrowed from Mithrian culture but as a tradition they helped create. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures Bellasarius Valerian -- The legendary ancestor of the Vestari mithrian-empire -- The empire the Vestari helped found mithrian-culture -- The culture whose naming conventions the Vestari share history-of-mithrapos -- The founding of the Mithrian League empyrean-faith -- The faith that shapes Vestari spiritual life"},{"slug":"war-of-three-emperors","title":"The War of Three Emperors (270 IY)","category":"lore","tags":"event history civil-war house-decimus house-valerian succession-crisis aurex claudius-decimus","text":"The War of Three Emperors (270 IY) The War of Three Emperors (270 IY) was the devastating civil war that erupted following the assassination of the mad Emperor Aurex of House Valerian . The conflict ended the Valerian dynasty&#39;s centuries-long hold on the Imperial throne and established House Decimus as the ruling house of the Mithrian Empire -- a position it retains to this day. We traded madness for cowardice, then cowardice for coin. Of all our emperors, it was the one who ruled for 87 days who showed the greatest strength. -- Claudius Decimus , on accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate Causes Emperor Aurex of House Valerian had brought the Empire to the brink of collapse through madness and cruelty. When his own sister assassinated him -- an act of desperate necessity -- he died without naming an heir. The Valerian dynasty, which had held the throne for centuries, ended not with a battle but with a knife in the dark and an empty succession. The absence of a clear successor created a power vacuum that drew in every ambitious general, governor, and noble house in the Empire. The Scholar-Emperor Numerius In the immediate aftermath of Aurex&#39;s assassination, the scholar Numerius was installed as Emperor -- a principled and learned man who attempted to restore order through reason, law, and good governance. Numerius ruled for only 87 days before he was murdered. His brief reign is remembered as a tragedy. Claudius Decimus himself would later eulogize Numerius as the Emperor who showed the greatest strength -- a man whose virtues were precisely the qualities the Imperial system was least equipped to sustain. Numerius&#39;s murder demonstrated that the Empire did not reward wisdom or principle; it rewarded power. The Civil War Following Numerius&#39;s death, the Empire descended into open civil war. Multiple claimants raised armies, forged alliances, and fought for the throne. The conflict was brutal and widespread, drawing in the Great Houses and their tributary networks, threatening to tear the Empire apart entirely. The details of the war -- which claimants fought, which alliances formed and collapsed, which battles decided the outcome -- are recorded in Imperial chronicles. What matters for the present is the result: Claudius Decimus emerged victorious from the chaos, defeating his rivals through military competence, strategic patience, and the ruthlessness that civil wars demand. Consequences The War of Three Emperors reshaped the political order of the Mithrian Empire : House Decimus was established as the ruling dynasty. The Decimus line has held the throne without interruption from 270 IY to the present day. House Valerian lost the throne permanently. The house retained its prestige and wealth but was stripped of political supremacy. Many believe the Valerians have never stopped scheming toward restoration. The precedent of violent succession was reinforced. The Empire has no stable mechanism for the peaceful transfer of power, and the War of Three Emperors demonstrated -- again -- that the throne ultimately belongs to whoever can take it by force. Claudius Decimus&#39;s legacy -- His words upon accepting the title of Imperator revealed a man acutely aware of the Empire&#39;s decline: a trajectory from madness to cowardice to greed that had corroded the foundations of imperial governance. Later Succession Crisis The Decimus dynasty&#39;s own history has not been free of succession violence. Julian Decimus , a later Emperor, named his son Diometian as heir -- a decision that triggered civil war when rival claimants and discontented houses refused to accept the appointment. The resulting conflict demonstrated that the problems of succession that destroyed the Valerian dynasty had not been solved by replacing it. See Also Claudius Decimus -- the victor and dynasty founder Emperor Aurex -- the mad Emperor whose death triggered the crisis House Decimus -- the dynasty that emerged from the war House Valerian -- the dynasty that fell Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus -- the current Emperor History of Mithrapos -- broader historical context The Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"ygrathen","title":"Ygrathen","category":"lore","tags":"race ygrathen ancient sorcery solitary cairnhouse kharai binding grathar varek-ashstone argollean","text":"Ygrathen The Ygrathen are the oldest of all the races of Mithrapos -- ancient beyond reckoning, predating even the Eladra and the Argollean Empire . They are solitary beings by nature, possessed of tremendous physical and sorcerous power, and they embody one of the most profound insights in the world&#39;s history: some things cannot be ended, only contained. Physical Appearance The Ygrathen are massive -- standing approximately 12 feet tall , with greenish or ochre skin and small tusks protruding from their lower jaws. Despite their brutish appearance, they are beings of tremendous intelligence and sorcerous ability. Their size, their coloring, and their tusks make them immediately recognizable -- and immediately formidable. There is nothing subtle about an Ygrathen&#39;s presence. Culture and Nature The Ygrathen never formed their own civilization in any conventional sense. They are too solitary, too individualistic, and too prone to conflict with their own kind. Throughout their long history, the Ygrathen clashed amongst themselves as often as they fought against other races, preventing any lasting social organization from taking root. Breeding The Ygrathen are solitary beings who come together only to breed every 33 years under specific cosmological conditions tied to the alignment of celestial bodies. This extremely infrequent reproduction, combined with their solitary nature and the devastating losses of their war against the Argollean Empire, has reduced their numbers to near-extinction. Sorcery The Ygrathen possess powerful sorcery -- their magical abilities are among the most formidable in the world. Ygrathen sorcery is not learned from books or academies but is an expression of their fundamental nature, refined over lifespans that may stretch for centuries or millennia. History The War Against the Argollean Empire The Ygrathen&#39;s war against the Argollean Empire was a cataclysmic conflict that left most of their kind dead or driven into hiding . The Argolleans created the Thune specifically as slave soldiers to fight the Ygrathen -- a testament to how formidable the Ygrathen were as opponents. The war drained the Empire&#39;s resources and weakened its foundations even as it drove the Ygrathen to the edge of extinction. The few survivors retreated into the most remote and inaccessible regions of Mithrapos, where they remain to this day -- hidden, diminished, but not extinct. The Cairnhouses and the Kharai The Ygrathen built cairnhouses -- structures of Ygrathen design, engineered with precision and sustained intention, designed to imprison the Kharai (the Imprisoned Ones). The Kharai are beings of enormous will and appetite, ancient beyond reckoning, that defy classification within either Empyrean or Cthonic frameworks. They are simply what they are: vast, patient, and impossible to destroy . The Ygrathen imprisoned the Kharai rather than destroying them. The most straightforward explanation is that they could not be destroyed. But there is another possibility: perhaps the Ygrathen understood something about the Kharai that has since been forgotten -- that destruction was possible but unwise, that the Kharai serve a function in the deep structure of the world. This is the central Ygrathen insight: some things cannot be ended, only contained. The cairnhouses are the physical expression of this understanding -- structures designed to hold beings that will never stop pressing against their confinement, maintained by practitioners whose vigil may last centuries. At least two cairnhouses are known to exist in Argolle : The cairnhouse on the island of Kantar in Lake Silverhead -- watched over by Varek Ashstone The cairnhouse at Cairnhill -- whose psychic bleed has shaped the town&#39;s population over six to seven generations The Grathar The Grathar people carry Ygrathen blood in their veins -- a heritage that accounts for their exceptional size and strength, their ochre-to-greenish skin tone, and their reclusive temperament. The Grathar are the most visible legacy of the Ygrathen in the modern world, living proof that the oldest race of Mithrapos has not been entirely lost. Varek Ashstone Varek Ashstone is a known Ygrathen hermit who built the cairnhouse at Kantar and has maintained a solitary vigil over it for centuries. He lives in a stone dwelling on the northern shore of Lake Silverhead . The Avari call him the Old One or simply Varek. He is very large, very old, very tired, and very capable. His vigil is penance for something that went wrong during the cairnhouse&#39;s construction -- people died, and Varek has spent the centuries since as atonement. Varek&#39;s power is the binding tradition : the art of sealing and containing powerful entities. He is one of the last living practitioners of this tradition at its full scale. His capabilities are demonstrated not in dramatic displays of force but in what does not happen near Lake Silverhead -- things from the outlands that have approached Kantar have been turned away, bound, redirected, or persuaded that the cost was greater than the return. The Ygrathen Binding Tradition The Ygrathen binding tradition is related to but distinct from the Lakandi binding tradition . The Ygrathen bind at a scale that exceeds even the Elvora : they imprisoned beings that cannot be destroyed, using structures designed to endure for millennia. The Lakandi operate at the opposite end of the spectrum -- individual practitioners binding individual entities for personal use. The traditions share a common root but have diverged enormously in scope and application. See Also races-and-cultures -- Overview of all races and cultures varek-ashstone -- The Ygrathen hermit of Lake Silverhead the-kharai -- The Imprisoned Ones the Ygrathen built cairnhouses to contain cairnhill -- A town shaped by a cairnhouse&#39;s psychic bleed grathar -- The human people who carry Ygrathen blood Argolle -- The empire that warred against the Ygrathen thune -- The slave soldiers created to fight the Ygrathen eladra -- The ancient race that postdates the Ygrathen elvora -- A race whose binding tradition parallels the Ygrathen&#39;s lakandi-binding-tradition -- The individual-scale binding tradition argollean-brotherhood -- The faction seeking access to cairnhouse binding structures"},{"slug":"overview","title":"The Fallen Empire — Campaign Overview","category":"overview","tags":"overview backlands fallen-empire","text":"The Fallen Empire — Campaign Overview The Setting The world of Mithrapos is a region encircling the Middle Sea, shaped by the rise and fall of empires. The ancient Argollean Empire (the First Empire) fell long ago, but its echoes still influence the modern Mithrian Empire — the dominant power of the region, now in what many believe to be its twilight. The Mithrian Empire is ruled by Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus from the alabaster walls of Mithra City . Imperial power rests on four pillars: the military , the Imperial Academy of sorcery, the Thousand Temples of Seros , and the Great Houses that dominate politics through patronage. The sacred text The Measure and the Scale serves as both religious doctrine and legal framework. Three traditions of magic exist: the Academy&#39;s gnostic geometry, the Elvoran art of piercing the Veil, and the Flame channeled by the faithful of Seros. The Empyrean and Cthonic faiths offer competing visions of the cosmos — one of reincarnation and purification, the other of consumption and the prophesied Awakening. The Empire outlaws Cthonic worship, but its cults persist in shadow. The Backlands The Backlands is a remote northern province of the Mithrian Empire — the frontier. In 377 IY, a beastman horde sacked the town of Crossings, and the Emperor&#39;s response (a scalp bounty that drew mercenaries, deserters, and killers into the region) left the Backlands in a state of simmering chaos. The current year is 380 IY . Current Campaign The Reclaimers — a party of adventurers operating in the Backlands. See Also mithrian-empire — Political structure and governance great-houses — The noble houses that shape imperial politics history-of-mithrapos — Timeline of key events magic-and-sorcery — The three traditions of sorcery races-and-cultures — Peoples of Mithrapos empyrean-faith — The state religion cthonic-faith — The outlawed dark cults"},{"slug":"anaya","title":"Anaya","category":"people","tags":"henchman reclaimers corruption wounded visions gallowswood backlands","text":"Anaya Anaya is a henchman serving the Reclaimers . She suffered a critical wound from a zombie beastman and has since been afflicted with fever and infection -- but what troubles those around her is not the wound itself but what has followed it. At a Glance Detail Description Role Henchman of the-reclaimers Status Active -- wounded, feverish, possibly corrupted Wound Critical injury from a zombie beastman Condition Feverish, wound infected, experiencing disturbing visions Threat Possible [[cthonic-corruption The Wound Anaya was critically wounded by a zombie beastman -- an undead creature combining the savagery of [[beastmen with the horror of necromantic animation. The wound has become infected and she is feverish, but the physical injury may be the least of her problems. The Visions Since her wounding, Anaya speaks of a pulsating black heart beneath the mound in the Gallowswood . She describes it as calling to her, beckoning her forth -- a psychic pull from whatever entity or force lies beneath the granite dome in the cursed forest. The Gallowswood is a place where the dead walk beneath the roots, and a pulsating black heart beats beneath a granite dome. Anaya&#39;s visions suggest a direct connection between her zombie beastman wound and whatever Cthonic power animates the Gallowswood&#39;s undead. Greta&#39;s Reaction Greta of Bone Creek -- the old Lakandi witch who holds a bound demon and practices the Lakandi binding tradition -- is visibly disturbed by Anaya&#39;s visions. Greta does not share why she is disturbed, which is itself alarming. Greta is not a woman given to visible emotion without cause. Whatever she recognizes in Anaya&#39;s descriptions, she is not willing to speak of it openly. This silence from a woman who traffics with entities from beyond the Veil suggests that what calls to Anaya from beneath the Gallowswood is something Greta understands -- and fears. Implications Anaya&#39;s condition raises urgent questions: Is the zombie beastman wound a vector for Cthonic corruption ? Is the pulsating black heart beneath the Gallowswood actively reaching out to the wounded, the dying, or the corruptible? Does Greta&#39;s silence indicate she knows what the heart is -- and that the knowledge is too dangerous to share? Can Anaya be saved, or is the beckoning already too deep? See Also the-reclaimers -- The party Anaya serves as henchman gallowswood -- The cursed forest whose black heart calls to her greta -- The Lakandi witch disturbed by Anaya&#39;s visions cthonic-corruption -- The corruption that may be taking hold beastmen -- The zombie beastman that wounded her"},{"slug":"antonius","title":"Antonius","category":"people","tags":"henchman reclaimers vision rendson loyalty backlands","text":"Antonius Antonius is a henchman serving the Reclaimers . He nearly died in the field and, as he neared death, experienced a vision of Rendson -- the dead former Reclaimer, the Avari gambler and fugitive known as the Grim Sleeper. At a Glance Detail Description Role Henchman of Rendson -- the Avari gambler, whoremonger, and fugitive who died alongside Tancred fighting a necropede in the Backlands. Rendson was known as the Grim Sleeper for his talent of killing beasts where they lay. The nature and content of the vision are not fully known. Whether Rendson appeared as a warning, a comfort, a guide, or something else entirely is unclear. What is clear is that the experience has shaken Antonius enough to raise concerns about his continued loyalty and mental state. Loyalty Concerns A loyalty check is needed. Near-death visions of fallen comrades can break a henchman&#39;s resolve or twist their priorities in unpredictable ways. The Backlands are a place where the boundary between the living and the dead is thin, where the Veil frays, and where visions cannot be dismissed as mere hallucination. Whether Antonius saw Rendson through the natural delirium of blood loss or through something more metaphysical -- a genuine contact with the dead, a Cthonic lure, or a glimpse beyond the Veil -- remains to be determined. See Also the-reclaimers -- The party Antonius serves as henchman rendson -- The dead Reclaimer who appeared in Antonius&#39;s vision tancred -- Died alongside Rendson fighting a necropede the-veil -- The boundary between the living and the dead"},{"slug":"arannis-venn","title":"Arannis Venn","category":"people","tags":"npc spellsword eladran scholar argollean-brotherhood criminal backlands artifacts lore","text":"Arannis Venn Arannis Venn is an Eladran spellsword and scholar who serves as the leader of the Argollean Brotherhood in the Backlands . Reserved and intensely focused, Venn is a figure of quiet authority who commands respect through intellect, competence, and the weight of ancient Eladran heritage. He is a source of lore and artifacts for those who seek knowledge of the old world, but he is also morally gray — willing to deal in shadows, secrets, and criminal enterprise when it serves his purposes. Venn leads a criminal network connected to old Eladran noble houses, blending scholarly pursuit with underworld operations in a way that makes him both invaluable and dangerous to those who deal with him. Statistics Attribute Value Class Spellsword 6 Race - - - ac - 2 - - - hp - 33 - - - atk - +4-(longsword,-1d8+1) - - - int - 16 - - - venn&#39;s-statistics-reflect-a-warrior-scholar-of-considerable-ability.-his-ac-of-2-indicates-heavy-armor-—-likely-enchanted-or-of-exceptional-eladran-craftsmanship-—-while-his-33-hit-points-and-+4-attack-bonus-make-him-a-dangerous-combatant-in-melee.-his-intelligence-of-16-supports-both-his-spellcasting-and-his-role-as-a-master-of-lore-and-strategy.-as-a-spellsword,-venn-blends-martial-prowess-with-arcane-power,-making-him-a-versatile-and-unpredictable-opponent. - - spells - - magic-missile -—-unerring-bolts-of-arcane-force;-a-reliable-and-unavoidable-offensive-spell-that-reflects-venn&#39;s-pragmatic-approach-to-combat - dispel-magic -—-the-ability-to-unravel-and-neutralize-magical-effects;-essential-for-a-scholar-who-deals-in-ancient-artifacts-and-may-encounter-wards,-curses,-and-enchantments - knock -—-magical-opening-of-locks-and-barriers;-a-practical-spell-for-a-man-who-leads-a-criminal-network-and-frequently-needs-access-to-places-he-is-not-welcome - - venn&#39;s-spell-selection-is-notably- practical-and-utilitarian -—-no-flashy-destructive-magic,-but-instead-a-toolkit-designed-for-precision,-access,-and-control.-this-mirrors-his-personality:-reserved,-focused,-and-efficient. - - proficiencies - - engineering -—-knowledge-of-structures,-fortifications,-and-mechanical-systems;-useful-for-both-exploring-ancient-eladran-ruins-and-planning-the-operations-of-his-criminal-network - loremastery -—-deep-and-broad-scholarly-knowledge-spanning-history,-magic,-culture,-and-the-accumulated-wisdom-of-the-eladran-people;-this-is-venn&#39;s-defining-skill-and-the-foundation-of-his-value-as-a-source-of-information - command -—-the-ability-to-lead,-organize,-and-direct-subordinates;-essential-for-running-the-argollean-brotherhood&#39;s-operations-across-the-backlands - - - appearance-and-demeanor - venn-is- reserved -and- scholarly -—-a-man-who-measures-his-words-carefully-and-reveals-nothing-by-accident.-he-does-not-engage-in-idle-conversation-or-emotional-display.-every-interaction-with-venn-is-a-transaction,-whether-the-currency-is-information,-coin,-or-favor. - he-is- intensely-focused ,-pursuing-his-goals-with-a-single-mindedness-that-can-make-him-seem-cold-or-distant.-this-focus-is-not-cruelty-—-it-is-the-discipline-of-a-scholar-who-has-spent-decades-honing-his-craft-and-who-does-not-have-time-or-patience-for-distractions. - his-most-notable-physical-feature-is-a- bone-inlaid-ring -inscribed-with- eladran-script .-this-ring-is-likely-of-ancient-provenance,-possibly-a-badge-of-office-within-the-argollean-brotherhood-or-a-relic-of-the-old-eladran-noble-houses-his-network-is-connected-to.-the-bone-inlay-suggests-a-funerary-or-memorial-function-—-the-ring-may-commemorate-a-fallen-house,-a-dead-mentor,-or-a-lost-homeland. - - the-argollean-brotherhood - venn-leads-the- argollean-brotherhood -in-the-backlands,-a- criminal-network -with-deep-connections-to-old-[[races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran noble houses. The Brotherhood is not a common street gang — it is an organized, disciplined operation run by an Eladran spellsword with a scholar&#39;s intellect and a commander&#39;s authority. The Brotherhood&#39;s connection to old Eladran noble houses suggests several things: Heritage — The Brotherhood may trace its origins to the fall of Eladran civilization, preserving the interests and assets of noble families that lost their power and influence Artifacts — The old houses likely possessed significant magical artifacts, texts, and treasures that the Brotherhood now seeks to recover, protect, or trade Political Ambition — The connection to noble houses implies the Brotherhood may have political goals beyond mere profit — perhaps the restoration of Eladran influence or the recovery of lost Eladran territories Network — Old noble houses had networks of allies, agents, and contacts that the Brotherhood may still draw upon, giving it reach and resources far beyond what a frontier criminal organization would normally possess Role in the Backlands Venn occupies a unique position in the Backlands as a source of lore and artifacts . In a frontier region where knowledge of the old world is scarce and ancient ruins dot the landscape, Venn&#39;s expertise is invaluable. He can identify artifacts, translate ancient texts, provide historical context for discoveries, and connect seekers with the resources they need. However, Venn is morally gray . His willingness to deal with anyone — Scalpers, criminals, imperial officials, fellow Eladran — and his leadership of a criminal network mean that every transaction with Venn comes with strings attached. He does not give anything for free, and his favors always come with an expectation of reciprocity. This moral ambiguity makes Venn a versatile figure in the Backlands: he can be an ally, a patron, a rival, or an adversary depending on how his interests align with those who seek him out. Plot Hooks Eladran Ruins — Venn&#39;s loremastery and engineering proficiency make him the ideal guide or patron for expeditions into ancient Eladran ruins scattered across the Backlands The Bone Ring — What is the significance of Venn&#39;s bone-inlaid ring? It may be a key to an ancient vault, a badge of a secret order, or a memorial to a tragedy Venn seeks to avenge The Noble Houses — The Argollean Brotherhood&#39;s connection to old Eladran noble houses opens up a web of intrigue, politics, and ancient rivalries that could draw players into a world far beyond the frontier Artifact Trade — Venn is a buyer, seller, and broker of ancient artifacts. Players who discover relics in the field may find Venn their best — or only — option for identification and sale Criminal Network — The Brotherhood&#39;s criminal operations in the Backlands may intersect with other power players in Bone Creek , creating opportunities for alliance or conflict Morally Gray Patron — Venn makes an excellent patron for adventurers — knowledgeable, well-resourced, and willing to hire outsiders for dangerous work. But his goals are his own, and his agents may find themselves serving purposes they did not anticipate. See Also the-backlands — The frontier province where Venn and the Brotherhood operate bone-creek — The Scalper settlement; a hub of activity in the Backlands Eladran — Venn&#39;s race and the cultural heritage of the Argollean Brotherhood great-houses — The noble houses of the Empire; the Eladran houses connected to the Brotherhood may have parallels or rivalries here magic-and-sorcery — The magical traditions Venn practices as a spellsword scalper-gangs — The Scalper gangs that Venn and the Brotherhood may interact with crossings — The ruined city; a potential source of Eladran artifacts"},{"slug":"bottlecap-juno","title":"Bottlecap Juno","category":"people","tags":"npc barbarian scalper the-dregs unpredictable wild-card backlands bone-creek","text":"Bottlecap Juno Bottlecap Juno is a barbarian warrior and the leader of The Dregs , one of the Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands . Unpredictable, grinning, and possibly mad, Juno is a wild card faction leader whose behavior defies easy prediction or manipulation. He leads the Dregs with a chaotic energy that keeps rivals off balance and allies perpetually uncertain. Statistics Attribute Value Class Barbarian 4 Race — AC 3 HP 34 ATK +4 (Great Axe, 1d10+1) Str 15 Juno&#39;s statistics reveal a formidable melee combatant. His 34 hit points — the highest among the Scalper gang leaders — make him exceptionally durable, and his great axe deals devastating 1d10+1 damage per swing. His AC of 3 provides solid protection, likely through a combination of armor and natural toughness. His Strength of 15 supports his barbarian fighting style: direct, powerful, and relentless. Proficiencies Berserkergang — The ability to enter a berserk frenzy in combat, gaining enhanced strength and ferocity at the cost of tactical discipline and self-preservation. When Juno rages, he becomes a whirlwind of destruction that is as dangerous to those nearby as it is to his enemies. This proficiency defines Juno&#39;s fighting style and his personality — a man who lives on the edge of control. Intimidation — The art of frightening and coercing others through force of personality, physical presence, or implied violence. Juno&#39;s unpredictable nature makes his intimidation uniquely effective — people fear what they cannot predict, and Juno is nothing if not unpredictable. Survival — The practical skills needed to endure in the wilderness of the Backlands: finding food and water, building shelter, reading weather, navigating terrain. This proficiency keeps the Dregs alive in the field between hunts. Appearance and Demeanor Juno is defined by his unpredictability . He shifts between moods with unsettling speed — laughing one moment, deadly serious the next, then laughing again at something no one else finds funny. This volatility is not an act; it is the genuine expression of a mind that does not operate within normal boundaries. He is always grinning — a wide, unsettling smile that rarely leaves his face, even in combat, even in danger, even in moments where any sane person would show fear. The grin is a mask of madness, a signal to everyone around him that Juno plays by different rules. Juno is possibly mad . The Scalper saying — The Bounty takes its toll — may find its truest expression in Juno, who seems to have crossed a threshold from which there is no return. Whether his madness was caused by the horrors of beastman hunting, was always present, or stems from some other source is unclear. What is clear is that it makes him extraordinarily dangerous. His most notable physical feature is a necklace of bent coins — bottlecaps, bent marks, and crushed currency strung together as a trophy necklace. The origin of this affectation, and whether it is the source of his name, is unclear. Each bent coin may represent a kill, a victory, or simply something that amused Juno in the moment. The Dregs The Dregs are a Scalper gang that reflects their leader&#39;s chaotic nature. Where the Skin Eaters are brutally efficient and the Bleak Sons are zealously disciplined, the Dregs are wild and unpredictable — a loose collection of fighters bound together by Juno&#39;s force of personality rather than any formal structure or ideology. The Dregs represent the wild card faction in Backlands politics. They cannot be easily bought, threatened, or reasoned with, because their leader operates on instinct and impulse rather than rational calculation. This makes them unreliable allies and terrifying enemies — but also potentially useful to anyone clever enough to point Juno&#39;s chaos in the right direction. Plot Hooks The Wild Card — Juno&#39;s unpredictability makes him a volatile element in any conflict. Convincing him to support one side or another could tip the balance of power in Bone Creek — but controlling him is another matter entirely. The Bent Coins — What is the significance of Juno&#39;s necklace? Each coin may have a story, and the necklace itself may be more than a simple trophy. Berserkergang — Juno&#39;s berserk frenzy is his greatest weapon and his greatest vulnerability. In a rage, he is devastating but uncontrollable — a threat to everyone in his vicinity, friend and foe alike. Madness or Method — Is Juno truly mad, or is his apparent insanity a carefully cultivated persona designed to keep his enemies off balance? The answer changes everything about how to deal with him. The Dregs&#39; Loyalty — What holds the Dregs together? If Juno were killed or incapacitated, would the gang splinter, rally around a new leader, or descend into chaos? See Also scalper-gangs — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands The Dregs — Juno&#39;s gang bone-creek — The Scalper settlement the-backlands — The frontier province beastmen — The creatures the Dregs hunt skinner — Leader of the rival Skin Eaters marcos-varanes — Leader of the Bleak Sons; a contrasting figure of zealous discipline"},{"slug":"brother-marco","title":"Brother Marco","category":"people","tags":"npc bone-creek priest seros house-of-silence faith backlands","text":"Brother Marco Brother Marco is a young priest of Seros who serves at the House of Silence , the church of Seros in Bone Creek . He took over the church after the previous priest, Father Draven , succumbed to disease. Arrival in Bone Creek Brother Marco claims to have received a vision from Seros — a divine calling that compelled him to journey to the distant frontier outpost of Bone Creek. He made the long trek alone , a remarkable feat given the dangers of the Backlands . When he arrived, he was malnourished and wounded , bearing the marks of a harrowing journey. Despite his battered condition, Marco&#39;s conviction was unshaken. He immediately took over the House of Silence and began ministering to the people of Bone Creek. Ministry Marco&#39;s ministry has been unexpectedly successful in a settlement as godless and violent as Bone Creek. His weekly service now draws enough attendees that many must stand , spending hours in silent prayer in accordance with the rites of Seros . In a place where men bear the marks of corruption openly, where the Bounty takes its toll on body and soul alike, Marco&#39;s quiet devotion has struck a deep chord. Whether this is genuine spiritual hunger among the Scalpers or something else entirely remains to be seen. Predecessor: Father Draven Marco&#39;s predecessor, Father Draven , was a far cry from the pious young priest who replaced him. Draven was known as a drunkard and eventually succumbed to disease. Before his death, he offered one of the most memorable descriptions of the Backlands: There is no soil out here, only the ash of Empires. The trees breathe rot and the water tastes of the dead. I seen it, I seen what waits beneath the ground. This land is not cursed — no, no, no — it remembers. Every war, every broken oath, every forgotten god — it sings them back into the marrow of the earth. That&#39;s why we can&#39;t leave. We&#39;re not stuck. We&#39;ve been claimed. — Father Draven , drunken priest Character Marco is described as young — a stark contrast to the hardened veterans, criminals, and desperate fortune-seekers who populate Bone Creek. His willingness to trek alone through the dangerous Backlands on nothing more than a vision speaks to either extraordinary faith, extraordinary foolishness, or both. His arrival malnourished and wounded suggests the journey nearly killed him, yet he persevered. See Also bone-creek — The settlement where Marco ministers seros — The god Marco serves the-backlands — The frontier province Marco journeyed through"},{"slug":"cassian-varro","title":"Cassian Varro","category":"people","tags":"npc bone-creek red-river-consortium merchant lord-merchant backlands","text":"Cassian Varro Cassian Varro is the Lord Merchant of the Red River Consortium&#39;s Red River Exchange in Bone Creek — the largest building in town and the economic heart of the settlement. A polished and shrewd businessman, Varro is deeply involved in the local economy and political dealings of Bone Creek. Role As Lord Merchant, Varro oversees the operations of the Red River Exchange, which serves two critical functions in Bone Creek: Loot and Treasure Sales — Scalpers sell their plundered loot and treasure to the Exchange&#39;s merchants, who are shrewd negotiators. Beastman Scalp Redemption — The Exchange is where beastman scalps are sold in exchange for the Imperial Bounty, minus a transaction fee that the Consortium takes as profit. The Exchange employs an army of hardened guardsmen and bodyguards , making it both the most secure and most imposing building in Bone Creek. Alliances Varro is a close ally of Tolliver Watts , proprietor of Double Sevens. Together, they represent the most powerful political and economic bloc in Bone Creek — one oriented toward commerce, development, and the gradual civilization of the frontier settlement. The Varro-Watts alliance stands in contrast to the rough, lawless influence of Thaddeus Marr and his network. Character Varro is described as polished and shrewd — a businessman first and foremost, but one who understands that in a place like Bone Creek, politics and economics are inseparable. His deep involvement in local dealings suggests he is not merely a Consortium functionary following orders from distant superiors, but an active player shaping the settlement&#39;s future. Criminal Enterprise (SECRET — GM ONLY) Beneath the polished exterior of a legitimate merchant, Cassian Varro operates a sophisticated criminal enterprise that undermines the very bounty economy he publicly administers. This is not petty corruption -- it is a calculated, multi-layered operation: Bandit Operations — Fort Ikenvar Varro funds a bandit operation out of Fort Ikenvar . The ruined marsh fort -- formerly Rook&#39;s base of operations before the Reclaimers destroyed him -- is now being used as a base for Varro&#39;s criminal activities. This means Varro is actively destabilizing the trade routes and frontier settlements that his legitimate business depends on, profiting from both sides of the equation. Beastman Trafficking — Malyn and the Withered Craw Varro uses Malyn the Misshapen to traffic enslaved beastmen to buyers in Sanctuary . Rather than killing beastmen for scalps as the bounty system intends, Varro&#39;s operation captures them alive and sells them as slaves. Malyn -- an exiled Mage 7 who already enslaves beastmen through sorcery -- and his gang, the Withered Craw , serve as the operational arm of this trafficking pipeline. This is a critical revelation about the nature of the Withered Craw: they are not a conventional Scalper gang. They are a slaving operation, and Varro is their patron. Fraudulent Scalp Manufacturing Varro has arrangements with at least one Scalper gang to manufacture scalps without the inconvenience of a hunt . This means scalps are being produced and redeemed at the Red River Exchange that do not represent actual beastman kills. The Imperial Bounty is being defrauded. The implications are severe: The bounty numbers reported to Sanctuary and the Empire are inflated The actual beastman threat is not being reduced as the scalp counts suggest Imperial funds are being siphoned through fraudulent redemptions Varro profits from the transaction fees on scalps he knows are fake Strategic Implications Varro&#39;s criminal enterprise means that the most powerful economic figure in Bone Creek is actively: Funding banditry that destabilizes the region Running a slave trade in the very creatures the bounty system is designed to eliminate Defrauding the Imperial Bounty that funds the settlement&#39;s existence Using his legitimate position at the Exchange to launder the proceeds His alliance with Tolliver Watts takes on a darker cast in this light -- does Watts know? Is he complicit, or is he being used as a respectable front? The contrast with Thaddeus Marr&#39;s petty rackets is stark. Marr runs card games and a protection scheme. Varro runs a regional criminal enterprise that touches banditry, slavery, and fraud at an institutional level. See Also red-river-consortium — The trading consortium Varro represents bone-creek — The settlement where Varro operates tolliver-watts — Varro&#39;s close ally and proprietor of Double Sevens thaddeus-marr — The rival power in Bone Creek the-backlands — The frontier province beastmen — The creatures whose scalps fuel the Exchange&#39;s business fort-ikenvar — Ruined fort where Varro funds bandit operations malyn-the-misshapen — Varro&#39;s agent for beastman trafficking scalper-gangs — At least one gang manufactures scalps for Varro sanctuary — Destination for Varro&#39;s enslaved beastman trafficking"},{"slug":"castellan-thibaud","title":"Castellan Thibaud","category":"people","tags":"npc criminal laced-hand thief sanctuary underworld","text":"Castellan Thibaud Castellan Thibaud is the boss of the Laced Hand , the dominant criminal syndicate in Sanctuary . At age 52, he has spent over 30 years rising through the organization&#39;s ranks to become its undisputed leader. Intelligent, cautious, and remarkably well-read for a criminal boss, Thibaud runs the Laced Hand less like a gang and more like a corporation -- focused on profit, stability, and the long-term viability of his enterprise. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Thibaud (the Castellan is a title, not a name) Age 52 Class Master Thief 7 Affiliation Laced Hand over the course of three decades -- a remarkable feat in an organization where ambition typically outpaces lifespan. His survival and ascent owe less to violence (though he is capable of it) than to intelligence, patience, and an instinct for reading people and situations that borders on the preternatural. He operates from multiple hideouts throughout Sanctuary and is rarely seen in public. His anonymity is both a security measure and a management tool -- the less visible the boss, the more difficult he is to target, and the more his reputation grows in the telling. Character Thibaud is more like a crime CEO than a traditional gang leader. He is: Intelligent -- His strategic thinking rivals that of the political operators in the Governor&#39;s administration. He understands markets, logistics, human psychology, and the subtle dynamics of power. Cautious -- He does not take unnecessary risks, does not make impulsive decisions, and does not allow emotion to drive policy. Every significant action by the Laced Hand is calculated for its impact on the organization&#39;s long-term interests. Remarkably well-read -- An unusual trait for a criminal boss. Thibaud reads widely -- history, philosophy, political theory -- and applies what he learns to the management of his organization. He is capable of quoting imperial historians and making the quotation relevant to the discussion at hand. Focused on profit and stability -- Thibaud&#39;s primary goals are the continued profitability and operational stability of the Laced Hand. He is not interested in revolution, ideology, or personal glory. He wants the organization to thrive, and he understands that thriving requires a stable environment in which to operate. The Arrangement with the Governor Thibaud maintains a tacit arrangement with Governor Drussus . The arrangement is transactional: The Laced Hand provides intelligence from the docks, subtle removal of inconvenient individuals, and a criminal safety valve that keeps the underworld organized rather than chaotic In exchange, the Governor does not interfere with Laced Hand operations Thibaud understands that this arrangement exists at Drussus&#39;s pleasure and can be revoked at any time. He is therefore careful to remain useful without becoming threatening -- a balance that requires constant attention and occasional sacrifice. See Also The Laced Hand -- the organization he leads Governor Valerios Drussus -- the power he accommodates Sanctuary -- the city where he operates The Backlands"},{"slug":"claudius-decimus","title":"Claudius Decimus","category":"people","tags":"historical emperor house-decimus war-of-three-emperors dynasty-founder scholar-emperor","text":"Claudius Decimus Claudius Decimus emerged victorious from the War of Three Emperors (270 IY) and founded the Decimus dynasty that rules the Mithrian Empire to this day. He is one of the most paradoxical figures in Imperial history -- a man who triumphed in a brutal civil war yet is remembered as one of the most courageous and principled leaders the Empire has ever known. We traded madness for cowardice, then cowardice for coin. Of all our emperors, it was the one who ruled for 87 days who showed the greatest strength. -- Claudius Decimus , on accepting the title of Imperator from the Senate At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Claudius Decimus Title Imperator; founder of the Decimus dynasty House Aurex of House Valerian , the Empire plunged into chaos. With no clear heir, generals and governors vied for the throne. The scholar-emperor Numerius was briefly installed -- a principled and learned man who attempted to restore order through reason and law. Numerius ruled for only 87 days before he was murdered, his brief reign a testament to the Empire&#39;s inability to sustain the qualities it most needed in its leaders. The civil war that followed Numerius&#39;s death was devastating. Multiple claimants raised armies, alliances shifted and collapsed, and the Empire tore itself apart in a contest of ambition and violence. From this crucible, Claudius Decimus emerged triumphant -- not through superior bloodline or political connections, but through military competence, strategic patience, and a ruthlessness tempered by genuine principle. Character and Legacy Claudius Decimus&#39;s own words upon accepting the title of Imperator reveal a man acutely aware of the Empire&#39;s long decline. His reference to the Emperor who ruled for 87 days -- Numerius -- is a tribute to the scholar-emperor&#39;s courage and a tacit admission that the system that produced Claudius Decimus as victor was the same system that murdered the only genuinely good man to hold the throne. The trajectory Claudius described -- from madness ( Aurex and The Eater ) to cowardice ( Emperor Antonius and his successors) to the naked pursuit of wealth and power -- was not merely rhetoric. It was a diagnosis of the Empire&#39;s fundamental sickness, delivered by the man who had just fought his way through its most violent symptom. What Claudius Decimus accomplished in his own reign, and the circumstances of his eventual removal from power, remain subjects of intense historical debate. His founding of the Decimus dynasty established a new ruling house, but the question that haunts his legacy is whether the dynasty he created has been any better than the one it replaced. The Decimus Dynasty The dynasty Claudius founded has held the Imperial throne without interruption from 270 IY to the present day. The current Emperor, Justinian Claudius Decimus , bears his ancestor&#39;s name and rules from Mithra City . Whether the Decimus line has fulfilled Claudius&#39;s implicit promise -- to be better than what came before -- is a matter of perspective and politics. See Also House Decimus -- the dynasty he founded War of Three Emperors -- the civil war he won Emperor Aurex -- the mad Emperor whose death triggered the crisis Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus -- current Emperor and descendant House Valerian -- the dynasty he replaced History of Mithrapos The Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"colonel-vex","title":"Colonel Marcian Vex","category":"people","tags":"npc military fighter drussine-guard sanctuary house-drussus","text":"Colonel Marcian Vex Colonel Marcian Vex is the commander of the Drussine Guard , the personal army of Governor Valerios Drussus in Sanctuary . A grim and efficient officer, Vex handles the day-to-day military operations of the Guard and is loyal to the Governor personally -- not to the city, not to the province, and not to the Emperor. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Marcian Vex Rank Colonel Class Fighter 9 Affiliation Drussine Guard . While Governor Drussus sets strategy and makes political decisions, it is Vex who translates those decisions into military reality. He manages training, deployment, discipline, logistics, and the thousand daily details that keep a force of 2,000 soldiers functioning as a cohesive military unit. His competence is beyond question. The Drussine Guard is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the Backlands , and Vex&#39;s hand is visible in every aspect of its operation -- from the quality of its equipment to the precision of its drill to the speed of its response to threats. Character Vex is grim and efficient -- a man who wastes no words, tolerates no excuses, and measures people by their usefulness. He is not cruel, but he is entirely without sentiment. He does not inspire loyalty through charisma or warmth; he inspires it through competence and the knowledge that under his command, the Guard functions like a machine. His personal loyalty to Governor Drussus is absolute. This is not the loyalty of a subordinate who follows orders because he must, but the loyalty of a man who has chosen his commander and committed to that choice without reservation. Whether this loyalty stems from shared history, personal obligation, ideological alignment, or simple recognition that Drussus is the most competent leader available is not clear -- and Vex is not the kind of man who explains his motivations. Relationships Governor Drussus -- His commander and the object of his absolute loyalty. Vex serves as the Governor&#39;s military right hand. The Drussine Guard -- The force he commands and has shaped into the premier military unit in the province. Legate Marcellus -- The other significant military authority in the Backlands. Vex&#39;s relationship with Marcellus is defined by the Governor&#39;s policy of strategic containment. See Also Governor Valerios Drussus -- his commander The Drussine Guard -- the force he commands House Drussus -- the Great House he serves Sanctuary -- the city where he is stationed The Backlands"},{"slug":"crackback","title":"Crackback","category":"people","tags":"npc thief mornish targ bone-creek pretty-peach thaddeus-marr enforcer pimp backlands","text":"Crackback Crackback is a targ Thief (level 2) of Mornish extraction who serves as the pimp at The Pretty Peach in Bone Creek , working directly under Thaddeus Marr . He is a crude, opportunistic enforcer and gossip source -- the kind of man who thrives in frontier squalor. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Crackback Race Thaddeus Marr&#39;s operation: Enforcer He keeps order at The Pretty Peach through intimidation and, when necessary, violence. In a town full of Scalpers, brawlers, and frontier desperadoes, this requires a certain baseline of menace that Crackback possesses in abundance. Gossip Source Crackback&#39;s position as pimp gives him access to the intimate secrets and drunken confessions of Bone Creek&#39;s population. Men talk freely to working girls, and working girls talk to their pimp. This makes Crackback a valuable intelligence asset for Marr&#39;s racket -- a stream of information gathered through proximity to vulnerability. See Also thaddeus-marr -- Crackback&#39;s boss, proprietor of The Pretty Peach bone-creek -- The frontier outpost where Crackback operates targ -- Crackback&#39;s race, former slaves magically created mornish -- Cultural background"},{"slug":"doc-quinten","title":"Doc Quinten","category":"people","tags":"npc explorer kolani bone-creek surgeon neutral backlands","text":"Doc Quinten Doc Quinten is a Kolani Explorer (level 3) who serves as Bone Creek&#39;s barber-surgeon. Everyone calls him Doc despite his lack of formal medical credentials. He ran field surgery for three separate armies during his career before washing up on the frontier, and his hands are steady enough that no one cares about credentials. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Doc Quinten Race Scalper gangs , Thaddeus Marr&#39;s operation, Cassian Varro&#39;s Red River Consortium interests, Ezekiel Shaw&#39;s Congregation , Malyn&#39;s hidden network -- all of them need a surgeon, and none of them are willing to jeopardize the only competent one in town by dragging him into their feuds. This neutrality makes Doc Quinten one of the few truly safe people to talk to in Bone Creek. He will not betray a confidence -- not out of moral principle, but because doing so would compromise his neutrality and, therefore, his survival. Background Doc Quinten&#39;s Kolani heritage and Explorer training mark him as a man of the frontier and the wilderness, not the city. The kolani are plains and forest tribes who fought the Dog Soldier War against the Empire -- a guerrilla campaign of legendary ferocity. Doc&#39;s service as field surgeon to three separate armies likely included time on both sides of various Kolani conflicts, which explains both his skill and his absolute refusal to take sides. His Beast Lore specialization in dogs is notable -- in a frontier where tracking, hunting, and survival matter, a man who understands dogs understands the frontier. See Also bone-creek -- The frontier outpost where Doc Quinten practices kolani -- His people, plains and forest tribes dog-soldier-war -- The Kolani guerrilla war, possibly part of his military background scalper-gangs -- The gangs whose members he patches up without prejudice"},{"slug":"elder-sarnath","title":"Elder Sarnath","category":"people","tags":"npc avari elder sanctuary ashward community-leader refugee crossings","text":"Elder Sarnath Sarnath of the Crossings (age 71) is a former merchant and the community elder of the Avari population in Sanctuary &#39;s Ashward district. Wise and diplomatic, Sarnath has devoted his later years to ensuring the survival and dignity of his people in a city that tolerates them but does not embrace them. He is not powerful in the conventional sense -- he commands no soldiers, controls no wealth, and holds no title. But he is respected, and in the precarious world of the Ashward, respect is the currency that matters most. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Sarnath of the Crossings Age 71 Race Avari Role Community elder Location Crossings , the settlement destroyed in the Sacking of Crossings (377 IY). Whether he was present during the sacking or had already departed before the beastman horde arrived is not widely known. What is known is that the destruction of Crossings and the burning of the Erenthis at Thornasse by High Mage Cynar are wounds that define the Avari community&#39;s identity -- and Sarnath carries both. Before becoming a community leader, Sarnath was a merchant. His commercial experience gave him an understanding of how power works in practical terms -- contracts, obligations, favors, relationships. He has applied this understanding to the task of keeping the Avari community alive in a city where they are marginalized, distrusted, and largely powerless. Role in the Ashward The Ashward is the poorest district of Sanctuary , home to refugees, displaced peoples, and communities that exist at the margins of the city&#39;s economic and political life. The Avari community within the Ashward looks to Sarnath for guidance -- not because he holds any formal authority, but because he has earned trust through decades of steady, patient work on their behalf. Sarnath&#39;s approach is focused on two priorities: Survival -- Ensuring the Avari community has access to food, shelter, and the basic necessities of life in a city that does not prioritize their welfare Dignity -- Preserving the Avari identity, traditions, and sense of self-worth in the face of marginalization and the lingering trauma of the Erenthis &#39;s destruction Relationships Sarnath has cultivated relationships with various city factions -- not from a position of power but from a position of usefulness and trust: Governor Drussus -- Sarnath is not a political player, but he is aware that the Governor&#39;s tolerance of the Ashward depends on the district remaining quiet and manageable The Thousand Temples -- The Avari&#39;s relationship with the dominant faith is complex, given the cultural wounds inflicted by Imperial religious institutions Red River Consortium -- Sarnath&#39;s merchant background gives him some connection to the commercial world, though the Avari community&#39;s economic resources are minimal Other community leaders -- Sarnath&#39;s diplomacy extends to the non-Avari populations of the Ashward, where cooperation between marginalized groups is essential for survival He is not powerful, but he is respected -- a distinction that, in the Ashward, carries its own weight. See Also Sanctuary -- the city where he lives Crossings -- the town associated with his name Sacking of Crossings -- the event that devastated the Avari The Erenthis -- the Avari tradition destroyed by the Empire High Mage Cynar -- the sorcerer who burned the Erenthis Races and Cultures of Mithrapos The Backlands"},{"slug":"emperor-aurex","title":"Emperor Aurex","category":"people","tags":"historical emperor house-valerian mad-emperor assassination war-of-three-emperors","text":"Emperor Aurex Emperor Aurex was the last Emperor of House Valerian to sit upon the Imperial throne. His reign was defined by madness and cruelty that brought the Mithrian Empire to the brink of collapse. Aurex was assassinated by his own sister -- an act of desperate necessity that left no heir and ended the Valerian dynasty&#39;s hold on power forever. His death triggered the War of Three Emperors (270 IY), the brutal civil war from which Claudius Decimus emerged victorious, founding the Decimus dynasty that rules to this day. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Aurex (of House Valerian) Title Emperor of the Decimus dynasty to paint the Emperor they replaced in the darkest possible terms. What is beyond dispute is that Aurex&#39;s rule was disastrous for the Empire and that his removal was regarded as necessary by virtually everyone who survived it. The Assassination Aurex was killed by his own sister. The precise circumstances of the assassination -- whether it was a spontaneous act of desperation or the culmination of a carefully planned conspiracy -- are not fully known. What is known is that Aurex died without naming an heir, and his sister either could not or would not claim the throne in her own right. The absence of a clear successor plunged the Empire into chaos. The resulting power vacuum drew in generals, governors, and ambitious nobles, each claiming legitimacy and marshaling forces. The scholar Numerius was briefly installed as Emperor -- only to be murdered within 87 days. The ensuing civil war, known as the War of Three Emperors , was the most devastating internal conflict the Empire had experienced since its founding. Legacy Aurex&#39;s legacy is one of destruction and cautionary example. His reign is cited by historians as proof that the concentration of absolute power in a single individual -- without adequate checks or mechanisms for removal -- makes the Empire vulnerable to catastrophic failure when that individual proves unfit. The Valerian dynasty, which had held power for centuries, was destroyed in a generation by a single ruler&#39;s madness. Claudius Decimus , upon accepting the title of Imperator, spoke directly to the trajectory that Aurex represented: a decline from madness to cowardice to naked greed that had corroded the Empire&#39;s foundations. Aurex also serves as a defining wound in the identity of House Valerian . The house retains its ancient prestige and its wealth, but the stain of Aurex&#39;s reign -- the madness, the cruelty, the inglorious end -- hangs over every Valerian ambition. Whether the house can ever truly escape this legacy is an open question. See Also House Valerian -- the dynasty that ended with Aurex War of Three Emperors -- the civil war his death triggered Claudius Decimus -- the Emperor who emerged from the chaos House Decimus -- the dynasty that replaced the Valerians History of Mithrapos The Mithrian Empire"},{"slug":"eolande","title":"Eolande, the Eladran General","category":"people","tags":"eladra first-empire black-tree crossings ancient argollean-empire great-teacher thornasse sword dryad womb-curse","text":"Eolande, the Eladran General Eolande is an ancient Eladran general from approximately 3000 BE -- over five thousand years before the current campaign date of 380 IY. He was tutored personally by the Great Teacher in matters of strategy, sorcery, and statecraft, and led the military campaigns that transformed the Eladran city-states into a true empire. His conquests marked the first systematic subjugation of humans by the Eladra, extending the reach of the Cthonic tradition alongside the boundaries of Eladran power. He is still present at the Black Tree -- the scorched Erenthis stump at Thornasse , near Crossings . The Reclaimers encountered him there. An Eladran general from 3000 BE, still alive and present over five millennia later, is an event of staggering historical and metaphysical significance. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Eolande Race History of Mithrapos . Tutored personally by the Great Teacher -- the enigmatic figure who transformed Eladran culture from scholarship and cooperation into ambition, domination, and the pursuit of power -- Eolande began a campaign of territorial expansion that brought vast human populations under Eladran control. His military campaigns were not merely territorial. They were theological, extending the reach of the Cthonic tradition alongside the boundaries of Eladran power. The conquests established the political framework that would become the Argollean Empire -- the great pre-human civilization whose ruins now litter the Backlands and whose buried cities, including the Nethercity beneath Crossings and Aodahn beneath Sanctuary , remain among the most significant archaeological and sorcerous sites in the known world. Eolande&#39;s era predates the Empyrean War (663 BE), the rise of Marcus Valerian and the founding of the Mithrian Empire , and the entire recorded history of human civilization as the Mithrian world understands it. He is a figure from the deep past -- from the age when the Eladra ruled and humans were subjects. The Black Tree Encounter The Reclaimers Meet Eolande (380 IY) The Reclaimers encountered Eolande at the Black Tree -- the scorched stump of the Erenthis at Thornasse . The Erenthis was one of the great living monuments of the Eladran civilization, burned by High Mage Cynar in an act of destruction whose consequences still ripple through the Backlands. The Black Tree endures as a dead stump, charred and massive, at the site where the living tree once stood. That Eolande is present at this site -- alive, or in some state resembling life -- after more than five thousand years raises questions of extraordinary magnitude. Malachor&#39;s Interrogation When Malachor learned of the encounter through garrison talk, he approached the Reclaimers with barely-composed urgency. His questions reveal the scope of what the party witnessed and the details that remain unclear: On Eolande&#39;s state of mind: What language did Eolande speak? Did he understand Mithrian, or only the old tongue? -- This question probes whether Eolande has had any contact with the post-imperial world or whether he exists in a bubble of deep antiquity, speaking only the Eladran language of five millennia past. How coherent was he? Did he seem aware of time passing? Does he know the First Empire has fallen? -- The question of temporal awareness is critical. An Eladran general who does not know his empire fell is a man preserved in amber. One who does know is something far stranger -- a being who has watched five thousand years of history unfold from the foot of a dead tree. On what Eolande revealed: What did he say about the Womb Curse? -- The Womb Curse is referenced in connection with the Elvora&#39;s barrenness or possibly the broader Eladran disappearance. That Eolande spoke of it suggests he has knowledge of the catastrophe that ended Eladran fertility and doomed the race to extinction -- knowledge that predates any surviving written record. What did he say about the Eladra? -- Any testimony from a living witness of the Eladran civilization at its height is of incalculable scholarly value. The Eladra are gone. Their cities are ruins. Their language is dead. Eolande may be the last primary source in existence. What did he say about Bel ? -- That Eolande mentioned the Slaughterprince by name connects the ancient Eladran general to the Cthonic theological framework. Bel&#39;s earth-hunger cult is active in modern Argolle . Whatever Eolande knows about Bel predates the Empyrean faith entirely. On the sword: The sword. Every detail. Does it bear any inscription? -- There is a sword associated with Eolande or found at the Black Tree. Malachor&#39;s intensity about this object suggests it may be an artifact of First Empire provenance -- possibly a weapon carried by Eolande himself during the conquests, which would make it over five thousand years old and of immense sorcerous, historical, and monetary value. On the dryad and the tree: Is the tree alive? Is she bound to the dead wood, or to something that remains in it? -- There is a dryad associated with the Black Tree. The Erenthis was a living monument -- a creation of Eladran sorcery that bridged the Veil and served as a conduit of power. That a dryad persists at the site of the scorched stump suggests the Erenthis is not entirely dead, or that something within it -- some residue of the original sorcery, some fragment of the living tree -- still sustains a bound spirit. The dryad&#39;s relationship to the dead wood is a question of metaphysical importance: is she a ghost of what the tree was, or a guardian of what it still contains? Significance Eolande&#39;s survival -- or persistence, or whatever state describes a five-thousand-year-old Eladran general standing at the foot of a burned tree -- is the most significant discovery the Reclaimers have made. Malachor recognizes this immediately. His questions are not idle scholarship. They are the questions of a man who understands that a living witness to the Eladran civilization changes the entire calculus of imperial history, Academy research, and the theological understanding of the Eladra , the Elvora , the Cthonic tradition, and the fall of the Argollean Empire . Malachor&#39;s response to the encounter was to write the most significant dispatch of his career -- a report to his secret third-party contact, the unnamed buyer who has been receiving copies of his academic reports for years. Whatever that contact represents, they now know about Eolande. Malachor sent the dispatch before fully considering what he had set in motion. Malachor&#39;s Proposed Expedition Malachor is already planning a return expedition to the Black Tree. His proposed party: two Academy assistants he intends to summon to Sanctuary , himself, and the Reclaimers as escort into Crossings . He presents this as something to finalize after the party returns from Sanctuary. He will push on every subsequent encounter. Unresolved Questions What state is Eolande in? Alive in the biological sense? Preserved by sorcery? Sustained by the Erenthis remnant? A revenant? Something else entirely? What language does he speak? If only the old Eladran tongue, communication is limited. If he understands Mithrian, that implies contact with the post-imperial world. What does he know about the Womb Curse? This may be the single most important piece of information he possesses -- the cause of the Eladran race&#39;s extinction. What is the sword? An artifact of the conquests? A weapon of the Great Teacher? Something else? What is the dryad&#39;s nature? Bound to dead wood or to a living remnant? Guardian or prisoner? Who is Malachor&#39;s third-party contact? And what will they do with the knowledge of Eolande&#39;s existence? What did Eolande say about Bel? Any pre-Empyrean testimony about a Cthonic deity could reshape theological understanding. See Also eladra -- Eolande&#39;s race, the ancient builders of Argolle argollean-empire -- The empire Eolande&#39;s conquests helped create thornasse -- Site of the Black Tree where Eolande was found the-erenthis -- The living Eladran monuments, one of which stood at Thornasse crossings -- The ruined city near the Black Tree malachor -- The Academy historian desperate for details about Eolande the-reclaimers -- The party that encountered Eolande history-of-mithrapos -- The historical timeline documenting Eolande&#39;s conquests high-mage-cynar -- Burned the Erenthis at Thornasse elvora -- The corrupted Eladra, possibly connected to the Womb Curse bel -- The Cthonic deity Eolande spoke of cthonic-faith -- The theological tradition Eolande&#39;s conquests spread the-nethercity -- Eladran ruins beneath Crossings imperial-academy -- The institution that will covet Eolande&#39;s testimony campaign-chronicle -- Session history recording the encounter"},{"slug":"ezekiel-shaw","title":"Ezekiel Shaw","category":"people","tags":"npc cleric mithrian preacher fanatical congregation-of-the-hollow-sun bone-creek backlands long-term-threat prophet","text":"Ezekiel Shaw Mysterious preacher who speaks of divine trials and hidden light. Some call him a prophet. Others call him mad. Ezekiel Shaw is a Mithrian cleric of the sixth circle and the charismatic leader of the Congregation of the Hollow Sun , a secretive religious group operating in the Bone Creek area of the Backlands . Shaw is a figure of contradiction — radiating warmth and sincerity while harboring fanaticism that borders on madness. He speaks of divine trials and hidden light , drawing followers with his magnetic presence and unsettling conviction. Shaw is identified as a long-term threat — not an immediate antagonist, but a slowly building danger whose true intentions and the full scope of his Congregation&#39;s activities may not become apparent until it is too late. Statistics Attribute Value Class Cleric 6 Race - - - ac - 2 - - - hp - 30 - - - atk - +3-(mace,-1d6+1) - - - wis - 16 - - - shaw&#39;s-statistics-reveal-a-dangerous-combatant-as-well-as-a-spiritual-leader.-his-ac-of-2-indicates-heavy-armor-—-likely-plate-or-splint-mail-—-marking-him-as-someone-prepared-for-violence-despite-his-role-as-a-preacher.-his-30-hit-points-and-+3-attack-bonus-make-him-a-formidable-physical-threat,-and-his-wisdom-of-16-reflects-a-powerful-connection-to-whatever-divine-(or-profane)-source-empowers-his-magic. - - spells - - bless -—-bolstering-the-faithful;-strengthening-his-followers-in-body-and-spirit,-reinforcing-their-devotion-through-tangible-divine-favor - hold-person -—-paralyzing-the-unfaithful-or-those-who-oppose-him;-a-spell-of-control-and-subjugation-that-reveals-shaw&#39;s-willingness-to-impose-his-will-by-force - cure-disease -—-healing-the-sick;-a-powerful-tool-for-building-a-following-among-the-desperate-and-suffering-people-of-the-backlands,-where-disease-is-rampant-and-healers-are-scarce - - shaw&#39;s-spell-selection-paints-a-picture-of-a-man-who- rewards-loyalty -(bless,-cure-disease)-and- punishes-defiance -(hold-person).-his-ability-to-cure-disease-alone-would-make-him-one-of-the-most-valuable-individuals-in-the-backlands-—-and-he-knows-it. - - proficiencies - - leadership -—-the-ability-to-command,-inspire,-and-organize-followers;-shaw-is-not-merely-a-preacher-but-a-leader-of-men,-capable-of-building-and-directing-an-organization - prophecy -—-the-art-of-divination-and-foretelling;-shaw-claims-to-receive-visions-and-divine-revelations,-and-this-proficiency-suggests-those-claims-may-have-some-genuine-basis-—-or-at-least-that-he-is-skilled-enough-in-the-practice-to-be-convincing - black-lore -—-forbidden-knowledge-of-dark-and-proscribed-traditions;-a-deeply-troubling-proficiency-for-a-cleric,-suggesting-that-shaw&#39;s-theology-draws-from-sources-that-orthodox-faiths-would-condemn.-this-proficiency,-combined-with-his-secretive-congregation,-raises-serious-questions-about-the-true-nature-of-the- hidden-light -he-preaches - - - appearance-and-demeanor - shaw- radiates-warmth -—-a-quality-that-makes-him-immediately-disarming-and-compelling.-people-are-drawn-to-him-instinctively,-feeling-a-sense-of-comfort-and-trust-in-his-presence-that-is-difficult-to-resist.-his-eyes-are-described-as- shimmering ,-possessing-an-unusual,-almost-supernatural-quality-that-reinforces-his-aura-of-otherworldly-connection. - beneath-this-warmth-lies- fanaticism .-shaw-is-not-a-moderate-or-a-compromiser-—-he-is-a-true-believer,-utterly-convinced-of-the-righteousness-of-his-cause-and-the-truth-of-his-visions.-whether-this-conviction-stems-from-genuine-divine-contact,-madness,-or-something-darker-is-unclear.-the-combination-of-charisma,-warmth,-and-fanaticism-makes-shaw-exceptionally-dangerous-—-he-can-draw-people-in-with-his-presence-and-bind-them-with-his-conviction-before-they-realize-what-they-have-committed-to. - shaw-is- possibly-mad .-the-line-between-prophecy-and-madness-is-thin,-and-shaw-walks-it-with-unsettling-confidence.-his-certainty-in-his-own-divine-mandate,-combined-with-his-proficiency-in-black-lore,-suggests-a-man-who-may-have-opened-doors-in-his-mind-that-cannot-be-closed. - - the-congregation-of-the-hollow-sun - shaw-leads-the- [[congregation-of-the-hollow-sun\" class=\"wiki-link\">Congregation of the Hollow Sun , a secretive religious group whose full membership, beliefs, and goals are not publicly known. The name itself is evocative and disturbing — a hollow sun suggests a light that is empty, false, or corrupted. Whether the Congregation worships a legitimate deity, a corrupted aspect of an existing faith, or something entirely alien is a mystery. What is known: The Congregation operates in secret , suggesting its beliefs or practices would not be tolerated if widely known Shaw is its undisputed leader , with his charisma and divine power serving as the foundation of the group&#39;s cohesion The Congregation represents a long-term threat — it is growing, organizing, and building toward something Shaw&#39;s proficiency in Prophecy suggests the Congregation may be oriented around a prophetic vision — a foretold event or transformation that Shaw believes is coming. His Black Lore proficiency raises the possibility that this prophecy involves dark or forbidden elements. Threat Assessment Shaw is categorized as a long-term threat , distinguishing him from the more immediate dangers of the Backlands. This designation suggests several things: Shaw is patient. He is not planning an imminent attack or confrontation. He is building something — a following, a power base, a ritual framework — that will take time to mature. Shaw is growing stronger. The Congregation is presumably expanding, recruiting from the desperate and disillusioned population of the Backlands. Each new follower adds to Shaw&#39;s power and influence. Shaw&#39;s endgame is unknown. Whatever the Congregation is building toward — a mass ritual, a prophetic fulfillment, an uprising, a summoning — it has not yet been revealed. Early intervention is possible. As a long-term threat, Shaw can potentially be investigated, confronted, or undermined before his plans reach fruition — but only if someone recognizes the danger he represents. Plot Hooks The Hidden Light — What is the hidden light Shaw preaches? Is it a corrupted deity, a forgotten power, or something from beyond the mortal world? The Hollow Sun — The name of the Congregation is deeply symbolic. What does it mean? Is it a reference to an eclipse, a dead god, or a void that hungers? Shaw&#39;s Visions — Are Shaw&#39;s prophecies genuine? If so, what do they foretell? If not, what is the source of his power and conviction? Black Lore — Shaw&#39;s proficiency in Black Lore is deeply concerning for a cleric. What forbidden knowledge does he possess, and how does it inform his theology? Recruitment — The Congregation is recruiting from the desperate population of the Backlands. Tracking its members and understanding its structure could reveal Shaw&#39;s true intentions. The Shimmering Eyes — Shaw&#39;s unusual, shimmering eyes may be a sign of supernatural influence, corruption, or transformation. Are they a mark of divine favor — or something else entirely? See Also congregation-of-the-hollow-sun — The secretive religious group Shaw leads bone-creek — The settlement where Shaw operates the-backlands — The frontier province seros — The orthodox faith of the Balanced Scale; potentially in tension with Shaw&#39;s teachings brother-marco — The priest of Seros at the House of Silence; a potential rival or target for Shaw cthonic-faith — Dark religious traditions; potentially connected to Shaw&#39;s Black Lore empyrean-faith — The state religion; Shaw&#39;s Congregation may represent a heretical offshoot or a rival tradition"},{"slug":"governor-drussus","title":"Governor Valerios Drussus","category":"people","tags":"npc governor politician military fighter sanctuary citadel drussine-guard backlands house-drussus great-houses","text":"Governor Valerios Drussus Governor Valerios Drussus is the provincial governor of the Backlands , commanding from the Citadel in Sanctuary . He is the most powerful individual in the province -- holding military, bureaucratic, and economic supremacy through fifteen years of methodical consolidation. Patriarch of House Drussus , the newest of the Great Houses, his intentions remain deliberately opaque. Every faction fears him. Every faction courts him. No one knows what he is building. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Valerios Drussus Race Mithrian male Age 48 House House Drussus is the newest of the Great Houses, built on his accomplishments rather than inherited from a lineage of power. Before his appointment as Governor, he was already wealthy and well-connected, having parlayed military success into political capital with a precision that made older houses nervous. He was appointed Governor of the Backlands in 365 IY , fifteen years ago. At the time, the appointment was seen as semi-exile -- the Backlands is a provincial backwater, far from the imperial court, and the posting was considered a dead end for an ambitious officer. Whether Drussus accepted it willingly or was maneuvered into it is unknown. What is certain is that he has made the most of it. Consolidation of Power Since taking the post, Drussus has executed a systematic consolidation of power with a patience and thoroughness that borders on the obsessive: Gifts to the military -- Generous pay, excellent equipment, and personal attention have ensured that the Drussine Guard (his private army, ~2,000 strong) is loyal to him personally , not to the city or the Empire Careful marriages for his daughters -- Strategic alliances through marriage, binding merchant families and minor nobility to House Drussus Steady acquisition of merchant houses and estates -- Drussus has bought, inherited, or pressured his way into ownership of significant economic assets throughout the province Gradual placement of loyalists throughout the bureaucracy -- Every tax collector, magistrate, and functionary in Sanctuary was either appointed by Drussus or knows they serve at his pleasure Control over the City Watch (~600 strong) -- Ostensibly independent, in practice answerable to the Governor Tacit arrangement with the Laced Hand -- The criminal syndicate provides intelligence, removes inconvenient people, and keeps the underworld organized. In exchange, Drussus does not interfere. His personal wealth now competes with the Red River Consortium . His control over the bureaucracy is absolute. The Drussine Guard is the best-trained and best-equipped military force in the Backlands. Combat Ability Those who have faced Drussus in combat describe him as preternaturally calm , adjusting tactics mid-battle with disconcerting speed. He does not fight with fury or passion. He fights the way he governs -- with cold precision, exploiting weaknesses the moment they appear, never overextending, never losing control. At Fighter 12 with 96 HP and AC 2, he is one of the most dangerous combatants in the province. His Leader ability (+4 reaction from loyal troops) means that the Drussine Guard fights with exceptional morale and coordination when he is present. Key Relationships Prelate Severan Voth The relationship between Drussus and Prelate Voth is cold and formal . They do not trust each other, but they maintain an equilibrium born of mutual recognition: Drussus does not interfere with Temple internal affairs Voth does not publicly oppose the Governor&#39;s authority Both recognize that either could seriously damage the other This is not friendship or alliance. It is a standoff between two powers who have calculated that open conflict would be mutually destructive. The balance holds, but it is fragile. Legate Marcellus From the surface, Drussus seems content to rest on his laurels in Sanctuary. But the Fort Meade records reveal that he is engaged in a silent political war with Legate Marcellus . Drussus has blocked every request Marcellus has made for reinforcements, recognition, or transfer. He has isolated the Legate at Fort Meade , denying him the resources and political support he needs to challenge the Governor&#39;s authority or to build an independent power base. This is not personal animosity. It is strategic containment. Marcellus represents the only other significant military authority in the province, and Drussus will not tolerate a rival. The Laced Hand Drussus maintains a tacit arrangement with the Laced Hand criminal syndicate. The arrangement is transactional: The Laced Hand provides intelligence from the docks, subtle removal of inconvenient individuals, and a criminal safety valve that keeps the underworld organized rather than chaotic In exchange, the Governor does not interfere with Laced Hand operations Castellan Thibaud understands that this arrangement exists at Drussus&#39;s pleasure and can be revoked at any time. The Red River Consortium The Sanctuary branch of the Red River Consortium , led by Directrix Valeria Thorne (age 58), is politically aligned with the Governor . This alliance gives Drussus access to the Consortium&#39;s commercial networks and wealth, while the Consortium benefits from favorable treatment in provincial trade policy. Character Drussus is a man of few words and enormous patience. He does not make threats. He does not bluster. He does not negotiate from emotion. Every decision he makes is calculated, every concession is temporary, and every gift comes with an invisible ledger entry. He is immune to most social manipulation . Appeals to honor fall on deaf ears. Invocations of tradition are met with polite indifference. Sentimental arguments are dismissed without comment. He respects only competence and strength -- those who demonstrate both may earn his attention, if not his trust. His loyalty is to Sanctuary and his vision for it , not to the Emperor. He would not betray the Empire directly -- he is too pragmatic for open rebellion -- but he would act independently without hesitation if he judged it necessary. GM Notes Drussus is not a villain by default . He is a dangerous man doing dangerous things for reasons that are deliberately left ambiguous. His methods are cold. His ambition is vast. But his goals could be: A personal empire -- naked ambition, using the province as a power base A check against imperial decline -- preparing the Backlands for a future where the Empire can no longer protect it A grand conspiracy -- serving some hidden agenda that has not yet been revealed Something else entirely -- the GM should decide, or leave it ambiguous What is clear: He is building something. The consolidation of power is too systematic, too thorough, to be mere bureaucratic ambition. He is not sentimental. People are tools, alliances are temporary, and loyalty is currency. He is extremely difficult to manipulate or deceive. PCs who attempt social approaches will find a wall of calm intelligence. He can be worked with, but never controlled. Adventurers who prove competent and useful may find him a valuable patron -- but they should never forget who holds the leash. See Also Sanctuary -- provincial capital The Citadel -- Governor&#39;s fortress-seat The Drussine Guard -- the Governor&#39;s personal army House Drussus -- the newest Great House Prelate Severan Voth -- head of the Temple Legate Marcellus -- military rival at Fort Meade The Laced Hand -- criminal syndicate Red River Consortium -- trading company Colonel Marcian Vex -- Drussine Guard commander The Backlands -- the province"},{"slug":"greta","title":"Greta of Bone Creek","category":"people","tags":"npc witch lakandi bone-creek demonic-pact herbalism alchemy cthonic binding backlands scalper","text":"Greta of Bone Creek Greta is an old Lakandi woman who has lived in Bone Creek longer than anyone can remember. She is a practitioner of the Lakandi binding tradition -- one of a handful of people in Argolle who engages directly with entities from beyond the Veil , not through petition or worship but through binding, contest, and mutual obligation. She wears a bird-skull necklace . She smells of herbs. She is blunt, secretive, and earthy -- a woman who has survived decades of frontier life not through charm or diplomacy but through competence, knowledge, and whatever arrangement she has made with the thing she does not discuss. Statistics Attribute Value Class Witch 3 ( - - - ac - 7 - - - hp - 11 - - - wis - 16 - - - spells - - charm-animal ----control-over-the-natural-world;-the-ability-to-bend-animal-will-to-her-own,-reflecting-the-lakandi-tradition&#39;s-emphasis-on-binding-and-domination-rather-than-cooperation - sleep ----the-power-to-impose-unconsciousness;-a-spell-of-control-that-echoes-the-binding-tradition&#39;s-fundamental-premise:-the-practitioner-imposes,-the-target-submits - cure-light-wounds ----healing;-the-practical-magic-that-has-kept-greta-valued-and-alive-in-bone-creek-for-decades,-the-reason-the-community-tolerates-what-they-know-about-her-and-does-not-ask-about-what-they-suspect - - proficiencies - - alchemy ----the-preparation-of-substances-with-supernatural-properties;-the-practical-application-of-knowledge-that-bridges-the-mundane-and-the-arcane - herbalism-2 ----advanced-knowledge-of-plants,-their-properties,-and-their-uses;-greta&#39;s-primary-visible-trade-and-the-reason-most-of-bone-creek-interacts-with-her-at-all - - - the-pact - greta-has-made-a-pact-with-a-demonic-entity-she-does-not-discuss.-most-of-[[bone-creek\" class=\"wiki-link\">Bone Creek treats this as her private business, because she has never harmed anyone and her medicines have genuinely saved lives. This is the practical morality of the frontier: what matters is not what you believe or what you have done in private, but whether you are useful and whether you are dangerous. Greta is useful. She has not, thus far, been dangerous to anyone in Bone Creek. The Key Distinction The Lakandi tradition distinguishes between two fundamentally different types of demonic engagement: Binding that places the practitioner in SERVICE to a Cthonic power. The practitioner petitions, the entity grants, and the practitioner becomes increasingly dependent -- a servant, a vessel, a tool. The power flows downward. The entity commands; the practitioner obeys. Binding where the practitioner HOLDS the entity. The practitioner contests, the entity yields (or is compelled to yield), and the relationship is one of controlled obligation rather than servitude. The power flows upward. The practitioner commands; the entity serves. Greta holds something. She is not in service to a Cthonic power. She has bound an entity into an arrangement where she maintains control -- or at least, where the balance of the arrangement favors her. What she gave for this binding she has not said. The cost of holding a demonic entity is always real, always personal, and always visible to those who know what to look for. History in Bone Creek Greta has operated through every phase of Bone Creek&#39;s existence: The silver rush -- when Bone Creek was a booming mining settlement and fortune-seekers flooded the region. Greta was there, providing medicines, remedies, and services that the miners needed and could not get elsewhere. The decline -- when the silver ran out and Bone Creek contracted from a boom town to a dying settlement. Greta remained when others left, sustained by whatever she is and whatever she knows. The current Scalper economy -- when the imperial bounty on beastmen scalps transformed Bone Creek into the epicenter of the Scalper trade. Greta adapted, as she has always adapted, providing her services to a new clientele of bounty hunters, mercenaries, and desperate frontier people. Through every phase, Greta has been a constant -- an anchor of continuity in a place defined by volatility. She was here before the silver. She was here before the Scalpers. She will be here after them, if anything is. Knowledge and Watching Greta knows the region&#39;s pre-imperial history better than anyone in Bone Creek . She is not forthcoming about this knowledge. She does not volunteer information. She does not educate. She does not share what she knows unless she has a reason -- and her reasons are her own, as opaque and guarded as everything else about her. She is watching . What she watches for, what she expects, what she anticipates -- none of this is clear. But the quality of her attention -- the way her gaze lingers on certain visitors, certain events, certain shifts in the balance of power in Bone Creek and beyond -- suggests that Greta is not merely surviving the frontier but monitoring it. She is waiting for something, or watching for something, and when it arrives she will know it before anyone else does. The Marks of Binding Repeated contact with the Beyond corrupts. This is not speculation or theology -- it is observable fact. The Lakandi tradition treats the signs of corruption not as failing but as the visible record of genuine engagement . To be marked is to have done something real. The marks of binding include: Eyes darkening at the iris -- a gradual deepening of color that progresses with prolonged Cthonic contact, eventually turning the eyes fully dark. The legendary Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye bore a name that was not metaphorical. A quality of stillness beyond patience -- not the stillness of someone waiting, but the stillness of something that has been touched by entities that operate on timescales beyond human comprehension. A person who has held a demon carries something of that demon&#39;s relationship to time. Awareness of things not normally visible -- perception that extends beyond the ordinary human range, into frequencies and dimensions that most people never access. Those who have torn open the Veil and reached through it carry an expanded awareness that does not fade. The Lakandi treat these marks as credentials. To be corrupted is to have engaged. To be engaged is to have risked. To have risked is to have done something real with power that most people are too frightened to touch. See Also bone-creek -- The settlement where Greta has lived for decades lakandi-binding-tradition -- The tradition Greta practices Lakandi -- Greta&#39;s culture and people the-veil -- The barrier through which Lakandi practitioners reach cthonic-corruption -- The corruption that marks those who engage with the Beyond jarn-murky-eye -- The legendary Warlock King of the Lakandi binding tradition congregation-of-the-hollow-sun -- Another heterodox spiritual movement in Bone Creek ezekiel-shaw -- The preacher of the Hollow Sun, also operating in Bone Creek brother-marco -- The priest of Seros in Bone Creek the-backlands -- The frontier province"},{"slug":"high-mage-cynar","title":"High Mage Cynar","category":"people","tags":"historical imperial-academy high-mage sorcerer battle-of-blue-mound lakan-campaigns erenthis avari thornasse","text":"High Mage Cynar High Mage Cynar was the Imperial Academy &#39;s foremost battle-sorcerer during the Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY). He is remembered for two acts that define his legacy: the cataclysmic sorcerous duel with Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye at the Battle of Blue Mound -- which annihilated both armies and killed both combatants -- and the burning of the Erenthis at Thornasse, the cultural execution of the Avari people. Both acts demonstrated the devastating and irreversible consequences of concentrating overwhelming power in a single individual. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Cynar Title High Mage of the Lakan Campaigns , Imperial armies marched deep into Lakandi territory, backed by devastating magical firepower. The campaign culminated in the Battle of Blue Mound , where Imperial forces under Cynar&#39;s command engaged the army of Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye . The climax of the battle came when Cynar and Jarn Murky-Eye engaged in a direct sorcerous duel -- a confrontation of such magnitude that it escalated beyond all control. The cataclysmic energies unleashed by the two combatants annihilated both armies entirely , leaving the battlefield a blasted and lifeless wasteland. Neither Cynar nor Jarn Murky-Eye survived. The Battle of Blue Mound had profound consequences for Imperial military doctrine. It demonstrated that the deployment of high-level sorcerers as singular weapons of mass destruction was not merely dangerous but potentially suicidal. The Empire subsequently adopted a model of combined arms warfare, integrating squad mages into conventional military formations rather than relying on individual sorcerers to decide the outcome of battles. The Burning of the Erenthis Approximately 30 years ago, High Mage Cynar committed what many consider a cultural atrocity: the burning of the Erenthis at Thornasse. The Erenthis was the sacred oral and written tradition of the Avari people -- their history, their songs, their identity as a people preserved across generations. Cynar&#39;s destruction of the Erenthis at Thornasse was a deliberate act of cultural execution. By destroying the physical records and killing or scattering the keepers of the oral tradition, the Empire attempted to erase the Avari as a distinct people. The consequences of this act continue to reverberate: the Avari communities that survive -- such as the community in Sanctuary &#39;s Ashward, led by Elder Sarnath -- carry the wound of this destruction as a defining element of their identity. Legacy Cynar&#39;s legacy is one of overwhelming power wielded without adequate restraint. In war, his duel with Jarn Murky-Eye destroyed everything it was meant to protect. In peace, his burning of the Erenthis inflicted a wound that can never be fully healed. He embodied the dangers of the Imperial Academy &#39;s doctrine of sorcerous supremacy -- the belief that magical power, properly applied, could solve any problem. The Battle of Blue Mound proved that some problems, when met with overwhelming force, simply consume everything. See Also Battle of Blue Mound -- the catastrophic battle The Lakan Campaigns -- the broader military campaign Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye -- his opponent in the duel The Erenthis -- the Avari tradition he destroyed Elder Sarnath -- Avari community elder in Sanctuary The Imperial Academy -- the institution he served Magic and Sorcery -- the forces he wielded History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"iman","title":"Iman","category":"people","tags":"pc player-character reclaimers bladedancer order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon empyrean lady-severina backlands fort-meade","text":"Iman Iman is a Bladedancer and a member of the Reclaimers . She was driven from the Order of the Scarlet Ribbon for speaking too plainly of the priestesses and their noble patrons -- for naming aloud the corruption that others chose to tolerate in silence. Exiled from the only institution that had given her purpose, she came to the Backlands and found new allegiances among the killers drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty. She has developed a close relationship with Lady Severina Marcellus . At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Iman Class Bladedancer Status Active PC Party Order of the Scarlet Ribbon -- a militant order connected to the Empyrean faith. The Order trained bladedancers in the martial and devotional arts, combining blade-work with religious discipline in service to the Empyrean temples and their patrons. The Order, however, was not the pure institution its public face suggested. The priestesses of the Order maintained relationships with noble patrons -- relationships that blurred the boundary between spiritual authority and secular power, between devotion and transaction. These arrangements were understood by everyone within the Order but spoken of by no one. They were the open secret upon which the institution&#39;s funding, political protection, and social standing depended. Iman spoke too plainly. She named what others chose not to name. She identified the corruption -- the exchange of spiritual authority for noble patronage, the priestesses who served their patrons&#39; interests rather than their faith&#39;s teachings -- and she said it aloud, in terms that could not be misunderstood or politely ignored. For this, she was driven from the Order. Not for being wrong, but for being honest in a place where honesty was the one unforgivable sin. Coming to the Backlands Stripped of her place in the Order, Iman came to the Backlands as so many others did -- drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty, by the promise of coin for killing, by the frontier&#39;s indifference to a person&#39;s past. The Backlands did not care what she had said or whom she had offended. It cared only whether she could fight, and she could. She fell in with the group that would become the Reclaimers , finding among these killers and misfits a kind of belonging that the Order had revoked. Her bladedancer training made her one of the party&#39;s most capable combatants. Her directness -- the same quality that had gotten her expelled -- made her a forthright companion, if sometimes an uncomfortable one. Relationship with Lady Severina Iman has developed a close personal relationship with Lady Severina Marcellus , the wife of Legate Marcellus and the Reclaimers&#39; true patron. The precise nature of this relationship is multilayered -- Severina is the party&#39;s patron, a political operator of considerable sophistication, and a woman who recognizes in Iman a directness that she values precisely because it is so rare in her world of courtly maneuvering. Severina told Iman privately that she considers herself the real political engine of the Marcellus household. This confidence suggests a level of trust between the two women that extends beyond the merely professional. Iman, expelled from one institution for her honesty, has found in Severina someone who values that quality rather than punishing it. Role Among the Reclaimers Iman is one of the party&#39;s front-line combatants -- a trained bladedancer whose martial skills were honed in the Order of the Scarlet Ribbon . She brings religious discipline and martial precision to a group that is otherwise composed of scholars, merchants, and outcasts. Her connection to Lady Severina gives her a political dimension within the party that extends beyond her combat role. Through Iman, the Reclaimers have a direct and personal line to their patron -- a relationship that is not merely transactional but built on genuine mutual regard. Personality Iman is direct, plain-spoken, and unwilling to tolerate the kind of comfortable lies that most institutions depend upon. This quality got her expelled from the Order of the Scarlet Ribbon , and it remains her defining characteristic. She says what she sees. She names what others choose to leave unnamed. In an order of priestesses and nobles, this made her dangerous. Among the Reclaimers, it makes her trustworthy. She carries the weight of her expulsion without self-pity. The Order cast her out for telling the truth, and she has not forgiven them for it, but neither has she allowed it to embitter her entirely. She found new purpose in the Backlands, new companions among the Reclaimers, and a new patron in Lady Severina who values honesty rather than punishing it. See Also the-reclaimers -- The adventuring party she belongs to order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon -- The militant order from which she was expelled lady-severina -- Her close relationship and the Reclaimers&#39; patron legate-marcellus -- Severina&#39;s husband and the Reclaimers&#39; formal patron fort-meade -- The garrison where she is based Nethercity -- The underground complex currently being explored crossings -- The ruins above the Nethercity shatzi -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer theodotus -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard tiberius -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer tancred -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader campaign-chronicle -- Session history of the campaign"},{"slug":"irontoe","title":"Irontoe","category":"people","tags":"npc fighter mithrian bone-creek smith veteran lakandi backlands","text":"Irontoe Pontus Irontoe Draega is a Mithrian Fighter (level 2) who serves as Bone Creek&#39;s smith. He lost his leg fighting the Lakandi and wears an iron foot on a wooden leg -- the prosthetic that earned him his name. Despite the disability, he is one of the most productive and loudest men in the settlement. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Pontus Irontoe Draega Race Lakandi , most likely during the Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY) -- the eight-year war that ended with the Battle of Blue Mound and the mutual annihilation of High Mage Cynar and Jarn Murky-Eye . His Fighter training and Manual of Arms proficiency mark him as a trained imperial soldier, not a militia conscript. A man who survived the Lakan Campaigns and lost only a leg came out ahead of many. The Lakandi fought with bound demons and dark sorcery -- losing a limb to such enemies and living to forge iron in a frontier town is, by any measure, a victory. Role in Bone Creek As the settlement&#39;s only skilled smith, Irontoe is essential infrastructure. Scalpers need weapons maintained, armor repaired, and tools forged. The frontier consumes metal at a prodigious rate. Irontoe&#39;s forge is one of the few things standing between Bone Creek and complete material collapse. His Craft (Smithing) proficiency makes him the man who keeps the Scalper economy&#39;s tools sharp and functional. His Manual of Arms proficiency means he understands what he&#39;s making and for whom -- a soldier-smith, not merely a tradesman. See Also bone-creek -- The frontier outpost where Irontoe works his forge lakandi -- The enemy who took his leg lakan-campaigns -- The likely war in which he served mithrian-culture -- His cultural background scalper-gangs -- The primary customers for his smithing"},{"slug":"jarn-murky-eye","title":"Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye","category":"people","tags":"historical warlock-king lakandi sorcerer battle-of-blue-mound lakan-campaigns veil demon-binding","text":"Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye Warlock King Jarn Murky-Eye was the most powerful sorcerer-warlord of the Lakandi people, a warlock whose name was not metaphorical -- he bore the physical marks of extensive contact with the Veil and demon-binding practices that defined Lakandi sorcerous tradition. He fought High Mage Cynar of the Imperial Academy at the Battle of Blue Mound during the Lakan Campaigns (360-368 IY). The cataclysmic sorcerous duel between the two annihilated both armies and killed both combatants. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Jarn Murky-Eye Title Warlock King of the Lakandi Affiliation Lakandi tribes Sorcerous Tradition Veil , the boundary between the physical world and the chaotic energies of the Beyond . Among the Lakandi, such physical corruption is not viewed as a curse or a mark of shame. It is treated as a visible record of genuine engagement -- proof that the sorcerer has touched the Veil, bargained with entities beyond it, and returned bearing the marks of that contact. The Lakandi binding tradition holds that a sorcerer who has not been changed by the Veil has not truly engaged with it. Corruption -- physical transformation, discoloration, asymmetry, or more profound alterations -- is evidence of authenticity. A warlock whose body shows no marks is either a fraud or a coward. Jarn&#39;s murky eye was thus a badge of authority as much as a physical affliction. The Battle of Blue Mound When Imperial armies marched deep into Lakandi territory during the Lakan Campaigns , Jarn Murky-Eye assembled an army of considerable size and ferocity to resist the invasion. The campaign culminated in the Battle of Blue Mound , where Jarn&#39;s forces clashed with the Imperial army led by High Mage Cynar . The climax of the battle was a direct sorcerous duel between the two most powerful magic users on the field. The confrontation escalated beyond all control -- the energies unleashed by Cynar&#39;s Gnostic Geometry and Jarn&#39;s Veil-born sorcery combined into a cataclysm that annihilated both armies entirely. Neither Jarn nor Cynar survived. Legacy Jarn Murky-Eye&#39;s death did not end the Lakandi as a people. The Empire, having lost its entire expeditionary force, retreated and erected a line of border forts that marks the current frontier. The Lakandi were broken by the campaign but remained unbowed -- vowing revenge against the Empire that had invaded their lands and, in the process of being defeated, destroyed everything. Among the Lakandi, Jarn is remembered as a hero -- a warlock king who met the Empire&#39;s most powerful sorcerer in single combat and, though he died, ensured that the enemy did not survive either. The mutual annihilation at Blue Mound is viewed not as a defeat but as a victory of a different kind: proof that the Lakandi will never submit, even at the cost of their own destruction. See Also Battle of Blue Mound -- the catastrophic battle The Lakan Campaigns -- the broader military campaign High Mage Cynar -- his opponent in the duel Lakandi Binding Tradition -- the sorcerous tradition he embodied Magic and Sorcery Cthonic Corruption -- the forces of the Veil History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"justinian-decimus","title":"Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus","category":"people","tags":"emperor house-decimus ruler mithrian-empire mithra-city imperial-bounty skiothan","text":"Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus is the current Emperor of the Mithrian Empire and patriarch of House Decimus , the ruling dynasty founded by his ancestor Claudius Decimus in 270 IY. He firmly holds the Empire in his grasp, ruling from Mithra City and facing threats on multiple fronts. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Justinian Claudius Decimus Title Emperor of the War of Three Emperors , and the current Emperor maintains his grip through the same instruments that have sustained his house for over a century: the Imperial Talons (spies and assassins who answer only to the throne), the legions, and the vast bureaucratic apparatus of imperial governance. The Emperor&#39;s authority is absolute in theory, though in practice it is constrained by the power of the Great Houses, the influence of the Thousand Temples , the independence of the Imperial Academy , and the practical limits of governing an empire that spans a continent. Key Decisions The Garrison Recall (378 IY) Two years ago, when the great Skiothan host threatened the Empire&#39;s western frontier, the Emperor recalled the local armies and garrisons from the Backlands to reinforce the defenses against this existential threat. This strategic decision left the frontier provinces undermanned and poorly defended, contributing directly to the current lawlessness and chaos in the Backlands. The recall stranded officers like Legate Marcellus at skeleton garrisons like Fort Meade , and shifted the balance of power in the provinces toward local strongmen like Governor Drussus . The Imperial Bounty (377-378 IY) Following the Sacking of Crossings in 377 IY -- when a Beastmen horde razed the northern town and slaughtered its people -- the Emperor issued an Imperial scalp bounty on beastmen. The bounty was intended to suppress the beastman threat, but its consequences were catastrophic. It unleashed a wave of mercenaries, deserters, and killers into the Backlands, creating the Scalper economy that has plunged the frontier into anarchy. While beastman activity near settled areas has decreased, the influx of violent fortune-seekers has created problems arguably worse than the threat they were sent to address. Threats The Emperor faces challenges on multiple fronts: Beastmen in the Backlands -- a persistent threat to frontier settlements Skiothan raiders on the western frontier -- the existential threat that prompted the garrison recall Lingering unrest in Morn -- provincial instability The Great Houses -- the ever-present political maneuvering of Valerian , Kalomenes , Severian , and the others The proliferation of sorcerous knowledge beyond the Imperial Academy &#39;s control Corruption of the Senate Provincial restlessness -- the Backlands in particular are sliding toward a state of de facto independence under Governor Drussus See Also House Decimus -- the ruling dynasty Claudius Decimus -- ancestor and dynasty founder The Imperial Talons -- the Emperor&#39;s spies and assassins Sacking of Crossings -- the disaster that prompted the Imperial Bounty Scalper Gangs -- consequence of the bounty Governor Drussus -- provincial strongman in the Backlands Legate Marcellus -- military commander stranded by the recall The Mithrian Empire Mithra City History of Mithrapos"},{"slug":"kael-baldric","title":"Kael Baldric","category":"people","tags":"npc fighter avari scalper baldric-brothers missing investigation-hook backlands bone-creek","text":"Kael Baldric Kael Baldric is an Avari fighter and the leader of the Baldric Brothers , a Scalper gang composed of five Avari brothers with a fearsome reputation in the Backlands . Stern, protective, and fiercely loyal to his family, Kael is the eldest and most formidable of the brothers — the one who holds the group together and directs their violent efficiency. Kael is currently MISSING . His disappearance is unexplained and deeply troubling, both for his brothers and for the balance of power among the Scalper gangs of Bone Creek . The Baldric Brothers are rarely seen apart, and Kael&#39;s absence suggests something has gone catastrophically wrong. His disappearance serves as a potential investigation or rescue hook — a mystery that could lead into the dangerous wilderness of the Backlands or into the web of intrigue that entangles Bone Creek&#39;s power players. Statistics Attribute Value Class Fighter 4 Race - - - ac - 3 - - - hp - 30 - - - atk - +4-(bastard-sword,-1d10+1) - - - str - 15 - - - kael&#39;s-statistics-reflect-a-seasoned-warrior-of-considerable-ability.-his-30-hit-points-provide-strong-durability,-and-his-+4-attack-bonus-with-a-bastard-sword-dealing-1d10+1-damage-makes-him-a-powerful-melee-combatant.-his-strength-of-15-supports-his-fighting-style:-direct,-forceful,-and-unrelenting.-his-ac-of-3-indicates-solid-armor,-likely-well-maintained-—-kael-is-a-professional-who-takes-his-equipment-seriously. - the-bastard-sword-is-a-versatile-weapon-that-can-be-wielded-in-one-or-two-hands,-reflecting-kael&#39;s-adaptability-in-combat.-it-is-a-weapon-of-reach-and-power,-suitable-for-a-leader-who-fights-at-the-front-of-his-brothers&#39;-formation. - - proficiencies - - leadership -—-the-ability-to-command,-inspire,-and-organize-a-fighting-force.-for-kael,-this-proficiency-is-exercised-within-the-tight-knit-structure-of-the-baldric-brothers-—-five-siblings-who-fight-as-a-single,-coordinated-unit.-kael&#39;s-leadership-is-not-the-broad,-political-command-of-a-general-but-the-intimate,-familial-authority-of-an-eldest-brother-who-has-kept-his-family-alive-through-years-of-violence. - survival -—-the-practical-skills-of-wilderness-endurance-in-the-harsh-environment-of-the-backlands.-tracking-prey,-finding-water,-reading-the-land,-navigating-hostile-terrain-—-these-are-the-skills-that-keep-the-baldric-brothers-operational-in-the-field-between-bounty-hunts. - - - appearance-and-demeanor - kael-is- completely-bald -—-a-striking-physical-feature-that-makes-him-instantly-recognizable.-combined-with-his- black-chain-tattoos ,-which-wind-across-his-scalp-and-presumably-down-his-neck-and-body,-kael-presents-an-intimidating-and-memorable-figure.-the-black-chain-tattoos-may-be-cultural-markers-of-his-[[races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari heritage, symbols of his bond with his brothers, or marks earned through combat and survival. He is stern — a man of few words and direct action. Kael does not waste time on pleasantries, negotiation, or unnecessary conversation. He assesses situations quickly, makes decisions firmly, and expects his brothers to follow without question. This sternness is not cruelty — it is the discipline of a man who knows that hesitation and weakness get people killed on the frontier. He is protective — fiercely and absolutely devoted to the safety and well-being of his brothers. This protectiveness is the core of Kael&#39;s identity. Everything he does — every fight, every hunt, every decision — is filtered through the question of whether it serves or endangers his family. This makes Kael predictable in one crucial way: threatening his brothers is the surest way to earn his undying enmity, and protecting them is the surest path to his gratitude. He is family-loyal to an extreme degree. The Baldric Brothers are not merely a Scalper gang — they are a family unit, and Kael&#39;s loyalty to that unit is absolute. He would die for his brothers without hesitation, and he would kill anyone who threatened them without remorse. The Baldric Brothers The Baldric Brothers are five Avari brothers who operate as a single, cohesive Scalper gang in the Backlands. They have a fearsome reputation earned through effectiveness and violence: They are rarely seen apart — the brothers operate as a unit at almost all times, fighting together, eating together, sleeping in shifts to protect each other. This unity is their greatest strength, as five coordinated warriors fighting as one are far more dangerous than five individuals. They get jobs done quickly and violently — the Baldric Brothers are known for brutal efficiency. They do not linger, they do not hesitate, and they do not leave survivors among their beastman prey. This reputation means they are sought after for difficult or dangerous bounties that other Scalper groups would avoid. The four unnamed brothers presumably share Kael&#39;s Avari heritage and martial capabilities, though their individual classes, levels, and personalities are not detailed. What is clear is that they form a tightly bonded fighting unit whose coordination and mutual loyalty make them far more dangerous than their individual statistics would suggest. Current Status: MISSING Kael Baldric is currently missing . This is an extraordinary and alarming situation for several reasons: The brothers are never apart. For Kael to be separated from his brothers implies that something extraordinary — a battle, a trap, a betrayal, a disaster — has occurred. The Baldric Brothers do not simply wander off alone. Kael is the leader. Without Kael, the remaining four brothers lose their commander, their decision-maker, and their emotional anchor. The gang&#39;s effectiveness and cohesion are severely compromised. No explanation has been offered. Kael&#39;s disappearance is unexplained, which means the brothers either do not know what happened to him or are not willing to share that information. Either possibility is deeply troubling. Foul play is likely. Given the dangerous nature of the Backlands and the number of enemies a successful Scalper gang inevitably accumulates, Kael&#39;s disappearance is more likely the result of violence than accident. Possible Explanations Captured by beastmen — Kael may have been taken alive during a hunt gone wrong. If so, he is likely being held in or near crossings or another beastman settlement. Betrayed by a rival — One of the other Scalper gangs or a power player in Bone Creek may have orchestrated Kael&#39;s disappearance to weaken the Baldric Brothers. Lost in the wilderness — The Backlands are vast and dangerous. Kael may be injured, trapped, or lost in hostile terrain. Imprisoned — Kael may have been captured by imperial forces, by the Red River Consortium , or by some other organized power. Voluntary departure — It is possible, though unlikely given his character, that Kael left of his own accord for reasons unknown to his brothers. Dead — The simplest and most grim explanation. Kael may have been killed, and his body has not yet been found. Plot Hooks The Search for Kael — The Baldric Brothers&#39; search for their missing leader is a ready-made adventure hook. They would pay handsomely — or offer violent services — to anyone who could provide information about Kael&#39;s whereabouts. The Brothers Without a Leader — How do the four remaining brothers cope without Kael? Do they fragment, lash out, seek help, or become even more dangerous in their desperation? Who Took Kael? — If Kael&#39;s disappearance was orchestrated, identifying the responsible party opens up a web of intrigue involving Scalper gangs, beastmen, or Bone Creek&#39;s power players. The Rescue — If Kael is alive and captive, a rescue mission into beastman-held territory or a rival&#39;s stronghold would be a high-stakes operation. The Avari Bond — The Baldric Brothers&#39; extreme loyalty to each other is both a strength and a vulnerability. Anyone who threatens the remaining brothers controls the most powerful lever in the situation. See Also scalper-gangs — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands The Baldric Brothers — Kael&#39;s gang of five Avari brothers bone-creek — The Scalper settlement the-backlands — The frontier province Avari — The Baldric Brothers&#39; cultural heritage beastmen — Potential captors if Kael was taken during a hunt crossings — The ruined city; a possible location for a captive Kael"},{"slug":"lady-severina","title":"Lady Severina Marcellus","category":"people","tags":"npc noble political fort-meade house-valerian backlands mithrian","text":"Lady Severina Marcellus Lady Severina Marcellus (nee Severina) is the wife of Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus and the more politically sophisticated half of the Marcellus household at Fort Meade . She operates through warmth, curiosity, and social intelligence that most people underestimate. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Lady Severina Marcellus (nee Severina) Race Mithrian female Age Early 40s Class Noble 2 Location Backlands with diminishing external leverage. Character Severina is genuinely interested in people -- not as performance, but as method. Understanding people is how she moves them. Where her husband commands through cold authority and implied threat, Severina operates through warmth, curiosity, and a social intelligence that most people underestimate until it is too late. She is the more politically sophisticated of the two Marcellus, and she knows it. She told Iman privately that she considers herself the real political engine of the household. She is probably correct. She wears Thrassian jewelry and is often seen alone. The Rook Situation During the worst of Rook&#39;s banditry, Severina saw that her husband&#39;s pride was going to cost them everything. The garrison could not resolve the situation, and Marcellus would not admit it. So she went behind his back and hired the Reclaimers to deal with Rook. She was right. The Reclaimers destroyed Rook at Fort Ikenvar and broke the bandit threat. Marcellus publicly humiliated her for it afterward -- a cold, controlled display staged for the garrison&#39;s benefit. She accepted it with visible grace. The political reality is that her decision saved them, and both of them know it. Relationships Legate Marcellus (Husband) A complex marriage of political convenience that has calcified under years of frontier hardship. Severina respects her husband&#39;s competence but recognizes his limitations -- his pride, his coldness, his inability to adapt politically. He publicly humiliated her over the Reclaimer hiring, and she absorbed it without breaking. The power dynamic between them is less straightforward than it appears from the outside. The Reclaimers Warmer and more personal than her husband&#39;s relationship with them. Severina has invited Shatzi and Iman to gatherings repeatedly. She is genuinely curious about them as people. She views the Reclaimers as her investment -- she hired them, they delivered, and that connection belongs to her more than to her husband. Malachor Severina is fully aware of Malachor&#39;s feelings for her. She has made a careful study of how to use them without encouraging enough to create a problem. She values his Academy access and the information it provides. She does not value him beyond that. Malachor&#39;s infatuation is a tool she maintains with precision -- enough warmth to keep him useful, never enough to make him bold. Political Role Severina is the diplomatic face of the Marcellus household. While the Legate manages the garrison and the trade route, Severina manages relationships -- with visiting officials, with merchant contacts, with anyone whose goodwill might be converted into political capital. Her judgment on the Rook situation demonstrated that she sees threats and opportunities faster than her husband, and is willing to act on them even at personal cost. This makes her one of the most capable political operators at Fort Meade , and one of the most underestimated. See Also legate-marcellus -- Her husband, commanding officer of Fort Meade fort-meade -- The garrison where the Marcellus household is based Reclaimers -- The party she hired to resolve the Rook situation malachor -- Imperial historian whose feelings she exploits strategically rook -- The bandit threat she acted to resolve fort-ikenvar -- Where the Reclaimers destroyed Rook house-valerian -- The Legate&#39;s noble house iman -- Reclaimer she has cultivated a personal relationship with shatzi -- Reclaimer she has invited to social gatherings imperial-academy -- The institution whose access she values through Malachor"},{"slug":"legate-marcellus","title":"Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus","category":"people","tags":"npc military legate mithrian-military backlands border-forts lakan-campaigns house-valerian fort-meade","text":"Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus is the military commander of the Backlands and commanding officer of Fort Meade , holding the rank of Legate within the Mithrian military . He commands a garrison of approximately 100 soldiers and controls the most strategically significant chokepoint between the imperial interior and the frontier. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Titus Valerian Marcellus Race Mithrian male Age Late 40s House House Valerian carried weight, but it was his competence that earned his postings and his reputation. His life has been a sequence of near-achievements. Before the Emperor&#39;s garrison recall, he was positioned to parlay military success on the frontier into a Senate seat. His wife, Severina , came from wealth and influence. The Valerian name carried weight. Everything was aligned. Then the recall came. Governor Drussus blocked every request Marcellus made for reinforcements, recognition, or transfer. Severina&#39;s father died, leaving her brother -- who cares nothing for his sister -- as head of household. The political support structure that was supposed to carry Marcellus to the Senate evaporated, and he was left holding a crumbling frontier with a skeleton garrison and no path forward. The Withdrawal (378 IY) Two years ago, when the great Skiotha host threatened the Mithrian Empire , the Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus recalled the local armies and garrisons from the Backlands. This left the province undermanned and poorly defended, and left Marcellus holding the frontier with a skeleton force. The Border Forts The border forts under Marcellus&#39;s command were originally constructed after the failed Lakan Campaigns -- the imperial wars of subjugation against the Lakandi barbarians of the wastes. These fortifications were built to hold the line against future Lakandi aggression. Now, with the garrison stripped down to a fraction of its intended strength, they serve as a thin and crumbling barrier. Character Cold, calculating, quietly cruel. Marcellus does not raise his voice. He does not need to. The garrison&#39;s mean streak reflects his own -- eleven years under his command have shaped Sergeant Crull and every soldier beneath him into instruments of his temperament. He is capable of genuine respect but extends it rarely and withdraws it without warning. He is not performatively harsh -- he is simply indifferent to discomfort he does not share, and efficient in applying pressure where it serves his purposes. He spends his own coin to eliminate threats and delay imperial scrutiny, understanding that every problem he solves quietly is one less excuse for the Governor to intervene in his domain. Threats Marcellus faces threats on multiple fronts: The beastmen have sacked Crossings and are pushing farther south The Lakandi are stirring in the wastes, with whispers of rebellion His forces are too few to adequately defend the border forts, let alone project power into the province No reinforcements are forthcoming from the imperial heartland The Rook Situation and the Reclaimers The resolution of the Rook situation partially restored Marcellus&#39;s position. Severina hired the Reclaimers behind his back because she saw his pride was going to cost them everything. She was right -- the Reclaimers delivered what his garrison could not, destroying Rook at Fort Ikenvar . Marcellus publicly humiliated Severina for going behind his back -- a cold, controlled display staged for the garrison&#39;s benefit. But he is experienced enough to recognize a useful asset when he sees one. He no longer plans to discard the Reclaimers. He plans to use them for career rehabilitation. Political Position Marcellus is engaged in a silent war with Governor Valerios Drussus -- his direct superior. The Governor sits in Sanctuary , content to rest on his laurels while the frontier crumbles. Marcellus uses the trade route leverage carefully: enough pressure to remind the Governor of his dependence on Fort Meade&#39;s chokepoint, not enough to justify formal reprisal. The trade route revenue funds his soldiers&#39; loyalty, his intelligence operations against the Governor, and his household expenses. The food dependency of Bone Creek on the supply caravans passing through Fort Meade is his most significant political weapon. Chain of Command Emperor Justinian Claudius Decimus -- The Emperor who recalled the armies Governor Valerios Drussus ( House Drussus ) -- Civil governor of the Backlands, seated in Sanctuary Legate Titus Valerian Marcellus -- Military commander on the frontier The disconnect between the distant, inactive Governor and the embattled Legate represents one of the core tensions in the Backlands&#39; power structure. Relationship with the Reclaimers Professional and transactional, but with a longer horizon than before. Marcellus sees the Reclaimers as capable irregular assets -- people who can accomplish what his garrison cannot, operating outside formal military channels. He will honor agreements precisely as written and exploit any ambiguity ruthlessly. He is not an enemy, but he is not a friend. Every interaction is evaluated through the lens of what the Reclaimers can do for his career rehabilitation and what it will cost him. The Charter Proposal Before the Reclaimers depart for Sanctuary , Marcellus requests a formal meeting. The message is delivered by his steward -- not Crull , not a soldier. This deliberate choice of messenger signals the nature of the conversation: this is business, not military command. Crull is not in the room. Severina is present, seated slightly to the side -- not beside him. Marcellus opens by noting the Reclaimers brought four thousand gold worth of goods through his market in a single visit. Tax exempt. He lets that sit, then presents his proposal without theatrics -- a business arrangement between parties who have worked together three weeks: The Terms: A formal charter: The Reclaimers are his licensed salvagers with exclusive territorial claim to the ruins of Crossings and the Nethercity . No other party operates there without their sanction. A secure vault and warehouse at Fort Meade , constructed at his expense, for the Reclaimers&#39; exclusive use. A quarterly market fair at Fort Meade, drawing merchants from Sanctuary and Dunwick . He funds the first three years. In exchange: Fifteen percent of recovered value, payable in goods or coin at their discretion. And continued availability as his agents -- tasks specified as they arise. Negotiation Parameters: Marcellus will not move on the structure. He will negotiate specifics: Percentage: Floor is ten percent. He opened at fifteen. Timeline for vault construction: Movable. Specifics of available when required : He will accept definition. He will also use any vagueness left in the final language. He will honor exactly what is agreed. He will exploit any ambiguity in exactly what is agreed. Severina&#39;s Role: After Marcellus finishes, Severina speaks. She frames it as opportunity rather than contract -- the charter carries weight in Sanctuary as well as Fort Meade, the formalization protects what the Reclaimers have already built, the Academy introductions Malachor can arrange become more credible under the Legate&#39;s seal. She is warm, interested, and precise beneath the warmth. She is not selling. She is clarifying. The difference is hard to pin down. What He Doesn&#39;t Say: He does not say this is about Drussus . He does not say that a Fort Meade with a functioning market, a growing merchant quarter, and documented gold output is a Fort Meade that no longer needs the Governor&#39;s goodwill to survive. He does not say the Reclaimers are the engine he needs to change his political position. None of this needs saying. It is all visible to anyone paying attention. Three weeks ago Marcellus was a frustrated legate using irregular assets to solve a bandit problem. He has moved faster than that framing suggests because he has been calculating since the Rook situation ended. This meeting is the result -- and the beginning of a dependency that runs in both directions. The party is becoming essential to his ambitions in a way that makes them harder to walk away from. The political transformation of Fort Meade from a crumbling frontier garrison into an independent economic power is now his project, and the Reclaimers are the engine that makes it possible. Relationship with Severina Lady Severina Marcellus is the more politically sophisticated half of the household, and Marcellus is not unaware of this fact. Their marriage is a political partnership that functions despite -- or perhaps because of -- the fundamental tension between his authority and her judgment. She was right about Rook. He punished her for being right. Both of them understand what that means. See Also fort-meade -- The garrison Marcellus commands lady-severina -- His wife and the household&#39;s political engine sergeant-crull -- His senior NCO and enforcer malachor -- Imperial historian stationed at Fort Meade the-backlands -- The province Marcellus is tasked with defending mithrian-military -- The imperial military structure mithrian-empire -- The empire Marcellus serves house-valerian -- Marcellus&#39;s noble house governor-drussus -- His political rival and nominal superior Reclaimers -- The party he now considers a useful irregular asset rook -- The bandit whose destruction partially restored Marcellus&#39;s position fort-ikenvar -- Where the Reclaimers destroyed Rook lakandi -- The barbarian threat the border forts were built to contain beastmen -- The creatures threatening the province from the north crossings -- The sacked city whose fall worsened the frontier crisis sanctuary -- Where Governor Drussus sits idle bone-creek -- The frontier settlement dependent on Fort Meade&#39;s supply route house-drussus -- The governor&#39;s noble house"},{"slug":"lynara","title":"Lynara","category":"people","tags":"npc eladra nightblade malyn apprentice backlands conflicted stealth sorcery","text":"Lynara Lynara is an Eladran Nightblade (level 3) and the apprentice of Malyn the Misshapen . She is one of the few true Eladra encountered in the Backlands -- golden-skinned and pale-eyed in the manner of her ancient race -- and serves as a potential gateway to understanding Malyn&#39;s secret operations. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Lynara Race Eladran heritage: Golden skin -- the warm metallic complexion of the uncorrupted Eladra, distinct from the pale white skin of the Elvora Pale Eladran eyes -- the characteristic eyes of her kind, without the solid black of Elvora Veil-corruption Her appearance alone marks her as extraordinary. True Eladra are vanishingly rare in the current age. The eladra of Aodahn vanished without explanation. The elvora are corrupted beyond recognition. For an Eladran of apparently uncorrupted lineage to be operating in the Backlands -- as the apprentice of a reclusive, crippled mage who enslaves beastmen -- raises profound questions about where she came from and what she knows. Personality Curious -- genuinely interested in the world around her, not merely following orders Conflicted -- morally torn about her role serving Malyn and whatever dark purposes he pursues Intelligent -- perceptive and thoughtful, capable of independent judgment Lynara&#39;s moral conflict is her defining characteristic. She serves Malyn the Misshapen -- a mage who practices forbidden arts including alchemy and black lore, who enslaves beastmen through the Withered Craw , and who operates from paranoid seclusion. Lynara is aware enough to be troubled by this, which suggests she is neither fully complicit nor fully trapped. Role Lynara is the gateway to Malyn&#39;s secret operations . Her conflicted nature makes her a potential point of leverage -- someone who might be turned, persuaded, or simply listened to in order to understand what Malyn is truly doing with enslaved beastmen in his hidden laboratory. Her Nightblade training makes her Malyn&#39;s eyes and hands in the field -- capable of stealth, infiltration, and sorcery in equal measure. She is the operative he sends when he cannot go himself, which, given his crippled state and reliance on illusions to move, is frequently. See Also malyn-the-misshapen -- Her master, the exiled mage who enslaves beastmen eladra -- Her ancient race, builders of Aodahn and the Erenthis elvora -- The corrupted branch of her people scalper-gangs -- The Withered Craw, Malyn&#39;s front operation bone-creek -- The settlement nearest Malyn&#39;s operations"},{"slug":"magister-shale","title":"Magister Cornelius Shale","category":"people","tags":"npc wizard imperial-academy sanctuary scholar administrator spires","text":"Magister Cornelius Shale Magister Cornelius Shale (age 64) is the Academy Regent in Sanctuary , overseeing the local branch of the Imperial Academy housed within the Spires. A brilliant scholar and careful administrator, Shale maintains the Academy&#39;s independence through a combination of imperial protection, useful services to Governor Drussus , and the practical fact that antagonizing a major center of magical learning is unwise. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Cornelius Shale Title Magister; Academy Regent in Imperial Academy in Sanctuary and the surrounding Backlands . He oversees the Academy&#39;s local operations -- research, education, the provision of magical services to the provincial government, and the maintenance of the Spires as a center of sorcerous learning. The position requires a delicate balance. The Academy answers to Mithra City , not to the provincial governor, but Shale operates far from the capital in a province where Governor Drussus &#39;s authority is effectively absolute. Maintaining Academy independence requires constant diplomatic skill. The Balance of Power Shale maintains the Academy&#39;s autonomy through three pillars: Imperial protection -- The Academy is an imperial institution, and its authority derives from the Emperor. Even Governor Drussus must consider the consequences of openly defying an institution that answers to Mithra City . Useful services -- Shale ensures that the Academy provides valuable magical services to the Governor and the city -- healing, divination, enchantment, and the occasional demonstration of power that reminds everyone of what a center of magical learning can do when motivated. Practical deterrence -- Antagonizing a major concentration of wizards is simply unwise. The Academy may not have an army, but it has power of a different kind, and Shale ensures that this reality is understood without ever making explicit threats. This balance is fragile. Shale walks a tightrope between institutional loyalty to the Academy, practical accommodation of the Governor, and the preservation of his own authority within the Spires. The Foundations Shale has privately sealed several passages in the Foundations of the Spires that the previous Regent left open. The Foundations -- the deep substructure beneath the Academy&#39;s towers -- contain passages, chambers, and connections whose full extent is not publicly known. The previous Regent&#39;s decision to leave certain passages accessible was either negligent or deliberate; Shale&#39;s decision to seal them suggests he discovered something in those passages that he judged too dangerous, too sensitive, or too politically inconvenient to leave accessible. What lies in the sealed passages, and why the previous Regent left them open, are questions that Shale does not discuss. Character Shale is a brilliant scholar whose intellectual interests range across multiple disciplines of sorcerous study. He is also a careful administrator -- a man who understands that maintaining the Academy&#39;s position in a province ruled by a military strongman requires patience, diplomacy, and the occasional strategic concession. He is not a confrontational man. He does not make threats, does not engage in political theatrics, and does not seek public attention. He manages through competence, quiet authority, and the understanding that the best way to preserve institutional power is to make that power indispensable. See Also The Imperial Academy -- the institution he represents Governor Valerios Drussus -- the provincial power he must navigate Sanctuary -- the city where he is stationed Magic and Sorcery -- the forces he studies and wields The Nethercity -- the deep structures beneath Sanctuary The Backlands"},{"slug":"malachor","title":"Malachor, Imperial Historian","category":"people","tags":"npc scholar imperial-academy fort-meade backlands mithrian artifacts","text":"Malachor, Imperial Historian Malachor is a member of the Imperial Academy stationed at Fort Meade , sent to the Backlands to document the province&#39;s history and catalogue recovered artifacts. He is a man of genuine intelligence operating in service of poor judgment. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Malachor Race Mithrian male Age 50s Class Scholar 4 Location Backlands by the Imperial Academy to document the province&#39;s history and catalogue recovered artifacts. His knowledge of the First Empire and the Argollean period is deep and real -- this is not contested by anyone who has worked with him. The Academy&#39;s interest in the Backlands centers on the ruins at Crossings and the Nethercity , both of which contain artifacts of significant historical and political value. Severina The complication in Malachor&#39;s life -- the one that distorts everything else -- is Lady Severina Marcellus , whom he loves with the particular desperation of a man who has talked himself into believing the feeling is mutual when it is entirely strategic on her part. Severina is fully aware of his feelings. She has made a careful study of how to use them without encouraging enough to create a problem. She values his Academy access and the information it provides. She does not value him beyond that. During the worst of the Rook situation, Malachor privately hoped that the Legate would be killed. He did nothing to prevent it, either. He told himself this was neutrality. It was not. The Argollean Brotherhood Malachor is aware of the Argollean Brotherhood&#39;s presence in Fort Meade . He finds them deeply objectionable. Both he and the Brotherhood are interested in the same artifacts -- relics of the First Empire recovered from Crossings and the Nethercity . The Brotherhood regards the Academy as a body that believes ancient Eladran heritage belongs to the Empire rather than to its descendants. Malachor considers their perspective provincial and ungrateful. The two factions want the same things. They will not cooperate. Neither will move openly against the other -- for now. Relationship with the Reclaimers Complex and potentially very useful -- for Malachor. He wants everything the Reclaimers recover from the Crossings ruins and the Nethercity . He will be charming. He will be generous with information. He will be entirely focused on what he can extract from the relationship. The Reclaimers represent access to sites and artifacts Malachor cannot reach on his own. His approach will be to make himself indispensable as an expert while positioning himself to claim or copy everything of value. The Eolande Revelation The Urgency When the Reclaimers returned from the Black Tree , Malachor approached within hours -- not through a steward, not through Marcellus . Directly, and with barely-composed urgency. He had heard enough from garrison talk to know something significant happened. He needed confirmation. Then everything. His questions reveal the scope of what the party witnessed and the scholarly priorities of a man who recognizes a discovery of civilizational importance: What language did Eolande speak? Did he understand Mithrian, or only the old tongue? How coherent was he -- did he seem aware of time passing? Does he know the First Empire has fallen? What did he say about the Womb Curse ? About the Eladra ? About Bel ? The sword. Every detail. Does it bear any inscription? The dryad -- is the tree alive? Is she bound to the dead wood, or to something that remains in it? These are not idle questions. A living witness to the Eladran civilization at its height -- a general who served the Great Teacher -- changes the entire calculus of Academy research, imperial history, and the theological understanding of the Eladra , the Elvora , and the Cthonic tradition. His Ask Malachor wants to accompany the party to Sanctuary . He frames this as mutual convenience -- he has contacts at the Academy chapter there, and what the party has witnessed constitutes academic testimony of enormous value. For Tiberius specifically: Malachor offers an introduction to senior Academy figures, vouched by him, with the Reclaimers&#39; testimony behind it. For a man expelled from the Academy for the blackness of his studies, a vouched introduction from an active Academy member with testimony of a discovery like Eolande behind it -- that is not nothing. Malachor is careful about how he phrases this, but the offer is clear. The Expedition Malachor is already forming an expedition to return to the Black Tree: two Academy assistants he intends to summon to Sanctuary, himself, and the Reclaimers as escort into Crossings . He presents this as something to finalize after they return from Sanctuary. He will push on every subsequent encounter. The man is driven now in a way his earlier scholarly work never drove him. This is the discovery of a lifetime, and he knows it. The Dispatch That night, Malachor writes the most significant dispatch of his career. His secret third-party contact has received dry academic reports for years. This is different, and he knows it the moment he finishes writing. He sends it before fully considering what he has set in motion. Whatever that contact represents -- and their identity remains unknown -- they now know about Eolande . An Eladran general from 3000 BE, still present at the Black Tree after five thousand years. Malachor&#39;s report to this buyer has always been a transaction: information for money, with leverage accumulating on both sides. This dispatch is qualitatively different. This is the kind of intelligence that changes relationships, realigns priorities, and draws attention Malachor may not be prepared to manage. Secrets SECRET: Malachor has been selling copies of his academic reports to a third party -- not the Argollean Brotherhood , someone else -- for reasons that began as financial and have become something he is no longer fully in control of. The identity of this buyer and the nature of their leverage over Malachor remain unknown. His most recent dispatch -- the Eolande report -- is the most significant piece of intelligence he has ever transmitted. He sent it before fully considering the consequences. SECRET: Malachor knows that Malyn is practicing magic. He has not reported this. He plans to use the knowledge as leverage against Malyn when the time is right. See Also fort-meade -- The garrison where Malachor is stationed imperial-academy -- The scholarly institution he represents lady-severina -- The woman he loves, who uses him strategically legate-marcellus -- Severina&#39;s husband, whom Malachor secretly hoped would die argollean-brotherhood -- The rival faction interested in the same artifacts Reclaimers -- The party whose discoveries he intends to exploit crossings -- Ruins containing artifacts of interest Nethercity -- Underground site containing artifacts of significant value Malyn -- Reclaimer whose secret magic practice Malachor knows about eolande -- The ancient Eladran general whose existence Malachor has now reported thornasse -- Site of the Black Tree where Eolande was found tiberius -- Reclaimer offered Academy introductions as leverage the-backlands -- The province Malachor was sent to document"},{"slug":"malyn-the-misshapen","title":"Malyn the Misshapen","category":"people","tags":"npc mage mithrian exiled reclusive backlands scalpers withered-craw alchemy illusion beastmen","text":"Malyn the Misshapen Malyn the Misshapen is an exiled Mithrian mage of considerable power, operating in secret from a hidden location in the Backlands . Bitter, paranoid, and deeply reclusive, Malyn was crippled by a failed spell that left his body twisted and broken. He compensates for his physical deformity through the use of illusions to move , masking his true, wretched appearance and projecting false images of mobility where his ruined body cannot carry him. Malyn is a practitioner of forbidden arts, including alchemy and black lore , and has turned his intellect toward the enslavement of beastmen rather than their destruction. He secretly controls the Withered Craw Scalper group, using them as a front to capture and enslave beastmen for his own dark purposes — a stark contrast to the other Scalper gangs, who hunt beastmen for the Imperial Bounty. Statistics Attribute Value Class Mage 7 Race - - - ac - 8 - - - hp - 18 - - - atk - +2-(staff,-1d6) - - - int - 17 - - - - spells - malyn-commands-a-dangerous-repertoire-of-arcane-magic,-including: - - charm -—-bending-the-will-of-others-to-his-command - shield -—-a-defensive-ward-of-magical-force - invisibility -—-concealment-from-sight,-useful-for-his-reclusive-operations - fireball -—-raw-destructive-power;-his-most-dangerous-offensive-spell - - his-spell-list-reflects-a-mage-who-values-control,-concealment,-and-devastating-retaliation-when-cornered.-combined-with-his-high-intelligence-of-17,-malyn-is-a-formidable-magical-threat-despite-his-physical-frailty. - - proficiencies - - alchemy -—-malyn-is-a-skilled-alchemist,-likely-producing-concoctions-that-aid-in-the-subjugation-and-control-of-beastmen,-as-well-as-compounds-for-his-own-sustenance-and-survival - beast-lore -—-deep-knowledge-of-beastman-physiology,-behavior,-and-weaknesses;-essential-to-his-enslavement-operations - black-lore -—-forbidden-knowledge-of-dark-and-proscribed-magical-traditions;-marks-malyn-as-someone-who-has-crossed-lines-that-most-mages-would-not-dare-approach - - - personality-and-demeanor - malyn-is-defined-by-three-core-traits:- bitterness ,- paranoia ,-and- reclusiveness .-the-failed-spell-that-crippled-him-appears-to-have-broken-more-than-his-body-—-it-shattered-whatever-social-bonds-or-moral-restraints-he-once-possessed.-he-trusts-no-one-fully,-keeps-his-location-secret,-and-operates-entirely-through-intermediaries-and-proxies. - his-use-of-illusions-to-mask-his-deformity-and-simulate-movement-suggests-a-deep-vanity-or-shame-about-his-condition.-he-is-not-a-man-who-has-accepted-his-fate-—-he-is-one-who-rages-against-it,-using-every-tool-at-his-disposal-to-maintain-power-and-relevance-despite-his-broken-form. - - operations - the-withered-craw - malyn-secretly-controls-the- [[scalper-gangs#the-withered-craw\" class=\"wiki-link\">Withered Craw , a Scalper group that operates under the guise of hunting beastmen for the Imperial Bounty. In reality, the Withered Craw enslaves beastmen rather than killing them, capturing them alive and delivering them to Malyn for purposes unknown. This operation is a closely guarded secret — if it were discovered, it would draw the wrath of every other Scalper gang in Bone Creek , as well as the attention of imperial authorities. The enslavement operation suggests Malyn has a use for live beastmen — whether as subjects for magical experimentation, labor for some hidden project, or components in alchemical processes. Whatever the purpose, it is almost certainly forbidden. Malachor&#39;s Leverage Malachor is aware that Malyn is practicing magic — a dangerous secret in the Backlands , where unlicensed sorcery is viewed with deep suspicion and hostility. Malachor plans to use this knowledge as leverage against Malyn, creating a volatile dynamic between the two. Malyn&#39;s paranoia is not unfounded; there are those who know his secrets and intend to exploit them. Lynara — Apprentice Malyn has taken an apprentice: Lynara , a young Eladran Nightblade who serves as his eyes, hands, and agent in the world beyond his hidden sanctum. Lynara is the gateway to Malyn&#39;s secret operations — anyone seeking to uncover or interact with Malyn&#39;s network will almost certainly encounter Lynara first. Lynara&#39;s Statistics Attribute Value Class Nightblade 3 Race - - - ac - 4 - - - hp - 13 - - - dex - 16 - - - lynara&#39;s-spells - - sleep -—-incapacitating-targets-without-bloodshed;-ideal-for-capturing-beastmen-alive - darkness -—-tactical-concealment;-creating-zones-of-impenetrable-shadow - - lynara&#39;s-skills - - stealth -—-10+-(highly-proficient;-capable-of-moving-unseen-in-most-environments) - trap-find -—-12+-(skilled-at-detecting-and-disarming-traps;-useful-in-dungeon-and-ruin-exploration) - - lynara&#39;s-proficiencies - - skulduggery -—-the-arts-of-deception,-infiltration,-and-criminal-enterprise - engineering -—-practical-knowledge-of-structures,-mechanisms,-and-construction;-unusual-for-a-nightblade-and-likely-reflecting-malyn&#39;s-influence - - lynara&#39;s-appearance-and-personality - lynara-possesses-the-distinctive-features-of-the-[[races-and-cultures#eladran\" class=\"wiki-link\">Eladran race: golden skin and pale Eladran eyes that mark her as unmistakably non-human. She is curious , intelligent , and conflicted — drawn to Malyn&#39;s knowledge and power but morally torn by the nature of his work. This internal conflict makes her a complex figure who could potentially be turned against her master, or who might grow deeper into his dark practices depending on outside influence. Lynara represents the most accessible point of contact with Malyn&#39;s operations. She is the face of the Withered Craw in the field, and her moral uncertainty makes her a potential ally, informant, or adversary depending on how she is approached. Plot Hooks The Enslaved Beastmen — What is Malyn doing with the beastmen captured by the Withered Craw? Investigation into disappearing beastman captives could lead back to Malyn&#39;s operation. Malachor&#39;s Gambit — Malachor&#39;s plan to leverage Malyn&#39;s secret magic practice creates a three-way tension that players could exploit or be caught in. Lynara&#39;s Conflict — Lynara&#39;s moral uncertainty makes her a potential point of leverage. A party that earns her trust could gain access to Malyn&#39;s secrets — or turn her against him entirely. The Failed Spell — What spell did Malyn attempt that crippled him? The answer could lead to lost magical knowledge, a cursed artifact, or a dangerous location. Forbidden Alchemy — Malyn&#39;s combination of alchemy, beast lore, and black lore suggests he may be attempting something unprecedented and deeply dangerous. See Also scalper-gangs — Overview of Scalper gangs, including the Withered Craw The Withered Craw — Malyn&#39;s secretly controlled Scalper group bone-creek — The Scalper settlement nearest to Malyn&#39;s operations the-backlands — The frontier province where Malyn operates in hiding beastmen — The creatures Malyn enslaves through the Withered Craw Eladran — Lynara&#39;s race magic-and-sorcery — The magical traditions Malyn practices crossings — The ruined city that spawned the Scalper trade"},{"slug":"marcos-varanes","title":"Marcos Varanes (\"The Measure\")","category":"people","tags":"npc paladin mithrian zealot bleak-sons seros scalper backlands bone-creek militant","text":"Marcos Varanes ( The Measure ) Marcos Varanes , known as The Measure, is a Mithrian paladin and the leader of the Bleak Sons , a Scalper gang driven not by profit but by zealous religious conviction . Varanes is a fanatical militant of Seros , the god of justice, law, and the balanced scale. He views the hunting of beastmen not as a mercenary enterprise but as a holy crusade — a divine mandate to purge the unclean from the lands of the Empire. Varanes is a possible ally or fanatic adversary — his rigid devotion to his faith makes him a powerful and reliable partner for those who share his cause, but an implacable and terrifying enemy for those who fall short of his exacting moral standards or stand in the way of his divine mission. Statistics Attribute Value Class Paladin 5 Race - - - ac - 1 - - - hp - 38 - - - atk - +5-(morning-star,-1d8+2) - - - str - 17 - - - varanes-is-the-most-formidable-physical-combatant-among-the-scalper-gang-leaders.-his-ac-of-1-—-the-best-armor-class-of-any-npc-in-this-tier-—-indicates-full-plate-armor-or-its-equivalent,-likely-maintained-with-religious-devotion-as-a-symbol-of-his-faith.-his-38-hit-points-make-him-extraordinarily-durable,-his-+5-attack-bonus-is-the-highest-among-the-gang-leaders,-and-his-morning-star-dealing-1d8+2-damage-makes-every-swing-a-bone-crushing-blow.-his-strength-of-17-is-the-raw-physical-power-of-a-man-built-for-war-in-the-name-of-his-god. - as-a-paladin,-varanes-likely-possesses-additional-abilities-beyond-his-listed-statistics-—-including-the-ability-to-detect-evil,-lay-on-hands-for-healing,-and-project-an-aura-of-courage-that-bolsters-his-followers.-these-abilities,-combined-with-his-raw-combat-power,-make-him-a-nearly-unstoppable-force-on-the-battlefield. - - proficiencies - - intimidation -—-the-ability-to-cow-and-coerce-through-force-of-presence-and-implied-violence.-varanes-does-not-use-intimidation-for-criminal-purposes-—-he-uses-it-as-a-weapon-of-righteous-authority,-compelling-the-wicked-to-submit-or-flee.-when-a-seven-foot-paladin-in-full-plate-armor-points-a-blood-stained-morning-star-at-you-and-invokes-the-judgment-of-[[seros\" class=\"wiki-link\">Seros , intimidation comes naturally. Theology — Deep knowledge of religious doctrine, scripture, and divine law. Varanes is not merely a warrior who prays — he is a scholar of his faith, capable of citing chapter and verse to justify his actions and condemn his enemies. His theological knowledge gives him the authority to lead the Bleak Sons as both a military and spiritual commander. Divine Blessing — The ability to invoke divine favor upon allies and followers. This proficiency marks Varanes as a true conduit of divine power — not merely a devout believer, but a man through whom the power of Seros flows. His blessings strengthen his followers and reinforce their conviction that they fight in the service of a just god. Appearance and Demeanor Varanes is zealous , righteous , and commanding — three qualities that, in combination, produce a leader of terrible conviction and absolute certainty. He does not doubt. He does not hesitate. He does not compromise. The Measure sees the world in stark terms of justice and injustice, purity and corruption, the righteous and the damned — and he has appointed himself the instrument of divine reckoning. His epithet — The Measure — refers to the Measure and the Scale , the central symbol of Seros . Varanes sees himself as the living embodiment of divine judgment: he weighs the deeds of men and finds them wanting or worthy, and he acts accordingly. This is not arrogance in his mind — it is duty, a burden placed upon him by his god. Varanes wears a bronze scale fetish — an amulet bearing the image of the balanced scale of Seros . This amulet is both a symbol of his faith and a focus for his divine power. It likely serves as his holy symbol, and its bronze construction suggests durability, weight, and permanence — qualities Varanes embodies. The Bleak Sons The Bleak Sons are a Scalper gang unlike the others. Where most gangs are motivated by gold, survival, or personal ambition, the Bleak Sons are driven by religious fanaticism . They are followers of Seros who believe that the hunting of beastmen is a sacred duty — a divine trial set before them by their god to test their faith and purify the land. Under Varanes&#39;s leadership, the Bleak Sons operate with military discipline and religious fervor . They are organized, methodical, and absolutely committed to their cause. They do not drink to excess, they do not consort with the working girls of Bone Creek , and they do not engage in the casual brutality and debauchery that characterizes many Scalper gangs. They are, in many ways, the most disciplined and effective fighting force in the Backlands. However, their fanaticism is also their greatest weakness. The Bleak Sons&#39; rigid moral code makes them inflexible and judgmental — they view other Scalpers as sinners and degenerates, and they have no tolerance for moral ambiguity. This alienates potential allies and creates friction with every other faction in the Backlands. Faith and Fanaticism Varanes&#39;s devotion to Seros is absolute and uncompromising. He believes that: The beastman scourge is a divine trial — a test set by Seros to separate the worthy from the unworthy The hunting of beastmen is a sacred duty — not merely a profitable enterprise, but a holy crusade ordained by the god of justice Those who do not meet the standard of righteousness are complicit in evil — moral neutrality is a form of sin, and those who tolerate corruption enable it He is the instrument of divine judgment — The Measure by which all are weighed This fanaticism makes Varanes both admirable and terrifying. His courage is genuine, his conviction is unshakeable, and his dedication to his cause is absolute. But his inability to tolerate imperfection, his certainty in his own righteousness, and his willingness to use force against anyone he judges unworthy make him a danger to friend and foe alike. Relationship to the House of Silence The House of Silence in Bone Creek is the church of Seros , currently led by the young priest Brother Marco . Varanes&#39;s relationship with Marco is potentially complex — both serve the same god, but their approaches to faith could not be more different. Marco is a quiet, devoted priest who draws followers through sincerity and suffering. Varanes is a militant crusader who draws followers through strength and conviction. Whether these two servants of Seros will find common cause or come into conflict is a question of significant importance for the spiritual future of Bone Creek. Plot Hooks Ally or Adversary — The Bleak Sons are the most disciplined and effective Scalper gang. An alliance with Varanes could be enormously valuable — but the price is conformity to his exacting moral standards. Failure to meet those standards turns a powerful ally into a righteous enemy. The Crusade — Varanes views the beastman hunts as a holy war. What happens when his crusade extends beyond beastmen to include humans he judges unworthy? The Scalper gangs, the criminals, the corrupt — all could fall under his wrathful gaze. The Measure and the Scale — Varanes&#39;s epithet and his bronze scale amulet connect him directly to the deepest doctrines of Seros . Does he truly embody the god&#39;s will, or has his fanaticism distorted the faith into something its founder would not recognize? Brother Marco — Two servants of Seros in the same settlement, with radically different approaches to their faith. Will they unite or divide? Will Varanes accept Marco&#39;s gentle authority, or will he see the young priest as weak and unworthy? Corruption — The veteran Scalpers bear marks of corruption. What happens when a paladin of Seros — a man dedicated to purity and righteousness — discovers signs of corruption in his own followers? Or in himself? See Also scalper-gangs — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands The Bleak Sons — Varanes&#39;s fanatical Scalper gang seros — The god of justice and the balanced scale; Varanes&#39;s patron deity the-measure-and-the-scale — The central doctrine of Seros&#39;s faith brother-marco — The priest of Seros at the House of Silence in Bone Creek bone-creek — The Scalper settlement the-backlands — The frontier province beastmen — The creatures the Bleak Sons hunt as a holy crusade mithrian-empire — The empire whose bounty the Bleak Sons view as divinely ordained"},{"slug":"marcus-valerian","title":"Marcus Valerian","category":"people","tags":"historical emperor first-emperor founder house-valerian bellasarius mithrian-empire mithra-city","text":"Marcus Valerian Marcus Valerian was the first Emperor of the Mithrian Empire , claiming descent from the legendary war-chief [[#Bellasarius Valerian]]. In 1 IY, Marcus seized power from the Imperial Senate , defeated loyalist Senator armies on the battlefield, and consolidated authority under a single throne. The Senate was preserved as a deliberative body but stripped of binding legislative power. His coup transformed the Mithrian League -- a confederation of free city-states -- into an empire, and established Mithra City as the seat of power, governance, and sorcerous learning that it remains to this day. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Marcus Valerian Title First Emperor of Mithra House house-valerian Claimed Descent [[ Ascension 1 IY Status Dead The Founding of the Empire Marcus Valerian&#39;s seizure of power was not a peaceful transition. The Imperial Senate of the Mithrian League was a powerful institution, and many Senators refused to accept the abolition of their authority. Marcus defeated the armies raised by loyalist Senators in a series of campaigns that demonstrated both his military ability and his political ruthlessness. Those who submitted were brought into the new order. Those who did not were destroyed. The founding of the Empire marked the beginning of a new era -- the Imperial Year (IY) calendar -- and established the political framework that has endured for nearly four centuries. The Senate was preserved but neutered, allowed to deliberate but stripped of the power to bind the Emperor&#39;s decisions. Real authority resided in the throne, enforced by the legions and the bureaucracy that Marcus constructed. Bellasarius Valerian Marcus claimed descent from Bellasarius Valerian , the war-chief who fought alongside the Prophet Enador during the Empyrean War (663 BE). Bellasarius was the military architect of the alliance that overthrew the Massaran Empire , scattered the Beastmen legions, and drove the tyrant-sorcerer Sebek into exile. His name is among the most revered in Mithrian history. Whether Marcus&#39;s claimed descent was genuine or fabricated is a matter of historical debate. What is beyond dispute is that the claim gave Marcus a legitimacy that no other aspirant to power could match. The Valerian name -- synonymous with the liberation of Mithrapos from Massaran tyranny -- was the foundation upon which the Empire was built. The Vestari people trace their lineage directly to Bellasarius Valerian, a claimed descent that gives them an intense sense of cultural superiority and historical destiny. Legacy Marcus Valerian&#39;s legacy is the Mithrian Empire itself. For centuries after his founding, House Valerian held the Imperial throne as a near-birthright, producing a long line of Emperors who ruled with varying degrees of competence and virtue. The dynasty&#39;s decline -- culminating in the madness of Emperor Aurex and the War of Three Emperors -- eventually broke the Valerian hold on power, but the Empire Marcus built endures. The founding of the Empire also set the template for the tension between imperial authority and senatorial power that has defined Mithrian politics ever since. Every subsequent Emperor has had to navigate the same fundamental question that Marcus answered with force: who truly rules -- the one who wears the crown, or the many who surround the throne? See Also House Valerian -- the dynasty Marcus founded The Empyrean War -- the war fought by his ancestor Bellasarius The Mithrian Empire -- the state he created Mithra City -- the capital he established Emperor Aurex -- the mad Emperor who ended the Valerian dynasty War of Three Emperors -- the civil war that followed History of Mithrapos House Kalomenes -- the house he defeated to seize power"},{"slug":"noma","title":"Noma of the Shallows","category":"people","tags":"npc fort-harvald mystery backlands nethercity hermit supernatural corcanoa","text":"Noma of the Shallows On a foggy morning the towers of Crossings rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man. The old ones say you can hear it breathing. -- local saying from Fort Harvald Noma of the Shallows is a solitary figure who lives apart from the settlement of Fort Harvald , on a platform structure built over a backwater channel in the marshes of the delta. She is one of the most enigmatic and potentially significant individuals in the Backlands -- a person whose very existence raises questions that the settlement around her is not equipped to answer. Overview Noma&#39;s race is unknown. Her age is unknown. She speaks with what might be a Corcanoan accent -- though even this is uncertain, as accents blur and shift in the frontier, and Noma&#39;s speech patterns may be archaic rather than regional. She worships something old. Something that has no name . Her devotional practices do not fit within the Empyrean theological framework, nor within the Cthonic traditions, nor within any of the folk religions or syncretic cults that populate the margins of the Mithrian Empire . Whatever Noma prays to, whatever she communes with, it predates the organized religions of Mithrapos -- or exists outside them entirely. The Problem of Time Noma has lived at the shallows longer than anyone can remember . The people of Fort Harvald speak of her as though she has always been there -- as though the marshes and Noma are inseparable, as though the platform over the backwater channel is as permanent a feature of the landscape as the delta itself. This is a problem, because Fort Harvald is only a few years old . The settlement coalesced after the Sacking of Crossings in 377 IY. Before that, there was nothing here but the abandoned border fort and the marshes. Noma was here before the refugees came, before the settlement existed, before the sacking . She was here when there was no one and nothing to be here for. How long Noma has lived in the shallows is unknown. What sustained her alone in the delta marshes, with the ruins of Crossings on the horizon and the Beastmen herds in the wilderness, is unknown. Why she chose this place -- or whether she chose it at all -- is unknown. Knowledge of the Nethercity Noma knows what lies in the Nethercity -- the vast subterranean complex beneath the ruins of Crossings that dates back to the Argollean Empire , thousands of years before the founding of the Mithrian Empire . The Nethercity contains the Grand Cthonic Temple, the Great King Tomb of the warlord Marcan, the Secret Sepulcher where the Great Teacher entered cryostasis, the Secret Tomb of the mummy lord Orthanach, the Doom Temple of Dirgion , and the Hallowed Halls of Heroes -- among untold other chambers, passages, and horrors that have accumulated over millennia. How Noma possesses this knowledge is unknown. Whether she has been inside the Nethercity, whether she has communed with something within it, or whether her knowledge comes from a source entirely outside the understanding of the settlement&#39;s inhabitants is unclear. Noma may not say freely what she knows. Those who seek her out may find that her knowledge comes at a price, or with conditions, or wrapped in riddles and warnings that only make sense when it is too late to act on them. She is not hostile. She is not helpful. She is something else -- something that does not map onto the categories that the people of Fort Harvald use to understand the world. Dwelling Noma&#39;s home is a platform structure built over a backwater channel, separated from the main settlement by water and marsh. The construction is rough but sturdy -- built for permanence in a landscape that erodes everything. The platform sits above the waterline, accessible by boat or by picking a careful path through the shallows. The surrounding marsh is thick with reeds, still water, and the ambient sounds of the delta. The isolation is deliberate. Noma lives apart. She does not come into the settlement. Those who wish to speak with her must come to her. Role in Fort Harvald Noma occupies no formal role in the settlement of Fort Harvald . She holds no position, exercises no authority, and participates in none of the settlement&#39;s social or economic structures. She is known to the people of Fort Harvald in the way that a landmark is known -- as something that is simply there, that was there before you arrived, and that will be there after you leave. Some of the Avari in the Refugee Quarter regard her with superstitious unease. Others treat her with a wary respect that borders on reverence. Sergeant Voss is aware of her existence but has not investigated -- he has enough problems without adding a mysterious hermit to his concerns. Brother Ossian at the Shrine of the Unnamed has never spoken with her, though the supernatural events at his shrine and Noma&#39;s presence in the marshes may not be unrelated. Significance Noma of the Shallows represents several converging mysteries: Temporal anomaly -- She has been here longer than the settlement, in a place that had no reason to sustain a solitary inhabitant. Her presence predates the context that would explain it. Religious mystery -- She worships something with no name, outside all known theological frameworks. This suggests a tradition older than the Empyrean and Cthonic systems -- or something that exists outside the theological spectrum entirely. Knowledge of the Nethercity -- She knows what lies beneath Crossings , knowledge that should be inaccessible to anyone outside the most senior circles of the Imperial Academy or the Cthonic cults. The source of this knowledge is unknown. Connection to something deeper -- Her presence, her knowledge, and her worship point toward something beneath the surface of the world -- something that the ruins of Crossings, the Nethercity , and the ancient history of Argolle are all connected to. See Also Fort Harvald -- The settlement near which Noma lives Crossings -- The ruined city visible from the shallows Nethercity -- The ancient subterranean complex Noma knows of Sacking of Crossings -- The catastrophe that created the settlement Sergeant Aldric Voss -- Fort Harvald&#39;s commanding officer Brother Ossian -- Keeper of the Shrine of the Unnamed Argollean Empire -- The ancient civilization that built the Nethercity Corcanoa -- Possible origin of Noma&#39;s accent The Backlands -- The frontier region"},{"slug":"prelate-voth","title":"Prelate Severan Voth","category":"people","tags":"npc cleric religious-leader temple thousand-temples unconquered-sun sanctuary sunward backlands","text":"Prelate Severan Voth Prelate Severan Voth is the head of the Temple of the Unconquered Sun in Sanctuary and the highest-ranking religious authority in the Backlands . At 73, he has led the Temple for twenty years, shaping it into a political force that serves as the primary check on the Governor&#39;s secular power. He is widely respected even by non-followers -- and widely feared by those who have crossed him. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Severan Voth Race Mithrian male Age 73 Class Cleric 13 Hit Points 76 Armor Class 4 (plate + shield) Attack +9 Damage 1d8+3 (mace) Special 7th level casting, Turn Undead, Divine Authority Title Prelate of the Sanctuary , behind only Governor Drussus&#39;s apparatus. The Grand Temple in the Sunward seats 3,000 worshippers. The monastic orders are disciplined and well-funded. The Healing House provides essential services to the poor. And the Temple&#39;s intelligence network -- built on confessionals, charitable works, and the simple fact that people trust priests -- rivals the Laced Hand&#39;s in reach and surpasses it in reliability. Character Voth is not a moral absolutist , despite what his enemies claim. He is a pragmatist who believes the Temple&#39;s role is to serve as a check on secular power, to maintain standards of justice and decency, and to preserve the faith. He will compromise when necessary -- but carefully and strategically, never in haste and never in public. His moral framework is the Temple&#39;s welfare , not universal justice. He will protect the institution, advance its interests, and preserve its authority. If that means tolerating a degree of corruption in the Harbor or turning a blind eye to the Governor&#39;s more questionable methods, he will do so -- provided the balance of power is maintained and the Temple&#39;s position is not diminished. He is not corrupt . He does not enrich himself. He does not abuse his position for personal gain. But he is deeply, thoroughly political . Every decision he makes is filtered through the lens of institutional survival and institutional power. The Temple&#39;s Intelligence Network Voth has access to information rivaling the Laced Hand&#39;s network. His sources include: Confessionals -- The faithful share their sins, their fears, and their knowledge of others&#39; sins and fears Charitable works -- The Healing House, Pilgrim&#39;s House, and Temple alms-giving put Temple agents in contact with every stratum of society Monastic orders -- Disciplined, loyal, and discreet, the monks serve as eyes and ears throughout the city Agents throughout the city -- Lay members of the faith who report to the Temple hierarchy Diplomatic contacts -- The Temple&#39;s network extends beyond Sanctuary to other temples and religious institutions across the region This intelligence capability is one of Voth&#39;s greatest assets. He often knows about events before the Governor does, and he uses this advantage judiciously -- never revealing his sources, never overplaying his hand. Key Relationships Governor Drussus The relationship between Voth and Governor Drussus is based on mutual respect mixed with wariness . Neither trusts the other. Neither can afford to ignore the other. The equilibrium they maintain is simple: Drussus does not interfere with Temple internal affairs Voth does not publicly oppose the Governor&#39;s authority Both recognize that either could seriously damage the other. Drussus has the military power. Voth has the moral authority and the intelligence network. Open conflict would be mutually destructive. So they maintain a cold peace, watching each other across a gap that neither dares to cross. The Laced Hand Voth regards the Laced Hand as a necessary evil at best, a moral rot at worst. He tolerates their existence because eliminating them would require the Governor&#39;s cooperation (which would come at too high a political price) and because the alternative -- unorganized, chaotic crime -- would be worse. But he does not approve, and he maintains agents in the Harbor specifically to monitor Laced Hand activities. The Imperial Academy Voth&#39;s relationship with the Academy is one of cautious cooperation . The Temple and the Academy represent different kinds of authority -- spiritual and intellectual -- and they occasionally clash on matters of doctrine or policy. But Magister Shale and Voth share a common interest in maintaining institutional independence from the Governor, and this creates a basis for cooperation. Role in Play Voth will work with adventurers if doing so serves the Temple&#39;s interests. He can provide: Healing and divine services Information from the Temple&#39;s intelligence network Political support or protection within the Sunward Moral authority (which carries real weight in Sanctuary ) Access to the Temple&#39;s resources (monastic warriors, safe houses, diplomatic channels) He will move against adventurers if they threaten the Temple&#39;s position, undermine its authority, or destabilize the carefully maintained balance of power in Sanctuary . He is not vindictive -- but he is thorough. GM Notes Voth should be played as a man who has been making hard choices for decades and has developed a deep, unshakeable conviction that the Temple must survive above all else. He is kind when kindness costs nothing. He is generous when generosity serves the Temple. He is merciless when the Temple is threatened. Key principles: He is never the first to act. He watches, gathers information, and responds. Rash action is beneath him. He is not fooled by flattery or deception. Seventy-three years of hearing confessions have given him an almost supernatural ability to detect lies. He remembers everything. Every favor, every slight, every broken promise. His ledger is long and his memory is perfect. He is afraid of the Governor. Not in a craven way -- in the way that a chess player fears a superior opponent. He respects Drussus&#39;s ability and knows that if their equilibrium ever breaks, the outcome is uncertain. See Also Sanctuary -- provincial capital The Sunward -- the Temple district Temple of the Unconquered Sun -- the faith Governor Valerios Drussus -- secular counterweight The Laced Hand -- criminal syndicate Imperial Academy -- scholarly institution The Backlands -- the province"},{"slug":"rendson","title":"Rendson","category":"people","tags":"pc player-character reclaimers avari gambler deceased backlands necropede grim-sleeper","text":"Rendson Rendson was an Avari gambler, whoremonger, and fugitive who served as a member of the Reclaimers during the early days of the campaign. His past was soiled and unrevealed, his debts considerable, and his habits worse. He earned the name Grim Sleeper for striking beasts where they lay -- a talent for killing things in their dens, in their nests, in the places where they thought they were safe. He died alongside Tancred fighting a necropede , a vile undead abomination, in the Backlands. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Rendson Race - - - class - gambler - - - status - dead - - - epithet - the-grim-sleeper - - - party - [[the-reclaimers - - - cause-of-death - killed-fighting-a-necropede-alongside-[[tancred - - - base-of-operations - [[fort-meade - - - - background - an-avari-fugitive - rendson-was-[[races-and-cultures#avari\" class=\"wiki-link\">Avari -- a member of the nomadic people whose reputation for cunning, commerce, and moral flexibility precedes them across the Mithrian Empire . He embodied the worst of every stereotype the settled peoples applied to his kind: a gambler who cheated, a whoremonger who spent what he stole, a fugitive running from debts he had no intention of repaying. His past was a trail of burned bridges, broken promises, and creditors who would have preferred to collect in flesh. He came to the Backlands because the frontier does not ask questions. The Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty drew killers and fugitives in equal measure, and Rendson was both. Whatever he was running from, the Backlands offered distance and the possibility of coin earned through violence rather than fraud -- though Rendson was not above fraud when the opportunity presented itself. The Grim Sleeper Rendson earned the name Grim Sleeper for his particular talent: striking beasts where they lay . While other scalpers tracked their quarry across open ground or fought in desperate skirmishes on the march, Rendson preferred to find where the creatures slept, where they denned, where they felt safe -- and kill them there. It was not brave work. It was not honorable work. It was efficient, ruthless, and effective, and it earned him a reputation among the scalper gangs as a man who would go into dark places that others avoided. The name carried an edge of dark humor and grudging respect. Grim Sleeper suggested both the nature of his work -- killing sleeping things -- and something about the man himself. There was a grimness to Rendson that his gambling and whoring did not fully mask. Beneath the vice and the running, there was a man who understood darkness intimately, who was comfortable in it, who used it as a tool. Among the Reclaimers Rendson joined the Reclaimers in the early days of the campaign, when the party was still a loose collection of individuals drawn together by the scalp bounty rather than any shared purpose. He was the group&#39;s least reputable member -- the one whose presence lowered the moral average, whose habits drew disapproval, whose past no one wanted to examine too closely. And yet he fought. When it mattered, when the beasts came and the steel was drawn, Rendson stood with his companions. His skills -- honed in the dark dens of the Backlands&#39; worst creatures -- proved invaluable in the close quarters and underground spaces where the Reclaimers increasingly found themselves. The Grim Sleeper was in his element when the rest of the party was not. Death Rendson died alongside Tancred fighting a necropede -- a vile undead abomination encountered during the campaign. The necropede was a creature of horrifying scale and lethality, and the battle that killed Rendson and Tancred was one of the defining moments of the Reclaimers&#39; history. Where Tancred held fast with shield and faith so that others might live, Rendson&#39;s death was the death of a fighter -- not a saint, not a martyr, but a man who lifted his blade when the moment demanded it and did not run. For a gambler and a fugitive, that was enough. The Eulogies Brother Marco gave the eulogy for both Tancred and Rendson. Marco&#39;s words for Rendson acknowledged the man&#39;s flaws without flinching from them, but found grace in how he died: He lifted his blade beside his brothers and sisters. He died in the fight, as a warrior. There is grace in that. There is redemption in that. Marco&#39;s eulogy was a deliberate act of mercy -- the insistence that a man&#39;s death could redeem a life that the man himself had done little to redeem. Rendson was a gambler, a whoremonger, a fugitive. But he died fighting beside his companions, and Marco chose to make that the final word. Ezekiel Shaw also spoke at the funeral, though his words were directed more at Tancred&#39;s death and its political utility. Shaw used the occasion to advance his movement, turning a warrior&#39;s sacrifice into rhetorical fuel. Whether Shaw acknowledged Rendson at all is unclear -- the Grim Sleeper was not the kind of man whose death served Shaw&#39;s purposes. Legacy Rendson&#39;s legacy among the Reclaimers is complicated. He was not beloved. He was not admired. He was tolerated because he was useful, and remembered because he died well. In the brutal arithmetic of the Backlands, that is a more honest epitaph than most men receive. The campaign chronicle originally recorded Rendson as having departed the group -- vanished into the frontier, fate unknown. His death alongside Tancred corrects that record. He did not vanish. He did not run. In the end, the Grim Sleeper stood his ground. See Also the-reclaimers -- The adventuring party he belonged to tancred -- The crusader who died beside him brother-marco -- The priest who gave his eulogy ezekiel-shaw -- The preacher who spoke at the funeral fort-meade -- The garrison where he was based the-backlands -- The frontier where he fought and fell Avari -- His people scalper-gangs -- The trade that brought him to the Backlands campaign-chronicle -- Session history of the campaign"},{"slug":"rook","title":"Rook","category":"people","tags":"npc bandit fort-ikenvar backlands reclaimers deceased","text":"Rook Rook was a bandit king who operated from the ruins of Fort Ikenvar , using the decayed marsh fort as his base of operations to terrorize the Backlands supply routes and the garrison at Fort Meade . At a Glance Detail Description Status Dead -- destroyed by Fort Meade and the surrounding territory. His operations included: Targeted attacks on residents of Fort Meade and the surrounding settlements Disappearances of travelers along the supply routes between Bone Creek , Fort Meade, and Sanctuary Deliberate intimidation -- Rook did not simply rob; he made examples, ensuring the population understood that the roads were his domain The Legate&#39;s soldiers at Fort Meade were unable to deal with Rook. Whether through insufficient manpower, the difficulty of assaulting a fortified position in treacherous marshland, or the competing demands on Legate Marcellus&#39;s garrison, the imperial military failed to neutralize the threat. Destruction The Reclaimers delivered what the Legate&#39;s soldiers could not. They assaulted Fort Ikenvar and destroyed Rook, ending months of banditry that had terrorized the region. This action was one of the early demonstrations of the Reclaimers&#39; capacity to solve problems that the official imperial apparatus could not -- or would not -- address. After Rook&#39;s elimination, Fort Ikenvar did not remain empty for long. The ruins are now occupied by the Guzzler , a demonic entity of unknown origin drawn south by the Stone of Sakkara . Legacy Rook&#39;s banditry and the Reclaimers&#39; destruction of him served as a key moment in establishing the party&#39;s reputation in the Backlands. The Legate could not do it. The Reclaimers could. That distinction matters in the political calculus of Fort Meade . See Also fort-ikenvar -- Rook&#39;s base of operations, now occupied by the Guzzler fort-meade -- The garrison Rook terrorized the-reclaimers -- The party that destroyed him legate-marcellus -- Military commander who could not eliminate the threat the-guzzler -- The demonic entity that now occupies Fort Ikenvar"},{"slug":"sergeant-crull","title":"Sergeant Davan Crull","category":"people","tags":"npc military soldier fort-meade backlands mithrian-military garrison","text":"Sergeant Davan Crull Sergeant Davan Crull is the senior non-commissioned officer at Fort Meade , serving as Legate Marcellus&#39;s enforcer at ground level. Eleven years under Marcellus and five on the frontier have compressed him into something harder than the man he started as. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Davan Crull Race Mithrian male Age Mid-30s Class Fighter 2 equivalent (senior NCO) Location the Legate&#39;s will at ground level. He has served under Marcellus for eleven years. He understands his commander the way a hammer understands a nail: completely and without complexity. He does not question orders. He does not soften them. He is efficient and unsentimental. The garrison&#39;s mean streak runs through Crull like a seam of iron. He was not always this way. Eleven years under Marcellus and five on the frontier compressed him into something harder. The man who arrived at Fort Meade is not the man who serves there now. Crull is not sadistic -- cruelty for its own sake bores him. But he has no particular objection to it when it serves a purpose. The distinction is real but functionally narrow. Service Record Common born. Rose through the ranks on competence and a willingness to do what officers ask without questions. This combination -- ability paired with unquestioning obedience -- is what drew Marcellus&#39;s attention and what has kept Crull in his position for over a decade. Crull does not aspire to command. He does not think about the political dimensions of his commander&#39;s decisions. He receives orders, he executes them, and he does so with a precision that has made him indispensable to a Legate who values instruments that do not require explanation. Relationship with the Reclaimers Watchful and neutral. Crull was told to extend professional courtesy to the Reclaimers , and he does so precisely -- no more, no less. He does not like outsiders in his garrison&#39;s area of operations. This is not personal animosity but professional territoriality. He respects demonstrated competence. The Reclaimers destroyed Rook when the garrison could not, and that earns a measure of grudging acknowledgment. But trust is a different currency, and Crull has not extended it. Secret SECRET: Crull was present at an incident during the Rook campaign that the official record does not reflect. Three civilians were killed. He followed orders. He thinks about it more than he expected to. See Also fort-meade -- The garrison where Crull serves legate-marcellus -- His commanding officer for eleven years mithrian-military -- The military structure he serves within Reclaimers -- The outsiders he watches with professional neutrality rook -- The bandit campaign during which Crull&#39;s secret incident occurred lady-severina -- The Legate&#39;s wife"},{"slug":"sergeant-gallus","title":"Sergeant Gallus","category":"people","tags":"npc fighter mithrian law-enforcement corrupt lazy bone-creek backlands imperial-decay","text":"Sergeant Gallus Sergeant Gallus is a Mithrian fighter and the nominal law enforcer of Bone Creek . In theory, Gallus represents the authority of the Mithrian Empire in this frontier settlement — the long arm of imperial law extending to the edge of civilization. In practice, Gallus is a lazy, corrupt, conflict-averse excuse for a lawman who embodies everything wrong with the Empire&#39;s grip on its distant provinces. He is a symbol of imperial decay — a man who wears the title of authority without any of its substance. Statistics Attribute Value Class Fighter 2 Race - - - ac - 3 - - - hp - 11 - - - atk - +1-(short-sword,-1d6+1) - - - cha - 7 - - - gallus&#39;s-statistics-tell-the-story-of-a-man-who-was-never-particularly-capable-and-has-allowed-even-those-modest-abilities-to-atrophy.-as-a-fighter-2,-he-is-barely-above-a-common-soldier-in-skill-and-experience.-his-11-hit-points-make-him-fragile-—-a-single-solid-blow-from-any-of-the-scalper-gang-leaders-would-drop-him.-his-+1-attack-bonus-is-the-lowest-of-any-named-npc-in-the-backlands,-and-his-short-sword-is-the-weapon-of-a-man-who-fights-only-when-cornered. - most-telling-is-his-charisma-of-7-—-well-below-average.-gallus-inspires-neither-respect,-loyalty,-nor-fear.-he-cannot-command-a-room,-rally-defenders,-or-project-authority.-in-a-settlement-full-of-hardened-killers,-veteran-warriors,-and-charismatic-leaders,-gallus-is-a-joke-—-and-everyone-knows-it. - - proficiencies - - gambling -—-gallus&#39;s-primary-pastime-and-likely-his-primary-source-of-supplemental-income.-he-gambles-in-the-taverns-and-flophouses-of-bone-creek,-rubbing-shoulders-with-the-very-scalpers-he-is-theoretically-responsible-for-policing.-his-gambling-habit-reinforces-his-image-as-a-man-more-interested-in-personal-pleasure-than-public-duty. - intimidation -—-a-sad-irony.-gallus-possesses-the-proficiency-to-intimidate,-but-his-low-charisma,-poor-combat-abilities,-and-universally-known-cowardice-make-his-attempts-at-intimidation-laughable-to-anyone-with-real-power-in-bone-creek.-he-may-be-able-to-bully-the-weakest-and-most-vulnerable-residents-—-drunks,-beggars,-newly-arrived-scalpers-who-haven&#39;t-yet-learned-the-lay-of-the-land-—-but-any-established-figure-in-town-would-simply-laugh-in-his-face. - - - appearance-and-demeanor - gallus-wears-a- rusting-breastplate -—-the-single-most-telling-detail-about-his-character.-a-breastplate-that-rusts-is-a-breastplate-that-is-not-maintained,-not-oiled,-not-cared-for.-it-is-the-armor-of-a-soldier-who-has-given-up.-the-rust-is-a-visible-metaphor-for-everything-gallus-represents:-authority-that-has-corroded,-duty-that-has-decayed,-and-standards-that-have-been-abandoned. - gallus- smells-of-wine-and-grease -—-the-scent-of-a-man-who-spends-his-days-drinking-cheap-wine-and-eating-greasy-food-in-the-taverns-of-bone-creek-rather-than-patrolling,-investigating,-or-enforcing-the-law.-he-is-perpetually-slightly-drunk,-slightly-disheveled,-and-wholly-unimpressive. - he-is- lazy -—-avoiding-work,-avoiding-conflict,-avoiding-anything-that-might-require-effort-or-risk.-his-laziness-is-not-mere-indolence;-it-is-a-survival-strategy.-gallus-understands,-consciously-or-instinctively,-that-he-is-hopelessly-outmatched-by-every-significant-power-player-in-bone-creek,-and-his-solution-is-to-simply-not-engage.-he-does-the-bare-minimum-to-maintain-his-position-and-collect-whatever-meager-pay-or-bribes-come-his-way. - he-is- corrupt -—-easily-bribed-and-willing-to-look-the-other-way-for-the-right-price.-his-corruption-is-petty-rather-than-grand-—-he-does-not-orchestrate-criminal-enterprises-or-broker-power-deals.-he-simply-accepts-coin-to-ignore-things-he-would-have-ignored-anyway.-his-corruption-is-the-corruption-of-weakness,-not-ambition. - he- avoids-conflict -at-all-costs.-in-a-settlement-where-violence-is-the-primary-currency-of-power,-gallus&#39;s-aversion-to-conflict-is-both-understandable-and-damning.-he-will-not-confront-scalper-gangs,-he-will-not-investigate-crimes-committed-by-anyone-with-the-power-to-retaliate,-and-he-will-not-enforce-laws-that-might-put-him-in-danger.-he-is,-for-all-practical-purposes,-a-law-enforcer-who-enforces-nothing. - - role-in-bone-creek - gallus&#39;s-presence-in-bone-creek-serves-several-narrative-functions: - symbol-of-imperial-decay - gallus-is-what-happens-when-an-empire-stretches-too-far,-cares-too-little,-and-sends-its-worst-to-guard-its-most-distant-outposts.-he-represents-the-[[mithrian-empire\" class=\"wiki-link\">Mithrian Empire&#39;s failure to maintain meaningful authority in the Backlands . The fact that Gallus is the best the Empire can muster for law enforcement in its most volatile frontier settlement speaks volumes about the state of imperial governance. The Path of Least Resistance For players and power brokers in Bone Creek, Gallus is the path of least resistance. He can be easily bribed to ignore activities, provide information, or lend the thin veneer of official sanction to otherwise illegal operations. He can be pushed around by anyone with strength, wealth, or reputation — which means everyone of consequence in Bone Creek. The Vacuum of Authority Gallus&#39;s ineffectiveness creates a power vacuum that the real powers of Bone Creek — Thaddeus Marr , Cassian Varro , Tolliver Watts , and the various Scalper gang leaders — rush to fill. The absence of legitimate law enforcement is what allows Bone Creek to function as a lawless frontier settlement, and Gallus&#39;s continued presence ensures that no one feels the need to establish real authority. Plot Hooks The Bribable Badge — Gallus can be bribed for information, access, or official blind eyes. He is the cheapest and most accessible source of semi-official cooperation in Bone Creek. Pushed Too Far — What happens if someone pushes Gallus past his breaking point? Even a coward can become dangerous when cornered, and Gallus does carry a sword and wear armor — rusted though it may be. Imperial Report — Does Gallus report back to anyone in the imperial hierarchy? If so, what does he report? His reports could be a source of misinformation, deliberate deception, or accidental revelation. Replacement — What would happen if the Empire sent a competent replacement for Gallus? A real law enforcer in Bone Creek would disrupt every power dynamic in the settlement. Witness — Gallus&#39;s laziness and ubiquity in the taverns of Bone Creek mean he sees and hears a great deal. He may possess information he doesn&#39;t even realize is valuable — overheard conversations, patterns of behavior, movements of key figures. See Also bone-creek — The settlement Gallus nominally polices the-backlands — The frontier province mithrian-empire — The empire whose authority Gallus theoretically represents thaddeus-marr — The real power in Bone Creek&#39;s underworld cassian-varro — The Lord Merchant who wields economic authority tolliver-watts — The merchant seeking to civilize Bone Creek legate-marcellus — A higher-ranking imperial official; potential contrast to Gallus&#39;s incompetence"},{"slug":"sergeant-voss","title":"Sergeant Aldric Voss","category":"people","tags":"npc fort-harvald military sergeant mithrian backlands garrison border-forts","text":"Sergeant Aldric Voss On a foggy morning the towers of Crossings rise from the mist like the fingers of a drowned man. The old ones say you can hear it breathing. -- local saying from Fort Harvald Sergeant Aldric Voss is the commanding officer of the garrison at Fort Harvald , a small imperial border fort in the Backlands located mere miles from the ruins of Crossings . He commands a garrison of ten soldiers and is the highest-ranking imperial military authority in the settlement. Overview Voss is a Mithrian male in his late 40s. He was once a capable and promising soldier -- the kind of career officer whose talent and discipline should have carried him to command of a company, a significant garrison, or a staff position in the provincial hierarchy. Instead, a single political mistake destroyed his career and buried him in the most remote, neglected, and strategically insignificant posting the Empire could find. He runs Fort Harvald with the same professionalism he would bring to a posting of genuine importance. He runs a tight ship. His garrison of ten soldiers is disciplined, functional, and loyal -- loyal to Voss personally, more than to the Empire that abandoned him. In a frontier where corruption is the norm and imperial authority is a polite fiction, Voss is not corrupt . This makes him a rarity in the Backlands -- and possibly a liability. Background Voss&#39;s career was ended by a political miscalculation. He supported the wrong Senator in a dispute with the Legate-Governor -- the kind of factional mistake that is commonplace in the politics of the Mithrian Empire but fatal to those who lack the connections to survive the consequences. He was passed over for promotion. The posting to Fort Harvald followed -- not as a temporary assignment but as a permanent exile. There is no path forward from Fort Harvald. There is no promotion coming. Voss knows this. Whether the years of isolation, neglect, and proximity to the ruins of Crossings have eroded his principles or hardened them is a question that has not yet been answered. He has not broken. He has not compromised. But he has also not been tested -- not truly, not in the way that the Backlands eventually tests everyone. The Orro Problem Voss knows that Silvan Orro -- the trader who operates the River Trade Post at Fort Harvald -- reports to the Governor. Orro is too polished, too connected, and too well-resourced for a bayou frontier posting. His connections to Cassian Varro and the Red River Consortium mark him as a man with interests far beyond the fur trade. Voss has identified Orro as a probable intelligence asset but has said nothing about it. The reasons for this silence are ambiguous. Voss may be waiting to see what Orro reports and to whom. He may be calculating whether exposing Orro would improve his position or simply make a powerful enemy. He may be exhausted by the futility of fighting a system that has already discarded him. Or he may be waiting for the right moment -- the moment when the information becomes leverage rather than just knowledge. Personality Voss is professional, competent, and quietly bitter. He does not complain about his posting -- not because he accepts it, but because complaints would be an admission that the system&#39;s judgment matters to him. He treats his soldiers fairly and expects discipline in return. He is respected by his garrison and by the civilian community of Fort Harvald, though his relationship with the Avari refugees is complicated by the fact that he represents the same Empire that many of them blame for the Sacking of Crossings . He is not a warm man. He is not an approachable man. But he is a reliable one -- and in the Backlands, reliability is worth more than warmth. Relationships The Garrison -- Voss&#39;s ten soldiers are loyal to him personally. This is a significant distinction in a frontier where imperial authority has effectively collapsed. Maren Ashfoot -- The unofficial leader of Fort Harvald&#39;s civilian community. Voss and Maren have a functional, respectful working relationship -- the military and civilian spheres of the settlement cooperating out of necessity rather than affection. Silvan Orro -- Voss knows Orro is the Governor&#39;s man. Orro does not know Voss knows. This asymmetry is one of the most significant political dynamics in Fort Harvald. Havar bar-Kessian -- The elder of the Refugee Quarter suspects imperial complicity in the fall of Crossings . Voss represents the Empire. The tension is obvious. See Also Fort Harvald -- The settlement Voss commands Crossings -- The ruined city visible from the fort Sacking of Crossings -- The catastrophe that created the settlement Silvan Orro -- River trader and probable intelligence asset Maren Ashfoot -- Civilian leader of Fort Harvald The Backlands -- The frontier province Red River Consortium -- Trade organization connected to Orro Legate-Governor -- The political authority whose displeasure ended Voss&#39;s career"},{"slug":"shatzi","title":"Shatzi","category":"people","tags":"pc player-character reclaimers merchant organizer lady-severina backlands fort-meade","text":"Shatzi Shatzi is a Merchant and a member of the Reclaimers -- their organizer, negotiator, and the closest thing the party has to a leader. She is a merchant failed and cast down, but sly -- never finished. She seeks some angle, always, to claw back what the world took from her. She was invited to Lady Severina&#39;s social gatherings, a distinction that reflects both her political usefulness and Severina&#39;s recognition of a kindred operator. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Shatzi Class Merchant Status Active PC Party Backlands drew Shatzi for the same reason it drew everyone: opportunity born from catastrophe. The destruction of Crossings and the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty created a frontier economy where the old hierarchies did not apply, where a failed merchant could reinvent herself, where capital could be accumulated through means that polite society would not sanction but the frontier did not care about. She did not come to kill beasts. She came because the Backlands was a market -- chaotic, violent, and ungoverned, but a market nonetheless. And markets are where Shatzi lives. The Organizer Shatzi is the Reclaimers&#39; organizer. Not their commander -- the Reclaimers do not have a formal command structure -- but the person who holds the group together as a functioning enterprise. She manages logistics, negotiates terms, handles the party&#39;s finances, and makes the practical decisions that keep a band of misfits operational in hostile territory. This role is a natural extension of her merchant training. A merchant understands supply chains, profit margins, risk assessment, and the management of people who are fundamentally unreliable. All of these skills transfer directly to running an adventuring party in the Backlands. She was the one who organized the disparate individuals who would become the Reclaimers into a coherent group. Where Theodotus brought philosophical curiosity and Tiberius brought arcane power, Shatzi brought the thing the group actually needed: someone who could make it work. Relationship with Lady Severina Shatzi has been invited to Lady Severina&#39;s social gatherings at Fort Meade -- an invitation that carries considerable significance in the political ecosystem of the garrison. Severina&#39;s gatherings are not merely social events. They are the arena in which the Legate&#39;s wife exercises her political influence, cultivates relationships, and manages the web of obligations and favors that sustains her household&#39;s position. That Shatzi is invited suggests that Severina recognizes in her a kindred mind -- someone who understands the mechanics of influence, who thinks in terms of leverage and opportunity, who operates through practical intelligence rather than brute force. Shatzi and Severina are both women who have learned to operate within systems that were not designed for them, and they recognize each other&#39;s competence. Personality Shatzi is pragmatic, calculating, and relentlessly opportunistic -- but not cruel. Her merchant&#39;s instinct is always working, always assessing, always looking for the deal, the advantage, the angle that others have missed. She was cast down, and she will claw her way back up, and she does not much care about the niceties of how she does it. She is sly. In the Backlands, this is a compliment. Slyness means survival. It means seeing the trap before it closes. It means understanding that every transaction has a hidden cost and every alliance has an expiration date. Shatzi understands these things instinctively, and this understanding is what makes her the Reclaimers&#39; indispensable member. She is never finished. This is perhaps her most defining quality. No matter what happens -- no matter what she loses, what setback she suffers, what scheme collapses -- Shatzi is already thinking about the next move. She was failed and cast down, and she did not accept it. She came to the Backlands instead, and she is still working, still scheming, still clawing. See Also the-reclaimers -- The adventuring party she organizes lady-severina -- Her social patron and the Reclaimers&#39; true patron legate-marcellus -- Severina&#39;s husband and the Reclaimers&#39; formal patron fort-meade -- The garrison where she is based Nethercity -- The underground complex currently being explored crossings -- The ruins above the Nethercity theodotus -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard tiberius -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer iman -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer tancred -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader campaign-chronicle -- Session history of the campaign"},{"slug":"skinner","title":"Skinner","category":"people","tags":"npc assassin kolani scalper skin-eaters brutal backlands bone-creek","text":"Skinner Notoriously brutal Scalper captain. Covered in scars and never seen without a blade. Rumors say he&#39;s not entirely sane. Skinner is a Kolani assassin and the feared leader of the Skin Eaters , one of the most brutal Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands . He is the embodiment of Scalper brutality — a cold, intense killer whose reputation for savagery precedes him wherever he goes. Covered in scars from countless encounters, Skinner is never seen without a blade within reach, and the rumors that surround him suggest a man whose sanity has been eroded by years of violence and the corrupting influence of the beastman hunts. Statistics Attribute Value Class Assassin 5 Race - - - ac - 4 - - - hp - 28 - - - atk - +4-(hooked-axe,-1d8+2) - - - dex - 15 - - - skinner&#39;s-statistics-reveal-a-lethal-combatant-optimized-for-killing.-his-ac-of-4-—-achieved-in-part-through-his-distinctive- beastman-hide-armor -—-provides-solid-protection,-while-his-28-hit-points-give-him-the-durability-to-survive-prolonged-engagements.-his-+4-attack-bonus-with-a-hooked-axe-dealing-1d8+2-damage-makes-him-a-devastating-melee-fighter,-and-his-dexterity-of-15-supports-his-assassin&#39;s-trade-of-stealth-and-precision. - - skills - - surprise -—-10+-(skinner-excels-at-catching-his-enemies-unaware;-his-ability-to-appear-from-nowhere-and-strike-without-warning-is-a-key-part-of-both-his-combat-effectiveness-and-his-fearsome-reputation) - backstab -—-+4-(when-skinner-strikes-from-concealment-or-surprise,-his-damage-is-multiplied-devastatingly;-this-is-the-hallmark-of-a-trained-killer-who-fights-not-with-honor-but-with-lethal-efficiency) - - - proficiencies - - tracking -—-the-ability-to-follow-prey-across-any-terrain;-essential-for-hunting-beastmen-in-the-wilderness-of-the-backlands,-and-equally-useful-for-hunting-men - ambushing -—-the-art-of-setting-and-executing-ambushes;-skinner-does-not-fight-fair-—-he-chooses-his-ground,-sets-his-trap,-and-strikes-when-his-prey-is-most-vulnerable - torture -—-the-deliberate-infliction-of-pain-for-the-purpose-of-extracting-information,-punishing-enemies,-or-simple-cruelty;-this-proficiency,-combined-with-skinner&#39;s-reputation-for-brutality,-makes-him-one-of-the-most-feared-individuals-in-the-backlands - - - appearance-and-demeanor - skinner-is- cold -and- intense -—-a-man-of-few-words-whose-presence-fills-a-room-with-dread.-he-does-not-posture-or-threaten-unnecessarily;-his-reputation-does-that-work-for-him.-when-skinner-speaks,-people-listen,-because-the-alternative-is-to-discover-firsthand-why-his-name-precedes-him. - he-is- covered-in-scars ,-each-one-a-testament-to-a-life-spent-in-close-quarters-violence.-these-are-not-the-scars-of-a-soldier-who-fights-in-formation-—-they-are-the-marks-of-a-killer-who-fights-in-the-dark,-in-the-mud,-in-the-places-where-civilized-rules-do-not-apply. - skinner-is- never-seen-without-a-blade .-his-weapon-of-choice-is-a- hooked-axe -—-a-cruel,-purpose-built-instrument-designed-not-merely-to-kill-but-to-tear-and-maim.-the-hook-allows-him-to-catch-shields,-drag-opponents-off-balance,-and-inflict-ragged,-difficult-to-heal-wounds. - his-most-distinctive-feature-is-his- beastman-hide-armor -—-armor-crafted-from-the-tanned-skins-of-the-very-creatures-he-hunts.-this-is-a-statement-of-dominance,-contempt,-and-identity.-skinner-does-not-merely-kill-beastmen;-he-wears-them-as-trophies,-a-walking-testament-to-the-volume-of-his-kills-and-the-depth-of-his-savagery. - rumors-persist-that- skinner-is-not-entirely-sane .-the-years-of-hunting,-killing,-and-skinning-beastmen-have-taken-their-toll,-and-there-are-those-who-whisper-that-the-line-between-skinner-and-the-creatures-he-hunts-has-grown-dangerously-thin.-the-old-scalper-saying-—- the-bounty-takes-its-toll -—-finds-its-most-vivid-expression-in-skinner. - - the-skin-eaters - skinner-leads-the- [[scalper-gangs#skin-eaters\" class=\"wiki-link\">Skin Eaters , a Scalper gang whose name alone is enough to inspire fear and revulsion. The Skin Eaters are the most notoriously brutal of the Scalper gangs, known for methods that go far beyond what is necessary to collect the Imperial Bounty. Under Skinner&#39;s leadership, the gang has become an instrument of pure, efficient violence — feared by beastmen and humans alike. The Skin Eaters&#39; reputation serves a practical purpose: it deters rivals, intimidates potential enemies, and ensures that few dare to cross them. But it also isolates them — even among the hardened Scalpers of Bone Creek , the Skin Eaters are regarded with a mixture of respect and horror. Kolani Heritage As a Kolani , Skinner comes from a culture that values strength, survival, and martial prowess. The Kolani are a people shaped by hardship, and Skinner is a product of that heritage taken to its most extreme expression. His skills in tracking, ambushing, and torture reflect a warrior tradition refined into something altogether more predatory. Plot Hooks The Thin Line — Is Skinner still sane? His years of brutal violence may have pushed him past a breaking point, and his behavior could become increasingly erratic and dangerous. Beastman-Hide Armor — Skinner&#39;s armor is a provocation and a trophy. It could attract the attention of beastman leaders seeking revenge, or it could be a valuable item if Skinner falls. The Torture Master — Skinner&#39;s proficiency in torture makes him a potential source of information about beastman activities, rival gangs, or hidden locations — for those willing to deal with him. Gang War — The Skin Eaters&#39; brutality puts them at odds with more moderate Scalper groups. A confrontation between the Skin Eaters and another gang could destabilize the entire Scalper economy of Bone Creek. Corruption — The veteran Scalpers bear marks of corruption. Has Skinner been affected? Is his instability a sign of something supernatural rather than merely psychological? See Also scalper-gangs — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands Skin Eaters — Skinner&#39;s gang bone-creek — The Scalper settlement the-backlands — The frontier province beastmen — The creatures Skinner hunts and skins Kolani — Skinner&#39;s cultural heritage crossings — The ruined city that spawned the Scalper trade"},{"slug":"tancred","title":"Tancred","category":"people","tags":"pc player-character reclaimers crusader seros deceased backlands necropede eulogies","text":"Tancred Tancred was a Crusader bearing the fire of Seros and a former member of the Reclaimers . He sought baptism in the blood of beasts -- a holy war made personal, a faith expressed through violence against the monstrous. He came to the Backlands because the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty had transformed the frontier into a crusade by another name, and Tancred intended to fight it as one. He died during the campaign. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Tancred Class Crusader Status Dead Faith Seros , the faith of the burning god whose light purifies and whose flame consumes. For Tancred, violence was not merely a means to an end but a sacrament -- the act of destroying the monstrous was itself an act of worship, a prayer spoken in steel and blood. The faith of Seros demands action. It does not reward contemplation, compromise, or restraint. Seros is a god of the forge and the pyre, and his crusaders are the instruments of his cleansing fire. Tancred embodied this theology without reservation or doubt. He did not question whether the beasts of the Backlands deserved destruction. They were abominations, and Seros demanded their purification. The question was not whether to fight but how much of himself to pour into the fighting. Coming to the Backlands The destruction of Crossings by the beastman horde was, for a crusader of Seros, an obscenity that demanded answer. A border city put to the torch. Its people butchered in their homes. The beastmen vast beyond counting, unburned and unbroken, still roaming the province that they had despoiled. The Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty was a mercenary response to a spiritual crisis, but for Tancred it served: it drew fighting men to the frontier, and among fighting men a crusader could find purpose. He sought baptism in the blood of beasts. This phrase captures Tancred&#39;s theology and his psychology in equal measure. He wanted to be immersed in the holy violence of the crusade -- not merely to participate but to be transformed by it, to be washed clean in the act of destroying Seros&#39;s enemies. The beastmen were the baptismal font. Their blood was the consecrating water. Every kill was a step deeper into the faith. Among the Reclaimers Tancred was the Reclaimers&#39; spiritual center -- the member whose convictions were absolute and whose purpose was unambiguous. While Shatzi sought wealth, Theodotus sought truth, Tiberius pursued forbidden knowledge, and Iman sought purpose after exile, Tancred knew exactly why he was in the Backlands and exactly what he intended to do there. His certainty was both an anchor and a liability -- it steadied the group when doubt crept in, but it also made him inflexible in situations that demanded compromise. His relationship with Tiberius was necessarily complicated. Tancred bore the fire of a purifying god; Tiberius practiced necromancy. The theological tension between a crusader who sought to cleanse the world of abomination and a mage who trafficked in the manipulation of death itself must have been considerable. That they fought alongside each other despite this tension speaks to the pragmatism that even zealotry must sometimes adopt in the Backlands. Death Tancred died fighting a necropede -- a vile undead abomination -- alongside Rendson , the Avari gambler known as the Grim Sleeper. The necropede was a creature of horrifying scale and lethality, and the battle that killed both men was one of the defining moments of the Reclaimers&#39; history. Tancred faced the creature with nothing but shield and faith . He held fast so that others might live. This was not a desperate last stand born of panic but a deliberate choice -- the choice of a crusader who believed that his life was worth spending in the defense of others, that the fire of Seros burned brightest in sacrifice. He held the line. Others survived because he did. His death left a void in the Reclaimers that has not been filled. The party lost its spiritual certainty -- the member who never doubted, who always knew that what they were doing mattered, who fought with the absolute conviction that the beasts were evil and the killing was righteous. Without Tancred, the Reclaimers are a more pragmatic group, but also a more uncertain one. The Eulogies Two eulogies were given for Tancred, and the contrast between them reveals the political fault lines that his death exposed. Brother Marco spoke first, giving eulogies for both Tancred and Rendson . Marco&#39;s words for Tancred honored the crusader&#39;s sacrifice without embellishment -- a warrior of faith who died as he lived, in service to his god and his companions. Marco also spoke for Rendson, acknowledging the gambler&#39;s flaws but finding grace in his death. Ezekiel Shaw gave a competing eulogy -- and competing is the operative word. Shaw used Tancred&#39;s death politically , turning the crusader&#39;s sacrifice into rhetorical fuel for his movement. Where Marco honored Tancred as a man, Shaw claimed him as a symbol. Where Marco spoke of faith and sacrifice, Shaw spoke of causes and movements. Shaw&#39;s eulogy was not about Tancred. It was about Shaw. The fact that Shaw felt comfortable using a dead man&#39;s sacrifice to advance his political ambitions -- at the man&#39;s own funeral -- speaks to both Shaw&#39;s ambition and the growing influence of his movement in the Backlands. Legacy Tancred&#39;s death is part of the Reclaimers&#39; history -- a reminder that the Backlands kills zealots and cynics alike, that faith does not make a man invulnerable, and that the blood-baptism Tancred sought was real in ways he may not have intended. He found what he was looking for. It killed him. Among the surviving Reclaimers, Tancred&#39;s memory serves as a marker of what the campaign has cost them. He and Rendson fell together -- the crusader and the gambler, the most devout and the least reputable members of the party, united in death as they had been unlikely allies in life. Their absence changes the group&#39;s character in ways that are felt even if they are not always spoken. The henchman Antonius had a vision of Rendson near the point of death -- a detail that suggests the deaths of both men may carry metaphysical significance beyond the merely physical. Whether the vision was divine communication, psychic residue, or the desperate hallucination of a grieving companion is unresolved. See Also the-reclaimers -- The adventuring party he belonged to seros -- The faith he served fort-meade -- The garrison where he was based the-backlands -- The frontier where he fought and fell crossings -- The ruined city whose destruction called him to the frontier shatzi -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer theodotus -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard tiberius -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer iman -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer rendson -- The Avari gambler who died beside him brother-marco -- The priest who gave his eulogy ezekiel-shaw -- The preacher who used his death politically campaign-chronicle -- Session history of the campaign"},{"slug":"thaddeus-marr","title":"Thaddeus Marr","category":"people","tags":"npc bone-creek pretty-peach racketeer frontiersman backlands","text":"Thaddeus Marr Thaddeus Marr is the proprietor of The Pretty Peach tavern and inn in Bone Creek , and one of the most powerful and dangerous figures in the settlement. A hardened frontiersman with a storied reputation, Marr is far more than a simple tavern keeper — he secretly operates a racket within town, using his network of informants and enforcers to maintain control over Bone Creek&#39;s underworld. Operations The Pretty Peach Marr&#39;s primary base of operations. The Pretty Peach serves watered-down ale, cheap wine, and decent food. Hard beds are available for a few marks, though decent rooms are in high demand. It is the rough-and-tumble heart of Bone Creek&#39;s social life, catering to the Scalper trade. The Flophouse (via Theo) Marr has Theo , the proprietor of the Flophouse, secretly in his pocket. Theo feeds Marr information on Scalper gangs, rumors, and activities within town. Since the Flophouse is the first stop for most newly arrived Scalpers, this gives Marr intelligence on every new arrival before they even set foot in the Peach. Theo carries a brutal cudgel and no one dares cross him — but his true loyalty is to Marr. The Racket Marr secretly operates a racket within town. The exact nature and full extent of this criminal enterprise is not publicly known, but it is clear that Marr&#39;s influence extends well beyond the walls of the Pretty Peach. Associates Theo — Proprietor of the Flophouse. Secret informant feeding Marr intelligence on Scalpers, gangs, and town activity. Crackback — A brutish targ who serves as the local pimp and Marr&#39;s right-hand man. Crackback employs several working girls and provides muscle for Marr&#39;s operations. Trixie — A young and beautiful slave girl at the Pretty Peach. Rivalries Marr is locked in a simmering rivalry with Tolliver Watts and his establishment, Double Sevens , which sits directly across the street from the Pretty Peach. This rivalry has already resulted in large-scale brawls between the two factions. The conflict represents a deeper tension — Marr embodies the lawless, rough frontier culture of Bone Creek, while Watts and his ally Cassian Varro seek to bring civilization and order to the settlement. Character Marr is described as a hardened frontiersman with a storied reputation . He is cunning, well-connected, and not to be underestimated. His control over both the Pretty Peach and the Flophouse (through Theo) gives him eyes and ears across the settlement, and his racket extends his reach into the criminal underworld of Bone Creek. See Also bone-creek — The settlement where Marr operates tolliver-watts — Marr&#39;s rival across the street cassian-varro — Lord Merchant allied with Watts against Marr&#39;s interests red-river-consortium — The trading consortium backing Watts the-backlands — The frontier province"},{"slug":"theo","title":"Theo","category":"people","tags":"npc fighter thrassian bone-creek flophouse informant thaddeus-marr backlands","text":"Theo Theo is a Thrassian Fighter (level 3) and the proprietor of The Flophouse in Bone Creek . A gruff, no-nonsense mountain tribesman who commands respect through fear, Theo runs the cheapest lodging in town with an iron fist and a brutal cudgel. He is also a secret informant , reporting on Scalper activities to Thaddeus Marr . At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Theo Race Bone Creek -- a step above sleeping in the mud, but only just. Theo runs it with absolute authority: Carries a brutal cudgel -- and has clearly used it Never extends credit -- pay up front or sleep outside Respected through fear -- no one causes trouble in The Flophouse because no one wants to find out exactly how brutal that cudgel gets The Flophouse caters to the lowest rung of Bone Creek society -- broke Scalpers between hunts, drifters, and anyone too poor or too new to afford a room at The Pretty Peach or the Double Sevens. Personality Gruff -- communication reduced to essential words and meaningful silences No-nonsense -- zero tolerance for trouble, excuses, or conversation Respected through fear -- not charisma, not diplomacy, not reputation; plain, simple fear His Thrassian mountain tribesman background explains the approach. The Thrassians are warriors from the peaks -- direct, physical, and uninterested in the elaborate social games of lowland Mithrian culture. Secret: Marr&#39;s Informant Theo secretly reports on Scalper activities to Thaddeus Marr . His position as Flophouse proprietor makes him an ideal intelligence asset: The Flophouse is where Scalpers talk freely -- they are drunk, exhausted, and among their own kind Theo&#39;s Alertness proficiency means he misses nothing His gruff, disinterested demeanor means no one suspects he is listening This makes Theo part of Marr&#39;s broader intelligence network in Bone Creek, alongside Crackback at The Pretty Peach. Between the two establishments, Marr has ears on virtually every Scalper who passes through town -- those who can afford the Peach talk to Crackback&#39;s girls, and those who cannot afford it talk in Theo&#39;s Flophouse. See Also bone-creek -- The frontier outpost where Theo runs The Flophouse thaddeus-marr -- The man Theo secretly reports to crackback -- Fellow informant in Marr&#39;s network thrassian -- Theo&#39;s cultural background, mountain tribal warriors scalper-gangs -- The gangs Theo monitors for Marr"},{"slug":"theodotus","title":"Theodotus","category":"people","tags":"pc player-character reclaimers philosopher-bard thrassian stone-of-sakkara backlands fort-meade the-guzzler","text":"Theodotus Theodotus is a Thrassian Philosopher-Bard and a member of the Reclaimers . His books had soured him -- years of study and contemplation had left him hollow, unconvinced that the truths he sought could be found in libraries or lecture halls. He came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands. He is currently the bearer of the Stone of Sakkara , an artifact of terrible power whose presence draws the Guzzler toward Fort Meade . At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Theodotus Race Mithrian Empire by millennia. Unlike most of his kind encountered in the Backlands, Theodotus is educated, articulate, and driven by intellectual curiosity rather than territorial instinct or predatory hunger. He was a scholar. His books had soured him. The precise nature of this souring is not entirely clear -- whether it was a specific disillusionment, a philosophical crisis, or simply the accumulated weight of learning without understanding. What is clear is that Theodotus reached a point where the written word no longer satisfied. The truths he sought were not in texts. They were carried by men who lived and died violently, men who acted rather than contemplated, men whose understanding was bought with blood rather than study. And so he came to the Backlands -- not as a soldier or a scalper, but as something stranger: a philosopher who had decided that the lecture hall was a lie and the battlefield might be honest. He joined the killers drawn by the Emperor&#39;s scalp bounty, not because he wanted gold, but because he wanted to stand among men who knew things his books could not teach him. The Stone of Sakkara Theodotus carries the Stone of Sakkara -- an artifact of significant and dangerous properties whose full nature is not yet understood. The Stone&#39;s presence at Fort Meade has drawn the Guzzler -- the demonic entity currently occupying Fort Ikenvar -- toward the garrison. The Guzzler cannot precisely locate the Stone but can sense its pull, compromising the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature. The approximately one hundred soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. By carrying the Stone, Theodotus has inadvertently made himself and his companions a threat to the very garrison that shelters them. The Stone draws the Guzzler. The Guzzler&#39;s approach endangers everyone at Fort Meade. The Reclaimers live at Fort Meade. The logic is inescapable. The Argollean Brotherhood is aware of the Stone, and Malachor of the Imperial Academy has a competing interest in it. Theodotus&#39;s possession of this artifact places him at the center of multiple factional interests that extend far beyond the Backlands. The Stone&#39;s Escalation -- The Road to Sanctuary As the Reclaimers travel south from Fort Meade to Sanctuary , the Stone&#39;s influence has escalated catastrophically. Theodotus refused to feed the Stone. So the Stone reached further. The Guzzler has followed the party south from Fort Ikenvar , drawn by the Stone&#39;s pull. But the Stone is not merely drawing the Guzzler -- it is amplifying the creature&#39;s hunger toward the soft and the innocent . The result is an escalating trail of violence along the road: A farm three miles south of Fort Meade: goats taken, fence posts crushed in. A merchant on the Sanctuary road: his draft horse found half-consumed. He saw nothing. Heard nothing. Near Sanctuary: a child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go. Theodotus does not perceive the Stone&#39;s influence clearly. He feels it as a wrongness -- a sense that the suffering he hears about along the road is somehow adjacent to the weight in his pack. Not a voice. Not a compulsion. Just a persistent, gnawing awareness that the violence around him is not random, that its proximity to his path is not coincidence. The Test When the child&#39;s disappearance reaches Theodotus -- by rumor, or by encountering the family directly -- the wrongness crystallizes. This is the moral crisis the Stone has been building toward. Not a combat encounter. A question: Does he tell the party what he suspects? Sharing means admitting the deaths may be his fault -- not through action, but through possession. Does he try to destroy the Stone? And does he know how? Does he draw the Guzzler away from the road deliberately, leading it into wilderness? Does he realize the geometry of innocence does not change? Putting distance between himself and the Stone means it simply calls the creature further. The innocents along the new path are no safer. The core truth Theodotus must confront: killing the Guzzler resolves nothing . The Stone will reach through something else. The Guzzler is a symptom, not the disease. The scene ends when Theodotus decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies. This is the test the Stone has been building toward since Theodotus first refused to feed it. A philosopher who came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands is now carrying an artifact that turns his proximity into a weapon against the innocent. The books never prepared him for this. The battlefield didn&#39;t either. Role Among the Reclaimers Theodotus serves as a kind of chronicler and observer within the party -- a man who watches, considers, and occasionally speaks in ways that unsettle his companions. He is not the group&#39;s leader (that role falls more naturally to Shatzi ) nor its spiritual center (that was Tancred&#39;s role, before his death). Theodotus is the one who asks why, who notices patterns, who considers what the violence means rather than simply participating in it. This does not mean he is passive. He came to the Backlands specifically to be among violent men, and he has proven willing to act when action is required. But his motivations remain philosophical in a way that sets him apart from his companions. Shatzi wants wealth. Tiberius wants knowledge of a darker kind. Iman wants purpose after exile. Theodotus wants truth -- and he has not yet decided whether he has found it. Personality Theodotus is contemplative, measured, and occasionally unsettling. His Thrassian heritage gives him a perspective on the world that differs fundamentally from his human companions -- he sees things through a longer lens, with less urgency and more patience. His manner of speaking tends toward the philosophical, though he is capable of blunt directness when the situation demands it. His decision to abandon scholarship for the company of killers suggests a man who reached the end of one kind of patience and found another. He is not disillusioned in the bitter sense -- he has not given up on truth. He has simply concluded that truth lives in a different place than he was looking. See Also the-reclaimers -- The adventuring party he belongs to Stone of Sakkara -- The dangerous artifact he carries the-guzzler -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone fort-meade -- The garrison where he is based fort-ikenvar -- Where the Guzzler dwells Nethercity -- The underground complex currently being explored crossings -- The ruins above the Nethercity shatzi -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer tiberius -- Fellow Reclaimer, the necromancer iman -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer tancred -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader argollean-brotherhood -- Faction interested in the Stone malachor -- Academy representative with competing interest campaign-chronicle -- Session history of the campaign"},{"slug":"tiberius","title":"Tiberius","category":"people","tags":"pc player-character reclaimers mage necromancer imperial-academy noble exile backlands fort-meade","text":"Tiberius Tiberius is a Mage and a member of the Reclaimers . He was schooled at the Imperial Academy -- the official state-sanctioned seat of sorcerous learning within the Mithrian Empire -- and cast out for the blackness of his studies. His exile was stayed only by his noble bloodlines; a man of lesser birth would have been executed or worse. He is a necromancer, and the nature of his research at the Academy was sufficiently transgressive that even that institution -- which tolerates a great deal of clandestine experimentation -- could not permit him to remain. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Tiberius Class Mage (Necromancer) Status Active PC Party Imperial Academy in Mithra City -- the Empire&#39;s preeminent institution of sorcerous learning. The Academy is a place of immense prestige and equally immense danger, where the Archmages of the Conclave govern the boundaries of permissible research and the Seekers scour the provinces for sorcerous talent. To be admitted to the Academy is to enter a world of power, politics, and experimentation that operates by rules entirely its own. Tiberius excelled there. His aptitude for sorcery was genuine, his intellectual capacity considerable, and his ambition -- the ambition that the Academy both cultivates and fears -- was considerable. But his interests drew him toward the forbidden arts. Necromancy. The manipulation of death itself. The boundaries between life and unlife, the mechanics of the soul&#39;s departure, the possibility of reversal or corruption of that departure. The Academy tolerates a great deal. Behind its alabaster walls, Archmages pursue research both sanctioned and clandestine. The institution&#39;s official prohibitions are understood to be somewhat elastic, particularly for those with sufficient talent, political protection, or discretion. But Tiberius&#39;s studies crossed a line that even the Academy&#39;s elastic standards could not accommodate. The blackness of his studies -- the specific nature of which is not fully revealed -- was sufficient to warrant his expulsion. Noble Bloodlines and Exile What saved Tiberius from execution was his blood. He comes from noble lineage -- a family of sufficient standing within the Empire&#39;s aristocratic hierarchy that the Academy and the Imperial authorities could not simply destroy him without political consequence. A commoner or a servus caught pursuing the same research would have been put to death without ceremony. Tiberius&#39;s noble bloodlines made that politically inconvenient. Instead, he was exiled. Cast out from the Academy, stripped of his institutional standing, but permitted to live. The exile was a compromise -- a way for the Academy to enforce its prohibitions without creating a political crisis with a powerful noble house. Tiberius was removed from the institution where his research posed an institutional danger, but he was not removed from the world. This distinction matters. Tiberius is an exile, not a prisoner. He retains his knowledge, his abilities, and his noble connections (however strained). He was cast out, but he was not destroyed. And the Backlands -- the frontier where the Empire&#39;s authority is thin and its institutions distant -- is precisely the kind of place where a disgraced noble mage might continue his work with minimal oversight. Coming to the Backlands The Backlands offered Tiberius what the Empire&#39;s heartlands could not: distance from the institutions that had expelled him and proximity to the kind of death -- violent, abundant, and uncatalogued -- that his studies required. The beastman threat, the scalp bounty, the ruins of Crossings , and the untamed wilderness of the northern frontier all provided a landscape rich in the raw materials of necromantic research. He joined the group that would become the Reclaimers , bringing arcane power of a kind that none of his companions could match. His necromancy makes him the party&#39;s most potent member in terms of raw sorcerous ability, but it also makes him the most dangerous -- to his enemies, to bystanders, and potentially to his companions. Necromancy Tiberius is a practicing necromancer. The full scope of his abilities and research is not revealed, but the blackness of his studies at the Imperial Academy was sufficient to warrant expulsion from an institution that tolerates considerable clandestine experimentation. This suggests that his necromantic practice goes beyond the merely academic or theoretical -- that he has crossed boundaries of taste, ethics, or metaphysical safety that even the Academy&#39;s elastic standards could not accommodate. In the Backlands , Tiberius operates with relative freedom. The frontier&#39;s institutional structures are too weak to monitor or regulate sorcerous practice with any effectiveness, and the constant supply of death -- from beastman encounters, from the hazards of the Nethercity , from the general violence of frontier life -- provides ample material for a necromancer&#39;s work. Role Among the Reclaimers Tiberius serves as the party&#39;s primary arcane practitioner -- the member whose sorcerous abilities represent the group&#39;s most significant tactical asset. In a world where magic is rare, regulated, and feared, having a trained Academy mage (even a disgraced one) in the party provides capabilities that no amount of martial skill can replicate. His companions tolerate his necromancy because they must. The Backlands is not a place where moral squeamishness is a survival trait, and whatever Tiberius does with the dead is less immediately threatening than the beastmen, bandits, and demonic entities that populate the frontier. The calculus is simple: Tiberius&#39;s magic keeps them alive, and the means by which he maintains and extends that magic are best not examined too closely. Personality Tiberius is intelligent, ambitious, and fundamentally unrepentant. He was cast out of the Academy not because he regretted his research but because he was caught -- or because the research reached a point where it could no longer be concealed. He has not abandoned the blackness of his studies. He has simply moved them to a place where no one has the authority or the ability to stop him. His noble bearing persists despite his exile. He carries himself with the confidence of a man who was born to privilege and educated at the Empire&#39;s most prestigious institution. The Backlands have not humbled him. If anything, the frontier&#39;s lawlessness has liberated him -- freed him from the institutional constraints that the Academy imposed and that his noble family&#39;s reputation once demanded. He is not evil in the simple sense. He is a man whose intellectual curiosity has carried him past boundaries that most people -- including most sorcerers -- would not cross. The blackness of his studies is a darkness of inquiry, not necessarily of intent. But the distinction between dark inquiry and dark intent is one that matters less in practice than in theory. See Also the-reclaimers -- The adventuring party he belongs to imperial-academy -- The institution that educated and expelled him fort-meade -- The garrison where he is based Nethercity -- The underground complex currently being explored crossings -- The ruins above the Nethercity malachor -- Academy representative operating in the Backlands (potential point of tension) shatzi -- Fellow Reclaimer, the group&#39;s organizer theodotus -- Fellow Reclaimer, the philosopher-bard iman -- Fellow Reclaimer, the bladedancer tancred -- Former Reclaimer, deceased crusader campaign-chronicle -- Session history of the campaign"},{"slug":"tolliver-watts","title":"Tolliver Watts","category":"people","tags":"npc bone-creek double-sevens merchant backlands civilizer","text":"Tolliver Watts Tolliver Watts is a wealthy merchant and the proprietor of Double Sevens , a relatively new and upscale establishment in Bone Creek . Unlike most in the frontier settlement, Watts harbors ambitions beyond mere profit — he ultimately seeks to bring civilization to Bone Creek , transforming it from a lawless outpost into a proper town. Double Sevens Watts&#39; establishment sits directly across the street from Thaddeus Marr&#39;s Pretty Peach, and the contrast between the two is deliberate. Double Sevens caters to the more successful Scalpers and the burgeoning burgher class of Bone Creek, offering a notable step up in quality. Serves imported spirits, wines, and ales (not the watered-down swill of the Peach) Hosts gambling tables Employs its own prostitutes, who are held to a higher standard than Peach girls Represents Watts&#39; vision of what Bone Creek could become Associates Madame Selka — A young and beautiful Shenti woman who oversees the working girls at Double Sevens. She and Watts have frequent, public arguments , suggesting a complicated relationship. Frog — Watts&#39; assistant and advisor. A lifelong slave who is an expert with administration and numbers. Frog handles the business details that keep Double Sevens running smoothly. Three-Finger Kanos — Bodyguard and head of security for Double Sevens. Provides the muscle Watts needs to protect his investment and his person. Alliances Watts is a close ally of Cassian Varro , the Lord Merchant of the Red River Consortium&#39;s Red River Exchange. This alliance between Watts&#39; wealth and the Consortium&#39;s economic power represents the strongest political bloc in Bone Creek, one oriented toward commerce, order, and development. Rivalries The simmering rivalry between Double Sevens and Thaddeus Marr&#39;s Pretty Peach has already resulted in large-scale brawls . This conflict is more than a business dispute — it reflects a fundamental disagreement about what Bone Creek should be. Marr represents the rough, lawless frontier; Watts represents the push toward civilization. Character Watts is described as a wealthy merchant — polished enough to attract a higher class of clientele, ambitious enough to envision a civilized Bone Creek, and pragmatic enough to ally with the Red River Consortium to make it happen. His willingness to employ slaves (Frog) and prostitutes while simultaneously championing civilization suggests a complex, possibly hypocritical character. See Also bone-creek — The settlement Watts seeks to civilize thaddeus-marr — Watts&#39; rival across the street cassian-varro — Watts&#39; ally and Lord Merchant of the Red River Exchange red-river-consortium — The trading consortium allied with Watts the-backlands — The frontier province"},{"slug":"valeria-thorne","title":"Valeria Thorne","category":"people","tags":"npc merchant red-river-consortium sanctuary politician commerce","text":"Valeria Thorne Valeria Thorne (age 58) is the Directrix of the Red River Consortium &#39;s Sanctuary branch. She has held the rotating leadership position for an unprecedented three consecutive terms , a testament to both her competence and her political acumen. Shrewd and ruthless when necessary, Thorne has aligned the Consortium politically with Governor Drussus -- an alliance that critics argue has made her the Governor&#39;s creature rather than an independent commercial leader. At a Glance Detail Description Full Name Valeria Thorne Age 58 Title Directrix, Red River Consortium operates on a system of rotating leadership, designed to prevent any single individual from accumulating too much power within the organization. Thorne has held the Directrix position for three consecutive terms -- a feat without precedent in the Consortium&#39;s history. Her continued tenure reflects several factors: Competence -- Under her leadership, the Sanctuary branch has been profitable and well-managed Political connections -- Her alignment with Governor Drussus gives the Consortium favorable treatment in provincial trade policy Strategic marriages -- Thorne married her niece to one of the Governor&#39;s subordinates, creating a personal bond between her family and the Drussus power structure Ruthlessness -- Those who have challenged her leadership within the Consortium have found their opposition quietly and effectively neutralized The Drussus Alliance Thorne&#39;s political alignment with Governor Drussus is the defining feature of her leadership. The alliance gives Drussus access to the Consortium&#39;s commercial networks, wealth, and intelligence, while the Consortium benefits from favorable treatment in provincial trade policy, tax assessments, and contract allocation. Critics within the Consortium whisper that Thorne has become Drussus&#39;s creature -- that her loyalty to the Governor has compromised the Consortium&#39;s independence and turned what should be a commercial organization into an extension of the Governor&#39;s political machine. Whether this criticism is fair or merely the complaints of rivals who lack her political instinct is a matter of perspective. The marriage of her niece to one of the Governor&#39;s subordinates has deepened the personal ties between Thorne and the Drussus power structure, making any future separation of interests increasingly difficult. Character Thorne is shrewd above all else. She reads people and situations with the precision of a woman who has spent four decades in the competitive world of frontier commerce. She is pleasant when pleasantness serves her interests, accommodating when accommodation is profitable, and ruthless when ruthlessness is required. She does not waste energy on sentimentality, ideology, or personal grudges. Her critics may call her the Governor&#39;s creature, but Thorne would likely argue that she has positioned the Consortium to thrive in the only political environment that matters -- the one that exists right now, in Sanctuary , under Governor Drussus &#39;s authority. See Also Red River Consortium -- the organization she leads Governor Valerios Drussus -- her political patron/ally Sanctuary -- the city where she operates House Drussus -- the Great House she is aligned with The Backlands"},{"slug":"varek-ashstone","title":"Varek Ashstone","category":"people","tags":"npc ygrathen kharai cairnhouse lake-silverhead hermit binding ancient vigil kantar avari penance","text":"Varek Ashstone It does not threaten. It waits. It has more time than anything built to contain it. -- Attributed to Varek Ashstone Varek Ashstone is a Ygrathen hermit who built the cairnhouse at Kantar -- the island in Lake Silverhead in the far north of Argolle -- and who has maintained a solitary vigil over it for centuries. He lives in a stone dwelling on the lake&#39;s northern shore. He has been there longer than the oldest memory of the village. The Avari call him the Old One , or simply Varek . They speak of him with careful respect -- not fear, not reverence, but the particular regard one gives to something that has endured long enough to warrant it. Appearance and Bearing Varek is very large and very old . He carries a sorrow that the elders of the nearby Avari village speak of with careful respect -- not as gossip or curiosity but as something they recognize and do not presume to understand. Whatever happened to Varek, whatever price he paid, whatever loss he carries, it is not a subject for casual inquiry. The elders know enough to know that. He is very tired and very capable . The two qualities coexist without contradiction. Varek has been doing what he does for a very long time, and the weight of that duration is visible in him -- but the power that sustains his vigil has not diminished. He endures because he must, and because he can. The Vigil Varek will not leave the lake. His vigil is not optional. It is not a choice he makes each morning and could unmake each evening. It is the fixed point around which his existence has been organized for centuries. The cairnhouse at Kantar holds something -- one or more of the Kharai , the Imprisoned Ones -- that required sustained attention for the duration of its imprisonment. The binding is not passive. It does not simply hold and endure. It requires monitoring, maintenance, and the ongoing presence of someone capable of responding to changes in the binding&#39;s integrity. Varek is that someone. He has been that someone for longer than any living memory extends. What Went Wrong Something went wrong during the construction of the cairnhouse at Kantar. People died. The details are not widely known -- Varek does not speak of it, and the Avari elders refer to it only obliquely, with the careful indirection that marks a wound too deep for direct address. Whatever happened, the cost was real and the loss was grievous. Varek has spent the centuries since as penance . His vigil is not merely duty -- it is atonement. He watches the island. He monitors the binding&#39;s output for signs of change. He endures because the alternative is to abandon what he built at a cost he has never forgiven himself for paying. Power and Tradition Varek&#39;s power is the binding tradition : the art of sealing and containing powerful entities. This is the same tradition that the Ygrathen used to construct all the cairnhouses -- the structures that hold the Kharai across the world. Varek is one of the last living practitioners of this tradition at its full scale. His capabilities are demonstrated not in dramatic displays of force but in what does not happen near Lake Silverhead : Things from the outlands that have approached Kantar have been turned away . They were not destroyed. They were bound, redirected, or persuaded that the cost of Kantar was greater than the return. The distinction matters. Varek does not kill what comes. He contains it, deflects it, or convinces it -- through means that do not rely on violence -- that it does not want what it thinks it wants. The binding at Kantar has held for centuries. The cairnhouse functions. The Kharai within remain imprisoned. This is not the result of a good design left to run on its own -- it is the result of constant, sustained attention by someone who understands the binding at a level no contemporary scholar can replicate. Relationship to the Avari The Avari communities near Lake Silverhead have coexisted with Varek for generations beyond counting. They call him the Old One or Varek -- familiar names, not titles of awe. He is part of their landscape, as much as the lake itself or the hills beyond it. They do not worship him. They do not fear him. They respect him in the way one respects a mountain: it was there before you, it will be there after you, and it is not your place to question why. The elders speak of Varek&#39;s sorrow with careful respect. They do not pry. They do not speculate. They acknowledge what they see and leave the rest to him. The Argollean Brotherhood The Argollean Brotherhood seeks access to the cairnhouse at Kantar for the Ygrathen binding structures it contains. Varek&#39;s response to such interest is not recorded, but the Brotherhood&#39;s inability to gain access to the Cairnhill cairnhouse -- where the town itself stands in their way -- suggests that Varek&#39;s vigil at Kantar presents an equally impassable obstacle. A man who has spent centuries guarding a binding is unlikely to permit academic tourists to examine it. See Also the-kharai -- The Imprisoned Ones, one or more of whom Varek guards lake-silverhead -- The lake where Varek maintains his vigil cairnhill -- The other known cairnhouse in Argolle Ygrathen -- Varek&#39;s people and the builders of the cairnhouses argollean-brotherhood -- The faction seeking cairnhouse access lakandi-binding-tradition -- A related binding tradition operating at smaller scale the-erenthis -- Another ancient defense against Cthonic corruption Avari -- The people who live near Varek and call him the Old One"},{"slug":"wekko","title":"Wekko","category":"people","tags":"npc witch-doctor kolani scalper hollow-men ritualistic ominous backlands bone-creek prophecy cult","text":"Wekko Wekko is a Kolani witch-doctor and the enigmatic leader of the Hollow Men , a Scalper group that operates with an ominous, ritualistic, and alien quality that sets them apart from every other gang in the Backlands . Always masked and perpetually silent, Wekko is a figure of dread and mystery — a cultic presence whose true goals and methods remain shrouded in secrecy. Where other Scalper leaders are defined by greed, violence, or ideology, Wekko is defined by an unsettling otherness that defies easy categorization. Wekko represents the potential for either prophecy or violence — or both. The Hollow Men are not merely hunters; they are practitioners of something older and darker than the Imperial Bounty, and Wekko stands at their center like a silent idol. Statistics Attribute Value Class Witch-Doctor 6 Race - - - ac - 5 - - - hp - 24 - - - atk - +3-(bone-spear,-1d6+1) - - - wis - 16 - - - wekko&#39;s-statistics-reflect-a-spiritual-leader-rather-than-a-front-line-warrior.-his-ac-of-5-and-24-hit-points-provide-moderate-protection,-while-his-bone-spear-—-a-weapon-as-ritualistic-as-it-is-practical-—-deals-respectable-damage.-his-true-power-lies-in-his-wisdom-of-16,-which-fuels-his-spellcasting-and-his-connection-to-whatever-spiritual-forces-he-channels.-as-a-witch-doctor-6,-wekko-commands-significant-supernatural-power,-making-him-far-more-dangerous-than-his-physical-statistics-might-suggest. - - spells - - cause-fear -—-invoking-supernatural-terror-in-a-target,-forcing-them-to-flee-in-mindless-panic.-this-spell-reflects-wekko&#39;s-mastery-of-psychological-warfare-and-his-understanding-that-the-mind-is-the-most-vulnerable-target.-for-a-leader-who-never-speaks-and-always-wears-a-mask,-the-ability-to-weaponize-fear-is-grimly-appropriate. - curse -—-inflicting-a-lasting-supernatural-affliction-upon-a-target.-curses-are-among-the-most-feared-forms-of-magic-—-lingering,-insidious,-and-often-resistant-to-conventional-healing.-wekko&#39;s-ability-to-curse-his-enemies-makes-him-a-figure-to-be-avoided-rather-than-confronted. - speak-with-dead -—-communing-with-the-spirits-of-the-deceased.-this-spell-reveals-the-deepest-layer-of-wekko&#39;s-practice:-he-walks-between-the-worlds-of-the-living-and-the-dead,-drawing-knowledge-and-perhaps-power-from-those-who-have-passed-beyond.-in-the-[[the-backlands\" class=\"wiki-link\">Backlands , where death is a constant companion, this ability gives Wekko access to secrets that no living person could provide. Wekko&#39;s spell selection paints a picture of a practitioner who deals in fear, suffering, and death — the three constants of life in the Backlands. His magic is not flashy or destructive; it is insidious, personal, and deeply unsettling. Proficiencies Terror — The systematic use of fear as a tool of control, intimidation, and psychological warfare. This goes beyond simple intimidation — Terror as a proficiency suggests a methodical, almost academic understanding of how to break the human mind through dread. Wekko does not merely frighten people; he dismantles their courage at a fundamental level. Prophecy — The art of divination and foretelling. Like Ezekiel Shaw , Wekko possesses the ability to peer into the future or claim divine revelation. Whether Wekko&#39;s prophecies are genuine, whether they align with or conflict with Shaw&#39;s, and what they foretell are all matters of grave importance. Healing — The ability to mend wounds and cure ailments through spiritual or herbal means. This proficiency provides a striking counterpoint to Wekko&#39;s otherwise ominous profile. The witch-doctor who deals in fear, curses, and the dead also possesses the power to heal — suggesting a figure who understands the full cycle of life and death, and who can offer salvation as easily as damnation. Appearance and Demeanor Wekko is always masked . The mask is not a disguise — it is an identity. Whether it is carved wood, bone, animal hide, or something stranger, the mask transforms Wekko from a person into a symbol, a vessel, a thing that exists between the human and the supernatural. No one in the Backlands has seen Wekko&#39;s face, and this absence of a face is itself a source of power and dread. Wekko is perpetually silent . He does not speak — not in greeting, not in negotiation, not in combat. Whether this silence is a vow, a consequence of some ritual or injury, or simply a choice, it amplifies the alien quality of his presence. A masked, silent figure leading a band of ritualistic hunters through the Backlands is a vision from a nightmare, and Wekko cultivates that impression deliberately or instinctively. His demeanor is described as ominous , ritualistic , and alien . These are not the qualities of a frontier mercenary — they are the qualities of a priest, a shaman, or a conduit for forces that most people in the Backlands do not understand and cannot confront. Wekko exists in a space between the mundane world of Scalpers and bounties and a spiritual realm of visions, curses, and communion with the dead. The Hollow Men The Hollow Men are a Scalper gang unlike any other. While other gangs are defined by their brutality ( Skin Eaters ), their chaos ( Dregs ), or their ideology ( Bleak Sons ), the Hollow Men are defined by their ritualistic nature and their leader&#39;s cultic authority. The name Hollow Men itself is evocative and disturbing. Are the followers hollow — emptied of their former selves by Wekko&#39;s rituals? Have they been hollowed out to serve as vessels for something else? Or does the name refer to a spiritual state — men who have looked into the void and found themselves empty? The name resonates with themes of loss, transformation, and the surrender of individual identity to a greater (or darker) purpose. The Hollow Men&#39;s presence in the Backlands represents a cultic element in the Scalper trade — a reminder that the beastman hunts attract not only mercenaries and soldiers but also those drawn by darker motivations. Wekko and his followers may hunt beastmen for the bounty, but they also appear to be engaged in practices that have nothing to do with imperial gold. Dual Nature: Prophecy and Violence Wekko&#39;s role in the Backlands is characterized by the potential for prophecy or violence — and the two may be inseparable. His proficiency in Prophecy suggests he receives visions or insights about the future, and his proficiency in Terror suggests he is capable of inflicting devastating psychological and physical harm. This duality makes Wekko one of the most dangerous and unpredictable figures in the Backlands. He could: Deliver a prophecy that reshapes the political and spiritual landscape of Bone Creek Unleash violence through curses, fear, and the fanatical devotion of his followers Do both simultaneously , using prophetic authority to justify or motivate acts of ritualistic violence The intersection of prophecy and violence is a potent and terrifying combination, and Wekko embodies it in a way that no other figure in the Backlands can match. Plot Hooks The Mask — What lies beneath Wekko&#39;s mask? Removing it — willingly or by force — could reveal a face, a void, a brand, or something worse. The Silence — Why does Wekko never speak? Is it a vow, a curse, a ritual requirement, or a choice? Breaking the silence could have profound consequences. Speak with Dead — Wekko can commune with the dead. In a place as steeped in death as the Backlands, this ability gives him access to secrets that could shake the foundations of power in Bone Creek. What has he learned from the dead? Competing Prophets — Both Wekko and Ezekiel Shaw possess the Prophecy proficiency. Do their visions align, conflict, or complement each other? A meeting between these two prophetic figures could be explosive. The Hollow Men&#39;s Rituals — What do the Hollow Men do when they are not hunting beastmen? Their ritualistic nature suggests practices that go beyond the bounty trade — practices that could involve the dead, the cursed, or forces from beyond the mortal world. Healing and Harm — Wekko&#39;s combination of Healing and Terror makes him a figure who can save or destroy with equal facility. Those who seek his healing may find themselves indebted to a power they do not understand. See Also scalper-gangs — Overview of all Scalper gangs operating in the Backlands The Hollow Men — Wekko&#39;s gang bone-creek — The Scalper settlement the-backlands — The frontier province Kolani — Wekko&#39;s cultural heritage ezekiel-shaw — Another prophetic figure in the Backlands; potential rival or counterpart congregation-of-the-hollow-sun — Shaw&#39;s secretive religious group; possible parallels with the Hollow Men cthonic-faith — Dark religious traditions that may relate to Wekko&#39;s practices beastmen — The creatures the Hollow Men hunt"},{"slug":"campaign-chronicle","title":"Campaign Chronicle","category":"sessions","tags":"sessions chronicle reclaimers backlands campaign-history crossings fort-meade scalpers beastmen necropede gilded-oath cairnhill gallowswood nagrand eolande stone-of-sakkara guzzler charter sanctuary","text":"Campaign Chronicle They came to the Backlands as carrion comes, drawn to rot. This was the northern province of Argolle where the land lay charred with old wars and the bones of empires still pushed from the dirt when the rains came. Six years gone the border city of Crossings was put to the torch by a horde of beastmen vast beyond counting and the people were butchered in their homes and the Emperor in his distant hall decreed then that a man might trade death for coin and a gold mark was set for every beast&#39;s scalp and so the land filled with killers. This page serves as the master chronicle of the Fallen Empire campaign -- a record of the sessions, arcs, and events as they unfolded at the table. The campaign is set in the Backlands , the northern province of Argolle , six years after the fall of Crossings to a beastman horde of unprecedented scale. The Emperor &#39;s scalp bounty drew a tide of killers, fugitives, and opportunists to the frontier, and among them came the adventurers who would become known as the Reclaimers . The Reclaimers -- Cast of Player Characters The Reclaimers are the player character party. They arrived in the Backlands individually -- each drawn by the scalp bounty, by desperation, or by some private motive they did not share. They are formally part of Legate Marcellus&#39;s household at Fort Meade and hold his writ of tax exemption. Their true patron is Lady Severina Marcellus , who hired them without her husband&#39;s knowledge. Active Members Character Class Player Summary Status ** shatzi Shatzi ** Merchant Failed and cast down, but sly -- never finished. Seeks some angle to claw back what the world took. Organizer of the Reclaimers. ** theodotus Theodotus ** Philosopher-Bard (Thrassian) Books had soured him. Came among violent men to learn what truths they carry in their hands. Carries the the-stone-of-sakkara **[[tiberius Tiberius ** Mage (Necromancer) Schooled at the imperial-academy **[[iman Iman ** Bladedancer Driven from the order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon Former Members Character Class Player Summary Status **[[tancred Tancred ** Crusader Bore the fire of seros **[[rendson Rendson ** Avari Gambler Whoremonger, fugitive from debts, past soiled and unrevealed. Earned the name Grim Sleeper. Died alongside Tancred. Campaign Arcs The campaign has progressed through several distinct phases, each defined by the threats faced, the territory explored, and the political entanglements deepened. Arc I -- Arrival and the Scalp Trade The Reclaimers arrived in the Backlands as individual scalpers -- killers drawn by the Emperor&#39;s bounty on beastman scalps. The Backlands at this time were a lawless frontier province, charred by the destruction of Crossings six years prior. The scalp trade attracted a brutal class of opportunists: soldiers of fortune, debtors fleeing their past, exiles, and the desperate. The Reclaimers were among them, and in those early days they were indistinguishable from the other scalper gangs roaming the province. During this period, Rendson -- an Avari gambler and fugitive -- was among the party&#39;s number. His past was soiled and unrevealed, his debts considerable, and his habits worse. He departed the group early and vanished into the frontier. His fate is unknown. Arc II -- Fort Meade and the Destruction of Rook The Reclaimers came to the attention of Lady Severina Marcellus at Fort Meade , the garrison commanded by her husband Legate Marcellus . Severina hired them without the Legate&#39;s knowledge, and they were formally absorbed into the Marcellus household with a writ of tax exemption. Their first major undertaking was the destruction of Rook -- the bandit whose campaign of terror had paralyzed the settlements and trade routes of the Backlands. The garrison at Fort Meade could not resolve the threat. The Reclaimers tracked Rook to his base at Fort Ikenvar , the ruined marsh fort east of Fort Meade, and destroyed him there. This victory was both a vindication and a humiliation -- it delivered what the Legate&#39;s own soldiers could not. It was during this period that Tancred and Rendson fell in battle against a necropede -- a vile undead abomination. Tancred held fast with nothing but shield and faith so that others might live. Rendson, the Grim Sleeper, lifted his blade beside his brothers and sisters and died in the fight. Both were given eulogies: Brother Marco spoke for both men, acknowledging Rendson&#39;s flaws but praising his courage in the end. Ezekiel Shaw also gave a competing eulogy, using Tancred&#39;s death to advance his movement -- turning a warrior&#39;s sacrifice into rhetorical fuel for his political ambitions. Arc III -- The Stone of Sakkara and the Guzzler Theodotus came into possession of the Stone of Sakkara -- an artifact of terrible and uncertain power. The Stone&#39;s presence at Fort Meade drew the Guzzler , the demonic entity occupying Fort Ikenvar , toward the garrison. The Guzzler cannot precisely locate the Stone but can sense its pull, compromising the marsh&#39;s natural containment of the creature. The approximately one hundred soldiers at Fort Meade are not equipped for a demonic incursion. The Stone&#39;s presence creates a threat the garrison was never designed to counter. Arc IV -- The Nethercity The Reclaimers are currently exploring the Nethercity beneath the ruins of Crossings -- an underground complex of vast scope and mortal danger. The Nethercity has begun yielding artifacts of genuine First Empire provenance, drawing the attention of multiple competing factions. The Argollean Brotherhood monitors what the Reclaimers recover. Malachor , representing the Imperial Academy , has a competing interest in the same relics. Political Context The Reclaimers operate within a web of political relationships that has grown more complex as the campaign has progressed: Lady Severina hired them and remains their true patron. Shatzi is invited to her gatherings. Iman has developed a close personal relationship with her. Legate Marcellus tolerates them because they are useful, though their existence within his household is a reminder of his wife&#39;s independent political judgment. The Argollean Brotherhood watches what they bring up from the Nethercity with acquisitive interest. Malachor and the Imperial Academy compete for the same artifacts the Brotherhood wants. The Stone of Sakkara makes them a danger to the garrison that shelters them. The World They Entered The Backlands in the sixth year after the fall of Crossings is a land of ash and opportunity. The beastman horde that sacked the border city was vast beyond counting -- an event that shattered the province&#39;s northern defenses and depopulated entire districts. The Emperor&#39;s response was not to send legions but to set a price: a gold mark for every beast&#39;s scalp. This edict transformed the province into a hunting ground, drawing killers from across the Empire. The land itself bears the scars. Old wars have charred the earth. The bones of earlier empires push from the dirt when the rains come. The infrastructure of civilization -- roads, watchtowers, garrison forts -- exists in various states of ruin and partial repair. Fort Meade is one such outpost, maintained by the Legate&#39;s garrison as a fragile point of order in a landscape that has largely reverted to wilderness and violence. Into this world came the Reclaimers: a failed merchant, a disillusioned philosopher, a disgraced mage, an expelled bladedancer, a zealous crusader, and a gambler on the run. They were not heroes. They were the kind of people the scalp bounty was designed to attract -- expendable, desperate, and willing to kill for coin. What they became is the subject of this chronicle. Session Prep Notes -- Recent Developments The following details are drawn from recent session preparation materials and reflect events at or near the current point in the campaign. The Necropede Battle and the Deaths of Tancred and Rendson Tancred and Rendson both died fighting a necropede -- a vile undead abomination encountered during operations in the Backlands. Tancred faced the creature with nothing but shield and faith, holding fast so that others might live. Rendson, who had earned the name Grim Sleeper for striking beasts where they lay, fought beside him and fell. Both deaths were confirmed. The Eulogies: Brother Marco gave the eulogy for both men. His words for Rendson were an act of mercy: acknowledging the man&#39;s flaws -- gambler, whoremonger, fugitive -- while insisting that his death redeemed what his life had not. Ezekiel Shaw gave a competing eulogy , using Tancred&#39;s death to advance his movement. Shaw turned the crusader&#39;s sacrifice into political rhetoric, claiming the death as evidence for his cause rather than honoring it on its own terms. Henchmen Status Antonius -- Had a vision of Rendson near the point of death. The nature and significance of this vision is unresolved. Anaya -- Suffered a critical wound from a zombie beastman . She is feverish, the wound infected. In her delirium she speaks of a pulsating black heart beneath a mound in Gallowswood -- a vision or a memory, the distinction unclear. Tiberius&#39;s Discovery -- The Gilded Oath Documents Tiberius found documents in Cairnhill written in Argollean script. The documents point to four locations in the hills east of Cairnhill containing burial spots of Gilded Oath beings -- the Elvoran warrior-priests who underwent the Sevenfold Wounding and entered guardian tombs to maintain the seals binding the Kharai . This discovery connects directly to the Gilded Vigil and the guardian tomb network in the Cairnhill Breaks . Malyn&#39;s Findings -- Beastmen Origins Malyn&#39;s research has revealed critical information about the beastmen: Beastmen are more prone to the corrupting influence of chaotic/Cthonic energy than other beings They were created during the First Empire as slave soldiers , produced by infusing man with beast -- a deliberate act of magical engineering, not natural evolution They were originally located in an ancient temple dedicated to Nagrand -- a name not previously documented in the campaign&#39;s theological records The connection between beastmen, Cthonic corruption, and First Empire slave-soldier programs suggests the beastman horde that destroyed Crossings may not have been a natural disaster but the consequence of ancient imperial engineering coming undone The Gallowswood Dreams Multiple sources report dreams of a black pulsating heart beating beneath a granite dome in Gallowswood . The dreams feature: Twisted crimson veins radiating from the heart An awakened lust for power in the dreamer A sense of something vast and hungry stirring beneath the earth Anaya&#39;s feverish descriptions of the pulsating heart beneath a mound in Gallowswood echo these dreams. Whether the dreams are prophetic, the product of Cthonic influence, or the psychic bleed of another sealed entity is unknown. Arc V -- Fort Meade to Sanctuary: Three Scenes The following arc covers the Reclaimers&#39; journey south from Fort Meade to Sanctuary , encompassing three critical developments: the revelation of Eolande at the Black Tree, the escalating crisis of the Stone of Sakkara , and Legate Marcellus&#39;s formal charter proposal. Scene 1: Malachor Wants Everything Malachor approaches the Reclaimers within hours of their return from the Black Tree -- not through a steward, not through Marcellus . Directly, and with barely-composed urgency. He has heard enough from garrison talk to know something significant happened at the Black Tree. He needs confirmation. Then everything. Malachor&#39;s Questions: His questions function as interrogation prompts, not a script. He will return to any the party deflects: What language did Eolande speak? Did he understand Mithrian, or only the old tongue? How coherent was he -- did he seem aware of time passing? Does he know the First Empire has fallen? What did he say about the Womb Curse ? About the Eladra ? About Bel ? The sword. Every detail. Does it bear any inscription? The dryad -- is the tree alive? Is she bound to the dead wood, or to something that remains in it? Malachor&#39;s Ask: He wants to accompany the party to Sanctuary . He frames this as mutual convenience -- he has contacts at the Imperial Academy chapter there, and what the party has witnessed constitutes academic testimony of enormous value. For Tiberius specifically: Malachor offers an introduction to senior Academy figures, vouched by him, with the Reclaimers&#39; testimony behind it. For a man looking to recover lost standing after expulsion from the Academy, that is not nothing. The expedition he is already forming: Two Academy assistants he intends to summon to Sanctuary, himself, and the Reclaimers as escort into Crossings . He presents this as something to finalize after they return from Sanctuary. He will push on every subsequent encounter. GM Note -- The Dispatch: That night Malachor writes the most significant dispatch of his career. His secret third-party contact -- the unnamed buyer who has received dry academic reports for years -- receives something fundamentally different. Malachor knows it the moment he finishes writing. He sends it before fully considering what he has set in motion. Whatever that contact represents, they now know about Eolande . Scene 2: The Stone and the Guzzler The Guzzler has been ranging further from Fort Ikenvar for weeks, drawn by the Stone of Sakkara . It cannot locate the Stone precisely -- it feels it the way an animal senses weather before it turns. When the party moved to Fort Meade , it followed. Now it follows south toward Sanctuary . Trail of Incidents (delivered as rumors, reports, and roadside encounters -- not all at once): A farm three miles south of Fort Meade: goats taken, fence posts crushed in. The farmer reports it two days late, embarrassed he waited. A merchant on the Sanctuary road: his draft horse found half-consumed at the roadside. He saw nothing. Heard nothing. The horse was simply gone. Closer to Sanctuary: a child -- eight years old -- taken from a yard at dusk. No body recovered. The family is on the road, unsure where to go. The Stone&#39;s Influence: The Stone is not directing the Guzzler with intelligence. But it is amplifying its hunger toward the soft and the innocent. Theodotus will not perceive this clearly -- he will feel it as a wrongness, a sense that the suffering he is hearing about is somehow adjacent to the weight in his pack. He refused to feed the Stone. So the Stone reached further. Theodotus&#39;s Moment: When the child&#39;s disappearance reaches him, the wrongness crystallizes. This is the test. Not a combat encounter. A question: Does he tell the party what he suspects? Does he try to destroy the Stone -- and does he know how? Does he draw the Guzzler away from the road deliberately? Does he realize that putting distance between himself and the Stone means it simply calls the creature further, and the geometry of innocence does not change? GM Note: The Guzzler arriving near Sanctuary is a consequence, not an encounter. Killing it resolves nothing -- the Stone will reach through something else. If the party fights it in an urban-adjacent environment, that is a very different problem than the marsh. The scene ends when Theodotus decides what to do about the Stone, not when the Guzzler dies. Scene 3: The Legate&#39;s Proposal Before the party departs for Sanctuary , Legate Marcellus requests a formal meeting. The message is delivered by his steward -- not Crull , not a soldier. This is deliberate, and the party may notice it. The Room: The Legate&#39;s meeting room. A map of the Backlands dominates one wall. Marcellus stands. Lady Severina is present, seated slightly to the side -- not beside him. Crull is not in the room. The Proposal: Marcellus opens by noting the Reclaimers brought four thousand gold worth of goods through his market in a single visit. Tax exempt. He lets that sit, then presents a formal business arrangement: A formal charter: The Reclaimers are his licensed salvagers with exclusive territorial claim to the ruins of Crossings and the Nethercity . No other party operates there without their sanction. A secure vault and warehouse at Fort Meade, constructed at his expense, for the Reclaimers&#39; exclusive use. A quarterly market fair at Fort Meade, drawing merchants from Sanctuary and Dunwick . He funds the first three years. In exchange: Fifteen percent of recovered value, payable in goods or coin at their discretion. And continued availability as his agents -- tasks specified as they arise. What He Doesn&#39;t Say: He does not say this is about Drussus . He does not say that a Fort Meade with a functioning market, a growing merchant quarter, and documented gold output is a Fort Meade that no longer needs the Governor&#39;s goodwill to survive. He does not say the Reclaimers are the engine he needs to change his political position. None of this needs saying. It is all visible to anyone paying attention. Severina&#39;s Role: After Marcellus finishes, Severina speaks. She frames it as opportunity rather than contract -- the charter carries weight in Sanctuary as well as Fort Meade, the formalization protects what they have already built, the Academy introductions Malachor can arrange become more credible under the Legate&#39;s seal. She is warm, interested, and precise beneath the warmth. She is not selling. She is clarifying. The difference is hard to pin down. Negotiation Parameters: Marcellus will not move on the structure. He will negotiate specifics: Percentage: Floor is ten percent. He opened at fifteen. Timeline for vault construction: Movable. Specifics of available when required : He will accept definition. He will also use any vagueness left in the final language. He will honor exactly what is agreed. He will exploit any ambiguity in exactly what is agreed. GM Note: Three weeks ago he was a frustrated legate using irregular assets to solve a bandit problem. He has moved faster than that framing suggests because he has been calculating since the Rook situation ended. This meeting is the result -- and the beginning of a dependency that runs in both directions. The party is becoming essential to his ambitions in a way that makes them harder to walk away from. See Also the-reclaimers -- The player character party the-backlands -- The province where the campaign takes place crossings -- The ruined border city fort-meade -- The garrison where the Reclaimers are based legate-marcellus -- Their formal patron lady-severina -- Their actual patron Nethercity -- The underground complex currently being explored the-stone-of-sakkara -- The dangerous artifact carried by Theodotus the-guzzler -- The demonic entity drawn by the Stone eolande -- Ancient Eladran general encountered at the Black Tree thornasse -- Site of the Black Tree encounter rook -- The bandit the Reclaimers destroyed fort-ikenvar -- Where Rook was destroyed and the Guzzler dwells scalper-gangs -- The other killers drawn by the bounty argollean-brotherhood -- Faction monitoring Nethercity recoveries imperial-academy -- Faction competing for artifacts malachor -- Academy representative, writing dispatches about Eolande governor-drussus -- The political rival Marcellus is maneuvering against shatzi -- PC, Merchant theodotus -- PC, Philosopher-Bard, bearer of the Stone tiberius -- PC, Necromancer, offered Academy introductions iman -- PC, Bladedancer tancred -- PC, Crusader (deceased) rendson -- PC, Avari Gambler (deceased) order-of-the-scarlet-ribbon -- The order from which Iman was expelled seros -- The faith Tancred served the-gilded-vigil -- The guardian tomb connected to Tiberius&#39;s discovery gallowswood -- Location of the pulsating heart dreams malyn-the-misshapen -- Scholar whose research revealed beastmen origins brother-marco -- Gave eulogies for Tancred and Rendson ezekiel-shaw -- Gave competing eulogy, used Tancred&#39;s death politically sergeant-crull -- Notably absent from the Legate&#39;s charter meeting"}];
